const SuttaQuotesData = [
     { text: `The merit of one who gives alms,<br>Always increases,<br>Gets rid of the mind of hatred.<br>Not storing, restraining,<br>The supremely good person abandons.<br>All unwholesome evil conduct,<br>Destroys greed, hatred, delusion.<br>The mind is liberated and pure.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Be a lamp unto yourselves, be a refuge unto yourselves. Do not seek refuge in anything else.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if someone were to revile me, revile the Dhamma, or revile the Saṅgha, you should not on that account become angry, resentful, or distressed. Bhikkhus, if someone reviles me, reviles the Dhamma, or reviles the Saṅgha, and you become angry, resentful, or distressed, that would be harmful to you. If you become angry and distressed, could you know whether what those people say is right or wrong?`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if someone were to praise me, praise the Dhamma, or praise the Saṅgha, you should not on that account be delighted, joyful, or elated. Bhikkhus, if someone praises me, praises the Dhamma, or praises the Saṅgha, and you become delighted, joyful, and elated, that would be harmful to you. Bhikkhus, if someone praises me, praises the Dhamma, or praises the Saṅgha, you should acknowledge what is factual as factual.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Stop, thoughts of sensual desire!<br>Stop, thoughts of ill will!<br>Stop, thoughts of harmfulness!<br>Enough of thoughts of sensual desire!<br>Enough of thoughts of ill will!<br>Enough of thoughts of harmfulness!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 17 – Mahāsudassanasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn17" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, in the past, sea-merchants when sailing across the ocean would take along a land-sighting bird. The bird would fly east, south, west, north, upwards, and in intermediate directions. If it saw land all around, it would fly towards that land. If it did not see land all around, it would return to the ship. So too, bhikkhu, you have searched as far as the Brahmā realm without finding an answer to that question, so you have returned to me. Bhikkhu, the question should not be asked thus: 'Venerable Sir, where do the four great elements — earth, water, fire, air — go after they have completely ceased?' Bhikkhu, the question should be asked thus: 'Where do earth, water, fire, and air, long and short, fine and coarse, pure and impure, find no footing? Where do name-and-form completely cease?' And this is the answer to that question: 'Consciousness is invisible, limitless, all-pervasive. Here, earth, water, fire, and air find no footing. Here, too, long and short, fine and coarse, pure and impure. Here name-and-form completely cease. When consciousness ceases, here everything ceases completely.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 11 – Kevaṭṭasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn11" },

{ text: `Lohicca, if a person were to say: 'King Pasenadi of Kosala lives in Kasi-Kosala; let King Pasenadi of Kosala enjoy alone all the products of Kasi-Kosala, no one else.' Would such a person be one who creates obstacles for those who depend on King Pasenadi of Kosala, or not? — Venerable Gotama, he would be one who creates obstacles. — Lohicca, being one who creates obstacles, does that person dwell with a mind of loving-kindness, wishing for the welfare of those others, or with a mind lacking loving-kindness? — Venerable Gotama, with a mind lacking loving-kindness. — Having a mind lacking loving-kindness, does that person dwell with a mind of loving-kindness or with a mind of harm? — Venerable Gotama, with a mind of harm! — Dwelling with a mind of harm, is that right view or wrong view? — Venerable Gotama, wrong view! — Lohicca, I say that a person with wrong view will be reborn in one of two lower realms: hell or the animal womb.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 12 – Lohiccasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn12" },

{ text: `Lohicca, there is here a teacher who has not attained the goal of the ascetic life for the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness. Not having attained that goal of the ascetic life, he teaches Dhamma to his disciples: 'This is for your good! This is for your happiness!' Those disciples do not listen to his words, do not lend ear, do not apply their minds to understanding, and live contrary to the teacher's teaching. Such a teacher should be censured: 'The Venerable One has not attained the goal of the ascetic life for the sake of which he went forth. Not having attained that goal, he teaches Dhamma to his disciples, saying "This is for your good! This is for your happiness!" Yet those disciples do not listen to him, do not lend ear, do not apply their minds to understanding, and live contrary to the teacher's teaching.' Lohicca, this is the first kind of teacher worthy of criticism, and whoever criticizes such a teacher criticizes rightly, properly, and without fault.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 12 – Lohiccasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn12" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Lohicca, there is here a teacher who has not attained the goal of the ascetic life for the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness. Not having attained that goal, he teaches Dhamma to his disciples: 'This is for your good! This is for your happiness!' Those disciples listen to his words, lend ear, apply their minds to understanding, and live not contrary to the teacher's teaching. Such a teacher should be censured: 'The Venerable One has not attained the goal of the ascetic life for the sake of which he went forth. Not having attained that goal, he teaches Dhamma to his disciples, saying "This is for your good! This is for your happiness!" Those disciples listen to him, lend ear, apply their minds to understanding, yet live contrary to the teacher's teaching. Like a person who abandons his own melon patch and thinks about weeding another's field. I say that such conduct is evil and greedy, for who would do work for another?' Lohicca, this is the second kind of teacher worthy of criticism, and whoever criticizes such a teacher criticizes rightly, properly, and without fault.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 12 – Lohiccasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn12" },

{ text: `Good friends, here someone associates with sensual pleasures and unwholesome states. After some time, he hears the noble Dhamma, gives proper attention, and attains the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it. Having heard the noble Dhamma, given proper attention, and attained the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it, he lives without associating with sensual pleasures or unwholesome states. Because he lives without associating with sensual pleasures or unwholesome states, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, just as from comfort joy is born, so too, good friends, because he lives without associating with sensual pleasures or unwholesome states, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, this is the first short path to well-being, realized by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Worthy One, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 18 – Janavasabhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn18" },

{ text: `Good friends, furthermore, here someone has coarse bodily conduct not yet calmed, coarse verbal conduct not yet calmed, coarse mental conduct not yet calmed. After some time, he hears the noble Dhamma, gives proper attention, and attains the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it. Having heard the noble Dhamma, given proper attention, and attained the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it, his coarse bodily conduct becomes calmed, his coarse verbal conduct becomes calmed, his coarse mental conduct becomes calmed. His bodily conduct being calmed, his verbal conduct being calmed, his mental conduct being calmed, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, just as from comfort joy is born, so too, good friends, because his coarse bodily conduct is calmed, his coarse verbal conduct is calmed, his coarse mental conduct is calmed, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, this is the second short path to well-being, realized by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Worthy One, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 18 – Janavasabhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn18" },

{ text: `Good friends, furthermore, here someone does not know as it actually is: 'this is wholesome,' does not know as it actually is: 'this is unwholesome,' does not know as it actually is: 'this is blameworthy,' 'this is blameless,' 'this should be followed,' 'this should be avoided,' 'this is inferior,' 'this is superior,' 'this is a mixture of dark and bright.' After some time, he hears the noble Dhamma, gives proper attention, and attains the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it. Having heard the noble Dhamma, given proper attention, and attained the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in conformity with it, he knows as it actually is: 'this is wholesome,' knows as it actually is: 'this is unwholesome,' knows as it actually is: 'this is blameworthy,' 'this is blameless,' 'this should be followed,' 'this should be avoided,' 'this is inferior,' 'this is superior,' 'this is a mixture of dark and bright.' Knowing thus, seeing thus, his ignorance is destroyed and knowledge arises. Because his ignorance is destroyed and knowledge has arisen, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, just as from comfort joy is born, so too, good friends, because his ignorance is destroyed and knowledge has arisen, ease arises, and more than ease, joy arises. Good friends, this is the third short path to well-being, realized by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Worthy One, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Good friends, these are the three short paths to well-being, realized by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Worthy One, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 18 – Janavasabhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn18" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, because of what fetter do devas, humans, asuras, nāgas, gandhabbas, and all other kinds of people wish: 'May we live without hatred, without violence, without enmity, without ill will, in peace,' yet with hatred, with violence, with enmity, with ill will, they live in hatred? - Lord of devas, it is because of envy and stinginess that devas, humans, asuras, nāgas, gandhabbas, and all other kinds of people, with hatred, with violence, with enmity, with ill will, live in hatred. - Venerable Sir, envy and stinginess — what is their cause, their origin, their arising, their source? What being present do envy and stinginess arise? What being absent do envy and stinginess not arise? - Lord of devas, envy and stinginess have liking and disliking as their cause, liking and disliking as their origin, liking and disliking as their arising, liking and disliking as their source. When liking and disliking are present, envy and stinginess arise; when liking and disliking are absent, envy and stinginess do not arise. - Venerable Sir, liking and disliking — what is their cause, their origin, their arising, their source? What being present do liking and disliking arise? What being absent do liking and disliking not arise? - Lord of devas, liking and disliking have desire as their cause, desire as their origin, desire as their arising, desire as their source. When desire is present, liking and disliking arise; when desire is absent, liking and disliking do not arise.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 21 – Sakkapañhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn21" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, liking and disliking — what is their cause, their origin, their arising, their source? What being present do liking and disliking arise? What being absent do liking and disliking not arise? - Lord of devas, liking and disliking have desire as their cause, desire as their origin, desire as their arising, desire as their source. When desire is present, liking and disliking arise; when desire is absent, liking and disliking do not arise. - Venerable Sir, but desire — what is its cause, its origin, its arising, its source? What being present does desire arise? What being absent does desire not arise? - Lord of devas, desire has thought as its cause, thought as its origin, thought as its arising, thought as its source. When thought is present, desire arises; when thought is absent, desire does not arise. - Venerable Sir, thought — what is its cause, its origin, its arising, its source? What being present does thought arise? What being absent does thought not arise? - Lord of devas, thought has perceptions and notions of proliferation as its cause, perceptions and notions of proliferation as its origin, perceptions and notions of proliferation as its arising, perceptions and notions of proliferation as its source. When perceptions and notions of proliferation are present, thought arises; when perceptions and notions of proliferation are absent, thought does not arise.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 21 – Sakkapañhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn21" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, how should a bhikkhu realize? What path is suitable and leads to the elimination of perceptions and notions of proliferation? - Lord of devas, I say that there are two kinds of proliferation: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. I say that there are two kinds of sorrow: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. I say that there are two kinds of equanimity: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. I say that there are two kinds of joy: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. This statement has been made. Why was it made? Here, regarding joy, one can know: 'When I cultivate this joy, unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease' — that joy should be avoided. Here, regarding joy, one can know: 'When I cultivate this joy, unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase' — that joy should be cultivated. Here, there is joy accompanied by thought and examination; there is joy without thought or examination. Joy without thought or examination is superior. Lord of devas, I say there are two kinds of joy: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. This is the reason for that statement. Lord of devas, I say there are two kinds of sorrow: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. This statement has been made. Why was it made? Here, regarding sorrow, one can know: 'When I cultivate this sorrow, unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease' — that sorrow should be avoided. Here, regarding sorrow, one can know: 'When I cultivate this sorrow, unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase' — that sorrow should be cultivated. Here, there is sorrow accompanied by thought and examination; there is sorrow without thought or examination. Sorrow without thought or examination is superior. Lord of devas, I say there are two kinds of sorrow: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. This is the reason for that statement.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 21 – Sakkapañhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn21" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, how should a bhikkhu be accomplished, how should he accomplish the restraint of the Pātimokkha? - Lord of devas, I say that there are two kinds of bodily conduct: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. I say that there are two kinds of verbal conduct: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. I say that there are two kinds of seeking: one to be cultivated, one to be avoided. This statement has been made. Why was it made? Here, regarding bodily conduct, one can know: 'When I cultivate this bodily conduct, unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease' — that bodily conduct should be avoided. Here, regarding bodily conduct, one can know: 'When I cultivate this bodily conduct, unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase' — that bodily conduct should be cultivated.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 21 – Sakkapañhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn21" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, do all ascetics and brahmins have the same ultimate goal, the same security, the same holy life, the same purpose? - Lord of devas, not all ascetics and brahmins have the same ultimate goal, the same security, the same holy life, the same purpose. - Venerable Sir, why is it that not all ascetics and brahmins have the same ultimate goal, the same security, the same holy life, the same purpose? - Lord of devas, only those ascetics and brahmins who are freed from craving have the same ultimate goal, the same security, the same holy life, the same purpose. Therefore, not all ascetics and brahmins have the same ultimate goal, the same security, the same holy life, the same purpose. This is the form of the Blessed One's answer to Lord of Devas Sakka's question. Delighted, Lord of Devas Sakka rejoiced, accepted the Blessed One's teaching, and said: - So it is, Venerable Sir! So it is, Well-farer! Venerable Sir, craving is a disease, craving is a boil, craving is an arrow; craving leads a person to rebirth in this state and that, making them sometimes high, sometimes low. Venerable Sir, while other ascetics and brahmins outside your sect do not give me the opportunity to ask such questions, the Blessed One has answered those questions for me, explained them at length for me, and the arrow of my doubt and uncertainty has been pulled out by the Blessed One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 21 – Sakkapañhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn21" },

{ text: `- Lord, just as a person born blind cannot see black or white colors, cannot see blue, yellow, red, or brown colors, cannot see fine or coarse objects, cannot see stars or the moon. That person says: 'There are no black or white colors, no one sees black or white colors; there is no blue color, no one sees blue color; there is no yellow color, no one sees yellow color; there is no red color, no one sees red color; there is no brown color, no one sees brown color; there are no fine or coarse objects, no one sees fine or coarse objects; there are no stars, no one sees stars; there is no moon or sun, no one sees moon or sun. I do not know this thing, I do not see this thing, therefore this thing does not exist.' Lord, would such a statement be reasonable? - No, Venerable Kassapa. There are black and white colors, and there are those who see black and white colors; there is blue color, and there are those who see blue color; there is yellow color, and there are those who see yellow color; there is red color, and there are those who see red color; there is brown color, and there are those who see brown color; there are fine and coarse objects, and there are those who see fine and coarse objects; there are stars, and there are those who see stars; there is moon and sun, and there are those who see moon and sun. 'I do not know this thing, I do not see this thing, therefore this thing does not exist.' Venerable Kassapa, anyone who speaks thus speaks unreasonably! - So too, Lord, you speak like the blind-born person when you say to me: 'Who told Venerable Kassapa to know: "There are devas in the Thirty-three," or "The devas in the Thirty-three have such a lifespan!" We do not believe Venerable Kassapa when he says: "There are devas in the Thirty-three," or "The devas in the Thirty-three have such a lifespan." Lord, the next world is not, as you think, to be seen with the fleshly eye. Lord, there are ascetics and brahmins who dwell in remote jungle lodgings, with little noise, little commotion. There they dwell diligent, ardent, and resolute, purifying the divine eye. Then with the divine eye, purified and surpassing the human, they see this world and the next, and all kinds of beings. Lord, the next world is to be seen thus, not as you think with the fleshly eye. Lord, since this is the case, I have knowledge and vision: 'There is a next world, there are beings who are spontaneously reborn, good and evil actions have results and fruits.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 23 – Pāyāsisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn23" },

{ text: `Brahmin, just as one hand washes the other, one foot washes the other, so wisdom is purified by virtue, and virtue is purified by wisdom. Where there is virtue, there is wisdom; where there is wisdom, there is virtue. One with virtue certainly has wisdom; one with wisdom certainly has virtue. Virtue and wisdom are considered supreme in the world. But, brahmin, what is virtue and what is wisdom?`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 4 – Soṇadaṇḍasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn4" },

{ text: `Samaṇa Gotama abstains from killing living beings, avoids killing, lays aside stick and sword, is conscientious and compassionate, dwelling with goodwill for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from taking what is not given, avoids taking what is not given, takes only what is given, desires only what is given, and lives purely without theft. Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Samaṇa Gotama abstains from false speech, avoids false speech, speaks truth, adheres to truth, is reliable, trustworthy, does not deceive, does not break his word to the world. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from divisive speech, avoids divisive speech; what he hears here he does not repeat elsewhere to cause division among these people; what he hears elsewhere he does not repeat to these people to cause division among those people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Thus Samaṇa Gotama unites those who are divided, encourages those who are united, delights in harmony, rejoices in harmony, speaks words that lead to harmony. Bhikkhus, Samaṇa Gotama abstains from harsh speech, avoids harsh speech; he speaks words that are blameless, pleasing to the ear, affectionate, touching the heart, courteous, delightful to many, agreeable to many. Samaṇa Gotama speaks such words.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, Samaṇa Gotama abstains from idle chatter, avoids idle chatter; he speaks at the right time, speaks what is true, speaks what is meaningful, speaks about the Dhamma, speaks about the Discipline, speaks words worth treasuring, timely, reasonable, coherent, connected, and beneficial. Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these are only trifling and minor matters, mere moral virtues, by which ordinary people praise the Tathāgata. There are other states, deep, difficult to see, difficult to realize, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of mere reasoning, subtle, to be understood by the wise. These states the Tathāgata, having realized them himself with direct knowledge, proclaims.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata understands thus: 'These views, thus grasped, thus adhered to, will lead to such destinies, such future states.' The Tathāgata knows this, and he knows more than that, yet he does not cling to that knowledge. Through not clinging to that knowledge, he has realized inner peace.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `He understands as it actually is the origin, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape from feelings. Knowing this, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata is completely liberated without clinging. Those dhammas, bhikkhus, are deep, difficult to see, difficult to realize ... and those who rightly and truly praise the Tathāgata speak of these very dhammas.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `The first being to be born there thinks: 'I am Brahmā, Great Brahmā, the All-powerful ... the Father of all beings who have been and will be. These beings are created by me. Why is that? Because I thought: "May other beings also come to this place." And my wish came true.' The beings who are born later also think: 'This is Brahmā, Great Brahmā ... We have been created by this Brahmā.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are some ascetics and brahmins who are logicians and investigators. Driven by their logical reasoning and following their own investigation, they declare: 'The self and the world are eternal, unborn, as firm as a mountain peak, as a stone pillar; while those beings wander and revolve, pass away and reappear, yet they remain eternal.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `When asked about this or that point, he evades the issue with evasive speech, wriggling like an eel: 'I don't say it is like that. I don't say it is like this. I don't say it is otherwise. I don't say it is not so. I don't say it is not not so.' Bhikkhus, this is the first case ... some ascetics and brahmins who hold the doctrine of evasive speech.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `He says: 'The self and the world arise without a cause. Why is that? Because previously I did not exist, now I exist. From a state of non-existence, I have become a being.' Bhikkhus, this is the first case ... some ascetics and brahmins who hold the doctrine of non-causality, asserting that the self and the world arise without a cause.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `That doctrine is the personal experience, the not-knowing, the not-seeing, the feeling of those ascetics and brahmins, the agitation, vacillation, and distortion of those who are dominated by craving. That doctrine arises from contact (of the faculties). These people could not experience those doctrines without contact.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `All these people have those feelings (the above doctrines) due to contact through the six sense bases. Dependent on feeling, craving arises; dependent on craving, clinging arises; dependent on clinging, existence arises; dependent on existence, birth arises; dependent on birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a skilled fisherman or his apprentice would cast a fine-meshed net over a small pond, and he would think: 'The large fish in this pond are all caught within this net, even if they leap about, they are trapped and caught here.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, whatever ascetics or brahmins speculate about the primordial past or speculate about the future ... proclaiming various diverse views — all of them are caught within the net of these sixty-two doctrines; even if they leap about, they are trapped and caught here.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Kevaddha, hearing this, I said to that bhikkhu: 'Bhikkhu, in the past, sea-merchants when sailing across the ocean would take along a land-sighting bird. When the ship had sailed far out and land was no longer visible, the merchants would release the land-sighting bird. The bird would fly east, south, west, north, upwards, and in intermediate directions. If it saw land all around, it would fly towards that land. If it did not see land all around, it would return to the ship. So too, bhikkhu, you have searched as far as the Brahmā realm without finding an answer to that question, so you have returned to me. Bhikkhu, the question should not be asked thus: "Venerable Sir, where do the four great elements — earth, water, fire, air — go after they have completely ceased?" Bhikkhu, the question should be asked thus: "Where do earth, water, fire, and air, long and short, fine and coarse, pure and impure, find no footing? Where do name-and-form completely cease?" And this is the answer to that question:<br><br>Consciousness is invisible, boundless, all-pervasive.<br>Here, earth, water, fire, wind element find no footing.<br>Here, also, long and short, fine and coarse, pure and impure.<br>Here, name and form completely cease.<br>When consciousness ceases, here everything ceases utterly.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 11 – Kevaṭṭasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn11" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's body remains, but the condition that leads to another life has been cut off. Just as a branch with a cluster of mangoes is cut off, all the mangoes attached to that branch share the same fate as the branch. So too, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's body remains, but the condition that leads to another life has been cut off.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `As long as this person's body remains, devas and humans can see that body. When the body breaks up and life ends, devas and humans cannot see it. Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's body remains, but the condition that leads to another life has been cut off. As long as this person's body remains, devas and humans can see that body.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Thus that bhikkhu unites those who are divided, encourages those who are united, delights in harmony, rejoices in harmony, speaks words that lead to harmony. He abstains from harsh speech, avoids harsh speech; he speaks words that are gentle, pleasing to the ear, affectionate, entering the heart, courteous, delightful to many people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abstains from false speech, avoids false speech; he speaks truth, adheres to truth, is reliable, trustworthy, does not deceive, does not break his word to the world. Such is his virtue in terms of moral discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `The bhikkhu abstains from divisive speech, avoids divisive speech; what he hears here he does not repeat elsewhere to cause division among these people; what he hears elsewhere he does not repeat to these people to cause division among those people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `So too, great king, that bhikkhu, being fully endowed with virtue, sees no danger from any quarter regarding the protection of his virtue. Being endowed with this noble virtue, he experiences inner well-being, without disturbance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great king, when the eye sees a form, the bhikkhu does not grasp the general appearance, does not grasp the particular details. Whatever causes — if the eye faculty were unrestrained — would give rise to craving, sorrow, and unwholesome states, that he restrains; he guards the eye faculty, undertakes the restraint of the eye faculty.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whatever causes — if the mind faculty were unrestrained — would give rise to craving, sorrow, and unwholesome states, that he restrains; he guards the mind faculty, undertakes the restraint of the mind faculty. By means of this noble restraint of the faculties, he experiences inner well-being, without disturbance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Ajàtasattu, son of Videhi, king of Magadha, looking at the assembly of bhikkhus, silent and serene like a clear lake, said with inspiration: 'May Prince Udāyibhadda also attain such silence as the silence of these bhikkhus.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great king, just as a bird, wherever it flies, carries its two wings with it; so too, great king, the bhikkhu is content with a robe to protect his body and almsfood to sustain his stomach, and wherever he goes, he takes only these. Thus, great king, the bhikkhu is content.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons craving for the world, dwelling with a mind free from craving, purifying the mind of craving. He abandons ill will, dwelling with a mind free from ill will, compassionate and kind towards all living beings, purifying the mind of ill will.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons dullness and drowsiness, dwelling free from dullness and drowsiness; with perception of light, mindful and clearly comprehending, purifying the mind of dullness and drowsiness.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons restlessness and remorse, dwelling without restlessness, with inner peace, purifying the mind of restlessness and remorse. He abandons doubt, dwelling free from doubt, without uncertainty or indecision, purifying the mind of doubt.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great king, just as a man free of debt, as a man free of disease, as a man released from prison, as a man free and independent, as a secure and pleasant land — great king, the bhikkhu reflects on the five hindrances as abandoned.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `When he reflects that these five hindrances have been abandoned in himself, joy arises; from joy, rapture arises; when the mind is rapturous, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he experiences ease; with ease, the mind becomes concentrated.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, the bhikkhu enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by thought and examination, with rapture and ease born of seclusion. He drenches, saturates, fills, and suffuses his body with the rapture and ease born of seclusion, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that rapture and ease born of seclusion.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He drenches, saturates, fills, and suffuses his body with the rapture and ease born of concentration, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that rapture and ease born of concentration. Great king, this is a visible fruit of the ascetic life, more excellent and sublime than previous visible fruits of the ascetic life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With the fading away of rapture, he dwells equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending, experiencing ease with the body; he enters and dwells in the third jhāna, of which the noble ones declare: 'Equanimous and mindful, one dwells in ease.' He drenches, saturates, fills, and suffuses his body with the ease free from rapture, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that ease free from rapture.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With the abandoning of pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and sorrow, he enters and dwells in the fourth jhāna, which has neither pain nor pleasure, and is purified by equanimity and mindfulness. He sits suffusing his body with a pure, bright mind, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that pure, bright mind.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He understands as it actually is: 'This is suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the origin of suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the cessation of suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'These are the taints' ... Knowing thus, seeing thus, his mind is liberated from the taint of sensual desire, liberated from the taint of existence, liberated from the taint of ignorance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `In that liberated state, he knows: 'Birth is exhausted, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done; there is no further existence beyond this present life.' Great king, this is a visible fruit of the ascetic life, more excellent and sublime than previous visible fruits of the ascetic life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `How beautiful is the full-moon night! Now let us go to pay homage to whichever ascetic or brahmin, through whose homage our minds may gain confidence." Jīvaka replied: "The Blessed One Gotama has a good reputation: 'He is the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, well-gone, knower of the world, unsurpassed trainer of persons to be tamed, teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One.' Great king, go to pay homage to the Blessed One. It is very likely that, through paying homage, the great king's mind may gain confidence.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `The bhikkhu abstains from false speech, avoids false speech; he speaks truth, adheres to truth, is reliable, trustworthy, does not deceive, does not break his word to the world. He abstains from divisive speech, unites those who are divided, encourages those who are united. Such is his virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some ascetics and brahmins ... still engage in frivolous, trivial talk such as talk about kings, talk about thieves, talk about ministers, talk about armies, talk about terrors, talk about wars, talk about food and drink, and other such vain talk, the ascetic Gotama abstains from such frivolous, trivial talk.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some ascetics and brahmins ... still use ornaments and cosmetics such as anointing, massaging, bathing, mirrors, ointments, garlands, perfumes, bracelets, head-wigs, walking sticks ... he does not use such ornaments and cosmetics.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He avoids wrong livelihood such as: consulting mirrors, consulting female mediums, consulting devas for signs of good or evil, worshipping the sun, worshipping the earth, spitting fire, invoking the goddess of fortune, using spells for good luck or causing misfortune. Such is his virtue in terms of moral discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He avoids wrong livelihood such as: using magical rites for peace, purification rituals, bathing rituals, sacrifice rituals, making oneself vomit, purging, expelling impurities ... treating eye diseases, practicing medicine, surgery on children, administering root medicines, neutralizing the effects of medicines.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `When the eye sees a form, the bhikkhu does not grasp the general appearance, does not grasp the particular details. Whatever causes — if the eye faculty were unrestrained — would give rise to craving, sorrow, and unwholesome states, that he restrains; he guards the eye faculty ... By means of this noble restraint of the faculties, he experiences inner well-being, without disturbance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `When the bhikkhu is going forward or returning, he clearly comprehends what he is doing; when looking ahead or looking aside, he clearly comprehends what he is doing; when bending or stretching his limbs, he clearly comprehends what he is doing ... Thus he dwells mindful and clearly comprehending, practicing mindfulness and clear comprehension.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, the bhikkhu enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by thought and examination, with rapture and ease born of seclusion. He drenches, saturates, fills, and suffuses his body with the rapture and ease born of seclusion, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that rapture.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With the abandoning of pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and sorrow, he enters and dwells in the fourth jhāna, which has neither pain nor pleasure, and is purified by equanimity and mindfulness. He sits suffusing his body with a pure, bright mind, so that no part of his entire body is not suffused with that pure, bright mind.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Knowing thus, seeing thus, his mind is liberated from the taint of sensual desire, liberated from the taint of existence, liberated from the taint of ignorance. In that liberated state, he knows: 'Birth is exhausted, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done; there is no further existence beyond this present life.' Great king, this is a visible fruit of the ascetic life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },


{ text: `Like a multi-storied mansion with an upper terrace at a crossroads, a person with eyes standing there would see people entering houses, leaving houses, and walking back and forth on the road... Likewise, a bhikkhu sees the death and rebirth of beings.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `The following good reports are spread about Samaṇa Gotama: 'He is the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, the Well-Gone, the Knower of the world, the Unsurpassed Trainer of persons, the Teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One.' He teaches the Dhamma, good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, and reveals the holy life completely perfect and pure.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `According to our tradition regarding the thirty-two marks of a great man, anyone who possesses these thirty-two marks has two paths, no other. If he remains at home, he becomes a Wheel-turning Monarch... If he goes forth... he becomes an Arahant, Perfectly Enlightened, clearing away all delusion in the world.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Ambattha, just as a young partridge can sing freely in its nest. Ambattha, Kapilavatthu belongs to the Sakya clan. It is not fitting for Ambattha to be displeased over such a trivial matter.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `This verse was spoken by the Brahma Sanamkumara:<br>'Among beings who believe in caste,<br>The Kshatriya is the foremost among humans.<br>But one perfect in conduct and wisdom,<br>That one is foremost among devas and humans.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Those who still cling to theories of birth, theories of caste, theories of pride, or still cling to marriage and bringing home the bride, those people are still very far from attaining supreme knowledge and virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Not clinging to theories of birth, not clinging to theories of caste, not clinging to theories of pride, not clinging to marriage and bringing home the bride, that person attains supreme knowledge and virtue. There is no other attainment of knowledge and virtue more excellent, more sublime than this attainment of knowledge and virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Wonderful, Master Gotama! Wonderful, Master Gotama! Just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms. So too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by Master Gotama.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One gradually taught the brahmin Pokkharasādi, speaking on giving, speaking on virtue, speaking on the heavens, explaining the danger, the degradation, and the defilement of sensual pleasures, and the benefit of renunciation. When the Blessed One knew that the mind of the brahmin Pokkharasādi was ready, pliant, free from hindrances, uplifted, and confident, then he taught the Dhamma that the Buddhas have realized, namely: suffering, origin, cessation, and path. Just as a pure cloth, freed from stains, would readily take a dye, so too, in that very seat, the dustless, stainless Dhamma-eye arose in the mind of the brahmin Pokkharasādi: 'Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Thus, Ambattha, you and your teacher are not true ascetics, you do not live the life of an ascetic. Ambattha, if there is anything you doubt or are uncertain about regarding me, ask me and I will answer.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `What do you think, Ambattha? Have you heard the brahmins who are elders, senior, teachers, and ancestors say? In the past, those ascetics among the brahmins, the authors of the mantras, the reciters of the mantras who sang, spoke, and compiled the sacred verses that today's brahmins sing, speak, and recite just as the former ones did. Those ascetics named Atthaka, Vāmaka, ..., Kassapa, Bhagu. Did they bathe well, groom well, keep their hair and beard well-trimmed, adorn themselves with garlands and jewels, wear white clothes, enjoy and indulge in the five strands of sensual pleasure, as you and your teacher do now?`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3" },

{ text: `Brahmin, wisdom is purified by virtue, virtue is purified by wisdom. Where there is virtue, there is wisdom; where there is wisdom, there is virtue. One with virtue certainly has wisdom; one with wisdom certainly has virtue. Virtue and wisdom are considered supreme in the world.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 5 – Kūṭadantasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn5" },

{ text: `Kassapa, if a bhikkhu dwells cultivating a mind of compassion, without hatred, without malice, and with the destruction of the taints, he personally realizes and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom in this very life. That bhikkhu, Kassapa, is called a samaṇa, is called a brahmin.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 8 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn8" },

{ text: `I go to them and say: 'Friends, let those points on which you disagree remain as they are. On those points on which you agree, let the wise among you question one another, investigate and discuss with one another, teacher with teacher, or groups of disciples with groups of disciples: "Those unwholesome states that are considered unwholesome, those faulty states that are considered faulty, those states not to be practiced that are considered not to be practiced, those states unbefitting the noble ones that are considered unbefitting the noble ones, those defiled states that are considered defiled."'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 8 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn8" },

{ text: `Kassapa, this situation occurs. When the wise question one another, investigate and discuss with one another, they say: 'Those wholesome states that are considered wholesome, those faultless states that are considered faultless, those states to be practiced that are considered to be practiced, those states befitting the noble ones that are considered befitting the noble ones, those pure states that are considered pure, Samaṇa Gotama has perfectly attained these states, while those other venerable teachers and leaders of sects have attained them only partially.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 8 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn8" },

{ text: `The wanderer Poṭṭhapāda saw the Blessed One coming from afar and exhorted his assembly: "Sirs, lower your voices, sirs, do not make noise. Now Samaṇa Gotama is coming, he loves quiet, and this venerable one praises quiet. If he knows this assembly is quiet, he might approach." Upon hearing this, the wanderers fell silent.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Similarly, Poṭṭhapāda, that bhikkhu, by being possessed of virtue, sees no danger anywhere in regard to restraint of virtue. By being possessed of this noble virtue, he experiences an inner, blameless sense of well-being. Thus, Poṭṭhapāda, a bhikkhu is one possessed of virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Poṭṭhapāda, when a bhikkhu here himself arouses a perception, he proceeds from one perception to another until he reaches the peak perception. And when he has reached the peak perception, he can think: 'Thinking is harmful to me, not thinking is better for me. If I continue to think, when these perceptions of mine cease, other gross perceptions might arise. So let me not think.' And he does not think. By not thinking, those perceptions cease and other gross perceptions do not arise. He experiences cessation. Thus, Poṭṭhapāda, is the gradual attainment of the cessation of higher perceptions through wisdom.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, does perception arise first, and knowledge later? Or does knowledge arise first, and perception later? Or do perception and knowledge arise simultaneously, without before or after? - Poṭṭhapāda, perception arises first, knowledge arises later. From the arising of perception, knowledge arises. He understands: 'Conditioned by perception, knowledge arises in me.' Poṭṭhapāda, by this teaching it should be understood that perception arises first, knowledge later; from perception, knowledge arises.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `- Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms. So too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by the Blessed One. Venerable Sir, I go for refuge to the Blessed One, to the Dhamma, and to the Bhikkhu Saṅgha. May the Blessed One accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Poṭṭhapāda, when defiled states are abandoned and pure states increase, one in this very life, with direct knowledge, attains and abides in full and extensive wisdom, then joy arises, gladness, tranquility, mindfulness, clear comprehension, and a pleasant abiding arise.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Poṭṭhapāda, what are the teachings that I have declared and explained definitively? 'This is suffering,' Poṭṭhapāda, that is a teaching I have declared definitively. 'This is the origin of suffering,' Poṭṭhapāda, that is a teaching I have declared definitively. 'This is the cessation of suffering,' Poṭṭhapāda, that is a teaching I have declared definitively. 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering,' Poṭṭhapāda, that is a teaching I have declared definitively.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Poṭṭhapāda, those teachings that pertain to the goal of liberation, pertain to the Dhamma, pertain to the fundamental holy life, leading to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbāna, are the teachings I have declared and explained definitively.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Kevaddha, what is the miracle of instruction? Here, a bhikkhu instructs as follows: 'Think like this, do not think like that; attend like this, do not attend like that; abandon this, attain and abide in that.' Kevaddha, this is called the miracle of instruction.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 11 – Kevaṭṭasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn11" },

{ text: `Consciousness is unmanifest, boundless,<br>All-illuminating.<br>There, earth, water,<br>Fire, and air find no footing.<br>There, likewise, long and short,<br>Subtle and gross, pure and impure.<br>There, name and form cease without remainder.<br>When consciousness ceases, here all ceases.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 11 – Kevaṭṭasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn11" },

{ text: `- Vāseṭṭha, those brahmins who are proficient in the three Vedas, not knowing, not seeing the path leading to co-residence with Brahmā, yet teach: 'This is the direct path, this is the right path leading to co-residence with Brahmā for those who practice it' - that is impossible. Vāseṭṭha, just as a string of blind men clinging to each other, the first does not see, the middle does not see, the last does not see. So too, Vāseṭṭha, the words of those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas are like blind words: the first does not see, the middle does not see, the last does not see. Such words of those brahmins are to be laughed at, are empty words, are worthless words, are void.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `A householder, or a householder's son, or one born in some lower clan, hears that Dhamma. After hearing the Dhamma, he gains faith in the Tathāgata. Having gained that faith, he reflects: 'Household life is crowded and dusty; the going forth is wide open. It is not easy for one living at home to live the holy life completely perfect and pure as a polished conch shell. Let me shave off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Having gone forth, he lives restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, possessed of proper conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules, pure in bodily and verbal conduct. His livelihood is pure, his virtue is complete, he guards the sense doors, he is mindful and clearly comprehending, and he is content.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, even if those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas sit with confidence, they are actually sinking in the mud, and while sinking in the mud, they live in disappointment, mistakenly thinking they have reached a more peaceful state. Therefore, for those brahmins proficient in the Vedas, that proficiency is called a waterless desert, that proficiency is also called a pathless jungle, that proficiency is also called misfortune.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī, on his way to the pleasure garden, saw an old man, bent over like a roof, leaning on a staff, trembling as he walked, afflicted, no longer young. Seeing this, the prince asked the charioteer: 'Friend, who is that man? Why is his body unlike that of others?' 'Your Highness, he is called an old man.' 'Friend, why is he called an old man?' 'Your Highness, he is called old because he does not have long to live.' 'Friend, will I too become old, not beyond old age?' 'Your Highness, you and I too, we will all become old, though we are not yet old.' 'Friend, then today's visit to the pleasure garden is enough. Drive me back to the palace.' 'Yes, Your Highness.' Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī returned to the palace, distressed, sorrowful, and reflecting: 'Shame indeed, this thing called birth. For anyone born, they must become old like that!'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then the Bodhisatta Vipassī reflected: 'This consciousness turns back and forth, it does not go beyond name-and-form. Only to this extent one is born, or becomes old, or dies, or passes away, or is reborn, that is: conditioned by name-and-form, consciousness arises; conditioned by consciousness, name-and-form arises; conditioned by name-and-form, the six sense bases arise; conditioned by the six sense bases, contact arises; conditioned by contact, feeling arises; conditioned by feeling, craving arises; conditioned by craving, clinging arises; conditioned by clinging, existence arises; conditioned by existence, birth arises; conditioned by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then the Bodhisatta Vipassī reflected: 'Oh, I have discovered the path to enlightenment, through the practice of contemplation. That is: with the cessation of name-and-form, consciousness ceases; with the cessation of consciousness, name-and-form ceases; with the cessation of name-and-form, the six sense bases cease; with the cessation of the six sense bases, contact ceases; with the cessation of contact, feeling ceases; with the cessation of feeling, craving ceases; with the cessation of craving, clinging ceases; with the cessation of clinging, existence ceases; with the cessation of existence, birth ceases; with the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī, on his way to the pleasure garden, saw a renunciant, shaven-headed, wearing the ochre robe. Seeing him, the prince asked the charioteer: 'Friend, what has this man done, that his head is different from others' heads, and his robe is different from others' robes?' 'Your Highness, he is called a renunciant.' 'Friend, why is he called a renunciant?' 'Your Highness, renunciation means living well the holy life, living well the pure life, doing good deeds, doing meritorious deeds, refraining from harming living beings, having loving-kindness towards living beings.' 'Friend, then drive the chariot close to that renunciant.' 'Yes, Your Highness.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then Prince Vipassī asked the renunciant: 'Venerable sir, what have you done, that your head is not like others' heads, and your robe is not like others' robes?' 'Your Highness, I am a renunciant.' 'Venerable sir, what is meant by a renunciant?' 'Your Highness, I am called a renunciant because I live well the holy life, live well the pure life, do good deeds, do meritorious deeds, refrain from harming living beings, have loving-kindness towards living beings.' 'Venerable sir, excellent is your renunciation, excellent is the well-lived holy life, the well-lived pure life, the doing of good deeds, the doing of meritorious deeds, the refraining from harming living beings, the having of loving-kindness towards living beings.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, while in seclusion, the Bodhisatta Vipassī reflected: 'Why should I live surrounded by this assembly? It would be better for me to live alone, secluded from this assembly!'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then the Bodhisatta Vipassī, after some time, dwelt contemplating arising and passing away in the five aggregates: 'Such is form, such is the arising of form, such is the passing away of form. Such is feeling... Such is perception... Such are formations... Such is consciousness, such is the arising of consciousness, such is the passing away of consciousness.' And for him, after dwelling contemplating arising and passing away in the five aggregates of clinging, before long, the taints were destroyed and he was liberated.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye, seeing beings with little dust in their eyes, with much dust in their eyes, with keen faculties, with dull faculties, with good qualities, with bad qualities, easy to teach, hard to teach, and some who saw the danger in future rebirth and the danger in faulty actions. Just as in a pond of blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses, some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, do not rise above the water, thrive while submerged; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, live reaching the water's surface; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, rise above the water and stand without being wetted by the water.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, recited this Pātimokkha among the bhikkhus:<br><br>'The Buddhas teach Nibbāna as foremost.<br>'Patience, austerity, endurance are foremost.<br>'A renunciant who harms another renunciant,<br>'One who harms others is not worthy to be called a samaṇa.<br><br>'Not doing any evil, directing the mind to wholesome deeds,<br>'Keeping the mind pure, that is the teaching of the Buddhas.<br><br>'Not criticizing, not striking, restraining oneself in the Pātimokkha,<br>'Eating in moderation, sleeping alone,<br>'Directing the mind to the sublime, that is the teaching of the Buddhas.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Ānanda, as long as the Vajjis do not enact any new decrees, do not abolish any existing decrees, and live in accordance with the traditional Vajji rules as enacted in the past, then Ānanda, the Vajjis will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, as long as the Vajjis honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Vajji elders and listen to their advice, then the Vajjis will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus assemble in harmony, disperse in harmony, and do the Saṅgha's business in harmony, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not enact any new rules, do not abolish any existing rules, and live in accordance with the training rules as laid down, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the elder bhikkhus, those who are experienced, senior, long ordained, the fathers of the Saṅgha, the leaders of the Saṅgha, and listen to their advice, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus are not overcome by craving that leads to renewed existence, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus delight in secluded dwellings, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus personally establish mindfulness, causing their good companions who have not yet come to come, and those who have come to dwell in comfort, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not delight in worldly business, do not enjoy worldly business, do not indulge in worldly business, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not delight in frivolous talk, do not enjoy frivolous talk, do not indulge in frivolous talk, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not delight in sleeping, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not delight in company, do not enjoy company, do not indulge in company, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not have evil desires, are not overcome by evil desires, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus do not have evil friends, evil companions, evil associates, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus, towards their fellow celibates, in public and in private, maintain bodily acts of loving-kindness, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus, towards their fellow celibates, in public and in private, maintain verbal acts of loving-kindness, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus, towards their fellow celibates, in public and in private, maintain mental acts of loving-kindness, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus share without partiality, together with their virtuous companions, all righteous, lawful gains, even down to the contents of their alms bowls, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus live with their companions, in public and in private, in accordance with the precepts that are proper to the samaṇa life, precepts that are unbroken, unblemished, unspotted, untarnished, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not polluted by wrong aims, conducive to concentration, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as the bhikkhus live with their companions, in public and in private, in accordance with the views that are proper to the samaṇa life, those noble views that lead to liberation, that lead to the destruction of suffering for those who practice them, then the bhikkhus will prosper and not decline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `This is virtue, this is concentration, this is wisdom. Concentration developed together with virtue brings great fruit, great benefit. Wisdom developed together with concentration brings great fruit, great benefit. The mind developed together with wisdom brings complete liberation from the taints, namely, the taint of sensual desire, the taint of existence, and the taint of ignorance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Here, householders, one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts, will squander much wealth because of living heedlessly. That is the first danger for one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts, gains a bad reputation. That is the second danger for one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts, when entering any assembly—whether of nobles, brahmins, householders, or ascetics—does so timidly and confusedly. That is the third danger for one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts, dies with a troubled mind. That is the fourth danger for one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts, after death, with the breaking up of the body, is reborn in the plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. That is the fifth danger for one who is immoral, who lives in violation of the precepts.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Here, householders, one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts, will have abundant wealth because of living heedfully. That is the first benefit for one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts, gains a good reputation. That is the second benefit for one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts, when entering any assembly—whether of nobles, brahmins, householders, or ascetics—does so without timidity and without confusion. That is the third benefit for one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts, dies with an untroubled mind. That is the fourth benefit for one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts.<br>Furthermore, householders, one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts, after death, with the breaking up of the body, is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. That is the fifth benefit for one who is virtuous, who lives in accordance with the precepts.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Wherever wise people take up residence,<br>They support the virtuous and the celibate.<br>And share merit with the devas dwelling there.<br>Honored, they will honor in return,<br>Respected, they will respect in return,<br>They will love that person as a mother loves her child.<br>And those who are loved by devas always see good fortune.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `The Blessed One saw those people, some looking for a boat, some looking for a raft, some tying a makeshift bridge to cross to the other shore. Understanding the meaning of this scene, the Blessed One then uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Those who build a bridge across the vast ocean,<br>Leaving behind the swampy ground, while ordinary people tie rafts.<br>Those people are truly the wise ones, liberated.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not understanding the Four Noble Truths that we have wandered and run on through this long course of rebirths, both I and you. What are the Four Noble Truths?<br>Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not understanding the Noble Truth of Suffering; not realizing, not understanding the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering; ...the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering; ...the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering that we have wandered and run on through this long course of rebirths, both I and you.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when this Noble Truth of Suffering is realized and understood; when this Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering is realized and understood; when this Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering is realized and understood; when this Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering is realized and understood, then craving for existence is destroyed, the conduit to a new life is cut off, now there is no further becoming.<br>The Blessed One spoke thus. The Well-Gone added further:<br>'Because the Four Noble Truths were not seen as they are, there was long wandering through many births. When these truths are recognized, the cause of another existence is destroyed; when the root of suffering is cut, there will be no further existence.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Therefore, Ānanda, I will teach you the Mirror of the Dhamma, so that a noble disciple, having realized this Dhamma, if he wishes, can declare of himself: 'For me, there is no more hell, no more rebirth as an animal, as a ghost, no plane of misery, bad destination. I have become a stream-enterer, no longer subject to falling into the lower realms, assured of final enlightenment.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, a noble disciple has perfect confidence in the Buddha: 'The Blessed One is an Arahant, perfectly enlightened, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, well-gone, knower of the world, unsurpassed trainer of persons, teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One.' He has perfect confidence in the Dhamma: 'The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One, visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `He has perfect confidence in the Saṅgha: 'The Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is practicing the good way, practicing the straight way, practicing the true way, practicing the proper way; that is, the four pairs of persons, the eight individuals. This Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is worthy of gifts, worthy of hospitality, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit for the world.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `He has perfect confidence in the virtue that is dear to the noble ones, complete and unbroken, unblemished, unspotted, untarnished, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not influenced by future lives, conducive to concentration.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, you should dwell with mindfulness established, with clear comprehension. This is my instruction to you.<br>Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu dwell with mindfulness established? Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he abides contemplating feelings as feelings... mind as mind... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Bhikkhus, this is called mindfulness established.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have clear comprehension? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu has clear comprehension when going forward and returning; clear comprehension when looking ahead and looking aside; clear comprehension when bending and stretching his limbs; clear comprehension when wearing his robes and carrying his bowl; clear comprehension when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; clear comprehension when defecating and urinating; clear comprehension when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and remaining silent. Bhikkhus, thus a bhikkhu dwells with clear comprehension. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell with mindfulness established and clear comprehension. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `While the Blessed One was staying for the rains, a severe illness arose, very painful, close to death. But the Blessed One endured it mindfully and clearly comprehending, without complaining. The Blessed One thought: 'It would not be proper for me to pass away without addressing my attendants, without taking leave of the Bhikkhu Saṅgha. Let me by means of effort suppress this illness, sustain the life force, and continue living.' Then the Blessed One, by means of effort, suppressed the illness and sustained the life force.<br>Soon after recovering, the Blessed One left the monastery and sat on the prepared seat in the shade of the monastery.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, I have seen the Blessed One in good health. Venerable Sir, I have seen the Blessed One enduring. Venerable Sir, seeing the Blessed One ill, my body felt as weak as a creeper, my sight became unclear, I could not see the directions, although, Venerable Sir, I had some comfort thinking that the Blessed One would not pass away without leaving a final instruction to the Bhikkhu Saṅgha.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, what more does the Bhikkhu Saṅgha expect from me? Ānanda, I have taught the Dhamma without making any distinction of esoteric and exoteric. For Ānanda, the Tathāgata has never been a teacher who keeps anything back. Ānanda, those who think: 'The Tathāgata is the leader of the Bhikkhu Saṅgha,' or 'the Bhikkhu Saṅgha is under my instruction' — such a one, Ānanda, would need to give a final instruction to the Saṅgha. But Ānanda, the Tathāgata does not think: 'I am the leader of the Bhikkhu Saṅgha,' or 'the Bhikkhu Saṅgha is under my instruction' — so Ānanda, why should the Tathāgata give a final instruction to the Saṅgha? Ānanda, I am now old, aged, advanced in years, coming to the end of my life, I am eighty years old. Just as an old cart keeps going only with the help of straps, so too, the Tathāgata's body is sustained only by the help of supports. Ānanda, only when the Tathāgata, not attending to any sign, with the cessation of certain feelings, enters and abides in the signless concentration of mind, it is then that the Tathāgata's body is at ease.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Therefore, Ānanda, be islands unto yourselves, refuges unto yourselves, with no other refuge. Let the Dhamma be your island, let the Dhamma be your refuge, with no other refuge.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, here a bhikkhu abides contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he abides contemplating feelings as feelings... mind as mind... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Ānanda, thus a bhikkhu is an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, with no other refuge; he has the Dhamma as his island, the Dhamma as his refuge, with no other refuge.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, those who, after my passing, are islands unto themselves, refuges unto themselves, with no other refuge; have the Dhamma as their island, the Dhamma as their refuge, with no other refuge — those, Ānanda, will be the foremost among my bhikkhus, if they are eager to learn.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Evil One, I will not attain final Nibbāna until my bhikkhus... my bhikkhunīs... my male lay followers... my female lay followers have become true disciples, wise, well-trained, confident, learned, upholding the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, living righteously, living in accordance with the Dhamma, and after learning the teaching, are able to proclaim, teach, describe, establish, reveal, analyze, and clearly explain the Dhamma; until they can refute and overcome with right logic any opposing doctrines that arise, and teach the wondrous Dhamma.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `And at the Capala shrine, the Blessed One, mindfully and clearly comprehending, relinquished the life force. When the Blessed One relinquished the life force, a great earthquake occurred, fearsome, making the hair stand up, and thunder rolled. The Blessed One, understanding the meaning of that event, then uttered this inspired verse:<br><br>Life is finite or infinite,<br>The ascetic relinquishes, does not prolong.<br>Inwardly composed, abiding in meditation,<br>Like removing the armor one wears.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, there are eight causes, eight conditions for a great earthquake to occur. What are the eight? Ānanda, this great earth is established upon water, the water upon air, and the air is in space. Ānanda, at a time when great winds arise, the strong wind makes the water surge, and when the water surges, the earth trembles. That is the first cause, the first condition for a great earthquake.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Evil One, I will not attain final Nibbāna until the holy life I have taught is successful, prosperous, widespread, popular, extensive, and well proclaimed among humans.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, have I not from the very beginning declared that all that is dear and beloved is subject to change, to vanish, to alteration? Ānanda, how could it be otherwise? That which is born, become, conditioned, subject to decay — how could it not decay? That is impossible. Ānanda, what the Tathāgata has abandoned, cut off, let go of, relinquished, rejected — that is the life force. The Tathāgata has said, and said definitively: 'Before long, the Tathāgata will attain final Nibbāna. Three months from today, the Tathāgata will attain final Nibbāna.' That the Tathāgata should live on by retracting that statement — that is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Dhamma that I have realized and taught to you, you should learn well, realize, practice, and spread it so that the holy life may last long, be permanent, for the happiness of beings, for the welfare of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the Dhamma that I have realized and taught, which you should learn well, realize, practice, and spread so that the holy life may last long, be permanent, for the happiness of beings, for the welfare of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans? They are the Four Foundations of Mindfulness, the Four Right Efforts, the Four Bases of Spiritual Power, the Five Faculties, the Five Powers, the Seven Factors of Enlightenment, and the Noble Eightfold Path. Bhikkhus, these are the Dhamma that I have realized and taught, which you should learn well, realize, practice, and spread so that the holy life may last long, be permanent, for the happiness of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, this is my instruction to you. All conditioned things are impermanent. Strive on with diligence for your own liberation. Before long, the Tathāgata will attain final Nibbāna. Three months from today, the Tathāgata will attain final Nibbāna.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `I am old, my remaining life is not much,<br>I bid you farewell, I go alone.<br>Be islands unto yourselves,<br>Strive on with mindfulness, maintain virtue,<br>Restrain your mind, protect your own heart.<br>Whoever strives on in this Dhamma and Discipline<br>Will end birth and death, and put an end to suffering.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not attaining four things that both I and you have wandered and run on through this long course of births and deaths. What are the four? Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not attaining Noble Virtue that both I and you have wandered and run on through this long course of births and deaths. Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not attaining Noble Concentration that both I and you have wandered and run on through this long course of births and deaths. Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not attaining Noble Wisdom that both I and you have wandered and run on through this long course of births and deaths. Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not attaining Noble Liberation that both I and you have wandered and run on through this long course of births and deaths.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when Noble Virtue is realized and attained; when Noble Concentration is realized and attained; when Noble Wisdom is realized and attained; when Noble Liberation is realized and attained, then craving for a future life is destroyed, what leads to a new existence is cut off, now there is no further existence.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Virtue, Concentration, Wisdom, and supreme Liberation<br>Have been realized by Gotama renowned.<br>The Enlightened One teaches the Dhamma to the bhikkhus.<br>The Teacher has destroyed suffering, has the Dhamma-eye, is pure and blissful.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu might say: 'At that residence there are many elder bhikkhus dwelling, who are learned, upholders of the tradition, experts in the Dhamma, experts in the Discipline, experts in the summaries. From the mouths of those elders I heard and received this: "This is the Dhamma, this is the Discipline, this is the Teacher's teaching."' Bhikkhus, you should neither praise nor reject that bhikkhu's statement. Without praising and without rejecting, each word and each phrase should be carefully studied and compared with the Suttas, and checked against the Discipline. When comparing with the Suttas and checking against the Discipline, if they do not fit the Suttas, if they do not correspond to the Discipline, then you may conclude: 'Surely, these are not the words of the Blessed One, and that bhikkhu has learned them incorrectly.' And, bhikkhus, you should abandon them. When comparing with the Suttas and checking against the Discipline, if they fit the Suttas and correspond to the Discipline, then you may conclude: 'Surely, these are the words of the Blessed One, and that bhikkhu has learned them correctly.' Bhikkhus, this is the third great instruction that you should remember.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `I heard: After eating the meal at the blacksmith Cunda's house,<br>A severe illness arose, almost to the point of death.<br>After eating the dish of mushrooms,<br>A violent illness arose in the Teacher.<br>Suppressing the illness, the Blessed One said:<br>'I am going to the city of Kusināra.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `The Venerable Ānanda thought: "How wonderful, how marvelous is the psychic power and majesty of the Tathāgata! This small river, flowing shallow, stirred up and turbid, when I approach, becomes clear, bright, calm and not turbid.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, how wonderful, how marvelous is the serenity of one who has gone forth!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Pukkusa, that man then thought: 'How wonderful, how marvelous is the serenity of the renunciant! Though the rain pours down heavily, lightning flashes, thunder crashes, and two farmer brothers and four oxen are struck dead by lightning, he sees nothing, hears nothing.' After expressing his faith in me, that man paid homage to me, circumambulated me, and departed.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, the faith I had in Alāra Kālāma, I now scatter to the great wind, I now let it float away in the current. Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Marvelous, Venerable Sir! Venerable Sir, just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms. So too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by the Blessed One. Venerable Sir, I go for refuge to the Blessed One, to the Dhamma, and to the Bhikkhu Saṅgha. May the Blessed One accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `The Buddha himself went to<br>The river Kakutthā.<br>The river flows clear,<br>Cool and pure.<br>The Teacher, wearied,<br>Walked slowly down to the riverbank.<br>The Tathāgata, the Supreme One,<br>Ruling in the world,<br>After bathing and drinking,<br>Crossed to the other side.<br>The Teacher went ahead,<br>Amidst the Saṅgha of bhikkhus,<br>Teaching as he walked,<br>The wonderful Dhamma.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Friend Cunda, I myself heard and received this saying from the Blessed One: 'There are two offerings of food that have the same result, the same fruition, greater fruit and benefit than any other food offerings. What are the two? The meal before the Tathāgata attains supreme perfect enlightenment, and the meal before the Tathāgata attains final Nibbāna without remainder. These two meals have the same result, the same fruition, greater fruit and benefit than any other food offerings. By this deed, the venerable Cunda will have long life; by this deed, the venerable Cunda will have beauty; by this deed, the venerable Cunda will have happiness; by this deed, the venerable Cunda will have fame; by this deed, the venerable Cunda will have a heavenly rebirth; by this deed, the venerable Cunda will have power.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, if any bhikkhu, bhikkhunī, male lay follower, or female lay follower lives in accordance with the Dhamma, rightly in the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma properly, that person honors, respects, reveres, and makes offerings to the Tathāgata with the supreme offering. Therefore, Ānanda, you should live in accordance with the Dhamma, rightly in the Dhamma, and practice the Dhamma properly. Ānanda, you should train yourselves thus.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Subhadda, in whatever teaching and discipline the Noble Eightfold Path is not found, there is no first samaṇa, no second samaṇa, no third samaṇa, no fourth samaṇa. Subhadda, in whatever teaching and discipline the Noble Eightfold Path is found, there is the first samaṇa, the second samaṇa, the third samaṇa, and the fourth samaṇa. Subhadda, it is in this teaching and discipline that the Noble Eightfold Path is found. Therefore, Subhadda, here there is the first samaṇa, here the second samaṇa, here the third samaṇa, here the fourth samaṇa. Other systems are empty of samaṇas. Subhadda, if these bhikkhus live rightly, the world would not be empty of Arahants.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Subhadda, at twenty-nine,<br>I went forth seeking the true good path.<br>Fifty years have passed, plus one more year<br>Since I went forth, Subhadda.<br>I have been a wanderer in knowledge and virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Ānanda, if any of you thinks: 'The Teacher's word is no more, we have no teacher,' Ānanda, do not think such a thought. Ānanda, the Dhamma and Discipline that I have taught and explained, after my passing, that Dhamma and Discipline will be your teacher.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, now I exhort you: 'All conditioned things are impermanent; strive on with diligence, do not be heedless.'<br>This is the Tathāgata's last word.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `All conditioned things are impermanent,<br>Whatever has arisen must pass away.<br>Having arisen, they cease;<br>Their stilling is bliss.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Neither in-breath nor out-breath<br>Is the mind that abides in concentration.<br>Without craving, tranquil,<br>The ascetic heads toward Nibbāna.<br>With mind pure and unshaken,<br>Enduring all feelings,<br>Like a lamp that has gone out,<br>The mind is completely liberated.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, this is the one and only path leading to the purification of beings, to overcoming sorrow and lamentation, to the extinguishing of pain and grief, to the attainment of the right way, to the realization of Nibbāna. That is the Four Foundations of Mindfulness.<br>What are the four? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating mind as mind, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu goes to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and sits down, folding his legs crosswise, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. Mindfully he breathes in, mindfully he breathes out. Breathing in long, he understands: 'I breathe in long'; or breathing out long, he understands: 'I breathe out long'; breathing in short, he understands: 'I breathe in short'; or breathing out short, he understands: 'I breathe out short'; 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe out,' he trains; 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe out,' he trains.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Thus he dwells contemplating the body as a body internally; or he dwells contemplating the body as a body externally; or he dwells contemplating the body as a body both internally and externally. Or he dwells contemplating the nature of arising in the body; or he dwells contemplating the nature of passing away in the body; or he dwells contemplating the nature of both arising and passing away in the body. 'There is a body,' mindfulness is established in him to the extent necessary for knowledge and mindfulness. And he dwells independent, not clinging to anything in the world. Bhikkhus, that is how a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when walking forward or returning, clearly comprehends what he is doing. When looking ahead or looking aside, he clearly comprehends what he is doing. When bending or stretching his limbs, he clearly comprehends what he is doing. When wearing his robe and carrying his bowl, he clearly comprehends what he is doing. When eating, drinking, chewing, tasting, he clearly comprehends what he is doing. When defecating or urinating, he clearly comprehends what he is doing. When walking, standing, sitting, falling asleep, waking up, speaking, or remaining silent, he clearly comprehends what he is doing.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a double-mouthed bag filled with various kinds of grains such as rice, paddy, green gram, cowpea, sesame, and husked rice, and a person with eyes, having opened it, examines them: 'This is rice, this is paddy, this is green gram, this is cowpea, this is sesame, this is husked rice.' So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu examines this very body from the soles of the feet upwards and from the hair of the head downwards, enclosed by skin and full of various impurities: 'In this body, there are head hairs, body hairs, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, stomach, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, mucus, synovial fluid, urine.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu when feeling a pleasant feeling understands: 'I feel a pleasant feeling'; when feeling a painful feeling understands: 'I feel a painful feeling'; when feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling understands: 'I feel a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling'. Or when feeling a pleasant feeling of the flesh understands: 'I feel a pleasant feeling of the flesh'; or when feeling a pleasant feeling not of the flesh understands: 'I feel a pleasant feeling not of the flesh'; or when feeling a painful feeling of the flesh understands: 'I feel a painful feeling of the flesh'; or when feeling a painful feeling not of the flesh understands: 'I feel a painful feeling not of the flesh'; or when feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling of the flesh understands: 'I feel a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling of the flesh'; or when feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling not of the flesh understands: 'I feel a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling not of the flesh.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu: 'With a mind of lust, he understands that the mind has lust'; or 'Without lust, he understands that the mind is without lust'; or 'With hatred, he understands that the mind has hatred'; or 'Without hatred, he understands that the mind is without hatred'; or 'With delusion, he understands that the mind has delusion'; or 'Without delusion, he understands that the mind is without delusion'; or 'With a concentrated mind, he understands that the mind is concentrated'; or 'With an unconcentrated mind, he understands that the mind is unconcentrated'; or 'With a liberated mind, he understands that the mind is liberated'; or 'With an unliberated mind, he understands that the mind is unliberated.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, when there is sensual desire internally, understands: 'There is sensual desire in me'; or when there is no sensual desire internally, understands: 'There is no sensual desire in me.' And he also understands how unarisen sensual desire arises; and he also understands how arisen sensual desire is abandoned; and he also understands how abandoned sensual desire will not arise in the future.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Or when there is hatred internally, he understands: 'There is hatred in me'; or when there is no hatred internally, he understands: 'There is no hatred in me.' And he understands how unarisen hatred arises; and he understands how arisen hatred is abandoned; and he understands how abandoned hatred will not arise in the future.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Or when there is sloth and torpor internally, he understands: 'There is sloth and torpor in me'; or when there is no sloth and torpor internally, he understands: 'There is no sloth and torpor in me.' And he understands how unarisen sloth and torpor arises; and he understands how arisen sloth and torpor is abandoned; and he understands how abandoned sloth and torpor will not arise in the future.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects: 'Such is form, such is the arising of form, such is the passing away of form. Such is feeling, such is the arising of feeling, such is the passing away of feeling. Such is perception, such is the arising of perception, such is the passing away of perception. Such are formations, such is the arising of formations, such is the passing away of formations. Such is consciousness, such is the arising of consciousness, such is the passing away of consciousness.' Thus he dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena internally; or he dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena externally; or he dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena both internally and externally. Or he dwells contemplating the nature of arising in phenomena; or he dwells contemplating the nature of passing away in phenomena; or he dwells contemplating the nature of both arising and passing away in phenomena. 'There are phenomena,' mindfulness is established in him to the extent necessary for knowledge and mindfulness. And he dwells independent, not clinging to anything in the world. Bhikkhus, that is how a bhikkhu dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena with respect to the five aggregates of clinging.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of Suffering? Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, death is suffering; sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are suffering; not getting what one wants is suffering; in short, the five aggregates of clinging are suffering.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, this craving, when arising, where does it arise? When abiding, where does it abide? Whatever in the world is endearing and agreeable: In the world, the eye is endearing and agreeable — this craving, when arising, arises there; when abiding, abides there. In the world, the ear ... the nose ... the tongue ... the body ... the mind is endearing and agreeable — this craving, when arising, arises there; when abiding, abides there.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering? It is this Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right View? Bhikkhus, the knowledge of suffering, the knowledge of the origin of suffering, the knowledge of the cessation of suffering, the knowledge of the path leading to the cessation of suffering. Bhikkhus, this is called Right View.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Intention? The intention of renunciation, the intention of non-ill-will, the intention of harmlessness. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Intention.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Speech? Refraining from false speech, refraining from divisive speech, refraining from harsh speech, refraining from idle chatter. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Speech.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Action? Refraining from killing living beings, refraining from taking what is not given, refraining from sexual misconduct. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Action.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Livelihood? Bhikkhus, here a noble disciple, having abandoned wrong livelihood, earns his living by right livelihood. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Livelihood.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Effort? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu generates desire for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the arising of unarisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the maintenance, non-decline, increase, expansion, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Effort.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Mindfulness? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Mindfulness.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is Right Concentration? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. With the stilling of initial and sustained thought, he enters and abides in the second jhāna, which has internal clarity and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of concentration. With the fading away of rapture, he dwells equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending, and experiences happiness with the body; he enters and abides in the third jhāna, of which the noble ones declare: 'Equanimous and mindful, one dwells happily.' With the abandoning of pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and grief, he enters and abides in the fourth jhāna, which is neither painful nor pleasant, with purity of mindfulness due to equanimity. Bhikkhus, this is called Right Concentration.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22" },

{ text: `Bhaggava, I know the origin of the world, and I know even more than that. And knowing thus, I do not cling. Because of not clinging, I personally understand that peace. It is by realizing this peace that the Tathāgata does not fall into error.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `But, Bhaggava, I do not say thus: 'When one attains purity and liberation, then he knows all things as impure.' Bhaggava, I say thus: 'When one attains purity and liberation, then he knows all things as pure.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `- Bhaggava, it is difficult for you, following different views, accepting different things, pursuing different goals, following different aims, trained under different methods, to attain purity and liberation. Bhaggava, place your confidence in me, and guard that faith well.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, if it is indeed difficult for me, following different views, accepting different things, pursuing different goals, following different aims, trained under different methods, to attain purity and liberation, then at least, Venerable Sir, I will place my confidence in the Blessed One, and I will guard that faith well.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `How different it is when these wanderers of other sects gather together, assemble, and live noisily, speaking loudly, arguing about useless topics such as stories of kings ... stories about being and non-being. How different it is that the Blessed One dwells in quiet places, in secluded forests and jungles, far away, with little sound, little noise, with winds blowing, remote from the eyes of people, suitable for seclusion.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `He chooses a secluded place, a quiet spot, such as a forest, the root of a tree, a mountain glen, a cave, a charnel ground, a thicket, an open space, or a heap of straw. After returning from his alms round, after his meal, he sits down, folding his legs crosswise, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. He abandons covetousness for the world, dwelling with a mind free from covetousness, purifying his mind from covetousness. He abandons ill-will, dwelling with a mind free from ill-will, compassionate for the welfare of all living beings, purifying his mind from ill-will. He abandons sloth and torpor, dwelling with a mind free from sloth and torpor, perceiving light, mindful and clearly comprehending, purifying his mind from sloth and torpor. He abandons restlessness and remorse, dwelling with a mind free from restlessness and remorse, inwardly calm, purifying his mind from restlessness and remorse. He abandons doubt, dwelling with a mind free from doubt, without perplexity, purifying his mind from doubt regarding wholesome states.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Nigrodha, what do you think? Have you ever heard the elderly, senior wanderers, the teachers and ancestors of the tradition say: 'The Arahants, the Perfectly Enlightened Ones of the past, those Blessed Ones — did they assemble, gather together, and live noisily, speaking loudly, arguing about useless topics such as stories of kings, stories of thieves ... stories about being and non-being, as you and your teacher now do? Or did those Blessed Ones dwell in quiet places, in secluded forests and jungles, far away, with little sound, little noise, with winds blowing, remote from the eyes of people, suitable for seclusion, as I now live?'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Nigrodha, you are wise and senior, have you ever thought: 'The Buddha, the Enlightened One, teaches the Dhamma that leads to enlightenment; the Blessed One, the Tamed One, teaches the Dhamma that leads to taming; the Blessed One, the Calmed One, teaches the Dhamma that leads to calming; the Blessed One, the One Gone to the Far Shore, teaches the Dhamma that leads to the far shore; the Blessed One, the One of Perfect Peace, teaches the Dhamma that leads to perfect peace.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `And, Nigrodha, there are unwholesome states that, if not abandoned, cause defilement, lead to renewed existence, bring suffering, yield painful results, and lead to future aging, sickness, and death. I teach the Dhamma for the abandonment of these states. If you practice in accordance with the teaching, then your defiled states will be abandoned, pure states will increase, and you will personally know, realize, attain, and abide in the here and now with perfect and complete wisdom.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Nigrodha, you might think: 'Samaṇa Gotama says this in order to gain disciples.' Nigrodha, do not think thus. Whoever is your teacher, let him remain your teacher. Nigrodha, you might think: 'Samaṇa Gotama says this to make us abandon our recitations.' Nigrodha, do not think thus. Whatever recitations you have, let them remain as your recitations. Nigrodha, you might think: 'Samaṇa Gotama says this to make us abandon our livelihood.' Nigrodha, do not think thus. Whatever your livelihood, let it remain your livelihood.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Nigrodha, I do not say this in order to gain disciples; I do not say this to make you abandon your recitations; I do not say this to make you abandon your livelihood; I do not say this to convince you regarding those unwholesome states that the tradition of your ancestors considered unwholesome; I do not say this to make you abandon those wholesome states that the tradition of your ancestors considered wholesome. And, Nigrodha, there are unwholesome states that, if not abandoned, cause defilement, lead to renewed existence, bring suffering, yield painful results, and lead to future aging, sickness, and death. I teach the Dhamma for the abandonment of these states. If you practice in accordance with the teaching, then your defiled states will be abandoned, pure states will increase, and you will personally know, realize, attain, and abide in the here and now with perfect and complete wisdom.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `- Nigrodha, here an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice of austerities, he becomes joyful and satisfied in mind. Nigrodha, that ascetic, due to his practice of austerities, experiences joy and satisfaction of mind. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.<br>Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice, he praises himself and disparages others. Nigrodha, that ascetic who practices austerities, because of that practice, praises himself and disparages others. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.<br>Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice, he becomes intoxicated, infatuated, and heedless. Nigrodha, that ascetic who practices austerities, because of that practice, becomes intoxicated, infatuated, and heedless. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice, he receives offerings, honor, and fame. Being offered to, honored, and famous, he becomes joyful and satisfied in mind. Nigrodha, that ascetic who practices austerities, because of that practice, receives offerings, honor, and fame, and being thus, becomes joyful and satisfied in mind. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice, he receives offerings, honor, and fame. Being offered to, honored, and famous, he praises himself and disparages others. Nigrodha, that ascetic who practices austerities, because of that practice, receives offerings, honor, and fame, and being thus, praises himself and disparages others. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities. Because of this practice, he receives offerings, honor, and fame. Being offered to, honored, and famous, he becomes intoxicated, infatuated, and heedless. Nigrodha, that ascetic who practices austerities, because of that practice, receives offerings, honor, and fame, and being thus, becomes intoxicated, infatuated, and heedless. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities, discriminating among foods: 'This is suitable for me, this is not suitable for me.' Regarding foods that are not suitable, he intentionally abandons them. Regarding foods that are suitable, he grasps them, indulges in them, clings to them, not seeing the danger, not discerning them as not liberating, and enjoys them ... Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic practices austerities, and because he longs for offerings, honor, and fame, he thinks: 'Kings will honor me, so will ministers, nobles, brahmins, householders, and leaders of sects.' Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic disparages another samaṇa or brahmin thus: 'This person lives eating all kinds of things, such as root-born seeds, stem-born seeds, joint-born seeds, cutting-born seeds, and fifthly seed-born seeds, chewing and grinding them all with a toothless mortar called the jaw, and yet he is called a samaṇa.' Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic sees another samaṇa or brahmin being honored, respected, revered, and offered to by families. Seeing that, he thinks: 'These families honor, respect, revere, and offer to this person who eats all kinds of things. They do not honor, respect, revere, or offer to me, an ascetic practicing austerities.' Thus he becomes jealous and envious of those families. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic becomes one who sits in public. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic. Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic, when walking among families (for alms), hides himself: 'Thus is my austerity, thus is my austerity.' Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.<br>Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic behaves secretively. When asked: 'Do you accept this?' Though not accepting, he replies: 'I accept.' Though accepting, he replies: 'I do not accept.' Thus he intentionally tells lies. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic is prone to anger and bears grudges. Nigrodha, because an ascetic is prone to anger and bears grudges. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.<br>Furthermore, Nigrodha, an ascetic is often deceitful, hypocritical, jealous, stingy, crafty, fraudulent, obstinate, and arrogant; he has evil intentions and is dominated by them; he has wrong view and extreme views; he clings to his own personal experience; he is stubborn and hard to liberate. Nigrodha, because an ascetic clings to his own personal experience, is stubborn and hard to liberate. Nigrodha, this is a defilement for an ascetic.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarika­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu live as an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as his island, the Dhamma as his refuge, with no other refuge? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body internally, ardent, diligent, mindful, clearly comprehending, to remove covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, diligent, mindful, clearly comprehending, to remove covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu lives as an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as his island, the Dhamma as his refuge, with no other refuge.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, walk within your own proper range, within the territory of your ancestors. Bhikkhus, if you walk within your own proper range, within the territory of your ancestors, then long life will increase, beauty will increase, happiness will increase, wealth will increase, power will increase.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have increase of long life? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu develops the basis for psychic power that possesses concentration due to desire and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for psychic power that possesses concentration due to energy and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for psychic power that possesses concentration due to mind and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for psychic power that possesses concentration due to investigation and the effort of striving. He develops these four bases of psychic power diligently; if he wishes, he might live for an aeon or for the remainder of an aeon. Bhikkhus, thus, I say, a bhikkhu has increase of long life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have increase of beauty? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu lives virtuous, restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Bhikkhus, thus a bhikkhu has increase of beauty.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have increase of happiness? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. Bhikkhus, thus a bhikkhu has increase of happiness.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have increase of wealth? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, likewise the second, likewise the third, likewise the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. He abides pervading with a mind imbued with compassion ... with a mind imbued with altruistic joy ... He abides pervading with a mind imbued with equanimity, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Bhikkhus, thus a bhikkhu has increase of wealth.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu have increase of power? Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, with the destruction of the taints, personally knows, realizes, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom in this very life. Bhikkhus, thus a bhikkhu has increase of power.<br>Bhikkhus, I have observed and see no other power more difficult to subdue than the power of Māra. Bhikkhus, it is precisely by accepting and practicing these wholesome states that this merit increases!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavatti­sīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26" },

{ text: `For them, the red-hot coals were extinguished, the smoke disappeared, the mortar and pestle fell askew. They ate in the evening for the evening meal, in the morning for the morning meal. They went into villages, towns, and capital cities for alms. Having obtained food, they returned to their leaf huts in the forest to practice meditation. Vāseṭṭha, they 'jhāyanti' (meditated), meaning they reflected. 'Jhāyaka' was the second name that arose.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 27 – Aggaññasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn27" },

{ text: `They abandoned evil, unwholesome states; they were 'brāhmaṇā' (brahmins). And the name 'brāhmaṇa' was the first name that arose. These people built leaf huts in the forests and meditated in those leaf huts. For them, the red-hot coals were extinguished, the smoke disappeared, the mortar and pestle fell askew. They ate in the evening for the evening meal, in the morning for the morning meal. They went into villages, towns, and capital cities for alms. Having obtained food, they returned to their leaf huts in the forests to practice meditation.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 27 – Aggaññasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn27" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, furthermore, this point is supreme: The Blessed One teaches the Dhamma regarding wholesome states. Here, the wholesome states are the Four Foundations of Mindfulness, the Four Right Efforts, the Four Bases of Spiritual Power, the Five Faculties, the Five Powers, the Seven Factors of Enlightenment, the Noble Eightfold Path. Venerable Sir, here a bhikkhu, with the destruction of the taints, can personally know, realize, attain, and abide in the here and now, this taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Venerable Sir, this is supreme regarding wholesome states. All of this, the Blessed One has known, and apart from his understanding, there is nothing left to understand further. There is no one else, no samaṇa or brahmin, who can know more than the Blessed One regarding wholesome states.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 28 – Sampasādanīyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn28" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, this point is supreme: The Blessed One teaches the Dhamma regarding correct conduct in speech. Venerable Sir, here, a person not only avoids speaking words connected with falsehood, but also, when seeking to win a point, does not use slanderous words, harsh speech, or divisive speech; on the contrary, he speaks gentle, clear words that are worthy of being remembered, and speaks at the proper time. Venerable Sir, this is supreme regarding correct conduct in speech.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 28 – Sampasādanīyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn28" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, this point is supreme: The Blessed One teaches the Dhamma regarding human virtue. Venerable Sir, here, there is a person who is truthful, faithful, not deceitful, not fraudulent, not hinting, not fortune-telling, not gaining profit from profit; he guards his sense faculties, eats in moderation, acts gently, is always vigilant, not dispirited, diligent, contemplative, mindful, speaks clearly, acts bravely, endures, knows what is appropriate, is without greed, clearly comprehending, and careful. Venerable Sir, this is supreme regarding human virtue.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 28 – Sampasādanīyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn28" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, whatever can be attained by a faithful, energetic, and persistent good man through human persistence, human effort, human progress, human endurance, that the Blessed One has attained. Venerable Sir, the Blessed One does not indulge in sensual pleasures, which are low, vulgar, worldly, unworthy of the noble ones, and unbeneficial. Nor does the Blessed One indulge in self-mortification, which is painful, unworthy of the noble ones, and unbeneficial. The Blessed One, if he wishes, can easily and fully attain the happiness that is present here and now, provided by the four jhānas.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 28 – Sampasādanīyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn28" },

{ text: `Therefore, Cunda, the Dhamma that I have personally known and declared to you, all of you should gather together and recite it, without quarrelling, but compare meaning with meaning, phrase with phrase, so that this holy life may last long, be established long, for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans. Those Dhamma are the Four Foundations of Mindfulness, the Four Right Efforts, the Four Bases of Spiritual Power, the Five Faculties, the Five Powers, the Seven Factors of Enlightenment, the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, you should assemble together in harmony and mutual respect, without disputing. A fellow celibate teaches the Dhamma in the midst of the Saṅgha. If you think: 'This venerable one has grasped the meaning incorrectly or the phrasing incorrectly,' you should neither praise nor reject him, but should carefully explain to him both the meaning and the phrasing.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, you should assemble together in harmony and mutual respect, without disputing. Cunda, another fellow celibate teaches the Dhamma in the midst of the Saṅgha. If you think: 'This venerable one has grasped the meaning incorrectly but the phrasing is correct,' you should neither praise nor reject him. Without praising or rejecting, you should say to him: 'Friend, among these phrasings, this meaning or that meaning, which meaning is more appropriate?' If he replies: 'Friend, among these phrasings, this meaning is more appropriate than that meaning,' you should not reject or disparage him, but should carefully explain the correct meaning to him.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, I do not teach merely for the sake of preventing the taints in the present life. Cunda, I do not teach only for the sake of eradicating the taints in the future. Cunda, I teach the Dhamma both for preventing the taints in the present life and for eradicating the taints in the future as well.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Therefore, Cunda, the robe that I have allowed you to wear is sufficient for you to ward off cold, to ward off heat, to ward off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things, and to conceal your private parts.<br>The almsfood that I have allowed you to use is sufficient to nourish the body, to sustain the body, to avoid harm, and to support the holy life, with the hope: 'Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings. So my life will be blameless and I shall dwell at ease.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `The lodging that I have allowed you to use is sufficient for you to ward off cold, to ward off heat, to ward off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things, merely for the purpose of avoiding the dangers of climate and for enjoying seclusion.<br>The medicines and medicinal requisites that I have allowed you to use are sufficient to ward off arisen feelings of illness and to maintain health.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, here a foolish person, after killing living beings, rejoices and is delighted. That is the first kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, here a person, after taking what is not given, rejoices and is delighted. That is the second kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, here a person, after speaking falsely, rejoices and is delighted. That is the third kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, here a person, infatuated and indulgent, lives surrounded by the five strands of sensual pleasure. That is the fourth kind of pleasure. Cunda, these four kinds of pleasure are low, vulgar, worldly, unworthy of the noble life, unbeneficial, and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, or Nibbāna. Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'The Sakyan samaṇas dwell indulging in these four kinds of pleasure.' They should be answered: 'That is not so; you speak wrongly. You misrepresent, it is not true, it does not exist.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, there are these four kinds of pleasure. What are the four? Cunda, here a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. That is the first kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, a bhikkhu, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, enters and abides in the second jhāna, which has internal clarity and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of concentration. That is the second kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, a bhikkhu, with the fading away of rapture, dwells equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending, and experiences happiness with the body; he enters and abides in the third jhāna... That is the third kind of pleasure. Furthermore, Cunda, a bhikkhu, with the abandoning of pleasure and pain... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna... That is the fourth kind of pleasure. Cunda, these four kinds of pleasure definitely lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'The Sakyan samaṇas dwell indulging in these four kinds of pleasure.' They should be answered: 'That is so; you speak rightly. You do not misrepresent, it is true, it exists.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'The Sakyan samaṇas dwell without a firm position.' Cunda, when wanderers of other sects say thus, they should be answered as follows: 'Friend, the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has taught and explained the Dhamma to his disciples for the sake of the entire life. Friend, just as a stone or iron pillar with its base well sunk into the earth does not shake or tremble. So too, friend, the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has taught and explained the Dhamma to his disciples for the sake of the entire life. Friend, just as a stone or iron pillar with its base well sunk into the earth does not shake or tremble. So too, friend, the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has taught and explained the Dhamma to his disciples for the sake of the entire life.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Friend, a bhikkhu who is an Arahant, with taints destroyed, who has lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge, cannot do nine things: Friend, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot intentionally deprive a living being of life; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot take what is not given, i.e., steal; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot engage in sexual intercourse; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot knowingly speak falsely; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot store up goods for sensual enjoyment as he did when he was a householder; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot follow the path of greed; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot follow the path of hatred; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot follow the path of delusion; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot follow the path of fear. Friend, a bhikkhu who is an Arahant, perfectly enlightened, with taints destroyed, who has lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge, cannot do these nine things.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'Regarding the past, Samaṇa Gotama has supernormal knowledge. But regarding the future, Samaṇa Gotama has no supernormal knowledge; as to how things happen and why they happen thus?' Thus these wanderers, being foolish and unintelligent, hold that knowledge of one matter can be explained by knowledge of another. Cunda, regarding the past, the Tathāgata can recollect past lives. As he wishes, he can recollect that far back. Regarding the future, the Tathāgata has knowledge born of wisdom: 'This is the last birth, now there is no further existence.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, if something pertaining to the past, future, or present is false, untrue, and unbeneficial, the Tathāgata does not answer. Cunda, if something pertaining to the past, future, or present is true and real but unbeneficial, the Tathāgata does not answer. Cunda, if something pertaining to the past, future, or present is true and real and beneficial, the Tathāgata knows the time and answers that question. Thus, Cunda, regarding past, future, and present phenomena, the Tathāgata speaks at the proper time, speaks truthfully, speaks beneficially, speaks in accordance with the Dhamma, speaks in accordance with the Discipline. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its samaṇas and brahmins, with its devas and humans, whatever is seen, heard, sensed, discriminated, attained, sought after, and reflected upon by the mind, all that the Tathāgata knows directly. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Cunda, from the night the Tathāgata attained supreme perfect enlightenment to the night he attains final Nibbāna without remainder, during that time, whatever he speaks, discusses, or explains, all of it is just so and not otherwise. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Cunda, as the Tathāgata speaks, so he acts; as he acts, so he speaks. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. In this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its samaṇas and brahmins, with its devas and humans, the Tathāgata is the Conqueror, unconquered by anyone, the All-Seeing, the Self-Master.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'Friend, why does Samaṇa Gotama not speak?' Cunda, when asked thus, you should answer those wanderers: 'Friend, because it is not connected with the beneficial, not connected with the Dhamma, not connected with the fundamentals of the holy life, and does not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. Therefore the Blessed One does not answer.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'Friend, what does Samaṇa Gotama speak?' Cunda, when asked thus, you should answer those wanderers: 'This is suffering, friend, that the Blessed One speaks. This is the origin of suffering, friend, that the Blessed One speaks. This is the cessation of suffering, friend, that the Blessed One speaks. This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering, friend, that the Blessed One speaks.'<br>Cunda, this situation may occur: wanderers of other sects might say: 'Friend, why does the Blessed One speak thus?' Cunda, when asked thus, you should answer those wanderers: 'Friend, because it is connected with the beneficial, connected with the Dhamma, connected with the fundamentals of the holy life, and definitely leads to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. Therefore the Blessed One speaks thus.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29" },

{ text: `Young householder, being addicted to laziness has six dangers: 'Too cold' and he does not work; 'Too hot' and he does not work; 'Too late' and he does not work; 'Too early' and he does not work; 'I am too hungry' and he does not work; 'I am too full' and he does not work. While the work that should be done remains undone. Wealth that he does not have does not get built up, and wealth that he has gets squandered. Young householder, such are the six dangers of being addicted to laziness. This the Blessed One teaches.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Friends, the Tathāgata is pure in bodily conduct. There is no evil bodily deed that the Tathāgata needs to hide, thinking: 'Let no one know this about me.' Friends, the Tathāgata is pure in verbal conduct. There is no evil verbal deed that the Tathāgata needs to hide, thinking: 'Let no one know this about me.' Friends, the Tathāgata is pure in mental conduct. There is no evil mental deed that the Tathāgata needs to hide, thinking: 'Let no one know this about me.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Four Right Efforts: Here, friends, a bhikkhu generates desire, strives, arouses energy, applies his mind, and exerts his mind for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states. He generates desire, strives, arouses energy, applies his mind, and exerts his mind for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states. He generates desire, strives, arouses energy, applies his mind, and exerts his mind for the arising of unarisen wholesome states. He generates desire, strives, arouses energy, applies his mind, and exerts his mind for the maintenance, non-confusion, increase, expansion, cultivation, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to blissful abiding here and now? Here, friends, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... second jhāna ... third jhāna ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. Friends, this is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to blissful abiding here and now.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to the attainment of knowledge and vision? Friends, here, a bhikkhu gives attention to the perception of light, fixes his mind on the perception of daytime. As by day, so by night; as by night, so by day. Thus with a mind open and unclosed, he develops a mind that is radiant. Friends, this is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to the attainment of knowledge and vision.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension? Friends, here, a bhikkhu knows the arising of feelings, knows their persisting, knows their passing away; knows the arising of perceptions, knows their persisting, knows their passing away; knows the arising of thoughts, knows their persisting, knows their passing away. Friends, this is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to the destruction of the taints? Friends, here, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating arising and passing away in the five aggregates of clinging: 'Such is form, such is the arising of form, such is the passing away of form. Such is feeling ... Such is perception ... Such are formations ... Such is consciousness, such is the arising of consciousness, such is the passing away of consciousness.' Friends, this is the development of concentration that, when developed and frequently practiced, leads to the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is content with any lodging, praises contentment with any lodging, does not strive improperly for lodging, is not distressed if he does not get a dwelling. When he gets a lodging, he does not become infatuated, intoxicated, or commit faults. He uses the lodging, seeing the danger and knowing the escape. Because he is content with any lodging, he does not praise himself or disparage others. Herein, he is skillful, diligent, clearly comprehending, mindful. Friends, that bhikkhu is called one who has stayed true to the noble lineage, following the ancient tradition.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu delights in abandoning, rejoices in abandoning; delights in cultivation, rejoices in cultivation. Because he delights in abandoning, rejoices in abandoning, delights in cultivation, rejoices in cultivation, he does not praise himself or disparage others. Herein, that bhikkhu is skillful, diligent, clearly comprehending, mindful. Friends, he is called one who has stayed true to the noble lineage, following the ancient tradition.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the effort of abandoning? Friends, here, a bhikkhu does not consent to arisen sensual thoughts; he abandons, dispels, destroys, and prevents them from arising. He does not consent to arisen thoughts of ill-will ... He does not consent to arisen thoughts of harmfulness; he abandons, dispels, destroys, and prevents them from arising. Friends, this is called the effort of abandoning.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `He possesses the virtue loved by the noble ones, unbroken, unblemished, untarnished, continuously practiced, without flaw, leading to freedom, praised by the wise, not defiled, conducive to concentration.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, due to robes, a bhikkhu arouses craving. Friends, due to almsfood, a bhikkhu arouses craving. Friends, due to lodging, a bhikkhu arouses craving. Friends, due to becoming and non-becoming, a bhikkhu arouses craving.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed cannot intentionally deprive a living being of life. A bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed cannot intentionally take what is not given, i.e., steal. A bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed cannot intentionally engage in sexual intercourse. A bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed cannot knowingly speak falsely. A bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed cannot enjoy stored-up goods for sensual pleasures as he did when he was a layman.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, a bhikkhu who wishes to admonish another should have five internal qualities: 'I will speak at the right time, not at the wrong time. I will speak truthfully, not falsely. I will speak gently, not harshly. I will speak beneficially, not unbeneficially. I will speak with a mind of loving-kindness, not with a mind of hatred.' Friends, these are the five internal qualities a bhikkhu should have if he wishes to admonish another.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, here a bhikkhu has faith, believing in the enlightenment of the Tathāgata. He has few ailments, few afflictions, his digestion is good, neither too cold nor too hot, but moderate and suitable for striving. He is not deceitful, not fraudulent, but reveals himself as he truly is to the Teacher, to the wise, or to his fellow celibates. He dwells energetic and diligent, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, resolute, persistently striving, not avoiding wholesome states. He is wise, possessing wisdom that understands the arising and passing away of phenomena, possessing noble penetrating wisdom that leads to the complete destruction of suffering.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu, regarding the precepts that are unbroken, unviolated, consistently maintained, unblemished, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not defiled, conducive to concentration — that bhikkhu maintains such samaṇa virtue, living thus in the presence or absence of his fellow celibates, this is a quality of concord, creating loving-kindness, creating respect, leading to unity, non-disputing, harmony, unanimity, unity of mind.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu, regarding lawful gains, even down to the contents of his alms bowl, he shares them equally among virtuous bhikkhus. This is a quality of concord, creating loving-kindness, creating respect, leading to unity, non-disputing, harmony, unanimity, unity of mind.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, when a bhikkhu, in the presence or absence of his fellow celibates, maintains bodily acts of loving-kindness, this is a quality of concord, creating loving-kindness, creating respect, leading to unity, non-disputing, harmony, unanimity, unity of mind.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Friends, here there is a duty a bhikkhu has to do. He thinks: 'There is work I must do. If I do the work, my body will become tired. So I shall lie down.' He lies down, without striving to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. That is the first way of being slothful.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `What is not doing evil deeds for four reasons? Evil deeds done from desire, evil deeds done from hatred, evil deeds done from delusion, evil deeds done from fear. Young householder, because the noble disciple is without desire, without hatred, without delusion, without fear, he does not do evil deeds for these four reasons.<br><br>Killing and stealing,<br>Lying, taking others' wives,<br>The wise do not praise<br>Such actions and deeds.<br><br>Who acts against the Dhamma,<br>Due to desire, hate, fear, delusion,<br>Their reputation is diminished<br>Like the moon in the dark half.<br>Who does not act against the Dhamma,<br>Due to desire, hate, fear, delusion,<br>Their reputation is full<br>Like the moon in the bright half.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `What are the six channels for squandering wealth? Young householder, addiction to intoxicants is a channel for squandering wealth. Wandering the streets at improper times is a channel for squandering wealth. Frequent fair-going is a channel for squandering wealth. Addiction to gambling is a channel for squandering wealth. Keeping bad company is a channel for squandering wealth. Being addicted to laziness is a channel for squandering wealth.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, addiction to intoxicants has six dangers: loss of present wealth, increase of quarrels, susceptibility to disease, damage to reputation, indecent exposure, and sixth, weakening of intellect. Young householder, such are the six dangers of addiction to intoxicants.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, wandering the streets at improper times has six dangers: oneself is unprotected and unguarded, one's wife and children are unprotected and unguarded, one's property is unprotected and unguarded, one is suspected of evil deeds, one is subject to false rumors, and one encounters many troubles. Young householder, such are the six dangers of wandering the streets at improper times.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, frequent fair-going has six dangers: always looking for where there is dancing, where there is singing, where there is music, where there is recitation, where there is hand-music, where there are cymbals. Young householder, such are the six dangers of frequent fair-going.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, addiction to gambling has six dangers: if you win, you earn enmity; if you lose, you grieve in mind; loss of present wealth; your word has no weight in the assembly; friends and colleagues despise you; you are not trusted in marriage because a gambler is not fit to have a wife. Young householder, such are the six dangers of addiction to gambling.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, keeping bad company has six dangers: gamblers, libertines, drunkards, swindlers, deceivers, and violent persons are his friends and companions. Young householder, such are the six dangers of keeping bad company.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, four kinds of persons should be regarded as not friends, though they pretend to be friends: the taker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend; the talker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend; the flatterer should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend; the spendthrift should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the taker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend: he takes everything, asks for much while giving little, does his duty out of fear, and acts for his own advantage. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the taker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the talker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend: he professes friendship for past deeds, professes friendship for future deeds, gains affection with empty phrases, and when there is work to be done, he shows his inability. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the talker should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the flatterer should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend: he consents to evil deeds, does not consent to good deeds, praises you to your face, and criticizes you behind your back. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the flatterer should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the spendthrift should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend: he is a companion when you are addicted to intoxicants, he is a companion when you wander the streets at improper times, he is a companion when you frequent fairs, he is a companion when you are addicted to gambling. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the spendthrift should be regarded as not a friend, though he pretends to be a friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `The taker friend,<br>The talker friend,<br>The flatterer,<br>The spendthrift.<br>These four are not friends,<br>Knowing this, the wise avoid them,<br>Like a dangerous path.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, four kinds of friends should be regarded as true friends: the helpful friend should be regarded as a true friend; the friend who is constant in happiness and suffering should be regarded as a true friend; the friend who gives beneficial advice should be regarded as a true friend; the compassionate friend should be regarded as a true friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the helpful friend should be regarded as a true friend: he guards you when you are heedless, he guards your property when you are heedless, he is a refuge when you are afraid, and when you have a task, he provides you with double the wealth you need. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the helpful friend should be regarded as a true friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the friend who is constant in happiness and suffering should be regarded as a true friend: he tells you his secrets, he keeps your secrets, he does not abandon you in your misfortune, and he would sacrifice his life for you. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the friend who is constant in happiness and suffering should be regarded as a true friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the friend who gives beneficial advice should be regarded as a true friend: he restrains you from evil, he encourages you to do good, he tells you what you have not heard, and he points out the path to heaven. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the friend who gives beneficial advice should be regarded as a true friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in four cases the compassionate friend should be regarded as a true friend: he does not rejoice in your misfortune, he rejoices in your good fortune, he restrains those who speak ill of you, and he encourages those who praise you. Young householder, these are the four cases in which the compassionate friend should be regarded as a true friend.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `The friend who is ready to help,<br>The friend constant in joy and sorrow,<br>The friend who gives good advice,<br>The compassionate friend.<br>Knowing these four friends,<br>The wise serve them,<br>As a mother her own son.<br>The wise, maintaining virtue,<br>Shine like a fire on a hilltop.<br>They gather wealth<br>Like bees gathering honey.<br>Wealth accumulates,<br>Like a growing ant-hill,<br>One who acts thus<br>Accumulates wealth<br>Sufficient for the benefit<br>Of his own family.<br>Wealth should be divided into four<br>To bind friends in alliance:<br>One part he enjoys,<br>Two parts he invests in his work,<br>The fourth he saves<br>For times of need and misfortune.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in five ways a child should attend on his parents as the eastern direction: 'Having been supported by them, I will support them in return; I will do my duty to them; I will maintain the family tradition; I will protect the inheritance; I will perform funeral rites when they pass away.' Young householder, when the child attends on his parents as the eastern direction in these five ways, the parents have compassion for the child in five ways: they restrain him from evil, they encourage him to do good, they teach him a profession, they find him a suitable wife, and at the proper time they hand over the inheritance.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in five ways a pupil should attend on his teachers as the southern direction: rising to greet them, waiting upon them, eager to learn, personal service, and attentive reception of instruction. Young householder, when the pupil attends on his teachers as the southern direction in these five ways, the teachers have compassion for the pupil in five ways: they train him in what they have been well trained, they make him retain what they have well retained, they thoroughly instruct him in every art and science, they speak well of him among friends and companions, and they provide for his safety in all quarters.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in five ways a husband should attend on his wife as the western direction: honoring her, not disrespecting her, being faithful to her, giving her authority, and providing her with adornments. Young householder, when the husband attends on his wife as the western direction in these five ways, the wife has compassion for her husband in five ways: she performs her duties well, she receives her relatives well, she is faithful to him, she protects his property, and she is skillful and diligent in all her work.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in five ways a gentleman should attend on his friends and companions as the northern direction: giving, speaking kindly, acting for their welfare, treating them as himself, and keeping his promises. Young householder, when the gentleman attends on his friends and companions as the northern direction in these five ways, the friends and companions have compassion for him in five ways: they guard him when he is heedless, they guard his property when he is heedless, they are a refuge when he is in danger, they do not abandon him in his misfortune, and they honor his family.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Young householder, in five ways a gentleman should attend on samaṇas and brahmins as the upper direction: acting with loving-kindness in body, acting with loving-kindness in speech, acting with loving-kindness in mind, keeping open house for them, and supplying their material needs. Young householder, when the gentleman attends on samaṇas and brahmins as the upper direction in these five ways, the samaṇas and brahmins have compassion for him in five ways: they restrain him from evil, they encourage him to do good, they have compassion for him with a mind of loving-kindness, they teach him what he has not heard, they purify what he has heard, and they point out the path to heaven.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Parents are the eastern direction,<br>Teachers the southern direction,<br>Spouse the western direction,<br>Friends and companions the northern direction,<br>Servants and employees the lower direction,<br>Samaṇas and brahmins the upper direction.<br>A layman for the sake of his family<br>Should worship these directions.<br>The wise, maintaining virtue,<br>Gentle and eloquent,<br>Humble and compliant,<br>Thus gain a good name.<br>Rising early, not lazy,<br>Unshaken amidst danger,<br>The good, not breaking precepts,<br>Thus gain a good name.<br>Gathering people, making friends,<br>Loving, broad-minded,<br>Guiding, encouraging,<br>Thus gain a good name.<br>Giving and kindly speech,<br>Beneficial conduct to all,<br>Impartiality in all matters,<br>Acting according to the situation.<br>These are the ways of gathering people,<br>They keep the world revolving,<br>Like a chariot wheel rolling<br>Around its axle.<br>If these ways were absent,<br>No mother would receive<br>The honor and service<br>Due from her child.<br>Therefore the wise,<br>Regarding these ways,<br>Observe and uphold them,<br>Thus they become great,<br>Praised and renowned.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 31 – Siṅgālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn31" },

{ text: `Samaṇa Gotama abstains from taking what is not given, avoids taking what is not given, takes only what is given, desires only what is given, lives purely without theft. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from sexual misconduct, leads the holy life, lives detached, abstains from base sensual desires. Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Samaṇa Gotama does not harm seeds or plants; Samaṇa Gotama eats once a day, does not eat at night, abstains from eating at improper times. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from watching dancing, singing, music, and shows. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from wearing garlands, perfumes, ointments, and adornments. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from using high or large beds. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting gold and silver. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting raw grain. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting raw meat. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting women and girls. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting female and male slaves. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting sheep and goats. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting fowl and pigs. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting elephants, cattle, horses, and mares. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from accepting fields and lands. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from running errands or acting as a go-between. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from buying and selling. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from cheating with weights, coins, or measures. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from crooked ways such as bribery, fraud, and deceit. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from wounding, killing, imprisoning, robbing, stealing, and plundering. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live harming seeds and plants — such as root-born seeds, stem-born seeds, joint-born seeds, cutting-born seeds, and fifthly, seed-born seeds — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from harming any seeds or plants. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live storing up and enjoying goods — such as storing up food, storing up drinks, storing up cloth, storing up vehicles, storing up bedding, storing up perfumes, storing up delicacies — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from storing up such goods. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live engaging in unrighteous games and sports such as dancing, singing, music, shows, recitations, hand-clapping, chanting, drum-playing, fairy dramas, martial arts, elephant fights, horse fights, buffalo fights, bull fights, goat fights, ram fights, cock fights, quail fights, stick fights, boxing, wrestling, mock fights, arraying troops, reviewing troops, and military exercises — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such unrighteous games and sports. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live playing board games and other diversions such as eight-square boards, ten-square boards, aerial chess, hopscotch, stepping into allowed squares, picking up cards without letting the pile collapse, dice games, stick games, finger-drawing, ball games, leaf-blowing, toy ploughs, somersaults, pinwheels, leaf toys, toy carts, toy bows, guessing letters written in the air or on the back, guessing thoughts, imitating deformities — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such board games and diversions. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live using high and large beds such as couches, long chairs, woolen covers, multi-colored patchwork covers, white woolen blankets, embroidered woolen blankets, cotton quilts, animal-figured quilts, double-fur rugs, single-fur rugs, jewel-studded rugs, silk covers, large carpets fit for sixteen dancers, elephant rugs, horse rugs, chariot rugs, rugs of antelope hide sewn together, rugs of kadali antelope hide, canopied bedspreads, and red-cushioned long chairs with footrests — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from using such high and large beds. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live using adornments and cosmetics such as anointing, massaging, bathing, limb-stretching, mirrors, face creams, garlands and rouge, face powder and lip salve, bracelets, head wigs, walking sticks, medicine tubes, swords, parasols, embroidered sandals, turbans, gems, whisks, and long-fringed white robes — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from using such adornments and cosmetics. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live talking about frivolous, low talk such as talk about kings, talk about thieves, talk about ministers, talk about armies, frightening tales, war stories, talk about food, talk about drink, talk about clothing, talk about bedding, talk about garlands, talk about perfumes, talk about relatives, talk about vehicles, talk about villages, talk about market towns, talk about cities, talk about countries, talk about women, talk about men, talk about heroes, street talk, talk at the water well, talk about the dead, miscellaneous gossip, talk about the origin of the world, talk about the origin of the ocean, talk about being and non-being — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such frivolous, low talk. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live engaging in disputes and quarrels, saying: 'You do not know this Dhamma and Discipline, I know this Dhamma and Discipline. How could you know this Dhamma and Discipline? You have fallen into wrong views, I speak rightly. My words are consistent, your words are not consistent. What should be said first you say last, what should be said last you say first. Your position has been refuted, your statement has been challenged, you are defeated. Go and try to extricate yourself, if you can, from this dilemma.' — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such disputes and quarrels. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live carrying messages or acting as go-betweens for kings, for ministers of kings, for nobles, for brahmins, for householders, for young men, saying: 'Go there, come back here; take this there, bring that from there' — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from carrying messages and acting as a go-between. Thus, ordinary people praise the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live practicing deceit, speaking flattery, hinting, belittling, and seeking gain by means of gain — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such deceit and flattery. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live maintaining themselves by wrong livelihood such as predicting: The king will march forth, the king will retreat; the local king will advance, the foreign king will withdraw; the foreign king will advance, the local king will withdraw; the local king will win, the foreign king will lose; the foreign king will win, the local king will lose — thus there will be victory for one side and defeat for the other. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such wrong livelihood.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live maintaining themselves by wrong livelihood such as predicting: There will be a lunar eclipse, there will be a solar eclipse, there will be a stellar eclipse; the moon and sun will go on their proper path, the moon and sun will go off their proper path; the stars will go on their proper path, the stars will go off their proper path; there will be a meteor, there will be fire in the sky, there will be an earthquake, there will be thunder; the moon, sun, and stars will rise, set, be dim, be bright; such will be the result of the lunar eclipse, such will be the result of the solar eclipse, such will be the result of the stellar eclipse; such will be the result of the moon and sun going on their proper path, such will be the result of them going off their proper path; such will be the result of the stars going on their proper path, such will be the result of a meteor, such will be the result of fire in the sky, such will be the result of an earthquake, such will be the result of thunder; such will be the result of the moon, sun, and stars rising, setting, being dim, being bright. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such wrong livelihood. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live maintaining themselves by wrong livelihood such as predicting: There will be much rain, there will be drought, there will be a good harvest, there will be a bad harvest, there will be safety, there will be danger, there will be disease, there will be health; or they engage in occupations such as counting on fingers, accounting, adding large numbers, writing verses, worldly treatises — Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such wrong livelihood. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live maintaining themselves by wrong livelihood such as: arranging auspicious days for wedding or betrothal, selecting favorable times for reconciliation, selecting favorable times for estrangement, selecting favorable times for debt collection, selecting favorable times for borrowing or spending, using charms to bring good luck, using charms to cause misfortune, using charms to induce abortion, using charms to make the tongue stick, using charms to lock the jaw, using charms to make the hand drop, using charms to cause deafness; consulting mirrors, consulting mediums, consulting girls, consulting devas for omens; worshipping the sun, worshipping the great earth, blowing fire, invoking the goddess of fortune. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such wrong livelihood. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live maintaining themselves by wrong livelihood such as: using magic to gain security, to avoid fulfilling vows, to gain protection in a house, to make the male organ firm, to cause impotence; finding a good site for a house, blessing a new house, mouth-washing rituals, sacrifice rituals, causing vomiting, causing purging, expelling impurities upwards, expelling impurities downwards, purifying the head, oiling the ears, eye-drops, nasal medicine, eye-ointment, eye-oiling; treating eye diseases, practicing surgery, treating children, giving root-medicines, counteracting the effects of medicine. Samaṇa Gotama abstains from such wrong livelihood. — Bhikkhus, these are the praises of the Tathāgata by ordinary people.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 1 – Brahmajālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn1" },

{ text: `Great King! How is a bhikkhu possessed of virtue? Here, Great King, a bhikkhu abandons killing living beings, abstains from killing, lays aside the stick and the sword, is conscientious and compassionate, dwelling with loving-kindness for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons taking what is not given, abstains from taking what is not given, takes only what is given, desires only what is given, lives purely without theft. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons divisive speech, abstains from divisive speech. Having heard something here, he does not repeat it elsewhere to cause division among these people; having heard something elsewhere, he does not repeat it to those people to cause division. Thus he lives as one who reunites those who are divided, encourages those who are united, rejoices in harmony, delights in harmony, loves harmony, and speaks words that promote harmony. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons harsh speech, abstains from harsh speech. He speaks such words as are blameless, pleasing to the ear, agreeable, reaching the heart, polite, and liked by many. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons idle chatter, abstains from idle chatter. He speaks at the right time, speaks what is true, speaks what is beneficial, speaks on the Dhamma, speaks on the Discipline, speaks words that are worth remembering, timely, reasonable, coherent, purposeful, and beneficial. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `He abandons harming seeds and plants; he eats one meal a day, abstains from eating at night; he abstains from eating at improper times; he abstains from watching dancing, singing, music, and shows; he abstains from wearing garlands, perfumes, ointments, and adornments; he abstains from using high and large beds; he abstains from accepting gold and silver; he abstains from accepting raw grain; he abstains from accepting raw meat; he abstains from accepting women and girls; he abstains from accepting female and male slaves; he abstains from accepting sheep and goats; he abstains from accepting fowl and pigs; he abstains from accepting elephants, cattle, horses, and mares; he abstains from accepting fields and lands; he abstains from running errands or acting as a go-between; he abstains from buying and selling; he abstains from cheating with weights, coins, or measures; he abstains from crooked ways such as bribery, fraud, and deceit; he abstains from wounding, killing, imprisoning, robbing, stealing, and plundering. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live harming seeds and plants such as root-born seeds, stem-born seeds, joint-born seeds, cutting-born seeds, and fifthly, seed-born seeds — he abstains from harming any seeds or plants. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live storing up and enjoying goods such as storing up food, storing up drinks, storing up cloth, storing up vehicles, storing up bedding, storing up perfumes, storing up delicacies — he abstains from storing up such goods. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live engaging in unrighteous games and sports such as dancing, singing, music, shows, recitations, hand-clapping, chanting, drum-playing, fairy dramas, martial arts, elephant fights, horse fights, buffalo fights, bull fights, goat fights, ram fights, cock fights, quail fights, stick fights, boxing, wrestling, mock fights, arraying troops, reviewing troops, military exercises — he abstains from such unrighteous games and sports. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live playing board games and other diversions such as eight-square boards, ten-square boards, aerial chess, hopscotch, stepping into allowed squares, picking up cards without letting the pile collapse, dice games, stick games, finger-drawing, ball games, leaf-blowing, toy ploughs, somersaults, pinwheels, leaf toys, toy carts, toy bows, guessing letters written in the air or on the back, guessing thoughts, imitating deformities — he abstains from such board games and diversions. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live using adornments and cosmetics such as anointing, massaging, bathing, limb-stretching, mirrors, face creams, garlands and rouge, face powder and lip salve, bracelets, head wigs, walking sticks, medicine tubes, swords, parasols, embroidered sandals, turbans, gems, whisks, long-fringed white robes — he abstains from using such adornments and cosmetics. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live talking about frivolous, low talk such as talk about kings, talk about thieves, talk about ministers, talk about armies, frightening tales, war stories, talk about food, talk about drink, talk about clothing, talk about bedding, talk about garlands, talk about perfumes, talk about relatives, talk about vehicles, talk about villages, talk about market towns, talk about cities, talk about countries, talk about women, talk about men, talk about heroes, street talk, talk at the water well, talk about the dead, miscellaneous gossip, talk about the origin of the world, talk about the origin of the great ocean, talk about being and non-being — he abstains from such frivolous, low talk. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live engaging in disputes and quarrels, saying: 'You do not know this Dhamma and Discipline, I know this Dhamma and Discipline. How could you know this Dhamma and Discipline? You have fallen into wrong views, I speak rightly. My words are consistent, your words are not consistent. What should be said first you say last, what should be said last you say first. Your position has been refuted, your statement has been challenged, you are defeated. Go and try to extricate yourself, if you can, from this dilemma.' — He abstains from such disputes and quarrels. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live carrying messages or acting as go-betweens for kings, for ministers of kings, for nobles, for brahmins, for householders, for young men, saying: 'Go there, come back here; take this there, bring that from there' — he abstains from carrying messages and acting as a go-between. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Whereas some samaṇas and brahmins, while enjoying food offered by the faithful, still live practicing deceit, speaking flattery, hinting, belittling, and seeking gain by means of gain — he abstains from such deceit and flattery. This is part of his virtue in terms of discipline.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Thus, Great King, a bhikkhu reflects on the five hindrances not yet abandoned as a debt, as a disease, as a prison, as slavery, as a desert road. Great King, just as being free from debt, free from disease, released from prison, free from slavery, and a safe, peaceful land, so the bhikkhu reflects on the five hindrances when they are abandoned.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `When he sees that these five hindrances have been abandoned in himself, gladness arises; from gladness, rapture arises; when the mind is filled with rapture, the body becomes tranquil; when the body is tranquil, he experiences happiness; and with happiness, the mind becomes concentrated. A bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. He drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades his very body with the rapture and happiness born of seclusion, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this rapture and happiness born of seclusion.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as a skilled bath attendant or his assistant, having sprinkled bath powder in a brass basin, kneads it with water, so that the ball of powder becomes soaked, saturated, filled, and pervaded inside and out with moisture, yet does not drip — so too, Great King, a bhikkhu drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades his very body with the rapture and happiness born of seclusion, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this rapture and happiness born of seclusion. Great King, this is a visible fruit of the samaṇa life, more excellent and sublime than the previous visible fruits of the samaṇa life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as a lake with water welling up from within, having no inlet from the east, west, north, or south, and occasionally receiving a heavy downpour of rain, yet the cool water springing up from within the lake drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades that very lake with cool water, so that no part of the lake is not pervaded by cool water — so too, Great King, a bhikkhu drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades his very body with the rapture and happiness born of concentration, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this rapture and happiness born of concentration. Great King, this is a visible fruit of the samaṇa life, more excellent and sublime than the previous visible fruits of the samaṇa life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as in a pond of blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses, some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, do not rise above the water, thrive while submerged, and from their roots to their tips they are drenched, saturated, filled, and pervaded with cool water, so that no part of those blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses is not pervaded by cool water — so too, Great King, a bhikkhu drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades his very body with happiness free from rapture, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this happiness free from rapture. Great King, this is a visible fruit of the samaṇa life, more excellent and sublime than the previous visible fruits of the samaṇa life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Great King, a bhikkhu, abandoning pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and grief, enters and abides in the fourth jhāna, which is neither painful nor pleasant, with purity of mindfulness due to equanimity. He sits pervading his very body with a pure, bright mind, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this pure, bright mind. Great King, just as a man sitting with a white cloth covering his head, so that no part of his body is not covered by the white cloth — so too, Great King, a bhikkhu sits pervading his very body with a pure, bright mind, so that no part of his entire body is not pervaded by this pure, bright mind. Great King, this is a visible fruit of the samaṇa life, more excellent and sublime than the previous visible fruits of the samaṇa life.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, he directs his mind to knowledge and vision. He understands: 'This body of mine is material, composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wearing away, dissolution, breaking up, and destruction. And my consciousness is dependent upon it and bound to it.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as a beautiful, brilliant, eight-faceted beryl gem, well-cut, well-polished, clear, unblemished, endowed with all excellent qualities, and a thread — blue, yellow, red, white, or light yellow — is strung through it. A person with eyes, holding it in his hand, would see: 'This beautiful, brilliant, eight-faceted beryl gem, well-cut, well-polished, clear, unblemished, endowed with all excellent qualities, and this thread — blue, yellow, red, white, or light yellow — is strung through it.' So too, Great King, with his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, the bhikkhu directs his mind to knowledge and vision. He understands: 'This body of mine is material, composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wearing away, dissolution, breaking up, and destruction. And my consciousness is dependent upon it and bound to it.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, he directs his mind to the knowledge of the passing away and rebirth of beings. With the divine eye, which is purified and surpasses the human, he sees beings passing away and being reborn. He knows that beings are base or noble, beautiful or ugly, fortunate or unfortunate, according to their actions: 'These beings, friends, who engaged in evil conduct of body, speech, and mind, who reviled the noble ones, who held wrong views and acted accordingly, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. But those beings, friends, who engaged in good conduct of body, speech, and mind, who did not revile the noble ones, who held right views and acted accordingly, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Thus with the divine eye, purified and surpassing the human, he sees beings passing away and being reborn, and he knows that beings are base or noble, beautiful or ugly, fortunate or unfortunate, according to their actions.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `With his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, he directs his mind to the knowledge of the destruction of the taints. He understands as it actually is: 'This is suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the origin of suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the cessation of suffering'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' He understands as it actually is: 'These are the taints'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the origin of the taints'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the cessation of the taints'; he understands as it actually is: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of the taints.' Knowing thus, seeing thus, his mind is liberated from the taint of sensual desire, liberated from the taint of existence, liberated from the taint of ignorance. When liberated, there comes the knowledge: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done; there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as a person who goes from his own village to another village, from that village to yet another, and then returns to his own village would think: 'I went from my village to that village, where I stood thus, sat thus, spoke thus, was silent thus. From that village I went to yet another, where I stood thus, sat thus, spoke thus, was silent thus. Then from that village I returned to my own village.' So too, Great King, with his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, the bhikkhu directs his mind to the knowledge of the recollection of past lives. He recollects his manifold past lives, that is, one birth, two births, three births, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand births, many eons of world-contraction, many eons of world-expansion, many eons of world-contraction and expansion. He recollects: 'There I had such a name, belonged to such a clan, such a caste, such was my food, such my experience of pleasure and pain, such my lifespan. Passing away from there, I arose elsewhere, where I had such a name, belonged to such a clan, such a caste, such was my food, such my experience of pleasure and pain, such my lifespan. Passing away from there, I arose here.' Thus he recollects his manifold past lives with their modes and details.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `Great King, just as a man with a multi-storied mansion with an upper terrace at a crossroads, standing there, would see people entering houses, leaving houses, walking back and forth on the road, sitting at the crossroads or on the upper terrace. He would think: 'These people are entering houses, these are leaving houses, these are walking back and forth on the road, these are sitting at the crossroads, on the upper terrace.' So too, Great King, with his mind thus concentrated, purified, bright, unblemished, free from defilements, pliant, workable, steady, and imperturbable, the bhikkhu directs his mind to the knowledge of the passing away and rebirth of beings. With the divine eye, which is purified and surpasses the human, he sees beings passing away and being reborn.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2" },

{ text: `- Friends, listen to me explain why it is truly worthy for us to go and see Samaṇa Gotama, rather than it being worthy for Samaṇa Gotama to come and see us. Friends, indeed, Samaṇa Gotama is virtuous, maintaining the virtue of the noble ones, of good character, possessed of good character. Friends, indeed, Samaṇa Gotama is well-spoken, uses well-spoken words, speaks elegantly, with clear meaning, his voice is not stammering or indistinct, he explains the meaning distinctly. Friends, indeed, Samaṇa Gotama is a teacher among teachers for many people. Friends, indeed, Samaṇa Gotama has abandoned sensual desire, has abandoned all mental agitation. Friends, indeed, Samaṇa Gotama teaches about karma, teaches about action, and emphasizes the supreme good when teaching the Dhamma to the assembly of brahmins.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 4 – Soṇadaṇḍasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn4" },

{ text: `Master Gotama, wisdom is purified by virtue, virtue is purified by wisdom. Where there is virtue, there is wisdom; where there is wisdom, there is virtue. One with virtue certainly has wisdom; one with wisdom certainly has virtue. Virtue and wisdom are considered supreme in the world. Master Gotama, just as one hand washes the other, one foot washes the other, so too, Master Gotama, wisdom is purified by virtue, virtue is purified by wisdom. Where there is virtue, there is wisdom; where there is wisdom, there is virtue. One with virtue certainly has wisdom; one with wisdom certainly has virtue. Virtue and wisdom are considered supreme in the world.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 4 – Soṇadaṇḍasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn4" },

{ text: `Kassapa, and this situation occurs. When the wise question one another, investigate and discuss with one another, they say: 'Those unwholesome states that are considered unwholesome, those faulty states that are considered faulty, those states not to be practiced that are considered not to be practiced, those states unbefitting the noble ones that are considered unbefitting the noble ones, those defiled states that are considered defiled — among these venerable ones, Samaṇa Gotama has completely abandoned these states, whereas those other venerable teachers and leaders of sects have abandoned them only partially.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 8 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn8" },

{ text: `Kassapa, there is a path, there is a method by which, following it, one will see and know for oneself: 'Samaṇa Gotama speaks at the right time, speaks truthfully, speaks beneficially, speaks in accordance with the Dhamma, speaks in accordance with the Discipline.' Kassapa, what is that path, what is that method by which, following it, one will see and know: 'Samaṇa Gotama speaks at the right time, speaks truthfully, speaks beneficially, speaks in accordance with the Dhamma, speaks in accordance with the Discipline?' It is just this Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration. Kassapa, this is the path, this is the method by which, following it, one will see and know for oneself: 'Samaṇa Gotama speaks at the right time, speaks truthfully, speaks beneficially, speaks in accordance with the Dhamma, speaks in accordance with the Discipline.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 8 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn8" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, is the world eternal? Is this the only truth, and everything else is delusion? - Poṭṭhapāda, I do not answer: 'The world is eternal, this alone is true, everything else is delusion.' - Venerable Sir, is the world not eternal? ... - Venerable Sir, is the world finite? ... - Venerable Sir, is the world infinite? ... - Venerable Sir, are the soul and the body the same? ... - Venerable Sir, are the soul and the body different? ... - Venerable Sir, does the Tathāgata exist after death? Is this the only truth, and everything else is delusion? - Poṭṭhapāda, I do not answer: 'The Tathāgata exists after death, this alone is true, everything else is delusion.' - Venerable Sir, does the Tathāgata not exist after death? ... - Venerable Sir, does the Tathāgata both exist and not exist after death? ... - Venerable Sir, does the Tathāgata neither exist nor not exist after death? Is this the only truth, and everything else is delusion? - Poṭṭhapāda, I do not answer: 'The Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death, this alone is true, everything else is delusion.' - Venerable Sir, why does the Blessed One not answer? - Poṭṭhapāda, this question is not connected with the goal, not connected with the Dhamma, not connected with the fundamentals of the holy life, and does not lead to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbāna. Therefore I do not answer. - Venerable Sir, what then does the Blessed One answer? - Poṭṭhapāda, I answer: 'This is suffering.' I answer: 'This is the origin of suffering.' I answer: 'This is the cessation of suffering.' I answer: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' - Venerable Sir, why does the Blessed One answer? - Poṭṭhapāda, this question is connected with the goal, connected with the Dhamma, connected with the fundamentals of the holy life, and leads to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbāna. Therefore I answer.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `- Poṭṭhapāda, there are three kinds of self-identification: the gross self-identification, the mind-made self-identification, and the formless self-identification. Poṭṭhapāda, what is the gross self-identification? Having form, composed of the four great elements, nourished by solid food — this is the gross self-identification. What is the mind-made self-identification? Having form, mind-made, complete with all major and minor parts, with all faculties intact — this is the mind-made self-identification. What is the formless self-identification? Formless, made of perception — this is the formless self-identification.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Poṭṭhapāda, I teach the Dhamma for the abandonment of the gross self-identification. If you practice accordingly, then defiled states will be abandoned, pure states will increase, and you will personally realize, attain, and abide in the here and now with full and extensive wisdom. Poṭṭhapāda, it is possible that you might think: 'Defiled states will be abandoned, pure states will increase, and one will personally realize, attain, and abide in the here and now with full and extensive wisdom, yet suffering still remains.' Poṭṭhapāda, do not think thus. When defiled states are abandoned and pure states increase, one in this very life, with direct knowledge, attains and abides in full and extensive wisdom, then joy arises, gladness, tranquility, mindfulness, clear comprehension, and a pleasant abiding arise.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, there are five strands of sensual pleasure. What are the five? Forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear... odors cognizable by the nose... flavors cognizable by the tongue... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. Vāseṭṭha, those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas cling to, are infatuated with, bound by these five strands of sensual pleasure, not seeing the danger, not understanding the escape, and enjoy them. Vāseṭṭha, that these brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, abandoning those qualities that make a brahmin, following those qualities that do not make a brahmin, clinging to, infatuated with, bound by these five strands of sensual pleasure, not seeing the danger, not understanding the escape, enjoying them, bound by the bondage of sensual desire, after death, with the breakup of the body, should be reborn in companionship with Brahmā — this is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, just as this river Aciravati is full to the brim so that a crow could drink from it. A person comes, having business on the further shore, seeking the further shore, heading for the further shore, wishing to cross over to the further shore. Standing on this bank, he calls out to the further shore: 'Come here, further shore! Come here, further shore!' Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Would the further shore of the river Aciravati come to this shore because of that person's calling, his praying, his hoping, his praising? — No, Master Gotama. — So too, Vāseṭṭha, those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, abandoning those qualities that make a brahmin, following those qualities that do not make a brahmin, say: 'We pray to Indra, we pray to Soma, we pray to Varuna, we pray to Īsāna, we pray to Pajāpati, we pray to Brahmā, we pray to Yama.' Vāseṭṭha, that those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, abandoning those qualities that make a brahmin, following those qualities that do not make a brahmin — through their calling, their praying, their hoping, their praising — after death, with the breakup of the body, should be reborn in companionship with Brahmā — this is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, just as a person who wishes to build a staircase to ascend to a mansion at a crossroads. Someone asks: 'Friend, you wish to build a staircase to ascend to a mansion. Do you know whether that mansion is to the east, west, north, or south? Is it high, low, or medium in height?' Asked thus, he answers that he does not know. They ask: 'Friend, are you then building a staircase to ascend to a mansion that you do not know, have not seen?' Asked thus, he answers yes. Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Would that person's words be correct and reasonable? — No, Master Gotama. In that case, his words would be incorrect and unreasonable. — So too, Vāseṭṭha, you say that the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas cannot see Brahmā face to face, nor can their teachers or their teachers' teachers see Brahmā face to face... Vāseṭṭha, those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, not knowing, not seeing the path leading to co-residence with Brahmā, yet teach: 'This is the direct path, this is the right path leading to co-residence with Brahmā for those who practice it' — this is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, just as this river Aciravati is full to the brim so that a crow could drink from it. A person comes, having business on the further shore, seeking the further shore, heading for the further shore, wishing to cross over to the further shore. This person, on this bank, covers his head and lies down to sleep. Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Could that person cross from this bank of the river Aciravati to the further shore? — No, Master Gotama. — So too, Vāseṭṭha, there are five hindrances which are called obstacles, also called hindrances, also called coverings, also called fetters in the Discipline of the noble ones. What are the five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of sloth and torpor, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. Vāseṭṭha, these five hindrances are called obstacles, hindrances, coverings, fetters. Vāseṭṭha, those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas are obstructed, hindered, covered, fettered by these five hindrances. Vāseṭṭha, that those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, abandoning those qualities that make a brahmin, following those qualities that do not make a brahmin, being obstructed, hindered, covered, fettered by these five hindrances, after death, with the breakup of the body, should be reborn in companionship with Brahmā — this is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Here, a person is born and raised in Manasākaṭa but has never left that place. — Yes, Venerable Sir. — Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Here, a person is born and raised in Manasākaṭa. Someone asks him about the road leading to Manasākaṭa. Vāseṭṭha, for that person who was born and raised in Manasākaṭa, there would be no doubt or difficulty, would there? — No, Master Gotama. Why is that? Because, Master Gotama, that person, having been born and raised in Manasākaṭa, knows all the roads leading to Manasākaṭa. — Vāseṭṭha, for that person who was born and raised in Manasākaṭa, there could still be doubt and difficulty when asked about the road to Manasākaṭa, but for the Tathāgata, there is no doubt or difficulty when asked about the Brahmā world or the path leading to the Brahmā world! Vāseṭṭha, I know Brahmā, the Brahmā world, and the path leading to the Brahmā world.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `He abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, likewise the second, likewise the third, likewise the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Vāseṭṭha, just as a strong trumpeter sounds his trumpet without difficulty in the four directions, so too, Vāseṭṭha, regarding all forms of life, there is no one he overlooks or neglects, but he pervades them with a mind of loving-kindness, liberated. Vāseṭṭha, this is the path leading to co-residence with Brahmā.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Vāseṭṭha, a bhikkhu abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness ... pervading one direction with a mind imbued with compassion ... with a mind imbued with altruistic joy ... pervading one direction with a mind imbued with equanimity, likewise the second, likewise the third, likewise the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with equanimity, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Vāseṭṭha, just as a strong trumpeter sounds his trumpet without difficulty in the four directions, so too, Vāseṭṭha, regarding all forms of life, there is no one he overlooks or neglects, but he pervades them with a mind of equanimity, liberated. Vāseṭṭha, this is the path leading to co-residence with Brahmā.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, just as a strong trumpeter sounds his trumpet without difficulty in the four directions, so too, Vāseṭṭha, regarding all forms of life, there is no one he overlooks or neglects, but he pervades them with a mind of loving-kindness, liberated. Vāseṭṭha, this is the path leading to co-residence with Brahmā. Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Does a bhikkhu who abides thus have sensual desire or not? — Master Gotama, he has no sensual desire. — Does he have hatred or not? — He has no hatred. — Does he have ill-will or not? — He has no ill-will. — Does he have defilement or not? — He has no defilement. — Does he have self-mastery or not? — He has self-mastery. — Vāseṭṭha, you say the bhikkhu has no sensual desire, and Brahmā has no sensual desire. Can there be association and co-residence between a bhikkhu without sensual desire and Brahmā without sensual desire? — Master Gotama, there can. — Good, Vāseṭṭha. Then, Vāseṭṭha, after death, with the breakup of the body, that bhikkhu will be reborn in companionship with Brahmā. That is indeed possible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, you say the bhikkhu has no hatred, and Brahmā has no hatred ... the bhikkhu has no ill-will, and Brahmā has no ill-will ... the bhikkhu has no defilement, and Brahmā has no defilement ... the bhikkhu has self-mastery, and Brahmā has self-mastery. Can there be association and co-residence between a bhikkhu with self-mastery and Brahmā with self-mastery? — Master Gotama, there can. — Good, Vāseṭṭha. Then, Vāseṭṭha, after death, with the breakup of the body, that bhikkhu will be reborn in companionship with Brahmā. That is indeed possible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Have you heard the elderly, senior brahmins, teachers and great teachers, talking together: Does Brahmā have sensual desire or not? — Master Gotama, he has no sensual desire. — Does he have hatred or not? — He has no hatred. — Does he have ill-will or not? — He has no ill-will. — Does he have defilement or not? — He has no defilement. — Does he have self-mastery or not? — He has self-mastery. — Vāseṭṭha, what do you think? Do the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas have sensual desire or not? — Master Gotama, they have sensual desire. — Do they have hatred or not? — They have hatred. — Do they have ill-will or not? — They have ill-will. — Do they have defilement or not? — They have defilement. — Do they have self-mastery or not? — They have no self-mastery. — Vāseṭṭha, you say that the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas have sensual desire, and Brahmā has no sensual desire. Can there be association and co-residence between the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas who have sensual desire and Brahmā who has no sensual desire? — Master Gotama, that is impossible. — Good, Vāseṭṭha. Then, Vāseṭṭha, that those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, being full of sensual desire, after death, with the breakup of the body, should be reborn in companionship with Brahmā — that is impossible.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī, while on his way to the pleasure garden, saw a sick person, afflicted, gravely ill, wallowing in his own urine and excrement, needing others to lift him up, needing others to support him. Seeing this, the prince asked the charioteer: 'Friend, what has happened to this person, that his eyes are not like others' eyes, his voice is not like others' voices?' 'Your Highness, he is called a sick person.' 'Friend, why is he called a sick person?' 'Your Highness, he is called a sick person because he has not yet recovered from his illness.' 'Friend, will I too become sick, I who am not yet sick?' 'Your Highness, you and I too, we will all become sick, though we are not yet sick.' 'Friend, then today's visit to the pleasure garden is enough. Drive me back to the palace.' 'Yes, Your Highness.' Bhikkhus, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove back to the palace. Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī returned to the palace, distressed, sorrowful, and reflecting: 'Shame indeed, this thing called birth! For anyone born, there is aging, there is sickness!'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove to the dead body. Bhikkhus, seeing the dead body, Prince Vipassī asked: 'Friend, why is this person called dead?' 'Your Highness, he is called dead because now his mother, father, and other blood relatives no longer see him, and he no longer sees his mother, father, or other blood relatives.' 'Friend, am I not yet dead, and will I die? Will my father, mother, and other blood relatives no longer see me, and will I no longer see my father, mother, and other blood relatives?' 'Your Highness, you and I too, though we are not yet dead, we will also die. Your father, mother, and other blood relatives will no longer see Your Highness, and Your Highness will no longer see your father, mother, and other blood relatives.' 'Friend, then today's visit to the pleasure garden is enough. Drive me back to the palace.' 'Yes, Your Highness.' Bhikkhus, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove back to the palace. Bhikkhus, Prince Vipassī returned to the palace, distressed, sorrowful, and reflecting: 'Shame indeed, this thing called birth! For anyone born, there is such aging, such sickness, such death!'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, thought: 'This Dhamma I have realized is deep, hard to see, hard to realize, peaceful, sublime, beyond reasoning, subtle, to be understood by the wise. But this generation delights in sensual pleasures, is excited by sensual pleasures, enjoys sensual pleasures. For a generation that delights in sensual pleasures, is excited by sensual pleasures, enjoys sensual pleasures, it is hard to see this principle of conditionality, this dependent origination. It is also hard to see the stilling of all formations, the abandoning of all basis for existence, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna. If I were to teach the Dhamma and others did not understand me, that would be wearisome and troublesome for me.' Bhikkhus, then these wonderful verses, unheard before, arose to the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One: 'Why should I now declare what I have realized with such difficulty? This Dhamma is not easily understood by those overcome by greed and hatred. Those stained by craving and shrouded by ignorance find it hard to see this Dhamma. It goes against the stream, subtle, deep, hard to see, and fine.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, with these words, the mind of the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, inclined towards inaction, to passivity, not wishing to teach the Dhamma. Then a certain Great Brahmā, having known with his mind the thought of the Blessed One Vipassī, thought: 'Alas, the world will be destroyed, the world will perish, if the mind of the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, inclines towards inaction, to passivity, not wishing to teach the Dhamma!' Bhikkhus, that Great Brahmā, just as a strong man might stretch his bent arm or bend his outstretched arm, vanished from the Brahmā world and appeared before the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Bhikkhus, then the Great Brahmā arranged his upper robe on one shoulder, knelt on his right knee on the ground, saluted the Blessed One Vipassī with joined palms, and said: 'Venerable Sir, let the Blessed One teach the Dhamma! Let the Well-Gone teach the Dhamma! There are beings with little dust in their eyes who will be lost if they do not hear the Dhamma. Having heard, they will understand the Dhamma.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Then the Great Brahmā, having known with his mind the thought of the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, spoke this verse to him:<br><br>As a person standing on a mountain peak sees the people all around below,<br>So you, O Sumedha, wise one, gone up to the Dhamma palace, the all-seeing one, free from sorrow,<br>Look down upon the people, immersed in sorrow, oppressed by birth and decay.<br>Arise, O hero! Victor in battle!<br>O caravan leader, free from debt! Wander the world, O Blessed One, teaching the Dhamma!<br>There will be those who understand!"<br><br>Bhikkhus, then the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, replied to the Great Brahmā with this verse:<br><br>Wide open are the doors of the Deathless,<br>Let those who have ears renounce their wrong beliefs.<br>Thinking of weariness, O Brahmā,<br>I did not want to teach the sublime Dhamma to humans.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `The Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, taught step by step, speaking on giving, speaking on virtue, speaking on the heavens, explaining the danger, the degradation, and the defilement of sensual desires, and the benefit of renunciation. When the Blessed One knew that their minds were ready, pliant, free from hindrances, elevated, and peaceful, he then taught the Dhamma that the Buddhas have extolled, namely: suffering, origin, cessation, path. Just as a pure cloth, free from stains, would readily take a dye, so too, those eighty-four thousand beings, in that very seat, attained the dustless, stainless Dhamma-eye: 'Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation.'`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, wander forth for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans. Do not go two together. Bhikkhus, teach the Dhamma that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, and reveal the holy life completely perfect and pure. There are beings with little dust in their eyes who will be lost if they do not hear the Dhamma. Having heard, they will understand the Dhamma.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14" },

{ text: `Earlier it was said: 'With consciousness as condition, name-and-form arises.' Ānanda, how should the meaning of this statement be understood? Ānanda, if consciousness were not to descend into the mother's womb, would name-and-form take shape there? — No, Venerable Sir. — Ānanda, if consciousness, having descended into the mother's womb, were to be destroyed, would name-and-form come to this state or that? — No, Venerable Sir. — Ānanda, if consciousness were to be cut off in a young child, whether boy or girl, would name-and-form grow, develop, and reach maturity? — No, Venerable Sir. — Therefore, Ānanda, this is the cause, this is the condition, this is the origination, this is the reason for name-and-form, namely consciousness. Earlier it was said: 'With name-and-form as condition, consciousness arises.' Ānanda, how should the meaning of this statement be understood? Ānanda, if consciousness were not to gain a footing in name-and-form, would the formation of birth, aging, death, suffering, and origination in the future come to be? — No, Venerable Sir. — Therefore, Ānanda, this is the cause, this is the condition, this is the origination, this is the reason for consciousness, namely name-and-form. Ānanda, within this limit one is born, grows old, dies, passes away, or is reborn. Within this limit is designation, within this limit is language, within this limit is conceptual description, within this limit is the sphere of wisdom, within this limit is the wandering on in saṃsāra, the state of being such and such, namely name-and-form together with consciousness.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 15 – Mahānidānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn15" },

{ text: `Ānanda, when feeling a pleasant feeling, one does not feel a painful feeling, nor a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling; one feels just a pleasant feeling. Ānanda, when feeling a painful feeling, one does not feel a pleasant feeling, nor a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling; one feels just a painful feeling. Ānanda, when feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, one does not feel a pleasant feeling, nor a painful feeling; one feels just a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Furthermore, Ānanda, pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to passing away, subject to fading away, subject to cessation. Ānanda, painful feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to passing away, subject to fading away, subject to cessation. Ānanda, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to passing away, subject to fading away, subject to cessation.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 15 – Mahānidānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn15" },

{ text: `Thus, Ānanda, with feeling as condition, craving arises; with craving as condition, seeking arises; with seeking as condition, gain arises; with gain as condition, decision arises; with decision as condition, desire and lust arise; with desire and lust as condition, attachment arises; with attachment as condition, possessiveness arises; with possessiveness as condition, miserliness arises; with miserliness as condition, guarding arises; with guarding as condition, various evil, unwholesome states arise, such as taking up sticks, taking up swords, conflicts, quarrels, disputes, verbal warfare, harsh speech, and false speech.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 15 – Mahānidānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn15" },

{ text: `All conditioned things,<br>Truly impermanent,<br>Arising and passing away,<br>Such is their nature.<br>They are born,<br>And then they cease.<br>Blissful is their<br>Peaceful stilling.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 17 – Mahāsudassanasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn17" },

{ text: `Good friends of the Thirty-three, what do you think? The Four Foundations of Mindfulness leading to true good have been realized by the Blessed One, the Wise One, the Seeing One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. What are the four? Good friends, here a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. By dwelling contemplating the body as a body internally, his mind becomes concentrated and fully calmed. With his mind thus concentrated and fully calmed, knowledge and vision arise regarding other bodies external to himself. A bhikkhu dwells contemplating feelings as feelings internally ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. By dwelling contemplating phenomena as phenomena, his mind becomes concentrated and fully calmed. With his mind thus concentrated and fully calmed, knowledge and vision arise regarding other phenomena. Good friends, these Four Foundations of Mindfulness leading to true good have been realized by the Blessed One, the Wise One, the Seeing One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 18 – Janavasabhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn18" },

{ text: `'This is wholesome', 'this is unwholesome' has been well explained by the Blessed One. 'This is blameworthy', 'this is blameless', 'this should be practiced', 'this should be avoided', 'this is low', 'this is sublime', 'this is the equal pairing of dark and bright' has been well explained by the Blessed One. A teacher who has well explained wholesome and unwholesome states, blameworthy and blameless states, what should be practiced and what should be avoided, low and sublime, the equal pairing of dark and bright, a teacher endowed with such qualities is hard to find in the past or present except the Blessed One. The path leading to Nibbāna for disciples, and Nibbāna itself, have been well explained by the Blessed One as coalescing into one, like the water of the Ganges river flowing and merging with the water of the Yamunā. So too, the path leading to Nibbāna for disciples, and Nibbāna itself, have been well explained by the Blessed One as coalescing into one. A teacher who has thus well explained the path leading to Nibbāna, a teacher endowed with such qualities, is hard to find in the past or present except the Blessed One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 19 – Mahāgovindasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn19" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, the Blessed One does not enable me to attain the superhuman states of psychic power. - Sunakkhatta, did I say to you: 'Come, Sunakkhatta, live under my guidance! I will enable you to attain the superhuman states of psychic power'? - No, Venerable Sir. - Did you say to me: 'Venerable Sir, I will live under the guidance of the Blessed One, and the Blessed One will enable me to attain the superhuman states of psychic power'? - No, Venerable Sir. - Sunakkhatta, since I did not say to you, and you did not say to me, you foolish man, who are you and who am I that you speak of abandoning? Sunakkhatta, whether the superhuman states of psychic power are realized or not, the purpose for which I teach the Dhamma is to lead the practitioner to the complete destruction of suffering. Sunakkhatta, what then are the superhuman states of psychic power that need to be realized? See how great your transgression is, you foolish man!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, the Blessed One does not explain the origin of the world to me. - Sunakkhatta, did I say to you: 'Come, Sunakkhatta, live under my guidance! I will explain the origin of the world to you'? - No, Venerable Sir. - Sunakkhatta, did you say to me: 'Venerable Sir, I will live under the guidance of the Blessed One, and then the Blessed One will explain the origin of the world to me'? - No, Venerable Sir. - Sunakkhatta, since I did not say to you, and you did not say to me, you foolish man, who are you and who am I that you speak of abandoning? Sunakkhatta, whether the origin of the world is explained or not, the purpose of the Blessed One in teaching the Dhamma is to lead the practitioner to the complete destruction of suffering. Sunakkhatta, what benefit would an explanation of the origin of the world be to you? See how great your transgression is, you foolish man!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 24 – Pāthikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn24" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is afflicted by a mild illness. He thinks: 'Now I have a mild illness; I need to rest. So I shall lie down.' He lies down, without striving to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. That is the seventh way of being slothful.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu has just recovered from an illness, not long after being ill. He thinks: 'I have just recovered from an illness, not long after being ill. This body of mine is weak, fit for nothing, so I shall lie down.' He lies down, without striving to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. That is the eighth way of being slothful.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is afflicted by a mild illness. He thinks: 'Now I have a mild illness; it is possible that this illness could become more severe. So I will strive with energy to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized.' And he strives with energy to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. That is the seventh way of energetic striving.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu has learned much, remembers what he has learned, and stores up what he has learned. Those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, proclaiming the holy life completely perfect and pure — such teachings he has learned much, retained, memorized by repeated recitation, mentally investigated, and well penetrated by right view.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu has good friends, good companions, good comrades. He is one who maintains such relationships. Friends, for a bhikkhu who has good friends, good companions, good comrades, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is well-spoken, endowed with gentleness and humility, patient and respectfully accepting criticism. Friends, for a bhikkhu who is well-spoken ... respectfully accepting criticism, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, when there are duties to be done for his fellow celibates of senior standing, he is skillful, not lazy, fully considering the appropriate means, sufficient for doing, sufficient for organizing. Friends, for a bhikkhu who is thus toward his fellow celibates ... sufficient for organizing, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu loves the Dhamma, delights in discussing the Dhamma, and is greatly joyful in the supreme Dhamma and Discipline. Friends, for a bhikkhu who loves the Dhamma ... is greatly joyful in the supreme Dhamma and Discipline, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is content with whatever gains he receives such as robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicines. Friends, for a bhikkhu who is content ... this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and diligent, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, resolute, persistently striving, enduring, not neglecting wholesome states. Friends, for a bhikkhu who dwells energetic and diligent ... enduring, not neglecting wholesome states, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is mindful, endowed with supreme mindfulness and clear comprehension, remembering and recalling what was said and done long ago. Friends, for a bhikkhu who is mindful, remembering what was said and done long ago, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Furthermore, friends, a bhikkhu is wise, endowed with the wisdom of arising and passing away, leading to the noble penetrating decision that rightly ends all suffering. Friends, for a bhikkhu who is wise ... that rightly ends all suffering, this is a supporting factor.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33" },

{ text: `Eight Thoughts of a Great Man: This Dhamma is for one of few desires, not for one of many desires. This Dhamma is for one who is content, not for one who is discontent. This Dhamma is for one who is solitary and secluded, not for one who delights in company. This Dhamma is for one who is energetic and diligent, not for one who is lazy. This Dhamma is for one who has mindfulness established, not for one who is forgetful. This Dhamma is for one who has a concentrated mind, not for one who is unconcentrated. This Dhamma is for one who is wise, not for one of poor wisdom. This Dhamma is for one who does not delight in proliferating theories, not for one who delights in proliferating theories. These are the eight things to be aroused.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 34 – Dasuttarasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn34" },


            
            
             { text: `Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, directly knows the earth element as earth element. Having directly known the earth element as earth element, he does not conceive (anything) about the earth element, does not conceive (anything) in the earth element, does not conceive (anything) as the earth element, does not conceive (anything) as 'the earth element is mine' — he does not delight in the earth element. Why is that? Because the Tathāgata understands that delight is the root of suffering, from existence it arises, and from aging and death come to beings. Therefore, bhikkhus, I say that through the complete destruction, fading away, cessation, relinquishment, and abandoning of all craving, the Tathāgata has awakened to supreme perfect enlightenment.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 1 – Mūlapariyāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are taints that are to be abandoned by seeing, there are taints that are to be abandoned by restraining, there are taints that are to be abandoned by using, there are taints that are to be abandoned by enduring, there are taints that are to be abandoned by avoiding, there are taints that are to be abandoned by dispelling, there are taints that are to be abandoned by developing.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the danger in forms? Bhikkhus, one may see that same woman at another time, at eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old, aged, crooked like a roof, bent over, leaning on a staff, trembling as she walks, afflicted, her youth gone, her teeth gone, her hair grey and falling, bald, wrinkled, her limbs spotted and pale. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared? — Yes, Venerable Sir. — Bhikkhus, this is called the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, one may see that same woman afflicted by illness, suffering, seriously ill, lying in her own urine and excrement, needing to be lifted up, needing to be laid down. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared? — Yes, Venerable Sir. — Bhikkhus, this is called the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, one sees that same woman's body thrown into the charnel ground, being eaten by crows, or being eaten by hawks, or being eaten by vultures, or being eaten by dogs, or being eaten by jackals, or being eaten by various creeping creatures. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared? — Yes, Venerable Sir. — Bhikkhus, this is called the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, one sees that same woman's body thrown into the charnel ground, a skeleton with flesh and blood still held together by sinews ... a skeleton without flesh but smeared with blood, still held together by sinews ... a skeleton without flesh or blood, still held together by sinews ... disconnected bones scattered in all directions, here a hand-bone, there a foot-bone, there a shin-bone, there a thigh-bone, there a hip-bone, there a spine, there a skull. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared? — Yes, Venerable Sir. — Bhikkhus, this is called the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who do not understand as it actually is the gratification of forms as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape — they will certainly not understand forms as they actually are, nor will they be able to place others in a similar position, that is, to understand forms as they actually are. This is impossible. Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who understand as it actually is the gratification of forms as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape — they will certainly understand forms as they actually are, and they will be able to place others in a similar position, that is, to understand forms as they actually are. This is possible.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `For one who does not attend wisely, one of these six wrong views arises: 'I have a self' — this view arises in him as true and real; 'I have no self' ... 'I perceive self by means of self' ... 'I perceive self by means of not-self' ... 'I perceive not-self by means of self' ... Or such a view as this arises: 'It is this self of mine that speaks and feels and experiences the results of good and bad deeds here and there; but this self of mine is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, and will endure as long as eternity.' This, bhikkhus, is called a thicket of views, a wilderness of views, a puppet-show of views, a writhing of views, a fetter of views. Bound by the fetter of views, the unlearned ordinary person is not liberated from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not liberated from suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple, who has seen the noble ones, is skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who has seen the true persons, is skilled in the teaching of the true persons, trained in the teaching of the true persons — he understands which things are to be attended to and which things are not to be attended to. He attends wisely: 'This is suffering' ... 'This is the origin of suffering' ... 'This is the cessation of suffering' ... 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' By attending thus, three fetters are abandoned: personality-view, doubt, and clinging to rules and rituals.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the taints that are to be abandoned by restraining? Here, a bhikkhu, reflecting wisely, dwells restraining the eye faculty. Bhikkhus, if when he dwells without restraining the eye faculty, harmful, afflicting taints might arise; but when he dwells restraining the eye faculty, those harmful, afflicting taints do not arise. These, bhikkhus, are called taints that are to be abandoned by restraining.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Reflecting wisely, he uses almsfood not for enjoyment, not for indulgence, not for beautification, not for ornamentation, but only for the support and maintenance of this body, for avoiding harm, for assisting the holy life, thinking: 'Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings; and there will be for me blamelessness and a comfortable abiding.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, reflecting wisely, endures cold, heat, hunger, thirst, the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things; he endures harsh and abusive speech. He endures bodily feelings that are painful, severe, sharp, racking, unpleasant, disagreeable, life-threatening. Bhikkhus, if he did not endure thus, harmful, afflicting taints might arise; but when he endures thus, those harmful, afflicting taints do not arise. These, bhikkhus, are called taints that are to be abandoned by enduring.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Reflecting wisely, he uses lodging only to ward off cold, to ward off heat, to ward off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things, only to remove the dangers of climate, and only for the purpose of seclusion and quietude.<br>Reflecting wisely, he uses medicines and medical requisites only to ward off arisen painful feelings and for the sake of complete freedom from affliction.<br>Bhikkhus, if he did not use thus, harmful, afflicting taints might arise; but when he uses thus, those harmful, afflicting taints do not arise. These, bhikkhus, are called taints that are to be abandoned by using.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, reflecting wisely, avoids a wild elephant, avoids a wild horse, avoids a wild ox, avoids a wild dog, a snake, a stump, a bramble patch, a pit, a precipice, a cesspool, a sewage pool. Seats that are improper to sit on, dwelling places that are improper to frequent, evil companions — if he were to associate with them, wise fellow celibates would suspect and despise him; reflecting wisely, he avoids such improper seats, such improper dwelling places, and such evil companions.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, reflecting wisely, does not consent to an arisen sensual thought; he abandons, dispels, destroys, and makes it disappear. He does not consent to an arisen thought of ill-will ... He does not consent to an arisen thought of harmfulness; he abandons, dispels, destroys, and makes it disappear. He does not consent to any arisen evil, unwholesome states; he abandons, dispels, destroys, and makes them disappear.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu, those taints that are to be abandoned by seeing have been abandoned by seeing, those taints that are to be abandoned by restraining have been abandoned by restraining ... That bhikkhu is called one who dwells restraining all taints, who has cut off craving, who has turned away from the fetters, who has fully broken through conceit, who has put an end to suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, be heirs of my Dhamma, not heirs of material things. I have compassion for you and think: 'How shall my disciples become heirs of my Dhamma, not heirs of material things?' And, bhikkhus, if you become heirs of my material things, not heirs of the Dhamma, then not only would you be called 'disciples who are heirs of material things, not heirs of the Dhamma,' but I also would be called 'teacher who is an heir of material things, not an heir of the Dhamma.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, even if that bhikkhu, after eating such food, overcomes his hunger and fatigue and spends the rest of that day and night thus, still the first bhikkhu is more worthy of reverence and praise. Why is that? Because it will lead for a long time to few desires, contentment, austerity, easy support, energy, and effort for that bhikkhu. Therefore, bhikkhus, be heirs of my Dhamma, not heirs of material things.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Friends, here the Teacher lives in seclusion, but the disciples do not follow the practice of seclusion. The things that the Teacher teaches to be abandoned, they do not abandon. And they live in abundance, lazy, leading the way to backsliding, neglecting the burden of seclusion.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Friends, senior bhikkhus are blameworthy in three cases. The Teacher lives in seclusion, but the disciples do not follow the practice of seclusion. This is the first case in which senior bhikkhus are blameworthy. The things that the Teacher teaches to be abandoned, they do not abandon. This is the second case in which senior bhikkhus are blameworthy. And they live in abundance, lazy, leading the way to backsliding, neglecting the burden of seclusion. This is the third case in which senior bhikkhus are blameworthy. Friends, senior bhikkhus are blameworthy in these three cases.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Friends, senior bhikkhus are praiseworthy in three cases. The Teacher lives in seclusion, and the disciples follow the practice of seclusion. This is the first case in which senior bhikkhus are praiseworthy. The things that the Teacher teaches to be abandoned, they abandon. This is the second case in which senior bhikkhus are praiseworthy. And they do not live in abundance, they are not lazy, they abandon the burden of backsliding and lead the way to seclusion. This is the third case in which senior bhikkhus are praiseworthy. Friends, senior bhikkhus are praiseworthy in these three cases.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Here, friends, greed is an unwholesome state, and hatred is also an unwholesome state. There is a Middle Way that abandons greed and abandons hatred, giving rise to (pure) vision, giving rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. And what, friends, is that Middle Way — (the way) that gives rise to (pure) vision, gives rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration. Friends, this is that Middle Way, giving rise to (pure) vision, giving rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Here, friends, anger is an unwholesome state, and resentment is also an unwholesome state; hypocrisy is an unwholesome state, and malice is also an unwholesome state; envy is an unwholesome state, and stinginess is also an unwholesome state; deceit is an unwholesome state, and treachery is also an unwholesome state; obstinacy is an unwholesome state, and impetuousness is also an unwholesome state; conceit is an unwholesome state, and arrogance is also an unwholesome state; vanity is an unwholesome state, and heedlessness is also an unwholesome state. There is a Middle Way that abandons vanity and abandons heedlessness, giving rise to (pure) vision, giving rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `And what, friends, is that Middle Way — (the way) that gives rise to (pure) vision, gives rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration. Friends, this is that Middle Way, giving rise to (pure) vision, giving rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3" },

{ text: `Brahmin, then I thought: 'Whatever samaṇas or brahmins have impure bodily conduct, yet dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest — due to their defilement, their impure bodily conduct — those venerable samaṇas or brahmins will certainly arouse fear, terror, and unwholesome states. I do not have impure bodily conduct; I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest. My bodily conduct is pure. I am one of those noble ones with pure bodily conduct, dwelling in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, reflecting on my own completely pure bodily conduct, I felt even more confident when dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, regarding this matter, I thought: 'Whatever samaṇas or brahmins are agitated, with unstill mind, yet dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest — due to their defilement, being agitated, with unstill mind — those venerable samaṇas or brahmins will certainly arouse fear, terror, and unwholesome states. I am not agitated, my mind is not unstill; I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest. I am not agitated, my mind is still. I am one of those noble ones who are not agitated, with still mind, dwelling in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, reflecting on my own still mind thus, I felt even more confident when dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, regarding this matter, I thought: 'Whatever samaṇas or brahmins are lazy, lacking effort, yet dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest — due to their defilement, being lazy, lacking effort — those venerable samaṇas or brahmins will certainly arouse fear, terror, and unwholesome states. I am not lazy, I do not lack effort; I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest. I am energetic and diligent. I am one of those noble ones who are energetic and diligent, dwelling in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, reflecting on my own energy and diligence thus, I felt even more confident when dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, regarding this matter, I thought: 'Whatever samaṇas or brahmins are unmindful, not clearly comprehending, yet dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest — due to their defilement, being unmindful, not clearly comprehending — those venerable samaṇas or brahmins will certainly arouse fear, terror, and unwholesome states. I am not unmindful, I am not without clear comprehension; I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest. I am established in mindfulness. I am one of those noble ones established in mindfulness, dwelling in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, reflecting on my own being established in mindfulness thus, I felt even more confident when dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, regarding this matter, I thought: 'Whatever samaṇas or brahmins are not concentrated, with distracted mind, yet dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest — due to their defilement, being not concentrated, with distracted mind — those venerable samaṇas or brahmins will certainly arouse fear, terror, and unwholesome states. I am concentrated, my mind is not distracted; I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest. I have attained concentration of mind. I am one of those noble ones who have attained concentration of mind, dwelling in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, reflecting on my own attainment of concentration of mind thus, I felt even more confident when dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, some samaṇas and brahmins regard day as night, regard night as day. Thus, I say that those samaṇas and brahmins dwell in delusion. Brahmin, I regard night as night, regard day as day. Brahmin, one speaking rightly would say: 'A being without delusion, born in the world for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.' That one, speaking rightly about me, would say: 'A being without delusion, born in the world for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, I am energetic, diligent, not lazy. I am established in mindfulness, not confused, my body is tranquil, not agitated, my mind is concentrated and unified.<br>Brahmin, secluded from sensual desires, secluded from unwholesome states, I enter and abide in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion.<br>With the stilling of initial and sustained thought, I enter and abide in the second jhāna, which has internal clarity and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of concentration.<br>With the fading away of rapture, I dwell equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending, and experience happiness with the body; I enter and abide in the third jhāna, of which the noble ones declare: 'Equanimous and mindful, one dwells happily.'<br>With the abandoning of pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and grief, I enter and abide in the fourth jhāna, which is neither painful nor pleasant, with purity of mindfulness due to equanimity.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, in the last watch of the night, I attained the third true knowledge; ignorance was destroyed, knowledge arose; darkness was destroyed, light arose, while I was dwelling heedful, ardent, and resolute.<br>Knowing thus, seeing thus, my mind was liberated from the taint of sensual desire, liberated from the taint of existence, liberated from the taint of ignorance. When liberated, the knowledge arose: 'I am liberated.' I directly knew: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further return to this state.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Brahmin, you might have such a thought: 'Now Samaṇa Gotama has not abandoned greed, has not abandoned hatred, has not abandoned delusion, therefore he dwells in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest.' Brahmin, do not think thus. It is because I see two purposes that I dwell in remote lodgings in the wilderness and forest: seeing for myself a pleasant abiding in the present life, and out of compassion for future beings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 4 – Bhayabheravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn4" },

{ text: `Here, friends, a person has defilements but does not truly understand: 'There are defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will not arouse desire, will not make effort, will not arouse energy to abandon those defilements. He will die while still having greed, still having hatred, still having delusion, still having defilements, still having a defiled mind.' Friends, just as a bronze bowl, brought from the market or from the smithy, covered with dust and grime, and its owner does not use it, does not clean it, and throws it into a dusty place. Friends, after a time, that bowl becomes even more defiled, even dustier.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Friends, thus a person who has defilements but does not truly understand: 'There are defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will not arouse desire, will not make effort, will not arouse energy to abandon those defilements. He will die while still having greed, still having hatred, still having delusion, still having defilements, still having a defiled mind.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Here, friends, a person has defilements and truly understands: 'There are defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will arouse desire, will make effort, will arouse energy to abandon those defilements. He will die without greed, without hatred, without delusion, without defilements, with an undefiled mind.' Friends, just as a bronze bowl, brought from the market or from the smithy, covered with dust and grime, and its owner uses it, cleans it, and does not throw it into a dusty place. Friends, after a time, that bowl becomes even purer, even cleaner.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Friends, thus a person who has defilements and truly understands: 'There are defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will arouse desire, will make effort, will arouse energy to abandon those defilements. He will die without greed, without hatred, without delusion, without defilements, with an undefiled mind.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Here, friends, a person has no defilements but does not truly understand: 'There are no defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will give attention to the sign of the beautiful. By giving attention to the sign of the beautiful, greed will defile his mind. He will die while still having greed, still having hatred, still having delusion, still having defilements, still having a defiled mind.' Friends, just as a bronze bowl, brought from the market or from the smithy, pure and clean, and its owner does not use it, does not clean it, and throws it into a dusty place. Friends, after a time, that bowl becomes even more defiled, even dustier.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `- Friends, thus a person who has no defilements but does not truly understand: 'There are no defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will give attention to the sign of the beautiful. By giving attention to the sign of the beautiful, greed will defile his mind. He will die while still having greed, still having hatred, still having delusion, still having defilements, still having a defiled mind.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Here, friends, a person has no defilements and truly understands: 'There are no defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will not give attention to the sign of the beautiful. By not giving attention to the sign of the beautiful, greed will not defile his mind. He will die without greed, without hatred, without delusion, without defilements, with an undefiled mind.' Friends, just as a bronze bowl, brought from the market or from the smithy, pure and clean, and its owner uses it, cleans it, and does not throw it into a dusty place. Friends, after a time, that bowl becomes even purer, even cleaner.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `- Friends, thus a person who has no defilements and truly understands: 'There are no defilements within me.' For such a person, this can be expected: 'He will not give attention to the sign of the beautiful. By not giving attention to the sign of the beautiful, greed will not defile his mind. He will die without greed, without hatred, without delusion, without defilements, with an undefiled mind.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `- Friends, defilement is called defilement — what is the synonym for what is called defilement?<br>- Friends, evil, unwholesome states, the domain of sensual desire, are the synonym for what is called defilement.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Friends, this situation occurs. Here, a bhikkhu might have the wish: 'If I commit an offense, may the bhikkhus not know that I have committed an offense.' Friends, this situation may occur: the bhikkhus may come to know that that bhikkhu has committed an offense. That bhikkhu thinks: 'The bhikkhus have known that I have committed an offense.' Because of that, he becomes angry and discontent. Anger and discontent both belong to defilement.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Those good men who, out of faith, have gone forth from home to homelessness — those who are not deceitful, not fraudulent, not hypocritical, not restless, not arrogant, not agitated, not talkative, not frivolous, who guard the sense doors, are moderate in eating, devoted to wakefulness, earnest in the ascetic life, ardently respectful of the Dhamma and Discipline, not living in abundance, not lazy, abandoning the burden of backsliding, leading the way in seclusion, energetic, diligent, striving, wakeful, concentrated, unified in mind, wise, not dull — those, after hearing this exposition from the Venerable Sāriputta, seem to be drinking it in, seem to be tasting it with their speech and mind. Excellent indeed, that a venerable fellow celibate has caused (us) to transcend unwholesomeness and to be established in true wholesomeness!`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I be liked, beloved, respected, and venerated by my fellow celibates!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts, persevering, internally tranquil, not neglecting meditation, endowed with insight practice, delighting in secluded lodgings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 6 – Ākaṅkheyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May my blood relatives, when they die and pass away, think of me with a joyful mind and thereby receive great fruit, great benefit!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts ... (as above) ... in secluded lodgings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 6 – Ākaṅkheyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I overcome displeasure and pleasure, and not be overcome by displeasure. May I always overcome displeasure whenever it arises!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts ... (as above) ... in secluded lodgings.<br>Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I overcome fear and dread, and not be overcome by fear and dread. May I always overcome fear and dread whenever they arise!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts ... (as above) ... in secluded lodgings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 6 – Ākaṅkheyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I, as I wish, without difficulty, without trouble, without strain, attain the four jhānas, which are higher mental states and provide a pleasant abiding in the present life!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts ... (as above) ... in secluded lodgings.<br>Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I, with the destruction of the three fetters, become a stream-enterer, no longer subject to falling into lower realms, bound for enlightenment!' — that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in the precepts ... (as above) ... in secluded lodgings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 6 – Ākaṅkheyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a dirty, stained cloth, if a dyer dips it in this or that dye — blue, yellow, red, or magenta — it will take the dye poorly, it will be impure in color. Why is that? Because the cloth was not clean. So too, bhikkhus, a bad destination awaits a defiled mind. Bhikkhus, just as a clean, pure cloth, if a dyer dips it in this or that dye — blue, yellow, red, or magenta — it will take the dye well, it will be pure in color. Why is that? Because the cloth is clean. So too, bhikkhus, a good destination awaits an undefiled mind.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what are the defilements of the mind? Covetousness and unrighteous greed are defilements of the mind; hatred is a defilement of the mind; anger is a defilement of the mind; resentment is a defilement of the mind; hypocrisy, malice, envy, stinginess, deceit, fraud, obstinacy, impetuosity, conceit, arrogance, vanity, heedlessness are defilements of the mind.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who thinks: 'Covetousness and unrighteous greed are defilements of the mind' and, knowing thus, abandons covetousness and unrighteous greed, the defilements of the mind; thinks: 'Hatred is a defilement of the mind' and, knowing thus, abandons hatred, the defilement of the mind; anger ... resentment ... hypocrisy ... malice, envy, stinginess, deceit, fraud ... obstinacy ... impetuosity ... conceit ... arrogance ... vanity; thinks: 'Heedlessness is a defilement of the mind' and, knowing thus, abandons heedlessness, the defilement of the mind.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `He thinks: 'I have perfect confidence in the Dhamma,' and he attains the meaning of faith, attains the Dhamma of faith, attains gladness connected with the Dhamma; from gladness, rapture arises; from rapture, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he experiences happiness; with happiness, the mind becomes concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `He thinks: 'At this stage, for me, there is giving up, abandoning, liberation, relinquishment, letting go,' and he attains the meaning of faith, attains the Dhamma of faith, attains gladness connected with the Dhamma; from gladness, rapture arises; from rapture, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he experiences happiness; with happiness, the mind becomes concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a dirty, stained cloth, if left in clean water, becomes clean and pure, or if put into a furnace, becomes clean and pure. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu of such virtue, such Dhamma, such wisdom — even if he eats almsfood consisting of choice rice with the black grains removed, with various soups and curries — that does not become an obstacle for him.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `He abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, likewise the second, likewise the third, likewise the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `He understands: 'There is this, there is the inferior, there is the superior, and there is liberation beyond these perceptions.'<br>Knowing thus, seeing thus, his mind is liberated from the taint of sensual desire, his mind is liberated from the taint of existence, his mind is liberated from the taint of ignorance. When liberated, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated. Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further return to this state.' Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has bathed with an inner bathing.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `In the river Bāhukā<br>At Adhikakkā,<br>Even in the river Gayā,<br>Though a fool bathes often,<br>Evil deeds are not washed away.<br>What can the Sundarikā river do?<br>What can Payāga do?<br>What can the Bāhukā river do?<br>They cannot wash away the dark deeds<br>Of a person who has done evil.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `For one who lives pure,<br>Every day is a holy day,<br>For one who lives pure,<br>Every day is a lucky day.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `Those with pure actions,<br>Always accomplish good conduct.<br>O brahmin, you should bathe only here,<br>Causing all beings<br>To live in safety.<br>If you do not speak falsely,<br>If you do not harm beings,<br>Do not take what is not given,<br>Have faith and no greed,<br>What use is Gayā,<br>Gayā is just a well?`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `Wonderful, Master Gotama! Wonderful, Master Gotama! Master Gotama, just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms. So too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by Master Gotama. Now I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha. May I receive the going forth with Master Gotama! May I receive the full ordination!`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7" },

{ text: `Cunda, just as an uneven road has a counterpart even road, Cunda, just as an uneven ford has a counterpart even ford, so too, Cunda: for a person who harms, there is non-harming as a counterpart. For a person who kills living beings, there is abandoning killing as a counterpart. For a person who takes what is not given, there is abandoning taking what is not given as a counterpart ... For a person who is worldly, clings to personal views, and is hard to persuade, there is being non-worldly, not clinging to personal views, and being easy to persuade as a counterpart.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 8 – Sallekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn8" },

{ text: `Cunda, just as all unwholesome states tend downwards, and all wholesome states tend upwards, so too, Cunda: a person who does no harm tends upwards compared to one who harms. A person who abandons killing tends upwards compared to one who kills. A person who abandons taking what is not given tends upwards compared to one who takes what is not given. A person who is non-worldly, does not cling to personal views, and is easy to persuade tends upwards compared to one who is worldly, clings to personal views, and is hard to persuade.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 8 – Sallekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn8" },

{ text: `Cunda, that a person who is himself sunk in mud could pull out another sunk in mud — this is impossible. Cunda, that a person who is not sunk in mud could pull out another sunk in mud — this is possible. Cunda, that a person who is not tamed, not trained, not fully liberated, could tame, train, and fully liberate another — this is impossible. That a person who is tamed, trained, fully liberated, could tame, train, and fully liberate another — this is possible.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 8 – Sallekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn8" },

{ text: `Cunda, whatever should be done by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, wishing their welfare, that I have done for you out of compassion. Cunda, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Cunda, practice jhāna, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 8 – Sallekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn8" },

{ text: `Friends, what is unwholesome, what is the root of unwholesome, what is wholesome, what is the root of wholesome? Friends, killing living beings is unwholesome, taking what is not given is unwholesome, sexual misconduct is unwholesome, false speech is unwholesome, divisive speech is unwholesome, harsh speech is unwholesome, idle chatter is unwholesome, covetousness is unwholesome, ill-will is unwholesome, wrong view is unwholesome. Friends, this is called unwholesome.<br>And, friends, what is the root of unwholesome? Greed is a root of unwholesome, hatred is a root of unwholesome, delusion is a root of unwholesome. Friends, this is called the root of unwholesome.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `And, friends, what is wholesome? Abandoning killing living beings is wholesome, abandoning taking what is not given is wholesome, abandoning sexual misconduct is wholesome, abandoning false speech is wholesome, abandoning divisive speech is wholesome, abandoning harsh speech is wholesome, abandoning idle chatter is wholesome, non-covetousness is wholesome, non-ill-will is wholesome, right view is wholesome. Friends, this is called wholesome.<br>Friends, what is the root of wholesome? Non-greed is a root of wholesome, non-hatred is a root of wholesome, non-delusion is a root of wholesome. Friends, this is called the root of wholesome.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Friends, when a noble disciple understands unwholesome, understands wholesome, understands the root of wholesome, then he abandons all underlying tendencies to greed, removes the underlying tendency to hatred, uproots the underlying tendency to the conceit 'I am', abandons ignorance, causes knowledge to arise, and makes an end of suffering here and now. Friends, thus a noble disciple has right view, straight view, perfect confidence in the Dhamma, and has attained this excellent Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Friends, what is nutriment, what is the arising of nutriment, what is the cessation of nutriment, what is the path leading to the cessation of nutriment? Friends, there are these four kinds of nutriment for the maintenance of beings that have already been born or for the support of those about to be born. What are the four? Physical food, coarse or fine; contact is the second; mental volition is the third; consciousness is the fourth. From the arising of craving comes the arising of nutriment; from the cessation of craving comes the cessation of nutriment. This Noble Eightfold Path is the path leading to the cessation of nutriment, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Friends, when a noble disciple understands suffering, understands the origin of suffering, understands the cessation of suffering, understands the path leading to the cessation of suffering — then, friends, that noble disciple has right view, straight view, perfect confidence in the Dhamma, and has attained this excellent Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Friends, what is suffering? Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, sickness is suffering, death is suffering, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are suffering, not getting what one wants is suffering; in short, the five aggregates of clinging are suffering. Friends, this is called suffering. Friends, what is the origin of suffering? It is craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, seeking delight here and there; that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. Friends, this is called the origin of suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Friends, what is the cessation of suffering? It is the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, its abandonment, relinquishment, liberation, and non-attachment. Friends, what is the path leading to the cessation of suffering? It is just this Noble Eightfold Path leading to the cessation of suffering, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, let alone half a month, if anyone would develop these Four Foundations of Mindfulness for seven days, he could expect one of two fruits: either final knowledge here and now, or if there is a residue of clinging, the state of non-returning. Bhikkhus, this is the one and only path leading to the purification of beings, to overcoming sorrow and lamentation, to the extinguishing of pain and grief, to the attainment of right knowledge, to the realization of Nibbāna. That is the Four Foundations of Mindfulness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 10 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn10" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, such is my seclusion. Sāriputta, mindfully I go forward, mindfully I go backward; I abide with loving-kindness even toward a drop of water, thinking: 'May I not harm even a tiny living creature in their evil destinies!' Sāriputta, such is my seclusion.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 12 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn12" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, then, on cold winter nights, between the eighths, when snow falls, on such nights I would dwell in the open air, and by day in the dense forest. In the last month of summer, I would dwell in the open air by day, and at night in the dense forest. Then, Sāriputta, these wonderful verses, unheard before, arose to me:<br><br>Now scorched, now frozen,<br>Alone, dwelling in the terrifying forest,<br>Naked, sitting without a warm fire,<br>The ascetic, pursuing his ideal.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 12 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn12" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, one speaking rightly would say: 'A being not overcome by delusion, born in the world for the benefit and happiness of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.' That one, speaking rightly, would say of me: 'A being not overcome by delusion, born in the world for the benefit and happiness of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 12 – Mahāsīhanādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn12" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as reason, with sensual desire itself as cause, kings contend with kings, nobles contend with nobles, brahmins contend with brahmins, householders contend with householders, mother contends with child, child contends with mother, father contends with child, child contends with father, brother contends with brother, brother contends with sister, sister contends with brother, friend contends with friend. When they have fallen into disputes, quarrels, and contention, they attack one another with fists, with stones, with sticks, with swords. There they meet death or deadly pain. Bhikkhus, such is the danger of sensual desires, a mass of suffering visible here and now, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as source, with sensual desire as reason.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as reason, with sensual desire itself as cause, they take up spears and shields, they don bows and arrows, they draw up battle lines on both sides, and arrows fly, and swords flash. They are pierced by arrows, slashed by swords, and their heads are cut off. There they meet death or deadly pain. Bhikkhus, such is the danger of sensual desires, a mass of suffering visible here and now, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as source, with sensual desire as reason.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as reason, with sensual desire itself as cause, they take up spears and shields, they don bows and arrows, they attack fortified citadels newly plastered with lime, and arrows fly, and swords flash. They are pierced by arrows, slashed by swords, drenched with boiling excrement, crushed with stones, and their heads are cut off. There they meet death or deadly pain. Bhikkhus, such is the danger of sensual desires, a mass of suffering visible here and now, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as source, with sensual desire as reason.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as reason, with sensual desire itself as cause, they engage in misconduct of body, misconduct of speech, misconduct of mind. Having engaged in misconduct of body, speech, and mind, after death, with the breakup of the body, they are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, such is the danger of sensual desires, bringing suffering in the future, a mass of suffering, with sensual desire as cause, with sensual desire as condition, with sensual desire as source, with sensual desire as reason.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, such is the danger in forms. Furthermore, bhikkhus, one sees that same woman's body thrown into the charnel ground, for one, two, or three days, bloated, discolored, festering. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared?<br>- Yes, Venerable Sir.<br>- Bhikkhus, such is the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, such is the danger in forms. Furthermore, bhikkhus, one sees that same woman's body thrown into the charnel ground, just a skeleton white like a conch shell ... just a heap of bones more than a year old ... just rotten bones reduced to powder. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Has her former beauty disappeared and danger appeared?<br>- Yes, Venerable Sir.<br>- Bhikkhus, such is the danger in forms.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the danger in feelings? Bhikkhus, feelings are impermanent, suffering, subject to change — that is the danger in feelings. And, bhikkhus, what is the escape from feelings? Bhikkhus, the removal of desire and lust for feelings, the abandoning of desire and lust — that is the escape from feelings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13" },

{ text: `Mahānāma, in the past, when I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet enlightened, not yet a Perfectly Enlightened One, I saw clearly with correct wisdom as it actually is: 'Sensual pleasures provide little gratification, much suffering, much despair, and the danger here is even greater.' Yet, although I saw clearly with correct wisdom as it actually is, I had not yet attained the rapture and happiness born of seclusion from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states, or something more sublime. And thus I knew that I was not yet free from the influence of sensual pleasures. And, Mahānāma, only when I saw clearly with correct wisdom as it actually is: 'Sensual pleasures provide little gratification, much suffering, much despair, and the danger here is even greater,' and I attained the rapture and happiness born of seclusion from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states, or something more sublime — then I knew that I was free from the influence of sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 14 – Cūḷadukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn14" },

{ text: `And, Mahānāma, what is the gratification of sensual pleasures? Mahānāma, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure: forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... flavors cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. Mahānāma, these are the five strands of sensual pleasure. Mahānāma, the pleasure and joy that arise dependent on these five strands of sensual pleasure — that is the gratification of sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 14 – Cūḷadukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn14" },

{ text: `Nigaṇṭha friends, I can remain without moving my body, without speaking a word, experiencing only pleasant feeling for an entire day and night. Nigaṇṭha friends, I can remain without moving my body, without speaking a word, experiencing only pleasant feeling for two days and two nights, for three days and three nights, for four days and four nights, for five days and five nights, for six days and six nights, for seven days and seven nights. Nigaṇṭha friends, what do you think? That being so, who lives more happily — King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha, or me?`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 14 – Cūḷadukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn14" },

{ text: `Friends, if a bhikkhu requests: 'May the venerable ones speak to me, may I be spoken to by the venerable ones!' But if he is difficult to speak to, possessing qualities that make him difficult to speak to, hard to endure, not respectfully accepting instruction — then his fellow celibates think that bhikkhu is not worth speaking to, think that bhikkhu is not worth instructing, think that one should not place confidence in him.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 15 – Anumānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn15" },

{ text: `Friends, here a bhikkhu should examine himself with himself thus:<br>'Do I have evil desires, am I dominated by evil desires?' Friends, if a bhikkhu, on examination, knows: 'I have evil desires and am dominated by evil desires,' then, friends, that bhikkhu should strive to abandon those evil, unwholesome states. Friends, if a bhikkhu, on examination, knows: 'I do not have evil desires and am not dominated by evil desires,' then, friends, that bhikkhu should dwell with a joyful mind, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 15 – Anumānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn15" },

{ text: `Friends, if, on examination, a bhikkhu sees clearly that all evil, unwholesome states have not been abandoned within him, then, friends, that bhikkhu should strive to abandon those evil, unwholesome states. Friends, if, on examination, a bhikkhu sees clearly that all evil, unwholesome states have been abandoned within him, then, friends, that bhikkhu should dwell with a joyful mind, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 15 – Anumānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn15" },

{ text: `Friends, just as a young woman or man, youthful, fond of adornment, would examine their own face in a clean, bright mirror or in a bowl of clear water. If they see dust or a blemish on their face, they strive to remove that dust or blemish. If they do not see dust or a blemish on their face, they are joyful, thinking: 'I have gained a good thing; I am pure indeed.' So too, friends, if on examination a bhikkhu sees clearly that all evil, unwholesome states have not been abandoned within him, then, friends, that bhikkhu should strive to abandon those evil, unwholesome states. Friends, if on examination a bhikkhu sees clearly that all evil, unwholesome states have been abandoned within him, then, friends, that bhikkhu should dwell with a joyful mind, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 15 – Anumānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn15" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who has not abandoned five wildernesses of the heart and has not cut off five shackles of the heart can grow, develop, and prosper in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is impossible.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },
{ text: `What are the five wildernesses of the heart that have not been abandoned? Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu is doubtful about the Teacher, hesitant, undecided, without confidence. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu is doubtful about the Teacher, hesitant, undecided, without confidence, his mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving. When one's mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving, that is the first wilderness of the heart that has not been abandoned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is angry with his fellow celibates, displeased, resentful, and stubborn. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu is angry with his fellow celibates, displeased, resentful, and stubborn, his mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving. When one's mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving, that is the fifth wilderness of the heart that has not been abandoned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `What are the five shackles of the heart that have not been cut off? Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu is not free from lust, desire, affection, thirst, fever, and craving for sensual pleasures. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu is not free from lust ... craving for sensual pleasures, his mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving. When one's mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving, that is the first shackle of the heart that has not been cut off.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu eats until his belly is full, and indulges in the pleasure of lying down, the pleasure of sleeping, the pleasure of sloth. His mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving. When one's mind does not incline towards effort, application, perseverance, and striving, that is the fourth shackle of the heart that has not been cut off.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `He develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to desire and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to energy and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to mind and the effort of striving; he develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to investigation and the effort of striving; with striving as the fifth. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who possesses these fifteen factors including striving is capable of breaking through, capable of enlightenment, capable of attaining the supreme security from bondage.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as there are eight, ten, or twelve hen's eggs that are properly covered, sat upon, incubated, and warmed by the hen — even if the hen does not wish: 'May my chicks pierce the eggshells with their sharp claws or beaks and emerge safely!' — yet those chicks are capable of piercing the eggshells with their sharp claws or beaks and emerging safely. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who possesses these fifteen factors including striving is capable of breaking through, capable of enlightenment, capable of attaining the supreme security from bondage.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16" },

{ text: `'Friend, according to my teaching, in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its samaṇas and brahmins, with its devas and humans, there is no quarrel with anyone in the world; perceptions will not obsess the brahmin who dwells free from the bondage of sensual pleasures, free from doubt and hesitation, with all remorse abandoned, without craving for existence or non-existence. Friend, such is my view, such is my teaching.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 18 – Madhupiṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn18" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, due to whatever condition, a number of conceptual proliferations obsess a person. If there is nothing here to be delighted in, welcomed, or clung to, then that is the end of the underlying tendency to greed, the end of the underlying tendency to hatred, the end of the underlying tendency to views, the end of the underlying tendency to doubt, the end of the underlying tendency to conceit, the end of the underlying tendency to craving for existence, the end of the underlying tendency to ignorance, the end of taking up sticks and swords, quarrels, disputes, arguments, strife, divisive speech, and false speech. Right here, these evil, unwholesome states cease without remainder.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 18 – Madhupiṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn18" },

{ text: `Friends, dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. What one feels, one perceives. What one perceives, one thinks about. What one thinks about, one proliferates. Due to that proliferation, a number of conceptual proliferations obsess a person regarding forms cognizable by the eye, past, future, and present.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 18 – Madhupiṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn18" },

{ text: `Friends, dependent on the ear and sounds, ear-consciousness arises ... dependent on the nose and odors, nose-consciousness arises ... dependent on the tongue and flavors, tongue-consciousness arises ... dependent on the body and tangibles, body-consciousness arises; dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. What one feels, one perceives. What one perceives, one thinks about. What one thinks about, one proliferates. Due to that proliferation, a number of conceptual proliferations obsess a person regarding mind-objects cognizable by the mind, past, future, and present.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 18 – Madhupiṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn18" },

{ text: `Friends, this situation occurs: when there is the eye, when there are forms, when there is eye-consciousness, then the designation of contact is manifest. This situation occurs: when there is the designation of contact, then the designation of feeling is manifest. This situation occurs: when there is the designation of feeling, then the designation of perception is manifest. This situation occurs: when there is the designation of perception, then the designation of thought is manifest. This situation occurs: when there is the designation of thought, then the designation of being obsessed by a number of conceptual proliferations is manifest.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 18 – Madhupiṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn18" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I thought: 'I live assailed by thoughts, dividing thoughts into two categories.' Whatever thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, or thoughts of harmfulness arose, I placed them in one category. Whatever thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, or thoughts of harmlessness arose, I placed them in the second category.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then I dwelt heedful, ardent, and resolute. When a thought of sensual desire arose, I understood: 'This thought of sensual desire has arisen in me, and it leads to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both, it destroys wisdom, is associated with distress, and does not lead to Nibbāna.' Bhikkhus, when I reflected: 'This thought of sensual desire leads to my own harm,' it subsided. When I reflected: 'It leads to others' harm,' it subsided. When I reflected: 'It leads to the harm of both,' it subsided. When I reflected: 'It destroys wisdom, is associated with distress, and does not lead to Nibbāna,' it subsided. Bhikkhus, thus I continued to abandon, relinquish, and cut off thoughts of sensual desire.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, whatever a bhikkhu frequently thinks about and ponders upon, that becomes the inclination of his mind. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu frequently thinks about and ponders upon thoughts of sensual desire, he has abandoned thoughts of renunciation. When his mind inclines towards thoughts of sensual desire, then his mind has the inclination towards thoughts of sensual desire. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu frequently thinks about and ponders upon thoughts of ill-will ... thoughts of harmfulness, he has abandoned thoughts of harmlessness. When his mind inclines towards thoughts of harmfulness, then his mind has the inclination towards thoughts of harmfulness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as at the end of the rainy season, in the autumn, when the crops are ripening, a cowherd, tending the cows, would strike the cows on this side and that with his stick, checking them and restraining them. Why is that? Because the cowherd sees that due to this he might incur death, imprisonment, beating, or blame. So too, bhikkhus, I saw the danger, the degradation, and the defilement of unwholesome states, and I saw the seclusion, the benefit, and the purification of wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, while I dwelt heedful, ardent, and resolute, when a thought of renunciation arose, I understood: 'This thought of renunciation has arisen in me, and it does not lead to my own harm, nor to others' harm, nor to the harm of both, it increases wisdom, is not associated with distress, and leads to Nibbāna.' Bhikkhus, if I reflected and pondered upon it at night, I saw no danger from that cause. If I reflected and pondered upon it by day, I saw no danger from that cause. If I reflected and pondered upon it night and day, I saw no danger from that cause. But if I reflected and pondered upon it for too long, my body would become fatigued; when the body is fatigued, the mind becomes agitated; when the mind is agitated, it is far from concentration. Bhikkhus, I then internally steadied my mind, settled it, unified it, and concentrated it. Why is that? So that my mind would not be agitated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as at the end of the summer, when all the grain has been gathered into the barn, a cowherd, tending the cows, sitting at the root of a tree or in the open, might think about what needs to be done, and thinks: 'These are the cows.' So too, bhikkhus, there was what needed to be done, and I thought: 'These are the states.'<br>Bhikkhus, I exerted myself, was energetic, not passive, mindfulness was established without confusion, my body was tranquil, without agitation, my mind was concentrated and unified.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, I entered and abided in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. With the stilling of initial and sustained thought, I entered and abided in the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... I entered and abided in the fourth jhāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as in a dense forest there is a large, deep lake, and a large herd of deer lives near one side. A man comes who does not want their good, their welfare, their security from bondage. He closes the safe, secure, pleasant path, opens a dangerous path, sets out a male decoy, and sets out a female decoy. After a time, that large herd of deer falls into ruin and destruction. Another man comes who wants their good, their welfare, their security from bondage. He opens the safe, secure path, closes the dangerous path, removes the male decoy, and destroys the female decoy. After a time, that large herd of deer increases, grows, and develops.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the large, deep lake refers to sensual pleasures. Bhikkhus, the large herd of deer refers to beings. Bhikkhus, the man who does not want their good, welfare, and security from bondage refers to Māra the Evil One. Bhikkhus, the dangerous path refers to the wrong eightfold path, namely: wrong view, wrong intention, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration. Bhikkhus, the male decoy refers to rapture and greed. Bhikkhus, the female decoy refers to ignorance. Bhikkhus, the man who wants their good, welfare, and security from bondage refers to the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. The safe, secure, pleasant path refers to the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, thus I have opened the safe, secure, pleasant path, I have closed the dangerous path, I have removed the male decoy, I have destroyed the female decoy. Bhikkhus, whatever should be done by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, that I have done for you out of compassion. Bhikkhus, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Practice jhāna, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a skilled carpenter or his apprentice uses a small peg to knock out, drive out, and remove a larger peg; so too, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu, by attending to a certain sign, gives rise to evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion, then that bhikkhu should attend to another sign connected with what is wholesome, different from that sign. By attending to another sign connected with what is wholesome, those evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion are abandoned and subside. Through their abandonment, his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if while attending to another sign connected with what is wholesome, evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion still arise in that bhikkhu, then that bhikkhu should examine the danger in those thoughts: 'These thoughts are unwholesome, these thoughts are blameworthy, these thoughts lead to painful results.' By examining the danger in those thoughts, those evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion are abandoned and subside. Through their abandonment, his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a young woman or man, fond of adornment, would be horrified, ashamed, and disgusted if the carcass of a snake, a dog, or a human were hung around their neck; so too, bhikkhus, if that bhikkhu examines the danger in those thoughts ... his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if while examining the danger in those thoughts, evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion still arise in that bhikkhu, then that bhikkhu should not attend to or give attention to those thoughts. By not attending to or giving attention to those thoughts, those evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion are abandoned and subside. Through their abandonment, his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated. Bhikkhus, just as a person with eyes, not wishing to see forms within their range, would close their eyes or look away; so too, bhikkhus, if that bhikkhu does not attend to or give attention to those thoughts ... his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu, by attending to a certain sign, gives rise to evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion; then he attends to another sign connected with what is wholesome, different from that sign, and those evil, unwholesome thoughts are abandoned and subside. Through their abandonment, his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20" },

{ text: `Phagguna, you should train thus: 'May my mind not become defiled! May I not utter harsh speech! May I dwell compassionate, with a mind of loving-kindness, without inner hatred!' Phagguna, you should train thus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I practice one-session eating. Bhikkhus, while practicing one-session eating, I feel free from disease, free from illness, lightness, strength, and comfort. Bhikkhus, you too should practice one-session eating. Bhikkhus, while practicing one-session eating, you will feel free from disease, free from illness, lightness, strength, and comfort.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, once my bhikkhus had minds very ripe and joyful. Bhikkhus, I had no need to instruct those bhikkhus; I merely needed to arouse mindfulness in them. Bhikkhus, just as on level ground at a crossroads, there is a chariot standing, yoked with thoroughbred horses, with a goad set ready. A skilled charioteer, a trainer of horses to be trained, mounts the chariot, takes the reins in his left hand and the goad in his right, and can drive the chariot back and forth wherever and however he wishes. So too, bhikkhus, I had no need to instruct those bhikkhus; I merely needed to arouse mindfulness in them.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Therefore, bhikkhus, abandon unwholesome states and strive for wholesome states. Thus you will achieve growth, prosperity, and increase in this Dhamma and Discipline. Bhikkhus, just as near a village or town there is a great grove of tala trees, overgrown with castor-oil plants. A man comes who wants the grove's good, welfare, and security from bondage. He cuts down the crooked, withered branches and throws them out, cleans up the grove, and tends the straight, well-grown tala branches. After a time, that grove grows, prospers, and increases. So too, bhikkhus, abandon unwholesome states and strive for wholesome states. Thus you will achieve growth, prosperity, and increase in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu is extremely gentle, extremely pliant, extremely mild when not spoken to with disagreeable, hurtful words. But, bhikkhus, only when a bhikkhu is spoken to with disagreeable, hurtful words and yet remains extremely gentle, extremely pliant, extremely mild — then he is considered gentle, pliant, mild. Bhikkhus, I do not call a bhikkhu easy to speak to because he is easy to speak to regarding robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicines, and because he acquires an easy manner. Why is that? Because if that bhikkhu does not get those requisites, he is no longer easy to speak to, he does not acquire an easy manner. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who respects the Dhamma, honors the Dhamma, reveres the Dhamma, and thus becomes easy to speak to and acquires an easy manner — him I call easy to speak to. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Respecting the Dhamma, honoring the Dhamma, revering the Dhamma, we will become easy to speak to and acquire an easy manner.' Bhikkhus, you should train thus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are five ways of speaking that others may use when addressing you: timely or untimely, true or false, gentle or harsh, beneficial or unbeneficial, with a mind of loving-kindness or with a mind of hatred. Bhikkhus, when others address you, they may speak timely or untimely. They may speak truly or falsely. They may speak gently or harshly. They may speak beneficially or unbeneficially. They may speak with a mind of loving-kindness or with a mind of hatred.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here you should train thus: 'We will keep our minds undefiled, we will not utter harsh speech, we will dwell compassionate, with a mind of loving-kindness, without inner hatred. We will dwell pervading that person with a mind imbued with loving-kindness. And with that person as a basis, we will dwell pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will.' Bhikkhus, you should train thus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, even if low-down bandits were to saw your limbs one by one with a two-handled saw, yet if anyone among you defiled his mind, that person would not be following my teaching. Here, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will keep our minds undefiled, we will not utter harsh speech, we will dwell compassionate, with a mind of loving-kindness, without inner hatred. We will dwell pervading that person with a mind imbued with loving-kindness. And with that person as a basis, we will dwell pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will.' Bhikkhus, you should train thus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21" },

{ text: `Indeed, bhikkhus, this situation does not occur: one could enjoy sensual pleasures apart from sensual pleasures, apart from perceptions of sensual pleasure, apart from thoughts of sensual pleasure.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here some foolish people learn the Dhamma: discourses, mixed prose and verse, explanations, verses, inspired utterances, quotations, birth stories, marvelous accounts, and questions-and-answers. Having learned the Dhamma, they do not examine the meaning of those teachings with wisdom. Not examining the meaning with wisdom, they do not gain a reflective acceptance of them. They learn the Dhamma only for the sake of criticizing others and for the sake of winning in debates, and they do not experience the purpose for which they learned the Dhamma. Those teachings, being wrongly grasped, lead to their long-term harm and suffering. Why is that? Because of wrong grasp of the teachings.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a person who wants a water-snake, looking for a water-snake, searching here and there, sees a large water-snake and grasps it by the coils or the tail. That snake might turn back and bite his hand, his arm, or some other part of his body, and from that cause he might die or suffer deadly pain. Why is that? Because of wrong grasp of the snake. So too, bhikkhus, here some foolish people learn the Dhamma ... they learn the Dhamma only for the sake of criticizing others and for the sake of winning in debates, and they do not experience the purpose for which they learned the Dhamma. Those teachings, being wrongly grasped, lead to their long-term harm and suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, here some good men learn the Dhamma ... bhikkhus, because of right grasp of the teachings. Therefore, bhikkhus, understand the meaning of what I have taught and grasp it accordingly. If anyone does not understand the meaning of what I have taught, they should ask me or ask those bhikkhus who are wise.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I will teach you the Dhamma compared to a raft, for the purpose of crossing over, not for the purpose of grasping. Here, bhikkhus, that person, having crossed over to the far shore, might think: 'This raft has been very helpful to me. With its help, having striven with hands and feet, I have safely crossed to the far shore. Now, let me pull this raft up onto dry land or let it sink in the water, and go wherever I wish.' Bhikkhus, by doing so, that person would use the raft properly. So too, bhikkhus, I have taught the Dhamma compared to a raft, for crossing over, not for grasping. Bhikkhus, you should understand the simile of the raft. Even the Dhamma should be abandoned, how much more so what is not the Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple, who has seen the noble ones, is skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who has seen the true persons, is skilled in the teaching of the true persons, trained in the teaching of the true persons — he regards form: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' He regards feeling: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' He regards perception: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' He regards formations: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' He regards whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, and reflected upon by the mind: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' And whatever views placeholders say: 'This is the world, this is my self; after death I will be permanent, everlasting, eternal, unchanging, and I will abide like that forever' — he regards that too: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Thus regarding, he is not anxious or troubled about what does not actually exist.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a person thinks: 'What certainly was mine is now certainly not mine. What certainly could be mine, I certainly do not get that.' He sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes confused. Bhikkhus, thus there is anxiety and distress over what does not actually exist externally.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, could you grasp any possession that would be permanent, everlasting, eternal, unchanging, and abide like that forever? — No, Venerable Sir. — Good, bhikkhus. I too do not see any possession ... that would abide like that forever.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, some samaṇas and brahmins misrepresent me falsely, groundlessly, vainly, untruthfully, saying: 'Samaṇa Gotama is a nihilist, he teaches annihilation, destruction, the nonexistence of beings.' But I am not like that, I do not say that. Bhikkhus, both formerly and now, I only teach suffering and the cessation of suffering. Bhikkhus, if others revile, abuse, and anger the Tathāgata, then, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata has no hatred, no bitterness, no displeasure. Bhikkhus, if others honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Tathāgata, then, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata has no joy, no delight, no pleasure. Bhikkhus, if others honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Tathāgata, then, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata thinks: 'This is something that was already known before; here is a task I must do.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if others revile, abuse, and anger you, you should not have hatred, bitterness, or displeasure. Therefore, bhikkhus, if others honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to you, you should not have joy, delight, or pleasure. Therefore, bhikkhus, if others honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to you, you should think: 'This is something that was already known before; here is a task I must do.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Bhikkhus, what is not yours? Form is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning form will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Feeling is not yours, abandon it ... Perception is not yours, abandon it ... Formations are not yours, abandon them ... Consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning consciousness will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what do you think? If people were to gather grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jeta's Grove and burn them or do whatever they wish, would you think: 'They are gathering us, burning us, doing whatever they wish'? — No, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because that is not our self nor what belongs to our self. — So too, bhikkhus, what is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. And what is not yours? Form is not yours, abandon it ... Feeling ... Perception ... Formations ... Consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning consciousness will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Dhamma has been well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, and stripped of its old wrappings. Because the Dhamma has been well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, and stripped of its old wrappings, for those bhikkhus who are Arahants, with taints destroyed, who have lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge — the cycle of rebirth cannot be traced for them.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the Dhamma has been well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, and stripped of its old wrappings. Because the Dhamma has been well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, and stripped of its old wrappings, even those who have merely faith in me, mere affection for me, all of them are bound for heaven.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is good that you, having gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, should meet together to discuss the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, when you meet together, there are two things to be done: either discussion of the Dhamma or noble silence.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of seeking: the noble seeking and the ignoble seeking. And what is the ignoble seeking? Here, bhikkhus, a person, being subject to birth himself, seeks what is also subject to birth; being subject to aging, he seeks what is also subject to aging; being subject to sickness ... death ... sorrow ... defilement, he seeks what is also subject to defilement. And what, bhikkhus, do you call subject to birth? Bhikkhus, wives and children are subject to birth; male and female slaves are subject to birth; goats and sheep are subject to birth; fowl and pigs are subject to birth; elephants, cattle, horses, and mares are subject to birth; gold and silver are subject to birth. Bhikkhus, these attachments are subject to birth, and a person who is himself subject to birth, clinging to them, infatuated with them, consumed by them, seeks what is subject to birth.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `And what, bhikkhus, do you call subject to sorrow? Bhikkhus, wives and children are subject to sorrow; male and female slaves ... goats and sheep ... fowl and pigs ... elephants, cattle, horses, and mares are subject to sorrow. Bhikkhus, these attachments are subject to sorrow, and a person who is himself subject to sorrow, clinging to them, infatuated with them, consumed by them, seeks what is subject to sorrow.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `And what, bhikkhus, is the noble seeking? Here, bhikkhus, a person, being subject to birth himself, having understood the danger in what is subject to birth, seeks the unborn, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna. Being subject to aging, having understood the danger in what is subject to aging, he seeks the unaging ... being subject to sickness ... the unsick ... being subject to death ... the deathless ... being subject to sorrow ... the sorrowless ... being subject to defilement, having understood the danger in what is subject to defilement, he seeks the undefiled, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna. Bhikkhus, this is called the noble seeking.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I too, before my enlightenment, while still a Bodhisatta, being subject to birth, sought what is subject to birth; being subject to aging ... sickness ... death ... sorrow ... defilement, sought what is subject to defilement. Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'Why am I, being subject to birth, seeking what is subject to birth? Being subject to aging ... sickness ... death ... sorrow ... defilement, why do I seek what is subject to defilement? Let me, being subject to birth, having understood the danger in what is subject to birth, seek the unborn, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna. Being subject to aging ... the unaging ... being subject to sickness ... the unsick ... being subject to death ... the deathless ... being subject to sorrow ... the sorrowless ... being subject to defilement, having understood the danger in what is subject to defilement, seek the undefiled, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Then, bhikkhus, after some time, while still young, a black-haired youth endowed with the blessing of youth in the prime of life, though my parents wished otherwise, weeping with tearful faces, I shaved off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and went forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, Alāra Kālāma, who was my teacher, placed me, his disciple, on the same level as himself and honored me with supreme honor. Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'This Dhamma does not lead to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbāna, but only to the attainment of the base of nothingness.' Thus, bhikkhus, I did not honor that Dhamma, and having left it, I departed.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, seeking what is wholesome, seeking the supreme, unsurpassed path of peace, I wandered by stages in the country of Magadha and arrived at the village of Uruvelā. There I saw a delightful place, a pleasant grove, a clear flowing river with a lovely ford, and a village nearby for alms. Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'Truly, this is a delightful place, a pleasant grove, a clear flowing river with a lovely ford, and a village nearby for alms. This is suitable for a good man who wishes to strive.' And, bhikkhus, I sat down there, thinking: 'This is suitable for striving.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then I thought: 'This Dhamma I have realized is deep, hard to see, hard to realize, peaceful, sublime, beyond reasoning, subtle, to be understood by the wise. But this generation delights in sensual pleasures, is excited by sensual pleasures, enjoys sensual pleasures. For a generation that delights in sensual pleasures, is excited by sensual pleasures, enjoys sensual pleasures, it is hard to see this principle of conditionality, this dependent origination. It is also hard to see the stilling of all formations, the abandoning of all basis for existence, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `'Why should I now declare what I have realized with such difficulty?<br>Those overcome by greed and hatred cannot understand this Dhamma.<br><br>It goes against the stream, subtle, deep, hard to see, and fine,<br>Those stained by craving and shrouded by ignorance do not see this Dhamma.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `'Formerly in Magadha, the Dhamma of impurity appeared,<br>Conceived by defiled minds, wrought by thought.<br>Open wide the doors of the Deathless!<br>Let them hear the Dhamma realized by the Stainless One.<br><br>As a person standing on a mountain peak<br>Looks down upon the people all around,<br>So, O all-seeing One, gone up to the Dhamma palace,<br>Free from sorrow, look down upon the people,<br>Oppressed by sorrow, overwhelmed by birth and aging.<br><br>Arise, O hero! Victor in battle!<br>O caravan leader, free from debt!<br>Wander the world, O Blessed One, teaching the Dhamma!<br>There will be those who understand!'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, having heard the request of Brahmā, out of compassion for beings, I surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye. With the Buddha-eye, I saw beings with little dust in their eyes, with much dust in their eyes, with keen faculties, with dull faculties, with good qualities, with bad qualities, easy to teach, hard to teach, and some who saw the danger in future rebirth and in faulty actions. Just as in a pond of blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses, some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, do not rise above the water, thrive while submerged; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, live reaching the water's surface; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, rise above the water and stand without being wetted by the water.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `The door to the Deathless is open,<br>For those who are willing to hear.<br>Renounce your inaccurate faith.<br>Thinking of the trouble,<br>I did not want to teach<br>The supreme sublime Dhamma<br>Among humans.<br>(O Brahmā)`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, then I thought: 'To whom shall I teach the Dhamma first? Who will quickly understand this Dhamma?' Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'Now Alāra Kālāma is wise, learned, intelligent, and for a long time has had little dust in his eyes. Let me teach the Dhamma first to Alāra Kālāma; he will quickly understand this Dhamma.' Then, bhikkhus, devas came to me and said: 'Venerable Sir, Alāra Kālāma passed away seven days ago.' And knowledge and vision arose in me: 'Alāra Kālāma has passed away seven days ago.' Bhikkhus, I thought: 'Great indeed is the loss for Alāra Kālāma! If he had heard this Dhamma, he would have quickly understood it.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata is the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Lend ear, the Deathless has been attained; I teach, I show the Dhamma. Living in accordance with the instruction, before long, having known for yourselves, realized for yourselves, attained for yourselves here and now, you will abide in the supreme goal of the holy life for the sake of which good men go forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are five strands of sensual pleasure. What are the five? Forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, stimulating sensual desire, enticing. Sounds cognizable by the ear ... (as above) ... odors cognizable by the nose ... flavors cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, stimulating sensual desire, enticing. Bhikkhus, these are the five strands of sensual pleasure.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, any samaṇas or brahmins who are bound, infatuated, and obsessed with these five strands of sensual pleasure, not seeing the danger in them, not knowing the escape from them, and enjoy them — these should be understood as: 'They have fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and are being used by Māra as he wishes.' Bhikkhus, just as a forest deer that has fallen into a trap lies down — that deer should be understood as: 'It has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is being used by the hunter as he wishes. When the hunter comes, the deer cannot leave as it wishes.' So too, bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who are bound ... are being used by Māra as he wishes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, any samaṇas or brahmins who are not bound, not infatuated, not obsessed with these five strands of sensual pleasure, see the danger in them, know the escape from them, and enjoy them — these should be understood as: 'They have not fallen into misfortune, not into calamity, and are not being used by Māra as he wishes.' Bhikkhus, just as a forest deer that has not fallen into a trap lies down — that deer should be understood as: 'It has not fallen into misfortune, not into calamity, and is not being used by the hunter as he wishes. When the hunter comes, the deer can leave as it wishes.' So too, bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who are not bound ... are not being used by Māra as he wishes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a forest deer, walking in the forest, walks with assurance, stands with assurance, sits with assurance, lies down with assurance. Why is that? Because it has escaped the reach of the hunter. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has blinded Māra, destroyed his tracks, and escaped the sight of Māra.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Having seen with wisdom, the taints are abandoned. Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has blinded Māra, destroyed his tracks, and escaped the sight of Māra. He has escaped all bondage in the world. He walks with assurance, stands with assurance, sits with assurance, lies down with assurance. Why is that? Because he has escaped the reach of Māra.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26" },

{ text: `Friends, if others should treat a bhikkhu who is not perfect, not good, not pleasant, by touching him with hands, with stones, with sticks, or with swords, he understands thus: 'Such is the nature of this body that hands can touch it, stones can touch it, sticks can touch it, swords can touch it. The Blessed One has said in the simile of the saw: "Bhikkhus, even if low-down bandits were to saw your limbs one by one with a two-handled saw, yet if anyone among you defiled his mind, that person would not be following my teaching." I will be energetic and diligent, not lazy. Mindfulness is established without confusion, my body is tranquil, not agitated, my mind is concentrated and unified. Now let hands touch this body, let stones touch this body, let sticks touch this body, let swords touch this body — the teaching of the Buddhas must be practiced.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 28 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn28" },

{ text: `Friends, if others should revile, criticize, provoke, and trouble a bhikkhu, he knows clearly: 'This painful feeling arisen in me is ear-contact; this feeling is conditioned, not unconditioned. Conditioned by what? Conditioned by contact.' He sees contact as impermanent; he sees feeling as impermanent; he sees perception as impermanent; he sees formations as impermanent; he sees consciousness as impermanent. His mind becomes joyful, pleased, settled, decided, based on the object.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 28 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn28" },

{ text: `The Blessed One has said: 'One who sees dependent origination sees the Dhamma; one who sees the Dhamma sees dependent origination.' These phenomena that arise through conditions are precisely the five aggregates of clinging. The desire, attachment, infatuation, and obsession in these five aggregates of clinging is the origin of suffering; the removal of desire, the abandonment of desire for these five aggregates of clinging is the cessation of suffering.' To this extent, friends, a bhikkhu has done much.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 28 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn28" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a good man, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness: 'I am immersed in birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, immersed in suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, he gains gains, honor, and fame. Because of these gains, honor, and fame, he becomes joyful and satisfied. Because of these gains, honor, and fame, he praises himself and disparages others: 'I have such gains, such fame; these other bhikkhus are unknown and of little influence.' Being infatuated, attached, and heedless because of these gains, honor, and fame, and dwelling heedlessly, he experiences suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 29 – Mahāsāropamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn29" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, this holy life is not for the sake of gain, honor, and fame; not for the sake of the benefit of virtue; not for the sake of the benefit of concentration; not for the sake of the benefit of knowledge and vision. And, bhikkhus, unshakable liberation of mind is the purpose of this holy life, its heartwood, its final goal.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 29 – Mahāsāropamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn29" },

{ text: `So too, brahmin, here a person, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness: 'I am immersed in birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, immersed in suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, he gains gains, honor, and fame. Because of these gains, honor, and fame, he becomes joyful and satisfied. Because of these gains, honor, and fame, he praises himself and disparages others: 'I have such gains, such fame; these other bhikkhus are unknown and of little influence.' And he does not arouse desire, does not strive, does not arouse energy for the attainment of other states higher and more sublime than those gains, honor, and fame. He becomes lazy and passive. Brahmin, just as a person needing heartwood, searching for heartwood, in search of heartwood, comes to a great tree standing with heartwood, but passes over the heartwood, passes over the sapwood, passes over the inner bark, passes over the outer bark, cuts down the branches and leaves, and takes them away thinking they are heartwood — that person will not achieve the purpose of heartwood. Brahmin, I say that person is like that simile.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 30 – Cūḷasāropamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn30" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, we think: 'It is a benefit for us, a great benefit for us, that we live with such fellow celibates.' Therefore, Venerable Sir, towards these fellow celibates, we maintain bodily acts of loving-kindness both in private and in public; we maintain verbal acts of loving-kindness both in private and in public; we maintain mental acts of loving-kindness both in private and in public. Therefore, Venerable Sir, we think: 'Let us give up our own minds and live in accordance with the minds of these venerable ones.' Venerable Sir, we give up our own minds and live in accordance with the minds of those venerable ones. Venerable Sir, although we have different bodies, we are as if of one mind. Venerable Sir, thus we live in harmony, delighting in each other, like milk and water, looking at each other with loving eyes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 31 – Cūḷagosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn31" },

{ text: `Dīgha, if in whatever family these three good men have gone forth from home to homelessness, the family members think of these three good men with a joyful mind, that family will have long-term welfare and happiness. Dīgha, if the relatives of the family from which these three good men have gone forth think of these three good men with a joyful mind, those relatives will have long-term welfare and happiness. Dīgha, see how these three good men live — for the happiness of beings, for the welfare of beings, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 31 – Cūḷagosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn31" },

{ text: `Venerable Ānanda, come here, welcome, Venerable Ānanda, attendant of the Blessed One, close companion of the Blessed One. Venerable Ānanda, lovely is the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood! The full-moon night is bright, the sāla trees are in full bloom, a heavenly fragrance seems to be wafted all around. Venerable Ānanda, what kind of bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood?<br>Here, Venerable Sāriputta, a bhikkhu is learned, remembers what he has learned, and stores up what he has learned. Those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, proclaiming the holy life completely perfect and pure — such teachings he has learned much, retained, recited verbally, mentally investigated, and well penetrated by right view. He teaches the Dhamma to the four assemblies with perfect, fluent phrasing, for the purpose of abandoning all underlying tendencies. Venerable Sāriputta, such a bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 32 – Mahāgosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn32" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Sāriputta, a bhikkhu delights in seclusion, takes delight in seclusion, internally practices the Dhamma for calming, does not neglect meditation, possesses insight practice, constantly resorts to secluded places. Venerable Sāriputta, such a bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 32 – Mahāgosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn32" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Sāriputta, a bhikkhu himself dwells in the forest and praises dwelling in the forest; himself lives on alms and praises living on alms; himself wears dust-heap robes and praises wearing dust-heap robes; himself uses the three robes and praises using three robes; himself has few desires and praises fewness of desires; himself is content and praises contentment; himself lives in solitude and praises living in solitude; himself is aloof from society and praises aloofness from society; himself is energetic and diligent and praises energy and diligence; himself possesses virtue and praises possession of virtue; himself possesses concentration and praises possession of concentration; himself possesses wisdom and praises possession of wisdom; himself possesses liberation and praises possession of liberation; himself possesses knowledge and vision of liberation and praises possession of knowledge and vision of liberation. Venerable Sāriputta, such a bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 32 – Mahāgosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn32" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Moggallāna, a bhikkhu has tamed his mind, not that he is untamed. Whatever attainment he wishes to abide in in the morning, he abides in that attainment in the morning; whatever attainment he wishes to abide in at midday, he abides in that attainment at midday; whatever attainment he wishes to abide in in the evening, he abides in that attainment in the evening. Venerable Moggallāna, such a bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 32 – Mahāgosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn32" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, listen to me as to what kind of bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood. Here, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu, after his meal, returning from his alms round, sits down cross-legged, keeping his body straight, establishing mindfulness in front of him, and thinks: 'I will not break this sitting posture until my mind is liberated from the taints by non-clinging.' Sāriputta, such a bhikkhu could illumine the Gosiṅga Sāla-wood.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 32 – Mahāgosiṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn32" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the further tasks to be done? 'Our bodily conduct must be purified, clear, open, without blemish or concealment. But we will not praise ourselves or disparage others because of that purified bodily conduct.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train. Bhikkhus, you might have the thought: 'We have achieved conscience and shame, our bodily conduct is pure; to this extent it is enough, to this extent it is done. We have attained the goal of the ascetic life. We have nothing further to do.' And to that extent you might be satisfied. Bhikkhus, I admonish you. Bhikkhus, I declare to you: While you are heading towards the goal of the ascetic life, do not abandon that goal when there are still further tasks to be done.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the further tasks to be done? 'We must guard the sense faculties. When the eye sees a form, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, we will restrain that cause, guard the eye faculty, practice the restraint of the eye faculty. When the ear hears a sound ... nose smells an odor ... tongue tastes a flavor ... body feels a touch ... mind cognizes a mental object, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, we will restrain that cause, guard the mind faculty, practice the restraint of the mind faculty.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the further tasks to be done? 'We must know moderation in eating. Reflecting wisely, we take food not for enjoyment, not for indulgence, not for beautification, not for ornamentation, but only for the support and maintenance of this body, for avoiding harm, for assisting the holy life, thinking: "Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings; and there will be for me blamelessness and a comfortable abiding."' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the further tasks to be done? 'We must be devoted to wakefulness. By day, while walking and sitting, we must purify the mind from obstructive states. In the first watch of the night, while walking and sitting, we must purify the mind from obstructive states. In the middle watch of the night, we must lie down on the right side in the lion's posture, one foot on the other, mindful and clearly comprehending, minding the time for rising. In the last watch of the night, after rising, while walking and sitting, we must purify the mind from obstructive states.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Knowing thus, seeing thus, his mind is liberated from the taint of sensual desire, liberated from the taint of existence, liberated from the taint of ignorance. When liberated, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu a samaṇa? He has tranquillized evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is a samaṇa.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who has bathed? He has bathed away evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is one who has bathed.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who knows and understands? He has known and understood evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is one who knows and understands.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who is learned? He has destroyed evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is one who is learned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu called a noble one? He has made evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death, far from him. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is called a noble one.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu called an Arahant? He has made evil, unwholesome states that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, fearful, yielding painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death, far from him. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is an Arahant.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, you admit that while you live contending, quarrelling, disputing, wounding each other with verbal weapons, there is no abiding with bodily acts of loving-kindness towards fellow celibates in private or in public, no abiding with verbal acts of loving-kindness ... no abiding with mental acts of loving-kindness ... Thus, you foolish men, knowing what, seeing what, do you live contending, quarrelling, disputing, wounding each other with verbal weapons, not appreciating each other, not accepting appreciation, not reconciling each other, not accepting reconciliation? Thus, you foolish men, you will experience suffering and distress for a long time.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 48 – Kosambiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn48" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are six principles of cordiality that create affection, create respect, leading to cohesion, to non-dispute, to harmony, to unity. What are the six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides with bodily acts of loving-kindness towards his fellow celibates, both in private and in public. This principle of cordiality creates affection, creates respect, leading to cohesion, to non-dispute, to harmony, to unity.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 48 – Kosambiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn48" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, regarding lawful gains, even down to the contents of his alms bowl, a bhikkhu is not one who does not share them; he shares them in common with his virtuous fellow celibates. This principle of cordiality creates affection, creates respect, leading to cohesion, to non-dispute, to harmony, to unity.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 48 – Kosambiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn48" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, regarding the precepts that are unbroken, unblemished, unspotted, untarnished, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, conducive to concentration — a bhikkhu lives possessing such precepts in common with his fellow celibates, both in private and in public. This principle of cordiality creates affection, creates respect, leading to cohesion, to non-dispute, to harmony, to unity.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 48 – Kosambiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn48" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, regarding the view that is noble, leading upwards, leading to the complete destruction of suffering for one who practices accordingly — a bhikkhu lives possessing that view in common with his fellow celibates, both in private and in public. This principle of cordiality creates affection, creates respect, leading to cohesion, to non-dispute, to harmony, to unity.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 48 – Kosambiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn48" },

{ text: `Kandaraka, in this Saṅgha of bhikkhus, there are bhikkhus who are learners, steadfast in virtue, steadfast in good conduct, intelligent, and who live with their minds well established in the Four Foundations of Mindfulness. What are the four? Here, Kandaraka, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 51 – Kandarakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn51" },

{ text: `Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Marvelous, Venerable Sir! These Four Foundations of Mindfulness have been well expounded by the Blessed One for the purification of beings, for the overcoming of sorrow and lamentation, for the extinguishing of pain and grief, for the attainment of the right way, for the realization of Nibbāna. Venerable Sir, we are laypeople dressed in white, and from time to time we dwell with our minds well established in these Four Foundations of Mindfulness. Here, Venerable Sir, we dwell contemplating the body as a body ... feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 51 – Kandarakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn51" },

{ text: `Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Marvelous, Venerable Sir! Venerable Sir, the Blessed One understands the happiness and unhappiness of beings, while humans live in such confusion, such scum, such deceit. Venerable Sir, humans are confused, while animals are open. Venerable Sir, I can tame an elephant so that whenever it goes to Campā, it displays all its trickery, falseness, wiles, and deceit. But, Venerable Sir, our servants, attendants, and workmen — their bodily conduct is one way, their verbal conduct is another way, their mental conduct is yet another way.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 51 – Kandarakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn51" },

{ text: `And, Mahānāma, how is a noble disciple possessed of virtue? Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple is virtuous, he lives restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Mahānāma, thus is a noble disciple possessed of virtue.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `And, Mahānāma, how does a noble disciple guard the sense faculties? Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple, when the eye sees a form, does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the eye faculty, practices the restraint of the eye faculty. When the ear hears a sound ... nose smells an odor ... tongue tastes a flavor ... body feels a touch ... mind cognizes a mental object, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the mind faculty, practices the restraint of the mind faculty. Mahānāma, thus does a noble disciple guard the sense faculties.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `And, Mahānāma, how does a noble disciple know moderation in eating? Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple, reflecting wisely, takes food not for enjoyment, not for indulgence, not for beautification, not for ornamentation, but only for the support and maintenance of this body, for avoiding harm, for assisting the holy life, thinking: 'Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings; and there will be for me blamelessness and a comfortable abiding.' Mahānāma, thus does a noble disciple know moderation in eating.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `And, Mahānāma, how is a noble disciple devoted to wakefulness? Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple, by day while walking and sitting, purifies the mind from obstructive states; in the first watch of the night, while walking and sitting, purifies the mind from obstructive states; in the middle watch of the night, he lies down on the right side in the lion's posture, one foot on the other, mindful and clearly comprehending, minding the time for rising; in the last watch of the night, after rising, while walking and sitting, purifies the mind from obstructive states. Mahānāma, thus a noble disciple is devoted to wakefulness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple has faith, faith in the enlightenment of the Tathāgata: 'He is the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, the Well-Gone, the Knower of the world, the Unsurpassed Trainer of persons, the Teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple has shame, feeling ashamed of bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, mental misconduct, feeling ashamed of having evil, unwholesome states. He has fear, feeling afraid of bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, mental misconduct, feeling afraid of having evil, unwholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple is learned, remembers what he has learned, and stores up what he has learned. Those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, proclaiming the holy life completely perfect and pure — such teachings he has learned much, retained, recited verbally, mentally investigated, and well penetrated by right view.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple dwells energetic and diligent, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, striving, persevering, not neglecting wholesome states. He is mindful, possessing supreme mindfulness and clear comprehension, remembering and recalling what was said and done long ago. He is wise, possessing wisdom of arising and passing away, possessing noble penetrating wisdom that leads to the complete destruction of suffering. Mahānāma, thus a noble disciple possesses the excellent Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53" },

{ text: `Having gone forth thus, he lives restrained by the training rules and the lifestyle of bhikkhus. He abandons killing living beings, abstains from killing, lays aside the stick and the sword, is conscientious and compassionate, dwelling with loving-kindness for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. He abandons taking what is not given, abstains from taking what is not given, desires only what is given, lives purely without theft. He abandons the non-holy life, lives the holy life, lives a life of seclusion, abstains from base sensual intercourse.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 60 – Apaṇṇakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn60" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One, leaving a little water in the water basin, addressed Venerable Rāhula: 'Rāhula, do you see this little remaining water in the water basin?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' — 'So little, Rāhula, is the asceticism of those who knowingly speak falsely, without shame and fear.' Then the Blessed One, pouring away that little water, said: 'Rāhula, do you see that little water being poured away?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' — 'So poured away, Rāhula, is the asceticism of those who knowingly speak falsely, without shame and fear.' Then the Blessed One, turning the water basin upside down, said: 'Rāhula, do you see this water basin turned upside down?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' — 'So turned upside down, Rāhula, is the asceticism of those who knowingly speak falsely, without shame and fear.' Then the Blessed One, turning the water basin right side up, said: 'Rāhula, do you see this empty water basin?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' — 'So empty, Rāhula, is the asceticism of those who knowingly speak falsely, without shame and fear.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, just as a royal elephant with tusks like ploughshafts, massive, well-trained, often found on the battlefield, when in battle uses its forefeet, hind feet, forebody, hindbody, head, ears, tusks, tail, but protects its trunk. There, the mahout thinks: 'This royal elephant ... protects its trunk; he does not give up his life.' But, Rāhula, when that royal elephant, in battle, uses its forefeet, hind feet, forebody, hindbody, head, ears, tusks, tail, and trunk, then the mahout thinks: 'This royal elephant ... uses his trunk; he has given up his life, and now there is nothing he won't do.' So too, Rāhula, for one who knowingly speaks falsely, without shame and fear, I say there is no evil he will not do. Therefore, Rāhula, 'I will not speak falsely, even for a joke' — thus, Rāhula, you should train.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, for one who knowingly speaks falsely, without shame and fear, I say there is no evil he will not do. Therefore, Rāhula, 'I will not speak falsely, even for a joke' — thus, Rāhula, you should train.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, what is the purpose of a mirror?" — "For reflection, Venerable Sir." — "So too, Rāhula, after repeatedly reflecting, bodily action should be done; after repeatedly reflecting, verbal action should be done; after repeatedly reflecting, mental action should be done.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, when you wish to do a verbal action, you should reflect on that same verbal action: 'Does this verbal action I wish to do lead to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both? Is this verbal action unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results?' Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This verbal action I wish to do leads to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both; it is unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results' — then such a verbal action you should definitely not do. Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This verbal action I wish to does not lead to my own harm, not to others' harm, not to the harm of both; it is wholesome, leading to happiness, with pleasant results' — then such a verbal action you should do.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, when you wish to do a mental action, you should reflect on that same mental action: 'Does this mental action I wish to do lead to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both? Is this mental action unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results?' Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This mental action I wish to do leads to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both; it is unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results' — then such a mental action you should definitely not do. Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This mental action I wish to do does not lead to my own harm, not to others' harm, not to the harm of both; it is wholesome, leading to happiness, with pleasant results' — then such a mental action you should do.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, when you wish to do a bodily action, you should reflect on that same bodily action: 'Does this bodily action I wish to do lead to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both? Is this bodily action unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results?' Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This bodily action I wish to do leads to my own harm, to others' harm, to the harm of both; it is unwholesome, leading to suffering, with painful results' — then such a bodily action you should definitely not do. Rāhula, if, on reflection, you know: 'This bodily action I wish to do does not lead to my own harm, not to others' harm, not to the harm of both; it is wholesome, leading to happiness, with pleasant results' — then such a bodily action you should do.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikarāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development of mindfulness of breathing. Rāhula, developing mindfulness of breathing, making it grow, yields great fruit, great benefit.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development like the earth. Rāhula, by developing like the earth, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain. Rāhula, just as people throw pure things, impure things, excrement, urine, spittle, pus, and blood on the earth, yet the earth is not troubled, not agitated, not disgusted — so too, Rāhula, develop like the earth. Rāhula, by developing like the earth, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development like water. Rāhula, by developing like water, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain. Rāhula, just as people wash pure things, impure things, excrement, urine, spittle, pus, and blood in water, yet water is not troubled, not agitated, not disgusted — so too, Rāhula, develop like water. Rāhula, by developing like water, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development like fire. Rāhula, by developing like fire, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain. Rāhula, just as fire burns pure things, impure things, excrement, urine, spittle, pus, and blood, yet fire is not troubled, not agitated, not disgusted — so too, Rāhula, develop like fire. Rāhula, by developing like fire, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development like air. Rāhula, by developing like air, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain. Rāhula, just as air blows on pure things, impure things, excrement, urine, spittle, pus, and blood, yet air is not troubled, not agitated, not disgusted — so too, Rāhula, develop like air. Rāhula, by developing like air, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development like space. Rāhula, by developing like space, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain. Rāhula, just as space is not established anywhere — so too, Rāhula, develop like space. Rāhula, by developing like space, agreeable and disagreeable contacts that arise do not take hold of the mind, do not remain.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development of loving-kindness. Rāhula, by developing loving-kindness, whatever belongs to ill-will will be abandoned. Rāhula, develop the development of compassion. Rāhula, by developing compassion, whatever belongs to harmfulness will be abandoned. Rāhula, develop the development of altruistic joy. Rāhula, by developing altruistic joy, whatever belongs to discontent will be abandoned. Rāhula, develop the development of equanimity. Rāhula, by developing equanimity, whatever belongs to hatred will be abandoned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `Rāhula, develop the development of the foul (asubha). Rāhula, by developing the foul, whatever belongs to craving will be abandoned. Rāhula, develop the development of impermanence. Rāhula, by developing impermanence, whatever belongs to the conceit 'I am' will be abandoned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is the path, what is the way leading to the abandoning of the five lower fetters? Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu, through the seclusion from all bases (upadhiviveka), through the abandoning of unwholesome states, through the complete calming down of all bodily coarseness, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 64 – Mahāmālukyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn64" },

{ text: `He contemplates all forms, feelings, perceptions, formations, and consciousness as impermanent, suffering, as a disease, a boil, a dart, a misfortune, an affliction, an enemy, a breaking up, empty, and non-self. He liberates his mind from these states. Having liberated his mind from these states, he focuses his mind on the deathless element (amata-dhātu) and thinks: 'This is peaceful, this is sublime, namely the stilling of all formations, the relinquishment of all bases, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.' If he is firmly established there, he attains the destruction of the taints. If he does not attain the destruction of the taints, then because of his desire and delight in that Dhamma, and because of the abandonment of the five lower fetters, he becomes one who is reborn spontaneously (in the Pure Abodes) and attains Nibbāna there, without ever returning from that world.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 64 – Mahāmālukyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn64" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I eat only one meal a day. Bhikkhus, by eating only one meal a day, I feel free from disease, free from affliction, lightness, strength, and a pleasant abiding. Bhikkhus, you too should eat only one meal a day. Bhikkhus, by eating only one meal a day, you too will feel free from disease, free from affliction, lightness, strength, and a pleasant abiding.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 65 – Bhaddālisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn65" },

{ text: `Bhaddali, truly, a transgression has overcome you; it was foolish, deluded, and unwholesome. While the Saṅgha of bhikkhus is practicing the training rule laid down by me, you declared your inability. Bhaddali, if you see your transgression as a transgression and make amends according to the Dhamma, we will accept your confession. For, Bhaddali, this is growth in the Discipline of the Noble One, that one sees a transgression as a transgression, makes amends according to the Dhamma, and restrains oneself in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 65 – Bhaddālisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn65" },

{ text: `Here, Bhaddali, a bhikkhu practices the training rules fully in the Teacher's dispensation. He thinks: 'Let me dwell in a remote lodging: a forest, the root of a tree, a hillside, a wilderness, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a jungle thicket, an open space, a heap of straw. And I may attain the superhuman state, the distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.' He dwells in a remote lodging ... a heap of straw. While dwelling thus secluded, the Teacher does not reproach him, wise fellow celibates after investigation do not reproach him, devas do not reproach him, and he does not reproach himself. Not reproached by the Teacher, not reproached by wise fellow celibates, not reproached by devas, not reproaching himself, he attains the superhuman state, the distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 65 – Bhaddālisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn65" },

{ text: `Then, while the Venerable Udāyi was alone in seclusion, the following thought arose in his mind: 'The Blessed One has indeed abandoned many painful states for us. The Blessed One has indeed brought us many pleasant states. The Blessed One has indeed abandoned many unwholesome states for us. The Blessed One has indeed brought us many wholesome states.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, in the past we used to eat in the evening, in the morning, during the day, and at improper times. Venerable Sir, on that occasion, the Blessed One addressed the bhikkhus and said: 'Bhikkhus, abandon eating at the improper time during the day.' Venerable Sir, at that I felt dejected and sorrowful, thinking: 'The excellent hard and soft foods that faithful donors offer to us during the day and at improper times, now the Blessed One tells us to abandon, the Well-Gone tells us to give up.' Venerable Sir, among us, those who look upon the Blessed One with affection, with respect, and with a sense of shame and fear, immediately gave up eating at the improper time during the day.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Udāyi, here some foolish people, when I say: 'Abandon this,' say: 'What does this trivial, insignificant matter matter? This samaṇa is too strict about restraint and reduction.' They do not give it up, and they arouse resentment against me and against the bhikkhus who wish to practice the training rules. This, Udāyi, becomes for them a strong fetter, a firm fetter, a stout fetter, a rotting fetter, a great log.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Udāyi, just as a poor, destitute person sees a bhikkhu in a monastery, with clean hands and feet, after eating a good meal, sitting in the shade, directing his mind to the higher mental states. He thinks: 'How pleasant is the ascetic life! How healthy is the ascetic life! Let me shave off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness.' But he cannot give up his dilapidated, crow-open, ugly hut; he cannot give up his dilapidated, ugly bed; he cannot give up the various grains stored in an ugly pot; he cannot give up his ugly wife, to shave off his hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Udāyi, a householder or a householder's son, rich, with great wealth and property, with abundant gold and silver, abundant grain, abundant fields and lands, abundant wives and children, abundant male and female slaves. He sees a bhikkhu in a monastery, with clean hands and feet, after eating a good meal, sitting in the shade, directing his mind to the higher mental states. He thinks: 'How pleasant is the ascetic life! How healthy is the ascetic life! Let me shave off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Here, Udāyi, a person lives dedicated to the abandoning of bases, to the relinquishment of bases. But while he lives dedicated to the abandoning of bases, to the relinquishment of bases, thoughts and reflections connected with bases arise. He tolerates them, does not abandon them, does not relinquish them, does not terminate them, does not destroy them. Udāyi, I say: 'That person is bound, not unbound.' Why is that? Because the difference in his faculties is clearly known to me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Here, Udāyi, a person lives dedicated to the abandoning of bases, to the relinquishment of bases. But while he lives dedicated to the abandoning of bases, to the relinquishment of bases, distorted thoughts, thoughts and reflections connected with bases, arise from time to time. Udāyi, mindfulness arises slowly, and he quickly abandons that thought, relinquishes it, terminates it, destroys it. Udāyi, just as a person lets two or three drops of water fall into an iron pot that has been heated all day — Udāyi, the drops fall slowly, but they quickly vanish and disappear. Udāyi, I say: 'That person is also bound, not unbound.' Why is that? Because the difference in his faculties is clearly known to me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `But here, Udāyi, a person thinks: 'The basis is the source of suffering.' Knowing thus, he becomes free from basis, liberated through the cessation of basis. Udāyi, I say: 'That person is unbound, not bound.' Why is that? Because the difference in his faculties is clearly known to me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Udāyi, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What are the five? Forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, stimulating sensual desire, enticing. Sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... flavors cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, stimulating sensual desire, enticing. These, Udāyi, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. Udāyi, whatever pleasure and joy arise dependent on these five strands of sensual pleasure — that is called sensual pleasure, filthy pleasure, ordinary pleasure, ignoble pleasure. It should not be pursued, should not be developed, should not be made much of. I say that such pleasure is to be feared.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Here, Udāyi, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the fourth jhāna. This is called the pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of enlightenment. It should be pursued, should be developed, should be made much of. I say that such pleasure is not to be feared.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66" },

{ text: `Good, good, Anuruddhas. It is truly fitting for you, good men who have gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, that you have delight in the holy life. Anuruddhas, while you are in the prime of youth, young, with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth, in the spring of life, you could enjoy sensual pleasures. Yet, Anuruddhas, in the prime of youth, you have gone forth from home to homelessness. Anuruddhas, it is not because of a king's command, not because of a thief's command, not because of debt, not because of fear, not because of loss of livelihood that you have gone forth. But with the thought: 'I am oppressed by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, oppressed by suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Yet perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 68 – Naḷakapānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn68" },

{ text: `And, Anuruddhas, having thus gone forth, what should a good man do? Anuruddhas, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states. If he does not attain rapture and happiness or some other state more peaceful than that, then sensual desire invades the mind and remains; ill-will ... sloth and torpor ... restlessness and remorse ... doubt ... discontent ... laziness invades the mind and remains. Anuruddhas, when not secluded from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states, he does not attain rapture and happiness or some other state more peaceful than that. Anuruddhas, when secluded from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states, he attains rapture and happiness or some other state more peaceful than that; then sensual desire does not invade the mind and remains; ill-will ... doubt ... discontent ... laziness does not invade the mind and remains. Anuruddhas, when secluded from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states, he attains rapture and happiness or some other state more peaceful than that.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 68 – Naḷakapānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn68" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I do not say that final knowledge is achieved all at once. Rather, bhikkhus, final knowledge is achieved by gradual training, gradual practice, gradual progress.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 70 – Kīṭāgirisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn70" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is final knowledge achieved by gradual training, gradual practice, gradual progress? Here, bhikkhus, one who has faith approaches; approaching, he pays respect; paying respect, he lends ear; lending ear, he hears the Dhamma; hearing the Dhamma, he remembers it; remembering it, he examines the meaning of the teachings; examining the meaning, he gains a reflective acceptance of the teachings; having reflective acceptance, desire arises; with desire, he makes an effort; having made an effort, he weighs the matter; weighing it, he strives; striving, he himself realizes the ultimate truth, and with wisdom he penetrates it and sees.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 70 – Kīṭāgirisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn70" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as a teacher lives over-attached to material things, being an heir to material things, and lives in connection with material things, this bargain does not occur: 'We will do this thus, and thus we will not do that.' How much more so for the Tathāgata, bhikkhus, who lives completely unconnected with material things.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 70 – Kīṭāgirisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn70" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a disciple who has faith in the Teacher's instruction and lives penetrating it, the Teacher's instruction becomes flourishing and vigorous. Bhikkhus, for a disciple who has faith in the Teacher's instruction and lives penetrating it, this appropriate practice arises: 'Let only skin, sinews, and bones remain, let the flesh and blood dry up in the body, but there will be energy for the attainment of what has not yet been attained, by manly strength, by manly effort, by manly striving.' Bhikkhus, for a disciple who has faith in the Teacher's instruction and lives penetrating it, one of two fruits is to be expected: either final knowledge here and now, or, if there is a residue of clinging, the state of non-returning.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 70 – Kīṭāgirisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn70" },

{ text: `But, Aggivessana, this body is material, composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wearing away, dissolution, breaking up, and destruction. It should be contemplated as impermanent, suffering, as a disease, a boil, a dart, a misfortune, an affliction, an enemy, a breaking up, empty, and non-self. When one contemplates this body as impermanent, suffering, as a disease, a boil, a dart, a misfortune, an affliction, an enemy, a breaking up, empty, and non-self, then bodily desire, bodily affection, bodily subservience are abandoned.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 74 – Dīghanakhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn74" },

{ text: `Aggivessana, pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, to vanishing, to fading away, to cessation. Aggivessana, painful feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, to vanishing, to fading away, to cessation. Aggivessana, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, to vanishing, to fading away, to cessation.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 74 – Dīghanakhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn74" },

{ text: `What do you think, Māgandiya? Here, a person was formerly infatuated with forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. Later, having truly understood the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of forms, having abandoned craving for forms, having removed fever for forms, he dwells with craving cut off, with inner peace. Surely, Māgandiya, that person would not long for those former forms, would he?`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `Then, after some time, having truly understood the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of sensual pleasures, having abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, having removed fever for sensual pleasures, I dwell with craving cut off, with inner peace. And I see other beings who have not abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, being devoured by craving for sensual pleasures, being burnt by fever for sensual pleasures, indulging in sensual pleasures. I do not wish to be like them; I take no delight in that. Why is that? Because, Māgandiya, there is this rapture and happiness, apart from sensual pleasures, apart from unwholesome states — having attained that heavenly happiness, I abide and delight in it. I do not long for anything lower; I take no delight in that.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `So too, Māgandiya, contact with sensual pleasures in the past was painful, very burning, very feverish; contact with sensual pleasures in the future will be painful, very burning, very feverish; contact with sensual pleasures in the present is painful, very burning, very feverish. Yet, Māgandiya, these beings who have not abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, being devoured by craving for sensual pleasures, being burnt by fever for sensual pleasures, with deteriorated faculties, due to painful contact with sensual pleasures, misconceive it as pleasant.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `Just as, Māgandiya, a leper with sores and blisters on his limbs, his body rotting and festering, being scratched by worms, scratches his sores with his nails and cauterizes his body over a bed of hot coals — the more he scratches and cauterizes, the more his sores become foul, stinking, and infected, yet he gets a certain satisfaction and enjoyment from the scratching of his sores. So too, Māgandiya, beings who have not abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, being devoured by craving for sensual pleasures, being burnt by fever for sensual pleasures, indulge in sensual pleasures. The more they indulge, the more their craving increases and the more they are burnt by fever for sensual pleasures, yet they get a certain satisfaction and enjoyment dependent on the five strands of sensual pleasure.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `Māgandiya, what do you think? Have you seen or heard of a king or a king's minister, enjoying the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly, without having abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, without having removed fever for sensual pleasures, who dwells or has dwelt or will dwell with craving cut off, with inner peace?" — "No, Master Gotama." — "Good, Māgandiya! I too have not seen or heard of any such person. But, Māgandiya, those samaṇas or brahmins who have dwelt, dwell, or will dwell with craving cut off, with inner peace — all these, having truly understood the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of sensual pleasures, with craving for sensual pleasures abandoned, with fever for sensual pleasures removed, have dwelt, dwell, or will dwell with craving cut off, with inner peace.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `Freedom from disease is the foremost gain,<br>Nibbāna is the foremost happiness,<br>The eightfold path is the only way,<br>Safe and leading to the Deathless.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `So too, Māgandiya, if I were to teach you the Dhamma: 'This is freedom from disease, this is Nibbāna,' you might know freedom from disease, you might see Nibbāna. And with the arising of the eye in you, your desire and lust for the five aggregates of clinging would be abandoned. And you might think: 'Indeed, for a long time I have been deceived, cheated, and deluded by this mind; for I clung to form, I clung to feeling, I clung to perception, I clung to formations, I clung to consciousness. With that clinging as condition, there is existence; with existence as condition, birth; with birth as condition, aging and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `Therefore, Māgandiya, associate with true persons. Māgandiya, by associating with true persons, you will hear the good Dhamma. By hearing the good Dhamma, you will practice in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma. By practicing in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, you will know for yourself and see for yourself: 'These are the afflictions, the boils, the darts. Here, these afflictions, boils, and darts cease without remainder. With the cessation of clinging in me, there is cessation of existence; with cessation of existence, cessation of birth; with cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgaṇḍiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75" },

{ text: `He lives content, satisfied with a robe to protect his body and with almsfood to sustain his belly, and wherever he goes, he takes these with him. Just as a bird, wherever it flies, takes its wings with it, so too, a bhikkhu is content with a robe to protect his body and with almsfood to sustain his belly, and wherever he goes, he takes these with him. Possessing this noble aggregate of virtue, he experiences an inner blameless bliss.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 76 – Sandakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn76" },

{ text: `Sirs, lower your voices! Sirs, be quiet! Now a disciple of Samaṇa Gotama, the Samaṇa Ānanda, is coming. When the disciples of Samaṇa Gotama are staying at Kosambī, this Ānanda is one of them. Those venerable ones love quiet, are trained in quiet, praise quiet. If they know this assembly is quiet, they might approach." Then those wanderers became silent.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 76 – Sandakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn76" },

{ text: `Venerable Sir, the Blessed One eats little and praises the practice of eating little. Venerable Sir, this is the first quality I see in the Blessed One. Because of this quality, disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Blessed One, and after honoring and respecting, they live depending on the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, the Blessed One is content with any kind of robe and praises contentment with any kind of robe. Venerable Sir, this is the second quality I see in the Blessed One. Because of this quality, disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Blessed One, and after honoring and respecting, they live depending on the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, the Blessed One is content with any kind of almsfood and praises contentment with any kind of almsfood. Venerable Sir, this is the third quality I see in the Blessed One. Because of this quality, disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Blessed One, and after honoring and respecting, they live depending on the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, the Blessed One is content with any kind of lodging and praises contentment with any kind of lodging. Venerable Sir, this is the fourth quality I see in the Blessed One. Because of this quality, disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Blessed One, and after honoring and respecting, they live depending on the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Here, Bhāradvāja, in the past, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, I thought: 'Household life is crowded and dusty; the going forth is wide open. It is not easy for one living at home to live the holy life completely perfect and pure as a polished conch shell. Let me shave off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness.' Then, Bhāradvāja, after some time, while still young, a black-haired youth endowed with the blessing of youth in the prime of life, though my parents wished otherwise, weeping with tearful faces, I shaved off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and went forth from home to homelessness. Having gone forth, seeking what is wholesome, seeking the supreme, unsurpassed path of peace.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `Bhāradvāja, upon hearing this, Uddaka Rāmaputta declared the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception. Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'Not only Rāma had faith; I too have faith. Not only Rāma had energy; I too have energy. Not only Rāma had mindfulness; I too have mindfulness. Not only Rāma had concentration; I too have concentration. Not only Rāma had wisdom; I too have wisdom. Let me strive to realize the Dhamma that Rāma declared: "Having known for himself, realized for himself, attained for himself, he abides."' Then, Bhāradvāja, before long, having known for myself, realized for myself, attained that Dhamma quickly, I abided in it.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `Having gone forth, seeking what is wholesome, seeking the supreme, unsurpassed path of peace, I went to Āḷāra Kālāma and said: 'Friend Kālāma, I wish to live the holy life in this Dhamma and Discipline.' Bhāradvāja, upon hearing this, Āḷāra Kālāma said to me: 'Venerable sir, you may stay and abide. This Dhamma is such that a wise person, not long after, will know for himself, realize for himself, attain for himself, and abide, as the teacher instructs.' Bhāradvāja, before long, I quickly mastered that Dhamma. And, Bhāradvāja, as far as lip-moving and speech-conveying, I spoke the doctrine of the wise and the doctrine of the elders, and I claimed that I, like others, knew and saw.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `Then, Bhāradvāja, I went to Āḷāra Kālāma and said: 'Friend Kālāma, is it to this extent that you have known for yourself, realized for yourself, attained for yourself, and declared this Dhamma?' — 'Yes, friend, to this extent I have known, realized, attained, and declared this Dhamma.' — 'Friend, I too have known, realized, attained, and declare this Dhamma to this extent.' — 'It is a gain for us, friend, a great gain for us, that we see such a fellow celibate as the venerable one. The Dhamma that I have known, realized, attained, and declared — you too have known, realized, attained, and abide; the Dhamma that you have known, realized, attained, and abide — I too have known, realized, attained, and declared. The Dhamma I know, you know; the Dhamma you know, I know. As I am, so are you; as you are, so am I. Come now, friend, let the two of us take care of this assembly!' Thus, Bhāradvāja, Āḷāra Kālāma, who was my teacher, placed me, his disciple, on the same level as himself and honored me with supreme honor.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `Bhāradvāja, I, seeking what is wholesome, seeking the supreme, unsurpassed path of peace, wandered by stages in the country of Magadha and arrived at the village of Uruvelā. There I saw a delightful place, a pleasant grove, a clear flowing river with a lovely ford, and a village nearby for alms. Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'Truly, this is a delightful place, a pleasant grove, a clear flowing river with a lovely ford, and a village nearby for alms. This is suitable for a good man who wishes to strive.' And, Bhāradvāja, I sat down there, thinking: 'This is suitable for striving.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'Previously, there have been samaṇas or brahmins who suddenly felt sharp, painful, severe, and harsh feelings. This pain was supreme, nothing could be greater. But with such severe austerity, I still have not attained the superhuman state, the distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones. Could there be another path to enlightenment?' Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'I recall that when my father the Sakyan was plowing and I was sitting in the shade of a rose-apple tree, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, I entered and abided in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. Could that be the path to enlightenment?' And following that memory, Bhāradvāja, the consciousness arose in me: 'This is indeed the path to enlightenment.' Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'Am I afraid of that pleasure, which is a pleasure apart from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states?' Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'I am not afraid of that pleasure, which is a pleasure apart from sensual pleasures and unwholesome states.' Then, Bhāradvāja, I thought: 'It is not easy to attain that pleasure with a body so extremely emaciated. Let me eat solid food, rice and porridge.' Then, Bhāradvāja, I ate solid food, rice and porridge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 100 – Saṅgāravasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn100" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is a decision in accordance with confession? Here, Ānanda, whether accused or not accused, a bhikkhu remembers an offense, reveals it, and discloses it. That bhikkhu should go to an elder bhikkhu, arrange his robe over one shoulder, bow at his feet, sit on his heels, join his palms, and say: 'Venerable sir, I have committed such-and-such an offense; I confess it.' The other says: 'Do you see it?' — 'I see it.' — 'Will you restrain yourself in the future?' — 'I will restrain myself.' Thus, Ānanda, this is a decision in accordance with confession; thus, here, the settling of certain disputes is by means of a decision in accordance with confession.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 104 – Sāmagāmasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn104" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is the covering over with grass? Here, Ānanda, some bhikkhus live quarrelling, disputing, and arguing, having done and said many things unbecoming to samaṇas. All those bhikkhus should assemble in harmony. Having assembled, a more learned and experienced bhikkhu from one group of bhikkhus rises from his seat, arranges his robe over one shoulder, joins his palms, and addresses the Saṅgha: 'Venerable sirs, let the Saṅgha hear me. When we were living quarrelling, disputing, and arguing, we did and said many things unbecoming to samaṇas. If it seems proper to the Saṅgha, I will reveal whatever offenses these venerable ones have and whatever offenses I have. For the benefit of the venerable ones and also for my own benefit, I will reveal them in the midst of the Saṅgha, like covering over with grass, except for the grave offenses and offenses connected with laypeople.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 104 – Sāmagāmasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn104" },

{ text: `Just as, Sunakkhatta, a person who has not been living in his own village or town for a long time might see a person who has just arrived from that village or town. He would ask that person about the safety of that village or town, about the abundance of food and drink, and about the absence of disease; and that person would tell him about the safety, abundance, and good health. Sunakkhatta, what do you think? Would that person listen to him, lend an ear, and fix his mind on that knowledge, and would he associate with that person with delight?" — "Yes, Venerable Sir." — "So too, Sunakkhatta, this situation occurs when some people are heavily inclined towards material things. For one heavily inclined towards material things, Sunakkhatta, a talk that is suitable for him must be in accordance with his reflections and thoughts, and he will only associate with that person with delight. But if the talk is only about the imperturbable (āneñja), he will not listen, will not lend an ear, will not fix his mind on supreme knowledge, and will not associate with that person with delight. He should be understood as: 'A person heavily inclined towards material things.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105" },

{ text: `Sunakkhatta, I give this simile for the purpose of conveying the meaning. The meaning here is this: The wound, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for the six sense-spheres (phassāyatana). The poison, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for ignorance. The dart, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for craving. The probing instrument, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for mindfulness. The knife, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for noble wisdom. The surgeon, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Indeed, Sunakkhatta, a bhikkhu who is guarded regarding the six sense-spheres, thinking: 'The basis (upadhi) is the source of suffering,' having known thus, becomes free from basis, liberated through the cessation of basis. It does not happen that he would direct his body towards a basis or set his mind on a basis.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105" },

{ text: `Just as, Sunakkhatta, a bronze drinking cup, beautiful and fragrant, but mixed with poison. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, and loathes suffering. Sunakkhatta, what do you think? Would that person drink from that cup, knowing: 'If I drink from it, I will meet death or deadly pain'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "So too, Sunakkhatta, that bhikkhu is surely guarded regarding the six sense-spheres. 'The basis is the source of suffering,' having known thus, he becomes free from basis, liberated through the cessation of basis. It does not happen that he would direct his body towards a basis or set his mind on a basis.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105" },

{ text: `Just as, Sunakkhatta, a very poisonous viper. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, and loathes suffering. Sunakkhatta, what do you think? Would that person give his hand or foot to that viper, knowing: 'If this viper bites me, I will meet death or deadly pain'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "So too, Sunakkhatta, that bhikkhu is surely guarded regarding the six sense-spheres. 'The basis is the source of suffering,' having known thus, he becomes free from basis, liberated through the cessation of basis. It does not happen that he would direct his body towards a basis or set his mind on a basis.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105" },

{ text: `Bodily action, bhikkhus, I say, is of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced; and such is the distinction regarding bodily action.' This has been said, and why was it said? Whatever bodily action, Sāriputta, when practiced, leads to the increase of unwholesome states and the decrease of wholesome states, such bodily action should not be practiced. And whatever bodily action, when practiced, leads to the decrease of unwholesome states and the increase of wholesome states, such bodily action should be practiced.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 114 – Sevitabbāsevitabbasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn114" },

{ text: `Forms cognizable by the eye, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.' Sounds cognizable by the ear, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.' Odors cognizable by the nose, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.' Flavors cognizable by the tongue, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.' Tangibles cognizable by the body, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.' Mind-objects cognizable by the mind, Sāriputta, I say, are of two kinds: 'To be practiced, not to be practiced.'<br><br>Whatever forms cognizable by the eye, Sāriputta, when practiced, lead to the increase of unwholesome states and the decrease of wholesome states, such forms should not be practiced. Whatever forms cognizable by the eye, when practiced, lead to the decrease of unwholesome states and the increase of wholesome states, such forms should be practiced. This has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 114 – Sevitabbāsevitabbasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn114" },

{ text: `Whatever fears arise, bhikkhus, all those fears arise for the foolish, not for the wise. Whatever disappointments arise, all those disappointments arise for the foolish, not for the wise. Whatever calamities arise, all those calamities arise for the foolish, not for the wise. Just as, bhikkhus, a spark from a grass hut can burn down a gabled house plastered inside and out, protected from the wind, with bolted doors and shutters — so too, bhikkhus, whatever fears arise, all those fears arise for the foolish, not for the wise; whatever disappointments arise, all those disappointments arise for the foolish, not for the wise; whatever calamities arise, all those calamities arise for the foolish, not for the wise. Thus, bhikkhus, the foolish is full of fear, the wise is without fear. The foolish is full of disappointment, the wise is without disappointment. The foolish is full of calamity, the wise is without calamity. Bhikkhus, there is no fear for the wise, no disappointment for the wise, no calamity for the wise. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves: 'We will become wise and reflective.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 115 – Bahudhātukasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn115" },

{ text: `At that time, on the Uposatha day, the fifteenth, the full moon night of the Komudi festival in the fourth month, the Blessed One was seated in the open air, surrounded by the assembly of bhikkhus. Then the Blessed One, after surveying the silent, utterly silent assembly of bhikkhus, addressed them: 'This assembly, bhikkhus, has no idle talk. This assembly, bhikkhus, has no superfluous talk; it is established in the pure heartwood. Such a community of bhikkhus, bhikkhus, such an assembly, bhikkhus, is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit for the world. Such a community of bhikkhus, bhikkhus, such an assembly, bhikkhus, is an assembly where a small offering yields great fruit, and a great offering yields even greater fruit. Such a community of bhikkhus, bhikkhus, such an assembly, bhikkhus, is hard to see in the world. Such a community of bhikkhus, bhikkhus, such an assembly, bhikkhus, is worthy of being traveled to for many leagues with a provisions-bag on one's shoulder in order to see it.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 118 – Ānāpānassatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn118" },

{ text: `Mindfulness of breathing, bhikkhus, developed and cultivated in this way, brings the Four Foundations of Mindfulness to completion. And how, bhikkhus, are the Four Foundations of Mindfulness developed and cultivated so as to bring the Seven Factors of Enlightenment to completion? Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world, at that time his mindfulness is established without confusion. When his mindfulness is established without confusion, bhikkhus, at that time the mindfulness enlightenment factor is aroused in him. At that time, he develops the mindfulness enlightenment factor. At that time, the mindfulness enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. Dwelling thus with mindfulness established, he reflects on, examines, and investigates that Dhamma with wisdom.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 118 – Ānāpānassatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn118" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when dwelling thus with mindfulness established, the bhikkhu reflects on, examines, and investigates that Dhamma with wisdom, at that time the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor. At that time, the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. When he reflects on, examines, and investigates that Dhamma with wisdom, unflagging energy is aroused in the bhikkhu. Bhikkhus, when the bhikkhu reflects on, examines, and investigates that Dhamma with wisdom, at that time unflagging energy is aroused in that bhikkhu. At that time, the energy enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the energy enlightenment factor. At that time, the energy enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. Non-material rapture arises in one who is energetic and striving.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 118 – Ānāpānassatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn118" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when non-material rapture arises in the bhikkhu who is energetic and striving, at that time the rapture enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the rapture enlightenment factor. At that time, the rapture enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. For one with joyful mind, the body becomes tranquil, and the mind also becomes tranquil. Bhikkhus, when the bhikkhu has a joyful mind, his body becomes tranquil and his mind becomes tranquil, at that time the tranquility enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the tranquility enlightenment factor. At that time, the tranquility enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. One whose body is tranquil experiences happiness; his mind becomes concentrated.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 118 – Ānāpānassatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn118" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the bhikkhu has a tranquil body and is happy, his mind becomes concentrated, at that time the concentration enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the concentration enlightenment factor. At that time, the concentration enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development. With mind thus concentrated, he looks upon things with equanimity. Bhikkhus, when the bhikkhu, with mind thus concentrated, looks upon things with equanimity, at that time the equanimity enlightenment factor is aroused in the bhikkhu. At that time, he develops the equanimity enlightenment factor. At that time, the equanimity enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment by development.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 118 – Ānāpānassatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn118" },

{ text: `Friend Bakkula, in those eighty years, how many times did the thought of sensual desire arise in you?" "Friend Kassapa, in the eighty years since I went forth, I have never perceived a thought of sensual desire arise." "Because Venerable Bakkula did not perceive a thought of sensual desire arise in eighty years, we consider this a wonderful and marvelous quality of Venerable Bakkula.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 124 – Bākulasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn124" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a man throws a yoke with a single hole into the great ocean. An easterly wind drives it westward, a westerly wind drives it eastward, a northerly wind drives it southward, a southerly wind drives it northward. There is a blind turtle that surfaces once every hundred years. Bhikkhus, what do you think? Would that blind turtle ever put its neck into that yoke with a single hole?" "If it ever does, Venerable Sir, it would be after a very long time." "More quickly, bhikkhus, could that blind turtle put its neck into that yoke with a single hole than a fool who has fallen into a plane of misery could regain human birth. Why is that? Because there, bhikkhus, there is no practice of Dhamma, no practice of peace, no wholesome practice, no meritorious practice. There, bhikkhus, they devour one another and prey on the weak.<br><br>And if, after a very long time, that fool regains human birth, he will be reborn in a low family, a family of outcasts, of hunters, of bamboo-weavers, of cart-makers, or of scavengers — a poor family with little food and drink, where even a rag for covering is hard to get. Moreover, he will be ugly, misshapen, dwarfish, sickly, blind, crippled, lame, or paralyzed, unable to get food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, perfumes, bedding, lodgings, and light. He engages in misconduct of body, speech, and mind; because of that, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 129 – Bālapaṇḍitasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn129" },

{ text: `Friends, what is pursuit of the past? 'My eye in the past was such and such, forms were such and such, and consciousness there was bound by desire and craving.' Because consciousness is bound by desire and craving, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he pursues the past. 'My ear in the past was such and such, sounds were such and such... My nose in the past was such and such, odors were such and such... My tongue in the past was such and such, flavors were such and such... My mind in the past was such and such, mental objects were such and such, and consciousness there was bound by desire and craving.' Because consciousness is bound by desire and craving, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he pursues the past. Thus, friends, is pursuit of the past.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 133 – Mahākaccānabhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn133" },

{ text: `And, friends, what is yearning for the future? 'My eye in the future will be such and such, forms will be such and such, and he directs his mind to obtain what is not yet obtained.' Because of that directing of mind, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he yearns for the future. 'My ear in the future will be such and such, sounds will be such and such... My nose in the future will be such and such, odors will be such and such... My tongue in the future will be such and such, flavors will be such and such... My body in the future will be such and such, tangibles will be such and such... My mind in the future will be such and such, mental objects will be such and such, and he directs his mind to obtain what is not yet obtained.' Because of that directing of mind, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he yearns for the future. Thus, friends, is yearning for the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 133 – Mahākaccānabhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn133" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhu, how is one drawn towards present phenomena? Here, bhikkhu, an unlearned ordinary person, who does not see the noble ones, is not skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, not trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who does not see the true persons, is not skilled in the teaching of the true persons, not trained in the teaching of the true persons — regards form as self, or self as possessing form, or form as in self, or self as in form; or he regards feeling as self ... perception as self ... formations as self ... consciousness as self, or self as possessing consciousness, or consciousness as in self, or self as in consciousness. Thus, bhikkhu, is one drawn towards present phenomena.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 134 – Lomasakaṅgiyabhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn134" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhu, how is there pursuit of the past? He thinks: 'Such was my form in the past,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such was my feeling in the past,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such was my perception in the past,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such were my formations in the past,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such was my consciousness in the past,' and he seeks delight in that. Thus, bhikkhu, is pursuit of the past. And, bhikkhu, how is there yearning for the future? He thinks: 'Such will my form be in the future,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such will my feeling be in the future,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such will my perception be in the future,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such will my formations be in the future,' and he seeks delight in that. 'Such will my consciousness be in the future,' and he seeks delight in that. Thus, bhikkhu, is yearning for the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 134 – Lomasakaṅgiyabhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn134" },

{ text: `Ānanda, if this foolish Samiddhi, when asked by the wanderer Potaliputta, had answered as follows: 'Friend Potaliputta, if one intends to perform a bodily, verbal, or mental action leading to pleasant feeling, he will experience pleasant feeling. If one intends to perform a bodily, verbal, or mental action leading to painful feeling, he will experience painful feeling. If one intends to perform a bodily, verbal, or mental action leading to neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he will experience neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling' — if he had answered thus, Ānanda, the foolish Samiddhi would have answered the wanderer Potaliputta correctly.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 136 – Mahākammavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn136" },

{ text: `'Bhikkhus, how should a bhikkhu investigate so that his consciousness is not distracted or scattered externally, does not dwell internally, and is not troubled by clinging? Bhikkhus, if consciousness is not distracted or scattered externally, does not dwell internally, and is not troubled by clinging, then there will be no arising, no origination of suffering — birth, aging, death — in the future.' Friends, how is consciousness distracted and scattered externally? Here, friends, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, consciousness pursues the sign of form, is bound by the gratification of form, is fettered by the gratification of form — this is called consciousness distracted and scattered externally. When a bhikkhu hears a sound with the ear... smells an odor with the nose... tastes a flavor with the tongue... feels a touch with the body... cognizes a mental object with the mind, consciousness pursues the sign of that mental object, is bound by its gratification, is fettered by its gratification — this is called consciousness distracted and scattered externally. Thus, friends, is consciousness distracted and scattered.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 138 – Uddesavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn138" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What are the five? Forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear... odors cognizable by the nose... flavors cognizable by the tongue... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. These, bhikkhus, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. Bhikkhus, the pleasure and joy that arise dependent on these five strands of sensual pleasure — this is called sensual pleasure, filthy pleasure, ordinary pleasure, ignoble pleasure. 'I say that this kind of pleasure should not be pursued, should not be developed, should not be cultivated, but should be feared.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. This is called the pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of enlightenment. 'I say that this kind of pleasure should be pursued, should be developed, should be cultivated, and should not be feared.' When it is said: 'One should know the evaluation of pleasure; having evaluated pleasure, one should be intent on inner pleasure' — it was for this reason that this was said.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139" },

{ text: `When it is said: 'One should not speak a secret word. One should not speak a hurtful word face to face' — for what reason was this said? Here, bhikkhus, if one knows a secret word to be untrue, false, and unbeneficial, one should, if possible, not speak that secret word. And if one knows a secret word to be true, not false, but unbeneficial, one should train oneself not to speak it. And if one knows a secret word to be true, not false, and beneficial, then one should know the time and speak that secret word. If one knows a hurtful word face to face to be untrue, false, and unbeneficial, one should, if possible, not speak that hurtful word face to face. If one knows a hurtful word face to face to be true, not false, but unbeneficial, one should train oneself not to speak it. And if one knows a hurtful word face to face to be true, not false, and beneficial, then one should know the time and speak that hurtful word face to face.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139" },

{ text: `When it is said: 'One should speak slowly, not hurriedly' — for what reason was this said? Here, bhikkhus, if one speaks hurriedly, the body becomes fatigued, the mind becomes disturbed, the voice becomes damaged, and the throat becomes sore. The speech of one who speaks hurriedly is not clear and is not understood. Here, bhikkhus, if one speaks slowly, the body is not fatigued, the mind is not disturbed, the voice is not damaged, and the throat is not sore. The speech of one who speaks slowly is clear and is understood. When it is said: 'One should speak slowly, not hurriedly' — it was for this reason that this was said.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is adherence to local language and excessive use of everyday speech? Here, bhikkhus, in various regions, people know words for 'dish', 'bowl', 'cup', 'plate', 'pot', 'basin', 'vessel'. Thus, as they know these words in those regions, someone insists, clings, and says: 'Only this is true; everything else is false.' Thus, bhikkhus, is adherence to local language and excessive use of everyday speech. And, bhikkhus, what is non-adherence to local language and non-excessive use of everyday speech? Here, bhikkhus, in various regions, people know words for 'dish', 'bowl', 'cup', 'plate', 'pot', 'basin', 'vessel'. Thus, as they know these words in those regions, a person, without clinging, explains: 'They, depending on this, speak thus.' Thus, bhikkhus, is non-adherence to local language and non-excessive use of everyday speech.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, tonight, a certain deity, when the night was nearly over, illuminating the entire Jeta's Grove with surpassing radiance, came to me, paid homage to me, and stood to one side. Standing to one side, that deity spoke this verse to me:<br><br>This Jeta's Grove,<br>So beautiful and blessed,<br>Frequented by devas and the Saṅgha,<br>Dwells in peace,<br>With the Dhamma King residing here,<br>Bringing joy to me.<br><br>Action, knowledge, and Dhamma,<br>Virtue, the supreme life,<br>It is by these that beings are purified,<br>Not by clan, not by wealth.<br><br>Therefore the wise,<br>Seeing their own good,<br>Reflecting on the true Dhamma,<br>Are purified right here.<br><br>Like Sāriputta,<br>In wisdom, virtue, and peace,<br>Whatever bhikkhu<br>Has reached the far shore,<br>Let him attain the supreme<br>Among these qualities.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 143 – Anāthapiṇḍikovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn143" },

{ text: `Just as, sisters, an oil lamp burns; the oil is impermanent, subject to change; the wick is impermanent, subject to change; the flame is impermanent, subject to change; the light is impermanent, subject to change. If someone were to say: 'This oil lamp burns; the oil is impermanent, subject to change; the wick is impermanent, subject to change; the flame is impermanent, subject to change; but this light is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change' — would that person be speaking correctly?" "No, venerable sir." "Why is that?" "Venerable sir, this oil lamp burns; the oil is impermanent, subject to change; the wick is also impermanent, subject to change; the flame is also impermanent, subject to change; let alone the light — that too is impermanent, subject to change!" "That is correct, sisters! If someone were to say: 'These six external bases are impermanent, and the feeling — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that arises dependent on these six external bases is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change' — would that person be speaking correctly?" "No, venerable sir." "Why is that?" "Venerable sir, dependent on this and that condition, this and that feeling arises. With the cessation of those conditions, those feelings cease and pass away." "Good, good, sisters! That is indeed the true perception of a noble disciple with right wisdom.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 146 – Nandakovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn146" },

{ text: `Just as, sisters, there is a great tree standing with heartwood, with roots that are impermanent, subject to change; with a trunk that is impermanent, subject to change; with branches and leaves that are impermanent, subject to change; with its shadow that is impermanent, subject to change. If someone were to say: 'This great tree standing with heartwood has roots that are impermanent, subject to change; a trunk that is impermanent, subject to change; branches and leaves that are impermanent, subject to change; but its shadow is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change' — would that person be speaking correctly?" "No, venerable sir." "Why is that?" "Venerable sir, this great tree has roots that are impermanent, subject to change; a trunk that is impermanent, subject to change; branches and leaves that are impermanent, subject to change; let alone its shadow — that too is impermanent, subject to change!" "That is correct, sisters! If someone were to say: 'These six internal bases are impermanent, and the feeling — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that arises dependent on these six internal bases is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change' — would that person be speaking correctly?" "No, venerable sir." "Why is that?" "Venerable sir, dependent on this and that condition, this and that feeling arises. With the cessation of those conditions, those feelings cease and pass away." "Good, good, sisters! That is indeed the true perception of a noble disciple with right wisdom.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 146 – Nandakovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn146" },

{ text: `Just as, sisters, a skilled butcher or his apprentice, after killing a cow, cuts it up with a sharp butcher's knife without damaging the inner flesh or the outer skin, and then cuts, severs, and removes all the inner sinews, inner tendons, and inner ligaments. After cutting, severing, and removing them, and after removing the outer skin, he covers the cow again with that same skin and says: 'This cow is attached to this skin as before' — would that person be speaking correctly?" "No, venerable sir." "Why is that?" "Even though, venerable sir, that skilled butcher or his apprentice, after killing the cow ... covers it again with that same skin, he could say: 'This cow is attached to this skin as before' — but the cow is already separated from that skin." "I give this simile, sisters, to convey the meaning. The meaning here is this: 'Inner flesh' is a synonym for the six internal bases. 'Outer skin' is a synonym for the six external bases. 'Inner sinews, inner tendons, inner ligaments' are a synonym for desire and lust and greed. 'The sharp butcher's knife' is a synonym for noble wisdom. With that noble wisdom, he cuts, severs, and removes the inner defilements, inner fetters, inner bonds.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 146 – Nandakovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn146" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, not knowing and not seeing the eye as it actually is; not knowing and not seeing forms as they actually are; not knowing and not seeing eye-consciousness as it actually is; not knowing and not seeing eye-contact as it actually is; not knowing and not seeing the feeling — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that arises dependent on eye-contact as it actually is — he becomes attached to the eye, attached to forms, attached to eye-consciousness, attached to eye-contact. Attached to the feeling that arises dependent on eye-contact, as he dwells contemplating gratification, being attached, entangled, and infatuated, the five aggregates of clinging accumulate for the future. And his craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, seeking delight here and there, that craving grows. Bodily afflictions grow, mental afflictions grow, bodily fevers grow, mental fevers grow, bodily pains grow, mental pains grow. He experiences bodily suffering and mental suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 149 – Mahāsaḷāyatanikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn149" },

{ text: `Householders, if wanderers of other sects ask you: 'Householders, what kind of samaṇas and brahmins are not worthy of veneration, respect, homage, and offerings?' When asked thus, householders, you should answer those wanderers: 'Those samaṇas and brahmins who are not free from greed, not free from hatred, not free from delusion regarding forms cognizable by the eye, whose minds are not inwardly peaceful, and whose bodily, verbal, and mental conduct are sometimes balanced, sometimes unbalanced — such samaṇas and brahmins are not worthy of veneration, respect, homage, and offerings. Why is that? Because we ourselves are not free from greed, hatred, and delusion regarding forms cognizable by the eye, our minds are not inwardly peaceful, and our bodily, verbal, and mental conduct are sometimes balanced, sometimes unbalanced, yet we do not see those venerable ones surpassing us in balanced conduct. Therefore, those samaṇas and brahmins are not worthy of veneration, respect, homage, and offerings.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 150 – Nagaravindeyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn150" },

{ text: `But, householders, if those wanderers ask you: 'On what basis, on what tradition, do you say of those venerable ones: "Surely those venerable ones are free from greed, or are on the path to taming greed; free from hatred, or on the path to taming hatred; free from delusion, or on the path to taming delusion"?' When asked thus, householders, you should answer those wanderers: 'Those venerable ones dwell in remote lodgings in quiet forests. In such places, there are no forms cognizable by the eye that they could see and delight in; there are no sounds cognizable by the ear... no odors cognizable by the nose... no flavors cognizable by the tongue... no tangibles cognizable by the body that they could experience and delight in. Friends, on this basis, on this tradition, we say of those venerable ones: "Surely those venerable ones are free from greed, or are on the path to taming greed; free from hatred, or on the path to taming hatred; free from delusion, or on the path to taming delusion."'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 150 – Nagaravindeyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn150" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu lives in some village... lives in some town... lives in some city... lives in some country... lives in some forest. While living in that forest, his unestablished mindfulness is not established, his unconcentrated mind is not concentrated, his unended taints are not ended, the supreme security from bondage is not attained. Yet the necessities of life required by one who has gone forth — robes, almsfood, lodging, medicines — are obtained without difficulty. Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should reflect: 'I live in this forest. While living here, my unestablished mindfulness is not established... the supreme security from bondage is not attained. Yet these necessities are obtained without difficulty. But it was not for the sake of robes that I went forth from home to homelessness; not for the sake of almsfood... not for the sake of lodging... not for the sake of medicines. While I live in this forest, my unestablished mindfulness is not established... the supreme security from bondage is not attained.' Bhikkhus, on this consideration alone, that bhikkhu should leave that forest and not stay.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 17 – Vanapatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn17" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu lives near a certain person. While living near that person, his unestablished mindfulness is not established... the supreme security from bondage is not attained. Yet these necessities... are obtained without difficulty. Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should reflect: 'I live near this person. While living near him, my unestablished mindfulness is not established... the supreme security from bondage is not attained. Yet these necessities... are obtained without difficulty. But it was not for the sake of robes that I went forth from home to homelessness... not for the sake of almsfood... not for the sake of lodging... not for the sake of medicines. And while I live near this person, my unestablished mindfulness is not established... the supreme security from bondage is not attained.' Bhikkhus, on this consideration alone, that bhikkhu should leave that person, without taking leave, without following after.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 17 – Vanapatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn17" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu lives near a certain person. While living near that person, his unestablished mindfulness becomes established, his unconcentrated mind becomes concentrated, his unended taints become ended, the supreme security from bondage is attained. Yet these necessities of life required by one who has gone forth — robes, almsfood, lodging, medicines — are obtained with difficulty. Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should reflect: 'I live near this person. While living near him, my unestablished mindfulness becomes established... the supreme security from bondage is attained. Yet these necessities... are obtained with difficulty. But it was not for the sake of robes that I went forth from home to homelessness... not for the sake of almsfood... not for the sake of lodging... not for the sake of medicines. And while I live near this person, my unestablished mindfulness becomes established... the supreme security from bondage is attained.' Bhikkhus, on this consideration alone, that bhikkhu should follow that person and not leave.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 17 – Vanapatthasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn17" },

{ text: `'Bhikkhu, the ant-hill' is a synonym for this body composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wearing away, dissolution, breaking up, and destruction. 'What is done by day, one thinks and reflects upon at night' — that is the smoke at night. 'What one thinks and reflects upon at night, one acts upon during the day in body, speech, and mind' — that is the flame by day. 'The brahmin' is a synonym for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. 'The wise man' is a synonym for a learner bhikkhu. 'The sword' is a synonym for noble wisdom. 'Digging up' is a synonym for effort and striving. 'The bolt' is a synonym for ignorance; 'lifting the bolt' is abandoning that ignorance; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 23 – Vammikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn23" },

{ text: `'Bhikkhu, the toad' is a synonym for anger and resentment; 'lifting the toad' is abandoning that anger and resentment; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The two-forked path' is a synonym for doubt; 'lifting the two-forked path' is abandoning that doubt; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The strainer' is a synonym for the five hindrances: the hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of sloth and torpor, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt; 'lifting the strainer' is abandoning these five hindrances; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The turtle' is a synonym for the five aggregates of clinging; 'lifting the turtle' is abandoning these five aggregates; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The butcher's knife' is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure; 'lifting the butcher's knife' is abandoning these five strands; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The piece of meat' is a synonym for desire and lust; 'lifting the piece of meat' is abandoning that desire and lust; 'the wise man, taking the sword, dug up' — that is the meaning. 'The cobra' is a synonym for a bhikkhu who has destroyed the taints; 'let the cobra be, do not touch the cobra, pay homage to the cobra' — that is the meaning.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 23 – Vammikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn23" },

{ text: `'Bhikkhus, who in this region is praised by his fellow celibates in the same region thus: 'He himself has few desires and speaks to the bhikkhus about fewness of desires; he himself is content and speaks about contentment; he himself is secluded and speaks about seclusion; he himself is aloof from society and speaks about aloofness; he himself is energetic and diligent and speaks about energy and diligence; he himself possesses virtue and speaks about possession of virtue; he himself possesses concentration and speaks about possession of concentration; he himself possesses wisdom and speaks about possession of wisdom; he himself possesses liberation and speaks about possession of liberation; he himself possesses knowledge and vision of liberation and speaks about possession of knowledge and vision of liberation; he is an instructor, a revealer, a presenter, an exhorter, an inspirer, a gladdening of his fellow celibates'?" "Venerable Sir, the Venerable Puṇṇa, son of Mantāṇī, is the bhikkhu in this region praised by his fellow celibates... gladdening of his fellow celibates." At that time, the Venerable Sāriputta was sitting not far from the Blessed One. The Venerable Sāriputta thought: "Fortunate is the Venerable Puṇṇa, son of Mantāṇī! Truly fortunate is the Venerable Puṇṇa, son of Mantāṇī! He has been praised point by point by wise fellow celibates in the presence of the Teacher, and has been accepted by the Teacher. Perhaps we shall meet the Venerable Puṇṇa, son of Mantāṇī, at some time, in some place, and perhaps have a conversation with him.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 24 – Rathavinītasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn24" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'the bait' is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure. 'The hunter' is a synonym for Māra. 'The hunter's retinue' is a synonym for Māra's retinue. 'The herd of deer' is a synonym for samaṇas and brahmins. Here, bhikkhus, the first class of samaṇas and brahmins enters, indulges, and consumes the bait spread by Māra and the world's goods. There, entering, indulging, and consuming, they become confused; confused, they become heedless; heedless, they are at the will of Māra among that bait and those world's goods. Thus, bhikkhus, this first class of samaṇas and brahmins does not escape Māra's power.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, the second class of samaṇas and brahmins reflects: 'This first class... did not escape Māra's power. Let us completely abandon the bait and the world's goods, abandon the fearsome things, go deep into the forest, and abide.' They completely abandon the bait and the world's goods, abandon the fearsome things, go deep into the forest, and abide. There they become grass-eaters, bran-eaters, husk-eaters, Nivara-seed eaters, scrap-eaters, chaff-eaters, rice-water drinkers, sesame-meal eaters, grass-eaters, cow-dung eaters, fruit-eaters, root-eaters in the forest, eaters of fallen fruits. At the end of the summer, when water and grass become scarce, their bodies become extremely emaciated. Because their bodies become extremely emaciated, their energy becomes exhausted. With energy exhausted, their mind-liberation becomes exhausted. With mind-liberation exhausted, they fall back to the bait spread by Māra and the world's goods. There, entering, indulging, and consuming, they become confused; confused, they become heedless; heedless, they are at the will of Māra among that bait and those world's goods. Thus, bhikkhus, this second class of samaṇas and brahmins does not escape Māra's power.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here the third class of samaṇas and brahmins reflects: 'This first class... did not escape Māra's power. This second class... also did not escape Māra's power. Let us make a hiding place near the bait spread by Māra and the world's goods. Having made a hiding place there, without entering, without indulging, we will consume the bait and the world's goods. By not entering, not indulging, we will not become confused; not confused, we will not become heedless; not heedless, we will not be at the will of Māra among that bait and those world's goods.' They make a hiding place near the bait... without entering, without indulging, they consume the bait... not becoming confused... not heedless... not at the will of Māra. But then they hold such wrong views as: 'The world is eternal; the world is not eternal; the world is finite; the world is infinite; ...' Thus, bhikkhus, this third class of samaṇas and brahmins does not escape Māra's power.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how is it that Māra and his retinue cannot be reached? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. Bhikkhus, this is called a bhikkhu who has blinded Māra, who has destroyed Māra's eye, leaving no trace, so that Māra cannot see the way. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, enters and abides in the second jhāna... This is called a bhikkhu who has blinded Māra, destroyed Māra's eye, leaving no trace, so that Māra cannot see the way.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not bind up the wound? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he grasps the general sign, grasps the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise; he does not restrain that cause, does not guard the eye faculty, does not practice the restraint of the eye faculty. When he hears a sound with the ear... smells an odor with the nose... tastes a flavor with the tongue... feels a touch with the body... cognizes a mental object with the mind, he grasps the general sign, grasps the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise; he does not restrain that cause, does not guard the mind faculty, does not practice the restraint of the mind faculty. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not bind up the wound.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not know forms? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not know as it actually is all forms of the four great elements and the forms derived from the four great elements. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not know forms. Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not skillfully (discern) the signs? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not know as it actually is the fool and the sign of a fool, the wise person and the sign of a wise person. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not skillfully discern the signs. Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not expel the gadfly eggs? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu tolerates arisen sensual thoughts; he does not abandon, dispel, terminate, or make them non-existent. He tolerates arisen thoughts of ill-will... tolerates arisen thoughts of harmfulness... tolerates arisen evil, unwholesome states; he does not abandon, dispel, terminate, or make them non-existent. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not expel the gadfly eggs.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not fumigate? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not teach the Dhamma extensively to others as he has heard and learned it. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not fumigate. And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not know the ford? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not from time to time approach those bhikkhus who are learned, who have received the tradition of the scriptures, who are experts in the Dhamma, experts in the Discipline, experts in the summaries; he does not ask them, does not question them: 'How is this, venerable sir? What is the meaning of this?' Those venerable ones do not reveal what is unrevealed, do not clarify what is unclear, and regarding various points of Dhamma, they do not remove doubt. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not know the ford. And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not know the drinking place? Here, bhikkhus, when the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is being taught, he does not attain the meaning of faith, the Dhamma of faith, does not attain gladness connected with the Dhamma. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not know the drinking place.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not know the path? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not know as it actually is the Noble Eightfold Path. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not know the path. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu not skilled in the pastures? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not know as it actually is the Four Foundations of Mindfulness. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who is not skilled in the pastures. And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu milk dry? Here, bhikkhus, when the lay followers, out of faith, offer the requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicines, the bhikkhu does not know how to accept just enough. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who milks dry. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who does not pay special respect and reverence to the elder bhikkhus who are senior, gone forth long ago, the fathers of the Saṅgha, the leaders of the Saṅgha? Here, bhikkhus, towards the elder bhikkhus who are senior, gone forth long ago, the fathers of the Saṅgha, the leaders of the Saṅgha, he does not maintain bodily acts of loving-kindness in private and in public; he does not maintain verbal acts of loving-kindness... mental acts of loving-kindness in private and in public. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who does not pay special respect and reverence to the elder bhikkhus. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who lacks these eleven qualities cannot grow, prosper, and develop in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33" },

{ text: `'In the past, bhikkhus, in Magadha, there was a foolish cowherd. At the end of the rainy season, during the harvest, without inspecting the near bank of the Ganges river, without inspecting the far bank of the Ganges river, he drove the herd across to the other shore at Suvideha, at an unsafe ford. Bhikkhus, the cows crowded together in mid-stream and met with disaster there. Why was that? Because the cowherd in Magadha was foolish, at the end of the rainy season, during the harvest, without inspecting the near bank, without inspecting the far bank, he drove the herd across to the other shore at Suvideha, at an unsafe ford. So too, bhikkhus, there are samaṇas or brahmins who do not know this world well, do not know the next world well, do not know Māra's realm well, do not know the non-Māra realm well, do not know the realm of death well, do not know the non-death realm well. Those who think that they should listen to and believe these persons will meet with long-term harm and suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 34 – Cūḷagopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn34" },

{ text: `'In the past, bhikkhus, in Magadha, there was a wise cowherd. At the end of the rainy season, during the harvest, after inspecting the near bank of the Ganges river, after inspecting the far bank, he drove the herd across to the other shore at Suvideha, at a safe ford. He first drove across the old bullocks, the leaders of the herd. These, having crossed the Ganges, reached the far shore safely. Then he drove across the strong, well-trained bullocks. These, having crossed, reached the far shore safely. Then he drove across the young bullocks and the young heifers. These, having crossed, reached the far shore safely. Then he drove across the small calves and the sucklings. These, having crossed, reached the far shore safely. Even a newly born calf, following its mother, crying as it ran, also crossed the Ganges and reached the far shore safely. Why was that? Because the cowherd in Magadha was wise, at the end of the rainy season, during the harvest, after inspecting the near bank, after inspecting the far bank, he drove the herd across to the other shore at Suvideha, at a safe ford. So too, bhikkhus, there are samaṇas or brahmins who know this world well, know the next world well, know Māra's realm well, know the non-Māra realm well, know the realm of death well, know the non-death realm well. Those who think that they should listen to and believe these persons will have long-term happiness and welfare.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 34 – Cūḷagopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn34" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as the old bullocks, the leaders of the herd, having crossed the Ganges, reached the far shore safely, so too, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus who are Arahants, with taints destroyed, who have lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge — these, having crossed the river of Māra, have reached the far shore safely. Bhikkhus, just as the strong, well-trained bullocks crossed and reached safety, so too, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus who, with the destruction of the five lower fetters, are reborn spontaneously (in the Pure Abodes) and attain Nibbāna there, without returning from that world — these, having crossed the river of Māra, have reached the far shore safely. Just as the young bullocks and young heifers crossed and reached safety, so too, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus who, with the destruction of three fetters and the reduction of greed, hatred, and delusion, have become once-returners, returning to this world once more to make an end of suffering — these, having crossed the river of Māra, have reached the far shore safely. Just as the small calves and sucklings crossed and reached safety, so too, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus who, with the destruction of three fetters, have become stream-enterers, no longer subject to falling into lower realms, bound for enlightenment — these, having crossed the river of Māra, have reached the far shore safely. Just as the newly born calf, following its mother, crying as it ran, also crossed and reached safety, so too, bhikkhus, those who practice in conformity with the Dhamma, who practice out of faith — these, having crossed the river of Māra, have reached the far shore safely. Bhikkhus, I know this world well, I know the next world well, I know Māra's realm well, I know the non-Māra realm well, I know the realm of death well, I know the non-death realm well. Those who think that they should listen to and believe me will have long-term happiness and welfare.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 34 – Cūḷagopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn34" },

{ text: `This world and the next,<br>The Wise One has well explained,<br>Knowing Māra's realm,<br>Beyond the reach of Death."<br><br>The Perfectly Enlightened One, All-Knowing,<br>Knows all worlds,<br>The door to the Deathless is open,<br>Reached the security of Nibbāna.<br><br>The stream of Māra is cut,<br>Shattered and destroyed,<br>Therefore, bhikkhus,<br>Live with abundant joy,<br>Attain the security of Nibbāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 34 – Cūḷagopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn34" },

{ text: `Aggivessana, what do you think? As you say: 'Form is my self,' do you have any power over that form, can you say: 'Let my form be thus, let my form not be thus'?" — "No, Master Gotama." — "Aggivessana, what do you think? Is form permanent or impermanent?" — "Impermanent, Master Gotama." — "What is impermanent, is that suffering or happiness?" — "Suffering, Master Gotama." — "What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change, is it fitting to regard it as: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Master Gotama." — "Aggivessana, what do you think? Feeling... perception... formations... consciousness — is it permanent or impermanent?" — "Impermanent, Master Gotama." — "What is impermanent, is that suffering or happiness?" — "Suffering, Master Gotama." — "What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change, is it fitting to regard it as: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Master Gotama." — "Aggivessana, what do you think? One who is attached to suffering, clings to suffering, infatuated with suffering, regards suffering as 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self' — can that person fully understand suffering or live to abandon suffering?" — "How could that be, Master Gotama?" — "Aggivessana, what do you think? Is it not that you are attached to suffering, clinging to suffering, infatuated with suffering, regarding suffering as 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "That cannot be, Master Gotama." — "Aggivessana, just as a person needing heartwood, searching for heartwood, going here and there in search of heartwood, takes a sharp axe and enters a forest. There he might see a large, straight, young plantain tree without joints. He cuts it at the base, then starts peeling the sheaths. As he peels, he does not even find sapwood, let alone heartwood. So too, Aggivessana, when questioned, cross-questioned, and interrogated by me about your own words, you have turned out to be empty, hollow, and mistaken.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 35 – Cūḷasaccakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn35" },

{ text: `Aggivessana, what is the untrained body and what is the untrained mind? Here, Aggivessana, an unlearned ordinary person experiences a pleasant feeling. Experiencing a pleasant feeling, he becomes attached to that pleasant feeling and falls into attachment to it. If that pleasant feeling ceases, with the cessation of the pleasant feeling, a painful feeling arises. Experiencing that painful feeling, he sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes confused. Aggivessana, that pleasant feeling that arose for that person invades his mind and remains — because the body is untrained. That painful feeling that arose invades his mind and remains — because the mind is untrained. Aggivessana, in whatever person, both ways, a pleasant feeling arises, invades the mind and remains — because the body is untrained; a painful feeling arises, invades the mind and remains — because the mind is untrained. Thus, Aggivessana, that person is one with an untrained body and an untrained mind.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 36 – Mahāsaccakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn36" },

{ text: `And, Aggivessana, what is the trained body and what is the trained mind? Here, Aggivessana, a learned noble disciple experiences a pleasant feeling. Experiencing a pleasant feeling, he is not attached to that pleasant feeling, does not fall into attachment to it. If that pleasant feeling ceases, with the cessation of the pleasant feeling, a painful feeling arises. Experiencing that painful feeling, he does not sorrow, grieve, lament, beat his breast, or become confused. Aggivessana, that pleasant feeling that arose for that person does not invade his mind and does not remain — because the body is trained. That painful feeling that arose for that person does not invade his mind and does not remain — because the mind is trained. Aggivessana, in whatever person, both ways, a pleasant feeling arises, does not invade the mind and does not remain — because the body is trained; a painful feeling arises, does not invade the mind and does not remain — because the mind is trained. Thus, Aggivessana, that person is one with a trained body and a trained mind.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 36 – Mahāsaccakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn36" },

{ text: `Lord of devas, if a bhikkhu hears: 'It is not fitting to be biased towards any states,' he fully knows all states. Having fully known all states, he finally knows all states. Because he finally knows all states, if any feeling arises — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he dwells contemplating impermanence in those feelings, dwelling contemplating dispassion, dwelling contemplating cessation, dwelling contemplating relinquishment. Dwelling thus, he does not cling to anything in the world; not clinging, he is not agitated; not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.' Lord of devas, in brief, to this extent a bhikkhu has the liberation through the destruction of craving, the ultimate attainment, the ultimate security from bondage, the ultimate holy life, the ultimate perfection, the foremost among devas and humans.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 37 – Cūḷataṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn37" },

{ text: `Sāti, is it true that the following evil wrong view has arisen in you: 'As I understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, it is this same consciousness that runs and wanders through the round of rebirths, not another'?" — "Indeed, Venerable Sir. As I understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, it is this same consciousness that runs and wanders through the round of rebirths, not another." — "Sāti, what is that consciousness?" — "Venerable Sir, it is this consciousness that speaks, feels, and experiences here and there the results of good and bad actions." — "Foolish man, from whom have you understood the Dhamma taught by me in this way? Foolish man, have I not stated in many ways that consciousness is dependently arisen, that without a condition there is no arising of consciousness? And, foolish man, not only do you misrepresent me by your wrong grasp, but you also destroy yourself and accumulate much demerit. This will lead to your long-term harm and suffering, foolish man.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 38 – Mahātaṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn38" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, dependent on a condition, fire arises, and the fire is named according to that condition. Dependent on sticks, fire arises, and it is called a stick-fire. Dependent on wood-chips, fire arises, and it is called a wood-chip-fire. Dependent on grass, fire arises, and it is called a grass-fire. Dependent on cow-dung, fire arises, and it is called a cow-dung-fire. Dependent on chaff, fire arises, and it is called a chaff-fire. Dependent on rubbish, fire arises, and it is called a rubbish-fire. So too, bhikkhus, dependent on a condition, consciousness arises, and it is named according to that condition. Dependent on the eye and forms, consciousness arises, and it is called eye-consciousness. Dependent on the ear and sounds, consciousness arises, and it is called ear-consciousness. Dependent on the nose and odors, consciousness arises, and it is called nose-consciousness. Dependent on the tongue and flavors, consciousness arises, and it is called tongue-consciousness. Dependent on the body and tangibles, consciousness arises, and it is called body-consciousness. Dependent on the mind and mental objects, consciousness arises, and it is called mind-consciousness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 38 – Mahātaṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn38" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when a child grows up and his faculties mature, he enjoys the full range of the five strands of sensual pleasure — forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, stimulating sensual desire, enticing; sounds... odors... flavors... tangibles... When he sees a form with the eye, he lusts after a pleasant form and dislikes a disagreeable form; he dwells without mindfulness of the body, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom, where those evil, unwholesome states cease without remainder. Thus, for him, with regard to bodily contact, whatever feeling arises — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he rejoices in that feeling, welcomes it, and remains attached to it. Because he rejoices, welcomes, and is attached to that feeling, delight arises. Having delight in those feelings, he is attached. With attachment as condition, existence arises; with existence as condition, birth arises; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 38 – Mahātaṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn38" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if, regarding this view thus purified and clarified, you cling to it, are elated by it, pursue it, and regard it as 'mine', would you then understand the simile of the raft, that the Dhamma is taught for crossing over, not for grasping?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "But, bhikkhus, if, regarding this view thus purified and clarified, you do not cling to it, are not elated by it, do not pursue it, do not regard it as 'mine', would you then understand the simile of the raft, that the Dhamma is taught for crossing over, not for grasping?" — "Yes, Venerable Sir.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 38 – Mahātaṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn38" },

{ text: `'Samaṇa! Samaṇa!' That is how people know you, bhikkhus. And if they ask you: 'Who are you?', you should identify yourselves: 'We are samaṇas.' Bhikkhus, you have such a designation, you have such a self-identification. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'We will practice those things that are proper to a samaṇa. Then our designation will be true and our self-identification correct. And the offerings we use — robes, almsfood, lodgings, medicines — will bring us great fruit and great benefit. And our going forth will not be in vain, but fruitful and successful.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 40 – Cūḷaassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu not practice the things proper to a samaṇa? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has a mind of covetous desire, and that covetous desire is not abandoned; he has a mind of ill-will, and that ill-will is not abandoned; he has a mind of anger, and that anger is not abandoned; he has a mind of resentment, and that resentment is not abandoned; he has a mind of hypocrisy, and that hypocrisy is not abandoned; he has a mind of malice, and that malice is not abandoned; he has a mind of envy, and that envy is not abandoned; he has a mind of stinginess, and that stinginess is not abandoned; he has a mind of deceit, and that deceit is not abandoned; he has a mind of fraud, and that fraud is not abandoned; he has a mind of craving, and that craving is not abandoned; he has wrong view, and that wrong view is not abandoned. Bhikkhus, I say that if he does not practice what is proper to a samaṇa, he cannot abandon the defilements of a samaṇa, the blemishes of a samaṇa, the faults of a samaṇa, the falling into a lower realm, and the suffering of bad destinations. Bhikkhus, just as a dangerous weapon called a mataja, with two very sharp edges, can be wrapped and put in a sheath. So too, bhikkhus, I say that such a bhikkhu's going forth is like that.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 40 – Cūḷaassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu practice the things proper to a samaṇa? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has a mind of covetous desire, but that covetous desire is abandoned; he has a mind of ill-will, and that ill-will is abandoned; he has a mind of anger, and that anger is abandoned; he has a mind of resentment, and that resentment is abandoned; he has a mind of hypocrisy, and that hypocrisy is abandoned; he has a mind of malice, and that malice is abandoned; he has a mind of envy, and that envy is abandoned; he has a mind of stinginess, and that stinginess is abandoned; he has a mind of deceit, and that deceit is abandoned; he has a mind of fraud, and that fraud is abandoned; he has a mind of craving, and that craving is abandoned; he has wrong view, and that wrong view is abandoned... Bhikkhus, I say that if he practices what is proper to a samaṇa, he can abandon the defilements of a samaṇa, the blemishes of a samaṇa, the faults of a samaṇa, the falling into a lower realm, and the suffering of bad destinations. He sees himself purified of all evil, unwholesome states, and sees himself liberated. Seeing himself purified and liberated, gladness arises; from gladness, rapture arises; from rapture, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he experiences happiness; with happiness, the mind becomes concentrated. I say that it is through this inner concentration that he practices the things proper to a samaṇa.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 40 – Cūḷaassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu practice the things proper to a samaṇa? He abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness... compassion... altruistic joy... equanimity, likewise the second, likewise the third, likewise the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with equanimity, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Bhikkhus, just as a lotus pond with clear, sweet, cool, limpid water, with beautifully arranged banks, is delightful — if a person comes from the east, overcome and afflicted by heat, exhausted, parched, and thirsty, and goes to that pond, he would quench his thirst and cool his heat... if a person comes from the west... from the north... from the south... from anywhere, overcome by heat, afflicted, exhausted, parched, and thirsty, and goes to that pond, he would quench his thirst and cool his heat. So too, bhikkhus, if a person from the noble warrior caste goes forth from home to homelessness and comes to the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, and having developed loving-kindness, compassion, altruistic joy, and equanimity, attains inner concentration — I say that through this inner concentration he practices the things proper to a samaṇa.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 40 – Cūḷaassapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn40" },

{ text: `'Friend, what is the meaning of wisdom?' — 'Friend, wisdom has the meaning of direct knowledge (abhiññatthā), the meaning of full understanding (pariññatthā), the meaning of abandoning (pahānatthā).' — 'Friend, how many conditions are there for the arising of right view?' — 'Friend, there are two conditions for the arising of right view: the voice of another and wise attention. Friend, dependent on these two conditions, right view arises.' — 'Friend, by how many factors must right view be supported to have the fruit of liberation of mind, the benefit of the fruit of liberation of mind, and the fruit of liberation by wisdom, the benefit of the fruit of liberation by wisdom?' — 'Friend, right view must be supported by five factors to have the fruit of liberation of mind, the benefit of the fruit of liberation of mind, and the fruit of liberation by wisdom, the benefit of the fruit of liberation by wisdom. Here, friend, right view is supported by virtue, supported by learning, supported by discussion, supported by tranquility, supported by insight. Friend, right view supported by these five factors has the fruit of liberation of mind, the benefit of the fruit of liberation of mind, and the fruit of liberation by wisdom, the benefit of the fruit of liberation by wisdom.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Friend, how does future rebirth occur?' — 'Friend, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving, beings delight in this and that — thus future rebirth occurs.' — 'Friend, how does future rebirth not occur?' — 'Friend, with the relinquishment of ignorance, with the arising of knowledge, with the destruction of craving — thus future rebirth does not occur.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Friend, what is the first jhāna?' — 'Here, friend, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. That, friend, is called the first jhāna.' — 'Friend, how many factors does the first jhāna have?' — 'Friend, the first jhāna has five factors. Here, friend, a bhikkhu who has attained the first jhāna possesses initial thought, sustained thought, rapture, happiness, and one-pointedness of mind. Thus, friend, the first jhāna has five factors.' — 'Friend, how many factors does the first jhāna abandon and how many does it possess?' — 'Friend, the first jhāna abandons five factors and possesses five factors. Here, friend, a bhikkhu who has attained the first jhāna abandons covetous desire, abandons ill-will, abandons sloth and torpor, abandons restlessness and remorse, abandons doubt, and possesses initial thought, sustained thought, rapture, happiness, and one-pointedness of mind. Thus, friend, the first jhāna abandons five factors and possesses five factors.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Friend, these five faculties have different domains, different ranges, and they do not experience one another's domain and range. That is, the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body. Friend, since these five faculties have different domains, different ranges, and do not experience one another's domain and range, what is their support, and what experiences their domain and range?' — 'Friend, these five faculties have different domains, different ranges, and they do not experience one another's domain and range, namely, the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body. Friend, among these five faculties, the mind is their support, and the mind experiences their domain and range.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Friend, dependent on what do these five faculties remain?' — 'Friend, these five faculties — eye, ear, nose, tongue, body — remain dependent on vitality (āyu).' — 'Friend, dependent on what does vitality remain?' — 'Vitality remains dependent on heat.' — 'Friend, dependent on what does heat remain?' — 'Heat remains dependent on vitality.' — 'Friend, just now we understood from the Venerable Sāriputta's statement that "vitality remains dependent on heat," and then we understood from his statement that "heat remains dependent on vitality." Friend, how should the meaning of this statement be understood?' — 'Friend, I will give you a simile. Through a simile, some intelligent people here will understand the meaning. Friend, just as when an oil lamp burns, dependent on the wick, the light is seen, and dependent on the light, the wick is seen. So too, friend, vitality remains dependent on heat, and heat remains dependent on vitality.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Friend, when how many things are abandoned from this body does it lie discarded, thrown away, abandoned like a senseless log?' — 'Friend, when three things are abandoned from this body — vitality, heat, and consciousness — then it lies discarded, thrown away, abandoned like a senseless log.' — 'Friend, what is the difference between a dead, deceased person and a bhikkhu who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling?' — 'Friend, in the case of a dead, deceased person, his bodily formation has ceased and subsided, his verbal formation has ceased and subsided, his mental formation has ceased and subsided; his vitality is exhausted, his heat has been extinguished, and his faculties are completely destroyed. But in the case of a bhikkhu who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, his bodily formation has ceased and subsided, his verbal formation has ceased and subsided, his mental formation has ceased and subsided; but his vitality is not exhausted, his heat is not extinguished, and his faculties are clear. Friend, this is the difference between a dead, deceased person and a bhikkhu who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, what is identity view?' — 'Here, friend Visākha, an unlearned ordinary person, who has not seen the noble ones, is not skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, not trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who has not seen the true persons, is not skilled in the teaching of the true persons, not trained in the teaching of the true persons — regards form as self, or self as possessing form, or form as in self, or self as in form; regards feeling as self... perception as self... formations as self... consciousness as self, or self as possessing consciousness, or consciousness as in self, or self as in consciousness. That, friend Visākha, is identity view.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, what is concentration, what are the signs of concentration, what are the requisites of concentration, what is the development of concentration?' — 'Friend Visākha, one-pointedness of mind is concentration; the Four Foundations of Mindfulness are the signs of concentration; the Four Right Efforts are the requisites of concentration; the repetition, development, and cultivation of these things are the development of concentration here.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, what is bodily formation, what is verbal formation, what is mental formation?' — 'In-breath and out-breath, friend Visākha, are bodily formation; initial and sustained thought are verbal formation; perception and feeling are mental formation.' — 'Venerable Nun, why are in-breath and out-breath bodily formation? Why are initial and sustained thought verbal formation? Why are perception and feeling mental formation?' — 'In-breath and out-breath, friend Visākha, are bodily; they are bound up with the body, so in-breath and out-breath are bodily formation. Friend Visākha, one first directs one's thoughts and sustains them, and then afterwards one breaks into speech; therefore initial and sustained thought are verbal formation. Perception and feeling are mental; they are bound up with the mind, so perception and feeling are mental formation.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, how many feelings are there?' — 'Friend Visākha, there are these three feelings: pleasant feeling, painful feeling, and neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is pleasant feeling, what is painful feeling, what is neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, whatever is felt physically or mentally as pleasant and agreeable — that is pleasant feeling. Whatever is felt physically or mentally as painful and disagreeable — that is painful feeling. Whatever is felt physically or mentally as neither painful nor agreeable — that is neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, with regard to pleasant feeling, what is pleasant and what is painful? With regard to painful feeling, what is painful and what is pleasant? With regard to neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, what is pleasant and what is painful?' — 'Friend Visākha, with regard to pleasant feeling, its presence is pleasant, its change is painful. With regard to painful feeling, its presence is painful, its change is pleasant. With regard to neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, knowledge of it is pleasant, ignorance of it is painful.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, in pleasant feeling, what underlying tendency (anusaya) persists? In painful feeling, what underlying tendency persists? In neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, what underlying tendency persists?' — 'Friend Visākha, in pleasant feeling, the underlying tendency to lust persists; in painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion persists; in neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, the underlying tendency to ignorance persists.' — 'Venerable Nun, does the underlying tendency to lust persist in all pleasant feeling? Does the underlying tendency to aversion persist in all painful feeling? Does the underlying tendency to ignorance persist in all neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, it is not that the underlying tendency to lust persists in all pleasant feeling, nor that the underlying tendency to aversion persists in all painful feeling, nor that the underlying tendency to ignorance persists in all neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, in pleasant feeling, what should be abandoned? In painful feeling, what should be abandoned? In neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, what should be abandoned?' — 'Friend Visākha, in pleasant feeling, the underlying tendency to lust should be abandoned; in painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion should be abandoned; in neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, the underlying tendency to ignorance should be abandoned.' — 'Venerable Nun, should the underlying tendency to lust be abandoned in all pleasant feeling? Should the underlying tendency to aversion be abandoned in all painful feeling? Should the underlying tendency to ignorance be abandoned in all neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, it is not that the underlying tendency to lust should be abandoned in all pleasant feeling, nor that the underlying tendency to aversion should be abandoned in all painful feeling, nor that the underlying tendency to ignorance should be abandoned in all neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of pleasant feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, painful feeling is the counterpart of pleasant feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of painful feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, pleasant feeling is the counterpart of painful feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling?' — 'Friend Visākha, ignorance is the counterpart of neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of ignorance?' — 'Friend Visākha, knowledge is the counterpart of ignorance.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of knowledge?' — 'Friend Visākha, liberation is the counterpart of knowledge.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of liberation?' — 'Friend Visākha, Nibbāna is the counterpart of liberation.' — 'Venerable Nun, what is the counterpart of Nibbāna?' — 'Friend Visākha, your question goes too far, beyond the limit of an answer. Friend Visākha, the holy life is grounded in Nibbāna, culminates in Nibbāna, and ends in Nibbāna.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 44 – Cūḷavedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn44" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is pleasant in the present but has a painful result in the future? Bhikkhus, some samaṇas hold such a view, such a doctrine: 'There is no fault in sensual pleasures.' They indulge in sensual pleasures. After indulging, with the breakup of the body, after death, they are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. There they experience painful, severe, harsh feelings. They say: 'Those samaṇas and brahmins see future fear in sensual pleasures and speak of the abandonment of sensual pleasures, proclaiming knowledge of sensual pleasures. Yet, because of these very sensual pleasures, as a cause, as a condition, we are experiencing painful, severe, harsh feelings.' Bhikkhus, this is called a course of practice that is pleasant in the present but has a painful result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 45 – Cūḷadhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn45" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is painful in the present but has a pleasant result in the future? Here, bhikkhus, a person is by nature strongly affected by lust, and he constantly experiences painful and sorrowful feelings due to lust. He is by nature strongly affected by hatred, and he constantly experiences painful and sorrowful feelings due to hatred. He is by nature strongly affected by delusion, and he constantly experiences painful and sorrowful feelings due to delusion. With pain and sorrow, with tearful face and crying, he lives the holy life completely perfect and pure. With the breakup of the body, after death, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Thus, bhikkhus, is called a course of practice that is painful in the present but has a pleasant result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 45 – Cūḷadhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn45" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is pleasant in the present and also has a pleasant result in the future? Here, bhikkhus, a person is not by nature strongly affected by lust, and he does not constantly experience painful and sorrowful feelings due to lust. He is not by nature strongly affected by hatred... not by nature strongly affected by delusion, and he does not constantly experience painful and sorrowful feelings due to delusion. Secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, he enters and abides in the first jhāna... the second jhāna... the third jhāna... the fourth jhāna. With the breakup of the body, after death, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Thus, bhikkhus, is called a course of practice that is pleasant in the present and also has a pleasant result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 45 – Cūḷadhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn45" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a bitter gourd mixed with poison. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, and loathes suffering. Someone says to him: 'Friend, this bitter gourd is mixed with poison. If you wish, eat it. While eating, you will not enjoy its color, smell, or taste. After eating, you may die or suffer deadly pain.' He might eat it without reflection, without giving it up. While eating, he does not enjoy its color, smell, or taste. After eating, he dies or suffers deadly pain. Bhikkhus, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — that is, a course of practice that is painful in the present and also has a painful result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a bronze cup of drinking water with a color, a smell, and a taste, and that water is mixed with poison. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, and loathes suffering. Someone says to him: 'Friend, this bronze cup of water has a color, a smell, and a taste, and the water is mixed with poison. If you wish, drink it. While drinking, you will enjoy its color, smell, and taste. After drinking, you may die or suffer deadly pain.' He might drink it without reflection, without giving it up. While drinking, he enjoys its color, smell, and taste. After drinking, he may die or suffer deadly pain. Bhikkhus, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — that is, a course of practice that is pleasant in the present but has a painful result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as urine mixed with various medicines. Then a person comes who is afflicted with jaundice. Someone says to him: 'Friend, this urine is mixed with various medicines. If you wish, drink it. While drinking, you will not enjoy its color, smell, or taste. But after drinking, you will be at ease.' He might drink it after reflection, without giving it up. While drinking, he does not enjoy its color, smell, or taste. But after drinking, he is at ease. Bhikkhus, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — that is, a course of practice that is painful in the present but has a pleasant result in the future.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as a hungry, weak dog comes to a butcher's shop. There a skilled butcher or his apprentice throws it a bone that has been well scraped, completely scraped, without meat, only smeared with blood. Householder, what do you think? Would that dog, by gnawing on that bone that has been well scraped, completely scraped, without meat, only smeared with blood, be able to dispel its hunger and weakness?' — 'No, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because that bone is well scraped, completely scraped, without meat, only smeared with blood; that dog would only get wearisome trouble.' — 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a bone; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as a vulture, a kite, or a hawk, having snatched a piece of meat, flies up. Other vultures, kites, or hawks fly after it, chasing it, tearing at it, and tearing that piece of meat apart. Householder, what do you think? If that vulture, kite, or hawk does not immediately let go of that piece of meat, would it, on that account, meet death or deadly pain?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' ... 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a piece of meat; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as a person carries a blazing grass torch and walks against the wind. Householder, what do you think? If that person does not immediately throw away that blazing grass torch, would that blazing grass torch burn his hand, his arm, or some part of his body, and would he, on that account, meet death or deadly pain?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' ... 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a grass torch; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as a pit of glowing embers, deeper than a man's height, filled with glowing embers that are flameless and smokeless. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, and loathes suffering. Two strong men grab him by both arms and drag him towards that pit of embers. Householder, what do you think? Would that person twist his body this way and that?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because he knows: "If I fall into this pit of embers, on that account I will meet death or deadly pain."' — 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a pit of embers; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as a person borrows goods — a magnificent vehicle, beautiful jeweled ornaments — and with those borrowed goods he goes to the market, goes ahead, is surrounded by many people, and the crowd seeing him says: "This person is truly wealthy; a wealthy person enjoys such goods." But the owners, wherever they see him, take back their property. Householder, what do you think? Has that person's display of being otherwise come to an end?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because the owners take back their property.' ... 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like borrowed goods; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `'Householder, just as near a village or market town there is a grove, and in it a tree laden with ripe fruits, but no fruit has fallen to the ground. A person comes wishing for fruit, seeking fruit, wandering about in search of fruit. He enters that grove and sees that tree laden with ripe fruits. He might think: "This tree is laden with ripe fruits, but no fruit has fallen. I know how to climb a tree. Let me climb this tree, eat as much as I want, and fill my clothes." He climbs the tree, eats as much as he wants, and fills his clothes. Then a second person comes, wishing for fruit, seeking fruit, wandering about in search of fruit, and he carries a sharp axe. He enters that grove and sees that tree laden with ripe fruits. He might think: "This tree is laden with ripe fruits, but no fruit has fallen. I do not know how to climb a tree. Let me cut this tree down at the root, eat as much as I want, and fill my clothes." He cuts it down at the root. Householder, what do you think? If that first person does not climb down quickly, when that tree falls, would it break his hand, his foot, or some part of his body, and would he, on that account, meet death or deadly pain?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' — 'So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: "The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a fruit tree; they provide much suffering, much distress, and the danger in them is even greater." Seeing this thus as it actually is with right wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, having devoted himself to the equanimity based on unity, where all clinging to the world's goods is completely cut off without remainder, he develops that equanimity.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54" },

{ text: `Here, Jīvaka, a bhikkhu lives in dependence on some village or town. He abides pervading one direction with a mind of loving-kindness; likewise the second, the third, and the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. A householder or a householder's son comes to that bhikkhu and invites him for the next day's meal. And, Jīvaka, that bhikkhu accepts. When the night has passed, in the morning, the bhikkhu puts on his robe, takes his bowl, and goes to that householder's or householder's son's place. Having arrived, he sits down on the prepared seat. And that householder or householder's son serves him with excellent almsfood. That bhikkhu does not think: 'How good it is that this householder or householder's son serves me with such excellent almsfood! May this householder or householder's son serve me with such excellent almsfood in the future!' He does not think thus. He uses that almsfood without being attached, infatuated, or obsessed, seeing the danger and understanding the escape. Jīvaka, what do you think? At that time, does that bhikkhu intend his own harm, or the harm of others, or the harm of both?' — 'No, Venerable Sir.' — 'Jīvaka, does that bhikkhu at that time use that food blamelessly?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir. Venerable Sir, I have heard: "Sublime is the abiding in loving-kindness!" Venerable Sir, the Blessed One has personally shown me this point. Venerable Sir, the Blessed One abides in loving-kindness.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 55 – Jīvakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn55" },

{ text: `'Jīvaka, one who, for the sake of the Tathāgata or a disciple of the Tathāgata, kills a living being, accumulates much demerit for five reasons. When he says: "Go and bring that animal," that is the first reason for accumulating much demerit. When that animal is led, it experiences suffering and distress because it is pulled by the neck — that is the second reason for accumulating much demerit. When he says: "Go and kill that animal," that is the third reason for accumulating much demerit. When that animal is killed, it experiences suffering and distress — that is the fourth reason for accumulating much demerit. When he makes an offering to the Tathāgata or his disciple in an improper way, that is the fifth reason for accumulating much demerit. Jīvaka, one who, for the sake of the Tathāgata or a disciple of the Tathāgata, kills a living being, accumulates much demerit for these five reasons.'" When this was said, Jīvaka Komārabhacca said to the Blessed One: "Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Marvelous, Venerable Sir! Venerable Sir, the bhikkhus indeed use food lawfully. Venerable Sir, the bhikkhus indeed use food blamelessly. Wonderful, Venerable Sir! Wonderful, Venerable Sir! May the Blessed One accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 55 – Jīvakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn55" },

{ text: `The wise one, clear-seeing,<br>Has abandoned all delusion,<br>Destroyed all thickets,<br>Conquered all enemies,<br>Suffering has ceased,<br>Mind is peaceful and calm,<br>Perfect in virtue, wisdom, and conduct,<br>The one who has crossed over, steadfast,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Doubt is cut off,<br>Contented, satisfied,<br>Freed from the world, joyful mind,<br>Born among humans,<br>Living the samaṇa life,<br>Living the final life,<br>Supreme and steadfast,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Without doubt, skillful,<br>Tamed, unsurpassed trainer,<br>Supreme, radiant,<br>Hero, abandoned conceit,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>The bull of a man, immeasurable,<br>Knowledge truly deep,<br>Wisdom and restraint,<br>Controlled, abiding in Dhamma,<br>Gone beyond attachment,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Noble one, ascetic,<br>Fetters have been cut,<br>Pure, eloquent,<br>Lowered the banner, free from sensual desire,<br>Tamed and restrained,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Marvelous one, upright,<br>Holy one, realized the three knowledges,<br>Pure, master of words,<br>Attained final knowledge, peaceful,<br>Protected by Sakka before,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Self-enlightened,<br>Realized, teaches,<br>Mindful, meditative,<br>One who neither advances nor retreats,<br>Skillful, imperturbable,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Supreme in jhāna,<br>Mind without defilement,<br>Solitary, fearless,<br>Secluded, attained the supreme,<br>Crossed over, helps others cross,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Peaceful, deep wisdom,<br>Great wisdom and free from hatred,<br>Realized the truth,<br>Without equal, incomparable,<br>Skillful and confident,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.<br><br>Abandoned craving, wakeful,<br>Pure, abandoned hatred,<br>Worthy of offerings,<br>Supreme, without equal,<br>Great, of supreme fame,<br>I am a disciple of the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 56 – Upālisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn56" },

{ text: `'Householder, for a long time your family has been like a wellspring for the Nigaṇṭhas. Give food to those who come to you.' — 'Venerable Sir, I am doubly pleased and satisfied with the words the Blessed One has spoken to me: "Householder, for a long time your family has been like a wellspring for the Nigaṇṭhas. Give food to those who come to you." Venerable Sir, I have heard: "Samaṇa Gotama says: 'Give only to me, not to others. Give only to my disciples, not to the disciples of others. Only giving to me yields great fruit; giving to others does not yield great fruit. Only giving to my disciples yields great fruit; giving to the disciples of others does not yield great fruit.'" Yet the Blessed One encourages me to give to the Nigaṇṭhas. Venerable Sir, we will know the proper time to act.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 56 – Upālisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn56" },

{ text: `And, Puṇṇa, what is dark action with a dark result? Here, Puṇṇa, a person performs a harmful bodily formation, a harmful verbal formation, a harmful mental formation. Having performed a harmful bodily formation, a harmful verbal formation, a harmful mental formation, he is reborn in a harmful world. Being reborn in a harmful world, harmful contacts touch him. Touched by harmful contacts, he experiences harmful feelings, exclusively painful feelings, like beings in hell. Thus, Puṇṇa, the arising of a being depends on the being; the being arises depending on his action; and once arisen, contacts touch him. Therefore, Puṇṇa, I say: 'Beings are heirs of their actions.' This, Puṇṇa, is called dark action with a dark result.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 57 – Kukkuravatikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn57" },

{ text: `And, Puṇṇa, what is bright action with a bright result? Here, Puṇṇa, a person performs a non-harmful bodily formation, a non-harmful verbal formation, a non-harmful mental formation. Having performed a non-harmful bodily formation, a non-harmful verbal formation, a non-harmful mental formation, he is reborn in a non-harmful world. Being reborn in a non-harmful world, non-harmful contacts touch him. Touched by non-harmful contacts, he experiences non-harmful feelings, exclusively pleasant feelings, like the Subhakiṇha devas. Thus, Puṇṇa, the arising of a being depends on the being; the being arises depending on his action; and once arisen, contacts touch him. Therefore, Puṇṇa, I say: 'Beings are heirs of their actions.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 57 – Kukkuravatikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn57" },

{ text: `And, Puṇṇa, what is dark-and-bright action with a dark-and-bright result? Here, Puṇṇa, a person performs bodily formations that are both harmful and non-harmful, verbal formations that are both harmful and non-harmful, mental formations that are both harmful and non-harmful. Having performed such formations, he is reborn in a world that is both harmful and non-harmful. Being reborn there, contacts that are both harmful and non-harmful touch him. Touched by them, he experiences feelings that are both harmful and non-harmful, a mixture of pleasant and painful feelings, like some humans, some devas, and some beings in the lower realms. Thus, Puṇṇa, the arising of a being depends on the being; the being arises depending on his action; and once arisen, contacts touch him. Therefore, Puṇṇa, I say: 'Beings are heirs of their actions.' This, Puṇṇa, is called dark-and-bright action with a dark-and-bright result.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 57 – Kukkuravatikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn57" },

{ text: `And, Puṇṇa, what is neither-dark-nor-bright action with a neither-dark-nor-bright result, action leading to the cessation of action? Here, Puṇṇa, the volition (cetanā) that abandons dark action with its dark result, the volition that abandons bright action with its bright result, the volition that abandons dark-and-bright action with its dark-and-bright result — this, Puṇṇa, is called neither-dark-nor-bright action with a neither-dark-nor-bright result, action leading to the cessation of action. Puṇṇa, these four kinds of action have been directly known, realized, and proclaimed by me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 57 – Kukkuravatikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn57" },

{ text: `At that time, a young infant lay on Prince Abhaya's lap. Then the Blessed One said to Prince Abhaya: 'Prince, what do you think? If this infant, through your negligence or the nurse's negligence, were to put a stick or a pebble into its mouth, what would you do?' — 'Venerable Sir, I would take it out. If I could not take it out immediately, with my left hand I would hold its head, and with my right hand I would use my finger as a hook and take it out, even if it made it bleed. Why is that? Because I have compassion for the child.' — 'So too, prince, when the Tathāgata knows that a statement is untrue, false, and unbeneficial, and it is also disagreeable and displeasing to others, he does not speak that statement. When he knows that a statement is true and real but unbeneficial, and it is also disagreeable and displeasing to others, he does not speak that statement. When he knows that a statement is true and real and beneficial, but it is disagreeable and displeasing to others, he knows the time to speak that statement. When he knows that a statement is untrue, false, and unbeneficial, but it is agreeable and pleasing to others, he does not speak that statement. When he knows that a statement is true and real but unbeneficial, but it is agreeable and pleasing to others, he does not speak that statement. When he knows that a statement is true and real and beneficial, and it is also agreeable and pleasing to others, he knows the time to speak that statement. Why is that? Because the Tathāgata has compassion for beings.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 58 – Abhayarājakumārasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn58" },

{ text: `'Venerable Sir, these wise nobles, wise brahmins, wise householders, and wise samaṇas, having prepared a question, come to the Tathāgata and ask: "Venerable Sir, does the Blessed One pre-think in his mind: 'If someone comes to me and asks thus, I will answer thus'? Or does the Blessed One answer immediately?' — 'Prince, I will ask you a question. If it pleases you, answer it. Prince, what do you think? Are you skilled in the parts of a chariot?' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir, I am skilled in the parts of a chariot.' — 'Prince, what do you think? If people come to you and ask: "What is this part of the chariot called?" Do you pre-think: "If someone comes to me and asks, I will answer thus"? Or do you answer immediately?' — 'Venerable Sir, I am a well-known charioteer, very skilled in the parts of a chariot. I will answer immediately.' — 'So too, prince, those wise nobles, wise brahmins, wise householders, and wise samaṇas, having prepared a question, come to the Tathāgata and ask; the Tathāgata answers immediately. Why is that? Because the Dhamma-element (dhammadhātu) has been well penetrated by the Tathāgata. Because the Dhamma-element has been well penetrated, the Tathāgata answers immediately.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 58 – Abhayarājakumārasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn58" },

{ text: `Māluṅkyaputta, just as a man shot with a dart thickly smeared with poison. His friends and relatives summon a surgeon. But the man says: 'I will not have this dart removed until I know whether the man who shot me was a noble, a brahmin, a merchant, or a worker.' He might say: 'I will not have this dart removed until I know the name and clan of the man who shot me.' He might say: 'I will not have this dart removed until I know whether the man who shot me was tall, short, or of medium height.' He might say: 'I will not have this dart removed until I know whether the man who shot me was dark, tawny, or golden.' ... Māluṅkyaputta, that man would die and still not know these things. So too, Māluṅkyaputta, whoever says: 'I will not live the holy life under the Blessed One until he answers me: "The world is eternal" or "the world is not eternal" ... "the Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death" — that person will die and still not have had these things answered by the Tathāgata. Māluṅkyaputta, the holy life does not depend on the view that the world is eternal. The holy life does not depend on the view that the world is not eternal. Whether there is the view that the world is eternal or the view that the world is not eternal, there is still birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, and I teach their abandonment here and now.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 63 – Cūḷamālukyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn63" },

{ text: `Therefore, Māluṅkyaputta, remember what I have left unanswered as unanswered, and what I have answered as answered. And what, Māluṅkyaputta, have I left unanswered? 'The world is eternal' — I have left unanswered. 'The world is not eternal' — I have left unanswered. 'The world is finite' — I have left unanswered. 'The world is infinite' — I have left unanswered. 'The soul and the body are the same' — I have left unanswered. 'The soul and the body are different' — I have left unanswered. 'The Tathāgata exists after death' — I have left unanswered. 'The Tathāgata does not exist after death' — I have left unanswered. And why have I left these unanswered? Because they are not connected with the goal, they are not fundamental to the holy life, they do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore I have left them unanswered. And what, Māluṅkyaputta, have I answered? 'This is suffering' — I have answered. 'This is the origin of suffering' — I have answered. 'This is the cessation of suffering' — I have answered. 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering' — I have answered. And why have I answered these? Because they are connected with the goal, they are fundamental to the holy life, they lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore I have answered them.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 63 – Cūḷamālukyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn63" },

{ text: `'Ānanda, what is that noise, that uproar? It sounds like fishermen quarreling over fish.' — 'Venerable Sir, about five hundred bhikkhus, led by Sāriputta and Moggallāna, have arrived at Cātumā to see the Blessed One. And the newly arrived bhikkhus are greeting the resident bhikkhus. While seats are being prepared and bowls and robes are being put away, there is this noise and uproar.' — 'Then, Ānanda, go and tell those bhikkhus in my name: "The Teacher calls the venerable ones."' — 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' Venerable Ānanda went to those bhikkhus and said: 'The Teacher calls the venerable ones.' — 'Yes, friend.' Those bhikkhus went to the Blessed One, paid homage, and sat down to one side. The Blessed One said to them: 'Bhikkhus, do you think that this noise and uproar sounds like fishermen quarrelling over fish?' — 'Venerable Sir, about five hundred bhikkhus, led by Sāriputta and Moggallāna, have arrived at Cātumā to see the Blessed One. The newly arrived bhikkhus are greeting the resident bhikkhus. While seats are being prepared and bowls and robes are being put away, there is this noise and uproar.' — 'Go, bhikkhus. I dismiss you. Do not stay near me.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 67 – Cātumasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn67" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the fear of waves? Here, bhikkhus, a good man, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness. He reflects: 'I am oppressed by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, oppressed by suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, his fellow celibates instruct and admonish him: 'You should go out thus, you should return thus; you should look forward thus, you should look around thus; you should bend your arm thus, you should stretch your arm thus; you should wear your robe and carry your bowl thus.' He thinks: 'Before, when we were not yet gone forth, we instructed and admonished others. These people, who are like our children, like our grandchildren, think they need to instruct and admonish us!' He gives up the training and returns to the lower life. Thus, bhikkhus, this person gives up the training and returns to the lower life, and is called one who fears the fear of waves. Bhikkhus, 'fear of waves' is a synonym for irritation.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 67 – Cātumasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn67" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the fear of crocodiles? Here, bhikkhus, a good man, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness. He reflects: 'I am oppressed by birth... Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, his fellow celibates instruct and admonish him: 'You should chew this, you should not chew that; you should eat this, you should not eat that; you should taste this, you should not taste that; you should drink this, you should not drink that. What is allowed, you should chew; what is not allowed, you should not chew... At the proper time, you should chew; at the improper time, you should not chew...' He thinks: 'Before, when we were not yet gone forth, we chewed what we wanted, we did not chew what we didn't want... When faithful laypeople offer us excellent hard and soft foods, it seems as if those foods are being blocked at the mouth.' He gives up the training and returns to the lower life. Thus, bhikkhus, this person gives up the training and returns to the lower life, and is called one who fears the fear of crocodiles. Bhikkhus, 'fear of crocodiles' is a synonym for gluttony.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 67 – Cātumasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn67" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the fear of whirlpools? Here, bhikkhus, a good man, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness. He reflects: 'I am oppressed by birth... Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, in the morning he puts on his robe, takes his bowl, and enters the village or town for alms, without guarding his body, without guarding his speech, with mindfulness unestablished, without restraining his senses. There he sees a householder or a householder's son enjoying the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly, and he delights in that. He thinks: 'Before, when we were not yet gone forth, we enjoyed the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly and delighted in them. Since our family has wealth, we can both enjoy wealth and do meritorious deeds.' He gives up the training and returns to the lower life. Thus, bhikkhus, this person gives up the training and returns to the lower life, and is called one who fears the fear of whirlpools. Bhikkhus, 'fear of whirlpools' is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 67 – Cātumasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn67" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the fear of sea monsters? Here, bhikkhus, a good man, out of faith, goes forth from home to homelessness. He reflects: 'I am oppressed by birth... Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be known.' Having gone forth thus, in the morning he puts on his robe, takes his bowl, and enters the village or town for alms, without guarding his body, without guarding his speech, with mindfulness unestablished, without restraining his senses. There he sees women who are improperly dressed or scantily dressed. When he sees women improperly or scantily dressed, lust invades his mind. With his mind invaded by lust, he gives up the training and returns to the lower life. Thus, bhikkhus, this person gives up the training and returns to the lower life, and is called one who fears the fear of sea monsters. Bhikkhus, 'fear of sea monsters' is a synonym for women.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 67 – Cātumasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn67" },

{ text: `Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu who comes to live among the Saṅgha should be respectful and reverential towards his fellow celibates. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu, coming to live among the Saṅgha, is not respectful and reverential towards his fellow celibates, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now shows no respect or reverence for his fellow celibates?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should be respectful and reverential towards his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 69 – Goliyānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn69" },

{ text: `Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should be skilled in knowing the seats: 'I will sit without occupying the seats of elder bhikkhus and without pushing out younger bhikkhus from their seats.' Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu, coming to live among the Saṅgha, is not skilled in knowing the seats, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now does not know proper conduct?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should be skilled in knowing the seats.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 69 – Goliyānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn69" },

{ text: `Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should not talk much or speak frivolously. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu, coming to live among the Saṅgha, talks much and speaks frivolously, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now talks much and speaks frivolously?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should not talk much or speak frivolously. Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should be easy to speak to and have good friends. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu, coming to live among the Saṅgha, is difficult to speak to and has bad friends, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now is difficult to speak to and has bad friends?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu coming to live among the Saṅgha should be easy to speak to and have good friends.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 69 – Goliyānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn69" },

{ text: `Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should guard the sense faculties. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu does not guard the sense faculties, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now does not guard the sense faculties?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should guard the sense faculties. Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should know moderation in eating. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu does not know moderation in eating, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now does not know moderation in eating?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should know moderation in eating. Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be devoted to wakefulness. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu is not devoted to wakefulness, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now is not devoted to wakefulness?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be devoted to wakefulness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 69 – Goliyānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn69" },

{ text: `Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be energetic and diligent. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu is lazy, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now is lazy?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be energetic and diligent. Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be mindful and clearly comprehending. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu is unmindful, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now is unmindful?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should be mindful and clearly comprehending. Friends, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should have concentration. Friends, if a forest-dwelling bhikkhu does not have concentration, then someone might say of him: 'What good is it that this venerable one, a forest-dweller, living alone in the forest, doing as he pleases, now does not have concentration?' Someone might say this of him. Therefore, a forest-dwelling bhikkhu should have concentration.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 69 – Goliyānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn69" },

{ text: `Vaccha, what do you think? If a fire were burning in front of you, would you know: 'This fire is burning in front of me'?" — "Master Gotama, if a fire were burning in front of me, I would know: 'This fire is burning in front of me'." — "But if someone asked you, Vaccha: 'This fire burning in front of you, dependent on what does it burn?' — being asked thus, Vaccha, how would you answer?" — "Master Gotama, if someone asked me: 'This fire burning in front of you, dependent on what does it burn?' — being asked thus, Master Gotama, I would answer: 'This fire burning in front of me burns dependent on fuel of grass and sticks.'" — "Vaccha, if that fire were to be extinguished in front of you, would you know: 'This fire has been extinguished in front of me'?" — "Master Gotama, if that fire were extinguished in front of me, I would know: 'This fire has been extinguished in front of me'." — "Vaccha, if someone asked you: 'This fire that has been extinguished in front of you, which direction has it gone? East, west, north, or south?' — being asked thus, Vaccha, how would you answer?" — "That does not apply, Master Gotama. Because, Master Gotama, that fire burned dependent on fuel of grass and sticks. When that fuel is exhausted and there is no other fuel, it is said to be without fuel, extinguished." — "So too, Vaccha, that by which one might designate the Tathāgata — that form has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, destroyed so that it is not subject to future arising. Freed from being reckoned by form, Vaccha, the Tathāgata is deep, immeasurable, unfathomable like the ocean. 'Arises' does not apply, 'does not arise' does not apply, 'both arises and does not arise' does not apply, 'neither arises nor does not arise' does not apply.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 72 – Aggivacchasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn72" },

{ text: `Master Gotama, just as a great sala tree not far from a village or town — due to impermanence, its branches and leaves fall off, its bark and shoots fall off, its sapwood falls off, and after a time, with its branches and leaves fallen, its bark and shoots fallen, its sapwood fallen, the tree stands purely as the heartwood. So too, this discourse of Master Gotama, with its branches and leaves fallen, its bark and shoots fallen, its sapwood fallen, stands purely as the heartwood. Wonderful, Master Gotama! Wonderful, Master Gotama! Just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms — so too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by Master Gotama. I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 72 – Aggivacchasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn72" },

{ text: `The wanderer Sakuludāyī saw the Blessed One coming from afar. Seeing him, he exhorted his own assembly: "Sirs, lower your voices! Sirs, be quiet! Now Samaṇa Gotama is coming. Samaṇa Gotama loves quiet and praises quiet. If he knows this assembly is quiet, he might approach." Then those wanderers became silent.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 79 – Cūḷasakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn79" },

{ text: `But, Venerable Sir, is there a world that is entirely happy? Is there a reasonable path leading to the attainment of a world that is entirely happy?" — "Udāyī, there is a world that is entirely happy; there is a reasonable path leading to the attainment of a world that is entirely happy." — "Venerable Sir, what is that reasonable path leading to the attainment of a world that is entirely happy?" — "Here, Udāyī, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures... enters and abides in the first jhāna; after the stilling of initial and sustained thought... enters and abides in the second jhāna... enters and abides in the third jhāna. That, Udāyī, is the reasonable path leading to the attainment of a world that is entirely happy.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 79 – Cūḷasakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn79" },

{ text: `But, Kaccāna, leave aside the past, leave aside the future. 'Let a wise person come here, honest, not deceitful, upright, not hypocritical — I will teach, I will instruct.' If he practices as instructed, before long he will know and see for himself: 'Truly, this is liberation from the binding, namely the binding of ignorance.' Just as, Kaccāna, a young, weak infant lying on its back is bound at the neck with five bonds, perhaps made of string. As it grows up and its faculties mature, it is freed from those bonds. When freed from bondage, it knows: 'I am freed.' So too, Kaccāna, 'Let a wise person come here...' If he practices as instructed, before long he will know and see for himself: 'Truly, this is liberation from the binding, namely the binding of ignorance.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 80 – Vekhanasasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn80" },

{ text: `What do you think, Great King? Here, a brahmin... here, a vessa... here, a sudda — who kills living beings, takes what is not given, engages in sexual misconduct, speaks falsely, speaks divisively, speaks harshly, speaks idly, is covetous, has ill-will, holds wrong view — after death, with the breakup of the body, would he be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell, or not? What do you think, Great King?" — "A sudda, Master Kaccāna, who kills living beings... holds wrong view, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. That is my view, and that is what I have heard from the Arahants." — "Good, good, Great King! That is your view, and it is good that you have heard that from the Arahants. What do you think, Great King? If that is the case, are the four classes equal or not? What do you think?" — "Indeed, Master Kaccāna, if that is the case, the four classes are equal. I see no difference here." — "Therefore, Great King, by this method it should be understood that the saying in the world — 'Only brahmins are the highest class, other classes are low; only brahmins are the white class, other classes are black; only brahmins are pure, non-brahmins are not; brahmins are the sons of Brahmā, born from his mouth, born of Brahmā, created by Brahmā, heirs of Brahmā' — is just a sound.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 84 – Madhurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn84" },

{ text: `At that time, Prince Bodhi, expecting the Blessed One's arrival, was standing at the outer gate. Prince Bodhi saw the Blessed One coming from afar. Having seen him, he went to meet him, paid homage, and led the way to the Kokanada palace. Then the Blessed One stood at the lowest step. Prince Bodhi said to the Blessed One: "Venerable Sir, let the Blessed One step on the cloth, let the Well-Gone step on the cloth, so that I may have long-term happiness and welfare." When this was said, the Blessed One remained silent. A second time, Prince Bodhi said... A third time, Prince Bodhi said: "Venerable Sir, let the Blessed One step on the cloth, let the Well-Gone step on the cloth, so that I may have long-term happiness and welfare." Then the Blessed One looked at Venerable Ānanda. Venerable Ānanda said to Prince Bodhi: "Prince, have the cloth rolled up. The Blessed One does not walk on cloth. The Tathāgata has regard for the lower people." Then Prince Bodhi had the cloth rolled up and had seats prepared on the upper floor of the Kokanada palace. Then the Blessed One ascended the Kokanada palace and sat down on the prepared seat with the Saṅgha of bhikkhus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 85 – Bodhirājakumārasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn85" },

{ text: `Prince, then Brahmā Sahampati arranged his upper robe over one shoulder, saluted me with joined palms, and said: 'Venerable Sir, let the Blessed One teach the Dhamma! Let the Well-Gone teach the Dhamma! There are beings with little dust in their eyes who will be lost if they do not hear the Dhamma. Having heard, they will understand the Dhamma.' Prince, Brahmā Sahampati spoke thus. Having spoken, he said further:<br><br>'Formerly in Magadha,<br>The Dhamma of impurity appeared,<br>Conceived by defiled minds, wrought by thought.<br>Open wide the doors of the Deathless!<br>Let them hear the Dhamma realized by the Stainless One.<br><br>As a person standing on a mountain peak<br>Looks down upon the people all around,<br>So, O all-seeing One, gone up to the Dhamma palace,<br>Free from sorrow, look down upon the people,<br>Oppressed by sorrow, overwhelmed by birth and aging.<br><br>Arise, O hero! Victor in battle!<br>O caravan leader, free from debt!<br>Wander the world, O Blessed One, teaching the Dhamma!<br>There will be those who understand!'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 85 – Bodhirājakumārasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn85" },

{ text: `Prince, having heard Brahmā's request, out of compassion for beings, I surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye. With the Buddha-eye, Prince, I saw beings with little dust in their eyes, with much dust in their eyes, with keen faculties, with dull faculties, with good qualities, with bad qualities, easy to teach, hard to teach, and some who saw the danger in future rebirth and in faulty actions. Just as in a pond of blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses, some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, do not rise above the water, thrive while submerged; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, live reaching the water's surface; some lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, rise above the water and stand without being wetted by the water. So too, Prince, with the Buddha-eye I saw beings with little dust in their eyes... And, Prince, I spoke this verse to Brahmā Sahampati:<br><br>The door to the Deathless is open,<br>For those who are willing to hear.<br>Renounce your inaccurate faith.<br>Thinking of the trouble,<br>I did not want to teach<br>The supreme sublime Dhamma<br>Among humans.<br>(O Brahmā)`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 85 – Bodhirājakumārasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn85" },

{ text: `Then the brahmin Brahmāyu addressed the Blessed One with a verse:<br><br>How is one a brahmin?<br>How is one versed in the Vedas?<br>How is one triple-knowledge?<br>How is one called auspicious?<br><br>How is one worthy of offerings?<br>How is one the Perfect One?<br>How is one a Muni?<br>How is one called a Buddha?"<br><br>Then the Blessed One answered the brahmin Brahmāyu with a verse:<br><br>Who knows former lives,<br>Sees the good and bad destinations,<br>Has ended rebirth,<br>Attained perfect direct knowledge,<br>That one is called a Muni.<br><br>Who knows the pure mind,<br>Liberated from greed,<br>Has ended birth and death,<br>Completed the holy life,<br>Penetrated all phenomena,<br>That one is called a Buddha.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 91 – Brahmāyusutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn91" },

{ text: `And, brahmin, if someone asked a Khattiya: 'Your servant — because of this service, does he become worse, not better? Or does he become better, not worse? And thus, which servant should you be served by?' — brahmin, if that Khattiya answered correctly, he would say: 'One who serves me and thereby becomes worse, not better — I do not need that person to serve me. But one who serves me and thereby becomes better, not worse — I need that person to serve me.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 96 – Esukārīsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn96" },

{ text: `Brahmin, I do not say that one is better because of birth in a high family. Brahmin, I do not say that one is worse because of birth in a high family. Brahmin, I do not say that one is better because of superior beauty. Brahmin, I do not say that one is worse because of superior beauty. Brahmin, I do not say that one is better because of superior wealth. Brahmin, I do not say that one is worse because of superior wealth. Here, brahmin, a person born in a high family may kill living beings, take what is not given, engage in sexual misconduct, speak falsely, speak divisively, speak harshly, speak idly, be covetous, have ill-will, hold wrong view. Therefore, I do not say that one is better because of birth in a high family. Here, brahmin, a person born in a high family may abandon killing... hold right view. Therefore, I do not say that one is worse because of birth in a high family. Here, brahmin, a person of superior beauty... Here, brahmin, a person of superior wealth may kill living beings... hold wrong view. Therefore, I do not say that one is better because of superior wealth. Here, brahmin, a person of superior wealth may abandon killing... hold right view. Therefore, I do not say that one is worse because of superior wealth. Brahmin, I do not say that everyone should be served. But brahmin, I do not say that no one should be served. Brahmin, when a person is served, and because of that service his faith increases, his virtue increases, his learning increases, his generosity increases, his wisdom increases — I say that person should be served. Brahmin, when a person is served, and because of that service his faith does not increase, his virtue does not increase, his learning does not increase, his generosity does not increase, his wisdom does not increase — I say that person should not be served.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 96 – Esukārīsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn96" },

{ text: `Brahmin, what do you think? In this matter, can only brahmins develop a mind of loving-kindness, without hostility, without ill-will? Cannot Khattiyas, cannot Vessas, cannot Suddas?" — "No, Master Gotama. Khattiyas, Master Gotama, can also in this matter develop a mind of loving-kindness, without hostility, without ill-will. Brahmins also... Vessas also... Suddas also... All four classes, Master Gotama, can in this matter develop a mind of loving-kindness, without hostility, without ill-will." — "So too, brahmin, if a person from a Khattiya family goes forth from home to homelessness in the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, he abandons killing... holds right view — he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma. If a person from a brahmin family... from a vessa family... from a sudda family goes forth, he abandons killing... holds right view — he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 96 – Esukārīsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn96" },

{ text: `Brahmin, what do you think? Can only brahmins take a back-scratcher and bath powder, go to a river, and wash off dirt and dust? Cannot Khattiyas, cannot Vessas, cannot Suddas?" — "No, Master Gotama. Khattiyas, Master Gotama, can also take a back-scratcher and bath powder, go to a river, and wash off dirt and dust. Brahmins also... Vessas also... Suddas also... All four classes, Master Gotama, can take a back-scratcher and bath powder, go to a river, and wash off dirt and dust." — "So too, brahmin, if a person from a Khattiya family goes forth from home to homelessness in the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, he abandons killing... holds right view — he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma. If a person from a brahmin family... from a vessa family... from a sudda family goes forth, he abandons killing... holds right view — he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 96 – Esukārīsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn96" },

{ text: `Brahmin, what do you think? Here, if a consecrated Khattiya king were to assemble a hundred people of various lineages and say: 'Come, those of you born in Khattiya families, in brahmin families, of royal birth — bring the upper part of a fire-making stick made of saka wood, sala wood, salala wood, sandalwood, or lotus wood, and turn it to produce fire and heat. And those of you born in low families, in hunter families, in bamboo-weaver families, in cart-maker families, in scavenger families — bring the upper part of a fire-making stick made of a dog-trough, a pig-trough, a laundry trough, or dry castor-oil wood, and turn it to produce fire and heat.' — Brahmin, what do you think? Does only the fire produced and the heat generated by those born in Khattiya families, brahmin families, of royal birth, have flame, color, and light, and can that fire be used for fire's purposes? And does the fire produced and the heat generated by those born in low families... have no flame, no color, no light, and cannot be used for fire's purposes?" — "No, Master Gotama. The fire produced and the heat generated by those born in Khattiya families, brahmin families, of royal birth — that fire has flame, color, and light, and can be used for fire's purposes. And the fire produced and the heat generated by those born in low families, hunter families, bamboo-weaver families, cart-maker families, scavenger families — that fire also has flame, color, and light, and can be used for fire's purposes. All fire has flame, color, and light, and all fire can be used for fire's purposes." — "So too, brahmin, if a person from a Khattiya family goes forth... he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma. If a person from a brahmin family... from a vessa family... from a sudda family goes forth... he can attain the right path, the wholesome Dhamma.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 96 – Esukārīsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn96" },

{ text: `I do not call that person a brahmin<br>Simply because of birth,<br>Even if he is high-born and wealthy,<br>As long as he is still attached to worldly gains.<br>One who is free from attachment to worldly gains,<br>Free from clinging to possessions,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>What the world calls 'name' and 'clan'<br>Are conventional designations, common names,<br>Words that have arisen in various places.<br><br>For a long time, the foolish have held<br>And clung to wrong views,<br>Fools declare that a brahmin is so by birth.<br><br>Not by birth is one a brahmin,<br>Not by birth is one a non-brahmin;<br>By action one is a brahmin,<br>By action one is a non-brahmin.<br><br>Action makes a farmer,<br>Action makes a craftsman,<br>Action makes a merchant,<br>Action makes a servant.<br><br>Action makes a thief,<br>Action makes a soldier,<br>Action makes a priest,<br>Action makes a king.<br><br>So the wise see action<br>Truly as it is.<br>Seeing dependent origination,<br>Knowing the result of action.<br><br>By action the world revolves,<br>By action beings wander;<br>Action binds beings<br>Like a chariot wheel its axle.<br><br>By austerity, by holy life,<br>By restraint and by taming,<br>One becomes a brahmin.<br>Such a brahmin<br>Is truly supreme.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 98 – Vāseṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn98" },

{ text: `One who has cut the fetters,<br>Who is not fearful,<br>Who has gone beyond all attachments,<br>Who is free from bondage,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Having cut the strap and the thong,<br>The bridle and the rope,<br>Having thrown away the bar,<br>That one I call a brahmin,<br>The enlightened one, awake.<br><br>One who, without anger, endures<br>Abuse, blows, and bonds,<br>With patience as his strength,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who is not angry, who keeps the precepts,<br>Virtuous, not proud,<br>Tamed, in his final body,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Like water on a lotus leaf,<br>A mustard seed on a needle's point,<br>One who is not attached to sensual pleasures,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who here knows the end of his own suffering,<br>Who has laid down the burden,<br>Who is freed from bondage,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>With deep wisdom, intelligent,<br>Skillful in what is path and what is not,<br>Having attained the supreme goal,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has no ties,<br>Neither to householders nor to the homeless,<br>Who wanders without a home, with few desires,<br>That one I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 98 – Vāseṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn98" },

{ text: `Who has laid down the rod towards beings,<br>Both the weak and the strong,<br>Who neither kills nor causes to kill,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Among the hostile, friendly,<br>Among the violent, peaceful,<br>Among the clinging, without clinging,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Whose lust, hatred, pride, and hypocrisy<br>Have fallen away like a mustard seed<br>From the point of a needle,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who speaks gentle, truthful words,<br>Instructive, not offensive to anyone,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who takes nothing in the world<br>That is not given — long, short, small, large,<br>Pure or impure, beautiful or ugly —<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has no longing for this world or the next,<br>Who is free from longing, free from bondage,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has no underlying tendencies,<br>Who by knowledge has cut off doubt,<br>Who has plunged into the Deathless,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who here has transcended the bonds<br>Of both merit and demerit,<br>Who is sorrowless, dustless, and pure,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who is spotless, pure, bright,<br>Luminous like the moon,<br>Who has destroyed delight in existence,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has crossed this dangerous swamp,<br>This cycle, this delusion,<br>Who has crossed to the far shore,<br>Who is meditative, unshaken,<br>Who is without doubt,<br>Peaceful, unattached,<br>That one I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 98 – Vāseṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn98" },

{ text: `Who here, having abandoned sensual pleasures,<br>Has gone forth from home to homelessness,<br>Having destroyed both sensual desire and existence,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who here, having abandoned craving,<br>Has gone forth from home to homelessness,<br>Having destroyed both craving and existence,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has abandoned the human yoke<br>And crossed beyond the divine yoke,<br>Who is free from all bonds,<br>Released from bondage,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has abandoned pleasure and displeasure,<br>Who is cool, without attachments,<br>Who has conquered all worlds,<br>That heroic one,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who knows fully the passing away and rebirth<br>Of beings in all their forms,<br>Who is unattached, well-gone, enlightened,<br>Attained the supreme enlightenment,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Whose destination is unknown<br>To devas, spirits, or humans,<br>Who is taintless, an Arahant,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has no clinging to the past, future, or present,<br>Who is without attachment, without possession,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who is the bull of a man, the hero,<br>The great sage, the conqueror,<br>The passionless, the purified, the awakened,<br>That one I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who knows his former lives,<br>Who sees the good and bad destinations,<br>Who has reached the end of birth,<br>That one I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 98 – Vāseṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn98" },

{ text: `Householders, those samaṇas and brahmins do not see the danger, the degradation, and the defilement of unwholesome states, nor the seclusion, the benefit, and the purification of wholesome states. Since there is a future life, if one holds the view that there is no future life, that is a wrong view. Since there is a future life, if one thinks that there is no future life, that is wrong intention. Since there is a future life, if one says that there is no future life, that is wrong speech. Since there is a future life, if one says that there is no future life, that is opposing the Arahants who know there is a future life. Since there is a future life, if one convinces another that there is no future life, that persuasion is against the good Dhamma, and because of that persuasion against the good Dhamma, one praises oneself and disparages others. Thus, before his good virtue is abandoned, evil virtue has been grasped. And thus, wrong view, wrong intention, wrong speech, opposition to the noble ones, persuasion against the good Dhamma, self-praise and disparagement of others — these various evil, unwholesome states arise dependent on wrong view.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 60 – Apaṇṇakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn60" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, the Blessed One lives in seclusion and praises the practice of seclusion. Venerable Sir, this is the fifth quality I see in the Blessed One. Because of this quality, disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to the Blessed One, and after honoring and respecting, they live depending on the Blessed One.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Udāyi, my disciples, being immersed in suffering, overwhelmed by suffering, come to me and ask about the Noble Truth of Suffering. Being asked about the Noble Truth of Suffering, I answer them. I satisfy their minds with my answer. They ask me about the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, the path leading to the cessation of suffering — I answer them. I satisfy their minds with my answer. This, Udāyi, is the fourth quality for which my disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to me, and after honoring and respecting, live depending on me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Udāyi, I teach the way of practice to my disciples. And my disciples, following that way of practice, develop the Four Foundations of Mindfulness. Here, Udāyi, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings... mind as mind... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. And here, the majority of my disciples abide, having realized the supreme perfection through direct knowledge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Udāyi, I teach the way of practice to my disciples. And my disciples, following that way of practice, develop the Four Right Efforts. Here, Udāyi, a bhikkhu generates desire for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. For the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states... For the arising of unarisen wholesome states... For the maintenance, non-decline, increase, expansion, cultivation, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states, he generates desire, makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. And here, the majority of my disciples abide, having realized the supreme perfection through direct knowledge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `Udāyi, my disciples praise the marvelous knowledge and vision, thinking: 'When he says "I know," Samaṇa Gotama knows; when he says "I see," Samaṇa Gotama sees. Samaṇa Gotama teaches the Dhamma with direct knowledge, not without direct knowledge. Samaṇa Gotama teaches the Dhamma with a reason, not without a reason. Samaṇa Gotama teaches the Dhamma with wonder, not without wonder.' This, Udāyi, is the second quality for which my disciples honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to me, and after honoring and respecting, live depending on me.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 77 – Mahāsakuludāyisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn77" },

{ text: `And, carpenter, how do these unwholesome thoughts arise? Their arising has also been stated. It should be answered: they arise from perception. What is perception? Perception is manifold, various, different: sensual perception, ill-will perception, harmfulness perception — from these, unwholesome thoughts arise.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78" },

{ text: `And, carpenter, how are these unwholesome thoughts abandoned without remainder? Their abandonment has also been stated. Here, carpenter, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. Here, unwholesome thoughts are abandoned without remainder.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78" },

{ text: `And, carpenter, what is the practice that leads to the abandonment of unwholesome thoughts? Here, a bhikkhu generates desire, makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states... for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states... for the arising of unarisen wholesome states... for the maintenance, non-decline, increase, expansion, cultivation, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states. Such a practice is the practice that leads to the abandonment of unwholesome thoughts.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78" },

{ text: `Carpenter, what are wholesome thoughts? Thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of harmlessness — these, carpenter, are called wholesome thoughts.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sir, as I understand the Blessed One's teaching, it is not easy for one living at home to practice the holy life completely perfect, completely pure, like a polished conch shell. Venerable Sir, I wish to shave off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe, and go forth from home to homelessness. Venerable Sir, may the Blessed One give me the going forth under the Blessed One, may he give me the full ordination.<br>- But, Raṭṭhapāla, have your parents given their permission for you to go forth?<br>- Venerable Sir, I have not yet obtained my parents' permission to go forth.<br>- Raṭṭhapāla, the Tathāgata does not give the going forth to anyone whose parents have not given permission.<br>- Then, Venerable Sir, I will do what is necessary so that my parents give their permission for me to go forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Then the good man Raṭṭhapāla, not receiving permission from his parents to go forth, lay down right there on the bare ground and said:<br>- I will die here, or else I will go forth.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Then the friends of the good man Raṭṭhapāla went to his parents and said:<br>- Dear mother and father, the good man Raṭṭhapāla is lying on the bare ground and says: "Here I will die, or else I will go forth." If you do not give your permission for the good man Raṭṭhapāla to go forth from home to homelessness, he will die right there. But if you give your permission for him to go forth, you will be able to see him after he has gone forth. If the good man Raṭṭhapāla does not find delight in going forth, he will have no other way but to return here. Please give your permission for him to go forth.<br>- Dear children, we give our permission for the good man Raṭṭhapāla to go forth from home to homelessness, but after going forth, he must visit his parents.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Then in the morning, Venerable Raṭṭhapāla put on his robe, took his bowl, and went to his father's house. Having arrived, he sat down on the prepared seat. Then Raṭṭhapāla's father had a heap of gold coins and bullion brought and said to him:<br>- Dear Raṭṭhapāla, this is your mother's wealth, that is your father's wealth, that is your ancestors' wealth. Dear Raṭṭhapāla, you can enjoy wealth and do meritorious deeds. Dear Raṭṭhapāla, give up the training, return to the lower life, enjoy wealth and do meritorious deeds.<br>- Householder, if you would follow my advice, you would load this heap of gold coins and bullion onto carts, transport them, and dump them in the middle of the Ganges river. Why is that? Because on account of this, householder, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair would arise for you.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Then Raṭṭhapāla's former wives, clasping each of his feet, said:<br>- Dear husband, for the sake of what kind of goddess are you living the holy life?<br>- Sisters, I am not living the holy life for the sake of any goddess.<br>- Raṭṭhapāla addresses us as "sisters."<br>Saying this, they fell to the ground unconscious.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Behold this adorned image,<br>A collection of many wounds,<br>Many afflictions, many sensual perceptions,<br>But nothing stable or everlasting.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and with earrings,<br>A skeleton covered with skin,<br>Made radiant by fine clothes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Feet painted with lac and ointment,<br>Face powdered with white powder,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Hair arranged in seven coils,<br>Eyes smeared with collyrium,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Like a newly decorated ointment box,<br>So is this defiled body adorned,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `The hunter set his snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach the trap.<br>Having eaten the crop, we go our way,<br>Leaving the deer-hunters to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `'The world is impermanent, heading towards destruction' — that, Great King, is the first exposition of the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Because I know, see, and have heard that exposition, I have gone forth from home to homelessness.<br>'The world is without shelter, without owner' — that, Great King, is the second exposition of the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Because I know, see, and have heard that exposition, I have gone forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `'The world is without possessions; one must leave all behind' — that, Great King, is the third exposition of the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Because I know, see, and have heard that exposition, I have gone forth from home to homelessness.<br>'The world is insufficient, ever craving, a slave to craving' — that, Great King, is the fourth exposition of the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Because I know, see, and have heard that exposition, I have gone forth from home to homelessness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `- Great King, what do you think? Can you say to your friends, companions, and blood relatives: 'May my dear friends, companions, and blood relatives lighten my suffering! Let all share this feeling so that I may have a lighter feeling'? Or must you endure that feeling alone?<br>- Venerable Raṭṭhapāla, I cannot say to my friends, companions, and blood relatives: 'May my dear friends... lighten my suffering! Let all share this feeling so that I may have a lighter feeling.' I must endure that feeling alone.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `- Great King, what do you think? Although you now live enjoying the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly, can you say: 'Thus I enjoy the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly'? Or will others enjoy this wealth, while you must go according to your action?<br>- Venerable Raṭṭhapāla, although I now live enjoying the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly, I cannot say: 'Thus I enjoy the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and abundantly.' Others will enjoy this wealth, while I must go according to my action.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `I see wealthy people in the world,<br>Who, from delusion, give no gift.<br>Greedy, they hoard wealth,<br>And ever pursue greater sensual pleasures.<br>The king, having conquered the earth by force,<br>Ruling to the ocean's edge,<br>Not satisfied with this shore's end,<br>Goes seeking the other shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Kings and many other people,<br>Not free from craving, come to death,<br>Lacking, they cannot leave their bodies,<br>Not satisfied with sensual pleasures here.<br>Relatives, distraught, lament over him:<br>'Alas, he is not immortal!'.<br>Wrapped in cloth, his body<br>Is placed on the pyre and burned.<br>Pierced with stakes, he burns,<br>Leaving behind his wealth, wearing only a single cloth.<br>Here, relatives and friends<br>Provide no refuge for the dead.<br>Heirs take his wealth,<br>But the person goes according to his action.<br>Wealth does not follow the dead,<br>Neither wife, children, property, nor kingdom.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Wealth cannot buy long life,<br>Riches cannot avoid aging and decay,<br>The wise say this life is truly short,<br>Truly impermanent, always changing.<br>Both rich and poor experience (feelings),<br>The fool and the wise both feel,<br>The fool, struck by ignorance, falls down,<br>The wise, feeling, does not tremble.<br>Therefore, wisdom surpasses wealth,<br>Through wisdom, one is fulfilled here.<br>Not fulfilled in existence or non-existence,<br>The fool performs evil actions.<br>Entering the womb, reborn in another world,<br>That person wanders on, continues to be born,<br>The one of little wisdom surely must<br>Enter the womb and be born in another world.<br>Like a thief caught while stealing,<br>An evil nature harms himself by his own action,<br>So too beings, dying in another life,<br>An evil nature harms himself by his own power.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Behold this adorned image,<br>A collection of many wounds,<br>Many afflictions, many sensual perceptions,<br>But nothing stable or everlasting.<br><br>Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and with earrings,<br>A skeleton covered with skin,<br>Made radiant by fine clothes.<br><br>Feet painted with lac and ointment,<br>Face powdered with white powder,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.<br><br>Hair arranged in seven coils,<br>Eyes smeared with collyrium,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Like a newly decorated ointment box,<br>So is this defiled body adorned,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.<br><br>The hunter set his snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach the trap.<br>Having eaten the crop, we go our way,<br>Leaving the deer-hunters to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Behold this adorned image,<br>A collection of many wounds,<br>Many afflictions, many sensual perceptions,<br>But nothing stable or everlasting.<br><br>Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and with earrings,<br>A skeleton covered with skin,<br>Made radiant by fine clothes.<br><br>Feet painted with lac and ointment,<br>Face powdered with white powder,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.<br><br>Hair arranged in seven coils,<br>Eyes smeared with collyrium,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.<br><br>Like a newly decorated ointment box,<br>So is this defiled body adorned,<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one seeking the far shore.<br><br>The hunter set his snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach the trap.<br>Having eaten the crop, we go our way,<br>Leaving the deer-hunters to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Sensual desires are many, sweet, agreeable,<br>They disturb the mind in many forms,<br>Seeing the danger in these strands of sensual pleasure,<br>I have gone forth, Great King!<br>Like a fruit that falls from here,<br>Both young and old, when the body breaks up,<br>Having seen this, I have gone forth,<br>The ascetic life must be supreme,<br>O Great King!`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82" },

{ text: `Whoever was heedless before and afterwards is not heedless,<br>Illumines this world like the moon freed from clouds.<br>Whoever does evil deeds, by wholesome deeds checks them,<br>Illumines this world like the moon freed from clouds.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86" },

{ text: `From time to time hearing the Dhamma, practicing in accordance with the Dhamma.<br>Such a person does not harm me,<br>Nor does he harm anyone else.<br>That one will attain supreme peace.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86" },

{ text: `Protecting all, the strong and the weak,<br>Like one who guides water, directing its flow,<br>Like the arrow-maker straightening the shaft,<br>Like the carpenter shaping wood.<br>The wise one himself, tames himself.<br>Some are tamed by rods, whips, hooks,<br>I have been tamed without rod, without sword.<br>(By such a one).`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86" },

{ text: `The fool, lacking wisdom, delights in heedlessness,<br>But the wise one, guards heedfulness,<br>As the highest, most precious treasure,<br>Do not indulge in heedlessness, do not indulge in sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86" },

{ text: `Guarding heedfulness, always in jhāna,<br>Attaining great bliss, vast and measureless,<br>Welcome! I have come, not having gone astray,<br>No one urged me to follow evil thoughts.<br>Among the truths well taught,<br>I follow the truth, the supreme truth,<br>Welcome! I have come, not having gone astray,<br>No one urged me to follow evil thoughts,<br>I have attained the three knowledges, fulfilled the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86" },

{ text: `- Householder, are your faculties changed?<br>- Venerable Sir, how could my faculties not be changed? Venerable Sir, my dear, beloved only son has passed away. Since his death, I no longer wish to work, I no longer wish to eat or drink, I constantly go to the charnel ground and lament: 'Where are you, my only son? Where are you, my only son?'<br>- It is so, householder. For, householder, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are born from affection, they arise from affection.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 87 – Piyajātikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn87" },

{ text: `Brahmin, this is a method by which it should be understood that sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are born from affection, arise from affection. Brahmin, in the past, right here in Sāvatthī, a man's mother died. Since her death, that man became mad, his mind confused, he went from street to street, from crossroad to crossroad, saying: 'Have you seen my mother? Have you seen my mother?'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 87 – Piyajātikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn87" },

{ text: `Brahmin, this is a method by which it should be understood that sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are born from affection, arise from affection. Brahmin, in the past, right here in Sāvatthī, a woman went to visit her relatives. Those relatives wanted to force her to leave her husband and give her to another man. The woman refused. Then she said to her husband: 'Dear husband, my relatives want to force me to leave you and give me to another man. I do not wish that.' Then he cut the woman in two, and then killed himself, thinking: 'We two will meet in the next life.' Brahmin, by this method it should be understood that sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are born from affection, arise from affection.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 87 – Piyajātikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn87" },

{ text: `Then, while walking and wandering for pleasure, King Pasenadi of Kosala saw some delightful, beautiful, quiet, low-noise, secluded, breezy trees, far from crowded gatherings, suitable for contemplation. Seeing this, the king thought of the Blessed One: 'These delightful, beautiful, quiet, low-noise, secluded, breezy trees, far from crowded gatherings, suitable for contemplation — here let us pay homage to the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 89 – Dhammacetiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn89" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Sir, I see bhikkhus living the holy life perfectly and purely for the whole of their life, until their last breath. Venerable Sir, I do not see any other holy life elsewhere that is so perfect and pure. Venerable Sir, this is my conviction regarding the Blessed One: 'The Blessed One is perfectly enlightened; the Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One; the Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is well practiced and well trained.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 89 – Dhammacetiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn89" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, kings quarrel with kings, nobles quarrel with nobles, brahmins quarrel with brahmins, householders quarrel with householders, mother quarrels with child, child quarrels with mother, father quarrels with child, child quarrels with father, brother quarrels with brother, brother quarrels with sister, sister quarrels with brother, friend quarrels with friend. But here, Venerable Sir, I see bhikkhus living in harmony, amicably, without quarreling, like milk and water, looking at each other with loving eyes. Venerable Sir, I do not see any other holy life elsewhere that is so perfect and pure. Venerable Sir, this is my conviction regarding the Blessed One: 'The Blessed One is perfectly enlightened; the Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One; the Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is well practiced and well trained.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 89 – Dhammacetiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn89" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Venerable Sir, I see bhikkhus joyful, elated, rapturous, with serene faculties, not agitated, calm, living on the alms of others, with minds like wild deer. Venerable Sir, I think: 'Surely these venerable ones have realized some supreme, excellent distinction in the Blessed One's teaching, a progressive attainment, that they are so joyful, elated, rapturous, with serene faculties, not agitated, calm, living on the alms of others, with minds like wild deer.' Venerable Sir, this is my conviction regarding the Blessed One: 'The Blessed One is perfectly enlightened; the Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One; the Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is well practiced and well trained.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 89 – Dhammacetiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn89" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Sir, when the Blessed One is teaching the Dhamma to an assembly of hundreds, no sound of sneezing or coughing arises. Venerable Sir, in the past, while the Blessed One was teaching the Dhamma to an assembly of hundreds, a disciple of the Blessed One coughed. A fellow celibate tapped him on the knee and said: 'Venerable sir, be silent! Venerable sir, do not make noise! The Blessed One, our Teacher, is teaching the Dhamma.' Venerable Sir, the following thought arose in me: 'How wonderful! How marvelous! This assembly is so well trained, without rod, without sword. Venerable Sir, I do not see any other assembly elsewhere that is as well trained as this assembly.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 89 – Dhammacetiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn89" },

{ text: `- Dhananjani, what do you think? Here, a person, for the sake of his wife and children, does what is unlawful and unjust. Because of doing what is unlawful and unjust, the hell-guards drag him to hell. What can that person do when he says: 'I did what is unlawful and unjust for the sake of my wife and children; do not let the hell-guards drag me to hell'? Or what can his wife and children do when they say: 'My husband, my father did what is unlawful and unjust for our sake; do not let the hell-guards drag our husband, our father to hell'?<br>- That is impossible, Venerable Sāriputta. The hell-guards will throw him into hell regardless of his lamentation.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 97 – Dhanañjānisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn97" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, sensual pleasures are impermanent, empty, false, of a delusive nature. Bhikkhus, this is the empty chatter of a fool built on falsehood. Present sensual pleasures and future sensual pleasures, present perceptions of sensual pleasure and future perceptions of sensual pleasure, both belong to Māra's realm, are Māra's domain, Māra's bait, Māra's feeding ground.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Here, these evil, unwholesome intentions lead to sensual desire, ill-will, and agitation, and these very states become an obstacle here for the noble disciple in his training. Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple reflects: 'Present sensual pleasures and future sensual pleasures, present perceptions of sensual pleasure and future perceptions of sensual pleasure, both belong to Māra's realm, are Māra's domain, Māra's bait, Māra's feeding ground. Therefore, let me abide with a vast mind, a great practice, after having conquered the world, after having determined the position of the mind. When I abide with a vast mind, a great practice conquering the world, determining the position of the mind, evil, unwholesome intentions of sensual desire, ill-will, and agitation will not arise; with these states abandoned, my mind does not become restricted, but rather becomes immeasurable, well developed.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple reflects: 'Present sensual pleasures and future sensual pleasures, present perceptions of sensual pleasure and future perceptions of sensual pleasure, whatever form, it is the four great elements and form derived from the four great elements.' While he practices thus, abides thus often, his mind becomes calm in that element. With a calm mind, he either attains the imperturbable (āneñja) here and now, or he is strongly inclined towards wisdom. With the breakup of the body after death, this situation occurs: that evolving consciousness may, following this, attain the imperturbable.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple reflects: 'Present sensual pleasures and future sensual pleasures, present perceptions of sensual pleasure and future perceptions of sensual pleasure, present forms and future forms, present perceptions of form and future perceptions of form, both are impermanent. What is impermanent is not fit to be delighted in, not fit to be welcomed, not fit to be clung to.' While he practices thus, abides thus often, his mind becomes calm in that element. With a calm mind, he either attains the imperturbable here and now, or he is strongly inclined towards wisdom. With the breakup of the body after death, this situation occurs: that evolving consciousness may, following this, attain the imperturbable.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu practices thus and reflects: 'If before there was not thus, it might not be mine. If now there is not thus, it might not be mine. I abandon whatever exists and whatever has arisen.' And thus he obtains equanimity. He delights in that equanimity, welcomes it, clings to it. Because he delights in it, welcomes it, and clings to it, his consciousness becomes dependent on that equanimity and clings to it. With clinging, Ānanda, that bhikkhu does not attain final Nibbāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Whatever should be done, Ānanda, by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, seeking their welfare, that I have done for you out of compassion. Ānanda, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Practice jhāna, Ānanda, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106" },

{ text: `Brahmin, in this Dhamma and Discipline, there is a gradual training, a gradual practice, a gradual path. Just as, brahmin, a skilled horse-trainer, having obtained a fine thoroughbred horse, first trains it to become accustomed to the bit, then trains it in other ways. So too, brahmin, when the Tathāgata obtains a person to be tamed, he first trains him: 'Come, bhikkhu, be virtuous, live restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, when the bhikkhu is virtuous, restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules, the Tathāgata then trains him further: 'Come, bhikkhu, guard the sense faculties. When the eye sees a form, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, restrain that cause, guard the eye faculty, practice the restraint of the eye faculty. When the ear hears a sound... nose smells an odor... tongue tastes a flavor... body feels a touch... mind cognizes a mental object, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, restrain that cause, guard the mind faculty, practice the restraint of the mind faculty.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, after the bhikkhu has guarded the sense faculties, the Tathāgata then trains him further: 'Come, bhikkhu, know moderation in eating. Reflecting wisely, take food not for enjoyment, not for indulgence, not for beautification, not for ornamentation, but only for the support and maintenance of this body, for avoiding harm, for assisting the holy life, thinking: "Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings; and there will be for me blamelessness and a comfortable abiding."'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, after the bhikkhu has known moderation in eating, the Tathāgata then trains him further: 'Come, bhikkhu, be devoted to wakefulness. By day, while walking and sitting, purify the mind from obstructive states. In the first watch of the night, while walking and sitting, purify the mind from obstructive states. In the middle watch of the night, lie down on the right side in the lion's posture, one foot on the other, mindful and clearly comprehending, minding the time for rising. In the last watch of the night, after rising, while walking and sitting, purify the mind from obstructive states.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, after the bhikkhu is devoted to wakefulness, the Tathāgata then trains him further: 'Come, bhikkhu, be possessed of mindfulness and clear comprehension. When going forward and returning, have clear comprehension; when looking ahead and looking aside, have clear comprehension; when bending and stretching, have clear comprehension; when wearing the robe, carrying the bowl, and wearing the outer robe, have clear comprehension; when eating, drinking, chewing, tasting, have clear comprehension; when defecating and urinating, have clear comprehension; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, being silent, have clear comprehension.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, after he has mindfulness and clear comprehension, the Tathāgata then trains him further: 'Come, bhikkhu, choose a secluded dwelling: a forest, the root of a tree, a mountain glen, a cave, a charnel ground, a jungle thicket, an open space, a heap of straw.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `He chooses a secluded, quiet dwelling: a forest, the root of a tree, a mountain glen, a cave, a charnel ground, a jungle thicket, an open space, a heap of straw. After returning from his alms round, after his meal, he sits down cross-legged, keeping his body straight, and establishes mindfulness in front of him. He abandons covetousness for the world, dwelling with a mind free from covetousness, purifying his mind from covetousness. He abandons ill-will, dwelling with a mind free from ill-will, compassionate for the welfare of all living beings, purifying his mind from ill-will. He abandons sloth and torpor, dwelling with a mind free from sloth and torpor, perceiving light, mindful and clearly comprehending, purifying his mind from sloth and torpor. He abandons restlessness and remorse, dwelling with a mind free from restlessness and remorse, inwardly calm, purifying his mind from restlessness and remorse. He abandons doubt, dwelling with a mind free from doubt, without perplexity, purifying his mind from doubt regarding wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `When he has abandoned these five hindrances, which are defilements of the mind and weaken wisdom, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, he enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. With the stilling of initial and sustained thought, he enters and abides in the second jhāna... the third jhāna... the fourth jhāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, for what reason, for what condition, given that Rājagaha exists, given that the path to Rājagaha exists, given that you exist as a guide, though you instruct and teach thus, one person takes the wrong path and goes westward, while another person can reach Rājagaha safely?" — "Master Gotama, what can I do? I am only a guide, Master Gotama." — "So too, brahmin, Nibbāna exists, the path to Nibbāna exists, and I exist as a guide. But my disciples, instructed and taught thus by me, some attain the ultimate goal of Nibbāna, some do not attain it. Here, brahmin, what can I do? The Tathāgata is only a guide.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Master Gotama, for those who have gone forth not out of faith but for a livelihood, who are deceitful, fraudulent, hypocritical, unbalanced, arrogant, agitated, talkative, frivolous, not guarding the sense faculties, not knowing moderation in eating, not devoted to wakefulness, indifferent to the ascetic life, not respecting training, living in abundance, lazy, leading the way to backsliding, neglecting the burden of seclusion, lazy, of inferior energy, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, not concentrated, with distracted mind, of weak wisdom, dull — Master Gotama cannot live with such people.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Master Gotama, with those good men who have gone forth out of faith, who are not deceitful, not fraudulent, not hypocritical, not unbalanced, not arrogant, not agitated, not talkative, not frivolous, who guard the sense faculties, know moderation in eating, are devoted to wakefulness, not indifferent to the ascetic life, respect training, do not live in abundance, are not lazy, abandon backsliding, lead the way to seclusion, energetic, diligent, mindful, established, clearly comprehending, concentrated, with unified mind, wise, not dull — Master Gotama lives in harmony with such ones.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Master Gotama, just as among root fragrances, black sandalwood is considered supreme; among heartwood fragrances, red sandalwood is considered supreme; among flower fragrances, jasmine is considered supreme. So too, the instruction of Master Gotama is considered supreme among instructions today.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Wonderful, Master Gotama! Wonderful, Master Gotama! Just as one might set upright what had been overturned, reveal what had been hidden, show the way to one who was lost, bring a lamp into the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms — so too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by Master Gotama. I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the Dhamma, and to the Bhikkhu Saṅgha. May Master Gotama accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107" },

{ text: `Brahmin, the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has laid down the training rules, has proclaimed the Pātimokkha for the bhikkhus. On Uposatha days we reside in the same village, all of us gather together in one place; having assembled, we ask about what has happened to each one. If, while thus questioning, a bhikkhu has committed an offense, a breach of the precepts, we make him act according to the Dhamma, according to the instruction. Truly, it is not the venerable ones who rule over us; it is the Dhamma that rules over us.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `Brahmin, among us, whoever possesses these qualities, we honor, respect, revere, and make offerings to him; after honoring and respecting, we abide depending on him. Here, brahmin, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, remembering what he has learned, storing up what he has learned; those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, proclaiming the holy life completely perfect and pure — such teachings he has learned much, retained, verbally recited, mentally investigated, and well penetrated by right view. He is content with the requisites — robes, almsfood, lodgings, medicines. He attains the four jhānas, which are higher mental states and provide a pleasant abiding in the present life, as he wishes, without difficulty, without trouble. With the destruction of the taints, he attains and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom, having directly known and realized it for himself in this very life.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `Truly, Venerable Ānanda, the Bamboo Grove is a delightful place, with little noise, little clamor, sheltered from the wind, secluded from crowded people, suitable for meditation, worthy of those who practice jhāna and are inclined to jhāna like yourselves. And the venerable ones are jhāna practitioners, inclined to jhāna. Venerable Ānanda, once the Blessed One was staying at Vesālī, in the Great Wood, at the Kutagarasala. Then, Venerable Ānanda, I went to the Blessed One. There, the Blessed One gave a talk on jhāna in many ways. The Blessed One is truly a jhāna practitioner, inclined to jhāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `Brahmin, what kind of jhāna does the Blessed One not praise? Here, brahmin, some persons dwell with their minds saturated by sensual desire, overcome by sensual desire, and do not truly understand the escape from arisen sensual desire. He makes sensual desire the ultimate object, and he practices jhāna, contemplates jhāna, concentrates in jhāna, enters jhāna. He dwells with his mind saturated by ill-will, overcome by ill-will... saturated by sloth and torpor, overcome by sloth and torpor... saturated by restlessness and remorse, overcome by restlessness and remorse... saturated by doubt, overcome by doubt, and does not truly understand the escape from arisen doubt. He makes doubt the ultimate object, and he practices jhāna, contemplates jhāna, concentrates in jhāna, enters jhāna. Brahmin, the Blessed One does not praise such jhāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `And, brahmin, what kind of jhāna does the Blessed One praise? Here, brahmin, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna... the second jhāna... the third jhāna... the fourth jhāna. Brahmin, the Blessed One praises such jhāna.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `Brahmin, the Blessed One is the one who makes the path arise which had not previously arisen, who makes the path known which had not previously been known, who declares the path which had not previously been declared; he is the knower of the path, the finder of the path, the expert in the path. And now his disciples dwell following the path and later become possessed of those qualities.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 108 – Gopakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn108" },

{ text: `Therefore, bhikkhus, whatever form, whether past, future, or present, internal or external... all form should be seen as it actually is: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Whatever feeling, whatever perception, whatever formations, whatever consciousness, whether past, future, or present, internal or external... all consciousness should be seen as it actually is: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 109 – Mahāpuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn109" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a wrong-headed person with wrong view like a wrong-headed person? Here, bhikkhus, a wrong-headed person holds wrong view: 'There is no giving, no sacrifice, no offering; no fruit or result of good and bad actions; no this world, no next world; no mother, no father; no spontaneously reborn beings; no samaṇas or brahmins in the world who, having practiced rightly, have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a wrong-headed person with wrong view like a wrong-headed person.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 110 – Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn110" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a wrong-headed person in giving like a wrong-headed person? Here, bhikkhus, a wrong-headed person gives without respect, gives not with his own hand, gives without careful consideration, gives things that are not needed, gives without regard for the future. Thus, bhikkhus, is a wrong-headed person in giving like a wrong-headed person.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 110 – Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn110" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a right-headed person in reflection like a right-headed person? Here, bhikkhus, a right-headed person does not reflect for his own harm, does not reflect for the harm of others, does not reflect for the harm of both. Thus, bhikkhus, is a right-headed person in reflection like a right-headed person.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 110 – Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn110" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a right-headed person with right view like a right-headed person? Here, bhikkhus, a right-headed person holds right view: 'There is giving, sacrifice, offering; there is fruit and result of good and bad actions; there is this world and the next world; there is mother, father; there are spontaneously reborn beings; there are samaṇas and brahmins in the world who, having practiced rightly, have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a right-headed person with right view like a right-headed person.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 110 – Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn110" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a right-headed person in giving like a right-headed person? Here, bhikkhus, a right-headed person gives with respect, gives with his own hand, gives with careful consideration, gives things that are needed, gives with regard for the future. Thus, bhikkhus, is a right-headed person in giving like a right-headed person.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 110 – Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn110" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly about Sāriputta, one could say: 'Sāriputta is master and consummate in noble virtue, master and consummate in noble concentration, master and consummate in noble wisdom, master and consummate in noble liberation.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 111 – Anupadasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn111" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly about Sāriputta, one could say: 'Sāriputta is the legitimate son of the Blessed One, born of his mouth, born of the Dhamma, fashioned by the Dhamma, an heir of the Dhamma, not an heir of material things.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 111 – Anupadasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn111" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed, who has lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge, the anudhamma answer would be: 'Friends, I do not feel attachment, nor opposition, being independent, not bound, liberated, unattached, I abide with an unlimited mind regarding what is seen... heard... sensed... cognized. Friends, because I know thus, see thus, regarding these four forms of declaration, I can say that my mind is liberated from the taints, without clinging.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 112 – Chabbisodhanasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn112" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a true person reflects: 'It is not because of belonging to a high family that the states of greed come to be abandoned, or the states of hatred come to be abandoned, or the states of delusion come to be abandoned. If a person who has gone forth not from a high family practices in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, practices rightly, practices in conformity with the Dhamma, then he is honored and praised here.' Having taken the path as the essential, he does not praise himself or disparage others because of his own high family. Thus, bhikkhus, is the true person's quality.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 113 – Sappurisasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn113" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a true person reflects: 'It is not because of being well known and famous that the states of greed come to be abandoned, or the states of hatred, or the states of delusion. If a person who has gone forth is not well known and is of no fame, yet practices in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, practices rightly, practices in conformity with the Dhamma, then he is honored and praised here.' Having taken the path as the essential, he does not praise himself or disparage others because of his own fame and renown. Thus, bhikkhus, is the true person's quality.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 113 – Sappurisasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn113" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a true person reflects: 'It is not because of being an expert on the Discipline that the states of greed come to be abandoned, or the states of hatred, or the states of delusion. If a person who has gone forth is not an expert on the Discipline, yet practices in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, practices rightly, practices in conformity with the Dhamma, then he is honored and praised here.' Having taken the path as the essential, he does not praise himself or disparage others because of his own being an expert on the Discipline. Thus, bhikkhus, is the true person's quality.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 113 – Sappurisasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn113" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, a true person reflects: 'It is not because of being a preacher of Dhamma that the states of greed come to be abandoned, or the states of hatred, or the states of delusion. If a person who has gone forth is not a preacher of Dhamma, yet practices in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, practices rightly, practices in conformity with the Dhamma, then he is honored and praised here.' Having taken the path as the essential, he does not praise himself or disparage others because of his own being a preacher of Dhamma. Thus, bhikkhus, is the true person's quality.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 113 – Sappurisasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn113" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, a true person reflects: 'It is not because of being a forest-dweller that the states of greed come to be abandoned, or the states of hatred, or the states of delusion. If a person who has gone forth is not a forest-dweller, yet practices in accordance with the Dhamma and in conformity with the Dhamma, practices rightly, practices in conformity with the Dhamma, then he is honored and praised here.' Having taken the path as the essential, he does not praise himself or disparage others because of his own being a forest-dweller. Thus, bhikkhus, is the true person's quality.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 113 – Sappurisasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn113" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is wrong view? There is no giving, no offering, no sacrifice; no fruit or result of good and bad actions; no this world, no next world; no mother, no father; no spontaneously reborn beings; no samaṇas or brahmins in the world who, having practiced rightly, have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge. Thus, bhikkhus, is wrong view.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 117 – Mahācattārīsakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn117" },

{ text: `Wrong mindfulness, bhikkhus, is destroyed by right mindfulness. And those evil, unwholesome states that arise with wrong mindfulness as condition are destroyed in one who has right mindfulness. And those wholesome states that arise with right mindfulness as condition are developed and brought to fulfillment.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 117 – Mahācattārīsakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn117" },

{ text: `While he dwells heedful, ardent, and resolute, the memories and thoughts of the household life are abandoned. With the abandoning of those states, his mind becomes inwardly steady, settled, unified, and concentrated. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops mindfulness of the body.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 119 – Kāyagatāsatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn119" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for one who has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, whatever wholesome states are internal all belong to the component of true knowledge. Just as, bhikkhus, the great ocean, if one pervades it with the mind, all rivers that flow into it belong to the great ocean. So too, bhikkhus, for one who has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, whatever wholesome states are internal all belong to the component of true knowledge.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 119 – Kāyagatāsatisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn119" },

{ text: `Ānanda, a bhikkhu is not splendid if he delights in his own assembly, if he rejoices in his own assembly, if he is pleased with his own assembly; if he delights in others' assemblies, if he rejoices in others' assemblies, if he is pleased with others' assemblies. Ānanda, if a bhikkhu delights in his own assembly... is pleased with others' assemblies, that he can attain at will, without difficulty, without trouble, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of solitude, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of enlightenment — this is impossible. But, Ānanda, a bhikkhu who lives alone, secluded from gatherings, can expect to attain at will, without difficulty, without trouble, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of solitude, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of enlightenment — this is possible.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },

{ text: `Ānanda, I do not see any form that, when delighted in, when enjoyed, is subject to change and alteration, without giving rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },

{ text: `But this abiding, Ānanda, has been fully realized by the Tathāgata, that is, by not attending to any sign, he attains and abides in internal voidness. And if, Ānanda, while the Tathāgata is abiding in this abiding, bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, laymen, laywomen, kings, ministers, wanderers, disciples of wanderers come to see him, then, Ānanda, the Tathāgata, with mind inclined towards seclusion, tending towards seclusion, gravitating towards seclusion, living alone, delighting in renunciation, making an end of all states that are based on the taints, speaks only words that are encouraging.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },

{ text: `Ānanda, he reflects: 'Regarding those low, vulgar, worldly, unworthy, unbeneficial thoughts that do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna — such as sensual thoughts, ill-will thoughts, harmfulness thoughts — I will not think those thoughts.' Here, he clearly comprehends this.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },
{ text: `Ānanda, regarding those noble thoughts that are conducive to progress, leading to the complete destruction of suffering — such as thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of harmlessness — he reflects: 'I will think those thoughts.' Here, he clearly comprehends this.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },
{ text: `And how, Ānanda, do disciples treat the Teacher with a friendly mind, not with a hostile mind? Here, Ānanda, the Teacher teaches the Dhamma to his disciples out of compassion, seeking their welfare, out of compassion saying: 'This is for your welfare, this is for your happiness.' His disciples listen, lend ear, do not direct their minds elsewhere, and do not go against the Teacher's instruction. Thus, Ānanda, disciples treat the Teacher with a friendly mind, not with a hostile mind. Therefore, Ānanda, treat me with a friendly mind, not with a hostile mind, and that will be for your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },
{ text: `I do not exhort you like a potter with unfired, unburnt clay. I will speak reproach upon reproach, exhortation upon exhortation. That which is heartwood will stand firm.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122" },
{ text: `Here, Ānanda, the feelings that arise in the Tathāgata are known to him; known, they remain; known, they disappear. Perceptions are known to him; thoughts that arise are known to him; known, they remain; known, they disappear. Ānanda, remember this as a wonderful and marvelous quality of the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 123 – Acchariyaabbhutasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn123" },
{ text: `Aggivessana, what benefit is there? Prince Jayasenna, living among sensual pleasures, enjoying sensual pleasures, being devoured by sensual thoughts, burnt by sensual fever, ardently pursuing sensual pleasures, could he know, see, or attain the state that is only known, seen, attained, or realized through seclusion from sensual pleasures? That is impossible.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 125 – Dantabhūmisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn125" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu endures cold, heat, hunger, thirst, the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things; he endures harsh, abusive speech; he lives enduring bodily feelings that are painful, sharp, racking, severe, disagreeable, unpleasant, life-threatening; he is cleansed of the defilements of greed, hatred, and delusion. He is worthy of offerings, veneration, respect, reverential salutation, and is the unsurpassed field of merit in the world.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 125 – Dantabhūmisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn125" },
{ text: `- Anuruddhas, do you live in harmony, delighting in each other, without quarreling, like milk and water, looking at each other with loving eyes?<br>- Venerable Sir, truly we live in harmony, delighting in each other, without quarreling, like milk and water, looking at each other with loving eyes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 128 – Upakkilesasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn128" },
{ text: `Venerable Sir, here we think: 'It is a benefit for us, a great benefit for us, that we live with such fellow celibates.' Therefore, Venerable Sir, towards these fellow celibates, we maintain bodily acts of loving-kindness in private and in public; we maintain verbal acts of loving-kindness in private and in public; we maintain mental acts of loving-kindness in private and in public. Therefore, Venerable Sir, we think: 'Let us give up our own minds and live in accordance with the minds of these venerable ones.' And, Venerable Sir, we give up our own minds and live in accordance with the minds of those venerable ones. Venerable Sir, although we have different bodies, we are as if of one mind. Venerable Sir, thus we live in harmony, delighting in each other, like milk and water, looking at each other with loving eyes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 128 – Upakkilesasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn128" },
{ text: `Then, bhikkhus, King Yāma says to that person: 'Friend, because of heedlessness you did not do good bodily, verbal, and mental deeds. Certainly they will treat you according to your heedlessness. For this evil deed was not done by your mother, not by your father, not by your brother, not by your sister, not by your friends and companions, not by your blood relatives, not by samaṇas and brahmins, not by devas. This evil deed was done by you yourself, and you yourself will experience its result.'`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 130 – Devadūtasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn130" },
{ text: `Though warned by the divine messengers,<br>Young men still remain heedless,<br>They grieve for a long time,<br>Reborn in a low state.<br>But the true person here,<br>Warned by the divine messengers,<br>Is never heedless<br>In the noble Dhamma.<br>Seeing fear in clinging,<br>In the process of birth and death,<br>Freed from clinging,<br>Birth and death are cut off,<br>They attain security and bliss,<br>Peaceful here and now,<br>All enmity and fear,<br>Those ones have overcome,<br>All pain and sorrow,<br>They have transcended entirely.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 130 – Devadūtasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn130" },
{ text: `One should not pursue the past,<br>Nor yearn for the future.<br>The past is already gone,<br>The future has not yet come.<br>Only the present Dhamma<br>Should be contemplated with insight.<br>Unmoved, unshaken,<br>Knowing thus, one should train.<br>Ardently do today,<br>Who knows about tomorrow?<br>No one can bargain<br>With the great army of Death.<br>Thus abiding ardently,<br>Day and night without fatigue,<br>He is called a peaceful, quiet sage,<br>One of excellent mindfulness.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 131 – Bhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn131" },
{ text: `Young man, beings are owners of their actions, heirs of their actions. Action is the womb, action is the relative, action is the support. Action divides beings, that is, into inferior and superior.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 135 – Cūḷakammavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn135" },
{ text: `And its former ignorant attachments are fully possessed and perfected. They are cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to exist in the future, without the capacity to arise again. Therefore, a bhikkhu thus endowed is endowed with the supreme intellectual offering. For, bhikkhu, this is the supreme noble intellectual offering, namely the abandonment of all attachments.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 140 – Dhātuvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn140" },
{ text: `And its former ignorant craving belonging to sensual desire and lust — that state is cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to exist in the future, without the capacity to arise again. And its former ignorant anger belonging to hatred and faults — that state is cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to exist in the future, without the capacity to arise again. And its former ignorant ignorance belonging to delusion and faults — that state is cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to exist in the future, without the capacity to arise again. Therefore, a bhikkhu thus endowed is endowed with the supreme peaceful state. Bhikkhu, this is the supreme noble peace, namely the peace of greed, hatred, and delusion.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 140 – Dhātuvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn140" },
{ text: `Bhikkhu, 'I am' is a conceiving. 'I am this' is a conceiving. 'I shall be' is a conceiving. 'I shall not be' is a conceiving. 'I shall have form' is a conceiving. 'I shall be formless' is a conceiving. 'I shall have perception' is a conceiving. 'I shall be without perception' is a conceiving. 'I shall be neither percipient nor non-percipient' is a conceiving. Conceiving, bhikkhu, is a disease, conceiving is a boil, conceiving is a dart. Bhikkhu, when one has gone beyond all conceivings, the sage is called peaceful. But, bhikkhu, the peaceful sage is not born, does not age, is not agitated, does not yearn. For there is nothing by which he might be born. Bhikkhu, if not born, how could he age? If not aged, how could he die? If not dead, how could he be agitated? If not agitated, how could he yearn?`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 140 – Dhātuvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn140" },
{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is an offering that is purified by both the giver and the recipient? Here, Ānanda, the giver is virtuous, of wholesome character; and the recipient is also virtuous, of wholesome character. Thus, Ānanda, is an offering purified by both the giver and the recipient.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 142 – Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn142" },
{ text: `One endowed with virtue,<br>Gives to the virtuous,<br>The gift given lawfully,<br>With a mind well pleased,<br>With firm faith<br>In the great result of action,<br>I say that such giving<br>Certainly brings great fruit.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 142 – Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn142" },
{ text: `One who has gone beyond craving,<br>Gives without craving,<br>The gift given lawfully,<br>With a mind well pleased,<br>With firm faith<br>In the great result of action,<br>I say that such giving<br>Is the supreme giving.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 142 – Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn142" },
{ text: `- Puṇṇa, the people of Sunaparanta are fierce. Puṇṇa, the people of Sunaparanta are rough. Puṇṇa, if the people of Sunaparanta insult and revile you, what will you think then?<br>- Venerable Sir, if the people of Sunaparanta insult and revile me, I will think: 'These people of Sunaparanta are good, truly excellent, because they do not hit me with their hands.' Venerable Sir, I will think thus. Venerable Sir, I will think thus.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 145 – Puṇṇovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn145" },
{ text: `Sāriputta, if a bhikkhu, on reflection, knows: 'On the path I entered the village for alms, at the place where I walked for alms, and on the path returning from the village, regarding forms cognizable by the eye, desire, greed, hatred, delusion, or ill-will have arisen in me' — then, Sāriputta, that bhikkhu should strive to abandon those evil, unwholesome states. But if, Sāriputta, on reflection, a bhikkhu knows: 'On the path I entered... returning from alms, regarding forms cognizable by the eye, no desire, greed, hatred, delusion, or ill-will have arisen in me' — then, Sāriputta, that bhikkhu should abide with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu should reflect: 'Have I abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure?' If, Sāriputta, on reflection, a bhikkhu knows: 'I have not yet abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,' then he should strive to abandon them. But if he knows: 'I have abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,' then he should abide with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu should reflect: 'Have I abandoned the five hindrances?' If he knows: 'I have not yet abandoned the five hindrances,' he should strive to abandon them. If he knows: 'I have abandoned the five hindrances,' he should abide with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu should reflect: 'Have I developed the Four Foundations of Mindfulness?' If he knows: 'I have not yet developed them,' he should strive to develop them. If he knows: 'I have developed them,' he should abide with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu should reflect: 'Have I developed serenity and insight?' If he knows: 'I have not yet developed them,' he should strive to develop them. If he knows: 'I have developed them,' he should abide with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151" },
{ text: `Thus, Ānanda, I have taught the supreme development of the faculties in the noble one's discipline, I have taught the path of the learner, I have taught the noble one whose faculties are developed. Whatever should be done, Ānanda, by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, seeking their welfare, that I have done for you. Ānanda, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Practice jhāna, Ānanda, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 152 – Indriyabhāvanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn152" },


            
            
             

{ text: `- Venerable sir, how did you cross the flood?<br>- Friend, by not standing still and not struggling, I crossed the flood.<br>- Venerable sir, how did you cross by not standing still and not struggling?<br>- Friend, when I stood still, I sank. When I struggled, I was swept away. Therefore, friend, by not standing still and not struggling, I crossed the flood.<br>(The devata):<br>After a long time I see<br>A brahmin who has attained Nibbāna.<br>Not standing, not struggling,<br>He has crossed attachment in the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.1" },
{ text: `- Venerable sir, do you know the liberation, release, and seclusion for beings?<br>- Friend, I know the liberation, release, and seclusion for beings.<br>- Venerable sir, how do you know them?<br>Destroying delight in existence,<br>Abolishing perception and consciousness,<br>Cessation of feelings, peace —<br>Thus, friend, I know<br>Liberation, release, and seclusion<br>For all kinds of beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.2" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Life is swept along,<br>One's life span is slight,<br>Swept on to old age,<br>There is no place to stop.<br>Reflecting on this fear of death,<br>One should do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Life is swept along,<br>One's life span is slight,<br>Swept on to old age,<br>There is no place to stop.<br>Reflecting on this fear of death,<br>One should abandon worldly gains,<br>Seek peace of mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.3" },
{ text: `... (At Sāvatthī). Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Time passes silently,<br>Nights and days move quickly,<br>Youth abandons us,<br>One by one.<br>Those who contemplate this fear of death,<br>Should do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Time passes silently,<br>Nights and days move quickly,<br>Youth abandons us,<br>One by one.<br>Those who contemplate this fear of death,<br>Should abandon worldly gains,<br>Seek peace of mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.4" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>How many must one cut,<br>How many must one abandon,<br>How many should one further develop,<br>How many fetters should one overcome,<br>To be called a bhikkhu<br>Who has crossed the flood?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One should cut off five,<br>Abandon five,<br>And further develop five,<br>A bhikkhu who has overcome five attachments<br>Is called one<br>Who has crossed the flood.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.5" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>How many are asleep when others are awake?<br>How many are awake when others are asleep?<br>How many courses of action bring us to defilement?<br>How many courses of action purify us?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Five are asleep when others are awake,<br>Five are awake when others are asleep,<br>Exactly five courses bring us to defilement,<br>Exactly five courses purify us.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.6" },
{ text: `Those who are excessively attached,<br>Confused about things,<br>Led astray by various sects,<br>They sleep on and on,<br>They are not awake.<br>Now indeed it is time<br>For them to awaken.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Those who are not excessively attached,<br>Not confused about things,<br>Not led astray by various sects,<br>They have attained perfect enlightenment.<br>They fully understand perfectly,<br>On the uneven path,<br>They walk evenly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.8" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>For one fond of conceit,<br>Here there is no taming,<br>No radiant wisdom,<br>No concentrated mind,<br>Living alone in the forest,<br>With a heedless mind,<br>He cannot cross beyond<br>Māra's power.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Abandoning all conceit,<br>Mind well concentrated,<br>With mind well examined,<br>Liberated from all stains,<br>Living alone in the forest,<br>With mind not heedless,<br>That one crosses beyond<br>Māra's power.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.9" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Those who live in the forest,<br>Holy ones living the holy life,<br>Eating one meal a day,<br>Why is their complexion so excellent?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>They do not grieve over the past,<br>They do not yearn for the future,<br>They live content with the present,<br>Therefore their complexion is excellent.<br>Through yearning for the future,<br>Through grieving over the past,<br>Fools wither away<br>Like a green reed cut down.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.10" },
{ text: `Why does the fool not understand<br>The saying of the Worthy One:<br>'All formations are impermanent,<br>Their nature is to arise and cease;<br>Having arisen, they cease;<br>Their stilling is bliss.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.11" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>A father delights in his son,<br>A cow-owner delights in his cows,<br>A person with attachments delights,<br>One without attachments does not delight.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>A father grieves over his son,<br>A cow-owner grieves over his cows,<br>A person with attachments grieves,<br>One without attachments does not grieve.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.12" },
{ text: `... Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>What love is like love for a son?<br>What wealth is like a cow?<br>What light is like the sun?<br>What water is better than the ocean?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Love for oneself is the best love,<br>Grain is the best wealth,<br>Wisdom is the best light,<br>Rain is the best water.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.13" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Among all two-legged beings,<br>The Enlightened One is supreme.<br>Among four-legged beings,<br>A thoroughbred is supreme.<br>Among wives,<br>A gentle one is supreme.<br>Among sons,<br>A dutiful one is supreme.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.14" },
{ text: `Now it is midday,<br>The birds are at rest,<br>The deep forest echoes —<br>That frightens me.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Now it is midday,<br>The birds are at rest,<br>The deep forest echoes —<br>I delight in it.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.15" },
{ text: `Drowsy, lazy, yawning,<br>Discontented, overeating,<br>For such beings,<br>The noble path is not revealed.<br>Drowsy, lazy, yawning,<br>Discontented, overeating,<br>By effort, abandoning these,<br>The noble path is purified.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.16" },
{ text: `Hard to do, hard to endure,<br>The ascetic life for the unintelligent,<br>Where fools falter,<br>There are many obstacles.<br>How many days can one practice asceticism<br>If the mind is not restrained?<br>With each step, one falls<br>Into slavery to thoughts.<br>Like a tortoise drawing its limbs<br>Into its own shell,<br>So too a bhikkhu,<br>Should gather all his thoughts,<br>Not attached to anything,<br>Not harming anyone,<br>Fully at peace,<br>Criticizing no one.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.17" },
{ text: `One restrained by conscience,<br>Who can be found in the world?<br>Who knows how to check criticism,<br>Like a fine horse the whip?<br>One restrained by conscience,<br>Always mindful,<br>That one attains the result,<br>Suffering is destroyed,<br>Walking with even steps<br>On the uneven path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.18" },
{ text: `You have no hut,<br>You have no nest,<br>You have no network,<br>You are free from bonds.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>I have no hut,<br>I have no nest,<br>I have no network,<br>I am free from bonds.<br>( Devata ):<br>What do you call a hut?<br>What do you call a nest?<br>What do you call a network?<br>What do you call bonds?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>'Hut' is mother,<br>'Nest' is wife,<br>'Network' is children,<br>'Bonds' are craving.<br>( Devata ):<br>Good indeed, you have no hut!<br>Good indeed, you have no nest!<br>Good indeed, you have no network!<br>Good indeed, you are free from bonds!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.19" },
{ text: `- Friend, I do not neglect the present to run after what is affected by time. And, friend, I neglect what is affected by time to run after the present. Friend, the Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are affected by time, full of suffering, full of despair; the danger there is even greater. But this Dhamma is present, not affected by time, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.20" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Thinking oneself equal, better, or worse,<br>Conflict arises from that;<br>One who is unmoved by these three,<br>For them equal and better do not arise.<br><br>Give up reckoning,<br>Do not chase after vain thoughts,<br>Abandon all craving<br>For name-and-form in the world.<br>That one cuts the fetters,<br>Without worry, without craving.<br>Devas and humans,<br>In this world or the next,<br>In the deva realms,<br>Or in any abode,<br>Searching, they cannot find<br>The footprint of that one.<br><br>Throughout the world, do not do<br>Evil by body, speech, or mind.<br>Abandon all sensual desires,<br>Mindful, with clear comprehension,<br>Without torturing the body,<br>Vain and unbeneficial.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.20" },
{ text: `... (At Sāvatthī). Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Like a sword touching the skin,<br>Like fire burning the head,<br>A bhikkhu should be mindful,<br>Gone forth, abandoning sensual desires.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Like a sword touching the skin,<br>Like fire burning the head,<br>A bhikkhu should be mindful,<br>Gone forth, abandoning identity view.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.21" },
{ text: `Inner and outer fetters,<br>Beings are fettered by them,<br>I ask Gotama,<br>Who can be freed from this fetter?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One established in virtue, wise,<br>Developing mind and wisdom,<br>Ardent and heedful,<br>That bhikkhu is freed from the fetter.<br>One who has abandoned<br>Greed, hatred, and ignorance,<br>The taint-free Arahant,<br>That one is freed from the fetter.<br>Where name-and-form<br>Is totally destroyed,<br>Where the impediment of form-perception is removed,<br>There the fetter is cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.23" },
{ text: `Where the mind is restrained,<br>There suffering ends.<br>By fully restraining the mind,<br>One is fully free from suffering.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One should not restrain the mind<br>Completely in every way,<br>Nor should one let the mind be unbridled<br>If self-control is to be attained.<br>Wherever evil states arise,<br>There one should restrain the mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.24" },
{ text: `An Arahant bhikkhu,<br>Who has done what had to be done,<br>The taints destroyed,<br>This body, his last body.<br>Can he say:<br>'I speak'?<br>Can he say:<br>'They speak to me'?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>An Arahant bhikkhu,<br>Who has done what had to be done,<br>The taints destroyed,<br>This body, his last body.<br>He can say:<br>'I speak',<br>He can say:<br>'They speak to me'.<br>Skilfully knowing<br>Mere conventions in the world,<br>Using such conventions,<br>He would speak accordingly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.25" },
{ text: `( Devata ):<br>An Arahant bhikkhu,<br>Who has done what had to be done,<br>The taints destroyed,<br>This body, his last body.<br>Would that bhikkhu,<br>Approach conceit<br>When he says:<br>'I speak'?<br>When he says:<br>'They speak to me'?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who has cut off conceit,<br>No longer has any ties.<br>All bonds of conceit<br>Are completely cut.<br>That wise one, clear-seeing,<br>Has gone beyond all vain thoughts.<br>He can say:<br>'I speak',<br>He can say:<br>'They speak to me'.<br>Skilfully knowing<br>Mere conventions in the world,<br>Using such conventions,<br>He would speak accordingly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.25" },
{ text: `What things illuminate the world,<br>By which the world is made bright?<br>I have come to ask the Blessed One,<br>Wanting to know the answer.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>There are four illuminators in the world,<br>A fifth does not exist here.<br>By day, the sun shines bright,<br>By night, the moon gives light,<br>Fire burns bright day and night,<br>Shining everywhere.<br>The Enlightened One's radiance is supreme,<br>This light is unsurpassed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.26" },
{ text: `Where does water not flow backwards?<br>Where does the whirlpool of water stop?<br>Where are name-and-form<br>Completely destroyed without remainder?<br>Where water and earth,<br>Fire and air find no footing,<br>There water flows backwards,<br>There the whirlpool stops,<br>There name-and-form<br>Are destroyed without remainder.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.27" },
{ text: `Wealthy nobles,<br>With great wealth and domains,<br>Always envy one another,<br>Enjoying sensual pleasures without satiety,<br>Among the restless ones,<br>Drifting in the stream of rebirth.<br>Who has abandoned envy and craving,<br>Not restless in the world?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who has left home,<br>Abandoned children, cattle, and self,<br>Abandoned greed and hatred,<br>And abandoned ignorance,<br>The taint-free Arahant,<br>Not restless in the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.28" },
{ text: `Four wheels, nine doors,<br>Full of defilement, bound by greed,<br>Immersed in the mire of filth,<br>O Great Hero,<br>Such is the human state,<br>What will its future be?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Cutting off delight and bonds,<br>Sensual desire and evil,<br>The root of craving destroyed,<br>Such will be the human state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.29" },
{ text: `With legs like an antelope,<br>Lean and strong,<br>Moderate in eating,<br>Not greedy, not infatuated,<br>Like a lion, like a wild elephant,<br>Solitary, without sensual desires,<br>Having come, I ask:<br>How to escape suffering?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>There are five strands of sensual pleasure in the world,<br>The mind as the sixth,<br>Here, by abandoning desire,<br>Thus one escapes suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.30" },
{ text: `Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One becomes better, not worse.<br><br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One is not sorrowful amidst sorrow.<br><br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>Beings are reborn in good destinations.<br><br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>Beings always enjoy happiness.<br><br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One is freed from all suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.31" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, a devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Through stinginess and heedlessness,<br>Thus one does not give.<br>One who desires merit,<br>Wise, should give.<br><br>Then another devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>What the miser fears,<br>Therefore he does not give,<br>That very fear comes to him<br>Because he does not give.<br>What the miser fears<br>Is hunger and thirst,<br>The fool experiences them<br>In this life and the next.<br>Therefore, restrain stinginess,<br>Give, remove the stain,<br>Beings are firmly established<br>In merit for the next life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.32" },
{ text: `Then another devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Hard is the act of giving,<br>Hard is the practice of that.<br>The evil person finds it hard to follow,<br>Hard is the Dhamma of the good.<br>Therefore, the good and evil<br>Have different destinations,<br>The evil go to hell,<br>The good go to heaven.<br><br>Even though one lives frugally,<br>Even though one supports a wife and children<br>With leftover food,<br>Yet one can give<br>From a small store.<br>Among a thousand givers,<br>Among a hundred thousand offerings,<br>Its value is not equal to<br>Such a giver.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.32" },
{ text: `Then another devata spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>Why do they give so lavishly,<br>So many offerings,<br>Their value not equal to<br>The poor person's true gift?<br>Why among a thousand givers,<br>Among a hundred thousand offerings,<br>Its value not equal to<br>Such a giver?<br><br>Then the Blessed One spoke this verse to that devata:<br>Some people give<br>In an improper way,<br>After killing and slaughtering,<br>Only then do they ease their sorrow.<br>Such giving, full of tears and beating,<br>Its value is not equal to<br>The poor person's true gift.<br>Among a thousand givers,<br>Among a hundred thousand offerings,<br>Its value is not equal to<br>Such a giver.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.32" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, a devata spoke this inspired utterance in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Excellent is giving!<br>Honored Sir.<br>Through stinginess and heedlessness,<br>Thus one does not give.<br>One who desires merit,<br>Wise, should give.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.33" },
{ text: `Then another devata spoke this inspired utterance in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Excellent is giving,<br>Honored Sir!<br>But even more excellent,<br>Giving in scarcity!<br>Excellent is giving<br>Arising from faith!<br>Excellent is giving<br>With lawfully obtained wealth!<br>Whoever gives<br>With lawfully obtained wealth,<br>Acquired through effort and striving,<br>That one crosses the stream<br>Of Yama's realm of death,<br>After death is reborn<br>In the deva world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.33" },
{ text: `Then another devata spoke this inspired utterance in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Excellent is giving,<br>Honored Sir!<br>But even more excellent,<br>Giving in scarcity!<br>Excellent is giving<br>Arising from faith!<br>Excellent is giving<br>With lawfully obtained wealth!<br>Excellent is giving<br>With wise consideration!<br>Giving with consideration,<br>The Well-Gone praises.<br>Giving to those<br>Worthy of respect in the world,<br>Giving to those ones,<br>One reaps great fruit,<br>Like good seed<br>Sown in a good field.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.33" },
{ text: `Giving with faith,<br>Is praised in many ways,<br>But there is a Dhamma better than giving,<br>That Dhamma is the Dhamma-verse.<br>From olden times, from long ago,<br>Good people, true persons,<br>With clear wisdom,<br>Attain Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.33" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, a devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Among humans,<br>Sensual pleasures are impermanent.<br>Those who enjoy them in the world,<br>Are bound and fettered by them.<br>Being heedless towards them,<br>It is hard to escape from them,<br>One who cannot escape<br>Is conquered by Death.<br>Danger arises from sensual desires,<br>Suffering arises from sensual desires,<br>When sensual desires are subdued,<br>Danger is subdued.<br>When danger is subdued,<br>Suffering is subdued.<br>The various things in the world,<br>They are not sensual desires;<br>It is the thought of greed<br>That is the sensual desire of humans.<br>The various things remain<br>As they are in the world,<br>Therefore the wise<br>Subdue sensual desire.<br>Abandon anger,<br>Subdue conceit,<br>Overcome all<br>Fetters and bonds.<br>Do not be attached<br>To that name-and-form,<br>Suffering cannot reach<br>One who has nothing.<br>Give up reckoning,<br>Do not chase after vain thoughts,<br>Cut off all craving<br>For name-and-form in the world.<br>That one cuts off the stains,<br>Without worry, without craving.<br>Devas and humans,<br>In this world or the next,<br>In the deva realms,<br>Or in any abode,<br>Searching, they cannot find<br>The footprint of that one.<br>They search but do not see<br>One thus liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.34" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, a devata spoke this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Faith is the second (wealth),<br>It is the companion of humans,<br>If one does not abide without faith,<br>One gains honor and praise,<br>After leaving this body,<br>One is reborn in heaven.<br>Abandon anger,<br>Subdue conceit,<br>Overcome all<br>Fetters and bonds.<br>Do not be attached<br>To that name-and-form.<br>Greed cannot reach<br>One who has nothing.<br>Fools without wisdom<br>Indulge in heedlessness,<br>The wise do not neglect heedfulness,<br>Like guarding a precious treasure.<br>Do not indulge in heedlessness,<br>Do not indulge in sensual desires,<br>Meditating without heedlessness,<br>One attains supreme bliss.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.36" },
{ text: `Then other devatas also recited a verse before the Blessed One:<br>Here, bhikkhus practice jhāna,<br>Their minds upright,<br>Like a charioteer holding the reins,<br>The wise protect their faculties.<br><br>Another devata also recited a verse before the Blessed One:<br>Like a broken lock, a removed bolt,<br>A dug-up pillar, greed cut off,<br>Living pure, stainless,<br>With eyes, the elephant well-tamed.<br><br>Another devata also recited a verse before the Blessed One:<br>Those who go for refuge to the Buddha,<br>Will not go to a lower realm,<br>After leaving the human body,<br>They will be reborn among devas.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.37" },
{ text: `Then another devata spoke this inspired utterance before the Blessed One:<br><br>Brahmins proficient in the five Vedas,<br>Though they practice austerities<br>For up to a hundred years,<br>Their minds cannot<br>Be rightly liberated.<br>Their nature is too low,<br>They do not reach the far shore,<br>Overcome by craving,<br>Bound by rules and rituals,<br>Though they practice austerities<br>For up to a hundred years,<br>Their minds cannot<br>Be rightly liberated.<br>Their nature is too low,<br>They do not reach the far shore.<br>One who does not subdue<br>Conceit and sensual desires,<br>Whose mind is not peaceful,<br>Who does not develop jhāna,<br>Living alone in the forest,<br>But with a heedless mind,<br>Hardly can that one escape<br>Death's dominion.<br>One who subdues conceit,<br>Skilfully develops jhāna,<br>Whose mind is peaceful,<br>Liberation perfected,<br>Living alone in the forest,<br>With mind not heedless,<br>That one escapes<br>Death's dominion.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.38" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One's foot was cut by a stone splinter. Severe feelings arose in the Blessed One — painful, sharp, racking, fierce, disagreeable, unpleasant. But the Blessed One endured them mindfully and clearly comprehending, without being distressed. Then the Blessed One had his outer robe folded in four and laid down on his right side in the lion's posture, one foot on the other, mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>Standing to one side, a devata spoke this inspired utterance before the Blessed One:<br>- Samaṇa Gotama is truly a bull elephant. And as a bull elephant, he endures bodily feelings that arise — painful, sharp, racking, fierce, disagreeable, unpleasant — mindfully and clearly comprehending, without being distressed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.38" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>In a burning house,<br>One should bring out the belongings;<br>What is brought out is beneficial,<br>Not what is burned.<br>So in this world,<br>Burning with aging and death,<br>One should bring out by giving;<br>What is given is well brought out.<br>What is given has a pleasant result,<br>What is not given does not.<br>Thieves and kings take away,<br>Fire burns and destroys,<br>When the final hour comes,<br>One leaves the body and possessions.<br>The wise, understanding this,<br>Both enjoy and give.<br>Having given and enjoyed,<br>According to one's power of action,<br>Blamed by no one,<br>That one is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.41" },
{ text: `What gift gives strength?<br>What gift gives beauty?<br>What gift gives happiness?<br>What gift gives vision?<br>What gift gives everything?<br>Please answer my question.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Giving food gives strength,<br>Giving clothes gives beauty,<br>Giving a vehicle gives happiness,<br>Giving a lamp gives vision.<br>One who gives a dwelling,<br>That one gives everything.<br>One who teaches the Dhamma,<br>That one gives the Deathless.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.42" },
{ text: `Heavenly beings and humans,<br>Both enjoy food and drink,<br>What kind of spirit (yakkha)<br>Does not enjoy food and drink?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who gives with faith,<br>With a pure mind,<br>Enjoys that food<br>In this life and the next.<br>Therefore, avoid stinginess,<br>Give, remove the stain,<br>Beings are firmly established<br>In merit for the next life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.43" },
{ text: `Those who day and night,<br>Always increase merit,<br>Abiding in Dhamma, possessed of virtue,<br>Who are reborn in heaven?<br>Those who plant gardens, plant forests,<br>Who build bridges,<br>Dig wells, give water,<br>Those who give dwellings,<br>Those ones day and night,<br>Always increase merit,<br>Abiding in Dhamma, possessed of virtue,<br>Those ones are reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.47" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>The miser in the world,<br>Stingy, refusing,<br>Creates obstacles,<br>Preventing others from giving,<br>Is reborn in hell,<br>In the animal realm, or Yama's world.<br>If reborn as a human,<br>He is born in a poor family,<br>Clothes, food, sensual pleasures, delight,<br>Are obtained with difficulty.<br>What fools wish for,<br>They do not achieve,<br>Such is the result in this life,<br>In the next life, they go to a bad destination.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.49" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Here, obtaining human birth,<br>Gentle, without stinginess,<br>Having faith in the Buddha and Dhamma,<br>And respect for the Saṅgha,<br>They shine among devas,<br>Reborn there.<br>If reborn as humans,<br>They are born in a wealthy family,<br>Clothes, food, sensual pleasures, delight,<br>Are obtained without difficulty,<br>Like the devas of the streaming realms,<br>They delight in enjoying,<br>Among possessions and wealth,<br>Honored by others,<br>Such is the result in this life,<br>In the next life, they are reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.49" },
{ text: `- What is good even in old age?<br>What is good when firmly established?<br>What is the treasure of humans?<br>What is hard for thieves to take?<br>- Virtue is good even in old age,<br>Faith is good when firmly established,<br>Wisdom is the treasure of humans,<br>Merit is hard for thieves to take.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.51" },
{ text: `- What is good that does not age?<br>What is good that is eternal?<br>What is the treasure of humans?<br>What cannot be taken by thieves?<br>- Virtue is good that does not age,<br>Faith is good that is eternal,<br>Wisdom is the treasure of humans,<br>Merit cannot be taken by thieves.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.52" },
{ text: `- Who is a companion for a traveler?<br>Who is a companion for one at home?<br>Who is a companion in times of need?<br>Who is a companion for the next life?<br>- The companion for a traveler is a fellow traveler,<br>The companion at home is one's mother,<br>A friend in times of need is a true friend,<br>Merit done by oneself is the companion for the next life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.53" },
{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>What do people fear?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind always runs,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Suffering is what people fear.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.55" },
{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>Because of what is there no liberation?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind always runs,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Because of suffering, there is no liberation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.56" },
{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>What is the support of a person?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind always runs,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Action is the support of a person.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.57" },
{ text: `- What is called the wrong path?<br>What destroys day and night?<br>What defiles the holy life?<br>What is a bath without water?<br>- Sensual desire is called the wrong path,<br>Aging destroys day and night,<br>Women defile the holy life,<br>Ensnaring humans,<br>Austerity and the holy life<br>Are a bath without water.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.58" },
{ text: `- What serves as a companion for humans?<br>What instructs a person?<br>What does a person love?<br>What frees from all suffering?<br>- Faith serves as a companion,<br>Wisdom instructs a person,<br>A person loves Nibbāna,<br>That frees from all suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.59" },
{ text: `- What surpasses all?<br>What is not outnumbered?<br>Is there one thing<br>To which everything is subject?<br>- Name surpasses all,<br>Nothing outnumbers name,<br>Name is that one thing<br>To which everything is subject.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.61" },


{ text: `- What leads the world along?<br>What torments oneself?<br>Is there one thing<br>To which everything is subject?<br>- The mind leads the world along,<br>The mind torments oneself,<br>The mind is that one thing<br>To which everything is subject.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.62" },
{ text: `- What binds the world?<br>What leads the world along?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Is Nibbāna called?<br>- Delight binds the world,<br>Seeking leads the world along,<br>By abandoning craving<br>Is Nibbāna called.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.64" },
{ text: `- What fetters the world?<br>What leads the world along?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Are all fetters cut?<br>- Delight fetters the world,<br>Seeking leads the world along,<br>By abandoning craving<br>Are all fetters cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.65" },
{ text: `- What oppresses the world?<br>What covers the world?<br>What dart has struck the world?<br>By what is it constantly scorched?<br>- Death oppresses the world,<br>Aging covers the world,<br>The dart of craving has struck the world,<br>By desires it is constantly scorched.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.66" },
{ text: `- What hangs over the world?<br>What covers the world?<br>What closes in the world?<br>On what is the world established?<br>- Craving hangs over the world,<br>Aging covers the world,<br>Death closes in the world,<br>On suffering the world is established.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.67" },
{ text: `- What closes in the world?<br>On what is the world established?<br>What hangs over the world?<br>What covers the world?<br>- Death closes in the world,<br>On suffering the world is established,<br>Craving hangs over the world,<br>Aging covers the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.68" },
{ text: `- What binds the world?<br>By taming what is one freed?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Are all bonds cut?<br>- Desire binds the world,<br>By taming desire one is freed,<br>By abandoning desire<br>Are all bonds cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.69" },
{ text: `Killing what is there happiness?<br>Killing what is there no sorrow?<br>What is that one thing<br>Whose killing you approve,<br>Master Gotama?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Killing anger one is happy,<br>Killing anger one does not sorrow,<br>Anger with its poisoned root,<br>With its sweetly deadly taste —<br>That killing the noble ones praise.<br>Killing that one does not sorrow,<br>O celestial being.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.71" },
{ text: `- What is the best wealth for humans in this world?<br>What when well practiced brings happiness?<br>What is the sweetest of all tastes?<br>Living in what way is called the best life?<br>- Faith is the best wealth in this world.<br>The Dhamma well practiced brings happiness.<br>Truth is the sweetest of all tastes.<br>Living with wisdom is called the best life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.73" },
{ text: `What is the supreme arising?<br>What is the supreme falling?<br>What always travels?<br>What is the supreme speaker?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Knowledge (vijjā) is the supreme arising,<br>Ignorance is the supreme falling,<br>The Saṅgha always travels,<br>The Buddha is the supreme speaker.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.74" },
{ text: `Why in this world so many people fear,<br>Though the path is pointed out<br>In many different forms?<br>I ask Gotama, the one of clear wisdom,<br>Where must one abide<br>To be fearless of the next life?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Let one establish right speech and mind,<br>Do no evil with the body.<br>If dwelling in a house with abundant wealth,<br>Let one have faith, be gentle,<br>Share wealth, be courteous.<br>Abiding in these four things,<br>One has no fear of the next life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.75" },
{ text: `- Who ages, who does not age?<br>What is called the wrong path?<br>What is an obstacle?<br>What destroys day and night?<br>What defiles the holy life?<br>What is a bath without water?<br>How many gaps are there in the world<br>Where the mind does not stay?<br>I have come to ask the Blessed One,<br>Wishing to know the answer!<br>- Living beings age, forms age,<br>Name-and-form does not age,<br>Covetous desire is called the wrong path,<br>Craving is an obstacle.<br>Aging destroys day and night,<br>Women defile the holy life,<br>In this defilement all beings are attached.<br>Austerity and the holy life<br>Are a bath without water.<br>Six gaps are there in the world<br>Where the mind does not stay:<br>Laziness and heedlessness,<br>Sloth and lack of self-control,<br>Drowsiness and torpor —<br>These six gaps should be completely avoided.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.76" },
{ text: `- What is master in the world?<br>What is the best commodity?<br>What is the rust that corrodes the sword in the world?<br>What in this world<br>Creates the hell realm?<br>Who, when they take, is stopped?<br>Who, when they take, is loved?<br>Who, constantly coming and going,<br>Is praised by the wise?<br>- Power is master in the world,<br>Women are the best commodity.<br>Anger is the rust that corrodes the sword in the world.<br>Thieves in this world<br>Create the hell realm.<br>The thief, when he takes, is stopped,<br>The samaṇa, when he takes, is loved,<br>The samaṇa, constantly coming and going,<br>Is praised by the wise.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.77" },
{ text: `- Seeking his own good, not giving to others,<br>What should a person abandon?<br>What good speech should be uttered?<br>What evil should be restrained?<br>- A person should not abandon himself,<br>He should utter good speech,<br>He should restrain evil speech.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.78" },
{ text: `- What binds food?<br>What attracts wealth?<br>What drags a person along?<br>What in the world is hard to give up?<br>What binds the ordinary person<br>Like a bird in a snare?<br>- Faith binds food,<br>Fortune attracts wealth,<br>Desire drags a person along,<br>Desire in the world is hard to give up.<br>Desire binds the ordinary person<br>Like a bird in a snare.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.79" },
{ text: `- What illuminates the world?<br>What awakens the world?<br>Who works together with humans?<br>What is their conduct?<br>Who nourishes both the lazy and the diligent,<br>Like a mother her child?<br>What beings sustain their lives<br>Depending on the earth?<br>- Wisdom illuminates the world,<br>Right mindfulness awakens the world,<br>Cattle work together with humans,<br>The plough is their path.<br>Rain nourishes both the lazy and the diligent,<br>Like a mother her child.<br>Rain sustains beings' lives,<br>Depending on the earth.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.80" },
{ text: `- Who does not quarrel in the world?<br>Who lives without destruction?<br>Who understands desire in the world?<br>Who is constantly self-reliant?<br>Who, abiding thus,<br>Do father, mother, brother respect?<br>Who, though low-born,<br>Is honored by nobles?<br>- The samaṇa does not quarrel in the world,<br>The samaṇa lives without destruction,<br>The samaṇa understands desire,<br>The samaṇa is constantly self-reliant.<br>The samaṇa, abiding thus,<br>Father, mother, brother respect.<br>The samaṇa, though low-born,<br>Is honored by nobles.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.81" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Kassapa said to the Blessed One: - The Blessed One extols a bhikkhu and the instruction of a bhikkhu to us.<br>- Then, Kassapa, speak out on that matter here.<br>(Kassapa):<br>Learn to speak well<br>In the ascetic life,<br>Secluded, sitting alone,<br>With mind at peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.1" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Kassapa spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>With mind liberated,<br>The bhikkhu practices jhāna,<br>And with the wish,<br>Attains the heart's desire.<br>Having known the world's<br>Rise and fall,<br>His mind pure, unattached,<br>He enjoys the true fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.2" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Māgadha said this verse to the Blessed One:<br>What things illuminate the world,<br>By which the world is made bright?<br>I have come to ask the Blessed One,<br>Wanting to hear the answer.<br>( Blessed One )<br>There are four illuminators in the world,<br>A fifth does not exist here.<br>By day, the sun shines bright,<br>By night, the moon gives light,<br>Fire burns bright day and night,<br>Shining everywhere.<br>The Enlightened One's radiance is supreme,<br>This light is unsurpassed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.4" },
{ text: `The devata Dāmali spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Here, a brahmin,<br>Diligent, not lazy,<br>Abandoning sensual desires,<br>Thus does not take rebirth.<br><br>Then the Blessed One answered:<br>O Dāmali,<br>For a brahmin<br>Who has nothing more to do,<br>Who has done what had to be done,<br>That is the brahmin.<br>Beings with hands and feet,<br>Not finding a standing place,<br>Drift and sink<br>In the vast ocean and river.<br>Finding a dry standing place,<br>That one stands,<br>Having reached the far shore,<br>That one does not drift.<br>Thus, Dāmali,<br>Such is the simile.<br>So too, a brahmin,<br>Having destroyed the taints,<br>Clear-seeing and discreet,<br>Diligently practicing jhāna,<br>That one has reached<br>The end of birth and death,<br>Has gone to the far shore,<br>Therefore does not drift.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.5" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Kāmada said to the Blessed One: - Hard to do, Venerable Sir, truly hard to do.<br>( Blessed One )<br>Nevertheless, Kāmada,<br>They do what is hard to do,<br>The learners (sekha),<br>Persevering in virtue and concentration,<br>Having chosen the homeless life,<br>Content, they bring happiness.<br>- Contentment, Venerable Sir, is hard to obtain.<br>( Blessed One )<br>Nevertheless, Kāmada,<br>They obtain what is hard to obtain,<br>Those whose minds delight in tranquility,<br>Their hearts purified,<br>Both day and night,<br>They train happily.<br>- Hard to calm, Venerable Sir, is the mind, truly hard to calm.<br>( Blessed One )<br>Nevertheless, Kāmada,<br>They calm the mind hard to calm,<br>Those whose minds delight in calming<br>Their faculties at peace,<br>Having cut through Death's tongue,<br>The noble sages go.<br>- Hard to travel, Venerable Sir, is the path, truly rough.<br>( Blessed One )<br>Nevertheless, Kāmada,<br>The noble sages still travel.<br>On the rough, uneven path,<br>Fools stumble and fall<br>On that uneven road.<br>For the noble ones, the road<br>Is an even road,<br>The noble ones walk evenly<br>On the uneven path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.6" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Pañcālacaṇḍa spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Though amidst obstacles,<br>The greatly wise Enlightened One<br>Still finds an escape,<br>Crosses beyond all obstacles.<br>The wise one knows jhāna,<br>Knows abandonment, the supreme,<br>The Muni, the sage.<br><br>The Blessed One spoke:<br>Pañcālacaṇḍa,<br>Though amidst obstacles,<br>They find an escape,<br>They find the Dhamma<br>Leading to Nibbāna.<br>Those who attain mindfulness,<br>Persevering, unshaken,<br>They are the truly upright ones,<br>With minds tamed, concentrated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.7" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Tāyana spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>O brahmin,<br>Strive, cut the stream,<br>Abandon and destroy<br>All attachment to sensual desires.<br>An ascetic who does not cut desire<br>Cannot attain one-pointedness.<br>If you do what should be done,<br>Be persevering and diligent.<br>If a renunciant is lazy,<br>He only scatters more dust.<br>Not doing is better than doing badly,<br>Doing badly brings later suffering.<br>Having done, do it well,<br>Doing well brings no suffering.<br>Like grasping grass wrongly,<br>One's hand may be cut.<br>So too, the ascetic life wrongly practiced<br>Leads to hell.<br>Every lazy action,<br>Every defiled practice,<br>Evil conduct in the holy life,<br>Does not bring great fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.8" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Candimasa spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>They will go safely,<br>Like deer in a mosquito-free zone,<br>Having attained jhāna,<br>One-pointed, mindful, aware,<br>They will reach the far shore,<br>Like fish breaking a net,<br>Having attained jhāna,<br>Self-controlled, beyond faults.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.11" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Veṇḍu spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Happy are those who,<br>After serving the Well-Gone,<br>Follow his instruction,<br>Training without heedlessness!<br><br>The Blessed One said:<br>Those who train in jhāna,<br>In the Dhamma-verses taught by me,<br>Diligent, not heedless,<br>In due time they will go,<br>Free from the hand of Death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.12" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Dīghalaṭṭhi spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>With mind liberated,<br>The bhikkhu practices jhāna,<br>And with the wish,<br>Attains the heart's desire,<br>Having known the world's<br>Arising and passing away,<br>His mind pure, unattached,<br>He enjoys the true fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.13" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Nandana said this verse to the Blessed One:<br>I ask Gotama,<br>The all-knowing Great Enlightened One,<br>I ask the Blessed One,<br>With all-seeing vision.<br>Who is called virtuous?<br>Who is called wise?<br>Who has crossed sorrow?<br>Who do devas worship?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who guards virtue,<br>Wisdom, mind developed,<br>Attentive, delighting in jhāna,<br>Mind established in mindfulness,<br>All sorrow<br>Is destroyed and ended,<br>The taints destroyed,<br>Living in the final body,<br>That one is called virtuous,<br>That one is called wise,<br>That one has crossed sorrow,<br>That one devas worship.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.14" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Candana said this verse to the Blessed One:<br>How to cross the flood,<br>Steadfast day and night,<br>Without standing, without clinging,<br>Who does not sink in the deep?<br>( Blessed One ):<br>One always virtuous,<br>Wise, well concentrated,<br>With energy and strength,<br>Crosses the hard-to-cross flood.<br>One who abandons, leaves sensual perceptions,<br>Crosses beyond the bonds of form,<br>Destroys delight and craving for existence,<br>Does not sink in the deep.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.15" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Sudatta spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Like a sword touching the skin,<br>Like fire burning the head,<br>A bhikkhu should be mindful,<br>Gone forth, abandoning sensual desires.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Like a sword touching the skin,<br>Like fire burning the head,<br>A bhikkhu should be mindful,<br>Gone forth, abandoning identity view.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.16" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Subrahmā said this verse to the Blessed One:<br>This mind is always fearful,<br>This mind is always agitated,<br>What is wished for does not arise,<br>What is not wished for arises,<br>If there is no fear,<br>Please answer my question.<br>( Blessed One ):<br>Apart from the enlightenment factor,<br>Apart from guarding the faculties,<br>Apart from abandoning all,<br>I see these things alone<br>Lead to safety<br>For all beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.17" },
{ text: `How is it, bhikkhu,<br>That you have no sorrow,<br>And yet also<br>Have no joy?<br>How is it that you now<br>Sit alone in solitude,<br>Having no joy,<br>And also not agitated?<br><br>Truly, yakkha,<br>I have no sorrow,<br>Yet in me<br>No joy arises.<br>Though now I sit<br>Alone in solitude,<br>I have no joy,<br>And also am not agitated.<br><br>How is it, bhikkhu,<br>That you have no sorrow,<br>How is it that in you<br>No joy arises?<br>How is it that you now<br>Sit alone in solitude,<br>Having no joy,<br>And also not agitated?<br><br>Joy only comes<br>To one with sorrowful mind,<br>Sorrow only comes<br>To one with joyful mind.<br>Therefore, a bhikkhu,<br>Neither joyful nor sorrowful.<br>So, sir,<br>You should know this.<br><br>After a long time I see<br>A brahmin at peace,<br>A bhikkhu without sorrow,<br>And without joy,<br>Safely crossed beyond<br>The attachment of the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.18" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Uttara spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Life is swept along,<br>One's life span is slight,<br>Swept on to old age,<br>There is no place to stop.<br>Reflecting on this fear of death,<br>One should do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br><br>Life is swept along,<br>One's life span is slight,<br>Swept on to old age,<br>There is no place to stop.<br>Reflecting on this fear of death,<br>One should abandon worldly gains,<br>Seek peace of mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.19" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Siva spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One only becomes better, not worse.<br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One gains wisdom, not otherwise.<br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One does not sorrow amidst sorrow.<br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>One shines among relatives.<br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>Beings are reborn in good destinations.<br>Associate with the good,<br>Be close to the virtuous,<br>Knowing the good Dhamma from the wise,<br>Beings always enjoy happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.21" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, the devata Khemā spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>Fools without wisdom<br>Treat the self as an enemy,<br>They do evil deeds<br>That bring bitter fruit.<br>A deed not well done,<br>Once done, torments one,<br>With tearful face,<br>Weeping, one experiences its result.<br>A deed well done,<br>Once done, does not torment one,<br>With joyful mind, at ease,<br>That one experiences its result.<br>Knowing what is good for oneself,<br>One should do what should be done first,<br>Not with the mind of a charioteer,<br>The wise one's mind is energetic.<br>Like a charioteer<br>Leaving the even highway,<br>Ascending a rough road,<br>Grieves over a broken axle.<br>So too, abandoning the Dhamma,<br>The fool follows non-Dhamma,<br>Falls into the mouth of Death,<br>Grieves like a broken axle.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.22" },
{ text: `( Blessed One )<br>One who gives with faith,<br>With a pure mind,<br>Enjoys that food<br>In this life and the next.<br>Therefore, avoid stinginess,<br>Give, remove the stain,<br>Beings still enjoy<br>Merit in the next life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.23" },
{ text: `Once a number of bhikkhus were dwelling in Kosala, on the slopes of the Himavanta (Snowy Mountain), in a small forest hut. They were conceited, self-satisfied, restless, talkative, garrulous, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, not concentrated, with distracted minds, with unguarded faculties.<br><br>Then the devata Jantu, on the Uposatha day, the fifteenth, went to those bhikkhus and spoke this verse to them:<br><br>In the past, bhikkhus,<br>Lived truly happily,<br>They were disciples<br>Of the Great Sage Gotama.<br>Not seeking food,<br>Not seeking lodgings,<br>Knowing the world as impermanent,<br>They made an end of suffering.<br>Now they have become evil-doers,<br>Like village chiefs.<br>They eat, then fall asleep,<br>Longing for others' possessions.<br>I salute the Saṅgha,<br>Pay homage to a few,<br>Others wander about<br>Without guidance or direction.<br>They are like the body<br>Of a dead person thrown away.<br>For those who live heedlessly,<br>I speak thus,<br>Those who are not heedless,<br>Sincere, I salute.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.25" },
{ text: `Time passes silently,<br>Nights and days move quickly,<br>Youth abandons us,<br>One by one.<br>Those who contemplate this fear of death,<br>Should do meritorious deeds<br>That bring happiness.<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Time passes silently,<br>Nights and days move quickly,<br>Youth abandons us,<br>One by one.<br>Those who contemplate this fear of death,<br>Should abandon worldly gains,<br>Attain true peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.27" },
{ text: `Four wheels, nine doors,<br>Full of defilement, bound by greed,<br>Immersed in the mire of filth,<br>O Great Hero,<br>Such is the human state,<br>What will its future be?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br><br>Cutting off delight and bonds,<br>Sensual desire and evil,<br>The root of craving destroyed,<br>Such will be the human state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.28" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br><br>Whatever forms there be,<br>In this world or the next,<br>With excellent color,<br>Shining in the sky,<br>All those forms<br>Praised by Māra,<br>Are merely bait<br>Thrown out to catch fish.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.30" },
{ text: `Greed, hatred, delusion — these three,<br>Are evil states for a person,<br>They harm the self,<br>They produce the self,<br>Like the bark and heartwood<br>Produce the fruit of the tree.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.2" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, King Pasenadi of Kosala said to the Blessed One: - Venerable Sir, is there anything that, being born, does not age and does not die?<br>- Great King, there is nothing that, being born, does not age and does not die. Great King, even those wealthy nobles, rich, with great wealth and property, with abundant gold and silver, abundant goods and grains — they, being born, are not free from aging and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.3" },
{ text: `Great King, even the bhikkhus who are Arahants, with taints destroyed, who have lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the ultimate goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge — even their bodies are subject to destruction, must be abandoned.<br><br>Even a king's magnificent chariot<br>Will eventually wear out,<br>So too this body<br>Will eventually grow old.<br>Only the Dhamma of the good does not age,<br>Thus the good declare.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.3" },
{ text: `Those who do evil with body, speak evil with speech, think evil with mind — those persons do not protect themselves. Even if they are protected by elephant troops, cavalry, chariot troops, or infantry, still the self is not protected. Why is that? Because that protection is external, not internal protection. Therefore, for those persons, the self is not protected.<br><br>And those who do good with body, speak good with speech, think good with mind — those persons protect themselves. Even if they are not protected by elephant troops, cavalry, chariot troops, or infantry, still the self is protected. Why is that? Because that protection is internal protection, not external protection. Therefore, for those persons, the self is protected.<br><br>Good is the protection of body!<br>Good is the protection of speech!<br>Good is the protection of mind!<br>Good is the protection of all!<br>The one with conscience protects,<br>Completely and everywhere,<br>That one is called<br>The one who is protected.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.5" },
{ text: `So it is, Great King. So it is, Great King. Few are those in this world who, having obtained abundant and plentiful wealth, are not intoxicated, not infatuated, not attached to sensual pleasures, and do not misbehave towards others. But many are those who, having obtained abundant wealth, become intoxicated, infatuated, attached to sensual pleasures, and misbehave towards others.<br><br>People are intoxicated<br>By wealth and by sensual desires,<br>They are greedy, deluded<br>In the sensual pleasures of the world,<br>Not clearly aware,<br>Excessively infatuated,<br>Like a deer that does not see the trap set,<br>Later they suffer,<br>Experiencing the result of evil deeds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.6" },
{ text: `- Great King, even wealthy nobles, wealthy brahmins, wealthy householders, rich, with great wealth and property, with abundant gold and silver, abundant goods and grains — it is for the sake of sensual pleasures, because of sensual pleasures, on account of sensual pleasures, that they consciously speak falsehood. Therefore, they will undergo long-term harm and suffering.<br><br>People are intoxicated<br>By wealth and by sensual desires,<br>They are greedy, deluded<br>In the sensual pleasures of the world,<br>Not clearly aware,<br>Excessively infatuated,<br>Like a fish that does not see the trap set,<br>Later they suffer,<br>Experiencing the result of evil deeds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.7" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion spoke this verse:<br><br>My mind, going everywhere,<br>To all directions,<br>Finds nothing<br>More dear than oneself.<br>Thus, for all beings,<br>The self is so dear.<br>Therefore, one who loves oneself<br>Should not harm another's self.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.8" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, those bhikkhus said to the Blessed One:<br>- Here, Venerable Sir, King Pasenadi of Kosala has had a great number of people bound. Some are bound with ropes, some with chains, some with clamps.<br><br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion spoke this verse:<br><br>The wise say that binding like that is not strong,<br>Binding with iron, with ropes of grass,<br>Clamps made of wood;<br>But passion for sensual pleasures,<br>For jewels and ornaments,<br>And the mind's vain thoughts<br>Directed towards children and wife —<br>The wise say that binding is truly strong.<br>Though it pulls one down,<br>Subtle and hard to escape,<br>True renunciants cut it in two,<br>Without longing or seeking,<br>Abandoning all sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.10" },
{ text: `Great King, it is by living together that one knows a person's virtue, and that over a long time, not otherwise; with attention, not without attention; with wisdom, not with poor wisdom.<br>Great King, it is in times of misfortune that one knows a person's steadfastness, and that over a long time, not otherwise; with attention, not without attention; with wisdom, not with poor wisdom.<br>Great King, it is by conversation that one knows a person's wisdom, and that over a long time, not otherwise; with attention, not without attention; with wisdom, not with poor wisdom.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.11" },
{ text: `Not by appearance<br>Is a person known,<br>Not by a quick glance<br>Can one place confidence.<br>Under the guise of morality,<br>With self-controlled appearance,<br>Those who live loosely,<br>Live carelessly in this world.<br>Like a clay earring<br>Faking a real earring,<br>Like a half-penny coin<br>Painted with gold.<br>Some live hidden,<br>Concealed beneath their exterior,<br>Their inner body is impure,<br>Their outside is made beautiful.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.11" },
{ text: `- Great King, according to the degree of liking, I say that particular sensual pleasure is supreme among the five strands of sensual pleasure. And, Great King, those forms, those sounds... those odors... those tastes... are liked by some people, disliked by others. Great King, if a person likes certain forms, and his mind is completely satisfied, not wishing for any other forms more excellent than those, then for him those forms are supreme, for him those forms are unsurpassed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.12" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion spoke this verse:<br><br>Thinking of their own benefit,<br>They rob and harm others,<br>When others rob and harm them,<br>They are harmed and harm in return.<br>The fool thinks thus,<br>When evil is not yet ripe,<br>When evil becomes ripe,<br>The fool experiences suffering.<br>Killing, one is killed,<br>Conquering, one is conquered,<br>Abusing, one is abused,<br>Harassing, one is harassed,<br>Thus action evolves,<br>Being harmed, one harms in return.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.14" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, is there one thing that can lead to the attainment and maintenance of both kinds of happiness: happiness in this life and happiness in the next?<br>- Heedfulness, Great King, is one thing that can lead to the attainment and maintenance of both kinds of happiness: happiness in this life and happiness in the next. Great King, just as among all beings with feet, the footprint of the elephant covers all of them and is considered foremost in size, so too, Great King, heedfulness is one thing that can lead to the attainment and maintenance of both kinds of happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.17" },
{ text: `Whoever wishes for long life,<br>Freedom from disease, excellent complexion,<br>Rebirth in heaven,<br>Or birth in noble families,<br>Should continuously increase<br>Effort and not stop.<br>The wise praise<br>Good deeds done without heedfulness.<br>For good people<br>Performing meritorious deeds,<br>The wise, not being heedless,<br>Obtain both benefits:<br>Benefit in this life,<br>Benefit in the next life.<br>The hero is called<br>A true wise person,<br>If he knows how to grasp<br>Happiness for himself.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.17" },
{ text: `Ānanda, it is because I rely on good friendship, associate with the good, that beings subject to birth are freed from birth; beings subject to aging are freed from aging; beings subject to sickness are freed from sickness; beings subject to death are freed from death; beings subject to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are freed from those. And by this method, Ānanda, you should understand how the entire holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.18" },
{ text: `Great King, if the Great King dwells heedfully, relying on heedfulness, then the self is protected and guarded, the inner palace is protected and guarded, the treasury is protected and guarded.<br><br>Whoever wishes for wealth<br>Should continuously increase,<br>The wise praise<br>Good deeds done without heedfulness.<br>For good people<br>Performing meritorious deeds,<br>The wise, not being heedless,<br>Obtain both benefits:<br>Benefit in this life,<br>Benefit in the next life.<br>The hero is called<br>A true wise person,<br>If he knows how to grasp<br>Happiness for himself.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.18" },
{ text: `Grain, wealth, gold and silver,<br>Or any possessions,<br>Slaves and servants,<br>And dependent lives,<br>That person must leave,<br>Cannot take any with him,<br>All must be left behind<br>When he goes alone.<br>Only actions done<br>By body, speech, and mind<br>Truly belong to him,<br>He takes them when he goes,<br>Action follows him<br>Like a shadow that never leaves.<br>Therefore, do good,<br>Store up for the next life,<br>Merit for the next life<br>Is a support for beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.20" },
{ text: `- So it is, Great King. So it is, Great King. All beings must die, end in death, do not overcome death. Just as, Great King, all pots made by a potter, whether unfired or fired, all those pots must break, end in breaking, do not overcome breaking. So too, Great King, all beings must die, end in death, do not overcome death.<br><br>All beings will die,<br>Life ends in death,<br>According to their actions they will go,<br>Receiving the results of good and evil,<br>Evil deeds go to hell,<br>Good deeds go to heaven.<br>Therefore, do good,<br>Store up for the next life,<br>Merit for the next life<br>Is a support for beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.22" },
{ text: `- Great King, there are three things in the world that, when arising, bring harm, suffering, and discomfort. What three? Great King, greed is a thing in the world that, when arising, brings harm, suffering, and discomfort. Great King, hatred is a thing in the world that, when arising, brings harm, suffering, and discomfort. Great King, delusion is a thing in the world that, when arising, brings harm, suffering, and discomfort. These three things, when arising, bring harm, suffering, and discomfort.<br><br>Greed, hatred, delusion — these three,<br>Are evil states for a person,<br>They harm the self,<br>They produce the self,<br>Like the bark and heartwood<br>Produce the fruit of the tree.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.23" },
{ text: `Like a great mountain of rock,<br>Standing high in the sky,<br>Advancing, surrounding<br>And crushing all four sides.<br>So too, aging and death<br>Come to living beings,<br>Noble warriors, brahmins,<br>Vessas, suddas, outcasts,<br>Scavengers, refuse collectors —<br>No one can escape,<br>All are conquered.<br>Here no elephant troops,<br>No chariots or infantry,<br>No magical spells,<br>No war of wealth<br>Can help win the battle<br>Against aging and death.<br>Therefore, the wise person,<br>Seeing his own good,<br>Places his trust<br>In the Buddha, Dhamma, and Saṅgha.<br>One who with body, speech, and mind<br>Practices the Dhamma rightly,<br>Is praised in this life,<br>And in the next life rejoices in heaven.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.25" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>I have been freed<br>From Māra's snare,<br>Freed from the rope of sensual pleasures,<br>Both in the heavenly and human worlds.<br>I have been freed<br>From Māra's bondage,<br>O Death, you are<br>defeated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.4" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I have been freed from all snares in the heavenly and human worlds. Bhikkhus, you too have been freed from all snares in the heavenly and human worlds. Bhikkhus, wander forth for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans. Do not go two together. Bhikkhus, teach the Dhamma that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing. Reveal the holy life completely perfect and pure. There are beings with little dust in their eyes who will perish if they do not hear the Dhamma. They will become those who understand the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, I will go to Uruvelā, the town of Senā, to teach the Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.5" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br><br>Excellent is the Muni,<br>Living in an empty hut,<br>Knowing how to tame himself,<br>There he abides.<br>Living having abandoned all,<br>With practice appropriate,<br>Many kinds of roaming beasts,<br>Many frightening things,<br>Many mosquitoes and poisonous snakes —<br>Not a single hair of the Muni<br>Living in the empty hut<br>Is disturbed.<br>Though the sky splits, the earth trembles,<br>Though all beings are terrified,<br>Though spears, swords, and arrows<br>Are thrown at his chest,<br>Buddhas do not create<br>Bases for attachment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.6" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>Why are you still sleeping,<br>Why are you still sleeping,<br>Why do you sleep like this,<br>Like a dead man curled up?<br>Thinking the house is empty,<br>Thus you sleep,<br>Why do you sleep like this<br>When the sun has risen?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>When there is no craving,<br>With its net and poison,<br>One thus freed<br>Is not led anywhere.<br>Māra! The Enlightened One,<br>All attachments destroyed,<br>If he sleeps,<br>What can you do?`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.7" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>A father is joyful because of his son,<br>A cowherd is joyful because of his cows,<br>A person is joyful because of attachments,<br>One without attachments is not joyful.<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>A father grieves because of his children,<br>A cowherd grieves because of his cows,<br>A person grieves because of attachments,<br>One without attachments does not grieve.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.8" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, the life span of humans in this world is short, and one must go to the future. Do good deeds, live the holy life. There is nothing that is born that does not die. Bhikkhus, one who lives long lives only a hundred years, or a little more or less.<br><br>Human life is short,<br>The good should be concerned,<br>Like a burning head, live,<br>Death will surely come.<br><br>Days and nights pass,<br>Life span ends,<br>The lives of people dry up<br>Like small streams on a mountain.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.9" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>Why do you lie there drowsy,<br>Or seek poetry and verse?<br>Is it because there are many things to do<br>That don't wait for you?<br>All alone and solitary<br>On your bed and seat,<br>With a sleepy face,<br>Why do you sleep like this?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>I do not lie there drowsy,<br>I do not seek poetry and verse,<br>My goal is attained,<br>What sorrow could I have!<br>I sit and lie down alone<br>On a quiet bed and seat,<br>Peacefully I rest,<br>With loving-kindness, compassion for beings.<br>Those whose chests are pierced,<br>Gasping with pounding hearts,<br>Still find sleep,<br>Though severely wounded.<br>Why should I not sleep<br>When I am unwounded,<br>When awake I have no worry,<br>When asleep I have no fear,<br>Day and night no afflictions<br>Disturb my mind?<br>I see no danger<br>Anywhere in the world,<br>Therefore I rest,<br>With loving-kindness, compassion for beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.13" },
{ text: `Then Māra thought: 'This Samaṇa Gotama, surrounded by a large lay assembly, is teaching the Dhamma. Let me approach Samaṇa Gotama and blind this assembly.' Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br><br>It is not fitting at all<br>For you to teach others,<br>Between those who agree and disagree,<br>Do not engage in that practice.<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>With loving-kindness and compassion,<br>The Enlightened One teaches others,<br>Between those who agree and disagree,<br>The Tathāgata is truly liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.14" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>All movements of the mind<br>Are a snare in the sky,<br>With that snare<br>I will bind you,<br>O samaṇa,<br>You have not escaped me.<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Forms, sounds, tastes, smells, touches —<br>They delight the mind,<br>I have no delight in them,<br>I have gone beyond them,<br>O Death, you are<br>defeated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.15" },
{ text: `And the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br>Form, feeling, perception, formations, consciousness —<br>That is not me,<br>That is not mine,<br>Thus, here I am detached,<br>Detached, the mind is at peace,<br>All fetters transcended,<br>Though searching everywhere,<br>Māra's army cannot find him.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.16" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br>Form, sound, taste, and smell,<br>Together with all touches and mind-objects,<br>They are terrifying things,<br>They delude the world.<br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Mindful, goes beyond them,<br>Beyond Māra's power,<br>Like the radiant sun.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.17" },
{ text: `Once the Blessed One was staying in Kosala, at the foot of the Snowy Mountain, in a small forest hut. While the Blessed One was alone in seclusion, the following thought arose: 'Is it possible to rule without killing, without causing others to kill; without conquering, without causing others to conquer; without sorrow, without causing others to sorrow, in accordance with Dhamma?'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Even if a whole mountain<br>Became solid gold,<br>Even double that,<br>It would not satisfy<br>The ambition of one person.<br>Knowing this, one should practice,<br>Who sees suffering clearly,<br>And the cause of suffering,<br>How could such a person<br>Incline towards sensual desires?<br>Having known that attachments<br>Are a bondage in the world,<br>Knowing thus, one should learn<br>To cut all bonds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.20" },
{ text: `Then Māra, having changed into the form of a brahmin with a large topknot, wearing an antelope skin, old, bent like a roof beam, breathing heavily, holding a staff of udumbara wood, went to those bhikkhus and said: 'Venerable sirs, you have gone forth too young, in your prime, with black hair, in the bloom of youth, in the spring of life, not yet enjoying sensual pleasures. Enjoy human sensual pleasures, venerable sirs, do not neglect the present to run after what is affected by time.'<br><br>- Brahmin, we do not neglect the present to run after what is affected by time. And, brahmin, we neglect what is affected by time to run after the present. Brahmin, the Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are affected by time, full of suffering, full of despair; the danger there is even greater. But this Dhamma is present, not affected by time, inviting inspection, leading onward, and to be experienced by the wise for themselves.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.21" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion spoke this verse:<br>Who sees suffering clearly,<br>And the cause of suffering,<br>How could such a person<br>Incline towards sensual desires?<br>Having known that attachments<br>Are a bondage in the world,<br>Knowing thus, one should learn<br>To cut all bonds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.21" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Samiddhi, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br>With faith,<br>I left home to homelessness,<br>My mindfulness and wisdom grow,<br>My mind is concentrated.<br>Whatever form you create,<br>It does not frighten me.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.22" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>The hero of steadfast mind,<br>Always delighting in jhāna, meditation,<br>Full of ardor day and night,<br>But not attached to life,<br>Conquers the army of Death,<br>Does not go to further rebirth,<br>Conquers craving, the root of craving.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.23" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the Blessed One; having approached, he spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>With a sorrowful mind,<br>You meditate in the forest,<br>Because your wealth has wasted away,<br>Or because you long for wealth?<br>Perhaps you have committed a crime in the village.<br>Why do you not make friends<br>With your relatives and neighbors?<br>Why can you not<br>Make friends with anyone?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>All roots of sorrow pulled out,<br>Without crime, I meditate,<br>Without sorrow, I meditate.<br>All craving for existence destroyed,<br>Taint-free, I meditate,<br>O heedless relative!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.24" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>With the goal achieved,<br>With body and mind at peace,<br>I conquered the army<br>Of lovely, delightful forms.<br>Alone I sit in jhāna,<br>Attaining true happiness,<br>Therefore, among beings,<br>I have no friend.<br>Making friends with anyone<br>Is not needed for me.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.25" },


{ text: `Then the daughter of Māra, Aratī, spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>How does a bhikkhu,<br>Living amidst many obstacles,<br>Having crossed five floods,<br>Strive to cross a sixth?<br>How can he meditate,<br>Amidst many sensual perceptions,<br>Kept outside of him,<br>Not captured by him?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>With body tranquil,<br>With mind well liberated,<br>Without any mental activities,<br>Mindful, not attached,<br>Knowing the Dhamma well,<br>Without thought, practicing jhāna.<br>Without anger, without distraction,<br>Without drowsiness, without laziness,<br>Thus that bhikkhu,<br>Living amidst many obstacles,<br>Having crossed five floods,<br>Strives to cross a sixth,<br>Thus he meditates,<br>Amidst many sensual perceptions,<br>Kept outside of him,<br>Not captured by him.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.25" },
{ text: `The bhikkhunī Alavikā, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse:<br><br>There is an escape in the world,<br>Through wisdom, I have realized it.<br>O heedless relative,<br>How can you know that Dhamma?<br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>The burning mass of aggregates is their head.<br>What you call sensual pleasure,<br>I call non-pleasure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.1" },
{ text: `The bhikkhunī Somā, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br><br>What does a woman's nature matter<br>When the mind is well concentrated,<br>When wisdom is developed,<br>Contemplating the Dhamma rightly?<br>One who thinks:<br>'Am I a woman, a man,<br>Or what am I?'<br>Is fit for Māra to address.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.2" },
{ text: `The bhikkhunī Vijayā, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to Māra:<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, smells, touches,<br>Make the mind infatuated.<br>I give them back to Māra,<br>I have no need for them.<br>With this impure body,<br>Fragile and easily broken,<br>I am disgusted and ashamed,<br>Sensual desire is destroyed.<br>Those born in the form realm,<br>Those deluded by the formless realm,<br>Attaining peaceful jhāna,<br>In every place, darkness is destroyed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.4" },
{ text: `( Calā ):<br>Having been born, one must die,<br>Having been born, one sees suffering,<br>Fetters bind and harm,<br>Therefore I do not delight in birth.<br>The Buddha teaches the Dhamma,<br>Leading beyond rebirth,<br>Destroying all suffering,<br>Helping me abide in truth.<br>Beings inclined to the form realm,<br>They are deluded by the formless realm,<br>If they do not know cessation,<br>They go to further rebirth.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.6" },
{ text: `Then Māra approached the bhikkhunī Sisupacālā; having approached, he said to the bhikkhunī Sisupacālā:<br>For whom are you shaven-headed,<br>Appearing as a female samaṇa?<br>Do you not like false teachings?<br>Then for whom do you practice,<br>O foolish one?<br><br>( Sisupacālā ):<br>Those who follow wrong view,<br>Followers of outside sects,<br>I do not like their Dhamma,<br>I am not skilled in their Dhamma!<br>There is the Sakya clan.<br>From them the unequaled Buddha was born,<br>He has conquered all,<br>He has crushed Māra's army,<br>Everywhere, in all places,<br>No one can defeat him.<br>He is completely liberated,<br>Not bound by anything.<br>The all-seeing Dhamma-eye,<br>All kamma destroyed,<br>Liberated, attachments destroyed.<br>The Blessed One is my Teacher,<br>I delight in his teaching.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.8" },
{ text: `By whom is this being born?<br>By whom is this being made?<br>Where is the maker of this being?<br>From where does being arise?<br>Where does being cease?"<br><br>Then the bhikkhunī Vajirā, knowing it was Māra, answered Māra with this verse:<br><br>Why do you keep saying<br>The word "being"?<br>Is it, Māra, that you<br>Have fallen into wrong view?<br>This is a heap of mere formations,<br>Here no being can be found.<br>For just as with the assembly of parts,<br>The word "chariot" is used,<br>So too, when the aggregates are present,<br>There is the convention "a being."<br>Only suffering arises,<br>Suffering remains, suffering ceases.<br>Nothing but suffering arises,<br>Nothing but suffering ceases.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.10" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, Brahmā Sahampati spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>Dwell in the mountains,<br>Remote from villages,<br>Live a life of liberation,<br>Abandoning all fetters!<br>If there you do not attain<br>What you love, what you like,<br>Then live among the Saṅgha,<br>Guarding, keeping mindfulness,<br>And wander for alms,<br>From house to house,<br>Faculties guarded,<br>Heedful, keeping mindfulness.<br>Dwell in the mountains,<br>Remote from villages,<br>Free from all fear,<br>Fearless, live liberated.<br>Where there are poisonous snakes,<br>Where there are lightning flashes and thunder,<br>In the pitch-black night,<br>The bhikkhu sits silently,<br>Not trembling, not frightened,<br>His hair does not stand on end.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 6.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn6.13" },
{ text: `So too, brahmin, if you slander us who are not slanderers; revile us who are not revilers; quarrel with us who are not quarrelers — we do not accept that from you. Then, brahmin, that matter returns to you. Brahmin, that matter belongs only to you. Brahmin, whoever, when slandered, slanders in return; when reviled, reviles in return; when quarreled with, quarrels in return — that person, brahmin, is considered to have partaken and shared with you. But we do not partake of that matter with you, do not share that matter with you. Therefore, brahmin, that matter returns to you! Brahmin, that matter returns to you!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.2" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>For one without anger,<br>Whence does anger come?<br>Living tamed, with right livelihood,<br>Liberated, through right knowledge.<br>That one lives thus,<br>A life of peace.<br>Those who, when reviled,<br>Revile in return,<br>Do evil to themselves,<br>And also evil to others.<br>Those who, when reviled,<br>Do not revile in return,<br>That person wins a battle,<br>A victory for both self and other.<br>That one seeks the benefit<br>Of both self and other.<br>And the one who reviled,<br>Understanding, calms down.<br>A physician to both,<br>Healing self and healing other,<br>People think him a fool,<br>Because they do not understand the Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.2" },
{ text: `Inner and outer fetters,<br>Beings are fettered by them.<br>I ask Gotama,<br>Who can be freed from this fetter?"<br><br>( Blessed One )<br>One with wisdom, established in virtue,<br>Developing mind and wisdom,<br>Ardent and heedful,<br>That bhikkhu is freed from the fetter.<br>One who has abandoned<br>Greed, hatred, and ignorance,<br>The taint-free Arahant,<br>That one is freed from the fetter.<br>Where name-and-form<br>Is completely destroyed without remainder,<br>Where the impediment of form-perception is removed,<br>There the fetter is cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.6" },
{ text: `Then the brahmin Sundarika Bhāradvāja went to the Blessed One; having arrived, he said to the Blessed One: "What is your birth, venerable sir?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Don't ask about birth,<br>Ask about conduct.<br>Fire is produced<br>From whatever wood.<br>Though from a low family,<br>A sage who strives diligently,<br>Is considered of noble birth,<br>Conscientious, restraining evil.<br>Tamed by truth,<br>Practiced in virtue,<br>A master of sacred scriptures,<br>The holy life perfected.<br>Bring your sacrificial offering,<br>Invite that one,<br>Perform the sacrifice at the proper time,<br>That one is worthy of offerings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.9" },
{ text: `Then the brahmin Kasī Bhāradvāja spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>You claim to be a farmer,<br>But I do not see you plowing.<br>When asked, a farmer should speak up —<br>How can we know that you really plow?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Faith is the seed,<br>Austerity is the rain,<br>Wisdom for me<br>Is the plow and yoke.<br>Conscience is the plow-pole,<br>Mind is the binding-tie,<br>Mindfulness for me<br>Is the plowshare and goad.<br>Body is guarded,<br>Speech is guarded,<br>In eating food,<br>I use just enough.<br>I pull out falsehood<br>With the truth,<br>Delight in Nibbāna<br>Is my liberation.<br>Energy for me<br>Is the yoke-carrying ability,<br>It draws me onward to<br>The security from bondage,<br>Going forward, not returning,<br>Where I go, no sorrow.<br>Thus this plowing,<br>Leads to the fruit of the Deathless,<br>After plowing this plowing,<br>One is freed from all suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.11" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Again and again,<br>They sow the seed.<br>Again and again,<br>The sky sends rain.<br>Again and again,<br>The farmer plows the field.<br>Again and again,<br>Grain comes to the country.<br>Again and again,<br>Beggars go about.<br>Again and again,<br>Donors give.<br>Again and again,<br>After giving,<br>Donors go to heaven.<br>Again and again,<br>The milkman milks the cows.<br>Again and again,<br>The calf goes to its mother.<br>Again and again,<br>They become weary and exhausted.<br>Again and again,<br>The fool enters the womb.<br>Again and again,<br>They are born and they die.<br>Again and again,<br>They are carried to the cemetery.<br>Those who have found the path,<br>Which does not lead to further rebirth,<br>The greatly wise one,<br>Does not be born again.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.12" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, the brahmin Devahitā said this verse to the Blessed One:<br>Where should one make an offering<br>Worthy of a donor?<br>Where does a gift<br>Bring great fruit?<br>What kind of offering?<br>What kind of homage?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who knows former lives,<br>Sees heaven and hell,<br>Has ended rebirth,<br>Direct knowledge, a sage.<br>One should give to that one,<br>Giving yields great fruit.<br>Thus should one offer,<br>Thus should one pay homage.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.13" },
{ text: `Then the brahmin Mānaṭṭhadda, after sitting on his own seat, spoke this verse to the Blessed One:<br>Toward whom should one not be proud?<br>Whom should one respect?<br>Whom should one revere?<br>Whom should one honor as good?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Toward mother and father,<br>Toward an elder brother,<br>Toward a teacher as the fourth,<br>One should not be proud,<br>One should respect them,<br>One should revere them,<br>One should honor them as good.<br>The Arahants,<br>Cool, taints destroyed,<br>Done what had to be done —<br>Subdue your pride before them,<br>That unsurpassed one,<br>You should indeed pay homage.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.15" },
{ text: `What are you doing now,<br>In the sāla forest,<br>That you live alone,<br>What happiness do you find,<br>Bhikkhu Gotama?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>I am not doing anything<br>In the sāla forest.<br>The root has been cut for me,<br>The whole dense forest.<br>Thus I am freed<br>From all jungle thorns.<br>My mind is not pierced,<br>Alone I live in bliss,<br>Abandoning all discontent,<br>I abide in delight and joy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.17" },
{ text: `In the deep forest,<br>Full of frightening terrors,<br>Empty, desolate,<br>You enter deep alone,<br>Body unmoving, steadfast,<br>Beautiful and majestic.<br>Bhikkhu, you meditate<br>With mind serene.<br>Here there is no singing,<br>Here there is no speech,<br>Alone in the deep forest,<br>The noble one dwells.<br>This to me is<br>Wonderful and marvelous.<br>When you live alone,<br>Delighting in the empty forest,<br>I think you wish to<br>Be born as a companion<br>Of the Lord of the World,<br>In the unsurpassed Triple Realm.<br>Why then, venerable sir,<br>Do you not leave the desolate forest,<br>Practice austerity here,<br>To attain Brahmā's realm?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Whatever wishes there are,<br>Whatever sensual delights there are,<br>Whatever ordinary people<br>Are attached to in various realms,<br>The cravings that arise<br>From the root of ignorance —<br>All that I have destroyed,<br>Both root and all.<br>Now I have no wishes,<br>No craving, no attachment;<br>Regarding all phenomena,<br>I see them as pure.<br>Having attained perfect enlightenment,<br>And the supreme goal,<br>I develop jhāna,<br>Peaceful, without fear.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.18" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, the brahmin Mātaposaka said to the Blessed One:<br>- Venerable Gotama, I seek material food in the proper way. Having sought material food in the proper way, I support my mother and father. Venerable Gotama, doing this, am I doing my duty?<br>- Brahmin, doing this, you are doing your duty. Brahmin, one who seeks material food in the proper way, and having done so, supports his mother and father, that person accumulates much merit.<br><br>Whoever in the proper way<br>Supports mother and father,<br>Because of this good deed<br>Toward father and mother,<br>The wise in this world<br>Praise that person,<br>After death, they are reborn<br>In heaven's bliss.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.19" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, the brahmin Bhikkhaka said to the Blessed One:<br>- Venerable Gotama, I am a beggar, and you are also a beggar. What difference is there between us?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Not everyone who begs<br>Is called a bhikkhu.<br>If one holds a harmful practice,<br>One is not a bhikkhu.<br>One who lives in this world,<br>Abandoning merit and evil,<br>Destroying all evil states,<br>Practicing the holy life,<br>Living with right knowledge,<br>That one is called a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.20" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>The good Dhamma is a lake,<br>Virtue is the bathing ford,<br>Stainless, pure,<br>Praised by the good,<br>Where the wise<br>Often bathe, removing impurities,<br>With clean hands and feet,<br>They cross to the far shore.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.21" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, having by himself abandoned discontent and aroused satisfaction, on that occasion spoke these verses:<br><br>I have gone forth<br>From home to homelessness,<br>My mind now wanders restlessly,<br>Arising from darkness.<br>A noble archer's son,<br>Skilled in the bow,<br>Though a thousand arrows shoot from all sides,<br>He would not flee in confusion.<br>Even if women come,<br>Though many, though numerous,<br>They would not disturb me,<br>For I am established in the Dhamma.<br>I have heard the Buddha,<br>Of the sun's lineage,<br>Teach the path to Nibbāna,<br>Herein I delight.<br>If I abide thus,<br>Māra, should you come,<br>Such is my conduct,<br>You will not find my path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.1" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, having by himself abandoned discontent and aroused satisfaction, on that occasion spoke this verse:<br><br>I have abandoned pleasure and displeasure,<br>All thoughts of household life,<br>Not creating any basis<br>For attachment to sensual desires.<br>One who is free from the forest of greed,<br>Free from all sensual desires,<br>Detached, without clinging,<br>Is truly called a bhikkhu.<br>Whatever is in the earth realm or formless realm,<br>All form realms in the world,<br>Everything is subject to change,<br>Everything is impermanent.<br>One who knows thus,<br>Will conduct oneself rightly.<br>Beings are always attached<br>To various attachments,<br>To what they see, hear,<br>Smell, taste, and touch.<br>One who has abandoned desire<br>For these, with mind not defiled,<br>Not clinging to any of this,<br>That one is called a sage.<br>Regarding the sixty<br>Vain, non-Dhamma thoughts,<br>Ordinary people are attached,<br>Grasping and clinging.<br>A bhikkhu without afflictions,<br>Who speaks no harsh words,<br>Clear-seeing, mind steady,<br>Not deceitful, heedful,<br>Free from all craving.<br>The sage has attained<br>The peaceful state of Nibbāna,<br>Waiting for the time of death,<br>With peaceful mind,<br>He has entered Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.2" },
{ text: `Disciples of Gotama,<br>Abandon conceit,<br>And also abandon<br>The path that leads to conceit.<br>If you are completely intoxicated<br>By the path of conceit,<br>You will torment yourselves<br>For a long time.<br>Those who despise others,<br>With contempt and conceit,<br>Walking the path of conceit,<br>Will fall into hell.<br>Those ones grieve<br>For a long time,<br>Led by conceit,<br>They are reborn in hell.<br>A bhikkhu never<br>Grieves or suffers,<br>Victorious on the right path,<br>His conduct is right,<br>That one enjoys<br>Honor and happiness,<br>Truly called<br>One who enjoys the Dhamma's bliss.<br>Therefore in this world,<br>Not rough, but energetic,<br>Abandoning all hindrances,<br>Living pure and clean,<br>And destroying conceit<br>Completely, without remainder,<br>Putting an end to all defilements,<br>With radiant wisdom,<br>That one is considered<br>To live peaceful and happy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.3" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa spoke this verse to the Venerable Ānanda:<br>Craving burns me,<br>My mind is on fire.<br>It would be good, O disciple of Gotama,<br>Out of compassion,<br>To speak the Dhamma that extinguishes the fire.<br><br>( Ānanda ):<br>It is from distorted perception<br>That your mind is burning.<br>Abandon the sign of the beautiful<br>That leads to sensual desire,<br>See the formations as impermanent,<br>Suffering, and not-self,<br>Extinguish the great craving,<br>Do not keep burning long;<br>Develop the mind on the foul,<br>One-pointed, well concentrated,<br>Practice mindfulness of the body,<br>Do much of the disgust;<br>Practice the signless,<br>Destroy the underlying tendency to conceit,<br>Then, by breaking through conceit,<br>You will live at peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.4" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Blessed One, spoke these appropriate verses of praise:<br><br>Whatever speech one utters,<br>If it does not torment oneself,<br>Nor harm others,<br>That speech is well spoken.<br>One who speaks affectionate speech,<br>Speech that brings delight,<br>Speech that is not evil,<br>That speech is affectionate.<br>True speech is the deathless speech,<br>This is the ancient Dhamma,<br>The good person is said to be<br>Established in truth,<br>In meaning and in Dhamma,<br>Thus the wise say.<br>The word spoken by the Buddha,<br>Leading to the security of Nibbāna,<br>Making an end of all suffering,<br>That is the supreme speech.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.5" },
{ text: `Then a devata dwelling in that forest, out of compassion for that bhikkhu, wishing for his welfare, wishing to arouse him, approached that bhikkhu. Having approached, that devata spoke these verses to him:<br><br>You wish for seclusion,<br>Have come to live in the forest,<br>Yet your mind wanders out,<br>Following the external world.<br>Face to face with yourself,<br>Control your desire,<br>Thus you will be happy,<br>Free from craving.<br>Abandon discontent,<br>Abide mindful,<br>You will become a good person,<br>We praise you.<br>The dust of hell is hard to cross.<br>Do not transport yourself<br>With the dust of sensual desires,<br>Like a bird, its body covered with dust,<br>Shakes itself so the dust falls.<br>So too a bhikkhu,<br>Diligent, mindful,<br>Struggling, shakes off<br>The dust that clings to him.<br><br>That bhikkhu, stirred by the devata, was greatly moved.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.1" },
{ text: `Bhikkhu, wake up,<br>Why are you still lying down?<br>What benefit do you have<br>From your sleep?<br>How can one who is sick, who has been struck by a dart,<br>Who has been beaten, sleep?<br>Through faith, you went forth,<br>Left home for homelessness,<br>That faith should be developed,<br>Do not let sleep conquer you.<br><br>( The bhikkhu ):<br>Sensual pleasures are impermanent,<br>Only fools delight in them.<br>Freed from the fetters,<br>No longer attached.<br>With such a gone forth life,<br>Why should sensual fever afflict me?<br>Having conquered sensual desire,<br>Crossed beyond the net of ignorance,<br>With pure right knowledge,<br>With such a gone forth life,<br>Why should sensual fever afflict me?<br>With knowledge destroying ignorance,<br>All taints destroyed,<br>Without sorrow, without grief,<br>With such a gone forth life,<br>Why should sensual fever afflict me?<br>Energetic and ardent,<br>Always striving onward,<br>Aspiring to Nibbāna,<br>With such a gone forth life,<br>Why should sensual fever afflict me?`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.2" },
{ text: `Those bhikkhus, having completed the rains retreat, after three months, started wandering. A devata dwelling in that forest, not seeing those bhikkhus, lamented and grieved, and on that occasion spoke this verse:<br><br>Today my mind<br>Feels no joy,<br>Seeing many seats<br>Empty, without people.<br>Those learned ones,<br>Who taught the Dhamma so beautifully,<br>Disciples of Gotama,<br>Where are they now?"<br><br>Hearing this, another devata spoke these verses to that devata:<br><br>They have gone to Magadha,<br>They have gone to Kosala,<br>And some of them<br>Have gone to the Vajji country.<br>Like deer freed from a trap,<br>They run about in all directions.<br>Bhikkhus have no homes,<br>Thus they live liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.4" },
{ text: `At that time, the Venerable Ānanda was living too busy with many contacts among laypeople. Then a devata dwelling in that forest, out of compassion for the Venerable Ānanda, wishing for his welfare, wishing to arouse him, approached him. Having approached, that devata spoke these verses to the Venerable Ānanda:<br><br>You have chosen to live<br>At the root of a tree,<br>Your mind has resolved on one thing:<br>The goal of Nibbāna.<br>Gotama, practice jhāna,<br>Live, do not be heedless,<br>What use are those idle talks<br>And meaningless conversations to you?`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.5" },
{ text: `Having approached, that devata spoke these verses to the Venerable Nāgadatta:<br><br>Nāgadatta,<br>Enter the village at the proper time,<br>And when you return from the village,<br>Return early.<br>You live too involved<br>With laypeople,<br>Overcome by too many<br>Feelings of pain and pleasure.<br>I fear that Nāgadatta,<br>This reckless one,<br>Will be bound and fettered<br>By household affairs.<br>Do not fall into<br>The power of Death,<br>How can one escape<br>Māra's control?<br><br>The Venerable Nāgadatta, stirred by that devata, was greatly moved.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.7" },
{ text: `On the riverbank, at the market,<br>At rest stops, along the road,<br>People gather,<br>Then disputes arise.<br>Between you and me,<br>What is the difference?"<br><br>( The bhikkhu ):<br>With many sounds back and forth,<br>An ascetic who endures them,<br>Should not feel annoyed,<br>Should not become attached.<br>One who is disturbed by sounds,<br>Like a deer in the forest,<br>Is called light-minded,<br>Difficult to practice successfully.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.8" },
{ text: `That bhikkhu, hearing the sound of musical instruments, drums, etc., a great noise arose, he lamented and on that occasion spoke these verses:<br><br>We live alone<br>In the solitary forest,<br>Like a peeled log<br>Rolling in the deep forest,<br>Delighting in the dark night,<br>As on this night,<br>Who lives a more miserable life<br>Than we do now?"<br><br>Then a devata dwelling in that forest, out of compassion for that bhikkhu, wishing for his welfare, wishing to arouse him, approached that bhikkhu. Having approached, that devata spoke these verses:<br><br>You live alone<br>In the solitary forest,<br>Like a peeled log<br>Rolling in the deep forest.<br>Many people long for<br>Such a life as yours,<br>Like those in hell<br>Long to be reborn in heaven.<br><br>That bhikkhu, stirred by that devata, was greatly moved.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.9" },
{ text: `Having approached, that devata spoke these verses to the bhikkhu:<br><br>You attend unwisely,<br>Therefore you are infatuated with thoughts.<br>Give up unwise attention,<br>Attend wisely.<br>Relying on the Buddha, Dhamma, and Saṅgha,<br>Keeping the precepts, not backsliding,<br>You will surely attain<br>Joy and rapture.<br>With joy suffused,<br>You will make an end of suffering.<br><br>That bhikkhu, stirred by that devata, was greatly moved.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.11" },
{ text: `Now it is midday,<br>The birds have settled in silence,<br>The great forest echoes,<br>It makes me tremble with fear."<br><br>( The bhikkhu ):<br>Now it is midday,<br>The birds have settled in silence,<br>The great forest echoes,<br>Joy comes to me.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.12" },
{ text: `In the past they lived happily,<br>The disciples of Gotama,<br>Not seeking food greedily,<br>Not seeking lodgings greedily,<br>Knowing the world is impermanent,<br>They made an end of suffering.<br>Now they have become evil-doers,<br>Like village chiefs,<br>They eat, then fall asleep,<br>Longing for others' possessions.<br>I salute the Saṅgha,<br>I pay homage to a few,<br>They wander without guidance.<br>They live like ghosts.<br>For those who live heedlessly,<br>I speak thus,<br>For those who are not heedless,<br>Sincere, I salute.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.13" },
{ text: `The Buddhas have taught<br>That form is not a living soul.<br>So how does this living soul<br>Come to be in this body?<br>Where do the bones and flesh come from<br>In this present body?<br>How does this living soul<br>Attach itself in the womb?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>First there is a drop of consciousness,<br>From that a small bud appears,<br>Soft flesh is produced,<br>Then it becomes a solid mass,<br>From that, the limbs arise,<br>Hair, nails, and teeth appear.<br>Whatever the mother eats,<br>Whatever food and drink,<br>The being inside the mother's womb,<br>Thereby is nourished.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.1" },
{ text: `It is not good at all<br>That a samaṇa like you,<br>Who has cut all fetters,<br>Who lives truly liberated,<br>Should continue to teach<br>Others to train."<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>O Yakkha Sakka,<br>Whatever reason beings<br>Live together in the world,<br>There is no reason<br>Worthy of the wise,<br>If with a compassionate mind,<br>With a mind full of faith,<br>One teaches others,<br>Therefore there is no attachment<br>Because of compassion.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.2" },
{ text: `( Yakkha ):<br>Greed and hatred,<br>From what cause do they arise?<br>Discontent and contentment,<br>Fear, from where do they arise?<br>From where do there arise<br>Thoughts and reflections,<br>Like crows that children<br>Let fly and then pull back?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Greed and hatred<br>Arise from this cause,<br>Discontent and contentment,<br>Fear arise from here.<br>From here there arise<br>Thoughts and reflections,<br>Like crows that children<br>Let fly and then pull back.<br>They arise from craving,<br>They arise from self.<br>Like a banyan tree<br>Grows from its own trunk.<br>Ordinary people cling to evil desires,<br>Like creepers spreading through the forest.<br>Those who understand<br>That from this cause they arise,<br>Destroy that cause.<br>Listen, yakkha,<br>They cross this flood,<br>The flood so hard to cross,<br>Never crossed before,<br>Without being reborn again.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.3" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Good indeed, constant mindfulness,<br>Through mindfulness, happiness grows,<br>With mindfulness, tomorrow is better,<br>Released from enmity.<br>For one who day and night<br>Has joy and non-harming,<br>Loving-kindness toward all beings,<br>That one has no enmity.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.4" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, does the Blessed One sleep happily?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>A brahmin at peace<br>Always lives happily,<br>Not clinging to sensual desires,<br>Cool, without attachments,<br>All clinging destroyed,<br>The mind's suffering tamed,<br>Peaceful, he lives happily,<br>His mind has attained peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.8" },
{ text: `( Yakkha ):<br>What for people in the world<br>Is the best treasure?<br>What when well practiced<br>Brings true happiness?<br>What among all tastes<br>Is the sweetest taste?<br>Living in what way<br>Is called the best life?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Faith for people in the world<br>Is the best treasure.<br>The Dhamma when well practiced<br>Brings true happiness.<br>Truth among all tastes<br>Is the sweetest taste.<br>Living with wisdom<br>Is called the best life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.12" },
{ text: `( Yakkha ):<br>How to cross the flood?<br>How to cross the great ocean?<br>How to escape suffering?<br>How to be purified?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>With faith, cross the flood.<br>With heedfulness, cross the ocean.<br>With energy, escape suffering.<br>With wisdom, be purified.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.12" },
{ text: `( Yakkha ):<br>How to obtain wisdom?<br>How to obtain wealth?<br>How to attain fame?<br>How to make friends?<br>From this life to the next,<br>How not to grieve?<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>One who trusts the Dhamma<br>Of the Arahants,<br>That Dhamma leads to attaining<br>Nibbāna (true bliss),<br>Well learned, not heedless,<br>The clear-eyed one discerns well,<br>By practicing thus,<br>That one obtains wisdom.<br>Doing what is proper,<br>Undertaking responsibilities,<br>Energetic, diligent,<br>Thus one obtains wealth,<br>With truth one attains fame,<br>Giving makes friends,<br>From this life to the next,<br>Thus one does not grieve.<br>A faithful householder<br>Seeking these four things:<br>Truth and self-control,<br>Perseverance and giving,<br>That one after death<br>Does not grieve.<br>From this life to the next,<br>After death, does not grieve.<br>I invite you to ask<br>Samaṇas and brahmins,<br>Is there any Dhamma<br>Better than these four:<br>Truth and self-control,<br>Giving and endurance?`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 10.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn10.12" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, Sakka, lord of devas, living on his own merit, ruling and governing the devas of the Thirty-three, will praise effort and energy. Here, bhikkhus, you shine forth, having gone forth in this well-taught Dhamma and Discipline, making effort, being diligent, or striving to attain the unattained, to realize the unrealized, to experience the unexperienced.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.1" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus,<br>In the forest or at the root of a tree,<br>Or in an empty hut,<br>Remember the Perfectly Enlightened One.<br>Your fear will disappear.<br>If you do not recollect the Buddha,<br>The supreme lord of the world,<br>And also the bull of a man,<br>Among the world of humans,<br>Then recollect the Dhamma,<br>Leading onward, well proclaimed.<br>If you do not recollect the Dhamma,<br>Leading onward, well proclaimed,<br>Then recollect the Saṅgha,<br>The unsurpassed field of merit.<br>Thus, bhikkhus,<br>Recollecting the Buddha,<br>Recollecting the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>Fear, terror,<br>Or hair-standing,<br>Will never arise.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.3" },
{ text: `In one's own welfare supreme,<br>Nothing surpasses patience.<br>One who has strength,<br>Endures the weak.<br>That patience is called supreme,<br>Always enduring the weak.<br>The strength of fools<br>Is considered strength,<br>Then the strength of the strong<br>Is called weakness.<br>A strong person protects the Dhamma,<br>Does not retaliate with words.<br>If reviled, reviling back,<br>The evil is even worse.<br>Reviled, not reviling back,<br>Wins a two-fold victory.<br>Living for the good of both,<br>One's own and the other's,<br>Knowing the other's anger,<br>He keeps mindfulness, calm.<br>He is a physician to both,<br>Healing himself and healing the other,<br>People think him a fool,<br>Because they are not skilled in the Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.4" },
{ text: `( Sakka ):<br>Everyone should strive<br>Until the goal is achieved.<br>When the goal is achieved,<br>One shines brilliantly.<br>There is nothing better<br>Than patience.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.8" },
{ text: `( Sakka ):<br>The fragrance of sages<br>Who have practiced for a long time,<br>Emanating from their bodies,<br>Let the wind carry it,<br>Like various garlands<br>Adorning the head.<br>Venerable ones, we<br>Desire that fragrance.<br>Nothing here<br>Makes the devas disgusted.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, in the past, when Sakka, lord of devas, was a human, he undertook and practiced seven vows. Because of undertaking these seven vows, Sakka attained the status of Sakka. What are the seven vows?<br><br>'For life, I will support my parents. For life, I will respect the elders of the family. For life, I will speak gently. For life, I will not speak divisively. For life, with a mind free from the stain of stinginess, I will live at home with a generous heart, with clean hands, delighting in giving, responsive to requests, happy to share gifts. For life, I will speak truthfully. For life, I will not get angry; if anger arises in me, I will quickly dispel it.'<br><br>Whoever supports his parents,<br>Respects the elders,<br>Speaks gentle words,<br>Abandons divisive speech,<br>Restrains stinginess,<br>Is a truthful person,<br>Tames his anger,<br>For such a person,<br>The devas of the Thirty-three<br>Call him a true person.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.11" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, in the past, in this very Rājagaha, there was a person who was poor, destitute, and miserable. That person undertook faith in the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, undertook virtue, undertook learning, undertook giving, undertook wisdom. Because of undertaking faith... virtue... learning... giving... wisdom, after death, with the breakup of the body, he was reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world, in the company of the devas of the Thirty-three. He surpassed the other devas in beauty and fame.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.14" },
{ text: `Whoever has faith in the Tathāgata,<br>Unshakable, well established,<br>Whoever has pure virtue,<br>Praised by the noble ones.<br>Whoever has faith in the Saṅgha,<br>Upright and with right view,<br>Is called 'not poor,'<br>Their life is not in vain.<br>Therefore, the wise person,<br>Should be devoted to the Buddha's teaching,<br>With faith and virtue,<br>And right view of the Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.14" },
{ text: `( Blessed One ):<br>Beautiful parks,<br>Beautiful forests,<br>Beautiful lotus ponds,<br>Are loved by people.<br>They are only worth<br>Little, insignificant.<br>In village or in forest,<br>On low ground or high,<br>Wherever an Arahant dwells,<br>That place is truly beautiful.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.15" },
{ text: `Humans perform sacrifices,<br>Beings wish for merit.<br>Those who do meritorious deeds<br>Leading to further rebirth,<br>Where does a gift<br>Have great fruit?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Those who have attained the four paths,<br>Those who have realized the four fruits,<br>That Saṅgha is upright,<br>Perfect in virtue, concentration, wisdom.<br>Humans perform sacrifices,<br>Beings wish for merit.<br>Those who do meritorious deeds<br>Leading to further rebirth,<br>Giving to the Saṅgha<br>Has great fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.16" },
{ text: `Then Sakka, lord of devas, spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br>Arise, O hero!<br>Victor in battle!<br>Who has laid down the burden,<br>Free from debt,<br>Wander the world,<br>Your mind well liberated,<br>Like the moon<br>Shining brightly on a full-moon night.<br><br>Brahmā Sahampati: - Not like that, lord of devas, is the homage to the Tathāgata. And this, lord of devas, is how the Tathāgata should be honored:<br><br>Arise, O hero!<br>Victor in battle!<br>Leader of the caravan,<br>Free from debt,<br>Wander the world,<br>Let the Blessed One teach the Dhamma,<br>There will be those who understand.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.17" },
{ text: `( Sakka ):<br>But I only pay homage<br>To those perfect in virtue and discipline,<br>Who for a long time have practiced jhāna,<br>Rightly gone forth,<br>Who have attained and realized<br>The ultimate goal of the holy life.<br>Besides those, householders<br>Who do merit, keep precepts,<br>Support their wives rightly,<br>Such lay followers,<br>I also pay homage to them,<br>O Mātali.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.18" },
{ text: `( Sakka ):<br>The Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>In this world with its devas,<br>The supreme Teacher,<br>That one I pay homage to,<br>O Mātali.<br>Those who have abandoned<br>Greed, hatred, and ignorance,<br>The taint-free Arahants,<br>Them I pay homage to.<br>Those who tame greed and hatred,<br>Have gone beyond the veil of ignorance,<br>Who delight in ending rebirth,<br>The learners,<br>Not heedless, training,<br>Them I pay homage to,<br>O Mātali.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.19" },
{ text: `( Sakka ):<br>Regarding those renunciants,<br>What pleases me<br>Is that when they return from the village,<br>They go without longing.<br>They have no grain stores,<br>No pots, no pans.<br>What they seek,<br>Others provide readily.<br>Therefore, they live<br>In this good manner.<br>They are wise,<br>Advising with good words.<br>Or they remain silent,<br>In a tranquil posture.<br>Devas fight with Asuras,<br>Humans also wage war.<br>O Mātali!<br>Among those who fight, they do not fight;<br>Among those with weapons, they are tranquil;<br>Among those who cling, they do not cling.<br>Therefore I pay homage to them,<br>O Mātali!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.20" },
{ text: `Killing what, is there happiness?<br>Killing what, is there no sorrow?<br>What is that one thing<br>Whose killing you approve,<br>Master Gotama?"<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>Killing anger one is happy,<br>Killing anger one does not sorrow.<br>Anger with its poisoned root,<br>With its sweetly deadly taste —<br>That killing the noble ones praise.<br>Killing that one does not sorrow,<br>O Vāsava!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.21" },
{ text: `My mind is not easily<br>Defeated,<br>Not easily drawn<br>Into the whirlpool of sensual desire.<br>For a long time I have known<br>That I am no longer angry.<br>Anger has no foothold<br>Anywhere in me.<br>I do not speak harsh words<br>Out of anger,<br>Nor do I praise<br>My own virtues.<br>Seeing my own benefit,<br>I restrain myself.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.22" },
{ text: `Do not let anger<br>Conquer and overwhelm a person!<br>Do not let hatred<br>Be a counterpart to hatred!<br>Without anger, harmless,<br>The noble ones always dwell.<br>Anger throws evil people<br>Like a stone falling into an abyss.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.25" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what is dependent origination? Bhikkhus, with ignorance as condition, formations arise; with formations as condition, consciousness; with consciousness as condition, name-and-form; with name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases; with the six sense bases as condition, contact; with contact as condition, feeling; with feeling as condition, craving; with craving as condition, clinging; with clinging as condition, existence; with existence as condition, birth; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Bhikkhus, this is called origination.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.1" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is birth? Whatever for this or that being, in this or that class of beings, there is birth, coming-to-be, descent, arising, the manifestation of the aggregates, the acquisition of the sense bases. Bhikkhus, this is called birth.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.2" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is ignorance? Not knowing suffering, not knowing the origin of suffering, not knowing the cessation of suffering, not knowing the path leading to the cessation of suffering. Bhikkhus, this is called ignorance.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.2" },
{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, with ignorance as condition, formations arise; ... (as above) ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. But with the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease; with the cessation of formations, consciousness ceases; ... with the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.2" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, before the Bodhisatta Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, before his enlightenment, while still a Bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, the following thought occurred: 'Indeed, this world has fallen into trouble: it is born, ages, dies, passes away, and is reborn. And from this suffering, no escape is known from aging and death; from this suffering, it is not known when escape from aging and death will be known.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.4" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of nutriment for the maintenance of beings that have already been born or for the support of those about to be born. What are the four? Physical food, coarse or fine; contact is the second; mental volition is the third; consciousness is the fourth. These four kinds of nutriment are for the maintenance of beings or for the support of those about to be born.<br><br>And, bhikkhus, what is the cause, what is the origination, what is the source, what is the condition for these four kinds of nutriment? These four kinds of nutriment have craving as their cause, craving as their origination, craving as their source, craving as their condition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.11" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who fully know aging and death, who fully know the origin of aging and death, who fully know the cessation of aging and death, who fully know the path leading to the cessation of aging and death ... who fully know birth ... existence ... clinging ... craving ... feeling ... contact ... the six sense bases ... name-and-form ... consciousness ... who fully know formations, who fully know the origin of formations, who fully know the cessation of formations, who fully know the path leading to the cessation of formations — those samaṇas or brahmins are accepted as samaṇas among samaṇas, or as brahmins among brahmins. And those venerable ones, in this very life, can by direct knowledge realize, attain, and abide in the goal of samaṇa-hood and the goal of brahmin-hood.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.13" },
{ text: `'Right view, right view,' Venerable Sir, is said. To what extent, Venerable Sir, is there right view?"<br>- Kaccāyana, this world for the most part relies on two extremes: existence and non-existence.<br>Kaccāyana, one who, with right wisdom, sees the world's arising as it actually is, does not hold that the world is non-existent. Kaccāyana, one who, with right wisdom, sees the world's cessation as it actually is, does not hold that the world is existent.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.15" },
{ text: `Kaccāyana, this world is for the most part bound by engagement, clinging, and adherence. But one who does not engage in, cling to, or adhere to that engagement, that clinging, that underlying tendency to adhere, who does not take a stand, does not become attached, does not think: 'This is my self.' When suffering arises, he sees it as arising; when suffering ceases, he sees it as ceasing. He is not doubtful, not perplexed, not dependent on another; knowledge arises here for him. To this extent, Kaccāyana, there is right view.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.15" },
{ text: `'Everything exists,' Kaccāyana, is one extreme. 'Nothing exists' is the second extreme. Avoiding both extremes, Kaccāyana, the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma by the middle way. With ignorance as condition, formations arise; with formations as condition, consciousness ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. But with the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease; with the cessation of formations, consciousness ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.15" },


{ text: `If a bhikkhu teaches the Dhamma for the purpose of disenchantment, dispassion, and the cessation of ignorance, that is sufficient for him to be called a teacher of Dhamma.<br>If a bhikkhu practices for the purpose of disenchantment, dispassion, and the cessation of ignorance, that is sufficient for him to be called a bhikkhu who practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma.<br>If a bhikkhu is liberated by non-clinging through disenchantment, dispassion, and the cessation of ignorance, that is sufficient for him to be called a bhikkhu who has attained Nibbāna in this very life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.16" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving, this body of the fool has originated. That ignorance, the fool does not abandon. That craving, the fool does not destroy. Why is that? Bhikkhus, the fool does not live the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering. Therefore, the fool, with the breakup of the body after death, goes to another body. Having gone to another body, he is not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say: 'He is not freed from suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.19" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving, this body of the wise person has originated. That ignorance, the wise person abandons. That craving, the wise person destroys. Why is that? Bhikkhus, the wise person lives the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering. Therefore, the wise person, with the breakup of the body after death, does not go to another body. Not going to another body, he is freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say: 'He is freed from suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.19" },
{ text: `- And, bhikkhus, what is dependent origination? With birth as condition, bhikkhus, aging and death arise. Whether Tathāgatas arise or do not arise, that element still persists, that stableness of Dhamma, that fixed course of Dhamma, that specific conditionality. The Tathāgata fully awakens to this, fully realizes it. Having fully awakened to it, having fully realized it, he declares, teaches, proclaims, establishes, reveals, analyzes, clarifies, and illuminates it.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.20" },
{ text: `With birth as condition, bhikkhus, aging and death come to be. With existence as condition, bhikkhus, birth comes to be. With clinging as condition, bhikkhus, existence comes to be. With craving as condition, bhikkhus, clinging comes to be. With feeling as condition, bhikkhus, craving comes to be. With contact as condition, bhikkhus, feeling comes to be. With the six sense bases as condition, bhikkhus, contact comes to be. With name-and-form as condition, bhikkhus, the six sense bases come to be. With consciousness as condition, bhikkhus, name-and-form comes to be. With formations as condition, bhikkhus, consciousness comes to be. With ignorance as condition, bhikkhus, formations come to be. Whether Tathāgatas arise or do not arise, that element still persists, that stableness of Dhamma, that fixed course of Dhamma, that specific conditionality. The Tathāgata fully awakens to this, fully realizes it. Having fully awakened to it, having fully realized it, he declares, teaches, proclaims, establishes, reveals, analyzes, clarifies, and illuminates it.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.20" },
{ text: `Therefore, bhikkhus, when a noble disciple has clearly seen with correct wisdom this dependent origination and these dependently arisen phenomena, it is impossible that he would run back to the past (with questions such as): 'Did I exist in the past? Did I not exist in the past? What was I in the past? How was I in the past? Having been what, what was I in the past?'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.20" },
{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, the Dhamma is well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, with the fetters cut off. It is enough for a good man who has gone forth out of faith to arouse energy (to practice and aspire). Thus, bhikkhus, the Dhamma is well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, with the fetters cut off. Surely, even if only skin, sinews, and bones remain on the body, even if flesh and blood become dry, let there be energy and perseverance to attain the unattained, by manly strength, by manly energy, by manly striving.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.22" },
{ text: `Suffering, bhikkhus, is for one who lives lazily, smeared with evil, unwholesome states, and the great goal is lost! Happiness, bhikkhus, is for one who lives energetically, diligently, far from evil, unwholesome states, and the great goal is fulfilled!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.22" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is not by the low that the supreme is attained. Bhikkhus, it is by the supreme that the supreme is attained. This holy life, bhikkhus, is worthy of praise because the Teacher is present. Therefore, bhikkhus, arouse energy to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.22" },
{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, the Dhamma is well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, with the fetters cut off. It is enough for a good man who has gone forth out of faith to arouse energy (to practice and aspire). Thus, bhikkhus, the Dhamma is well taught by me, made manifest, opened up, shown, with the fetters cut off. Surely, even if only skin, sinews, and bones remain on the body, even if flesh and blood become dry, let there be energy and perseverance to attain the unattained, by manly strength, by manly energy, by manly striving.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.22" },
{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, you should train. Bhikkhus, seeing one's own good is sufficient to arouse energy without heedlessness. Or, bhikkhus, seeing the good of others is sufficient to arouse energy without heedlessness. Or, bhikkhus, seeing the good of both is sufficient to arouse energy without heedlessness. Then this going forth of ours will not be in vain, but will be fruitful and successful. And the requisites we use — robes, almsfood, lodging, medicines — even though they are humble, will bring us great fruit, great benefit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.22" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how for one who knows, for one who sees, are the taints destroyed? This is form, this is the arising of form, this is the cessation of form. This is feeling ... This is perception ... These are formations ... This is consciousness, this is the arising of consciousness, this is the cessation of consciousness. Thus, bhikkhus, for one who knows, for one who sees thus, the taints are destroyed.<br><br>Bhikkhus, regarding that destruction, the knowledge of destruction, I say that knowledge has a condition, not without a condition. And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for the knowledge of destruction? Liberation is the answer. Bhikkhus, I say that liberation has a condition, not without a condition. And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for liberation? Dispassion is the answer.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.23" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for true knowledge and vision? Concentration is the answer. Bhikkhus, I say that concentration has a condition, not without a condition. And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for concentration? Happiness is the answer.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.23" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for gladness? Faith is the answer. Bhikkhus, I say that faith has a condition, not without a condition. And, bhikkhus, what is the condition for faith? Suffering is the answer. Bhikkhus, I say that suffering has a condition, not without a condition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.23" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, when it rains heavily on a mountain top, the water flows down the slopes, filling the clefts, gullies, and valleys. When the clefts, gullies, and valleys are full, the small ponds become full; when the small ponds are full, the large ponds become full; when the large ponds are full, the small rivers become full; when the small rivers are full, the large rivers become full; when the large rivers are full, the great ocean, the sea, becomes full.<br><br>So too, bhikkhus, with ignorance as condition, formations arise; with formations as condition, consciousness; with consciousness as condition, name-and-form; with name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases; with the six sense bases as condition, contact; with contact as condition, feeling; with feeling as condition, craving; with craving as condition, clinging; with clinging as condition, existence; with existence as condition, birth; with birth as condition, suffering; with suffering as condition, faith; with faith as condition, gladness; with gladness as condition, rapture; with rapture as condition, tranquility; with tranquility as condition, happiness; with happiness as condition, concentration; with concentration as condition, true knowledge and vision; with true knowledge and vision as condition, disenchantment; with disenchantment as condition, dispassion; with dispassion as condition, liberation; with liberation as condition, knowledge of destruction.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.23" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what are formations? There are these three formations, bhikkhus: bodily formation, verbal formation, mental formation. These three, bhikkhus, are called formations.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.28" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is a support for the establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the production of future renewed existence. When there is future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one does not intend, does not plan, but still has a tendency towards something, that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is a support for the establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the production of future renewed existence. When there is future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, then there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, there is no support for the establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no production of future renewed existence. When there is no future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, consciousness becomes established. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the descent of name-and-form.<br><br>With name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases arise. With the six sense bases as condition, contact arises. With contact as condition, feeling arises ... craving ... clinging ... existence ... birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one does not intend, does not plan, but still has a tendency towards something, that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, consciousness becomes established. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the descent of name-and-form. With name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, then there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, consciousness is not established. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no descent of name-and-form. With the cessation of name-and-form, the six sense bases cease ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39" },
{ text: `- Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects, reflecting thus: 'The various diverse kinds of suffering that arise in the world, such as aging and death — what is the cause of this suffering, what is its origination, what gives it birth, what makes it manifest? When what exists does aging and death come to be? When what does not exist does aging and death not come to be?'<br><br>Reflecting thus, he knows: 'The various diverse kinds of suffering that arise in the world, such as aging and death — this suffering has birth as its cause, birth as its origination, birth as its source, birth as its condition. When birth exists, aging and death come to be. When birth does not exist, aging and death do not come to be.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu has abandoned ignorance and aroused true knowledge, then, with the abandonment of ignorance and the arising of knowledge, without intending, without planning, he does not cling to anything in the world. Not clinging, he is not agitated. Not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51" },
{ text: `If he feels a pleasant feeling, he understands that it is impermanent; he understands that it is not to be clung to; he understands that it is not to be delighted in. If he feels a painful feeling, he understands that it is impermanent; he understands that it is not to be clung to; he understands that it is not to be delighted in. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands that it is impermanent; he understands that it is not to be clung to; he understands that it is not to be delighted in. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it detached; if he feels a painful feeling, he feels it detached; if he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it detached.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a man takes a hot pot from a potter's kiln and places it on level ground to cool, and the broken pieces are swept aside. So too, bhikkhus, when he feels a feeling ending with the body, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with the body.' When he feels a feeling ending with life, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with life.' He understands: 'With the breakup of the body after death, all feelings that are not delighted in will become cool, the body will be left aside.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a great bonfire made of ten, twenty, thirty, or forty cartloads of wood is burning. From time to time a man throws dry grass and dry sticks on it. Thus, bhikkhus, that great bonfire, being nourished, being supplied, would burn for a long time. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be clung to, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging comes to be. With clinging as condition, existence comes to be. With existence as condition, birth comes to be. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.52" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, dependent on oil and a wick, an oil lamp burns. From time to time a man pours in oil and adjusts the wick. Bhikkhus, that oil lamp, being nourished, being supplied, would burn for a long time. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be fettered, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging comes to be ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.53" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, dependent on oil and a wick, an oil lamp burns. Then a man does not pour in oil from time to time and does not adjust the wick. Thus, bhikkhus, that oil lamp, as its former fuel is consumed and no other fuel is supplied, being not nourished, would be extinguished. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing danger in things that can be fettered, craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases. With the cessation of clinging, existence ceases. With the cessation of existence, birth ceases. With the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.53" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a great tree, all its roots going downward and spreading out, bring sap to the tree. Thus, bhikkhus, that great tree, being nourished, being supplied, would stand for a long time. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be clung to, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises. With clinging as condition, existence arises. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.55" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a great tree, a man comes with a shovel and a basket. He cuts the tree's roots. After digging a trench, he pulls out all the large roots, the small roots, and the rootlets. Then he cuts the tree into pieces. After cutting it into pieces, he splits it. After splitting it, he chops it into small chips. After chopping it into small chips, he dries them in the wind and sun. After drying them in the wind and sun, he burns them with fire. After burning them with fire, he piles up the ashes. After piling up the ashes, he winnows them in a strong wind or lets them be carried away by a swift stream. Thus, bhikkhus, that great tree has its roots cut, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, unable to live again in the future. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing danger in things that can be clung to, craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases. With the cessation of clinging, existence ceases. With the cessation of existence, birth ceases. With the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.55" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person might become disenchanted, detached, and liberated regarding this body composed of the four great elements. Why is that? Because they see this body composed of the four great elements increasing and decreasing, being taken up and being laid aside. Therefore, an unlearned ordinary person might become disenchanted, detached, and liberated regarding it. But regarding what is called mind, intellect, consciousness, an unlearned ordinary person is not able to become disenchanted, not able to become detached, not able to become liberated. Why is that? For a long time, bhikkhus, the unlearned ordinary person has been attached, has taken it as 'mine,' has clung to it: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self.' Therefore, regarding it, an unlearned ordinary person is not able to become disenchanted, not able to become detached, not able to become liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.61" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, it would be better for an unlearned ordinary person to take this body composed of the four great elements as a self, rather than the mind. Why is that? This body composed of the four great elements is seen to stand for one year, two years, three years, four years, five years, ten years, twenty years, thirty years, forty years, fifty years, a hundred years, even longer. But what is called mind, intellect, consciousness, bhikkhus, arises as one thing and ceases as another by day and by night.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.61" },
{ text: `With the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease. With the cessation of formations, consciousness ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.61" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple reflects wisely on dependent origination: 'When this exists, that comes to be. With the arising of this, that arises. When this does not exist, that does not come to be. With the cessation of this, that ceases.'<br><br>Bhikkhus, with contact leading to pleasant feeling as condition, pleasant feeling arises. With the cessation of that contact leading to pleasant feeling, the pleasant feeling that arose conditioned by that contact ceases and is stilled. Bhikkhus, with contact leading to painful feeling ... with contact leading to neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling as condition, that feeling arises. With the cessation of that contact, the corresponding feeling ceases and is stilled.<br><br>Just as, bhikkhus, from the friction and conjunction of two sticks, heat is generated and fire arises. With the separation and disjunction of those two sticks, that heat ceases and is stilled. So too, bhikkhus, with contact leading to pleasant feeling as condition, pleasant feeling arises ... Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with contact, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.62" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if there is lust, delight, and craving for physical food, consciousness becomes established and grows. Where consciousness becomes established and grows, there is the descent of name-and-form. Where there is the descent of name-and-form, there is the growth of formations. Where there is the growth of formations, there is future renewed existence. Where there is future renewed existence, there is future birth, aging, and death. Where there is future birth, aging, and death, I say that there is sorrow, suffering, and despair.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.64" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if there is no lust, no delight, no craving for physical food, consciousness does not become established and does not grow. Where consciousness does not become established and does not grow, there is no descent of name-and-form. Where there is no descent of name-and-form, there is no growth of formations. Where there is no growth of formations, there is no future renewed existence. Where there is no future renewed existence, there is no future birth, aging, and death. Where there is no future birth, aging, and death, I say that there is no sorrow, no suffering, no despair.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.64" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a house with a roof or a roofed veranda, with windows on the north, south, or east. When the sun rises, the light enters through the window — where does it fall?" — "Venerable Sir, it falls on the western wall." — "Bhikkhus, if there is no western wall, where does it fall?" — "Venerable Sir, it falls on the ground." — "Bhikkhus, if there is no ground, where does it fall?" — "Venerable Sir, it falls on the water." — "Bhikkhus, if there is no water, where does it fall?" — "Venerable Sir, it falls nowhere."<br><br>So too, bhikkhus, if there is no lust, no delight, no craving for consciousness as nutriment, consciousness does not become established. Where consciousness does not become established, there is no descent of name-and-form. Where there is no descent of name-and-form, there is no growth of formations ... no future renewed existence ... no future birth, aging, death ... I say that there is no sorrow, no suffering, no despair.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.64" },
{ text: `- Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, by taking hold of internal contact, considers: 'The various diverse kinds of suffering that arise in the world with aging and death — what is the cause of this suffering, or what is its origination, what gives it birth, what makes it manifest? When what exists does aging and death come to be? When what does not exist does aging and death not come to be?' He, taking hold of internal contact, knows: 'The various diverse kinds of suffering that arise in the world with aging and death — this suffering has attachment (upadhi) as its cause, attachment as its origination, attachment as its source, attachment as its condition. When attachment exists, aging and death come to be. When attachment does not exist, aging and death do not come to be.' He knows aging and death. He knows the origin of aging and death. He knows the cessation of aging and death. He knows the appropriate path leading to the cessation of aging and death. By practicing thus, he becomes one who practices in accordance with the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, this is called a bhikkhu who practices for the complete destruction of suffering, for the complete cessation of aging and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66" },
{ text: `He again takes hold of internal contact and considers: 'This attachment, what is its cause, its origination, its source, its condition? When what exists does attachment come to be? When what does not exist does attachment not come to be?' He, taking hold of internal contact, knows: 'Attachment has craving as its cause, craving as its origination, craving as its source, craving as its condition. When craving exists, attachment comes to be. When craving does not exist, attachment does not come to be.' He knows attachment, knows the origin of attachment, knows the cessation of attachment, and knows the appropriate path leading to the cessation of attachment. By practicing thus, he is called one who practices in accordance with the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, this is called a bhikkhu who has rightly practiced for the complete destruction of suffering and the complete cessation of attachment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66" },
{ text: `He again takes hold of internal contact and considers: 'But this craving, where does it arise, where does it settle?' He, taking hold of internal contact, knows: 'Whatever in the world is agreeable and enticing — there craving arises, there craving settles. And what in the world is agreeable and enticing? The eye in the world is agreeable and enticing — there craving arises, there craving settles.' ... The ear in the world ... the nose in the world ... the tongue in the world ... the body in the world ... the mind in the world is agreeable and enticing — there craving arises, there craving settles.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those in the past ... those in the future ... those now present who are samaṇas or brahmins, who see what is agreeable and enticing in the world as permanent, as happiness, as health, as security, as self — they make craving grow. Those who make craving grow make attachment grow. Those who make attachment grow make suffering grow. Those who make suffering grow cannot be freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that they cannot be freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those in the past ... those in the future ... those now present who are samaṇas or brahmins, who see what is agreeable and enticing in the world as impermanent, as suffering, as not-self, as a disease, as fearful — they abandon craving. Those who abandon craving abandon attachment. Those who abandon attachment abandon suffering. Those who abandon suffering are freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that they are freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, when the great ocean swells, the great rivers swell; when the great rivers swell, the small rivers swell; when the small rivers swell, the large lakes swell; when the large lakes swell, the small lakes swell. So too, bhikkhus, when ignorance swells, formations swell; when formations swell, consciousness swells; when consciousness swells, name-and-form swells; when name-and-form swells, the six sense bases swell; when the six sense bases swell, contact swells; when contact swells, feeling swells; when feeling swells, craving swells; when craving swells, clinging swells; when clinging swells, existence swells; when existence swells, birth swells; when birth swells, aging and death swell.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.69" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the great ocean does not swell, the great rivers do not swell; ... the small lakes do not swell. So too, bhikkhus, when ignorance does not swell, formations do not swell; ... aging and death do not swell.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.69" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, for one who does not truly know and see formations as they are, one must seek a Teacher in order to have true knowledge of formations. For one who does not truly know and see the origin of formations, one must seek a Teacher in order to have true knowledge of the origin of formations. For one who does not truly know and see the cessation of formations, one must seek a Teacher in order to have true knowledge of the cessation of formations. For one who does not truly know and see the path leading to the cessation of formations, one must seek a Teacher in order to have true knowledge of the path leading to the cessation of formations.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.82" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One took a little dust on his fingernail and addressed the bhikkhus: 'What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: this little dust I have taken on my fingernail, or this great earth?'<br><br>'This is greater, Venerable Sir, namely the great earth. The little dust taken by the Blessed One on his fingernail is insignificant. Compared to the great earth, it is not a hundredth, not a thousandth, not a hundred thousandth part.'<br><br>'So too, bhikkhus, for a noble disciple who has achieved perfect view, for a person who has achieved vision and knowledge, this is greater: the suffering that has been destroyed and ended; what remains is insignificant. Compared to the former mass of suffering that has been destroyed and ended, it is not a hundredth, not a thousandth, not a hundred thousandth part — it is only seven times more. Such is the great benefit, bhikkhus, of attaining the Dhamma-eye.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 13.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn13.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is according to their element that beings associate and come together. Beings of inferior disposition associate and come together with beings of inferior disposition. Beings of good disposition associate and come together with beings of good disposition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.14" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is according to their element that in the past, beings associated and came together. Beings of inferior disposition associated and came together with beings of inferior disposition. Beings of good disposition associated and came together with beings of good disposition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.15" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is according to their element that in the future, beings will associate and come together. Beings of inferior disposition will associate and come together with beings of inferior disposition. Beings of good disposition will associate and come together with beings of good disposition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.15" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, milk associates and comes together with milk; oil with oil; clarified butter with clarified butter; honey with honey; molasses with molasses. So too, bhikkhus, it is according to their element that beings associate and come together. Beings of good disposition associate and come together with beings of good disposition.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.16" },
{ text: `Through association, lust is born;<br>Through association, it is not cut off.<br>Like one on a small plank,<br>Sinking in the great waves,<br>So too, the lazy one sinks,<br>The one who lives well also sinks.<br><br>Therefore, avoid the lazy one,<br>Who is not energetic.<br>Associate with the wise,<br>Noble ones living in seclusion,<br>Always energetic and diligent,<br>Practicing jhāna with exertion.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.16" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is according to their element that beings associate and come together. The faithless associate and come together with the faithless. The shameless associate and come together with the shameless. The fearless associate and come together with the fearless. Those of little learning associate and come together with those of little learning. The lazy associate and come together with the lazy. The unmindful associate and come together with the unmindful. Those of poor wisdom associate and come together with those of poor wisdom.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.17" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is according to their element that beings associate and come together. The faithful associate and come together with the faithful. The shameful associate and come together with the shameful. The fearful associate and come together with the fearful. Those of great learning associate and come together with those of great learning. The energetic associate and come together with the energetic. The mindful associate and come together with the mindful. The wise associate and come together with the wise.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.17" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as beings have not directly known as it actually is, regarding these four elements, the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, they do not live with a mind of seclusion, unattached, unrelated, abandoning obstacles, in relation to the heavenly world, the Māra world, the Brahmā world, together with the generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans.<br><br>And, bhikkhus, when beings have directly known as it actually is, regarding these four elements, the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, they live with a mind of seclusion, unattached, unrelated, abandoning obstacles, in relation to the heavenly world, the Māra world, the Brahmā world, together with the generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.33" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if the earth element were exclusively suffering, immersed in suffering, not immersed in happiness, beings would not become attached to the earth element. But because, bhikkhus, the earth element is happiness, immersed in happiness, not immersed in suffering, beings become attached to the earth element.<br><br>Bhikkhus, if the earth element were exclusively happiness, immersed in happiness, not immersed in suffering, beings would not become disenchanted with the earth element. But because, bhikkhus, the earth element is suffering, immersed in suffering, not immersed in happiness, beings become disenchanted with the earth element.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.34" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, one who delights in the earth element delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. Bhikkhus, one who delights in the water element ... one who delights in the fire element ... one who delights in the air element delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.35" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one who does not delight in the earth element does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. Bhikkhus, one who does not delight in the water element ... one who does not delight in the fire element ... one who does not delight in the air element does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.35" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the arising, the continuation, the production, the manifestation of the earth element is the arising of suffering, the continuation of diseases, the manifestation of aging and death. Bhikkhus, of the water element ... of the fire element ... Bhikkhus, the arising, the continuation, the production, the manifestation of the air element is the arising of suffering, the continuation of diseases, the manifestation of aging and death.<br><br>Bhikkhus, the cessation, the stilling, the passing away of the earth element is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of diseases, the passing away of aging and death. Bhikkhus, of the water element ... of the fire element ... Bhikkhus, the cessation, the stilling, the passing away of the air element is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of diseases, the passing away of aging and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 14.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn14.36" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. Just as, bhikkhus, a man cuts all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jambudīpa and piles them into a heap, then makes them into sticks and puts them in a square formation, then taking them one by one he puts them down, saying: 'This is my mother, this is my mother's mother.' And the number of that man's mothers and grandmothers would not be exhausted, but the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jambudīpa might be used up and finished.<br><br>Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. For a long time, bhikkhus, you have experienced suffering, experienced torment, experienced disaster, and the cemeteries have been enlarged. Thus, bhikkhus, it is enough to become disenchanted with all formations, enough to become detached, enough to be liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.1" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: the stream of tears that you have shed as you wandered and roamed on this long journey, weeping and lamenting because of being united with the disagreeable and separated from the agreeable — this or the water in the four great oceans?<br><br>- Venerable Sir, as we understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, this is greater, the stream of tears we have shed as we wandered and roamed on this long journey, weeping and lamenting because of being united with the disagreeable and separated from the agreeable — not the water in the four great oceans.<br><br>- Good, good, bhikkhus! It is good that you thus understand the Dhamma taught by me!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.3" },


{ text: `This is greater, bhikkhus, namely the stream of tears you have shed as you wandered and roamed on this long journey, weeping and lamenting because of being united with the disagreeable and separated from the agreeable — not the water in the four great oceans. For a long time, bhikkhus, you have experienced the death of a mother... the death of a son... the death of a daughter... the loss of relatives... the loss of wealth... For a long time, bhikkhus, you have experienced the disaster of disease. This is greater, the stream of tears you have shed as you wandered and roamed on this long journey, weeping and lamenting because of being united with the disagreeable and separated from the agreeable, while experiencing the disaster of disease — not the water in the four great oceans. Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus ... fettered by craving. Thus, bhikkhus, it is enough to become disenchanted with all formations, enough to become detached, enough to be liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.3" },
{ text: `- How many eons have passed and gone by, Venerable Sir?<br>- Many eons, brahmin, have passed and gone by. It is not easy to count them as just a few eons, a few hundred eons, a few thousand eons, a few hundred thousand eons.<br>- Can the Venerable Gotama give a simile?<br>- I can, brahmin. Just as, brahmin, the Ganges river from its source to where it flows into the great ocean, the sand in between is not easy to count as just a few grains, a few hundred grains, a few thousand grains, a few hundred thousand grains. Even more than that, brahmin, are the eons that have passed and gone by. It is not easy to count them as just a few eons, a few hundred eons, a few thousand eons, a few hundred thousand eons.<br>Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, brahmin. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. For a long time, brahmin, you have experienced suffering, experienced torment, experienced disaster, and the cemeteries have been enlarged. Thus, brahmin, it is enough to become disenchanted with all formations, enough to become detached, enough to be liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.8" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. Just as, bhikkhus, a stick thrown up into the air sometimes falls on its base, sometimes in the middle, sometimes on its tip. So too, bhikkhus, beings shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving, roaming and wandering on, sometimes go from this world to another world, sometimes from another world to this world. Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus ... enough to be liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.9" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus ... The bones of a person, bhikkhus, roaming and wandering on, would be as great as a mountain of bones, a heap of bones, a pile of bones, like this Mount Vepulla, if someone collected them and kept them without letting them decay. Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus ... enough to be liberated from all formations.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.10" },
{ text: `The accumulation of bones from a single eon<br>Would be a mountain as high,<br>So said the Great Teacher.<br><br>That mountain is said to be<br>As great as Mount Vepulla,<br>North of Vulture's Peak<br>In the Magadhan hills.<br><br>But one who sees the Four Noble Truths<br>With perfect wisdom,<br>Suffering and its origin,<br>Will transcend all suffering;<br>The Noble Eightfold Path<br>Leads to suffering's stilling.<br><br>That person will wander on<br>At most seven more lives.<br>He has made an end of suffering,<br>Destroyed all fetters.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.10" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. Bhikkhus, when you see a situation of misery and misfortune, you should conclude: 'We have experienced such for a long time.' Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus ... enough to be liberated from all formations.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.11" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: the stream of blood that has flowed from your cut heads as you roamed and wandered on this long journey, or the water in the four great oceans? This is greater, bhikkhus, the stream of blood that has flowed from your cut heads as you roamed and wandered on this long journey — not the water in the four great oceans. Bhikkhus, the stream of blood that has flowed from your cut heads when you were born as cows and roamed for a long time as cows... when you were born as sheep... as goats... as deer... as fowl... as pigs... Bhikkhus, the stream of blood that has flowed from your cut heads when you were bandits, village thieves caught for a long time... when you were bandits, adulterers caught for a long time — that stream is greater, not the water in the four great oceans.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.13" },
{ text: `- Kassapa here is content with any kind of robe, and he praises contentment with any kind of robe; ... praises contentment with any kind of almsfood; ... praises contentment with any kind of lodging; ... praises contentment with any kind of medicine; and he does not, because of medicine, do anything improper or inappropriate. If he does not get medicine, he is not agitated. And if he gets medicine, he uses it without being attached, infatuated, or committed, seeing the danger, and understanding the escape with wisdom.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.1" },
{ text: `Therefore, bhikkhus, train yourselves thus: 'We will be content with any kind of robe, and we will praise contentment with any kind of robe. And we will not, because of a robe, do anything improper or inappropriate. If we do not get a robe, we will not be agitated. And if we get a robe, we will use it without being attached, infatuated, or committed, seeing the danger, and understanding the escape with wisdom. We will be content with any kind of almsfood... with any kind of lodging... with any kind of medicine, and we will praise contentment with any kind of medicine. And we will not, because of medicine, do anything improper or inappropriate. If we do not get medicine, we will not be agitated. And if we get medicine, we will use it without being attached, infatuated, or committed, seeing the danger, and understanding the escape with wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.1" },
{ text: `And, friends, how is there ardor? Here, friends, a bhikkhu reflects: 'If evil, unwholesome states that have not arisen in me were to arise, that would lead to my harm' — thus he arouses ardor. 'If evil, unwholesome states that have arisen in me are not abandoned, that would lead to my harm' — thus he arouses ardor. 'If wholesome states that have not arisen in me do not arise, that would lead to my harm' — thus he arouses ardor. 'If wholesome states that have arisen in me were to cease, that would lead to my harm' — thus he arouses ardor. Thus, friends, is there ardor.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.2" },
{ text: `And, friends, how is there fear of wrongdoing? Here, friends, a bhikkhu reflects: 'If evil, unwholesome states that have not arisen in me were to arise, that would lead to my harm' — thus he has fear. 'If evil, unwholesome states that have arisen in me are not abandoned, that would lead to my harm' — thus he has fear. 'If wholesome states that have not arisen in me do not arise, that would lead to my harm' — thus he has fear. 'If wholesome states that have arisen in me were to cease, that would lead to my harm' — thus he has fear. Thus, friends, is there fear of wrongdoing. Thus, friends, having ardor and fear of wrongdoing, one is capable of enlightenment, capable of Nibbāna, capable of attaining the supreme security from bondage.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.2" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person looking at an old well, a steep precipice, or a waterfall, is careful with body and careful with mind. So too, bhikkhus, like the moon, when going to families, be careful with body and careful with mind, always being newcomers among families, not forward.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.3" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, this hand in the air is not stuck, not grasped, not bound. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu going to families, his mind is not stuck, not grasped, not bound, thinking: 'Let those who want gain gain! Let those who want merit do meritorious deeds!'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.3" },
{ text: `- And, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who teaches Dhamma to others with a mind thus: 'The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One, visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves. Oh, may they hear the Dhamma I teach! Having heard, may they understand the Dhamma! Having understood, may they practice accordingly!' — because of the very quality of the Dhamma, he teaches Dhamma to others. Because of compassion, because of loving-kindness, out of sympathy, he teaches Dhamma to others. Such a bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who teaches Dhamma purely.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.3" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who goes to families with a mind thus: 'Regarding others' families, how could one wish: "May they give to me, not not give. May they give me much, not little. May they give me good things, not bad things. May they give me quickly, not slowly. May they honor me, not dishonor me"?'<br><br>Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu with such a mind, when going to families, does not get anything, he is not frustrated because of that, does not experience pain and grief. They give little, not much... they give bad things, not good things... they give slowly, not quickly... they give dishonorably, not honorably — the bhikkhu is not frustrated because of that, does not experience pain and grief.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.4" },
{ text: `- Good, good, Kassapa! It is for the happiness of the many, Kassapa, that you have practiced thus, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of devas and humans. Therefore, Kassapa, wear coarse rag-robe that is to be discarded. Live on alms and dwell in the forest!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.5" },
{ text: `- Truly, bhikkhus, you have committed an offense, so foolish, so deluded, so unwholesome! Because you have gone forth in this well-taught Dhamma and Discipline, you have said to each other: 'Come, bhikkhu, who will speak more? Who will speak better? Who will speak longer?' And because you have seen an offense as an offense and have made amends according to the Dhamma, I accept your confession!<br><br>Bhikkhus, this is growth in the Noble One's Discipline, that after seeing an offense as an offense, one makes amends according to the Dhamma, to restrain oneself in the future!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.6" },
{ text: `Just as the moon, Kassapa, in the dark fortnight, whether by day or by night, its shape diminishes, its roundness diminishes, its light diminishes, its course diminishes. So too, Kassapa, for one who has no faith in wholesome states, no shame... no fear... no energy... no wisdom in wholesome states — whether by day or by night, one can expect diminution in wholesome states, not growth.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.7" },
{ text: `Just as the moon, Kassapa, in the bright fortnight, whether by day or by night, its shape increases, its roundness increases, its light increases, its course increases. So too, Kassapa, for one who has faith in wholesome states, who has shame... fear... energy... wisdom in wholesome states — whether by day or by night, one can expect growth in wholesome states, not diminution.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.7" },
{ text: `- Kassapa, in the past, the elder bhikkhus were forest-dwellers and praised forest-dwelling, were alms-goers and praised alms-going, wore rag-robes and praised wearing rag-robes, used three robes and praised using three robes, had few desires and praised fewness of desires, were content and praised contentment, were secluded and praised seclusion, were non-associative and praised non-association, were energetic and praised energy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.8" },
{ text: `Here, a bhikkhu who is a forest-dweller and praises forest-dwelling, an alms-goer and praises alms-going, a rag-robe wearer and praises wearing rag-robes, a three-robe user and praises using three robes, one of few desires and praises fewness of desires, content and praises contentment, secluded and praises seclusion, non-associative and praises non-association, energetic and praises energy — that bhikkhu is invited by the elder bhikkhus to sit, and they say: 'Come, bhikkhu, what is this bhikkhu's name? This bhikkhu is good! This bhikkhu is eager to learn! Come, bhikkhu, sit on this seat!'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.8" },
{ text: `Here, Kassapa, the newly ordained bhikkhus reflect: 'That bhikkhu who is a forest-dweller and praises forest-dwelling, an alms-goer... energetic and praises energy — he is invited by the elder bhikkhus to sit, and they say: "Come, bhikkhu, what is this bhikkhu's name? This bhikkhu is good! This bhikkhu is eager to learn! Come, bhikkhu, sit on this seat!"' They practice accordingly, and thus they gain happiness and bliss for a long time.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.8" },
{ text: `Kassapa, one speaking rightly would say: 'One living the holy life must endure the hardships of the holy life. One living the holy life must be oppressed by the pressures of the holy life.' Speaking thus, Kassapa, one speaks rightly. One living the holy life must endure the hardships of the holy life. One living the holy life must be oppressed by the pressures of the holy life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.8" },
{ text: `Just as, Kassapa, a boat sinks because it is overloaded. It is not because of that, Kassapa, that the true Dhamma disappears. Kassapa, there are five corrupting factors that lead to the confusion and disappearance of the true Dhamma. What are the five? Here, Kassapa, the bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers live without respect, without deference for the Teacher; live without respect, without deference for the Dhamma; live without respect, without deference for the Saṅgha; live without respect, without deference for the training; live without respect, without deference for concentration. These, Kassapa, are the corrupting factors that lead to the confusion and disappearance of the true Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.13" },
{ text: `Kassapa, these corrupting factors lead to the confusion and disappearance of the true Dhamma. And there are five factors, Kassapa, that lead to the continuation, steadfastness, and non-disappearance of the true Dhamma. What are the five? Here, Kassapa, the bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers live with respect, with deference for the Teacher; live with respect, with deference for the Dhamma; live with respect, with deference for the Saṅgha; live with respect, with deference for the training; live with respect, with deference for concentration. These five factors, Kassapa, lead to the continuation, steadfastness, and non-disappearance of the true Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 16.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn16.13" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame; they are bitter, malicious, and an obstacle to attaining the supreme security from bondage. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will abandon gains, honor, and fame that have arisen. We will not let gains, honor, and fame that have not yet arisen invade our minds and remain.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.1" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a fisherman casts a short hook baited with meat into a deep lake, and a fish with a keen eye sees the bait and swallows the hook. Thus, bhikkhus, that fish, having swallowed the fisherman's hook, has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is at the fisherman's mercy. The fisherman, bhikkhus, is a symbol for Māra; the hook, bhikkhus, is a symbol for gains, honor, and fame. Any bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who enjoys and delights in gains, honor, and fame that have arisen — that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who has swallowed Māra's hook, has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is at Māra's mercy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.2" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a long-haired she-goat enters a thorny thicket; here and there it gets caught, here and there it gets entangled, here and there it gets bound, here and there it falls into misfortune and calamity. So too, bhikkhus, a certain bhikkhu, overcome by gains, honor, and fame, his mind obsessed, in the morning puts on his robe, takes his bowl, and enters the village or town for alms. Here and there, he gets caught, here and there he gets entangled, here and there he gets bound, here and there he falls into misfortune and calamity.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.4" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a dung-beetle, feeding on dung, full of dung, stuffed with dung, sees a great pile of dung before it. It despises other dung-beetles and says: 'I feed on dung, I am full of dung, I am stuffed with dung, and before me is this great pile of dung.'<br><br>So too, bhikkhus, a certain bhikkhu, overcome by gains, honor, and fame, his mind obsessed, in the morning puts on his robe, takes his bowl, and enters the village or town for alms. There he eats and drinks to satiety, and is invited again for the next day, and his bowl is filled.<br><br>He goes to the monastery and boasts among the Saṅgha of bhikkhus: 'I have eaten and drunk to satiety, I am invited again for tomorrow, and my bowl is full. I receive requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicines. But these other bhikkhus, of little merit and influence, do not receive requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicines.'<br><br>Overcome by gains, honor, and fame, his mind obsessed, he despises other virtuous bhikkhus. This will bring that fool long-term harm and suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.5" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... How, bhikkhus, is a lightning strike (compared to) a learner (sekha) with ardent mind, when touched by gains, honor, and fame? The lightning strike, bhikkhus, is a symbol for gains, honor, and fame touching one. Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.6" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... How, bhikkhus, is being struck by a poisoned dart (compared to) a learner with ardent mind, when touched by gains, honor, and fame? The dart, bhikkhus, is a symbol for gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.7" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Here, bhikkhus, I see a person overcome by honor, his mind obsessed, and after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Here, bhikkhus, I see a person overcome by dishonor, his mind obsessed, and after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery... Here, bhikkhus, I see a person overcome by both honor and dishonor, his mind obsessed, and after death... he is reborn in a plane of misery... Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.10" },
{ text: `One who is honored,<br>Who is dishonored,<br>In both cases,<br>Mind steady, unshaken,<br>Living without heedfulness,<br><br>Mind constantly in jhāna,<br>With subtle thoughts,<br>Contemplating what is seen,<br>No longer delighting in clinging,<br>Is called a true person.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.10" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Here, bhikkhus, I know a person's mind thus with my mind: 'Even for a silver bowl filled with gold dust, this person would not deliberately tell a lie.' Yet later, I see him overcome by gains, honor, and fame, his mind obsessed, deliberately telling a lie. Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.12" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who do not truly know the gratification, the danger, the escape regarding gains, honor, and fame — those samaṇas or brahmins are not recognized by me as samaṇas among samaṇas or brahmins among brahmins, and they do not, in this very life, by direct knowledge, realize and abide in the goal of samaṇa-hood or the goal of brahmin-hood.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.25" },
{ text: `- Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Gains, honor, and fame, bhikkhus, cut through the outer skin. Having cut through the outer skin, they cut through the inner skin. Having cut through the inner skin, they cut through the flesh. Having cut through the flesh, they cut through the sinews. Having cut through the sinews, they cut through the bone. Having cut through the bone, they reach the marrow and remain. Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.28" },
{ text: `- Rāhula, what do you think? Is the eye permanent or impermanent?" — "Impermanent, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent, is that suffering or happiness?" — "Suffering, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change, is it fitting to regard it as: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent, is that suffering or happiness?" — "Suffering, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change, is it fitting to regard it as: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Seeing thus, Rāhula, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the eye, disenchanted with the ear, disenchanted with the nose, disenchanted with the tongue, disenchanted with the body, disenchanted with the mind. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 18.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn18.1" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, by knowing and seeing in what way, in this conscious body and in all external signs, is there no I-making, mine-making, and underlying tendency to conceit?<br>- Rāhula, whatever form, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — he sees all form as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Whatever feeling ... whatever perception ... whatever formations ... whatever consciousness, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — he sees all consciousness as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.'<br>Rāhula, by knowing and seeing thus, in this conscious body and in all external signs, there is no I-making, mine-making, and underlying tendency to conceit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 18.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn18.21" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, by knowing and seeing in what way, in this conscious body and in all external signs, the mind has become free from I-making, mine-making, and conceit, has transcended all conceit, peaceful, and liberated?<br>- Rāhula, whatever form, whether past, future, or present ... whatever feeling ... whatever perception ... whatever formations ... whatever consciousness, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — he sees all consciousness as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Seeing thus with right wisdom, he is liberated by non-clinging.<br>Rāhula, by knowing and seeing thus, in this conscious body and in all external signs, the mind has become free from I-making, mine-making, and conceit, has transcended all conceit, peaceful, and liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 18.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn18.22" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, a house with a peaked roof, whatever rafters there are, all go to the peak, all rest on the peak, all converge at the peak, all are joined together at the peak. So too, bhikkhus, whatever unwholesome states there are, they all have ignorance as their root, all have ignorance as their foundation, all converge on ignorance, all are joined together at ignorance. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will live heedfully.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what do you think? Which is greater: this little dust I have taken on my fingernail, or this great earth?" — "This is greater, Venerable Sir, namely the great earth. The little dust the Blessed One has taken on his fingernail is insignificant. It cannot be reckoned, cannot be compared, cannot be a fraction, compared to the great earth."<br>- So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings reborn as humans; many are the beings reborn elsewhere than as humans! Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will live heedfully.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.2" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, those families that have many women and few men are easily harassed by thieves and robbers. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who does not develop and cultivate the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is easily harassed by non-humans. - Just as, bhikkhus, those families that have few women and many men are not easily harassed by thieves and robbers. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who develops and cultivates the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is not easily harassed by non-humans. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will develop the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, cultivate it, make it our vehicle, make it our base, establish it, accumulate it, and properly undertake it.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.3" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if someone gives a hundred pots as alms in the morning, gives a hundred pots at noon, gives a hundred pots in the evening, and if someone in the morning, for the time it takes to milk a cow, develops the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, or at noon... or in the evening... — this is much more fruitful than the former. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will develop the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, cultivate it, make it our vehicle, make it our base, establish it, accumulate it, and properly undertake it.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.4" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, in the future, there will be bhikkhus. Those suttas spoken by the Tathāgata, profound, deeply meaningful, transcendent, dealing with emptiness, they will not listen to when they are being taught; they will not lend an ear; they will not apply their minds to true knowledge; and they will not think that those teachings are worth learning and mastering. But those suttas that are composed by poets, beautiful verses with beautiful phrases, belonging to outsiders, spoken by disciples, they will listen to when they are being taught; they will lend an ear; they will apply their minds to true knowledge; and they will think that those teachings are worth learning and mastering. Thus, bhikkhus, those suttas spoken by the Tathāgata, profound, deeply meaningful, transcendent, dealing with emptiness, will disappear. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Those suttas spoken by the Tathāgata, profound, deeply meaningful, transcendent, dealing with emptiness — we will listen to when they are being taught; we will lend an ear; we will apply our minds to true knowledge; and we will think that those teachings are worth learning and mastering.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.7" },
{ text: `Living on a straw mat, bhikkhus, is the present practice of bhikkhus, heedful, ardent in effort. Māra finds no opportunity, no object to attack. In the future, bhikkhus, bhikkhus will become soft, with tender hands and feet. They will lie on soft bedding. They will sleep until sunrise on cotton pillows. Māra will get an opportunity, will find an object (to attack). Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will live on a straw mat, heedful, ardent in effort.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.8" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, here the elder bhikkhus in the morning put on their robes, take their bowls, and enter the village or town for alms. There they teach the Dhamma. The laypeople, pleased, do their duty towards them. Those bhikkhus accept the gains without being attached, infatuated, committed, seeing the danger, and understanding the escape with wisdom. Therefore, those bhikkhus gain beauty and strength, and they do not, on that account, meet death or deadly pain. But, bhikkhus, trained by the elder bhikkhus, the newly ordained bhikkhus in the morning put on their robes, take their bowls, and enter the village or town for alms. There they teach the Dhamma. The laypeople, pleased, do their duty. Those bhikkhus accept the gains, being attached, infatuated, committed, not seeing the danger, not understanding the escape with wisdom. Therefore, those bhikkhus do not gain beauty and strength, and they, on that account, meet death or deadly pain. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will accept gains without being attached, infatuated, committed, seeing the danger, and understanding the escape with wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.9" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, here some bhikkhus in the morning put on their robes, take their bowls, and enter the village or town for alms, with body unguarded, speech unguarded, mind unguarded, mindfulness unestablished, faculties unrestrained. There they see women improperly dressed or scantily dressed. Seeing women improperly or scantily dressed, lust invades their mind. With lust invading their mind, they meet death or deadly pain. This is death, bhikkhus, in the Noble One's Discipline, namely giving up the training and returning to the lower life. This is deadly pain, bhikkhus, namely committing a defiled offense, an offense that can be confessed and purified. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will enter the village or town for alms with body guarded, speech guarded, mind guarded, mindfulness established, faculties restrained.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.10" },
{ text: `- Have you heard, bhikkhus, how in the last watch of the night, an old jackal howled loudly?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "It may well be, bhikkhus, that an old jackal has more gratitude and thankfulness than someone here who claims to be a Sakyan son! Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will be grateful and thankful. Even a little done for us, we will not let go to waste.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.12" },
{ text: `- Thera, how is solitary dwelling perfected in detail? Here, Thera, what is past has been abandoned; what is future has been relinquished; and regarding the present self, desire and lust are well subdued. Thus, Thera, is solitary dwelling perfected in detail. This the Blessed One said. The Well-Gone having said this, the Teacher further said:<br><br>One who conquers all,<br>Who knows all,<br>Who is the wise one,<br>Not stained by any Dhamma,<br>Who has abandoned all,<br>With craving destroyed, liberated —<br>That one, I say, is truly a solitary dweller.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 21.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn21.10" },
{ text: `- So it is, householder. So it is, householder. Your body, householder, is afflicted, diseased, covered by defilement. One who carries this body, householder, and claims to be healthy even for a moment, that person must be a fool! Therefore, householder, you should train thus: 'Even though my body may be diseased, my mind will not be diseased.' Thus, householder, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.1" },
{ text: `- The form element, householder, is the home of consciousness. Consciousness bound by lust for the form element, householder, is called one who wanders in a home. The feeling element, householder, is the home of consciousness... The perception element... The formation element... The consciousness element, householder, is the home of consciousness. Consciousness bound by lust for the consciousness element, householder, is called one who wanders in a home. Thus, householder, is wandering in a home.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `And, householder, how is one who wanders without a home? Regarding the form element, householder, whatever there is of desire, lust, delight, craving, engagement, clinging, mental standpoints, adherence, underlying tendencies — these the Tathāgata has abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called one who wanders without a home. Regarding the feeling element... perception element... formation element... consciousness element, householder, whatever there is of desire, lust, delight, craving, engagement, clinging, mental standpoints, adherence, underlying tendencies — these the Tathāgata has abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called one who wanders without a home.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `How, householder, is one who wanders without abode? The bondage of dwelling on the sign of form, householder, has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called one who wanders without abode. The bondage of dwelling on the sign of sound... sign of odor... sign of taste... sign of touch... sign of mental object, householder, has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called one who wanders without abode. Thus, householder, is one who wanders without abode.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `How, householder, is there becoming entangled in a village? Here, householder, a person lives intimately with householders, sharing their happiness and their suffering. When they are happy, he is happy; when they are suffering, he suffers. When a task arises that needs doing, he engages himself in it. Thus, householder, is becoming entangled in a village.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `And, householder, how is there not becoming entangled in a village? Here, householder, a bhikkhu does not live intimately with householders, does not share their happiness and suffering, is not happy when they are happy, not suffering when they are suffering. When a task arises that needs doing, he does not engage himself in it. Thus, householder, is not becoming entangled in a village.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `How, householder, is there vain hope? Here, householder, a person thinks: 'May I have such form in the future! May I have such feeling in the future! May I have such perception in the future! May I have such formations in the future! May I have such consciousness in the future!' Thus, householder, is vain hope.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },
{ text: `The noble one has left the home life,<br>Wanders without abode,<br>Toward the villagers,<br>Not becoming entangled.<br>He has no sensual desires,<br>No vain hopes,<br>Has ended all disputes<br>With anyone whatsoever.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3" },


{ text: `- Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are. Understands what as they actually are? The arising and passing away of form; the arising and passing away of feeling; the arising and passing away of perception; the arising and passing away of formations; the arising and passing away of consciousness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.5" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the arising of form? What is the arising of feeling? What is the arising of perception? What is the arising of formations? What is the arising of consciousness? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu delights, welcomes, and remains attached. Delights, welcomes, remains attached to what? He delights, welcomes, and remains attached to form. Because he delights, welcomes, and remains attached to form, delight in form arises. With delight in form, clinging to form arises. With clinging to form as condition, existence arises. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.<br><br>He delights, welcomes, and remains attached to feeling ... to perception ... to formations ... to consciousness. Because he delights, welcomes, and remains attached to consciousness, delight arises. With delight in consciousness, clinging to consciousness arises. With clinging as condition, existence arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Bhikkhus, this is the arising of form, the arising of feeling, the arising of perception, the arising of formations, the arising of consciousness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.5" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what is grasping and anxiety? Here, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person, who does not see the noble ones, is not skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, not trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who does not see the true persons, is not skilled in the teaching of the true persons, not trained in the teaching of the true persons — regards form as self, or self as possessing form, or form as in self, or self as in form. For him, that form changes and alters. For him, when form changes and alters, consciousness follows the change of form. The states of anxiety that arise due to consciousness following the change of form invade the mind and remain. Because the mind is invaded, fear, obstacles, and longing arise, and there is anxiety.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.7" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, how is there no grasping and no anxiety? Here, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple regards form: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' For him, that form changes and alters. When form changes and alters, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair do not arise in him. He regards feeling ... perception ... formations ... consciousness: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' For him, that consciousness changes and alters. When consciousness changes and alters, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair do not arise in him. Thus, bhikkhus, is there no grasping and no anxiety.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.8" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, form is impermanent, past and future, let alone the present. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple has no regret for past form, does not delight in future form, and for present form practices for disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation. Bhikkhus, feeling is impermanent ... perception is impermanent ... formations are impermanent ... Bhikkhus, consciousness is impermanent, past and future, let alone the present. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple has no regret for past consciousness, does not delight in future consciousness, and for present consciousness practices for disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, form is suffering, past and future, let alone the present. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple has no regret for past form, does not delight in future form, and for present form practices for disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation. Bhikkhus, feeling is suffering ... perception is suffering ... formations are suffering ... Bhikkhus, consciousness is suffering, past and future, let alone the present. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple has no regret for past consciousness, does not delight in future consciousness, and for present consciousness practices for disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.10" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, form is impermanent; what is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self; what is non-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Bhikkhus, feeling is impermanent ... perception is impermanent ... formations are impermanent ... Bhikkhus, consciousness is impermanent; what is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self; what is non-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... ' ... there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.15" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, form is suffering. What is suffering is non-self; what is non-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Bhikkhus, feeling is suffering ... perception is suffering ... formations are suffering ... Bhikkhus, consciousness is suffering. What is suffering is non-self; what is non-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... ' ... there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.16" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the burden? The five aggregates of clinging is the answer. What are the five? The form aggregate of clinging, the feeling aggregate of clinging, the perception aggregate of clinging, the formation aggregate of clinging, the consciousness aggregate of clinging. Bhikkhus, this is called the burden. And, bhikkhus, what is the carrier of the burden? The person is the answer. This venerable one has such a name, such a clan. Bhikkhus, this is called the carrier of the burden. And, bhikkhus, what is the taking up of the burden? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, seeking delight here and there; that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. Bhikkhus, this is called the taking up of the burden. And, bhikkhus, what is the laying down of the burden? It is the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, its abandonment, relinquishment, liberation, and non-clinging. Bhikkhus, this is called the laying down of the burden.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.22" },
{ text: `The five aggregates are the burden,<br>The carrier of the burden is the person;<br>Taking up the burden is suffering in the world.<br>Laying down the burden is bliss, free from suffering.<br>Having laid down the heavy burden,<br>Without taking up another burden,<br>Having pulled out craving with its root,<br>One is free from hunger, fully quenched.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.22" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what are the things to be fully understood? Form, bhikkhus, is a thing to be fully understood; feeling is a thing to be fully understood; perception is a thing to be fully understood; formations are things to be fully understood; consciousness is a thing to be fully understood. These, bhikkhus, are the things to be fully understood. And, bhikkhus, what is full understanding? The destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion, bhikkhus, is called full understanding.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.23" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet perfectly enlightened, I thought: 'What is the gratification, what is the danger, what is the escape regarding form? What is the gratification, the danger, the escape regarding feeling? Regarding perception? Regarding formations? Regarding consciousness?' Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'The pleasure and joy that arise dependent on form — that is the gratification of form. The impermanence, suffering, and changeability of form — that is the danger of form. The removal and abandonment of desire and lust for form — that is the escape from form.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.26" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if there were no gratification in form, beings would not become attached to form. But because there is gratification in form, bhikkhus, beings become attached to form. - Bhikkhus, if there were no danger in form, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because there is danger in form, bhikkhus, beings become disenchanted with form. And, bhikkhus, when beings, regarding these five aggregates of clinging, directly know as they actually are the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then those beings, bhikkhus, in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, can live detached, free from involvement, liberated, with autonomous minds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.28" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what is called the arising, continuation, manifestation of form — that is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. Bhikkhus, what is called the arising, continuation, manifestation of feeling ... perception ... formations ... Bhikkhus, what is called the arising, continuation, manifestation of consciousness — that is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. Bhikkhus, what is called the cessation, stilling, disappearance of form — that is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the disappearance of aging and death. Bhikkhus, what is called the cessation, stilling, disappearance of feeling ... perception ... formations ... Bhikkhus, what is called the cessation, stilling, disappearance of consciousness — that is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the disappearance of aging and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.30" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I will teach you suffering and the root of suffering. Listen ... Bhikkhus, what is suffering? Form, bhikkhus, is suffering; feeling is suffering; perception is suffering; formations are suffering; consciousness is suffering. This, bhikkhus, is called suffering. Bhikkhus, what is the root of suffering? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, seeking delight here and there; that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.31" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, whatever is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Bhikkhus, what is not yours? Form, bhikkhus, is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Feeling, bhikkhus, is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Perception, bhikkhus ... Formations, bhikkhus ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.33" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person were to take the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves of this Jeta's Grove, and burn them or use them as he wishes. Would you think: 'That person takes us, burns us, or uses us as he wishes'?" — "No, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because that is not us. Venerable Sir, that is not our self." — "So too, bhikkhus, form is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Feeling is not yours ... Perception is not yours ... Formations are not yours ... Consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.33" },
{ text: `- For a bhikkhu who practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, this is the appropriate practice: He dwells often in disenchantment towards form; he dwells often in disenchantment towards feeling; he dwells often in disenchantment towards perception; he dwells often in disenchantment towards formations; he dwells often in disenchantment towards consciousness. By dwelling often in disenchantment towards form ... towards feeling ... towards perception ... towards formations ... by dwelling often in disenchantment towards consciousness, he fully understands form ... fully understands feeling ... fully understands perception ... fully understands formations ... fully understands consciousness. By fully understanding form ... feeling ... perception ... formations ... by fully understanding consciousness, he is liberated from form, liberated from feeling, liberated from perception, liberated from formations, liberated from consciousness, liberated from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is liberated from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.39" },
{ text: `- Live as islands unto yourselves, bhikkhus, as refuges unto yourselves, with no other refuge. Let the Dhamma be your island, let the Dhamma be your refuge, with no other refuge. For those who live as islands unto themselves, bhikkhus, as refuges unto themselves, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as their island, the Dhamma as their refuge, with no other refuge, you should investigate wisely: 'From what cause do sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise? From what condition do they become manifest?'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.43" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, knowing form as impermanent ... Bhikkhus, knowing feeling as impermanent ... Bhikkhus, knowing perception as impermanent ... Bhikkhus, knowing formations as impermanent ... Bhikkhus, knowing consciousness as impermanent, changing, fading away, ceasing — he sees all consciousness, past and present, as impermanent, suffering, subject to change. Seeing thus as it actually is with right wisdom, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are cut off. With their cutting off, he is not distressed. Without distress, he lives happily. Living happily, that bhikkhu is called one who has stilled all signs and is totally headed for Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.43" },
{ text: `- Form, bhikkhus, is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Seeing thus as it actually is with right wisdom, the mind becomes detached and liberated, not clinging to the taints.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.45" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu's mind is detached from the form element, liberated, not clinging to the taints; detached from the feeling element ... from the perception element ... from the formation element ... detached from the consciousness element, liberated, not clinging to the taints. Through liberation, he is steady. Through steadiness, he is content. Through contentment, he is not distressed. Not distressed, he personally attains Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.45" },
{ text: `- Form, bhikkhus, is burning; feeling is burning; perception is burning; formations are burning; consciousness is burning! Seeing thus, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... with feeling ... with perception ... with formations ... becomes disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.61" },
{ text: `Bhikkhu, one who conceives form is bound by Māra. One who does not conceive is freed from the Evil One. One who conceives feeling ... perception ... formations ... One who conceives consciousness is bound by Māra. One who does not conceive is freed from the Evil One. Bhikkhu, this brief statement of mine should be understood in detail in this way.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.64" },
{ text: `- Rādha, whatever form, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all form should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Whatever feeling ... whatever perception ... whatever formations ... whatever consciousness, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all consciousness should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Rādha, by knowing thus, by seeing thus, regarding this conscious body and all external signs, there is no I-making, mine-making, and underlying tendency to conceit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.71" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who recollect their manifold past lives all recollect the five aggregates of clinging or one of them. What are the five? Bhikkhus, someone recollects: 'In the past, my form was thus.' Recollecting thus, he recollects form. Or someone recollects: 'In the past, my feeling was thus.' Recollecting thus, he recollects feeling. Or someone recollects: 'In the past, my perception was thus ... my formations were thus ... my consciousness was thus.' Recollecting thus, he recollects consciousness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, why is it called form? It is deformed, bhikkhus, therefore it is called form. Deformed by what? Deformed by cold, deformed by heat, deformed by hunger, deformed by thirst, deformed by the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things. Deformed, bhikkhus, therefore it is called form. Bhikkhus, why is it called feeling? It is felt, bhikkhus, therefore it is called feeling. What is felt? Feeling pleasure, feeling pain, feeling neither-pain-nor-pleasure. Felt, bhikkhus, therefore it is called feeling. Bhikkhus, why is it called perception? It is perceived, bhikkhus, therefore it is called perception. What is perceived? Perceiving blue, perceiving yellow, perceiving red, perceiving white. Perceived, bhikkhus, therefore it is called perception.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, why are they called formations? They form the conditioned, bhikkhus, therefore they are called formations. What conditioned do they form? They form form with the nature of form; they form feeling with the nature of feeling; they form perception with the nature of perception; they form formations with the nature of formations; they form consciousness with the nature of consciousness. They form the conditioned, bhikkhus, therefore they are called formations. And, bhikkhus, why is it called consciousness? It cognizes, bhikkhus, therefore it is called consciousness. What does it cognize? It cognizes sour, it cognizes bitter, it cognizes pungent, it cognizes sweet, it cognizes alkaline ... it cognizes non-alkaline, it cognizes salty, it cognizes non-salty. It cognizes, bhikkhus, therefore it is called consciousness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple reflects: 'Now I am being oppressed by form. In the past too, I was oppressed by form, just as I am now oppressed by present form. If I were to delight in future form, then in the future I would be oppressed by form, just as I am now oppressed by present form.' Reflecting thus, he has no regret for past form, no delight in future form, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, this is the most lowly livelihood, namely the alms-round. It is a curse in the world, bhikkhus, when they say: 'You, beggar with bowl in hand, you go here and there and that's your livelihood.' Yet, bhikkhus, this is accepted by good men who live for a purpose, for the sake of a purpose; not because of Māra's coercion, not because of thieves' coercion, not because of debt, not because of fear, not because of loss of livelihood, but with the thought: 'I am immersed in birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair; immersed in suffering, surrounded by suffering. Perhaps the end of this whole mass of suffering can be found.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80" },
{ text: `And thus, bhikkhus, a good man goes forth. He has sensual desire for sensual pleasures, intense craving, a mind of hatred, defiled thoughts, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, not concentrated, with distracted mind, unguarded faculties. Just as, bhikkhus, a charnel-ground stick, burned at both ends, smeared with dung in the middle, is not used as wood in the village nor as wood in the forest. Using that simile, bhikkhus, I describe that person who has lost both the household life and does not fulfill the purpose of the ascetic life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three unwholesome thoughts: sensual thought, ill-will thought, harmfulness thought. And these three unwholesome thoughts are completely abandoned without remainder in one whose mind is well established in the Four Foundations of Mindfulness or who develops the signless concentration. Bhikkhus, develop the signless concentration well. Bhikkhus, the signless concentration, when developed and cultivated, yields great fruit and great benefit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these two views: the view of existence and the view of non-existence. Here, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple reflects: 'Is there anything in the world that I could cling to without fault?' And he knows: 'There is nothing in the world that I could cling to without fault.' If I were to cling to form ... feeling ... perception ... formations ... If I were to cling to consciousness, then with clinging as condition, existence would become mine. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, by knowing and seeing in what way are the taints instantly destroyed? Here, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person, who does not see the noble ones, is not skilled in the teaching of the noble ones, not trained in the teaching of the noble ones; who does not see the true persons, is not skilled in the teaching of the true persons, not trained in the teaching of the true persons — regards form as self. Such regarding is a formation. What is the cause, what is the origination, what is the source, what is the condition for that formation? For an unlearned ordinary person, bhikkhus, touched by feeling born of contact with ignorance, craving arises. From that craving, that formation arises. Thus, bhikkhus, that formation is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That craving is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That feeling ... that contact ... that ignorance is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. By knowing thus, by seeing thus, the taints are instantly destroyed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.81" },
{ text: `For an unlearned ordinary person, bhikkhus, touched by feeling born of contact with ignorance, craving arises. From that craving, that formation arises. Thus, bhikkhus, that formation is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That craving is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That contact is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That ignorance is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. By knowing thus, seeing thus, the taints are instantly destroyed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.81" },
{ text: `The forked path, Tissa, is a simile for the state of doubt. The left-hand path, Tissa, is a simile for the wrong eightfold path, that is, wrong view ... wrong concentration. The right-hand path, Tissa, is a simile for the Noble Eightfold Path, that is, right view ... right concentration. The thicket, Tissa, is a simile for ignorance. The low-lying marshes, Tissa, are a simile for sensual pleasures. The deep chasm, Tissa, is a simile for anger and distress. The delightful level ground, Tissa, is a simile for Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.84" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I do not dispute with the world; it is the world that disputes with me. Bhikkhus, a speaker of Dhamma does not dispute with anyone in the world. Bhikkhus, what the wise in the world accept as non-existent, I too say it is non-existent. Bhikkhus, what the wise in the world accept as existent, I too say it is existent. And what, bhikkhus, do the wise in the world accept as non-existent that I too say is non-existent? Bhikkhus, the wise in the world accept as non-existent that form ... feeling ... perception ... formations ... consciousness is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change — that I too say is non-existent. And what, bhikkhus, do the wise in the world accept as existent that I too say is existent? Bhikkhus, the wise in the world accept as existent that form ... feeling ... perception ... formations ... consciousness is impermanent, not everlasting, not eternal, subject to change — that I too say is existent. Just as, bhikkhus, a blue lotus, a red lotus, or a white lotus, born in the water, grown in the water, rises above the water and stands without being stained by the water. So too, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata, born in the world, grown in the world, has risen above the world and lives without being stained by the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.94" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, the Ganges river carries a great mass of foam. A man with good eyesight, looking at it, would carefully examine it. As he carefully examines it, it appears to him as empty, void, without substance. For what substance could there be in a mass of foam? So too, bhikkhus, whatever form, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — a bhikkhu sees form, carefully examines it. As he carefully examines it, it appears to him as empty, void, without substance. For what substance could there be in form?`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.95" },
{ text: `Form is like a lump of foam,<br>Feeling like a water bubble,<br>Perception like a mirage,<br>Formations like a banana tree,<br>Consciousness like a magic trick,<br>So taught the Kinsman of the Sun.<br><br>If one thus examines,<br>Carefully observes them as they are,<br>They appear as empty and hollow<br>When seen properly.<br><br>With regard to this body,<br>The Great Wise One has taught,<br>When three things are abandoned,<br>One sees this form discarded.<br><br>When vitality, heat, and consciousness<br>Leave this body,<br>Then it lies cast away,<br>Food for others.<br><br>This continuous body<br>Is a magician's trick, the fool says,<br>It is called a murderer,<br>No substance is found here.<br><br>Thus a bhikkhu, energetic,<br>Should contemplate the aggregates,<br>Both by day and by night,<br>Mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>He should abandon all fetters,<br>Make himself his own refuge,<br>Live as if his head were on fire,<br>Yearning for the unshakable state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.95" },
{ text: `- There is no form, bhikkhu, that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, and that would endure as long as eternity. There is no feeling ... no perception ... no formation ... no consciousness that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, and that would endure as long as eternity.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.98" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. There may come a time, bhikkhus, when the great ocean dries up, completely vanishes, and is no more. But still, bhikkhus, I say that there is no end of suffering for beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. There may come a time, bhikkhus, when Sineru, the king of mountains, erodes, perishes, and is no more. But still, bhikkhus, I say that there is no end of suffering for beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving! There may come a time, bhikkhus, when the great earth erodes, perishes, and is no more. But still, bhikkhus, I say that there is no end of suffering for beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.99" },
{ text: `- This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning, bhikkhus. A first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving. Just as, bhikkhus, a dog tied by a leash to a strong post or pillar — if it walks, it walks around that post or pillar; if it stands, it stands near that post or pillar; if it sits, it sits near that post or pillar; if it lies down, it lies down near that post or pillar. So too, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person regards form: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'; regards feeling ... perception ... formations ... regards consciousness: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self.' If he walks, he walks only around these five aggregates of clinging; if he stands, he stands near them; if he sits, he sits near them; if he lies down, he lies down near them. Therefore, bhikkhus, one should always contemplate one's own mind thus: 'For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the mind's defilement, beings are defiled; through the mind's purification, beings are purified.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, have you seen a painting called 'The Wandering One'?" — "Yes, Venerable Sir." — "Bhikkhus, that painting was painted by the mind. Therefore, bhikkhus, the mind is even more diverse than that painting. Therefore, bhikkhus, one should always contemplate one's own mind thus: 'For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the mind's defilement, beings are defiled; through the mind's purification, beings are purified.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I do not see any other class of beings as diverse as the mind. Even the animals, bhikkhus, are diverse because of the mind. Therefore, bhikkhus, the mind is even more diverse than those animals. Therefore, bhikkhus, one should always contemplate one's own mind thus: 'For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the mind's defilement, beings are defiled; through the mind's purification, beings are purified.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu lives without being devoted to development, even if he wishes: 'May my mind be liberated from the taints without clinging!' yet his mind will not be liberated from the taints without clinging. Why is that? It should be said: because he has not developed. What has he not developed? He has not developed the Four Foundations of Mindfulness. He has not developed the Four Right Efforts. He has not developed the Four Bases of Spiritual Power. He has not developed the Five Faculties. He has not developed the Five Powers. He has not developed the Seven Factors of Enlightenment. He has not developed the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.101" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, eight, ten, or twelve hen's eggs, not properly covered, not properly incubated, not properly nurtured — even if the hen wishes: 'May my chicks, with their claws, nails, and head, or with their mouth and beak, break the eggshell and emerge safely!' yet those chicks cannot break the eggshell and emerge safely. Why is that? Because the eggs were not properly covered, not properly incubated, not properly nurtured. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who lives without being devoted to development — even if he wishes: 'May my mind be liberated from the taints without clinging!' yet his mind will not be liberated from the taints without clinging. Why is that? It should be said: because he has not developed. What has he not developed? He has not developed the Four Foundations of Mindfulness ... He has not developed the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.101" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a smith or his apprentice, when looking at his adze handle, sees the marks of his fingers and thumb. He cannot know: 'So much of my adze handle wore away today, so much yesterday, so much on other days.' But he knows it is wearing away by the wearing away itself. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is devoted to development does not know: 'So much of my taints wore away today, so much yesterday, so much on other days.' But he knows they are wearing away by the wearing away itself. Just as, bhikkhus, a seafaring ship, fully rigged, stranded for six months due to lack of water in the dry season — its rigging gets damaged by wind and sun, then when the rains come, it becomes weak and rots. So too, bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu who is devoted to development, the fetters easily weaken and rot.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.101" },
{ text: `- By developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all sensual lust is abandoned, all lust for form is abandoned, all craving for existence is abandoned, all ignorance is abandoned, all conceit is uprooted. Just as, bhikkhus, in the autumn, a farmer plowing with a large plow cuts through all the spreading roots while plowing. So too, bhikkhus, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all sensual lust is abandoned ... all conceit is uprooted. Just as, bhikkhus, a grass-cutter, having cut the grass, grasps its tip and shakes it up, down, left, and right, then throws it away. So too, bhikkhus, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all sensual lust is abandoned ... all conceit is uprooted. Just as, bhikkhus, when a bunch of mangoes is cut from the stem, all the mangoes attached to the stem are cut off with it. So too, bhikkhus, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all sensual lust is abandoned ... all conceit is uprooted.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.102" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in the autumn, when the sky is clear and cloudless, the sun rises in the sky, dispelling all darkness from space, shining, glowing, and radiating. So too, bhikkhus, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all sensual lust is abandoned, all lust for form is abandoned, all craving for existence is abandoned, all ignorance is abandoned, all conceit is uprooted. How is the perception of impermanence developed and cultivated, bhikkhus, so that all sensual lust is abandoned ... all conceit is uprooted? This is form; this is the arising of form; this is the cessation of form. This is feeling ... this is perception ... these are formations ... this is consciousness; this is the arising of consciousness; this is the cessation of consciousness. The perception of impermanence developed and cultivated in this way, bhikkhus, leads to the abandoning of all sensual lust, all lust for form, all craving for existence, all ignorance, and the uprooting of all conceit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.102" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I will teach you suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the path leading to the cessation of suffering. Listen. And what, bhikkhus, is suffering? It should be answered: the five aggregates of clinging. What are the five? That is, the form aggregate of clinging ... the consciousness aggregate of clinging. This, bhikkhus, is called suffering. And what, bhikkhus, is the origin of suffering? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence ... craving for non-existence. This, bhikkhus, is called the origin of suffering. And what, bhikkhus, is the cessation of suffering? It is the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, its abandonment, relinquishment, liberation, and non-clinging. This, bhikkhus, is called the cessation of suffering. And what, bhikkhus, is the path leading to the cessation of suffering? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, that is, right view ... right concentration. This, bhikkhus, is called the path leading to the cessation of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.104" },
{ text: `'Knowledge, knowledge,' Venerable Sir, is said. What is knowledge, Venerable Sir, and to what extent is a person knowledgeable?" — "Here, bhikkhu, a learned noble disciple knows form, knows the origin of form, knows the cessation of form, knows the path leading to the cessation of form. He knows feeling ... knows perception ... knows formations ... knows consciousness, knows the origin of consciousness, knows the cessation of consciousness, knows the path leading to the cessation of consciousness. This, bhikkhu, is called knowledge. And to this extent a person is knowledgeable.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.114" },
{ text: `- Here, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person, who does not see the noble ones ... does not train in the teaching of the true persons, regards form as self, or self as possessing form, or form as in self, or self as in form. Such a person, bhikkhus, is called an unlearned ordinary person, bound by the bonds of form, bound by internal and external bonds, one who does not see this shore, does not see the far shore, bound at birth, bound at death, bound when passing from this world to the next.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.117" },
{ text: `- What do you think, bhikkhus, do you regard form: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self'?" — "Yes, Venerable Sir." — "Good! Bhikkhus, you should see form as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.119", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.119" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I will teach you the things that are fettered and the fetter. Listen. And what, bhikkhus, are the things that are fettered? What is the fetter? Form, bhikkhus, is a thing that is fettered. The desire and lust for form is the fetter of form. Feeling ... Perception ... Formations ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is a thing that is fettered. The desire and lust for consciousness is the fetter of consciousness. These, bhikkhus, are called the things that are fettered, and this is the fetter.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.120" },


{ text: `- Friend Sāriputta, what things should a virtuous bhikkhu attend to wisely? - Friend Kotthika, a virtuous bhikkhu should attend wisely to the five aggregates of clinging as impermanent, suffering, a disease, a boil, a dart, a calamity, an affliction, alien, breaking up, empty, and non-self. What are the five? That is, the form aggregate of clinging, the feeling aggregate of clinging, the perception aggregate of clinging, the formation aggregate of clinging, the consciousness aggregate of clinging. Friend Kotthika, a virtuous bhikkhu should attend wisely to the five aggregates of clinging as impermanent, suffering, a disease, a boil, a dart, a calamity, an affliction, alien, breaking up, empty, and non-self.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.122", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.122" },
{ text: `'Ignorance, ignorance,' Venerable Sir, is said. What is ignorance, Venerable Sir, and to what extent is one called ignorant?" - "Here, bhikkhu, an unlearned ordinary person does not truly understand: 'Form is subject to arising' as form is subject to arising; does not truly understand: 'Form is subject to passing away' as form is subject to passing away; does not truly understand: 'Form is subject to arising and passing away' as form is subject to arising and passing away. This, bhikkhu, is called ignorance. And to this extent one is called ignorant.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.126", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.126" },
{ text: `- Form, bhikkhus, is a burning ember! Feeling is a burning ember! Perception is a burning ember! Formations are burning embers! Consciousness is a burning ember! Seeing thus, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.136" },
{ text: `- Whatever is impermanent, bhikkhus, therein you should abandon desire. Bhikkhus, what is impermanent? Form, bhikkhus, is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. Feeling ... Perception ... Formations ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. Whatever is impermanent, bhikkhus, therein you should abandon desire.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.137", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.137" },
{ text: `- For a good man who has gone forth out of faith, bhikkhus, this is the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma: Let him dwell often in disenchantment towards form ... towards feeling ... towards perception ... towards formations; let him dwell often in disenchantment towards consciousness. By dwelling often in disenchantment towards form ... towards feeling ... towards perception ... towards formations; by dwelling often in disenchantment towards consciousness, he fully understands form ... fully understands feeling ... fully understands perception ... fully understands formations ... fully understands consciousness. One who fully understands form, fully understands feeling, fully understands perception, fully understands formations, fully understands consciousness, is liberated from form, liberated from feeling, liberated from perception, liberated from formations, liberated from consciousness, liberated from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is liberated from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.146", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.146" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, for what purpose is right contemplation?" - "Right contemplation, Rādha, has disenchantment as its purpose." - "Venerable Sir, what is the purpose of disenchantment?" - "Disenchantment, Rādha, has dispassion as its purpose." - "Venerable Sir, what is the purpose of dispassion?" - "Dispassion, Rādha, has liberation as its purpose." - "Venerable Sir, what is the purpose of liberation?" - "Liberation, Rādha, has Nibbāna as its purpose." - "Venerable Sir, what is the purpose of Nibbāna?" - "Rādha, your question goes too far; you cannot grasp the limit of the question. The holy life is grounded in Nibbāna, culminates in Nibbāna, ends in Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.1" },
{ text: `- If there is form, Rādha, then there is death, or a killer, or being killed. Therefore, Rādha, you should see form as death, as a killer, as being killed, as a disease, as a boil, as a dart, as a calamity, as a disaster. Those who see form thus see rightly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.1" },
{ text: `Just as, Rādha, young boys or young girls play with sandcastles. As long as they are not free from lust, desire, love, thirst, passion, and craving for those sandcastles, they still have fun with them, play with them, treasure them, and delight in them. But when those boys or girls become free from lust, desire, love, thirst, passion, and craving for those sandcastles, then they break them apart, smash them, demolish them, and do not play with them. So too, Rādha, break apart, smash, demolish, and do not play with form; direct your mind to the destruction of craving for form. The destruction of craving, Rādha, is Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.2" },
{ text: `'A being, a being,' Venerable Sir, is said. To what extent, Venerable Sir, is one called a being?" - "Rādha, any desire, lust, delight, craving for form, any engagement there, any settling there — to that extent one is called a being. ... for feeling ... for perception ... for formations ... Any desire, lust, delight, craving for consciousness, any engagement there, any settling there — to that extent one is called a being.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.2" },
{ text: `'The cutting off of the conduit of rebirth, the cutting off of the conduit of rebirth,' Venerable Sir, is said. What is the conduit of rebirth, Venerable Sir? What is the cutting off of the conduit of rebirth?" - "Rādha, any desire, lust, delight, craving, any engagement, mental adherence, underlying tendency regarding form — that is called the conduit of rebirth. Their cutting off is the cutting off of the conduit of rebirth. ... regarding feeling ... regarding perception ... regarding formations ... Any desire, lust, delight, craving, any engagement, mental adherence, underlying tendency regarding consciousness — that is called the conduit of rebirth. Their cutting off is the cutting off of the conduit of rebirth.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.3" },
{ text: `- Rādha, any desire, lust, delight, craving for form — abandon them. Thus that form will be cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future. ... for feeling ... for perception ... for formations ... Rādha, any desire, lust, delight, craving for consciousness — abandon them. Thus that consciousness will be cut off, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, not to be born in the future.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, when a noble disciple, regarding these six bases, has cut off doubt; regarding suffering, has cut off doubt; regarding the origin of suffering, has cut off doubt; regarding the cessation of suffering, has cut off doubt; regarding the path leading to the cessation of suffering, has cut off doubt — then, bhikkhus, he is called a noble disciple who is a stream-enterer, no longer subject to falling, bound for enlightenment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 24.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn24.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, the arising, continuation, production, manifestation of the eye is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. The arising, continuation, production, manifestation of the ear ... of the nose ... of the tongue ... of the body ... of the mind is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. The cessation, stilling, passing away of the eye is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the passing away of aging and death. The cessation, stilling, passing away of the ear ... nose ... tongue ... body ... mind is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the passing away of aging and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 26.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn26.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, desire and lust for the eye is a corruption of the mind. Desire and lust for the ear ... for the nose ... for the tongue ... for the body ... for the mind is a corruption of the mind. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu, regarding these six bases, has abandoned the corruption of the mind, his mind inclines towards renunciation. With renunciation fully developed, his mind is considered to be capable and to have realized the things to be fully understood.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 27.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn27.1" },
{ text: `- There are these four types of meditators, bhikkhus. What are the four? Here, bhikkhus, a certain meditator is skilled in attainment in concentration but not skilled in duration in concentration. Here, bhikkhus, a certain meditator is skilled in duration in concentration but not skilled in attainment in concentration. Here, bhikkhus, a certain meditator is skilled neither in attainment nor in duration in concentration. Here, bhikkhus, a certain meditator is skilled both in attainment and in duration in concentration. Among these four meditators, the one who is skilled both in attainment and in duration in concentration is the foremost, best, chief, highest, and most excellent.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 34.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn34.11" },
{ text: `- One who delights in forms, bhikkhus, delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who delights in sounds ... in odors ... in tastes ... in tangibles ... One who delights in mind-objects, delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who does not delight in forms, bhikkhus, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in sounds ... in odors ... in tastes ... in tangibles ... One who does not delight in mind-objects, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.20" },
{ text: `The eye, bhikkhus, is burning. Forms are burning. Eye-consciousness is burning. Eye-contact is burning. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that too is burning. Burning with what? Burning with the fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. I say it is burning with birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue is burning. Tastes are burning. Tongue-consciousness is burning. Tongue-contact is burning. Whatever feeling arises dependent on tongue-contact ... that too is burning. Burning with what? Burning with the fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. I say it is burning with birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. ... The body ... The mind is burning. Mind-objects are burning. Mind-consciousness is burning. Mind-contact is burning. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... that too is burning. Burning with what? Burning with the fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. I say it is burning with birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.28" },
{ text: `- By knowing and seeing in what way, Venerable Sir, is ignorance abandoned and knowledge arisen?" - "Bhikkhu, by knowing and seeing the eye as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises. By knowing and seeing forms as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises ... eye-consciousness ... eye-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — by knowing and seeing that feeling as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises. The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... By knowing and seeing the mind as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises. Mind-objects ... mind-consciousness ... mind-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... by knowing and seeing that feeling as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises. By knowing thus, by seeing thus, bhikkhus, ignorance is abandoned and knowledge arises.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.53" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Dhamma leading to the full understanding of all clinging? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the eye, disenchanted with forms, disenchanted with eye-consciousness, disenchanted with eye-contact, disenchanted with feeling. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. Through liberation, he understands: 'I have fully understood clinging.' Dependent on the ear and sounds ... Dependent on the nose and odors ... Dependent on the tongue and tastes ... Dependent on the body and tangibles ... Dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the mind, disenchanted with mind-objects, disenchanted with mind-consciousness, disenchanted with mind-contact, disenchanted with feeling. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. Through liberation, he understands: 'I have fully understood clinging.' Thus, bhikkhus, is the Dhamma leading to the full understanding of all clinging.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.60" },
{ text: `Migajāla, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights, praises, and abides with attachment to them; because he delights, praises, and abides with attachment, delight arises. With delight as condition, sensual desire is present. With sensual desire as condition, bondage is present. Bound by the bond of delight, Migajāla, that bhikkhu is called one who lives with a second. Even if he dwells in remote lodgings, in forests, in jungle groves, with little noise, little clamor, secluded from people, remote, suitable for seclusion — still he is called one who lives with a second. Why is that? Because craving, the second, has not been abandoned; therefore he is called one who lives with a second.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63" },
{ text: `And, Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment to them; because he does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment, delight ceases. With delight absent, sensual desire is absent. With sensual desire absent, bondage is absent. Not bound by the bond of delight, Migajāla, that bhikkhu is called one who lives alone.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63" },
{ text: `Migajāla, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment to them; because he does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment, delight ceases. With delight absent, sensual desire is absent. With sensual desire absent, bondage is absent. Not bound by the bond of delight, Migajāla, that bhikkhu is called one who lives alone. Even if he dwells in the midst of a village crowded with bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers, kings, kings' ministers, wanderers, and wanderers' disciples — still he is called one who lives alone. Why is that? Because craving, the second, has been abandoned; therefore he is called one who lives alone.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63" },
{ text: `- Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights, praises, and abides with attachment to those forms; because he delights, praises, and abides with attachment, delight arises. Migajāla, I say that with the arising of delight, suffering arises. ... Sounds ... Odors ... Tastes ... Tangibles ... Migajāla, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights, praises, and abides with attachment to those mind-objects; because he delights, praises, and abides with attachment, delight arises. Migajāla, I say that with the arising of delight, suffering arises.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.64" },
{ text: `Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment to those forms; because he does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment, delight ceases. Migajāla, I say that with the cessation of delight, suffering ceases. ... Sounds ... Odors ... Tastes ... Tangibles ... Migajāla, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment to those mind-objects; because he does not delight, does not praise, and abides without attachment, delight ceases. Migajāla, I say that with the cessation of delight, suffering ceases.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.64" },
{ text: `'The world, the world,' Venerable Sir, is said. To what extent, Venerable Sir, is there the world or the concept of the world?" - "Where, Samiddhi, there is the eye, there are forms, there is eye-consciousness, there are things cognizable by the eye — there the world or the concept of the world exists. ... Where there is the mind, there are mind-objects, there is mind-consciousness, there are things cognizable by the mind — there the world or the concept of the world exists. And where, Samiddhi, there is no eye, no forms, no eye-consciousness, no things cognizable by the eye — there the world or the concept of the world does not exist. ... Where there is no mind, no mind-objects, no mind-consciousness, no things cognizable by the mind — there the world or the concept of the world does not exist.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.68" },
{ text: `'Directly visible, directly visible (sanditthiko),' Venerable Sir, is said. To what extent, Venerable Sir, is the Dhamma directly visible, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves?" - "There, Upavāna, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he experiences the form but does not experience lust for the form, and there is no inner lust for form. He knows: 'There is no inner lust for form in me.' To whatever extent, Upavāna, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he experiences the form but does not experience lust for the form, and there is no inner lust for form, and he knows: 'There is no inner lust for form in me' — to that extent, Upavāna, the Dhamma is directly visible, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.70" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who does not truly know the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape regarding the six sense-spheres — that bhikkhu has not lived the holy life, he is far from this Dhamma and Discipline. - What do you think, bhikkhu? Do you regard the eye as 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Good, bhikkhu. Here, bhikkhu, when you see the eye as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self' — that is seeing rightly. This is the end of suffering. ... the ear ... the nose ... the tongue ... the body ... What do you think, bhikkhu? Do you regard the mind as 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Good, bhikkhu. Here, bhikkhu, when you see the mind as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self' — that is seeing rightly. This is the end of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.71" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, I do not understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One regarding the purpose of the purity of virtue." - "Bhikkhu, if you do not understand the Dhamma taught by me regarding the purpose of the purity of virtue, then, bhikkhu, how do you understand the Dhamma taught by me?" - "Venerable Sir, I understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One as greed and the abandoning of greed." - "Good, good, bhikkhu! It is good that you understand the Dhamma taught by me as greed and the abandoning of greed. For the purpose of greed and its abandoning, bhikkhu, is the Dhamma taught by me. What do you think, bhikkhu? Is the eye permanent or impermanent?" — "Impermanent, Venerable Sir." — "The ear ... the nose ... the tongue ... the body ... Is the mind permanent or impermanent?" — "Impermanent, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent is suffering or happiness?" — "Suffering, Venerable Sir." — "What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change, is it fitting to regard it as: 'This is mine, this I am, this is my self'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Seeing thus, bhikkhu, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the eye ... ' ... there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.74" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, the Venerable Rādha said to the Blessed One: - It would be good, Venerable Sir, if the Blessed One would teach me the Dhamma in brief. Having heard the Dhamma from the Blessed One, I will live alone, secluded, heedful, ardent, and resolute. - Whatever is impermanent, Rādha, therein you should abandon desire. And what, Rādha, is impermanent? The eye, Rādha, is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. Forms are impermanent ... Eye-consciousness is impermanent ... Eye-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. Mind-objects ... Mind-consciousness ... Mind-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... that feeling is impermanent; therein you should abandon desire. Whatever is impermanent, Rādha, therein you should abandon desire.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.76" },
{ text: `- Whatever is suffering, Rādha, therein you should abandon desire. And what, Rādha, is suffering? The eye, Rādha, is suffering; therein you should abandon desire. Forms ... Eye-consciousness ... Eye-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact ... that feeling is suffering; therein you should abandon desire. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind is suffering; therein you should abandon desire. Mind-objects ... Mind-consciousness ... Mind-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... that feeling is suffering; therein you should abandon desire. Whatever is suffering, Rādha, therein you should abandon desire.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.77" },
{ text: `'Empty is the world, empty is the world,' Venerable Sir, is said. To what extent, Venerable Sir, is the world called empty?" - "Because, Ānanda, the world is empty of self and of anything belonging to self, therefore the world is called empty. And what, Ānanda, is empty of self and of anything belonging to self? The eye, Ānanda, is empty of self and of anything belonging to self. Forms are empty of self and of anything belonging to self. Eye-consciousness is empty of self and of anything belonging to self. Eye-contact is empty ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact ... that feeling is empty of self and of anything belonging to self. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind is empty of self and of anything belonging to self. Mind-objects ... Mind-consciousness ... Mind-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... that feeling is empty of self and of anything belonging to self. And because it is empty of self and of anything belonging to self, Ānanda, the world is called empty.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.85" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, there is a country named Sunāparanta where I will live." - "Fierce, Puñña, are the people of Sunāparanta. Rough, Puñña, are the people of Sunāparanta. If the people of Sunāparanta revile and insult you, Puñña, what will you think then?" - "Venerable Sir, if the people of Sunāparanta revile and insult me, I will think: 'These people of Sunāparanta are good, truly excellent, because they do not hit me with their hands.' Thus, Venerable Sir, I will think. Thus, Venerable Sir, I will think." - "Good, good, Puñña! With this self-taming and peace, you can live in the Sunāparanta country. Now, Puñña, do what you think is timely.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.88" },
{ text: `- Craving, bhikkhus, is a disease; craving is a boil; craving is a dart. Therefore, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata lives without craving, without being wounded by the dart. Therefore, bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has any wish, let him wish to live without craving, without being wounded by the dart. Do not conceive the eye, do not conceive in the eye, do not conceive from the eye, do not conceive: 'The eye is mine.' Do not conceive forms, do not conceive in forms, do not conceive from forms, do not conceive: 'Forms are mine.' Do not conceive eye-consciousness, do not conceive in eye-consciousness, do not conceive from eye-consciousness, do not conceive: 'Eye-consciousness is mine.' Do not conceive eye-contact, do not conceive in eye-contact, do not conceive from eye-contact, do not conceive: 'Eye-contact is mine.' Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — do not conceive that feeling, do not conceive in that feeling, do not conceive from that feeling, do not conceive: 'That feeling is mine.' Do not conceive everything, do not conceive in everything, do not conceive from everything, do not conceive: 'Everything is mine.' Through not conceiving, he does not cling to anything in the world. Not clinging, he is not agitated. Not agitated, he personally attains complete Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.90" },
{ text: `- There are these six sense-spheres, bhikkhus, that, if unrestrained, unguarded, unprotected, untamed, bring suffering. What six? The eye-sense-sphere, bhikkhus, if unrestrained, unguarded, unprotected, untamed, brings suffering. The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind-sense-sphere, bhikkhus, if unrestrained, unguarded, unprotected, untamed, brings suffering. These six sense-spheres, bhikkhus, if unrestrained, unguarded, unprotected, untamed, bring suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94" },
{ text: `There are these six sense-spheres, bhikkhus, that, if well restrained, well guarded, well protected, well tamed, bring happiness. What six? The eye-sense-sphere, bhikkhus, if well restrained, well guarded, well protected, well tamed, brings happiness. The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind-sense-sphere, bhikkhus, if well restrained, well guarded, well protected, well tamed, brings happiness. These six sense-spheres, bhikkhus, if well restrained, well guarded, well protected, well tamed, bring happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94" },
{ text: `O bhikkhus,<br>These six sense-spheres indeed,<br>Where they are untamed,<br>There is suffering.<br>Those who learn to know them,<br>Restraining, guarding them,<br>With faith as companion,<br>Live free from sensual desires.<br><br>Seeing pleasant forms,<br>Seeing unpleasant forms,<br>Restrain the path of lust<br>Toward pleasant forms,<br>Do not let the mind be defiled<br>By thinking: 'I dislike forms.'<br><br>Having heard sounds,<br>Pleasant and unpleasant,<br>Do not let the mind be intoxicated<br>By pleasant sounds.<br>Restrain hatred<br>Toward unpleasant sounds,<br>Do not let the mind be defiled<br>By thinking: 'I dislike sounds.'<br><br>Having smelled odors,<br>Fragrant and pleasant,<br>Having smelled odors,<br>Foul and repulsive;<br>Restrain hatred<br>Toward repulsive odors,<br>And toward pleasant odors,<br>Do not let lust overcome you.<br><br>Having tasted sweet tastes,<br>And tastes that are not sweet,<br>Do not become attached<br>When enjoying sweet tastes,<br>Do not speak in opposition<br>When tasting unpleasant tastes.<br><br>When feeling pleasant touch,<br>Do not become intoxicated with attachment,<br>When feeling painful touch,<br>Do not be strongly disturbed.<br>Toward both touches,<br>Pleasant and painful, be mindful, equanimous,<br>Without attraction and without aversion,<br>Whatever the touch may be.<br><br>Toward others who follow<br>Proliferating perceptions,<br>They are confused by proliferation,<br>They act on vain thoughts;<br>Abandon all<br>Household matters created by the mind,<br>Restrain your actions,<br>Direct them to seclusion.<br><br>Thus, regarding the six bases,<br>When the mind is well trained,<br>Whatever contact arises,<br>The mind is not shaken.<br>Bhikkhu, restrain<br>Both greed and hatred,<br>Go to the far shore,<br>Beyond the bonds of birth and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94" },
{ text: `- What do you think, Mālukyaputta? Regarding forms cognizable by the eye, you have not seen, you have never seen, you do not see, and you have no desire to see — would there be desire, lust, or craving for them?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Regarding sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... tastes cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body, you have not felt, you have never felt, you do not feel, and you have no desire to feel — would there be desire, lust, or craving for them?" — "No, Venerable Sir."<br><br>Seeing a form, mindfulness confused,<br>Attending to a sign of attraction,<br>Mind attached to that feeling,<br>Clinging to the form remains.<br>For him, feelings increase,<br>Many, arising from the form,<br>Greed and thoughts of harm<br>Afflict his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>He is called far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Hearing a sound, mindfulness confused,<br>Attending to a sign of attraction,<br>Mind attached to that feeling,<br>Clinging to the sound remains.<br>For him, feelings increase,<br>Many, arising from the sound,<br>Greed and thoughts of harm<br>Afflict his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>He is called far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Tasting a taste, mindfulness confused,<br>Attending to a sign of attraction,<br>Mind attached to that feeling,<br>Clinging to the taste remains.<br>For him, feelings increase,<br>Many, arising from the taste,<br>Greed and thoughts of harm<br>Afflict his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>He is called far from Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.95" },
{ text: `He does not lust for forms,<br>Seeing a form, not attached,<br>Mind not stuck in that feeling,<br>Not clinging to the form remains.<br>As he sees the form,<br>As he feels the feeling,<br>It wears away, not accumulating,<br>Thus mindful, he lives his life.<br>Thus suffering does not accumulate,<br>He is called near to Nibbāna.<br><br>He does not lust for sounds,<br>Hearing a sound, not attached,<br>Mind not stuck in that feeling,<br>Not clinging to the sound remains.<br>As he hears the sound,<br>As he feels the feeling,<br>It wears away, not accumulating,<br>Thus mindful, he lives his life.<br>Thus suffering does not accumulate,<br>He is called near to Nibbāna.<br><br>He does not lust for odors,<br>Smelling an odor, not attached,<br>Mind not stuck in that feeling,<br>Not clinging to the odor remains.<br>As he smells the odor,<br>As he feels the feeling,<br>It wears away, not accumulating,<br>Thus mindful, he lives his life.<br>Thus suffering does not accumulate,<br>He is called near to Nibbāna.<br><br>He does not lust for tastes,<br>Tasting a taste, not attached,<br>Mind not stuck in that feeling,<br>Not clinging to the taste remains.<br>As he tastes the taste,<br>As he feels the feeling,<br>It wears away, not accumulating,<br>Thus mindful, he lives his life.<br>Thus suffering does not accumulate,<br>He is called near to Nibbāna.<br><br>He does not lust for tangibles,<br>Feeling a touch, not attached,<br>Mind not stuck in that feeling,<br>Not clinging to the touch remains.<br>As he feels the touch,<br>As he feels the feeling,<br>It wears away, not accumulating,<br>Thus mindful, he lives his life.<br>Thus suffering does not accumulate,<br>He is called near to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.95" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Dhamma of decline? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, evil, unwholesome states, memories, and thoughts connected with the fetters arise. If the bhikkhu accepts them, does not abandon them, does not eliminate them, does not destroy them, does not make them cease — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls the Dhamma of decline. ... When he hears a sound with the ear ... smells an odor with the nose ... tastes a taste with the tongue ... feels a touch with the body ... Furthermore, bhikkhus, when he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, evil, unwholesome states, memories, and thoughts connected with the fetters arise. If the bhikkhu accepts them, does not abandon them, does not eliminate them, does not destroy them, does not make them cease — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls the Dhamma of decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is the Dhamma of decline.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.96" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Dhamma of non-decline? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, evil, unwholesome states, memories, and thoughts connected with the fetters arise. If the bhikkhu does not accept them, abandons them, eliminates them, destroys them, makes them cease — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am not declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls the Dhamma of non-decline. ... When he hears a sound ... smells an odor ... tastes a taste ... feels a touch ... Furthermore, bhikkhus, when he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, evil, unwholesome states, memories, and thoughts connected with the fetters arise. If the bhikkhu does not accept them, abandons them, eliminates them, destroys them, makes them cease — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am not declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls the Dhamma of non-decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is the Dhamma of non-decline.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.96" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is dwelling in heedlessness? One who lives without restraining the eye faculty, bhikkhus, his mind is stained by forms cognizable by the eye. For one with a stained mind, there is no gladness. Without gladness, there is no rapture. Without rapture, there is no tranquility. Without tranquility, suffering abides. For one suffering, the mind does not become concentrated. Without concentration, phenomena are not manifest. When phenomena are not manifest, that person is called one who dwells in heedlessness. ... the ear faculty ... the nose faculty ... the tongue faculty ... the body faculty ... One who lives without restraining the mind faculty, his mind is stained by mind-objects cognizable by the mind. For one with a stained mind, there is no gladness. Without gladness, no rapture. Without rapture, no tranquility. Without tranquility, suffering abides. For one suffering, the mind does not become concentrated. Without concentration, phenomena are not manifest. When phenomena are not manifest, that person is called one who dwells in heedlessness. Thus, bhikkhus, is dwelling in heedlessness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.97" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is dwelling in heedfulness? One who lives restraining the eye faculty, bhikkhus, his mind is not stained by forms cognizable by the eye. For one with an unstained mind, gladness arises. With gladness, rapture arises. With rapture, the body becomes tranquil. With a tranquil body, he experiences happiness. For one who is happy, the mind becomes concentrated. With concentration, phenomena become manifest. When phenomena are manifest, that person is called one who dwells in heedfulness. ... the ear faculty ... the nose faculty ... the tongue faculty ... the body faculty ... One who lives restraining the mind faculty, his mind is not stained by mind-objects cognizable by the mind. For one with an unstained mind, gladness arises. With gladness, rapture arises. With rapture, the body becomes tranquil. With a tranquil body, he experiences happiness. For one who is happy, the mind becomes concentrated. With concentration, phenomena become manifest. When phenomena are manifest, that person is called one who dwells in heedfulness. Thus, bhikkhus, is dwelling in heedfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.97" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is non-restraint? And, bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls decline. ... There are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... There are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is non-restraint.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is restraint? Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am not declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls non-decline. ... There are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... And, bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those mind-objects, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am not declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls non-decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is restraint.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are. And what does he understand as they actually are? He understands the eye as actually impermanent, he understands forms as actually impermanent, he understands eye-consciousness as actually impermanent, he understands eye-contact as actually impermanent. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he understands that feeling as actually impermanent. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... He understands the mind as actually impermanent, he understands mind-objects as actually impermanent, he understands mind-consciousness as actually impermanent, he understands mind-contact as actually impermanent. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... he understands that feeling as actually impermanent. Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.99" },
{ text: `- Whatever is not yours, bhikkhus, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. And what, bhikkhus, is not yours? The eye, bhikkhus, is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Forms are not yours, abandon them. Abandoning them will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Eye-consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Eye-contact is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. ... The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... The mind is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Mind-objects are not yours, abandon them. Abandoning them will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Mind-consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Mind-contact is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... that feeling is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.101" },


{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, if someone in this Jeta's Grove were to take away, burn, or do whatever they wished with all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves, would you think: 'That person takes us away, burns us, or does whatever they wish with us'?" — "No, Venerable Sir." — "Why is that? Because that is not our self nor what belongs to our self. So too, bhikkhus, the eye is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Forms are not yours... Eye-consciousness is not yours... Eye-contact is not yours... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.101" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the arising of suffering? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. This is the arising of suffering. Dependent on the ear ... on the nose ... on the tongue ... on the body ... Dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. This, bhikkhus, is the arising of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.106" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the cessation of suffering? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. With the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, clinging ceases. With the cessation of clinging, existence ceases. With the cessation of existence, birth ceases. With the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. This is the cessation of suffering. Dependent on the ear ... on the nose ... on the tongue ... on the body ... Dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. With the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, clinging ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. This is the cessation of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.106" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the arising of the world? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. With craving as condition, clinging arises. With clinging as condition, existence arises. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. This is the arising of the world. Dependent on the ear ... on the nose ... on the tongue ... on the body ... Dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. With craving as condition, clinging arises. With clinging as condition, existence arises. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Bhikkhus, this is the arising of the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.107" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has gone to Māra's abode, who has been conquered by Māra. Māra's snare has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is at the Evil One's mercy. ... Bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment to them — then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has gone to Māra's abode, who has been conquered by Māra. Māra's snare has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is at the Evil One's mercy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.114" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet perfectly enlightened, the following thought occurred: 'The five strands of sensual pleasure that my mind formerly experienced — past, ceased, changed — there my mind becomes feverish for those present, and it becomes diminished for those not yet come, in the future.' Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'The five strands of sensual pleasure that my mind formerly experienced — past, ceased, changed — for your own benefit, live heedfully, guarding your mind with mindfulness.' Therefore, bhikkhus, regarding the five strands of sensual pleasure that your mind formerly experienced — past, ceased, changed — there your mind becomes feverish for those present, and it becomes diminished for those not yet come, in the future. Therefore, bhikkhus, regarding the five strands of sensual pleasure that your mind formerly experienced — past, ceased, changed — for your own benefit, live heedfully, guarding your mind with mindfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.117" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, what is the cause, what is the condition why some beings here and now do not attain Nibbāna? And what is the cause, what is the condition why some beings here and now attain Nibbāna?" - "Lord of devas, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment to them, then his consciousness becomes dependent on that and clings to it. With clinging, lord of devas, that bhikkhu does not attain Nibbāna. Lord of devas, there are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... Lord of devas, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment to them, then his consciousness becomes dependent on that and clings to it. With clinging, lord of devas, that bhikkhu does not attain Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.118", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.118" },
{ text: `And, lord of devas, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them, then his consciousness is not dependent on that and does not cling to it. Without clinging, lord of devas, that bhikkhu attains Nibbāna. There are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... Lord of devas, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those mind-objects, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them, then his consciousness is not dependent on that and does not cling to it. Without clinging, lord of devas, that bhikkhu attains Nibbāna. This, lord of devas, is the cause, this is the condition why some beings here and now attain Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.118", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.118" },
{ text: `Sitting to one side, that bhikkhu said to the Venerable Sāriputta: - Friend Sāriputta, a fellow bhikkhu has given up the training and returned to the lower life. - Friend, that happens to one who does not guard the sense faculties, does not know moderation in eating, and is not devoted to wakefulness. For life, that one could live the holy life completely pure — that is impossible. Friend, a bhikkhu who guards the sense faculties, knows moderation in eating, and is devoted to wakefulness — for life, that one could live the holy life completely pure — that is possible. Therefore, friend, you should train thus: 'We will guard the sense faculties, know moderation in eating, and be devoted to wakefulness.' Thus, friend, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120" },
{ text: `And, friend, what is guarding the sense faculties? Friend, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the eye faculty, practices the restraint of the eye faculty. When he hears a sound with the ear ... smells an odor with the nose ... tastes a taste with the tongue ... feels a touch with the body ... cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the mind faculty, practices the restraint of the mind faculty. Thus, friend, is guarding the sense faculties.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120" },
{ text: `Friend, what is moderation in eating? Here, friend, a bhikkhu, reflecting wisely, takes food. Not for enjoyment, not for indulgence, not for beautification, not for ornamentation, but only for the support and maintenance of this body, for avoiding harm, for assisting the holy life, thinking: 'Thus I shall destroy old feelings and not arouse new feelings; and there will be for me blamelessness and a comfortable abiding.' Thus, friend, is moderation in eating.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120" },
{ text: `And, friend, what is devotion to wakefulness? Here, friend, a bhikkhu by day, while walking and sitting, purifies his mind from obstructive states. In the first watch of the night, while walking and sitting, he purifies his mind from obstructive states. In the middle watch of the night, he lies down on his right side in the lion's posture, one foot on the other, mindful and clearly comprehending, noting the time for rising. In the last watch of the night, after rising, while walking and sitting, he purifies his mind from obstructive states. Thus, friend, is devotion to wakefulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120" },
{ text: `- Venerable Bharadvāja, what is the cause, what is the condition why these young bhikkhus, in their prime, with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth, in the spring of life, do not indulge in sensual desires, but live the holy life completely pure for life, and live the full time perfectly?" - "Great King, the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has said: 'Come, bhikkhus, toward those who are only mothers, establish the mind of a mother. Toward those who are only sisters, establish the mind of a sister. Toward those who are only daughters, establish the mind of a daughter.' Great King, this is the cause, this is the condition why these young bhikkhus... live the holy life completely pure for life, and live the full time perfectly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127" },
{ text: `- Householder, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment to them, his consciousness becomes dependent on that and clings to it. Householder, with clinging, that bhikkhu does not attain complete peace... Householder, there are tastes cognizable by the tongue... Householder, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment to them, his consciousness becomes dependent on that and clings to it. With clinging, householder, that bhikkhu does not attain Nibbāna. This, householder, is the cause, this is the condition why some beings here and now do not attain complete peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.124" },
{ text: `Householder, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them, his consciousness is not dependent on that and does not cling to it. Householder, without clinging, that bhikkhu attains complete peace... Householder, there are tastes... Householder, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind... If a bhikkhu does not delight in those mind-objects, does not praise them, and abides without attachment to them, his consciousness is not dependent on that and does not cling to it. Without clinging, householder, that bhikkhu attains Nibbāna. This, householder, is the cause, this is the condition why some beings here and now attain complete peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.124" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the jackal saw the tortoise from afar, went to it, stood nearby, and thought: 'Whenever this tortoise extends any of its limbs or its neck as the fifth, right then I will grab it, break it, and eat it.' But, bhikkhus, because the tortoise did not extend any limb or its neck as the fifth, the jackal, frustrated, left without getting an opportunity. So too, bhikkhus, Māra constantly and uninterruptedly stands watching for you, thinking: 'Perhaps I will get an opportunity through the eye... through the tongue... or through the mind.' Therefore, bhikkhus, live guarding the sense faculties. When seeing a form with the eye, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, restrain that cause, guard the eye faculty, practice the restraint of the eye faculty. When hearing a sound with the ear... smelling an odor with the nose... tasting a taste with the tongue... feeling a touch with the body... cognizing a mind-object with the mind, do not grasp the general sign, do not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, restrain that cause, guard the mind faculty, practice the restraint of the mind faculty. Bhikkhus, when you live guarding the sense faculties, Māra will become frustrated with you and leave, without getting an opportunity, like the jackal with the tortoise.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.240", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.240" },
{ text: `- Greed, Venerable Bharadvāja, is the mind. Sometimes toward those who are only mothers, greedy thoughts arise. Toward those who are only sisters, greedy thoughts arise. Toward those who are only daughters, greedy thoughts arise. Bharadvāja, there is another cause, another condition why these young bhikkhus... perfectly?" - "Great King, the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has said: 'Come, bhikkhus, contemplate this very body from the soles of the feet upwards and from the hair of the head downwards, enclosed by skin and full of various impurities. In this body, there are head hairs, body hairs, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, stomach, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, mucus, synovial fluid, urine.' Great King, this is the cause, this is the condition why these young bhikkhus... live the holy life completely pure for life, and live the full time perfectly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127" },
{ text: `- Wonderful, Venerable Bharadvāja! Marvelous, Venerable Bharadvāja! This is a good saying of the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. This very cause, Venerable Bharadvāja, this very condition, why these young bhikkhus... do not indulge in sensual desires, but live the holy life completely pure for life, and live the full time perfectly. I too, Venerable Bharadvāja, whenever I enter the inner palace with body unguarded, speech unguarded, mind unguarded, mindfulness unestablished, faculties unrestrained — at that time, greedy thoughts conquer me. But, Venerable Bharadvāja, whenever I enter the inner palace with body guarded, speech guarded, mind guarded, mindfulness established, faculties restrained — at that time, greedy thoughts do not conquer me.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127" },
{ text: `The ancients of old,<br>Supreme in virtue,<br>The brahmins,<br>Remembered the ancient rules.<br>Faculties guarded,<br>Skilfully restrained,<br>They subdued and ended<br>All anger and rage.<br><br>They delighted in the Dhamma,<br>They delighted in jhāna,<br>They were brahmins,<br>Remembering the ancient rules.<br>But those who hide from this rule,<br>Only babble recitations,<br>Infatuated with caste,<br>They walk haltingly.<br><br>Overcome by anger,<br>Using various clubs,<br>They fall into danger,<br>Among the greedy, the noble,<br>Empty are their vows,<br>When faculties are unrestrained,<br>Like one who gains wealth<br>In a dream.<br><br>Not eating, determined to fast,<br>Sleeping on the bare ground,<br>Rising early, bathing away sins,<br>Reciting the three Vedas,<br>Wearing rough animal hides,<br>Twisted locks, body smeared with mud,<br>Reciting spells,<br>Clinging to rites and rituals, austerities.<br><br>Deceit and fraud,<br>Using clubs,<br>Using water for bathing,<br>Using water for rinsing the mouth,<br>These are the signs<br>Of the brahmin class,<br>They do and perform them,<br>Hoping for petty gains.<br><br>One-pointed, well concentrated,<br>Pure, without defilement,<br>Gentle toward all beings,<br>That is the supreme path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.132" },
{ text: `- Venerable Kaccāna speaks about guarding the faculties. To what extent, Venerable Kaccāna, is there guarding of the faculties?" - "Here, brahmin, when a person sees a form with the eye, his mind inclines toward agreeable forms and recoils from disagreeable forms; he lives with mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not completely abandoned without remainder. ... when he hears a sound with the ear ... smells an odor with the nose ... tastes a taste with the tongue ... feels a touch with the body ... when he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, his mind inclines toward agreeable mind-objects and recoils from disagreeable mind-objects; he lives with mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not completely abandoned without remainder. Thus, brahmin, is non-guarding of the faculties.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.132" },
{ text: `- It is wonderful, Venerable Kaccāna, it is marvelous, Venerable Kaccāna, how Venerable Kaccāna has defined non-guarding of the faculties. Guarding of the faculties, guarding of the faculties, Venerable Kaccāna has said. To what extent, Venerable Kaccāna, is there guarding of the faculties?" - "Here, brahmin, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, his mind does not incline toward agreeable forms nor recoil from disagreeable forms; he lives with mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. ... when he hears a sound ... smells an odor ... tastes a taste ... feels a touch ... when he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, his mind does not incline toward agreeable mind-objects nor recoil from disagreeable mind-objects; he lives with mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. Thus, brahmin, is guarding of the faculties.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.132" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are agreeable and disagreeable. Though they touch the mind again and again, they do not overpower the mind and remain. Because the mind is not overpowered, energy and diligence arise, without laziness; mindfulness is established, without loss; the body becomes tranquil, without fever; the mind becomes concentrated and unified. Bhikkhus, seeing this fruit of heedfulness for those bhikkhus, I declare that one must strive heedfully regarding the six sense-spheres. Bhikkhus, there are sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... tastes cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body ... Bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are agreeable and disagreeable. Though they touch the mind again and again, they do not overpower the mind and remain. Because the mind is not overpowered, energy and diligence arise... the mind becomes concentrated and unified. Bhikkhus, seeing this fruit of heedfulness for those bhikkhus, I declare that one must strive heedfully regarding the six sense-spheres.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.134", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.134" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I have seen a hell called the six-sense-sphere hell. There, whatever form the eye sees — it sees a form that is not desirable, not lovely, not agreeable; whatever sound the ear hears ... whatever odor the nose smells ... whatever taste the tongue tastes ... whatever tangible the body feels ... whatever mind-object the mind cognizes — it cognizes a mind-object that is not desirable, not lovely, not agreeable. Bhikkhus, you have gained a gain. Bhikkhus, you have gained a good gain. You have obtained the opportunity to live the holy life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.135", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.135" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I have seen a heaven called the six-sense-sphere heaven. There, whatever form the eye sees — it sees a form that is desirable, lovely, agreeable; whatever sound the ear hears ... whatever odor the nose smells ... whatever taste the tongue tastes ... whatever tangible the body feels ... whatever mind-object the mind cognizes — it cognizes a mind-object that is desirable, lovely, agreeable. Bhikkhus, you have gained a gain. Bhikkhus, you have gained a good gain. You have obtained the opportunity to live the holy life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.135", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.135" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, devas and humans delight in form, are excited by form. When form changes, fades away, and ceases, bhikkhus, devas and humans live in suffering. They delight in sound ... in odor ... in taste ... in touch ... Bhikkhus, devas and humans delight in mind-objects, are excited by mind-objects. When mind-objects change, fade away, and cease, bhikkhus, devas and humans live in suffering. Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, having truly understood the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape regarding form, does not delight in form, does not enjoy form, is not excited by form. When form changes, fades away, and ceases, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata lives in happiness. He does not delight in sound ... in odor ... in taste ... in touch ... Having truly understood the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape regarding mind-objects, the Tathāgata does not delight in mind-objects, does not enjoy them, is not excited by them. When mind-objects change, fade away, and cease, the Tathāgata lives in happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136" },
{ text: `Form, sound, odor, taste, touch,<br>And all mind-objects,<br>Desirable, lovely, agreeable —<br>Thus they are called.<br><br>Devas and humans<br>Consider them delightful.<br>Where they cease,<br>Devas and humans see suffering.<br><br>The noble one sees happiness<br>When identity view ceases.<br>The noble one sees the opposite<br>Of all the world's views.<br><br>What people call happiness,<br>The noble one calls suffering.<br>What people call suffering,<br>The noble one knows as happiness.<br><br>Seeing the Dhamma hard to discern,<br>The ignorant are confused.<br>Darkness for the ignorant,<br>Blindness for those who do not see.<br><br>The good person with open eyes,<br>Sees clearly the light,<br>Lives near, knows clearly,<br>Skilled in the great Dhamma.<br><br>Overcome by the thirst for becoming,<br>Swept away by the stream of existence,<br>Controlled by Māra,<br>They do not awaken to this Dhamma.<br><br>Apart from the noble ones, no one<br>Awakens to this path,<br>The path to Nibbāna,<br>With right knowledge, free from taints.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, sees things as they actually are. And what does he see as they actually are? He sees the eye as actually impermanent. He sees forms as actually impermanent. He sees eye-consciousness as actually impermanent. He sees eye-contact as actually impermanent. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he sees that feeling as actually impermanent. The ear ... The nose ... The tongue ... The body ... He sees the mind as actually impermanent. He sees mind-objects as actually impermanent. He sees mind-consciousness as actually impermanent. He sees mind-contact as actually impermanent. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact ... he sees that feeling as actually impermanent. Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, sees things as they actually are.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.160", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.160" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. This, bhikkhus, is not called the ocean in the Noble One's Discipline. Here, this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, for the most part sink into them, become tangled like a ball of thread, covered like a wound, become like a grass rope, unable to cross the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra! Bhikkhus, there are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... Bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. This, bhikkhus, is not called the ocean in the Noble One's Discipline. Here, this world ... for the most part sink into them, become tangled like a ball of thread, covered like a wound, become like a grass rope, unable to cross the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.229", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.229" },
{ text: `Like a tortoise drawing its limbs<br>Into its own shell,<br>So too, a bhikkhu,<br>Gathering all his thoughts,<br>Not dependent on anyone,<br>Not harming anyone,<br>Fully at peace,<br>Criticizing no one.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.240", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.240" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do you see this great log floating down the Ganges river?" — "Yes, Venerable Sir." — "Bhikkhus, if that log does not run against the near shore, does not run against the far shore, does not sink in the middle, does not get stranded on a high bank, is not taken by humans, is not taken by non-humans, is not caught in a whirlpool, is not rotten inside — then, bhikkhus, that log will drift towards the ocean, flow towards the ocean, incline towards the ocean. Why is that? Because the Ganges river drifts towards the ocean, flows towards the ocean, inclines towards the ocean. So too, bhikkhus, if you do not run against the near shore, do not run against the far shore, do not sink in the middle, do not get stranded on a high bank, are not taken by humans, are not taken by non-humans, are not caught in a whirlpool, are not rotten inside — then, bhikkhus, you will drift towards Nibbāna, flow towards Nibbāna, incline towards Nibbāna. Why is that? Because right view drifts towards Nibbāna, flows towards Nibbāna, inclines towards Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.241", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.241" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, what is the near shore? What is the far shore? What is sinking in the middle? What is getting stranded on a high bank? What is being taken by humans? What is being taken by non-humans? What is being caught in a whirlpool? What is being rotten inside?" - "The near shore, bhikkhu, is a synonym for these six internal bases. The far shore, bhikkhu, is a synonym for the six external bases. Sinking in the middle, bhikkhu, is a synonym for delight and greed. Getting stranded on a high bank, bhikkhu, is a synonym for conceit. And, bhikkhu, what is being taken by humans? Here, a bhikkhu lives too intimately with laypeople, shares their happiness and their suffering, is happy when they are happy, suffers when they suffer, and involves himself in the tasks that arise for them. This, bhikkhu, is called being taken by humans. And, bhikkhu, what is being taken by non-humans? Here, a bhikkhu lives the holy life with the wish to be reborn in the company of a certain class of devas, thinking: 'By this virtue, this vow, this austerity, this holy life, I will become a deva or one of the devas.' This, bhikkhu, is called being taken by non-humans. Being caught in a whirlpool, bhikkhu, is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure. And, bhikkhu, what is being rotten inside? Here, bhikkhu, a person is evil, of bad character, impure, of suspicious behavior, secretive in his actions, not a samaṇa though pretending to be one, not a celibate though pretending to be one, inwardly rotten, full of lust, a heap of filth. This, bhikkhu, is called being rotten inside.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.241", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.241" },
{ text: `- And, friends, what is being defiled by sensual taints? Here, friends, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he inclines toward agreeable forms, recoils from disagreeable forms, lives with mindfulness of the body unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not completely abandoned without remainder. ... When he tastes a taste with the tongue ... When he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he inclines toward agreeable mind-objects, recoils from disagreeable mind-objects, lives with mindfulness of the body unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not completely abandoned without remainder. Friends, this is called a bhikkhu who is defiled by sensual taints regarding forms cognizable by the eye ... regarding tastes cognizable by the tongue ... regarding mind-objects cognizable by the mind. A bhikkhu living thus, friends, if Māra should approach him through the eye, Māra gets an opportunity, Māra gets an object. ... If Māra should approach him through the tongue, Māra gets an opportunity, Māra gets an object. ... If Māra should approach him through the mind, Māra gets an opportunity, Māra gets an object.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.243" },
{ text: `And, friends, what is being undefiled by sensual taints? Here, friends, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he does not incline toward agreeable forms nor recoil from disagreeable forms; he lives with mindfulness of the body established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. ... When he tastes a taste with the tongue ... When he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he does not incline toward agreeable mind-objects nor recoil from disagreeable mind-objects; he lives with mindfulness of the body established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. Friends, this is called a bhikkhu who is undefiled by sensual taints regarding forms cognizable by the eye ... regarding tastes ... regarding mind-objects ... A bhikkhu living thus, friends, if Māra should approach him through the eye, Māra does not get an opportunity, Māra does not get an object. ... If Māra should approach him through the tongue, Māra does not get an opportunity, Māra does not get an object. ... If Māra should approach him through the mind, Māra does not get an opportunity, Māra does not get an object.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.243" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu see sensual pleasures? When sensual pleasures are seen, then desire, sensual craving, sensual infatuation, sensual fever regarding sensual pleasures have no underlying tendency. Just as, bhikkhus, a pit of glowing embers deeper than a man's height, filled with glowing embers, flameless and smokeless. Then a person comes who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, loathes suffering. Two strong men grab him by both arms and drag him towards the pit of embers. That person twists his body this way and that. Why is that? He knows: 'I will fall into this pit of embers. On that account, I will meet death or deadly pain.' So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu sees sensual pleasures as a pit of embers. One who sees sensual pleasures thus has no underlying tendency of desire, sensual craving, sensual infatuation, sensual fever regarding sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244" },
{ text: `How, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu's practice and dwelling known? Because by such a practice, covetousness, grief, and evil, unwholesome states have no footing. Just as, bhikkhus, a person enters a forest full of thorns; before him are thorns, behind him are thorns, to the north, south, above, below are thorns. Wherever he goes forward or backward, he thinks: 'May I not get stuck on a thorn.' So too, bhikkhus, whatever is desirable, lovely — that is called a thorn in the Noble One's Discipline.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is non-restraint? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he inclines toward agreeable forms, recoils from disagreeable forms, lives with mindfulness of the body unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not truly understand the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not completely abandoned without remainder. Thus, bhikkhus, is non-restraint.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is restraint? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he does not incline toward agreeable forms nor recoil from disagreeable forms; he lives with mindfulness of the body established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. ... When he tastes a taste with the tongue ... When he cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he does not incline toward agreeable mind-objects nor recoil from disagreeable mind-objects; he lives with mindfulness of the body established, with an immeasurable mind. He truly understands the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, the evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are completely abandoned without remainder. Thus, bhikkhus, is restraint.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhu, a king's frontier city is built with strong fortifications, with strong walls and watchtowers, and has six gates. There is a gatekeeper there, wise, experienced, and intelligent, who keeps out strangers and lets in acquaintances. From the east, two swift messengers come and ask the gatekeeper: 'Friend, where is the lord of this city?' The gatekeeper says: 'Venerable sirs, he is sitting in the middle of the crossroads.' Those two swift messengers then deliver their truthful message to the lord of the city, and then continue on the path they came. From the west... from the north, two swift messengers come and ask the gatekeeper: 'Friend, where is the lord of this city?' The gatekeeper says: 'Venerable sirs, he is sitting in the middle of the crossroads.' Then the two swift messengers deliver their truthful message to the lord of the city, and then continue on the path they came.<br><br>Bhikkhu, I give this simile to convey the meaning, and this is the meaning: The city, bhikkhu, is a synonym for this body composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wear and tear, breaking up, and destruction. The six gates, bhikkhu, are a synonym for the six internal bases. The gatekeeper, bhikkhu, is a synonym for mindfulness. The two swift messengers, bhikkhu, are a synonym for serenity and insight. The lord of the city is a synonym for consciousness. The middle of the crossroads is a synonym for the four great elements: the earth element, the water element, the fire element, and the air element. The truthful message, bhikkhu, is a synonym for Nibbāna. The path they came is a synonym for the Noble Eightfold Path, that is, right view ... right concentration.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.245", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.245" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a king or a king's minister who had never heard the sound of a lute before, upon hearing it, says: 'Friend, what is that sound — so lovely, so delightful, so intoxicating, so enthralling, so enticing?' They say to him: 'Sire, that is a lute, with such a lovely, intoxicating, delightful, enthralling, enticing sound.' He says: 'Go and bring that lute to me.' They bring him the lute and say: 'Sire, this is the lute, with such a lovely, delightful, intoxicating, enthralling, enticing sound.' He then says: 'Enough, this lute. Bring me the sound.' They say to him: 'Sire, this thing called a lute consists of many components, a great many components. Because of these many components, it produces sound. Dependent on the body, the skin, the neck, the head, the strings, the bow, and the appropriate effort of a person. Thus, sire, this thing called a lute consists of many components, a great many components. Because of these many components, it produces sound.' Then that king breaks the lute into ten pieces, a hundred pieces; having broken it, he splits it into small pieces; having split it, he burns it with fire; having burned it, he piles up the ashes; having piled up the ashes, he winnows them in a strong wind or lets them be carried away by a swift stream. Then he says: 'Wretched is this thing called a lute, whatever a lute may be. Here, people are heedless and led astray.'<br><br>So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu investigates form up to the province of form, he investigates feeling ... perception ... formations ... he investigates consciousness up to the province of consciousness. In all that investigation, there is no 'I,' no 'mine,' no 'I am.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.246", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.246" },


{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person catches six animals of different domains and different feeding grounds, and ties them with a strong rope. Having caught a snake, he ties it with a strong rope. Having caught a crocodile, he ties it with a strong rope. Having caught a bird, he ties it with a strong rope. Having caught a dog, he ties it with a strong rope. Having caught a jackal, he ties it with a strong rope. Having caught a monkey, he ties it with a strong rope. Having tied them all with strong ropes, he ties a knot in the middle and lets them go. Bhikkhus, those six animals of different domains and different feeding grounds will each pull towards their own feeding ground and domain. The snake pulls, thinking: 'I will go into an anthill.' The crocodile pulls, thinking: 'I will go into the water.' The bird pulls, thinking: 'I will fly into the sky.' The dog pulls, thinking: 'I will go into the village.' The jackal pulls, thinking: 'I will go into the charnel ground.' The monkey pulls, thinking: 'I will go into the forest.' Bhikkhus, when these six animals become exhausted, then whichever animal is strongest among them, they will follow it, obey it, submit to it. So too, bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu whose mindfulness of the body is not developed, not cultivated, the eye will pull him towards agreeable forms and repel him from disagreeable forms. The mind will pull him towards agreeable mind-objects and repel him from disagreeable mind-objects.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.247", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.247" },
{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, you should understand: 'I am,' bhikkhus, is a conceit. 'This is me' is a conceit. 'I shall be' is a conceit. 'I shall not be' is a conceit. 'I shall have form' is a conceit. 'I shall be formless' is a conceit. 'I shall have perception' is a conceit. 'I shall be without perception' is a conceit. 'I shall be neither percipient nor non-percipient' is a conceit. Conceit, bhikkhus, is a disease. Conceit is a boil. Conceit is a dart. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will live with a mind that has abandoned conceit.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.248", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.248" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. These, bhikkhus, are the three feelings.<br><br>The Buddha's disciple,<br>Concentrated, clearly comprehending, mindful,<br>Clearly understands feelings,<br>And the escape from feelings.<br><br>Here, they cease,<br>And the path to cessation,<br>The bhikkhu has ended feelings,<br>Without craving, at peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. These, bhikkhus, are the three feelings.<br><br>Pleasant feeling or painful feeling,<br>And neither-painful-nor-pleasant,<br>Internal feeling and external feeling,<br>Whatever feeling there is.<br><br>Knowing: 'This is suffering,'<br>Deceptive and subject to change,<br>Seeing contact, contact's cessation,<br>Here, one lives with dispassion.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.2" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Bhikkhus, the underlying tendency to lust for pleasant feeling should be abandoned. The underlying tendency to aversion for painful feeling should be abandoned. The underlying tendency to ignorance for neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling should be abandoned. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu has abandoned the underlying tendency to lust for pleasant feeling, abandoned the underlying tendency to aversion for painful feeling, abandoned the underlying tendency to ignorance for neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has abandoned the underlying tendencies, who has right view, who has cut off craving, who has destroyed the fetters. By rightly breaking through conceit, he has made an end of suffering.<br><br>If one feels a pleasant feeling,<br>But does not understand that feeling,<br>That is called the underlying tendency to lust,<br>Not seeing the escape.<br><br>If one feels a painful feeling,<br>But does not understand that feeling,<br>That is called the underlying tendency to aversion,<br>Not seeing the escape.<br><br>Regarding neither-painful-nor-pleasant,<br>The One of Great Wisdom has taught,<br>If one delights in that feeling,<br>One is not free from suffering.<br><br>A bhikkhu who is ardent,<br>Clearly comprehending, not deluded,<br>Regarding all feelings,<br>The wise one fully understands.<br><br>He who fully understands feelings,<br>In this very life is taint-free,<br>At death, the Dhamma-abider,<br>The great sage, beyond measure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.3" },
{ text: `An unlearned ordinary person, when experiencing a painful bodily feeling, sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes confused. Bhikkhus, this is called an unlearned ordinary person who does not stand up on the precipice, who has not reached a foothold. But a learned noble disciple, bhikkhus, when experiencing a painful bodily feeling, does not sorrow, does not grieve, does not lament, does not beat his breast, does not become confused. Bhikkhus, this is called a learned noble disciple who has stood up on the precipice, who has reached a foothold.<br><br>Who cannot endure<br>The arisen painful feelings,<br>Bodily pain that harms life,<br>When touched, he trembles.<br>One who wails and cries,<br>Weak, lacking courage,<br>Does not stand on the deep precipice,<br>Has not reached a foothold.<br><br>Who can endure<br>The arisen painful feelings,<br>Bodily pain that harms life,<br>When touched, does not tremble,<br>That one has crossed the deep precipice,<br>Has reached a foothold.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.4" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Bhikkhus, a pleasant feeling should be seen as suffering. A painful feeling should be seen as a dart. A neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling should be seen as impermanent. When, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu sees a pleasant feeling as suffering, sees a painful feeling as a dart, sees a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling as impermanent, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has right view, who has cut off craving, who has destroyed the fetters. By rightly breaking through conceit, he has made an end of suffering.<br><br>Who sees pleasure as suffering,<br>Sees pain as a dart,<br>Regarding neither-painful-nor-pleasant,<br>Sees that feeling as impermanent,<br>That bhikkhu has right view,<br>He fully understands feelings.<br><br>He who fully understands feelings,<br>In this very life is taint-free,<br>At death, the Dhamma-abider,<br>The great sage, beyond measure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person is shot with a dart, and then they shoot him with a second dart. Thus, bhikkhus, that person experiences the feeling of both darts. So too, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person, when touched by a painful feeling, sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes confused. That person experiences two feelings: a bodily feeling and a mental feeling. Touched by that painful feeling, he feels aversion. Because he feels aversion towards that painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion towards painful feeling persists. Touched by that painful feeling, he delights in sensual pleasure. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, the unlearned ordinary person does not know any escape from painful feeling other than sensual pleasure. Delighting in that sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency to lust for pleasant feeling persists. He does not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of those feelings. Because he does not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of those feelings, the underlying tendency to ignorance for neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling persists. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. Bhikkhus, this is called an unlearned ordinary person who is bound by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is bound by suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.6" },
{ text: `The learned wise one,<br>Is not overcome by pleasure and pain,<br>Between the wise and the ordinary,<br>The difference is very great.<br><br>The learned one, investigating the Dhamma,<br>Sees this world and the next,<br>Desirable things do not disturb his mind,<br>Without attraction, without aversion.<br><br>Favorable or adverse,<br>Scattered, ceased, no more,<br>He knows the path,<br>The path without dust, without sorrow,<br>With right knowledge, ending rebirth,<br>He has reached the shore of awakening.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.6" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person is shot with a dart, and they do not shoot him with a second dart. Thus, bhikkhus, that person experiences the feeling of only one dart. So too, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple, when touched by a painful feeling, does not sorrow, does not grieve, does not lament, does not beat his breast, does not become confused. He experiences only one feeling: a bodily feeling, not a mental feeling. He does not feel aversion towards that painful feeling. Because he does not feel aversion, the underlying tendency to aversion towards painful feeling does not persist. Touched by that painful feeling, he does not delight in sensual pleasure. Why is that? Because the learned noble disciple knows another escape from painful feeling besides sensual pleasure. Because he does not delight in sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency to lust for pleasant feeling does not persist. He truly understands the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of those feelings. Because he truly understands the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of those feelings, the underlying tendency to ignorance for neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling does not persist. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. Bhikkhus, this is called a bhikkhu who is unbound by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is unbound by suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.6" },
{ text: `If he feels a pleasant feeling, he understands: 'That feeling is impermanent.' He understands: 'I am not attached to that feeling.' He understands: 'I do not delight in that feeling.' If he feels a painful feeling... If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands: 'That feeling is impermanent.' He understands: 'I am not attached to that feeling.' He understands: 'I do not delight in that feeling.' If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is unbound. When he feels a feeling ending with the body's endurance, he understands: 'I am feeling a feeling ending with the body's endurance.' When he feels a feeling ending with life's endurance, he understands: 'I am feeling a feeling ending with life's endurance.' He understands: 'With the breakup of the body after death, here, a feeling that is not delighted in will become calm.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.7" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu lives mindfully, clearly comprehending, heedful, ardent, and resolute, and a painful feeling arises, he understands: 'This painful feeling has arisen in me. That painful feeling has a condition, not without a condition. Conditioned by what? Conditioned by this very body. But this body is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. When that which is the condition is impermanent, conditioned, and dependently arisen, how could the painful feeling that has arisen be permanent?' He abides contemplating impermanence in the body and in the painful feeling. He abides contemplating vanishing. He abides contemplating dispassion. He abides contemplating cessation. He abides contemplating relinquishment. Because he abides contemplating impermanence, vanishing, dispassion, cessation, relinquishment regarding the body and the painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion towards the body and painful feeling is abandoned.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.7" },
{ text: `There are two extremes that one who has gone forth should not practice: indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is low, vulgar, worldly, unworthy, and unbeneficial; and self-mortification, which is painful, unworthy, and unbeneficial. Avoiding both extremes, the Middle Way has been realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna.<br><br>What, headman, is that Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, headman, is the Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 42.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn42.12" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the unconditioned? Bhikkhus, the destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion. Bhikkhus, this is called the unconditioned. And, bhikkhus, what is the path leading to the unconditioned? Mindfulness of the body, bhikkhus, is the path leading to the unconditioned. Thus, bhikkhus, I have taught the unconditioned, I have taught the path leading to the unconditioned. Bhikkhus, whatever should be done by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, seeking their welfare, out of compassion, that I have done for you. Bhikkhus, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Practice jhāna, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 43.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn43.1" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I will teach you the unconditioned and the path leading to the unconditioned. Listen. And what, bhikkhus, is the unconditioned? Bhikkhus, the destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion. Bhikkhus, this is called the unconditioned. And what, bhikkhus, is the path leading to the unconditioned? Serenity and insight, bhikkhus, are the path leading to the unconditioned.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 43.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn43.2" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I will teach you the going to the far shore and the path leading to the far shore. Listen. Bhikkhus, what is the going to the far shore? Bhikkhus, the destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion — this, bhikkhus, is called the going to the far shore. And what, bhikkhus, is the path leading to the far shore? Mindfulness of the body, bhikkhus, is the path leading to the far shore. Thus, bhikkhus, I have taught the going to the far shore, I have taught the path leading to the far shore. Bhikkhus, whatever should be done by a teacher out of compassion for his disciples, seeking their welfare, out of compassion, that I have done for you. Bhikkhus, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Practice jhāna, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 43.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn43.44" },
{ text: `- Friend, for one who has not abandoned lust for form, not abandoned desire, not abandoned love, not abandoned thirst, not abandoned passion, not abandoned craving, that person may have the view: 'The Tathāgata exists after death. Or the Tathāgata does not exist after death. Or the Tathāgata both exists and does not exist after death. Or the Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death.' Friend, for one who has abandoned lust for form, abandoned desire, abandoned love, abandoned thirst, abandoned passion, abandoned craving, that person will not have the view: 'The Tathāgata exists after death... Or the Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death.' Friend, this is the cause, this is the condition, this is the reason why the Blessed One does not answer that question.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 44.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn44.5" },
{ text: `- Venerable Kotthika, does the Tathāgata exist after death?... Does the Tathāgata neither exist nor does not exist after death?... When asked thus, the venerable one answers: 'The Blessed One does not answer: "The Tathāgata exists after death... The Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death."' For what reason, venerable sir, for what condition does the Blessed One not answer that question?" - "Friend, for one who has lust for form, who delights in form, who rejoices in form, who does not truly know and see the cessation of form, that person may have the view: 'The Tathāgata exists after death... The Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death.' Friend, for one who has lust for feeling... for perception... for formations... Friend, for one who has lust for consciousness, who delights in consciousness, who rejoices in consciousness, who does not truly know and see the cessation of consciousness, that person may have the view: 'The Tathāgata exists after death... The Tathāgata neither exists nor does not exist after death.' Friend, this is the cause, this is the condition, this is the reason why the Blessed One does not answer that question.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 44.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn44.6" },
{ text: `Master Gotama, I have doubt and uncertainty: 'How should one understand the Dhamma of Samaṇa Gotama?' - "Vaccha, enough of your doubt. Enough of your uncertainty. It is because you doubt that uncertainty has arisen. I declare the coming-to-be, Vaccha, for one who has clinging, not for one without clinging. Just as, Vaccha, a fire burns when it has fuel, not without fuel. So too, Vaccha, I declare the coming-to-be for one who has clinging, not for one without clinging." - "Master Gotama, when a flame is blown far away by the wind, what does Master Gotama declare as its fuel?" - "Vaccha, when a flame is blown far away by the wind, I say that the wind itself is its fuel. At that time, Vaccha, the wind is the fuel (upādāna)." - "Master Gotama, when a being abandons this body and is reborn in another body, what does Master Gotama declare as the fuel for that body?" - "Vaccha, when a being abandons this body and is reborn in another body, Vaccha, I declare that at that time craving itself is the fuel (upādāna).`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 44.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn44.9" },
{ text: `- When ignorance is the forerunner, bhikkhus, leading to the attainment of unwholesome states, then lack of conscience and lack of fear of wrongdoing follow. For a person overcome by ignorance, lacking wisdom, bhikkhus, wrong view arises. For one with wrong view, wrong intention arises. For one with wrong intention, wrong speech arises. For one with wrong speech, wrong action arises. For one with wrong action, wrong livelihood arises. For one with wrong livelihood, wrong effort arises. For one with wrong effort, wrong mindfulness arises. For one with wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration arises.<br><br>When knowledge is the forerunner, bhikkhus, leading to the attainment of wholesome states, then conscience and fear of wrongdoing follow. For a person guided by knowledge, endowed with wisdom, bhikkhus, right view arises. For one with right view, right intention arises. For one with right intention, right speech arises. For one with right speech, right action arises. For one with right action, right livelihood arises. For one with right livelihood, right effort arises. For one with right effort, right mindfulness arises. For one with right mindfulness, right concentration arises.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.1" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, this half of the holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association." - "Do not say that, Ānanda! Do not say that, Ānanda! This entire holy life, Ānanda, is good friendship, good companionship, good association. For a bhikkhu with good friends, good companions, good associates, Ānanda, it can be expected that the Noble Eightfold Path will be developed, that the Noble Eightfold Path will be cultivated. Ānanda, by this method you should understand how the entire holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association. Because I have good friends, Ānanda, beings subject to birth are freed from birth; beings subject to aging are freed from aging; beings subject to death are freed from death; beings subject to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are freed from sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. By this method, Ānanda, you should understand how the entire holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.2" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Sāriputta went to the Blessed One, paid homage, and sat down to one side. Sitting to one side, the Venerable Sāriputta said: 'Venerable Sir, this entire holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association.' - 'Good, good, Sāriputta! This entire holy life is good friendship, good companionship, good association. Sāriputta, for a bhikkhu with good friends, good companions, good associates, it can be expected that the Noble Eightfold Path will be developed, that the Noble Eightfold Path will be cultivated.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.3" },
{ text: `One who has faith and wisdom,<br>Always conjoined together,<br>With conscience as the pole,<br>With mind as the yoke.<br>Mindfulness is the charioteer,<br>Knowing how to guard and protect,<br>The chariot has virtue<br>As its requisite.<br>Jhāna is the axle,<br>Energy is the wheel,<br>Equanimity is the constant,<br>Non-craving is the seat.<br>Non-hatred and non-harming,<br>Seclusion is the weapon,<br>Patience is the armor,<br>Security from bondage<br>Is the goal attained,<br>The chariot is driven.<br>This Dhamma is self-made,<br>Becoming one's own.<br>It is the supreme chariot,<br>Unsurpassed, incomparable.<br>Sitting on that chariot,<br>The wise one leaves the world,<br>Surely, not going astray,<br>They attain victory.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.4" },
{ text: `'The holy life, the holy life,' Venerable Sir, is said. What is the holy life, Venerable Sir? What is the ultimate goal of the holy life?" - "Bhikkhu, this Noble Eightfold Path itself is the holy life, that is, right view ... right concentration. Bhikkhu, the destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion — this is the ultimate goal of the holy life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.6" },
{ text: `'The removal of greed, the removal of hatred, the removal of delusion,' Venerable Sir, is thus said. What is the synonym for the removal of greed, the removal of hatred, the removal of delusion?" - "It is a synonym for the Nibbāna element, bhikkhu, and is also called the destruction of the taints." When this was said, that bhikkhu said: "'The Deathless, the Deathless,' Venerable Sir, is thus said. What is the Deathless, Venerable Sir? What is the path leading to the Deathless?" - "The destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion, bhikkhu, is called the Deathless. This Noble Eightfold Path is the path leading to the Deathless, that is, right view ... right concentration.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.7" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is right view? Bhikkhus, knowledge of suffering, knowledge of the origin of suffering, knowledge of the cessation of suffering, knowledge of the path leading to the cessation of suffering. Bhikkhus, this is called right view. And, bhikkhus, what is right intention? Bhikkhus, intention of renunciation, intention of non-ill-will, intention of harmlessness. Bhikkhus, this is called right intention. And, bhikkhus, what is right speech? Bhikkhus, abstaining from false speech, abstaining from divisive speech, abstaining from harsh speech, abstaining from idle chatter. Bhikkhus, this is called right speech. And, bhikkhus, what is right action? Bhikkhus, abstaining from killing living beings, abstaining from taking what is not given, abstaining from sexual misconduct. Bhikkhus, this is called right action. And, bhikkhus, what is right livelihood? Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple, having abandoned wrong livelihood, earns his living by right livelihood. Bhikkhus, this is called right livelihood.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is right effort? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu generates desire for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the arising of unarisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the maintenance, non-decline, increase, expansion, cultivation, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. Bhikkhus, this is called right effort.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is right mindfulness? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, for the purpose of removing covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating feelings as feelings, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, for the purpose of removing covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating mind as mind, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, for the purpose of removing covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, for the purpose of removing covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Bhikkhus, this is called right mindfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is right concentration? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. With the stilling of initial and sustained thought, he enters and abides in the second jhāna, which has internal clarity and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of concentration. With the fading away of rapture, he dwells equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending, and experiences happiness with the body; he enters and abides in the third jhāna, of which the noble ones declare: 'Equanimous and mindful, one dwells happily.' With the abandoning of pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and grief, he enters and abides in the fourth jhāna, which is neither painful nor pleasant, with purity of mindfulness due to equanimity. Bhikkhus, this is called right concentration.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, just as a barley or wheat stalk placed wrongly, when pressed by hand or foot, cannot pierce the hand or foot, or draw blood — this is impossible. Why is that? Because the stalk is placed wrongly. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu whose view is placed wrongly, whose path of cultivation is placed wrongly, cannot pierce ignorance, arouse knowledge, or attain Nibbāna — this is impossible. Why is that? Because the view is placed wrongly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I wish to go into seclusion for half a month. No one should approach me except the one who brings almsfood." - "Yes, Venerable Sir." Those bhikkhus replied to the Blessed One. Thus no one approached the Blessed One except the one who brought almsfood. Then the Blessed One, after half a month, arose from seclusion and addressed the bhikkhus: "I have dwelt in the abiding that I dwelt in when I first attained perfect enlightenment, but I have only dwelt in part of it. Thus I have directly known feelings conditioned by wrong view, feelings conditioned by right view ... feelings conditioned by wrong concentration, feelings conditioned by right concentration, feelings conditioned by desire, feelings conditioned by thought, feelings conditioned by perception. When desire is not stilled, thought is not stilled, perception is not stilled — conditioned by that, feelings arise. And when desire is stilled, but thought is not yet stilled, perception is not yet stilled — conditioned by that, feelings arise. And when desire is stilled, thought is stilled, but perception is not yet stilled — conditioned by that, feelings arise. And when desire is stilled, thought is stilled, perception is stilled — conditioned by that, feelings arise. For one who has not yet attained, one must strive to attain. For one who has already attained, conditioned by that, feelings arise.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.11" },
{ text: `- There are these eight things, bhikkhus, that are pure, bright, without defilement, free from corruption, which, if not yet arisen, arise only when a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One appears. What eight? That is, right view ... right concentration. These eight things, bhikkhus, are pure, bright, without defilement, free from corruption, which, if not yet arisen, arise only when a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One appears.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.16" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, just as a pot without a stand is easy to tip over, but with a stand is hard to tip over. So too, bhikkhus, the mind without a stand is easy to tip over, but with a stand is hard to tip over. And what, bhikkhus, is the stand for the mind? It is this Noble Eightfold Path, that is, right view ... right concentration. This is called the stand for the mind. Bhikkhus, just as a pot without a stand is easy to tip over, but with a stand is hard to tip over. So too, bhikkhus, the mind without a stand is easy to tip over, but with a stand is hard to tip over.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.27" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings born of contact, with contact as their root, contact as their source, contact as their condition. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Just as, bhikkhus, when two sticks are rubbed together, brought into close contact, heat is generated and fire appears. When those two sticks are separated and the condition is cut off, the heat that arose from that condition ceases and is stilled. So too, bhikkhus, these three feelings are born of contact, with contact as their root, contact as their source, contact as their condition. In dependence on the corresponding contact, the corresponding feeling arises. With the cessation of the corresponding contact, the corresponding feeling ceases.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.10" },
{ text: `Bhikkhu, I say that these three feelings exist: pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. These three feelings have been spoken of by me. But, bhikkhu, I also say: 'Whatever is felt is included in suffering.' It is in reference to the impermanent nature of formations that this statement was made by me: 'Whatever is felt is included in suffering.' It is in reference to the nature of cessation, vanishing, dispassion, cessation, and change of formations that this statement was made by me: 'Whatever is felt is included in suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.11" },
{ text: `- Just as in the sky various winds blow. Winds blow from the east, from the west, from the north, from the south. Winds blow with dust, without dust. Cold winds blow, hot winds blow. Winds blow in small amounts, winds blow in large amounts. So too, bhikkhus, in this body various different feelings arise. Pleasant feelings arise. Painful feelings arise. Neither-painful-nor-pleasant feelings arise.<br><br>Just as in the sky,<br>Various winds blow,<br>From the east, from the west,<br>From the north, from the south.<br><br>Winds with dust, without dust,<br>Cold winds, hot winds,<br>Great winds, small winds,<br>Many kinds of winds blow.<br><br>So too, in this body,<br>Various feelings arise,<br>Pleasant feelings and painful feelings,<br>Neither-painful-nor-pleasant feelings.<br><br>When a bhikkhu is ardent,<br>Clearly comprehending, without attachment,<br>Therefore, the wise one,<br>Fully understands all feelings.<br><br>He who fully understands feelings,<br>In this very life is taint-free,<br>At death, the Dhamma-abider,<br>The great sage, beyond measure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.12" },
{ text: `- For what purpose, friend Sāriputta, is the holy life lived under Samaṇa Gotama?" - "Friend, the holy life is lived under the Blessed One for the purpose of fully understanding suffering." - "Is there a path, is there a way, friend, leading to the full understanding of suffering?" - "There is a path, there is a way, friend, leading to the full understanding of suffering." - "What, friend, is that path, that way?" - "It is this Noble Eightfold Path, friend, that is, right view ... right concentration. This, friend, is the path, this is the way leading to the full understanding of suffering." - "Excellent, friend, is that path, excellent is that way leading to the full understanding of suffering. It is enough, friend, to be heedful.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 38.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn38.4" },
{ text: `- Friend Sāriputta, in this Dhamma and Discipline, what is difficult to do?" - "Going forth, friend, is difficult to do in this Dhamma and Discipline." - "For one who has gone forth, friend, what is difficult to do?" - "For one who has gone forth, friend, delight is difficult to do." - "For one who delights, friend, what is difficult to do?" - "For one who delights, friend, the practice in accordance with the Dhamma is difficult to do." - "For one practicing in accordance with the Dhamma, friend, how long before one becomes an Arahant?" - "Not long, friend.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 38.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn38.16" },
{ text: `- So too, venerable sirs, the eye is not the fetter of forms, nor are forms the fetter of the eye. The desire and lust that arise dependent on both — that is the fetter there. The ear is not the fetter of sounds... The nose is not the fetter of odors... The tongue is not the fetter of tastes... The body is not the fetter of tangibles... The mind is not the fetter of mind-objects, nor are mind-objects the fetter of the mind. The desire and lust that arise dependent on both — that is the fetter there.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 41.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn41.1" },
{ text: `The part is purified,<br>The white-roofed shelter,<br>Having only one wheel,<br>The chariot runs continuously.<br>Behold the one who is coming,<br>Without offense,<br>Who has cut the stream,<br>No longer bound.<br><br>: 'The part is purified,' venerable sir, is a synonym for the precepts. 'The white-roofed shelter,' venerable sir, is a synonym for liberation. 'One wheel,' venerable sir, is a synonym for mindfulness. 'Runs continuously,' venerable sir, is a synonym for going forward and returning. 'The chariot,' venerable sir, is a synonym for this body composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to wear and tear, breaking up, and destruction. Greed, venerable sir, is an offense. Hatred is an offense. Delusion is an offense. For a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed, these have been abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, not subject to further arising, not able to arise in the future. Therefore, a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed is called one without offense. 'The one who is coming,' venerable sir, is a synonym for an Arahant. 'The stream,' venerable sir, is a synonym for craving. For a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed, that craving has been abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, not subject to further arising, not able to arise in the future. Therefore, a bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed is called one who has cut the stream.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 41.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn41.5" },
{ text: `- Just as, headman, a person throws a large stone into a deep lake. Then a great crowd of people assembles and gathers, praying, praising, circumambulating with joined palms, and says: 'Rise up, great stone! Float up, great stone! Come to the shore, great stone!' What do you think, headman? Would that great stone, because of that great crowd's prayers, praises, or circumambulation with joined palms, rise up, float up, or drift to the shore?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "So too, headman, a person who kills living beings, takes what is not given, engages in sexual misconduct, speaks falsely, speaks divisively, speaks harshly, speaks idly, is covetous, has ill-will, holds wrong view. Then a great crowd of people assembles and gathers, praying, praising, circumambulating with joined palms, and says: 'May this person, after death, with the breakup of the body, be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world!' But that person, after death, with the breakup of the body, is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 42.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn42.6" },
{ text: `Headman, the Sakyan samaṇas are not permitted to use gold and silver. The Sakyan samaṇas do not accept gold and silver. The Sakyan samaṇas do not receive gold and silver. The Sakyan samaṇas have abandoned gems and gold and silver. They have renounced gold and silver. For one who is permitted to use gold and silver, that person is also permitted to use the five strands of sensual pleasure. For one who is permitted to use the five strands of sensual pleasure, that person completely upholds what is not the samaṇa's practice, not the Sakyan's practice. Headman, I say this: Grass is to be sought by one who needs grass. Wood is to be sought by one who needs wood. A vehicle is to be sought by one who needs a vehicle. A person is to be sought by one who needs a person. But for no reason whatsoever, headman, do I say that gold and silver are to be accepted, are to be sought.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 42.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn42.10" },
{ text: `- What do you think, headman? If your son Ciravāsi were to be killed, captured, harmed, or criticized, would you experience sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair?" - "Venerable Sir, if my son Ciravāsi were to be killed, captured, harmed, criticized, or his life were to change, how could I not experience sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair?" - "By this method, headman, it should be understood: Whatever suffering arises, all of it has desire as its root, desire as its cause. Desire is the root of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 42.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn42.11" },
{ text: `Few are those among people<br>Who have reached the far shore.<br>The rest of the populace<br>Run back and forth on this shore.<br><br>Those who follow the teaching,<br>The Dhamma well proclaimed,<br>They will reach the far shore,<br>Crossing Māra's realm so hard to cross.<br><br>Having abandoned dark states,<br>The wise one cultivates bright states,<br>Leaving home for homelessness,<br>In seclusion, hard to delight in.<br><br>There, desiring delight,<br>Abandon all sensual desires,<br>The wise one purifies himself,<br>His mind of defilements.<br><br>Those who develop well,<br>Their minds in the enlightenment factors,<br>Abandoning all attachments,<br>Delighting in non-clinging,<br>With taints destroyed, radiant,<br>They attain Nibbāna in this very life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.34" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, just as the dawn is the forerunner and precursor of the rising of the sun, so too, bhikkhus, the forerunner and precursor of the arising of the Noble Eightfold Path is good friendship. Bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu with good friends, it can be expected that the Noble Eightfold Path will be developed, that the Noble Eightfold Path will be cultivated. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu with good friends develop the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops right view connected with seclusion, connected with dispassion, connected with cessation, maturing in relinquishment. He develops right intention ... right concentration connected with seclusion, connected with dispassion, connected with cessation, maturing in relinquishment. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with good friends develops the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivates the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.50-54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.50-54" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who possesses wise attention like this can expect that the Noble Eightfold Path will be developed, that the Noble Eightfold Path will be cultivated. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu who possesses wise attention develop the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops right view culminating in the removal of greed, culminating in the removal of hatred, culminating in the removal of delusion. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who possesses wise attention ... develops right concentration culminating in the removal of greed, culminating in the removal of hatred, culminating in the removal of delusion ... Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who possesses wise attention develops the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivates the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.62" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, whatever footprints of living beings that walk there are, all are contained within the elephant's footprint, because the elephant's footprint is called the supreme among all footprints in terms of size. So too, bhikkhus, whatever wholesome states there are, all have heedfulness as their root, all converge on heedfulness, heedfulness is called the supreme among wholesome states. For a heedful bhikkhu, bhikkhus, it can be expected that the Noble Eightfold Path will be developed, that the Noble Eightfold Path will be cultivated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.140", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.140" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, a tree inclines to the east, slants to the east, leans to the east, when cut at the root, which way will it fall?" - "Venerable Sir, in the direction it inclines, in the direction it slants, in the direction it leans." - "So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who develops the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivates the Noble Eightfold Path inclines to Nibbāna, slants to Nibbāna, leans to Nibbāna. Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops right view connected with seclusion ... develops right concentration connected with seclusion, connected with dispassion, connected with cessation, maturing in relinquishment. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who develops the Noble Eightfold Path and cultivates the Noble Eightfold Path inclines to Nibbāna, slants to Nibbāna, leans to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.152", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.152" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of seeking. What three? Seeking for sensual pleasures, seeking for existence, seeking for the holy life. These, bhikkhus, are the three kinds of seeking. It is for the full understanding of these three kinds of seeking that the Noble Eightfold Path is developed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.161", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.161" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of conceit. What three? The conceit 'I am superior,' the conceit 'I am equal,' the conceit 'I am inferior.' These, bhikkhus, are the three kinds of conceit. It is for the purpose of direct knowledge, full understanding, cessation, and abandoning of these three kinds of conceit that the Noble Eightfold Path is developed. How is the Noble Eightfold Path developed? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops right view ... develops right concentration connected with seclusion, connected with dispassion, connected with cessation, maturing in relinquishment. It is for the purpose of direct knowledge, full understanding, cessation, and abandoning of these three kinds of conceit that this Noble Eightfold Path should be developed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.162", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.162" },
{ text: `- Depending on the king of mountains, the Himalayas, bhikkhus, great serpents grow their bodies and acquire strength. There, having grown their bodies and acquired strength, they descend into small lakes. Having descended into small lakes, they descend into large lakes. Having descended into large lakes, they descend into small rivers. Having descended into small rivers, they descend into large rivers. Having descended into large rivers, they enter the great ocean, the sea. There, their bodies become large and vast.<br><br>So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who depends on virtue, established in virtue, develops the seven factors of enlightenment and cultivates them, attains greatness and vastness in states.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.1" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, this body depends on nutriment, by means of nutriment it remains; without nutriment it does not remain. So too, bhikkhus, the five hindrances depend on nutriment, by means of nutriment they remain; without nutriment they do not remain. And, bhikkhus, what is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, or for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire? Bhikkhus, there is the sign of beauty. Here, if one gives unwise attention to it repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, and for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.2" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen ill-will, or for the growth and increase of arisen ill-will? Bhikkhus, there is the sign of aversion. Here, if one gives unwise attention to it repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen ill-will, and for the growth and increase of arisen ill-will.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.2" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sloth and torpor, or for the growth and increase of arisen sloth and torpor? Bhikkhus, there are lack of gladness, laziness, sluggishness, overeating, and mental recoil. Here, if one gives unwise attention to them repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sloth and torpor, and for the growth and increase of arisen sloth and torpor.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.2" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen concentration enlightenment factor, or for the development and fulfillment of arisen concentration enlightenment factor? Bhikkhus, there are the sign of tranquility and the sign of non-distraction. Here, if one gives wise attention to them repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen concentration enlightenment factor, and for the development and fulfillment of arisen concentration enlightenment factor.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.2" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are endowed with virtue, endowed with concentration, endowed with wisdom, endowed with liberation, endowed with knowledge and vision of liberation — I say that seeing those bhikkhus brings great benefit. Hearing those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, I say brings great benefit. Paying homage to those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, I say brings great benefit. Associating with those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, I say brings great benefit. Remembering those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, I say brings great benefit. Following those bhikkhus into homelessness, bhikkhus, I say brings great benefit. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, when hearing the Dhamma from such bhikkhus, one lives in seclusion, with two kinds of seclusion: seclusion of body and seclusion of mind. One who lives in seclusion thus will recollect that Dhamma and reflect on that Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.3" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, while a bhikkhu lives in seclusion thus, recollecting and reflecting on that Dhamma, at that time the mindfulness enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. While the bhikkhu develops the mindfulness enlightenment factor, at that time, through development, the mindfulness enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment. Abiding with such mindfulness, he wisely investigates, examines, and contemplates that Dhamma. While, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abiding with such mindfulness wisely investigates, examines, and contemplates that Dhamma, at that time the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. While the bhikkhu develops the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor, at that time, through development, the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment. While he wisely investigates, examines, and contemplates that Dhamma, unflagging energy is aroused in him.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.3" },
{ text: `While, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with joyful mind, his body becomes tranquil, his mind becomes tranquil; at that time the tranquility enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. While the bhikkhu develops the tranquility enlightenment factor, at that time, through development, the tranquility enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment. For one with a tranquil body, happiness arises. For one who is happy, the mind becomes concentrated. While, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has a tranquil body, experiences happiness, and his mind is concentrated; at that time the concentration enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. While the bhikkhu develops the concentration enlightenment factor, at that time, through development, the concentration enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment. With mind thus concentrated, he looks upon things with equanimity. While, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with mind thus concentrated looks upon things with equanimity, at that time the equanimity enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. While the bhikkhu develops the equanimity enlightenment factor, at that time, through development, the equanimity enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.3" },
{ text: `The defilements of gold, bhikkhus, are those due to which gold becomes defiled, not pliant, not workable, not radiant, brittle, and does not lend itself properly to work. So too, bhikkhus, there are these five defilements of the mind, due to which the mind becomes defiled, not pliant, not workable, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. What are the five? Sensual desire, bhikkhus, is a defilement of the mind. Due to that defilement, the mind becomes defiled, not pliant, not workable, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. ... (With ill-will, sloth and torpor, restlessness and remorse, doubt) These, bhikkhus, are the five defilements of the mind. Due to these defilements, the mind is not pliant, not workable, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.33" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, here a good man, having abandoned sensual desires, goes forth from home to homelessness, but because of those sensual desires, or because of worse sensual desires, he is destroyed, harmed, falls down, lies prostrate. These five hindrances and obstructions, bhikkhus, cover the mind and weaken wisdom. What are the five? Sensual desire, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance, covering the mind, weakening wisdom. Ill-will, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance, covering the mind, weakening wisdom. Sloth and torpor ... Restlessness and remorse ... Doubt, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance, covering the mind, weakening wisdom. These five obstructions and hindrances, bhikkhus, cover the mind and weaken wisdom. These seven factors of enlightenment, bhikkhus, are not obstructions, not hindrances, do not cover the mind; when developed and cultivated, they lead to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation. What are the seven? The mindfulness enlightenment factor, bhikkhus, is not an obstruction, not a hindrance, does not cover the mind; when developed and cultivated, it leads to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation. ... The equanimity enlightenment factor, bhikkhus, is not an obstruction, not a hindrance, does not cover the mind; when developed and cultivated, it leads to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation. These seven factors of enlightenment, bhikkhus, are not obstructions, not hindrances, do not cover the mind; when developed and cultivated, they lead to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.39" },
{ text: `- When the mind is sluggish, bhikkhus, that is not the time to cultivate the tranquility enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the concentration enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the equanimity enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because when the mind is sluggish, bhikkhus, it is hard to arouse the mind with these things. Just as, bhikkhus, a person who wants to kindle a small fire, if he throws wet grass, wet cow-dung, and wet wood onto it, exposes it to rain and wind, and scatters dust on it, could he kindle that small fire?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "So too, bhikkhus, when the mind is sluggish, that is not the time to cultivate the tranquility enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the concentration enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the equanimity enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because when the mind is sluggish, it is hard to arouse the mind with these things.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.53" },
{ text: `- And, bhikkhus, when the mind is sluggish, that is the time to cultivate the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the energy enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the rapture enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, when the mind is sluggish, it is easy to arouse the mind with these things. Just as, bhikkhus, a person who wants to kindle a small fire, if he throws dry grass, dry cow-dung, and dry wood onto it, blows with his mouth, and does not scatter dust on it, could he kindle that small fire?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "So too, bhikkhus, when the mind is sluggish, that is the time to cultivate the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the energy enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the rapture enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, when the mind is sluggish, it is easy to arouse the mind with these things.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.53" },
{ text: `- And, bhikkhus, when the mind is agitated, that is not the time to cultivate the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the energy enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the rapture enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, the agitated mind is hard to calm down with these things. Just as, bhikkhus, a person who wants to extinguish a great fire, if he throws dry grass, dry cow-dung, and dry wood onto it, blows with his mouth, and does not scatter dust on it, could he extinguish that great fire?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "So too, bhikkhus, when the mind is agitated, that is not the time to cultivate the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the energy enlightenment factor, not the time to cultivate the rapture enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because the agitated mind is hard to calm down with these things.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.53" },
{ text: `- And, bhikkhus, when the mind is agitated, that is the time to cultivate the tranquility enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the concentration enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the equanimity enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because the agitated mind is easy to calm down with these things. Just as, bhikkhus, a person who wants to extinguish a great fire, if he throws wet grass, wet cow-dung, and wet wood onto it, exposes it to wind and rain, and scatters dust on it, could he extinguish that great fire?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "So too, bhikkhus, when the mind is agitated, that is the time to cultivate the tranquility enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the concentration enlightenment factor, that is the time to cultivate the equanimity enlightenment factor. Why is that? Because the agitated mind is easy to calm down with these things. But regarding mindfulness, bhikkhus, I say that it is beneficial in every case.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.53" },
{ text: `- This is the one and only path, bhikkhus, for the purification of beings, for the overcoming of sorrow and lamentation, for the extinguishing of pain and grief, for the attainment of the right way, for the realization of Nibbāna. That is, the four foundations of mindfulness. What are the four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating feelings as feelings, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating mind as mind, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful ... He dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. This is the one and only path, bhikkhus, for the purification of beings, for the overcoming of sorrow and lamentation, for the extinguishing of pain and grief, for the attainment of the right way, for the realization of Nibbāna — that is, the four foundations of mindfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell mindful and clearly comprehending. This is my instruction to you. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu mindful? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. He dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu mindful. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu clearly comprehending? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu when going forward and returning, clearly comprehends; when looking ahead and looking aside, clearly comprehends; when bending and stretching his limbs, clearly comprehends; when wearing his robe and carrying his bowl, clearly comprehends; when eating, drinking, chewing, tasting, clearly comprehends; when defecating and urinating, clearly comprehends; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, being silent, clearly comprehends. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu clearly comprehending. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell mindful and clearly comprehending. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.2" },
{ text: `- Therefore, bhikkhu, you should purify the two fundamental qualities regarding wholesome states. And what are the two fundamental qualities regarding wholesome states? They are virtue well purified and view straight and correct. Bhikkhu, when your virtue is well purified and your view is straight and correct, then, bhikkhu, depending on virtue, established on virtue, you should develop the four foundations of mindfulness in three ways. What are the four? Here, bhikkhu, dwell contemplating the body as a body internally, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Or dwell contemplating the body as a body externally, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Or dwell contemplating the body as a body both internally and externally, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Or dwell contemplating feelings as feelings internally ... Or dwell contemplating mind as mind internally ... Or dwell contemplating phenomena as phenomena internally, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Or dwell contemplating phenomena as phenomena externally ... Or dwell contemplating phenomena as phenomena both internally and externally, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Bhikkhu, when you, depending on virtue, established on virtue, develop the four foundations of mindfulness in these three ways, then, bhikkhu, whether by day or by night, growth in wholesome states is to be expected, not decline.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.3" },
{ text: `'Come, bhikkhus, dwell contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, single-minded, with a pure, concentrated, unified mind, for the sake of true knowledge of the body as it actually is. Dwell contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, single-minded, with a pure, concentrated, unified mind, for the sake of true knowledge of phenomena as they actually are.' Bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are newly ordained, who have gone forth not long ago, who have recently come to this Dhamma and Discipline — these, bhikkhus, should be encouraged, instructed, and established in the development of these four foundations of mindfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.4" },
{ text: `- The heap of the unwholesome, bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly, one would say is the five hindrances. This entire heap of the unwholesome, bhikkhus, is the five hindrances. What are the five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of sloth and torpor, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. This heap of the unwholesome, bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly, one would say is the five hindrances. The heap of the wholesome, bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly, one would say is the four foundations of mindfulness. This entire heap of the wholesome, bhikkhus, is the four foundations of mindfulness. What are the four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body ... feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. This heap of the wholesome, bhikkhus, if one were to speak rightly, one would say is the four foundations of mindfulness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.5" },
{ text: `- In the past, bhikkhus, a female hawk suddenly swooped down and seized a quail. Then, bhikkhus, the quail, caught by the female hawk, lamented: 'Thus, misfortune for me! Thus, little merit for me! Because I have walked in what is not my own domain, in another's territory. If I had walked in my own domain, in the territory of my parents, this hawk would not have been a match for me in a fight.' - 'Quail, what is your own domain, what is the territory of your parents?' - 'It is the field clod turned over by the plough.' Then, bhikkhus, the female hawk, without tightening her grip, without pressing hard, released the quail and said: 'Go, quail. After you go there, I will not let you go.' Then, bhikkhus, the quail went to the field clod turned over by the plough, climbed onto a large clod of earth, stood there, and said to the hawk: 'Come to me, hawk! Come to me, hawk!' Then, bhikkhus, the female hawk, tightening her grip, pressing hard, folding both wings, suddenly swooped down on the quail. Bhikkhus, when the quail knew: 'This hawk is swooping down hard on me,' it hid behind that clod of earth. There, bhikkhus, the hawk's chest was broken. So too, bhikkhus, for one who walks in what is not his own domain, in another's territory. Therefore, bhikkhus, do not walk in what is not your own domain, in another's territory. Bhikkhus, walking in what is not your own domain, in another's territory, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.6" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, for one who walks in what is not his own domain, in another's territory. Therefore, bhikkhus, do not walk in what is not your own domain, in another's territory. Bhikkhus, walking in what is not your own domain, in another's territory, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object. And what, bhikkhus, is not a bhikkhu's own domain, what is another's territory? It is the five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? There are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. There are sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... tastes cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. Bhikkhus, this is not a bhikkhu's own domain, this is another's territory. Bhikkhus, walk in your own domain, in the territory of your parents. Bhikkhus, walking in your own domain, in the territory of your parents, Māra does not gain an opportunity, Māra does not gain an object. And what, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu's own domain, what is the territory of his parents? It is the four foundations of mindfulness. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body ... feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. This, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu's own domain, the territory of his parents.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.6" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, at the king of mountains, the Himalayas, there are rough, uneven stretches where neither monkeys nor humans go. Bhikkhus, at the king of mountains, the Himalayas, there are rough, uneven stretches where only monkeys go, not humans. At the king of mountains, the Himalayas, there are level, delightful stretches where both monkeys and humans go. There, bhikkhus, hunters set up traps on the monkey paths to catch monkeys. Here, bhikkhus, those monkeys that are not foolish, not greedy, seeing the trap, avoid it. But the foolish, greedy monkey, seeing the trap, reaches out with its hand and gets stuck. 'I'll free my hand,' it reaches out with the other hand and gets stuck. 'I'll free both hands,' it lifts a foot and gets stuck. 'I'll free both hands and one foot,' it lifts the other foot and gets stuck. 'I'll free both hands and both feet,' it uses its mouth and gets stuck. Thus, bhikkhus, that monkey, caught in five places, lies down groaning, fallen into misfortune, into calamity, at the hunter's mercy. The hunter pierces it, roasts it over a pile of coals, and then goes away as he pleases. So too, bhikkhus, is one who goes to what is not his own domain, another's territory. Bhikkhus, going to what is not your own domain, another's territory, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.7" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, here a foolish, unintelligent, unskilled bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Yet, though he dwells contemplating the body as a body, his mind is not concentrated, his defilements are not abandoned; he does not learn that sign. Though he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... He dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Yet, though he dwells contemplating phenomena as phenomena, his mind is not concentrated, his defilements are not abandoned; he does not learn that sign. Bhikkhus, that foolish, unintelligent, unskilled bhikkhu does not attain a pleasant abiding in the present life, nor does he attain mindfulness and clear comprehension. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, that foolish, unintelligent, unskilled bhikkhu has not learned the sign of his own mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.8" },
{ text: `- Ānanda, have I not previously declared to you that all that is dear and agreeable has the nature of change, the nature of separation, the nature of alteration? How, Ānanda, could it be expected here: 'May what is born, become, conditioned, and subject to decay not decay!'? That is impossible. Just as, Ānanda, a large branch breaks off from a great, straight-standing, heartwood tree. So too, Ānanda, from the Saṅgha of bhikkhus standing straight, with heartwood, Sāriputta has passed away. How, Ānanda, could it be expected here: 'May what is born, become, conditioned, and subject to decay not decay!'? That is impossible. Therefore, Ānanda, be islands unto yourselves, refuges unto yourselves, with no other refuge. Let the Dhamma be your island, let the Dhamma be your refuge, with no other refuge.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.13" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how, by protecting oneself, does one protect others? Through practice, through development, through cultivation. Thus, bhikkhus, by protecting oneself, one protects others. And, bhikkhus, how, by protecting others, does one protect oneself? Through patience, through non-harming, through loving-kindness, through compassion. Thus, bhikkhus, by protecting others, one protects oneself. Bhikkhus, 'I will protect myself' — that is to say, the foundation of mindfulness should be practiced. Bhikkhus, 'I will protect others' — that is to say, the foundation of mindfulness should be practiced. By protecting oneself, bhikkhus, one protects others. By protecting others, one protects oneself.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.19" },
{ text: `- Just as a great crowd of people, bhikkhus, would gather together and say: 'The national beauty! The national beauty!' And that national beauty, with all her charms, would dance for them, with all her charms, would sing for them. And an even larger crowd would gather and say: 'The national beauty dances and sings.' Then a man would come who wants to live, not to die, who wants happiness and loathes suffering. They would say to him: 'Friend, look here. This is a bowl filled with oil. You must carry this bowl of oil through the great crowd and the national beauty. And a man with a drawn sword will follow behind you. Wherever you spill even a little of the oil, there your head will fall.' What do you think, bhikkhus, would that man, not attending to the bowl of oil, let his mind wander outside?" - "Bhikkhus, I give this simile to convey the meaning. And this is the meaning: 'The bowl filled with oil' is a synonym for mindfulness of the body. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will develop mindfulness of the body, cultivate it, make it our vehicle, make it our base, establish it, accumulate it, and properly undertake it.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.20" },
{ text: `'Contemplating the body as a body,' bhikkhus — concerning phenomena not heard before, there arose vision, knowledge, wisdom, and light. 'This contemplating the body as a body is to be developed' ... 'This contemplating the body as a body has been developed' — concerning phenomena not heard before, there arose vision, knowledge, wisdom, and light. 'Contemplating feelings as feelings' ... 'Contemplating mind as mind' ... 'Contemplating phenomena as phenomena,' bhikkhus — concerning phenomena not heard before, there arose vision, knowledge, wisdom, and light. 'This contemplating phenomena as phenomena is to be developed' ... 'This contemplating phenomena as phenomena has been developed' — concerning phenomena not heard before, there arose vision, knowledge, wisdom, and light.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.31" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell mindful and clearly comprehending. This is my instruction to you. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu mindful? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world ... Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu mindful. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu clearly comprehending? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu knows feelings as they arise, knows feelings as they persist, knows feelings as they pass away; knows perceptions as they arise, knows perceptions as they persist, knows perceptions as they pass away. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu clearly comprehending. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell mindful and clearly comprehending. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.35" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, live restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Bhikkhu, having lived restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules, then, bhikkhu, depending on virtue, established on virtue, develop the four foundations of mindfulness. What are the four? Here, bhikkhu, dwell contemplating the body as a body ... dwell contemplating feelings as feelings ... dwell contemplating mind as mind ... dwell contemplating phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. When, bhikkhu, you, depending on virtue, established on virtue, develop these four foundations of mindfulness, then, bhikkhu, whether by day or by night, growth in wholesome states is to be expected, not decline.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.48" },
{ text: `- But, Master Gotama, what is the support for the mind?" - "Brahmin, mindfulness is the support for the mind." - "But, Master Gotama, what is the support for mindfulness?" - "Brahmin, liberation is the support for mindfulness." - "But, Master Gotama, what is the support for liberation?" - "Brahmin, Nibbāna is the support for liberation." - "But, Master Gotama, what is the support for Nibbāna?" - "Brahmin, your question goes too far; you cannot grasp the limit of the question. Brahmin, the holy life is lived for the sake of entering Nibbāna, the holy life has Nibbāna as its goal, Nibbāna as its final end.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 48.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn48.42" },
{ text: `And, Sāriputta, what is the supreme respect that a bhikkhu with taints destroyed shows to the Tathāgata or to the Tathāgata's teaching?" - "Here, Venerable Sir, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed lives respecting and revering the Teacher; lives respecting and revering the Dhamma; lives respecting and revering the Saṅgha; lives respecting and revering the training; lives respecting and revering concentration. This, Venerable Sir, is the supreme respect that a bhikkhu with taints destroyed shows to the Tathāgata or to the Tathāgata's teaching." - "Good, good, Sāriputta! This is the supreme respect that a bhikkhu with taints destroyed shows to the Tathāgata or to the Tathāgata's teaching.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 48.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn48.58" },
{ text: `One develops the basis for psychic power that possesses concentration due to desire and the effort of striving, thinking: 'Thus my mind will not be overly sluggish nor overly energetic, will not be inwardly contracted nor outwardly scattered, and will abide with perceptions of before and after as the same. As before, so after; as after, so before. As below, so above; as above, so below. As by day, so by night; as by night, so by day.' Thus, with a mind that is open, not confined, and radiant, he develops the mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.11" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is desire that is too sluggish? Whatever desire, bhikkhus, is accompanied by laziness, associated with laziness — this, bhikkhus, is called desire that is too sluggish. Bhikkhus, what is desire that is too energetic? Whatever desire, bhikkhus, is accompanied by restlessness, associated with agitation — this, bhikkhus, is called desire that is too energetic. Bhikkhus, what is desire that is inwardly contracted? Whatever desire, bhikkhus, is accompanied by sloth and torpor, associated with sloth and torpor — this, bhikkhus, is called desire that is inwardly contracted. Bhikkhus, what is desire that is outwardly scattered? Whatever desire, bhikkhus, is directed outward, is dispersed and distracted by the five strands of sensual pleasure — this, bhikkhus, is called desire that is outwardly scattered.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.20" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu abide with perceptions of before and after as the same, so that as before, so after; as after, so before? Here, bhikkhus, the bhikkhu's perceptions of before and after are well grasped, well attended to, well retained, and well penetrated by wisdom. Thus, bhikkhus, he abides with perceptions of before and after as the same, so that as before, so after; as after, so before.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.20" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu abide so that as below, so above; as above, so below? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu contemplates this very body from the soles of the feet upwards and from the hair of the head downwards, enclosed by skin, full of various impurities: 'In this body, there are head hairs, body hairs, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, stomach, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, mucus, synovial fluid, urine.' Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides so that as below, so above; as above, so below.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.20" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, how does a bhikkhu, with an open mind, not confined, a radiant mind, develop the mind? Here, bhikkhus, the perception of light is well grasped by the bhikkhu, the perception of daytime is well established. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with an open mind, not confined, a radiant mind, develops the mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.20" },
{ text: `- So too, friends, a bhikkhu who develops the four foundations of mindfulness and cultivates them. Even if kings, ministers, friends, companions, or blood relatives should offer him wealth and say: 'Come, good man, why should these yellow robes torment you? Why should you go about with a shaven head and a bowl? Return to the lower life, enjoy wealth and do meritorious deeds!' — that bhikkhu, friends, who has developed and cultivated the four foundations of mindfulness, cannot give up the training and return to the lower life. Why is that? Because, friends, his mind has for a long time inclined to seclusion, slanted to seclusion, leaned to seclusion — that he should return to the lower life is impossible.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 52.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn52.8" },
{ text: `Once, the Venerable Anuruddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Andhavana forest, afflicted with a severe illness, suffering, gravely ill. Then many bhikkhus went to the Venerable Anuruddha and said to him: 'What abiding does the Venerable Anuruddha abide in, so that arisen painful bodily feelings do not affect his mind?' - 'Friends, because my mind is well established in the four foundations of mindfulness, arisen painful bodily feelings do not affect my mind. What four? Here, friends, I dwell contemplating the body as a body ... feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Friends, because my mind is well established in these four foundations of mindfulness, arisen painful bodily feelings do not affect my mind.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 52.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn52.10" },
{ text: `- There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, yields great fruit and great benefit. What is that one thing? Mindfulness of breathing. And how, bhikkhus, is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated so that it yields great fruit and great benefit? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, sits down, folding his legs crosswise, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. Mindfully he breathes in, mindfully he breathes out. Breathing in long, he understands: 'I breathe in long'; breathing out long, he understands: 'I breathe out long'; breathing in short, he understands: 'I breathe in short'; breathing out short, he understands: 'I breathe out short'. 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'experiencing the whole body, I will breathe out,' he trains. 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe out,' he trains. ... Developed and cultivated in this way, bhikkhus, mindfulness of breathing yields great fruit and great benefit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do you see that bhikkhu's body shaking or trembling?" - "Venerable Sir, we see that venerable one sitting in the midst of the Saṅgha or sitting alone, secluded; we do not see that venerable one's body shaking or trembling." - "For one with such concentration, bhikkhus, through development and cultivation, his body does not shake or tremble, his mind does not shake or tremble. For that bhikkhu, so concentrated, there is no difficulty, no trouble, no fatigue. And, bhikkhus, what concentration does he develop and cultivate so that his body does not shake or tremble, or his mind does not shake or tremble? Bhikkhus, by developing and cultivating the concentration of mindfulness of breathing, his body does not shake or tremble, nor does his mind shake or tremble.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.7" },


{ text: `- Bhikkhus, this concentration through mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated, is peaceful, sublime, pure, a pleasant abiding, and it makes evil, unwholesome states that have arisen vanish and subside immediately. Just as, bhikkhus, at the end of the summer, dust and dirt fly up, and a great out-of-season rain cloud makes them vanish and subside immediately. So too, bhikkhus, this concentration through mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated, is peaceful, sublime, pure, a pleasant abiding, and it makes evil, unwholesome states that have arisen vanish and subside immediately. And how, bhikkhus, is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated so that it is peaceful, sublime, pure, a pleasant abiding, and makes evil, unwholesome states that have arisen vanish and subside immediately? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, sits down cross-legged ... 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe in,' he trains. 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe out,' he trains. Bhikkhus, mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated in this way is peaceful, sublime, pure, a pleasant abiding, and evil, unwholesome states that have arisen vanish and subside immediately.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.9" },
{ text: `Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu breathing in long understands: 'I breathe in long'; or breathing out long, he understands: 'I breathe out long'; or breathing in short, he understands: 'I breathe in short'; or breathing out short, he understands: 'I breathe out short'; 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe out,' he trains; 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe out,' he trains. Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating the body as a body, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Why is that? Ānanda, I say that this is a certain body, namely, in-breath and out-breath. Therefore, Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating the body as a body, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.10" },
{ text: `Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu trains: 'Experiencing rapture, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Experiencing rapture, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Experiencing happiness, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Experiencing happiness, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Experiencing mental formation, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Experiencing mental formation, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Tranquilizing mental formation, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Tranquilizing mental formation, I will breathe out'. Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating feelings as feelings, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Why is that? Ānanda, I say that this is a certain feeling, namely, close attention to in-breath and out-breath. Therefore, Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating feelings as feelings, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.10" },
{ text: `Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu trains: 'Experiencing the mind, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Experiencing the mind, I will breathe out'; trains: 'With a joyful mind, I will breathe in'; trains: 'With a joyful mind, I will breathe out'; trains: 'With a concentrated mind, I will breathe in'; trains: 'With a concentrated mind, I will breathe out'; trains: 'With a liberated mind, I will breathe in'; trains: 'With a liberated mind, I will breathe out'. Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating mind as mind, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Why is that? Ānanda, I say that the development of mindfulness of breathing is not for one who is unmindful and not clearly comprehending. Therefore, Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating mind as mind, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.10" },
{ text: `Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu trains: 'Contemplating impermanence, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Contemplating impermanence, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Contemplating dispassion, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Contemplating dispassion, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Contemplating cessation, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Contemplating cessation, I will breathe out'; trains: 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe in'; trains: 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe out'. Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating phenomena as phenomena, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world, having abandoned covetousness and displeasure; having seen with wisdom, he abides well in equanimity. Therefore, Ānanda, at that time, dwelling contemplating phenomena as phenomena, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.10" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if wanderers of other sects should ask you: 'In what abiding, friends, does Samaṇa Gotama dwell much during the rains?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those wanderers: 'In the concentration of mindfulness of breathing, friends, the Blessed One dwells much during the rains.' Here, bhikkhus, mindful I breathe in, mindful I breathe out. Or breathing in long, I understand: 'I breathe in long'; or breathing out long, I understand: 'I breathe out long'; or breathing in short, I understand: 'I breathe in short'; or breathing out short, I understand: 'I breathe out short' ... 'Contemplating relinquishment, I breathe in,' I understand thus; 'Contemplating relinquishment, I breathe out,' I understand thus. Bhikkhus, one speaking rightly, if he were to say 'This is a noble abiding, this is a Brahmā abiding, this is the Tathāgata's abiding,' should say that the concentration of mindfulness of breathing is a noble abiding, a Brahmā abiding, the Tathāgata's abiding.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.11" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are learners, whose minds have not yet attained the goal, who dwell aspiring to the supreme security from bondage — they develop and cultivate the concentration of mindfulness of breathing, which leads to the destruction of the taints. And, bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are Arahants, with taints destroyed, who have lived the holy life, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of existence, liberated by final knowledge — they develop and cultivate the concentration of mindfulness of breathing, which leads to a pleasant abiding here and now, to mindfulness and clear comprehension. Bhikkhus, one speaking rightly, if he were to say 'This is a noble abiding, this is a Brahmā abiding, this is the Tathāgata's abiding,' should say that the concentration of mindfulness of breathing is a noble abiding, a Brahmā abiding, the Tathāgata's abiding.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.11" },
{ text: `- Ānanda, there is one thing that, when developed and cultivated, perfects four things. Four things, when developed and cultivated, perfect seven things. Seven things, when developed and cultivated, perfect two things. - What is that one thing, Venerable Sir, that when developed and cultivated perfects four things? And what four things, when developed and cultivated, perfect seven things? And what seven things, when developed and cultivated, perfect two things? - Ānanda, mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated, perfects the four foundations of mindfulness. The four foundations of mindfulness, when developed and cultivated, perfect the seven factors of enlightenment. The seven factors of enlightenment, when developed and cultivated, perfect true knowledge and liberation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.13" },
{ text: `How, Ānanda, is it that four foundations of mindfulness, when developed and cultivated, perfect the seven factors of enlightenment? Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, his mindfulness is established; at that time, Ānanda, a bhikkhu is mindful, not forgetful. Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu abides mindful, not forgetful, then the mindfulness enlightenment factor is aroused in that bhikkhu. Whenever, Ānanda, a bhikkhu develops the mindfulness enlightenment factor, then, through development, the mindfulness enlightenment factor comes to fulfillment. Abiding thus mindful, he wisely investigates, examines, and contemplates that Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.13" },
{ text: `Here, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'I want to live, I do not want to die; I want happiness, I loathe suffering. If someone were to take my life, for me who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, loathes suffering, that would be undesirable and unpleasing. But if I were to take the life of another who wants to live, does not want to die, wants happiness, loathes suffering, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from killing living beings, encourages others to abstain from killing, and speaks in praise of abstaining from killing. Thus, in bodily conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to take from me what is not given, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to take from another what is not given, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from taking what is not given, encourages others to abstain from taking what is not given, and speaks in praise of abstaining from taking what is not given. Thus, in bodily conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to commit sexual misconduct with my wife, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to commit sexual misconduct with another's wife, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from sexual misconduct, encourages others to abstain from sexual misconduct, and speaks in praise of abstaining from sexual misconduct. Thus, in bodily conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to harm my welfare by false speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to harm another's welfare by false speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from false speech, encourages others to abstain from false speech, and speaks in praise of abstaining from false speech. Thus, in verbal conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to break up my friends by divisive speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to break up another's friends by divisive speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from divisive speech, encourages others to abstain from divisive speech, and speaks in praise of abstaining from divisive speech. Thus, in verbal conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to address me with harsh speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to address another with harsh speech, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from harsh speech, encourages others to abstain from harsh speech, and speaks in praise of abstaining from harsh speech. Thus, in verbal conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `Furthermore, householders, a noble disciple reflects: 'If someone were to address me with idle chatter, with frivolous talk, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for me. But if I were to address another with idle chatter, with frivolous talk, that would be undesirable and unpleasing for that person. This state that is undesirable and unpleasing for me is also undesirable and unpleasing for others. Since this state is undesirable and unpleasing for me, why should I impose it on others?' Reflecting thus, he himself abstains from idle chatter, encourages others to abstain from idle chatter, and speaks in praise of abstaining from idle chatter. Thus, in verbal conduct, he becomes completely pure.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.7" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, all those for whom you have compassion, and those who you think should listen to you, friends, companions, relatives, blood relations — all of them, bhikkhus, should be encouraged, established, and grounded in the four factors of stream-entry. What four? They should be encouraged, established, and grounded in unwavering confidence in the Buddha: 'He is the Arahant ... the Buddha, the Blessed One.' ... in the Dhamma ... in the Saṅgha ... and in the virtues dear to the noble ones ... leading to concentration. Bhikkhus, all those for whom you have compassion, and those who you think should listen to you, friends, companions, relatives, blood relations — they should be encouraged, established, and grounded in these four factors of stream-entry.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.16" },
{ text: `- Do not fear, Mahānāma! Do not fear, Mahānāma! Your death will not be evil! Your death will not be evil! Mahānāma, for one whose mind has long been fully developed in faith, fully developed in virtue, fully developed in learning, fully developed in generosity, fully developed in wisdom — for such a person, even though this material body, composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished by rice and porridge, is subject to impermanence, destruction, breaking up, and cessation — even though this body may be eaten here by crows, vultures, hawks, dogs, jackals, or various other creatures — nevertheless, if his mind has long been fully developed in faith, fully developed in virtue, fully developed in learning, fully developed in generosity, fully developed in wisdom, then his mind rises upward, goes toward excellence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.21" },
{ text: `Just as, Mahānāma, a person submerges a pot of buttermilk or a pot of oil in a deep lake and breaks it. There, the pot shards and fragments sink down, but the buttermilk or oil rises up, floats up. So too, Mahānāma, for one whose mind has long been fully developed in faith, fully developed in virtue, fully developed in learning, fully developed in generosity, fully developed in wisdom — for such a person, even though this material body ... is subject to impermanence ... may be eaten here by crows ... or various other creatures — nevertheless, if his mind has long been fully developed in faith ... fully developed in wisdom, then his mind rises upward, goes toward excellence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.21" },
{ text: `Mahānāma, your mind has long been fully developed in faith, fully developed in virtue, fully developed in learning, fully developed in generosity, fully developed in wisdom. Do not fear, Mahānāma! Do not fear, Mahānāma! Your death will not be evil! Your death will not be evil! Just as, Mahānāma, a tree that inclines to the east, slants to the east, leans to the east, if cut at the root, which way will it fall?" - "Venerable Sir, in the direction it inclines, in the direction it slants, in the direction it leans." - "So too, Mahānāma, a noble disciple who possesses these four things inclines to Nibbāna, slants to Nibbāna, leans to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.21" },
{ text: `One who has faith in the Tathāgata,<br>Unshakable and well established,<br>Who has good virtue,<br>Dear to the noble ones,<br>Who has faith in the Saṅgha,<br>And whose view is upright,<br>That person is called 'not poor';<br>His life is not in vain.<br>Therefore, the wise person,<br>Mindful of the Buddha's teaching,<br>Should devote himself to faith and virtue,<br>To the Dhamma and clear vision.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.26" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these four streams of merit, streams of the wholesome, nutriments of happiness. What are the four? Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple possesses unwavering confidence in the Buddha: 'He is the Arahant ... the Buddha, the Blessed One.' This is the first stream of merit, stream of the wholesome, nutriment of happiness. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple possesses unwavering confidence in the Dhamma: 'The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One ... to be experienced by the wise for themselves.' This is the second stream of merit ... Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple possesses unwavering confidence in the Saṅgha: 'The Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is practicing the good way ... the unsurpassed field of merit for the world.' This is the third stream of merit ... Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple possesses the virtues dear to the noble ones ... leading to concentration. This is the fourth stream of merit, stream of the wholesome, nutriment of happiness. These, bhikkhus, are the four streams of merit, streams of the wholesome, nutriments of happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.31" },
{ text: `- Furthermore, bhikkhus, a noble disciple living at home, with a mind free from the stain of stinginess, gives freely, with open hands, delighting in relinquishment, responsive to requests, delighting in sharing gifts. This is the fourth stream of merit, stream of the wholesome, nutriment of happiness. These, bhikkhus, are the four streams of merit, streams of the wholesome, nutriments of happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.32" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, when a great rain pours down on a mountain top, the water flows down the slopes, fills the clefts, gullies, and valleys; having filled them, it fills the small ponds; having filled the small ponds, it fills the large ponds; having filled the large ponds, it fills the small rivers; having filled the small rivers, it fills the large rivers; having filled the large rivers, it fills the great ocean, the sea. So too, bhikkhus, for a noble disciple, unwavering confidence in the Buddha, unwavering confidence in the Dhamma, unwavering confidence in the Saṅgha, and the virtues dear to the noble ones — these things flow onward to the far shore, leading to the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.38" },
{ text: `Here, Nandiya, a noble disciple possesses unwavering confidence in the Buddha: 'He is the Arahant ... the Buddha, the Blessed One.' Not being satisfied with that unwavering confidence, he strives further, dwelling in seclusion by day and in jhāna by night. Because he dwells heedfully, gladness arises. With gladness, rapture arises. With rapture, his body becomes tranquil. With a tranquil body, he experiences happiness. With happiness, his mind becomes concentrated. With a concentrated mind, phenomena become manifest. With phenomena manifest, he is called one who dwells heedfully. Furthermore, Nandiya, a noble disciple ... in the Dhamma ... in the Saṅgha ... he possesses the virtues dear to the noble ones ... leading to concentration. Not being satisfied with those virtues, he strives further ... With phenomena manifest, he is called one who dwells heedfully. Thus, Nandiya, is a noble disciple who dwells heedfully.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.40" },
{ text: `The great ocean, the sea,<br>Vast and wide,<br>Full of terrifying things,<br>Holding countless jewels,<br>Serving hundreds of thousands,<br>Great and small rivers,<br>They flow swiftly,<br>They pour into the ocean.<br>So too, those people<br>Who give food, drink, cloth,<br>Give beds, seats,<br>Blankets, mattresses, bedding,<br>Boundless streams of merit<br>Flow from the wise,<br>Like rivers full of water<br>Flowing into the great sea.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.41" },
{ text: `Whoever wishes for merit,<br>Firmly established in good,<br>Practices the path<br>Leading to the Deathless,<br>Attains the heartwood of the Dhamma,<br>Delighting in the destruction of taints,<br>That one does not tremble<br>When thinking of death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.43" },
{ text: `A wise lay follower who is sick, suffering, gravely ill, Mahānāma, should be instructed by a wise lay follower with these four consolations. It should be said: 'If he says, "I have attachment to my parents," one should say: "Venerable sir, you will die anyway. Whether you have attachment to your parents or not, you will die. It would be better for you to abandon your attachment to your parents." If he says, "I have attachment to my wife and children," one should say: "Venerable sir, you will die anyway. Whether you have attachment to your wife and children or not, you will die. It would be better for you to abandon your attachment to your wife and children.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 55.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn55.54" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, whatever good men in the past rightly went forth from home to homelessness, all did so to fully realize the Four Noble Truths as they are. Whatever good men in the future will rightly go forth from home to homelessness, all will do so to fully realize the Four Noble Truths as they are. Whatever good men in the present rightly go forth from home to homelessness, all do so to fully realize the Four Noble Truths as they are. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Whatever good men in the past rightly went forth ... in the future will go forth ... in the present go forth, all do so to fully realize these Four Noble Truths. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.3" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do not think evil, unwholesome thoughts, such as sensual thoughts, ill-will thoughts, harmfulness thoughts. Why is that? Those thoughts, bhikkhus, are not connected with the goal, are not fundamental to the holy life, and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. When you think, bhikkhus, you should think: 'This is suffering' ... you should think: 'This is the origin of suffering' ... you should think: 'This is the cessation of suffering' ... you should think: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Why is that? Those thoughts, bhikkhus, are connected with the goal, are fundamental to the holy life, and lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.7" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do not engage in disputes with one another, saying: 'You do not understand this Dhamma and Discipline; I understand this Dhamma and Discipline. How could you understand this Dhamma and Discipline? You practice wrongly; I practice rightly. What should be said first you say last; what should be said last you say first. My words are consistent; yours are not. What you have held and argued has been overturned. Your view is challenged. Go and untangle your view; free yourself if you can.' Why is that? Those talks, bhikkhus, are not connected with the goal, are not fundamental to the holy life, and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. And, bhikkhus, when you speak, speak thus: 'This is suffering' ... speak thus: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Why is that? Those talks, bhikkhus, are connected with the goal, are fundamental to the holy life, and lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do not engage in animal talk, such as talk about kings, talk about thieves, talk about ministers, talk about armies, frightening tales, war stories, talk about food, talk about drink, talk about clothing, talk about bedding, talk about garlands, talk about perfumes, talk about relatives, talk about vehicles, talk about villages, talk about market towns, talk about cities, talk about countries, talk about women, talk about men, talk about heroes, street talk, talk at the water well, talk about the dead, miscellaneous gossip, talk about the origin of the world, talk about the origin of the ocean, talk about being and non-being. Why is that? These talks, bhikkhus, are not connected with the goal, are not fundamental to the holy life, and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.10" },
{ text: `These four things, bhikkhus, are true, not false, not otherwise. What four? 'This is suffering,' bhikkhus, is true, not false, not otherwise. 'This is the origin of suffering,' bhikkhus, is true, not false, not otherwise. 'This is the cessation of suffering,' bhikkhus, is true, not false, not otherwise. 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering,' bhikkhus, is true, not false, not otherwise. These four things, bhikkhus, are true, not false, not otherwise. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.20" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is because of not realizing, not penetrating the Four Noble Truths that you and I have wandered and run on through this long course for such a long time. What four? Because of not realizing, not penetrating the Noble Truth of Suffering, bhikkhus, you and I have wandered and run on through this long course ... the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering ... Because of not realizing, not penetrating the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering, bhikkhus, you and I have wandered and run on through this long course. But now, bhikkhus, the Noble Truth of Suffering has been realized and penetrated; the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering has been realized and penetrated; the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering has been realized and penetrated; the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering has been realized and penetrated. Craving for existence has been cut off; the conduit to renewed existence has been destroyed; now there is no further existence. This the Blessed One said ... the Teacher further said:<br><br>Because the Four Noble Truths<br>Were not seen as they are,<br>Long was the wandering<br>Through many births.<br>When they are seen clearly,<br>The root of rebirth is pulled up,<br>The root of suffering is cut off,<br>Now there is no further existence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.21" },
{ text: `Those who do not know<br>Suffering and its origin,<br>And do not know how<br>Suffering ceases without remainder,<br>And do not know the path<br>Leading to the stilling of suffering —<br>Those ones do not have<br>Liberation of mind and wisdom,<br>They cannot make an end,<br>They go to birth and aging.<br>Those who know<br>Suffering and its origin,<br>And know how<br>Suffering ceases without remainder,<br>And know the path<br>Leading to the stilling of suffering —<br>They are accomplished in<br>Liberation of mind and wisdom,<br>They can make an end,<br>They do not go to birth and aging.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.22" },
{ text: `- What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: the few Simsapā leaves I have taken in my hand, or the leaves in the Simsapā forest?" - "Venerable Sir, the few Simsapā leaves the Blessed One has taken in his hand are very few, and the leaves in the Simsapā forest are far more numerous." - "So too, bhikkhus, what I have directly known but not taught to you is far more numerous; what I have taught you is very little. But why, bhikkhus, have I not taught those things? Because they are not connected with the goal, not fundamental to the holy life, and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore, I have not taught them. And what, bhikkhus, have I taught? 'This is suffering,' bhikkhus, I have taught. 'This is the origin of suffering,' I have taught. 'This is the cessation of suffering,' I have taught. 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering,' I have taught. And why, bhikkhus, have I taught these things? Because they are connected with the goal, fundamental to the holy life, and lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. Therefore, I have taught them.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.31" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, a stick thrown up into the sky sometimes falls on its base, sometimes in the middle, sometimes on its tip. So too, bhikkhus, beings shrouded by ignorance and fettered by craving, wandering and roaming on, sometimes go from this world to another world, sometimes from another world to this world. Why is that? Because they do not see the Four Noble Truths. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.33" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, when a turban or head is on fire, what should be done?" - "Venerable Sir, when a turban or head is on fire, to extinguish the burning turban or head, one should arouse extraordinary desire, effort, exertion, energy, without backsliding, with mindfulness and clear comprehension." - "Leaving aside the burning turban or head, bhikkhus, for the sake of truly realizing the Four Noble Truths that have not yet been realized, one should arouse extraordinary desire, effort, exertion, energy, without backsliding, with mindfulness and clear comprehension. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.34" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, a person with a lifespan of a hundred years, living a hundred years, has someone come and say to him: 'Friend, in the morning you will be struck by a hundred spears; at noon you will be struck by a hundred spears; in the evening you will be struck by a hundred spears. Thus, friend, each day you will be struck by three hundred spears. With a lifespan of a hundred years, living a hundred years, after a hundred years you will realize the Four Noble Truths that have not yet been realized.' Bhikkhus, would a good man who understands the meaning accept that?" - "Why is that? The beginning of this wandering is not known, bhikkhus, for (the suffering of) being struck by spears, being cut by swords, being hacked by axes. Yet, bhikkhus, I do not declare that the Four Noble Truths are realized through suffering and grief. But, bhikkhus, I declare that the Four Noble Truths are realized through happiness and joy. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.35" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, a person throws a yoke with a single hole into the great ocean. There is a blind turtle that surfaces once every hundred years. What do you think, bhikkhus, would that blind turtle, surfacing once every hundred years, put its neck into that yoke with a single hole?" - "It might, Venerable Sir, after a very long time." - "I say, bhikkhus, that the blind turtle surfacing once every hundred years would put its neck into that yoke with a single hole more quickly than a fool who has fallen into a plane of misery could regain human birth. Why is that? Because there, bhikkhus, there is no practice of Dhamma, no righteous conduct, no wholesome deeds, no meritorious deeds. There, bhikkhus, they devour one another, and the weak are eaten. Why is that? Because they do not see the Four Noble Truths. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.47" },
{ text: `- Just as, bhikkhus, this great earth were entirely covered with water, and a person throws a yoke with a single hole into it. An east wind would carry it west, a west wind would carry it east, a north wind would carry it south, a south wind would carry it north. There is a blind turtle that surfaces once every hundred years. What do you think, bhikkhus, would that blind turtle, surfacing once every hundred years, put its neck into that yoke with a single hole?" - "It would be hard, Venerable Sir, for that blind turtle, surfacing once every hundred years, to put its neck into that yoke with a single hole!" - "It is just as hard, bhikkhus, to obtain human birth! It is just as hard, bhikkhus, for a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One, to appear in the world! It is just as hard, bhikkhus, for the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata to shine in the world! But now, bhikkhus, you have obtained human birth, and a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One, has appeared in the world, and the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata shines in the world. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.48" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One took a little dust on his fingernail and said to the bhikkhus: 'What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: this little dust I have taken on my fingernail, or this great earth?' - 'This is greater, Venerable Sir, namely the great earth. The little dust the Blessed One has taken on his fingernail is insignificant. It cannot be reckoned, cannot be compared, cannot be a fraction, compared to the great earth.' - 'So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who, after death from the human state, are reborn as humans again. And many more are the beings who, after death from the human state, are reborn in hell. Why is that? Because they do not see the Four Noble Truths. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.102" },
{ text: `'Damsels in assembly gather,<br>Ghosts come and go,<br>That forest is called the forest of delusion,<br>How can there be an escape?'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>'That path is called the straight path,<br>That direction is called fearless,<br>The chariot is called noiseless,<br>Fitted with the Dhamma-wheel.<br><br>Conscience is the chariot's leaning-board,<br>Mindfulness is its canopy,<br>I say the charioteer<br>Is the true Dhamma,<br>And right view itself<br>Goes quickly ahead.'<br><br>Whether a man or a woman,<br>Both use that chariot.<br>By means of that chariot,<br>They go towards Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.46" },
{ text: `'This is Jeta's Grove,<br>The dwelling place of the noble Saṅgha,<br>The abode of the Dhamma King,<br>Bringing joy to my mind.<br><br>Action, knowledge, and mind-Dhamma,<br>Virtue, the supreme life —<br>It is by these excellent Dhammas<br>That beings are purified,<br>Not by clan, not by wealth.<br><br>Therefore the wise,<br>Seeing their own good,<br>Wisely investigate the Dhamma,<br>Thus they become pure.<br><br>Like Sāriputta,<br>In wisdom, virtue, and peace,<br>The bhikkhu who has reached the shore of enlightenment<br>Is supreme here.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.48" },
{ text: `'What leads the world along?<br>What torments oneself?<br>Is there one thing<br>To which everything is subject?'<br><br>'Craving leads the world along,<br>Craving torments oneself,<br>Craving is that one thing<br>To which everything is subject.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.63" },
{ text: `Standing to one side, that devata spoke this verse before the Blessed One:<br><br>'Those who regarding phenomena,<br>Do not thoroughly understand them,<br>Are led astray,<br>Wandering among various sects.<br>They sleep on and on,<br>They are not awake,<br>Now indeed it is time<br>For them to awaken.'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>'Those who regarding phenomena,<br>Thoroughly understand them with wisdom,<br>Are not led astray,<br>Wandering among various sects,<br>They have attained perfect enlightenment.<br>They fully understand perfectly,<br>On the uneven path,<br>They walk evenly.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.7" },
{ text: `'Here, Venerable Sir, two bhikkhus are quarreling. One bhikkhu commits an offense. Venerable Sir, that bhikkhu confesses the offense as an offense to the other bhikkhu. The other bhikkhu does not accept it.' - 'Bhikkhus, these two bhikkhus are fools: one does not see the offense as an offense, the other does not accept the confession of the offense according to the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, these two bhikkhus are fools. Bhikkhus, these two bhikkhus are wise: one sees the offense, the other accepts the confession according to the Dhamma. Bhikkhus, these two bhikkhus are wise.<br><br>Subdue anger,<br>Preserve friendship without decay,<br>Do not revile one who should not be reviled,<br>Do not speak divisively.<br>Anger throws evil people<br>Like a stone falling into an abyss.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn11.24" },


{ text: `Bhikkhus, this body is not yours, nor is it another's. This body, bhikkhus, should be seen as produced by past action, by volition, by intention, by feeling. Here, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple wisely attends to dependent origination itself: 'When this exists, that comes to be. With the arising of this, that arises. When this does not exist, that does not come to be. With the cessation of this, that ceases.' That is: with ignorance as condition, formations arise; with formations as condition, consciousness arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. With the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease; with the cessation of formations, consciousness ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.37" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is a support for the establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is bending (nati). When there is bending, there is a going to rebirth. When there is a going to rebirth, there is coming and going. When there is coming and going, then future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Bhikkhus, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, then there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, consciousness is not established. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no bending. When there is no bending, there is no going to rebirth. When there is no going to rebirth, there is no coming and going. When there is no coming and going, then future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.40" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the origination of suffering? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. Bhikkhus, this is the origination of suffering. Dependent on the ear and sounds ... on the nose and odors ... on the tongue and tastes ... on the body and tangibles ... Dependent on the mind and mind-objects, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling arises. With feeling as condition, craving arises. Bhikkhus, this is the origination of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.43" },
{ text: `- Master Gotama, does everything exist?" - "Brahmin, 'everything exists' is the first extreme of the world." - "Master Gotama, does everything not exist?" - "'Everything does not exist' is the second extreme, brahmin." - "Master Gotama, is everything a unity?" - "'Everything is a unity' is the third extreme, brahmin." - "Master Gotama, is everything a plurality?" - "'Everything is a plurality' is the fourth extreme, brahmin." - "Brahmin, avoiding these two extremes, the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma by the middle way: 'With ignorance as condition, formations arise; with formations as condition, consciousness arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. With the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease; with the cessation of formations, consciousness ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.'" - "Wonderful, Master Gotama! ... May Master Gotama accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.48" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as an oil lamp burns dependent on oil and a wick. From time to time a man pours in oil and adjusts the wick. Bhikkhus, that oil lamp, being nourished, being supplied, would burn for a long time. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be fettered, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Bhikkhus, just as an oil lamp burns dependent on oil and a wick. Then a man does not pour in oil from time to time and does not adjust the wick. Thus, bhikkhus, that oil lamp, as its former fuel is consumed and no other fuel is supplied, being not nourished, would be extinguished. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing danger in things that can be fettered, craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.54" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a great tree, all its roots going downward and spreading out, bring sap to the tree. Bhikkhus, that great tree, being nourished, being supplied, would stand for a long time. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be clung to, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Bhikkhus, just as a great tree, a man comes with a shovel and a basket. He cuts the tree's roots ... or lets the ashes be carried away by a swift stream. Thus, bhikkhus, that great tree has its roots cut, made like a palm stump, made not to arise again, unable to live again in the future. So too, bhikkhus, one who lives seeing danger in things that can be clung to, craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.56" },
{ text: `Deep, Ānanda, is this dependent origination, and deep is its manifestation. It is because of not understanding, not penetrating this Dhamma, Ānanda, that this generation has become tangled like a ball of thread, covered with a tumor, like munja grass, like rushes, and does not escape the lower realms, the bad destinations, the plane of misery, saṃsāra. Ānanda, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be clung to, craving increases. With craving as condition, existence arises. With existence as condition, birth arises. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Ānanda, just as a great tree, all its roots going downward and spreading out, bring sap to the tree. Ānanda, that great tree, being nourished, being supplied, would stand for a long time. So too, Ānanda, one who lives seeing gratification in things that can be clung to, craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises. With clinging as condition, existence arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.60" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a person walking through a forest, a wilderness, sees an ancient path, an ancient road traveled by people of former times. He follows that path. Following it, he sees an ancient city, an ancient capital inhabited by people of former times, with parks, groves, ponds, and walls, a delightful place. Then, bhikkhus, that person reports to the king or his minister: 'Sirs, know that while walking through a forest, a wilderness, I saw an ancient path... a delightful place. Sirs, rebuild that city.' Then, bhikkhus, the king or his minister rebuilds that city. And that city, after a time, becomes prosperous, flourishing, populous, crowded with people. So too, bhikkhus, I have seen an ancient path, an ancient road traveled by the Perfectly Enlightened Ones of former times. And what, bhikkhus, is that ancient path, that ancient road? It is just this Noble Eightfold Path, that is: right view ... right concentration. This, bhikkhus, is the ancient path, the ancient road traveled by the Perfectly Enlightened Ones of former times. I followed that path. Following it, I directly knew aging and death; I directly knew the origin of aging and death; I directly knew the cessation of aging and death; I directly knew the path leading to the cessation of aging and death. I followed that path. Following it, I directly knew birth ... existence ... I directly knew the cessation of formations; I directly knew the path leading to the cessation of formations. Having directly known them, I have declared them to bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers. Bhikkhus, thus this holy life has become prosperous, flourishing, widespread, numerous, widespread, and well proclaimed among devas and humans.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.65" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhu, a great stone mountain, one yojana long, one yojana wide, one yojana high, without cracks, without fissures, a solid mass of rock. Then a person comes, and once every hundred years he wipes it with a piece of Kāsi cloth. Bhikkhu, that great stone mountain, treated thus, would wear away and perish more quickly than an eon. Thus long, bhikkhu, is an eon. And with eons thus long, more than one eon has passed, more than a hundred eons, more than a thousand eons, more than a hundred thousand eons. Why is that? This saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning ... enough to be liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 15.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn15.5" },
{ text: `Painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Gains, honor, and fame, bhikkhus, cut through the outer skin. Having cut through the outer skin, they cut through the inner skin. Having cut through the inner skin, they cut through the flesh. Having cut through the flesh, they cut through the sinews. Having cut through the sinews, they cut through the bone. Having cut through the bone, they reach the marrow and remain. Just as, bhikkhus, a strong man takes a horsehair rope, wraps it around his shin, and tightens it. That rope cuts through the outer skin, cuts through the inner skin, cuts through the flesh, cuts through the sinews, cuts through the bone, and reaches the marrow and remains. So too, bhikkhus, gains, honor, and fame cut through the outer skin ... they reach the marrow and remain. Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.29" },
{ text: `In the past, bhikkhus, in a lake, there was a family of turtles that had lived there for a long time. Then, bhikkhus, one turtle said to another: 'Dear turtle, do not go to that place.' But that turtle, bhikkhus, went to that place. A hunter hit it with a harpoon attached to a rope. Then that turtle went back to the other turtle. Bhikkhus, the other turtle, seeing him coming from afar, said: 'Dear turtle, did you go to that place?' 'Dear turtle, I went to that place.' 'Dear turtle, are you wounded, are you hit?' 'Dear turtle, I am not wounded, I am not hit. But this rope is dragging behind me.' 'Dear turtle, you are indeed wounded, you are indeed hit. Dear turtle, it was because of this hunter's device that your father and grandfather fell into misfortune and calamity. Now go, dear turtle. You are no longer one of us.' Bhikkhus, 'the hunter' is a symbol for Māra. 'The harpoon' is a symbol for gains, honor, and fame. 'The rope' is a symbol for delight and greed. Any bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who enjoys and delights in gains, honor, and fame — that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one hit by the harpoon, who has fallen into misfortune and calamity, and is at Māra's mercy. Thus, painful, bhikkhus, are gains, honor, and fame ... Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 17.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn17.3" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a spear with a sharp blade. Then a person comes and says: 'With my hand or fist, I will bend this sharp spear blade double, I will fold it back, I will twist it.' What do you think, bhikkhus, could that person, with his hand or fist, bend that sharp spear blade double, fold it back, twist it?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "Why is that?" - "Venerable Sir, it is not easy to bend that sharp spear blade double, fold it back, twist it, without causing himself fatigue and affliction." - "So too, bhikkhus, for one who develops and cultivates the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, makes it his vehicle, makes it his base, establishes it, accumulates it, and properly undertakes it — any non-human who might think he could overthrow such a mind would only get tired and afflicted. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will develop the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, cultivate it, make it our vehicle, make it our base, establish it, accumulate it, and properly undertake it.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, four strong archers, trained, skilled, proficient in archery, stand in the four directions. Then a person comes and says: 'I will catch and bring back the arrows shot by these four strong, trained, skilled archers before they fall to the ground.' What do you think, bhikkhus, would that suffice to call that person a very swift person, possessing supreme speed?" - "Venerable Sir, if he could catch and bring back one arrow shot by a single strong, trained, skilled archer, that would suffice to call him a very swift person, possessing supreme speed. What to speak of four such archers!" - "Thus, bhikkhus, is that person's speed. And thus is the speed of the moon and sun, even faster than that. And thus is the speed of those devas who run ahead of the moon and sun, even faster than that. But even faster than that is the perishing of the life force (of formations). Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will live heedfully.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 20.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn20.6" },
{ text: `Here, friends, while I was alone in seclusion, the following thought arose in my mind: 'Noble silence, noble silence is said. What is noble silence?' Then, friends, I thought: 'Here, a bhikkhu, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, enters and abides in the second jhāna, which has internal clarity and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of concentration. This is called noble silence.' Then, friends, I, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, entered and abided in the second jhāna. Friends, while I abided in this abiding, perceptions and attention accompanied by thought arose and persisted. Then, friends, the Blessed One, by psychic power, came to me and said: 'Moggallāna, Moggallāna, do not be heedless, brahmin. Regarding noble silence, establish your mind in noble silence, unify your mind in noble silence, concentrate your mind in noble silence.' Then, friends, after some time, I, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, entered and abided in the second jhāna. Friends, one speaking rightly would say: 'The disciple attained great direct knowledge through the Teacher's assistance.' Speaking rightly, one would say of me: 'The disciple attained great direct knowledge through the Teacher's assistance.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn21.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do you see that bhikkhu coming, ugly, misshapen, bent over, despised by the bhikkhus?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "That bhikkhu, bhikkhus, has great psychic power, great might. It is not easy to achieve the attainment that he has not yet attained. And he has realized for himself, by direct knowledge, in this very life, and dwells in the supreme goal of the holy life for the sake of which a good man goes forth from home to homelessness." The Blessed One said this. The Well-Gone having said this, the Teacher further said:<br><br>Swan, heron, peacock, elephant,<br>Spotted deer, all fear the lion,<br>Even though their bodies are not equal.<br><br>So too, among humans,<br>If one has wisdom,<br>That one is great there,<br>Not by body like a fool.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 21.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn21.6" },
{ text: `- Tissa, why are you sitting there distressed, sorrowful, with tears streaming?" - "Venerable Sir, the bhikkhus have been reviling and mocking me all over." - "Because, Tissa, you speak everything and cannot endure others speaking. This is not proper for you, Tissa, as a good man who has gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, that you speak everything and cannot endure others speaking. This is proper for you, Tissa, as a good man who has gone forth ... that you speak nothing and endure others speaking." The Blessed One said this. The Well-Gone having said this, the Teacher further said:<br><br>Why are you angry?<br>Do not be angry,<br>Not being angry, Tissa,<br>Is truly good for you.<br>Subdue anger, conceit, and stinginess,<br>Tissa, live the holy life.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 21.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn21.9" },
{ text: `Form, bhikkhus, is impermanent. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of form, that too is impermanent. Form arisen from what is impermanent, bhikkhus, how could it be permanent? Feeling, bhikkhus, is impermanent. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of feeling, that too is impermanent. Feeling arisen from what is impermanent, bhikkhus, how could it be permanent? Perception, bhikkhus, is impermanent ... Formations, bhikkhus, are impermanent ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is impermanent. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of consciousness, that too is impermanent. Consciousness arisen from what is impermanent, bhikkhus, how could it be permanent? Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... ' ... there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.18" },
{ text: `Form, bhikkhus, is suffering. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of form, that too is suffering. Form arisen from what is suffering, bhikkhus, how could it be happiness? Feeling, bhikkhus, is suffering ... Perception, bhikkhus, is suffering ... Formations, bhikkhus, are suffering ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is suffering. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of consciousness, that too is suffering. Consciousness arisen from what is suffering, bhikkhus, how could it be happiness? Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... ' ... there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.19" },
{ text: `'Friends, for one who has abandoned lust for form, abandoned desire, abandoned love, abandoned thirst, abandoned passion, abandoned craving for form — when that form changes and alters, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair do not arise. For one who has abandoned lust for feeling ... for perception ... for formations ... For one who has abandoned lust for consciousness, abandoned desire, abandoned love, abandoned thirst, abandoned passion, abandoned craving for consciousness — when that consciousness changes and alters, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair do not arise. Seeing this benefit, friends, our Teacher speaks of the removal of desire and lust for form ... for feeling ... for perception ... for formations; our Teacher speaks of the removal of desire and lust for consciousness.' And, friends, because he attains and abides in wholesome states, and in this very life lives happily, without obstruction, without distress, without fever, and after death, with the breakup of the body, is reborn in a good destination — therefore this is the achievement of wholesome states praised by the Blessed One.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.2" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I have searched for the gratification of form. Whatever gratification there is in form, I have found it. I have seen with wisdom how the gratification of form is. Bhikkhus, I have searched for the danger of form. Whatever danger there is in form, I have found it. I have seen with wisdom how the danger of form is. Bhikkhus, I have searched for the escape from form. Whatever escape there is from form, I have found it. I have seen with wisdom how the escape from form is. Bhikkhus, I have searched for the gratification of feeling ... of perception ... of formations ... Bhikkhus, I have searched for the gratification of consciousness. Whatever gratification there is in consciousness, I have found it. I have seen with wisdom how the gratification of consciousness is. Bhikkhus, I have searched for the danger of consciousness ... the escape from consciousness ... I have seen with wisdom how the escape from consciousness is. Bhikkhus, as long as I did not directly know as they actually are, regarding these five aggregates of clinging, the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, I did not declare ... samaṇas, brahmins, devas, and humans. Then the knowledge and vision arose in me: 'My mind is liberated, unshakable. This is the last birth, now there is no further existence.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.27" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one who delights in form delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. Bhikkhus, one who delights in feeling ... in perception ... in formations ... in consciousness delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. And, bhikkhus, one who does not delight in form does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. And, bhikkhus, one who does not delight in feeling ... in perception ... in formations ... in consciousness does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.29" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, it is through attachment that one is not liberated. Through attachment to form, bhikkhus, consciousness, having a foothold, becomes established. With form as object, with form as support, seeking delight, it comes to growth, increase, and expansion. Through attachment to feeling ... through attachment to perception ... through attachment to formations, bhikkhus, consciousness, having a foothold, becomes established. With formations as object, with formations as support, seeking delight, it comes to growth, increase, and expansion. Bhikkhus, one who says: 'Apart from form, apart from feeling, apart from perception, apart from formations, I will describe the coming and going, the passing away and arising, the growth, increase, and expansion of consciousness' — that is impossible. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has abandoned lust for the form element, with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, and the support of consciousness does not exist. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has abandoned lust for the feeling element ... for the perception element ... for the formation element ... Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has abandoned lust for the consciousness element, with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, and the support of consciousness does not exist. Without that support, consciousness does not grow, does not form, is liberated. Through liberation, it is steady. Through steadiness, it is content. Through contentment, it is not distressed. Not distressed, he personally attains Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.53" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five kinds of seeds. What five? Root-seeds, stem-seeds, joint-seeds, cutting-seeds, and seed-seeds as the fifth. Bhikkhus, if these five kinds of seeds are not broken, not rotten, not damaged by wind and sun, are fertile, well planted, but there is no earth and no water, would these five kinds of seeds be able to grow, increase, and expand?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "Bhikkhus, if these five kinds of seeds are not broken, not rotten, not damaged by wind and sun, are fertile, well planted, and there is earth and water, would these five kinds of seeds be able to grow, increase, and expand?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "Bhikkhus, the earth element should be seen as the four stations of consciousness. Bhikkhus, the water element should be seen as delight and greed. Bhikkhus, the five kinds of seeds should be seen as consciousness together with its nutriment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.54" },
{ text: `Through attachment to form, bhikkhus, consciousness, having a foothold, becomes established. With form as object, with form as support, seeking delight, it comes to growth, increase, and expansion. Through attachment to feeling ... through attachment to perception ... through attachment to formations, bhikkhus, consciousness, having a foothold, becomes established. With formations as object, with formations as support, seeking delight, it comes to growth, increase, and expansion. Bhikkhus, one who says: 'Apart from form, apart from feeling, apart from perception, apart from formations, I will describe the coming and going, the passing away and arising, the growth, increase, and expansion of consciousness' — that is impossible. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has abandoned lust for the form element, with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, and the support of consciousness does not exist. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has abandoned lust for the feeling element ... for the perception element ... for the formation element ... for the consciousness element, with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, and the support of consciousness does not exist. Without that support, consciousness does not grow, does not form, is liberated. Through liberation, it is steady. Through steadiness, it is content. Through contentment, it is not distressed. Not distressed, he personally attains Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.54" },
{ text: `Form, bhikkhus, is not-self. Bhikkhus, if form were self, then form would not lead to affliction, and one could have it of form: 'Let my form be thus, let my form not be thus.' But because form is not-self, it leads to affliction, and one cannot have it of form: 'Let my form be thus, let my form not be thus.' Feeling, bhikkhus, is not-self ... Perception is not-self ... Formations are not-self ... Consciousness, bhikkhus, is not-self. If consciousness were self, then consciousness would not lead to affliction, and one could have it of consciousness: 'Let my consciousness be thus, let my consciousness not be thus.' But because consciousness is not-self, it leads to affliction, and one cannot have it of consciousness: 'Let my consciousness be thus, let my consciousness not be thus.' Therefore, bhikkhus, whatever form, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all form should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Whatever feeling ... whatever perception ... whatever formations ... Whatever consciousness, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all consciousness should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Seeing this, bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.59" },
{ text: `- Mahāli, there is a cause, a condition for the defilement of beings. Mahāli, there is a cause, a condition for the purification of beings. - Venerable Sir, what is the cause, what is the condition for the defilement of beings?" - "Mahāli, if form were exclusively suffering, immersed in suffering, not immersed in happiness, beings would not become attached to form. But because, Mahāli, form is happiness, immersed in happiness, not immersed in suffering, beings become attached to form. Through attachment, they are fettered. Through being fettered, they become defiled. Mahāli, this is the cause, this is the condition for the defilement of beings. Thus, through this cause, through this condition, beings become defiled.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.60" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, what is the cause, what is the condition for the purification of beings?" - "Mahāli, if form were exclusively happiness, immersed in happiness, not immersed in suffering, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because, Mahāli, form is suffering, immersed in suffering, not immersed in happiness, beings become disenchanted with form. Through disenchantment, they become detached. Through detachment, they are purified. Mahāli, this is the cause, this is the condition for the purification of beings. Thus, through this cause, through this condition, beings become purified. Mahāli, if feeling were exclusively happiness ... if perception were exclusively happiness ... if formations were exclusively happiness ... if consciousness were exclusively happiness, immersed in happiness, not immersed in suffering, beings would not become disenchanted with consciousness. But because, Mahāli, consciousness is suffering, immersed in suffering, not immersed in happiness, beings become disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, they become detached. Through detachment, they are purified. Mahāli, this is the cause, this is the condition for the purification of beings. Thus, through this cause, through this condition, beings become purified.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.60" },
{ text: `'One who clings, bhikkhu, is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One.' - 'Venerable Sir, I understand. Well-Gone Sir, I understand.' - 'How, bhikkhu, do you understand in detail the meaning of my brief statement?' - 'Venerable Sir, one who clings to form is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. One who clings to feeling ... to perception ... to formations ... to consciousness is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. Venerable Sir, this is how I understand in detail the meaning of the Blessed One's brief statement.' - 'Good, good, bhikkhu! It is good that you understand thus the meaning of my brief statement. One who clings to form, bhikkhu, is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. One who clings to feeling ... to perception ... to formations ... to consciousness is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.63" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person does not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of form. Of feeling ... of perception ... of formations ... He does not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of consciousness. Bhikkhus, a learned noble disciple truly understands the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of form. Of feeling ... of perception ... of formations ... He truly understands the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of consciousness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.74" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, form is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Feeling ... perception ... formations ... Consciousness is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it actually is with right wisdom: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Bhikkhus, seeing this, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form ... with feeling ... with perception ... with formations ... with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'<br><br>Happy are the Arahants,<br>In whom craving is no more,<br>Conceit well cut off,<br>The net of delusion shattered.<br><br>They have attained the unshakable,<br>Their minds are far from stains,<br>Not stained by the world,<br>The taint-free Brahmās.<br><br>Fully understanding the five aggregates,<br>Practicing the seven good qualities,<br>Praised by the true persons,<br>Born as sons of the Buddha.<br><br>Possessing seven jewels,<br>Trained in the three trainings,<br>The great heroes wander,<br>Having ended all fear.<br><br>Possessing ten powers,<br>The bull-elephant, meditative,<br>They are supreme in the world,<br>Craving is destroyed.<br><br>Possessing learner's knowledge,<br>This body is their last,<br>The ultimate of the holy life,<br>Attained by themselves, not by others.<br><br>Unmoved by perceptions,<br>Liberated from rebirth,<br>Having attained the tamed state,<br>They are victorious in the world.<br><br>Above, below, and across,<br>They have no delight,<br>They roar the lion's roar,<br>The unsurpassed Buddhas in the world!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.76" },
{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, when a Tathāgata appears in the world, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One ... Teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One. He teaches the Dhamma: 'This is form, this is the arising of form, this is the cessation of form, this is the path leading to the cessation of form. This is feeling ... This is perception ... These are formations ... This is consciousness, this is the arising of consciousness, this is the cessation of consciousness, this is the path leading to the cessation of consciousness.' Bhikkhus, there are devas of long life, of great beauty, enjoying much happiness, living long in great mansions. These devas, having heard the Tathāgata's teaching, for the most part become fearful, terrified, and agitated. They think: 'We are impermanent, sirs, but we thought we were permanent. We are not everlasting, sirs, but we thought we were everlasting. We are not eternal, sirs, but we thought we were eternal. Sirs, we are impermanent, not everlasting, not eternal, included within this body.' Thus, bhikkhus, such is the Tathāgata's great psychic power over devas and the deva world, such is his great might, such is his great influence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.78" },
{ text: `When feeling a pleasant feeling, he understands: 'It is impermanent'; he understands: 'It is not to be clung to'; he understands: 'It is not to be delighted in.' When feeling a painful feeling, he understands: 'It is impermanent'; he understands: 'It is not to be clung to'; he understands: 'It is not to be delighted in.' When feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands: 'It is impermanent'; he understands: 'It is not to be clung to'; he understands: 'It is not to be delighted in.' If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it without being attached. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it without being attached. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it without being attached. When he feels a feeling ending with the body, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with the body.' When he feels a feeling ending with life, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with life.' He understands: 'With the breakup of the body after death, when life ends, here whatever is felt, whatever is delighted in, will become cool!' Just as, Assaji, an oil lamp burns dependent on oil and a wick. When the oil and wick of that lamp are consumed and no other fuel is supplied, that lamp is extinguished. So too, Assaji, when a bhikkhu feels a feeling ending with the body, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with the body.' When he feels a feeling ending with life, he understands: 'I feel a feeling ending with life.' With the breakup of the body after death, when life ends, here whatever is felt, whatever is delighted in, will become cool!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.88" },


{ text: `This world, Kaccāna, relies on two (views): existence and non-existence. One who sees with right wisdom the arising of the world as it actually is does not hold that the world is non-existent. But, Kaccāna, one who sees with right wisdom the cessation of the world as it actually is does not hold that the world exists. For the most part, Kaccāna, this world is engaged in clinging to means and bound by bias. For one who does not approach, cling to, or abide in the clinging to means, whose mind does not abide in the underlying tendency to bias, that one does not say: 'This is my self.' For one who thinks that what arises is suffering and what ceases is suffering, there is no doubt, no perplexity. Here, knowledge does not depend on another. To that extent, Kaccāna, there is right knowledge. 'Everything exists,' Kaccāna, is one extreme. 'Everything does not exist' is the second extreme. Avoiding these two extremes, Kaccāna, the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma by the middle way. With ignorance as condition, formations arise. With formations as condition, consciousness arises ... Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. With the complete fading away and cessation of ignorance, formations cease ... Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.90" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One took a little dust on his fingernail and said to that bhikkhu: 'Bhikkhu, even this little form is not permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, not forever permanent, eternal. If even this little form, bhikkhu, were permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, forever permanent, eternal, then the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering could not be taught. But because even this little form, bhikkhu, is impermanent, not everlasting, not eternal, subject to change, not forever permanent, eternal, therefore the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering can be taught.' What do you think, bhikkhu? Is form permanent or impermanent?' - 'Impermanent, Venerable Sir.' - 'Feeling ... perception ... formations ... consciousness, is it permanent or impermanent?' - 'Impermanent, Venerable Sir.' - 'Therefore ... seeing thus ... there is no further existence after this life. He understands thus.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.97" },
{ text: `'Māra, Māra,' Venerable Sir, is said. What is Māra, Venerable Sir?" - "Form, Rādha, is Māra. Feeling is Māra. Perception is Māra. Formations are Māra. Consciousness is Māra. Seeing this, Rādha, a learned noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Through disenchantment, he becomes detached; through detachment, he is liberated. In liberation, the knowledge arises: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.11" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the eye is impermanent, changing, altering. The ear is impermanent, changing, altering. The nose is impermanent, changing, altering. The tongue is impermanent, changing, altering. The body is impermanent, changing, altering. The mind is impermanent, changing, altering. Bhikkhus, one who has faith and conviction in these things is called a faith-follower, who has entered the fixed course of rightness, entered the plane of true persons, transcended the plane of ordinary persons. He cannot do any action that would cause him to be reborn in hell, the animal realm, or the ghost realm; he cannot pass away without realizing the fruit of stream-entry. One who, with wisdom, has a degree of acceptance of these things is called a Dhamma-follower, who has entered the fixed course of rightness, entered the plane of true persons, transcended the plane of ordinary persons. He cannot do any action that would cause him to be reborn in hell, the animal realm, or the ghost realm; he cannot pass away without realizing the fruit of stream-entry. One who knows and sees these things as they are is called a stream-enterer, no longer subject to falling, bound for enlightenment.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 25.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn25.1" },
{ text: `Those samaṇas or brahmins, sister, who live by wrong livelihood such as geomancy and low arts — those, sister, are called samaṇas and brahmins who eat with their heads bent down. Those samaṇas or brahmins, sister, who live by wrong livelihood such as astrology and low arts — those, sister, are called samaṇas and brahmins who eat looking up. Those samaṇas or brahmins, sister, who live by wrong livelihood such as carrying messages and acting as go-betweens — those, sister, are called samaṇas and brahmins who eat facing the four main directions. Those samaṇas or brahmins, sister, who live by wrong livelihood such as fortune-telling and low arts — those, sister, are called samaṇas and brahmins who eat facing the four intermediate directions. But I, sister, do not live by wrong livelihood such as geomancy and low arts; I do not live by wrong livelihood such as astrology and low arts; I do not live by wrong livelihood such as carrying messages and acting as go-betweens; I do not live by wrong livelihood such as fortune-telling and low arts. I seek food lawfully. Having sought food lawfully, I use that food." Then the female wanderer Sucimukhī went from street to street, from crossroad to crossroad in Rājagaha, and proclaimed: "The Sakyan samaṇas use food lawfully. The Sakyan samaṇas use food blamelessly. Give alms to the Sakyan samaṇas!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 28.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn28.10" },
{ text: `- Great King, there are four kinds of young people who should not be despised or looked down upon because they are young. What four? Great King, a young noble warrior should not be despised or looked down upon because he is young. Great King, a young snake should not be despised or looked down upon because it is young. Great King, a young fire should not be despised or looked down upon because it is young. Great King, a young bhikkhu should not be despised or looked down upon because he is young. Great King, these four kinds of young people should not be despised or looked down upon because they are young.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.1" },
{ text: `The young man Sudassana, having assented to King Pasenadi of Kosala, learned this verse from the Blessed One, and while serving food to King Pasenadi of Kosala, recited this verse:<br><br>'One who is always mindful,<br>Moderate in eating,<br>Feels less discomfort,<br>Ages slowly, and lives long.'<br><br>Then King Pasenadi of Kosala gradually reduced his intake until he ate at most one nālika of rice. After some time, the king's body became healthy. Rubbing his limbs with his own hands, he uttered this inspired utterance: 'Oh, indeed the Blessed One has shown compassion for me, for my welfare both in this life and the next!'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.13" },
{ text: `Thinking of their own good,<br>They rob and harm others,<br>When others rob and harm them,<br>The robber becomes the robbed.<br><br>The fool thinks thus,<br>When evil is not yet ripe,<br>When evil becomes ripe,<br>The fool experiences suffering.<br><br>Killing, one is killed,<br>Conquering, one is conquered,<br>Abusing, one is abused,<br>Harassing, one is harassed,<br>Thus action evolves,<br>The robber becomes the robbed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.15" },
{ text: `Like cool, clear water<br>Lying in a deserted place,<br>With no one to drink or use it,<br>It goes to waste.<br>So too, the wealth of a low person,<br>Who does not enjoy it himself,<br>Nor gives to anyone.<br><br>The wise person, clear-seeing,<br>Having acquired wealth,<br>Knows how to use and serve<br>Relatives and companions,<br>Becomes like a bull leader,<br>Nurturing and helping,<br>Blameless at death,<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.19" },
{ text: `- Where, Venerable Sir, should a gift be given?" - "Great King, wherever the mind finds confidence." - "Venerable Sir, where does a gift yield great fruit?" - "Great King, the question 'Where should a gift be given?' is one thing, and the question 'Where does a gift yield great fruit?' is another. Great King, giving to a virtuous one yields great fruit, not so to an immoral one. Regarding this, Great King, I will ask you a question; answer as you like. What do you think, Great King? Here, Great King, you are engaged in battle, and a fierce battle is raging. Then a young noble warrior comes, unlearned, untrained, unpracticed, inexperienced, timid, fearful, terrified. Would you accept him, would you employ him? Would such a one be of any use to you?" - "No, Venerable Sir, I would not accept him, nor would such a one be of any use to me." - "What do you think, Great King? Here, you are engaged in battle, and a fierce battle is raging. Then a young noble warrior comes, learned, trained, practiced, experienced, not timid, not fearful, not terrified. Would you accept him, would you employ him? Would such a one be of any use to you?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir, I would accept him, and such a one would be of use to me." - "So too, Great King, whether one has gone forth from any family, from home to homelessness, if he has abandoned five factors and possesses five factors, giving to such a person yields great fruit. What five factors are abandoned? Sensual desire is abandoned, ill-will is abandoned, sloth and torpor are abandoned, restlessness and remorse are abandoned, doubt is abandoned. These five factors are abandoned. What five factors are possessed? The aggregate of noble virtue is possessed, the aggregate of noble concentration is possessed, the aggregate of noble wisdom is possessed, the aggregate of noble liberation is possessed, the aggregate of noble knowledge and vision of liberation is possessed. These five factors are possessed. Giving to such a person, who has abandoned five factors and possesses five factors, yields great fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.24" },
{ text: `Great King, those who live doing evil with body, speech, and mind — for them, the self is an enemy. Even if they say: 'The self is dear to us,' still the self is an enemy to them. Why is that? Whatever an enemy does to an enemy, their self does to their self. Therefore, for them, the self is an enemy. Great King, those who live doing good with body, speech, and mind — for them, the self is a friend. Even if they say: 'The self is an enemy to us,' still the self is a friend to them. Why is that? Whatever a friend does to a friend, their self does to their self. Therefore, for them, the self is a friend.<br><br>'If one knows,<br>The self is dear,<br>One would not engage,<br>In evil deeds.<br><br>One who does evil deeds,<br>Hardly finds true happiness,<br>Captured by Death,<br>Leaving the human body.<br>For one with such deeds,<br>What is one's own?<br>What does one take?<br>What follows one,<br>Like a shadow following a form?<br><br>Here the dying one,<br>Does both meritorious and evil deeds,<br>Takes both away.<br>Both belong to that one,<br>Like a shadow following a form.<br><br>Both follow that one,<br>Therefore do good,<br>Store up for the next life,<br>Merit for the next life,<br>Is a support for beings.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.4" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four types of meditators. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a certain meditator is skilled in concentration as an attainment in concentration, but not skilled in concentration as a duration in concentration. Here, a certain meditator is skilled in concentration as a duration in concentration, but not skilled in concentration as an attainment in concentration. Here, a certain meditator is skilled neither in concentration as an attainment nor in concentration as a duration. Here, a certain meditator is skilled both in concentration as an attainment and in concentration as a duration. Among these four meditators, the one who is skilled both in attainment and in duration is the foremost, best, chief, highest, and most excellent. Just as, bhikkhus, from a cow comes milk; from milk comes curds; from curds comes butter; from butter comes ghee; from ghee comes the cream of ghee, which is called the foremost. So too, bhikkhus, among these four meditators, the one skilled both in attainment and in duration is the foremost, best, chief, highest, and most excellent.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 34.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn34.1" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, practice seclusion. A bhikkhu who is secluded, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are. And what does he understand as they actually are? He understands the eye as actually impermanent, he understands forms as actually impermanent, he understands eye-consciousness as actually impermanent, he understands eye-contact as actually impermanent ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he understands that feeling as actually impermanent. Bhikkhus, practice seclusion. A bhikkhu who is secluded, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.100" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, whatever is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. And what, bhikkhus, is not yours? The eye, bhikkhus, is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Forms are not yours, abandon them. Abandoning them will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Eye-consciousness is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Eye-contact is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Just as, bhikkhus, if someone in this Jeta's Grove were to take away, burn, or do whatever they wished with all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves, would you think: 'That person takes us away, burns us, or does whatever they wish with us'?" - "No, Venerable Sir." - "Why is that?" - "Because that is not our self nor what belongs to our self." - "So too, bhikkhus, the eye is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness. Forms ... eye-consciousness ... eye-contact ... Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your long-term welfare and happiness.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.101" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has gone to Māra's abode, who has been conquered by Māra. Māra's snare has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is at the Evil One's mercy. Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and abides without attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has not gone to Māra's abode, who has not been conquered by Māra. Māra's snare has not surrounded him. Freed from Māra's bondage, he is not at the Evil One's mercy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.114" },
{ text: `- A fellow bhikkhu, Venerable Sāriputta, has given up the training and returned to the lower life." - "Friend, that happens to one who does not guard the sense faculties, does not know moderation in eating, and is not devoted to wakefulness. 'Friend, a bhikkhu who does not guard the sense faculties, does not know moderation in eating, and is not devoted to wakefulness — for life, that one could live the holy life completely pure — that is impossible.' 'Friend, a bhikkhu who guards the sense faculties, knows moderation in eating, and is devoted to wakefulness — for life, that one could live the holy life completely pure — that is possible. Therefore, friend, you should train thus: "We will guard the sense faculties, know moderation in eating, and be devoted to wakefulness." Thus, friend, you should train.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120" },
{ text: `Devas and humans, bhikkhus, delight in form, are excited by form. When form changes, fades away, and ceases, bhikkhus, devas and humans live in suffering. Devas and humans, bhikkhus, delight in sound ... in odor ... in taste ... in touch ... Devas and humans, bhikkhus, delight in mind-objects, are excited by mind-objects. When mind-objects change, fade away, and cease, bhikkhus, devas and humans live in suffering.<br><br>'Form, sound, odor, taste, touch,<br>And all mind-objects,<br>Desirable, lovely, agreeable —<br>Thus they are called.<br><br>Devas and humans<br>Consider them delightful.<br>Where they cease,<br>Devas and humans see suffering.<br><br>The noble one sees happiness<br>When identity view ceases.<br>The noble one sees the opposite<br>Of all the world's views.<br><br>What people call happiness,<br>The noble one calls suffering.<br>What people call suffering,<br>The noble one knows as happiness.<br><br>Seeing the Dhamma hard to discern,<br>The ignorant are confused.<br>Darkness for the ignorant,<br>Blindness for those who do not see.<br><br>The wise one is open,<br>Like light fully illuminating,<br>The fool, though near,<br>Does not understand the Dhamma.<br><br>Overcome by the thirst for becoming,<br>Swept away by the stream of existence,<br>Controlled by Māra,<br>They do not awaken to this Dhamma.<br><br>Apart from the noble ones, no one<br>Awakens to this path,<br>The path to Nibbāna,<br>With right knowledge, free from taints.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136" },
{ text: `- Venerable Sir, it would be good if the Blessed One would teach me the Dhamma in brief. Having heard the Dhamma from the Blessed One, I will live alone, secluded, heedful, ardent, and resolute." - "What is suffering, Koṭṭhita, therein you should abandon desire. What, Koṭṭhita, is suffering? The eye is suffering, therein you should abandon desire. Forms are suffering, therein you should abandon desire. Eye-consciousness is suffering, therein you should abandon desire. Eye-contact is suffering, therein you should abandon desire. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is suffering, therein you should abandon desire.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.163" },
{ text: `If there were no gratification in form, bhikkhus, beings would not become attached to form. But because there is gratification in form, bhikkhus, beings become attached to form. If there were no danger in form, bhikkhus, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because there is danger in form, bhikkhus, beings become disenchanted with form. If there were no escape from form, bhikkhus, beings could not escape from form. But because there is escape from form, bhikkhus, beings escape from form. As long as beings, regarding these six internal bases, have not directly known the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then, bhikkhus, those beings, together with the worlds of devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with the generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, have not lived with a mind detached, free from entanglement, liberated, without boundaries. And because beings, regarding these six internal bases, have directly known the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, therefore, bhikkhus, those beings, together with the worlds of devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with the generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, have lived with a mind detached, free from entanglement, liberated, without boundaries.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.18" },
{ text: `One who delights in the eye, bhikkhus, delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who delights in the ear ... in the nose ... One who delights in the tongue, bhikkhus, delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who delights in the body ... One who delights in the mind, delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. And one who does not delight in the eye, bhikkhus, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in the ear ... in the nose ... One who does not delight in the tongue, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in the body ... One who does not delight in the mind, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.19" },
{ text: `'The ocean, the ocean,' bhikkhus, says an unlearned ordinary person. That, bhikkhus, is not the ocean in the Noble One's Discipline. That is just a great mass of water, a great flood. Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. This, bhikkhus, is not called the ocean in the Noble One's Discipline. Here, this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, for the most part sink into them, become tangled like a ball of thread, covered like a wound, become like a grass rope, unable to cross the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra!<br><br>'When ignorance, greed, and hatred cease,<br>This ocean, full of terrible creatures,<br>With various monsters, whirlpools, and dangerous waves,<br>Is very hard to cross.<br><br>Crossing the bond, escaping death,<br>Without any attachment,<br>Ending all suffering,<br>No further rebirth.<br><br>Birth and death are ended,<br>The incomparable one,<br>I say that one<br>Has blinded Death.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.229", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.229" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a fisherman casts a baited hook into a deep lake. A fish, looking at the bait, swallows the hook. Thus, bhikkhus, that fish, having swallowed the fisherman's hook, falls into misfortune, into calamity, and is at the fisherman's mercy. So too, bhikkhus, there are these six hooks in the world, bringing misfortune to beings, bringing calamity to creatures. What six? Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has swallowed Māra's hook, who has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is at the Evil One's mercy. ... There are sounds cognizable by the ear ... odors cognizable by the nose ... tastes cognizable by the tongue ... tangibles cognizable by the body ... There are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has swallowed Māra's hook, who has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is at the Evil One's mercy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.230", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.230" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and abides without attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has not swallowed Māra's hook, who has broken the hook, smashed the hook, who has not fallen into misfortune, not into calamity, and is not at the Evil One's mercy. Bhikkhus, there are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... tangibles ... Bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu does not delight in those mind-objects, does not praise them, and abides without attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who has not swallowed Māra's hook, who has broken the hook, smashed the hook, who has not fallen into misfortune, not into calamity, and is not at the Evil One's mercy.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.230", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.230" },
{ text: `Craving, bhikkhus, is a disease; craving is a boil; craving is a dart. Therefore, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata lives without craving, without being wounded by the dart. Therefore, bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu has any wish, let him wish to live without craving, without being wounded by the dart. Do not conceive the eye, do not conceive in the eye, do not conceive from the eye, do not conceive: 'The eye is mine.' Do not conceive forms, do not conceive in forms, do not conceive from forms, do not conceive: 'Forms are mine.' Do not conceive eye-consciousness, do not conceive in eye-consciousness, do not conceive from eye-consciousness, do not conceive: 'Eye-consciousness is mine.' Do not conceive eye-contact, do not conceive in eye-contact, do not conceive from eye-contact, do not conceive: 'Eye-contact is mine.' Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact, whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — do not conceive that feeling, do not conceive in that feeling, do not conceive from that feeling, do not conceive: 'That feeling is mine.' Through not conceiving, he does not cling to anything in the world. Not clinging, he is not agitated. Not agitated, he personally attains complete Nibbāna. He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no further existence after this life.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.90" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is non-restraint? And, bhikkhus, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those forms, praises them, and abides with attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls decline. ... And, bhikkhus, there are sounds ... odors ... tastes ... And, bhikkhus, there are mind-objects cognizable by the mind that are desirable, lovely, agreeable, pleasing, connected with sensual desire, enticing. If a bhikkhu delights in those mind-objects, praises them, and abides with attachment, then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should understand: 'I am declining from wholesome states.' This the Tathāgata calls decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is non-restraint.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I declare that the stilling of formations is gradual. When one attains the first jhāna, speech is stilled ... For a bhikkhu with taints destroyed, greed is stilled, hatred is stilled, delusion is stilled. Bhikkhus, there are six kinds of tranquility. When one attains the first jhāna, speech is tranquil. When one attains the second jhāna, initial and sustained thought are tranquil. When one attains the third jhāna, rapture is tranquil. When one attains the fourth jhāna, in-breath and out-breath are tranquil. When one attains the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling are tranquil. For a bhikkhu with taints destroyed, greed is tranquil, hatred is tranquil, delusion is tranquil.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.17" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who do not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of these three feelings — these, bhikkhus, I do not call samaṇas or brahmins. Because they do not realize the goal of samaṇa-hood or brahmin-hood, they do not truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of these three feelings. Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who truly understand the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape of these three feelings — these, bhikkhus, I call samaṇas or brahmins. Because they realize the goal of samaṇa-hood or brahmin-hood, with direct knowledge, they personally realize, attain, and abide in the Dhamma.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.27" },
{ text: `Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a woman, after death, with the breakup of the body, is mostly reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a woman, in the morning, lives at home with a mind obsessed by stinginess and miserliness; at noon, lives at home with a mind obsessed by envy and jealousy; in the evening, lives at home with a mind obsessed by sensual desire. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a woman, after death, with the breakup of the body, is mostly reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 37.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn37.4" },
{ text: `'Nibbāna, Nibbāna,' friend Sāriputta, is said. What, friend, is Nibbāna?" - "Friend, the destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion — this is called Nibbāna." - "Is there a path, is there a way, friend, leading to the realization of Nibbāna?" - "There is a path, there is a way, friend, leading to the realization of Nibbāna." - "What, friend, is that path, that way?" - "Friend, this Noble Eightfold Path is the path leading to the realization of Nibbāna, that is, right view ... right concentration. Friend, this is the path, this is the way leading to the realization of Nibbāna." - "Excellent, friend, is the path, excellent is the way leading to the realization of Nibbāna. It is enough, friend, to be heedful.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 38.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn38.1" },
{ text: `'Attaining the calming of breathing, attaining the calming of breathing,' friend Sāriputta, is said. To what extent, friend, is the calming of breathing attained?" - "Friend, when a bhikkhu truly understands as they actually are the arising, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape regarding the six sense-spheres — to that extent is the calming of breathing attained." - "Is there a path, is there a way, friend, leading to the attainment of that calming of breathing?" - "There is a path, there is a way, friend, leading to the attainment of that calming of breathing." - "What, friend, is that path, that way?" - "Friend, this Noble Eightfold Path is the path, the way leading to the attainment of that calming of breathing, that is, right view ... right concentration. Friend, this is the path, this is the way leading to the attainment of that calming of breathing." - "Excellent, friend, is the path, excellent is the way leading to the attainment of that calming of breathing. It is enough, friend Sāriputta, to be heedful.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 38.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn38.5" },
{ text: `- Friend Sāriputta, in this Dhamma and Discipline, what is difficult to do?" - "Going forth, friend, is difficult to do in this Dhamma and Discipline." - "For one who has gone forth, friend, what is difficult to do?" - "For one who has gone forth, friend, delight is difficult to do." - "For one who delights, friend, what is difficult to do?" - "For one who delights, friend, the practice in accordance with the Dhamma is difficult to do." - "For one practicing in accordance with the Dhamma, friend, how long before one becomes an Arahant?" - "Not long, friend.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 39.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn39.16" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the life span of humans in this world is short, and one must go to the future. Do good deeds, live the holy life. There is nothing that is born that does not die. Bhikkhus, one who lives long lives only a hundred years, or a little more or less." Then Māra approached the Blessed One and spoke this verse to him:<br><br>'Day and night do not pass,<br>Life span does not end,<br>The life of humans turns around<br>Like a chariot wheel around its axle.'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>'Day and night do pass,<br>Life span does end,<br>The lives of people dry up<br>Like small streams on a mountain.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.10" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One was sitting in the open air, in the pitch dark, and it was raining in droplets. Then Māra, wanting to cause fear, terror, and hair-raising to the Blessed One, approached him, and not far from the Blessed One, he sent down great boulders. Then the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to him:<br><br>'Even if you shake<br>The whole of Vulture's Peak,<br>You cannot shake<br>The Enlightened One, the Liberated.'<br><br>Then Māra, knowing 'The Blessed One knows me, the Well-Gone knows me,' sad and disappointed, disappeared right there.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.11" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One was sitting in the open air, in the pitch dark, and it was raining in droplets. Then Māra, wanting to cause fear, terror, and hair-raising to the Blessed One, approached him. Having approached, not far from the Blessed One, he manifested various forms, both high and low, beautiful and ugly. Then the Blessed One, knowing it was Māra, spoke this verse to him:<br><br>'You have wandered for a long time,<br>In forms beautiful and ugly.<br>Enough, Evil One,<br>You are defeated.<br><br>Those who in body, speech, and mind,<br>Are well restrained and tamed,<br>O Evil One, those ones,<br>Are not under your power,<br>Nor are they your disciples.'<br><br>Then Māra, knowing ... disappeared right there.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.3" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if wanderers of other sects should ask you: 'For what purpose, friends, is the holy life lived under Samaṇa Gotama?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those wanderers: 'For the purpose of the destruction of greed, friends, the holy life is lived under Samaṇa Gotama.' Bhikkhus, if then those wanderers ask you: 'Is there a path, is there a way, friends, leading to the destruction of greed?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those wanderers: 'There is a path, there is a way leading to the destruction of greed.' And what, bhikkhus, is that path, that way? It is this Noble Eightfold Path, that is, right view ... right concentration. Bhikkhus, this is the path, this is the way leading to the destruction of greed. Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those wanderers in this way.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.41" },
{ text: `- Cunda, speak on the enlightenment factors." - "Venerable Sir, there are these seven enlightenment factors rightly taught by the Blessed One, which, when developed and cultivated, lead to direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. What seven? Venerable Sir, the mindfulness enlightenment factor rightly taught by the Blessed One, when developed and cultivated, leads to direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna ... Venerable Sir, the equanimity enlightenment factor rightly taught by the Blessed One, when developed and cultivated, leads to direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. Venerable Sir, these seven enlightenment factors rightly taught by the Blessed One, when developed and cultivated, lead to direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna." - "Indeed, Cunda, they are enlightenment factors. Indeed, Cunda, they are enlightenment factors." The Venerable Mahācunda spoke thus, and the Teacher approved. And the Blessed One recovered from that illness. That illness of the Blessed One was thus ended.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.16" },
{ text: `- What, bhikkhus, is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, or for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire? There is the sign of beauty, bhikkhus. Here, if one gives unwise attention to it repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, and for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire. What, bhikkhus, is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen ill-will, or for the growth and increase of arisen ill-will? There is the sign of aversion, bhikkhus. Here, if one gives unwise attention to it repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen ill-will, and for the growth and increase of arisen ill-will. What, bhikkhus, is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sloth and torpor, or for the growth and increase of arisen sloth and torpor? There are lack of gladness, laziness, sluggishness, overeating, and mental recoil, bhikkhus. Here, if one gives unwise attention to them repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen sloth and torpor, and for the growth and increase of arisen sloth and torpor. What, bhikkhus, is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen restlessness and remorse, or for the growth and increase of arisen restlessness and remorse? There is an unstill mind, bhikkhus. Here, if one gives unwise attention to it repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen restlessness and remorse, and for the growth and increase of arisen restlessness and remorse. What, bhikkhus, is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen doubt, or for the growth and increase of arisen doubt? There are things that are the basis for doubt, bhikkhus. Here, if one gives unwise attention to them repeatedly, that is the nutriment for the arising of unarisen doubt, and for the growth and increase of arisen doubt.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.51" },
{ text: `And, Ānanda, how is a bhikkhu an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as his island, the Dhamma as his refuge, with no other refuge? Ānanda, here a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world; he dwells contemplating feelings as feelings ... mind as mind ... phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Ānanda, that is how a bhikkhu is an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as his island, the Dhamma as his refuge, with no other refuge. Ānanda, those who now or after my passing are islands unto themselves, refuges unto themselves, with no other refuge, having the Dhamma as their island, the Dhamma as their refuge, with no other refuge — these, Ānanda, will be the foremost among my bhikkhus, if they are eager to learn.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.9" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated so as to perfect the four foundations of mindfulness? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, sits down, folding his legs crosswise, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. Mindfully he breathes in, mindfully he breathes out ... 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe out,' he trains. Whenever, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu breathing in long understands: 'I breathe in long'; or breathing out long, he understands: 'I breathe out long' ... breathing in short, he understands: 'I breathe in short'; breathing out short, he understands: 'I breathe out short' ... 'Experiencing the whole body, I will breathe in,' he trains ... 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Tranquilizing the bodily formation, I will breathe out,' he trains. At that time, bhikkhus, dwelling contemplating the body as a body, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world. Why is that? Bhikkhus, I say that this is a certain body, namely, in-breath and out-breath. Therefore, bhikkhus, at that time, dwelling contemplating the body as a body, a bhikkhu abides ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and displeasure in regard to the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.16" },
{ text: `'Bhikkhus, develop mindfulness of breathing.' When this was said, the Venerable Ariṭṭha said to the Blessed One: 'Venerable Sir, I develop mindfulness of breathing.' - 'Ariṭṭha, how do you develop mindfulness of breathing?' - 'Venerable Sir, regarding past sensual pleasures, I have abandoned desire and lust. Regarding future sensual pleasures, I have abandoned desire and lust. Regarding internal and external objects, the perception of aversion is well subdued in me. Mindfully I breathe in, mindfully I breathe out. Thus, Venerable Sir, I develop mindfulness of breathing.' - 'This also, Ariṭṭha, is mindfulness of breathing, but I declare that it is not. Ariṭṭha, I will teach you how mindfulness of breathing is developed and cultivated to perfection. Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.' - 'Yes, Venerable Sir.' Then the Blessed One said: 'Ariṭṭha, how is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated to perfection? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to the forest ... "Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe in," he trains; "Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe out," he trains. Thus, Ariṭṭha, mindfulness of breathing is developed and cultivated to perfection.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.6" },
{ text: `The concentration of mindfulness of breathing, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, yields great fruit and great benefit. And how, bhikkhus, is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated so that it yields great fruit and great benefit? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, sits down, folding his legs crosswise, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. Mindfully he breathes in, mindfully he breathes out. Breathing in long, he understands: 'I breathe in long'; breathing out long, he understands: 'I breathe out long' ... 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe in,' he trains; 'Contemplating relinquishment, I will breathe out,' he trains. Mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated in this way, bhikkhus, yields great fruit and great benefit. Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet perfectly enlightened, I dwelt much in this abiding. Bhikkhus, because I dwelt much in this abiding, my body and eyes were not fatigued, and my mind was liberated from the taints without clinging. Therefore, bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May my body and eyes not be fatigued, and may my mind be liberated from the taints without clinging,' he should give close attention to this concentration of mindfulness of breathing.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 54.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn54.8" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are. And what does he understand as they actually are? He understands as it actually is: 'This is suffering.' He understands as it actually is: 'This is the origin of suffering.' He understands as it actually is: 'This is the cessation of suffering.' He understands as it actually is: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Bhikkhus, develop concentration. A bhikkhu who is concentrated, bhikkhus, understands things as they actually are. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the origin of suffering.' An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the cessation of suffering.' An exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.1" },
{ text: `There are these two extremes, bhikkhus, that one who has gone forth should not practice. What two? Indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is low, vulgar, worldly, unworthy, and unbeneficial; and self-mortification, which is painful, unworthy, and unbeneficial. Avoiding both extremes, bhikkhus, the Middle Way has been realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. And what, bhikkhus, is that Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, bhikkhus, is the Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, producing vision, producing knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. This, bhikkhus, is the Noble Truth of Suffering. Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, sickness is suffering, death is suffering; sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are suffering; association with the disliked is suffering; separation from the liked is suffering; not getting what one wants is suffering. In short, the five aggregates of clinging are suffering. This, bhikkhus, is the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering. It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, seeking delight here and there; that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. This, bhikkhus, is the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering. It is the complete fading away and cessation of that craving, its abandonment, relinquishment, liberation, and non-attachment. This, bhikkhus, is the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.11" },
{ text: `As long, bhikkhus, as the moon and sun do not appear in the world, for so long there is no great light, no great radiance. Then there is only darkness, only gloom. There is no distinction between night and day, no distinction between months and fortnights, no distinction between seasons of the year. But when, bhikkhus, the moon and sun appear in the world, then there is great light, great radiance. Then there is no darkness, no gloom. And there is distinction between night and day, distinction between months and fortnights, distinction between seasons of the year. So too, bhikkhus, as long as a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One does not appear in the world, for so long there is no great light, no great radiance. Then there is only darkness, only gloom. For so long, there is no declaration, no teaching, no exposition, no establishment, no revelation, no analysis, no manifestation of the Four Noble Truths. But when, bhikkhus, a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One appears in the world, then there is great light, great radiance. Then there is no darkness, no gloom. For so long, there is declaration, teaching, exposition, establishment, revelation, analysis, manifestation of the Four Noble Truths. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering ... the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.38" },
{ text: `'What do you think, Ānanda, which is more difficult to do or to achieve: to shoot a hair split into a hundred parts with an arrow, shooting from a distance through a small keyhole, arrow after arrow without missing, or to pierce the tip of a hair split into a hundred parts?' - 'This is more difficult, Venerable Sir, more difficult to achieve: to pierce the tip of a hair split into a hundred parts.' - 'So too, Ānanda, those who truly pierce 'This is suffering' ... truly pierce 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering' pierce something even more difficult to pierce. Therefore, Ānanda, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering.' ... an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.45" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who do not truly understand 'This is suffering' ... who do not truly understand 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering' — they delight in formations leading to birth, they delight in formations leading to aging, they delight in formations leading to death, they delight in formations leading to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. Because they delight in formations leading to birth ... leading to aging ... leading to death ... leading to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, they create formations leading to birth, they create formations leading to aging ... leading to death ... leading to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. Because they create formations leading to birth ... leading to aging ... leading to death ... leading to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, they fall into the darkness of birth, they fall into the darkness of aging, they fall into the darkness of death, they fall into the darkness of sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. They are not freed from birth, from aging, from death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say they are not freed from suffering.<br><br>And, bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins who truly understand 'This is suffering' ... who truly understand 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering' — they do not delight in formations leading to birth ... leading to aging ... leading to death ... leading to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. Because they do not delight in those formations, they do not create them. Because they do not create them, they do not fall into the darkness of birth ... aging ... death ... sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. They are freed from birth, from aging, from death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say they are freed from suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.46" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those samaṇas or brahmins in the past who perfectly awakened to things as they are, all perfectly awakened to these Four Noble Truths. Those samaṇas or brahmins in the future who will perfectly awaken to things as they are, all will perfectly awaken to these Four Noble Truths. Those samaṇas or brahmins in the present who perfectly awaken to things as they are, all perfectly awaken to these Four Noble Truths. What four? The Noble Truth of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering, the Noble Truth of the Path leading to the Cessation of Suffering. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: 'This is suffering' ... to understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.5" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One took a little dust on his fingernail and said to the bhikkhus: 'What do you think, bhikkhus, which is greater: this little dust I have taken on my fingernail, or this great earth?' - 'This is greater, Venerable Sir, namely the great earth. The little dust the Blessed One has taken on his fingernail is insignificant. It cannot be reckoned, cannot be compared, cannot be a fraction, compared to the great earth.' - 'So too, bhikkhus, for a noble disciple who has achieved right view, for a person who has attained, this is greater: the suffering that has been destroyed and ended. What remains is very little, not a hundredth, not a thousandth, not a hundred thousandth part compared to the former mass of suffering that has been destroyed and ended. That is, for one who knows: "This is suffering" ... who knows: "This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering," at most seven more lives. Therefore, bhikkhus, an exertion should be made to understand: "This is suffering" ... an exertion should be made to understand: "This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.51" },
{ text: `'Without breathing in or out,<br>The mind abides in concentration,<br>Without craving, at peace,<br>The Dhamma-eye has attained final Nibbāna.'<br><br>With mind steady, unshaken,<br>Enduring all feelings,<br>Like a lamp that suddenly goes out,<br>The mind is liberated, Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 6.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn6.15" },
{ text: `'It is indeed difficult to live without reverence and obedience. Let me respect, honor, and dwell in dependence on a certain samaṇa or brahmin. But I do not see any other samaṇa or brahmin in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans, who is superior to me in virtuous conduct, whose virtues I could respect, honor, and dwell in dependence upon. Therefore, let me respect, honor, and dwell in dependence on this Dhamma to which I have fully awakened.'<br><br>Then Brahmā Sahampati, arranging his upper robe over one shoulder, saluted the Blessed One with joined palms and said: 'So it is, Venerable Sir! So it is, Well-Gone! Venerable Sir, in the past, the Arahants, the Perfectly Enlightened Ones, those Blessed Ones, also respected, honored, and dwelt in dependence on the (true) Dhamma. Venerable Sir, in the future, those who will be Arahants, Perfectly Enlightened Ones, will also respect, honor, and dwell in dependence on the (true) Dhamma. Venerable Sir, may the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, also respect, honor, and dwell in dependence on the (true) Dhamma.'<br><br>'The Buddhas of the past,<br>The Buddhas of the future,<br>And the present Buddha,<br>Who dispels the sorrow of many.<br><br>All of these,<br>Have lived, will live, and live,<br>Respecting and honoring<br>The true and sublime Dhamma.<br>This is the natural law<br>For the Buddhas.<br><br>Therefore, wishing for one's own good,<br>Aspiring to greatness,<br>One should respect and honor<br>The true and sublime Dhamma,<br>Remembering the teaching<br>Of the Perfectly Enlightened Buddhas.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 6.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn6.2" },
{ text: `At that time, a brahmin of the Bhāradvāja clan had lost fourteen oxen. While searching for those oxen, he came to that forest. There he saw the Blessed One sitting cross-legged, keeping his body straight, and establishing mindfulness in front of him. Seeing him, the brahmin approached the Blessed One and spoke these verses to him:<br><br>'This samaṇa has no<br>Fourteen oxen lost,<br>No six days passed<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Sesame field ruined,<br>With one or two leaves,<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Empty barn, no rats,<br>Running and dancing,<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Seven-month-old mattress,<br>Filled with lice,<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Seven widows,<br>With one or two children,<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Dark, pockmarked wife,<br>Kicking her awake with a foot,<br>Therefore he is at ease.<br><br>This samaṇa has no<br>Creditors in the morning,<br>Scolding: 'Pay back!'<br>Therefore he is at ease.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.10" },
{ text: `The brahmin Asurindaka Bhāradvāja heard: 'The brahmin of the Bhāradvāja clan has gone forth under the Blessed One, from home to homelessness.' Angry and displeased, he went to the Blessed One and, having arrived, reviled and abused the Blessed One with rude, harsh words. Hearing this, the Blessed One remained silent. Then the brahmin Asurindaka Bhāradvāja said to the Blessed One: 'You are defeated, samaṇa! You are defeated, samaṇa!'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>'The fool thinks he wins<br>When he speaks harsh words.<br>One who knows how to endure<br>That one truly wins.<br><br>Those who, when reviled,<br>Revile in return,<br>Do evil to themselves,<br>And also evil to others.<br>Those who, when reviled,<br>Do not revile in return,<br>That person has won a battle,<br>A victory for both self and other.<br><br>That one seeks the benefit<br>Of both self and other.<br>And the one who reviled,<br>Understanding, calms down.<br><br>A physician to both,<br>Healing self and healing other,<br>People think him a fool,<br>Because they do not understand the Dhamma.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.3" },
{ text: `Then the brahmin Ahiṃsaka (Non-harming) Bhāradvāja went to the Blessed One and exchanged greetings with him. After exchanging friendly greetings, he sat down to one side. Sitting to one side, the brahmin Ahiṃsaka Bhāradvāja said to the Blessed One: 'I am Ahiṃsaka, Master Gotama! I am Ahiṃsaka, Master Gotama!'<br><br>( Blessed One ):<br>'One's name should match one's nature,<br>One should be truly non-harming!<br>One who by body, speech, and mind,<br>Does no harm to anyone,<br>One who does not harm others,<br>That one is truly non-harming.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.5" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Blessed One, spoke these appropriate verses in praise of the Venerable Mahāmoggallāna:<br><br>'High on the mountain slope,<br>Those who have attained the three knowledges,<br>Those who have conquered death,<br>The disciples attend upon<br>The noble sage, the Muni,<br>Who has transcended suffering.<br><br>Mahāmoggallāna of great psychic power,<br>He surveys their minds,<br>Knowing they are liberated,<br>Without any attachments.<br><br>Thus they attend upon<br>The Muni Gotama,<br>Who has transcended suffering,<br>Complete in all conduct,<br>Perfect in all qualities.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.10" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Blessed One, spoke these appropriate verses in praise:<br><br>'As the moon in the sky,<br>With clouds cleared away,<br>Shining like the sun,<br>Pure, without defilement.<br>So you, the Great Muni,<br>The noble sage,<br>Your fame shines brightly,<br>Surpassing all worlds.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.11" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Venerable Sāriputta, spoke these appropriate verses in praise:<br><br>'Deep in wisdom, with understanding,<br>Skilled in the path and what is not path,<br>Venerable Sāriputta,<br>Is a person of great wisdom.<br>He is teaching the Dhamma<br>To the assembly of bhikkhus.<br><br>He teaches in brief,<br>He also teaches in detail.<br>Like the wonderful sound<br>Of the Sāli bird,<br><br>His discourse flows forth,<br>His voice is sweet to hear.<br>With a charming tone,<br>Pleasing to the ear and delightful,<br>They lend ear to the Dhamma,<br>Their minds uplifted with joy,<br>O bhikkhus.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.6" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Blessed One, spoke these appropriate verses in praise:<br><br>'Today is the pure fifteenth,<br>Five hundred bhikkhus have gathered,<br>The noble ones have cut the fetters,<br>Without afflictions, ended rebirth.<br><br>Like a Wheel-turning Monarch,<br>With ministers attending him,<br>Travels all the four directions,<br>From this land to the ocean's edge.<br><br>So too, the disciples,<br>Who have attained the three knowledges,<br>Have slain death,<br>These ones attend upon<br>The victor in battle,<br>The supreme caravan leader.<br><br>All are sons of the Blessed One,<br>None is useless.<br>I reverently pay homage<br>To the one who has pulled out the dart of craving,<br>I respectfully honor<br>The one of the sun's lineage.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.7" },
{ text: `'Bhikkhus, I invite you to speak. Do you have any criticism of me regarding body or speech?' When this was said, the Venerable Sāriputta rose from his seat, arranged his upper robe over one shoulder, saluted the Blessed One with joined palms, and said: 'Venerable Sir, we have no criticism of the Blessed One regarding body or speech. Venerable Sir, the path that had not arisen, the Blessed One has caused to arise; the path that was not known, the Blessed One has made known; the path that had not been taught, the Blessed One has taught. The Blessed One knows the path, understands the path, is skilled in the path. And, Venerable Sir, the disciples now live following the path and will later become possessed of those qualities. And, Venerable Sir, I invite the Blessed One to speak. Does the Blessed One have any criticism of me regarding body or speech?' - 'Sāriputta, I have no criticism of you regarding body or speech. Sāriputta, you are of great wisdom. Sāriputta, you are of wide wisdom. Sāriputta, you are of swift wisdom. Sāriputta, you are of quick wisdom. Sāriputta, you are of sharp wisdom. Sāriputta, you are of penetrating wisdom. Sāriputta, just as the eldest son of a Wheel-turning Monarch properly keeps turning the wheel that his father has set in motion, so too, Sāriputta, you properly keep turning the supreme Wheel of Dhamma that I have set in motion.' - 'Venerable Sir, if the Blessed One has no criticism of me regarding body or speech, then, Venerable Sir, regarding these five hundred bhikkhus, does the Blessed One have any criticism regarding body or speech?' - 'Sāriputta, I have no criticism regarding body or speech of these five hundred bhikkhus. Sāriputta, among these five hundred bhikkhus, sixty bhikkhus are those with the three knowledges, sixty bhikkhus are those with the six direct knowledges, sixty bhikkhus are those who are liberated both ways, and the rest are those liberated by wisdom.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.7" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, in the presence of the Blessed One, spoke these appropriate verses in praise of the Venerable Koṇḍañña:<br><br>'The elder who was enlightened,<br>Right after the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>It is Koṇḍañña,<br>Ardent and diligent,<br>He attained a pleasant abiding,<br>Always living in seclusion.<br><br>Whatever a disciple<br>Practicing the Teacher's instruction attains,<br>All that he has attained,<br>Through diligent training.<br><br>Great in psychic power, with the three knowledges,<br>Skilled in knowing the minds of others,<br>He is the Dhamma-heir of the Buddha,<br>Koṇḍañña pays homage<br>At the feet of the Teacher.'`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.9" },
{ text: `Once a certain bhikkhu was dwelling among the Kosalans in a forest grove. At that time, after his meal, on his return from alms round, that bhikkhu went down to a lake and smelled a red lotus. Then a devata dwelling in that forest, out of compassion for that bhikkhu, wishing for his welfare, wishing to arouse him, approached him and spoke these verses to him:<br><br>'This flower, born of water,<br>You smell without having been given.<br>This is a kind of theft,<br>I call you a stealer of scent,<br>O my friend.'<br><br>( The bhikkhu ):<br>'I do not take it, do not break it,<br>From a distance I smell the flower.<br>Then on what basis<br>Am I called a "stealer of scent"?'<br><br>'One who digs up lotus roots,<br>Eats various lotuses,<br>By such actions,<br>Why is he not called a stealer of scent?'<br><br>( The devata ):<br>'A low, evil person,<br>Like a dirty cloth of a wet-nurse,<br>For such a person,<br>My words are not meant.<br>But it is for you that I speak,<br>My words are appropriate<br><br>For one who is without stain,<br>Always seeking purification.<br>For an evil person, even the size<br>Of a tip of a hair,<br>He sees as huge,<br>Like a cloud in the sky.'<br><br>( The bhikkhu ):<br>'Indeed, yakkha,<br>You know me and have compassion for me.<br>Please speak to me again,<br>When you see me thus.'<br><br>( The devata ):<br>'I do not depend on you,<br>I am not your attendant.<br>You, bhikkhu, should know<br>The path to a good destination.'<br><br>That bhikkhu, stirred by that devata, was greatly moved.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 9.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn9.14" },

            
            
                

{ text: `I do not see any other form, bhikkhus, that so obsesses and takes hold of a man's mind as the form of a woman. The form of a woman, bhikkhus, obsesses and takes hold of a man's mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.1" },
{ text: `I do not see any other form, bhikkhus, that so obsesses and takes hold of a woman's mind as the form of a man. The form of a man, bhikkhus, obsesses and takes hold of a woman's mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.6" },
{ text: `I do not see any other sound, bhikkhus, that so obsesses and takes hold of a man's mind as the sound of a woman. The sound of a woman, bhikkhus, obsesses and takes hold of a man's mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.2" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that so gives rise to unarisen sensual desire, or leads to the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire, as the sign of beauty. For one who gives unwise attention to the sign of beauty, bhikkhus, unarisen sensual desire arises, and arisen sensual desire grows and increases.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.11" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that so gives rise to unarisen sloth and torpor, or leads to the growth and increase of arisen sloth and torpor, as lack of gladness, laziness, sluggishness, overeating, and a sluggish mind. For one with a sluggish mind, bhikkhus, unarisen sloth and torpor arise, and arisen sloth and torpor grow and increase.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.13" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that so prevents the arising of unarisen sensual desire, or leads to the abandoning of arisen sensual desire, as the sign of the foul. For one who gives wise attention to the sign of the foul, bhikkhus, unarisen sensual desire does not arise, and arisen sensual desire is abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.16" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that so prevents the arising of unarisen ill-will, or leads to the abandoning of arisen ill-will, as the liberation of mind by loving-kindness. For one who gives wise attention to the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, bhikkhus, unarisen ill-will does not arise, and arisen ill-will is abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.17" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that so prevents the arising of unarisen sloth and torpor, or leads to the abandoning of arisen sloth and torpor, as the element of energy, the element of exertion, the element of striving. For one who is energetic and striving, bhikkhus, unarisen sloth and torpor do not arise, and arisen sloth and torpor are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.18" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that is so difficult to handle as the mind that is not developed. The mind that is not developed, bhikkhus, is difficult to handle.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.21" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that is so easy to handle as the mind that is developed. The mind that is developed, bhikkhus, is easy to handle.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.22" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that leads to such great disadvantage as the mind that is not developed. The mind that is not developed, bhikkhus, leads to great disadvantage.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.23" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as the mind that is developed. The mind that is developed, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.34" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, knowing a person's mind as defiled with my own mind, I understand: 'If this person were to die at this time, he would be reborn in hell accordingly.' Why is that? Because his mind is defiled. It is because of a defiled mind, bhikkhus, that some beings here, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.43" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, knowing a person's mind as purified with my own mind, I understand: 'If this person were to die at this time, he would be reborn in heaven accordingly.' Why is that? Because his mind is purified. It is because of a purified mind, bhikkhus, that some beings here, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.44" },
{ text: `This mind, bhikkhus, is naturally luminous, but it is defiled by adventitious defilements.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.49" },
{ text: `If a bhikkhu, bhikkhus, were to develop a mind of loving-kindness even for the duration of a finger-snap, that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who dwells in jhāna without being empty, who acts upon the Teacher's instruction, who follows his advice, and who does not eat the country's almsfood in vain. How much more so those who make much of it!`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.53" },
{ text: `Whatever unwholesome states there are, bhikkhus, all are rooted in mind, all proceed from mind. Mind is the forerunner of those unwholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.56" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as heedlessness. For one who is heedless, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.58" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as laziness. For one who is lazy, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.60" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as energy. For one who is energetic, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.61" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as fewness of desires. For one who has few desires, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.63" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as discontentment. For one who is discontent, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.64" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as contentment. For one who is content, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.65" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as wise attention. For one who attends wisely, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.67" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as clear comprehension. For one who is clearly comprehending, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.69" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as evil friendship. For one who has evil friends, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.70" },
{ text: `I do not see any other single thing, bhikkhus, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as good friendship. For one who has good friends, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.71" },
{ text: `Of little value, bhikkhus, are these losses, such as loss of wealth. This is the worst of all losses, bhikkhus: loss of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.78" },
{ text: `Of little value, bhikkhus, are these losses, such as loss of reputation. This is the worst of all losses, bhikkhus: loss of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.80" },
{ text: `Of little value, bhikkhus, are these increases, such as increase of reputation. This is the foremost of all increases, bhikkhus: increase of wisdom. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will attain the increase of wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.81" },
{ text: `Those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, who explain what is Dhamma as Dhamma and what is not Dhamma as not Dhamma, such bhikkhus, bhikkhus, acting for the happiness of the many, the welfare of the many, the benefit of the many, for the happiness and welfare of devas and humans. And besides, bhikkhus, those bhikkhus accumulate much merit and maintain this true Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.140", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.140" },
{ text: `'Venerable Sir, among those who dwell in various dwellings, in which dwelling should we dwell?' - 'Nandiya, dwell with faith, not without faith. Dwell with virtue, not without virtue. Dwell with energy, not with laziness. Dwell with mindfulness, not with unmindfulness. Dwell with concentration, not without concentration. Dwell with wisdom, not with poor wisdom. Having dwelt in these six things, Nandiya, further develop these five things. Here, Nandiya, you should recollect the Tathāgata: "He is the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, the Well-Gone, the Knower of the world, the Unsurpassed Trainer of persons, the Teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One." Thus, Nandiya, based on the Tathāgata, you should establish mindfulness internally. Furthermore, Nandiya, you should recollect the Dhamma: "The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One, visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves." Thus, Nandiya, based on the Dhamma, you should establish mindfulness internally. Furthermore, Nandiya, you should recollect your good friends: "It is a gain for me, a great gain for me, that I have good friends who love me, who want my good, who instruct and teach me." Thus, Nandiya, based on good friends, you should establish mindfulness internally. Furthermore, Nandiya, you should recollect your own generosity: "It is a gain for me, a great gain for me, that among people obsessed by the stain of stinginess, I dwell at home with a mind free from stinginess, freely generous, with open hands, delighting in relinquishment, responsive to requests, delighting in sharing gifts." Thus, Nandiya, based on generosity, you should establish mindfulness internally. Just as, Nandiya, an overturned pot, its water poured out, cannot be gathered back; just as a fire that has spread through a dry forest does not come back to burn what is already burned. So too, Nandiya, a noble disciple endowed with these eleven things abandons evil, unwholesome states without clinging to them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.13" },
{ text: `Subhūti, a bhikkhu is learned, remembers what he has learned, and stores up what he has learned. Those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with full meaning and phrasing, proclaiming the holy life completely perfect and pure — such teachings he has learned much, retained, verbally recited, mentally investigated, and well penetrated by right view. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who is learned ... well penetrated by right view — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith. Furthermore, Subhūti, a bhikkhu has good friends, good companions, good associates. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who has good friends, good companions, good associates — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith. Furthermore, Subhūti, a bhikkhu is easy to speak to, possessing qualities that make him easy to speak to, patient and receptive to instruction. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who is easy to speak to, possessing those qualities — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith. Furthermore, Subhūti, a bhikkhu, regarding whatever tasks are to be done for his fellow celibates, whether great or small, is skillful and diligent, possessing sufficient means to do and to organize. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who is thus regarding his duties — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith. Furthermore, Subhūti, a bhikkhu loves the Dhamma, delights in talking about the Dhamma, and has great joy in the supreme Dhamma and Discipline. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who loves the Dhamma ... has great joy in the supreme Dhamma and Discipline — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith. Furthermore, Subhūti, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and diligent, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, striving, persevering, not neglecting wholesome states. Subhūti, a bhikkhu who dwells energetic and diligent ... not neglecting wholesome states — this, Subhūti, is a criterion of faith for a person of faith.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.14" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, there is no need for the intention: 'Let non-remorse arise in me.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that non-remorse arises in a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue. For one without remorse, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let gladness arise in me.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that gladness arises in one without remorse. For one who is glad, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let rapture arise in me.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that rapture arises in one who is glad. For one with rapture, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let my body become tranquil.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that the body becomes tranquil in one with rapture. For one with a tranquil body, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let me feel happiness.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that happiness is felt by one with a tranquil body. For one who is happy, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let my mind become concentrated.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that the mind becomes concentrated in one who is happy. For one with a concentrated mind, bhikkhus, there is no need for the intention: 'Let me know and see things as they actually are.' It is natural, bhikkhus, that one with a concentrated mind knows and sees things as they actually are.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.2" },
				
		
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu reviles, criticizes, or reproaches the noble ones who are his fellow celibates, it is impossible, there is no chance that he will not encounter one of eleven misfortunes. What eleven? He does not attain what has not been attained; what has been attained he loses; the true Dhamma is not made clear to him; or he becomes puffed up in the true Dhamma; or he does not delight in living the holy life; or he commits a defiled offense; or he gives up the holy life and returns to the lower life; or he contracts a severe illness; or he becomes mad or mentally deranged; or he dies confused; or after death, with the breakup of the body, he falls into a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu reviles, criticizes, or reproaches the noble ones who are his fellow celibates, it is impossible, there is no chance that he will not encounter one of these eleven misfortunes.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.6" },
{ text: `Sandha, practice jhāna like a thoroughbred horse, not like an unbroken horse. And how, Sandha, is the jhāna of an unbroken horse? An unbroken horse, when tied at the feeding trough, thinks: 'Fodder, fodder!' Why is that? Because the unbroken horse, when tied at the feeding trough, does not think: 'What task will the horse-trainer set for me today? What can I do to repay him?' The horse tied at the feeding trough only thinks: 'Fodder, fodder!' So too, Sandha, here an unbroken person, going to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, abides with a mind obsessed by sensual desire, overwhelmed by sensual desire, not understanding as it actually is the escape from arisen sensual desire. He harbors sensual desire within and then jhānas, reflects, continuously jhānas, contemplates. He abides with a mind obsessed by ill-will ... obsessed by sloth and torpor ... obsessed by restlessness and remorse ... obsessed by doubt, overwhelmed by doubt, not understanding as it actually is the escape from arisen doubt. He harbors doubt within and then jhānas, reflects, continuously jhānas, contemplates. This, Sandha, is the jhāna of an unbroken person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.9" },
{ text: `'How, Venerable Sir, does a good, tamed person practice jhāna? He practices jhāna without depending on earth, without depending on water, without depending on fire, without depending on air, without depending on the base of infinite space, without depending on the base of infinite consciousness, without depending on the base of nothingness, without depending on the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception, without depending on this world, without depending on the next world, and whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, sought after, attained, or reflected upon by the mind — he practices jhāna without depending on that. Yet he does practice jhāna.' - 'Here, Sandha, for a good, tamed person, the perception of earth with regard to earth is clearly discerned; the perception of water with regard to water is clearly discerned; the perception of fire with regard to fire is clearly discerned; the perception of air with regard to air is clearly discerned; the perception of the base of infinite space with regard to the base of infinite space is clearly discerned; the perception of the base of infinite consciousness with regard to the base of infinite consciousness is clearly discerned; the perception of the base of nothingness with regard to the base of nothingness is clearly discerned; the perception of the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception with regard to the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception is clearly discerned; the perception of this world with regard to this world is clearly discerned; the perception of the next world with regard to the next world is clearly discerned; whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, sought after, attained, or reflected upon by the mind — that perception is clearly discerned. Practicing jhāna thus, Sandha, is the good, tamed person. He practices jhāna without depending on earth, without depending on water, without depending on fire, without depending on air, without depending on the base of infinite space, without depending on the base of infinite consciousness, without depending on the base of nothingness, without depending on the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception, without depending on this world, without depending on the next world. Whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, or reflected upon by the mind — he practices jhāna without depending on that. Yet he does practice jhāna. Practicing jhāna thus, Sandha, a good, tamed person is honored from afar by devas with their lord, and by Brahmās with their company.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.9" },
{ text: `And how, Sandha, is the jhāna of a thoroughbred horse? A thoroughbred horse, Sandha, a trained horse, when tied at the feeding trough, does not think: 'Fodder, fodder!' Why is that? Because a trained horse, when tied at the feeding trough, reflects: 'What task will the horse-trainer set for me today? What can I do to repay him?' The horse tied at the feeding trough does not think: 'Fodder, fodder!' A thoroughbred horse, Sandha, when trained, regards the application of the goad to a thoroughbred horse as a debt, as a bondage, as a loss, as a bad omen. So too, Sandha, a good, tamed person, going to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, abides with a mind not obsessed by sensual desire, not conquered by sensual desire, understanding as it actually is the escape from arisen sensual desire. He abides with a mind not obsessed by ill-will ... not obsessed by delusion ... not obsessed by sloth and torpor ... not obsessed by restlessness and remorse ... He abides with a mind not obsessed by doubt, not conquered by doubt, understanding as it actually is the escape from arisen doubt. He practices jhāna without depending on earth, without depending on water, without depending on fire, without depending on air, without depending on the base of infinite space, without depending on the base of infinite consciousness, without depending on the base of nothingness, without depending on the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception, without depending on this world, without depending on the next world. Whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, or reflected upon by the mind — he practices jhāna without depending on that. Yet he does practice jhāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.9" },
{ text: `There are these two hopes, bhikkhus, that are hard to abandon. What two? The hope for gain and the hope for life. These two hopes are hard to abandon. There are these two kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who are hard to find in the world. What two? The one who does a good deed first, and the one who is grateful for help done. These two kinds of persons are hard to find in the world. There are these two kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who are hard to satisfy. What two? The one who hoards gains and the one who squanders gains. These two kinds of persons are hard to satisfy. There are these two kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who are easy to satisfy. What two? The one who does not hoard gains and the one who does not squander gains. These two kinds of persons are easy to satisfy in the world. There are these two conditions, bhikkhus, for the arising of lust. What two? The sign of beauty and unwise attention. These are the two conditions for the arising of lust. There are these two conditions, bhikkhus, for the arising of hatred. What two? The sign of aversion and unwise attention. These are the two conditions for the arising of hatred. There are these two conditions, bhikkhus, for the arising of wrong view. What two? The voice of another and unwise attention. These are the two conditions for the arising of wrong view. There are these two conditions, bhikkhus, for the arising of right view. What two? The voice of another and wise attention. These are the two conditions for the arising of right view.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.118", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.118" },
{ text: `These, bhikkhus, are two powers. What two? The power of reflection and the power of development. And what, bhikkhus, is the power of reflection? Here, bhikkhus, a person reflects: 'With bodily misconduct, the result is evil in the present life and in the future life. With verbal misconduct, the result is evil in the present life and in the future life. With mental misconduct, the result is evil in the present life and in the future life.' Reflecting thus, he abandons bodily misconduct and develops bodily good conduct; he abandons verbal misconduct and develops verbal good conduct; he abandons mental misconduct and develops mental good conduct; he maintains purity of reflection. This, bhikkhus, is called the power of reflection. And what, bhikkhus, is the power of development? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... the fourth jhāna. This, bhikkhus, is called the power of development. These, bhikkhus, are the two powers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.13" },
{ text: `There are these two kinds of giving, bhikkhus. What two? Giving of material goods and giving of the Dhamma. These are the two kinds of giving. The foremost among these two kinds of giving, bhikkhus, is the giving of the Dhamma. There are these two kinds of offerings, bhikkhus. What two? Offering of material goods and offering of the Dhamma. These are the two kinds of offerings. The foremost among these two kinds of offerings, bhikkhus, is the offering of the Dhamma. There are these two kinds of wealth, bhikkhus. What two? Material wealth and Dhamma wealth. These are the two kinds of wealth. The foremost among these two kinds of wealth, bhikkhus, is Dhamma wealth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.141", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.141" },
{ text: `There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Skill in entering concentration and skill in emerging from concentration. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Truth and gentleness. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Patience and softness. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Concord and hospitality. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Harmlessness and purity. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Non-guarding of the sense faculties and lack of moderation in eating. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Guarding the sense faculties and moderation in eating. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Power of mindfulness and power of concentration. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Serenity and insight. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Not being content with wholesome states and not giving up energy. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Unmindfulness and lack of clear comprehension. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Mindfulness and clear comprehension. These, bhikkhus, are two things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.163" },
{ text: `There are two kinds of striving that are very hard to do in the world. What two? The striving of householders living at home for the purpose of giving requisites such as almsfood, lodgings, and medicines; and the striving of those who have gone forth from home to homelessness for the purpose of abandoning all attachments. These two kinds of striving, bhikkhus, are very hard to do in the world. Among these two kinds of striving, bhikkhus, the foremost is striving for the purpose of abandoning all attachments. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will strive with energy for the purpose of abandoning all attachments.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.2" },
{ text: `There are these two kinds of foolish persons, bhikkhus. What two? The one who commits an offense but does not see it as an offense, and the one who does not accept another's confession of an offense according to the Dhamma. These are the two kinds of foolish persons. There are these two kinds of wise persons, bhikkhus. What two? The one who commits an offense sees it as an offense, and the one who accepts another's confession of an offense according to the Dhamma. These are the two kinds of wise persons.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.21" },
{ text: `There are these two kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who misrepresent the Tathāgata. What two? The malicious one with a mind full of hatred, and the faithful one with wrong view. These two kinds of persons misrepresent the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.22" },
{ text: `Having seen two benefits, bhikkhus, I resort to secluded forests and remote lodgings. What two? Seeing for myself a pleasant abiding in the present life, and having compassion for future generations. Having seen these two benefits, bhikkhus, I resort to secluded forests and remote lodgings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.30" },
{ text: `There are these two things, bhikkhus, that are components of true knowledge. What two? Serenity and insight. When serenity is developed, bhikkhus, what benefit is to be expected? The mind is developed. When the mind is developed, what benefit is to be expected? Greed is abandoned. When insight is developed, bhikkhus, what benefit is to be expected? Wisdom is developed. When wisdom is developed, what benefit is to be expected? Ignorance is abandoned. Defiled by greed, bhikkhus, the mind is not liberated. Defiled by ignorance, wisdom is not developed. Therefore, through the removal of greed, there is liberation of mind; through the removal of ignorance, there is liberation by wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.31" },
{ text: `For direct knowledge of greed, bhikkhus, two things should be developed. What two? Serenity and insight. For direct knowledge of greed, bhikkhus, these two things should be developed. For full understanding ... for utter ending ... for abandoning ... for destruction ... for vanishing ... for dispassion ... for cessation ... for relinquishment ... for giving up greed, these two things should be developed. For hatred ... delusion ... anger ... resentment ... hypocrisy ... malice ... envy ... stinginess ... deceit ... fraud ... obstinacy ... impetuosity ... conceit ... arrogance ... vanity ... heedlessness ... for full understanding ... for utter ending ... for abandoning ... for destruction ... for vanishing ... for dispassion ... for cessation ... for relinquishment ... for giving up hatred ... heedlessness, these two things should be developed. What two? Serenity and insight. For giving up heedlessness, bhikkhus, these two things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.310", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.310" },
{ text: `Then a brahmin went to the Blessed One and exchanged greetings with him ... sat down to one side. That brahmin said to the Blessed One: 'What does Master Gotama say? What does he teach?' - 'Brahmin, I teach about action and I teach about inaction.' - 'How does Master Gotama teach about action and inaction?' - 'I teach inaction, brahmin, regarding bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, and mental misconduct. I teach inaction regarding various evil, unwholesome states. I teach action, brahmin, regarding bodily good conduct, verbal good conduct, and mental good conduct. I teach action regarding various wholesome states. Thus, brahmin, I teach about action and about inaction.' - 'Wonderful, Master Gotama! ... From today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.34" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is there the dwelling of an evil person and how do evil persons dwell together? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu thinks: 'Let the elder not admonish me, let the middle not admonish me, let the junior not admonish me; and let me not admonish the elder, let me not admonish the middle, let me not admonish the junior. If an elder admonishes me, he admonishes me with the intention of harming me, not for my welfare. I will say "no" to him, I will make him feel disrespected, and if I see that he speaks rightly, I will not follow his instruction.' Thus, bhikkhus, is the dwelling of an evil person and thus do evil persons dwell together.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.62" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is there the dwelling of a good person and how do good persons dwell together? Here, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu thinks: 'Let the elder admonish me, let the middle admonish me, let the junior admonish me. I will admonish the elder, I will admonish the middle, I will admonish the junior. If an elder admonishes me, he admonishes me with the intention of my welfare, not with the intention of harming me. I will say "good" to him, I will not make him feel disrespected, and if I see that he speaks rightly, I will follow his instruction. If a middle bhikkhu admonishes me ... If a junior bhikkhu admonishes me, he admonishes me with the intention of my welfare, not with the intention of harming me. I will say "good" to him, I will not make him feel disrespected, and if I see that he speaks rightly, I will follow his instruction.' Thus, bhikkhus, is the dwelling of a good person and thus do good persons dwell together.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.62" },
{ text: `There are these two kinds of pleasure, bhikkhus. What two? Material pleasure and non-material pleasure. These, bhikkhus, are the two kinds of pleasure. The foremost among these two kinds of pleasure, bhikkhus, is non-material pleasure.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.68" },
{ text: `There are these two kinds of pleasure, bhikkhus. What two? Bodily pleasure and mental pleasure. These, bhikkhus, are the two kinds of pleasure. The foremost among these two kinds of pleasure, bhikkhus, is mental pleasure.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.70" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with a sign, not without a sign. By abandoning that very sign, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur. Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with a cause, not without a cause. By abandoning that very cause, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur. Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with form, not without form. By abandoning that very condition, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur. Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with feeling, not without feeling. By abandoning that very condition, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur. Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with perception, not without perception. By abandoning that very condition, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur. Bhikkhus, evil, unwholesome states arise with consciousness, not without consciousness. By abandoning that very condition, such evil, unwholesome states do not occur.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.77" },
{ text: `There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Energy and unification of mind. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Name and form. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? True knowledge and liberation. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Lack of conscience and lack of fear of wrongdoing. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Conscience and fear of wrongdoing. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Being difficult to speak to and having evil friends. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Being easy to speak to and having good friends. These, bhikkhus, are two things. There are these two things, bhikkhus. What two? Skill in the training rules and skill in attention. These, bhikkhus, are two things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.87" },
{ text: `Whatever fear arises, bhikkhus, all that fear arises from the fool, not from the wise person. Whatever danger arises, all that danger arises from the fool, not from the wise person. Whatever calamity arises, all that calamity arises from the fool, not from the wise person. Just as, bhikkhus, a fire that starts from a house of reeds or a house of grass burns down even a gabled house, plastered inside and out, protected from the wind, with bolted doors and shuttered windows. So too, bhikkhus, whatever fear arises, all that fear arises from the fool, not from the wise person. The fool has danger, the wise person has no danger. The fool has calamity, the wise person has no calamity. Bhikkhus, there is no fear for the wise person, no danger for the wise person, no calamity for the wise person. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Recognizing by what three qualities a fool is known, we will abandon those three qualities. Recognizing by what three qualities a wise person is known, we will undertake those three qualities and practice them.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.1" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person does a trivial evil deed, and that evil deed leads him to hell. Here, bhikkhus, a person does a similarly trivial evil deed, but that evil deed leads him to be experienced in this very life, not even a trace being seen (in the next life), let alone much. What kind of person, bhikkhus, does a trivial evil deed that leads him to hell? Here, bhikkhus, a person has an undeveloped body, undeveloped virtue, undeveloped mind, undeveloped wisdom; he is restricted, of petty nature, living in little suffering. Such a person, bhikkhus, does a trivial evil deed, and that evil deed leads him to hell. What kind of person, bhikkhus, does a similarly trivial evil deed that leads him to be experienced in this very life, not even a trace being seen, let alone much? Here, bhikkhus, a person has a developed body, developed virtue, developed mind, developed wisdom; he is not restricted, of great nature, living immeasurably. Such a person, bhikkhus, does a similarly trivial evil deed, and that evil deed leads him to be experienced in this very life, not even a trace being seen, let alone much. Just as, bhikkhus, a person throws a lump of salt into a small bowl of water. What do you think, bhikkhus, would that water become salty and undrinkable because of that lump of salt?' - 'Yes, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because there is only a little water in the bowl; that lump of salt makes it salty and undrinkable.' - 'Just as, bhikkhus, a person throws a lump of salt into the Ganges river. What do you think, bhikkhus, would the Ganges river become salty and undrinkable because of that lump of salt?' - 'No, Venerable Sir. Why is that? Because the mass of water in the Ganges river is great; it would not become salty and undrinkable because of that lump of salt.' - 'So too, bhikkhus, a person does a trivial evil deed that leads him to hell. And a person does a similarly trivial evil deed that leads him to be experienced in this very life, not even a trace being seen, let alone much.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.100" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a goldsmith or his apprentice builds a smelting furnace. Having built the furnace, he lights a fire in it. Having lit the fire, he takes gold with his tongs and puts it into the furnace. From time to time he blows the bellows, from time to time he sprinkles water, from time to time he closely observes. If, bhikkhus, the goldsmith or his apprentice blows the bellows all the time, the gold would get burnt. If he sprinkles water all the time, the gold would get cooled. If he observes closely all the time, the gold would not come to proper maturity. But if, bhikkhus, the goldsmith or his apprentice from time to time blows the bellows, from time to time sprinkles water, from time to time observes closely, the gold becomes pliant, workable, radiant, not brittle, and is properly finished. Then whatever ornament he wishes to make from it, whether a golden leaf, a ring, a necklace, or a chain, he can accomplish as he wishes. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is intent on developing the higher mind should from time to time attend to three signs. If a bhikkhu intent on developing the higher mind attends only to the sign of concentration, his mind tends to sluggishness. If he attends only to the sign of energy, his mind tends to restlessness. If he attends only to the sign of equanimity, his mind is not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. But if he from time to time attends to the sign of concentration, from time to time to the sign of energy, from time to time to the sign of equanimity, his mind becomes pliant, workable, radiant, not brittle, and is properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. Then, for whatever state he directs his mind for direct knowledge and realization, he attains that state with capability and power, in whatever sphere.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.102" },
{ text: `Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, accordingly one is reborn in hell. What three? One kills living beings oneself, encourages others to kill, and approves of killing. Possessing these three qualities, accordingly one is reborn in hell. Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, accordingly one is reborn in heaven. What three? One abstains from killing oneself, encourages others to abstain from killing, and approves of abstaining from killing. Possessing these three qualities, accordingly one is reborn in heaven. One takes what is not given oneself ... One abstains from taking what is not given oneself ... One engages in sexual misconduct oneself ... One abstains from sexual misconduct oneself ... One speaks falsely oneself ... One abstains from false speech oneself ... One speaks harshly oneself ... One abstains from harsh speech oneself ... One is covetous oneself ... One is not covetous oneself ... One has ill-will oneself ... One does not have ill-will oneself ... One holds wrong view oneself ... One abstains from wrong view oneself ... Possessing these three qualities, accordingly one is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.163" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the mark of a fool is seen in his actions; the mark of a wise person is seen in his actions. Wisdom shines forth in one's way of life. Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, a fool is known. What three? Bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, mental misconduct. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a fool is known. Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, a wise person is known. What three? Bodily good conduct, verbal good conduct, mental good conduct. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a wise person is known. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Recognizing by what three qualities a fool is known, we will abandon those three qualities. Recognizing by what three qualities a wise person is known, we will undertake those three qualities and practice them.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.2" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of persons who appear in the world, comparable to three kinds of sick persons. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a certain person, whether he sees the Tathāgata or does not see him, whether he hears the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata or does not hear it, does not enter into the fixed course of rightness regarding wholesome states. Here, bhikkhus, a certain person, whether he does not see the Tathāgata, whether he hears the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata or does not hear it, enters into the fixed course of rightness regarding wholesome states. Here, bhikkhus, a certain person, whether he sees the Tathāgata, not that he does not see him, whether he hears the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, not that he does not hear it, enters into the fixed course of rightness regarding wholesome states. It is because of this kind of person, bhikkhus, that the teaching of the Dhamma is accepted. It is because of this kind of person, bhikkhus, that the Dhamma is taught to others. These three kinds of persons appear in the world, comparable to three kinds of sick persons.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.22" },
{ text: `There are these three kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who appear in the world. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a person accumulates harmful bodily formations, accumulates harmful verbal formations, accumulates harmful mental formations. Having accumulated harmful bodily formations, harmful verbal formations, harmful mental formations, he is reborn in a harmful world. Being reborn in a harmful world, harmful contacts touch him. Touched by harmful contacts, he experiences harmful feelings, exclusively painful, like beings in hell. Here, bhikkhus, a person accumulates non-harmful bodily formations ... non-harmful mental formations. Having accumulated non-harmful bodily formations ... non-harmful mental formations, he is reborn in a non-harmful world. Being reborn in a non-harmful world, non-harmful contacts touch him. Touched by non-harmful contacts, he experiences non-harmful feelings, exclusively pleasant, like the Subhakiṇha devas. Here, bhikkhus, a person accumulates both harmful and non-harmful bodily formations ... both harmful and non-harmful mental formations. Having accumulated both harmful and non-harmful bodily formations ... both harmful and non-harmful mental formations, he is reborn in a world that is both harmful and non-harmful. Being reborn in a world that is both harmful and non-harmful, contacts that are both harmful and non-harmful touch him. Touched by them, he experiences feelings that are both harmful and non-harmful, a mixture of pleasure and pain, like humans, some devas, and some beings in the lower realms. These three kinds of persons, bhikkhus, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.23" },
{ text: `There are these three causes, bhikkhus, for the origination of kamma. What three? Greed is a cause for the origination of kamma. Hatred is a cause for the origination of kamma. Delusion is a cause for the origination of kamma. Whatever kamma is done through greed, bhikkhus, born from greed, caused by greed, originating from greed, wherever one's identity arises, there that kamma ripens. Where that kamma ripens, its result is experienced either in this very life, or in the next life, or in some future life. Whatever kamma is done through hatred, bhikkhus, born from hatred, caused by hatred, originating from hatred, wherever one's identity arises, there that kamma ripens. Where that kamma ripens, its result is experienced either in this very life, or in the next life, or in some future life.<br><br>Whatever kamma is done from greed, hatred, delusion,<br>By an ignorant person, whether little or much,<br>Is experienced right here,<br>Not elsewhere.<br><br>Therefore a bhikkhu should abandon<br>Greed, hatred, and delusion,<br>Generating true knowledge,<br>Abandoning all bad destinations.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.34" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, seeds that are not broken, not rotten, not damaged by wind and sun, fertile, well planted, and a person burns them with fire, reduces them to ashes, winnows them in a strong wind or lets them be carried away by a swift stream — those seeds are destroyed, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future. So too, bhikkhus, whatever kamma is done through non-greed, born from non-greed, caused by non-greed, originating from non-greed — since greed has been abandoned, that kamma is destroyed, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future. Whatever kamma is done through non-hatred, born from non-hatred, caused by non-hatred, originating from non-hatred — since hatred has been abandoned, that kamma is destroyed, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future. Whatever kamma is done through non-delusion, born from non-delusion, caused by non-delusion, originating from non-delusion — since delusion has been abandoned, that kamma is destroyed, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.34" },
{ text: `There are these three divine messengers, bhikkhus. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a person does evil with body, speech, and mind. After death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Then the hell-wardens seize him by both arms and present him to King Yama, saying: 'Your Majesty, this person did not respect his mother, did not respect his father, did not respect samaṇas, did not respect brahmins, did not honor the elders of the family. Let Your Majesty punish him!' Then King Yama questions, cross-questions, and examines him about the first divine messenger: 'Good man, did you not see the first divine messenger appearing among humans?' He replies: 'I did not see, sire.' Then, bhikkhus, King Yama says to him: 'Good man, did you never see among humans a man or a woman eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old, aged, crooked like a roof, bent over, leaning on a staff, trembling as they walk, afflicted, their youth gone, teeth fallen out, hair grey and falling, bald, wrinkled, with limbs spotted and pale?' He says: 'Yes, sire, I have seen.' Then, bhikkhus, King Yama says to him: 'Good man, being intelligent and mature, did you not think: "I too am subject to aging, I cannot escape aging. Let me do good deeds by body, speech, and mind"?' He says: 'No, sire, I did not. I was heedless, sire.' Then, bhikkhus, King Yama says to him: 'Good man, because of heedlessness, you did not do good deeds by body, speech, and mind. Indeed, good man, they will treat you according to your heedlessness. That evil deed was not done by your mother, not by your father, not by your brother, not by your sister, not by your friends and companions, not by your relatives, not by devas, not by samaṇas and brahmins. That evil deed was done by you yourself, and you will experience its result.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.36" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, on the Uposatha day of the fifteenth, the four great kings themselves travel through this world to see: 'Among humans, are there many who respect their mother, respect their father, honor samaṇas and brahmins, honor the elders of the family, observe the Uposatha, are heedful, and do meritorious deeds?' If there are many among humans who respect their mother, respect their father, honor samaṇas and brahmins, honor the elders of the family, observe the Uposatha, are heedful, and do meritorious deeds, then the four great kings report to the devas of the Thirty-three who are sitting assembled in the Sudhammā assembly hall: 'Sirs, there are many among humans who respect their mother, respect their father, honor samaṇas and brahmins, honor the elders of the family, observe the Uposatha, are heedful, and do meritorious deeds.' Then, bhikkhus, the devas of the Thirty-three rejoice and say: 'Indeed, the deva host will increase, and the asura host will diminish!'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.37" },


{ text: `Depending on the king of mountains, the Himalayas, bhikkhus, great sāla trees grow in three ways. What three? They grow in branches, leaves, and foliage; they grow in inner bark, outer bark, and shoots; they grow in sapwood and heartwood. Depending on the king of mountains, the Himalayas, bhikkhus, great sāla trees grow in these three ways. So too, bhikkhus, depending on a good man with faith, the members of his family grow in three ways. What three? They grow in faith, they grow in virtue, they grow in wisdom. Depending on a good man with faith, bhikkhus, the members of his family grow in these three ways.<br><br>Like a rocky mountain,<br>In a deep, dense forest,<br>The great trees depending on it,<br>Grow as forest spirits.<br>So too, a good man<br>With faith and virtue,<br>Depending on him, grow strong:<br>Wife, children, and relatives,<br>With attendants and kinsmen,<br>Relying on him for life.<br>Seeing that virtuous one's conduct,<br>Virtue, giving, good deeds,<br>If they have clear vision,<br>They follow that one's example.<br>Here, practicing the Dhamma rightly,<br>The path to a good destination,<br>In heavenly realms of bliss,<br>They rejoice in their wish.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.48" },
{ text: `Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, a fool is known. What three? He asks questions unwisely; he answers questions unwisely; when another answers a question wisely with well-rounded words and phrases, with smooth, polished prose, he does not accept it. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a fool is known. Possessing three qualities, bhikkhus, a wise person is known. What three? He asks questions wisely; he answers questions wisely; when another answers a question wisely with well-rounded words and phrases, with smooth, polished prose, he accepts it. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a wise person is known.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.5" },
{ text: `Indeed, brahmins, this world is led by aging, sickness, and death. Since the world is thus led by aging, sickness, and death, brahmins, the restraint of body, restraint of speech, restraint of mind in this life — for one who has gone to death — is a refuge, a shelter, an island, a place of safety, and a destination.<br><br>In a burning house,<br>Goods are brought out,<br>That goods benefit them,<br>Not those that are burned.<br>So too, the world is burning,<br>Consumed by aging and death,<br>By giving, one saves oneself,<br>Well saved, the gift is given.<br>Here, restraint of body,<br>Restraint of speech and mind —<br>That one, even when dying,<br>Attains happiness,<br>Because while still alive,<br>He did meritorious deeds.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.52" },
{ text: `'To what extent, Master Gotama, is the Dhamma visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves?' - 'When obsessed by craving, brahmin, overcome, with mind possessed, one intends harm for oneself, intends harm for others, intends harm for both, and experiences mental suffering and grief. When craving is abandoned, one does not intend harm for oneself, does not intend harm for others, does not intend harm for both, and does not experience mental suffering and grief. When obsessed by craving, overcome, with mind possessed, one does evil bodily deeds, evil verbal deeds, evil mental deeds. When craving is abandoned, one does not do evil bodily deeds, evil verbal deeds, evil mental deeds. When obsessed by craving, overcome, with mind possessed, one does not truly understand one's own good, nor the good of others, nor the good of both. When craving is abandoned, one truly understands one's own good, the good of others, and the good of both. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.54" },
{ text: `When obsessed by hatred, brahmin, overcome, with mind possessed, one intends harm for oneself, intends harm for others, intends harm for both, and experiences mental suffering and grief. When hatred is abandoned, one does not intend harm for oneself, does not intend harm for others, does not intend harm for both, and does not experience mental suffering and grief. When obsessed by hatred, overcome, with mind possessed, one does evil bodily deeds, evil verbal deeds, evil mental deeds. When hatred is abandoned, one does not do evil bodily deeds, evil verbal deeds, evil mental deeds. When obsessed by hatred, overcome, with mind possessed, one does not truly understand one's own good, nor the good of others, nor the good of both. When hatred is abandoned, one truly understands one's own good, the good of others, and the good of both. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.54" },
{ text: `Vaccha, those who say: 'Samaṇa Gotama says: "Give only to me, not to others. Give only to my disciples, not to the disciples of others. Giving to me yields great fruit, giving to others does not yield great fruit. Giving to my disciples yields great fruit, giving to the disciples of others does not yield great fruit"' — those persons do not speak correctly about what I say; they misrepresent me with what is false, they speak falsely. Vaccha, one who prevents another from giving creates three obstacles and steals away three things. What three? He obstructs the giver from gaining merit; he obstructs the recipient from receiving the gift; and he himself has already ruined himself and is further harmed. Vaccha, one who prevents another from giving creates these three obstacles and steals away these three things. Vaccha, I say this: 'Those who pour dishwater or rinsings into a cesspool or a rubbish pit, thinking: "Let the beings there obtain food and thus live" — even from that, I say, there is merit. What to speak of giving to human beings!'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.57" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Vaccha, I declare that giving to a virtuous one yields great fruit, not so to an immoral one. A virtuous one is one who has abandoned five factors and possesses five factors. What five factors has he abandoned? He has abandoned sensual desire, abandoned ill-will, abandoned sloth and torpor, abandoned restlessness and remorse, abandoned doubt. These five factors have been abandoned. What five factors does he possess? He possesses the noble virtue aggregate, possesses the noble concentration aggregate, possesses the noble wisdom aggregate, possesses the noble liberation aggregate, possesses the noble knowledge and vision of liberation aggregate. He possesses these five factors. Here, I declare that giving to one who has abandoned five factors and possesses five factors yields great fruit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.57" },
{ text: `As in a herd of cattle,<br>There are black, white, red,<br>Tawny, or spotted,<br>And also pigeon-colored.<br><br>Whatever the color of the cow,<br>When a fine bull is obtained,<br>A strong, handsome, swift,<br>And spirited animal,<br>Regardless of its color,<br>It is yoked to the load.<br><br>So too, among humans,<br>Wherever they are born,<br>Whether nobles, brahmins,<br>Merchants, or servants,<br>Outcasts, or lowly refuse-collectors,<br><br>Among such people,<br>Whoever is well tamed,<br>Upright, perfect in virtue,<br>Truthful, with conscience and shame,<br><br>Ended birth and death,<br>Perfect in the holy life,<br>Laid down the burden,<br>No longer bound,<br>Done what had to be done,<br>Without taints,<br><br>Has reached the far shore,<br>Without attachment to states, peaceful,<br>That stainless field of merit<br>Yields great fruit worthy of offerings.<br><br>Like the fool who does not know,<br>Lacking wisdom, having heard little,<br>Gives only externally,<br>Not approaching the good.<br><br>Those who approach the good,<br>With wisdom, honoring the noble,<br>They trust the Well-Gone,<br>Established at the root.<br><br>Born in heaven or here,<br>Born in a good family,<br>The wise, progressing step by step,<br>Attain Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.57" },
{ text: `There are these three fears, bhikkhus, that separate mother and child. What three? Fear of aging, fear of sickness, fear of death. Bhikkhus, a mother does not want her child to age: 'I am aging, may my child not age!' Or the child does not want its mother to age: 'I am aging, may my mother not age!' Bhikkhus, a mother does not want her child to be sick: 'I am sick, may my child not be sick!' Or the child does not want its mother to be sick: 'I am sick, may my mother not be sick!' Bhikkhus, a mother does not want her child to die: 'I am dying, may my child not die!' Or the child does not want its mother to die: 'I am dying, may my mother not die!' These are the three fears that separate mother and child. There is a path, bhikkhus, there is a way leading to the abandoning and overcoming of these three fears that do not separate mother and child, and of these three fears that separate mother and child. And what, bhikkhus, is that path, that way? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, bhikkhus, is the path, this is the way leading to the abandoning and overcoming of these three fears that do not separate mother and child, and of these three fears that separate mother and child.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.62" },
{ text: `Speaking with hostility,<br>Bias and conceit,<br>Opposing the noble ones' qualities,<br>Finding fault with others,<br>Delighting in hearing bad things about others,<br>One errs, one is confused;<br>One is defeated, one is harmed;<br>The noble ones do not act thus.<br>If one wishes to converse,<br>The wise know the proper time —<br>Concerning Dhamma and meaning —<br>That is the noble ones' talk.<br>The wise speak,<br>Without hostility or conceit.<br>With mind unattached,<br>Without hatred or domination,<br>Without heedlessness,<br>They speak with right wisdom.<br>They delight in well-spoken words,<br>They do not delight in poorly spoken ones.<br>Not learning to criticize,<br>Not seizing upon others' faults,<br>Not abusing, striking,<br>Not speaking frivolously.<br>The noble ones' speech<br>Both instructs and delights.<br>Thus the noble ones speak,<br>Thus the noble ones converse.<br>The wise, knowing this,<br>Speak words that are humble.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.67" },
{ text: `By discussion, bhikkhus, a person can be known as capable or incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, does not give a categorical answer to a question requiring a categorical answer, does not give an analytical answer to a question requiring an analytical answer, does not give a counter-question to a question requiring a counter-question, does not set aside a question requiring to be set aside — then, bhikkhus, such a person is incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, gives a categorical answer to a question requiring a categorical answer, gives an analytical answer to a question requiring an analytical answer, gives a counter-question to a question requiring a counter-question, sets aside a question requiring to be set aside — then, bhikkhus, such a person is capable of conversation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.67" },
{ text: `By discussion, bhikkhus, a person can be known as capable or incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, does not acknowledge what is correct or incorrect, does not acknowledge a hypothesis, does not acknowledge the view of the wise, does not acknowledge common practice — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, acknowledges what is correct or incorrect, acknowledges a hypothesis, acknowledges the view of the wise, acknowledges common practice — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is capable of conversation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.67" },
{ text: `By discussion, bhikkhus, a person can be known as capable or incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, evades the question with another question, leads the talk outside the matter, shows anger, hatred, and displeasure — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, does not evade the question with another question, does not lead the talk outside the matter, does not show anger, hatred, and displeasure — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is capable of conversation. By discussion, bhikkhus, a person can be known as capable or incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, reviles, strikes, mocks, and seizes upon faults — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is incapable of conversation. If a person, bhikkhus, when asked a question, does not revile, does not strike, does not mock, does not seize upon faults — if this is so, bhikkhus, such a person is capable of conversation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.67" },
{ text: `By discussion, bhikkhus, a person can be known as having a condition or not having a condition. Not lending ear, bhikkhus, is not having a condition. Lending ear is having a condition. One who has a condition directly knows one thing, fully understands one thing, abandons one thing, attains one thing — having directly known one thing, fully understood one thing, abandoned one thing, attained one thing, he experiences right liberation. Thus, bhikkhus, is the benefit of discussion; thus is the benefit of conversation; thus is the benefit of having a condition; thus is the benefit of listening to advice, namely, liberation of mind without clinging.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.67" },
{ text: `'There are these three things, friends. What three? Greed, hatred, delusion. These, friends, are three things. Among these three things, friends, what is the particular characteristic, what is the superior characteristic, what is the difference?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those wanderers: 'Greed, friends, is of minor fault, but its fading away is slow. Hatred is of great fault, but its fading away is quick. Delusion is of great fault, and its fading away is slow.' 'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen greed arise, and arisen greed come to growth and increase?' The answer should be: 'The sign of beauty.' For one who gives unwise attention to the sign of beauty, unarisen greed arises, and arisen greed comes to growth and increase. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the arising of unarisen greed and for the growth and increase of arisen greed.' 'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen hatred arise, and arisen hatred come to growth and increase?' The answer should be: 'The sign of aversion.' For one who gives unwise attention to the sign of aversion, unarisen hatred arises, and arisen hatred comes to growth and increase. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the arising of unarisen hatred and for the growth and increase of arisen hatred.' 'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen delusion arise, and arisen delusion come to growth and increase?' The answer should be: 'Unwise attention.' For one who gives unwise attention, unarisen delusion arises, and arisen delusion comes to growth and increase. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the arising of unarisen delusion and for the growth and increase of arisen delusion.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.68" },
{ text: `'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen greed not arise, or arisen greed is abandoned?' The answer should be: 'The sign of the foul.' For one who gives wise attention to the sign of the foul, unarisen greed does not arise, and arisen greed is abandoned. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the non-arising of unarisen greed and for the abandoning of arisen greed.' 'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen hatred not arise, or arisen hatred is abandoned?' The answer should be: 'The liberation of mind by loving-kindness.' For one who gives wise attention to the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, unarisen hatred does not arise, and arisen hatred is abandoned. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the non-arising of unarisen hatred and for the abandoning of arisen hatred.' 'For what reason, friends, for what condition does unarisen delusion not arise, or arisen delusion is abandoned?' The answer should be: 'Wise attention.' For one who gives wise attention, unarisen delusion does not arise, and arisen delusion is abandoned. This, friends, is the cause, this is the condition for the non-arising of unarisen delusion and for the abandoning of arisen delusion.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.68" },
{ text: `Do not kill living beings,<br>Do not take what is not given,<br>Do not speak falsehood,<br>Do not drink intoxicants;<br>Abandon non-celibacy,<br>Abandon, do not commit sexual misconduct,<br>Do not eat at night,<br>Avoid eating at improper times.<br><br>Do not wear garlands,<br>Do not use perfumes,<br>Lie on a mat<br>Spread on the ground;<br>This eight-factored observance,<br>Called the uposatha,<br>Proclaimed by the Buddha,<br>Leads to the end of suffering.<br><br>The moon and sun,<br>Seen as beautiful,<br>Wherever they go,<br>They shine with radiance;<br>They make the clouds bright,<br>Traveling through the sky,<br>They shine in the heavens,<br>Illuminating all directions.<br><br>In that space,<br>Treasures are found,<br>Pearls and gems,<br>Beryl, lucky stones;<br>Gold nuggets in the earth,<br>Or the kind called Kancana,<br>And the bright gold<br>Called Hattaka.<br><br>Yet they are worth<br>Only one-sixteenth part<br>Of the observance of the uposatha,<br>Complete with all eight factors,<br>Including the moon's light,<br>Including the starry sky.<br><br>Therefore, women and men,<br>Let them keep pure precepts,<br>Practice the uposatha observance,<br>Complete with all eight factors;<br>Do meritorious deeds,<br>Bringing great happiness,<br>Reborn in heaven,<br>Not mocked by people.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.70" },
{ text: `'Venerable Ānanda, whose Dhamma is well taught? Who are well practiced in the world? Who are well liberated in the world?' - 'Then, householder, I will ask you about this matter. Answer as you like. What do you think, householder, those who teach the Dhamma for the abandonment of greed, for the abandonment of hatred, for the abandonment of delusion — is their Dhamma well taught or not? Or what do you think here?' - 'Venerable sir, those who teach for the abandonment of greed, hatred, and delusion — their Dhamma is well taught. And here, I think so.' - 'What do you think, householder, those who practice for the abandonment of greed, hatred, and delusion — are they well practiced in the world or not? Or what do you think here?' - 'Venerable sir, those who practice for the abandonment of greed, hatred, and delusion — they are well practiced in the world. And here, I think so.' - 'What do you think, householder, those for whom greed has been abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future; those for whom hatred has been abandoned ... those for whom delusion has been abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made not to exist, unable to arise in the future — are they well liberated in the world or not? Or what do you think here?' - 'Venerable sir, those for whom greed ... hatred ... delusion have been abandoned ... unable to arise in the future — they are well liberated in the world. And here, I think so.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.72" },
{ text: `'For a long time, Venerable Sir, I have known the Dhamma taught thus: "Knowledge comes to one who is concentrated, not to one who is not concentrated." Venerable Sir, does concentration come first and then knowledge, or does knowledge come first and then concentration?' Then the Venerable Ānanda thought: 'The Blessed One has just recovered from an illness, not long after being ill. This Sakyan Mahānāma asks a very profound question. Let me take the Sakyan Mahānāma aside and teach him the Dhamma.' Then the Venerable Ānanda took the Sakyan Mahānāma by the hand, led him aside, and said to him: 'The virtue of a learner, Mahānāma, has been spoken of by the Blessed One. And the virtue of a non-learner has also been spoken of by the Blessed One. The concentration of a learner has been spoken of by the Blessed One. The concentration of a non-learner has also been spoken of by the Blessed One. The wisdom of a learner has been spoken of by the Blessed One. The wisdom of a non-learner has also been spoken of by the Blessed One. And what, Mahānāma, is the virtue of a learner?'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.73" },
{ text: `Ānanda, for whomever you have compassion, and those who you think should listen to you, friends, companions, relatives, or blood relations — for them, Ānanda, you should encourage, instruct, and establish in three things. What three? Encourage, instruct, and establish in unwavering confidence in the Buddha: 'He is the Blessed One, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, the Well-Gone, the Knower of the world, the Unsurpassed Trainer of persons, the Teacher of devas and humans, the Buddha, the Blessed One.' Encourage, instruct, and establish in unwavering confidence in the Dhamma: 'The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One, visible here and now, timeless, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be experienced by the wise for themselves.' Encourage, instruct, and establish in unwavering confidence in the Saṅgha: 'The Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is practicing the good way, the straight way, the true way, the proper way; that is, the four pairs of persons, the eight individuals. This Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is worthy of gifts, worthy of hospitality, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit for the world.' Ānanda, even if the four great elements — earth, water, fire, air — were to change, a noble disciple who possesses unwavering confidence in the Buddha does not change. Here, change is this: That noble disciple, Ānanda, who possesses unwavering confidence in the Buddha, would be reborn in hell, the animal realm, or the ghost realm — this is impossible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.75" },
{ text: `'Ānanda, do all observances, modes of living, and fundamental services have a result?' - 'Here, Venerable Sir, it cannot be answered categorically.' - 'Then, Ānanda, analyze it further!' - 'Venerable Sir, whatever observance, mode of living, or fundamental service, when practiced, leads to the increase of unwholesome states and the decline of wholesome states — such observance, mode of living, or fundamental service has no result. And, Venerable Sir, whatever observance, mode of living, or fundamental service, when practiced, leads to the decline of unwholesome states and the increase of wholesome states — such observance, mode of living, or fundamental service has a result.' The Venerable Ānanda spoke thus. The Teacher approved. Then the Venerable Ānanda thought: 'The Teacher has approved me,' rose from his seat, circumambulated him, and departed. Then the Blessed One, not long after Ānanda had left, said to the bhikkhus: 'Bhikkhus, Ānanda is still a learner, but it is not easy to find one equal to him in wisdom.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.78" },
{ text: `'There are kinds of tree fragrances, Ānanda, that have fragrance with the wind, fragrance against the wind, and fragrance both with and against the wind.' - 'Venerable Sir, what kind of tree fragrance has fragrance with the wind, fragrance against the wind, and fragrance both with and against the wind?' - 'Here, Ānanda, in whatever village or town, a woman or a man has gone for refuge to the Buddha, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha. He abstains from killing living beings, abstains from taking what is not given, abstains from sexual misconduct, abstains from false speech, abstains from intoxicating drinks that cause heedlessness. He is virtuous, of good character, living at home with a mind free from the stain of stinginess, giving freely with open hands, delighting in relinquishment, responsive to requests, delighting in sharing gifts. Such a person is praised by samaṇas and brahmins in all directions, and also praised by devas and non-humans: 'In that village or town, a woman or a man has gone for refuge to the Buddha ... delighting in sharing gifts.'<br><br>No fragrance of flowers<br>Blows against the wind,<br>Even of sandalwood,<br>Jasmine, or tagara;<br>Only the fragrance of the virtuous<br>Blows against the wind;<br>Only the true person's<br>Fragrance pervades all directions.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.79" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a donkey follows behind a herd of cattle, thinking: 'I am also a cow, I am also a cow.' But it does not have the color of a cow, nor the sound of a cow, nor the feet of a cow. Yet it still follows behind the herd, thinking: 'I am also a cow, I am also a cow.' So too, bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu follows behind the Saṅgha of bhikkhus, thinking: 'I am also a bhikkhu, I am also a bhikkhu.' But he does not have the desire to undertake the higher virtue training like the other bhikkhus. He does not have the desire to undertake the higher mind training like the other bhikkhus. He does not have the desire to undertake the higher wisdom training like the other bhikkhus. Yet he still follows behind the Saṅgha, thinking: 'I am also a bhikkhu, I am also a bhikkhu.' Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Keen will be our desire to undertake the higher virtue training. Keen will be our desire to undertake the higher mind training. Keen will be our desire to undertake the higher wisdom training.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.82" },
{ text: `There are these three things, bhikkhus, that a farmer householder must do first. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a farmer householder first plows and harrows well. Having plowed and harrowed well, he sows seeds at the proper time. Having sown seeds at the proper time, he lets water in and out at the proper time. These three things, bhikkhus, a farmer householder must do first. So too, bhikkhus, there are these three things a bhikkhu must do first. What three? Undertaking the higher virtue training, undertaking the higher mind training, undertaking the higher wisdom training. These three things, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu must do first. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher virtue training. Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher mind training. Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher wisdom training.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.83" },
{ text: `'Venerable Sir, there are over a hundred and fifty training rules that I have to recite every half month. Venerable Sir, I cannot learn them.' - 'Bhikkhu, can you learn the three trainings: the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training?' - 'Venerable Sir, I can learn the three trainings: the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training.' - 'Therefore, bhikkhu, you should train in the three trainings: the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training. If you train in the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training, then, bhikkhu, through training in these three trainings, greed will be abandoned, hatred will be abandoned, delusion will be abandoned. Through abandoning greed, abandoning hatred, abandoning delusion, you will not do what is unwholesome, you will not follow what is evil.' That bhikkhu, after some time, trained in the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training. Through training in them, greed was abandoned, hatred was abandoned, delusion was abandoned. Through abandoning greed, abandoning hatred, abandoning delusion, he did not do what was unwholesome, he did not follow what was evil.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.84" },
{ text: `There are these three trainings. What three? The higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training. What is the higher virtue training? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. This, bhikkhus, is called the higher virtue training. And what, bhikkhus, is the higher mind training? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. This, bhikkhus, is called the higher mind training. And what, bhikkhus, is the higher wisdom training? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu understands as it actually is: 'This is suffering'; understands as it actually is: 'This is the origin of suffering'; understands as it actually is: 'This is the cessation of suffering'; understands as it actually is: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' This, bhikkhus, is called the higher wisdom training. These, bhikkhus, are the three trainings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.89" },
{ text: `'A transgression has overcome me, Venerable Sir, foolish, deluded, and unwholesome as I am. For while the Blessed One was teaching the bhikkhus a Dhamma talk connected with the training, encouraging, inspiring, and gladdening them, I felt impatient and displeased, thinking: 'This samaṇa is too meticulous.' Venerable Sir, may the Blessed One accept my transgression as a transgression, so that I may restrain myself in the future.' - 'Indeed, Kassapogotta, a transgression has overcome you, foolish, deluded, and unwholesome as you are. For while I was teaching the bhikkhus a Dhamma talk connected with the training, encouraging, inspiring, and gladdening them, you felt impatient and displeased, thinking: 'This samaṇa is too meticulous.' And, Kassapogotta, since you see your transgression as a transgression and make amends according to the Dhamma, I accept your confession. This is growth in the Noble One's Discipline, that one sees a transgression as a transgression, makes amends according to the Dhamma, and restrains oneself in the future.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.91" },
{ text: `If an elder bhikkhu, Kassapa, does not delight in the training, does not praise undertaking the training, and does not encourage those bhikkhus who do not delight in the training, and does not genuinely and timely praise those bhikkhus who delight in the training — such an elder bhikkhu, Kassapa, I do not praise. Why is that? Because other bhikkhus might associate with that elder bhikkhu, thinking: 'The Teacher praises him.' And those who associate with him might adopt his views. And those who adopt his views would bring about their own long-term harm and suffering. Therefore, Kassapa, I do not praise such an elder bhikkhu. If a middle bhikkhu, Kassapa ... If a junior bhikkhu, Kassapa, does not delight in the training, does not praise undertaking the training, and does not encourage those bhikkhus who do not delight in the training, and does not genuinely and timely praise those bhikkhus who delight in the training — such a junior bhikkhu, Kassapa, I do not praise. Why is that? Because other bhikkhus might associate with that junior bhikkhu, thinking: 'The Teacher praises him.' And those who associate with him might adopt his views. And those who adopt his views would bring about their own long-term harm and suffering. Therefore, Kassapa, I do not praise such a junior bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.91" },
{ text: `If an elder bhikkhu, Kassapa, delights in the training, praises undertaking the training, and encourages those bhikkhus who do not delight in the training, and genuinely and timely praises those bhikkhus who delight in the training — such an elder bhikkhu, Kassapa, I praise. Why is that? Because other bhikkhus might associate with that elder bhikkhu, thinking: 'The Teacher praises him.' And those who associate with him might adopt his views. And those who adopt his views would bring about their own long-term welfare and happiness. Therefore, Kassapa, I praise such an elder bhikkhu. If a middle bhikkhu, Kassapa ... If a junior bhikkhu, Kassapa, delights in the training, praises undertaking the training, and encourages those bhikkhus who do not delight in the training, and genuinely and timely praises those bhikkhus who delight in the training — such a junior bhikkhu, Kassapa, I praise. Why is that? Because other bhikkhus might associate with that junior bhikkhu, thinking: 'The Teacher praises him.' And those who associate with him might adopt his views. And those who adopt his views would bring about their own long-term welfare and happiness. Therefore, Kassapa, I praise such a junior bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.91" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three urgent tasks that a farmer householder must do. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a farmer householder quickly plows the field well, quickly harrows it well. Having quickly plowed and harrowed the field well, he quickly sows the seeds. Having quickly sown the seeds, he quickly lets water in and out. These, bhikkhus, are the three urgent tasks a farmer householder must do. That farmer householder, bhikkhus, has no psychic power or influence (to command): 'Let my crops sprout today, let them head tomorrow, let them ripen the day after.' But in due time, as the farmer householder proceeds, the crops, through the influence of the seasons, sprout, head, and ripen. So too, bhikkhus, there are these three urgent tasks a bhikkhu must do. What three? Undertaking the higher virtue training, undertaking the higher mind training, undertaking the higher wisdom training. These three urgent tasks, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu must do. That bhikkhu, bhikkhus, has no psychic power or influence (to command): 'Let my mind be liberated from the taints without clinging today, or tomorrow, or the day after.' But in due time, as that bhikkhu undertakes the higher virtue training, the higher mind training, the higher wisdom training, his mind becomes liberated from the taints without clinging. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher virtue training. Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher mind training. Keen will be my desire to undertake the higher wisdom training.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.92", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.92" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu in this Dhamma and Discipline possesses three kinds of seclusion. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu guards the precepts, abandons immoral conduct, is secluded from immoral conduct; he has right view, abandons wrong view, is secluded from wrong view; he has destroyed the taints, abandons the taints, is secluded from the taints. Because, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu guards the precepts, abandons immoral conduct, is secluded from immoral conduct; has right view, abandons wrong view, is secluded from wrong view; has destroyed the taints, abandons the taints, is secluded from the taints — therefore, bhikkhus, this bhikkhu is called one who has attained the supreme, attained the basis of purity, established on the basis. Just as, bhikkhus, when a farmer householder's crops are ripe, he quickly harvests them; having quickly harvested, he quickly piles them; having quickly piled them, he quickly brings them home; having quickly brought them home, he quickly stores them; having quickly stored them, he quickly threshes them; having quickly threshed them, he quickly winnows them to get the rice. Thus, bhikkhus, that farmer householder's grain attains the supreme, attains the basis of purity, attains establishment on the basis. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu guards the precepts, abandons immoral conduct, is secluded from immoral conduct; has right view, abandons wrong view, is secluded from wrong view; has destroyed the taints, abandons the taints, is secluded from the taints — therefore, bhikkhus, this bhikkhu is called one who has attained the supreme, attained the basis of purity, established on the basis.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.93" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four kinds of persons, like rain clouds, appear in the world. What four? And how, bhikkhus, is a person with thunder but no rain? Here, bhikkhus, a person speaks but does not act. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person with thunder but no rain. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with rain but no thunder? Here, bhikkhus, a person acts but does not speak. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person with rain but no thunder. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with neither thunder nor rain? Here, bhikkhus, a person neither speaks nor acts. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person with neither thunder nor rain. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with both thunder and rain? Here, bhikkhus, a person speaks and acts. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person with both thunder and rain. Bhikkhus, these four kinds of persons, like rain clouds, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.101" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a Bodhisatta, not yet perfectly enlightened, I thought: 'What is the gratification in the world? What is the danger? What is the escape?' Then, bhikkhus, this thought occurred to me: 'Whatever pleasure and joy arise dependent on the world — that is the gratification in the world. That the world is impermanent, suffering, subject to change — that is the danger in the world. The removal and abandonment of desire and lust for the world — that is the escape from the world.' Bhikkhus, as long as I did not directly know as they actually are the gratification in the world as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then, bhikkhus, I did not claim to have awakened to unsurpassed perfect enlightenment in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans. But when I directly knew as they actually are the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then, bhikkhus, I claimed to have awakened to unsurpassed perfect enlightenment in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its generations of samaṇas and brahmins, devas and humans. And knowledge and vision arose in me: 'Unshakable is my liberation of mind. This is my last birth. Now there is no further existence.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.103", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.103" },

	
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four kinds of persons, like water tanks, appear in the world. What four? Shallow but appears deep, deep but appears shallow, shallow and appears shallow, deep and appears deep. And how, bhikkhus, is a person shallow but appears deep? Here, bhikkhus, a person has a pleasing demeanor when going forward and returning, when looking ahead and aside, when bending and stretching, when wearing the robe and carrying the bowl. But he does not truly understand: 'This is suffering' ... 'This is the origin of suffering' ... 'This is the cessation of suffering' ... he does not truly understand: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a person shallow but appears deep. And how, bhikkhus, is a person deep but appears shallow? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not have a pleasing demeanor ... But he truly understands: 'This is suffering' ... 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a person deep but appears shallow. And how, bhikkhus, is a person shallow and appears shallow? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not have a pleasing demeanor ... and he does not truly understand the Four Noble Truths. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person shallow and appears shallow. And how, bhikkhus, is a person deep and appears deep? Here, bhikkhus, a person has a pleasing demeanor ... and he truly understands the Four Noble Truths. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person deep and appears deep. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, like water tanks, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.104" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is a person who is sapwood surrounded by sapwood? Here, bhikkhus, a person is immoral, of evil character, and his assembly is also immoral, of evil character. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who is sapwood surrounded by sapwood. And how, bhikkhus, is a person who is sapwood surrounded by heartwood? Here, bhikkhus, a person is immoral, of evil character, but his assembly is virtuous, of good character. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who is sapwood surrounded by heartwood. And how, bhikkhus, is a person who is heartwood surrounded by sapwood? Here, bhikkhus, a person is virtuous, of good character, but his assembly is immoral, of evil character. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who is heartwood surrounded by sapwood. And how, bhikkhus, is a person who is heartwood surrounded by heartwood? Here, bhikkhus, a person is virtuous, of good character, and his assembly is also virtuous, of good character. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who is heartwood surrounded by heartwood. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, like the simile of trees, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.109" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is a person with venom but not malice? Here, bhikkhus, a person is quick to anger, but the anger does not last long. Thus is a person with venom but not malice. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with malice but not venom? Here, bhikkhus, a person is not quick to anger, but the anger lasts long. Thus is a person with malice but not venom. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with both venom and malice? Here, bhikkhus, a person is quick to anger and the anger lasts long. Thus is a person with both venom and malice. And how, bhikkhus, is a person with neither venom nor malice? Here, bhikkhus, a person is not quick to anger and the anger does not last long. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person with neither venom nor malice. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.110", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.110" },
{ text: `'Kesi, if the person to be tamed is not tamed by my gentle training, nor by harsh training, nor by gentle and harsh training, then, Kesi, I kill that person!' - 'But, Venerable Sir, killing is not worthy of the Blessed One. Yet the Blessed One says: "Kesi, I kill that person."' - 'Indeed, Kesi, killing is not worthy of the Tathāgata. However, if the person to be tamed is not tamed by gentle training, nor by harsh training, nor by gentle and harsh training, then the Tathāgata considers that person not worth speaking to, not worth instructing. And the wise fellow celibates consider that person not worth speaking to, not worth instructing. "Killed," Kesi, is this person in the Noble One's Discipline, when the Tathāgata considers him not worth speaking to, not worth instructing, and the wise fellow celibates consider him not worth speaking to, not worth instructing.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.111", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.111" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a good, tamed person hears: 'In such and such a village or town, a woman or a man is in distress or has died.' He is stirred and moved by that. Being moved, he strives wisely. Through striving, with his body he realizes the supreme truth; with wisdom, having penetrated it, he sees that truth. Just as, bhikkhus, a good, tamed thoroughbred horse, seeing the shadow of the goad, is stirred and moved — that, bhikkhus, I say, is like this good, tamed person. Thus, bhikkhus, here is a good person. Bhikkhus, this is the first kind of good, tamed person appearing in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.113", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.113" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu knows how to listen, knows how to kill, knows how to endure, knows how to go. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu know how to listen? Here, bhikkhus, when the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata are being taught, he listens with eager attention, applying his whole mind, lending ear. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who knows how to listen. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu know how to kill? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not consent to arisen sensual thoughts; he abandons, dispels, terminates, and makes them non-existent. He does not consent to arisen thoughts of ill-will ... to arisen thoughts of harmfulness; he abandons, dispels, terminates, and makes them non-existent. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who knows how to kill. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu know how to endure? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu endures cold, heat, hunger, thirst, the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and creeping things; he endures harsh and abusive speech; he endures bodily feelings that are painful, sharp, racking, severe, disagreeable, unpleasant, life-threatening. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who knows how to endure. And how, bhikkhus, does a bhikkhu know how to go? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, in whatever direction he has never gone before, where all formations are stilled, all attachments are relinquished, craving is destroyed — Nibbāna — to that place he goes quickly. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who knows how to go. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of reverential salutation, worthy of offerings, the unsurpassed field of merit in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.114" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. He relishes that jhāna, desires it, and thus finds happiness; he abides in it, focuses on it, dwells often in that jhāna, without falling away; at death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Brahmā assembly. The life span of the devas of the Brahmā assembly, bhikkhus, is an eon. There, an ordinary person, having remained until the end of that life span, after living the full life span of those devas, goes to hell, to the animal realm, to the ghost realm. But a disciple of the Tathāgata, having remained there until the end of that life span, after living the full life span of those devas, attains Nibbāna in that very existence. This, bhikkhus, is the distinction, the difference, the disparity between a learned noble disciple and an unlearned ordinary person, namely, the destination of rebirth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.123", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.123" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness; likewise the second, the third, the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. He relishes that jhāna, desires it, and thus finds happiness; he abides in it, focuses on it, dwells often in that jhāna, without falling away; at death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Brahmā assembly. The life span of the devas of the Brahmā assembly, bhikkhus, is an eon. There, an ordinary person, having remained until the end of that life span, after living the full life span of those devas, goes to hell, to the animal realm, to the ghost realm. But a disciple of the Tathāgata, having remained there until the end of that life span, after living the full life span of those devas, attains Nibbāna in that very existence. This, bhikkhus, is the distinction, the difference, the disparity between a learned noble disciple and an unlearned ordinary person, namely, the destination of rebirth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.125", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.125" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness ... with compassion ... with altruistic joy ... with equanimity, likewise the second, the third, the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with equanimity, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Regarding whatever is form, feeling, perception, formations, consciousness, he contemplates them as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease, a boil, a dart, a calamity, an affliction, as alien, as breaking up, as empty, as not-self. At death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Pure Abodes. Bhikkhus, this rebirth is not shared with ordinary persons.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.126", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.126" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four right efforts. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu generates desire for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the arising of unarisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He generates desire for the maintenance, non-decline, increase, expansion, cultivation, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. These, bhikkhus, are the four right efforts.<br><br>With the Dhamma of right effort,<br>They conquer Māra's realm,<br>Not clinging, they cross beyond<br>The fear of birth and death,<br>Delighting in the removal of sensual desires,<br>They conquer Māra and his army,<br>All the forces of the Evil One,<br>They are liberated and at peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.13" },
{ text: `There are these four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, appearing in the world. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not respect virtue, does not regard virtue as supreme; does not respect concentration, does not regard concentration as supreme; does not respect wisdom, does not regard wisdom as supreme. Here, bhikkhus, a person respects virtue, regards virtue as supreme; but does not respect concentration, does not regard concentration as supreme; does not respect wisdom, does not regard wisdom as supreme. Here, bhikkhus, a person respects virtue, regards virtue as supreme; respects concentration, regards concentration as supreme; but does not respect wisdom, does not regard wisdom as supreme. Here, bhikkhus, a person respects virtue, regards virtue as supreme; respects concentration, regards concentration as supreme; respects wisdom, regards wisdom as supreme. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, appear in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.137", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.137" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of striving. What four? Striving by restraint, striving by abandonment, striving by development, striving by protection. And what, bhikkhus, is striving by restraint? Here, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu sees a form with the eye, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the eye faculty, practices the restraint of the eye faculty. When he hears a sound with the ear ... smells an odor with the nose ... tastes a taste with the tongue ... feels a touch with the body ... cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil, unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the mind faculty, practices the restraint of the mind faculty. This, bhikkhus, is called striving by restraint. And what, bhikkhus, is striving by abandonment? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not consent to arisen sensual thoughts; he abandons, dispels, terminates, and makes them non-existent. He does not consent to arisen thoughts of ill-will ... to arisen thoughts of harmfulness ... to arisen evil, unwholesome states; he abandons, dispels, terminates, and makes them non-existent. This, bhikkhus, is called striving by abandonment. And what, bhikkhus, is striving by development? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops the mindfulness enlightenment factor, based on seclusion, based on dispassion, based on cessation, maturing in relinquishment; he develops the investigation-of-states enlightenment factor ... the energy enlightenment factor ... the rapture enlightenment factor ... the tranquility enlightenment factor ... the concentration enlightenment factor ... the equanimity enlightenment factor, based on seclusion, based on dispassion, based on cessation, maturing in relinquishment. This, bhikkhus, is called striving by development. And what, bhikkhus, is striving by protection? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu protects an arisen excellent sign of concentration: the sign of a skeleton, the sign of a worm-eaten corpse, the sign of a discolored corpse, the sign of a festering corpse, the sign of a fissured corpse, the sign of a bloated corpse. This, bhikkhus, is called striving by protection. These, bhikkhus, are the four kinds of striving.<br><br>Restraint and abandonment,<br>Development and protection:<br>These four kinds of striving<br>Were taught by the Kinsman of the Sun.<br>A bhikkhu who is ardent towards them<br>Attains the end of suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.14" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of radiance. What four? The radiance of the moon, the radiance of the sun, the radiance of fire, the radiance of wisdom. These, bhikkhus, are the four kinds of radiance. And the foremost among these four kinds of radiance, bhikkhus, is the radiance of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.141", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.141" },
{ text: `There are these four times. What four? Hearing the Dhamma at the right time, discussing the Dhamma at the right time, calming at the right time, contemplating at the right time. These, bhikkhus, are the four times.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.146", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.146" },
{ text: `Then the Venerable Ānanda went to that bhikkhunī, sat down on the prepared seat, and said to her: 'Sister, this body is produced by food, depends on food. Food is to be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by craving, depends on craving. Craving is to be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by conceit, depends on conceit. Conceit is to be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by sexual intercourse, depends on sexual intercourse. Concerning sexual intercourse, the Blessed One has spoken of the breaking of the bridge. 'Sister, this body is produced by food, depends on food. Food is to be abandoned.' Thus it was said. For what reason was this said?'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.159", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.159" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is painful with slow direct knowledge? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the foul on the body, with perception of disgust for food, with perception of non-delight in the entire world, contemplating impermanence in all formations, and the perception of death is well established internally. He lives depending on the five learner's powers, that is, the power of faith, the power of conscience, the power of fear of wrongdoing, the power of energy, the power of wisdom. For him, these five faculties appear very soft: the faculty of faith, the faculty of energy, the faculty of mindfulness, the faculty of concentration, the faculty of wisdom. Because these five faculties appear very soft, he attains the immediate concentration for the destruction of the taints slowly. This, bhikkhus, is called the course of practice that is painful with slow direct knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.163" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is painful with quick direct knowledge? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the foul on the body ... the perception of death is well established internally. He lives depending on the five learner's powers ... For him, these five faculties appear very keen: the faculty of faith ... the faculty of wisdom. Because these five faculties appear very keen, he attains the immediate concentration for the destruction of the taints quickly. This, bhikkhus, is called the course of practice that is painful with quick direct knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.163" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is pleasant with slow direct knowledge? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and abides in the first jhāna ... with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, enters and abides in the second jhāna ... with the fading away of rapture, enters and abides in the third jhāna ... with the abandoning of pleasure and pain, enters and abides in the fourth jhāna ... He lives depending on the five learner's powers: the power of faith, the power of conscience, the power of fear of wrongdoing, the power of energy, the power of wisdom. For him, these five faculties appear very soft: the faculty of faith, the faculty of energy, the faculty of mindfulness, the faculty of concentration, the faculty of wisdom. Because these five faculties appear very soft, he attains the immediate concentration for the destruction of the taints slowly. This, bhikkhus, is called the course of practice that is pleasant with slow direct knowledge. And, bhikkhus, what is the course of practice that is pleasant with quick direct knowledge? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna ... He lives depending on the five learner's powers ... For him, these five faculties appear very keen: the faculty of faith ... the faculty of wisdom. Because these five faculties appear very keen, he attains the immediate concentration for the destruction of the taints quickly. This, bhikkhus, is called the course of practice that is pleasant with quick direct knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.163" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four courses of action that should not be taken. What four? Taking a course of action due to desire, taking a course of action due to hatred, taking a course of action due to delusion, taking a course of action due to fear. These four courses of action should not be taken.<br><br>Led by desire, hatred,<br>By fear and delusion,<br>Whoever transgresses the Dhamma,<br>That person's reputation<br>Is diminished and harmed,<br>Like the moon in the dark fortnight.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.17" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there is no samaṇa, brahmin, deva, Māra, Brahmā, or anyone in the world who can obtain assurance regarding four things. What four? The nature of aging — may I not age — no samaṇa ... regarding this. The nature of sickness — may I not be sick — no samaṇa ... regarding this. The nature of death — may I not die — no samaṇa ... regarding this. The painful results of those evil deeds that are defiled, leading to renewed existence, bringing distress, bringing painful results of future birth, aging, and death — may those results not occur — no samaṇa ... regarding this. Bhikkhus, there is no samaṇa, brahmin, deva, Māra, Brahmā, or anyone in the world who can obtain assurance regarding these four things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.182", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.182" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four things to be realized. What four? There are things, bhikkhus, to be realized by the body; there are things, bhikkhus, to be realized by mindfulness; there are things, bhikkhus, to be realized by the eye; there are things, bhikkhus, to be realized by wisdom. And what, bhikkhus, are the things to be realized by the body? The eight liberations, bhikkhus, are to be realized by the body. And what, bhikkhus, are the things to be realized by mindfulness? Past lives, bhikkhus, are to be realized by mindfulness. And what, bhikkhus, are the things to be realized by the eye? The passing away and rebirth of beings, bhikkhus, are to be realized by the eye. And what, bhikkhus, are the things to be realized by wisdom? The destruction of the taints, bhikkhus, is to be realized by wisdom. These, bhikkhus, are the four things to be realized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.189", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.189" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu one who dwells attaining the state of devas? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures ... enters and abides in the first jhāna ... the second jhāna ... the third jhāna ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who dwells attaining the state of devas. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu one who dwells attaining the state of Brahmā? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness ... with compassion ... with altruistic joy ... with equanimity, likewise the second, the third, the fourth. Thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he abides pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with equanimity, vast, great, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who dwells attaining the state of Brahmā.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.190", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.190" },
{ text: `And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu one who dwells attaining the imperturbable? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, having completely transcended perceptions of form, having ended perceptions of resistance, not attending to perceptions of diversity, thinking: 'Space is infinite,' enters and abides in the base of infinite space. Having completely transcended the base of infinite space, thinking: 'Consciousness is infinite,' enters and abides in the base of infinite consciousness. Having completely transcended the base of infinite consciousness, thinking: 'There is nothing,' enters and abides in the base of nothingness. Having completely transcended the base of nothingness, enters and abides in the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who well attains the imperturbable. And how, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who attains the state of the noble ones? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu truly understands: 'This is suffering' ... 'This is the origin of suffering' ... 'This is the cessation of suffering' ... truly understands: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who attains the state of the noble ones.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.190", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.190" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four cases are to be understood with four cases. What four? Bhikkhus, by living together, virtue is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom. Bhikkhus, by doing a task together, purity of conduct is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom. Bhikkhus, in times of misfortune, fortitude is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom. Bhikkhus, by discussion, wisdom is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.192", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.192" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, by living together with another person, one knows: 'For a long time, this venerable one's virtue is broken, cracked, stained, blemished, black; his practice is not consistent, his conduct is not consistent in the precepts. This venerable one is immoral, this venerable one is not virtuous.' But here, bhikkhus, by living together with another person, one knows: 'For a long time, this venerable one's virtue is not broken, not cracked, not stained, not blemished, not black; his practice is consistent, his conduct is consistent in the precepts. This venerable one is virtuous, this venerable one is not immoral.' Bhikkhus, by living together, virtue is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom — thus it was said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.192", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.192" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, by doing a task together with another person, one knows: 'This venerable one is one way when working with one person, another way with two, another way with three, another way with many; his conduct is inconsistent, his earlier actions differ from his later actions. This venerable one's conduct is impure, this venerable one is impure in conduct.' But here, bhikkhus, by doing a task together with another person, one knows: 'Just as this venerable one is when working with one person, so he is with two, so with three, so with many; his conduct is consistent, his earlier actions are the same as his later actions. This venerable one's conduct is pure, this venerable one is pure in conduct.' Bhikkhus, by doing a task together, purity of conduct is to be understood — thus, over a long time, not otherwise, with attention, not without attention, with wisdom, not with poor wisdom — thus it was said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.192", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.192" },
{ text: `Bhaddiya, do not be led by report, do not be led by tradition, do not be led by hearsay, do not be led by the authority of scriptures, do not be led by logical reasoning, do not be led by inference, do not be led by reflection on appearances, do not be led by agreement with a considered opinion, do not be led by what seems possible, do not be led by the thought: 'He is our teacher.' But, Bhaddiya, when you know for yourselves: 'These things are unwholesome; these things are blameworthy; these things are criticized by the wise; these things, when undertaken and practiced, lead to harm and suffering' — then, Bhaddiya, you should abandon them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.193", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.193" },
{ text: `What do you think, Bhaddiya? When greed arises in a person's mind, does it arise for welfare or for harm?" - "For harm, Venerable Sir." - "Bhaddiya, a greedy person, overcome by greed, with mind obsessed, kills living beings, takes what is not given, commits adultery, speaks falsely, and encourages others to do likewise. Would that lead to his long-term harm and suffering?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "What do you think, Bhaddiya? When hatred arises ... when delusion arises ... when anger arises in a person's mind, does it arise for welfare or for harm?" - "For harm, Venerable Sir." - "Bhaddiya, an angry person, overcome by anger, with mind obsessed, kills living beings ... and encourages others to do likewise. Would that lead to his long-term harm and suffering?" - "Yes, Venerable Sir." - "What do you think, Bhaddiya, are these things wholesome or unwholesome?" - "Unwholesome, Venerable Sir." - "Blameworthy or blameless?" - "Blameworthy, Venerable Sir." - "Criticized by the wise or praised by the wise?" - "Criticized by the wise, Venerable Sir." - "When undertaken and practiced, do they lead to harm and suffering, or what is your view?" - "When undertaken and practiced, they lead to harm and suffering. That is our view.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.193", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.193" },
{ text: `Bhaddiya, all the noble ones who are at peace in the world encourage their disciples thus: 'Come, friend! Subdue greed, live with greed subdued! By living with greed subdued, you will not do deeds born of greed by body, speech, or mind! Subdue hatred! Subdue hatred! By living with hatred subdued, you will not do deeds born of hatred by body, speech, or mind! Subdue delusion! Subdue delusion! By living with delusion subdued, you will not do deeds born of delusion by body, speech, or mind! Subdue anger! Subdue anger! By living with anger subdued, you will not do deeds born of anger by body, speech, or mind!'" When this was said, Bhaddiya the Licchavi said to the Blessed One: 'Wonderful, Venerable Sir! ... May the Blessed One accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I go for refuge.' - 'Bhaddiya, did I ever say to you: "Come, Bhaddiya, become my disciple, Bhaddiya; I will be your teacher"?' - 'No, Venerable Sir.' - 'Thus, Bhaddiya, those samaṇas and brahmins who say and declare such things are unvirtuous, empty, false, and misrepresenting with untruth: "Samaṇa Gotama is a magician; he knows a magic trick to draw in disciples of other sects!"' - 'Venerable Sir, that enticing magic trick is good, that enticing magic trick is excellent. Venerable Sir, may all my beloved blood relatives be enticed by that magic trick! Thus all my blood relatives would have long-term welfare and happiness!'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.193", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.193" },
{ text: `Byagghapajjā, this is called purity of virtue. With the resolution: 'If this purity of virtue is incomplete, I will complete it. If this purity of virtue is complete, I will learn further here and there with wisdom.' Here, the desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension — these, Byagghapajjā, are called the factor of striving for purity of virtue. Here, Byagghapajjā, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures ... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. This, Byagghapajjā, is called purity of mind. With the resolution: 'If this purity of mind is incomplete, I will complete it. If it is complete, I will learn further here and there with wisdom.' Here, the desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension — these, Byagghapajjā, are called the factor of striving for purity of mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.194", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.194" },
{ text: `Here, Byagghapajjā, a bhikkhu truly understands: 'This is suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the origin of suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the cessation of suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' This, Byagghapajjā, is called purity of view. With the resolution: 'If this purity of view is incomplete, I will complete it. If it is complete, I will learn further here and there with wisdom.' Here, the desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension — these, Byagghapajjā, are called the factor of striving for purity of view. And, Byagghapajjā, what is the factor of striving for purity of liberation? When a noble disciple, Byagghapajjā, possesses this factor of striving for purity of virtue, this factor of striving for purity of mind, and this factor of striving for purity of view, his mind becomes detached from states that are enticing, his mind becomes liberated from states that are to be liberated. Having detached his mind from enticing states and liberated it from states to be liberated, he experiences right liberation. This, Byagghapajjā, is called purity of liberation. With the resolution: 'If this purity of liberation is incomplete, I will complete it. If it is complete, I will learn further here and there with wisdom.' Here, the desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension — these, Byagghapajjā, are called the factor of striving for purity of liberation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.194", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.194" },
{ text: `'Householder, when the mind is agitated, then bodily action is agitated, verbal action is agitated, mental action is agitated. For one whose bodily action is corrupted, verbal action is corrupted, mental action is corrupted, death is not good, the end is not good. Householder, just as a house with a poorly thatched roof — the ridgepole is agitated, the rafters are agitated, the walls are agitated. So too, householder, when the mind is agitated, then bodily action is agitated ... death is not good, the end is not good.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.110", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.110" },
{ text: `There are these three causes, bhikkhus, for the origination of action. What three? Greed is a cause for the origination of action, hatred is a cause for the origination of action, delusion is a cause for the origination of action. Whatever action is done through greed, bhikkhus, born from greed, caused by greed, originating from greed — that action is unwholesome, that action is blameworthy, that action has a painful result, that action leads to the origination of action, that action does not lead to the cessation of action. Whatever action is done through hatred ... through delusion, bhikkhus, born from delusion, caused by delusion, originating from delusion — that action is unwholesome, that action is blameworthy, that action has a painful result, that action leads to the origination of action, that action does not lead to the cessation of action. These three things, bhikkhus, are the three causes for the origination of action.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.111", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.111" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three deficiencies. What three? Deficiency in virtue, deficiency in mind, deficiency in view. And what, bhikkhus, is deficiency in virtue? Here, bhikkhus, a person kills living beings, takes what is not given, engages in sexual misconduct, speaks falsely, speaks divisively, speaks harshly, speaks idly. This, bhikkhus, is called deficiency in virtue. And what, bhikkhus, is deficiency in mind? Here, bhikkhus, a person is covetous and has a mind of ill-will. This, bhikkhus, is called deficiency in mind. And what, bhikkhus, is deficiency in view? Here, bhikkhus, a person holds wrong view, a distorted view: 'There is no giving, no sacrifice, no offering; no fruit or result of good and bad actions; no this world, no next world; no mother, no father; no spontaneously reborn beings; no samaṇas or brahmins in the world who, having practiced rightly, have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge.' This, bhikkhus, is called deficiency in view. Due to deficiency in virtue ... due to deficiency in mind ... due to deficiency in view, bhikkhus, beings, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.117" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three perfections. What three? Perfection in virtue, perfection in mind, perfection in view. And what, bhikkhus, is perfection in virtue? Here, bhikkhus, a person abstains from killing living beings, abstains from taking what is not given, abstains from sexual misconduct, abstains from false speech, abstains from divisive speech, abstains from harsh speech, abstains from idle chatter. This, bhikkhus, is called perfection in virtue. And what, bhikkhus, is perfection in mind? Here, bhikkhus, a person is not covetous and has a mind without ill-will. This, bhikkhus, is called perfection in mind. And what, bhikkhus, is perfection in view? Here, bhikkhus, a person holds right view, an undistorted view: 'There is giving, sacrifice, offering; there is fruit and result of good and bad actions; there is this world and the next world; there is mother, father; there are spontaneously reborn beings; there are samaṇas and brahmins in the world who, having practiced rightly, have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge.' This, bhikkhus, is called perfection in view. Due to perfection in virtue ... due to perfection in mind ... due to perfection in view, bhikkhus, beings, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. These, bhikkhus, are the three perfections.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.117" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of purity. What three? Purity of body, purity of speech, purity of mind. What is purity of body? Here, bhikkhus, a person abstains from killing living beings, abstains from taking what is not given, abstains from sexual misconduct. This, bhikkhus, is called purity of body. And what, bhikkhus, is purity of speech? Here, bhikkhus, a person abstains from false speech, abstains from divisive speech, abstains from harsh speech, abstains from idle chatter. This, bhikkhus, is called purity of speech. And what, bhikkhus, is purity of mind? Here, bhikkhus, a person is not covetous, has a mind without ill-will, and holds right view. This, bhikkhus, is called purity of mind. These, bhikkhus, are the three kinds of purity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.120" },
			
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is purity of mind? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, if there is sensual desire internally, he knows: 'There is sensual desire internally.' If there is no sensual desire internally, he knows: 'There is no sensual desire internally.' How unarisen sensual desire arises, he knows that. How arisen sensual desire is abandoned, he knows that. And how abandoned sensual desire does not arise in the future, he knows that. If there is ill-will internally, he knows: 'There is ill-will internally.' ... If there is dullness and drowsiness ... if there is restlessness and remorse ... if there is doubt internally, he knows: 'There is doubt internally.' If there is no doubt internally, he knows: 'There is no doubt internally.' How unarisen doubt arises, he knows that. How arisen doubt is abandoned, he knows that. And how abandoned doubt does not arise in the future, he knows that. This, bhikkhus, is called purity of mind.<br><br>Purity of body and speech,<br>Mind's purity without taints.<br>Being clean and purified,<br>Is called the destruction of evil.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.121" },

{ text: `When that night had passed, that bhikkhu in the morning, having dressed, taking his robe and bowl, went to the dwelling of a householder or a householder's son. Having gone there, he sat down on the prepared seat. Then the householder or the householder's son, with their own hands, served and satisfied that bhikkhu with various exquisite foods, both hard and soft. He did not think: 'How good that this householder or householder's son, with their own hands, serves and satisfies me with various exquisite foods, both hard and soft!' And he did not think: 'May this householder or householder's son in the future, with their own hands, serve and satisfy me with various exquisite foods, both hard and soft!' He partook of that almsfood without attachment, without infatuation, without obsession, seeing the danger, seeing the escape. Therein, he aroused thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming. Bhikkhus, I say that giving to such a bhikkhu is of great fruit. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu does not dwell heedlessly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.123", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.123" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who shoots like a lightning flash? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu truly understands as it really is: 'This is suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the origin of suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the cessation of suffering'; truly understands: 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who shoots like a lightning flash. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who pierces a great mass? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu pierces the great mass of ignorance. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who pierces a great mass. Possessing these three qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.133", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.133" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, possessing three qualities, a friend should be associated with. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu gives what is hard to give, does what is hard to do, endures what is hard to endure. Bhikkhus, possessing these three qualities, a friend should be associated with.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.135", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.135" },

{ text: `Whether Tathāgatas arise or do not arise, bhikkhus, that element still persists, that fixity of Dhamma, that specific conditionality: 'All conditioned things are impermanent.' This the Tathāgata has fully awakened to, has fully understood. Having fully awakened to it and fully understood it, he declares, teaches, proclaims, establishes, discloses, analyzes, and elucidates: 'All conditioned things are impermanent.' Whether Tathāgatas arise or do not arise, bhikkhus, that element still persists, that fixity of Dhamma, that specific conditionality: 'All conditioned things are suffering.' This the Tathāgata has fully awakened to, has fully understood... he declares... 'All conditioned things are suffering.' Whether Tathāgatas arise or do not arise, bhikkhus, that element still persists, that fixity of Dhamma, that specific conditionality: 'All phenomena are not-self.' This the Tathāgata has fully awakened to, has fully understood. Having fully awakened to it and fully understood it, he declares, teaches, proclaims, establishes, discloses, analyzes, and elucidates: 'All phenomena are not-self.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.136" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, among all kinds of woven cloth, a hair-blanket is considered the lowest. A hair-blanket, bhikkhus, is cold when it is cold, hot when it is hot, ugly, foul-smelling, and unpleasant to the touch. So too, bhikkhus, among the doctrines of the outside ascetics, the doctrine of Makkhali is considered the lowest. Bhikkhus, the foolish Makkhali has this view, this opinion: 'There is no action, no result of action, no striving.' Bhikkhus, those who were Arahants, Perfectly Enlightened Ones, Blessed Ones in the past, they all taught that there is action, that there is result of action, that there is striving. But, bhikkhus, the foolish Makkhali contradicts them all, saying: 'There is no action, no result of action, no striving.' Bhikkhus, those who will be Arahants, Perfectly Enlightened Ones, Blessed Ones in the future, they will all teach that there is action, that there is result of action, that there is striving. But, bhikkhus, the foolish Makkhali contradicts them all, saying: 'There is no action, no result of action, no striving.' And I myself, bhikkhus, now an Arahant, Perfectly Enlightened One, also teach that there is action, that there is result of action, that there is striving. But, bhikkhus, the foolish Makkhali contradicts me, saying: 'There is no action, no result of action, no striving.' Just as, bhikkhus, at the mouth of a river, someone sets a fish-trap, bringing misfortune, suffering, loss, and calamity to the fish. Just so, bhikkhus, at the mouth of a river, someone sets a fish-trap, bringing misfortune, suffering, loss, and calamity to the fish.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.137", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.137" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, in accordance with Dhamma, the Dhamma-King, relying on Dhamma, honoring Dhamma, respecting Dhamma, venerating Dhamma, having Dhamma as his banner, having Dhamma as his flag, having Dhamma as his supremacy, gives protection, shelter, and support in accordance with Dhamma regarding bodily action, thinking: 'Such bodily action should be practiced, such bodily action should not be practiced.' Furthermore, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata... gives protection, shelter, and support in accordance with Dhamma regarding verbal action, thinking: 'Such verbal action should be practiced, such verbal action should not be practiced'; regarding mental action, thinking: 'Such mental action should be practiced, such mental action should not be practiced.' That Tathāgata... having given protection, shelter, and support... regarding bodily action, verbal action, mental action, sets in motion the wheel of Dhamma. That wheel is not to be turned back by any ascetic, brahmin, deva, Māra, Brahmā, or anyone in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.14" },

{ text: `One person, bhikkhus, when he arises in the world, his arising is for the welfare of the many, for the happiness of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of devas and humans. Who is that one person? It is the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. This one person, bhikkhus, when he arises in the world, his arising is for the welfare of the many, for the happiness of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of devas and humans.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.170" },

{ text: `The arising of one person, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world. Of whom? Of the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. The arising of this one person, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.171", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.171-174" },

{ text: `This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that a person possessed of right view could regard any conditioned thing as permanent. This is impossible. And it is possible, bhikkhus, that an ordinary person could regard any conditioned thing as permanent. This is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.268", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.268" },

{ text: `This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that the result of an evil bodily action could be desirable, pleasant, and agreeable. This is impossible. And it is possible, bhikkhus, that the result of an evil bodily action is undesirable, unpleasant, and disagreeable. This is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.284", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.284-286" },

{ text: `For a person of right view, bhikkhus, all bodily actions that are undertaken and accepted in accordance with that right view, all verbal actions... all mental actions that are undertaken and accepted in accordance with that right view, whatever intentions, decisions, aspirations, and whatever volitional activities — all those states lead to what is desirable, pleasant, and agreeable, leading to happiness and well-being.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.315", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.315" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, someone reflects thus: 'The result of evil bodily action in the hereafter is evil and painful. The result of evil verbal action in the hereafter is evil and painful. The result of evil mental action in the hereafter is evil and painful. If I do evil bodily action, speak evil speech, think evil thoughts, then after death, with the breakup of the body, I might be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.' That person, fearing the result of evil in the hereafter, abandons evil bodily action and cultivates good bodily action, abandons evil verbal action and cultivates good verbal action, abandons evil mental action and cultivates good mental action, and maintains completely pure conduct.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'We will have fear of evil results in the present life. We will have fear of evil results in the hereafter. We will avoid evil deeds. We will see the danger in evil deeds.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves. For one who avoids evil deeds, bhikkhus, and sees the danger in evil deeds, it is to be expected that he will be freed from all evil deeds.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if you do not backslide, striving thus: 'Let only skin, sinews, and bones remain, let the flesh and blood dry up in my body, but I will not relax my energy until I have attained what can be attained by human strength, human effort, human persistence' — then before long, bhikkhus, you will attain that supreme goal of the holy life for which clansmen rightly go forth from home to homelessness, namely the unsurpassed final goal of the holy life, having directly known and realized it for yourselves here and now and abide in it.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.5" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, whoever dwells seeing the gratification in states that are prone to being fettered, for him, bhikkhus, greed is not abandoned, hatred is not abandoned, delusion is not abandoned. Through greed not being abandoned, hatred not being abandoned, delusion not being abandoned, he is not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not freed from suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, whoever dwells seeing the danger in states that are prone to being fettered, for him, bhikkhus, greed is abandoned, hatred is abandoned, delusion is abandoned. Through greed being abandoned, hatred being abandoned, delusion being abandoned, he is freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is freed from suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.6" },

{ text: `These two bright qualities, bhikkhus, protect the world. What two? Moral shame and moral dread. If these two bright qualities did not protect the world, then one would not recognize 'this is my mother,' or 'this is my sister,' or 'this is my aunt,' or 'this is my brother's wife,' or 'this is my teacher's wife,' or 'the wife of respected elders.' And the world would fall into promiscuity, like goats, chickens, pigs, dogs, and jackals.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.9" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the power of reflection? Here, bhikkhus, someone reflects thus: 'Evil bodily action has an evil result in the present life and in the hereafter. Evil verbal action... Evil mental action has an evil result in the present life and in the hereafter.' Having reflected thus, he abandons evil bodily action and cultivates good bodily action, abandons evil verbal action and cultivates good verbal action, abandons evil mental action and cultivates good mental action, and reflects on complete purity. This, bhikkhus, is called the power of reflection.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.11" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the power of development? Here, bhikkhus, the power of development is the power of a learner. Thus, bhikkhus, by the power of development, he abandons greed, abandons hatred, abandons delusion. Having abandoned greed, hatred, and delusion, he does no evil action, he does not engage in what is bad. This, bhikkhus, is called the power of development.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.11" },

{ text: `In any dispute, bhikkhus, if the bhikkhu who commits an offense and the bhikkhu who accuses him do not carefully examine themselves, then that dispute can be expected to be prolonged, harsh, and severe, and the bhikkhus will not dwell at ease. And in any dispute, bhikkhus, if the bhikkhu who commits an offense and the bhikkhu who accuses him do carefully examine themselves, then that dispute can be expected not to be prolonged, harsh, or severe, and the bhikkhus will dwell at ease.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.15" },

{ text: `Ānanda, I have declared unequivocally that evil bodily action, evil verbal action, and evil mental action should not be done. If one does what should not be done, the following dangers are to be expected: self-reproach; after being known, the wise reproach; a bad reputation spreads; one dies confused; and after death, with the breakup of the body, one is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Therefore, Ānanda, I have declared unequivocally that evil bodily action, evil verbal action, and evil mental action should not be done. For one who does what should not be done, these are the dangers to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.18" },

{ text: `Ānanda, I have declared unequivocally that good bodily action, good verbal action, and good mental action should be done. If one does what should be done, the following benefits are to be expected: self-reproach does not arise; after being known, the wise praise; a good reputation spreads; one does not die confused; and after death, with the breakup of the body, one is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world, in this world. Therefore, Ānanda, I have declared unequivocally that good bodily action, good verbal action, and good mental action should be done. For one who does what should be done, these are the benefits to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.18" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, abandon what is unwholesome. Bhikkhus, it is possible to abandon what is unwholesome. If it were impossible to abandon what is unwholesome, I would not have said: 'Bhikkhus, abandon what is unwholesome.' But since it is possible to abandon what is unwholesome, therefore I say: 'Bhikkhus, abandon what is unwholesome.' And if abandoning what is unwholesome led to harm and suffering, I would not have said: 'Bhikkhus, abandon what is unwholesome.' But since abandoning what is unwholesome leads to happiness and well-being, therefore I say: 'Bhikkhus, abandon what is unwholesome.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.19" },

{ text: `These two things, bhikkhus, lead to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. What two? Misplaced words and misinterpreted meaning. When words are misplaced, the meaning is misinterpreted. These two things, bhikkhus, lead to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.20" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the status of a non-genuine person? A non-genuine person, bhikkhus, is ungrateful and does not acknowledge help. For wicked people, this is their characteristic, bhikkhus: being ungrateful and not acknowledging help. That is entirely the status of a non-genuine person, bhikkhus: being ungrateful and not acknowledging help. A genuine person, bhikkhus, is grateful and acknowledges help. For good people, this is their characteristic, bhikkhus: being grateful and acknowledging help. That is entirely the status of a genuine person, bhikkhus: being grateful and acknowledging help.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.32" },

{ text: `There are two persons, bhikkhus, whom I say cannot be repaid. What two? Mother and father. Even if one should carry one's mother on one shoulder and one's father on the other for a hundred years, living a hundred years; and if one should anoint them, bathe them, rub them, massage them, and they might even urinate and defecate there — even so, bhikkhus, one would not have done enough nor repaid one's mother and father. Moreover, bhikkhus, if one were to establish one's parents in supreme sovereignty over this great earth abounding in the seven treasures — even so, bhikkhus, one would not have done enough nor repaid one's mother and father. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, parents have done much for their children: they nourish them, bring them up, and introduce them to this world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.33" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, whoever encourages, guides, and establishes his unbelieving parents in faith; his morally lax parents in virtuous conduct; his stingy parents in generosity; his unwise parents in wisdom — thus, bhikkhus, he has done enough and repaid his mother and father.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.33" },

{ text: `- How many persons, Bhante, are worthy of offerings in the world? And where should one give alms and offerings?<br>- There are two persons, householder, worthy of offerings in the world: the learner and the non-learner. These two persons are worthy of offerings in the world, householder; it is to them that one should give alms and offerings.<br>The Blessed One said this, and the Well-Farer having spoken, the Teacher further said:<br><br>Learner and non-learner<br>Both here in the world<br>Are worthy of offerings<br>To those who pay homage<br>They keep body upright<br>And speech and mind as well<br>Field of merit for givers<br>Here gift bears great fruit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.35" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, you should train yourselves thus: 'We will have peaceful faculties, peaceful minds.' Sāriputta, you should train thus. For those with peaceful faculties, Sāriputta, and peaceful minds, their bodily action will also be peaceful, verbal action peaceful, mental action peaceful. 'We will offer a peaceful gift to our fellow celibates.' Thus, Sāriputta, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.36" },

{ text: `- For what reason, Venerable Kaccāna, for what condition, do nobles dispute with nobles, brahmins with brahmins, householders with householders?<br>- Because of attachment to sensual pleasures, being bound, infatuated, possessed, and obsessed, brahmin, nobles dispute with nobles, brahmins with brahmins, householders with householders.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.37" },

{ text: `- For what reason, Venerable Kaccāna, for what condition, do ascetics dispute with ascetics?<br>- Because of attachment to views, being bound, infatuated, possessed, and obsessed, brahmin, ascetics dispute with ascetics.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.37" },

{ text: `If an elder, brahmin, 80, 90, or 100 years old, enjoys sensual pleasures, lives amidst sensual pleasures, is burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, consumed by thoughts of sensual pleasures, and strives in search of sensual pleasures — such a one is called a fool, not an elder. Even if a person is young, brahmin, a youthful youth with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth in the prime of life, but he does not enjoy sensual pleasures, does not live amidst sensual pleasures, is not burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, is not consumed by thoughts of sensual pleasures, and does not strive in search of sensual pleasures — such a one is called a wise person, an elder.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.38" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when evil bhikkhus are strong, then pure bhikkhus are weak. At that time, bhikkhus, pure bhikkhus maintain silence, or they hide themselves among the community of bhikkhus, or they go to border countries. And thus, bhikkhus, that is for the unhappiness of the many, for the lack of well-being of the many, for the disadvantage of the many, for the unhappiness and suffering of devas and humans.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.39" },

{ text: `Those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, who obstruct both the letter and the meaning by misrepresenting the discourses and the appropriate texts — those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, are responsible for the unhappiness of the many, for the lack of well-being of the many, for the disadvantage of the many, for the unhappiness and suffering of devas and humans. Moreover, those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, accumulate much demerit and cause the good Dhamma to disappear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.41" },

{ text: `Those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, who follow both the letter and the meaning by correctly representing the discourses and the appropriate texts — those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, are responsible for the happiness of the many, for the well-being of the many, for the advantage of the many, for the happiness and well-being of devas and humans. Moreover, those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, accumulate much merit and maintain the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.41" },

{ text: `There are these two kinds of assemblies, bhikkhus. What two? A superficial assembly and a profound assembly. And, bhikkhus, what is a superficial assembly? Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly there are bhikkhus who are restless, arrogant, talkative, garrulous, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, unconcentrated, with distracted minds and loose faculties. This, bhikkhus, is called a superficial assembly. And, bhikkhus, what is a profound assembly? Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly there are bhikkhus who are not restless, not arrogant, not agitated, not talkative, not garrulous, mindful, clearly comprehending, concentrated, with unified minds and guarded faculties. This, bhikkhus, is called a profound assembly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.42" },

{ text: `There are these two kinds of assemblies, bhikkhus. What two? A disunited assembly and a united assembly. And, bhikkhus, what is a disunited assembly? Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, bhikkhus live in rivalry, disputation, conflict, wounding one another with verbal weapons. This, bhikkhus, is called a disunited assembly. And, bhikkhus, what is a united assembly? Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, bhikkhus live in harmony, cordially, without conflict, like milk mixed with water, looking upon one another with loving eyes. This, bhikkhus, is called a united assembly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.43" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, the elder bhikkhus live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. And those who come after, following their example, also live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. This, bhikkhus, is called a non-superior assembly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.44" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, the elder bhikkhus do not live in abundance, are not lazy, abandon the burden of decline, are leaders in the life of seclusion, make an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. And those who come after, following their example, also do not live in abundance, are not lazy, abandon the burden of decline, are leaders in the life of seclusion, make an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. This, bhikkhus, is called a superior assembly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.44" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, when the discourses spoken by the Tathāgata, deep, profound, transcendent, connected with the void, are being taught, the bhikkhus do not listen well, do not lend an ear, do not apply their minds to understand them, and they do not think that these teachings should be learned and memorized. But when the poetic discourses composed by poets, with beautiful vowels and consonants, of outsiders, spoken by disciples of outsiders, are being taught, they listen well, lend an ear, apply their minds to understand them, and they think that these teachings should be learned and memorized. This, bhikkhus, is called an assembly trained in display, not trained in questioning.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.47" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, in whatever assembly, when the discourses spoken by the Tathāgata, deep, profound, transcendent, connected with the void, are being taught, the bhikkhus listen well, lend an ear, apply their minds to understand them, and they think that these teachings should be learned and memorized. And having learned those teachings, they ask each other questions and cross-question, and they open up for discussion: 'What is this? What is the meaning of this?' They reveal what is hidden, they disclose what is undisclosed, they dispel doubt regarding various doubtful points in the good Dhamma. This, bhikkhus, is called an assembly trained in questioning, not trained in display.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.47" },

{ text: `There are these two kinds of happiness, bhikkhus. What two? The happiness of household life and the happiness of renunciation. These, bhikkhus, are the two kinds of happiness. The foremost of these two kinds of happiness, bhikkhus, is the happiness of renunciation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.64" },

{ text: `There are these two kinds of happiness, bhikkhus. What two? Sensual happiness and the happiness of renunciation. These, bhikkhus, are the two kinds of happiness. The foremost of these two kinds of happiness, bhikkhus, is the happiness of renunciation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.65" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person with hope? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is of good character. He hears: 'A bhikkhu named such-and-such has, through the destruction of the taints, in this very life, having directly known and realized it for himself, entered and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.' He reflects thus: 'When will I too, through the destruction of the taints, in this very life, having directly known and realized it for myself, enter and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom?' Such a person, bhikkhus, is called one with hope.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.13" },

{ text: `These three things, bhikkhus, lead to harm to oneself, harm to others, and harm to both. What three? Evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. These three things, bhikkhus, lead to harm to oneself, harm to others, and harm to both.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.17" },

{ text: `These three things, bhikkhus, do not lead to harm to oneself, do not lead to harm to others, do not lead to harm to both. What three? Good bodily action, good verbal action, good mental action. These three things, bhikkhus, do not lead to harm to oneself, do not lead to harm to others, do not lead to harm to both.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.17" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, possessing three qualities, a bhikkhu obtains unattained wholesome states and increases attained wholesome states. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu applies ardent attention to the sign of concentration in the morning, applies ardent attention to the sign of concentration at noon, and applies ardent attention to the sign of concentration in the evening. Possessing these three qualities, a bhikkhu obtains unattained wholesome states and increases attained wholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.19" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who strives well? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, arousing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, energetic, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who strives well.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.20" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who has established a foundation? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu repeatedly visits those bhikkhus who are learned, who have mastered the collections of scriptures (Āgamas), who are bearers of the Dhamma, bearers of the Discipline, bearers of the summaries; he inquires of them, asks them: 'How is this, Venerable Sir? What is the meaning of this?' Those venerable ones reveal what is unrevealed, disclose what is undisclosed, and regarding various doubtful points, they dispel his doubts. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who has established a foundation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.20" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person accumulates harmful bodily actions, harmful verbal actions, harmful mental actions. Having accumulated harmful bodily actions, harmful verbal actions, harmful mental actions, he is reborn in a harmful world. Being reborn in a harmful world, he experiences harmful contacts. Experiencing harmful contacts, he feels harmful feelings, exclusively painful, like beings in hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.24" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person with a mind like a wound? Here, bhikkhus, a person is irritable and very resentful; even when spoken to lightly, he becomes exasperated, angry, hostile, and displays irritation, hatred, and bitterness. Just as a festering wound, if struck by a stick or a shard, discharges even more pus, so too, bhikkhus, here a person is irritable and resentful. This, bhikkhus, is called a person who is like a festering wound.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.25" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is inferior in virtue, concentration, and wisdom. Such a person, bhikkhus, should not be associated with, should not be dwelt with, should not be served or attended upon, unless out of compassion and pity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.26" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is equal to oneself in virtue, concentration, and wisdom. Such a person, bhikkhus, should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon. Why is that? Thinking: 'We are both skilled in virtue, our conversation will be about virtue, which will be beneficial for both of us and lead to our well-being. We are both skilled in concentration... We are both skilled in wisdom, our conversation will be about wisdom, which will be beneficial for both of us and lead to our well-being.' Therefore, such a person should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.26" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is superior in virtue, concentration, and wisdom. Such a person, bhikkhus, should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon, after paying homage and respect. Why is that? Thinking: 'Thus, if I am incomplete in virtue, I will complete it; or if I am complete in virtue, I will further support it here and there with wisdom. If I am incomplete in concentration... If I am incomplete in wisdom, I will complete it; or if I am complete in wisdom, I will further support it here and there with wisdom.' Therefore, such a person, after paying homage and respect, should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.26" },

{ text: `One who associates with the inferior<br>Becomes inferior himself;<br>Associating with an equal,<br>One does not decline;<br>One who associates with the superior<br>Quickly advances;<br>Therefore live with those<br>Who are superior to yourself.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.26" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is virtuous and of good character. Such a person, bhikkhus, should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon. Why is that? Even if one does not at all follow the view of such a person, still one's good reputation spreads that one has good friends, good companions, and reveres the good. Therefore, such a person should be associated with, dwelt with, served and attended upon.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.27" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person who speaks like excrement? Here, bhikkhus, when a person enters an assembly hall, or enters a meeting, or goes among his relatives, or goes among his guild, or goes to the royal court, or is called as a witness and asked: 'Come, tell what you know,' then that person, not knowing, says 'I know'; knowing, says 'I do not know'; not seeing, says 'I see'; seeing, says 'I do not see.' Thus for his own sake, or for the sake of another, or for some trifling gain, he deliberately speaks falsely. Such a person, bhikkhus, is called one who speaks like excrement.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.27" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person who speaks like flowers? Here, bhikkhus, when a person enters an assembly hall, or enters a meeting, or goes among his relatives, or goes among his guild, or goes to the royal court, or is called as a witness and asked: 'Come, tell what you know,' then that person, not knowing, says 'I do not know'; knowing, says 'I know'; not seeing, says 'I do not see'; seeing, says 'I see.' He does not deliberately speak falsely for his own sake, or for the sake of another, or for some trifling gain. Such a person, bhikkhus, is called one who speaks like flowers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.27" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person who speaks like honey? Here, bhikkhus, a person has abandoned harsh speech and refrains from harsh speech. His speech is harmless, pleasing to the ear, affectionate, going to the heart, courteous, liked by many, pleasing to many. He speaks such words. This, bhikkhus, is called a person who speaks like honey.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.27" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person with inverted wisdom? Here, bhikkhus, a person goes to the monastery and often hears the Dhamma from the bhikkhus. The bhikkhus teach him the Dhamma, beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life. While sitting there, he does not attend to the beginning of that discourse, does not attend to the middle, does not attend to the end. Likewise, when he rises from that seat, he does not attend to the beginning, does not attend to the middle, does not attend to the end. Just as, bhikkhus, an overturned pot pours out the water contained in it and does not retain it, so too, bhikkhus, here a person goes to the monastery... does not attend to the end. Likewise, when he rises from that seat, he does not attend to the beginning... does not attend to the end. This, bhikkhus, is called a person with inverted wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.30" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a person with expansive wisdom? Here, bhikkhus, a person goes to the monastery and often hears the Dhamma from the bhikkhus. The bhikkhus teach him the Dhamma, beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life. While sitting there, he attends to the beginning of that discourse, attends to the middle, attends to the end. Likewise, when he rises from that seat, he attends to the beginning, attends to the middle, attends to the end. Just as, bhikkhus, an upright pot retains the water poured into it and does not pour it out, so too, bhikkhus, here a person goes to the monastery... attends to the end. Likewise, when he rises from that seat, he attends to the beginning... attends to the end. This, bhikkhus, is called a person with expansive wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.30" },

{ text: `One with expansive wisdom<br>Is said to be the best<br>They constantly go to<br>Approach the bhikkhus<br>The beginning of the teaching<br>The middle and the end<br>Sitting in their place<br>They grasp the words<br>Remember what is heard<br>Contemplate the supreme<br>With mind undisturbed<br>Such is that person<br>Practicing Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma<br>They can end suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.30" },

{ text: `In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children at home honor their mother and father, those families are considered equal to Brahmā. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children at home honor their mother and father, those families are considered like the ancient teachers. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children at home honor their mother and father, those families are considered worthy of offerings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.31" },

{ text: `Brahmā, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. The ancient teachers, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Worthy of offerings, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Why is that? Because parents have done much for their children: they nourish them, bring them up, and introduce them to this world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.31" },

{ text: `Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'This is peaceful, this is sublime, namely the stilling of all formations, the relinquishment of all attachments, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.' Thus, Ānanda, it is possible that a bhikkhu, being such, in this conscious body has no conceit 'I am,' no conceit 'mine,' and no underlying tendency to conceit; regarding all external signs, he has no conceit 'I am,' no conceit 'mine,' and no underlying tendency to conceit; and by attaining and abiding in the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom, free from conceit 'I am,' free from conceit 'mine,' free from the underlying tendency to conceit, he can attain and abide in the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.32" },

{ text: `Having sat down to one side, Hatthaka of Āḷavī said to the Blessed One: "Bhante, does the Blessed One dwell at ease?" - "Yes, prince, I dwell at ease. And among those who feel at ease in the world, I am one of them." - "Bhante, the winter night is cold, the period between the eighths is the time of snowfall, the ground is hard from being trampled by oxen and cattle, the leaf-bed is thin, the leaves on the trees are sparse, the robe is cold, and the wind blows cold." Then the Blessed One said: "Nevertheless, prince, I dwell at ease. And among those who feel at ease in the world, I am one of them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.35" },

{ text: `What do you think, prince? For that householder or householder's son, do there arise physical or mental fevers born of craving? Being burned by those fevers born of craving, does he feel suffering?" - "Yes, Bhante." - "That householder or householder's son, prince, being burned by fevers born of craving, feels suffering. That craving has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made nonexistent, made unable to arise in the future. Therefore, I feel at ease.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.35" },

{ text: `Always at ease,<br>Transgressing calm and peace,<br>Not stained by sensual defilements,<br>Cool, without attachment,<br>All clinging abandoned,<br>Overcoming sorrow and grief,<br>Peaceful, he feels happiness<br>With mind attained to peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.35" },

{ text: `For me, bhikkhus, endowed with such great wealth, with such a refined and complete nourishment, I reflected thus: 'An unlearned ordinary person, himself subject to aging, not beyond aging, when seeing another who is aged, is disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted, forgetting that he himself is likewise. I too am subject to aging, not beyond aging; after seeing another who is aged, can I be disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted? That would not be proper for me.' Having reflected on myself thus, bhikkhus, the pride of youth in youth was completely abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `For me, bhikkhus, endowed with such great wealth, with such a refined and complete nourishment, I reflected thus: 'An unlearned ordinary person, himself subject to sickness, not beyond sickness, when seeing another who is sick, is disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted, forgetting that he himself is likewise. I too am subject to sickness, not beyond sickness; after seeing another who is sick, can I be disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted? That would not be proper for me.' Having reflected on myself thus, bhikkhus, the pride of health in health was completely abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `For me, bhikkhus, endowed with such great wealth, with such a refined and complete nourishment, I reflected thus: 'An unlearned ordinary person, himself subject to death, not beyond death, when seeing another who has died, is disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted, forgetting that he himself is likewise. I too am subject to death, not beyond death; after seeing another who has died, can I be disturbed, ashamed, and disgusted? That would not be proper for me.' Having reflected on myself thus, bhikkhus, the pride of life in life was completely abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `There are these three kinds of pride, bhikkhus. What three? Pride of youth, pride of health, pride of life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `Intoxicated with the pride of youth, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person does evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions. Having done evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `Intoxicated with the pride of health, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person does evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions. Having done evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `Intoxicated with the pride of life, bhikkhus, an unlearned ordinary person does evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions. Having done evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `Intoxicated with the pride of youth, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu gives up the training and returns to the lay life. Intoxicated with the pride of health, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu gives up the training and returns to the lay life. Intoxicated with the pride of life, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu gives up the training and returns to the lay life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.39" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to a forest, or to the foot of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects thus: 'It is not for the sake of robes that I have gone forth from home to homelessness. It is not for the sake of almsfood, not for the sake of lodging, not for the sake of this or that state of existence that I have gone forth from home to homelessness. But rather, thinking: "I am subject to birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair; I am subject to suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Perhaps the complete destruction of this whole mass of suffering can be made known." And having gone forth from home to homelessness, if I were to pursue sensual desires again, even worse than before, that would not be proper for me.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.40" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'My energy is striven, not lax; my mindfulness is established, not forgetful; my body is tranquil, not agitated; my mind is concentrated, one-pointed.' He makes himself supreme, abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons the blameworthy, develops the blameless, and maintains himself in purity. This, bhikkhus, is called self-supremacy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.40" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu goes to a forest, or to the foot of a tree, or to an empty hut, and examines thus: 'It is not for the sake of robes... nor for the sake of almsfood, lodging, or this or that state of existence that I have gone forth from home to homelessness. But rather, thinking: "I am subject to birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair; I am subject to suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Perhaps the complete destruction of this whole mass of suffering can be made known." And having gone forth thus, if I were to think thoughts of sensual desire, or thoughts of ill-will, or thoughts of harming, that would not be proper for me.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.40" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'There are devas with psychic power, with divine eye, with knowledge of others' minds. They can see from afar, yet even though near they are not seen, and they can know my mind with their minds. They might know of me thus: "See this clansman who has gone forth from home to homelessness out of faith, yet he dwells mixed with evil, unwholesome states."'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.40" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'The Dhamma is well taught by the Blessed One, directly visible, immediate, inviting investigation, onward-leading, to be personally experienced by the wise. I have fellow celibates who know and see. Having gone forth in such a well-taught Dhamma and Discipline, should I dwell heedlessly and lazily? That would not be proper for me.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.40" },

{ text: `By the presence of three things, bhikkhus, a faithful clansman produces much merit. What three? By the presence of faith, bhikkhus, a faithful clansman produces much merit. By the presence of a gift, bhikkhus, a faithful clansman produces much merit. By the presence of those worthy of offerings, bhikkhus, a faithful clansman produces much merit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.41" },

{ text: `By three factors, bhikkhus, a person is known to be faithful. What three? He delights in seeing virtuous people; he delights in hearing the good Dhamma; with a mind free from the stain of miserliness, he dwells at home, generously giving with clean hands, delighting in relinquishment, ready to be asked, delighting in distributing gifts. By these three factors, bhikkhus, a person is known to be faithful.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.42" },

{ text: `These three things, bhikkhus, are proclaimed by the wise, proclaimed by genuine persons. What three? Giving, bhikkhus, is proclaimed by the wise, proclaimed by genuine persons. Going forth, bhikkhus, is proclaimed by the wise, proclaimed by genuine persons. Serving mother and father, bhikkhus, is proclaimed by the wise, proclaimed by genuine persons. These three things, bhikkhus, are proclaimed by the wise, proclaimed by genuine persons.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.45" },

{ text: `Near whatever village or town, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants dwell, there people, by three factors, reap much merit. What three? By body, by speech, by mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.46" },

{ text: `When a bhikkhu, bhikkhus, regarding unarisen evil, unwholesome states, makes a great effort to prevent their arising; regarding arisen unwholesome states, makes a great effort to abandon them; regarding unarisen wholesome states, makes a great effort to arouse them; and to endure arisen bodily feelings that are painful, sharp, racking, severe, disagreeable, unpleasant, life-threatening, he makes a great effort — that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who is ardent, careful, and mindful for the proper ending of suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.49" },

{ text: `Truly, brahmins, this world is led by aging, sickness, and death. For this world being led by aging, sickness, and death, brahmins, restraint of body, restraint of speech, restraint of mind in this life, for one who has gone to the realm of death, is the shelter, the cave, the island, the refuge, and the destination.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.51" },

{ text: `Life is led on,<br>The life span is brief,<br>Led on by aging,<br>There is no shelter.<br>Contemplate always<br>This fear of death.<br>Do meritorious deeds<br>Leading to true bliss.<br>Here restrain body,<br>Restrain speech and mind.<br>That one, even dying,<br>Enjoys happiness,<br>Because while living<br>He did meritorious deeds.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.51" },

{ text: `Infatuated by craving, brahmin, overcome, mind-possessed, one thinks of harming oneself, thinks of harming others, thinks of harming both, and experiences mental suffering and distress. When craving is abandoned, one does not think of harming oneself, does not think of harming others, does not think of harming both, and does not experience mental suffering and distress. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is directly visible, timeless, inviting investigation, onward-leading, to be personally experienced by the wise.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.53" },

{ text: `Defiled by hatred, brahmin, overcome, mind-possessed, one thinks of harming oneself, thinks of harming others, thinks of harming both, and experiences mental suffering and distress. When hatred is abandoned, one does not think of harming oneself, does not think of harming others, does not think of harming both, and does not experience mental suffering and distress. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is directly visible, timeless, inviting investigation, onward-leading, to be personally experienced by the wise.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.53" },

{ text: `Excellent, Venerable Gotama! Excellent, Venerable Gotama! Just as one sets upright what was overturned, or reveals what was hidden, or shows the way to one who is lost, or holds up a lamp in the darkness so that those with eyes can see forms, so too, the Dhamma has been explained in many ways by Venerable Gotama. I go for refuge to Venerable Gotama, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha. May Venerable Gotama accept me as a lay follower, from today until the end of my life, I take refuge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.53" },

{ text: `Nowadays, brahmins, human beings are infatuated by unlawful craving, overcome by evil greed, and dominated by wrong view. Infatuated by unlawful craving, overcome by evil greed, dominated by wrong view, they take up sharp swords and kill one another. Therefore, many people die. This is the cause, brahmins, this is the condition that nowadays human beings are being destroyed and visibly diminish, villages become non-villages, towns become non-towns, cities become non-cities, countries become non-countries.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.56" },

{ text: `Unshakable virtue,<br>Wise and concentrated,<br>With mind subdued,<br>One-pointed, well-composed,<br>The wise have destroyed darkness,<br>Three knowledges, death's end.<br>He is called the one<br>Great practice for devas and humans,<br>'The all-destroyer',<br>Complete in three knowledges.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.58" },

{ text: `One complete in virtue,<br>Ardent and concentrated,<br>With mind subdued,<br>One-pointed, well-composed,<br>Who knows former lives,<br>Sees heavens and lower realms,<br>He is a sage,<br>Destroying birth, attaining direct knowledge.<br>Whatever brahmin<br>Has realized these three knowledges,<br>I call him three-knowledge<br>Not as commonly called.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.59" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of Suffering?<br>Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, sickness is suffering, death is suffering, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are suffering. Not getting what one wants is suffering. In short, the five aggregates of clinging are suffering. This, bhikkhus, is the Noble Truth of Suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.61" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering?<br>With ignorance as condition, volitional formations arise; with volitional formations as condition, consciousness; with consciousness as condition, name-and-form; with name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases; with the six sense bases as condition, contact; with contact as condition, feeling; with feeling as condition, craving; with craving as condition, clinging; with clinging as condition, existence; with existence as condition, birth; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. This, bhikkhus, is called the Noble Truth of the Origin of Suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.61" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering?<br>With the remainderless fading away and cessation of ignorance, volitional formations cease; with the cessation of volitional formations, consciousness ceases... with the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. This, bhikkhus, is called the Noble Truth of the Cessation of Suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.61" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the Noble Truth of the Path Leading to the Cessation of Suffering?<br>It is this Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, bhikkhus, is called the Noble Truth of the Path Leading to the Cessation of Suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.61" },

{ text: `Here, brahmin, I dwell near a village or town. In the morning, having dressed, taking my robe and bowl, I enter that village or town for alms. After the meal, on returning from the alms round, I go to the foot of a certain forest. There, I gather some grass or leaves into a heap and sit down, crossing my legs, holding my body upright, establishing mindfulness before me. Secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, I enter and dwell in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.63" },

{ text: `Kālāmas, do not be led by report, do not be led by tradition, do not be led by hearsay, do not be led by the authority of scriptures, do not be led by logical reasoning, do not be led by inference, do not be led by reflection on appearances, do not be led by agreement with a considered opinion, do not be led by what seems possible, do not be led by the thought: 'He is our teacher.' But, Kālāmas, when you know for yourselves: 'These things are unwholesome; these things are blameworthy; these things are criticized by the wise; these things, when undertaken and practiced, lead to harm and suffering' — then, Kālāmas, you should abandon them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.65" },

{ text: `He knows thus: 'Formerly I had greed, which was unwholesome. Now I do not have it. Thus it is wholesome. Formerly I had hatred, which was unwholesome. Now I do not have it. Thus it is wholesome. Formerly I had delusion, which was unwholesome. Now I do not have it. Thus it is wholesome.' Thus, in this very life, he is freed from longing, peaceful, cooled, experiencing happiness, and dwells personally in the Brahma-state.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.66" },

{ text: `Whatever is greed, bhikkhus, that is unwholesome. Whoever, with greed, does anything by body, speech, or mind, that is unwholesome. Whoever, overcome by greed, mind not self-controlled, falsely accuses another of suffering, by killing, binding, confiscation, scolding or banishment, based on 'I am powerful, I have power' — that is unwholesome. Thus, many evil unwholesome states arise in that person born from greed, conditioned by greed, originated from greed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.69" },

{ text: `- Whatever is hatred, bhikkhus, that is unwholesome. Whoever, with hatred, does anything by body, speech, or mind, that is unwholesome. Whoever, overcome by hatred, mind not self-controlled, falsely accuses another of suffering... that is unwholesome. Thus, many evil unwholesome states arise in that person born from hatred, conditioned by hatred, originated from hatred.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.69" },

{ text: `Thus, Ānanda, action is the field, consciousness is the seed, craving is the moisture. For beings obstructed by ignorance and fettered by craving, consciousness is established in a lower realm. Thus there is the production of renewed existence in the future. Thus, Ānanda, existence comes to be.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.76" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'Strong shall be our desire to undertake the higher training in virtue. Strong shall be our desire to undertake the higher training in mind. Strong shall be our desire to undertake the higher training in wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.81" },

{ text: `One who is ardent, energetic,<br>Persistent and meditative,<br>Living with guarded senses,<br>Practice the three higher trainings.<br>As before, so after;<br>As after, so before;<br>As below, so above;<br>As above, so below;<br>As by day, so by night;<br>As by night, so by day.<br>Subdue every direction<br>With immeasurable concentrated mind.<br>This is called a learner's practice,<br>Pure conduct and virtue.<br>This is called Perfect Enlightenment,<br>The wise attain the ultimate.<br>With consciousness destroyed,<br>Craving ceased, liberated,<br>Like a lamp's going out,<br>That one's mind is freed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.90" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in the autumn, when the sky is clear and cloudless, the sun rises in the sky, dispelling all darkness in space, and shines, blazes, and radiates; so too, for the noble disciple, the dust-free, stainless Dhamma-eye arises. And with this arising of knowledge and vision, bhikkhus, three fetters are abandoned: personality view, doubt, and clinging to rites and rituals. Moreover, he is freed from two things: greed and hatred. Secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, he enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and happiness born of seclusion. If, bhikkhus, at that time, that noble disciple should die, there is no fetter bound by which he might return to this world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.94" },

{ text: `Whenever, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus dwell in harmony, rejoicing, without dispute, like milk mixed with water, looking at one another with loving eyes — at that time, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus generate much merit; at that time, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus dwell in the Brahma-state. That is, for one who rejoices with mind-liberation connected to happiness, happiness arises; for one with happiness, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he feels pleasant feeling; for one feeling pleasant feeling, the mind becomes concentrated.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.95" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu complete in beauty?<br>Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu observes the precepts, lives restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, he undertakes and trains in the training rules. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu complete in beauty.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.96" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu complete in strength?<br>Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, energetic, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu complete in strength.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.96" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, if an elder bhikkhu speaks in the midst of the Saṅgha, the other bhikkhus say: 'Let the venerable ones be silent; the elder bhikkhu is speaking on the Dhamma and Discipline, and his words become a treasure to be stored away, like a person storing a Kāsi cloth in a fragrant box.' Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'We will be like the Kāsi cloth example, not like the bark-cloth example.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.99" },

{ text: `Such concentration is not peaceful, not sublime, not tranquil, not attaining one-pointedness, but is a state of constant suppression and restraint. But in time, bhikkhus, his mind becomes inwardly settled, calm, unified, and concentrated. That concentration is peaceful, sublime, tranquil, attains one-pointedness, not a state of constant suppression and restraint. Regarding whatever state he directs his mind to for direct knowledge and realization, he has the ability and capacity to attain that state, in whichever sphere.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.101" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, before my enlightenment, while I was still a bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I reflected thus: 'What is the gratification in the world? What is the danger? What is the escape?' Then, bhikkhus, this thought arose in me: 'Whatever happiness and joy arise in dependence on the world, that is the gratification in the world. Whatever in the world is impermanent, suffering, and subject to change, that is the danger in the world. The removal and abandonment of desire and lust for the world, that is the escape from the world.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.104" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I sought the gratification in the world. Whatever gratification there is in the world, I found it. To whatever extent gratification exists in the world, I have seen it well with wisdom. Bhikkhus, I sought the danger in the world. Whatever danger there is in the world, I found it. To whatever extent danger exists in the world, I have seen it well with wisdom. Bhikkhus, I sought the escape from the world. Whatever escape there is from the world, I found it. To whatever extent escape exists from the world, I have seen it well with wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.104" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as I did not directly know as it really is the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then, bhikkhus, I did not claim to have awakened to the unsurpassed Perfect Enlightenment in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its devas and humans. But when I directly knew as it really is the gratification as gratification, the danger as danger, the escape as escape, then, bhikkhus, I claimed to have awakened to the unsurpassed Perfect Enlightenment... And knowledge and vision arose in me: 'Unshakable is my liberation of mind. This is my last birth. Now there is no more renewed existence.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.104" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if there were no gratification in the world, beings would not become enamored with the world. But because there is gratification in the world, beings become enamored with the world. Bhikkhus, if there were no danger in the world, beings would not become disenchanted with the world. But because there is danger in the world, beings become disenchanted with the world. Bhikkhus, if there were no escape from the world, beings would not escape from the world. But because there is an escape from the world, beings escape from the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.105" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, this is considered weeping and wailing in the Noble One's Discipline, namely singing. Bhikkhus, this is considered madness in the Noble One's Discipline, namely dancing. Bhikkhus, this is considered childishness in the Noble One's Discipline, namely excessive laughter showing the teeth. Therefore, bhikkhus, break the bridge to singing. Break the bridge to dancing. It is enough that you rejoice in the Dhamma, and smile to show your joy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.107" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the enjoyment of three things in the world is never enough. What three? The enjoyment of sleep, bhikkhus, is never enough. The enjoyment of liquor and fermented drink, bhikkhus, is never enough. The enjoyment of sexual intercourse, bhikkhus, is never enough.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.108", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.108" },

{ text: `Householder, just as a house with a poorly thatched roof — the ridgepole is not protected, the rafters are not protected, the walls are not protected; the ridgepole becomes saturated and leaks, the rafters become saturated and leak, the walls become saturated and leak; the ridgepole decays, the rafters decay, the walls decay. So too, householder, when the mind is not protected, bodily action is not protected, verbal action... mental action... then bodily action becomes saturated with lust and leaks; verbal action becomes saturated with lust and leaks; mental action becomes saturated with lust and leaks. For one whose bodily action is saturated with lust and leaks, whose verbal action... mental action... then bodily action decays, verbal action decays, mental action decays. For one whose bodily action decays, verbal action decays, mental action decays, death is not good, the end is not good.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.109" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these three kinds of persons fall into a state of misery, fall into hell, unless they abandon this practice. What three? One who lives the non-holy life but claims to live the holy life; one who baselessly accuses one who lives the pure holy life, the truly pure holy life, of not being holy; one who holds the view: 'There is no fault in sensual pleasures' and falls into indulgence in sensual pleasures. These three kinds of persons, bhikkhus, fall into a state of misery, fall into hell, unless they abandon this practice.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.113", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.113" },

{ text: `The arising of these three persons, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world. What three? The arising of a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world. One who can teach the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world. One who is grateful and thankful, bhikkhus, is hard to find in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.114" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is not restless, not arrogant, not agitated, not talkative, not garrulous, mindful, clearly comprehending, concentrated, one-pointed, with guarded faculties. This, bhikkhus, is called a person hard to fathom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.115" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person is restless, arrogant, agitated, talkative, garrulous, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, unconcentrated, with distracted mind and loose faculties. This, bhikkhus, is called a person easy to fathom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.115" },

{ text: `In whatever direction, bhikkhus, bhikkhus live in rivalry, disputation, conflict, wounding one another with verbal weapons, that direction is not comfortable for me, bhikkhus, to think of, let alone to go there. Therein, I come to this conclusion: 'Surely, those bhikkhus have abandoned three things and cultivated three things too much.' What three have they abandoned? Thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming. These three they have abandoned. What three have they cultivated too much? Thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming. These three they have cultivated too much.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.124" },

{ text: `In whatever direction, bhikkhus, bhikkhus dwell in harmony, rejoicing, without conflict, like milk mixed with water, looking at one another with loving eyes — that direction is comfortable for me, bhikkhus, to go to, let alone to think of. Therein, I come to this conclusion: 'Surely, those bhikkhus have abandoned three things and cultivated three things too much.' What three have they abandoned? Thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming. These three they have abandoned. What three have they cultivated too much? Thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.124" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, here, having dressed in the morning, taking my robe and bowl, I entered Varanasi for alms. Bhikkhus, while walking for alms at Goyogapilakkha, I saw a bhikkhu enjoying the taste of emptiness, without meditation, enjoying the external taste of sense objects, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, unconcentrated, with distracted mind and loose faculties. Having seen him, I said to that bhikkhu: 'Bhikkhu, bhikkhu! Do not let yourself rot. Bhikkhu, if one lets oneself rot, becoming saturated, emitting a foul smell, and then wishes: "Flies will not swarm and settle on me," such a thing is impossible.' Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu, being exhorted by me with this exhortation, was deeply stirred.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.128" },

{ text: `Craving, bhikkhus, is rot; hatred is foul smell; evil unwholesome thoughts are flies. Bhikkhus, if one lets oneself rot, becoming saturated, emitting a foul smell, and then wishes: 'Flies will not swarm and settle on me,' such a thing is impossible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.128" },

{ text: `Without restraint of ear and eye,<br>Faculties unguarded,<br>Flies will swarm,<br>Thoughts of craving.<br>The bhikkhu rots,<br>Saturated with foul smells.<br>Far away is Nibbāna!<br>He gets only misfortune.<br>In village or forest,<br>Self not peaceful,<br>The foolish and unwise,<br>Walking and standing full of flies.<br>One complete in virtue,<br>Delighting in peace and wisdom,<br>Dwells peaceful and happy,<br>All flies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.128" },

{ text: `These three things, bhikkhus, shine forth, are manifest, not hidden. The orb of the moon, bhikkhus, shines forth, is manifest, not hidden. The orb of the sun, bhikkhus, shines forth, is manifest, not hidden. The Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, bhikkhus, shines forth, is manifest, not hidden. These three things shine forth, are manifest, not hidden.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.131", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.131" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person, even when spoken to sharply, even when spoken to harshly, even when spoken to rudely, nevertheless is easy to reconcile, friendly, and joyful. Bhikkhus, just as writing on water quickly disappears and does not last long, so too, bhikkhus, a person, even when spoken to sharply, harshly, rudely, is easy to reconcile, friendly, and joyful. This, bhikkhus, is called a person who is like writing on water.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.132" },

{ text: `Whatever beings, bhikkhus, in the morning do good bodily actions, good verbal actions, good mental actions — those beings, bhikkhus, have a good morning. Whatever beings, bhikkhus, at noon do good bodily actions, good verbal actions, good mental actions — those beings, bhikkhus, have a good noon. Whatever beings, bhikkhus, in the evening do good bodily actions, good verbal actions, good mental actions — those beings, bhikkhus, have a good evening.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.155", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.155" },

{ text: `Virtue, concentration, wisdom,<br>And unsurpassed liberation,<br>Gotama by name,<br>Awakened to these things.<br>The Buddha, having fully known them,<br>Teaches the Dhamma to bhikkhus.<br>The teacher, destroyer of suffering,<br>The Visionary, at peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.1" },

{ text: `Those who live in the world,<br>Not restraining the senses,<br>Not abandoning dispassion,<br>Enjoying sensual desires,<br>They go to birth and aging,<br>Come again and again,<br>Fettered by craving,<br>They go with the stream of life.<br>Therefore the wise,<br>In the world, mindful,<br>Do not enjoy the senses,<br>Do not practice evil.<br>Even though suffering,<br>They abandon sensual desires.<br>They are called those<br>Who go against the stream.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.5" },

{ text: `Those who have abandoned<br>Five mental fetters,<br>Perfect learners,<br>Not liable to fall,<br>Have attained subdued mind,<br>Faculties calm.<br>They are called<br>Those who stand firm.<br>Regarding states inferior and superior,<br>They have known,<br>Have swept and cleaned,<br>All states are ended.<br>They are the wise,<br>The holy life accomplished,<br>Called by name<br>Those who have reached the world's end,<br>Those who have gone to the other shore.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.5" },

{ text: `One with craving as companion<br>Wanders on for a long time.<br>Being here and there,<br>Existence after existence,<br>That one cannot stop<br>The wandering in birth.<br>Knowing this danger,<br>That craving gives birth to suffering,<br>The bhikkhu, abandoning craving,<br>Not grasping, not clinging,<br>Mindful, he dwells,<br>Living the homeless life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.9" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person truly understands the origin, the passing away, the gratification, the danger, and the escape regarding sensual pleasures. By truly understanding the origin, passing away, gratification, danger, and escape regarding sensual pleasures, sensual lust, sensual delight, sensual affection, sensual infatuation, sensual thirst, sensual fever, sensual clinging, sensual craving for sensual pleasures do not invade and remain. This, bhikkhus, is called being free from the yoke of sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.10" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if while walking... while standing... while sitting... while lying down, thoughts of sensual desire, or thoughts of ill-will, or thoughts of harming arise in a bhikkhu, and if he accepts them, does not abandon them, does not dispel them, does not terminate them, does not make them nonexistent — then, bhikkhus, if while lying down, his consciousness behaves thus, he is called one who is not ardent, not conscientious, constantly lazy, of inferior energy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.11" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if while walking... while standing... while sitting... while lying down, thoughts of sensual desire, or thoughts of ill-will, or thoughts of harming arise in a bhikkhu, and he does not accept them, abandons them, dispels them, terminates them, makes them nonexistent — then, bhikkhus, if while lying down, his consciousness behaves thus, he is called one who is ardent, conscientious, constantly energetic, strenuous, diligent.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.11" },

{ text: `If while walking, while standing,<br>While sitting or lying down,<br>Evil thoughts arise<br>Connected to household life,<br>Practicing the wrong path,<br>Obscured by delusion,<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Does not attain supreme enlightenment.<br>One who, while walking, standing,<br>While sitting or lying down,<br>Subdues his thoughts,<br>Delighting in peaceful thoughts,<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Attains supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.11" },

{ text: `If, bhikkhus, while walking... while standing... while sitting... while lying down, a bhikkhu abandons greed, hatred, delusion... abandons dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, doubt, and is energetic, strenuous, not lax, with mindfulness established, not forgetful, with body tranquil, not agitated, with mind concentrated and one-pointed — then, bhikkhus, if while conscious his behavior is such, he is called one who is ardent, conscientious, constantly energetic, strenuous, diligent.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.12" },

{ text: `Walking and standing with self-control,<br>Sitting and lying down with self-control,<br>The bhikkhu, self-controlled,<br>When bending and stretching his limbs.<br>Above, across, and all around,<br>As far as the end of the world,<br>Regarding whatever kind of existence,<br>In this world,<br>He well observes the arising and passing<br>Of all aggregates.<br>With mind peaceful, in right conduct,<br>Constantly training,<br>Continuously, diligently,<br>The bhikkhu is so called.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.12" },

{ text: `- Once, bhikkhus, I was dwelling at Uruvelā on the bank of the river Nerañjarā, under the Ajapāla banyan tree, just after my enlightenment. While I was meditating in seclusion, bhikkhus, this thought arose in me: 'It is difficult to live without reverence and obedience. Let me then honor, respect, and dwell in reliance on an ascetic or brahmin.' Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'For the sake of completing the aggregate of virtue... the aggregate of concentration... the aggregate of wisdom... the aggregate of liberation that is not yet complete, should I honor, respect, and dwell in reliance on some other ascetic or brahmin?' But I saw no one in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the multitude of ascetics and brahmins, devas and humans, who was more complete in virtue than I, whom I could honor, respect, and rely upon. Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'Let me then honor, respect, and dwell in reliance on this Dhamma to which I have fully awakened.' And I dwell honoring, respecting, and relying on that Dhamma. And because the Saṅgha possesses greatness, I especially respect the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.21" },

{ text: `If an elder, bhikkhus, is 80, 90, or 100 years old, yet he speaks at the wrong time, speaks what is false, speaks what is meaningless, speaks contrary to Dhamma, speaks contrary to Discipline, speaks words that are not worth preserving, words that are untimely, unreasonable, limitless, unconnected with the goal — then he is called a foolish elder. If a young person, bhikkhus, a youth with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth in the prime of life, speaks at the right time, speaks what is true, speaks what is meaningful, speaks in accordance with Dhamma, speaks in accordance with Discipline, speaks words that are worth preserving, words that are timely, reasonable, limited, connected with the goal — then he is called a wise elder.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.22" },


{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four qualities constitute an elder. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned; those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, remembers, recites verbally, investigates with the mind, and penetrates well with right view. Regarding the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, he obtains them without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. By the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, he realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Bhikkhus, these four qualities constitute an elder.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.22" },

{ text: `One with an arrogant mind,<br>Speaking many frivolous words,<br>With unsettled thoughts,<br>Like a beast not delighting in Dhamma,<br>Far from an elder's status,<br>Evil views, without respect.<br>But one complete in virtue,<br>Learned, with wisdom and eloquence,<br>Living restrained, wise,<br>Regarding all phenomena,<br>With wisdom he sees<br>The true meaning.<br>He has reached the end of all phenomena,<br>Not barren, eloquent,<br>He has ended birth and death,<br>Perfect in the holy life.<br>Him I call an elder,<br>Taint-free.<br>By the destruction of taints,<br>He is called an elder.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.22" },

{ text: `Whatever, bhikkhus, in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the multitude of ascetics and brahmins, devas and humans, is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, and examined by the mind — all that the Tathāgata has fully awakened to. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. From the night, bhikkhus, when the Tathāgata fully awakens to unsurpassed perfect enlightenment until the night he attains final Nibbāna, whatever he speaks, utters, or declares — all that is just so and not otherwise. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata does what he speaks and speaks what he does. Because he does what he speaks and speaks what he does, therefore he is called the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.23" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, whatever in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the multitude of ascetics and brahmins, devas and humans, is seen ... examined by the mind — all that I know. Bhikkhus, whatever in this world ... is seen ... examined by the mind — I have directly known it thus: 'All that the Tathāgata has known. The Tathāgata does not hold to it.' Bhikkhus, if I were to say: 'I know all that in this world ... is seen ... examined by the mind' — that would be false speech in me. If I were to say: 'I both know and do not know' — that would be false speech in me. If I were to say: 'I neither know nor do not know' — that would be false speech in me. Thus there would be an error in me.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.24" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata has seen what is to be seen, but he does not conceive what is seen, does not conceive what is not seen, does not conceive what is to be seen, does not conceive a seer. He has heard what is to be heard, but he does not conceive what is heard, does not conceive what is not heard, does not conceive what is to be heard, does not conceive a hearer. He has sensed what is to be sensed, but he does not conceive what is sensed, does not conceive what is not sensed, does not conceive what is to be sensed, does not conceive a senser. He has cognized what is to be cognized, but he does not conceive what is cognized, does not conceive what is not cognized, does not conceive what is to be cognized, does not conceive a cognizer. Thus, bhikkhus, the Tathāgata, regarding phenomena that are seen, heard, sensed, and cognized, is just thus. Moreover, beyond one who is thus, there is no one else more excellent or superior. So I declare.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.24" },

{ text: `The holy life is lived, bhikkhus, not for the purpose of deceiving people, not for the purpose of flattering people, not for the sake of gain, honor, and renown, not for the benefit of escaping criticism, nor with the thought: 'Let people know me thus.' Rather, bhikkhus, the holy life is lived for the purpose of restraint, for the purpose of abandonment, for the purpose of dispassion, for the purpose of cessation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.25" },

{ text: `For the purpose of restraint,<br>For the purpose of abandonment,<br>The holy life is lived,<br>Far from idle speech.<br>The Blessed One declared<br>It leads to Nibbāna.<br>This path is traveled<br>By the great men, the great sages.<br>Whoever steps forth and practices<br>Just as the Buddha taught,<br>Will end suffering,<br>Doing as the Teacher advised.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.25" },

{ text: `Those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, who are deceitful, stubborn, talkative, fraudulent, haughty, and unconcentrated — those bhikkhus are not my bhikkhus. Those bhikkhus have fallen away from this Dhamma and Discipline. And they do not achieve growth, increase, or expansion in this Dhamma and Discipline. And those bhikkhus, bhikkhus, who are not deceitful, not talkative, wise, not stubborn, well-concentrated — those bhikkhus are indeed my bhikkhus. Those bhikkhus have not fallen away from this Dhamma and Discipline, and they achieve growth, increase, and expansion in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.26" },

{ text: `The deceitful, stubborn,<br>Talkative, fraudulent,<br>Haughty, unconcentrated,<br>Do not grow in the Dhamma,<br>As proclaimed and taught<br>By the Perfectly Enlightened One.<br>Not deceitful, not talkative,<br>Wise, not stubborn,<br>With mind well-concentrated,<br>They grow in the Dhamma,<br>As proclaimed and taught<br>By the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.26" },

{ text: `Content with things,<br>Not important, easily gained,<br>And also not committing offenses,<br>Mind not disturbed,<br>Regarding dwelling places,<br>Robes and food,<br>Mind not worried<br>About the direction one should go.<br>The Dhamma proclaimed,<br>Conducive to the ascetic's practice,<br>They possess fully.<br>For one who knows contentment,<br>For one who is not heedless,<br>Ardent in training.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.27" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is content with any kind of robe, and he speaks in praise of contentment with any kind of robe. He does not, for the sake of a robe, engage in improper, unsuitable seeking. If he does not get a robe, he is not worried or regretful; if he gets a robe, he uses it without greed, infatuation, or clinging, seeing the danger and understanding the escape. He does not, because of contentment with any kind of robe, praise himself or disparage others. Whoever here is skilled, not lax, clearly comprehending, mindful — this bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who stands on the ancient, original noble tradition.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.28" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is content with any kind of almsfood, and he speaks in praise of contentment with any kind of almsfood. He does not, for the sake of almsfood, engage in improper, unsuitable seeking. If he does not get almsfood, he is not worried or regretful; if he gets almsfood, he uses it without greed, infatuation, or clinging, seeing the danger and understanding the escape. He does not, because of contentment with any kind of almsfood, praise himself or disparage others. Whoever here is skilled, not lax, clearly comprehending, mindful — this bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who stands on the ancient, original noble tradition.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.28" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu delights in development, enjoys development, delights in abandonment, enjoys abandonment. Yet he does not, because of delighting in development and abandonment, praise himself or disparage others. Whoever here is skilled, not lax, clearly comprehending, mindful — this bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called one who stands on the ancient, original noble tradition.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.28" },

{ text: `Dwell without greed,<br>With mind free from hatred,<br>Mindful and one-pointed,<br>Internally well-composed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.29" },

{ text: `There are these four wheels, bhikkhus, possessing which, when these four wheels turn, devas and humans, possessing them, before long attain greatness and prosperity in wealth. What four? A suitable dwelling place, associating with good persons, right resolution, and merit made in the past.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.31" },

{ text: `Whatever beings, bhikkhus, whether footless or two-footed, four-footed or many-footed, whether having form or formless, whether percipient or non-percipient or neither-percipient-nor-non-percipient — the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One is declared the foremost among them. Those who have confidence in the Buddha have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.34" },

{ text: `Whatever kind of conditioned phenomena, bhikkhus, the Noble Eightfold Path is declared the foremost among them. Those who have confidence in the Noble Eightfold Path have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.34" },

{ text: `Whatever kind of phenomena, bhikkhus, whether conditioned or unconditioned, dispassion is declared the foremost among them, that is, the subduing of pride, the subduing of thirst, the removal of attachment, the cutting off of renewed existence, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna. Those who have confidence in the Dhamma of dispassion, bhikkhus, have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.34" },

{ text: `Whatever kind of Saṅgha or assembly, bhikkhus, the Saṅgha of the Tathāgata's disciples is declared the foremost among them, that is, the four pairs of persons, the eight individuals — this Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is worthy of gifts, worthy of hospitality, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit in the world. Those who have confidence in the Saṅgha, bhikkhus, have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost. Bhikkhus, these are the four foremost kinds of confidence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.34" },

{ text: `Confidence in the foremost,<br>Knowing the foremost Dhamma,<br>Confidence in the Buddha, foremost,<br>Worthy of supreme respect,<br>Confidence in the Dhamma, foremost,<br>Dispassion, peace, bliss,<br>Confidence in the Saṅgha, foremost,<br>The unsurpassed field of merit,<br>Giving to the foremost,<br>Foremost merit increases,<br>Foremost in life span,<br>Complexion and fame,<br>Foremost in happiness,<br>Foremost in strength,<br>The wise give to the foremost,<br>Established in foremost Dhamma,<br>Whether devas or humans,<br>Attain foremost joy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.34" },

{ text: `Brahmin, I have practiced for the welfare of the many, for the happiness of the many, I have established many people in the noble truth, namely, in the nature of goodness, the nature of the good Dhamma. I am one who, regarding whatever thought I think should be thought, I think that thought; regarding whatever thought I think should not be thought, I do not think that thought. Regarding whatever intention I intend should be intended, I intend that intention; regarding whatever intention I intend should not be intended, I do not intend that intention. Brahmin, I have attained mastery of mind regarding the directions of thought. Brahmin, regarding the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, I obtain them without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. Brahmin, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, I realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.35" },

{ text: `One who among all beings<br>Understands liberation<br>From the trap of death,<br>For the happiness of devas and humans,<br>Declares the noble truth,<br>Declares the true Dhamma.<br>The multitude seeing and hearing this<br>Rejoice with serene faith.<br>Skilled in the path and non-path,<br>What should be done has been done,<br>Taintless, Enlightened,<br>With this last body,<br>He is called by name,<br>Great Wisdom, Great Man.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.35" },

{ text: `Just as, brahmin, a blue lotus, or a red lotus, or a white lotus, born in the water, grown up in the water, rises up above the water and stands without being stained by the water, so too, brahmin, I was born in the world, grown up in the world, yet having conquered the world, I dwell untainted by the world. Brahmin, remember me as the Buddha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.36" },

{ text: `A bhikkhu established in virtue,<br>Living with restrained senses,<br>Knowing moderation in eating,<br>And devoted to wakefulness,<br>Dwelling thus,<br>Untiring by day and night,<br>Developing wholesome states,<br>Attains security from bondage.<br>Delighting in heedfulness,<br>Seeing fear in heedlessness,<br>He cannot decline,<br>The bhikkhu is close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.37" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of concentration development. What four? There is concentration development, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to a pleasant abiding in this very life. There is concentration development, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to the attainment of knowledge and vision. There is concentration development, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension. There is concentration development, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.41" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is concentration development that, when developed and cultivated, leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension? Here, bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu, feelings are known as they arise, known as they persist, known as they cease; perceptions are known as they arise, known as they persist, known as they cease; thoughts are known as they arise, known as they persist, known as they cease. This, bhikkhus, is called concentration development that, when developed and cultivated, leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.41" },

{ text: `These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, exist and are found in the world. What four? One who respects anger, not the good Dhamma; one who respects disparagement, not the good Dhamma; one who respects gain, not the good Dhamma; one who respect honor, not the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.43" },

{ text: `These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, exist and are found in the world. What four? One who respects the good Dhamma, not anger; one who respects the good Dhamma, not disparagement; one who respects the good Dhamma, not gain; one who respects the good Dhamma, not honor.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.43" },

{ text: `Those bhikkhus who respect<br>Anger and disparagement,<br>Who respect gains,<br>Who respect honor,<br>Do not grow<br>In the Dhamma taught by the Buddha.<br>But those who live or have lived<br>Respecting the true good Dhamma,<br>They grow<br>In the Dhamma taught by the Buddha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.43" },

{ text: `I declare, friend, that it is at the very place where there is no birth, no aging, no death, no passing away (from this life), no arising (in another life), that one cannot go to see, to know, to reach the end of the world. Yet, friend, in this very fathom-long body with its perceptions and thoughts, I declare the world, the origin of the world, the cessation of the world, and the path leading to the cessation of the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.45" },

{ text: `By going, one never<br>Reaches the end of the world.<br>If not, without reaching,<br>The end of the world,<br>Then there is no liberation<br>From suffering.<br>Therefore, the wise one,<br>Knowing the world thoroughly,<br>Gets to the end of the world,<br>With the holy life accomplished.<br>The peaceful one, knowing<br>The end of the world,<br>Does not long for this life,<br>Does not long for the next.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.45" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four things are extremely far, far apart from each other. What four? The sky and the earth, bhikkhus, are the first thing extremely far, far apart. The near shore and the far shore of the ocean, bhikkhus, are the second thing extremely far, far apart. The place where the sun rises and the place where the sun sets, bhikkhus, are the third thing extremely far, far apart. The Dhamma of an evil person and the Dhamma of a good person, bhikkhus, are the fourth thing extremely far, far apart.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.47" },

{ text: `If he does not speak,<br>They do not know him,<br>Thus the wise man<br>Gets mixed with fools.<br>If he speaks,<br>They know him,<br>When he teaches<br>The path to the Deathless.<br>Therefore, let him teach,<br>Illuminate the true Dhamma,<br>Let him raise high the banner,<br>The banner of the sages.<br>Well-spoken is the banner<br>Of the sages,<br>And the Dhamma is the banner<br>Of the sages.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.48" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four perversions of perception, perversions of mind, perversions of view. What four? Regarding the impermanent as permanent, bhikkhus, that is a perversion of perception, perversion of mind, perversion of view. Regarding the painful as pleasurable, bhikkhus, that is a perversion of perception, perversion of mind, perversion of view. Regarding the non-self as self, bhikkhus, that is a perversion of perception, perversion of mind, perversion of view. Regarding the impure as pure, bhikkhus, that is a perversion of perception, perversion of mind, perversion of view.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.49" },

{ text: `Some ascetics and brahmins,<br>Bound by greed and hatred,<br>Covered by ignorance,<br>People delighting in beautiful forms,<br>Drinking liquor and fermented drink,<br>Indulging in sexual intercourse,<br>Infatuated, they accept,<br>Receive gold and silver,<br>Those ascetics and brahmins,<br>Living by wrong livelihood.<br>The Buddha, kinsman of the Sun,<br>Spoke of those defilements.<br>Defiled by them,<br>Those ascetics and brahmins,<br>Do not burn brightly, do not shine,<br>Their light is dirtied.<br>Covered by darkness,<br>Slaves to sensual desire,<br>Dragged and led by craving,<br>They keep filling up<br>The dreadful charnel ground.<br>Again they are reborn.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.50" },

{ text: `The great ocean, limitless,<br>The great lake, very fearful,<br>Is a treasure trove storing<br>Countless jewels,<br>And is also a shelter<br>For countless species of fish,<br>It is where great waves<br>Converge and flow into the ocean.<br>So too, a giver of<br>Food and drink,<br>Clothing and bedding,<br>Seats and mats,<br>Thus the wise one giving,<br>Merit flows to him<br>As rivers carry water<br>Flowing into the great ocean.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.51" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu, while enjoying the robes of someone... while enjoying the almsfood of someone... while enjoying the lodging of someone... while enjoying the medicinal requisites of someone, attains and abides in immeasurable mental concentration, then that is an immeasurable source of merit for the donor, a source of good leading to happiness, pertaining to heaven, resulting in happiness, leading to heaven, leading to what is desirable, pleasant, agreeable, happiness, and well-being.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.51" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when a noble disciple possesses these four sources of merit, sources of good, it is not easy to calculate his merit and say: 'There is this much source of merit, source of good, leading to happiness, pertaining to heaven, resulting in happiness, leading to heaven, leading to what is desirable, pleasant, agreeable, happiness, and well-being'; for it is reckoned simply as a great, immeasurable, incalculable mass of merit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.51" },

{ text: `One who has confidence in the Tathāgata,<br>Unshakable, well-established,<br>One who has virtuous conduct, good,<br>Loved and praised by the Noble ones,<br>One who has serene confidence in the Saṅgha,<br>With a straight view,<br>That person is called<br>Not poor.<br>The life of such a person<br>Is not in vain.<br>Therefore, faith and virtue,<br>Serene confidence and insight into Dhamma,<br>The wise person should focus mindful attention<br>On the teaching of the Buddhas.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.52" },

{ text: `When a noble female disciple gives food, Suppavāsā, she gives four things to the recipients. What four? She gives life, gives beauty, gives happiness, gives strength. Having given life, she has a share in life, whether celestial or human. Having given beauty, she has a share in beauty, whether celestial or human. Having given happiness, she has a share in happiness, whether celestial or human. Having given strength, she has a share in strength, whether celestial or human. This, Suppavāsā, is what a noble female disciple gives when she gives food: she gives these four things to the recipients.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.57" },

{ text: `Those who are well-restrained,<br>Living by giving to others,<br>Who at the proper time ardently<br>Give food and drink,<br>Bestow upon the recipients<br>These four things:<br>They give life, beauty,<br>Give happiness, strength.<br>The giver of life,<br>The giver of beauty,<br>The giver of happiness,<br>The giver of strength,<br>Long life and fame,<br>Wherever he is reborn.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.59" },

{ text: `Householder, that noble disciple, having known that sensual desire is a defilement of the mind, abandons sensual desire, the defilement of the mind; having known that hatred is a defilement of the mind, abandons hatred, the defilement of the mind; having known that dullness and drowsiness are defilements of the mind, abandons dullness and drowsiness, the defilements of the mind; having known that restlessness and remorse are defilements of the mind, abandons restlessness and remorse, the defilements of the mind; having known that doubt is a defilement of the mind, abandons doubt, the defilement of the mind. This, householder, is called a noble disciple of great wisdom, of wide wisdom, one who has entered the domain of clear vision, possessed of wisdom. This is called being complete in wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.61" },

{ text: `In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered like Brahmā. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered like the ancient teachers. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families, bhikkhus, are considered like the devas of old. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered worthy of offerings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.62" },

{ text: `Brahmā, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; the ancient teachers, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; the devas of old, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; worthy of offerings and reverence, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, mother and father have done much for their children: they nourish them, bring them up, and introduce them to this world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.62" },

{ text: `Craving for beautiful things,<br>Delighting in pleasant forms,<br>Bound by ignorance,<br>Base beings,<br>Increase the fetter.<br>Even a wise person<br>Does unwholesome deeds<br>Born of greed, hatred, delusion,<br>Causing distress and trouble,<br>Making suffering arise,<br>Surrounded by ignorance,<br>A blind person without eyes,<br>Such is their nature,<br>They cannot think:<br>'I can be otherwise.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.66" },

{ text: `It leads to his own harm, bhikkhus, when gain, honor, and renown arise for Devadatta; it leads to the unhappiness of others, bhikkhus, when gain, honor, and renown arise for Devadatta! Just as, bhikkhus, a banana tree, when it produces fruit, leads to its own harm; when it produces fruit, leads to the unhappiness of others. So too, bhikkhus, it leads to his own harm when gain, honor, and renown arise for Devadatta; it leads to the unhappiness of others when gain, honor, and renown arise for Devadatta. Just as, bhikkhus, a bamboo tree, when it produces fruit, leads to its own harm; when it produces fruit, leads to the unhappiness of others. So too, bhikkhus, it leads to his own harm when gain, honor, and renown arise for Devadatta.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.68" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a genuine person is one who, even when asked, does not speak words of praise for others; what to say when not asked! But if asked and required to answer, hesitantly and reluctantly, he does not speak words of praise for others. This person, bhikkhus, should be understood as a genuine person. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a genuine person is one who, even when not asked, speaks words of praise for others; what to say when asked! If asked and required to answer, without hesitation or reluctance, he speaks words of praise for others fully and completely. This person, bhikkhus, should be understood as a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.73" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a genuine person is one who, even when not asked, speaks words not praising himself; what to say when asked! If asked and required to answer, without hesitation or reluctance, he speaks words not praising himself fully and completely. This person, bhikkhus, should be understood as a genuine person. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a genuine person is one who, even when asked, does not speak words of praise for himself; what to say when not asked! If asked and required to answer, hesitantly and reluctantly, he speaks words of praise for himself, not fully, not completely. This person, bhikkhus, should be understood as a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.73" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a young bride, on the night or day she is brought to her husband's home, feels extreme shame and fear towards her mother-in-law, father-in-law, her husband, and even the servants and laborers. After some time, through living together and familiarity, she can speak to her mother-in-law, father-in-law, and husband: 'Go away, what do you know?' So too, bhikkhus, here a bhikkhu, on the night or day he goes forth from home to homelessness, feels extreme shame and fear towards the bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers, and even the monastery workers and novice monks. After some time, through living together and familiarity, he can speak to his preceptor and teacher: 'Go away, what do you know?'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.74" },

{ text: `There are these four inconceivable things, bhikkhus, that should not be speculated about; one who speculates about them would be subject to madness and distress. What four? The sphere of a Buddha, bhikkhus, is inconceivable; one who speculates about it would be subject to madness and distress. The sphere of one in meditation, bhikkhus, is inconceivable; one who speculates... distress. The result of kamma, bhikkhus, is inconceivable; one who speculates... distress. Speculation about the world, bhikkhus, is inconceivable; one who speculates would be subject to madness and distress.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.77" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, when a cloth is on fire or the head is on fire, to extinguish the cloth and the head one should arouse extraordinary desire, effort, exertion, striving, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. So too, bhikkhus, that person, to attain those wholesome states, should arouse extraordinary desire, effort, exertion, striving, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. After some time, he becomes one who has attained internal serenity of mind and the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. Then, bhikkhus, this person, having attained internal serenity of mind and the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena, should, after establishing himself in those wholesome states, focus even more on training for the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.93" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person has not attained internal serenity of mind and has not attained the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. That person, bhikkhus, should approach someone who has attained internal serenity of mind and the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena and say to him: 'Friend, how should the mind be established? How should the mind be settled? How should the mind be unified? How should the mind be concentrated? How should formations be seen? How should formations be known? How should formations be contemplated?' That person answers him: 'As has been seen, as has been known, thus, friend, should the mind be established; thus should the mind be settled; thus should the mind be unified; thus should the mind be concentrated; thus should formations be seen; thus should formations be known; thus should formations be contemplated.' After some time, that person attains internal serenity of mind and attains the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. Then, bhikkhus, this person, after establishing himself in those wholesome states, should focus on training for the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.94" },

{ text: `In four cases, bhikkhus, one should be heedful. What four? Abandon evil bodily action, bhikkhus, and cultivate good bodily action, and therein do not be heedless. Abandon evil verbal action, bhikkhus, and cultivate good verbal action, and therein do not be heedless. Abandon evil mental action, bhikkhus, and cultivate good mental action, and therein do not be heedless. Abandon wrong view, bhikkhus, and cultivate right view, and therein do not be heedless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.116", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.116" },

{ text: `When, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, regarding states that would cause greed, his mind does not become greedy, and he himself is dispassionate; regarding states that would cause hatred, his mind does not become hateful, and he himself is free from hatred; regarding states that would cause delusion, his mind does not become deluded, and he himself is free from delusion; regarding states that would cause infatuation, his mind does not become infatuated, and he himself is free from infatuation — then he has no fear, no trembling, no terror, does not fall into panic, and does not go because of anything any ascetic might say.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.117" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person reflects: 'If I do evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action, then my own self might reproach me in terms of virtue, saying: "Why did you do that deed?"' That person, through fear of self-reproach, abandons evil bodily action and cultivates good bodily action, abandons evil verbal action and cultivates good verbal action, abandons evil mental action and cultivates good mental action, and dwells with a pure self. This, bhikkhus, is called fear of self-reproach.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.121" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person reflects: 'If I do evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action, then others might reproach me in terms of virtue, saying: "Why did you do that deed?"' That person, through fear of reproach by others, abandons evil bodily action and cultivates good bodily action, abandons evil verbal action and cultivates good verbal action, abandons evil mental action and cultivates good mental action, and dwells with a pure self. This, bhikkhus, is called fear of reproach by others.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.121" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person reflects thus: 'For one who does evil bodily action, there is an evil result in the hereafter; for one who does evil verbal action... evil mental action, there is an evil result in the hereafter. What if after death, with the breakup of the body, I were to be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell?' That person, through fear of an evil destination, abandons evil bodily action and cultivates good bodily action; abandons evil verbal action and cultivates good verbal action; abandons evil mental action and cultivates good mental action; and dwells with a pure self. This, bhikkhus, is called fear of an evil destination.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.121" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a clansman goes forth from home to homelessness out of faith. He reflects thus: 'I am oppressed by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair; oppressed by suffering, overwhelmed by suffering. Yet perhaps I may see the end of this whole mass of suffering.' Having gone forth thus, in the morning he dresses, takes his robe and bowl, and enters the village or town for alms, without guarding his body, without guarding his speech, without guarding his mind, with mindfulness unestablished, with senses unrestrained. There he sees women dressed indecently or wearing indecent garments. Seeing women dressed indecently or wearing indecent garments, sensual desire corrupts his mind. With his mind corrupted by sensual desire, he gives up the training and returns to the lay life. This, bhikkhus, is called a bhikkhu who, frightened by the fear of the fish-monster, gives up the training and returns to the lay life. The fear of the fish-monster, bhikkhus, is a designation for women. This, bhikkhus, is called the fear of the fish-monster.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.122", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.122" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna. Regarding whatever things there are there — form, feeling, perception, formations, consciousness — he contemplates them as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease, a boil, a dart, a misfortune, an affliction, as alien, as decaying, as empty, as not-self. After death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Pure Abodes. This kind of rebirth, bhikkhus, is not shared with ordinary persons.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.124" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the multitude delights in grasping, takes pleasure in grasping, rejoices in grasping. When the Dhamma of non-grasping is taught by the Tathāgata, they listen well, lend an ear, and apply their minds with right understanding. This, bhikkhus, is the first wonderful, marvelous quality that appears when the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One appears.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.128" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the multitude delights in conceit, takes pleasure in conceit, rejoices in conceit. When the Dhamma of non-conceit is taught by the Tathāgata, they listen well, lend an ear, and apply their minds with right understanding. This, bhikkhus, is the second wonderful, marvelous quality that appears when the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One appears.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.128" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the multitude delights in non-peace, takes pleasure in non-peace, rejoices in non-peace. When the Dhamma of peace is taught by the Tathāgata, they listen well, lend an ear, and apply their minds with right understanding. This, bhikkhus, is the third wonderful, marvelous quality that appears when the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One appears.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.128" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the multitude is immersed in ignorance, blind, covered and fettered. When the Dhamma that subdues ignorance is taught by the Tathāgata, they listen well, lend an ear, and apply their minds with right understanding. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth wonderful, marvelous quality that appears when the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One appears.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.128" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is bodily seclusion without mental seclusion? Here, bhikkhus, a person lives in the mountains, forests, remote dwellings; yet he thinks thoughts of sensual desire, thinks thoughts of ill-will, thinks thoughts of harming. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who has bodily seclusion but not mental seclusion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.138", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.138" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is no bodily seclusion but mental seclusion? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not live in the mountains, forests, remote dwellings; yet he thinks thoughts of renunciation, thinks thoughts of non-ill-will, thinks thoughts of non-harming. Thus, bhikkhus, is a person who does not have bodily seclusion but has mental seclusion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.138", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.138" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of light. What four? The light of the moon, the light of the sun, the light of fire, the light of wisdom. Bhikkhus, these are the four kinds of light. And the foremost among these four kinds of light, bhikkhus, is the light of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.142", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.142" },

{ text: `There are these four occasions, bhikkhus, that, if well developed and well conducted, lead progressively to the destruction of the taints. What four? Hearing the Dhamma at the right time, discussing the Dhamma at the right time, calming at the right time, contemplating at the right time. These four occasions, bhikkhus, if well developed and well conducted, lead progressively to the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.147", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.147" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these two kinds of illness. What two? Bodily illness and mental illness. Bhikkhus, I have seen beings who claim to be free from bodily illness for one year, claim to be free from bodily illness for two years, three... four... five... ten... twenty... thirty... forty... fifty years, claim to be free from bodily illness for a hundred years. Those beings, bhikkhus, are hard to find in the world who would claim to be free from mental illness even for a moment, except for those who have destroyed the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.157", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.157" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four afflictions for one gone forth. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a person has great desires, is discontented, dissatisfied with such things as robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicinal requisites. Because he has great desires, is discontented, dissatisfied with robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicinal requisites, he gives rise to longing, evil desires, wishing for things that are not praised, wishing for gain, honor, and renown. He strives, struggles, and makes effort to get things that are not praised, to get gain, honor, and renown. He calculates and then approaches families; calculating, he sits down; calculating, he teaches the Dhamma; calculating, he holds in his urine and feces. Thus, bhikkhus, are these four afflictions for one gone forth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.157", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.157" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī sees these four qualities in themselves should conclude: 'I have declined from wholesome states.' This the Blessed One calls decline. What four? Increased greed, increased hatred, increased delusion, and regarding matters present or absent, no penetrating eye of wisdom. Venerable sirs, whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī sees these four qualities in themselves should conclude: 'I have declined from wholesome states.' This the Blessed One calls decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.158", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.158" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when elder bhikkhus live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized — and later generations follow their wrong view, and they too live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized — this, bhikkhus, is the fourth quality leading to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.160", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.160" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of practice. What four? Painful practice with slow direct knowledge; painful practice with quick direct knowledge; pleasant practice with slow direct knowledge; pleasant practice with quick direct knowledge. Bhikkhus, these are the four kinds of practice.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.161", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.161" }, 

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is painful practice with slow direct knowledge? Here, a person has a very strong greedy nature, always experiencing suffering and distress born of greed; a very strong hateful nature, always experiencing suffering and distress born of hatred; a very strong deluded nature, always experiencing suffering and distress born of delusion. For that person, these five faculties appear very soft: the faculty of faith, the faculty of energy, the faculty of mindfulness, the faculty of concentration, the faculty of wisdom. Because these five faculties are soft, he attains the immediate concentration for the destruction of the taints slowly. This, bhikkhus, is called painful practice with slow direct knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.162", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.162" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the practice of non-endurance? Here, bhikkhus, a person reviles back at one who has reviled, gets angry at one who has become angry, quarrels with one who has quarreled. This, bhikkhus, is called the practice of non-endurance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the practice of endurance? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not revile back at one who has reviled, does not get angry at one who has become angry, does not quarrel with one who has quarreled. This, bhikkhus, is called the practice of endurance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the practice of restraint? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when seeing a form with the eye, does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the eye faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the eye faculty, practices the restraint of the eye faculty. When he hears a sound with the ear... smells an odor with the nose... tastes a taste with the tongue... feels a touch with the body... cognizes a mind-object with the mind, he does not grasp the general sign, does not grasp the particular sign. For whatever reason, if the mind faculty were unrestrained, covetousness, grief, evil unwholesome states might arise, he restrains that cause, guards the mind faculty, practices the restraint of the mind faculty. This, bhikkhus, is called the practice of restraint.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is called the practice of calming? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not consent to arisen thoughts of sensual desire; he abandons, dispels, calms, terminates, and makes them nonexistent. He does not consent to arisen thoughts of ill-will... does not consent to arisen thoughts of harming... does not consent to arisen evil unwholesome states; he abandons, dispels, calms, terminates, and makes them nonexistent. This, bhikkhus, is called the practice of calming.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu develops insight preceded by serenity. By developing insight preceded by serenity, the path is born. He practices that path, develops it, and cultivates it. By practicing, developing, and cultivating that path, the fetters are abandoned, the underlying tendencies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.170" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu develops serenity preceded by insight. By developing serenity preceded by insight, the path is born. He practices that path, develops it, and cultivates it. By practicing, developing, and cultivating that path, the fetters are abandoned, the underlying tendencies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.170" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu develops both serenity and insight coupled together. By developing both serenity and insight coupled together, the path is born. He practices that path, develops it, and cultivates it. By practicing, developing, and cultivating that path, the fetters are abandoned, the underlying tendencies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.170" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu's mind is completely rid of agitation regarding phenomena. Venerable sirs, this is the time when his mind is inwardly settled, composed, unified, concentrated. For him, the path is born. He practices that path, develops it, and cultivates it. By practicing, developing, and cultivating that path, the fetters are abandoned, the underlying tendencies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.170" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who has faith, if he rightly aspires, should aspire thus: 'May I be like Sāriputta and Moggallāna.' Bhikkhus, they are the standard and measure for my bhikkhu disciples, namely Sāriputta and Moggallāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.176", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.176" },

{ text: `Rāhula, whatever internal earth element and whatever external earth element, that is just the earth element... whatever internal water element and whatever external water element, that is just the water element... whatever internal fire element and whatever external fire element, that is just the fire element... whatever internal air element and whatever external air element, that is just the air element. That should be seen with right wisdom as it really is: 'This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.' Having seen it as it really is with right wisdom, he becomes disenchanted with the air element. With wisdom, he cleanses his mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.177", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.177" },

{ text: `When, Rāhula, a bhikkhu no longer regards these four elements as self or as belonging to self, then, Rāhula, he is called a bhikkhu who has cut off craving, untied the fetters, rightly demolished conceit, and made an end of suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.177", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.177" },

{ text: `Here, Venerable Ānanda, beings do not truly understand as it really is: 'These perceptions are for decline'; they do not truly understand: 'These perceptions are for stability'; they do not truly understand: 'These perceptions are for distinction'; they do not truly understand: 'These perceptions are for penetration.' This, Venerable Ānanda, is the cause, this is the condition, that some beings in this very life do not attain Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.179", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.179" },

{ text: `Brahmin, if speaking about what is seen causes unwholesome states to increase and wholesome states to decrease, then I say that such a seen thing should not be spoken of. And, brahmin, if speaking about what is seen causes unwholesome states to decrease and wholesome states to increase, then I say that such a seen thing should be spoken of. Brahmin, if speaking about what is heard... if speaking about what is sensed... if speaking about what is cognized causes unwholesome states to increase and wholesome states to decrease, then I say that such a cognized thing should not be spoken of. And, brahmin, if speaking about what is cognized causes unwholesome states to decrease and wholesome states to increase, then I say that such a cognized thing should be spoken of.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.183", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.183" },

{ text: `Here, brahmin, a person is not dispassionate towards sensual pleasures, not free from desire, not free from affection, not free from thirst, not free from fever, not free from craving. Then a severe illness arises in him. Affected by that severe illness, he reflects: 'Indeed, these delightful sensual pleasures will leave me,' or 'I will leave these delightful sensual pleasures.' He grieves, laments, weeps, beats his breast, and falls into confusion. This, brahmin, is a person who, by nature, being subject to death, is afraid and falls into terror when thinking of death.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.184", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.184" },

{ text: `Furthermore, brahmin, here a person is not dispassionate towards the body... Then a severe illness arises in him. Affected by that severe illness, he reflects: 'Indeed, this delightful body will leave me,' or 'I will leave this delightful body.' He grieves, laments, weeps, beats his breast, and falls into confusion. This, brahmin, is a person who, by nature, being subject to death, is afraid and falls into terror when thinking of death.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.184", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.184" },

{ text: `Furthermore, brahmin, here a person has not done what is good, has not done what is wholesome, has not given protection to the fearful, has done evil, has done cruel deeds, has done transgressive deeds. Then a severe illness arises in him. Affected by that severe illness, he reflects: 'Indeed, I have not done what is good, have not done what is wholesome, have not given protection to the fearful, have done evil, have done cruel deeds, have done transgressive deeds. To whatever realm those who have not done what is good... go after death, I will go to that realm.' He grieves, laments, weeps, beats his breast, and falls into confusion. This, brahmin, is a person who, by nature, being subject to death, is afraid and falls into terror when thinking of death.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.184", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.184" },

{ text: `Here, wanderers, the brahmin says thus: 'All living beings should not be killed.' The brahmin who says this speaks the truth, not falsehood. Therefore, he does not think of 'ascetic,' does not think of 'brahmin,' does not think 'I am superior,' does not think 'I am equal,' does not think 'I is inferior.' Furthermore, by directly knowing the truth contained therein, he practices compassion and loving-kindness towards living beings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.185", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.185" },

{ text: `Furthermore, wanderers, the brahmin says thus: 'All sensual pleasures are impermanent, suffering, subject to change.' The brahmin who says this speaks the truth, not falsehood. Therefore, he does not think of 'ascetic,' does not think of 'brahmin,' does not think 'I am superior,' does not think 'I am equal,' does not think 'I am inferior.' Furthermore, by directly knowing the truth contained therein, he practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.185", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.185" },

{ text: `Furthermore, wanderers, the brahmin says thus: 'All kinds of existence are impermanent, suffering, subject to change.' The brahmin who says this speaks the truth, not falsehood. Therefore, he does not think of 'ascetic,' does not think of 'brahmin,' does not think 'I am superior,' does not think 'I am equal,' does not think 'I am inferior.' Furthermore, by directly knowing the truth contained therein, he practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding all kinds of existence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.185", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.185" },

{ text: `Furthermore, wanderers, the brahmin says thus: 'I am not anyone's, not anything's anywhere, nor am I anything anywhere. There is nothing belonging to me anywhere, in any way.' The brahmin who says this speaks the truth, not falsehood. Therefore, he does not think of 'ascetic,' does not think of 'brahmin,' does not think 'I am superior,' does not think 'I am equal,' does not think 'I am inferior.' Furthermore, by directly knowing the truth contained therein, he practices the path of nothingness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.185", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.185" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhu, a wise person, a person of great wisdom, does not think of harming himself, does not think of harming others, does not think of harming both; whatever he thinks, he thinks of benefiting himself, benefiting others, benefiting both, benefiting the whole world. Thus, bhikkhu, is a wise person, a person of great wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.186", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.186" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, it is by mind that the world is led; it is by mind that the world is drawn along; and the world follows the mastery of mind once it has arisen.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.186", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.186" },

{ text: `Here, Mallikā, a certain woman is irritable and very malicious; even when spoken to lightly, she becomes exasperated, angry, hostile, aggressive, provocative, displaying irritation, hatred, and displeasure. She does not give to ascetics or brahmins food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, lamps; she is stingy; seeing others receiving gain, honor, respect, reverence, homage, offerings, she envies, resents, and is bound by envy. That woman, after leaving this life, returning to this state, is reborn in a lowly position, with bad complexion, ugly appearance, inferior form, poor, with few possessions, little property, little influence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.197", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.197" },

{ text: `Here, Mallikā, a certain woman is not irritable and not very malicious; even when spoken to much, she does not become exasperated, angry, hostile, aggressive, provocative, does not display irritation, hatred, or displeasure. She gives to ascetics and brahmins food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, lamps; she is not stingy; seeing others receiving gain, honor, respect, reverence, homage, offerings, she does not envy, resent, or become bound by envy. That woman, after leaving this life, returning to this state, is reborn with beautiful complexion, good appearance, serene, possessing excellent form, wealthy, with great property, great possessions, great influence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.197", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.197" },

{ text: `Craving, bhikkhus, is a net that makes the wandering in saṃsāra spread out, sticky; it is because of that craving that this world is destroyed, bound, tangled like a ball of thread, like a matted cocoon, like twisted muñja grass and babhaja reeds, unable to escape from the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, birth and death.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.199", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.199" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person himself possesses faith and also encourages others to have faith; himself possesses moral shame and encourages others to have moral shame; himself possesses moral dread and encourages others to have moral dread; himself is learned and encourages others to be learned; himself is energetic and encourages others to be energetic; himself is mindful and encourages others to be mindful; himself possesses wisdom and encourages others to possess wisdom. Such a person, bhikkhus, is called a genuine person even more than a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.202", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.202" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a person himself abstains from killing living beings and encourages others to abstain from killing; himself abstains from taking what is not given and encourages others to abstain from taking what is not given; himself abstains from sexual misconduct and encourages others to abstain from sexual misconduct; himself abstains from false speech and encourages others to abstain from false speech; himself abstains from divisive speech and encourages others to abstain from divisive speech; himself abstains from harsh speech and encourages others to abstain from harsh speech; himself abstains from idle chatter and encourages others to abstain from idle chatter. This, bhikkhus, is called a genuine person even more than a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.203", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.203" },

{ text: `Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell. What four? Possessing evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action, and being ungrateful, unthankful. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell.<br>Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven. What four? Possessing good bodily action, good verbal action, good mental action, and being grateful, thankful. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.213", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.213" },

{ text: `Here, Ānanda, an evil bhikkhu, being of evil conduct, of evil nature, impure, of doubtful behavior, concealing his actions, not a true ascetic but claiming to be an ascetic, not living the holy life but claiming to live the holy life, inwardly rotten, saturated with desires, a heap of filth. He thinks thus: 'If the bhikkhus know that I am of evil conduct, evil nature, impure... a heap of filth, then if they are united, they will harm me; if they are divided, they cannot harm me.' Seeing this first benefit, Ānanda, an evil bhikkhu delights in schism in the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.243" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Ānanda, an evil bhikkhu has wrong livelihood, living by wrong livelihood. He thinks thus: 'If the bhikkhus know that I have wrong livelihood, living by wrong livelihood, then if they are united, they will harm me; if they are divided, they cannot harm me.' Seeing this third benefit, Ānanda, an evil bhikkhu delights in schism in the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.243" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, the training rules for superior conduct have been laid down by me for the disciples, so that those of little faith might arouse faith. For, bhikkhus, the training rules for superior conduct have been laid down by me for the disciples, so that those of little faith might arouse faith, and those with faith might have their faith increased. Therefore, a disciple, having undertaken and trained in the training rules, should have unimpaired conduct, uncut conduct, unstained conduct, unblemished conduct in that training. Thus, bhikkhus, is the benefit of training.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.245", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.245" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, the training rules for the holy life have been laid down by me for the disciples, for the complete and proper ending of suffering. For, bhikkhus, the training rules for the holy life have been laid down by me for the disciples, for the complete and proper ending of suffering. Therefore, a disciple, having undertaken and trained in the training rules, should have unimpaired conduct, uncut conduct, unstained conduct, unblemished conduct in that training. Thus, bhikkhus, is the benefit of training.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.245", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.245" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four ignoble searches. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a person himself being subject to aging seeks what is subject to aging; himself being subject to sickness seeks what is subject to sickness; himself being subject to death seeks what is subject to death; himself being subject to defilement seeks what is subject to defilement. Bhikkhus, these are the four ignoble searches.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.255" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four noble searches. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a person himself being subject to aging, having known the danger in what is subject to aging, seeks the unaging, the unsurpassed security from bondage, Nibbāna; himself being subject to sickness, having known the danger in what is subject to sickness, seeks the sickness-free, the unsurpassed security from bondage, Nibbāna; himself being subject to death, having known the danger in what is subject to death, seeks the deathless, the unsurpassed security from bondage, Nibbāna; himself being subject to defilement, having known the danger in defilement, seeks the undefiled, the unsurpassed security from bondage, Nibbāna. Bhikkhus, these are the four noble searches.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.255" },

{ text: `Whatever families, bhikkhus, achieve growth in wealth and last long, all do so through these four conditions or one of them. What four? Searching for what is lost; repairing what is worn out; eating and drinking in moderation; placing a virtuous woman or man in a position of authority. Whatever families, bhikkhus, achieve growth in wealth and last long, all do so through these four conditions or one of them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.258", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.258" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has no faith, no moral shame, no moral dread, is lazy, and of evil wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.3" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has faith, has moral shame, has moral dread, is energetic, and possesses wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.3" },

{ text: `There is no entering upon the unwholesome, bhikkhus, as long as moral shame... moral dread... energy... wisdom are established in wholesome states. When moral shame... moral dread... energy... wisdom disappear, bhikkhus, then shamelessness... fearlessness... laziness... evil wisdom arise and persist, then there is entering upon the unwholesome.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, as long as a bhikkhu has not aroused faith regarding wholesome states, has not aroused moral shame regarding unwholesome states, has not aroused moral dread regarding unwholesome states, has not aroused energy regarding wholesome states, has not aroused wisdom regarding wholesome states — as long as that, bhikkhus, I need to guard that bhikkhu. When, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has aroused faith regarding wholesome states, has aroused moral shame regarding unwholesome states, has aroused moral dread regarding unwholesome states, has aroused energy regarding wholesome states, has aroused wisdom regarding wholesome states — then, bhikkhus, I no longer care for that bhikkhu, thinking: 'Now that bhikkhu knows how to protect himself, he is no longer heedless.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.7" },

{ text: `For the most part, bhikkhus, beings find pleasure in sensual pleasures. For a clansman, bhikkhus, who has set aside the sickle and the carrying pole, and gone forth from home to homelessness, it is enough to be called: 'A clansman who has gone forth out of faith.' Why is that?<br>Sensual pleasures are found in youth, these or other sensual pleasures. And, bhikkhus, inferior sensual pleasures, middling sensual pleasures, and superior sensual pleasures — all are considered to be sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.7" },

{ text: `A bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who is without reverence, without deference, and not living in concord with his fellow celibates — it is impossible that he will fulfill the practice of superior conduct. Not fulfilling the practice of superior conduct, it is impossible that he will fulfill the learner's practice. Not fulfilling the learner's practice, it is impossible that he will fulfill the rules of virtuous conduct. Not fulfilling the rules of virtuous conduct, it is impossible that he will fulfill right view. Not fulfilling right view, it is impossible that he will fulfill right concentration.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.21" },

{ text: `A bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who has reverence, deference, and lives in concord with his fellow celibates — it is possible that he will fulfill the practice of superior conduct. Having fulfilled the practice of superior conduct, it is possible that he will fulfill the learner's practice. Having fulfilled the learner's practice, it is possible that he will fulfill the rules of virtuous conduct. Having fulfilled the rules of virtuous conduct, it is possible that he will fulfill right view. Having fulfilled right view, it is possible that he will fulfill right concentration.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five defilements of the mind, defiled by which the mind becomes not pliant, not wieldy, not radiant, but brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. What five? Sensual desire, ill-will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, doubt. These five defilements of the mind, bhikkhus, defiled by which the mind becomes not pliant, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.23" },

{ text: `And when, bhikkhus, the mind is liberated from these five defilements: sensual desire, ill-will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, doubt — then that mind becomes pliant, wieldy, radiant, not brittle, and properly concentrated for the destruction of the taints. Regarding whatever state he directs his mind to for direct knowledge and realization, in each case he has the ability and capacity to attain that state, in whichever sphere.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.23" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with its branches and leaves destroyed: then its shoots do not reach completeness, its bark does not reach completeness, its sapwood does not reach completeness, its heartwood does not reach completeness. So too, bhikkhus, for an immoral person, one of broken virtue, right concentration is thereby destroyed. When right concentration is absent, for one whose right concentration is destroyed, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is thereby destroyed. When true knowledge and vision is absent, for one whose true knowledge and vision is destroyed, disenchantment and dispassion are thereby destroyed. When disenchantment and dispassion are absent, for one whose disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed, the knowledge and vision of liberation is thereby destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.24" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with its branches and leaves complete: then its shoots reach completeness, its bark reaches completeness, its sapwood reaches completeness, its heartwood reaches completeness. So too, bhikkhus, for a virtuous person, one who maintains virtue, right concentration is thereby complete. When right concentration is present, for one who has accomplished right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is thereby complete. When true knowledge and vision is present, for one who has accomplished true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are thereby complete. When disenchantment and dispassion are present, for one who has accomplished disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is thereby complete.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.24" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, being wise and mindful, develop immeasurable concentration. For one who is wise and mindful developing immeasurable concentration, five kinds of knowledge arise in each person. What five? This concentration is pleasant in the present and leads to pleasant results in the future — knowledge arises in each person. This concentration is noble, not material — knowledge arises in each person. This concentration is not practiced by evil persons — knowledge arises in each person. This concentration is peaceful, sublime, leading to tranquility, attaining one-pointedness, not a state of constant suppression and restraint — knowledge arises in each person. 'Peacefully I enter this concentration; peacefully I emerge from this concentration' — knowledge arises in each person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.27" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits of walking meditation. What five? It endures long journeys; it endures exertion; it has few illnesses; it leads to good digestion of food, drink, chewed, and tasted; the concentration attained while walking meditation lasts long. These, bhikkhus, are the five benefits of walking meditation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.29" },

{ text: `- Nāgita, who are those who have come and are making a noise like fish in a great heap of fish?<br>- Those people, Bhante, are the brahmin householders from Icchānaṅgala, standing at the outer gate, bringing many kinds of hard and soft food for the Blessed One and the Saṅgha.<br>- Nāgita, I have no connection with honor, and honor has no connection with me. Nāgita, those who find without difficulty, without trouble, without effort, find the bliss of seclusion, the bliss of peace, the bliss of enlightenment — that I have found without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. Let them enjoy that bliss which is like excrement, the bliss of sleeping, the bliss of gain, honor, and renown.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.30" },

{ text: `Nāgita, for those who are heavy with craving for pleasure, Nāgita, with the change and alteration of that, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. That is the natural consequence for that person. For those who focus their minds on the sign of the foul, Nāgita, disenchantment with the sign of the beautiful becomes established. That is the natural consequence for that person. For one who dwells contemplating impermanence in the six sense-spheres, Nāgita, disenchantment with contact becomes established. That is the natural consequence for that person. For one who dwells contemplating arising and passing away in the five aggregates of clinging, Nāgita, disenchantment with clinging becomes established. That is the natural consequence for that person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.30" },

{ text: `A giver, Sumanā, when reborn as a human, surpasses a non-giver on five grounds: in terms of life span, in terms of beauty, in terms of happiness, in terms of fame, in terms of supremacy. A giver, Sumanā, when reborn as a human, surpasses a non-giver on these five grounds. Such is the case, Sumanā, that it is enough to give, enough to do meritorious deeds. They are aid and merit for devas. They are aid and merit for humans. They are aid and merit for those who have gone forth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.31" },

{ text: `Like the moon unstained<br>Moving through the firmament,<br>With radiance blazing<br>Among the starry host in the world.<br>So too, one of virtue,<br>A person with faith,<br>With giving, blazes forth<br>Among the stingy in the world.<br>Like a cloud with rain and thunder,<br>A garland with a hundred crests,<br>Filling up the valleys,<br>Spreading over the plains.<br>So too, full of vision,<br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>The wise one surpasses stinginess<br>In five respects:<br>Life span and fame,<br>Beauty and happiness,<br>With abundant wealth,<br>Upon death he enjoys heavenly bliss.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.31" },

{ text: `A giver, Sīha, a donor, is loved and liked by the multitude. This, Sīha, is a directly visible benefit of giving. Furthermore, Sīha, good people, genuine persons, associate with a giver, a donor. This, Sīha, is a directly visible benefit of giving. Furthermore, Sīha, a giver, a donor, gains a good reputation. This, Sīha, is a directly visible benefit of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.34" },

{ text: `A giver, Sīha, a donor, whatever assembly he approaches — whether an assembly of nobles, brahmins, householders, or ascetics — he approaches with confidence, without hesitation or perplexity. This, Sīha, is a directly visible benefit of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.34" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits of giving. What five? One is loved and liked by many people; good people, genuine persons, associate with one; a good reputation spreads; one does not deviate from the householder's duty; after death, with the breakup of the body, one is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. These, bhikkhus, are the five benefits of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.35" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five timely gifts. What five? Giving to a newcomer; giving to one who is leaving; giving to a sick person; giving during a famine; and whatever newly harvested fruits, one first offers them to the virtuous. Bhikkhus, these five are timely gifts.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.36" },

{ text: `A giver of a meal, bhikkhus, a donor, gives five things to the recipient. What five? He gives life, gives beauty, gives happiness, gives strength, gives eloquence. Giving life, he has a share in life, whether celestial or human. Giving beauty, he has a share in beauty, whether celestial or human. Giving happiness, he has a share in happiness, whether celestial or human. Giving strength, he has a share in strength, whether celestial or human. Giving eloquence, he has a share in eloquence, whether celestial or human. A giver of a meal, bhikkhus, a donor, gives these five things to the recipient.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.37" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits for a faithful clansman. What five? Good people, genuine persons, first have compassion for the faithful, not so for the faithless; when visiting, they first visit the faithful, not so for the faithless; when receiving, they first receive from the faithful, not from the faithless; they teach the Dhamma first to the faithful, not to the faithless; the faithful, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. These, bhikkhus, are the five benefits for a faithful clansman.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.38" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, on good ground at a crossroads, a great banyan tree is a refuge for the surrounding birds, so too, bhikkhus, a faithful clansman is a refuge for the multitude, for bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, and female lay followers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.38" },

{ text: `Like a great banyan tree,<br>With branches, leaves, and fruit,<br>With trunk, roots, full of fruit,<br>A shelter for birds.<br>In a pleasant abode,<br>Birds build their nests,<br>Need shade, enjoy coolness,<br>Need fruit, eat fruit.<br>So too, one of virtue,<br>A person of serene faith,<br>Humble and gentle,<br>Kind, with gentle speech,<br>Truly mild in nature,<br>One who has abandoned greed, abandoned hatred,<br>Abandoned delusion, taintless,<br>Is a field of merit in the world.<br>They come to such a one,<br>They teach the Dhamma; that person<br>Ends all suffering.<br>That one, having understood<br>That true Dhamma here,<br>Attains Nibbāna,<br>Completely taintless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.38" },

{ text: `Who gives a pleasant thing,<br>Receives a pleasant thing,<br>Gives a supreme thing,<br>Receives a supreme result.<br>One who has an excellent thing,<br>Receives an excellent thing,<br>One who has a superior thing,<br>Receives a superior thing.<br>Whoever gives superior,<br>Excellent, and supreme things,<br>That one has long life<br>And also gains fame,<br>Wherever he is reborn.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.44" },

{ text: `The great ocean, limitless,<br>The great lake, very fearful,<br>Is a treasure trove storing<br>Countless jewels,<br>And is also a shelter<br>For countless species of fish,<br>It is where great rivers<br>Converge and flow into the ocean.<br>So too, a giver of<br>Food and drink,<br>Clothing and bedding,<br>Seats and mats,<br>Thus the wise one giving,<br>Merit flows to him<br>As rivers carry water<br>Flowing into the great ocean.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.45" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple dwelling at home, with mind free from the stain of miserliness, gives generously, with open hand, delighting in relinquishment, ready to be asked, delighting in distributing gifts. This, bhikkhus, is called the wealth of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.47" },

{ text: `One who has confidence in the Tathāgata,<br>Unshakable, well-established,<br>Who guards good virtue,<br>Loved and praised by the Noble ones,<br>One who has serene confidence in the Saṅgha,<br>Seen as straight,<br>That person is called not poor,<br>His life is not in vain.<br>Therefore, faith and virtue,<br>Serene confidence seeing true Dhamma,<br>The wise person, mind focused,<br>Remembers the Buddha's words.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.47" },

{ text: `For an unlearned ordinary person, bhikkhus, who is subject to aging and aging comes... subject to sickness and sickness comes... subject to death and death comes... subject to destruction and destruction comes... subject to perishing and perishing comes; when perishing comes, he does not reflect: 'It is not only I who am subject to perishing and to whom perishing comes, but for all beings who come and go, who perish and arise, all beings are subject to perishing and perishing comes. If, being subject to perishing, when perishing comes, I were to grieve, lament, weep, beat my breast, and fall into confusion, then food would not please me; my body would become ugly; work would not progress; enemies would rejoice; friends would grieve.' Being subject to perishing, when perishing comes, he grieves, laments, weeps, beats his breast, and falls into confusion. This, bhikkhus, is called an unlearned ordinary person struck by the poisoned arrow of sorrow, who torments himself.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.48" },

{ text: `With well-spoken truth,<br>With proper giving,<br>With tradition well-maintained,<br>Wherever benefit is found,<br>There one should strive.<br>If one knows that benefit is not gained,<br>Neither for oneself nor for others,<br>Without sorrow, knowing endurance,<br>Let that one think:<br>What should I do now?<br>How should I persevere?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.50" },

{ text: `Sensual desire, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance that covers the mind and weakens wisdom. Ill-will, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance that covers the mind and weakens wisdom. Dullness and drowsiness, bhikkhus, are an obstruction, a hindrance that covers the mind and weakens wisdom. Restlessness and remorse, bhikkhus, are an obstruction, a hindrance that covers the mind and weakens wisdom. Doubt, bhikkhus, is an obstruction, a hindrance that covers the mind and weakens wisdom. These, bhikkhus, are the five obstructions, hindrances that cover the mind and weaken wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.51" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a river flowing down from the mountain, flowing far, with a swift current, carrying everything before it. Then a man opens channels on both sides of the river. Thus, bhikkhus, that river in the middle is obstructed, spreads out, is diverted, no longer flows far, no longer flows swiftly, no longer carries everything before it. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who has not abandoned these five obstructions, hindrances that cover the mind and weaken wisdom, weak in strength and poor in wisdom, cannot know his own benefit, cannot know the benefit of others, cannot know the benefit of both, cannot realize a superior human state, the truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision — this is impossible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.51" },

{ text: `Speaking of a heap of the unwholesome, bhikkhus, if one would speak rightly, one would speak of the five hindrances. For truly, bhikkhus, the entire heap of the unwholesome is just the five hindrances. What five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of dullness and drowsiness, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. Speaking of a heap of the unwholesome, bhikkhus, if one would speak rightly, one would speak of the five hindrances. For truly, bhikkhus, this entire heap of the unwholesome is just the five hindrances.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.52" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if anyone were to say: 'A complete snare of Māra,' he would rightly say that of women. Truly, 'a complete snare of Māra' — that is what women are.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.55" },


{ text: `Speak with a person<br>Who has a sword in hand,<br>Speak with a demon,<br>Or sit very close.<br>A snake with venom,<br>If bitten, death follows,<br>But never alone<br>Speak with a woman.<br>Unmindful, they bind you<br>With glances, with smiles,<br>With loose garments,<br>With sweet words.<br>That person still unsatisfied,<br>Confused, meets death.<br>Those five nurturing sensual pleasures<br>Are seen in female form:<br>Forms, sounds, scents, tastes, touches,<br>Alluring and delightful.<br>By the waterfall of sensual desires,<br>Flooded and swept away,<br>The foolish, unwise person<br>Does not understand sensual pleasures.<br>Humans, upon death,<br>Realm of existence or non-existence,<br>They are led along<br>Through many rounds of rebirth.<br>One who understands sensual pleasures,<br>Whose conduct is fearless,<br>They reach the further shore,<br>Attain the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.55" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, when a person lives with unguarded senses, without moderation in eating, without devotion to wakefulness, without regard for wholesome states, without diligently developing the factors of enlightenment in the evening and in the morning, then his body feels as if intoxicated, his eyes do not see directions clearly, the Dhamma is not remembered by him. Dullness and drowsiness overcome his mind and persist. Without joy, he lives the holy life. He has doubts regarding the true Dhamma. Therefore, bhikkhu, you should train thus: 'I will guard my senses, have moderation in eating, be devoted to wakefulness, regard wholesome states, and in the evening and morning I will diligently develop the factors of enlightenment.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.56" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, when a person lives with guarded senses, with moderation in eating, with devotion to wakefulness, with regard for wholesome states, diligently developing the factors of enlightenment in the evening and in the morning, then his body does not feel as if intoxicated, directions are clear, and the Dhamma is remembered by him. Dullness and drowsiness do not overcome his mind. With joy, he lives the holy life. He has no doubts regarding wholesome states. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'I will guard my senses, have moderation in eating, be devoted to wakefulness, regard wholesome states, and in the evening and morning I will diligently develop the factors of enlightenment.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.56" },

{ text: `Subject to sickness and to aging,<br>And also subject to death,<br>Such is the nature of the frail,<br>Such is the nature of beings.<br>If an ordinary person becomes disenchanted,<br>That would truly not be proper for me,<br>If I too were to become disenchanted<br>With beings<br>Who share the same fate.<br>While my life<br>Is no different from theirs,<br>Thus I dwell,<br>Knowing the Dhamma without attachment.<br>Pride in health,<br>In youth, in life —<br>All I have subdued,<br>Arising from security.<br>I see the bliss of seclusion,<br>I arouse courageous mind,<br>See the state of Nibbāna.<br>Now I cannot<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures.<br>I will not decline,<br>I will attain the ultimate goal of the holy life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.57" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless. What five? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of danger, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world. These five perceptions, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.61" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless. What five? The perception of impermanence, the perception of non-self, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world. These five perceptions, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.62" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, by growing in five kinds of growth, a noble disciple grows in noble growth, bringing steadfastness and distinction to himself. What five? He grows in faith, grows in virtue, grows in learning, grows in giving, grows in wisdom. By growing in these five kinds of growth, bhikkhus, a noble disciple grows in noble growth, bringing steadfastness and distinction to himself.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.63" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these five things, when developed and cultivated, lead to the destruction of the taints. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating foulness in the body, with perception of disgust for food, with perception of non-delight in the entire world, contemplating impermanence in all conditioned things, and with the perception of death well established internally. These five things, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, lead to the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.70" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu teaches the Dhamma to others extensively as he has heard and learned. He spends the whole day explaining the Dhamma to others, neglecting the peaceful life of seclusion, not striving to focus on internal serenity of mind. This, bhikkhus, is called a bhikkhu who is much in recitation but does not live in accordance with the Dhamma.<br>Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu recites the Dhamma extensively as he has heard and learned. He spends the whole day reciting, neglecting the peaceful life of seclusion, not striving to focus on internal serenity of mind. This, bhikkhus, is called a bhikkhu who is much in recitation but does not live in accordance with the Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.73" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with applied and sustained thought, with his mind contemplating the Dhamma as he has heard and learned, spends the whole day thinking about the Dhamma, neglecting the peaceful life of seclusion, not striving to focus on internal serenity of mind. This, bhikkhus, is called a bhikkhu who is much in thought but does not live in accordance with the Dhamma.<br>Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu learns the Dhamma, that is, the discourses, mixed prose and verse, expositions, verses, inspired utterances, quotations, birth stories, marvelous accounts, and explanations, or the expanded texts. He does not spend the whole day learning the Dhamma, does not neglect the peaceful life of seclusion, but strives to focus on internal serenity of mind. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who lives in accordance with the Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.73" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, whatever a Teacher should do for his disciples out of compassion and concern for their welfare, that I have done for you. Bhikkhu, these are the roots of trees, these are empty huts. Meditate, bhikkhu, do not be heedless, lest you regret it later. This is my instruction to you.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.73" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'Now I am young, youthful, a young man with black hair, in the prime of life, at the beginning of my years. But there will come a time when old age will touch this body. When old and frail, overcome by old age, it is not easy to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas, nor to dwell in remote forest and mountain dwellings. Before that undesirable, unlovely, disagreeable condition comes to me, let me arouse energy and strive before that time comes, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. And if I attain that state, even though I grow old, I will dwell at ease.'<br>Bhikkhus, by seeing this first fear regarding the future, it is enough for a bhikkhu to dwell heedful, ardent, and resolute, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.78" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'Now I have few illnesses, few afflictions, my digestion is good, not too cold, not too hot, moderate, suitable for exertion. But there will come a time when sickness will touch this body. When sick and overcome by sickness, it is not easy to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas, nor to dwell in remote forest and mountain dwellings. Before that undesirable, unlovely, disagreeable condition comes to me, let me arouse energy and strive before that time comes, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. And if I attain that state, even though I fall sick, I will dwell at ease.'<br>Bhikkhus, by seeing this second fear regarding the future, it is enough for a bhikkhu to dwell heedful, ardent, and resolute, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.78" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'Now there is no famine; there is a good harvest; almsfood is easy to obtain; it is easy to support oneself by gathering almsfood with effort. But there will come a time of famine, poor harvest; almsfood obtained with effort is not easy to obtain; it is not easy to support oneself by gathering almsfood with effort. And those afflicted by famine will move to wherever there is plenty of food. There, they will have to live in a crowd, in confusion. When living in a crowd, in confusion, it is not easy to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas, nor to dwell in remote forest and mountain dwellings. Before that undesirable, unlovely, disagreeable condition comes to me, let me arouse energy and strive before that time comes, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. And if I attain that state, even though there is famine, I will dwell at ease.'<br>Bhikkhus, by seeing this third fear regarding the future, it is enough for a bhikkhu to dwell heedful, ardent, and resolute, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.78" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'Now people dwell together in harmony, rejoicing with one another, without quarreling, like milk mixed with water, looking at one another with loving eyes. But there will come a time of fear from jungle bandits; people in the country will mount vehicles and flee to where there is safety. There, they will have to live in a crowd, in confusion. When living in a crowd, in confusion, it is not easy to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas, nor to dwell in remote forest and mountain dwellings. Before that undesirable, unlovely, disagreeable condition comes to me, let me arouse energy and strive before that time comes, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. And if I attain that state, even though there is fear, I will dwell at ease.'<br>Bhikkhus, by seeing this fourth fear regarding the future, it is enough for a bhikkhu to dwell heedful, ardent, and resolute, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.78" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'Now the Saṅgha is united, rejoicing together, without dispute, dwelling at ease with a single teaching... But there will come a time when the Saṅgha is divided. When the Saṅgha is divided, it is not easy to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas, nor to dwell in remote forest and mountain dwellings. Before that undesirable, unlovely, disagreeable condition comes to me, let me arouse energy and strive before that time comes, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. And if I attain that state, even though the Saṅgha is divided, I will dwell at ease.'<br>Bhikkhus, by seeing this fifth fear regarding the future, it is enough for a bhikkhu to dwell heedful, ardent, and resolute, to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.78" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, in the future, bhikkhus will desire fine robes. Because they desire fine robes, they will abandon the robe taken from a dust heap, abandon the forests, the remote highland dwellings, and go to villages, towns, and royal cities, dwelling there. Because of robes, they will fall into improper, unsuitable seeking. This, bhikkhus, is the first fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.80" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, in the future, bhikkhus will desire delicious almsfood. Because they desire delicious almsfood, they will abandon the almsfood round, abandon the forests, the remote highland dwellings, and go to villages, towns, and royal cities, dwelling there, seeking exquisite flavors with their tongues. Because of almsfood, they will fall into improper, unsuitable seeking. This, bhikkhus, is the second fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.80" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, in the future, bhikkhus will desire fine lodgings. Because they desire fine lodgings, they will abandon the dwelling at the foot of a tree, abandon the forests, the remote highland dwellings, and go to villages, towns, and royal cities, dwelling there. Because of lodgings, they will fall into improper, unsuitable seeking. This, bhikkhus, is the third fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.80" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, in the future, bhikkhus will live in association with bhikkhunīs, female probationers, and female novices. When living in association with bhikkhunīs, female probationers, and female novices, bhikkhus, it is to be expected: they will not delight in living the holy life, or they will fall into one of the corrupting offenses, give up the training and return to the lay life. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.80" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a person with wrong view, wrong intention, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration, wrong knowledge, wrong liberation — whatever bodily actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with that view, whatever verbal actions... whatever mental actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with that view, whatever intentions, decisions, aspirations, and whatever volitional activities — all those states lead to the undesirable, the unpleasant, the disagreeable, to harm and suffering. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, the view is evil. Just as, bhikkhus, a neem seed, or a kosātaki seed, or a bitter gourd seed, planted in moist soil — whatever taste it draws from the earth, whatever taste it draws from the water, all that taste leads to bitterness, acridity, and unpleasantness. Why is that? Because the seed is evil, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.104" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a person with right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration, right knowledge, right liberation — whatever bodily actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with that view, whatever verbal actions... whatever mental actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with that view, whatever intentions, decisions, aspirations, and whatever volitional activities — all those states lead to the desirable, the pleasant, the agreeable, to happiness and well-being. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, the view is wholesome. Just as, bhikkhus, a sugar cane seed, or a rice seed, or a grape seed, planted in moist soil — whatever taste it draws from the earth, whatever taste it draws from the water, all that taste leads to sweetness, pleasantness, and purity. Why is that? Because the seed is wholesome, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.104" },

{ text: `When ignorance leads the way, bhikkhus, for the attainment of unwholesome states, then moral shamelessness and moral fearlessness follow. For one overcome by ignorance, lacking wisdom, bhikkhus, wrong view arises. For one with wrong view, wrong intention arises. For one with wrong intention, wrong speech arises. For one with wrong speech, wrong action arises. For one with wrong action, wrong livelihood arises. For one with wrong livelihood, wrong effort arises. For one with wrong effort, wrong mindfulness arises. For one with wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration arises. For one with wrong concentration, wrong knowledge arises. For one with wrong knowledge, wrong liberation arises.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.105" },

{ text: `When true knowledge leads the way, bhikkhus, for the attainment of wholesome states, then moral shame and moral dread follow. For one overcome by true knowledge, possessing wisdom, bhikkhus, right view arises. For one with right view, right intention arises. For one with right intention, right speech arises. For one with right speech, right action arises. For one with right action, right livelihood arises. For one with right livelihood, right effort arises. For one with right effort, right mindfulness arises. For one with right mindfulness, right concentration arises. For one with right concentration, right knowledge arises. For one with right knowledge, right liberation arises.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.105" },

{ text: `Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practices the direct path and has the right foundations for the destruction of the taints. What four? Thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming, and right view. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practices the direct path and has the right foundations for the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.72" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four kinds of self-confidence of the Tathāgata, possessing which the Tathāgata claims the bull's place, roars his lion's roar in the assemblies, and sets in motion the wheel of Brahmā. What four? 'I claim to be Perfectly Enlightened, but these things are not fully known to me' — if any ascetic, brahmin, deva, Māra, Brahmā, or anyone in the world should reprove me in accordance with the Dhamma thus, I do not see this case. 'I claim to have destroyed the taints, but these taints are not destroyed' — if any... should reprove me thus, I do not see this case. 'These things that I have declared as obstructions are not able to obstruct one who engages in them' — if any... should reprove me thus, I do not see this case. 'The Dhamma and purpose that I declare does not lead one who practices it to the complete destruction of suffering' — if any... should reprove me thus, I do not see this case.<br><br>All these various discussions,<br>Widely relied upon,<br>Ascetics and brahmins,<br>Depend on and rely on them.<br>When they come to the Tathāgata,<br>They no longer exist,<br>The discussions that were spoken;<br>They tremble, they fear.<br><br>One who conquers all,<br>Who turns the wheel of Dhamma,<br>Out of compassion for all,<br>For all living beings.<br>For such a one,<br>Foremost among devas and humans,<br>All beings pay homage,<br>One who has overcome existence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.8" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the person who dwells in darkness heading toward light? Here, bhikkhus, a person is born into a low family — a scavenger's family, a hunter's family, a basket-maker's family, a bamboo-worker's family, a trapper's family, a cart-maker's family, or a sweeper's family — a poor family with little food and drink, where livelihood is hard, where food and clothing are hard to find. And he is ugly, unsightly, deformed, ill, blind in one eye, crooked-limbed, lame, or half-paralyzed; he does not obtain food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, or lamps. He dwells doing good bodily actions, good verbal actions, good mental actions. Having done so, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who dwells in darkness heading toward light.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.85" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the person who dwells in light heading toward darkness? Here, bhikkhus, a person is born into a high family — a wealthy noble family, a wealthy brahmin family, or a wealthy householder family — rich, with great wealth and property, with much gold and silver, many possessions and means of subsistence, much money and grain. And he is handsome, pleasant, lovely, with excellent complexion, beautiful. And he obtains food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, lamps. He does evil bodily actions, evil verbal actions, evil mental actions. Having done so, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who dwells in light heading toward darkness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.85" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if one would rightly speak of a refined ascetic among ascetics, then, bhikkhus, one would rightly speak of me as a refined ascetic among ascetics. Bhikkhus, I am often asked to accept robes, rarely am I not asked; often asked to accept almsfood, rarely not asked; often asked to accept lodging, rarely not asked; often asked to accept medicinal requisites, rarely not asked. I live with whatever bhikkhus, and they behave towards me with much bodily action that is pleasing, little that is unpleasing; with much verbal action that is pleasing, little that is unpleasing; with much mental action that is pleasing, little that is unpleasing; they assist me with much assistance that is pleasing, little that is unpleasing. Whatever feelings arise — arising from bile, phlegm, wind, from the combination of humors, from change of weather, from rough treatment, from external assault, or as result of kamma — those feelings do not arise often in me. I have few illnesses. Regarding the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, I obtain them without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. By the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, I realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Bhikkhus, if one would rightly speak of a refined ascetic among ascetics, then, bhikkhus, one would rightly speak of me as a refined ascetic among ascetics.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.87" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four kinds of persons exist and are found in the world. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a person has attained internal serenity of mind but not the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. Here, bhikkhus, a person has attained the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena but not internal serenity of mind. Here, bhikkhus, a person has attained neither internal serenity of mind nor the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. Here, bhikkhus, a person has attained both internal serenity of mind and the higher wisdom of insight into phenomena. Bhikkhus, these four kinds of persons exist and are found in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.92", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.92" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the person who practices for his own benefit and for the benefit of others? Here, bhikkhus, a person practices the subduing of greed for himself and encourages others to subdue greed; practices the subduing of hatred for himself and encourages others to subdue hatred; practices the subduing of delusion for himself and encourages others to subdue delusion. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who practices for his own benefit and for the benefit of others.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.96" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, without reverence and respect, cannot grow, increase, or expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. What five? Without faith, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, without reverence and respect, cannot grow, increase, or expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. Without moral shame, bhikkhus... without moral dread... lazy... of evil wisdom, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, without reverence and respect, cannot grow, increase, or expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, without reverence and respect, cannot grow, increase, or expand in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.10" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with reverence and respect, can grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. What five? With faith, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with reverence and respect, can grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. With moral shame, bhikkhus... with moral dread... energetic... with wisdom, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with reverence and respect, can grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, with reverence and respect, can grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.10" },

{ text: `- To what extent, Bhante, does the community of bhikkhus dwell at peace?<br>- Ānanda, when a bhikkhu himself is accomplished in virtue and does not trouble others regarding the higher virtue. To that extent, Ānanda, does the community of bhikkhus dwell at peace.<br>- Bhante, is there another way of exposition by which the community of bhikkhus dwells at peace?<br>- There could be, Ānanda. Ānanda, when a bhikkhu is accomplished in virtue and does not trouble others regarding the higher virtue, and he examines himself, not examining others. To that extent, Ānanda, does the community of bhikkhus dwell at peace.<br>- Bhante, is there another way of exposition by which the community of bhikkhus dwells at peace?<br>- There could be, Ānanda. Ānanda, when a bhikkhu is accomplished in virtue and does not trouble others regarding the higher virtue; he examines himself, not examining others; he has not become famous, and he does not feel distressed at not being famous. To that extent, Ānanda, does the community of bhikkhus dwell at peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.106" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of gifts from all quarters. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned; those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, remembers, has memorized by repeated recitation, investigates with the mind, and has well penetrated by right view. He is content with the basic necessities: robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicinal requisites. Regarding the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, he obtains them without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. By the destruction of the taints, he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of gifts from all quarters.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.109" },

{ text: `Ānanda, those bhikkhus who are newly ordained, who have gone forth recently and have newly come to this Dhamma and Discipline — they, Ānanda, should indeed be encouraged, established, and settled in five things. What five? 'Come, venerable sirs, you should observe the precepts, live restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertake and train in the training rules.' Thus they should be encouraged, established, and settled in the restraint of the Pātimokkha. 'Come, venerable sirs, you should live with guarded sense faculties, possessing mindfulness protection, with mindfulness and clear comprehension, with mind well-guarded, with mind protected by mindfulness.' Thus they should be encouraged, established, and settled in sense restraint. 'Come, venerable sirs, speak little, restrict your speech.' Thus they should be encouraged, established, and settled in restriction of speech. 'Come, venerable sirs, be forest-dwellers, use remote forest and mountain dwellings.' Thus they should be encouraged, established, and settled in physical seclusion. 'Come, venerable sirs, have right view, possess right view.' Thus they should be encouraged, established, and settled in right view.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.114" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if these five things do not leave a sick person, then it is to be expected of him: before long, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, he will realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating foulness in the body, with perception of disgust for food, with perception of non-delight in the entire world, contemplating impermanence in all conditioned things, and with the perception of death well established internally. Bhikkhus, if these five things do not leave a sick person, then it is to be expected of him: before long, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, he will realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.121" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, do not promote longevity. What five? Doing unsuitable work, not knowing moderation in suitable work, eating indigestible food, immoral conduct, and evil friends. These five things, bhikkhus, do not promote longevity. These five things, bhikkhus, promote longevity. What five? Doing suitable work, knowing moderation in suitable work, eating digestible food, virtuous conduct, and good friends. These five things, bhikkhus, promote longevity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.126", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.126" },

{ text: `Bhikkhu, the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, as the righteous Dhamma-King, relying on Dhamma, honoring Dhamma, respecting Dhamma, venerating Dhamma, having Dhamma as his banner, having Dhamma as his flag, having Dhamma as his supremacy, establishes proper protection, shelter, and restraint among the bhikkhus, among the bhikkhunīs, among the male lay followers, among the female lay followers: 'Such bodily action should be practiced, such bodily action should not be practiced; such verbal action should be practiced, such verbal action should not be practiced; such mental action should be practiced, such mental action should not be practiced; such livelihood should be practiced, such livelihood should not be practiced; such village or town should be approached, such village or town should not be approached.' Having established proper protection, shelter, and restraint among the bhikkhus, among the bhikkhunīs, among the male lay followers, among the female lay followers, the Tathāgata sets in motion the unsurpassed wheel of Dhamma by means of Dhamma; that wheel cannot be turned back by any ascetic or brahmin, deva or Māra or Brahmā, or anyone in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.133", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.133" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhu, the Wheel-turning Monarch, as the righteous Dhamma-King, relying on Dhamma, honoring Dhamma, respecting Dhamma, venerating Dhamma, having Dhamma as his banner, having Dhamma as his flag, having Dhamma as his supremacy, establishes proper protection, shelter, and restraint for the people in his realm. Furthermore, bhikkhu, the Wheel-turning Monarch, as the righteous Dhamma-King, relying on Dhamma, honoring Dhamma, respecting Dhamma, venerating Dhamma, having Dhamma as his banner, having Dhamma as his flag, having Dhamma as his supremacy, establishes proper protection, shelter, and restraint for the nobles, the attendants, the army, the brahmins and householders, the people of towns and countryside, the ascetics and brahmins, and for the beasts and birds. Thus, bhikkhu, that Wheel-turning Monarch, the righteous Dhamma-King, having established proper protection, shelter, and restraint for the people in his realm, and proper protection, shelter, and restraint for the nobles, attendants, army, brahmins and householders, people of towns and countryside, ascetics and brahmins, beasts and birds, sets the wheel in motion by means of Dhamma; that wheel cannot be turned back by any human hand, even by an enemy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.133", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.133" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, possessing five qualities, a bhikkhu may place his hope in the destruction of the taints. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'I have faith in the Tathāgata's enlightenment: "This is the Blessed One, the Arahant... the Buddha, the Blessed One." Why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I have few illnesses, few afflictions, good digestion, not too cold, not too hot, moderate, suitable for exertion. Why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I am not deceitful, not fraudulent; I reveal myself as I truly am to the Teacher, to the wise, or to my fellow celibates. Why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I dwell energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I have wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates the arising and passing away of phenomena, possessing the noble penetration leading to the complete destruction of suffering. Why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints?' Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu may place his hope in the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.135", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.135" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing five qualities may place his hope in the destruction of the taints. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu reflects thus: 'I am virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, I undertake and train in wholesome states; why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I am learned, preserving what I have learned, accumulating what I have learned. Regarding those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings I have learned much, remembered, memorized by recitation, investigated with the mind, and well penetrated by right view; why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I have well established my mind in the four establishments of mindfulness; why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I dwell energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states; why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints? I am wise, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, with the noble penetration leading to the end of suffering; why should I not place my hope in the destruction of the taints?' Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu may place his hope in the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.136" },

{ text: `Possessing five factors, bhikkhus, a royal elephant eats much food, occupies much space, scatters excrement, and receives a food token, yet is still called a royal elephant. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a royal elephant cannot endure forms, cannot endure sounds, cannot endure odors, cannot endure tastes, cannot endure touches. So too, bhikkhus, possessing five qualities, a bhikkhu eats much food, occupies much space, overturns his bed, and receives a food token, yet is still considered just a bhikkhu. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu cannot endure forms, cannot endure sounds, cannot endure odors, cannot endure tastes, cannot endure touches. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu eats much food, occupies much space, overturns his bed, and receives a food token; he is called merely a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.138", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.138" },


{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the person who, after giving, despises? Here, bhikkhus, a person gives others the basic necessities such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. He thinks: 'I am the giver; this person is the receiver.' After giving, he despises (the receiver). Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who, after giving, despises. And, bhikkhus, what is the person who, after living together, despises? Here, bhikkhus, a person lives together with another for two or three years. Because of living with that person, he despises that person. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who, after living together, despises. And, bhikkhus, what is the person with a mouth that swallows everything? Here, bhikkhus, when a person hears others praised or criticized, he quickly becomes excited and delighted. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person with a mouth that swallows everything. And, bhikkhus, what is the person who is not steadfast? Here, bhikkhus, a person has little faith, little devotion, little affection, little serene confidence. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who is not steadfast. And, bhikkhus, what is the person who is dull and foolish? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not know wholesome and unwholesome states, does not know blameworthy and blameless states, does not know inferior and superior states, does not know the states that are dark and bright. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who is dull and foolish. These five kinds of persons, bhikkhus, exist and are found in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.141", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.141" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, for what benefit should a bhikkhu dwell with the perception of disgust toward what is not disgusting? Thinking: 'May greed not arise in me regarding desirable states.' For this benefit, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell with the perception of disgust toward what is not disgusting. And, bhikkhus, for what benefit should a bhikkhu dwell with the perception of non-disgust toward what is disgusting? Thinking: 'May hatred not arise in me regarding hateful states.' For this benefit, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should dwell with the perception of non-disgust toward what is disgusting. And, bhikkhus, for what benefit should a bhikkhu, having abandoned both the non-disgusting and the disgusting, dwell equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending? Thinking: 'Whatever it is, wherever and however it is, may greed not arise in me regarding desirable states; may hatred not arise in me regarding hateful states; may delusion not arise in me regarding states that could cause delusion.' For this benefit, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, having abandoned both the non-disgusting and the disgusting, dwells equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.144", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.144" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, lead to decline for a bhikkhu who has attained temporary liberation. What five? Delight in work (physical activity), delight in talking, delight in sleeping, lack of sense restraint, and not knowing moderation in eating. These five things, bhikkhus, lead to decline for a bhikkhu who has attained temporary liberation. These five things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a bhikkhu who has attained temporary liberation. What five? Not delighting in work, not delighting in talking, not delighting in sleeping, sense restraint, and knowing moderation in eating. These five things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a bhikkhu who has attained temporary liberation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.150", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.150" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What five? Disparaging the discourse, disparaging the speaker, disparaging himself, listening to the Dhamma with a distracted mind, not one-pointed, and not attending wisely. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma can enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What five? Not disparaging the discourse, not disparaging the speaker, not disparaging himself, listening to the Dhamma with a mind not distracted, one-pointed, and attending wisely. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma can enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.151", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.151" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What five? Listening to the Dhamma with a critical mind, obsessed with criticism; listening with a mind seeking faults, looking for defects; while the Dhamma is being taught, his mind is stunned and hardened; he has evil wisdom; he is dull, deaf, and not attending with understanding to matters he does not understand. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma can enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What five? Listening to the Dhamma without a critical mind, not obsessed with criticism; listening without a mind seeking faults, not looking for defects; while the Dhamma is being taught, his mind is not stunned or hardened; he has wisdom; he is not dull or deaf, attending with understanding to matters he does not understand. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a person listening to the good Dhamma can enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.153", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.153" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, lead to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. What five? Here, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus do not learn — the discourses, mixed prose and verse, expositions, verses, inspired utterances, quotations, birth stories, marvelous accounts, or explanations, or the expanded texts. This is the first thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus do not teach the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the second thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus do not cause others to teach the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the third thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus do not recite the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the fourth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus do not with applied and sustained thought, with their minds contemplating the Dhamma as they have heard and learned. This is the fifth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. These five things, bhikkhus, lead to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.155", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.155" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, lead to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. What five? Here, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus learn — the discourses, mixed prose and verse, expositions, verses, inspired utterances, quotations, birth stories, marvelous accounts, or explanations, or the expanded texts. This is the first thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus teach the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the second thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus cause others to teach the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the third thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus recite the Dhamma extensively as they have heard and learned. This is the fourth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus with applied and sustained thought, with their minds contemplating the Dhamma as they have heard and learned. This is the fifth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance. These five things, bhikkhus, lead to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.155", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.155" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus learn the scriptures that are wrongly held, with misplaced words and phrases. Bhikkhus, when words and phrases are misplaced, the meaning is wrongly interpreted. This is the first thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the bhikkhus are difficult to speak to, possessing qualities that make them difficult to admonish, difficult to endure, not respectfully accepting instruction. This is the second thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the learned bhikkhus who are the bearers of the tradition, the bearers of the Dhamma, the bearers of the Discipline, the bearers of the summaries, are not careful in having others teach the Dhamma. Because of this, the discourses are cut off at the root, no longer serving as a refuge. This is the third thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.156" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, the elder bhikkhus live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. And the later generations follow their view. They too become those who live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, and will not make an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. This is the fourth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the Saṅgha becomes divided. When the Saṅgha is divided, bhikkhus, there is mutual abuse, mutual quarreling, mutual censure, mutual expulsion. Those who have no faith do not gain faith, and those who have faith may change. This is the fifth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the confusion and disappearance of the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.156" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, the Saṅgha is united, rejoicing, without dispute, with a single teaching, dwelling peacefully. When the Saṅgha is united, bhikkhus, there is no mutual abuse, no mutual quarreling, no mutual censure, no mutual expulsion. Those who have no faith gain faith, and those who have faith do not change. This is the fifth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.156" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, the elder bhikkhus do not live in abundance, are not lazy, abandon the burden of decline, lead in the life of seclusion, make an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. And the later generations follow their view. This is the fourth thing, bhikkhus, that leads to the establishment of the good Dhamma, to non-confusion and non-disappearance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.156" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, why is speaking about faith to a faithless person considered a wrong discourse? A faithless person, bhikkhus, when spoken to about faith, becomes irritated, angry, hostile, loses composure, and displays irritation, hatred, and displeasure. Why is that? Because he does not see in himself the possession of faith, therefore he has no joy or delight. Therefore, speaking about faith to a faithless person is a wrong discourse. And, bhikkhus, why is speaking about virtue to an immoral person considered a wrong discourse? An immoral person, bhikkhus, when spoken to about virtue, becomes irritated, angry... Why is that? Because he does not see in himself the possession of virtue, therefore he has no joy or delight. Therefore, speaking about virtue to an immoral person is a wrong discourse.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.157", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.157" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu falls into fear. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has no faith, is immoral, has little learning, is lazy, and has evil wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu falls into fear. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fearless. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has faith, is virtuous, learned, energetic, and has wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fearless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.158", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.158" },

{ text: `There are these five ways of removing resentment, bhikkhus, by which any resentment that arises in a bhikkhu should be fully removed. What five? Toward whomever resentment arises, loving-kindness should be developed toward that person. Thus resentment toward that person should be removed. Toward whomever resentment arises, compassion should be developed toward that person. Thus resentment toward that person should be removed. Toward whomever resentment arises, equanimity should be developed toward that person. Thus resentment toward that person should be removed. Toward whomever resentment arises, non-attention and non-reflection should be practiced regarding that person. Thus resentment toward that person should be removed. Toward whomever resentment arises, the fact of one's own kamma should be established: 'The venerable one is the owner of his kamma, heir to his kamma, born of his kamma, related to his kamma, supported by his kamma. Whatever kamma he does, whether good or evil, he will be the heir of that kamma.' Thus resentment toward that person should be removed. These, bhikkhus, are the five ways of removing resentment by which any resentment that arises in a bhikkhu should be fully removed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.161", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.161" },

{ text: `Just as, venerable sirs, a person who is sick, suffering, gravely ill, walking along the road, with a village far ahead and a village far behind. He does not obtain suitable food, suitable medicine, suitable assistance, or a guide to take him to the end of the village. Another person walking along the road sees him. That person arouses love, compassion, and pity for him: 'Oh, may this person obtain suitable food, suitable medicine, suitable assistance, and a guide to take him to the end of the village. Why is that? So that he may not perish or die here.' So too, venerable sirs, for a person whose bodily conduct is impure, verbal conduct impure, and whose mind is occasionally not expansive and serene, one should arouse love, compassion, and pity: 'Oh, may this venerable one, having abandoned evil bodily action, cultivate good bodily action; having abandoned evil verbal action, cultivate good verbal action; having abandoned evil mental action, cultivate good mental action. Why is that? So that after death, with the breakup of the body, he may not be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.' Thus resentment toward that person should be removed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.162", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.162" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is an exemplar for his fellow celibates. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu himself possesses virtue and answers questions pertaining to the topic of virtue; himself possesses concentration and answers questions pertaining to the topic of concentration; himself possesses wisdom and answers questions pertaining to the topic of wisdom; himself possesses liberation and answers questions pertaining to the topic of liberation; himself possesses the knowledge and vision of liberation and answers questions pertaining to the topic of the knowledge and vision of liberation. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is capable of conversing with his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.164" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, whatever question one asks another, all fall within these five cases, or one of them. What five? Out of dullness and foolishness, one asks another a question; out of evil desire and greed, one asks another a question; out of contempt, one asks another a question; with a desire to know, one asks another a question; with a doubtful mind, one asks another a question, thinking: 'If, by my asking, he answers correctly, then that is good; but if, by my asking, he answers incorrectly, then I will answer correctly for him.' Venerable sirs, whatever question one asks another, all fall within these five cases, or one of them. Venerable sirs, I ask others a question with this mind: 'If, by my asking, he answers correctly, then that is good; if I ask and he answers incorrectly, then I will answer correctly.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.165", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.165" },

{ text: `Just as, venerable sirs, a tree with its branches and leaves destroyed: then its shoots do not reach completeness, its bark does not reach completeness, its sapwood does not reach completeness, its heartwood does not reach completeness. So too, venerable sirs, for an immoral person, one of broken virtue, right concentration is thereby destroyed. When right concentration is absent, for one whose right concentration is destroyed, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is thereby destroyed. When true knowledge and vision is absent, for one whose true knowledge and vision is destroyed, disenchantment and dispassion are thereby destroyed. When disenchantment and dispassion are absent, for one whose disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed, the knowledge and vision of liberation is thereby destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.168", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.168" },

{ text: `In terms of internal factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great harm as laziness. Laziness, bhikkhus, causes great harm. In terms of internal factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great benefit as energy. Energy, bhikkhus, causes great benefit. In terms of internal factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great harm as great desire... few desires... discontent... contentment... unwise attention... wise attention... lack of clear comprehension... clear comprehension. In terms of external factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great harm as bad friendship. Bad friendship, bhikkhus, causes great harm. In terms of external factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great benefit as good friendship. Good friendship, bhikkhus, causes great benefit. In terms of internal factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great harm as adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states. Adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states, bhikkhus, causes great harm. In terms of internal factors, bhikkhus, I do not see any other single factor causing such great benefit as adherence to wholesome states and non-adherence to unwholesome states. Adherence to wholesome states and non-adherence to unwholesome states, bhikkhus, causes great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.100-113" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that causes unarisen restlessness and remorse to arise or arisen restlessness and remorse to increase and expand, as an unpeaceful mind. For one with an unpeaceful mind, bhikkhus, unarisen restlessness and remorse arise and arisen restlessness and remorse increase and expand.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.14" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as a mind that is developed. A developed mind, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.24" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that brings such suffering as a mind that is not developed and not cultivated. An undeveloped, uncultivated mind, bhikkhus, brings suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.29" },

{ text: `This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that a person who has done evil bodily actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. This is impossible. It is possible, bhikkhus, that a person who has done evil bodily actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. This is possible. This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that a person who has done evil verbal actions... evil mental actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. This is impossible. It is possible, bhikkhus, that a person who has done evil bodily actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. This is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.290", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.290" },

{ text: `This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that a person who has done good bodily actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. This is impossible. It is possible, bhikkhus, that a person who has done good bodily actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. This is possible. This is impossible, bhikkhus, it cannot happen: that a person who has done good verbal actions... good mental actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. This is impossible. It is possible, bhikkhus, that a person who has done good verbal actions... good mental actions, by reason thereof, after death, with the breakup of the body, could be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. This is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.293", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.293" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that brings such happiness as a mind that is developed and cultivated. A developed and cultivated mind, bhikkhus, brings happiness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.30" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen right view arises and arisen right view increases, as wise attention. By wise attention, bhikkhus, unarisen right view arises and arisen right view increases.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.311", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.311" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a neem seed, or a kosātaki seed, or a bitter gourd seed, planted in moist soil — whatever taste it draws from the earth, whatever taste it draws from the water, all that taste leads to bitterness, acridity, and unpleasantness. Why is that? Because the seed is evil, bhikkhus. So too, bhikkhus, whatever bodily actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with wrong view, whatever verbal actions... whatever mental actions are fully undertaken and accepted in accordance with wrong view, whatever intentions, decisions, aspirations, and whatever volitional activities — all those states lead to the undesirable, the unpleasant, the disagreeable, to harm and suffering. Why is that? Because the view is evil, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.314", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.314" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as an unguarded mind. An unguarded mind, bhikkhus, leads to great harm.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.33" },

{ text: `Just as in this Jambudīpa, there are few pleasant parks, pleasant forests, pleasant lands, pleasant lakes and ponds, while there are many rough, uneven places, difficult rivers to cross, places dense with stumps and thorns, rugged mountains. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings reborn on dry land, while many are the beings reborn in water. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings reborn among humans, while many are the beings reborn outside of humanity. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings reborn in the central countries, while many are the beings reborn in the borderlands among uncivilized people who are uneducated. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who are wise, quick-minded, not deaf, not dumb, capable of discerning the meaning of well-spoken and poorly spoken words, while many are the beings of evil wisdom, slow-minded, deaf and dumb, incapable of discerning the meaning of well-spoken and poorly spoken words. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who possess the noble eye of wisdom, while many are the beings who are immersed in ignorance and delusion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.333" },

{ text: `Just as in this Jambudīpa, there are few pleasant parks, pleasant forests, pleasant lands, pleasant lakes and ponds, while there are many rough, uneven places, difficult rivers to cross, places dense with stumps and thorns, rugged mountains. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings reborn on dry land, while many are the beings reborn in water. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who hear the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, while many are the beings who do not hear the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who, having heard, remember the Dhamma, while many are the beings who, having heard, do not remember the Dhamma. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who examine the meaning of the teachings they have memorized, while many are the beings who do not examine the meaning of the teachings they have memorized. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who, having understood the meaning, having understood the Dhamma, practice in accordance with the Dhamma and the practice in conformity with the Dhamma, while many are the beings who, having understood the meaning, having understood the Dhamma, do not practice in accordance with the Dhamma and the practice in conformity with the Dhamma. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who are stirred by matters that are stirring, while many are the beings who are not stirred by matters that are stirring. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who, being stirred, strive wisely, while many are the beings who, being stirred, do not strive wisely. So too, bhikkhus, few are the beings who, having abandoned the object of reflection, gain concentration, gain one-pointedness of mind, while many are the beings who, having abandoned the object of reflection, do not gain concentration, do not gain one-pointedness of mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.333" },

{ text: `Truly, this is one of the benefits, bhikkhus, namely dwelling in the forest... going for alms... wearing dust-heap robes... using only three robes... teaching the Dhamma... being learned in the Discipline... knowing much about the truth... being an elder for a long time... having proper demeanor... having a following... being surrounded by a great assembly... coming from a good family... having a handsome appearance... having pleasant speech... having few desires... being without illness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.378", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.378" },

{ text: `If only for the duration of a finger-snap, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops the first jhāna, then that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called 'one who dwells in jhāna not in vain, who follows the Teacher's instruction, who follows his advice, who does not eat the country's almsfood in vain.' What to say of one who cultivates that jhāna thoroughly?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.394", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.394" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as a mind that is tamed, guarded, restrained, and protected. A tamed, guarded, restrained, and protected mind, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as the awns of wheat or the awns of barley, when rightly directed, pressed by hand or foot, can pierce the hand or foot or draw blood — this is possible. Why is that? Because the awns are rightly directed. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu whose mind is rightly directed can pierce ignorance, arouse true knowledge, and realize Nibbāna — this is possible. Why is that? Because the mind is rightly directed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.42" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a lake that is foul, stirred up, muddy. A person with good eyes standing on the bank cannot see the oysters, the shells, the gravel, the pebbles, the schools of fish moving about and resting. Why is that? Because the water is stirred up. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with a stirred-up mind cannot know his own benefit, cannot know the benefit of others, cannot know the benefit of both, cannot realize a superior human state, the truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision — this is impossible. Why is that? Because the mind is stirred up, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.45" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a lake that is clear, bright, not stirred up. A person with good eyes standing on the bank can see the oysters, the shells, the gravel, the pebbles, the schools of fish moving about and resting. Why is that? Because the water is not stirred up, bhikkhus. So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with a mind not stirred up can know his own benefit, can know the benefit of others, can know the benefit of both, can realize a superior human state, the truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision — this is possible. Why is that? Because the mind is not stirred up, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.46" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that changes so quickly as the mind. It is not easy, bhikkhus, to give a simile for how quickly the mind changes.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.48" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single form, bhikkhus, that so captivates and dominates a man's mind as the form of a woman. The form of a woman, bhikkhus, captivates and dominates a man's mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.5" },

{ text: `This mind, bhikkhus, is luminous. But it is defiled by adventitious defilements. The uninstructed ordinary person does not understand that as it really is. Therefore, I say that the mind of the uninstructed ordinary person is not developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.51" },

{ text: `If only for the duration of a finger-snap, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu develops a mind of loving-kindness; that bhikkhu, bhikkhus, is called 'one who dwells in jhāna not in vain, who follows the Teacher's instruction, who follows his advice, who does not eat the country's almsfood in vain.' What to say of one who cultivates that loving-kindness thoroughly?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.54" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, one who pervades the great ocean with his mind includes all the small rivers that flow into the ocean. So too, bhikkhus, one who develops and cultivates mindfulness of the body includes all wholesome states that are part of true knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.575", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.575" },

{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to great inspiration, great benefit, great security from bondage, to mindfulness and clear comprehension, to the attainment of knowledge and vision, to a pleasant abiding in this very life, to the realization of the fruits of knowledge and liberation. What is that one thing? It is mindfulness of the body. This one thing, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, leads to great inspiration... to the realization of the fruits of knowledge and liberation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.576", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.576" },

{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to tranquility of body, tranquility of mind, the calming of applied and sustained thought, and the complete development and perfection of all states pertaining to true knowledge. What is that one thing? It is mindfulness of the body. When this one thing is developed and cultivated, body becomes tranquil, mind becomes tranquil, applied and sustained thought are calmed, and all states pertaining to true knowledge reach development and perfection.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.583", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.583" },

{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, prevents unarisen unwholesome states from arising and causes arisen unwholesome states to be abandoned. What is that one thing? It is mindfulness of the body. When this one thing is developed and cultivated, unarisen unwholesome states do not arise, and arisen unwholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.584", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.584" },

{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, causes unarisen wholesome states to arise and leads to the growth and expansion of arisen wholesome states. What is that one thing? It is mindfulness of the body. When this one thing is developed and cultivated, unarisen wholesome states arise... and arisen wholesome states lead to growth and expansion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.585", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.585" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states are abandoned, as heedfulness. For a heedful person, bhikkhus, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.59" },

{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, that, when developed and cultivated, leads to the attainment of wisdom, to the growth of wisdom, to the expansion of wisdom, to great wisdom, to widespread wisdom, to abundant wisdom, to profound wisdom, to unequaled wisdom, to boundless wisdom, to manifold wisdom, to quick wisdom, to light wisdom, to joyful wisdom, to swift wisdom, to sharp wisdom, to penetrative wisdom. What is that one thing? It is mindfulness of the body. When this one thing is developed and cultivated, it leads to the attainment of wisdom... to penetrative wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.596", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.596" },

{ text: `Those who do not develop mindfulness of the body, bhikkhus, do not partake of the Deathless. Those who develop mindfulness of the body, bhikkhus, partake of the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.616", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.616" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned, as great desire. For one with great desire, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.62" },

{ text: `The Deathless is not realized, bhikkhus, by those who do not realize mindfulness of the body. The Deathless is realized, bhikkhus, by those who realize mindfulness of the body.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.627", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.627" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned, as unwise attention. For one with unwise attention, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.66" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned, as lack of clear comprehension. For one without clear comprehension, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.68" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned, as adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states. Due to adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states, bhikkhus, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states are abandoned.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.72" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, by which unarisen factors of enlightenment arise and arisen factors of enlightenment come to full development, as wise attention. By wise attention, bhikkhus, unarisen factors of enlightenment arise and arisen factors of enlightenment come to development and perfection.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.75" },

{ text: `Of little value, bhikkhus, are these kinds of growth, such as growth in wealth. This is the foremost among kinds of growth, bhikkhus, namely growth in wisdom. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will achieve growth in wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.79" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as heedlessness. Heedlessness, bhikkhus, leads to great harm.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.82" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as heedfulness. Heedfulness, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.83" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as laziness. Laziness, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as energy. Energy, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as great desire. Great desire, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as few desires. Few desires, bhikkhus, lead to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.84" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as discontentment. Discontentment, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as contentment. Contentment, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as unwise attention. Unwise attention, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as wise attention. Wise attention, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as lack of clear comprehension. Lack of clear comprehension, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as clear comprehension. Clear comprehension, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.84" },

{ text: `I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as bad friendship. Bad friendship, bhikkhus, leads to great harm. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great benefit as good friendship. Good friendship, bhikkhus, leads to great benefit. I do not see any other single factor, bhikkhus, that leads to such great harm as adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states. Adherence to unwholesome states and non-adherence to wholesome states, bhikkhus, leads to great harm.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.84" },

{ text: `- Venerable sir, what is supreme among things seen? What is supreme among things heard? What is supreme among kinds of happiness? What is supreme among perceptions? What is supreme among kinds of existence?<br>- When one sees without interruption, and the taints are destroyed, that is the supreme seeing. When one hears without interruption, and the taints are destroyed, that is the supreme hearing. When one feels pleasant feeling without interruption, and the taints are destroyed, that is the supreme happiness. When one perceives without interruption, and the taints are destroyed, that is the supreme perception. When one exists without interruption, and the taints are destroyed, that is the supreme existence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.170", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.170" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a male lay follower is an outcast among lay followers, a stain among lay followers, the lowest among lay followers. What five? He has no faith; he is immoral; he predicts the future through special rituals, believes in omens, and does not believe in action (kamma); he seeks outside (the Saṅgha) for those worthy of respect; and he serves there first. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a male lay follower is an outcast among lay followers, a stain among lay followers, the lowest among lay followers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.175", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.175" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a male lay follower is a jewel among lay followers, a red lotus among lay followers, a white lotus among lay followers. What five? He has faith; he is virtuous; he does not predict the future through special rituals; he does not believe in omens; he believes in action (kamma); he does not seek outside the Saṅgha for those worthy of respect; and he serves there first. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a male lay follower is a jewel among lay followers, a red lotus among lay followers, a white lotus among lay followers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.175", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.175" },

{ text: `What do you think, bhikkhus, have you seen or heard the following: 'This person has abandoned killing living beings, refrains from killing. Then, because of abandoning killing, kings have him killed, bound, expelled, or do whatever they wish to him?' - 'No, Bhante.' - 'Good, bhikkhus. I too have not seen nor heard: 'This person has abandoned killing living beings, refrains from killing. Then, because of abandoning killing, kings have him killed, bound, expelled, or do whatever they wish to him.' But if someone speaks of that person's evil deed thus: 'This person took the life of a woman or a man.' Then kings, because of that killing, have him killed, bound, expelled, or do whatever they wish to him. Have you seen or heard such a thing?' - 'Bhante, we have seen and heard such things, and will hear of them again.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.178", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.178" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, do you know any white-robed householder whose conduct is protected by the five training rules, and who obtains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, so that, if he wishes, he can declare of himself: 'I have destroyed hell, destroyed the animal realm, destroyed the ghost realm, destroyed the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm. I am a stream-enterer, no longer subject to decline, assured of enlightenment.' Protected by which five training rules? Here, Sāriputta, a noble disciple abandons killing living beings, abandons taking what is not given, abandons sexual misconduct, abandons false speech, abandons intoxication with liquor and fermented drink. His conduct is protected by these five training rules. And which four higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, does he obtain without difficulty, without trouble, without effort? Here, Sāriputta, a noble disciple has unshakable serene confidence in the Buddha: 'The Blessed One is an Arahant, Perfectly Enlightened, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, well-gone, knower of the world, unsurpassed trainer of persons to be tamed, teacher of devas and humans, the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.' This is the first higher state of mind, a pleasant abiding in this very life, attained by purifying a mind not yet purified, by clarifying a mind not yet clarified. Furthermore, Sāriputta, a noble disciple has unshakable serene confidence in the Dhamma... Furthermore, Sāriputta, a noble disciple has unshakable serene confidence in the Saṅgha... Furthermore, Sāriputta, a noble disciple possesses the virtues loved by the noble ones, unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, conducive to well-being, leading to concentration.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.179", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.179" },

{ text: `Seeing the fear of hell,<br>Avoid evil deeds,<br>Wisely accept the true Dhamma,<br>The wise one avoids.<br><br>Do not harm living beings,<br>Those that have vitality,<br>Knowing, do not speak falsely,<br>Do not take what is not given.<br><br>Be content with one's own wife,<br>Avoid others' wives,<br>One who knows does not drink alcohol,<br>Which confuses the mind.<br><br>Recollect the Buddha,<br>Recollect the Dhamma,<br>Develop a mind without hatred,<br>Develop a mind of benefit,<br>To be worthy of birth<br>In the realm of devas.<br><br>Seeking merit and benefit,<br>Provide gifts,<br>First give to the most excellent,<br>Hoping for great results.<br><br>Sāriputta,<br>I will tell you,<br>Those most excellent ones,<br>Listen to me:<br>As in a herd of cattle,<br>There are black, white, red,<br><br>Bay or spotted,<br>Or pigeon-colored,<br>Whatever the color,<br>One may find a tame bull.<br><br>The animal that pulls with strength,<br>Beautiful, quick, and energetic,<br>Regardless of its color,<br>Is yoked to the burden.<br><br>So too, among humans,<br>Wherever they are born,<br>Nobles, brahmins,<br>Merchants or servants,<br>The casteless,<br>Or lowly scavengers.<br><br>Among such people,<br>Whoever is tamed and trained,<br>Upright, virtuous,<br>Truthful, with moral shame and dread,<br><br>Birth and death destroyed,<br>The holy life fulfilled,<br>The burden laid down,<br>No longer bound,<br>What should be done has been done,<br>No more taints.<br><br>Gone to the further shore,<br>Non-attached, peaceful,<br>That field of merit, undefiled,<br>Of great fruit, worthy of offerings.<br><br>Fools who do not know,<br>Lacking wisdom, little learned,<br>Give only externally,<br>Do not approach the good.<br><br>Those who approach the good,<br>Wise, revering the noble ones,<br>They trust the Well-Gone One,<br>Established at the root.<br><br>Born in heaven or here,<br>Reborn in a good family,<br>The wise, progressing step by step,<br>Attain the state of Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.179", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.179" },

{ text: `- Venerable sir, just as a person who has been satisfied with the highest sweetness no longer craves other inferior sweets. So too, venerable sir, having heard the Dhamma of Venerable Gotama, one no longer craves the theories of others, of inferior ascetics and brahmins. Just as, venerable sir, a person who is faint with hunger and fatigue finds a honey cake. With every morsel he tastes, with every morsel he experiences pure sweetness. So too, venerable sir, having heard the Dhamma of Venerable Gotama, he gains joy and serene confidence. Just as, venerable sir, a person finds a sandalwood branch, whether yellow sandalwood or red sandalwood. Wherever he smells it — from the root, the middle, or the tip — he experiences a pure, sublime fragrance. So too, venerable sir, having heard the Dhamma of Venerable Gotama, he experiences delight, experiences joy. Just as, venerable sir, a person who is sick, suffering, gravely ill, and then a physician immediately cures his illness. So too, venerable sir, having heard the Dhamma of Venerable Gotama, then sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are destroyed. Just as, venerable sir, a lotus pond with clear water, sweet water, cool water, limpid water, with well-arranged, beautiful banks. Then a person comes, afflicted by heat, oppressed by heat, tired, thirsty, craving water. After plunging into that lotus pond, after bathing and drinking, all his suffering, tiredness, and fever are appeased. So too, venerable sir, having heard the Dhamma of Venerable Gotama, then all suffering, tiredness, and fever are stilled.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.194", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.194" },

{ text: `Licchavis, the appearance of five treasures is hard to find in the world. What five? The appearance of a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One is hard to find in the world. One who can teach the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is hard to find in the world. One who understands the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is hard to find in the world. One who practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, having understood the exposition of the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, is hard to find in the world. One who is grateful and thankful is hard to find in the world. Licchavis, the appearance of these five treasures is hard to find in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.195", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.195" },

{ text: `Possessing five factors, bhikkhus, speech is well-spoken, not ill-spoken, blameless, and not criticized by the wise. What five? Speaking at the right time, speaking what is true, speaking gently, speaking what is beneficial, speaking with a mind of loving-kindness. Possessing these five factors, bhikkhus, speech is well-spoken, not ill-spoken, blameless, and not criticized by the wise.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.198", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.198" },

{ text: `When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, then by five cases, that family gains much merit. What five? When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, upon seeing them the people gain serene confidence in their minds. This, bhikkhus, leads to heaven, and at that time that family has entered upon that path. When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, the people rise up, pay homage to them, and invite them to sit. This, bhikkhus, leads to being reborn in high families, and at that time that family has entered upon that path. When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, the people abandon the stain of miserliness. This, bhikkhus, leads to great influence, and at that time that family has entered upon that path. When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, the people share according to their ability and according to their means. This, bhikkhus, leads to great wealth, and at that time that family has entered upon that path. When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, the people ask questions, inquire, and listen to the Dhamma. This, bhikkhus, leads to great wisdom, and at that time that family has entered upon that path. When, bhikkhus, virtuous renunciants come to a family, then by these five cases, that family gains much merit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.199", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.199" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is the near shore and what is the far shore? Wrong view, bhikkhus, is the near shore; right view is the far shore... Wrong liberation is the near shore; right liberation is the far shore. This, bhikkhus, is the near shore; this is the far shore.<br><br>Few among humans<br>Reach the far shore,<br>While the rest of people<br>Run along this shore.<br><br>Those who practice the Dhamma<br>According to the well-taught teaching,<br>Will reach the far shore,<br>Crossing the realm of death so hard to cross.<br><br>The wise, abandoning dark states,<br>Develop bright states,<br>Leaving home for homelessness,<br>In seclusion, hard to delight in.<br><br>Seek delight in Nibbāna,<br>Abandon sensual pleasures, have no obstructions,<br>The wise cleanse themselves<br>Of defilements from within.<br><br>Those with right mind,<br>Well develop the factors of enlightenment,<br>Abandon all attachments,<br>Rejoicing, not clinging,<br>Without taints, radiant,<br>They live at peace in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.118", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.118" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I will teach you the Dhamma leading to suffering and the Dhamma leading to happiness. Listen and pay close attention, I will speak... And, bhikkhus, what is the Dhamma leading to suffering? Wrong view, wrong intention, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration, wrong knowledge, wrong liberation. Thus, bhikkhus, this is the Dhamma leading to suffering. And, bhikkhus, what is the Dhamma leading to happiness? Right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration, right knowledge, right liberation. Bhikkhus, this is called the Dhamma leading to happiness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.143", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.143" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. This bhikkhu, bhikkhus, being virtuous, living restrained by the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules — this is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned. Those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, remembers, recites verbally, investigates with the mind, and penetrates well with right view. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.17" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has good friends, good companions, good associates. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is easy to speak to, possessing qualities that make him easy to admonish, patient, and well-receptive to instruction. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, for whatever duties his fellow celibates have to do, whether great or small, he is skillful and diligent, possessing the right consideration of means, able to do and to organize. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu loves the Dhamma, speaks pleasantly, rejoices greatly in the supreme Dhamma and supreme Discipline. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.17" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is content with the basic necessities: robes, almsfood, lodging, and medicinal requisites. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is mindful, possessing supreme mindfulness and recollection, remembering and recollecting what was done and said long ago. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, noble wisdom that penetrates and leads to the complete destruction of suffering. This, bhikkhus, is a quality that constitutes a guardian. Bhikkhus, dwell with a guardian, do not dwell without a guardian. Bhikkhus, suffering is for one who dwells without a guardian.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.17" },

{ text: `Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, a person should not be associated with. What ten? Killing living beings, taking what is not given, sexual misconduct, false speech, divisive speech, harsh speech, idle chatter, covetousness, ill-will, wrong view. Bhikkhus, a person possessing these ten qualities should not be associated with. Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, a person should be associated with. What ten? Abstaining from killing living beings, abstaining from taking what is not given, abstaining from sexual misconduct, abstaining from false speech, abstaining from divisive speech, abstaining from harsh speech, abstaining from idle chatter, non-covetousness, non-ill-will, right view. Bhikkhus, a person possessing these ten qualities should be associated with.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.199", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.199" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu one who has completely abandoned all searches? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has abandoned the search for sensual pleasures, has abandoned the search for existence, and the search for the holy life has been calmed. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who has completely abandoned all searches. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu whose thoughts are without defilement? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has abandoned thoughts of sensual desire, has abandoned thoughts of ill-will, has abandoned thoughts of harming. Thus, bhikkhus, are thoughts without defilement. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu whose mental activities are calmed? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, having abandoned pleasure and pain, and with the previous passing away of joy and grief, enters and dwells in the fourth jhāna, neither painful nor pleasant, with purity of mindfulness and equanimity. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu whose mental activities are calmed. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu whose mind is well liberated? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu's mind is liberated from greed, his mind is liberated from hatred, his mind is liberated from delusion. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu whose mind is well liberated. And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu with wisdom well liberated? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu knows: 'Greed has been abandoned in me, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future'; he knows: 'Hatred has been abandoned in me... unable to arise in the future'; he knows: 'Delusion has been abandoned in me, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future.' Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu with wisdom well liberated. Bhikkhus, all those noble ones in the past who lived the noble abiding, all of them lived in these ten noble abidings. All those noble ones in the future who will live the noble abiding, all of them will live in these ten noble abidings. All those noble ones in the present who live the noble abiding, all of them live in these ten noble abidings. Bhikkhus, these are the ten noble abidings in which the noble ones have lived, are living, and will live.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, the lion, the king of beasts, in the evening, comes out of his lair. After coming out, he stretches; after stretching, he looks around in all four directions; after looking around, he roars three times his lion's roar; after roaring three times, he goes out in search of prey. Why does he roar? Thinking: 'May I not cause harm to small beasts that stray off the path.' Bhikkhus, 'lion' is a designation for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Bhikkhus, when the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma in an assembly, that is the lion's roar. Bhikkhus, there are these ten Tathāgata powers of the Tathāgata, possessing which the Tathāgata claims the bull's place, roars his lion's roar in the assemblies, and sets in motion the wheel of Brahmā. What are the ten?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.21" },

{ text: `Here a person is without craving, does not covet others' property, does not think: 'Oh, may all others' property become mine!' And a person has no hateful mind, does not arouse harmful intentions or harmful thoughts, but thinks: 'May these beings live without enmity, without hostility, without trouble, happy, and care for themselves.' And has right view, without distorted thoughts, thinking: 'There is giving, there is offering, there is sacrifice; there is fruit and result of good and evil actions; there is this world, there is the next world; there is mother, there is father; there are spontaneously reborn beings; in this world there are ascetics and brahmins who have practiced rightly, who have realized and declared this world and the next by their own direct knowledge.' Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.212", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.212" },

{ text: `As one does, so one is reborn; as one is reborn, so one experiences accordingly. Thus, bhikkhus, is the arising of beings. Bhikkhus, I say that beings are the heirs of their kamma. Bhikkhus, beings are the owners of kamma, heirs of kamma, born of kamma, related to kamma, supported by kamma. Whatever kamma they do, good or evil, they will be the heirs of that kamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.216", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.216" },

{ text: `I declare, bhikkhus, that actions that have been intended, done, and accumulated, without experiencing their result, there is no end. Whether that result arises in this very life or in a subsequent life. I declare, bhikkhus, that actions that have been intended, done, and accumulated, without experiencing their result, there is no end to suffering. Just as, bhikkhus, a perfectly round gem, thrown upwards, falls and becomes well-established wherever it lands. So too, bhikkhus, due to unwholesome intentions, the threefold fault of bodily action, beings, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Or, bhikkhus, due to unwholesome intentions, the fourfold fault of verbal action... Or, bhikkhus, due to unwholesome intentions, the threefold fault of mental action... I declare, bhikkhus, that actions that have been intended, done, and accumulated, without experiencing their result, there is no end, whether that result belongs to this present life or to a subsequent life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.217", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.217" },

{ text: `A noble disciple, bhikkhus, having thus abandoned greed, abandoned hatred, abandoned delusion, clearly comprehending, mindful, dwells pervading one direction with a mind imbued with loving-kindness; likewise the second, the third, the fourth; thus above, below, across, everywhere, in all respects, he dwells pervading the entire world with a mind imbued with loving-kindness, vast, immeasurable, without hostility, without ill-will. He knows thus: 'Formerly, this mind of mine was limited and undeveloped. But now this mind of mine is immeasurable and well developed. Moreover, whatever action was done with limitation, now it will not remain within that limitation, it will not stand within that limitation.' What do you think, bhikkhus, if this child, from youth onwards, developed the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, could he do an evil action?' - 'No, Bhante.' - 'By not doing evil, would he experience suffering?' - 'No, Bhante. By not doing evil, Bhante, how could he experience suffering?' - 'Bhikkhus, this liberation of mind by loving-kindness should be developed by women and men. Bhikkhus, this body is not taken up and carried away by women or men. Bhikkhus, this path to death lies amid one's thoughts. He knows thus: 'Whatever evil action I formerly did with this body produced by kamma, all that must be experienced here; it will not follow me and arise hereafter.' Thus, bhikkhus, the liberation of mind by loving-kindness, when developed, leads to non-returning for a wise bhikkhu who has not yet penetrated to a higher liberation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.219", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.219" },

{ text: `Possessing forty qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell. What forty? He himself kills living beings, encourages others to kill, consents to killing, and praises killing; he himself takes what is not given, encourages others to take what is not given, consents to taking what is not given, and praises taking what is not given; he himself engages in sexual misconduct, encourages others to engage in sexual misconduct, consents to sexual misconduct, and praises sexual misconduct; he himself speaks falsely, encourages others to speak falsely, consents to false speech, and praises false speech; he himself speaks divisively, encourages others to speak divisively, consents to divisive speech, and praises divisive speech; he himself speaks harshly, encourages others to speak harshly, consents to harsh speech, and praises harsh speech; he himself speaks idly, encourages others to speak idly, consents to idle chatter, and praises idle chatter; he himself is covetous, encourages others to be covetous, consents to covetousness, and praises covetousness; he himself has ill-will, encourages others to have ill-will, consents to ill-will, and praises ill-will; he himself has wrong view, encourages others to have wrong view, consents to wrong view, and praises wrong view. Possessing these forty qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.224", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.224" },

{ text: `Possessing forty qualities, as such is placed in heaven. What forty? He himself abstains from killing living beings, does not encourage others to kill, does not consent to killing, and does not praise killing; he himself abstains from taking what is not given, does not encourage others to take what is not given, does not consent to taking what is not given, and does not praise taking what is not given; he himself abstains from sexual misconduct, does not encourage others to engage in sexual misconduct, does not consent to sexual misconduct, and does not praise sexual misconduct; he himself does not speak falsely, does not encourage others to speak falsely, does not consent to false speech, and does not praise false speech; he himself abstains from divisive speech, does not encourage others to speak divisively, does not consent to divisive speech, and does not praise divisive speech; he himself does not speak harshly, does not encourage others to speak harshly, does not consent to harsh speech, and does not praise harsh speech; he himself abstains from idle chatter, does not encourage others to speak idly, does not consent to idle chatter, and does not praise idle chatter; he himself is not covetous, does not encourage others to be covetous, does not consent to covetousness, and does not praise covetousness; he himself has no ill-will, does not encourage others to have ill-will, does not consent to ill-will, and does not praise ill-will; he himself has right view, encourages others to have right view, consents to right view, and praises right view. Possessing these forty qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.224", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.224" },

{ text: `For direct knowledge of craving, bhikkhus, ten things should be developed. What ten? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of non-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. For direct knowledge of greed, bhikkhus, these ten things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.237", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.237" },

{ text: `Upāli, for ten reasons are the training rules laid down for the disciples of the Tathāgata and the Pātimokkha is recited. What ten? For the excellence of the community, for the comfort of the community, for the restraint of the stubborn, for the comfortable dwelling of well-behaved bhikkhus, for the restraint of taints in this very life, for the prevention of taints in future lives, to inspire faith in those without faith, to increase faith in those with faith, for the duration of the good Dhamma, and for the support of the Discipline. For these ten reasons, Upāli, are the training rules laid down for the disciples of the Tathāgata and the Pātimokkha recited.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.31" },

{ text: `Upāli, a bhikkhu possessing ten qualities is fit to be a judge. What ten? Here, Upāli, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned. Those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, remembers, recites verbally, investigates with the mind, and has well penetrated by right view. Both Pātimokkhas are well transmitted in detail, well analyzed, well understood, well decided according to the sutta and in detail. He is well established in the Discipline, without wavering; he is capable of making both opposing parties understand, to convince them, to make them see, to reconcile them. He is skilled in the arising and settling of disputes; he knows disputes, knows the arising of disputes, knows the cessation of disputes, knows the path leading to the cessation of disputes. Possessing these ten qualities, Upāli, a bhikkhu is considered fit to be a judge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.33" },

{ text: `Possessing ten qualities, Upāli, a bhikkhu is capable of conferring the full ordination. What ten? Here, Upāli, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned. Those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, remembers, recites verbally, investigates with the mind, and has well penetrated by right view. Both Pātimokkhas are well transmitted in detail, well analyzed, well understood, well decided according to the sutta and in detail. He is capable of tending the sick or causing them to be tended. He is capable of allaying discontent or causing it to be allayed. He is capable of properly removing an offense that has arisen. He is capable of correcting a wrong view that has arisen. He is capable of encouraging in the higher virtue, capable of encouraging in the higher mind, capable of encouraging in the higher wisdom. Possessing these ten qualities, Upāli, a bhikkhu is capable of conferring the full ordination.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.34" },

{ text: `- 'Schism in the Saṅgha, schism in the Saṅgha,' Bhante, is spoken of. To what extent, Bhante, is there schism in the Saṅgha?<br>- Here, Upāli, bhikkhus explain what is not Dhamma as Dhamma, what is Dhamma as not Dhamma; what is not Discipline as Discipline, what is Discipline as not Discipline; what was not spoken, not uttered by the Tathāgata as spoken, uttered by the Tathāgata; what was spoken, uttered by the Tathāgata as not spoken, not uttered; what was not regularly practiced by the Tathāgata as regularly practiced; what was regularly practiced by the Tathāgata as not regularly practiced; what was not laid down by the Tathāgata as laid down; what was laid down by the Tathāgata as not laid down. By these ten matters, they split and separate, they perform a legal act differently, they recite the Pātimokkha differently. To that extent, Upāli, is there schism in the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.37" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, if a bhikkhu is not skilled in the modes of others' minds, then he should aspire: 'I will be skilled in the modes of my own mind.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves. And, venerable sirs, how is a bhikkhu skilled in the modes of his own mind? Just as, venerable sirs, a woman or a man, young, youthful, fond of adornment, examines the image of her or his own face in a clean, bright mirror or in a bowl of clear water. If they see any dust or blemish on the face, they strive to remove that dust or blemish. If they see no dust or blemish, they are joyful and satisfied: 'What a gain for me! I am truly clean!' So too, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu should examine thus, for great benefit in wholesome states: 'Do I dwell much with greed? Do I dwell much without greed? Do I dwell much with a hateful mind? Do I dwell much with a mind without hatred? Do I dwell much overcome by dullness and drowsiness, or do I dwell much with dullness and drowsiness abandoned? Do I dwell much with restlessness, or do I dwell much without restlessness? Do I dwell much with doubt, or do I dwell much beyond doubt? Do I dwell much with anger, or do I dwell much without anger? Do I dwell much with a defiled mind, or do I dwell much with an undefiled mind? Do I dwell much with bodily fever, or do I dwell much without bodily fever? Do I dwell much with laziness, or do I dwell much with energy and effort? Do I dwell much with an unconcentrated mind, or do I dwell much with a concentrated mind?'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.52" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, if a bhikkhu, examining thus, knows: 'I dwell much with a greedy mind; I dwell much with a hateful mind; I dwell much overcome by dullness and drowsiness; I dwell much with restlessness; I dwell much with doubt; I dwell much with anger; I dwell much with a defiled mind; I dwell much with bodily fever; I dwell much with laziness; I dwell much with an unconcentrated mind,' then that bhikkhu should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to abandon those evil unwholesome states. Just as, venerable sirs, when a cloth is on fire or the head is on fire, one should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to extinguish the burning cloth or head. So too, venerable sirs, that bhikkhu should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to abandon those evil unwholesome states. Venerable sirs, if a bhikkhu, examining thus, knows: 'I dwell much with a mind without greed; I dwell much with a mind without hatred; I dwell much with a mind without dullness and drowsiness; I dwell much with a mind without restlessness; I dwell much with a mind beyond doubt; I dwell much with a mind without anger; I dwell much with an undefiled mind; I dwell much with a body without fever; I dwell much with an energetic and striving mind; I dwell much with a concentrated mind,' then that bhikkhu, having established himself in those wholesome states, should further focus on the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.52" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, for one who has no faith in wholesome states, no moral shame... no moral dread... no energy... no wisdom... no listening... no remembering of the Dhamma... no reflection on meaning... no practice in accordance with the Dhamma... who is heedless in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, a decline in wholesome states is to be expected, not growth. Just as, venerable sirs, at the time of the waning moon, whether by day or by night, the moon wanes in color, wanes in roundness, wanes in radiance, wanes in the width of its orbit. So too, venerable sirs, for one who has no faith in wholesome states, no moral shame... no moral dread... no energy... no wisdom... no listening... no remembering of the Dhamma... no reflection on meaning... no practice in accordance with the Dhamma... who is heedless in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, a decline in wholesome states is to be expected, not growth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.68" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, for one who has faith in wholesome states, has moral shame... has moral dread... has energy... has wisdom... has listening... has remembering of the Dhamma... has reflection on meaning... has practice in accordance with the Dhamma... who is not heedless in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, growth in wholesome states is to be expected, not decline. Just as, venerable sirs, at the time of the waxing moon, whether by day or by night, the moon grows in color, grows in roundness, grows in radiance, grows in the width of its orbit. So too, venerable sirs, for one who has faith in wholesome states... who is not heedless in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, growth in wholesome states is to be expected, not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.68" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, live complete in virtue, complete in the Pātimokkha. Live restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May my fellow celibates love me, be fond of me, respect me, and follow my example,' that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in virtue, persistent, internally peaceful, without break in meditation, possessing insight practice, delighting in dwelling in secluded lodgings. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I obtain such requisites as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites,' that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in virtue... delighting in dwelling in secluded lodgings. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May my blood relatives, when they have died and passed away, recollect me with a joyful mind and thereby gain great fruit, great benefit,' that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in virtue... delighting in dwelling in secluded lodgings. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I overcome pleasure and displeasure, not letting pleasure and displeasure overcome me. May I dwell constantly overcoming whatever pleasure and displeasure arise,' that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in virtue... delighting in dwelling in secluded lodgings. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu wishes: 'May I, as I wish, without difficulty, without trouble, without effort, attain the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life,' that bhikkhu should be perfectly accomplished in virtue... delighting in dwelling in secluded lodgings. 'Bhikkhus, live complete in virtuous conduct, complete in the Pātimokkha, live restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules.' Thus it was said, and it was for this reason that it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.71" },

{ text: `With regard to true knowledge of the defilement, the purification, the emergence of attainments in jhāna, liberation, concentration, I declare that knowledge is for one who has jhāna, not for one without jhāna. Here, bhikkhus, with regard to true knowledge, the recollection of past lives, I declare that knowledge is for one who has jhāna, not for one without jhāna. With regard to true knowledge of the passing away and rebirth of beings, I declare that knowledge is for one who has jhāna. Here, bhikkhus, with regard to true knowledge of the destruction of the taints, I declare that knowledge is for one who has jhāna, not for one without jhāna. Thus, bhikkhus, concentration is the right path; lack of concentration is the wrong path.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.64" },

{ text: `A bhikkhu with faith, bhikkhus, but without virtue, is not perfect in that factor. He should perfect that factor, thinking: 'How can I have faith and also have virtue?' Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu has faith and virtue, then in that factor he is perfect. And, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu with faith and virtue but without learning... with learning but without teaching the Dhamma... He should perfect that factor, thinking: 'How can I have faith, virtue, learning, teaching the Dhamma, frequenting assemblies, teaching the Dhamma to assemblies without fear, knowing the Discipline, being a forest-dweller in remote dwellings, attaining without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, and by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom?' And, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu has faith, virtue, learning, teaches the Dhamma, frequents assemblies, teaches the Dhamma to assemblies without fear, knows the Discipline, is a forest-dweller in remote dwellings, attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life, and by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom — then in that factor he is perfect. Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu inspires universal confidence and is perfect in every way.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.8" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these ten ways of removing (overcoming) resentment. What ten? Resentment is overcome by thinking: 'He has done me harm, but what benefit would there be in thinking like that?' Resentment is overcome by thinking: 'He is doing me harm, but what benefit would there be in thinking like that?' Resentment is overcome by thinking: 'He will do me harm, but what benefit would there be in thinking like that?' Resentment is overcome by thinking: 'He has harmed someone I love, someone I like...' ... 'He is harming someone I love, someone I like...' ... 'He will harm someone I love, someone I like, but what benefit would there be in thinking like that?' Resentment is overcome by thinking: 'He has benefited someone I do not love, someone I do not like...' ... 'He is benefiting someone I do not love, someone I do not like...' ... 'He will benefit someone I do not love, someone I do not like, but what benefit would there be in thinking like that?' Not getting angry without reason. Bhikkhus, these are the ten cases for overcoming resentment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.80" },

{ text: `- Bhante, for what reason, for what condition, does the Blessed One sometimes teach the Dhamma and sometimes not teach the Dhamma?<br>- Punniya, a bhikkhu has faith, comes to pay respects, serves, asks questions, lends an ear to listen; after listening, he remembers the Dhamma; he reflects on the meaning of the Dhamma he has remembered; after knowing the meaning, after knowing the Dhamma, he practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma; he speaks well, utters well, possesses refined speech, speaks clearly explaining the meaning, and he expounds, encourages, inspires, and delights his fellow celibates. To that extent, the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma. Possessing these ten qualities, Punniya, the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma all the time.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.83" },

{ text: `Just as, venerable sirs, a friend says to his companion: 'Friend, whenever you need wealth, ask me for wealth and I will give you wealth.' That other friend, when he needs wealth, says to his friend: 'Friend, now I need wealth, give me wealth.' He replies: 'Then, friend, dig here.' The other digs there and finds nothing. He says: 'Friend, you have lied to me. Friend, you have spoken empty words to me.' He says: 'Friend, I have not lied to you. I have not spoken empty words to you. Then, friend, dig here.' The other digs there and finds nothing. He says: 'Friend, you have lied to me. Friend, you have spoken empty words to me.' He says: 'Friend, I have not lied to you. I have not spoken empty words to you, but I have gone mad, my mind is deranged.' So too, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu is boastful, exaggerating his attainments: 'I enter and emerge from the first jhāna... the second jhāna... the third jhāna... the fourth jhāna... the base of infinite space... the base of infinite consciousness... the base of nothingness... the base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception... I enter and emerge from the cessation of perception and feeling.' The Tathāgata or a disciple of the Tathāgata who is a meditator, skilled in the attainments of jhāna, skilled in the modes of others' minds, skilled in the patterns of others' minds, questions, cross-questions, and discusses with him. When he is questioned, cross-questioned, and discussed with by the Tathāgata or a disciple of the Tathāgata who is a meditator... skilled in the patterns of others' minds, he falls into emptiness, falls into confusion, falls into a dead end, falls into misfortune, falls into a dead end and misfortune. The Tathāgata or a disciple of the Tathāgata, those meditators... skilled in the patterns of others' minds, say: 'For a long time, this venerable one has had broken conduct, shattered conduct, blemished conduct, defiled conduct, inappropriate conduct, inappropriate habits in the precepts. This venerable one is immoral; and being immoral means decline in the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.85" },

{ text: `At that time, the outside wanderers were sitting in a meeting, gathered together, making a loud noise, speaking loudly, discussing frivolous matters. Those outside wanderers saw the householder Anāthapiṇḍika coming from afar. Seeing him, they warned each other: 'Be quiet, venerable sirs, do not make noise, venerable sirs. This householder Anāthapiṇḍika is coming, a disciple of the ascetic Gotama. Among the white-robed lay disciples of the ascetic Gotama living in Sāvatthī, the householder Anāthapiṇḍika is one of them. Those venerable ones dislike noise, are trained in quiet, and praise quiet. If he sees the assembly quiet, he might consider visiting here.' Then those outside wanderers fell silent. Then the householder Anāthapiṇḍika went to those wanderers. After going, he exchanged greetings with them. After exchanging friendly greetings, he sat down to one side. Those outside wanderers said to the sitting householder Anāthapiṇḍika: 'Householder, tell us, what is the view of the ascetic Gotama?' 'Venerable sirs, I do not know all the views of the Blessed One.' 'Householder, you may not know all the views of the ascetic Gotama. But, householder, tell us your own view.' 'Venerable sirs, whatever is born, produced, thought out, arisen through conditions — that is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is: "This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self." That is my view, venerable sirs.' 'Venerable sirs, whatever is born, produced, thought out, arisen through conditions — that is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is: "This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self." Thus it is rightly seen with perfect wisdom as it really is. And beyond that suffering, I truly know the escape.' When this was said, those outside wanderers sat silent, confused, with shoulders drooping, heads down, stunned, unable to speak.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.93" },

{ text: `- Bhante, among people dwelling with various dwellings, which dwelling should we dwell in?<br>- Mahānāma, dwell with faith, not without faith. Dwell with energy, not with laziness. Dwell with mindfulness, not with forgetfulness. Dwell with concentration, not without concentration. Dwell with wisdom, not with evil wisdom. After dwelling in these five things, Mahānāma, develop six further things. Here, Mahānāma, recollect the Tathāgata: 'This Blessed One is an Arahant, Perfectly Enlightened, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, well-gone, knower of the world, unsurpassed trainer of persons to be tamed, teacher of devas and humans, the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.' Mahānāma, while a noble disciple recollects the Tathāgata, at that time his mind is not obsessed by greed, not obsessed by hatred, not obsessed by delusion. At that time, his mind becomes straight because of the Tathāgata. Mahānāma, with a straight mind, the noble disciple gains inspiration in the meaning, gains inspiration in the Dhamma, gains joy connected with the Dhamma. When joyful, rapture arises; when there is rapture, the body becomes tranquil; when the body is tranquil, he feels a pleasant feeling; when feeling pleasant, his mind becomes concentrated. Mahānāma, this is called a noble disciple who dwells attaining equality with beings who are unequal, dwells attaining non-hatred with beings who are hateful, enters the stream of Dhamma, and develops recollection of the Buddha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.11" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Mahānāma, recollect your own virtue: 'unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, leading to concentration.' Mahānāma, while a noble disciple recollects virtue, at that time his mind is not obsessed by greed... becomes straight because of virtue. Mahānāma, with a straight mind... his mind becomes concentrated. Mahānāma, this is called a noble disciple who dwells attaining equality with beings who are unequal... enters the stream of Dhamma, and develops recollection of virtue.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.11" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Mahānāma, recollect your own giving: 'What a gain for me! What a great gain for me! For among people obsessed by the stain of miserliness, I dwell at home with a mind free from the stain of miserliness, giving generously, with open hand, delighting in relinquishment, ready to be asked, delighting in distributing gifts.' Mahānāma, while a noble disciple recollects giving, at that time his mind is not obsessed by greed... becomes straight because of giving. Mahānāma, with a straight mind... his mind becomes concentrated. Mahānāma, this is called a noble disciple who dwells attaining equality with beings who are unequal... enters the stream of Dhamma, and develops recollection of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.11" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, in the future there will be bhikkhus who live in association with gardeners and with novice monks. When living in association with gardeners and novice monks, bhikkhus, it is to be expected that they will live enjoying stored-up goods, and they will make rough signs regarding land and agricultural products. This, bhikkhus, is the fifth fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.80" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is not loved, not liked, not respected, and not an example for his fellow celibates. What five? He is greedy for what is agreeable, hateful toward what is hateful, deluded about what is deluding, angry at what is angering, and infatuated with what is infatuating. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is not loved, not liked, not respected, and not an example for his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.81" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates. What five? He is not greedy for what is agreeable, not hateful toward what is hateful, not deluded about what is deluding, not angry at what is angering, and not infatuated with what is infatuating. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.81" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is not loved, not liked, not respected, and not an example for his fellow celibates. What five? Deceit, flattery (false talk), making signs (hinting), disparagement, and seeking gain for gain. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is not loved, not liked, not respected, and not an example for his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.83" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates. What five? He has faith, has moral shame, has moral dread, is energetic and strenuous, and has wisdom. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.84" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates. What five? He is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules; he is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned. Those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, memorized, remembered by repeated recitation, investigated with the mind, and well penetrated by right view; he speaks well, uses fine speech, his words are refined, clear in meaning, his voice not faltering or hoarse, he explains the meaning clearly; he attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life; by the destruction of the taints, he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.<br>Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, an elder bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and an example for his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.87" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu. What five? Delight in work, delight in talking, delight in sleeping, delight in company, and not examining the mind as it is liberated. These five things, bhikkhus, lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.89" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu. What five? Not delighting in work, not delighting in talking, not delighting in sleeping, not delighting in company, and examining the mind as it is liberated. These five things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.89" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a learner bhikkhu has many duties, many things to do, is skilled in what needs to be done, abandons secluded meditation, does not focus on internal serenity of mind. This is the first thing that leads to decline for a learner bhikkhu. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a learner bhikkhu spends the whole day doing trifling tasks, abandons secluded meditation, does not focus on internal serenity of mind. This is the second thing that leads to decline for a learner bhikkhu. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a learner bhikkhu lives in close association with laypeople and renunciants, is involved with unsuitable lay affairs, abandons secluded meditation, does not focus on internal serenity of mind. This is the third thing that leads to decline for a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.90" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a learner bhikkhu, regarding serious talk that opens the heart, such as talk on few desires, talk on contentment, talk on seclusion, talk on non-association, talk on energy and exertion, talk on virtue, talk on concentration, talk on wisdom, talk on liberation, talk on the knowledge and vision of liberation — these talks he obtains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort, does not abandon secluded meditation, focuses on internal serenity of mind. This is the fifth thing, bhikkhus, that does not lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.90" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practicing mindfulness of breathing will before long penetrate the imperturbable. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has few wants, few duties, easy support, is well content with the necessities of life; eats little, is not devoted to his stomach; sleeps little, is devoted to wakefulness; is learned, remembers much, accumulates what he has learned; those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, memorized, remembered by repeated recitation, investigated with the mind, well penetrated by right view; he examines the mind as it is liberated. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practicing mindfulness of breathing will before long penetrate the imperturbable.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.96" },

{ text: `Lion, bhikkhus, is a designation for the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. When the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma to an assembly, that is his lion's roar. Bhikkhus, if the Tathāgata teaches the Dhamma to bhikkhus, he teaches with utmost care and thoroughness, not without care and thoroughness. If he teaches the Dhamma to bhikkhunīs, he teaches with utmost care and thoroughness, not without care and thoroughness. If he teaches the Dhamma to male lay followers, he teaches with utmost care and thoroughness, not without care and thoroughness. If he teaches the Dhamma to female lay followers, he teaches with utmost care and thoroughness, not without care and thoroughness. If he teaches the Dhamma to ordinary persons, to bird-catchers or beggars, he teaches with utmost care and thoroughness, not without care and thoroughness. Why is that? Because the Tathāgata is one who reveres the Dhamma, bhikkhus, one who respects the Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.99" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has faith, virtue, learning, energy, and wisdom. Whatever the faithless fear, bhikkhus, that does not frighten the faithful. Therefore, this quality is a non-fearful quality for a learner. Whatever the immoral fear, bhikkhus, that does not frighten the virtuous. Therefore, this quality is a non-fearful quality for a learner. Whatever the ignorant fear, bhikkhus, that does not frighten the learned. Therefore, this quality is a non-fearful quality for a learner. Whatever the lazy fear, bhikkhus, that does not frighten the energetic. Therefore, this quality is a non-fearful quality for a learner. Whatever the evil-witted fear, bhikkhus, that does not frighten the wise. Therefore, this quality is a non-fearful quality for a learner.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.101" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five secure abidings. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides with bodily action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately; abides with verbal action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately; abides with mental action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately; regarding the virtues that are unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, leading to concentration — he dwells possessing such virtues toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately; and regarding this view that is noble, leading to escape, leading one who practices it to the complete destruction of suffering — he dwells possessing such view toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. These five qualities, bhikkhus, are the five secure abidings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.105" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who approaches families is loved, liked, respected, and an example for those families. What five? He does not become intimate with those who are not confident, does not interfere where he has no authority, does not associate with opposing factions, does not whisper in private, and does not ask for too much. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who approaches families is loved, liked, respected, and an example for those families.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.111", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.111" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu cannot attain and abide in right concentration. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu cannot endure forms, cannot endure sounds, cannot endure odors, cannot endure tastes, cannot endure touches. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu cannot attain and abide in right concentration.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.113", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.113" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu can attain and abide in right concentration. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu endures forms, endures sounds, endures odors, endures tastes, endures touches. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu can attain and abide in right concentration.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.113", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.113" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, promote longevity. What five? Doing suitable work, knowing moderation in suitable work, eating digestible food, walking at the proper time, and living the holy life. These five things, bhikkhus, promote longevity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.125", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.125" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, a bhikkhu is not fit to live separate from the Saṅgha. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not content with such robes as he receives here and there; is not content with such almsfood as he receives here and there; is not content with such lodgings as he receives here and there; is not content with such medicinal requisites as he receives here and there; and he dwells with many thoughts of sensual desire. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not fit to live separate from the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.127" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fit to live separate from the Saṅgha. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is content with such robes as he receives here and there; is content with such almsfood as he receives here and there; is content with such lodgings as he receives here and there; is content with such medicinal requisites as he receives here and there; and he dwells with many thoughts of renunciation. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fit to live separate from the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.127" },

{ text: `There are these five hardships for an ascetic. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not content with such robes as he receives here and there; is not content with such almsfood as he receives here and there; is not content with such lodgings as he receives here and there; is not content with such medicinal requisites as he receives here and there; and he does not delight in living the holy life. Bhikkhus, these are the five hardships for an ascetic.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.128" },

{ text: `There are these five pleasures for an ascetic. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is content with such robes as he receives here and there; is content with such almsfood as he receives here and there; is content with such lodgings as he receives here and there; is content with such medicinal requisites as he receives here and there; and he delights in living the holy life. Bhikkhus, these are the five pleasures for an ascetic.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.128" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five kinds of loss. What five? Loss of relatives, loss of wealth, loss through illness, loss of virtue, loss of view. Bhikkhus, it is not because of loss of relatives, nor because of loss of wealth, nor because of loss through illness that beings, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, it is because of loss of virtue or loss of view that beings, after death, with the breakup of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, these are the five kinds of loss.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.130", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.130" },

{ text: `Licchavis, the existence of five treasures is hard to find in the world. And what five? The existence of a Tathāgata, an Arahant, a Perfectly Enlightened One is hard to find in the world. A person who can teach the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is hard to find in the world. A person who understands the exposition of the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is hard to find in the world. A person who practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, having understood the exposition of the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, is hard to find in the world. A person who is grateful and thankful is hard to find in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.143", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.143" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not worth being a friend. What five? He tells to do farm work; delights in litigation; opposes the leading bhikkhus; lives a purposeless life, prolonging it thus; is not able from time to time to expound, encourage, inspire, and delight with a Dhamma talk. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not worth being a friend.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.146", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.146" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worth being a friend. What five? He does not tell to do farm work; does not delight in litigation; does not oppose the leading bhikkhus; does not live a purposeless life, prolonging it thus; is able from time to time to expound, encourage, inspire, and delight with a Dhamma talk. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worth being a friend.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.146", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.146" },

{ text: `There are these five kinds of giving, bhikkhus, that are not worthy of a genuine person. What five? Giving without respect, giving without consideration, giving not with one's own hand, giving what is discarded, and giving without regard for the future. These, bhikkhus, are the five kinds of giving not worthy of a genuine person. These five kinds of giving, bhikkhus, are worthy of a genuine person. What five? Giving with respect, giving with consideration, giving with one's own hand, giving what is not discarded, and giving with regard for the future. These, bhikkhus, are the five kinds of giving worthy of a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.147", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.147" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these five kinds of giving are worthy of a genuine person. What five? Giving with faith, giving with respect, giving at the right time, giving with a mind without reluctance, and giving without harming oneself or others. Bhikkhus, these are the five kinds of giving worthy of a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.148", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.148" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when one gives with faith anywhere, the result of that giving bears fruit: one becomes rich, greatly wealthy, with abundant property, handsome, pleasant to look at, trustworthy, and possessing excellent complexion like a lotus. And, bhikkhus, when one gives with respect anywhere, the result of that giving bears fruit: one becomes rich, greatly wealthy, with abundant property; and one's sons, wives, servants, messengers, workers all readily obey one, they listen and serve with understanding.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.148", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.148" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, when one gives at the right time anywhere, the result of that giving bears fruit: one becomes rich, greatly wealthy, with abundant property; and possessions come to one at the right time and in abundance. And, bhikkhus, when one gives without harming oneself or others anywhere, the result of that giving bears fruit: one becomes rich, greatly wealthy, with abundant property; and no misfortune from anywhere befalls one's property, whether from fire, water, kings, thieves, enemies, or heirs.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.148", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.148" },

{ text: `Ānanda, it is not easy to teach the Dhamma to others. To teach the Dhamma to others, Ānanda, after establishing five qualities internally, should one teach the Dhamma to others. What five? 'I will teach the Dhamma gradually' — one who teaches the Dhamma to others should think thus. 'I will teach with an eye to the method' — one who teaches the Dhamma to others should think thus. 'I will teach out of compassion' — one who teaches the Dhamma to others should think thus. 'I will teach not for material gain' — one who teaches the Dhamma to others should think thus. 'I will teach without harming myself or others' — one who teaches the Dhamma to others should think thus. Ānanda, it is not easy to teach the Dhamma to others. To teach the Dhamma to others, Ānanda, after establishing these five qualities internally, should one teach the Dhamma to others.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.159", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.159" },

{ text: `These five things, bhikkhus, when they arise, are hard to remove. What five? Greed when arisen is hard to remove; hatred when arisen is hard to remove; delusion when arisen is hard to remove; talkativeness when arisen is hard to remove; a wandering mind when arisen is hard to remove. These five things, bhikkhus, when they have arisen, are hard to remove.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.160", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.160" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, when an accusing bhikkhu wants to accuse another, he should establish five qualities internally and then accuse. What five? 'I will speak at the right time, not at the wrong time'; 'I will speak truthfully, not falsely'; 'I will speak gently, not harshly'; 'I will speak words connected with benefit, not unconnected with benefit'; 'I will speak with a mind of loving-kindness, not with hatred.' Venerable sirs, when an accusing bhikkhu wants to accuse another, he should establish these five qualities internally and then accuse another.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.167", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.167" },

{ text: `The Blessed One said to the householder Anāthapiṇḍika who was sitting to one side: 'Householder, you have provided the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with necessities such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. But do not be satisfied with the thought: "We have provided the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with necessities such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites." Therefore, householder, you should train thus: "How can we from time to time attain and abide in the joy born of seclusion?" Thus, householder, you should train yourself.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.176", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.176" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, while a noble disciple attains and abides in the joy born of seclusion, at that time five things do not occur for him: Suffering and grief connected with sensual pleasures do not occur for him at that time. Pleasure and joy connected with sensual pleasures do not occur for him at that time. Suffering and grief connected with the unwholesome do not occur for him at that time. Pleasure and joy connected with the unwholesome do not occur for him at that time. Suffering and grief connected with the wholesome do not occur for him at that time. Sāriputta, while a noble disciple attains and abides in the joy born of seclusion, at that time these five things do not occur for him.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.176", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.176" },

{ text: `There are these five trades, bhikkhus, that a male lay follower should not engage in. What five? Trading in weapons, trading in human beings, trading in meat, trading in alcohol, trading in poison. These five trades, bhikkhus, a male lay follower should not engage in.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.177", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.177" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, from a cow comes milk, from milk comes curds, from curds comes butter, from butter comes ghee, from ghee comes the skimmings of ghee — this is called the foremost. So too, bhikkhus, among the five kinds of forest-dwellers, the one who dwells in the forest out of few desires, out of contentment, out of reduction, out of seclusion, out of seeking this good practice — that person among the five is foremost, best, chief, highest, most excellent.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.181", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.181" },

{ text: `Here, Kimbila, after the Tathāgata has passed away, the bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers live without reverence and obedience to the Teacher; live without reverence and obedience to the Dhamma; live without reverence and obedience to the Saṅgha; live without reverence and obedience to the training; live without reverence and obedience to one another. For this cause, for this condition, Kimbila, after the Tathāgata has passed away, the good Dhamma does not last long. Here, Kimbila, after the Tathāgata has passed away, the bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers live with reverence and obedience to the Teacher; live with reverence and obedience to the Dhamma; live with reverence and obedience to the Saṅgha; live with reverence and obedience to the training; live with reverence and obedience to one another. This is the cause, this is the condition, Kimbila, after the Tathāgata has passed away, for the good Dhamma to last long.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.201", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.201" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits of listening to the Dhamma. What five? One hears what has not been heard, one clarifies what has been heard, one dispels doubt, one straightens one's view, and one's mind becomes serene. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits of listening to the Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.202", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.202" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five dangers for a person who is unmindful, not clearly comprehending, when falling asleep. What five? He sleeps badly; he wakes up badly; he sees bad dreams; devas do not protect him; impurities are discharged, nocturnal emissions, seminal loss. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for a person who is unmindful, not clearly comprehending, when falling asleep. Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits for a person who is mindful, clearly comprehending, when falling asleep. What five? He sleeps well; he wakes up well; he does not see bad dreams; devas protect him; impurities are not discharged. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for a person who is mindful, clearly comprehending, when falling asleep.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.210", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.210" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who reviles and insults those living the holy life, who slanders the noble ones, can expect five dangers. What five? He commits an offense that leads to expulsion, cutting off the upward path; or he commits a corrupt offense; or he experiences a severe illness; at the time of death his mind is confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who reviles and insults those living the holy life, who slanders the noble ones, can expect these five dangers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.211", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.211" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is a maker of quarrels, a maker of disputes, a maker of conflicts, a maker of verbal fights, a maker of litigation in the Saṅgha, can expect five dangers. What five? He does not attain what has not been attained; he falls away from what has been attained; a bad reputation spreads about him; at the time of death his mind is confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is a maker of quarrels, a maker of disputes, a maker of conflicts, a maker of verbal fights, a maker of litigation in the Saṅgha, can expect these five dangers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.212", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.212" },


{ text: `There are these five dangers for a talkative person. What five? False speech; divisive speech; harsh speech; idle chatter; and after death, with the breakup of the body, rebirth in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for a talkative person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.214", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.214" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers for an impatient person. What five? People do not love him or like him; many people hate him; many people avoid him; at the time of death his mind is confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for an impatient person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.215", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.215" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits for a patient person. What five? People love him and like him; no one hates him; not many people avoid him; at the time of death his mind is not confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for a patient person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.215", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.215" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, for a person without serene confidence. What five? Those without faith are not inspired; some who have faith may change; he does not follow the Teacher's instruction; later generations follow wrong view; his mind is not serene. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for a person without serene confidence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.218", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.218" },

{ text: `There are these five benefits, bhikkhus, for a person with serene confidence. What five? Those without faith gain faith; those with faith increase in faith; he follows the Teacher's instruction; later generations follow right view; his mind is serene. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for a person with serene confidence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.218", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.218" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, in living too long in one place. What five? Many belongings, storing up many belongings; many medicines, storing up many medicines; many duties, many things to do, not being skilled in what needs to be done; living in close association with laypeople and renunciants, indulging in lay connections; and when leaving that dwelling, one leaves with regret. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers in living too long in one place.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.223", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.223" },

{ text: `There are these five benefits, bhikkhus, in living with moderation in each place. What five? Few belongings, not storing up many belongings; few medicines, not storing up many medicines; few duties, few things to do, being skilled in what needs to be done; not living in close association with laypeople and renunciants, not indulging in lay connections; and when leaving that dwelling, one leaves without regret. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits in living with moderation in each place.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.223", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.223" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, in living too long in one place. What five? Stinginess regarding dwellings; stinginess regarding families; stinginess regarding offerings; stinginess regarding merit; stinginess regarding Dhamma. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers in living too long in one place.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.224", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.224" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, for one who visits families. What five? He commits the offense of going without an invitation; he commits the offense of sitting alone in private; he commits the offense of sitting in a concealed place; he commits the offense of teaching Dhamma to a woman in more than five or six words; he dwells with many thoughts of sensual desire. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for one who visits families.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.225", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.225" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu who lives in too much association with families. What five? He constantly sees women; through seeing, there is association; through association, there is intimacy; through intimacy, there is opportunity (for sexual intercourse); when the mind has been corrupted, it is to be expected that he will not delight in living the holy life, or he will fall into a corrupt offense, or he will give up the training and return to the lay life. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for a bhikkhu who lives in too much association with families.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.226", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.226" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu benefits himself and benefits others. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu himself possesses virtue and encourages others to possess virtue; himself possesses concentration and encourages others to possess concentration; himself possesses wisdom and encourages others to possess wisdom; himself possesses liberation and encourages others to possess liberation; himself possesses the knowledge and vision of liberation and encourages others to possess the knowledge and vision of liberation. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu benefits himself and benefits others.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five mental fetters. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not without greed for sensual pleasures, not without desire, not without affection, not without thirst, not without fever, not without craving. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is not without greed for sensual pleasures... not without craving — his mind does not incline to exertion, perseverance, persistence, effort. For one whose mind does not incline to exertion, perseverance, persistence, effort, that is the first mental fetter. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not without greed for the body... not without greed for forms... A bhikkhu who eats until full, until his belly is filled, dwells devoted to the pleasure of resting, the pleasure of sleeping, the pleasure of drowsiness... A bhikkhu who lives the holy life aspiring for a heavenly realm, thinking: 'By this virtue, this practice, this austerity, this holy life, I will become a deva of this or that kind.' Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who lives the holy life... that is the fifth mental fetter. Bhikkhus, these are the five mental fetters.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.206", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.206" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five dangers for one who teaches the Dhamma with a drawn-out singing voice. What five? He himself becomes infatuated with that voice; others become infatuated with that voice; the laypeople criticize: 'Just as we sing, so do these Sakyan ascetics sing!' Because he strives to perfect his voice, concentration is interrupted; later generations imitate him. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for one who teaches the Dhamma with a drawn-out singing voice.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.209", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.209" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers for an impatient person. What five? People do not love him, do not like him; he is violent, he is without moral shame; at the time of death his mind is confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for an impatient person. Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits for a patient person. What five? People love him and like him; he is gentle, he has moral shame; at the time of death his mind is not confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for a patient person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.216", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.216" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, for a person without serene confidence. What five? He reproaches himself; after consideration, the wise reproach him; a bad reputation spreads about him; at the time of death his mind is confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for a person without serene confidence. There are these five benefits, bhikkhus, for a person with serene confidence. What five? He does not reproach himself; after consideration, the wise praise him; a good reputation spreads about him; at the time of death his mind is not confused; after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for a person with serene confidence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.217", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.217" },

{ text: `A bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who is without reverence, without deference, and not living in concord with his fellow celibates — it is impossible that he will fulfill the practice of superior conduct. Not fulfilling the practice of superior conduct, it is impossible that he will fulfill the learner's practice. Not fulfilling the learner's practice, it is impossible that he will fulfill the aggregate of virtue. Not fulfilling the aggregate of virtue, it is impossible that he will fulfill the aggregate of concentration. Not fulfilling the aggregate of concentration, it is impossible that he will fulfill the aggregate of wisdom.<br><br>A bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who has reverence, deference, and lives in concord with his fellow celibates — it is possible that he will fulfill the practice of superior conduct. Having fulfilled the practice of superior conduct, it is possible that he will fulfill the learner's practice. Having fulfilled the learner's practice, it is possible that he will fulfill the aggregate of virtue. Having fulfilled the aggregate of virtue, it is possible that he will fulfill the aggregate of concentration. Having fulfilled the aggregate of concentration, it is possible that he will fulfill the aggregate of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.22" },

{ text: `There are these five dangers, bhikkhus, for one who wanders long, wandering aimlessly. What five? He does not attain what has not been attained; he does not purify what has been attained; he has fear regarding part of what has been attained; he experiences a severe illness; he has no friends. Bhikkhus, these are the five dangers for one who wanders long, wandering aimlessly. Bhikkhus, there are these five benefits for one who wanders purposefully. What five? He attains what has not been attained; he purifies what has been attained; he has no fear regarding part of what has been attained; he does not experience a severe illness; he has friends. Bhikkhus, these are the five benefits for one who wanders purposefully.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.222", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.222" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place illuminates that place. What five? He is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules; he is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned; those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, memorized, remembered by repeated recitation, investigated with the mind, and well penetrated by right view; he speaks well, uses fine speech, his words are refined, clear in meaning, his voice not faltering or hoarse, he explains the meaning clearly; he is capable of expounding, encouraging, inspiring, and delighting with a Dhamma talk those who come to see him; he attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place illuminates that place.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.233", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.233" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is of great help to that dwelling. What five? He is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules; he is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned; those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, memorized, remembered by repeated recitation, investigated with the mind, and well penetrated by right view; he repairs what is broken or damaged; when a large group of bhikkhus arrives from various regions, he says to the approaching laypeople: 'Now a large group of bhikkhus has arrived from various regions. Please do meritorious deeds. Now is the time to do meritorious deeds!' He attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is of great help to that dwelling.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.234", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.234" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is, as such, placed in hell. What five? Stinginess regarding dwellings, stinginess regarding families, stinginess regarding gains, stinginess regarding praise, and causing donated goods to be wasted. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is, as such, placed in hell. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is, as such, placed in heaven. What five? No stinginess regarding dwellings, no stinginess regarding families, no stinginess regarding gains, no stinginess regarding praise, and not causing donated goods to be wasted. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is, as such, placed in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.239", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.239" },

{ text: `Whoever possesses impure bodily action, impure verbal action, impure mental action, a bad reputation spreads about him. I say that this is his foul smell. Just as, bhikkhus, that foul smell of a charnel ground — I say that this person is like that simile. For one possessing impure bodily action, impure verbal action, impure mental action, the pure fellow celibates become dissatisfied upon seeing him and say: 'Oh, how painful for us, we have to live with such a person.' I say that this is making the multitude lament. Just as, bhikkhus, a charnel ground is a place that makes many lament, I say that this person is like that simile.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.249", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.249" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy to receive full ordination. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possesses the Arahant's aggregate of virtue, possesses the Arahant's aggregate of concentration, possesses the Arahant's aggregate of wisdom, possesses the Arahant's aggregate of liberation, possesses the Arahant's aggregate of the knowledge and vision of liberation. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy to receive full ordination.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.251", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.251" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, the Teacher or a fellow celibate in the role of a teacher teaches the Dhamma to a bhikkhu. As the Teacher or a fellow celibate in the role of a teacher teaches the Dhamma to a bhikkhu in such and such a manner, accordingly that bhikkhu gains inspiration in the meaning and inspiration in the Dhamma. Because of his inspiration in the meaning and inspiration in the Dhamma, joy arises. Because of joy, rapture arises. Because of a joyful mind, the body becomes tranquil. Because of a tranquil body, he feels a pleasant feeling. Because of a pleasant feeling, his mind becomes concentrated. This is the first liberation base; here a bhikkhu who dwells heedful, ardent, and resolute — if his mind is not liberated, it becomes liberated; or if his taints are not completely destroyed, they come to complete destruction; or if he has not attained the unsurpassed security from bondage, he attains it.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.26" },

{ text: `Because of not abandoning these five things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain and abide in the first jhāna. What five? Stinginess regarding dwellings, stinginess regarding families, stinginess regarding gains, stinginess regarding praise, and being ungrateful and unthankful. Because of not abandoning these five things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain the fruit of Arahantship. Because of abandoning these five things, bhikkhus, one can attain and abide in the first jhāna. What five? Stinginess regarding dwellings, stinginess regarding families, stinginess regarding gains, stinginess regarding praise, and being ungrateful and unthankful. Because of abandoning these five things, bhikkhus, one can attain and abide in the first jhāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.264", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.264" },

{ text: `Cundī, whatever kind of virtue there is, the virtues loved by the noble ones are called the foremost among those virtues, that is, virtue that is unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, leading to right concentration. Those who are complete in the virtues loved by the noble ones are complete in the foremost. Those who have confidence in the foremost have the foremost result.<br><br>Confidence in the foremost,<br>Knowing the foremost Dhamma,<br>Confidence in the Buddha, foremost,<br>Worthy of respect, unsurpassed.<br><br>Confidence in the Dhamma, foremost,<br>Dispassion, peace, bliss,<br>Confidence in the Saṅgha, foremost,<br>The unsurpassed field of merit.<br><br>Giving to the foremost,<br>Foremost merit increases,<br>Foremost in life span,<br>Complexion and fame,<br>Foremost in happiness,<br>Foremost in strength.<br><br>The wise give to the foremost,<br>Established in foremost Dhamma,<br>Whether devas or humans,<br>Attain foremost joy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.32" },

{ text: `Based on the Himalayas, the king of mountains, bhikkhus, great sal trees grow in five respects. What five? They grow in branches, leaves, and full foliage; they grow in shoots; they grow in bark; they grow in sapwood; they grow in heartwood. Based on the Himalayas, bhikkhus, great sal trees grow in these five respects. So too, bhikkhus, based on a faithful clansman, the members of his family grow in five respects. What five? They grow in faith; they grow in virtue; they grow in learning; they grow in giving; they grow in wisdom. Based on a faithful clansman, the members of his family grow in these five kinds of growth.<br><br>Like a rock mountain,<br>In a forest, in a great mountain,<br>Trees based on it,<br>The great groves grow.<br><br>So too, one of virtue,<br>A faithful clansman,<br>Based on him they grow:<br>Wife, children, and relatives,<br>Friends and companions,<br>And all his followers.<br><br>Those of good conduct,<br>With the eye that has seen,<br>Imitate this one's virtue,<br>Imitate his generosity.<br><br>Having practiced this Dhamma,<br>Seeking the good destination,<br>In the heavenly realm joyful,<br>They experience joy,<br>Enjoying sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as a great rain that brings the harvests to full ripeness brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to many people. So too, bhikkhus, a genuine person born in a family brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to many people; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his mother and father; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his wife and children; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his servants and workers; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his friends and companions; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to ascetics and brahmins.<br><br>For the happiness of many,<br>One should acquire wealth,<br>Devas protect the person<br>Who guards rightly,<br>Good reputation does not abandon him,<br>He is learned, well-educated,<br>Complete in the precepts,<br>Established in the good Dhamma.<br>Who can reproach him?<br><br>One who abides in Dhamma, of virtue,<br>One who speaks truth, with moral shame and dread,<br>Like an ornament of pure gold,<br>Devas praise that person,<br>Brahmā also praises.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.42" },

{ text: `Householder, a noble disciple who desires long life cannot obtain long life by praying for it or by praising (its cause). A noble disciple who desires long life should practice the path leading to long life. By practicing the path leading to long life, that practice leads him to obtain long life; he obtains long life, whether celestial or human. Householder, a noble disciple who desires beauty... a noble disciple who desires happiness... a noble disciple who desires a good reputation cannot obtain a good reputation by praying for it or by praising (its cause). A noble disciple who desires a good reputation should practice the path leading to a good reputation. By practicing the path leading to a good reputation, that practice leads him to obtain a good reputation; he obtains a good reputation, whether celestial or human.<br><br>Long life and beauty,<br>Good reputation and renown,<br>Heavenly realm and nobility,<br>People by day and night,<br>Always and widely,<br>Pray and beseech.<br><br>But the wise praise<br>Heedful meritorious deeds,<br>The wise, not heedless,<br>Obtain two benefits:<br><br>Benefit in this very life,<br>And benefit in the hereafter,<br>Whoever achieves<br>Benefit and purpose,<br>That one is called<br>Wise, a true person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.43" },

{ text: `Whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, gives up the training and returns to the lay life, five legitimate grounds for self-reproach and criticism come to that person in this very life. What five? 'In you there is no faith in wholesome states; in you there is no moral shame regarding unwholesome states; in you there is no moral dread regarding unwholesome states; in you there is no energy regarding wholesome states; in you there is no wisdom regarding wholesome states.' Whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, gives up the training and returns to the lay life, these five legitimate grounds for self-reproach and criticism come to that person in this very life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.5" },

{ text: `Whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, even with suffering, with grief, with tearful face, weeping, still lives the completely pure holy life, five legitimate grounds for self-praise come to that person in this very life. What five? 'In you there is faith in wholesome states; in you there is moral shame regarding unwholesome states; in you there is moral dread regarding unwholesome states; in you there is energy regarding wholesome states; in you there is wisdom regarding wholesome states.' Whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, even with suffering, with grief, with tearful face, weeping, still lives the completely pure holy life, these five legitimate grounds for self-praise come to that person in this very life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.5" },

{ text: `There are these five inopportune times for striving, bhikkhus. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is old, worn out, overcome by old age. This, bhikkhus, is the first inopportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is sick, overcome by illness. This, bhikkhus, is the second inopportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, there is a famine, poor harvest, almsfood is hard to obtain, not easy to support oneself by gathering almsfood with effort. This, bhikkhus, is the third inopportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, there is fear from jungle bandits; people in the country mount vehicles and flee. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth inopportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the Saṅgha is divided. When the Saṅgha is divided, bhikkhus, there is mutual abuse, mutual quarreling, mutual accusation, mutual expulsion. Those without faith do not gain faith, and those with faith may change. This, bhikkhus, is the fifth inopportune time for striving. These, bhikkhus, are the five inopportune times for striving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.54" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five opportune times for striving. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is young, youthful, a young man with black hair, in the prime of life, at the beginning of his years. This, bhikkhus, is the first opportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has few illnesses, few afflictions, good digestion, not too cold, not too hot, moderate, suitable for exertion. This, bhikkhus, is the second opportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, there is plenty of food, a good harvest; almsfood is easy to obtain; it is easy to support oneself by gathering almsfood with effort. This, bhikkhus, is the third opportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, you dwell together in harmony, rejoicing, without quarreling, like milk mixed with water, looking at one another with loving eyes. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth opportune time for striving. Furthermore, bhikkhus, the Saṅgha is united, rejoicing together, without dispute, dwelling at ease with a single teaching. When the Saṅgha is united, there is no mutual abuse, no mutual quarreling, no mutual accusation, no mutual expulsion. There, those without faith gain faith, and those with faith increase even more. This, bhikkhus, is the fifth opportune time for striving. These, bhikkhus, are the five opportune times for striving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.54" },

{ text: `Furthermore, Mahānāma, a clansman, with the wealth he has earned through energetic striving, accumulated through the strength of his arms, through the sweat of his brow, righteously, righteously gained, honors, respects, reveres, and makes offerings to ascetics and brahmins. Those ascetics and brahmins, being thus honored, respected, revered, and offered to with a benevolent mind, arouse compassion for him: 'May he live long! May his life be protected for a long time!' And, Mahānāma, for a clansman who is compassionately regarded by ascetics and brahmins, growth is to be expected, not decline.<br><br>Mother and father serve him,<br>Wife and children always love him,<br>For the happiness of the household,<br>And for his followers.<br><br>For the happiness of both,<br>Gentle speech, virtue,<br>For the happiness of relatives,<br>For the departed ancestors,<br>For the present life.<br><br>For ascetics and brahmins,<br>For the wise devas,<br>He becomes a giver of happiness,<br>Living at home, righteously.<br><br>That one does good deeds,<br>Is honored and praised,<br>In this life he is praised,<br>In the next he rejoices,<br>In the heavenly realms.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.58" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, in the future there will be bhikkhus who are undeveloped in body, undeveloped in virtue, undeveloped in mind, undeveloped in wisdom. Because they are undeveloped in body, undeveloped in virtue, undeveloped in mind, undeveloped in wisdom, the elder bhikkhus will live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, not making an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. And later generations will follow their wrong view. They will become those who live in abundance, lazy, leaders in decline, discarding the burden of seclusion, and will not make an effort to attain what has not been attained, to achieve what has not been achieved, to realize what has not been realized. Thus, bhikkhus, from defilement of the Dhamma comes defilement of the Discipline; from defilement of the Discipline comes defilement of the Dhamma. This, bhikkhus, is the fifth fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.79" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, in the future there will be bhikkhus who are undeveloped in body, undeveloped in virtue, undeveloped in mind, undeveloped in wisdom. Because they are undeveloped in body, undeveloped in virtue, undeveloped in mind, undeveloped in wisdom, when the discourses spoken by the Tathāgata, deep, profound, transcendent, connected with the void, are being taught, they do not listen, they do not lend an ear, they do not apply their minds to understand them, and they do not think that these teachings should be learned and memorized. But when the poetic discourses composed by poets, with beautiful words and phrases, belonging to outsiders, spoken by disciples, are being taught, they will listen, they will lend an ear, they will apply their minds to understand them, and they will think that these teachings should be learned and memorized. This, bhikkhus, is due to defilement of the Dhamma leading to defilement of the Discipline; due to defilement of the Discipline leading to defilement of the Dhamma. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth fear regarding the future, not yet arisen now but will arise in the future. You should fully understand them. Having fully understood them, you should strive to abandon that fear.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.79" },

{ text: `Possessing five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practicing mindfulness of breathing will before long penetrate the imperturbable. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has few wants, few duties, easy support, is well content with the necessities of life; eats little, is not devoted to his stomach; sleeps little, is devoted to wakefulness; regarding serious talk that opens the heart, such as talk on few desires, talk on contentment, talk on seclusion, talk on non-association, talk on energy and exertion, talk on virtue, talk on concentration, talk on wisdom, talk on liberation, talk on the knowledge and vision of liberation — these talks he obtains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort; he examines the mind as it is liberated. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu practicing mindfulness of breathing will before long penetrate the imperturbable.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.97" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three things. What three? Greed, hatred, delusion. Bhikkhus, these are the three things. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, three things should be developed. What three? For the abandonment of greed, the perception of foulness should be developed. For the abandonment of hatred, loving-kindness should be developed. For the abandonment of delusion, wisdom should be developed. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.107" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three things. What three? Thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming. Bhikkhus, these are the three things. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, three things should be developed. What three? For the abandonment of thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of renunciation should be developed. For the abandonment of thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of non-ill-will should be developed. For the abandonment of thoughts of harming, thoughts of non-harming should be developed. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.109" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these six principles of cordiality. What six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides with bodily action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. This is a principle of cordiality. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides with verbal action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. This is a principle of cordiality. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu abides with mental action that is loving toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. This is a principle of cordiality. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, regarding righteous gains obtained righteously, even down to the contents of his alms bowl, does not use them without sharing; he shares them in common with his virtuous fellow celibates. This is a principle of cordiality. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, regarding the virtues that are unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, leading to concentration — he dwells possessing such virtues toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, regarding the view that is noble, leading to escape, leading one who practices it to the complete destruction of suffering — he dwells possessing such view toward his fellow celibates, both openly and privately. Bhikkhus, these are the six principles of cordiality.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.11" },

{ text: `Without abandoning six things, bhikkhus, one cannot dwell contemplating the body in the body. What six? Delight in work, delight in talking, delight in sleeping, delight in company, lack of sense restraint, and lack of moderation in eating. Bhikkhus, without abandoning these six things, one cannot dwell contemplating the body. Having abandoned six things, bhikkhus, one can dwell contemplating the body in the body. What six? Delight in work, delight in talking, delight in sleeping, delight in company, lack of sense restraint, and lack of moderation in eating. Having abandoned these six things, bhikkhus, one can dwell contemplating the body in the body.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.117" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, if a bhikkhu lives a life in such and such a way, due to that way of life, at the time of death he will have regret, upon passing away he will have regret. And how, venerable sirs, does a bhikkhu live a life in such a way that at the time of death he has regret, upon passing away he has regret? Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu delights in work, takes pleasure in work, is devoted to delight in work; delights in talking, takes pleasure in talking, is devoted to delight in talking; delights in sleeping, takes pleasure in sleeping, is devoted to delight in sleeping; delights in company, takes pleasure in company, is devoted to delight in company; delights in association, takes pleasure in association, is devoted to delight in association; delights in frivolous talk, takes pleasure in frivolous talk, is devoted to delight in frivolous talk. Thus, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu lives a life in such a way that at the time of death he has regret, upon passing away he has regret. Venerable sirs, this is called: 'A bhikkhu who delights in identity, who does not abandon identity for the complete ending of suffering.'<br><br>One who devotes himself to frivolous talk,<br>Delighting in frivolous talk,<br>Goes against Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security.<br><br>One who abandons frivolous talk,<br>Delights in non-frivolous talk,<br>Heads toward Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.15" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, when a cloth is on fire or the head is on fire, to extinguish that cloth or head, one should arouse extraordinary desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. So too, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu, to abandon those evil unwholesome states, should arouse extraordinary desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. If that bhikkhu, while reflecting, knows thus: 'I have evil unwholesome states that are not yet abandoned; if I were to die today, they could be an obstacle for me.' Then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should dwell with joy and delight, and day and night he should train in wholesome states. Bhikkhus, mindfulness of death, developed and cultivated in this way, is of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.20" },

{ text: `This is the sixth recollection; remember it here. Ānanda, a bhikkhu goes out mindfully, enters mindfully, sits mindfully, lies down mindfully, is mindful while working. Ānanda, this is a recollection; developed and cultivated in this way, it leads to mindfulness and clear comprehension.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.29" },

{ text: `- Venerable sirs, do you see that great pile of wood?<br>- Yes, venerable sir, we see it.<br>- If he wishes, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu with psychic power, who has attained mastery of mind, could perceive that pile of wood as earth. Why is that? Because there is the earth element in that great pile of wood; relying on that, a bhikkhu with psychic power, who has attained mastery of mind, could perceive that pile of wood as earth. If he wishes, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu with psychic power, who has attained mastery of mind, could perceive that pile of wood as water... as fire... as air... as beautiful... as foul. Why is that? Because there is foulness in that great pile of wood; relying on that, a bhikkhu with psychic power, who has attained mastery of mind, could perceive that pile of wood as foul.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.41" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, poverty is a suffering for a person with sensual desire in the world; indebtedness is also a suffering for a person with sensual desire in the world; interest is also a suffering; being pressed and urged is also a suffering; being hounded and pursued is also a suffering; being bound is also a suffering. So too, bhikkhus, whoever has no faith in wholesome states, no moral shame in wholesome states, no moral dread in wholesome states, no energy in wholesome states, no wisdom in wholesome states — that person, bhikkhus, is called one who is poor, destitute, living in want in the Noble One's Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.45" },

{ text: `Poverty and indebtedness<br>Are called suffering in the world!<br>A poor person in debt,<br>Enjoying, is harmed,<br><br>Then pursued by creditors,<br>Even to being bound.<br>Being bound is indeed suffering<br>For one seeking sensual pleasures.<br><br>So too in the Noble Discipline,<br>Whoever lives without faith,<br>Without shame, without dread,<br>Decides on evil deeds.<br><br>Having done evil deeds<br>By body, speech, and mind,<br>And wishes: 'May no one know what I did.'<br><br>That person well conceals<br>With body, speech, and mind,<br>Increases evil deeds,<br>Here and there doing more.<br><br>An evil-witted, evil-deed person,<br>Knowing the evil he has done,<br>Like a poor person in debt,<br>Enjoying, is harmed.<br><br>Painful thoughts<br>Born from remorse<br>Still pursue that person,<br>In the village or in the forest.<br><br>An evil-deed, evil-witted person,<br>Knowing the evil he has done,<br>Either falls into the animal realm<br>Or is bound in hell.<br><br>This binding is suffering.<br>The wise are liberated.<br>One with serene mind who gives<br>With righteously gained goods,<br><br>Sowing good fortune on both paths,<br>A faithful householder seeking,<br>In the present obtains happiness,<br>In the hereafter obtains bliss.<br>Thus a householder's giving<br>Increases merit.<br><br>So too in the Noble Discipline<br>Faith is established.<br>With shame, with dread,<br>With wisdom, protecting virtue,<br><br>That one, in the Noble Discipline,<br>Is called 'one who dwells happily.'<br>He gains non-material happiness,<br>Established in equanimity.<br><br>Abandoning the five hindrances,<br>Always diligent, energetic,<br>Attains jhāna, one-pointed mind,<br>Careful, mindful.<br><br>Knowing that as it really is,<br>He destroys all fetters,<br>Without any clinging,<br>Rightly, his mind is liberated.<br><br>With that right liberation,<br>If such knowledge arises:<br>'Unshakable is my liberation,<br>The fetter of existence is destroyed.'<br><br>This knowledge is supreme knowledge,<br>This happiness is unsurpassed happiness,<br>Without sorrow, without defilement,<br>Secure, liberated.<br>This state of being free from debt<br>Is considered the highest.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.45" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is not worthy to be an example. What five? He is not perfect in deportment, not perfect in responsibility; he is not learned, does not remember what he has learned; he does not know the life of reduction, does not delight in secluded meditation; his speech is not good, he is not one who speaks good words; he has evil wisdom, dull, deaf. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is not worthy to be an example.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.231", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.231" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is worthy to be an example. What five? He is perfect in deportment, perfect in responsibility; he is learned, remembers what he has learned; he knows the life of reduction, delights in secluded meditation; his speech is good, he speaks good words; he has wisdom, not dull, not deaf. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is worthy to be an example.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.231", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.231" },


{ text: `Householder, a noble disciple who gives food gives four things to the recipients. What four? He gives life, gives beauty, gives happiness, gives strength. Having given life, the giver has a share in life, whether celestial or human. Having given beauty, the giver has a share in beauty, whether celestial or human. Having given happiness, the giver has a share in happiness, whether celestial or human. Having given strength, the giver has a share in strength, whether celestial or human. Householder, a noble disciple who gives food gives these four things to the recipients.<br><br>Those who are well-restrained,<br>Living by the gifts of others,<br>Who at the proper time ardently<br>Give food and drink,<br>Bestow upon the recipients<br>Four harvests as follows:<br>They give life, beauty,<br>Give happiness, strength.<br>The giver of life,<br>The giver of beauty,<br>The giver of happiness,<br>The giver of strength,<br>Long life and fame,<br>Wherever he is reborn.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.58" },

{ text: `Possessing four qualities, householder, a noble disciple enters the proper path for a householder, the path that brings a good reputation, the path that leads to heaven. What four? Here, householder, a noble disciple supports the Saṅgha of bhikkhus, supports the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with robes, supports the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with almsfood, supports the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with lodgings, supports the Saṅgha of bhikkhus with medicinal requisites. Possessing these four qualities, householder, a noble disciple enters the proper path for a householder, the path that brings a good reputation, the path that leads to heaven.<br><br>The wise person follows<br>The truly worthy path<br>Of a householder,<br>Supporting the virtuous,<br>Those of right conduct,<br>Supporting them with robes,<br>With almsfood,<br>Lodgings, and medicines,<br>Their merit grows<br>Constantly, day and night,<br>By doing good deeds,<br>They go to the heavenly realm.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.60" },

{ text: `In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered like Brahmā. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered like the ancient teachers. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families, bhikkhus, are considered like the devas of old. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the parents are honored and revered by the children in the home, those families are considered worthy of offerings. Brahmā, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; the ancient teachers, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; the devas of old, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father; worthy of offerings and reverence, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, mother and father have done much for their children: they nourish them, bring them up, and introduce them to this world.<br><br>Mother and father are called Brahmā,<br>The ancient teachers,<br>Worthy of offerings,<br>Out of compassion for their children.<br>Therefore the wise<br>Pay homage and respect them,<br>Offer them food and drink,<br>Clothing and bedding,<br>Anoint their bodies,<br>Bathe their hands and feet.<br>By acting thus<br>Toward mother and father,<br>In this life the wise praise them,<br>In the next they enjoy heavenly bliss.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.63" },

{ text: `There are these four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who exist and are found in the world. What four? One who measures by form and is satisfied with form; one who measures by sound and is satisfied with sound; one who measures by coarseness and is satisfied with coarseness; one who measures by Dhamma and is satisfied with Dhamma. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, exist and are found in the world.<br><br>Those who measure by form,<br>Those who go by sound,<br>Led by sensual desire,<br>They do not know that person,<br>Do not know the inner mind,<br>Do not see the external object.<br>The fool is surrounded,<br>Controlled by speech,<br>Does not know the inner mind,<br>Sees the external object,<br>Sees the external fruit,<br>Controlled by speech.<br>Knows the inner mind,<br>Sees the external object,<br>Sees clearly without obstruction,<br>Not controlled by speech.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.65" },

{ text: `There are these four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, who are wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearers of the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha. What four? A bhikkhu, bhikkhus, who is wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearing the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha. A bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, who is wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearing the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha. A male lay follower, bhikkhus, who is wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearing the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha. A female lay follower, bhikkhus, who is wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearing the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha. These four kinds of persons, bhikkhus, are wise, well-trained, fearless, learned, bearers of the Dhamma, practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, illuminating the Saṅgha.<br><br>Whoever is wise,<br>Who is fearless,<br>And also learned,<br>And a bearer of the Dhamma,<br>Regarding the true good Dhamma,<br>Practicing Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma,<br>Such a person is called<br>One who illuminates the Saṅgha.<br><br>A bhikkhu of virtue,<br>A learned bhikkhunī,<br>A faithful male layman,<br>A faithful female laywoman,<br>They illuminate the Saṅgha,<br>They are the light of the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.7" },

{ text: `When, bhikkhus, unrighteous kings are present, then the king's unrighteous ministers are present. When the king's unrighteous ministers are present, then the townspeople and villagers become unrighteous. When the townspeople and villagers are unrighteous, then the moon and sun go off course. When the moon and sun go off course, then the seasons and the year go off course. When the seasons and the year go off course, then the rain does not fall properly. When the rain does not fall properly, then the crops ripen out of season. Bhikkhus, when crops ripen out of season, then people living on that rice have short life spans, bad complexion, weak strength, and many illnesses.<br><br>When, bhikkhus, righteous kings are present, then the king's righteous ministers are present. When the king's righteous ministers are present, then the townspeople and villagers become righteous. When the townspeople and villagers are righteous, then the moon and sun go on course. When the moon and sun go on course, then the seasons and the year go on course. When the seasons and the year go on course, then the rain falls properly. When the rain falls properly, then the crops ripen in season. Bhikkhus, when crops ripen in season, then people living on that rice have long life spans, beautiful complexion, strength, and few illnesses.<br><br>When the lead cow crosses the river,<br>If the leader goes astray,<br>The whole herd goes astray,<br>Because the guide is wrong.<br>So too among humans,<br>Who is considered supreme,<br>If his conduct is unrighteous,<br>What to say of others?<br>The whole country suffers,<br>If the king lives unrighteously.<br>When the lead cow crosses the river,<br>If the leader goes straight,<br>The whole herd goes straight,<br>Because the guide is right.<br>So too among humans,<br>Who is considered supreme,<br>If his conduct is righteous,<br>What to say of others?<br>The whole country lives happily,<br>If the king lives righteously.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.70" },

{ text: `Whoever encourages the acceptance of an ill-proclaimed Dhamma and Discipline, bhikkhus, both the encourager and the one who follows that encouragement — all produce much demerit. Why is that? Because the Dhamma is ill-proclaimed, bhikkhus. Whoever encourages the acceptance of a well-proclaimed Dhamma and Discipline, both the encourager and the one who follows that encouragement — all produce much merit. Why is that? Because the Dhamma is well-proclaimed, bhikkhus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.320-321", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.320" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is hatred born from affection? Here, bhikkhus, a certain person is desirable, pleasant, agreeable to someone. Then others treat that person in an undesirable, unpleasant, disagreeable way. That person thinks: 'This person is desirable, pleasant, agreeable to me, but others treat him in an undesirable, unpleasant, disagreeable way.' Therefore hatred arises in him toward those others. Thus, bhikkhus, is hatred born from affection. And, bhikkhus, what is hatred born from hatred? Here, bhikkhus, a certain person is undesirable, unpleasant, disagreeable to someone. Then others treat that person in a desirable, pleasant, agreeable way. That person thinks: 'This person is undesirable, unpleasant, disagreeable to me, yet others treat him in a desirable, pleasant, agreeable way.' Therefore hatred arises in him toward those others. Thus, bhikkhus, is hatred born from hatred.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.200", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.200" },

{ text: `Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell. What four? Not having seen, he says he has seen; not having heard, he says he has heard; not having sensed, he says he has sensed; not having cognized, he says he has cognized. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven. What four? Not having seen, he says he has not seen; not having heard, he says he has not heard; not having sensed, he says he has not sensed; not having cognized, he says he has not cognized.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.217", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.217" },

{ text: `These four things, bhikkhus, lead to the growth of wisdom. What four? Associating with good persons, listening to the good Dhamma, wise attention (proper reflection), and practicing Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma. These four things, bhikkhus, lead to the growth of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.248", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.248" },

{ text: `Māluṅkyaputta, there are these four births of craving from which craving arises for a bhikkhu. What four? Either because of robes, Māluṅkyaputta, craving arises, from which craving arises for a bhikkhu. Or because of almsfood... or because of lodging... or because of this or that kind of existence. Māluṅkyaputta, there are these four births of craving from which craving arises for a bhikkhu. When, Māluṅkyaputta, craving is abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future — then, Māluṅkyaputta, that bhikkhu is called one who has destroyed craving, untied the fetters, rightly demolished conceit, and made an end of suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.257", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.257" },

{ text: `Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not fit to dwell in the forest, in remote jungle dwellings, in secluded lodgings. What four? With thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming, and with evil wisdom, dull, deaf. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not fit to dwell in the forest, in remote jungle dwellings, in secluded lodgings. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fit to dwell in the forest, in remote jungle dwellings, in secluded lodgings. What four? With thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming, and not dull, not deaf. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is fit to dwell in the forest, in remote jungle dwellings, in secluded lodgings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.262", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.262" },

{ text: `Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell. What four? He himself takes what is not given, encourages others to take what is not given, consents to taking what is not given, and praises taking what is not given. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in hell. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven. What four? He himself abstains from taking what is not given, encourages others to abstain from taking what is not given, consents to abstaining from taking what is not given, and praises abstaining from taking what is not given. Possessing these four qualities, bhikkhus, as such is placed in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.265", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.265" },

{ text: `There are these four Dhamma statements, bhikkhus, that are known to be primal, of long standing, known as tradition, ancient, unadulterated, not adulterated before, not adulterated now, not to be adulterated in the future, not criticized by wise ascetics and brahmins. What four? Non-greed, bhikkhus, is a Dhamma statement known to be primal, of long standing, known as tradition, ancient, unadulterated, not adulterated before, not adulterated now, not to be adulterated in the future, not criticized by wise ascetics and brahmins. Non-hatred... Right mindfulness... Right concentration... is a Dhamma statement known to be primal, of long standing, known as tradition, ancient, unadulterated, not adulterated before, not adulterated now, not to be adulterated in the future, not criticized by wise ascetics and brahmins.<br><br>Always without hatred, mindful,<br>With mind well concentrated,<br>Having subdued greed, training,<br>He is called heedful.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these four grounds for sympathy. What four? Giving, pleasant speech, beneficial conduct, and equality (treating others as oneself). Bhikkhus, these are the four grounds for sympathy.<br><br>Giving and pleasant speech,<br>Beneficial conduct and equality,<br>Regarding these things,<br>In dealing with one another,<br>Here and there,<br>Thus it is appropriate,<br>And these four grounds for sympathy<br>Are like the hub of a chariot wheel.<br><br>If these grounds for sympathy were lacking,<br>Then neither mother nor father<br>Would receive from their children<br>Honor and respect.<br><br>Therefore the wise,<br>Looking at these grounds for sympathy equally,<br>Through them they attain<br>Greatness and praise.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.32" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is a bhikkhu who dwells alone? Here, bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu, conceit has been abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, made unable to arise in the future. Thus, bhikkhus, is a bhikkhu who dwells alone. A bhikkhu who has removed personal truth, bhikkhus, who has completely abandoned all searches, or whose bodily activities are calmed — he is called one who walks alone.<br><br>The search for sensual pleasures and existence,<br>And the search for the holy life,<br>Clinging to this truth,<br>The accumulation of views.<br><br>Who does not delight in all greed,<br>Liberated through the destruction of craving,<br>Has abandoned the searches,<br>Uprooted the grounds of views.<br><br>That bhikkhu is peaceful,<br>Truly mindful, calm,<br>Not defeated by anyone,<br>With conceit fully seen,<br>He is called by name,<br>The Enlightened One who dwells alone.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.38" },

{ text: `- Does Venerable Gotama not praise sacrifice?<br>- Brahmin, I do not praise all kinds of sacrifice. But, brahmin, I do not refrain from praising all kinds of sacrifice. In whatever sacrifice, brahmin, cattle are killed, goats and sheep are killed, poultry and pigs are killed, and other living creatures come to be killed — that kind of sacrifice, brahmin, involves killing; I do not praise that kind of sacrifice. Why is that? For such a sacrifice involving killing, brahmin, Arahants and those who have entered the path to Arahantship do not attend. In whatever sacrifice, brahmin, no cattle are killed, no goats and sheep are killed, no poultry and pigs are killed, no other living creatures are killed — that kind of sacrifice without killing, brahmin, I praise, that is, regular giving, a sacrifice for the welfare of the family. Why is that? For such a sacrifice without killing, brahmin, Arahants and those who have entered the path to Arahantship do attend.<br><br>The horse sacrifice, human sacrifice,<br>The victory-drinking sacrifice,<br>The luck-throwing sacrifice,<br>The locked-door sacrifice,<br>Those sacrifices with much killing<br>Do not yield great fruit.<br><br>Where goats and sheep are killed,<br>Cattle and other creatures,<br>Those following the right path,<br>Those great sages,<br>At such a sacrifice<br>They do not attend.<br><br>A sacrifice without killing,<br>Always seeking the family's welfare,<br>No killing of goats, sheep, cattle,<br>No killing of other creatures,<br>Those following the right path,<br>Those great sages,<br>At such a sacrifice<br>They attend that sacrifice.<br><br>That sacrifice the wise perform,<br>That sacrifice is of great fruit,<br>That sacrifice is good,<br>It leads to no harm,<br>The greater the sacrifice,<br>The more the devas rejoice.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.39" },

{ text: `Right conduct toward mother, bhikkhus, — the wise, intelligent, genuine person, by behaving rightly, is not like one who has lost his roots, is not injured, does not commit an offense, is not criticized by the wise, and produces much merit. Right conduct toward father, bhikkhus... Right conduct toward the Tathāgata, bhikkhus... Right conduct toward the Tathāgata's disciple, bhikkhus — the wise, intelligent, genuine person, by behaving rightly, is not like one who has lost his roots, is not injured, does not commit an offense, is not criticized by the wise, and produces much merit. By right conduct in these four cases, bhikkhus, the wise, intelligent, genuine person, behaving rightly, is not like one who has lost his roots, is not injured, does not commit an offense, is not criticized by the wise, and produces much merit.<br><br>Toward mother and father<br>Whoever behaves wrongly,<br>Toward the Perfectly Enlightened Tathāgata,<br>Or toward His disciple,<br>One who behaves thus<br>Produces much demerit.<br><br>Those of evil conduct<br>Toward mother and father,<br>In this life the wise reproach them,<br>In the next they are reborn in a lower realm.<br><br>Toward mother and father<br>Whoever behaves rightly,<br>Toward the Perfectly Enlightened Tathāgata,<br>Or toward His disciple,<br>One who behaves thus<br>Produces much merit.<br><br>Those of right conduct<br>Toward mother and father,<br>In this life the wise praise them,<br>In the next they enjoy the heavenly realm.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.4" },

{ text: `Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is compassionate toward the laypeople. What five? He encourages them in the higher virtue; he makes them live in accordance with the Dhamma as an example; when visiting the sick, he establishes mindfulness in the sick person as follows: 'Establish your mindfulness on the goal of Arahantship'; when a large group of bhikkhus arrives from various regions, he says to the approaching laypeople: 'Now a large group of bhikkhus has arrived from various regions. Please do meritorious deeds. Now is the time to do meritorious deeds'; whatever food they offer, whether coarse or fine, he himself uses it, not letting donated goods be wasted. Possessing these five qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu residing in a place is compassionate toward the laypeople.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.235", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.235" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, an unsurpassed field of merit in the world. What six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when seeing a form with the eye, is neither pleased nor displeased, but dwells equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending; when hearing a sound with the ear... smelling an odor with the nose... tasting a taste with the tongue... feeling a touch with the body... cognizing a mind-object with the mind, he is neither pleased nor displeased, but dwells equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending. Possessing these six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, an unsurpassed field of merit in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.1" },

{ text: `Mahānāma, a noble disciple recollects his own virtue: 'Virtue that is unbroken, unblemished, unstained, untainted, leading to liberation, praised by the wise, not clung to, leading to concentration.' Mahānāma, while a noble disciple recollects virtue, at that time his mind is not obsessed by greed, not obsessed by hatred, not obsessed by delusion; at that time his mind becomes straight because of virtue. And, Mahānāma, a noble disciple with a straight mind gains inspiration in the meaning, gains inspiration in the Dhamma, gains joy connected with virtue. When joyful, rapture arises; when there is rapture, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he feels a pleasant feeling; feeling pleasant, his mind becomes concentrated. Mahānāma, of this noble disciple it is said: 'With beings who are not equanimous, he dwells equanimously. With beings who are afflicted, he dwells without affliction. Having entered the stream of Dhamma, he develops recollection of virtue.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.10" },

{ text: `Mahānāma, a noble disciple himself recollects his own giving: 'What a gain for me! What a great gain for me! For among people obsessed by the stain of miserliness, I dwell at home with a mind free from the stain of miserliness, giving generously, with open hand, delighting in relinquishment, ready to be asked, delighting in distributing gifts.' Mahānāma, while a noble disciple recollects giving, at that time his mind is not obsessed by greed, not obsessed by hatred, not obsessed by delusion; at that time his mind becomes straight because of giving. And, Mahānāma, a noble disciple with a straight mind gains inspiration in the meaning, gains inspiration in the Dhamma, gains joy connected with giving. When joyful, rapture arises; when there is rapture, the body becomes tranquil; with a tranquil body, he feels a pleasant feeling; feeling pleasant, his mind becomes concentrated. Mahānāma, of this noble disciple it is said: 'With beings who are not equanimous, he dwells equanimously. With beings who are afflicted, he dwells without affliction. Having entered the stream of Dhamma, he develops recollection of giving.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.10" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a certain bhikkhu says: 'I have abandoned the thought "I am." I do not dwell contemplating "This is me," yet the arrow of doubt and uncertainty obsesses my mind and remains.' He should be told: 'Do not say so, venerable sir, do not say so. Do not misrepresent the Blessed One, for misrepresentation of the Blessed One is not good. The Blessed One would not say that. Venerable sir, that is not the case. It cannot be so. For one who has abandoned the thought "I am," for one who does not dwell contemplating "This is me," it is impossible for the arrow of doubt and uncertainty to obsess his mind and remain. Venerable sir, what is capable of liberating the arrow of doubt and uncertainty is the uprooting of the conceit "I am."'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.13" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu delights in work, takes pleasure in work, is devoted to delight in work; delights in talking, takes pleasure in talking, is devoted to delight in talking; delights in sleeping, takes pleasure in sleeping, is devoted to delight in sleeping; delights in company, takes pleasure in company, is devoted to delight in company; delights in association, takes pleasure in association, is devoted to delight in association; delights in frivolous talk, takes pleasure in frivolous talk, is devoted to delight in frivolous talk. Thus, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu lives a life in such a way that at the time of death he does not have a good end, upon passing away he does not have a good end. Venerable sirs, this is called: 'A bhikkhu who delights in identity, who does not abandon identity for the complete ending of suffering.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.14" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu does not delight in work, does not take pleasure in work, is not devoted to delight in work; does not delight in talking... does not delight in sleeping... does not delight in company... does not delight in association... does not delight in frivolous talk, does not take pleasure in frivolous talk, is not devoted to delight in frivolous talk. Thus, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu lives a life in such a way that at the time of death he has a good end, upon passing away he has a good end. Venerable sirs, this is called: 'A bhikkhu who delights in Nibbāna, who abandons identity for the complete ending of suffering.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.14" },

{ text: `One who devotes himself to frivolous talk,<br>Delighting in frivolous talk,<br>Goes against Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security.<br>One who abandons frivolous talk,<br>Delights in non-frivolous talk,<br>Heads toward Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.14" },

{ text: `Good, bhikkhus. I too have not seen nor heard, bhikkhus, that an ascetic or brahmin, dwelling devoted to the enjoyment of the pleasure of resting, the pleasure of lying down, the pleasure of sleeping, without guarding the sense doors, without moderation in eating, without devotion to wakefulness, without regard for wholesome states, without diligently developing the factors of enlightenment in the evening and in the morning, could, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'With guarded sense doors, with moderation in eating, devoted to wakefulness, regarding wholesome states, diligently developing the factors of enlightenment in the evening and in the morning, we will, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realize, attain, and abide in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.17" },

{ text: `Truly, bhikkhus, whoever with evil intent looks at animals that are being killed, being led to slaughter — because of that, he is not fit to ride an elephant, not fit to ride a horse, not fit to ride a chariot, not fit to ride a carriage, not fit to enjoy wealth, or not fit to live among great or heaped-up wealth. What to say of one who with evil intent looks at human beings who are being killed, being led to slaughter! Truly, bhikkhus, it is for his long-term harm and suffering that, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.18" },

{ text: `- Bhante, there are three things that lead to a bhikkhu's decline. What three? Delight in work, delight in talking, delight in sleeping. These three things, Bhante, lead to a bhikkhu's decline.<br>- Bhikkhus, what are the three things that lead to decline? Delight in company, evil speech, evil friendship. These three things, bhikkhus, lead to decline. Bhikkhus, those in the past who declined in wholesome states, all declined because of these six things. Bhikkhus, those in the future who will decline in wholesome states, all will decline because of these six things. Bhikkhus, those in the present who are declining in wholesome states, all are declining because of these six things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.21" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these six non-declining things; listen. And, bhikkhus, what are the six non-declining things? Not delighting in work, not delighting in talking, not delighting in sleeping, not delighting in company, good speech, good friendship. Bhikkhus, those in the past who did not decline in wholesome states, all did not decline because of these six things. Bhikkhus, those in the future who will not decline in wholesome states, all will not decline because of these six things. Bhikkhus, those in the present who are not declining in wholesome states, all are not declining because of these six things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.22" },

{ text: `Fear, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Suffering, bhikkhus, is a companion of sensual pleasures. Illness, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. A boil, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Clinging, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. A swamp, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. And, bhikkhus, why is fear a designation for sensual pleasures? Bhikkhus, being infatuated by sensual desire, bound by sensual desire, one does not escape from fear in this very life, nor does one escape from fear in the hereafter. Therefore, fear is a designation for sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.23" },

{ text: `Fear and suffering,<br>Illness and boil,<br>Both clinging and swamp,<br>Are called sensual pleasures.<br>There the ordinary person,<br>Infatuated and clinging,<br>Sees fear in clinging,<br>The origin of birth and death.<br>Without clinging, liberated,<br>Birth and death are destroyed,<br>They attain security,<br>Pure bliss in this life,<br>Overcome fear and enmity,<br>All suffering is overcome.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.23" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu can crush the Himālayan king of mountains, let alone lowly ignorance. What six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is skilled in attaining jhāna, skilled in abiding in jhāna, skilled in emerging from jhāna, skilled in the happiness of jhāna, skilled in the range of jhāna, and skilled in inducing jhāna. Possessing these six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu can crush the Himālayan king of mountains, let alone lowly ignorance.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.24" },

{ text: `One who has seen the supreme,<br>And heard the unsurpassed,<br>Gained the unsurpassed,<br>Delights in the unsurpassed training,<br>Established in service,<br>Develops the specific recollections,<br>Connected to seclusion,<br>Attains security, the Deathless,<br>Joyful, not heedless,<br>Careful, guarding virtue,<br>When the time has ripened,<br>Suffering is destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.30" },

{ text: `These six things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu. What six? Not delighting in work, not delighting in talking, not delighting in sleeping, not delighting in company, guarding the sense faculties, and moderation in eating. These six things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.31" },

{ text: `There are these six things, bhikkhus, that do not lead to decline for a bhikkhu. What six? Respect for the Teacher, respect for the Dhamma, respect for the Saṅgha, respect for the training, respect for heedfulness, respect for hospitality. These six things, bhikkhus, do not lead to decline for a bhikkhu.<br><br>A bhikkhu who respects the Teacher,<br>Reveres the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>The training, heedfulness,<br>Respects hospitality,<br>Cannot decline,<br>He is certainly close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.32" },

{ text: `Respecting the Teacher,<br>Respecting the great Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>Fully endowed with moral shame and dread,<br>Deferential and respectful,<br>Cannot decline,<br>He is certainly close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.33" },

{ text: `There are these six things that are part of true knowledge. What six? The perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of non-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. These six things, bhikkhus, are part of true knowledge.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.35" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, there are three factors of the donor and three factors of the recipients. What are the three factors of the donor? Here, bhikkhus, before giving, the donor's mind is pleased; while giving, his mind is serene; after giving, he feels joy. These are the three factors of the donor. What are the three factors of the recipients? Here, bhikkhus, the recipients are either free from greed or practicing the way to be free from greed; free from hatred or practicing the way to be free from hatred; free from delusion or practicing the way to be free from delusion. These are the three factors of the recipients. Thus there are three factors of the donor and three factors of the recipients. Thus, bhikkhus, the gift consists of six factors.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.37" },

{ text: `Before giving, the mind is pleased,<br>When giving, the mind is faithful,<br>After giving, joy arises,<br>This is a complete offering.<br>Free from greed and hatred,<br>Free from delusion, without taints,<br>Those of holy life, restrained,<br>Are the field of merit for offerings.<br>If one purifies oneself,<br>With one's own hand gives,<br>Oneself, in the hereafter,<br>That offering is of great fruit.<br>That offering, the wise,<br>With faith, mind liberated,<br>Without enmity, happy,<br>The wise are born in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.37" },

{ text: `Venerable sirs, you should train yourselves thus: 'We, being those who are devoted to Dhamma, will praise the bhikkhus who meditate.' Venerable sirs, you should train thus. Why is that? Truly, venerable sirs, those excellent persons are hard to find in the world who experience the Deathless element with the body and abide in it.<br>Venerable sirs, you should train yourselves thus: 'We, being meditators, will praise the bhikkhus who are devoted to Dhamma.' Venerable sirs, you should train thus. Why is that? Truly, venerable sirs, those excellent persons are hard to find in the world who, with wisdom, penetrate and see the deep path leading to the goal.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.46" },

{ text: `With unguarded faculties, bhikkhus, for one deficient in sense restraint, virtue is destroyed. With virtue absent, for one deficient in virtue, right concentration is destroyed. With right concentration absent, for one deficient in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is destroyed. With true knowledge and vision absent, for one deficient in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed. With disenchantment and dispassion absent, for one deficient in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with its branches and leaves deficient: then its shoots do not reach completeness, its bark does not reach completeness, its sapwood does not reach completeness, its heartwood does not reach completeness. So too, bhikkhus, with unguarded faculties, for one deficient in sense restraint... the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.50" },

{ text: `With guarded faculties, bhikkhus, for one complete in sense restraint, virtue is complete. With virtue present, for one complete in virtue, right concentration is complete. With right concentration present, for one complete in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is complete. With true knowledge and vision present, for one complete in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are complete. With disenchantment and dispassion present, for one complete in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with its branches and leaves complete: then its shoots reach completeness, its bark reaches completeness, its sapwood reaches completeness, its heartwood reaches completeness. So too, bhikkhus, with guarded faculties, for one complete in sense restraint... the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.50" },

{ text: `- But for an ascetic, Venerable Gotama, what is the desire, what is the proximate practice, what is the support, what is the inclination, what is the final goal?<br>- For an ascetic, brahmin, patience and gentleness are the desire; wisdom is the proximate practice; virtue is the support; non-possession is the inclination; Nibbāna is the final goal.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.52" },

{ text: `Heedfulness, brahmin, is one thing, when developed and cultivated, that encompasses and establishes both benefits: benefit in this present life and benefit in the future life. Just as, brahmin, whatever footprints of living creatures there are, all are included in the footprint of the elephant. The elephant's footprint is declared the foremost among them, so too, brahmin, heedfulness is one thing, when developed and cultivated, that encompasses and establishes both benefits: benefit in this present life and benefit in the future life. Thus, brahmin, heedfulness is one thing, when developed and cultivated, that encompasses and establishes both benefits: benefit in this present life and benefit in the future life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.53" },

{ text: `Sona, when energy is overstrained, it leads to restlessness; when energy is too lax, it leads to laziness. Therefore, Sona, you should establish energy in balance, penetrate the faculties in balance, and there grasp the sign.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.55" },

{ text: `One whose mind inclines to renunciation,<br>The mind tends toward seclusion,<br>One whose mind inclines to non-hatred,<br>The mind tends toward the cessation of clinging,<br>One whose mind inclines to the destruction of craving,<br>The mind tends toward non-delusion,<br>He sees the arising of the base,<br>His mind is rightly liberated.<br>For one rightly liberated,<br>That bhikkhu, with mind purified,<br>There is nothing more to be done,<br>Nothing left to do.<br>Like a solid mountain of rock,<br>The wind cannot shake it,<br>So too, all forms,<br>Tastes, sounds, and scents, touches,<br>And even all phenomena,<br>Desirable, undesirable,<br>Cannot shake him.<br>One who is thus,<br>With mind firmly established, liberated,<br>Sees their nature of cessation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.55" },

{ text: `- Bhante, in my family there is giving. Bhikkhus who are forest-dwellers, almsfood-eaters, rag-robe wearers, Arahants or those practicing the Arahant path, Bhante, such bhikkhus receive alms.<br>- Certainly, householder, this is indeed difficult for you, a layperson enjoying sensual pleasures, bound by children, using Kāsi sandalwood, wearing and anointing with garlands, scents, perfumes, using gold and silver, to know who is an Arahant and who is practicing the Arahant path. A forest-dwelling bhikkhu, householder, if he is restless, arrogant, agitated, talkative, garrulous, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, unconcentrated, with distracted mind, loose faculties — then in that respect he is to be criticized. Nevertheless, householder, make offerings to the Saṅgha. If you make offerings to the Saṅgha, your mind will be serene. If your mind is serene, at death, with the breakup of the body, you will be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.59" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a certain person, while living near the Teacher or near a fellow celibate acting as a preceptor, is the most gentle among the gentle, the most humble among the humble, the most peaceful among the peaceful. But when he leaves the Teacher, leaves the fellow celibate acting as preceptor, he lives in association with bhikkhus, with bhikkhunīs, with male lay followers, female lay followers, with kings and royal ministers, with wanderers and disciples of wanderers. By living in such association, he becomes loose, rough, addicted to talk, and craving attacks his mind. With his mind attacked by craving, he gives up the training and returns to the lay life. Just as, venerable sirs, a grain-eating ox tied with a rope or confined in a pen. Venerable sir, if someone were to say: 'This grain-eating ox will never again go down into the rice field,' would that be said rightly?<br>- No, venerable sir. This is possible, venerable sir: that grain-eating ox, having broken the rope or smashed the pen, could go down into the rice field again.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.60" },

{ text: `Contact, bhikkhus, is one extreme. The origin of contact is the second extreme. The cessation of contact is the middle. Craving is the weaver; because craving weaves, it causes one to be born in this existence. To that extent, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu fully knows what can be fully known, and fully understands what can be fully understood. By fully knowing what can be fully known, and fully understanding what can be fully understood, in this very life he can make an end of suffering.<br><br>One who knows the two extremes,<br>The middle, the wise are not stained,<br>I call that great person,<br>He has gone beyond the weaver.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.61" },


{ text: `- Here, Ānanda, with my mind I know the mind of another person: 'In this person, there are wholesome states and unwholesome states.' At another time, likewise, with my mind I know that person's mind: 'In this person, the wholesome states have disappeared, unwholesome states are present, but the wholesome root has not been cut off. And wholesome states will arise from that wholesome root.' Thus this person will not decline in the future. Just as, Ānanda, seeds that are unbroken, unspoiled, undamaged by wind and heat, still possessing vitality, planted in a well-prepared field — Ānanda, could you know that these seeds will grow, increase, and flourish?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.62" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure: forms cognizable by the eye — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, likable, connected with sensual desire, alluring. Sounds cognizable by the ear... odors cognizable by the nose... tastes cognizable by the tongue... tangibles cognizable by the body — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, likable, connected with sensual desire, alluring. Bhikkhus, though these are not sensual pleasures, they are called 'strands of sensual pleasure' in the Noble One's Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.63" },

{ text: `The thoughts of craving<br>Are a person's sensual pleasures,<br>The beautiful things in the world<br>Are not the sensual pleasures,<br>The thoughts of craving<br>Are a person's sensual pleasures,<br>The beautiful things remain<br>As they are in the world,<br>But the wise<br>Subdue desire for them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.63" },

{ text: `Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who has good friends, good companions, good comrades, who associates with, serves, honors, and respects good friends, and accepts their right view, will fulfill the practice of the Dhamma — this is possible. Having fulfilled the practice of the Dhamma, he will fulfill the learner's practice — this is possible. Having fulfilled the learner's practice, he will fulfill the virtues — this is possible. Having fulfilled the virtues, he will abandon sensual desire, desire for form, or desire for formlessness — this is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.67" },

{ text: `- Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who delights in company, takes pleasure in company, is devoted to delight in company, delights in a group, takes pleasure in a group, is devoted to delight in a group — that he will rejoice in dwelling alone, in seclusion — this is impossible. Not rejoicing in dwelling alone, in seclusion, he will grasp the sign of the mind — this is impossible. Not grasping the sign of the mind, he will fulfill right view — this is impossible. Not fulfilling right view, he will fulfill right concentration — this is impossible. Not fulfilling right concentration, he will abandon the fetters — this is impossible. Not abandoning the fetters, he will realize Nibbāna — this is impossible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.68" },

{ text: `Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who does not delight in company, does not take pleasure in company, is not devoted to delight in company, does not delight in a group, does not take pleasure in a group, is not devoted to delight in a group — that he will rejoice in dwelling alone, in seclusion — this is possible. Rejoicing in dwelling alone, in seclusion, he will grasp the sign of the mind — this is possible. Grasping the sign of the mind, he will fulfill right view — this is possible. Fulfilling right view, he will fulfill right concentration — this is possible. Fulfilling right concentration, he will abandon the fetters — this is possible. Abandoning the fetters, he will realize Nibbāna — this is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.68" },

{ text: `Without abandoning six things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain and abide in the first jhāna. What six? Sensual desire, ill-will, dullness, drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, doubt, and not seeing the danger in sensual pleasures well with right wisdom. Without abandoning these six things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain and abide in the first jhāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.73" },

{ text: `Without abandoning six things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain and abide in the first jhāna. What six? Thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming, perceptions of sensual desire, perceptions of ill-will, perceptions of harming. Without abandoning these six things, bhikkhus, one cannot attain and abide in the first jhāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.74" },

{ text: `- Bhante, a bhikkhu who is an Arahant, with taints destroyed, the holy life fulfilled, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, attained the goal, destroyed the fetter of existence, liberated by final knowledge — he does not think: 'There is one better than me,' or 'There is one equal to me,' or 'There is one inferior to me.'" Thus said the Venerable Sumana. The Teacher approved. Then the Venerable Sumana, thinking, 'The Blessed One has approved me,' rose from his seat, bowed to the Blessed One, circumambulated him keeping the right side toward him, and departed. Then the Blessed One, not long after the Venerable Khema and the Venerable Sumana had left, addressed the bhikkhus: "Thus, bhikkhus, clansmen speak about final knowledge. They speak about the goal but do not refer to themselves. Yet here some foolish persons speak about final knowledge arrogantly, puffed up.<br><br>Neither superior nor inferior,<br>There is no one equal to me,<br>Such thoughts do not<br>Occur to them.<br>Birth is ended,<br>The holy life is accomplished,<br>They have abandoned the fetters,<br>Completely liberated.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.49" },

{ text: `Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who sees any conditioned thing as pleasant will acquire acquiescent patience — this is impossible. Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who sees any conditioned thing as suffering will acquire acquiescent patience — this is possible ...`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.99" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a family that possesses seven factors — if not yet visited, it is not worth visiting; if already visited, it is not worth sitting down in. What seven? They are not pleased to rise up, not pleased to welcome, not pleased to invite to sit; they hide the seat; from much they give little, from excellent things they give inferior things; they give without respect, without reverence. Bhikkhus, a family possessing these seven factors — if not yet visited, it is not worth visiting; if already visited, it is not worth sitting down in. Bhikkhus, a family that possesses seven factors — if not yet visited, it is worth visiting; if already visited, it is worth sitting down in. What seven? They are pleased to rise up, pleased to welcome, pleased to invite to sit; they do not hide the seat; from much they give much, from excellent things they give excellent things; they give with respect, with reverence. Bhikkhus, a family possessing these seven factors — if not yet visited, it is worth visiting; if already visited, it is worth sitting down in.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.13" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the person who, having risen, sinks down again? Here, bhikkhus, a person rises up and thinks: 'Good is faith in wholesome states! Good is moral shame... Good is moral dread... Good is energy... Good is wisdom in wholesome states!' That person's faith does not become established, does not grow, but diminishes. That person's moral shame... moral dread... energy... wisdom does not become established, does not grow, but diminishes. Thus, bhikkhus, is the person who, having risen, sinks down again. Good is energy...`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.15" },

{ text: `These seven things, bhikkhus, lead to a male lay follower's decline. What seven? He neglects to visit the bhikkhus; he is lax in listening to the good Dhamma; he does not train in the higher virtue; he has little confidence in the elder, middle, and newly ordained bhikkhus; he listens to the Dhamma with a mind seeking faults, looking for defects; he seeks outside the Saṅgha for those worthy of offerings; and he serves there first. These seven things, bhikkhus, lead to a male lay follower's decline. These seven things, bhikkhus, lead to a male lay follower's non-decline. What seven? He does not neglect to visit the bhikkhus; he is not lax in listening to the good Dhamma; he trains in the higher virtue; he has much confidence in the elder, middle, and newly ordained bhikkhus; he listens to the Dhamma without a mind seeking faults, without looking for defects; he does not seek outside the Saṅgha for those worthy of offerings; and he serves there first. These seven things, bhikkhus, lead to a male lay follower's non-decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.29" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, when Sāriputta's mind is sluggish, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is sluggish'; when his mind is dull, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is dull'; when his mind is distracted and outwardly directed, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is distracted and outwardly directed.' He understands feelings as they arise, understands feelings as they persist, understands feelings as they cease; he understands perceptions as they arise, understands perceptions as they persist, understands perceptions as they cease; he understands thoughts as they arise, understands thoughts as they persist, understands thoughts as they cease. Regarding states that are suitable or unsuitable, inferior or superior, dark or bright, he well grasps the sign, well attends, well remembers, well penetrates with wisdom. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, before long Sāriputta, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the four analytical knowledges.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.39" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, Sāriputta controls his mind and does not let the mind control him. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, Sāriputta is skilled in concentration, skilled in attaining concentration, skilled in abiding in concentration, skilled in emerging from concentration, skilled in the comfort of concentration, skilled in the range of concentration, and skilled in inducing concentration. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, Sāriputta controls his mind and does not let the mind control him.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.41" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu knows moderation (what is sufficient) when receiving requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu does not know moderation when receiving requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites, then he is not called one who knows moderation. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu knows moderation when receiving requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites, therefore he is called one who knows moderation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.68" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu knows the time: 'This is the time for teaching, this is the time for questioning, this is the time for training, this is the time for meditative seclusion.' Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu does not know the time: 'This is the time for teaching, this is the time for questioning, this is the time for training, this is the time for meditative seclusion,' then he is called one who does not know the time. And, bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu knows the time: 'This is the time for teaching, this is the time for questioning, this is the time for training, this is the time for meditative seclusion,' therefore he is called one who knows the time.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.68" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, a bhikkhu who reveres, respects, and dwells in dependence on the Teacher can abandon the unwholesome and develop the wholesome. Sāriputta, a bhikkhu who reveres, respects, and dwells in dependence on the Dhamma... on the Saṅgha... on the training... on concentration... on energy... Sāriputta, a bhikkhu who reveres, respects, and dwells in dependence on hospitality can abandon the unwholesome and develop the wholesome.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.70" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is a master of the Discipline. What seven? He knows an offense; he knows a non-offense; he knows a light offense; he knows a grave offense; both Pātimokkhas are well transmitted in detail, well analyzed, well regulated, well decided in terms of sutta and in detail; he attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life; by the destruction of the taints, he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is a master of the Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.76" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is cultivated, developed, practiced, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, eight benefits are to be expected. What eight? He sleeps well, wakes up well, does not see bad dreams, is loved by human beings, is loved by non-humans, devas protect him, fire, poison, and sword do not harm him, and if he does not penetrate further, he attains the Brahmā world. Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is cultivated, developed, practiced, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, these eight benefits are to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.1" },

{ text: `One who develops loving-kindness,<br>Mindful, immeasurable,<br>The fetters grow thin,<br>He sees the destruction of attachments.<br><br>With a mind not cruel,<br>Compassionate toward all beings,<br>Therefore he becomes<br>A perfectly pure, excellent one.<br>With a mind of compassion<br>Toward all beings,<br>The noble one well performs<br>Much good merit.<br><br>Having conquered<br>A great multitude of people,<br>Kings and sages<br>By sacrificial rites,<br>The horse sacrifice, human sacrifice,<br>The victory-drinking sacrifice,<br>The luck-throwing sacrifice,<br>The locked-door sacrifice.<br><br>They do not reach one-sixteenth<br>Of one well developed in loving-kindness,<br>As the light of the moon<br>Outshines all the stars.<br><br>He does not kill, nor cause to kill,<br>Does not conquer, nor cause to conquer,<br>With loving-kindness toward all beings,<br>He has enmity toward none.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.1" },

{ text: `Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama is tasteless.' Brahmin, the tastes of forms, tastes of sounds, tastes of odors, tastes of flavors, tastes of touches — these tastes the Tathāgata has abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future. 'Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama is penniless.' Brahmin, the wealth of forms, wealth of sounds, wealth of odors, wealth of flavors, wealth of touches — these forms of wealth the Tathāgata has abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.11" },

{ text: `Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama teaches non-action.' Brahmin, I teach non-action regarding evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. I teach non-action regarding evil, unwholesome states. 'Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama teaches annihilation.' Brahmin, I declare the annihilation of greed, hatred, and delusion. I declare the annihilation of evil, unwholesome states. 'Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama is disgusted.' Brahmin, I am disgusted with evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. I am disgusted with the acquisition of evil, unwholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.11" },

{ text: `Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama is a nihilist.' Brahmin, I teach the Dhamma for the nihilating of greed, hatred, and delusion. I teach the Dhamma for the nihilating of evil, unwholesome states. 'Brahmin, there is a method by which, if one speaks rightly of me, one could say: 'The ascetic Gotama is an ascetic.' Brahmin, I declare that one should be ascetic regarding evil, unwholesome states, evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. Brahmin, for whom evil, unwholesome states, evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action have been asceticized, abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future — him I declare to be an ascetic. Brahmin, for the Tathāgata, evil, unwholesome states, evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action have been asceticized, abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.11" },

{ text: `- To what extent, Bhante, is a male lay follower one who practices for his own benefit and for the benefit of others?<br>- Jīvaka, when a male lay follower himself possesses faith and encourages others to possess faith; when he himself observes the precepts and encourages others to observe the precepts; when he himself gives and encourages others to give; when he himself desires to visit the bhikkhus and encourages others to visit the bhikkhus; when he himself desires to listen to the good Dhamma and encourages others to listen to the good Dhamma; when he himself remembers the teachings he has heard and encourages others to remember the teachings they have heard; when he himself reflects on the meaning of the teachings he has remembered and encourages others to reflect on the meaning; when, having himself understood the meaning and understood the Dhamma, he practices Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, and encourages others, after understanding the meaning and understanding the Dhamma, to practice Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma. To that extent, Jīvaka, is a male lay follower one who practices for his own benefit and for the benefit of others.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.26" },

{ text: `Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates. What eight? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu praises those who are not liked, criticizes those who are liked, desires gain, desires honor, has no moral shame, has no moral dread, has evil desires, and has wrong view. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates. And, bhikkhus, what eight? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not praise those who are not liked, does not criticize those who are liked, does not desire gain, does not desire honor, has moral shame, has moral dread, has few desires, and has right view. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.3" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight kinds of giving. What eight? One gives because a person has come; one gives out of fear; one gives thinking: 'He gave to me'; one gives thinking: 'He will give to me'; one gives thinking: 'Giving is good'; one gives thinking: 'I cook, these people do not cook. It is not proper for me, the cook, not to give to those who do not cook'; one gives thinking: 'By this giving of mine, a good reputation will spread'; one gives for the adornment of the mind, for the equipment of the mind. Bhikkhus, these are the eight kinds of giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.31" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight bases for giving. What eight? One gives out of desire; one gives out of hatred; one gives out of delusion; one gives out of fear; one gives thinking: 'Earlier our ancestors gave, they did this before. It is not proper for me to let this ancient tradition be neglected'; one gives thinking: 'Having given this gift, after death, with the breakup of the body, I will be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world'; one gives thinking: 'When I give this gift, my mind becomes serene, and joy and happiness arise'; one gives for the adornment of the mind, for the equipment of the mind. Bhikkhus, these are the eight bases for giving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.33" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has abandoned killing living beings, refrains from killing. Bhikkhus, by abandoning killing, a noble disciple gives freedom from fear to countless beings, gives freedom from enmity to countless beings, gives freedom from harm to countless beings. Having given freedom from fear, freedom from enmity, freedom from harm to countless beings, he himself has a share in boundless freedom from fear, freedom from enmity, freedom from harm. Bhikkhus, this is the first giving, a great giving, known as primal, of long standing, known as ancient tradition, unadulterated before, unadulterated now, not to be adulterated in the future, not criticized by wise ascetics and brahmins.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.39" },

{ text: `Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates. What eight? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu desires gain, desires honor, desires praise, does not know the right time, does not know moderation, is impure, talks much, and reviles and reproaches his fellow celibates. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates. What eight? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not desire gain, does not desire honor, does not desire praise, knows the right time, knows moderation, is pure, does not talk much, and does not revile or reproach his fellow celibates. Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.4" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned killing living beings, refrained from killing, laid down the rod, laid down the sword, have moral shame and dread, have loving-kindness, and dwell compassionate for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon killing living beings, refrain from killing, lay down the rod, lay down the sword, have moral shame and dread, have loving-kindness, and dwell compassionate for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.41" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned non-celibacy, live the celibate life, live aloof, abstain from the vulgar practice of sexual intercourse. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon non-celibacy, live the celibate life, live aloof, abstain from the vulgar practice of sexual intercourse. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.41" },

{ text: `Not killing, not stealing,<br>Not speaking falsely,<br>Not drinking alcohol, intoxicants,<br>Celibacy, no sexual intercourse,<br>Not eating at night,<br>Avoiding untimely food.<br><br>Not wearing garlands,<br>Not using perfumes,<br>Sleep on a low bed<br>Or spread a mat and lie down.<br>This eight-factor uposatha<br>Is proclaimed by the Buddha,<br>It ends all suffering.<br><br>The moon and the sun,<br>Beautiful and radiant,<br>They shine in the sky,<br>Illumining all directions,<br>Wherever they pass,<br>Darkness disappears.<br><br>Wealth in this world,<br>Pearls and precious gems,<br>And bright beryl,<br>Gold refined or natural,<br>Or gold excavated by ants.<br><br>They are not worth<br>One sixteenth part<br>Of observing the eight-factored precepts.<br>The light of all stars<br>Cannot equal the moon's light.<br><br>Whether a man or a woman,<br>One of virtuous conduct,<br>Observing the eight-factored precepts,<br>Doing wholesome meritorious deeds,<br>Bringing much happiness,<br>Blameless everywhere,<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.43" },

{ text: `There are these four things, Byagghapajja, that lead to a clansman's future happiness and future well-being. What four? Accomplishment in faith, accomplishment in virtue, accomplishment in giving, accomplishment in wisdom. And, Byagghapajja, what is accomplishment in faith? Here, Byagghapajja, a clansman has faith, he believes in the Tathāgata's enlightenment: 'This Blessed One is... teacher of devas and humans, the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.' Byagghapajja, this is called accomplishment in faith. And, Byagghapajja, what is accomplishment in virtue? Here, Byagghapajja, a clansman abstains from killing... abstains from intoxication with liquor and fermented drink. Byagghapajja, this is called accomplishment in virtue. And, Byagghapajja, what is accomplishment in giving? Here, Byagghapajja, a clansman dwells at home with a mind free from the stain of miserliness, giving generously, with open hand, delighting in relinquishment, ready to be asked, delighting in distributing gifts. Byagghapajja, this is called accomplishment in giving. And, Byagghapajja, what is accomplishment in wisdom? Here, Byagghapajja, a clansman has wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, with noble penetration leading to the complete destruction of suffering. Byagghapajja, this is called accomplishment in wisdom. These four things, Byagghapajja, lead to a clansman's future happiness and future well-being.<br><br>Resourceful in work,<br>Not heedless, agile,<br>Living a balanced life,<br>He preserves his earned wealth.<br><br>Having faith, possessing virtue,<br>Giving, not stingy,<br>He clears the supreme path,<br>Safe for the future.<br><br>These are the eight qualities<br>That faithful householders seek,<br>The truthful ones declare,<br>They lead to bliss in both worlds.<br><br>Happiness in the present,<br>And well-being in the future,<br>This is the householder's dwelling,<br>Giving increases merit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.54" },

{ text: `These eight worldly conditions, bhikkhus, revolve around the world, and the world revolves around these eight worldly conditions. What eight? Gain and loss, fame and disgrace, praise and blame, happiness and pain. These eight worldly conditions, bhikkhus, revolve around the world, and the world revolves around these eight worldly conditions. For an uninstructed ordinary person, bhikkhus, there arise gain, loss, fame, disgrace, praise, blame, happiness, pain. For a learned noble disciple, bhikkhus, there also arise gain, loss, fame, disgrace, praise, blame, happiness, pain. Here, bhikkhus, what is the distinction, the difference, the disparity between a learned noble disciple and an uninstructed ordinary person?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.6" },

{ text: `For an uninstructed ordinary person, bhikkhus, gain arises. He does not reflect: 'This gain has arisen for me. It is impermanent, suffering, subject to change.' He does not know it as it really is. Loss... fame... disgrace... blame... praise... happiness... pain arises. He does not reflect: 'This pain has arisen for me. It is impermanent, suffering, subject to change.' He does not know it as it really is. Thus gain obsesses his mind and remains; loss obsesses his mind and remains; fame obsesses his mind and remains; disgrace obsesses his mind and remains; praise obsesses his mind and remains; blame obsesses his mind and remains; happiness obsesses his mind and remains; pain obsesses his mind and remains. He acquiesces in the gain that has arisen and opposes loss; he acquiesces in the fame that has arisen and opposes disgrace; he acquiesces in the praise that has arisen and opposes blame; he acquiesces in the happiness that has arisen and opposes pain. Being thus full of acquiescence and opposition, he is not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not freed from suffering.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.6" },

{ text: `Gain and loss,<br>Fame and disgrace,<br>Praise and blame,<br>Happiness and pain,<br>These conditions are impermanent,<br>Not lasting, subject to change.<br><br>Knowing them, mindful,<br>The wise person observes their change,<br>What is agreeable does not disturb him,<br>What is disagreeable does not arouse hatred.<br><br>All acquiescence and opposition<br>Have disappeared, no longer remain,<br>Having known the path,<br>Without defilement, without sorrow,<br>Rightly understanding existence,<br>He has gone to the far shore.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who develops mindfulness of death thinking: 'May I, as long as I eat and swallow one morsel of food, attend to the Blessed One's teaching. I have done much in that way.' Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who develops mindfulness of death thinking: 'May I, as long as when I breathe in, I breathe out, or after breathing out, I breathe in, attend to the Blessed One's teaching. I have done much in that way.' Bhikkhus, that bhikkhu is called one who dwells heedful, who sharpens mindfulness of death well for the destruction of the taints. Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train thus: 'We will dwell heedful. We will sharpen mindfulness of death well for the destruction of the taints.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.73" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, when a cloth is on fire or the head is on fire, to extinguish that cloth or head, one should arouse extraordinary desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. So too, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu, to abandon those evil unwholesome states, should arouse extraordinary desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension. If that bhikkhu, while reflecting, knows thus: 'I do not have evil unwholesome states that are not yet abandoned; if I were to die today, they could be an obstacle for me.' Then, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should dwell with joy and delight, and day and night he should train in wholesome states. Bhikkhus, mindfulness of death, developed and cultivated in this way, is of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.74" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, many other devas came to me and said: 'Bhante, when we lived among humans in the past, renunciants without families came to our homes. Bhante, we rose up, we bowed, we offered them seats, we shared according to our ability and strength, we sat around to listen to the Dhamma, we lent ear to the Dhamma, after listening we remembered the Dhamma, we reflected on the meaning of the Dhamma we had remembered, after understanding the meaning and understanding the Dhamma, we practiced Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma. Bhante, because we fulfilled our duties, we did not have regret or remorse, and we were reborn with an excellent body.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.19" },

{ text: `Both in the past and now, Sajjha, I have said: 'A bhikkhu who is an Arahant, with taints destroyed, accomplished, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, attained the goal, destroyed the fetter of existence, rightly liberated — he cannot transgress nine things: A bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot intentionally deprive a living being of life; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot take what is not given, that is, stealing; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot engage in sexual intercourse; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot knowingly speak falsely; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot enjoy sensual pleasures from stored-up goods as he did when he was a householder. A bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot reject the Buddha; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot reject the Dhamma; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot reject the Saṅgha; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot reject the training.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.8" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected. What six? With thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill-will, thoughts of harming, perceptions of sensual desire, perceptions of ill-will, perceptions of harming. Possessing these six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.75" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected. With thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill-will, thoughts of non-harming, perceptions of renunciation, perceptions of non-ill-will, perceptions of non-harming. Possessing these six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.75" },

{ text: `Without abandoning six things, bhikkhus, one cannot realize a superior human state, the truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision. What six? Forgetfulness, lack of clear comprehension, unguarded sense faculties, lack of moderation in eating, deceit, and flattery (false talk). Without abandoning these six things, bhikkhus, one cannot realize a superior human state, the truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.77" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells with much joy and happiness, and the cause for the destruction of the taints is established in him. What six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu delights in the Dhamma, delights in development, delights in abandonment, delights in seclusion, delights in non-hatred, delights in non-frivolous talk. Possessing these six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells with much joy and happiness, and the cause for the destruction of the taints is established in him.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.78" },

{ text: `If a bhikkhu possesses six qualities, bhikkhus, whether by day or by night, a decline in wholesome states is to be expected, not growth. What six? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has great desires, is discontented, is not satisfied with any kind of basic necessities such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, medicinal requisites; he has no faith, is immoral, is lazy, has forgetful mindfulness, and has evil wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.84" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu can realize the unsurpassed cooling. What six? Here, bhikkhus, when the mind should be restrained, he restrains the mind; when the mind should be uplifted, he uplifts the mind; when the mind should be gladdened, he gladdens the mind; when the mind should be left equanimous and observed, he leaves the mind equanimous and observes; he inclines toward the supreme; he delights in Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.85" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, even if one hears the good Dhamma, one cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What six? He is possessed of kamma-obstruction, defilement-obstruction, result-obstruction; he has no faith, no desire (to listen), and he has evil wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.86" },

{ text: `Possessing six qualities, bhikkhus, even if one hears the good Dhamma, one cannot enter the fixed course of rightness in wholesome states. What six? When the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata is being taught, he does not want to listen, does not lend an ear, does not apply his mind to understand; he grasps what is not beneficial and rejects what is beneficial; he does not possess acquiescent patience.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.88" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these six impossible cases. What six? A person possessed of right view cannot live without reverence and deference toward the Teacher; a person possessed of right view cannot live without reverence and deference toward the good Dhamma; a person possessed of right view cannot live without reverence and deference toward the Saṅgha; a person possessed of right view cannot live without reverence and deference toward the training; a person possessed of right view cannot revert to what should not be reverted to; a person possessed of right view cannot bring about an eighth state of existence. Bhikkhus, these are the six impossible cases.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.92", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.92" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these six impossible cases. What six? A person possessed of right view cannot regard any conditioned thing as permanent; a person possessed of right view cannot regard any conditioned thing as pleasurable; a person possessed of right view cannot regard any conditioned thing as self; a person possessed of right view cannot commit an immediate retribution deed; a person possessed of right view cannot seek purification through special rites and rituals; a person possessed of right view cannot seek outside the Saṅgha for those worthy of offerings. Bhikkhus, these are the six impossible cases.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.93" },

{ text: `Truly, bhikkhus, that a bhikkhu who sees any conditioned thing as impermanent will acquire acquiescent patience — this is possible. Having acquired acquiescent patience, he will enter the fixed course of rightness — this is possible. Having entered the fixed course of rightness, he will realize the fruit of stream-entry, the fruit of once-return, the fruit of non-return, or the fruit of Arahantship — this is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.98" },

{ text: `Seeing six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of impermanence without limit in all conditioned things. What six? 'All conditioned things will appear to me as not standing fast; my mind will not delight in the entire world; my mind will emerge from the entire world; my mind will incline toward Nibbāna; my fetters will come to destruction; and I will attain the supreme ascetic practice.' Seeing these six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of impermanence without limit in all conditioned things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.102" },

{ text: `Seeing these six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of suffering without limit in all conditioned things. What six? 'The perception of Nibbāna will be established in me regarding all conditioned things, like a murderer raising his sword; my mind will emerge from the entire world; I will become one who sees peace in Nibbāna; the underlying tendencies in me will be uprooted; I will be one who has done what had to be done; I will serve the Teacher with loving-kindness.' Seeing these six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of suffering without limit in all conditioned things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.103", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.103" },

{ text: `Seeing six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of non-self without limit in all conditioned things. What six? 'I will not partake in anything in the entire world; the "I-making" in me will be cut off; the "mine-making" in me will be cut off; I will possess wisdom that is not shared with others; causes and phenomena born of causes will be well seen by me.' Seeing these six benefits, bhikkhus, is enough for a bhikkhu to establish the perception of non-self without limit in all conditioned things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.104" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three things. What three? Discontentment, lack of clear comprehension, and great desires. Bhikkhus, these are the three things. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed. What three? For the abandonment of discontentment, contentment should be developed. For the abandonment of lack of clear comprehension, clear comprehension should be developed. For the abandonment of great desires, few desires should be developed. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.114" },


{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three things. What three? Evil speech, evil friendship, and an agitated mind. Bhikkhus, these are the three things. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed. What three? For the abandonment of evil speech, good speech should be developed. For the abandonment of evil friendship, good friendship should be developed. For the abandonment of an agitated mind, mindfulness of breathing should be developed. For the abandonment of those three things, bhikkhus, these three things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.115" },

{ text: `For direct knowledge of greed, bhikkhus, six things should be developed. What six? The perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of non-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. For direct knowledge of greed, bhikkhus, these six things should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.142", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.142" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu desires gain, desires honor, desires praise, has no moral shame, has no moral dread, has evil desires, and has wrong view. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is not loved, liked, respected, or emulated by his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.1" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu does not desire gain, does not desire honor, does not desire praise, has moral shame, has moral dread, has few desires, and has right view. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is loved, liked, respected, and emulated by his fellow celibates.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.1" },

{ text: `The power of faith and the power of energy,<br>The power of moral shame and the power of moral dread,<br>The power of mindfulness and the power of concentration,<br>And wisdom, the seventh power;<br>A bhikkhu with these powers,<br>Lives happily and wisely,<br>Reflecting on the Dhamma appropriately,<br>Clearly seeing the goal with wisdom,<br>Like a lamp going out,<br>With mind liberated.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.3" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these seven powers. What seven? The power of faith, the power of energy, the power of moral shame, the power of moral dread, the power of mindfulness, the power of concentration, the power of wisdom. And, bhikkhus, what is the power of faith? Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has faith, he believes in the Tathāgata's enlightenment: 'This Blessed One is... the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.' Bhikkhus, this is called the power of faith.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.4" },

{ text: `These things, bhikkhus, are seven things. The power of faith and the power of energy, The power of moral shame and the power of moral dread, The power of mindfulness and the power of concentration, And wisdom, the seventh power; A bhikkhu with these powers, Lives happily and wisely, Reflecting on the Dhamma appropriately, Clearly seeing the goal with wisdom, Like a lamp going out, With mind liberated.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.4" },

{ text: `The wealth of faith and the wealth of virtue,<br>The wealth of moral shame and the wealth of moral dread,<br>The wealth of learning and the wealth of giving,<br>And wisdom, the seventh wealth;<br>Whoever has these treasures,<br>Whether woman or man,<br>Is called not poor,<br>Their life is not in vain.<br>Therefore faith and virtue,<br>Serene confidence and seeing the Dhamma,<br>The wise, focusing their minds,<br>Remember the Buddha's words.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.6" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these seven excellent qualities. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu ardently practices the training and in the future aspires to practice the training; he ardently examines the Dhamma and in the future aspires to examine the Dhamma; he ardently subdues desire and in the future aspires to subdue desire; he ardently engages in meditative seclusion and in the future aspires to engage in meditative seclusion; he ardently strives with energy and in the future aspires to strive with energy; he ardently practices mindful wisdom and in the future aspires to practice mindful wisdom; he ardently penetrates knowledge and vision and in the future aspires to penetrate knowledge and vision. Bhikkhus, these are the seven grounds for being praised.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.20" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus is not obsessed by craving, which leads to renewed existence, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus delights in quiet dwellings, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus themselves establish mindfulness, so that well-behaved fellow practitioners who have not yet come will come, and those who have come will dwell at ease, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.23" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus gathers in harmony, disperses in harmony, and carries out Saṅgha business in harmony, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus does not decree what has not been decreed, does not abolish what has been decreed, and lives following the training rules as decreed, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus honors, respects, reveres, and makes offerings to the elder bhikkhus — those of long experience, long ordained, the fathers and leaders of the Saṅgha — and listens to their guidance, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.23" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus does not delight in worldly work, does not take pleasure in worldly work, is not devoted to delight in worldly work, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus does not delight in idle talk, does not take pleasure in idle talk, is not devoted to delight in idle talk, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus does not delight in sleeping, does not take pleasure in sleeping, is not devoted to delight in sleeping, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus does not delight in company, does not take pleasure in company, is not devoted to delight in company, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.24" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what are the seven non-declining qualities? Bhikkhus, when the community of bhikkhus has faith, has moral shame, has moral dread, is learned, is energetic, has mindfulness, and has wisdom, then, bhikkhus, the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline. Bhikkhus, when these seven non-declining qualities are maintained among the bhikkhus, when the bhikkhus are instructed in these seven non-declining qualities, then the community of bhikkhus will grow and not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.25" },

{ text: `Possessing seven factors, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should be associated with as a friend. What seven? He gives what is hard to give, does what is hard to do, endures what is hard to endure, reveals his own secrets, keeps others' secrets, does not abandon one in misfortune, and does not despise one who is destitute. Possessing these seven factors, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should be associated with as a friend.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.36" },

{ text: `A friend who gives what is hard to give,<br>Does what is hard to do,<br>Endures words<br>That are hard to endure,<br>Reveals his own secrets,<br>Keeps others' secrets,<br>Does not abandon one in misfortune,<br>Does not despise one who is destitute —<br>In these cases,<br>If one finds such a person,<br>Whoever needs a friend,<br>Should associate with that friend.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.36" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu before long, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the four analytical knowledges. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, when his mind is sluggish, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is sluggish'; when his mind is dull, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is dull'; when his mind is distracted and outwardly directed, he knows as it really is: 'My mind is distracted and outwardly directed.' He understands feelings as they arise, understands feelings as they persist, understands feelings as they cease; he understands perceptions as they arise, understands perceptions as they persist, understands perceptions as they cease; he understands thoughts as they arise, understands thoughts as they persist, understands thoughts as they cease. Regarding states that are suitable or unsuitable, inferior or superior, dark or bright, he well grasps the sign, well attends, well remembers, well penetrates with wisdom. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu before long, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the four analytical knowledges.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.38" },

{ text: `- Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu controls his mind and does not let his mind control him. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is skilled in concentration, skilled in attaining concentration, skilled in abiding in concentration, skilled in emerging from concentration, skilled in the comfort of concentration, skilled in the range of concentration, and skilled in inducing concentration. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu controls his mind and does not let his mind control him.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.40" },

{ text: `Sāriputta, in this Dhamma and Discipline, it is not possible to specify a bhikkhu as praiseworthy solely by counting up to five. These seven excellent qualities, Sāriputta, I have myself, with direct knowledge, realized, attained, abided in, and declared. What seven? Here, Sāriputta, a bhikkhu ardently practices the training and in the future aspires to practice the training; he ardently examines the Dhamma and in the future aspires to examine the Dhamma; he ardently subdues desire and in the future aspires to subdue desire; he ardently engages in meditative seclusion and in the future aspires to engage in meditative seclusion; he ardently strives with energy and in the future aspires to strive with energy; he ardently practices mindful wisdom and in the future aspires to practice mindful wisdom; he ardently penetrates knowledge and vision and in the future aspires to penetrate knowledge and vision. Sāriputta, these seven excellent qualities I have myself, with direct knowledge, realized, attained, abided in, and declared.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.42" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these seven requisites for concentration. What seven? Right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness. One-pointedness of mind, bhikkhus, with these seven as requisites, is called noble right concentration, bhikkhus, with its supports and requisites.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.45" },

{ text: `These three fires, brahmin, are to be honored, respected, and offered to, and they should bring right happiness. What three? The fire worthy of honor, the householder's fire, and the fire worthy of offerings. And, brahmin, what is the fire worthy of honor? Here, brahmin, a person's mother and father — this, brahmin, is called the fire worthy of honor. Why is that? Because this fire worthy of honor is the means for giving birth and for raising. Therefore, brahmin, this fire worthy of honor should be honored, respected, and offered to, and it should bring right happiness. And, brahmin, what is the householder's fire? Here, brahmin, a person's children, wife, servants, messengers, or workers — this, brahmin, is called the householder's fire. Therefore, this householder's fire should be honored, respected, and offered to, and it should bring right happiness. And, brahmin, what is the fire worthy of offerings? Here, brahmin, those ascetics and brahmins who have abandoned conceit and heedlessness, who live patiently and gently, each one taming himself, each one calming himself, each one pacifying himself — this, brahmin, is called the fire worthy of offerings. Therefore, this fire worthy of offerings should be honored, respected, and offered to, and it should bring right happiness. Brahmin, these three fires are to be honored, respected, and offered to, and they should bring right happiness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.47" },

{ text: `The perception of foulness, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, is of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless — so it is said. For what reason is it said? Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu frequently dwells in the perception of foulness, his mind retreats, turns back, and rolls back from sexual intercourse, and does not stretch out; equanimity or revulsion becomes established in him. Just as, bhikkhus, a cock's feather or a sinew thrown into a fire retreats, turns back, and rolls back, and does not stretch out; so too, bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu frequently dwells in the perception of foulness, his mind retreats, turns back, and rolls back from sexual intercourse, and does not stretch out; equanimity or revulsion becomes established in him. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu frequently dwells in the perception of foulness, yet his mind runs and stretches out toward sexual intercourse, and revulsion does not become established in him, then that bhikkhu should understand: 'The perception of foulness has not been developed by me; there is no distinction between before and after in me; I have not attained the fruit of development.' Therein, he is clearly comprehending thus. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu frequently dwells in the perception of foulness, and his mind retreats, turns back, and rolls back from sexual intercourse, and does not stretch out; equanimity or revulsion becomes established in him, then that bhikkhu should understand: 'The perception of foulness has been developed by me; there is a distinction between before and after in me; I have attained the fruit of development.' Therein, he is clearly comprehending thus. 'The perception of foulness, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, is of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless' — it is for this reason that it is said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.49" },

{ text: `A woman, bhikkhus, attending to her own female faculty, female behavior, female appearance, female nature, female desires, female voice, female adornments, becomes attached and delighted there. Being attached and delighted there, she attends to the external male faculty, male behavior, male appearance, male nature, male desires, male voice, male adornments, and becomes attached and delighted there. Being attached and delighted there, she desires external bonding. Through that bonding, joy and happiness arise, and she desires that joy and happiness. Bhikkhus, because of delighting in their own femininity, beings become bonded with men. Thus, bhikkhus, a woman does not escape from her femininity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.51" },

{ text: `A man, bhikkhus, attending to his own male faculty, male behavior, male appearance, male nature, male desires, male voice, male adornments, becomes attached and delighted there. Being attached and delighted there, he attends to the external female faculty, female behavior, female appearance, female nature, female desires, female voice, female adornments, and becomes attached and delighted there. Being attached and delighted there, he desires external bonding. Through that bonding, joy and happiness arise, and he desires that joy and happiness. Bhikkhus, because of delighting in their own masculinity, beings become bonded with women. Thus, bhikkhus, a man does not escape from his masculinity.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.51" },

{ text: `Here, Sāriputta, a certain person gives with a longing mind, gives with a bound mind, gives with a mind longing for accumulation, giving with the thought: 'I will enjoy this in the hereafter.' Giving thus, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Four Great Kings. And when that kamma is exhausted, that spiritual power, that reputation, that authority is exhausted, he becomes a 'returner,' returning to this state.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.52" },

{ text: `Here, Sāriputta, someone gives not with a longing mind, not with a bound mind, not with a mind longing for accumulation, not with the thought: 'I will enjoy this in the hereafter', not with the thought: 'It is good to give', not with the thought: 'This was given in the past, done by ancestors in the past, I should not let this family tradition be neglected', not with the thought: 'By giving this gift, my mind becomes serene, and joy arises.' But he gives for the adornment of the mind, for the equipment of the mind. Giving thus, after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in companionship with the devas of the Brahmā assembly. And when that kamma is exhausted, that spiritual power, that reputation, that authority is exhausted, he becomes a non-returner, not returning to this state.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.52" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are four things that the Tathāgata does not conceal, and regarding three things he has no fault. What are the four things the Tathāgata does not conceal? Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's bodily action is pure. The Tathāgata has no evil bodily action that he would need to conceal, thinking: 'Let others not know this of me!' Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's verbal action is pure. The Tathāgata has no evil verbal action that he would need to conceal... Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's mental action is pure. The Tathāgata has no evil mental action that he would need to conceal... Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata's livelihood is pure. The Tathāgata has no wrong livelihood that he would need to conceal, thinking: 'Let others not know this of me!'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.58" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, possessing seven qualities, a bhikkhu before long destroys the taints... realizes, attains, and abides. What seven? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has faith, has virtue, is learned, dwells in meditative seclusion, is energetic, has mindfulness, and has wisdom. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu before long, by destroying the taints, realizes, attains, and abides.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.60" },

{ text: `Therefore, Moggallāna, you should train thus: 'I will not speak provoking words.' Thus, Moggallāna, you should train. When there are provoking words, Moggallāna, then much back-and-forth speech is to be expected. When there is much back-and-forth speech, then there is agitation. For one who is agitated, there is no sense restraint. For one without sense restraint, the mind is far from concentration. Moggallāna, I do not praise all kinds of association, but neither do I refrain from praising all kinds of association. Truly, Moggallāna, I do not praise association with laypeople for those gone forth. But association with dwellings that are quiet, free from noise, free from the breath of crowds, solitary, remote from people, suitable for meditative seclusion — I praise association with such dwellings.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.61" },

{ text: `The angry person is ugly,<br>He sleeps in pain,<br>Having gained benefits,<br>He experiences loss instead.<br>Anger harms him<br>With body and with speech,<br>An angry person conquered,<br>His wealth is destroyed.<br>Driven mad by anger,<br>His reputation is destroyed,<br>Relatives and friends<br>Avoid the angry person.<br>Anger brings loss,<br>Anger agitates the mind,<br>Fear arises from within,<br>That person does not know.<br>Anger does not know benefit,<br>Anger does not see the Dhamma,<br>Whoever is conquered by anger,<br>That person is in darkness.<br>An angry person delights<br>In doing evil as if good,<br>Later, when anger ceases,<br>He suffers as if burned by fire,<br>Like a smoky fire,<br>Seen flickering and burning,<br>When anger spreads,<br>When a youth gets angry,<br>Without shame or fear,<br>His speech is not respectful.<br>Conquered by anger,<br>He has no island, no refuge.<br>Deeds that bring remorse<br>Are far from the true Dhamma.<br>I will declare them — listen to the declaration:<br>Anger kills even one's father,<br>Anger kills even one's mother,<br>Anger kills a brahmin,<br>Anger kills an ordinary person.<br>Because it is the mother who nurtures,<br>One sees this world,<br>Yet an angry ordinary person<br>Kills the one who gave life.<br>Beings use themselves as example,<br>They love themselves as supreme,<br>Yet an ordinary person kills himself,<br>In many forms of madness,<br>With a sword he kills himself,<br>Mad, he drinks poison,<br>He hangs himself with a rope,<br>In a mountain cave,<br>Killing actions<br>That cause one's own death.<br>They act without knowing,<br>The angry person harms others,<br>In the form of anger,<br>Māra's trap lies hidden in the mind.<br>Subdue and cut it off<br>With wisdom, energy, right view,<br>The wise cut off<br>Each and every unwholesome state.<br>Thus training in the Dhamma,<br>Do not let the mind be discouraged,<br>Free from hatred, without distress,<br>Free from greed, without envy,<br>Subduing, abandoning anger,<br>Taintless, enter Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.64" },

{ text: `When moral shame and dread are absent, bhikkhus, for one deficient in moral shame and dread, sense restraint is destroyed. When sense restraint is absent, for one deficient in sense restraint, virtue is destroyed. When virtue is absent, for one deficient in virtue, right concentration is destroyed. When right concentration is absent, for one deficient in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is destroyed. When true knowledge and vision is absent, for one deficient in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed. When disenchantment and dispassion are absent, for one deficient in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree lacking branches and leaves: its shoots do not reach completeness, its bark does not reach completeness, its sapwood does not reach completeness, its heartwood does not reach completeness. So too, bhikkhus, when moral shame and dread are absent, for one deficient in moral shame and dread... the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.65" },

{ text: `When moral shame and dread are present, bhikkhus, for one complete in moral shame and dread, sense restraint is complete. When sense restraint is present, for one complete in sense restraint, virtue is complete. When virtue is present, for one complete in virtue, right concentration is complete. When right concentration is present, for one complete in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is complete. When true knowledge and vision is present, for one complete in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are complete. When disenchantment and dispassion are present, for one complete in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with branches and leaves: its shoots reach completeness, its bark reaches completeness, its sapwood reaches completeness, its heartwood reaches completeness. So too, bhikkhus, when moral shame and dread are present, for one complete in moral shame and dread... the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.65" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there is a moat, both deep and wide, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has moral shame. He is ashamed of evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. He is ashamed of falling into evil, unwholesome states. Using moral shame as the moat, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this second excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there is a surrounding rampart, both high and wide, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has moral dread. He dreads evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action. He dreads falling into evil, unwholesome states. Using moral dread as the rampart, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this third excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there are many weapons stored, such as bows and arrows and spears, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple is learned, remembers what he has learned, accumulates what he has learned. Those teachings that are beautiful in the beginning, beautiful in the middle, beautiful in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life — such teachings he has learned much, memorized, recited verbally, investigated with the mind, and well penetrated by right view. Using learning as the weapon, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this fourth excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there are many stationed troops, such as elephant riders, cavalry, charioteers, archers, standard-bearers, quartermasters, supply officers, brave princes, shock troops, great elephants, heroes, armored soldiers, and slaves' sons, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Using energy as the army, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this fifth excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there is a gatekeeper who is wise, intelligent, discerning, blocking strangers and admitting acquaintances, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has mindfulness, endowed with supreme mindfulness and recollection, remembering and recollecting what was done and said long ago. Using mindfulness as the gatekeeper, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this sixth excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, in a king's frontier fortress there is a high, wide wall, with a coating of plaster on the outside, to protect those inside the fortress and to keep out those outside. So too, bhikkhus, a noble disciple has wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, with the noble penetration leading to the complete destruction of suffering. Using wisdom as the plaster coating, bhikkhus, the noble disciple abandons the unwholesome, develops the wholesome, abandons what is blameworthy, develops what is blameless, and keeps himself pure. With this seventh excellent quality he is accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.67" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, even if a bhikkhu who is not devoted to development wishes: 'May my mind be liberated from the taints without clinging!' — yet his mind is not liberated from the taints without clinging. Why is that? It should be said: because he has not developed. Not developed what? He has not developed the four establishments of mindfulness, not developed the four right efforts, not developed the four bases of psychic power, not developed the five faculties, not developed the five powers, not developed the seven factors of enlightenment, not developed the Noble Eightfold Path.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.71" },

{ text: `I declare to you, bhikkhus, I make known to you, bhikkhus: For an immoral person, of evil character, impure, it would be better to have a strong man take a red-hot iron plate, blazing, flaming, and wrap it around his body. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, from that cause he might meet death or death-like suffering, but not because of that cause, after death, with the breakup of the body, would he be reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. But when an immoral person, of evil character, impure in conduct... impure, enjoys the robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites offered out of faith by wealthy nobles, wealthy brahmins, or wealthy householders, then, bhikkhus, that leads to his long-term harm and suffering, and after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.<br>Therefore, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'When we enjoy the requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites of those donors, may our conduct be of great fruit and great benefit. And may our going forth not be in vain, but fruitful and rewarding.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.72" },

{ text: `Possessing seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is a master of the Discipline. What seven? He knows an offense; he knows a non-offense; he knows a light offense; he knows a grave offense; he is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules; he attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life; by the destruction of the taints, he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Possessing these seven qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is a master of the Discipline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.75" },

{ text: `Upāli, those things that you know: 'These things do not lead to complete disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna' — then, Upāli, you should definitely hold: 'This is not the Dhamma, this is not the Discipline, this is not the Teacher's teaching.' And, Upāli, those things that you know: 'These things lead to complete disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna' — then, Upāli, you should definitely hold: 'This is the Dhamma, this is the Discipline, this is the Teacher's teaching.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.83" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is cultivated, developed, practiced, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, eight benefits are to be expected. What eight?<br>He sleeps well, wakes up well, does not see bad dreams, is loved by human beings, is loved by non-humans, devas protect him, fire, poison, and sword do not harm him, and if he does not penetrate further, he attains the Brahmā world. Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is cultivated, developed, practiced, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, these eight benefits are to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.1" },

{ text: `One who develops loving-kindness,<br>Mindful, immeasurable,<br>The fetters grow thin,<br>He sees the destruction of attachments.<br>With a mind not cruel,<br>Compassionate toward all beings,<br>Therefore he becomes<br>A perfectly pure, excellent one.<br>With a mind of compassion<br>Toward all beings,<br>The noble one well performs<br>Much good merit.<br>Having conquered<br>A great multitude of people,<br>Kings and sages<br>By sacrificial rites,<br>The horse sacrifice, human sacrifice,<br>The victory-drinking sacrifice,<br>The luck-throwing sacrifice,<br>The locked-door sacrifice.<br>They do not reach one-sixteenth<br>Of one well developed in loving-kindness,<br>As the light of the moon<br>Outshines all the stars.<br>He does not kill, nor cause to kill,<br>Does not conquer, nor cause to conquer,<br>With loving-kindness toward all beings,<br>He has enmity toward none.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.1" },

{ text: `These eight worldly conditions, bhikkhus, revolve around the world, and the world revolves around these eight worldly conditions. What eight? Gain and loss, fame and disgrace, praise and blame, happiness and pain. These eight worldly conditions, bhikkhus, revolve around the world, and the world revolves around these eight worldly conditions.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.5" },

{ text: `Gain and loss,<br>Fame and disgrace,<br>Praise and blame,<br>Happiness and pain,<br>These conditions are impermanent,<br>Not lasting, subject to change.<br>Knowing them, mindful,<br>The wise person observes their change,<br>What is agreeable does not disturb him,<br>What is disagreeable does not arouse hatred.<br>All acquiescence and opposition<br>Have disappeared, no longer remain,<br>Having known the path,<br>Without defilement, without sorrow,<br>Rightly understanding existence,<br>He has gone to the far shore.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.5" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, possessing these eight qualities, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration... the unsurpassed field of merit in the world. What eight? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Whatever food he receives, whether coarse or fine, he eats it carefully, without complaint; he is disgusted with evil bodily action, evil verbal action, evil mental action, disgusted with the acquisition of evil, unwholesome states. He is joyful and easy to live with, and does not frighten other bhikkhus. Whatever deceit, flattery, pretense, or crookedness he may have, he reveals it as it really is to the Teacher or to wise fellow celibates, striving to subdue it. While training, he thinks: 'Let other bhikkhus train or not, I will train here.' When walking, he walks on the straight path — here the straight path is right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. He dwells energetic, thinking: 'Let only skin, sinews, and bones remain, let the flesh and blood dry up in my body, without attaining what can be attained by human strength, human effort, human persistence, there will be no stopping of effort.' Possessing these eight qualities, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is worthy of veneration, worthy of respect, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.13" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight defilements of the mind. What eight? Bhikkhus, not reciting is the defilement of the scriptures; bhikkhus, not getting up is the defilement of a house; bhikkhus, laziness is the defilement of beauty; bhikkhus, heedlessness is the defilement of vigilance; bhikkhus, evil conduct is the defilement of a woman; bhikkhus, miserliness is the defilement of giving; evil, unwholesome states are the defilements of this world and the next. But, bhikkhus, there is a defilement greater than these defilements. Ignorance is the greatest defilement. Bhikkhus, these are the eight defilements.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.15" },

{ text: `By eight features, bhikkhus, a woman binds a man. What eight? Bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by form; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by smile; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by speech; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by song; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by tears; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by clothing; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by a gift; bhikkhus, a woman binds a man by touch. By these eight features, bhikkhus, a woman binds a man. Beings are well bound by these features, as if bound by a snare.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.17" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight powers. What eight? Bhikkhus, the power of a child is crying; the power of a woman is anger; the power of a thief is a weapon; the power of kings is authority; the power of a fool is overwhelming; the power of a wise person is reflection; the power of a learned person is examination; the power of an ascetic or brahmin is patience. Bhikkhus, these are the eight powers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.27" },

{ text: `- Here, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed sees well with right wisdom as it really is that all conditioned things are impermanent. Because, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed sees well with right wisdom as it really is that all conditioned things are impermanent.<br>Furthermore, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed sees well with right wisdom as it really is that sensual pleasures are like a pit of glowing coals. Because, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed sees well with right wisdom as it really is that sensual pleasures are like a pit of glowing coals.<br>Furthermore, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed has a mind that bends toward seclusion, slopes toward seclusion, inclines toward seclusion, dwells in seclusion, delights in renunciation, and has completely abandoned all things that are a basis for the taints.<br>Furthermore, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed has developed and well developed the four establishments of mindfulness. Because, Bhante, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed has developed and well developed the four establishments of mindfulness.<br>This, Bhante, is the power of a bhikkhu with taints destroyed. By this power, a bhikkhu with taints destroyed declares the destruction of the taints: 'My taints are destroyed.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.28" },

{ text: `For one who is born a human,<br>When the good Dhamma is taught,<br>If they do not seize the opportunity,<br>They pass beyond the moment.<br>Many inopportune times are spoken of<br>That obstruct human beings.<br>Only five or ten calamities [occur],<br>The Tathāgata appears in the world.<br>To encounter him face to face<br>Is very hard to find in the world.<br>To be born as a human<br>And for the good Dhamma to be taught<br>Is enough for one to strive<br>For whoever desires their welfare.<br>How could one, knowing the good Dhamma,<br>Let the opportunity pass by!<br>Whoever lets the opportunity pass<br>Grieves in hell.<br>Here, whoever abandons<br>The fixed course of the good Dhamma,<br>Like a merchant who loses goods,<br>Will grieve for a long time.<br>One covered by ignorance,<br>Transgressing the good Dhamma,<br>Must endure for a long time<br>Wandering in birth and death.<br>Whoever is born as a human<br>At a time when the Dhamma is well taught,<br>Whether past, present, or future,<br>Acts according to the Teacher's advice,<br>Seizes the opportunity in this world<br>For the unsurpassed holy life.<br>Whoever has entered the path<br>Proclaimed by the Tathāgata,<br>Whoever lives restrained<br>As taught by the One with the Eye of Dhamma,<br>As declared by the Kinsman of the Sun,<br>Let them dwell always mindful,<br>Guarding, without greed for sensual pleasures,<br>Cutting off all underlying tendencies,<br>Not running into Māra's realm.<br>They, in this world,<br>Reach the far shore,<br>And they also attain<br>The destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.29" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, what are the eight thoughts of a great person?<br>Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one with few desires, not for one with many desires. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who is content, not for one who is discontent. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who lives in seclusion, not for one who delights in company. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who is energetic, not for one who is lazy. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who is mindful, not for one who is forgetful. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who is concentrated, not for one who is unconcentrated. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who is wise, not for one of evil wisdom. Bhikkhus, this Dhamma is for one who does not delight in frivolous talk, who does not take pleasure in frivolous talk, not for one who delights in frivolous talk, who takes pleasure in frivolous talk.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },


{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one with few desires, this Dhamma is not for one with great desires' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu of few desires does not wish: 'May people know me as one of few desires'; content, he does not wish: 'May people know me as content'; living in seclusion, he does not wish: 'May people know me as living in seclusion'; energetic, he does not wish: 'May people know me as energetic'; mindful, he does not wish: 'May people know me as mindful'; concentrated, he does not wish: 'May people know me as concentrated'; wise, he does not wish: 'May people know me as wise'; one who does not delight in frivolous talk, he does not wish: 'May people know me as one who does not delight in frivolous talk.' Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one with few desires, this Dhamma is not for one with great desires' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is content, this Dhamma is not for one who is discontent' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu is content with any kind of requisite such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is content, this Dhamma is not for one who is discontent' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who lives in seclusion, this Dhamma is not for one who delights in company' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, for a bhikkhu living in seclusion, many people come to visit: bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, male lay followers, female lay followers, kings, royal ministers, wanderers, disciples of wanderers. There, that bhikkhu, with mind bent toward seclusion, sloping toward seclusion, inclining toward seclusion, dwelling in seclusion, delighting in renunciation, speaks words connected solely with solitude. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who lives in seclusion, this Dhamma is not for one who delights in company' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is energetic, this Dhamma is not for one who is lazy' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is energetic, this Dhamma is not for one who is lazy' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is mindful, this Dhamma is not for one who is forgetful' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu has mindfulness, endowed with supreme mindfulness and recollection, remembering and recollecting what was done and said long ago. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is mindful, this Dhamma is not for one who is forgetful' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is concentrated, this Dhamma is not for one who is unconcentrated' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu, secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states... enters and abides in the fourth jhāna. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is concentrated, this Dhamma is not for one who is unconcentrated' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is wise, this Dhamma is not for one of evil wisdom' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu has wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, with the noble penetration leading to the complete destruction of suffering. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who is wise, this Dhamma is not for one of evil wisdom' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who does not delight in frivolous talk, who does not take pleasure in frivolous talk, this Dhamma is not for one who delights in frivolous talk, who takes pleasure in frivolous talk' — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said?<br>Bhikkhus, here, a bhikkhu's mind is inspired, serene, established, and inclined toward the cessation of frivolous talk. Bhikkhus, 'This Dhamma is for one who does not delight in frivolous talk, who does not take pleasure in frivolous talk, this Dhamma is not for one who delights in frivolous talk, who takes pleasure in frivolous talk' — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.30" },

{ text: `When the field is complete,<br>The seed is sown complete,<br>When the rain falls complete,<br>The harvest is complete,<br>When no calamity is present,<br>Growth is complete,<br>Expansion is complete,<br>The result is complete.<br>So too, giving<br>Among those of complete virtue,<br>And the gift material<br>Is also completely obtained,<br>It leads to completeness<br>Because of complete conduct.<br>Therefore, whoever wishes completeness<br>Must themselves be complete,<br>Serving those of complete wisdom,<br>Thus success is complete.<br>Complete in wisdom and virtue,<br>With mind complete,<br>Doing deeds complete,<br>Benefit is complete.<br>Knowing the world as it really is,<br>One attains complete view.<br>The complete path leads to<br>Attaining complete intention.<br>Abandoning all defilements,<br>One attains complete Nibbāna.<br>Liberated from all suffering,<br>That is complete perfection.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.34" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a virtuous person succeeds because his mind inclines toward purification. Bhikkhus, a virtuous person succeeds because his mind inclines toward dispassion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.35" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are three bases of meritorious action. What three? The base of meritorious action through giving, the base of meritorious action through virtue, and the base of meritorious action through development. Bhikkhus, these are the three bases of meritorious action.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.36" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight kinds of giving of a genuine person. What eight? Giving what is pure; giving what is excellent; giving at the right time; giving what is suitable; giving with care; giving constantly; with a serene mind at the time of giving; and after giving, being joyful. Bhikkhus, these are the eight kinds of giving of a genuine person.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.37" },

{ text: `Pure and excellent,<br>Timely and suitable,<br>Drink and food,<br>Always performing giving,<br>In good fields,<br>Living the holy life,<br>With nothing to regret,<br>Giving much wealth.<br>Such giving<br>Is praised by the wise.<br>The wise give thus,<br>With faithful, liberated mind,<br>Without harm, mind at ease,<br>The wise are born in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.37" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, a great rain makes all kinds of crops fully mature, bringing benefit, happiness, and well-being to many people. So too, bhikkhus, a genuine person born into whatever family brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to many people; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his mother and father; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his wife and children; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his servants and workers; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to his friends and companions; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to departed ancestors; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to kings; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to devas; brings benefit, happiness, and well-being to ascetics and brahmins.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.38" },

{ text: `For the benefit of many,<br>The wise person lives at home,<br>Untiring by day and night,<br>Making offerings righteously.<br>To mother and father and ancestors,<br>Remembering what was done in the past,<br>To the homeless renunciants,<br>Paying homage to those of holy life.<br>With firm faith, offering,<br>Knowing the Dhamma, behaving well,<br>He brings benefit<br>To kings and to devas.<br>He brings benefit<br>To relatives and friends.<br>He brings benefit<br>To all people.<br>Well established in the good Dhamma,<br>Having subdued the stain of miserliness,<br>He enjoys a happy life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.38" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, killing living beings, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of killing living beings is to become human with a short life span.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, taking what is not given, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of taking what is not given is to become human with loss of wealth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, sexual misconduct, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of sexual misconduct is to become human with enmity from enemies.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, false speech, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of false speech is to become human subject to false accusations.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, divisive speech, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of divisive speech is to become human with broken friendships.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, harsh speech, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of harsh speech is to become human and hear disagreeable sounds.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, idle chatter, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of idle chatter is to become human and hear unacceptable words.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, drinking liquor and fermented drink, when practiced, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, leads to the animal realm, leads to the ghost realm. The very lightest result of drinking liquor and fermented drink is to become human with a deranged mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40" },

{ text: `Do not kill living beings,<br>Do not take what is not given,<br>Do not speak falsehood,<br>Do not drink intoxicants,<br>Abandon non-celibacy,<br>Abstain from sexual intercourse,<br>Do not eat at night,<br>Avoid untimely food,<br>Do not wear garlands,<br>Do not use perfumes,<br>Sleep on a mat<br>Spread on the ground.<br>This virtuous observance day<br>Is called the eight-factored,<br>Proclaimed by the Buddha,<br>It leads to the end of suffering.<br>The moon and the sun,<br>Both seen as beautiful,<br>Wherever they go,<br>They shine with radiance.<br>They make the clouds bright,<br>Moving through the sky,<br>They shine in the heavens,<br>Illumining all directions.<br>In that space,<br>Treasures are found:<br>Pearls and precious gems,<br>Beryl, lucky stones,<br>Gold nuggets in the earth,<br>Or the Kancana kind,<br>And the bright golden kind<br>Called Hataka.<br>Yet their value is<br>Only one-sixteenth<br>Of the observance day practice<br>Complete with eight factors.<br>Including the moon's light<br>And the entire starry sky,<br>Therefore, women and men,<br>Observing the pure precepts,<br>Practicing the Bodhisatta uposatha,<br>Complete with eight factors,<br>Doing wholesome meritorious deeds,<br>Bringing much happiness,<br>Are reborn in heaven,<br>Not subject to mockery.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.42" },

{ text: `- Gotamī, those things that you know: 'These things lead to greed, not to dispassion; lead to bondage, not to release from bondage; lead to accumulation, not to non-accumulation; lead to great desires, not to few desires; lead to discontent, not to contentment; lead to company, not to seclusion; lead to laziness, not to energy; lead to being hard to support, not to being easy to support' — then, Gotamī, you should definitely hold: 'That is not the Dhamma, that is not the Discipline, that is not the Teacher's teaching.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.53" },

{ text: `And, Gotamī, those things that you know: 'These things lead to dispassion, not to greed; lead to release from bondage, not to bondage; lead to non-accumulation, not to accumulation; lead to few desires, not to great desires; lead to contentment, not to discontent; lead to seclusion, not to company; lead to energy, not to laziness; lead to being easy to support, not to being hard to support' — then, Gotamī, you should definitely hold: 'That is the Dhamma, that is the Discipline, that is the Teacher's teaching.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.53" },

{ text: `Fear, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Suffering, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Illness, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. A boil, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. A dart, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Bondage, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. Mud, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures. The womb, bhikkhus, is a designation for sensual pleasures.<br>How, bhikkhus, is fear a designation for sensual pleasures? Because those who are infatuated by sensual desire, bound by sensual lust, are not freed from fear in the present life, not freed from fear in the future; therefore, fear is a designation for sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.56" },

{ text: `Fear, suffering, and illness,<br>Boil and dart,<br>Bondage and mud,<br>Both the womb —<br>These are called sensual pleasures,<br>Where ordinary beings are infatuated,<br>Sinking in beautiful forms,<br>They again enter the womb.<br>When a bhikkhu is ardent,<br>Not slack, mindful,<br>He crosses this dangerous path,<br>The path so hard to cross.<br>He sees beings<br>Living in fear,<br>Because they are oppressed and conquered<br>By birth and aging.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.56" },

{ text: `'My mind will become inwardly established, well settled. Evil, unwholesome states that arise will not obsess my mind and will not find a foothold.' Thus, bhikkhu, you should train. Bhikkhu, when your mind becomes inwardly established, well settled, and evil, unwholesome states that arise obsess your mind and find a foothold, then, bhikkhu, you should train thus:<br><br>'The liberation of mind by loving-kindness will be developed by me, cultivated, made the vehicle, made the foundation, made persistent, accumulated, and properly undertaken.' Thus, bhikkhu, you should train.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.63" },

{ text: `'I will dwell contemplating the body in the body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, subduing covetousness and grief in the world.' Thus, bhikkhu, you should train. Bhikkhu, when this concentration of yours is thus developed and cultivated, then, bhikkhu, you should develop this concentration with applied and sustained thought; develop it without applied thought but with sustained thought; develop it without applied thought and without sustained thought; develop it with rapture; develop it without rapture; develop it accompanied by pleasure; develop it accompanied by equanimity. Bhikkhu, when this concentration of yours is thus developed and cultivated, then, bhikkhu, wherever you go, you will go in peace; wherever you stand, you will stand in peace; wherever you sit, you will sit in peace; wherever you lie down, you will lie down in peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.63" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight ignoble speeches. What eight? Not having seen, he says he has seen; not having heard, he says he has heard; not having thought, he says he has thought; not having known, he says he has known; having seen, he says he has not seen; having heard, he says he has not heard; having thought, he says he has not thought; having known, he says he has not known. Bhikkhus, these are the eight ignoble speeches.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.67" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these eight noble speeches. What eight? Not having seen, he says he has not seen; not having heard, he says he has not heard; not having thought, he says he has not thought; not having known, he says he has not known; having seen, he says he has seen; having heard, he says he has heard; having thought, he says he has thought; having known, he says he has known. Bhikkhus, these are the eight noble speeches.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.68" },

{ text: `Here, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu, while living in seclusion, not being energetic, arouses a desire for gain. He becomes eager, aroused, and energetic to gain gain. Through being eager, aroused, and energetic to gain gain, gain arises. With that gain, he becomes infatuated, heedless, falls into infatuation and heedlessness. This is called a bhikkhu who desires gain, who is eager, aroused, and energetic to gain gain; having gained gain, he becomes infatuated and heedless, and abandons the good Dhamma.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.77" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, these eight things lead to the decline of a learner bhikkhu. What eight? Delight in work, delight in talking, delight in sleeping, delight in company, lack of sense restraint, lack of moderation in eating, delight in association, delight in frivolous talk. Bhikkhus, these eight things lead to the decline of a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.79" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, these eight things lead to the non-decline of a learner bhikkhu. What eight? Not delighting in work, not delighting in talking, not delighting in sleeping, not delighting in company, sense restraint, moderation in eating, not delighting in association, not delighting in frivolous talk. Bhikkhus, these eight things lead to the non-decline of a learner bhikkhu.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.79" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has work to do. He thinks: 'I have work to do. If I do it, my body will get tired. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the first ground for laziness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has work to do. He thinks: 'I have done work. Because I have done work, my body is tired. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the second ground for laziness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when walking for alms in the village or town, does not receive coarse or fine food as much as he wishes. He thinks: 'I walked for alms in the village or town and did not receive coarse or fine food as much as I wished. Now my body is tired and cannot bear it. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the fifth ground for laziness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when walking for alms in the village or town, receives coarse or fine food as much as he wishes. He thinks: 'I walked for alms in the village or town and received coarse or fine food as much as I wished. Now my body is heavy, cannot bear it, heavy like a bean soaked in water. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the sixth ground for laziness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has a slight illness. He thinks: 'Now this slight illness has arisen in me; there is reason to lie down. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the seventh ground for laziness.<br>Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has just recovered from an illness, not long recovered. He thinks: 'I have just recovered from an illness, not long recovered. My body is weak due to illness and cannot bear it. Let me lie down.' He lies down, not making an effort... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the eighth ground for laziness.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has work to do. He thinks: 'I have work to do. If I do the work, it will not be easy for me to attend to the teaching of the Buddhas. So first, let me arouse energy to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.' He arouses energy to attain... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the first ground for diligence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has done some work. He thinks: 'I have done some work. Because I did the work, I could not attend to the teaching of the Buddhas. So first, let me arouse energy to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.' He arouses energy to attain... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the second ground for diligence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when walking for alms in the village or town, does not receive coarse or fine food as much as he wishes. He thinks: 'I walked for alms in the village or town and did not receive coarse or fine food as much as I wished. (Because of that) my body is light and can bear it. Let me arouse energy... to realize the unrealized.' He arouses energy... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the fifth ground for diligence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, when walking for alms in the village or town, receives coarse or fine food as much as he wishes. He thinks: 'I walked for alms in the village or town and received coarse or fine food as much as I wished. My body has strength and can bear it. Let me arouse energy... to realize the unrealized.' He arouses energy... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the sixth ground for diligence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has just recovered from a slight illness. He thinks: 'This slight illness arose in me. This is possible: this illness could increase in me. So first, let me arouse energy... unrealized.' Bhikkhus, this is the seventh ground for diligence.<br>Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has just recovered from an illness, not long recovered. He thinks: 'I have just recovered from an illness, not long recovered. This is possible: this illness could return. So first, let me arouse energy to attain the unattained, to achieve the unachieved, to realize the unrealized.' He arouses energy to attain... unrealized. Bhikkhus, this is the eighth ground for diligence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.80" },

{ text: `When mindfulness and clear comprehension are absent, bhikkhus, for one lacking mindfulness and clear comprehension, moral shame and dread are destroyed. When moral shame and dread are absent, for one deficient in moral shame and dread, sense restraint is destroyed. When sense restraint is absent, for one deficient in sense restraint, virtue is destroyed. When virtue is absent, for one deficient in virtue, right concentration is destroyed. When right concentration is absent, for one deficient in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is destroyed. When true knowledge and vision is absent, for one deficient in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed. When disenchantment and dispassion are absent, for one deficient in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree lacking branches and leaves: its shoots do not reach completeness, its bark, sapwood, and heartwood do not reach completeness. So too, bhikkhus, when mindfulness and clear comprehension are absent, for one lacking mindfulness and clear comprehension, moral shame and dread are destroyed... the knowledge and vision of liberation is destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.81" },

{ text: `When mindfulness and clear comprehension are present, bhikkhus, for one possessing mindfulness and clear comprehension, moral shame and dread are complete. When moral shame and dread are present, bhikkhus, for one complete in moral shame and dread, sense restraint is complete. When sense restraint is present, for one complete in sense restraint, virtue is complete. When virtue is present, for one complete in virtue, right concentration is complete. When right concentration is present, for one complete in right concentration, true knowledge and vision of things as they really are is complete. When true knowledge and vision is present, for one complete in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are complete. When disenchantment and dispassion are present, for one complete in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete. Just as, bhikkhus, a tree with branches and leaves: its shoots, bark, sapwood, and heartwood reach completeness. So too, bhikkhus, when mindfulness and clear comprehension are present, for one possessing mindfulness and clear comprehension... the knowledge and vision of liberation is complete.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.81" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if outside wanderers were to ask: 'Venerable sirs, what is the root of all things? What is the origin of all things? What is the accumulation of all things? What is the meeting place of all things? What is the foremost of all things? What is the master of all things? What is the supreme of all things? What is the core of all things?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer them: 'Venerable sirs, all things have desire as root. All things have attention as origin. All things have contact as accumulation. All things have feeling as meeting place. All things have concentration as foremost. All things have mindfulness as master. All things have wisdom as supreme. All things have liberation as core.' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you should answer those outside wanderers in that way.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.83" },

{ text: `Here, Nāgita, when I see bhikkhus who, after eating until satisfied, until their bellies are full, dwell devoted to the pleasure of lying down, the pleasure of touch, the pleasure of sleeping, then, Nāgita, I think: 'Indeed, these venerable ones find with difficulty, with trouble, with effort, the bliss of security, the bliss of seclusion, the bliss of peace, the bliss of enlightenment; while I attain without difficulty, without trouble, without effort, the bliss of security, the bliss of seclusion, the bliss of peace, the bliss of enlightenment — because these venerable ones, after eating until satisfied, until their bellies are full, dwell devoted to the pleasure of lying down, the pleasure of touch, the pleasure of sleeping.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.86" },

{ text: `Here, Nāgita, when I see a bhikkhu dwelling at the edge of the village, sitting in jhāna. Then, Nāgita, I think: 'Now the park-keeper will come and disturb him, or a novice will make him give up his jhāna.' Therefore, Nāgita, I do not rejoice in that bhikkhu dwelling at the edge of the village.<br>Here, Nāgita, I see a bhikkhu dwelling in the forest, sitting dozing in the forest. Then, Nāgita, I think: 'Now this venerable one, having eliminated drowsiness and fatigue, will attend to the perception of the forest and dwell one-pointed.' Therefore, Nāgita, I rejoice in that bhikkhu dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.86" },

{ text: `Here, Nāgita, I see a bhikkhu dwelling in the forest, sitting unconcentrated in the forest. Then, Nāgita, I think: 'Now this venerable one will concentrate his unconcentrated mind, and will protect his concentrated mind.' Therefore, Nāgita, I rejoice in that bhikkhu dwelling in the forest.<br>Here, Nāgita, I see a bhikkhu sitting in jhāna in the forest. Then, Nāgita, I think: 'Now this venerable one will liberate his unliberated mind or will protect his liberated mind.' Therefore, Nāgita, I rejoice in that bhikkhu dwelling in the forest.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.86" },

{ text: `Furthermore, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Venerable sirs, this is the second support for developing the states pertaining to enlightenment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1" },

{ text: `Furthermore, venerable sirs, a bhikkhu is concentrated; he obtains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort, talk that is conducive to reduction, leading to opening of the heart, such as talk on few desires, talk on contentment, talk on seclusion, talk on non-association, talk on energy and exertion, talk on virtue, talk on concentration, talk on wisdom, talk on liberation, talk on the knowledge and vision of liberation. Venerable sirs, this is the third support for developing the states pertaining to enlightenment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1" },

{ text: `Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, accomplishing wholesome states, steadfast, persistent, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. Venerable sirs, this is the fourth support for developing the states pertaining to enlightenment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu with good friends, good companions, good associates, this is to be expected: he will be virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, when that bhikkhu has dwelt in these five things, four more things should be developed. The perception of foulness should be developed to abandon greed; loving-kindness should be developed to abandon hatred; mindfulness of breathing should be developed to cut off thoughts; the perception of impermanence should be developed to uproot conceit. Bhikkhus, for a bhikkhu with the perception of impermanence, the perception of non-self becomes established; for a bhikkhu with the perception of non-self, conceit is uprooted, and in this very life he attains Nibbāna.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the power of wisdom? Whatever is unwholesome is seen as unwholesome; whatever is wholesome is seen as wholesome; whatever is blameworthy is seen as blameworthy; whatever is blameless is seen as blameless; whatever is dark is seen as dark; whatever is bright is seen as bright; whatever is not to be practiced is seen as not to be practiced; whatever is to be practiced is seen as to be practiced; whatever is unworthy of the noble ones is seen as unworthy of the noble ones; whatever is worthy of the noble ones is seen as worthy of the noble ones. Those things should be well observed, well investigated with wisdom. Bhikkhus, this is called the power of wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.5" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what is the power of energy? Whatever is unwholesome is seen as unwholesome; whatever is blameworthy is seen as blameworthy; whatever is dark is seen as dark; whatever is not to be practiced is seen as not to be practiced; whatever is unworthy of the noble ones is seen as unworthy of the noble ones. Regarding those things, one arouses desire, effort, energy, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to abandon them. Whatever is wholesome is seen as wholesome; whatever is blameless is seen as blameless; whatever is bright is seen as bright; whatever is to be practiced is seen as to be practiced; whatever is worthy of the noble ones is seen as worthy of the noble ones. Regarding those things, one arouses desire, effort, energy, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to attain them. Bhikkhus, this is called the power of energy.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.5" },

{ text: `- Sutavā, a bhikkhu who is an Arahant, with taints destroyed, accomplished, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, attained the goal, destroyed the fetter of existence, rightly liberated — he cannot do five things: A bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot intentionally deprive a living being of life; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot take what is not given, that is, stealing; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot engage in sexual intercourse; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot knowingly speak falsely; a bhikkhu with taints destroyed cannot enjoy sensual pleasures from stored-up goods as he did when he was a householder.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.7" },

{ text: `Just as, Bhante, on the earth, people throw pure things, throw impure things, throw excrement, throw urine, spit, throw pus, and throw blood, yet the earth is not worried, not ashamed, nor disgusted. So too, Bhante, I dwell with a mind like the earth, vast, expansive, immeasurable, without enmity, without ill-will. Bhante, for one who does not have mindfulness of the body established, if he offends a fellow celibate, he might go off wandering without apologizing.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.11" },

{ text: `Just as, Bhante, a person carries a bowl full of oil, with many holes, many openings, leaking, dripping. So too, Bhante, I carry this body, with many holes, many openings, leaking, dripping. Bhante, for one who does not have mindfulness of the body established, if he offends a fellow celibate, he might go off wandering without apologizing.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.11" },

{ text: `A boil, bhikkhus, is a designation for this body composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, built up by rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to erosion, dissolution, destruction, decay, having nine orifices, nine openings. From these, whatever flows out is surely impure, surely foul-smelling, surely disgusting; whatever oozes out is surely impure, surely foul-smelling, surely disgusting. Therefore, bhikkhus, be disgusted with this body.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.15" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these nine perceptions that, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless. What nine? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of non-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion. Bhikkhus, these nine perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.16" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, a family that possesses nine factors — if not yet visited, it is worth visiting; if already visited, it is worth sitting down in. What nine? They are pleased to rise up; they are pleased to bow; they are pleased to invite to sit; if they have anything, they do not hide it; from much they give much, from excellent things they give excellent things; they give carefully; they give respectfully; they sit around to listen to the Dhamma; they appreciate the words. Bhikkhus, a family possessing these nine factors — if not yet visited, it is worth visiting; if already visited, it is worth sitting down in.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.17" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, a family that possesses nine factors — if not yet visited, it is not worth visiting; if already visited, it is not worth sitting down in. What nine? They are not pleased to rise up; they are not pleased to bow; they are not pleased to invite to sit; if they have anything, they hide it; from much they give little, from excellent things they give inferior things; they give carelessly; they give without respect; they do not sit around to listen to the Dhamma; they do not appreciate the words. Bhikkhus, a family possessing these nine factors — if not yet visited, it is not worth visiting; if already visited, it is not worth sitting down in.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.17" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a noble disciple reflects: 'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned killing living beings, refrained from killing, laid down the rod, laid down the sword, have moral shame and dread, have loving-kindness, and dwell compassionate for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon killing living beings, refrain from killing, lay down the rod, lay down the sword, have moral shame and dread, have loving-kindness, and dwell compassionate for the welfare of all living beings and creatures. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the first factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned taking what is not given, refrained from taking what is not given, take only what is given, desire only what is given, live purely, without stealing. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon taking what is not given, refrain from taking what is not given, take only what is given, desire only what is given, live purely, without stealing. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the second factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned non-celibacy, live the celibate life, live aloof, abstain from the vulgar practice of sexual intercourse. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon non-celibacy, live the celibate life, live aloof, abstain from the vulgar practice of sexual intercourse. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the third factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned false speech, refrained from false speech, speak truth, adhere to truth, are trustworthy, reliable, not deceivers, not breaking promises to the world. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon false speech, refrain from false speech, speak truth, adhere to truth, are trustworthy, reliable, not deceivers, not breaking promises to the world. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the fourth factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned intoxication with liquor and fermented drink. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon intoxication with liquor and fermented drink. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the fifth factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants eat once a day, do not eat at night, do not eat at the wrong time. Today, this night and this day, I also eat once a day, do not eat at night, do not eat at the wrong time. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the sixth factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned dancing, singing, music, and shows, do not adorn themselves with garlands, perfumes, ointments, or finery. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon dancing, singing, music, and shows, do not adorn myself with garlands, perfumes, ointments, or finery. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the seventh factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },


{ text: `'For their whole life, the Arahants have abandoned high and large beds, refrained from high and large beds, they lie down on a low bed, on a small bed, on a grass mat. Today, this night and this day, I also abandon high and large beds, refrain from high and large beds, I lie down on a low bed, on a small bed, on a grass mat. By this factor, following the example of the Arahants, I will observe the uposatha day.' This is the eighth factor accomplished.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18" },

{ text: `- Householder, even if one gives coarse or fine things, if one gives carelessly, gives without attention, gives not with one's own hand, gives what is discarded, gives without regard for the future — then wherever that giving ripens in result, the mind does not incline toward enjoying excellent food, does not incline toward enjoying excellent robes, does not incline toward enjoying excellent vehicles, does not incline toward enjoying the five excellent strands of sensual pleasure. And one's sons, or wife, or servants, or messengers, or workers do not listen well, do not lend ear, do not apply their minds to understand. Why is that? Because, householder, that is the result of deeds done carelessly.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.20" },

{ text: `Householder, even if one gives coarse or fine things, if one gives carefully, gives with attention, gives with one's own hand, gives what is not discarded, gives with regard for the future — then wherever that giving ripens in result, the mind inclines toward enjoying excellent food, inclines toward enjoying excellent robes, inclines toward enjoying excellent vehicles, inclines toward enjoying the five excellent strands of sensual pleasure. And one's sons, or wife, or servants, or messengers, or workers listen well, lend ear, and apply their minds to understand. Why is that? Because, householder, that is the result of deeds done carefully.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.20" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, I will teach you nine things rooted in craving. Listen and pay close attention, I will speak. And, bhikkhus, what are the nine things rooted in craving? Dependent on craving, seeking arises; dependent on seeking, gain arises; dependent on gain, decision arises; dependent on decision, desire and lust arises; dependent on desire and lust, attachment arises; dependent on attachment, possessiveness arises; dependent on possessiveness, stinginess arises; dependent on stinginess, guarding arises; from guarding, there arise the taking up of rods, the taking up of swords, quarrels, disputes, conflicts, divisive speech, false speech, and many other evil, unwholesome states. Bhikkhus, these are the nine things rooted in craving.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.23" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu's mind is well accumulated with wisdom, then it is proper for that bhikkhu to say: 'I know: "Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more returning to this state."' And, bhikkhus, how is a bhikkhu's mind well accumulated?<br>'My mind is free from greed' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind is free from hatred' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind is free from delusion' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of non-greed' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of non-hatred' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of non-delusion' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of not inclining toward the existence of sensual pleasures' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of not inclining toward the existence of form' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom. 'My mind has the nature of not inclining toward the existence of formlessness' — thus his mind is well accumulated with wisdom.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.25" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these nine grounds for conflict. What nine? 'He has harmed me' — conflict arises. 'He is harming me' — conflict arises. 'He will harm me' — conflict arises. 'He has harmed someone I love, someone I like'... 'He is harming someone I love, someone I like'... 'He will harm someone I love, someone I like' — conflict arises. 'He has benefited someone I do not love, someone I do not like'... 'He is benefiting someone I do not love, someone I do not like'... 'He will benefit someone I do not love, someone I do not like' — conflict arises. Bhikkhus, these are the nine grounds for conflict.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.29" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these nine ways of allaying conflict. What nine? 'He has harmed me — what benefit is there in thinking like that?' thus conflict is allayed. 'He is harming me — what benefit is there in thinking like that?' thus conflict is allayed. 'He will harm me — what benefit is there in thinking like that?' thus conflict is allayed. 'He has harmed someone I love — what benefit is there in thinking like that?'... 'He is harming someone I love...' 'He will harm someone I love...' 'He has benefited someone I do not love...' 'He is benefiting someone I do not love...' 'He will benefit someone I do not love — what benefit is there in thinking like that?' thus conflict is allayed. Bhikkhus, these are the nine ways of allaying conflict.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.30" },

{ text: `Ānanda, before my enlightenment, while I was still a bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I thought: 'Good is renunciation! Good is dwelling in seclusion!' But my mind did not become inspired in that renunciation, did not become serene, did not become established, did not become liberated, even though I saw: 'This is peaceful.' Then, Ānanda, I thought: 'For what reason, for what condition, does my mind not become inspired in that renunciation, not serene, not established, not liberated, even though I see: "This is peaceful"?' Then, Ānanda, I thought: 'Because I do not see the danger in sensual pleasures, because I have not cultivated that danger, and the benefit of renunciation has not been attained, I have not tasted that benefit. Therefore my mind does not become inspired in that renunciation, not serene, not established, not liberated.' Then, Ānanda, I thought: 'If, after seeing the danger in sensual pleasures, I cultivate that danger, and after attaining the benefit in renunciation, I taste that benefit,' then this is possible: my mind may become inspired in renunciation, serene, established, liberated, because I see: 'This is peaceful.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.41" },

{ text: `The wise one finds<br>Liberation in bondage,<br>The awakened one with jhāna,<br>The sage, the awakened,<br>One who has abandoned, not clinging,<br>The hero, the seer.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.42" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five things that weaken the training. What five? Killing living beings, taking what is not given, sexual misconduct, false speech, intoxication with liquor and fermented drink. Bhikkhus, these are the five things that weaken the training. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five things that weaken the training, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body in the body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, subduing covetousness and grief in the world. He dwells contemplating feelings in feelings... contemplating mind in mind... contemplating phenomena in phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, subduing covetousness and grief in the world. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five things that weaken the training, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.63" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five hindrances. What five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of dullness and drowsiness, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. Bhikkhus, these are the five hindrances. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five hindrances, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed. What four? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells contemplating the body in the body... contemplating phenomena in phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, subduing covetousness and grief in the world. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of the five hindrances, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.64" },

{ text: `- There are these five wildernesses of the mind. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is doubtful, uncertain, not decisive, without serene confidence regarding the Teacher. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is doubtful, uncertain, not decisive, without serene confidence regarding the Teacher, does not incline to energy, exertion, persistence, and effort. When his mind does not incline to energy, exertion, persistence, and effort, this is called the first wilderness of the mind. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is doubtful regarding the Dhamma... regarding the Saṅgha... regarding the training... he is angry with his fellow celibates, displeased, his mind agitated, becomes wilderness. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu is angry with his fellow celibates, displeased, his mind agitated, becomes wilderness, that bhikkhu does not incline to energy, exertion, persistence, and effort. This is called the fifth wilderness of the mind. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five wildernesses of the mind... the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.71" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five lower fetters. What five? Personality view, doubt, clinging to rites and rituals, sensual desire, ill-will. Bhikkhus, these are the five lower fetters. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five lower fetters, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed. What four? ... these four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.67" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, likable, connected with sensual desire, alluring; sounds cognizable by the ear... alluring. Bhikkhus, these are the five strands of sensual pleasure. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five strands of sensual pleasure, these four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.65" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five aggregates subject to clinging. What five? The aggregate of form subject to clinging, the aggregate of feeling subject to clinging, the aggregate of perception subject to clinging, the aggregate of formations subject to clinging, the aggregate of consciousness subject to clinging. Bhikkhus, these are the five aggregates subject to clinging. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five aggregates subject to clinging, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed. What four? ... the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.66" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five kinds of stinginess. What five? Stinginess regarding dwellings, stinginess regarding families, stinginess regarding gains, stinginess regarding beauty, stinginess regarding Dhamma. Bhikkhus, for the abandonment of these five kinds of stinginess, the four establishments of mindfulness should be developed. What four? ... these four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.69" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these five mental fetters. What five? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu's mind is not free from greed, not free from desire, not free from affection, not free from thirst, not free from fever, not free from craving for sensual pleasures. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu whose mind is not free from greed, not free from desire, not free from affection, not free from thirst, not free from fever, not free from craving for sensual pleasures — his mind does not incline to energy, exertion, persistence, and effort. One whose mind does not incline... that is the first mental fetter. Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu's mind is not free from greed for the body... not free from greed for forms... he eats to the full capacity of his stomach, enjoying the pleasure of lying down, the pleasure of sleeping... Furthermore, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu lives the holy life aspiring for a certain kind of devas: 'By this virtue, by this practice, by this austerity, or by this holy life, I will become a deva of this or that kind.' Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu lives the holy life aspiring for a certain kind of devas... his mind does not incline to energy, exertion, persistence, and effort. One whose mind... that is the fifth mental fetter. Bhikkhus, these are the five mental fetters. For the abandonment of these five mental fetters, these four establishments of mindfulness should be developed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.72" },

{ text: `Ānanda, good virtues have non-regret as their purpose, non-regret as their benefit. Non-regret has joy as its purpose, joy as its benefit. Joy has rapture as its purpose, rapture as its benefit. Rapture has tranquility as its purpose, tranquility as its benefit. Tranquility has happiness as its purpose, happiness as its benefit. Happiness has concentration as its purpose, concentration as its benefit. Concentration has true knowledge and vision of things as they really are as its purpose, true knowledge and vision as its benefit. True knowledge and vision has disenchantment and dispassion as its purpose, disenchantment and dispassion as its benefit. Disenchantment and dispassion has the knowledge and vision of liberation as its purpose, the knowledge and vision of liberation as its benefit. Thus, Ānanda, good virtues lead step by step to the supreme. Thus, Ānanda, good virtues step by step lead to the supreme.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.1" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, disenchantment and dispassion have the knowledge and vision of liberation as their purpose, the knowledge and vision of liberation as their benefit; true knowledge and vision have disenchantment and dispassion as their purpose, disenchantment and dispassion as their benefit; concentration has true knowledge and vision as its purpose, true knowledge and vision as its benefit; happiness has concentration as its purpose, concentration as its benefit; tranquility has happiness as its purpose, happiness as its benefit; rapture has tranquility as its purpose, tranquility as its benefit; joy has rapture as its purpose, rapture as its benefit; non-regret has joy as its purpose, joy as its benefit; good virtues have non-regret as their purpose, non-regret as their benefit. Thus, bhikkhus, (these) conditions lead to (other) conditions; conditions complete (other) conditions, leading from the near shore to the far shore.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.2" },

{ text: `Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possesses five factors. And, bhikkhus, what is a dwelling that possesses five factors? Here, bhikkhus, a dwelling is not too far, not too near, convenient for going and coming; during the day it is not crowded, at night it is not noisy, not boisterous, with little contact with flies, mosquitoes, wind, heat, and creeping things. In that dwelling, he obtains without difficulty the requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. In that dwelling, elder bhikkhus who are learned, bearers of the scriptures, bearers of the Dhamma, bearers of the Discipline, bearers of the summaries, come to dwell; he frequently approaches them, inquires and asks: 'How is this, Venerable Sir? What is the meaning of this?' Those venerable ones reveal what is unrevealed, disclose what is undisclosed, and regarding various doubtful points, they dispel his doubts. Bhikkhus, such a dwelling possesses five factors.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.11" },

{ text: `No sensual desire, no ill-will,<br>No dullness and drowsiness,<br>No restlessness, no doubt,<br>A bhikkhu completely without them.<br>With the Arahant's aggregate of virtue,<br>With the Arahant's aggregate of concentration,<br>Complete with liberation,<br>With such knowledge.<br>Such a bhikkhu,<br>Possessing five factors,<br>Having abandoned five factors,<br>In this Dhamma and Discipline,<br>Is called complete<br>In every way.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.12" },

{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, whatever footprints of living creatures there are, all are included in the footprint of the elephant, and the elephant's footprint is declared the foremost among them, that is, in terms of size; so too, bhikkhus, whatever wholesome states there are, all are rooted in heedfulness, all converge on heedfulness, and heedfulness is declared the foremost among all wholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.15" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, among whatever beings there are — whether footless, two-footed, four-footed, or many-footed, whether having form or formless, whether percipient, non-percipient, or neither-percipient-nor-non-percipient — the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One is declared the foremost among them. So too, bhikkhus, whatever wholesome states there are, all are rooted in heedfulness, all converge on heedfulness, and heedfulness is declared the foremost among them.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.15" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, what are evil desires? Here, bhikkhus, a person has no faith, yet wishes: 'May they know me as faithful'; he is immoral, yet wishes: 'May they know me as learned'; he delights in company, yet wishes: 'May they know me as one living in seclusion'; he is lazy, yet wishes: 'May they know me as energetic'; he is forgetful, yet wishes: 'May they know me as mindful'; he is unconcentrated, yet wishes: 'May they know me as concentrated'; he has evil wisdom, yet wishes: 'May they know me as wise'; he has not destroyed the taints, yet wishes: 'May they know me as one who has destroyed the taints.' Bhikkhus, these are called evil desires.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.23" },

{ text: `- 'Schism in the Saṅgha, schism in the Saṅgha,' Bhante, is spoken of. To what extent, Bhante, is there schism in the Saṅgha?<br>- Here, Upāli, bhikkhus explain what is not Dhamma as Dhamma, what is Dhamma as not Dhamma; what is not Discipline as Discipline, what is Discipline as not Discipline; what was not spoken, not uttered by the Tathāgata as spoken, uttered by the Tathāgata; what was spoken, uttered by the Tathāgata as not spoken, not uttered; what was not regularly practiced by the Tathāgata as regularly practiced; what was regularly practiced by the Tathāgata as not regularly practiced; what was not laid down by the Tathāgata as laid down; what was laid down by the Tathāgata as not laid down. By these ten matters, they split and separate, they perform a legal act differently, they recite the Pātimokkha differently. To that extent, Upāli, is there schism in the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.35" },

{ text: `- What is the result of causing a schism in a united Saṅgha?<br>- Ānanda, it brings an evil result lasting for an eon.<br>- Bhante, what evil result lasts for an eon?<br>- Ānanda, being boiled in hell for an eon.<br>One who causes schism in the Saṅgha<br>Falls into a state of misery,<br>Falls into hell<br>For an eon;<br>Delighting in disharmony,<br>Established in unrighteousness,<br>Secure from bonds of suffering,<br>He has abandoned and left;<br>Whoever destroys the harmony<br>Of the community of bhikkhus,<br>For an eon that person<br>Is boiled in hell.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.38" },

{ text: `- Bhante, what is the result of reconciling a divided Saṅgha?<br>- Ānanda, it brings Brahmā-like merit!<br>- Bhante, what is Brahmā-like merit?<br>- Ānanda, for an eon, one rejoices in the heavenly world.<br>Happy is the person<br>Who reconciles the Saṅgha;<br>Happy is the person<br>Who helps the Saṅgha to be united;<br>Delighting in harmony,<br>Established on the right Dhamma.<br>Whoever makes the Saṅgha<br>Live in harmony,<br>For an eon that person<br>Rejoices in the heavenly world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.40" },

{ text: `Which five qualities should be internally established? 'I will speak at the right time, not at the wrong time; I will speak truthfully, not falsely; I will speak gently, not harshly; I will speak words connected with benefit, not unconnected with benefit; I will speak with a mind of loving-kindness, not with hatred.' These five qualities should be internally established. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who wishes to accuse another should, after examining these five qualities internally, after establishing these five qualities internally, accuse another.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.44" },

{ text: `- Bhante, for what reason, for what condition, is evil kamma done, is evil kamma continued to be done?<br>- Mahāli, due to greed, because of greed, evil kamma is done, evil kamma is continued to be done. Mahāli, due to hatred, because of hatred, evil kamma is done, evil kamma is continued to be done. Due to delusion, because of delusion, evil kamma is done, evil kamma is continued to be done. Mahāli, due to unwise attention, because of unwise attention, evil kamma is done, evil kamma is continued to be done. Mahāli, due to a wrongly directed mind, because of a wrongly directed mind, evil kamma is done, evil kamma is continued to be done. Mahāli, this is the cause, this is the condition, for evil kamma to be done, for evil kamma to be continued to be done.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.47" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, these ten things should be constantly reflected upon by one who has gone forth. What ten? One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'I have now entered the state of being casteless.' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'My livelihood depends on others.' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'My deportment should be different (from laypeople).' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'Do I reproach myself regarding virtue?' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'Do my wise fellow celibates, after examination, reproach me regarding virtue?' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'All things that are dear and agreeable to me are subject to change and alteration.' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'I am the owner of my kamma, heir of my kamma, born of my kamma, related to my kamma, supported by my kamma; whatever kamma I will do, good or evil, of that I will be the heir.' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'How do I spend my days and nights? What has become of me?' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'Do I delight in empty huts or not?' One who has gone forth should constantly reflect: 'Have I attained a superior human state, a truly noble distinction of knowledge and vision, so that when questioned by my fellow celibates on my last days, I will not be ashamed?' Bhikkhus, these ten things should be constantly reflected upon by one who has gone forth.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.48" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, what matter are you now discussing? What conversation has been interrupted among you?<br>- Here, Bhante, after the meal, returning from the alms round, we gathered in the assembly hall, competing, disputing, quarrelling, wounding one another with verbal weapons.<br>- Bhikkhus, it is not proper for you, clansmen who have gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, to live competing, disputing, quarrelling, wounding one another with verbal weapons. Bhikkhus, there are these ten things that are to be remembered, that create love, create respect, lead to concord, lead to non-dispute, to unity, to harmony. What ten?`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.50" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu examining thus gains great benefit in wholesome states: 'Do I dwell much with greed? Do I dwell much without greed? Do I dwell much with a hateful mind? Do I dwell much with a mind without hatred? Do I dwell much overcome by dullness and drowsiness, or do I dwell much with dullness and drowsiness abandoned? Do I dwell much with restlessness, or do I dwell much without restlessness? Do I dwell much with doubt, or do I dwell much beyond doubt? Do I dwell much with anger, or do I dwell much without anger? Do I dwell much with a defiled mind, or do I dwell much with an undefiled mind? Do I dwell much with bodily fever, or do I dwell much without bodily fever? Do I dwell much with laziness, or do I dwell much with energy and effort? Do I dwell much with an unconcentrated mind, or do I dwell much with a concentrated mind?'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.51" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu, examining thus, knows: 'I dwell much with a greedy mind; I dwell much with a hateful mind; I dwell much overcome by dullness and drowsiness; I dwell much with restlessness; I dwell much with doubt; I dwell much with anger; I dwell much with a defiled mind; I dwell much with bodily fever; I dwell much with laziness; I dwell much with an unconcentrated mind,' then that bhikkhu should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to abandon those evil unwholesome states. Just as, bhikkhus, when a cloth is on fire or the head is on fire, one should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to extinguish the burning cloth or head. So too, bhikkhus, that bhikkhu should arouse determination, desire, energy, effort, exertion, non-backsliding, mindfulness, and clear comprehension to abandon those evil unwholesome states.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.51" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu, examining thus, knows: 'I dwell much with a mind without greed; I dwell much with a mind without hatred; I dwell much with a mind without dullness and drowsiness; I dwell much with a mind without restlessness; I dwell much with a mind beyond doubt; I dwell much with a mind without anger; I dwell much with an undefiled mind; I dwell much with a body without fever; I dwell much with an energetic and striving mind; I dwell much with a concentrated mind,' then that bhikkhu, having established himself in those wholesome states, should further focus on the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.51" },

{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu strives to attain faith, virtue, learning, giving, and eloquence with wisdom. Those things do not remain stagnant in him, do not decline. Bhikkhus, I call this growth in wholesome states, not stagnation, not decline. Thus, bhikkhus, is growth in wholesome states, not stagnation, not decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.53" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I say that almsfood is of two kinds: to be used and not to be used — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said? Here, if one knows of a certain almsfood: 'This almsfood, when I use it, unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease' — then such almsfood should not be used. Here, if one knows of a certain almsfood: 'This almsfood, when I use it, unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase' — then such almsfood should be used.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.54" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I say that a person is of two kinds: to be associated with and not to be associated with — thus it has been said. For what reason is it said? Here, if one knows of a certain person: 'This person, if I associate with him, unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease' — then such a person should not be associated with. Here, if one knows of a certain person: 'This person, if I associate with him, unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase' — then such a person should be associated with. Bhikkhus, I say that a person is of two kinds: to be associated with and not to be associated with — thus it has been said, and for this reason it was said.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.54" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these ten perceptions that, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless. What ten? The perception of impermanence, the perception of non-self, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of a skeleton, the perception of a worm-eaten corpse, the perception of a discolored corpse, the perception of a fissured corpse, the perception of a bloated corpse. Bhikkhus, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.57" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless. What ten? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of non-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. Bhikkhus, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, culminating in the Deathless, ending in the Deathless.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.56" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if outside wanderers were to ask: 'Venerable sirs, what is the root of all things? What is the origin of all things? What is the accumulation of all things? What is the meeting place of all things? What is the foremost of all things? What is the master of all things? What is the supreme of all things? What is the core of all things? What is the penetration of all things? What is the final goal of all things?' Being asked thus, bhikkhus, you could answer them: 'All things have desire as root. All things have attention as origin. All things have contact as accumulation. All things have feeling as meeting place. All things have concentration as foremost. All things have mindfulness as master. All things have wisdom as supreme. All things have liberation as core. All things have the Deathless as penetration. All things have Nibbāna as final goal.'`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.58" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, you should train yourselves thus: 'Our minds will be practiced and accumulated as when we went forth; unarisen unwholesome states will not overcome our minds and remain; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of impermanence; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of non-self; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of foulness; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of danger; having known the world's evenness and unevenness, our minds will be practiced and accumulated with that perception; having known the world's arising and passing away, our minds will be practiced and accumulated with that perception; having known the world's origination and cessation, our minds will be practiced and accumulated with that perception; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of abandoning; our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of dispassion; and our minds will be practiced and accumulated with the perception of cessation.' Thus, bhikkhus, you should train yourselves.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.59" },

{ text: `- Venerable Girimānanda, Bhante, is sick, suffering, gravely ill. It would be good, Bhante, if the Blessed One would visit Venerable Girimānanda out of compassion.<br>- Ānanda, if you go to the bhikkhu Girimānanda and recite ten perceptions, then this is possible: after hearing the ten perceptions, the bhikkhu Girimānanda's illness may immediately subside! What ten? The perception of impermanence, the perception of non-self, the perception of foulness, the perception of danger, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence in all conditioned things, and mindfulness of breathing.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60" },

{ text: `- Venerable Girimānanda, Bhante, is sick, suffering, gravely ill. It would be good, Bhante, if the Blessed One would visit Venerable Girimānanda out of compassion.<br>- Ānanda, if you go to the bhikkhu Girimānanda and recite ten perceptions, then this is possible: after hearing the ten perceptions, the bhikkhu Girimānanda's illness may immediately subside! What ten? The perception of impermanence, the perception of non-self, the perception of foulness, the perception of danger, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence in all conditioned things, and mindfulness of breathing.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is the perception of impermanence? Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu goes to a forest, or to the foot of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects thus: 'Form is impermanent, feeling is impermanent, perception is impermanent, formations are impermanent, consciousness is impermanent.' Thus he dwells contemplating impermanence in these five aggregates subject to clinging. This, Ānanda, is called the perception of impermanence.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is the perception of non-self? Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu goes to a forest, or to the foot of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects thus: 'The eye is non-self, forms are non-self; the ear is non-self, sounds are non-self; the nose is non-self, odors are non-self; the tongue is non-self, tastes are non-self; the body is non-self, tangibles are non-self; the mind is non-self, mental phenomena are non-self.' This, Ānanda, is called the perception of non-self.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60" },

{ text: `And, Ānanda, what is the perception of danger? Here, Ānanda, a bhikkhu goes to a forest, or to the foot of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects thus: 'This body is of much suffering, of much danger. In this body, many kinds of illness arise. Such as eye disease, ear disease, nose disease, tongue disease, body disease, head disease, ear-canal disease, mouth disease, tooth disease, cough, asthma, catarrh, fever, aging disease, abdominal pain, fainting, dysentery, colic, cholera, leprosy, boils, eczema, tuberculosis, epilepsy, skin disease, itching, scabies, ringworm, scabies, blood-bile disease, diabetes, hemorrhoids, cancer, abscesses, ulcerations, diseases arising from bile, diseases arising from phlegm, from mucus, diseases arising from wind; diseases arising from the combination of humors; diseases arising from change of weather, diseases arising from overexertion, diseases arising from accidental causes; diseases due to kamma ripening, cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, urination.' Thus he dwells contemplating danger in this body.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, the first point of ignorance cannot be known such that one could say: 'Before this point, ignorance did not exist, then later it came into being.' Thus, bhikkhus, this has been said. Nevertheless, this matter is known: 'Due to this condition, ignorance (exists).' Bhikkhus, I say that ignorance has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for ignorance? The five hindrances, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that the five hindrances have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for the five hindrances? The three evil conducts, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that the three evil conducts have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for the three evil conducts? Unrestrained faculties, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that unrestrained faculties have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for unrestrained faculties? Lack of mindfulness and clear comprehension, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that lack of mindfulness and clear comprehension has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for lack of mindfulness and clear comprehension? Unwise attention, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that unwise attention has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for unwise attention? Lack of faith, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that lack of faith has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for lack of faith? Not hearing the good Dhamma, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that not hearing the good Dhamma has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for not hearing the good Dhamma? Not associating with good persons, one should answer.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.61" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, when not associating with good persons is complete, it completes not hearing the good Dhamma; when not hearing the good Dhamma is complete, it completes lack of faith; when lack of faith is complete, it completes unwise attention; when unwise attention is complete, it completes lack of mindfulness and clear comprehension; when lack of mindfulness and clear comprehension is complete, it completes unrestrained faculties; when unrestrained faculties are complete, it completes the three evil conducts; when the three evil conducts are complete, it completes the five hindrances; when the five hindrances are complete, it completes ignorance. Thus, this is the nutriment for ignorance, and thus is its completion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.61" },

{ text: `And, bhikkhus, I say that knowledge and liberation have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for knowledge and liberation? The seven factors of enlightenment, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that the seven factors of enlightenment have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for the seven factors of enlightenment? The four establishments of mindfulness, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that the four establishments of mindfulness have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for the four establishments of mindfulness? The three good conducts, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that the three good conducts have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for the three good conducts? Restrained faculties, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that restrained faculties have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for restrained faculties? Mindfulness and clear comprehension, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that mindfulness and clear comprehension have nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for mindfulness and clear comprehension? Wise attention, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that wise attention has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for wise attention? Faith, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that faith has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for faith? Hearing the good Dhamma, one should answer. Bhikkhus, I say that hearing the good Dhamma has nutriment, not without nutriment. And what is the nutriment for hearing the good Dhamma? Associating with good persons, one should answer.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.61" },

{ text: `So too, bhikkhus, when associating with good persons is complete, it completes hearing the good Dhamma; when hearing the good Dhamma is complete, it completes faith; when faith is complete, it completes wise attention; when wise attention is complete, it completes mindfulness and clear comprehension; when mindfulness and clear comprehension is complete, it completes restrained faculties; when restrained faculties are complete, it completes the three good conducts; when the three good conducts are complete, it completes the four establishments of mindfulness; when the four establishments of mindfulness are complete, it completes the seven factors of enlightenment; when the seven factors of enlightenment are complete, it completes knowledge and liberation. Thus, this is the nutriment for knowledge and liberation, and thus is its completion.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.61" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sāriputta, what is happiness and what is suffering?<br>- Venerable sir, birth is suffering, non-birth is happiness. When there is birth, venerable sir, this suffering is to be expected: cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, urination, contact with fire, contact with rod, contact with sword. Even relatives and friends, when they meet and gather, cause distress. Venerable sir, birth is suffering; when there is birth, this suffering is to be expected. When there is no birth, venerable sir, this happiness is to be expected: no cold, no heat, no hunger, no thirst, no defecation, no urination, no contact with fire, no contact with rod, no contact with sword. Even relatives and friends, when they meet and gather, cause no distress. Venerable sir, when there is no birth, this happiness is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.65" },

{ text: `- Venerable Sāriputta, in this Dhamma and Discipline, what is happiness and what is suffering?<br>- Displeasure, venerable sir, in this Dhamma and Discipline is suffering; pleasure is happiness. When displeasure is present, venerable sir, this suffering is to be expected: when walking, one does not find enjoyment; when standing... when sitting... when lying down... when going to the village... when going to the forest... when going to the foot of a tree... when going to an empty hut... when going to an open space... when going among the bhikkhus, one does not find enjoyment. When displeasure is present, venerable sir, this suffering is to be expected. When pleasure is present, venerable sir, this happiness is to be expected: when walking, one finds enjoyment; when standing... when sitting... when lying down... when going to the village... when going to the forest... when going to the foot of a tree... when going to an empty hut... when going to an open space... when going among the bhikkhus, one finds enjoyment. When pleasure is present, venerable sir, this happiness is to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.66" },

{ text: `- Venerable sirs, for one who has no faith in wholesome states, no moral shame... no moral dread... no energy... no wisdom in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, a decline in wholesome states is to be expected, not growth.<br>Just as, venerable sirs, at the time of the waning moon, whether by day or by night, the moon wanes in color, wanes in roundness, wanes in radiance, wanes in the width of its orbit. So too, venerable sirs, for one who has no faith in wholesome states, no moral shame... no moral dread... no energy... no wisdom in wholesome states, for that person, whether by day or by night, a decline in wholesome states is to be expected, not growth. A person without faith, venerable sirs, is decline. A person without moral dread, venerable sirs, is decline. An angry person, venerable sirs, is decline. A person of evil desires, venerable sirs, is decline. A person of evil friendship, venerable sirs, is decline. A person of wrong view, venerable sirs, is decline.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.67" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is not proper for you, clansmen who have gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, to dwell devoted to various kinds of talk, such as talk about kings... talk about existence and non-existence. Bhikkhus, there are these ten topics of conversation. What ten? Talk on few desires, talk on contentment, talk on seclusion, talk on non-association, talk on energy, talk on virtue, talk on concentration, talk on wisdom, talk on liberation, talk on the knowledge and vision of liberation. Bhikkhus, these are the ten topics of conversation. Bhikkhus, if you continue to speak about these ten topics of conversation, then you could outshine even the light of the moon and sun, those great mighty and powerful things, let alone the outside wanderers.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.69" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these ten praiseworthy things. What ten? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu himself has few desires and makes the topic of few desires to be discussed among the bhikkhus. A bhikkhu with few desires and who makes the topic of few desires to be discussed among the bhikkhus — this is a praiseworthy thing. And a bhikkhu himself is content... himself lives in seclusion... himself does not delight in company... himself is energetic... himself is virtuous... himself is concentrated... himself is wise... himself is liberated... himself possesses the knowledge and vision of liberation, and makes the topic of the knowledge and vision of liberation to be discussed among the bhikkhus — this is a praiseworthy thing. Bhikkhus, these are the ten praiseworthy things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.70" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, 'Noise is a thorn for jhāna' — thus have I said. Bhikkhus, there are these ten thorns. What ten? For one who delights in seclusion, delight in company is a thorn. For one who focuses on the sign of foulness, focusing on the sign of beauty is a thorn. For one who guards the sense faculties, watching shows and performances is a thorn. For one who lives the celibate life, association with women is a thorn. For one who has attained the first jhāna, noise is a thorn. For one who has attained the second jhāna, applied and sustained thought is a thorn. For one who has attained the third jhāna, rapture is a thorn. For one who has attained the fourth jhāna, breathing is a thorn. For one who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling are a thorn. Greed is a thorn. Hatred is a thorn. Delusion is a thorn. Bhikkhus, live without thorns. Bhikkhus, live free from thorns. Bhikkhus, live without thorns and free from thorns. Bhikkhus, one without thorns is the Arahant. Bhikkhus, one free from thorns is the Arahant. Bhikkhus, one who is without thorns and free from thorns is the Arahant.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.72" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for these ten desirable, pleasant, agreeable things that are hard to find in the world, these ten are obstructions. What ten? Laziness and lack of energy are an obstruction for wealth. Lack of adornment and decoration are an obstruction for beauty. Inappropriate action is an obstruction for freedom from illness. Evil friendship is an obstruction for virtue. Lack of sense restraint is an obstruction for the celibate life. Deceit is an obstruction for friendship. Lack of learning is an obstruction for great knowledge. Not listening, not asking is an obstruction for wisdom. Lack of attention and examination is an obstruction for (understanding) phenomena. Wrong conduct is an obstruction for the heavenly world. Bhikkhus, for these ten desirable, pleasant, agreeable things that are hard to find in the world, these ten are obstructions.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.73" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, for these ten desirable, pleasant, agreeable things that are hard to find in the world, these ten are nutriments. What ten? Not being lazy, being energetic is nutriment for wealth. Adornment and decoration are nutriment for beauty. Appropriate action is nutriment for freedom from illness. Friendship with good friends is nutriment for virtue. Sense restraint is nutriment for the celibate life. Not being deceitful is nutriment for friendship. Learning is nutriment for wisdom. Attention and examination are nutriment for (understanding) phenomena. Right conduct is nutriment for the heavenly world. Bhikkhus, for these ten desirable, pleasant, agreeable things that are hard to find in the world, these ten are nutriments.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.73" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, because of not abandoning three things, one cannot abandon unwise attention, cannot abandon practicing the wrong path, cannot abandon a sluggish nature. What three? Not abandoning forgetfulness, not abandoning lack of clear comprehension, not abandoning an agitated mind. Because of not abandoning these three things, bhikkhus, one cannot abandon unwise attention, cannot abandon practicing the wrong path, cannot abandon a sluggish nature.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.76" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, because of not abandoning three things, one cannot abandon forgetfulness, cannot abandon lack of clear comprehension, cannot abandon an agitated mind. What three? Not abandoning the desire not to visit the noble ones, not abandoning the desire not to listen to the noble Dhamma, not abandoning fault-finding. Because of not abandoning these three things, bhikkhus, one cannot abandon forgetfulness, cannot abandon lack of clear comprehension, cannot abandon an agitated mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.76" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, because of not abandoning three things, one cannot abandon restlessness, cannot abandon lack of restraint, cannot abandon immorality. What three? Not abandoning lack of faith, not abandoning stinginess, not abandoning laziness. Because of not abandoning these three things, bhikkhus, one cannot abandon restlessness, cannot abandon lack of restraint, cannot abandon immorality.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.76" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, a crow possesses ten evil qualities. What ten? Arrogant, ferocious, strong desire, gluttonous, cruel, without compassion, cowardly, harsh-voiced, forgetful, and storing up possessions. Bhikkhus, a crow possesses these ten evil qualities. So too, bhikkhus, an evil bhikkhu possesses ten evil qualities. What ten? Arrogant, ferocious, strong desire, gluttonous, cruel, without compassion, cowardly, harsh-voiced, forgetful, and storing up possessions. Bhikkhus, an evil bhikkhu possesses these ten evil qualities.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.77" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there are these ten grounds for resentment. What ten? Resentment is formed thinking: 'He has harmed me.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He is harming me.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He will harm me.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He has harmed someone I love, someone I like...' 'He is harming someone I love, someone I like...' 'He will harm someone I love, someone I like.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He has benefited someone I do not love, someone I do not like.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He is benefiting someone I do not love, someone I do not like.' Resentment is formed thinking: 'He will benefit someone I do not love, someone I do not like.' Getting angry without reason. Bhikkhus, these are the ten grounds for resentment.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.79" },

{ text: `- From how many things, Bhante, does the Tathāgata dwell withdrawn, detached, liberated, with unlimited mind?<br>- From ten things, Bāhuna, does the Tathāgata dwell withdrawn, detached, liberated, with unlimited mind. What ten? From form, Bāhuna, the Tathāgata dwells withdrawn, detached, liberated, with unlimited mind. From feeling, Bāhuna... From perception, Bāhuna... From formations, Bāhuna... From consciousness, Bāhuna... From birth, Bāhuna... From aging, Bāhuna... From death, Bāhuna... From this suffering, Bāhuna... From defilements, Bāhuna, the Tathāgata dwells withdrawn, detached, liberated, with unlimited mind. Just as, Bāhuna, a blue lotus, or a red lotus, or a white lotus, born in the water, grown up in the water, rises up above the water and stands without being stained by the water. So too, Bāhuna, from these ten things, the Tathāgata dwells withdrawn, detached, liberated, with unlimited mind.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.81" },

{ text: `- Ānanda, that a bhikkhu without faith will grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is impossible. Ānanda, that a bhikkhu who is immoral... who does not hear the Dhamma... who is difficult to speak to... who has evil friends... who is lazy... who is forgetful... who is discontent... who has evil desires... Ānanda, that a bhikkhu with wrong view will grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is impossible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.82" },

{ text: `Ānanda, that a bhikkhu with faith will grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is possible. Ānanda, that a bhikkhu who is virtuous... who hears the Dhamma and remembers what he has heard... who is easy to speak to... who has good friends... who is energetic... who is mindful... who is content... who has few desires... Ānanda, that a bhikkhu with right view will grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is possible. Ānanda, that a bhikkhu possessing these ten qualities will grow, increase, and expand in this Dhamma and Discipline — this is possible.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.82" },

{ text: `- Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu reviles, criticizes, and scolds the noble ones and his fellow celibates, it is impossible, it cannot happen that he will not encounter one of these ten misfortunes. What ten? He does not attain what has not been attained; what has been attained declines; he does not become well-versed in the good Dhamma; he becomes over-conceited regarding the good Dhamma; he does not live the holy life with joy; he commits a corrupt offense; he experiences a severe illness; he becomes mentally deranged; he becomes confused at the time of death; or after death, with the breakup of the body, he is reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu reviles, criticizes, and scolds the noble ones and his fellow celibates, it is impossible, it cannot happen that he will not encounter one of these ten misfortunes.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.88" },

{ text: `A person is born<br>With an axe in his mouth;<br>The fool speaking evil<br>Cuts himself with that.<br>Whoever praises the blameworthy,<br>Whoever blames the praiseworthy,<br>Heaps up misfortune<br>By his very mouth.<br>And because of that misfortune,<br>He does not find happiness.<br>Small is this misfortune<br>Caused by gambling,<br>When one loses one's wealth,<br>All is lost.<br>Far greater is the misfortune,<br>Not only losing everything,<br>But losing oneself as well.<br>One who harbors evil intent<br>Toward the Well-Gone Ones.<br>Whoever slanders the noble ones<br>With speech, with evil mind,<br>For a hundred thousand periods,<br>And thirty-six more ni-rab-bu-da,<br>And five ab-bu-da,<br>Will be reborn in hell,<br>Suffering there.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.89" },

{ text: `Householder, whatever austerity is practiced, if unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease, then that austerity, I say, should not be practiced. But, householder, whatever austerity is practiced, if unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase, then that austerity, I say, should be practiced. Householder, whatever adherence is taken up, if unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease, then that adherence, I say, should not be taken up. Whatever adherence is taken up, if unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase, then that adherence, I say, should be taken up. Householder, whatever effort is exerted, if unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease, then that effort, I say, should not be exerted. Whatever effort is exerted, if unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase, then that effort, I say, should be exerted. Householder, whatever abandoning is abandoned, if unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease, then that abandoning, I say, should not be abandoned. Whatever abandoning is abandoned, if unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase, then that abandoning, I say, should be abandoned. Householder, whatever liberation is liberated, if unwholesome states increase and wholesome states decrease, then that liberation, I say, should not be liberated. Whatever liberation is liberated, if unwholesome states decrease and wholesome states increase, then that liberation, I say, should be liberated.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.94" },

{ text: `Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, wherever an elder dwells, he dwells in peace. What ten? An elder who is long known, long gone forth, is virtuous... undertaking and training in the training rules; he is learned... well penetrated by right view; both Pātimokkhas are well transmitted in detail, well analyzed, well understood, well decided according to the sutta and in detail; he is skilled in the arising and settling of disputes; he loves the Dhamma; he speaks pleasant words, rejoices greatly in the supreme Dhamma and supreme Discipline; he is content with any kind of requisites such as robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites; he is gracious and well-restrained in going forward and returning, when sitting in the house; he attains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort the four jhānas that are higher states of mind, pleasant abidings in this very life; by the destruction of the taints, he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Possessing these ten qualities, bhikkhus, wherever an elder bhikkhu dwells, in whatever place, he dwells in peace.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.98" },

{ text: `He is content, satisfied with a robe to cover his body and with almsfood to sustain his belly, and wherever he goes, he takes only these with him. Just as a bird, wherever it flies, carries its wings with it; so too, he is content with a robe to cover his body and with almsfood to sustain his belly, and wherever he goes, he takes only these with him. Possessing this aggregate of virtue, he experiences within himself a blameless bliss.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.99" },

{ text: `These three ascetic perceptions, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, fulfill seven things. What seven? He is constantly one who acts continuously, practicing continuously in the rules of conduct; without craving; without hatred; without over-conceit, delighting in training; regarding the basic necessities of life, he thinks: 'This is the purpose of living energetically.' Bhikkhus, these three ascetic perceptions, when developed and cultivated, fulfill these seven things.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.101" },

{ text: `For a person with right view, bhikkhus, wrong view is cleansed, and whatever evil, unwholesome states arise due to wrong view are also cleansed for that person. And wholesome states due to right view lead to fulfillment in development. For a person with right intention, bhikkhus, wrong intention is cleansed... For a person with right speech... For a person with right action... For a person with right livelihood... For a person with right effort... For a person with right mindfulness... For a person with right concentration... For a person with right knowledge... For a person with right liberation, bhikkhus, wrong liberation is cleansed, and whatever evil, unwholesome states arise due to wrong liberation are also cleansed for that person. And wholesome states due to right liberation lead to fulfillment in development. Bhikkhus, this is the noble cleansing, this cleansing leads to complete disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. By reason of this cleansing, beings subject to birth are liberated from birth; beings subject to aging are liberated from aging; beings subject to death are liberated from death; beings subject to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are liberated from sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.107" },

{ text: `Few among humans<br>Reach the far shore,<br>While the rest of people<br>Run along this shore.<br>Those who practice the Dhamma<br>According to the well-taught teaching,<br>Will reach the far shore,<br>Crossing the realm of death so hard to cross.<br>The wise, abandoning dark states,<br>Develop bright states,<br>Leaving home for homelessness,<br>In seclusion, hard to delight in.<br>Seek delight in Nibbāna,<br>Abandon sensual pleasures, have no possessions,<br>The wise cleanse themselves<br>Of defilements from within.<br>Those with right mind,<br>Well develop the factors of enlightenment,<br>Abandon all attachments,<br>Rejoicing, not clinging,<br>Without taints, radiant,<br>They live at peace in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.117" },

{ text: `When the sun rises, bhikkhus, this is the forerunner, this is the herald, namely the dawn. So too, bhikkhus, for wholesome states, this is the forerunner, this is the herald, namely right view. From right view, bhikkhus, comes right intention. From right intention comes right speech. From right speech comes right action. From right action comes right livelihood. From right livelihood comes right effort. From right effort comes right mindfulness. From right mindfulness comes right concentration. From right concentration comes right knowledge. From right knowledge comes right liberation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.121", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.121" },

{ text: `These ten things, bhikkhus, are pure, bright, exist only in the Discipline of the Well-Gone One. What ten? Right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration, right knowledge, right liberation. These ten things, bhikkhus, are pure, bright, exist only in the Discipline of the Well-Gone One.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.123", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.123" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, I say that killing living beings is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that taking what is not given is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that sexual misconduct is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that false speech is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that divisive speech is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that harsh speech is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that idle chatter is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that covetousness is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that ill-will is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Bhikkhus, I say that wrong view is of three kinds: due to greed, due to hatred, due to delusion. Thus, bhikkhus, greed is a cause for the origination of action, hatred is a cause for the origination of action, delusion is a cause for the origination of action. With the cessation of greed comes the cessation of action, with the cessation of hatred comes the cessation of action, with the cessation of delusion comes the cessation of action.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.174", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.174" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is practiced, developed, cultivated, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, eleven benefits are to be expected. What eleven? One sleeps well, wakes up well, does not see bad dreams, is loved by human beings, is loved by non-humans, devas protect him, fire, poison, and sword do not touch him, his mind becomes concentrated quickly, his complexion is clear, he dies without confusion; and if he does not penetrate further, he attains the Brahmā world. Bhikkhus, when the liberation of mind by loving-kindness is practiced, developed, cultivated, made the vehicle, made the foundation, established, consolidated, and properly undertaken, these eleven benefits are to be expected.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 11.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an11.15" },
            
         
               


{ text: `Mind precedes all phenomena,<br>Mind is their master, mind is their maker.<br>If one speaks or acts with a corrupted mind,<br>Suffering follows,<br>Like the wheel follows the ox's foot.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `Mind precedes all phenomena,<br>Mind is their master, mind is their maker.<br>If one speaks or acts with a pure mind,<br>Happiness follows,<br>Like a shadow that never leaves.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `'He abused me, he struck me,<br>He overpowered me, he robbed me.'<br>For those who harbor such thoughts,<br>Hatred is not appeased.<br><br>'He abused me, he struck me,<br>He overpowered me, he robbed me.'<br>For those who do not harbor such thoughts,<br>Hatred is appeased.<br><br>Not by hatred are hatreds ever appeased in this world.<br>Only by non-hatred are hatreds appeased.<br>This is the eternal law.<br><br>Others do not understand<br>That we must restrain ourselves here.<br>But those who understand this,<br>Their quarrels cease.<br><br>Victory begets enmity,<br>The defeated lie down in pain.<br>The peaceful live happily,<br>Having abandoned both victory and defeat.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `One who dwells perceiving the beautiful,<br>Not restraining the senses,<br>Immoderate in food,<br>Lazy, of little energy,<br>Māra overcomes that person,<br>Like a weak tree in the wind.<br><br>One who dwells perceiving the foul,<br>Well restraining the senses,<br>Moderate in food,<br>Having faith, energetic,<br>Māra does not overcome that person,<br>Like a rocky mountain in the wind.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `One who wears the robe,<br>Yet with mind not free from defilements,<br>Not self-controlled, not truthful,<br>Is not worthy of the robe.<br><br>One who casts off defilements,<br>Well-established in virtue,<br>Self-controlled, truthful,<br>Is indeed worthy of the robe.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `The unreal they take for real,<br>The real they take for unreal.<br>They never reach the real,<br>By their wrong thoughts and wrong conduct.<br><br>Having known the real as real,<br>And the unreal as unreal,<br>They reach the real,<br>By their right thoughts and right conduct.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `As rain penetrates a poorly thatched house,<br>So lust penetrates an undeveloped mind.<br><br>As rain does not penetrate a well-thatched house,<br>So lust does not penetrate a well-developed mind.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `Here he grieves, hereafter he grieves,<br>The evil-doer grieves in both worlds.<br>He grieves, he is afflicted,<br>Seeing the defilement of his own deeds.<br><br>Here he rejoices, hereafter he rejoices,<br>The merit-maker rejoices in both worlds.<br>He rejoices, he delights,<br>Seeing the purity of his own deeds.<br><br>Here he laments, hereafter he laments,<br>The evil-doer laments in both worlds.<br>He laments: 'I have done evil,'<br>And even more he laments, fallen to a lower realm.<br><br>Here he is happy, hereafter he is happy,<br>The merit-maker is happy in both worlds.<br>He is happy: 'I have done good,'<br>And even more he is happy, reborn in a good destination.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `Though one recites many scriptures,<br>If heedless, not practicing,<br>Like a cowherd counting others' cattle,<br>One has no share in the ascetic life.<br><br>Though one recites few scriptures,<br>But practices the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma,<br>Having abandoned greed, hatred, and delusion,<br>Clearly comprehending, mind liberated,<br>Clinging to nothing in both worlds,<br>One has a share in the ascetic life.`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20" },

{ text: `Heedfulness is the path to the Deathless,<br>Heedlessness is the path to death.<br>The heedful do not die,<br>The heedless are as if dead already.<br><br>Clearly understanding this distinction,<br>The wise are not heedless,<br>Delighting in heedfulness,<br>They rejoice in the domain of the noble ones.<br><br>Those who constantly meditate,<br>Persistently striving,<br>The wise attain Nibbāna,<br>The supreme security from bondage.<br><br>Striving, mindful,<br>Pure in conduct, acting carefully,<br>Self-controlled, living the Dhamma,<br>One who dwells heedfully,<br>His fame grows.<br><br>By striving, by heedfulness,<br>By self-control, by restraint,<br>The wise person builds an island<br>That no flood can overwhelm.`, ref: "Dhammapada 21-32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp21-32" },

{ text: `The foolish, ignorant people<br>Are devoted to heedlessness.<br>The wise protect heedfulness<br>As their greatest treasure.<br><br>Do not give way to heedlessness,<br>Do not be drawn into the enjoyment of sensual pleasures.<br>One who is heedful and meditative<br>Attains great happiness.<br><br>When the wise person dispels heedlessness<br>By heedfulness,<br>Having climbed the tower of wisdom,<br>Sorrowless, he looks at the sorrowing,<br>Standing on the mountain peak,<br>He looks down at the fools on the plain.<br><br>Ardent among the heedless,<br>Awake among those who sleep,<br>The wise person advances<br>Like a swift horse leaving behind a weak horse.<br><br>Delighting in heedfulness,<br>A bhikkhu seeing fear in heedlessness,<br>Advances like a blazing fire,<br>Burning fetters great and small.<br><br>Delighting in heedfulness,<br>A bhikkhu seeing fear in heedlessness,<br>Cannot decline,<br>He is indeed close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Dhammapada 21-32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp21-32" },

{ text: `The mind is fickle, agitated,<br>Difficult to guard, difficult to restrain.<br>The wise one makes it straight,<br>Like a fletcher makes an arrow straight.<br><br>Like a fish thrown on dry ground,<br>Cast out of its watery home,<br>This mind struggles and trembles,<br>One should abandon the realm of Māra.<br><br>Difficult to hold down, nimble,<br>It alights wherever it desires.<br>Good is the taming of the mind;<br>A tamed mind brings happiness.<br><br>The mind is very subtle, hard to see,<br>It alights wherever it desires.<br>The wise one guards the mind;<br>A guarded mind brings happiness.`, ref: "Dhammapada 33-43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp33-43" },

{ text: `Going far, wandering alone,<br>Without form, dwelling in a cave.<br>One who subdues the mind<br>Is freed from Māra's bonds.<br><br>One whose mind is not settled,<br>Who does not know the true Dhamma,<br>Whose faith is wavering,<br>Does not perfect wisdom.<br><br>One whose mind is not flooded by lust,<br>Not attacked by hatred,<br>Having transcended both good and evil,<br>An awakened one has no fear.<br><br>An enemy can harm an enemy,<br>One who hates can harm another,<br>But a wrongly directed mind<br>Can do even greater harm.<br><br>Not mother, not father,<br>Nor any other relative,<br>Can do what a well-directed mind<br>Can do for one's own good.`, ref: "Dhammapada 33-43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp33-43" },

{ text: `Know the body as a clay pot,<br>Establish the mind as a fortress,<br>Fight Māra with the sword of wisdom,<br>Guard your conquest, be free from attachment.<br><br>Before long, alas, this body<br>Will lie upon the ground,<br>Discarded, without consciousness,<br>Like a useless piece of wood.`, ref: "Dhammapada 33-43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp33-43" },

{ text: `Seeing the body as like foam,<br>Realizing its nature as a mirage,<br>Break the flowers of Māra's arrow,<br>Go beyond the sight of the King of Death.<br><br>The person who gathers flowers (of sensual pleasure),<br>With a mind attached and infatuated,<br>Is carried away by Death,<br>As a flood carries away a sleeping village.<br><br>The person who gathers flowers (of sensual pleasure),<br>With a mind attached and infatuated,<br>Before they are satisfied,<br>Death overpowers them.`, ref: "Dhammapada 44-59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp44-59" },

{ text: `The fragrance of flowers does not travel against the wind,<br>But the fragrance of a virtuous person travels against the wind,<br>Only a genuine person suffuses all directions.<br><br>Sandalwood, jasmine, lotus, and trumpet flower:<br>Among these fragrances,<br>The fragrance of virtue is supreme.<br><br>Little is this fragrance of sandalwood and jasmine,<br>But the fragrance of the virtuous person<br>Suffuses even the devas, supreme.<br><br>But those who possess virtue,<br>Dwelling heedfully,<br>Liberated by perfect knowledge,<br>Māra cannot find their path.`, ref: "Dhammapada 44-59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp44-59" },

{ text: `As on a heap of rubbish<br>Thrown on the main road,<br>A lotus flower might grow,<br>Fragrant and delightful.<br><br>So among the multitude of beings,<br>Defiled, blind, and worldly,<br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One<br>Shines forth with wisdom.`, ref: "Dhammapada 44-59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp44-59" },

{ text: `Like a beautiful flower,<br>Colorful but without fragrance,<br>So well-spoken words are fruitless<br>If not acted upon.<br><br>Like a beautiful flower,<br>Colorful and also fragrant,<br>So well-spoken words are fruitful<br>When acted upon.<br><br>From a heap of flowers<br>Many garlands are made.<br>So too, for one born mortal,<br>Many good deeds should be done.`, ref: "Dhammapada 44-59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp44-59" },

{ text: `Long is the night for the sleepless,<br>Long is the journey for the weary,<br>Long is saṃsāra for the fool<br>Who does not know the true Dhamma.<br><br>If one cannot find a companion<br>Better than or equal to oneself,<br>One should resolutely live alone,<br>For there is no fellowship with a fool.`, ref: "Dhammapada 60-75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp60-75" },

{ text: `'My sons, my wealth!' — <br>Thus the fool worries.<br>Even oneself does not belong to oneself,<br>How much less sons and wealth?<br><br>The fool who knows his folly<br>Is thereby wise.<br>The fool who thinks himself wise<br>Is indeed a fool.<br><br>Though a fool may associate all his life<br>With a wise person,<br>He no more knows the Dhamma<br>Than a spoon knows the taste of soup.<br><br>Though a wise person may associate only a moment<br>With a wise person,<br>He quickly knows the Dhamma,<br>As the tongue knows the taste of soup.`, ref: "Dhammapada 60-75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp60-75" },

{ text: `The foolish, ignorant person<br>Treats himself as an enemy,<br>Doing evil deeds<br>That bear bitter fruit.<br><br>That deed is not well done<br>Which, having been done, one regrets,<br>And for which, with tearful face,<br>One weeps, receiving its result.<br><br>But that deed is well done<br>Which, having been done, one does not regret,<br>And for which, joyful and happy,<br>One receives its result.<br><br>The fool thinks it sweet<br>As long as evil has not ripened,<br>But when evil ripens,<br>The fool experiences suffering.<br><br>The evil deed done does not curdle immediately,<br>Like milk just milked;<br>Burning, it follows the fool,<br>Like fire covered with ash.`, ref: "Dhammapada 60-75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp60-75" },

{ text: `Only to his own ruin<br>Does the fool gain knowledge;<br>It destroys his good fortune,<br>Splitting his head.<br><br>Desiring undeserved prestige,<br>Wanting precedence among bhikkhus,<br>Authority in the monasteries,<br>And honor from families.<br><br>Let both laypeople and ascetics think:<br>'This is done by me.'<br>In every task, great or small,<br>Let them follow my command.'<br>Such are the thoughts of the fool;<br>His desire and conceit increase.<br><br>Different is the path of worldly gain,<br>Different is the path to Nibbāna.<br>Let the bhikkhu, the Buddha's disciple,<br>Understanding this clearly,<br>Not delight in honors,<br>But cultivate seclusion.`, ref: "Dhammapada 60-75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp60-75" },

{ text: `If one sees a wise person<br>Who points out faults and reproaches,<br>Like one who reveals hidden treasure,<br>One should associate with such a wise person.<br>Associating with such a one,<br>One becomes better, not worse.<br><br>Those who advise and instruct,<br>Who restrain others from evil,<br>Are dear to the good,<br>But hateful to the bad.<br><br>Do not associate with evil friends,<br>Do not associate with the base.<br>Associate with good friends,<br>Associate with the noble ones.<br><br>One who delights in the Dhamma<br>With a clear mind,<br>The wise person always rejoices<br>In the Dhamma proclaimed by the noble ones.`, ref: "Dhammapada 76-89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp76-89" },

{ text: `Irrigators guide water,<br>Fletchers shape arrows,<br>Carpenters shape wood,<br>The wise tame themselves.<br><br>Like a solid rock<br>Is not shaken by the wind,<br>So the wise are not shaken<br>By praise and blame.<br><br>Like a deep lake,<br>Clear and undisturbed,<br>So the wise become clear<br>Upon hearing the Dhamma.<br><br>The good abandon everything,<br>The pure do not speak of sensual desires,<br>Whether touched by pleasure or pain,<br>The wise show neither elation nor dejection.`, ref: "Dhammapada 76-89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp76-89" },

{ text: `Not for one's own sake, not for another's sake,<br>Not to seek sons, wealth, or kingdom,<br>Nor to achieve one's own success<br>Through unjust means.<br>That person is truly virtuous,<br>Wise, and righteous.<br><br>Few among humans<br>Reach the far shore,<br>While the rest of people<br>Run along this shore.<br><br>Those who practice the Dhamma<br>According to the well-taught teaching,<br>Will reach the far shore,<br>Crossing the realm of death so hard to cross.`, ref: "Dhammapada 76-89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp76-89" },

{ text: `The wise, abandoning dark states,<br>Develop bright states,<br>Leaving home for homelessness,<br>In seclusion, hard to delight in.<br><br>Seek delight in Nibbāna,<br>Abandon sensual pleasures, have nothing,<br>The wise cleanse themselves<br>Of defilements from within.<br><br>Those with right mind,<br>Well develop the factors of enlightenment,<br>Abandon all attachments,<br>Rejoicing, not clinging,<br>Without taints, radiant,<br>They live at peace in the world.`, ref: "Dhammapada 76-89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp76-89" },

{ text: `One who has reached the goal is without sorrow,<br>Liberated from everything,<br>Having cut off all bonds,<br>He is not afflicted.<br><br>Mindful, striving,<br>Not delighting in any dwelling,<br>Like a swan leaving a lake,<br>They abandon all their shelters.<br><br>Those who do not store up possessions,<br>Who know moderation in food,<br>Who are free in their range,<br>The Void, the Signless, liberation —<br>Like birds in the sky,<br>Their path is hard to trace.<br><br>One whose taints are destroyed,<br>Not attached to food,<br>Free in his range,<br>The Void, the Signless liberation —<br>Like birds in the sky,<br>His path is hard to trace.`, ref: "Dhammapada 90-99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp90-99" },

{ text: `One who has restrained his senses,<br>Like a driver with a well-trained horse,<br>Who has abandoned conceit, taints destroyed,<br>Such a one is dear to the devas.<br><br>Like the earth, without resentment,<br>Like a door-post, steadfast,<br>Like a lake free from mud,<br>No more wandering on, such a one.<br><br>One whose mind is still,<br>Whose speech and action are still,<br>Liberated by perfect knowledge, at peace,<br>Such a one is a tranquil one.<br><br>In village or forest,<br>In valley or on hill,<br>Wherever Arahants dwell,<br>That place is delightful.<br><br>Delightful are the forests,<br>Where people do not rejoice,<br>The passion-free rejoice there,<br>For they seek no sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Dhammapada 90-99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp90-99" },

{ text: `Better than a thousand words<br>That are meaningless,<br>Is a single meaningful word,<br>Upon hearing which, one becomes peaceful.<br><br>Better than a thousand verses<br>That are meaningless,<br>Is a single verse of meaning,<br>Upon hearing which, one becomes peaceful.<br><br>Better than reciting a hundred meaningless verses,<br>Is a single line of Dhamma,<br>Upon hearing which, one becomes peaceful.`, ref: "Dhammapada 100-115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp100-115" },

{ text: `Though one should conquer thousands upon thousands of enemies on the battlefield,<br>Yet one who conquers oneself is indeed the greatest conqueror.<br><br>Conquering oneself is better than conquering others.<br>One who is self-tamed,<br>Who lives constantly self-controlled,<br><br>No deva nor gandhabba,<br>No Māra nor Brahmā,<br>Can turn the victory of such a person into defeat.`, ref: "Dhammapada 100-115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp100-115" },

{ text: `Month after month one may offer a thousand pieces of gold,<br>Sacrificing for a hundred years,<br>Yet for a moment one might pay homage to a self-developed person.<br>That homage is better than a hundred years of sacrifice.<br><br>Even if for a hundred years one worships the sacred fire in the forest,<br>Yet for a moment one might pay homage to a self-developed person.<br>That homage is better than a hundred years of sacrifice.<br><br>Whatever sacrifice or offering one makes in the world for a year,<br>To gain merit,<br>All that is not worth a quarter of the respect shown to the upright.<br><br>One who always respects and honors the elders,<br>Four things increase for him:<br>Life span, beauty, happiness, and strength.`, ref: "Dhammapada 100-115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp100-115" },

{ text: `Though one should live a hundred years<br>Immoral, without concentration,<br>Better is a single day<br>Lived virtuously and meditatively.<br><br>Though one should live a hundred years<br>Without wisdom, without concentration,<br>Better is a single day<br>Lived with wisdom and meditatively.<br><br>Though one should live a hundred years<br>Lazy, without energy,<br>Better is a single day<br>Lived with energetic effort.<br><br>Though one should live a hundred years<br>Without seeing the arising and passing of things,<br>Better is a single day<br>Seeing the arising and passing of things.<br><br>Though one should live a hundred years<br>Without seeing the Deathless state,<br>Better is a single day<br>Seeing the Deathless state.<br><br>Though one should live a hundred years<br>Without seeing the supreme Dhamma,<br>Better is a single day<br>Seeing the supreme Dhamma.`, ref: "Dhammapada 100-115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp100-115" },

{ text: `Make haste in doing good,<br>Restrain the mind from evil.<br>For one who is slow in doing good,<br>The mind delights in evil.<br><br>If a person does evil,<br>Let him not do it again and again.<br>Let him not desire such evil,<br>For accumulation of evil leads to suffering.<br><br>If a person does good,<br>Let him do it again and again.<br>Let him desire such good,<br>For accumulation of good leads to happiness.`, ref: "Dhammapada 116-128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp116-128" },

{ text: `The evil-doer sees it as good<br>As long as evil has not ripened.<br>But when evil ripens,<br>The evil-doer sees the evil.<br><br>Do not overlook evil,<br>Thinking 'It will not come to me.'<br>By the falling of water drops,<br>A water jar is filled.<br>The fool becomes full of evil,<br>Accumulating it little by little.<br><br>Do not overlook good,<br>Thinking 'It will not come to me.'<br>By the falling of water drops,<br>A water jar is filled.<br>The wise person becomes full of good,<br>Accumulating it little by little.`, ref: "Dhammapada 116-128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp116-128" },

{ text: `Few companions, many dangers,<br>Like a merchant avoiding a dangerous road.<br>Like one who loves life avoiding poison,<br>So avoid evil.<br><br>If there is no wound on the hand,<br>One can handle poison.<br>Without a wound, poison does not harm.<br>One who does no evil, no evil befalls.`, ref: "Dhammapada 116-128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp116-128" },

{ text: `One who harms an innocent person,<br>A pure, blameless one,<br>Evil returns to that fool,<br>Like fine dust thrown against the wind.<br><br>Some are reborn in the womb,<br>Evil-doers are reborn in hell,<br>The righteous go to heaven,<br>The taintless attain Nibbāna.<br><br>Not in the sky, not in the middle of the ocean,<br>Not by entering a mountain cave,<br>Nowhere in the world can one find a place<br>Where one can escape from the result of evil actions.<br><br>Not in the sky, not in the middle of the ocean,<br>Not by entering a mountain cave,<br>Nowhere in the world can one find a place<br>Where one can escape from the hands of Death.`, ref: "Dhammapada 116-128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp116-128" },

{ text: `All tremble at the rod,<br>All fear death.<br>Comparing oneself with others,<br>One should neither kill nor cause to kill.<br><br>All tremble at the rod,<br>All love life.<br>Comparing oneself with others,<br>One should neither kill nor cause to kill.<br><br>Seeking happiness for themselves,<br>Those who strike others with the rod,<br>Seeking happiness for themselves,<br>Will not find happiness in the hereafter.<br><br>Seeking happiness for themselves,<br>Those who do not strike others with the rod,<br>Seeking happiness for themselves,<br>Will find happiness in the hereafter.`, ref: "Dhammapada 129-145", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp129-145" },

{ text: `Do not speak harshly to anyone,<br>Those spoken to might retort.<br>Painful indeed is retaliation,<br>The rod may strike you in return.<br><br>If you remain silent,<br>Like a broken gong,<br>You have already attained Nibbāna,<br>No anger is found in you.<br><br>As with a goad the cowherd drives the cows to pasture,<br>So old age and death drive the life of beings.<br><br>A fool, doing evil deeds,<br>Does not realize what he does.<br>By his own actions, the fool<br>Is tormented, like one burned by fire.`, ref: "Dhammapada 129-145", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp129-145" },

{ text: `Not by nakedness, nor by matted hair,<br>Nor by smearing oneself with dust,<br>Nor by fasting, nor by sleeping on the ground,<br>Nor by being filthy, nor by squatting,<br>Does a person become pure,<br>If he has not removed doubt.<br><br>One who lives adorned,<br>Yet is peaceful, tamed,<br>Persistent, living the holy life,<br>Not harming any living beings,<br>He is a brahmin, an ascetic, a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Dhammapada 129-145", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp129-145" },

{ text: `Hard to find in the world is a person<br>Who feels shame, who restrains himself,<br>Who avoids reproach,<br>Like a good horse avoids the whip.<br><br>Like a good horse touched by the whip,<br>Be ardent and energetic.<br>With faith, virtue, and energy,<br>Concentration and investigation of states,<br>Endowed with clear knowledge and conduct, mindful,<br>Abandon this boundless suffering.<br><br>Irrigators guide water,<br>Fletchers shape arrows,<br>Carpenters shape wood,<br>The wise tame themselves.`, ref: "Dhammapada 129-145", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp129-145" },

{ text: `Why is there laughter, why is there joy,<br>When the world is constantly burning?<br>Shrouded in darkness,<br>Why do you not seek a light?<br><br>Behold this painted image,<br>A mass of sores, a composite body,<br>Full of many ailments, the object of many thoughts,<br>In which nothing is permanent or stable.<br><br>This form is worn out by old age,<br>A nest of diseases, fragile,<br>This heap of corruption breaks apart,<br>Death is the end of life.<br><br>These dove-colored bones,<br>Like gourds discarded in autumn,<br>Having seen them, what pleasure is there?`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },

{ text: `This city is built of bones,<br>Plastered with flesh and blood,<br>Here dwell old age and death,<br>Conceit and deceit are stored.`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },
{ text: `The king's beautiful chariot also decays,<br>This body too will decay,<br>But the Dhamma of the good does not decay.<br>Thus the truly good speak to the good.`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },
{ text: `One of little learning, like a bull,<br>Grows old, his flesh increases,<br>But his wisdom does not grow.`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },
{ text: `Through many a birth in saṃsāra I wandered,<br>Seeking but not finding the builder of this house.<br>Painful is birth again and again.<br><br>Oh housebuilder! Now you are seen!<br>You shall not build a house again.<br>All your rafters are broken,<br>Your ridgepole is shattered.<br>My mind has attained the unconditioned,<br>Craving is destroyed.`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },
{ text: `When young, not living the holy life,<br>Not acquiring wealth,<br>One languishes like an old heron<br>By a lake without fish.<br><br>When young, not living the holy life,<br>Not acquiring wealth,<br>One lies like a broken bow,<br>Sighing over the past.`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156" },
{ text: `If one holds oneself dear,<br>One should guard oneself well.<br>Let the wise person keep vigil<br>During any of the three watches.<br><br>First establish oneself<br>In what is proper.<br>Then instruct others;<br>The wise should not be defiled.<br><br>Let one do as one teaches others;<br>Well tamed, one may tame others.<br>Self-taming is indeed difficult.<br><br>Oneself is the refuge of oneself;<br>What other refuge could there be?<br>With oneself well tamed,<br>One gains a refuge hard to gain.`, ref: "Dhammapada 157-166", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp157-166" },
{ text: `The evil done by oneself,<br>Born of oneself, produced by oneself,<br>Crushes the foolish one,<br>As a diamond crushes a gem.<br><br>One who is extremely immoral,<br>Like a creeper strangling a tree,<br>Brings harm to oneself,<br>As an enemy wishes.<br><br>Easy to do are things that are evil,<br>Things harmful to oneself.<br>But what is beneficial and good<br>Is truly difficult to do.`, ref: "Dhammapada 157-166", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp157-166" },
{ text: `By oneself evil is done,<br>By oneself one is defiled.<br>By oneself evil is left undone,<br>By oneself one is purified.<br>Purity and impurity depend on oneself;<br>No one can purify another.<br><br>Do not follow the inferior Dhamma,<br>Do not live heedlessly,<br>Do not embrace wrong views,<br>Do not be a worldling.`, ref: "Dhammapada 157-166", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp157-166" },
{ text: `Strive, do not be heedless!<br>Live righteously.<br>One who lives righteously<br>Attains happiness in this life and the next.<br><br>Live righteously,<br>Do not live unrighteously.<br>One who lives righteously<br>Attains happiness in this life and the next.<br><br>Look upon the world as a bubble,<br>Look upon it as a mirage.<br>One who sees the world thus<br>Is not seen by the King of Death.<br><br>Come, look upon this world<br>Like a beautiful royal chariot.<br>Fools are attached to it,<br>But the wise have no attachment.`, ref: "Dhammapada 167-178", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp167-178" },
{ text: `One who was heedless before<br>And afterwards is not heedless,<br>Illumines this world<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>One who overcomes evil deeds<br>With wholesome deeds,<br>Illumines this world<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>This world is truly blind,<br>Few are those who see clearly.<br>Like birds escaping from a net,<br>Few go to heaven.<br><br>Like a swan flying through the sky,<br>With psychic power moving through space,<br>Having conquered Māra and his army,<br>The wise depart from this world.`, ref: "Dhammapada 167-178", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp167-178" },
{ text: `Whoever transgresses one thing,<br>Whoever speaks falsely,<br>Whoever denies the world beyond,<br>No evil remains undone by them.<br><br>The miserly do not go to heaven,<br>Fools do not praise giving.<br>But the wise rejoice in giving,<br>And thereby become happy in the hereafter.<br><br>Better than ruling over the earth,<br>Better than going to heaven,<br>Better than lordship over the universe,<br>Is the fruit of stream-entry.`, ref: "Dhammapada 167-178", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp167-178" },
{ text: `The victor is never defeated,<br>The victor walks in the world,<br>No trace of victory is found.<br>The Buddha's domain is vast —<br>Who can trace the footprint of the One who leaves no trace?<br><br>One who has disentangled the net of craving,<br>No longer led by attachment,<br>The Buddha's domain is vast —<br>Who can trace the footprint of the One who leaves no trace?<br><br>The wise who are devoted to meditation,<br>Who delight in the peace of seclusion,<br>Even devas hold them dear —<br>The fully enlightened, mindful ones.`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196" },
{ text: `Hard is it to be born as a human,<br>Hard is the life of mortals,<br>Hard is the hearing of the good Dhamma,<br>Hard is the arising of a Buddha.<br><br>To refrain from all evil,<br>To accomplish what is wholesome,<br>To purify one's mind —<br>This is the teaching of the Buddhas.<br><br>The Buddhas always teach:<br>Patience is the supreme austerity,<br>Nibbāna is supreme.<br>One who goes forth does not harm another;<br>An ascetic does not harm others.<br><br>Not reviling, not harming,<br>Restrained in the Pātimokkha,<br>Moderate in food,<br>Dwelling in a secluded lodging,<br>Devoted to the higher mind —<br>This is the teaching of the Buddhas.`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196" },
{ text: `Even with a shower of gold coins,<br>Sensual desires are never satisfied.<br>Sensual pleasures are bitter and of little sweetness.<br>Knowing this, the wise person does not delight in them.<br><br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One<br>Does not seek sensual pleasures,<br>Even those of the devas.<br>They delight only in the destruction of craving.`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196" },
{ text: `Human beings, frightened, seek many refuges:<br>Forests, mountains, parks, groves, and shrines.<br><br>That refuge is not secure,<br>That refuge is not supreme.<br>Having taken that refuge,<br>One is not freed from all suffering.<br><br>One who takes refuge in the Buddha,<br>The Dhamma, and the Saṅgha,<br>Sees with right knowledge<br>The Four Noble Truths.<br><br>Suffering, the origin of suffering,<br>The overcoming of suffering,<br>And the Noble Eightfold Path<br>Leading to the cessation of suffering.<br><br>That is the secure refuge,<br>That is the supreme refuge.<br>Having taken that refuge,<br>One is freed from all suffering.`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196" },
{ text: `Hard to find is a noble person;<br>They are not born everywhere.<br>Where such a wise one is born,<br>That family is happy.<br><br>Happy is the arising of a Buddha!<br>Happy is the teaching of the Dhamma!<br>Happy is the harmony of the Saṅgha!<br>Happy is the practice of those in harmony!<br><br>Honoring those worthy of honor,<br>Whether Buddhas or their disciples,<br>Those who have transcended frivolous talk,<br>Who have abandoned sorrow and lamentation.<br><br>Honoring such ones,<br>Peaceful and fearless,<br>Such merit cannot be measured.`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196" },
{ text: `Happy indeed we live,<br>Without hatred among the hateful.<br>Among hateful people,<br>We dwell without hatred.<br><br>Happy indeed we live,<br>Without illness among the ill.<br>Among ill people,<br>We dwell without illness.<br><br>Happy indeed we live,<br>Without restlessness among the restless.<br>Among restless people,<br>We dwell without restlessness.<br><br>Happy indeed we live,<br>We who have nothing called our own.<br>We shall feed on joy,<br>Like the radiant devas.`, ref: "Dhammapada 197-208", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp197-208" },
{ text: `What fire compares to the fire of greed?<br>What evil compares to hatred?<br>What suffering compares to the aggregates?<br>What happiness compares to peace?<br><br>Hunger is the worst disease,<br>Conditioned things are the worst suffering.<br>Knowing this as it really is,<br>Nibbāna is the supreme happiness.<br><br>Freedom from illness is the highest gain,<br>Contentment is the highest wealth,<br>Trustworthiness is the best relative,<br>Nibbāna is the supreme happiness.<br><br>Having tasted the flavour of solitude,<br>One tastes the flavour of peace.<br>Fearless and free from evil,<br>One drinks the taste of Dhamma joy.`, ref: "Dhammapada 197-208", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp197-208" },
{ text: `Good it is to see the noble ones,<br>Living with them is always blissful.<br>Not seeing fools is always blissful.<br><br>Living with a fool brings long sorrow.<br>Painful is association with a fool,<br>As living with an enemy.<br>Happy is association with the wise,<br>As living with relatives.<br><br>The wise one, the intelligent,<br>The learned, the virtuous,<br>The self-controlled, the noble one —<br>Associate and befriend that good, wise person,<br>Like the moon following the path of the stars.`, ref: "Dhammapada 197-208", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp197-208" },
{ text: `One who is diligent in what should not be done,<br>And not diligent in what should be done,<br>Abandoning the goal, grasping the pleasant,<br>Envies those who are diligent.<br><br>Do not follow the dear,<br>Spend your life avoiding the disliked.<br>Not to see the dear is suffering,<br>To see the disliked is also suffering.<br><br>Therefore one should not hold anything dear,<br>Separation from the dear is evil.<br>For those who hold nothing dear or disliked,<br>No bonds exist.<br><br>From affection arises sorrow,<br>From affection arises fear.<br>For one freed from affection,<br>There is no sorrow, how then fear?`, ref: "Dhammapada 209-220", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp209-220" },
{ text: `From attachment arises sorrow,<br>From attachment arises fear.<br>For one freed from attachment,<br>There is no sorrow, how then fear?<br><br>From delight arises sorrow,<br>From delight arises fear.<br>For one freed from delight,<br>There is no sorrow, how then fear?<br><br>From sensual desire arises sorrow,<br>From sensual desire arises fear.<br>For one freed from sensual desire,<br>There is no sorrow, how then fear?<br><br>From craving arises sorrow,<br>From craving arises fear.<br>For one freed from craving,<br>There is no sorrow, how then fear?`, ref: "Dhammapada 209-220", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp209-220" },
{ text: `Whoever checks the arising anger<br>Like a chariot going straight,<br>I call a charioteer.<br>Others merely hold the reins.<br><br>Conquer anger by non-anger,<br>Conquer evil by good,<br>Conquer stinginess by giving,<br>Conquer falsehood by truth.<br><br>Speak the truth, do not be angry,<br>When asked, give even from little.<br>By these three conditions,<br>One may go to the presence of the devas.<br><br>The wise do not harm anyone,<br>Their bodies are always restrained.<br>They go to the Deathless state,<br>Where there is no sorrow.`, ref: "Dhammapada 221-234", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp221-234" },
{ text: `Those who are always awake,<br>Who train day and night,<br>Who are intent on Nibbāna,<br>Their taints are destroyed.<br><br>At dawn one should examine carefully.<br>The wise praise the one who is virtuous.<br>The wise, without blemish,<br>Complete in virtue, concentration, and wisdom.<br><br>One whose conduct is like pure gold,<br>Who can criticize that person?<br>Devas praise such a one,<br>Brahmā also praises.`, ref: "Dhammapada 221-234", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp221-234" },
{ text: `Guard the body, do not be angry,<br>Protect the body well.<br>Abandon evil bodily deeds,<br>Cultivate good bodily deeds.<br><br>Guard speech, do not be angry,<br>Protect speech well.<br>Abandon harsh speech,<br>Speak what is good.<br><br>Guard the mind, do not be angry,<br>Protect the mind well.<br>Abandon evil thoughts,<br>Cultivate good thoughts.<br><br>The wise guard the body,<br>Guard also speech,<br>Guard the mind as well,<br>All three are well guarded.`, ref: "Dhammapada 221-234", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp221-234" },
{ text: `Make yourself an island,<br>Strive quickly, be wise.<br>Removing defilements, purified,<br>Go to the divine land of the noble ones.<br><br>Make yourself an island,<br>Strive quickly, be wise.<br>Removing defilements, purified,<br>You will not come again to birth and decay.<br><br>The wise, step by step,<br>Moment by moment, remove impurities,<br>Like a goldsmith purifying silver,<br>Removing the defilements of oneself.`, ref: "Dhammapada 235-255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp235-255" },
{ text: `Just as rust is born from iron,<br>And, born, eats away the iron,<br>So excessive gain and honor lead<br>One's own deeds to a bad destination.<br><br>Among these defilements,<br>Ignorance is the worst.<br>Bhikkhu, abandon that defilement,<br>Become free from defilements.<br><br>Easy is life for the shameless,<br>One who is bold as a crow,<br>One who is backbiting and boastful,<br>One who is reckless and defiled.<br><br>Difficult is life for the modest,<br>One who always seeks purity,<br>One who is unassuming and humble,<br>One who is pure and bright.`, ref: "Dhammapada 235-255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp235-255" },
{ text: `What fire is like the fire of greed?<br>What clinging is like hatred?<br>What net is like delusion?<br>What river is like craving?<br><br>In the sky there is no footprint,<br>Outside here there is no ascetic.<br>Beings delight in frivolous talk,<br>The Tathāgatas are free from frivolous talk.<br><br>In the sky there is no footprint,<br>Outside here there is no ascetic.<br>No conditioned thing is permanent,<br>The Buddhas are not shaken.`, ref: "Dhammapada 235-255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp235-255" },
{ text: `One should not look at the faults of others,<br>At what they have done or left undone.<br>One should look at oneself,<br>At what one has done or left undone.<br><br>Easy to see are the faults of others,<br>But one's own faults are hard to see.<br>One sifts the faults of others like chaff,<br>But hides one's own faults like a cheat hiding a losing throw.<br><br>One who constantly sees faults in others,<br>Who is ever censorious,<br>Increases his taints;<br>He is far from the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Dhammapada 235-255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp235-255" },
{ text: `You are not a Dhamma-abider,<br>Your conduct is too authoritarian.<br>The wise person should distinguish both right and wrong.<br><br>One who is not authoritarian, but just,<br>Who leads others with Dhamma,<br>One who lives according to Dhamma,<br>Is truly called a Dhamma-abider.<br><br>Not because of much talk<br>Is one called wise.<br>Peaceful, without enmity and fear,<br>That one is called wise.<br><br>Not because of much talk<br>Is one called a bearer of the Dhamma.<br>Though one hears little,<br>If one practices the Dhamma bodily,<br>Not being heedless of the Dhamma,<br>That one is indeed a bearer of the Dhamma.`, ref: "Dhammapada 256-272", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp256-272" },
{ text: `One is not an elder because one's head is grey.<br>One is just an old person,<br>Called one who has grown old in vain.<br><br>One in whom there is truth, Dhamma,<br>Non-harming, and self-control,<br>That wise one, free from defilements,<br>Is called an elder.<br><br>Not by eloquent speech,<br>Nor by beautiful complexion,<br>Does a person become good,<br>If they are envious, greedy, and deceitful.<br><br>One who cuts off, uproots,<br>Destroys that (evil) completely,<br>That wise one, having abandoned hatred,<br>Is called a good person.`, ref: "Dhammapada 256-272", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp256-272" },
{ text: `Not by a shaven head does an undisciplined, lying person become an ascetic.<br>How can one who is full of desire and greed be an ascetic?<br><br>One who completely calms all evil deeds, great and small,<br>Because he has calmed all evil,<br>He is called an ascetic.<br><br>One who lives on alms from others is not thereby a bhikkhu.<br>One who follows the entire Dhamma is a bhikkhu, not otherwise.<br><br>Whoever transcends both good and evil,<br>Who lives the holy life,<br>Who examines the world,<br>Is truly called a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Dhammapada 256-272", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp256-272" },
{ text: `Silent but foolish — is that a sage?<br>Like one holding a scale,<br>The wise one picks the good.<br><br>One who avoids evil deeds<br>Is truly a sage.<br>One who understands both worlds<br>Is called a sage.<br><br>One who harms living beings<br>Is not a noble one.<br>One who does not harm any living being<br>Is called a noble one.`, ref: "Dhammapada 256-272", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp256-272" },
{ text: `Not by mere morality or learning,<br>Nor by much concentration,<br>Nor by living in seclusion alone.<br><br>I enjoy the bliss of security<br>Not known by ordinary people.<br>A bhikkhu, do not be satisfied<br>As long as the taints are not destroyed.`, ref: "Dhammapada 256-272", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp256-272" },
{ text: `The Noble Eightfold Path is the best of paths,<br>The four truths are the best of truths,<br>Dispassion is the best of states,<br>Among two-footed beings, the One with the Eye is the best.<br><br>This is the path, there is no other<br>For the purification of vision.<br>If you follow this path,<br>You will bewilder Māra.<br><br>If you follow this path,<br>You will make an end of suffering.<br>I have taught you the path,<br>Knowing the removal of thorns.<br><br>You yourselves must make the effort,<br>The Tathāgatas are only teachers.<br>Those who practice and meditate<br>Are freed from the bonds of Māra.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289" },
{ text: `'All conditioned things are impermanent' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>'All conditioned things are suffering' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>'All phenomena are not-self' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289" },
{ text: `When one does not strive when one should,<br>Though young and strong but lazy,<br>With a weak will and slothful,<br>With wisdom inactive,<br>How can one find the right path?<br><br>Speech should be guarded,<br>The mind well protected,<br>The body should not do evil.<br>Keep these three actions pure,<br>And attain the path taught by the noble ones.<br><br>From meditation arises wisdom,<br>Without meditation wisdom wanes.<br>Knowing these two paths —<br>The path to becoming and to non-becoming —<br>Make effort yourself,<br>So that wisdom may grow.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289" },
{ text: `Cut down the forest, not a single tree;<br>From the forest arises fear.<br>Cut down the forest and sensual desire,<br>Bhikkhu, be peaceful.<br><br>As long as a man's desire for women,<br>Even the slightest, is not cut off,<br>His mind is bound,<br>Like a calf to its mother's milk.<br><br>Cut off affection for oneself<br>Like an autumn lily with the hand.<br>Cultivate the path of peace,<br>Nibbāna, taught by the Well-Gone One.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289" },
{ text: `'Here I will dwell in the rains,<br>Here in winter and summer.'<br>Thus thinks the fool,<br>Not understanding the danger.<br><br>One whose mind is obsessed<br>By children and cattle,<br>Death carries that person away,<br>As a great flood carries away a sleeping village.<br><br>When death comes,<br>There are no children to protect,<br>No father, no relatives,<br>No kinsmen to protect.<br><br>Knowing this meaning,<br>The wise person, restrained by virtue,<br>Quickly purifies the path<br>Leading to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289" },
{ text: `By giving up a small happiness,<br>One sees a greater happiness.<br>The wise give up the small happiness<br>For the sake of the greater happiness.<br><br>One who inflicts suffering on others<br>Seeking happiness for oneself,<br>Bound by enmity,<br>Cannot be free from enmity.<br><br>What should be done is left undone,<br>What should not be done is done.<br>For the arrogant and heedless,<br>The taints increase.<br><br>Those who are ever mindful,<br>Constantly contemplating the body,<br>Do not do what should not be done,<br>Persist in what should be done.<br>For the mindful and aware,<br>The taints are destroyed.`, ref: "Dhammapada 290-305", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp290-305" },
{ text: `The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>They constantly recollect the Buddha.<br><br>The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>They constantly recollect the Dhamma.<br><br>The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>They constantly recollect the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Dhammapada 290-305", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp290-305" },
{ text: `The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>They constantly recollect the body.<br><br>The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>Their mind delights in non-harming.<br><br>The disciples of Gotama<br>Are always awake,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>Their mind delights in meditation.`, ref: "Dhammapada 290-305", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp290-305" },
{ text: `One who has faith and virtue,<br>Possessing fame and wealth,<br>Wherever that person goes,<br>There they are honored.<br><br>The good shine from afar,<br>Like the snowy mountain.<br>The evil are not seen even nearby,<br>Like arrows shot in the night.<br><br>One who sits or lies alone,<br>Walks alone, not depressed,<br>Alone tames oneself,<br>And delights in the deep forest.`, ref: "Dhammapada 290-305", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp290-305" },
{ text: `False speech leads to hell,<br>Saying 'I did not do' what one did.<br>Both are equal after death,<br>As lowly men with evil deeds.<br><br>Many who wear the yellow robe,<br>Of evil conduct, unrestrained.<br>Those evil ones, by their evil deeds,<br>Are reborn in hell.<br><br>Better to swallow a red-hot iron ball,<br>Blazing like a fire,<br>Than as an immoral, unrestrained person<br>To eat the almsfood of the country.`, ref: "Dhammapada 306-319", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp306-319" },
{ text: `As wrongly grasped grass<br>Cuts the hand,<br>So the wrongly practiced ascetic's life<br>Drags one to hell.<br><br>Loose and heedless conduct,<br>Following impure precepts,<br>Living a dubious holy life —<br>How can one attain great fruit?<br><br>What should be done, do it,<br>Do it with all your might.<br>A heedless wandering ascetic<br>Only stirs up more dust.`, ref: "Dhammapada 306-319", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp306-319" },
{ text: `What is evil is better not done;<br>Doing it leads to suffering.<br>What is good is better done;<br>Doing it brings no regret.<br><br>Like a border fortress<br>Guarded within and without,<br>So guard yourself,<br>Do not let the moment pass.<br>The moment passed brings sorrow,<br>When one falls into hell.`, ref: "Dhammapada 306-319", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp306-319" },
{ text: `Those who are ashamed of what is not shameful,<br>But not ashamed of what is shameful,<br>By embracing wrong views,<br>Go to an evil destination.<br><br>Those who fear what is not fearful,<br>But do not fear what is fearful,<br>By embracing wrong views,<br>Go to an evil destination.<br><br>Seeing fault where there is no fault,<br>But seeing no fault where there is fault,<br>By embracing wrong views,<br>Go to an evil destination.<br><br>Knowing fault as fault,<br>And no fault as no fault,<br>By embracing right views,<br>Go to a good destination.`, ref: "Dhammapada 306-319", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp306-319" },
{ text: `Like an elephant in battle,<br>Enduring arrows shot from a bow,<br>I will endure abuse;<br>Indeed, many people are immoral.<br><br>A trained elephant is led into a crowd,<br>A trained horse is ridden by a king,<br>A trained person is the best,<br>One who endures abuse.<br><br>Good indeed is a well-bred mule,<br>And a well-bred horse of Sindh,<br>And a great tusked elephant.<br>But one who has tamed oneself is even better.`, ref: "Dhammapada 320-333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp320-333" },
{ text: `One who loves sleep, eats much,<br>Rolls around lying down,<br>Is like a fattened pig —<br>That fool is repeatedly reborn.<br><br>Formerly this mind wandered,<br>Chasing after desire, pleasure, and delight.<br>Now I will restrain it wisely,<br>As a mahout controls an elephant.<br><br>Delight in heedfulness,<br>Guard your mind well.<br>Lift yourself from the evil way,<br>Like an elephant sunk in mud.`, ref: "Dhammapada 320-333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp320-333" },
{ text: `If one finds a wise companion,<br>Worthy to live with, virtuous and steadfast,<br>Overcoming all dangers,<br>One should live with that person, joyful and mindful.<br><br>If one does not find a wise companion,<br>Worthy to live with, virtuous and steadfast,<br>Like a king abandoning a conquered kingdom,<br>Live alone like an elephant in the forest.<br><br>Better to live alone,<br>There is no fellowship with a fool.<br>Live alone, do no evil,<br>Carefree like an elephant in the forest.`, ref: "Dhammapada 320-333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp320-333" },
{ text: `Happy is friendship when need arises,<br>Happy is contentment with little,<br>Happy is merit at the end of life,<br>Happy is the abandonment of all suffering.<br><br>Happy is reverence to one's mother,<br>Happy is reverence to one's father,<br>Happy is reverence to ascetics,<br>Happy is reverence to the noble ones.<br><br>Happy is virtue in old age,<br>Happy is faith established,<br>Happy is the attainment of wisdom,<br>Happy is not doing evil.`, ref: "Dhammapada 320-333", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp320-333" },
{ text: `One who lives heedlessly,<br>Craving grows like a creeper.<br>One jumps from this life to the next,<br>Like a monkey seeking fruit in the forest.<br><br>Whoever in this world is overcome by this wretched craving,<br>Their sorrows grow,<br>Like birana grass after rain.<br><br>Whoever in this world overcomes this wretched craving,<br>Sorrows fall away from that person,<br>Like water drops from a lotus leaf.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `This good Dhamma I teach you:<br>Gather here, all of you.<br>Uproot the root of craving,<br>As one uproots birana grass.<br>Do not let Māra destroy you,<br>As a stream destroys reeds.<br><br>Just as a tree cut down grows again,<br>If its root is undamaged and firm,<br>So when the underlying tendency to craving is not uprooted,<br>This suffering arises again and again.<br><br>The thirty-six streams of craving<br>Flow toward pleasurable objects.<br>Thoughts of lust and greed<br>Sweep away the person of wrong view.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Everywhere the streams of craving flow,<br>The creeper of craving sprouts and stands.<br>Seeing that creeper sprouting,<br>Cut its root with wisdom.<br><br>Beings are engrossed by sensual pleasures,<br>They delight in pleasurable things.<br>Though they seek happiness,<br>They are still subject to birth and old age.<br><br>People bound by craving<br>Are frightened and agitated,<br>Like a hare caught in a snare.<br>Bound by craving,<br>They undergo long suffering.<br><br>People bound by craving<br>Are frightened and agitated,<br>Like a hare caught in a snare.<br>Therefore, a bhikkhu who desires his own dispassion<br>Should abandon craving.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Leaving the forest, he runs to the forest,<br>Freed from the forest, he runs back to the forest.<br>Look at that person:<br>Freed from bondage,<br>He runs right back into bondage.<br><br>Iron, wood, or rope — these bonds,<br>The wise say, are not strong.<br>Longing for jewels and ornaments,<br>Longing for children and wives —<br>That is a much stronger bond.<br><br>The wise say that bond is strong.<br>It pulls one down, though loose, it is hard to free.<br>The wise cut it off,<br>And leave sensual pleasures, not looking back.<br><br>Those who are intoxicated with sensual pleasures<br>Throw themselves into the stream,<br>Like a spider into its own web.<br>The wise cut it off,<br>And leave all suffering, not looking back.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Leaving behind the past, future, and present,<br>One goes to the far shore of existence.<br>With mind liberated in every way,<br>One does not again undergo birth and old age.<br><br>One with evil thoughts, who is disturbed,<br>Who sees only the beautiful in the sensual,<br>Increases craving even more,<br>Making the bond even tighter.<br><br>One who delights in calming the mind,<br>Who always contemplates the foul,<br>Will destroy craving;<br>He cuts Māra's bond.<br><br>One who has reached the goal, fearless,<br>Free from craving, without defilement,<br>Has removed the arrow of existence;<br>This body is his last.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Free from craving, without grasping,<br>Skilled in the phraseology of the Dhamma,<br>Knowing the sequence of words and their meaning,<br>Understanding the order of earlier and later.<br>This is his last body;<br>Such a person is called<br>One of great wisdom, a great person.<br><br>I have overcome all,<br>I know all,<br>I am not defiled by any dhamma.<br>I have abandoned all,<br>With craving destroyed, I am liberated.<br>Having directly known all for myself,<br>Whom should I call my teacher?<br><br>The gift of Dhamma surpasses all gifts.<br>The taste of Dhamma surpasses all tastes.<br>The delight in Dhamma surpasses all delights.<br>The destruction of craving conquers all suffering.<br><br>Worldly wealth destroys the foolish,<br>But not those who seek the far shore.<br>The fool, due to greed for wealth,<br>Destroys himself and destroys others.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Weeds are the bane of fields,<br>Greed is the bane of this world.<br>Therefore, giving to those free from greed<br>Brings great fruit.<br><br>Weeds are the bane of fields,<br>Hatred is the bane of this world.<br>Therefore, giving to those free from hatred<br>Brings great fruit.<br><br>Weeds are the bane of fields,<br>Delusion is the bane of this world.<br>Therefore, giving to those free from delusion<br>Brings great fruit.<br><br>Weeds are the bane of fields,<br>Desire is the bane of this world.<br>Therefore, giving to those free from desire<br>Brings great fruit.`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359" },
{ text: `Good it is to guard the eye,<br>Good it is to guard the ear,<br>Good it is to guard the nose,<br>Good it is to guard the tongue.<br><br>Good it is to guard the body,<br>Good it is to guard speech,<br>Good it is to guard the mind,<br>Good it is to guard all.<br>A bhikkhu guarding all things<br>Is freed from all suffering.<br><br>One who controls his hands and feet,<br>Controls his speech and head,<br>Delights in inner meditation,<br>Alone, knowing contentment,<br>Is truly called a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu who controls his mouth,<br>Speaks moderately, without conceit,<br>When explaining the Dhamma's meaning,<br>His words are gentle and sweet.<br><br>A bhikkhu who delights in the Dhamma,<br>Who loves the Dhamma and reflects on the Dhamma,<br>Who remembers the true Dhamma,<br>Does not fall away from the true Dhamma.<br><br>One should not despise what one receives,<br>Nor envy the gains of others.<br>A bhikkhu who envies others<br>Does not attain concentration.<br><br>Though a bhikkhu receives little,<br>He should not despise his own gain.<br>Living pure, not lazy,<br>Even devas praise such a one.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `For one who has no 'I' and 'mine' in regard to name-and-form,<br>Who does not grieve over what is not,<br>That one is truly called a bhikkhu.<br><br>A bhikkhu who dwells in loving-kindness,<br>With faith in the Buddha's teaching,<br>Attains the peaceful state,<br>The blissful state of peace.<br><br>Bhikkhu, empty this boat;<br>Empty, it will go quickly.<br>Having cut off greed and hatred,<br>You will go to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `Bhikkhu, practice meditation,<br>Do not be heedless,<br>Do not let your mind whirl in sensual pleasures.<br>Do not, being heedless, swallow a red-hot iron ball,<br>And when burning, cry 'This is suffering!'<br><br>There is no jhāna without wisdom,<br>There is no wisdom without jhāna.<br>One who has both jhāna and wisdom<br>Is indeed close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Entering an empty hut,<br>The bhikkhu with peaceful mind<br>Enjoys a superhuman delight<br>When he sees the Dhamma clearly.<br><br>Whenever one is mindful<br>Of the rise and fall of the aggregates,<br>One experiences joy and happiness.<br>That is the Deathless for those who know.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `This wise bhikkhu should gather the fundamental Dhamma,<br>Guard the senses, know moderation,<br>Guard the fundamental virtues,<br>Frequent good friends,<br>Live purely and diligently.<br><br>Being courteous and friendly,<br>Conducting oneself properly,<br>Thus one gains great joy,<br>And will make an end of suffering.<br><br>Like the jasmine flower sheds its withered petals,<br>So, bhikkhu, abandon greed and hatred.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `With body calmed, speech calmed,<br>Calmed and well concentrated,<br>A bhikkhu who has abandoned worldly things<br>Is truly called 'peaceful'.<br><br>By oneself reproach oneself,<br>By oneself examine oneself.<br>A bhikkhu who guards himself,<br>Mindful, dwells happily.<br><br>Oneself is the refuge of oneself,<br>Oneself is one's own destination.<br>Therefore, tame yourself,<br>Like a merchant tames a fine horse.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu of great joy,<br>With faith in the Buddha's teaching,<br>Attains the peaceful state,<br>The blissful state of peace.<br><br>Though a bhikkhu is young,<br>If he diligently practices the Buddha's teaching,<br>He illuminates this world,<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382" },
{ text: `O brahmin, strive to cut the stream,<br>Abandon sensual pleasures,<br>Knowing the destruction of conditioned things,<br>You are the one who knows the uncreated.<br><br>By always dwelling in two states,<br>One reaches the far shore.<br>The wise brahmin,<br>All fetters are destroyed.<br><br>Without near shore or far shore,<br>Having no shore at all,<br>Freed from suffering, without bondage,<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Meditative, dwelling dust-free,<br>Duty done, taintless,<br>Attained the supreme goal,<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `The sun shines by day,<br>The moon shines by night.<br>The warrior shines in armor,<br>The brahmin shines in meditation.<br>But the Buddha shines all day and night,<br>Radiant with glory.<br><br>Having abandoned evil, one is called a brahmin;<br>Living peacefully, one is called an ascetic;<br>Having removed one's own impurities,<br>One is called a renunciant.<br><br>For a brahmin, this is no small gain:<br>When the mind is free from attachment,<br>When the intention to harm is cut off,<br>Then suffering is calmed.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `One who is restrained in body, speech, and mind,<br>Who does no evil deeds,<br>Whose three doors are guarded,<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One from whom one can learn the good Dhamma<br>Taught by the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>One should venerate that person,<br>As a brahmin venerates the sacrificial fire.<br><br>One is not a brahmin because of matted hair,<br>Nor because of family or birth.<br>One in whom there is truth and Dhamma,<br>Who is pure — that one is a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `What good is matted hair, O fool,<br>What good is a goatskin garment?<br>Your inward life is full of thorns,<br>You brighten only the outside.<br><br>One who wears dust-heap robes,<br>Lean, with visible veins,<br>Alone, meditating in the forest —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>I do not call one a brahmin because of birth from a (particular) mother.<br>If he has defilements, he is just a 'sir' who says 'sir'.<br>One who is free from defilements and grasping —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Having cut off all fetters,<br>Having no fear,<br>Gone beyond attachment, unbound —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `Without anger, dutiful,<br>Virtuous, without craving,<br>Tamed, bearing his final body —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Like water on a lotus leaf,<br>Like a mustard seed on a needle's point,<br>One not attached to sensual pleasures —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who here in this very life<br>Knows the end of suffering,<br>Who has laid down the burden, liberated —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `A person of deep wisdom,<br>Skilled in the path and the non-path,<br>Who has attained the highest goal —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Not associated with householders or renunciants,<br>Wandering with few wants, without a home —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has laid down the rod against all beings,<br>Both the timid and the strong,<br>Who neither kills nor causes to be killed —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Friendly among the hostile,<br>Peaceful among the violent,<br>Not grasping among those who grasp —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `One whose greed, hatred, conceit, and envy have fallen away,<br>Like a mustard seed from a needle's point —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who speaks gentle, beneficial, and truthful words,<br>Who does not offend anyone —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who in this world takes nothing not given,<br>Whether long or short, small or large, beautiful or ugly —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has no longings for this world or the next,<br>Without longings, liberated —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `One who has no craving,<br>Wise, without doubt,<br>Who has realized the Deathless —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who here has transcended both good and evil,<br>Sorrowless, stainless, pure —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Pure as the moon, unstained,<br>Clear, tranquil,<br>Who has destroyed delight in existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has crossed this dangerous path,<br>Overcome delusion and saṃsāra,<br>Reached the far shore, meditative,<br>Without desire, without doubt,<br>Without grasping, at peace —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `One who here has abandoned sensual desires,<br>Who has gone forth from home to homelessness,<br>Who has destroyed sensual existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who here has abandoned craving,<br>Who has gone forth from home to homelessness,<br>Who has destroyed craving for existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Having left behind human bonds,<br>Having transcended celestial bonds,<br>Freed from all bonds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Having left behind delight and aversion,<br>Cooled, without attachments,<br>The hero who has conquered all worlds,<br>Who has subdued all —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
{ text: `One who knows the passing away and rebirth of beings everywhere,<br>Not attached, well-gone,<br>Awakened, enlightened —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One whose destination is not known by devas, gandhabbas, or humans,<br>A taintless one, an Arahant —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has nothing in the past, future, or present,<br>Who has nothing, who clings to nothing —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>The bull, the excellent, the hero,<br>The great sage, the conqueror,<br>The passion-free, the purified, the awakened —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who knows his former lives,<br>Who sees heaven and hell,<br>Who has reached the end of birth,<br>Who has attained direct knowledge, perfected,<br>The sage, the seer,<br>Perfect in all accomplishments —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423" },
           
                





{ text: `Standing to one side, that deva said to the Blessed One in verse:<br><br>Many devas and humans<br>Reflect on auspicious signs,<br>Yearning and waiting for<br>A life of safety.<br>Please tell us, O Blessed One,<br>What is the supreme auspicious sign?<br><br>Not to associate with fools,<br>But to associate with the wise,<br>To honor those worthy of honor —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To dwell in a suitable place,<br>Merit made in the past,<br>To direct oneself rightly —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To have much learning, skilled in craft,<br>Well-trained in discipline,<br>To speak well-spoken words —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To support one's mother and father,<br>To cherish one's wife and children,<br>To have an unconfused livelihood —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To give, to live righteously,<br>To support one's relatives,<br>To do blameless deeds —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp5" },
{ text: `To cease and abstain from evil,<br>To abstain from intoxicants,<br>To be heedful in the Dhamma —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To be respectful and humble,<br>To be content and grateful,<br>To hear the Dhamma at the proper time —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>To be patient and of gentle speech,<br>To visit ascetics,<br>To discuss the Dhamma at the proper time —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>Austerity and the holy life,<br>To see the noble truths,<br>The realization of Nibbāna —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>When touched by worldly things,<br>One's mind does not tremble,<br>Sorrowless, stainless, secure —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.<br><br>Having performed these things,<br>They are everywhere undefeated,<br>Everywhere they go in safety —<br>This is the supreme auspicious sign.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp5" },
{ text: `Whatever beings are gathered together,<br>Whether on the earth or in the sky,<br>May all beings be happy,<br>May they be safe and well.<br>Therefore, listen to this recitation carefully.<br><br>Thus all beings, all creatures,<br>Pay attention!<br>Arouse loving-kindness toward all beings;<br>By day and by night they bring offerings.<br>Therefore, heedfully guard them.<br><br>Whatever treasure there is here or hereafter,<br>Or in the heavens,<br>There is no jewel equal to the Tathāgata.<br>Thus, in the Buddha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>The Deathless — cessation, dispassion —<br>The Buddha, the Sakyan Sage, realized that supreme Dhamma in jhāna.<br>There is no equal to that Dhamma.<br>Thus, in the Dhamma there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp6" },
{ text: `The supreme Buddha praised the pure Dhamma<br>That leads to concentration, without interruption.<br>There is no equal to that Dhamma.<br>Thus, in the Dhamma there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>These eight individuals, the four pairs,<br>Are praised by the good.<br>They are the disciples of the Well-Gone One,<br>Worthy of offerings.<br>What is given to them yields great fruit.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>Those who are firm in the teaching of Gotama,<br>With few desires, mindful,<br>Attain the state of the Deathless,<br>Enjoying the peace attained for free.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>Like a stone pillar deeply grounded,<br>Unshaken by the four winds,<br>So the genuine person, I say,<br>Is one who sees the noble truths.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp6" },
{ text: `Those who have well explained the noble truths,<br>Taught with deep wisdom,<br>Even if they are extremely heedless,<br>They will not take an eighth existence.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>With the attainment of right view,<br>Three things are abandoned:<br>Personality view, doubt,<br>And clinging to rites and rituals.<br><br>One is released from the four lower worlds,<br>And cannot commit the six great evils.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>Even though one may do some evil deed,<br>By body, speech, or mind,<br>One cannot conceal it;<br>Such a one is said to have seen the path.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp6" },
{ text: `Beautiful are the trees in the forest<br>With blossoming flowers at their tips,<br>In the hot summer months,<br>The first days of summer.<br>So is the supreme Dhamma taught,<br>Leading to Nibbāna, the supreme bliss.<br>Thus, in the Buddha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>The Supreme One knows the Supreme,<br>Gives the Supreme,<br>Brings the Supreme —<br>The unsurpassed Teacher speaks the supreme Dhamma.<br>Thus, in the Buddha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.<br><br>Old kamma is destroyed,<br>New kamma is not produced,<br>The mind is free from longing for future existence.<br>The seeds are destroyed,<br>Desire does not grow.<br>The wise realize Nibbāna,<br>Like this lamp going out.<br>Thus, in the Saṅgha there is this excellent jewel.<br>By this truth, may there be happiness.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp6" },
{ text: `Whatever beings are gathered together,<br>Whether on the earth or in the sky,<br>Let them worship the Buddha, the Tathāgata,<br>Honored by devas and humans.<br>May there be happiness for all beings.<br><br>Whatever beings are gathered together,<br>Whether on the earth or in the sky,<br>Let them worship the Dhamma, the Tathāgata's teaching,<br>Honored by devas and humans.<br>May there be happiness for all beings.<br><br>Whatever beings are gathered together,<br>Whether on the earth or in the sky,<br>Let them worship the Saṅgha, the Tathāgata's community,<br>Honored by devas and humans.<br>May there be happiness for all beings.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp6" },
{ text: `One who is skilled in the goal,<br>One who knows the peaceful path,<br>Should act like this:<br>After understanding clearly,<br>Being capable, upright,<br>Truly, well direct, easy to speak to,<br>Gentle, without conceit.<br><br>Content, easily supported,<br>With few duties, living simply,<br>With peaceful faculties, wise,<br>Not arrogant, without greed for families.<br><br>One should not commit any trivial fault<br>That other wise people might criticize.<br>May all beings be happy and secure,<br>May they attain happiness and well-being.<br><br>Whatever living beings there are,<br>Frail or strong, without exception,<br>Long or large, medium or short,<br>Subtle or gross, seen or unseen,<br>Those living far or near,<br>Those already born or seeking birth,<br>May all beings be happy and well.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp9" },
{ text: `Let no one deceive another,<br>Let no one despise anyone anywhere,<br>Let no one, out of anger or hatred,<br>Wish suffering for another.<br><br>Just as a mother would protect<br>Her only child with her life,<br>Even so, let one cultivate<br>A boundless mind toward all beings.<br><br>Let one cultivate loving-kindness<br>Toward the entire world,<br>Above, below, and across,<br>Without obstruction, without enmity.<br><br>Whether standing, walking, sitting,<br>Or lying down, as long as one is not drowsy,<br>One should establish this mindfulness.<br>This is called the divine abiding here.<br><br>Not falling into wrong view,<br>Virtuous, endowed with right view,<br>Having overcome desire for sensual pleasures,<br>One will never again come to a womb.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp9" },
{ text: `What is one? All beings subsist on food.<br>What are two? Name and form.<br>What are three? Three kinds of feeling.<br>What are four? Four noble truths.<br>What are five? Five aggregates subject to clinging.<br>What are six? Six internal sense spheres.<br>What are seven? Seven factors of enlightenment.<br>What are eight? The noble eightfold path.<br>What are nine? Nine abodes of beings.<br>What are ten? One endowed with ten qualities is called an Arahant.`, ref: "Khuddakapāṭha 4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/kp4" },
        
               { text: `When this exists, that exists. With the arising of this, that arises. That is: With ignorance as condition, volitional formations arise; with volitional formations as condition, consciousness; with consciousness as condition, name-and-form; with name-and-form as condition, the six sense bases; with the six sense bases as condition, contact; with contact as condition, feeling; with feeling as condition, craving; with craving as condition, clinging; with clinging as condition, existence; with existence as condition, birth; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origination of this whole mass of suffering."<br><br>Truly, when these things<br>Are present and arise,<br>For that brahmin who is<br>Ardent and meditating,<br><br>Then, for that person,<br>All doubts are dispelled,<br>Since he fully knows<br>The Dhamma together with its causes.`, ref: "Udāna 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.1" },
{ text: `When this does not exist, that does not exist. With the cessation of this, that ceases. That is: With the cessation of ignorance, volitional formations cease; with the cessation of volitional formations, consciousness ceases; with the cessation of consciousness, name-and-form ceases; with the cessation of name-and-form, the six sense bases cease; with the cessation of the six sense bases, contact ceases; with the cessation of contact, feeling ceases; with the cessation of feeling, craving ceases; with the cessation of craving, clinging ceases; with the cessation of clinging, existence ceases; with the cessation of existence, birth ceases; with the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering."<br><br>Truly, when these things<br>Are present and arise,<br>For that brahmin who is<br>Ardent and meditating,<br><br>Then, for that person,<br>All doubts are dispelled,<br>Since he has fully known<br>The cessation of conditions.`, ref: "Udāna 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.2" },
{ text: `Truly, when these things<br>Are present and arise,<br>For that brahmin who is<br>Ardent and meditating,<br><br>Having swept away the hosts of Māra,<br>He stands and dwells,<br>Like the light of the sun<br>Illumining the sky.`, ref: "Udāna 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.3" },
{ text: `- Venerable Gotama, to what extent is one a brahmin, and what are the qualities that constitute a brahmin?<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>That brahmin who has<br>Abandoned all evil states,<br>Not proud, without defilements,<br>Self well-tamed,<br>Who has mastered the Veda,<br>And fulfilled the holy life,<br><br>That brahmin can indeed utter<br>The Brahma-word in accordance with Dhamma.<br>He has no conceit whatsoever<br>Anywhere in this world.`, ref: "Udāna 1.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.4" },
{ text: `- To what extent, Bhante, is one a brahmin, and how many qualities constitute a brahmin?<br><br>Having abandoned evil states,<br>One who constantly practices mindfulness,<br>Who has destroyed the fetters, awakened —<br>Those ones in this world<br>Are truly brahmins.`, ref: "Udāna 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.5" },
{ text: `One who lives without relying on others,<br>Not known to people,<br>Living self-controlled,<br>Established on the core,<br><br>Whose taints are destroyed,<br>Hatred eliminated,<br>That one I call<br>A brahmin.`, ref: "Udāna 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.6" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw those many matted-hair ascetics, on cold winter nights, between the eighths, during snowfall, plunging in and out of the water, doing the diving and surfacing, sprinkling water and tending the sacred fire, thinking: "By this action, one becomes purified." Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Purity is not by water,<br>Though many bathe here.<br>In whom there is truth,<br>And also the Dhamma,<br>That person is pure,<br>That person is a brahmin.`, ref: "Udāna 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.9" },
{ text: `- Therefore, Bāhiya, you should train yourself thus: 'In the seen, there will be only the seen. In the heard, there will be only the heard. In the sensed, there will be only the sensed. In the cognized, there will be only the cognized.' Thus, Bāhiya, you should train yourself. For, Bāhiya, if for you, in the seen, there will be only the seen; in the heard, only the heard; in the sensed, only the sensed; in the cognized, only the cognized. Then, Bāhiya, you are not 'there'. For, Bāhiya, you are not 'in this life', not 'in the next life', not 'in the intermediate life'. Thus is the end of suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.10" },
{ text: `Where water and earth,<br>Fire and air do not gain a footing,<br>There stars do not shine,<br>The sun does not shine,<br>The moon does not shine,<br>There is no darkness.<br><br>When the seer, the brahmin,<br>By himself, with wisdom,<br>Penetrates the Dhamma,<br>That one is liberated<br>From form and formlessness,<br>From happiness and suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud1.10" },
{ text: `Seclusion is happiness<br>For one who knows contentment,<br>For one who has heard the Dhamma,<br>For one who has right view.<br><br>Non-hatred is happiness<br>For those in this world<br>Who restrain themselves<br>Toward living beings.<br><br>Dispassion is happiness,<br>Transcending all sensual desires.<br>One who subdues conceit<br>Attains the supreme happiness.`, ref: "Udāna 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.1" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, it is not proper for you, clansmen who have gone forth out of faith from home to homelessness, to engage in such talk. Bhikkhus, when you gather together, there are two things to be done: discussing the good Dhamma or maintaining noble silence.<br><br>Whatever sensual pleasures there are in the world,<br>Even the heavenly pleasures,<br>They are not worth a sixteenth part<br>Of the happiness from the destruction of craving.`, ref: "Udāna 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.2" },
{ text: `In village or forest,<br>Experiencing suffering and happiness,<br>Do not attribute them to oneself,<br>Do not attribute them to others.<br><br>Feelings arise dependent on bases.<br>For one without bases,<br>How could feelings touch him?`, ref: "Udāna 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.4" },
{ text: `- It has been a long time, householder, that you have made this opportunity, namely coming here!<br>- Bhante, for a long time I have wanted to see the Blessed One, but I have been busy with these many duties, so I could not come to see the Blessed One.<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>One skilled in the Dhamma,<br>Who has heard much Dhamma,<br>Does not regard anything<br>As one's own happiness.<br><br>Behold the affliction<br>Of those who have possessions,<br>Which causes one person<br>To be bound to another.`, ref: "Udāna 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.5" },
{ text: `Happy indeed is the person<br>Who has nothing of one's own.<br>One of perfect knowledge,<br>Having nothing of one's own.<br><br>Behold the affliction<br>Of those who have possessions,<br>Which causes one person<br>To be bound to another.`, ref: "Udāna 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.6" },
{ text: `- Bhante, our beloved, agreeable only son has passed away. Therefore we have come here too early, with wet clothes and wet hair.<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Bound and dominated<br>By what is dear and agreeable,<br>Many devas and many humans,<br>Afflicted and languishing,<br>Are overcome by the King of Death.<br><br>But those who, day and night,<br>Not heedless, abandon the beautiful,<br>They dig up the root of suffering,<br>Māra's bait so hard to cross.`, ref: "Udāna 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.7" },
{ text: `Unhappy, pretending to be happy,<br>Not loving, pretending to love,<br>Suffering, pretending to be happy —<br>They overcome the heedless.`, ref: "Udāna 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.8" },
{ text: `For one in whom there is no anger internally,<br>Who has transcended becoming and non-becoming,<br>That one is free from fear,<br>Happy, without sorrow,<br>Not seen by devas.`, ref: "Udāna 2.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.10" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One saw that bhikkhu sitting cross-legged, holding his body straight, enduring painful, sharp, severe, racking feelings, the result of past kamma, mindful and clearly comprehending, without sorrow. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>A bhikkhu who has abandoned all kamma,<br>Who has shaken off the dust of the past,<br>Established, without conceit 'I am',<br>Not needing to speak to anyone.`, ref: "Udāna 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.1" },
{ text: `One who has crossed over this mud,<br>Crushed the thorn of sensual pleasures,<br>Attained the destruction of delusion,<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Does not experience suffering or happiness!`, ref: "Udāna 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.2" },
{ text: `One who has conquered the thorn of sensual pleasures,<br>Sun, harm, and bondage,<br>That one stands unmoving,<br>Like a mountain firmly established.<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Is not shaken by suffering or happiness.`, ref: "Udāna 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.3" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Sāriputta sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, establishing mindfulness before him. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Like a stone mountain,<br>Unshaken, well-established,<br>So a bhikkhu who has destroyed delusion,<br>Like a stone mountain,<br>Is not shaken.`, ref: "Udāna 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Mahā Moggallāna sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, with mindfulness of the body well established internally. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>With mindfulness of the body established,<br>Restrained in the six contact spheres,<br>A bhikkhu always meditating,<br>Attains Nibbāna for himself.`, ref: "Udāna 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.5" },
{ text: `In whom there is no deceit,<br>No conceit, greed destroyed,<br>Without 'I-making', without desire,<br>Hatred eliminated,<br>Cooled within,<br>That one is a brahmin,<br>An ascetic, a bhikkhu.`, ref: "Udāna 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.6" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu who lives on alms,<br>Living independently,<br>Devas hold that one dear,<br>Always peaceful and mindful.`, ref: "Udāna 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.7" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu who lives on alms,<br>Living independently,<br>Devas hold that one dear,<br>But if that bhikkhu delights in fame,<br>Devas do not hold him dear.`, ref: "Udāna 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.8" },
{ text: `When you gather together, bhikkhus, there are two things to be done: discussing the Dhamma or maintaining noble silence." Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>One who lives without worldly work,<br>Light, desiring welfare,<br>With faculties restrained,<br>Fully liberated,<br><br>Homeless, without 'I-making',<br>Without sensual desire, having slain Māra,<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Lives alone.`, ref: "Udāna 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.9" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One, after seven days, emerged from that concentration and surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye. He saw beings being burned by various kinds of burning, afflicted by various fevers of greed, hatred, and delusion. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>This world is burning,<br>Its parts touched by contact.<br>It speaks of its own<br>Affliction, calling it 'I'.<br><br>Because it perceives things,<br>Therefore it changes.<br>Changed because of existence,<br>Dependent on existence,<br>This world is ruled by existence,<br>And delights in existence.<br><br>Where there is delight,<br>There is fear.<br>For one who fears,<br>That is suffering.<br>It is precisely by the destruction of existence<br>That this holy life is lived.`, ref: "Udāna 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.10" },
{ text: `From a basis, suffering arises. By the complete destruction of all bases, suffering no longer exists.<br><br>Behold this widespread world,<br>Ruled by ignorance.<br>Beings are born,<br>They delight in becoming,<br>Not freed from existence.<br><br>For one who burns up existence,<br>At all times, in all places,<br>All this existence<br>Is impermanent, suffering, subject to change.<br><br>Seeing this as it really is<br>With right wisdom,<br>Craving for existence is abandoned,<br>And delight in non-existence.<br><br>With the complete destruction of craving,<br>Dispassion, cessation, complete —<br>Thus is Nibbāna.<br>That bhikkhu, cooled,<br>Not grasping, not reborn,<br>Has conquered Māra,<br>Won the battle.<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Has overcome all existences.`, ref: "Udāna 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.10" },
{ text: `Here, good friendship, good companionship, is the first quality, Meghiya, that leads to the maturity of the unripe liberation of mind. Furthermore, Meghiya, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. This is the second quality, Meghiya, that leads to the maturity of the unripe liberation of mind. Furthermore, Meghiya, whatever serious talk is suitable for opening the heart, leading to complete disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna — such as talk on few desires, talk on contentment, talk on seclusion, talk on non-association, talk on energy and exertion, talk on virtue, talk on concentration, talk on wisdom, talk on liberation, talk on the knowledge and vision of liberation — such talk he obtains without difficulty, without trouble, without effort. This is the third quality, Meghiya, that leads to the maturity of the unripe liberation of mind.`, ref: "Udāna 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.1" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Meghiya, a bhikkhu dwells energetic and strenuous, abandoning unwholesome states, arousing wholesome states, steadfast, resolute, not discarding the burden regarding wholesome states. This is the fourth quality, Meghiya, that leads to the maturity of the unripe liberation of mind. Furthermore, Meghiya, a bhikkhu has wisdom, possessing wisdom that penetrates arising and passing away, with the noble penetration leading to the complete destruction of suffering. This is the fifth quality, Meghiya, that leads to the maturity of the unripe liberation of mind.`, ref: "Udāna 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.1" },
{ text: `Furthermore, Meghiya, when a bhikkhu is well established in these five qualities, four further things should be developed: The perception of foulness should be developed to abandon greed; loving-kindness should be developed to abandon hatred; mindfulness of breathing should be developed to cut off thoughts; the perception of impermanence should be developed to uproot the conceit 'I am'. For one with the perception of impermanence, Meghiya, the perception of non-self becomes established. For one with the perception of non-self, the conceit 'I am' is uprooted, and Nibbāna is directly realized in this very life.`, ref: "Udāna 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.1" },
{ text: `Subtle, small thoughts<br>Arisen from mental delight,<br>Not knowing them,<br>The mind runs about, often wandering.<br><br>One who knows these thoughts,<br>Ardent and mindful,<br>Controls the thoughts,<br>When the mind does not delight.<br>The Enlightened One has abandoned them,<br>Leaving no remainder.`, ref: "Udāna 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.1" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw that large group of bhikkhus living in forest huts, restless, arrogant, agitated, talkative, garrulous, unmindful, not clearly comprehending, unconcentrated, with distracted minds and loose faculties. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>With body unguarded,<br>Ruled by wrong view,<br>Overcome by dullness and drowsiness,<br>Conquered and subdued,<br>That one falls under<br>Māra's power.<br><br>Therefore, guard the mind,<br>Practice right intention,<br>Set right view foremost,<br>Knowing the nature of arising and passing away,<br><br>Subdue and conquer<br>Dullness and drowsiness.<br>Such a bhikkhu,<br>Abandoning all evil destinations.`, ref: "Udāna 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.2" },
{ text: `One whose mind is like a rock,<br>Established, not shaking,<br>Not greedy for the agreeable,<br>Not angry at the disagreeable,<br>One whose mind is thus developed,<br>How could suffering come to that one?`, ref: "Udāna 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Piṇḍola Bhāradvāja sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, dwelling in the forest, going for alms, wearing dust-heap robes, using only three robes, of few desires, content, secluded, not delighting in company, energetic, speaking of the ascetic practices, devoted to the higher mind. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Not abusing, not harming,<br>Restrained in the Pātimokkha,<br>Moderate in food,<br>Sitting and lying down alone,<br>Devoted to the higher mind —<br>This is the teaching of the Buddhas.`, ref: "Udāna 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.6" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Sāriputta sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, of few desires, content, secluded, not delighting in company, energetic, devoted to the higher mind. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>With higher mind, a seer,<br>Not heedless, developing,<br>On the path of right knowledge,<br>That one does not long,<br>Always peaceful,<br>Ever mindful.`, ref: "Udāna 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.7" },
{ text: `One who does not know restraint,<br>With words stabbing others,<br>Like an elephant being stabbed<br>When entering the battle.<br><br>Hearing harsh words,<br>A bhikkhu should endure,<br>Keeping silent, not speaking,<br>Without resentment in mind.`, ref: "Udāna 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.8" },
{ text: `One who lives without fever,<br>At death does not grieve.<br>If the wise person sees the path,<br>Among the grieving, does not grieve.<br><br>A bhikkhu who has cut off craving for existence,<br>With mind at peace,<br>The wandering in birth and death is ended,<br>That one is not reborn.`, ref: "Udāna 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.9" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Sāriputta sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, contemplating his own peace. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>A bhikkhu with peaceful mind,<br>Has cut the cord of birth and death.<br>The wandering in birth and death is ended,<br>Freed from Māra's bonds.`, ref: "Udāna 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.10" },
{ text: `My mind has traveled all around,<br>To every direction,<br>Yet I have not found anything<br>Dearer than myself.<br><br>Since the self is so dear to everyone,<br>Therefore, one who loves oneself<br>Should not harm another's self.`, ref: "Udāna 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.1" },
{ text: `All beings that will exist in the world,<br>All of them will go,<br>Having left the physical body behind.<br>Understanding all this,<br>The good person, ardent,<br>Lives the holy life.`, ref: "Udāna 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.2" },
{ text: `As a person with eyes,<br>Striving to avoid rough ground,<br>So the wise person avoids<br>Evil in this world.`, ref: "Udāna 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.3" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw many young boys between Sāvatthī and Jetavana torturing fish. Seeing them, he went to those young boys and said: "Young boys, do you fear suffering? Do you dislike suffering?" - "Yes, Bhante, we fear suffering. We dislike suffering." Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>If you dislike suffering,<br>Wherever it may be,<br>Do not do evil deeds,<br>Openly or in secret.<br><br>If you do or will do<br>Evil, unwholesome deeds,<br>You will not escape suffering,<br>Even if you leap and run.`, ref: "Udāna 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.4" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, the great ocean slopes gradually, inclines gradually, deepens gradually, not abruptly like a precipice. So too, bhikkhus, in this Dhamma and Discipline, the training is gradual, the results are gradual, the path is gradual, there is no sudden penetration of final knowledge. Because, bhikkhus, in this Dhamma and Discipline, the training is gradual, the results are gradual, the path is gradual, there is no sudden penetration of final knowledge. This, bhikkhus, is the first wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, the great ocean does not contain a corpse. If there is a corpse in the great ocean, it is immediately cast onto the shore or thrown onto dry land. So too, bhikkhus, whoever is immoral, of evil nature, impure, of doubtful behavior, concealing his actions, not a true ascetic but claiming to be an ascetic, not living the holy life but claiming to live the holy life, inwardly rotten, saturated with sensual desires, of unstable character — the Saṅgha does not live with that person, but immediately gathers and expels him. Even if he sits among the Saṅgha of bhikkhus, he lives far from the Saṅgha, and the Saṅgha lives far from him. This, bhikkhus, is the third wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, whatever great rivers there are, such as the Ganges, the Yamunā, the Aciravatī, the Sarabhū, the Mahī, when they reach the great ocean, they abandon their former names and identities and are simply called the great ocean. So too, bhikkhus, these four castes — nobles, brahmins, merchants, laborers — when they go forth from home to homelessness in the Dhamma and Discipline proclaimed by the Tathāgata, they abandon their former names and identities and become simply ascetics following the Sakyan. This, bhikkhus, is the fourth wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, whatever streams flow into the great ocean and whatever rain falls from the sky, the great ocean does not thereby appear to decrease or increase. So too, bhikkhus, even if many bhikkhus attain final Nibbāna without remainder, Nibbāna does not thereby appear to decrease or increase. This, bhikkhus, is the fifth wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, the great ocean has only one taste — the taste of salt. So too, bhikkhus, this Dhamma has only one taste — the taste of liberation. Because, bhikkhus, this Dhamma has only one taste — the taste of liberation. This, bhikkhus, is the sixth wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `Just as, bhikkhus, the great ocean has many jewels, there are these jewels: pearls, gems, lapis lazuli, conch, quartz, coral, silver, gold, rubies, agate. So too, bhikkhus, this Dhamma and Discipline has many jewels, various kinds of jewels: the four establishments of mindfulness, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven factors of enlightenment, the Noble Eightfold Path. This, bhikkhus, is the seventh wonderful, marvelous quality in this Dhamma and Discipline. Seeing this, seeing this, bhikkhus delight in this Dhamma and Discipline.`, ref: "Udāna 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.5" },
{ text: `- Bhante, for a long time I have seen the danger in sensual pleasures, the bondage of household life, with many duties, many things to do.<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Seeing the danger in the world,<br>Knowing the Dhamma without basis,<br>The noble one does not delight in evil,<br>The pure one does not delight in evil!`, ref: "Udāna 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.6" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Khankhārevata sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, contemplating his own purity through the overcoming of doubt. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Whatever doubts there are<br>In this life or the next,<br>Not experienced by oneself<br>Or experienced by others,<br>A meditator abandons them all,<br>Completely.<br>Ardent, he lives the holy life.`, ref: "Udāna 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.7" },
{ text: `Easy to do is a good deed<br>For one who does good;<br>Hard to do is an evil deed<br>For one who does good.<br><br>Easy to do is an evil deed<br>For one who does evil;<br>Hard to do is a good deed<br>For the noble ones.`, ref: "Udāna 5.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.8" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Cūḷapanthaka sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, establishing mindfulness before him. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>With body and mind established,<br>Standing, sitting, or lying down,<br>A bhikkhu established in mindfulness,<br>Attains excellence before and after,<br>Attains excellence before and after,<br>And passes beyond the sight of Māra.`, ref: "Udāna 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud5.10" },
{ text: `One should strive diligently<br>Wherever one may be,<br>One should not become a person<br>Belonging to another.<br><br>Do not live dependent,<br>Relying on others.<br>Do not live by trading,<br>Selling the Dhamma for gain.`, ref: "Udāna 6.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.2" },
{ text: `Because they do not know the goal, because they do not know the non-goal, because they do not know the Dhamma, because they do not know the non-Dhamma, they live in rivalry, disputation, conflict, wounding one another with verbal weapons: 'This is the Dhamma, this is the Dhamma. This is not the Dhamma, this is not the Dhamma.'" Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Some ascetics and brahmins,<br>They cling and quarrel<br>Over these various doctrines,<br>Disputing and contending,<br>They see only one side.`, ref: "Udāna 6.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.4" },
{ text: `Some people in this world<br>Take 'the doer' as 'self',<br>Bound by the thought<br>That 'the doer' is another.<br>They do not understand this,<br>They see it as a dart.<br><br>But one who sees this dart<br>With proper careful attention,<br>No longer holds 'the doer is me',<br>Nor holds 'the doer is another'.<br><br>People in this world,<br>Conquered by conceit,<br>Bound by conceit,<br>Fettered by conceit.<br>In various doctrines,<br>They compete and dispute.<br>They cannot transcend<br>The wandering in birth and death.`, ref: "Udāna 6.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.6" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Subhūti sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, entering into thought-free concentration. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>One whose thoughts are swept away,<br>Internally well cut off,<br>Leaving no remainder,<br>Having transcended that attachment,<br><br>Attaining the formless perception,<br>Having crossed the four yokes,<br>Does not go to birth.`, ref: "Udāna 6.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.7" },
{ text: `The firefly shines<br>When the sun has not yet risen.<br>When the sun rises,<br>The firefly's light fades.<br><br>So too is the light<br>Of the outside schools.<br>When the Perfectly Enlightened One<br>Has not yet appeared in the world,<br><br>Those who delight in sophistry<br>Have no light.<br>So too, their disciples,<br>And those of wrong views,<br>They are not liberated<br>From all suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 6.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.10" },
{ text: `Above, below, everywhere,<br>Fully liberated,<br>One no longer contemplates<br>'This is me.'<br><br>Thus liberated, one crosses the stream<br>Never crossed before.<br>One does not fall back<br>Into birth and existence.`, ref: "Udāna 7.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.1" },
{ text: `Having cut off the cycle,<br>Attained the state of non-desire,<br>Completely dried up,<br>The river no longer flows.<br>The cycle of birth is cut,<br>It does not turn again.<br>This is the end of suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.2" },
{ text: `- Here, Bhante, many people in Sāvatthī are excessively intoxicated with sensual pleasures, living infatuated, attached, desiring, obsessed, bound, and intoxicated by sensual pleasures." Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Beings are attached<br>To various kinds of sensual pleasures.<br>They do not see the fault<br>In the defilements and fetters.<br><br>Certainly, beings<br>Bound by the fetters<br>Cannot cross<br>This great, powerful flood.`, ref: "Udāna 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.3" },
{ text: `Then the Blessed One saw those people in Sāvatthī, most of them excessively intoxicated with sensual pleasures, living infatuated, attached, desiring, obsessed, bound, and intoxicated by sensual pleasures. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Blinded by sensual pleasures,<br>Covered by the net,<br>Enveloped by craving,<br>And also bound<br>By the bond of heedlessness,<br>Like fish caught in a trap,<br>They go to old age and death,<br>Like a calf to its mother's milk.`, ref: "Udāna 7.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Aññā Kondañña sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, contemplating liberation through the destruction of craving. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Without roots in the ground,<br>Without leaves, no creeper,<br>The wise one freed from bonds,<br>Who is worthy of praise?<br>Devas praise that one,<br>Brahmā also praises.`, ref: "Udāna 7.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.6" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One was sitting contemplating the abandonment and destruction of perceptions of frivolous talk. Then the Blessed One, having understood his own abandonment and destruction of perceptions of frivolous talk, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>For one in whom frivolous talk<br>No longer finds a footing,<br>Released from connection,<br>Released from illusion,<br><br>Devas and the world<br>Cannot know<br>The conduct of that seer<br>Who has gone beyond craving.`, ref: "Udāna 7.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.7" },
{ text: `The Blessed One saw the Venerable Mahā Kaccāna sitting not far away, cross-legged, holding his body straight, with mindfulness of the body well established internally before him. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>One who always, constantly,<br>Dwells in mindfulness of the body,<br>'The past could not exist for me,<br>The future could not exist for me,<br>The present could not exist for me.'<br>Dwelling thus continuously,<br>One may in time overcome sensual desire.`, ref: "Udāna 7.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.8" },
{ text: `The world is bound by delusion,<br>Seen as being reborn,<br>Bound by attachment,<br>Fools are surrounded by darkness.<br>They see themselves as permanent,<br>But for one who sees,<br>There will be nothing.`, ref: "Udāna 7.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.10" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there is that sphere, where there is no earth, no water, no fire, no air; no base of infinite space, no base of infinite consciousness, no base of nothingness, no base of neither-perception-nor-non-perception; no this world, no next world, no both moon and sun. There, bhikkhus, I say there is no coming, no going, no staying, no passing away, no arising; no establishment, no continuity, no basis. This is the end of suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.1" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One was teaching the Dhamma to the bhikkhus with a discourse on Nibbāna, encouraging, inspiring, and gladdening them. Those bhikkhus were attentive, applying their minds, concentrating all their attention, listening to the Dhamma. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Difficult to see is the non-self,<br>Not easy to see is the truth.<br>For one who understands,<br>Craving is well penetrated.<br>For one who sees clearly,<br>There is nothing.`, ref: "Udāna 8.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.2" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, there is the unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned. Bhikkhus, if there were no unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, then escape from the born, become, made, conditioned would not be discerned. Because, bhikkhus, there is the unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, therefore escape from the born, become, made, conditioned is discerned.`, ref: "Udāna 8.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.3" },
{ text: `- Whatever is dependent, that is agitated. Whatever is not dependent, that is not agitated. With no agitation, there is tranquility. With tranquility, there is no inclination. With no inclination, there is no coming and going. With no coming and going, there is no passing away and arising. With no passing away and arising, there is no this world, no next world, no intermediate state. This is the end of suffering.`, ref: "Udāna 8.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.4" },
{ text: `The merit of a giver<br>Always increases,<br>He overcomes hatred,<br>Does not store up restraint.<br><br>A good person abandons<br>All evil, unwholesome deeds,<br>Destroys greed, hatred, delusion.<br>His mind is liberated, pure.`, ref: "Udāna 8.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.5" },
{ text: `- Householders, there are these five benefits for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. What five? Here, householders, a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, by reason of heedfulness, acquires great wealth. This is the first benefit for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. Furthermore, householders, a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, obtains a good reputation. This is the second benefit for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. Furthermore, householders, a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, when approaching any assembly — whether of nobles, brahmins, householders, or ascetics — approaches with confidence, without fear or trepidation. This is the third benefit for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. Furthermore, householders, a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, does not die confused. This is the fourth benefit for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. Furthermore, householders, a virtuous person, one of perfect virtue, after death, with the breakup of the body, is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. This is the fifth benefit for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue. Householders, these are the five benefits for a virtuous person, for one of perfect virtue.`, ref: "Udāna 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.6" },
{ text: `Wherever the wise<br>Establish a dwelling,<br>Offer food to those<br>Who are virtuous and restrained,<br>Who live the holy life.<br>There the devas dwell;<br>Make offerings to them.<br><br>Being honored, the devas<br>Honor that person in return.<br>Being respected, the devas<br>Respect that person in return.<br>They have compassion for that person<br>As a mother for her child.<br>One who is loved by devas<br>Always sees what is good.`, ref: "Udāna 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.6" },
{ text: `And the Blessed One went to the Ganges river. The river was full to the brim, so that crows could drink. Some people were looking for a boat, some were looking for a raft, some were tying a raft to cross to the other side. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Those who build a bridge across the mighty ocean,<br>Leaving behind the marshy land,<br>While ordinary people are tying rafts —<br>Those are indeed the wise, the liberated.`, ref: "Udāna 8.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.6" },
{ text: `- Bhante, in Rājagaha, two groups were infatuated with a courtesan, their minds obsessed. They competed and quarreled. They fought with fists, with clods of earth, with sticks, with swords. They went to their death, or to death-like suffering.<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Whatever has been attained,<br>Whatever needs to be attained,<br>Both are dust-stained,<br>For one afflicted with illness,<br>Whose training is not mature.<br><br>One who is devoted to training,<br>Living by virtuous restraint,<br>Devoted to the holy life —<br>This is one extreme.<br><br>And the doctrine that there is no fault in sensual pleasures<br>Is the second extreme.<br><br>Both these extremes<br>Increase cemeteries.<br>It is precisely by wrong views<br>That cemeteries increase.<br><br>Those who do not fully know<br>Both these extremes,<br>Some are drowned,<br>Some run too far.<br><br>Those who fully know them<br>Have no such thoughts,<br>Have no over-conceit,<br>They have no wandering<br>To be declared.`, ref: "Udāna 6.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.8" },
{ text: `At that time, the Blessed One was sitting in the open, in a pitch-dark night, with oil lamps burning. At that time, many kinds of winged insects kept falling into those oil lamps and met with disaster, destruction, and ruin. The Blessed One saw those many kinds of winged insects falling into the oil lamps and meeting with disaster, destruction, and ruin. Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>They run past in haste,<br>But miss the path,<br>They cause new bonds to grow,<br><br>Like insects falling<br>Into the light,<br>Some people rely on<br>What is seen and heard.`, ref: "Udāna 6.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud6.9" },
{ text: `- Bhikkhus, do you see this bhikkhu coming from afar, following behind many bhikkhus, ugly, unsightly, bent over, mostly despised by the other bhikkhus?<br>- Yes, Bhante.<br>- That bhikkhu, bhikkhus, has great psychic power, great might. His jhāna attainment is not easy to attain. He has attained what he had never attained before. And for the purpose for which clansmen rightly go forth from home to homelessness — the unsurpassed goal of the holy life — he in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in it.<br>Then the Blessed One, having understood the meaning of this, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Without defective parts,<br>With a white canopy covering,<br>Having only one wheel,<br>The chariot moves.<br>See him coming,<br>Without sorrow, without difficulty,<br>The stream is cut,<br>He is without bonds.`, ref: "Udāna 7.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.5" },
{ text: `- Visākhā, those who have one hundred beloved ones have one hundred sufferings. Those who have ninety beloved ones have ninety sufferings. Those who have eighty... seventy... sixty... fifty... forty... thirty... twenty... ten... nine... eight... seven... six... five... four... three... two... one beloved one have one suffering. Those who have no beloved ones have no suffering. I say that they are without sorrow, without attachment, without distress.`, ref: "Udāna 8.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.8" },
{ text: `Sorrow, lamentation, and suffering,<br>Various kinds exist in the world.<br>They arise dependent on attachment;<br>Without attachment, they do not arise.<br>Therefore, those who are happy,<br><br>Without sorrow in the world,<br>Are those who have no attachments.<br>Therefore, whoever wishes<br>To be without sorrow, without attachment,<br>Should not form attachment<br>To anyone in the world.`, ref: "Udāna 8.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.8" },
{ text: `Like a spark of fire<br>Struck from a smith's hammer,<br>Gradually cooling,<br>Its destination unknown.<br><br>So too are those<br>Who are rightly liberated,<br>Who have crossed the flood of sensual desires,<br><br>They attain happiness that is not shaken,<br>They have no destination<br>That could be pointed out.`, ref: "Udāna 8.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud8.10" },
            
                { text: `Bhikkhus, abandon one thing. I guarantee you non-return. What one thing? Greed, bhikkhus, abandon that one thing. I guarantee you non-return." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>With greed, beings go to an evil destination.<br>A seer with clear knowledge,<br>Having abandoned that greed,<br>Never returns to this world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti1" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, abandon one thing. I guarantee you non-return. What one thing? Conceit, bhikkhus, abandon that one thing. I guarantee you non-return." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>With conceit, beings go to an evil destination.<br>A seer with clear knowledge,<br>Having abandoned that conceit,<br>Never returns to this world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti6" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one who does not fully know and fully understand all, whose mind is not dispassionate towards it, who has not abandoned it, is incapable of making an end of suffering. But one who fully knows and fully understands all, whose mind is dispassionate towards it, who has abandoned it, is capable of making an end of suffering." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>One who knows and understands<br>All as 'all',<br>In every place,<br>Has no attachment to anything.<br>Such a one certainly<br>Has fully understood all,<br>And has crossed beyond<br>All suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti7" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one who does not fully know and fully understand conceit, whose mind is not dispassionate towards it, who has not abandoned it, is incapable of making an end of suffering. But one who fully knows and fully understands conceit, whose mind is dispassionate towards it, who has abandoned it, is capable of making an end of suffering." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>People are dominated by conceit,<br>Bound by conceit,<br>They delight in existence.<br>Not understanding conceit,<br>They come to renewed existence.<br><br>But those who have abandoned conceit,<br>Liberated, with conceit destroyed,<br>They have conquered the bond of conceit,<br>They have overcome all suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti8" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I do not see any other single hindrance such that, being hindered by it, beings wander for a long time, running on and on. That is, the hindrance of ignorance. Bhikkhus, hindered by the hindrance of ignorance, beings wander for a long time, running on and on.<br><br>There is no other single thing<br>That so keeps beings wandering<br>Day and night,<br>As being caught in delusion.<br><br>But those who have abandoned delusion,<br>Who have pierced the mass of darkness,<br>Do not wander on;<br>In them, the cause is no more.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti14" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I do not see any other single fetter such that, being fettered by it, beings wander for a long time, running on and on. That is, the fetter of craving. Bhikkhus, fettered by the fetter of craving, beings wander for a long time, running on and on.<br><br>One with craving as companion<br>Wanders for a long time.<br>They cannot cross beyond<br>This existence or that.<br><br>Knowing this danger,<br>That craving gives birth to suffering,<br>Free from craving, without clinging,<br>Mindful, the bhikkhu<br>Lives the homeless life.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti15" },


{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a learner bhikkhu whose mind has not yet attained the goal, who dwells aspiring for the unsurpassed security from bondage, having made internal factors, I do not see any other single factor that brings such great benefit as wise attention. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who attends wisely abandons the unwholesome and develops the wholesome." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>A learner bhikkhu<br>Who practices wise attention,<br>There is no other single factor<br>That brings such great benefit,<br>For the attainment of the highest good.<br>A bhikkhu attending wisely,<br>Ardent and diligent,<br>Can attain the destruction of suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti16" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a learner bhikkhu whose mind has not yet attained the goal, who dwells aspiring for the unsurpassed security from bondage, having made external factors, I do not see any other single factor that brings such great benefit as good friendship. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who has good friends abandons the unwholesome and develops the wholesome." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>A bhikkhu with good friends,<br>Honoring and respecting them,<br>Heeding the words<br>Of his companions,<br>Mindful and awake,<br>Step by step he will attain<br>The destruction of all fetters.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti17" },
{ text: `What is the one thing? The harmony of the Saṅgha. Bhikkhus, when the Saṅgha is harmonious, there are no mutual disputes, no mutual reproaches, no mutual hostilities, no mutual abandonments. There, those who are not harmonious become harmonious, and those who are harmonious become even more harmonious." Thus said the Blessed One. Regarding this, it is said:<br><br>Happy is the Saṅgha<br>Living in harmony,<br>Aiding, delighting in harmony,<br>Rejoicing in harmony, abiding in Dhamma,<br>Not falling away, having crossed beyond,<br>Secure from bondage.<br>One who brings harmony<br>To the community of bhikkhus,<br>For an eon rejoices<br>In the heavenly world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti19" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, do not fear meritorious deeds. Bhikkhus, meritorious deeds is a designation for happiness, for what is desirable, pleasant, agreeable, and lovely. Bhikkhus, I directly know that for a long time I have enjoyed the desirable, pleasant, agreeable, lovely result of meritorious deeds done for a long time. Having developed loving-kindness for seven years, I did not return to this world for seven aeons of expansion and contraction. Bhikkhus, I thought: 'What kamma have I done, the result of which, the fruit of which, is such that I now have such great power, such great might?' Then, bhikkhus, I thought: 'This is the result, the fruit, of three kammas that I have done, whereby I now have such great power, such great might: namely, giving, restraint, and self-control.'`, ref: "Itivuttaka 22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti22" },
{ text: `Let one train in meritorious deeds<br>That yield long-lasting happiness:<br>Cultivate giving, a life of peace,<br>And develop a mind of loving-kindness.<br><br>Having cultivated these three things<br>That cause happiness to arise,<br>The wise person is reborn<br>In a happy, harmless world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti22" },
{ text: `There is one thing, bhikkhus, which, when developed and cultivated, brings two benefits: benefit in the present life and benefit in the future life. What one thing? Heedfulness in wholesome states. This one thing, bhikkhus, when developed and cultivated, brings two benefits: benefit in the present life and benefit in the future life.<br><br>The wise praise heedfulness<br>In doing wholesome deeds.<br>The wise one, not heedless,<br>Obtains two benefits:<br><br>Benefit in this very life<br>And benefit in the future.<br>One who has attained benefit<br>Is called a wise person.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti23" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the bones of a single person, running on and wandering on, would become a heap of bones, a pile of bones, a mass of bones as great as this Mount Vepulla, if there were someone to collect them and if they were not destroyed.<br><br>The accumulation of bones of a single person<br>Running on for a single aeon<br>Would be a heap like a mountain,<br>So said the Great Seer.<br><br>That mountain is called Vepulla,<br>North of Vulture's Peak<br>In the mountain range of Magadha.<br><br>One who sees the Four Noble Truths<br>With perfect wisdom —<br>Suffering, the origin of suffering,<br>The overcoming of suffering,<br>And the Noble Eightfold Path<br>Leading to the cessation of suffering —<br><br>That person, having wandered on,<br>At most seven more times,<br>Makes an end of suffering,<br>Destroys all fetters.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti24" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, for a person who transgresses one thing, I say that there is no evil deed that cannot be done. What one thing? Knowing, speaking falsely.<br><br>Whoever speaks falsely,<br>Transgressing that one thing,<br>Disregarding the world beyond,<br>There is no evil they cannot do.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti25" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if beings knew, as I know, the result of sharing gifts, they would not eat without having given, nor would the stain of miserliness obsess their minds. Even if it were their last morsel, their final mouthful, they would not eat without sharing it, if there were someone to receive it.<br><br>If beings knew what the Great Seer proclaimed,<br>The great result of sharing gifts,<br>They would dispel the stain of miserliness<br>With a brightened mind<br>And give at the proper time to the noble ones.<br><br>Having given much food to those worthy of offerings,<br>Departing from the human state,<br>Givers go to heaven,<br>Rejoicing there in the heavenly world,<br>Enjoying all delights as they wish.<br><br>The non-miserly experience abundant results<br>Of sharing gifts.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti26" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, just as the light of all the stars is not worth one-sixteenth of the light of the moon, and the light of the moon surpasses them, shines, and radiates — so too, bhikkhus, whatever deeds are based on attachment, all of them are not worth one-sixteenth of the liberation of mind by loving-kindness. The liberation of mind by loving-kindness alone surpasses them, shines, and radiates.<br><br>Just as, bhikkhus, in the last month of the rainy season, in the autumn, when the sky is clear and cloudless, the sun rises and dispels all darkness from the sky, shines, blazes, and radiates — so too, bhikkhus, whatever deeds are based on attachment... the liberation of mind by loving-kindness alone surpasses them, shines, and radiates.<br><br>Just as, bhikkhus, in the night near the dawn, the morning star shines, blazes, and radiates — so too, bhikkhus, whatever deeds are based on attachment... the liberation of mind by loving-kindness alone surpasses them, shines, and radiates.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti27" },
{ text: `One who develops loving-kindness,<br>Mindful, not heedless,<br>Sees the destruction of attachments,<br>And the fetters wear thin.<br><br>Toward even one being, with a mind free from malice,<br>That person becomes good.<br>With a mind of compassion for all beings,<br>The noble one makes much merit.<br><br>Those royal sages who conquered the earth<br>Teeming with beings, who performed sacrifices —<br>The horse sacrifice, the human sacrifice,<br>The stake sacrifice, the victory-drinking sacrifice,<br>The locked-door sacrifice —<br>They do not amount to one sixteenth<br>Of a mind well developed in loving-kindness,<br>Just as the light of the moon outshines all the stars.<br><br>One who neither kills nor causes to be killed,<br>Neither conquers nor causes to be conquered,<br>With loving-kindness toward all beings,<br>Has no enmity toward anyone.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti27" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing two things dwells in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected. What two? Unrestraint of the sense faculties and lack of moderation in eating. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing these two things dwells in suffering in this very life... an evil destination is to be expected.<br><br>Eye, ear, and nose,<br>Tongue, body, and mind —<br>A bhikkhu who leaves these doors unguarded,<br>Who lacks moderation in eating,<br>Experiences bodily suffering,<br>Experiences mental suffering.<br>Burning in body,<br>Burning in mind,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>He dwells in suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti28" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing two things dwells happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected. What two? Restraint of the sense faculties and moderation in eating. Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing these two things dwells happily in this very life... a good destination is to be expected.<br><br>Eye, ear, and nose,<br>Tongue, body, and mind —<br>A bhikkhu who guards these doors well,<br>Who has moderation in eating,<br>Experiences bodily happiness,<br>Experiences mental happiness.<br>Burning in body,<br>Burning in mind,<br>Whether by day or by night,<br>He dwells in happiness.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti29" },
{ text: `Abandoning evil bodily conduct,<br>Evil verbal conduct,<br>Evil mental conduct,<br>And whatever else is blameworthy,<br><br>Not doing evil deeds,<br>Doing many wholesome deeds,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>A person of superior wisdom<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti31" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu who is not ardent, who has no moral dread, cannot achieve enlightenment, cannot attain Nibbāna, cannot attain the unsurpassed security from bondage. But a bhikkhu who is ardent and has moral dread can achieve enlightenment, can attain Nibbāna, can attain the unsurpassed security from bondage.<br><br>One who is not ardent,<br>Who has no moral dread,<br>Lazy, of little energy,<br>Given to dullness and drowsiness,<br>Without moral shame, without respect —<br>Such a bhikkhu cannot reach<br>Supreme enlightenment.<br><br>But one who is mindful,<br>Intelligent, meditative,<br>Ardent and morally dread,<br>Not heedless,<br>Cutting the fetter of birth and aging,<br>Here and now can attain<br>Supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti34" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the holy life is lived not for the purpose of deceiving people, not for the purpose of flattering people, not for the sake of gain, honor, and renown, not with the thought: 'Let people know me thus.' Rather, bhikkhus, the holy life is lived for the purpose of restraint and for the purpose of abandonment.<br><br>For the purpose of restraint,<br>For the purpose of abandonment,<br>Regard for what others say aside,<br>The Blessed One taught the holy life<br>That leads to Nibbāna.<br><br>This path is followed<br>By the great persons, the great seers.<br>Those who practice it<br>As taught by the Buddha,<br>Following the Teacher's advice,<br>Will make an end of suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti35" },
{ text: `Possessing two things, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells with much joy and happiness in this very life, and makes effort for the destruction of the taints. What two? Inspiration in inspiring cases and wise effort in inspiration. Possessing these two things, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells with much joy and happiness in this very life, and makes effort for the destruction of the taints.<br><br>The wise one who is inspired<br>In cases that should inspire,<br>That bhikkhu, ardent,<br>Intelligent and careful,<br>Contemplates phenomena<br>With wisdom,<br><br>Thus ardently dwelling,<br>Living peacefully,<br>Not restless, striving,<br>His mind calmed,<br>He can attain<br>The destruction of suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti37" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, two kinds of thoughts are frequently practiced: the thought of security and the thought of seclusion. Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata delights in non-harming, takes pleasure in non-harming. For the Tathāgata, bhikkhus, this delight in non-harming, this pleasure in non-harming, these thoughts are frequently practiced: 'By this conduct I harm no one, whether frail or strong.'<br><br>Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata delights in seclusion, takes pleasure in seclusion. For the Tathāgata, bhikkhus, this delight in seclusion, this pleasure in seclusion, these thoughts are frequently practiced: 'Whatever is unwholesome, that is abandoned.'`, ref: "Itivuttaka 38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti38" },
{ text: `The Tathāgata, the Enlightened One,<br>The one who endures what others cannot,<br>Practices and pursues two thoughts:<br>The first mentioned is the thought of security,<br>The second proclaimed is seclusion.<br><br>Dispelling darkness,<br>Gone to the far shore,<br>The Great Sage, attained to power,<br>Taintless, bearing his final body,<br>Liberated by the destruction of craving.<br>That seer, bearing his final body,<br>Having abandoned conceit, I say,<br>Is free from old age, has gone to the far shore.<br><br>As one standing on a rocky peak,<br>On a mountain top, looks down<br>At people all around,<br>So the wise one, having climbed<br>The tower of the Dhamma,<br>With the eye of wisdom, sorrowless,<br>Looks down at the multitude<br>Oppressed by sorrow and grief,<br>Overcome by birth and old age.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti38" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of teaching proclaimed by the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, one following the other. What two? 'See evil as evil' — this is the first teaching. Having seen evil as evil, 'Be disenchanted, abandon it, be liberated from it' — this is the second teaching. Bhikkhus, these are the two kinds of teaching proclaimed by the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, one following the other.<br><br>By the Tathāgata, the Buddha,<br>Compassionate to all beings,<br>Two teachings are expounded<br>Step by step, Dhamma after Dhamma,<br>One following the other.<br><br>First, see evil as evil,<br>Then, being dispassionate toward it,<br>Abandon it completely.<br>From that, with mind dispassionate,<br>Make an end of suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti39" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, ignorance leads the way for the attainment of unwholesome states, and then shamelessness and fearlessness follow. Bhikkhus, clear knowledge leads the way for the attainment of wholesome states, and then moral shame and moral dread follow.<br><br>Whatever evil destinations there are<br>In this world and the next,<br>All have ignorance as their root,<br>As the accumulation of desire.<br><br>Since a person of evil desires<br>Is shameless and disrespectful,<br>From that, evil arises,<br>And thus he goes to a bad destination.<br><br>Therefore, abandoning desire and ignorance,<br>Desiring clear knowledge,<br>A bhikkhu should abandon<br>All evil destinations.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti40" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those beings who have fallen away from noble wisdom are indeed well fallen away; they dwell in suffering in this very life, with trouble, with distress, with fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, an evil destination is to be expected.<br><br>Bhikkhus, those beings who have not fallen away from noble wisdom are not fallen away; they dwell happily in this very life, without trouble, without distress, without fever; and after death, with the breakup of the body, a good destination is to be expected.<br><br>Fallen away from wisdom,<br>Behold the world<br>With its devas<br>Dwelling in name-and-form,<br>Thinking 'This is true.'<br><br>For wisdom is supreme in the world,<br>It leads to the penetration of Nibbāna<br>And to the complete understanding<br>Of the destruction of birth and existence.<br><br>Devas and humans hold dear<br>Those who are awakened and mindful,<br>Possessing wisdom,<br>Bearing their final bodies.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti41" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these two bright qualities protect the world. What two? Moral shame and moral dread. Bhikkhus, if these two bright qualities did not protect the world, then there would be no recognition of 'this is my mother,' 'this is my aunt,' 'this is my brother's wife,' 'this is my teacher's wife,' 'this is the wife of a respected elder'; the world would fall into promiscuity, like goats, sheep, poultry, pigs, dogs, and jackals.<br><br>But since, bhikkhus, these two bright qualities protect the world, there is recognition of 'this is my mother,' 'this is my aunt,' 'this is my brother's wife,' 'this is my teacher's wife,' 'this is the wife of a respected elder.'<br><br>Those for whom moral shame and dread<br>Are not always present<br>Have deviated from the bright root,<br>And go to birth and death.<br><br>But those for whom moral shame and dread<br>Are always well established,<br>Who are mature in the holy life,<br>Have peace, and an end of renewed existence.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti42" },
{ text: `There is the born, the become, the made, the conditioned. If there were not this unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, then escape from the born, become, made, conditioned would not be discerned. But because there is the unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, therefore escape from the born, become, made, conditioned is discerned.<br><br>Whatever is born, become, arisen,<br>Made, conditioned, impermanent,<br>Consisting of birth and aging,<br>A nest of sickness, frail,<br>Subject to destruction, arisen from nutriment —<br>That is not fit to be delighted in.<br><br>There is escape from that, peaceful,<br>Beyond reasoning, eternal,<br>The unborn, unproduced,<br>The sorrowless, stainless, cessation of conditions,<br>The stilling of volitional activities, bliss.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti43" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, dwell delighting in seclusion and meditation, taking pleasure in seclusion and meditation, devoted to internal serenity of mind, not neglecting jhāna, possessed of insight, frequenting empty huts.<br><br>Bhikkhus, dwelling thus, one can expect one of two results: either final knowledge in this very life, or, if there is a residue of clinging, the state of non-return.<br><br>Those who are peaceful in mind,<br>Intelligent, mindful,<br>Meditating, rightly seeing the Dhamma,<br>Without longing for sensual pleasures,<br><br>Delighting in heedfulness,<br>Living peacefully,<br>Seeing fear in heedlessness,<br>They cannot decline,<br>They are close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti45" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, living for the benefit of training, for supreme wisdom, for the core of liberation, for mindfulness as master, one can expect one of two results: either final knowledge in this very life, or, if there is a residue of clinging, the state of non-return.<br><br>One perfect in the learner's stage,<br>Not subject to decline,<br>Attained to supreme wisdom,<br>Sees the destruction of birth.<br>That sage, I say, bears his final body,<br>Has abandoned conceit,<br>Gone beyond old age,<br><br>Therefore, delight always in jhāna,<br>Be ardent and diligent,<br>Seeing the destruction of birth,<br>O bhikkhus, conquer Māra's army,<br>And go beyond birth and old age.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti46" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu should live vigilant, mindful, clearly comprehending, concentrated, joyful, faithful, and at the proper time he should investigate wholesome states. For a bhikkhu living thus, one of two results is to be expected: either final knowledge in this very life, or, if there is a residue of clinging, the state of non-return.<br><br>Those who are vigilant, hear this:<br>You who are sleeping, awake!<br>Wakefulness is better than sleep<br>For those who are fearful.<br>Those who are wakeful, who have woken up,<br>Mindful, understanding,<br>Concentrated, joyful,<br>Ardent, faithful,<br>Knowing the proper time, discerning the Dhamma,<br>Attain one-pointedness of mind,<br>Dispelling darkness.<br><br>Therefore, train in wakefulness and ardency;<br>A wise bhikkhu, careful,<br>Should attain jhāna,<br>Cut the fetter of birth and aging,<br>And here and now attain<br>Supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti47" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these two kinds of persons are heading for ruin, heading for hell, unless they abandon that fault. What two? One who, not living the holy life, pretends to live the holy life; and one who, without cause, baselessly accuses one who lives the pure, complete holy life of not living the holy life. These two persons are heading for ruin, heading for hell, unless they abandon that fault.<br><br>One who speaks falsely goes to hell,<br>One who says 'I did not do' what one did.<br>Both after death become equal:<br>They are lowly men of evil deeds in the hereafter.<br><br>Many who wear the yellow robe,<br>Unrestrained in evil deeds,<br>By their evil deeds are reborn in hell.<br><br>Better for them to swallow a red-hot iron ball<br>Blazing like fire,<br>Than to be immoral and unrestrained<br>And eat the country's almsfood.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti48" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is meant by 'some people are attached'? Here, bhikkhus, some devas and humans delight in existence. When the Dhamma for the cessation of existence is taught to them, their minds do not enter into it, do not become confident, do not become established, are not drawn to it. Thus, bhikkhus, some are attached.<br><br>And what, bhikkhus, are 'some people who overreach'? Here, bhikkhus, some people are troubled, ashamed, and disgusted with existence, and they delight in non-existence, saying: 'With the breakup of the body, this self is annihilated, destroyed, and does not exist after death.' This is their view, which is immediate, supreme, and true. Thus, bhikkhus, some overreach.<br><br>And what, bhikkhus, are 'some people with vision'? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu sees what has come to be as having come to be. Having seen what has come to be as having come to be, he practices for disenchantment, for dispassion, for cessation regarding it. Thus, bhikkhus, some have vision.<br><br>Those who have seen<br>What has come to be as it is,<br>And have seen the escape<br>From what has come to be,<br>Are liberated in accordance with what has come to be,<br>By the destruction of craving for becoming.<br><br>If a bhikkhu fully understands<br>What has come to be as it is,<br>Free from craving for becoming and non-becoming,<br>He will not come again to birth.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti49" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of feeling. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, and neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of feeling.<br><br>Concentrated, clearly comprehending,<br>Mindful, a disciple of the Buddha<br>Understands feelings,<br>And the origin of feelings,<br><br>Where they cease, and the path<br>Leading to their cessation.<br>With the destruction of feelings,<br>A bhikkhu is without longing, fully quenched.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti52" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of feeling. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, and neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling.<br><br>Bhikkhus, pleasant feeling should be regarded as suffering; painful feeling should be regarded as a dart; neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling should be regarded as impermanent. When a bhikkhu has regarded pleasant feeling as suffering, painful feeling as a dart, and neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling as impermanent, then he is called a noble one who sees rightly, who has cut off craving, untied the fetters, and by the full penetration of conceit has made an end of suffering.<br><br>One who sees pleasure as suffering,<br>Sees pain as a dart,<br>Sees the neutral feeling as impermanent,<br>That bhikkhu indeed sees rightly,<br>And thereby becomes liberated.<br>Having perfected direct knowledge,<br>That peaceful seer has crossed beyond all bonds.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti53" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of seeking. What three? Seeking for sensual pleasures, seeking for existence, and seeking for the holy life. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of seeking.<br><br>Seeking for sensual pleasures and existence,<br>And the seeking for the holy life —<br>If one grasps them as truth,<br>That is the accumulation of views,<br>The ground of views.<br><br>But one who is unattached to all desires,<br>Liberated by the destruction of craving,<br>Has abandoned all seeking,<br>Uprooted the ground of views.<br><br>A bhikkhu, with the destruction of seeking,<br>Without longing, free from doubt.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti55" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three taints. What three? The taint of sensual desire, the taint of existence, and the taint of ignorance. Bhikkhus, these are the three taints.<br><br>One who has abandoned the taint of sensual desire,<br>And the taint of ignorance,<br>Who has destroyed the taint of existence,<br>Is liberated from all attachments.<br>Bearing his final body,<br>He has conquered Māra and his host.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti57" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of craving. What three? Craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, and craving for non-existence. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of craving.<br><br>Bound by the bond of craving,<br>Their minds attached to becoming and non-becoming,<br>Those beings are bound by Māra's bond,<br>Not secure from bondage.<br>They go through the cycle of birth and death,<br>Going from birth to death.<br><br>But those who have abandoned craving,<br>Free from craving for existence and non-existence,<br>Having reached the far shore in this world,<br>Have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti58" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possessing three things has overcome Māra's power and shines like the sun. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu possesses the Arahant's aggregate of virtue, the Arahant's aggregate of concentration, and the Arahant's aggregate of wisdom. Possessing these three things, a bhikkhu has overcome Māra's power and shines like the sun.<br><br>Virtue, concentration, and wisdom —<br>For one who has well developed these,<br>Having overcome Māra's power,<br>He shines and blazes like the sun.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti59" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three bases of meritorious action. What three? The basis of meritorious action through giving, the basis of meritorious action through virtue, and the basis of meritorious action through development. Bhikkhus, these are the three bases of meritorious action.<br><br>Let one train in deeds of merit<br>That yield long-lasting happiness:<br>Cultivate giving, a life of peace,<br>And develop a mind of loving-kindness.<br><br>Having cultivated these three things<br>That cause happiness to arise,<br>The wise person is reborn<br>In a happy, harmless world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti60" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of evil conduct. What three? Evil bodily conduct, evil verbal conduct, and evil mental conduct. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of evil conduct.<br><br>By doing evil with the body,<br>Evil with speech,<br>Evil with the mind,<br>And whatever else is blameworthy,<br><br>Not doing what is wholesome,<br>Doing much that is unwholesome,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of evil wisdom<br>Is reborn in hell.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti64" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of good conduct. What three? Good bodily conduct, good verbal conduct, and good mental conduct. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of good conduct.<br><br>Abandoning evil bodily action,<br>Abandoning evil verbal action,<br>Abandoning evil mental action,<br>And whatever else is blameworthy,<br><br>Not doing evil,<br>Doing much that is wholesome,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of superior wisdom<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti65" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of purity. What three? Purity of body, purity of speech, and purity of mind. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of purity.<br><br>Purity of body and speech,<br>Purity of mind, without taints,<br>One who is pure, possessing purity,<br>Is called one who has abandoned all.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti66" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of peace. What three? Peace of body, peace of speech, and peace of mind. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of peace.<br><br>Peace of body, peace of speech,<br>Peace of mind, without taints,<br>One who is perfect in peace,<br>A sage, is called one who has washed away evil.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti67" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one in whom greed is not abandoned, hatred is not abandoned, delusion is not abandoned — that person, bhikkhus, is called one bound by Māra, caught in Māra's snare, subject to Māra's will.<br><br>Bhikkhus, one in whom greed is abandoned, hatred is abandoned, delusion is abandoned — that person, bhikkhus, is called one not bound by Māra, freed from Māra's snare, not subject to Māra's will.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Hatred, and ignorance,<br>Is called one who has developed the self,<br>Become a Brahmā, a Tathāgata, a Buddha,<br>One who has overcome hatred and fear,<br>One who has abandoned all.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti68" },
{ text: `For whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, greed is not abandoned, hatred is not abandoned, delusion is not abandoned, that one, bhikkhus, is called one who has not crossed the ocean with its waves, whirlpools, sharks, and demons.<br><br>For whatever bhikkhu or bhikkhunī, bhikkhus, greed is abandoned, hatred is abandoned, delusion is abandoned, that one, bhikkhus, is called one who has crossed the ocean with its waves, whirlpools, sharks, and demons, who has gone to the far shore, a brahmin standing on dry ground.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Hatred, and ignorance,<br>Has crossed this ocean<br>With its sharks, demons,<br>And fearsome waves,<br>So hard to cross.<br><br>He has transcended birth and death,<br>Without attachments, abandoned suffering,<br>Without renewed existence, gone to the goal,<br>Not to be measured, I say,<br>He has bewildered the King of Death.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti69" },
{ text: `Directing the mind in wrong ways,<br>Speaking wrong speech,<br>Doing wrong deeds with the body,<br>A person here in the world,<br><br>Of little learning, not doing merit,<br>Living a short life here,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of evil wisdom<br>Is reborn in hell.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti70" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three elements of escape. What three? Escape from sensual pleasures is renunciation. Escape from forms is formlessness. And the cessation of whatever is born, become, conditioned, arisen — that is the escape. Bhikkhus, these are the three elements of escape.<br><br>Knowing the escape from sensual pleasures,<br>And going beyond forms,<br>Always ardent, one who stills all volitional activities:<br><br>That bhikkhu, seeing rightly,<br>Is thereby liberated.<br>Perfect in direct knowledge,<br>Living peacefully,<br>That sage has crossed all bonds.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti72" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, formless states are more peaceful than form states. Cessation is more peaceful than formless states.<br><br>Those who fully understand forms,<br>Not established in formless states,<br>Are liberated in cessation,<br>Leaving death behind.<br><br>Having touched the deathless element,<br>Without attachments,<br>Having abandoned attachments,<br>Realized, without taints,<br>The Perfectly Enlightened One teaches the path<br>Without sorrow, without stain.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti73" },
{ text: `These sons in the world become male lay followers,<br>Endowed with faith and virtue,<br>Knowing the words of others,<br>Free from stinginess.<br>Such sons shine in the assembly,<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti74" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of persons existing in the world. What three? A person like a drought, a person like a local rain, and a person like rain pouring everywhere. And how, bhikkhus, is a person like a drought? Here, bhikkhus, a person does not give anything to anyone — not food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, lamps — to ascetics, brahmins, or to poor, needy, indigent beggars. Such a person, bhikkhus, is like a drought, not raining. And how, bhikkhus, is a person like a local rain? Here, bhikkhus, a person gives to some but not to others. To some ascetics, brahmins, or poor, needy, indigent beggars he gives food... lamps, but to others he does not give. Such a person, bhikkhus, is like a local rain. And how, bhikkhus, is a person like rain pouring everywhere? Here, bhikkhus, a person gives to everyone — to ascetics, brahmins, and to poor, needy, indigent beggars — food, drink, clothing, vehicles, garlands, scents, ointments, beds, dwellings, lamps. Bhikkhus, these are the three kinds of persons existing in the world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti75" },
{ text: `Hopeful of three kinds of happiness, the wise person maintains virtue. What three? Hoping 'Praise will come to me,' the wise person maintains virtue. Hoping 'Wealth will arise for me,' the wise person maintains virtue. Hoping 'After death, with the breakup of the body, I will be reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world,' the wise person maintains virtue.<br><br>One who maintains virtue,<br>Hopeful of three kinds of happiness,<br>Is praised, gains wealth,<br>And after death rejoices in heaven.<br><br>If one does no evil,<br>But associates with an evil-doer,<br>One is suspected of evil,<br>And one's bad reputation increases.<br><br>Whatever a person befriends,<br>Whomever one follows,<br>One becomes like that person,<br>By sharing the same dwelling.<br><br>Association, the associated,<br>Contact, the contacted —<br>Like an arrow smeared with poison<br>Contaminates a quiver of arrows,<br>So a wise person, fearing contamination,<br>Should not associate with evil friends.<br><br>A man who wraps rotten fish<br>In a blade of kusa grass<br>Makes the grass smell foul.<br>So it is with one who associates with fools.<br><br>But one who wraps tagara powder<br>In a leaf makes the leaf fragrant.<br>So it is with one who associates with the wise.<br><br>Therefore, knowing the outcome as with a leaf-basket,<br>The wise person should not associate with the unwholesome,<br>But should associate with the good and wholesome.<br><br>The unwholesome lead to hell,<br>The good lead to a good destination.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti76" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, this body is decaying, consciousness is fading away, all attachments are impermanent, suffering, subject to change.<br><br>Knowing the body as decaying,<br>And consciousness as fading away,<br>Seeing fear in attachments,<br>Understanding birth and death,<br><br>Having attained supreme peace,<br>One develops the self, awaiting the time.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti77" },
{ text: `The forest of sensual desires arises from association; it is cut down by non-association. Just as a small plank of wood sinks in the great river, so does a good person sink when associating with a lazy person. Therefore, avoid the lazy, the unenergetic.<br><br>Dwell with the noble seers,<br>The secluded, the diligent,<br>Those devoted to jhāna,<br>Ever ardent and mindful.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 78", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti78" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these three things lead to the decline of a learner bhikkhu. What three? Here, bhikkhus, a learner bhikkhu delights in work, takes pleasure in work, is devoted to delight in work; delights in talking, takes pleasure in talking, is devoted to delight in talking; delights in sleeping, takes pleasure in sleeping, is devoted to delight in sleeping.<br><br>A bhikkhu who delights in work,<br>Delights in talking,<br>Delights in sleeping,<br>Is restless and agitated.<br>Such a bhikkhu cannot attain<br>Supreme enlightenment.<br><br>Therefore, let him have few duties,<br>Little sleep, no restlessness,<br>Such a bhikkhu can attain<br>Supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti79" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three evil thoughts. What three? The thought of comparing oneself to others (conceit), the thought of gain, honor, and renown, and the thought of caring for others. Bhikkhus, these are the three evil thoughts.<br><br>One who is attached to comparing himself,<br>Attached to gain and honor,<br>Delighting in company with friends,<br>Stands far from the destruction of fetters.<br><br>But one who has abandoned children and cattle,<br>And the rites of marriage,<br>Who has stored up no possessions,<br>That bhikkhu can attain<br>Supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti80" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I have seen beings who, overcome and obsessed by honor, at the breaking up of the body, have been reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. I have seen beings who, overcome and obsessed by dishonor, at the breaking up of the body, have been reborn in a plane of misery... I have seen beings who, overcome and obsessed by both honor and dishonor, at the breaking up of the body, have been reborn in a plane of misery...<br><br>One who, when honored or dishonored,<br>In both cases, with mind unshaken,<br>Lives heedfully, constantly meditating,<br>With subtle perceptions, seeing what is seen,<br>Delighting in the destruction of clinging,<br>Is called a genuine person.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti81" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, when a noble disciple shaves off his hair and beard, puts on the yellow robe, and thinks of going forth from home to homelessness, at that moment, bhikkhus, a divine shout arises among the devas: 'This noble disciple intends to do battle with Māra!' This, bhikkhus, is the first divine shout that arises from time to time among the devas.<br><br>Furthermore, bhikkhus, when a noble disciple dwells devoted to developing the seven factors of enlightenment, at that moment, bhikkhus, a divine shout arises among the devas: 'This noble disciple does battle with Māra!' This, bhikkhus, is the second divine shout that arises from time to time among the devas.<br><br>Furthermore, bhikkhus, when a noble disciple, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom, at that moment, bhikkhus, a divine shout arises among the devas: 'This noble disciple has won the battle! Standing at the head of the battle, having been victorious, he dwells.' This, bhikkhus, is the third divine shout that arises from time to time among the devas.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti82" },

{ text: `Bhikkhus, dwell contemplating foulness in the body, establish well mindfulness of breathing, set mindfulness before you, turn it inward; dwell contemplating impermanence in all volitional formations. Bhikkhus, when one dwells contemplating foulness in the body, the underlying tendency to greed for the beautiful is abandoned; when mindfulness of breathing is well established, set before you, turned inward, there are no outward-directed thoughts that partake of harm; when one dwells contemplating impermanence in all volitional formations, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises.<br><br>Contemplating foulness in the body,<br>Mindfulness of breathing in and out,<br>Stilling all volitional formations,<br>Always ardent, with right view,<br><br>Such a bhikkhu, seeing rightly,<br>Is thereby liberated here.<br>Perfect in direct knowledge, at peace,<br>That sage has surely crossed beyond all bonds.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti85" },
{ text: `For a bhikkhu who practices Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma, when he speaks, he speaks Dhamma, not non-Dhamma; when he thinks, he thinks Dhamma-thoughts, not non-Dhamma-thoughts. Having abandoned both, he dwells equanimous, mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>Delighting in Dhamma, rejoicing in Dhamma,<br>Reflecting on the true Dhamma,<br>A bhikkhu mindful of Dhamma<br>Does not fall away from the true Dhamma.<br><br>Whether walking or standing,<br>Sitting or lying down,<br>With mind internally restrained,<br>He attains peace.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti86" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, thoughts of sensual desire produce blindness, produce lack of vision, produce lack of knowledge, lead to the destruction of wisdom, partake of harm, and do not lead to Nibbāna. Thoughts of ill-will produce blindness, produce lack of vision, produce lack of knowledge, lead to the destruction of wisdom, partake of harm, and do not lead to Nibbāna. Thoughts of harming produce blindness, produce lack of vision, produce lack of knowledge, lead to the destruction of wisdom, partake of harm, and do not lead to Nibbāna.<br><br>Reflect and think upon the three wholesome thoughts;<br>Abandon and avoid the three evil thoughts.<br>That one will surely restrain the patterns of thought,<br><br>Like rain dispels accumulated dust.<br>That one indeed will calm thoughts and mind.<br>Here he attains the path of peace.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti87" },
{ text: `Greed gives rise to harm; greed agitates the mind.<br>Fear itself arises from within; people do not know that special greed.<br><br>A greedy person does not know what is beneficial,<br>A greedy person does not see the true Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness will appear<br>In anyone who dwells with greed.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Not greedy for things to be greedy about,<br>For one from whom greed has fallen away<br>Like a water drop from a lotus leaf.<br><br>Hatred gives rise to harm; hatred agitates the mind.<br>Fear itself arises from within; people do not know that special hatred.<br><br>A hateful person does not know what is beneficial,<br>A hateful person does not see the true Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness will appear<br>In anyone who dwells with hatred.<br><br>One who has abandoned hatred,<br>Not hateful toward things to be hated about,<br>For one from whom hatred has fallen away<br>Like a palm fruit cut from its stem.<br><br>Delusion gives rise to harm; delusion agitates the mind.<br>Fear itself arises from within; people do not know that special delusion.<br><br>A deluded person does not know what is beneficial,<br>A deluded person does not see the true Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness will appear<br>In anyone who dwells with delusion.<br><br>One who has abandoned delusion,<br>Not deluded about things to be deluded about,<br>That one has swept away all delusion,<br>Like the rising sun dispels all darkness.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti88" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three internal stains, internal enemies, internal opponents, internal murderers, internal adversaries. What three? Greed, bhikkhus, is an internal stain, internal enemy, internal opponent, internal murderer, internal adversary. Hatred, bhikkhus, is an internal stain, internal enemy, internal opponent, internal murderer, internal adversary. Delusion, bhikkhus, is an internal stain, internal enemy, internal opponent, internal murderer, internal adversary. These are the three internal stains, internal enemies, internal opponents, internal murderers, internal adversaries.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti88" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three supreme kinds of confidence. What three? Bhikkhus, among whatever beings there are — footless, two-footed, four-footed, or many-footed, whether having form or formless, whether percipient, non-percipient, or neither-percipient-nor-non-percipient — the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One is declared the foremost among them. Bhikkhus, those who have confidence in the Buddha have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost.<br><br>Bhikkhus, among whatever states there are — whether conditioned or unconditioned — dispassion is declared the foremost among them, that is, the subduing of pride, the removal of thirst, the uprooting of attachment, the cutting off of the round (of rebirth), the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna. Bhikkhus, those who have confidence in the Dhamma of dispassion have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost.<br><br>Bhikkhus, among whatever Saṅghas or assemblies there are, the Saṅgha of the Tathāgata's disciples is declared the foremost among them, that is, the four pairs of persons, the eight individuals — this Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is worthy of gifts, worthy of hospitality, worthy of offerings, worthy of reverential salutation, the unsurpassed field of merit in the world. Bhikkhus, those who have confidence in the Saṅgha have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the result is foremost. These, bhikkhus, are the three supreme kinds of confidence.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti90" },
{ text: `Those who have confidence,<br>Confidence in the foremost,<br>Know the foremost Dhamma,<br>Have confidence in the Buddha foremost,<br>The unsurpassed One worthy of offerings.<br><br>Those who have confidence<br>In the foremost Dhamma,<br>The Dhamma of dispassion, peaceful, blissful.<br>Those who have confidence<br>In the foremost Saṅgha,<br>The unsurpassed field of merit.<br><br>Those who give to the foremost,<br>Foremost merit increases,<br>Foremost in life span, beauty, fame,<br>Happiness and strength.<br><br>The wise who give to the foremost,<br>Established in the foremost Dhamma,<br>Whether devas or humans,<br>Attain foremost joy.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti90" },
{ text: `Household wealth is abandoned, but hard to share in the goal of asceticism.<br>One brings harm to oneself and brings distraction,<br>Like a funeral torch that goes to destruction.<br><br>Many who wear the yellow robe,<br>Of evil nature, unrestrained,<br>By their evil deeds, certainly go to hell.<br><br>Better to swallow a red-hot iron ball,<br>Blazing like a fire,<br>Than for an immoral, unrestrained person<br>To eat the country's almsfood.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti91" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, this is the ultimate livelihood among livelihoods, namely, going for alms. In the world, the abusive term is: 'You are a beggar, carrying a bowl, wandering everywhere.' Yet this livelihood is accepted by good clansmen who live for the sake of the goal, who live dependent on the goal, not driven to it by fear of kings, fear of thieves, by debt, by fear, not because of loss of livelihood, but thinking: 'I am fallen into birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair, fallen into suffering, overcome by suffering. Perhaps the complete destruction of this whole mass of suffering can be made known.' Bhikkhus, such a clansman who has gone forth, if he still has craving for sensual pleasures, strong greed, a hateful mind, evil thoughts, forgetfulness, lack of clear comprehension, unconcentrated, with distracted mind and loose faculties — then, bhikkhus, like a funeral torch taken from a cremation ground, burning at both ends, smeared with excrement in the middle, not serving as a log in the village or in the forest — I say that such a person is like that simile. Though he has left household wealth, he does not fulfill the goal of asceticism.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti91" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu takes hold of the hem of my robe and follows right behind me, placing his feet where my feet have been, yet if he has craving for sensual pleasures, strong greed, a hateful mind, evil thoughts, forgetfulness, lack of clear comprehension, unconcentrated, with distracted mind and loose faculties — that one is far from me, and I am far from him. Why is that? That bhikkhu does not see the Dhamma. Not seeing the Dhamma, he does not see me.<br><br>Bhikkhus, if a bhikkhu lives a hundred leagues away, yet if he has no craving for sensual pleasures, no strong greed, no hateful mind, no evil thoughts, is mindful, clearly comprehending, concentrated, one-pointed, with restrained faculties — that one is close to me, and I am close to him. Why is that? That bhikkhu sees the Dhamma. Seeing the Dhamma, he sees me.<br><br>Though one may follow at the heel,<br>But full of desire and discontent,<br>Behold such a person: truly far, far away,<br>Far between one with craving and one without,<br>Far between the calm and the uncalm,<br>Far between one with greed and one who has abandoned greed.<br><br>Having fully known the Dhamma,<br>The wise one who knows the Dhamma,<br>Like a windless lake, unshaken, calm.<br>Behold such a person: truly near, very near,<br>Near between one without craving and one without craving,<br>Near between the calm and the calmed,<br>Near between the non-greedy and the one who has abandoned greed.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 92", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti92" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three fires. What three? The fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. These are the three fires.<br><br>The fire of greed burns the person<br>Infatuated with sensual pleasures.<br>The fire of hatred burns those<br>Who have hateful minds,<br>Who kill and harm beings.<br><br>The fire of delusion burns those<br>Who are confused,<br>Who are not trained in the noble Dhamma.<br>Not knowing such fires,<br>People delight in existence.<br><br>They swell the realm of hell,<br>As well as the animal realm,<br>The sphere of animals,<br>Together with the asuras,<br>And the realm of hungry ghosts.<br>They are not freed from Māra's bondage.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti93" },
{ text: `Those who day and night<br>Are devoted to training,<br>Learning the words of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>They calm the fire of greed,<br>Always perceiving the foulness of things.<br><br>With loving-kindness and compassion,<br>The foremost of persons,<br>They calm and still the fire of hatred.<br>And the fire of delusion<br>They extinguish with wisdom,<br>Wisdom that leads to penetration of the truth.<br><br>The vigilant, the wise,<br>Day and night they calm such fires,<br>Without weariness.<br>They calm them completely, leaving no trace.<br><br>The noble ones who have seen,<br>The wise who know,<br>Are the truly wise, seeing with right knowledge.<br>Having fully known the destruction of birth,<br>They do not go to birth again and again.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti93" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of arising of sensual desire. What three? Sensual desire for present things, delight in things one has created, and acceptance of things created by others. These are the three kinds of arising of sensual desire.<br><br>Devas who enjoy sensual pleasures,<br>Devas of great power,<br>Devas who create pleasure,<br>And other devas<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures,<br>Whether in this realm or that,<br>They do not escape from saṃsāra.<br><br>Knowing this danger,<br>The wise person regarding sensual pleasures,<br>In this life and the next,<br>Abandons all sensual pleasures,<br>Whether deva or human.<br><br>Those who have cut the stream so hard to cross,<br>The intoxication with things dear and beautiful,<br>They calm it completely, leaving no trace.<br>They go beyond suffering, leaving nothing behind.<br><br>The noble ones who have seen,<br>The wise who know,<br>Are the truly wise, seeing with right knowledge.<br>Having fully known the destruction of birth,<br>They do not go to birth again and again.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti95" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, what is good virtue? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu is virtuous, living restrained by the restraint of the Pātimokkha, perfect in conduct and resort, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has good virtue.<br><br>And what is good Dhamma? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu dwells devoted to the development of the seven factors of enlightenment. Thus, bhikkhus, he has good Dhamma. Thus he has good virtue and good Dhamma. And what is good wisdom? Here, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu, by the destruction of the taints, in this very life, with direct knowledge, realizes, attains, and abides in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Thus, bhikkhus, a bhikkhu has good wisdom. Thus, one with good virtue, good Dhamma, and good wisdom is called one who is complete in this Dhamma and Discipline.<br><br>One who in body, speech, and mind does no evil,<br>That one has good virtue, a bhikkhu with moral shame.<br><br>One who has well developed the states that lead to enlightenment,<br>That one has good Dhamma, a bhikkhu without leaking desire.<br><br>One who has fully understood suffering here and abandoned suffering,<br>That one has good wisdom, a bhikkhu without taints.<br><br>Possessing these things,<br>Free from distress, having cut off all doubt,<br>Not attached to any thing in the world,<br>He is called one who has abandoned all.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti97" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of giving: giving of material goods and giving of the Dhamma. Of these two kinds of giving, the giving of the Dhamma is supreme. Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of sharing: sharing of material goods and sharing of the Dhamma. Of these two, sharing of the Dhamma is supreme. Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of help: help with material goods and help with the Dhamma. Of these two, help with the Dhamma is supreme.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti98" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, these four things are few, easily obtained, and blameless. What four? Among robes, the dust-heap rag is few, easily obtained, and blameless. Among foods, the lump of almsfood is few, easily obtained, and blameless. Among lodgings, the foot of a tree is few, easily obtained, and blameless. Among medicines, fermented cow's urine is few, easily obtained, and blameless. These four things are few, easily obtained, and blameless. Bhikkhus, when a bhikkhu is content with these few, easily obtained things, I declare that this is a factor of asceticism for him.<br><br>Content with things that are few,<br>Easily obtained, and blameless,<br>Mind not disturbed<br>Regarding lodgings, robes, food and drink.<br>Not worried about the direction one should go,<br>The Dhamma proclaimed, conducive to asceticism,<br>He possesses them fully,<br>For a bhikkhu who knows contentment, who is not heedless.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti101" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are complete in virtue, complete in concentration, complete in wisdom, complete in liberation, complete in the knowledge and vision of liberation — those who instruct, teach, proclaim, encourage, inspire, and delight, who are worthy of expounding the good Dhamma — such bhikkhus, I declare, are of great benefit to those bhikkhus just by seeing them; I declare that just hearing them is of great benefit; I declare that just approaching them is of great benefit; I declare that just associating with them is of great benefit; I declare that just remembering them is of great benefit; I declare that just going forth after them is of great benefit. Why is that? Because, bhikkhus, by serving, sharing with, and associating with such bhikkhus, the aggregate of virtue that is incomplete comes to fulfillment, the aggregate of concentration that is incomplete comes to fulfillment, the aggregate of wisdom that is incomplete comes to fulfillment, the aggregate of liberation that is incomplete comes to fulfillment, the aggregate of the knowledge and vision of liberation that is incomplete comes to fulfillment. Such bhikkhus, bhikkhus, are called teachers, caravan leaders, those who have abandoned the causes of harm, those who dispel darkness, those who produce light, those who produce radiance, those who produce illumination, those who carry a torch, those who emit light, the noble ones, those with vision.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti104" },
{ text: `Because of robes, bhikkhus, craving arises for a bhikkhu. Because of almsfood, bhikkhus, craving arises for a bhikkhu. Because of lodgings, bhikkhus, craving arises for a bhikkhu. Because of this or that kind of existence, bhikkhus, craving arises for a bhikkhu. These are the four kinds of arising of craving from which craving arises for a bhikkhu.<br><br>One with craving as companion<br>Wanders for a long time.<br>He does not transcend the round of existence,<br>From this life to the next.<br><br>Knowing this danger,<br>That craving gives birth to suffering,<br>Free from craving, without clinging,<br>Mindful, the bhikkhu wanders.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti105" },
{ text: `In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children honor their parents in the home, those families are considered like Brahmā. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children honor their parents in the home, those families are considered like the ancient teachers. In whatever families, bhikkhus, the children honor their parents in the home, those families are considered worthy of offerings. Brahmā, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. The ancient teachers, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Worthy of offerings, bhikkhus, is a designation for mother and father. Why is that? Because mother and father have done much for their children: they nourish them, bring them up, and introduce them to this world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti106" },
{ text: `Mother and father are called Brahmā,<br>The ancient teachers,<br>Worthy to be supported and honored by children.<br><br>Therefore the wise pay homage and respect them,<br>Offer food and drink,<br>Clothing and bedding,<br>Anoint their bodies,<br>Bathe their hands and feet.<br><br>By acting thus toward mother and father,<br>In this life the wise praise them,<br>In the next they enjoy heavenly bliss.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti106" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the brahmin householders are very helpful to you. They provide you with robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicinal requisites. And you, bhikkhus, are very helpful to the brahmin householders, for you teach them the Dhamma that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with meaning and phrasing, revealing the completely perfected and purified holy life. Thus, bhikkhus, the holy life is lived in mutual dependence for the purpose of crossing the flood and making an end of suffering.<br><br>Those with homes and those without homes,<br>Each relying on the other,<br>Attain the supreme Dhamma,<br>The unsurpassed security from bondage.<br><br>From those with homes,<br>The homeless receive robes, lodging,<br>And other necessities;<br>Thus they avoid hardships.<br><br>Householders, longing for their homes,<br>Relying on the Well-Gone One,<br>With faith in the worthy ones,<br>Faith in noble wisdom,<br>They develop jhāna.<br><br>Here, practicing the Dhamma,<br>The path to a good destination,<br>Rejoicing in the heavenly world,<br>They live in delight,<br>As they wish.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti107" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those bhikkhus who are deceitful, stubborn, talkative, loose, disrespectful, unconcentrated — those bhikkhus are not my disciples; they have fallen away from this Dhamma and Discipline; they do not achieve growth, increase, or expansion in this Dhamma and Discipline. And those bhikkhus who are not deceitful, not talkative, dignified, not stubborn, well concentrated — those bhikkhus are my disciples; they have not fallen away from this Dhamma and Discipline; they achieve growth, increase, and expansion in this Dhamma and Discipline.<br><br>Deceitful and stubborn,<br>Talkative and loose,<br>Disrespectful, unconcentrated —<br>Such persons do not grow in the Dhamma<br>Proclaimed by the Perfectly Enlightened One.<br><br>Not deceitful, not talkative,<br>Dignified and calm,<br>Not stubborn, well concentrated —<br>They grow in the Dhamma<br>Proclaimed by the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 108", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti108" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, suppose a person was being swept away by a beautiful, lovely river. A man with good eyes standing on the bank saw him and said: 'Good man, though you are being swept away by this beautiful, lovely river, further downstream there is a lake with waves and whirlpools, with crocodiles and demons. If you reach that place, you will die or suffer death-like pain.' Then that person, hearing the words of that man, used his hands and feet to swim against the stream. Bhikkhus, I have given this simile to explain the meaning. The meaning is this: 'The river' is a designation for craving. 'Beautiful, lovely' is a designation for the six internal sense spheres. 'The lake downstream' is a designation for the five lower fetters. 'The waves' is a designation for anger and distress. 'The whirlpools' is a designation for the five strands of sensual pleasure. 'The crocodiles and demons' is a designation for women. 'Against the stream' is a designation for renunciation. 'Exertion with hands and feet' is a designation for energy and striving. 'The man with good eyes standing on the bank' is the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti109" },
{ text: `With suffering, abandon sensual pleasures,<br>Seeking future security from bondage.<br>Having rightly understood, the mind is well liberated.<br><br>There, right there, the contacts are liberated,<br>He attains knowledge, fulfills the holy life,<br>Reaches the world's end, goes to the far shore.<br>That one is so called.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti109" },
{ text: `Whether walking or standing,<br>Sitting or lying down,<br>Evil thoughts arise<br>Connected to household life,<br><br>Practicing the wrong path,<br>Obscured by delusion,<br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Cannot attain supreme enlightenment.<br><br>One who, while walking, standing,<br>Sitting or lying down,<br>Concentrates the mind,<br>Delighting in peaceful thoughts,<br><br>Such a bhikkhu<br>Attains supreme enlightenment.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 110", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti110" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I am a brahmin, one who is approached for alms, with hands always pure, bearing my final body, the unsurpassed surgeon and physician. You are truly my children, born from my mouth, born from the Dhamma, created by the Dhamma, heirs of the Dhamma, not heirs of material things. Bhikkhus, there are two kinds of giving: giving of material goods and giving of the Dhamma. Of these two, the giving of the Dhamma is supreme. There are two kinds of sharing: sharing of material goods and sharing of the Dhamma. Of these two, sharing of the Dhamma is supreme. There are two kinds of help: help with material goods and help with the Dhamma. Of these two, help with the Dhamma is supreme. There are two kinds of sacrifice: material sacrifice and Dhamma sacrifice. Of these two, Dhamma sacrifice is supreme.<br><br>One who sacrifices the Dhamma,<br>The sacrifice without stinginess,<br>The Tathāgata, compassionate toward all beings,<br>Such a supreme one among devas and humans,<br>Beings pay homage to him,<br>One who has crossed the stream of existence,<br>Gone to the far shore.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti100" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, I teach the destruction of the taints for one who knows and sees, not for one who does not know and does not see. And, bhikkhus, for one who knows what and sees what is the destruction of the taints? Bhikkhus, for one who knows and sees 'This is suffering' is the destruction of the taints. For one who knows and sees 'This is the origin of suffering' is the destruction of the taints. For one who knows and sees 'This is the cessation of suffering' is the destruction of the taints. For one who knows and sees 'This is the path leading to the cessation of suffering' is the destruction of the taints. Thus, bhikkhus, for one who knows and sees is the destruction of the taints.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti102" },
{ text: `A learner training, practicing the straight path,<br>In the destruction of evil states is the first knowledge,<br>Next is final knowledge — that final knowledge is unsurpassed.<br><br>After that final knowledge, liberation itself,<br>Liberation knowledge unsurpassed<br>In the destruction of evil states, the wise.<br>Here the various fetters are destroyed.<br><br>Not the lazy, the fool who knows nothing,<br>Can attain this unsurpassed Nibbāna,<br>The complete liberation from all bonds.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti102" },
{ text: `Those who do not fully understand suffering,<br>And the arising of suffering,<br>Where suffering is completely destroyed without remainder,<br>And do not know the path leading to the calming of suffering,<br><br>They do not possess liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom,<br>They cannot make an end; they go to birth and old age.<br><br>Those who do fully understand suffering,<br>And the arising of suffering,<br>Where suffering is completely destroyed without remainder,<br>And know the path leading to the calming of suffering,<br><br>They possess liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom,<br>They can make an end; they do not go to birth and old age.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 103", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti103" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the world has been fully awakened to by the Tathāgata; the Tathāgata is detached from the world. Bhikkhus, the origin of the world has been fully awakened to by the Tathāgata; the origin of the world has been abandoned by the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, the cessation of the world has been fully awakened to by the Tathāgata; the cessation of the world has been realized by the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, the path leading to the cessation of the world has been fully awakened to by the Tathāgata; the path leading to the cessation of the world has been developed by the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, whatever in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the multitude of ascetics and brahmins, devas and humans, is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, and examined by the mind — all that the Tathāgata has fully awakened to. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, from the night when the Tathāgata fully awakens to unsurpassed perfect enlightenment until the night he attains final Nibbāna without remainder, whatever he speaks, utters, or declares — all that is just so and not otherwise. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, the Tathāgata does what he speaks and speaks what he does. Because he does what he speaks and speaks what he does, therefore he is called the Tathāgata. Bhikkhus, in this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, among the multitude of ascetics and brahmins, devas and humans, the Tathāgata is the conqueror, unconquered, all-seeing, all-knowing, supremely self-controlled. Therefore he is called the Tathāgata.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 112", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti112" },
{ text: `Having fully known the whole world,<br>The whole world as it really is,<br>Detached from the whole world,<br>Not like the whole world.<br><br>Having conquered all, the wise one,<br>Released from all bonds,<br>He experiences supreme peace,<br>Nibbāna, fearless.<br><br>This one, with taints destroyed,<br>Awakened, the sage,<br>Unshaken, untroubled,<br>All doubt cut off,<br>Reached the destruction of all kamma,<br>Liberated by the destruction of attachments.<br><br>He is the Blessed One, the Buddha,<br>The supreme lion,<br>In the world with its devas<br>He sets in motion the Brahma-wheel.<br><br>Thus devas and humans go for refuge to the Buddha;<br>Meeting together, they honor him,<br>The Great One free from existence.<br><br>Tamed, the foremost among the tamed,<br>Peaceful, the seer among the peaceful,<br>Liberated, the foremost among the liberated,<br>Crossed over, the foremost among the crossed over.<br><br>Thus they honor him,<br>The Great One free from existence.<br>In the deva-world and this world,<br>There is no one equal to him.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 112", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti112" },
{ text: `With malice, beings go to an evil destination.<br>A seer with clear knowledge, abandoning that malice,<br>Having abandoned, never returns to this world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti13" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, one thing, when it arises in the world, arises for the unhappiness of the many, for the disadvantage of the many, for the unhappiness and suffering of devas and humans. What one thing? Schism in the Saṅgha. When the Saṅgha is divided, there are mutual disputes, mutual reproaches, mutual hostilities, mutual abandonments. There, those who are not harmonious do not become harmonious, and those who are harmonious become otherwise.<br><br>Fallen into a state of misery,<br>Fallen into hell,<br>For an entire aeon,<br>One who causes schism in the Saṅgha.<br>Delighting in discord, established in non-Dhamma,<br>He falls away from security from bondage.<br>Whoever destroys the harmony of the united Saṅgha,<br>For an aeon is boiled in hell.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti18" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, abandon one thing. I guarantee you non-return. What one thing? Hatred, bhikkhus, abandon that one thing. I guarantee you non-return.<br><br>With hatred, beings go to an evil destination.<br>A seer with clear knowledge, having abandoned that hatred,<br>Having abandoned, never returns to this world.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti2" },
{ text: `Here, bhikkhus, with my mind I know the mind of a person with evil intent thus: 'If this person were to die at this moment, he would be placed in hell as surely as if carried there.' Why is that? Because his mind is evil. Bhikkhus, it is because of an evil mind that some beings, at the breaking up of the body, are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell.<br><br>Knowing the evil mind<br>Of a person here,<br>The Buddha, among bhikkhus,<br>Spoke this meaning.<br><br>If that person should die at this very moment,<br>He would be reborn in hell,<br>Because his mind is evil.<br><br>Just as one takes what one carries<br>And is placed accordingly,<br>So it is accordingly<br>Because of an evil mind,<br>Beings go to an evil destination.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti20" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these two things that torment. What two? Here, bhikkhus, someone has not done what is good, not done what is wholesome, not given protection to the fearful, has done evil, has been cruel, has done unwholesome deeds.<br><br>That person is tormented by the thought: 'I have done evil.' He is also tormented by the thought: 'I am doing evil.' He is also tormented by the thought: 'I will do evil.' These two things torment him.<br><br>Having done evil bodily action,<br>Evil verbal action,<br>Evil mental action,<br>Or whatever else is blameworthy,<br><br>Not doing wholesome deeds,<br>Doing many unwholesome deeds,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of evil wisdom is reborn in hell.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti30" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, possessing two things, a person is placed in hell as surely as if carried there. What two? Immoral conduct and wrong view. Possessing these two things, a person is placed in hell.<br><br>One who is endowed with these two things,<br>Immoral conduct and wrong view,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of evil wisdom<br>Is reborn in hell.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti32" },
{ text: `Possessing two things, bhikkhus, a person is placed in heaven as surely as if carried there. What two? Good virtue and right view. Possessing these two things, a person is placed in heaven.<br><br>One who is endowed with these two things,<br>Good virtue and right view,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of right wisdom<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti33" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, the holy life is lived not for the purpose of deceiving people, not for the purpose of flattering people, not for the sake of gain, honor, and renown, not with the thought: 'Let people know me thus.' Rather, bhikkhus, the holy life is lived for the purpose of direct knowledge and full understanding.<br><br>For the purpose of direct knowledge,<br>For the purpose of full understanding,<br>Regard for what others say aside,<br>The Blessed One taught the holy life<br>That leads to Nibbāna.<br><br>This path is followed<br>By the great persons, the great seers.<br>Those who practice it<br>As taught by the Buddha,<br>Following the Teacher's advice,<br>Will make an end of suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti36" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, there are these three kinds of seeking. What three? Seeking for sensual pleasures, seeking for existence, and seeking for the holy life. These are the three kinds of seeking.<br><br>Concentrated, clearly comprehending,<br>Mindful, a disciple of the Buddha<br>Understands the seekings,<br>And the origin of seekings,<br><br>Where they cease, and the path<br>Leading to their cessation.<br>With the destruction of the seekings,<br>A bhikkhu, without longing, is fully quenched.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti54" },
{ text: `And, bhikkhus, because I myself know, myself see, myself find, I declare: 'Bhikkhus, I have seen beings who, accomplished in good bodily conduct, good verbal conduct, good mental conduct, not criticizing the noble ones, holding right view, acting under the influence of right view, at the breaking up of the body, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world.'<br><br>Directing the mind in right ways,<br>Speaking right speech,<br>Doing right deeds with the body,<br>A person here in the world,<br><br>Of much learning, doing merit,<br>Living a short life here,<br>At the breaking up of the body,<br>One of wisdom, acting thus,<br>Is reborn in heaven.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti71" },
{ text: `Bhikkhus, those who are bound by the bond of sensual desire and bound by the bond of existence are those who return, who come back to this state.<br><br>Those who have cut off the bond of sensual desire, bhikkhus, but are still bound by the bond of existence, are non-returners, not coming back to this state.<br><br>Those who have cut off the bond of sensual desire and cut off the bond of existence are Arahants, with taints destroyed.<br><br>Those who are overcome by the bond of sensual desire,<br>By the bond of existence, by both bonds,<br>Those beings go to the round of rebirth,<br>They go to birth and death.<br><br>Those who have abandoned sensual desire<br>But have not yet reached the destruction of taints,<br>Still overcome by the bond of existence,<br>Are called non-returners.<br><br>Those who have cut off all doubt,<br>Destroyed conceit and renewed existence,<br>Certainly have gone to the far shore in this world,<br>For they have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti96" },
{ text: `Walking and standing with self-control,<br>Sitting and lying down with self-control,<br>A bhikkhu, self-controlled when bending and stretching his limbs.<br><br>Above, across, and all around,<br>As far as the end of the world,<br>Regarding whatever kind of existence<br>In this world,<br>He well observes the arising and passing<br>Of all aggregates.<br><br>Thus dwelling ardently, with mind peaceful,<br>Rightly, with mind peaceful, unshaken,<br>Constantly training,<br>Continuously, diligently,<br>That bhikkhu is so called.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 111", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti111" },
            
               { text: `One who subdues the arising anger<br>Like using an antidote to stop snake venom from spreading,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who has cut off craving for sensual pleasures without remainder,<br>Like one plucking a lotus born from a pond,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },
{ text: `One who has cut off craving, leaving nothing,<br>Making the fast-flowing stream dry up,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who has destroyed conceit, leaving nothing,<br>Like a great flood destroying a weak clump of reeds,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },
{ text: `One who does not find a core among various existences,<br>Like one seeking flowers on a fig tree that has none,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One in whom there is no anger internally,<br>Who has transcended both existence and non-existence,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One whose thoughts have been dispersed,<br>Internally well prepared, leaving no residue,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },
{ text: `One who does not overreach nor lag behind,<br>Who has fully conquered all this proliferation,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who does not overreach nor lag behind,<br>Knowing that this is all unreal,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who does not overreach nor lag behind,<br>Free from greed for what is unreal,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },
{ text: `One who does not overreach nor lag behind,<br>Free from hatred for what is unreal,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who does not overreach nor lag behind,<br>Free from delusion for what is unreal,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One in whom there are no underlying tendencies,<br>The roots of unwholesome states uprooted and removed,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },
{ text: `One in whom there is nothing that arises from affliction<br>That could cause a return to this shore,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One in whom there is nothing that arises from the forest of craving<br>That creates the cause for binding humans to renewed existence,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.<br><br>One who has abandoned the five hindrances,<br>Sorrowless, free from anxiety,<br>Beyond doubt, freed from the dart,<br>That bhikkhu abandons both the near and far shores,<br>Like a snake shedding its old worn-out skin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1" },

{ text: `Dhāniya:<br>My rice is cooked, my milking is done,<br>I dwell on the bank of the Mahī river,<br>My hut is well thatched, my fire is kindled.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>I have abandoned anger, I have no perturbation,<br>I dwell for one night on the bank of the Mahī river,<br>My hut is open, my fire is extinguished.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `Dhāniya:<br>No gadflies or mosquitoes are found here,<br>The cattle roam on the grassy meadow,<br>They can endure the rain when it comes.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>A raft is well made, firmly bound together,<br>Having crossed to the far shore, having overcome the flood,<br>There is no further need for a raft.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>My mind is well tamed, liberated, expanded,<br>For a long time it has been trained, well subdued,<br>No evil states are found in me.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>I am not hired by anyone in the world,<br>With what I have realized I wander the world,<br>No wages are needed for me.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `Dhāniya:<br>Here are cows, here are calves,<br>Here are cows with calf, breeding stock,<br>Here is the bull, the leader of the herd.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Here are no cows, here are no calves,<br>Here are no cows with calf, breeding stock,<br>Here is no bull, the leader of the herd.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>Like a bull breaking its bonds,<br>Like an elephant tearing rotten creepers,<br>I will not enter a womb again.<br>So if you wish, O deva of rain, let it rain!`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `Māra:<br>He who has sons rejoices in sons,<br>He who has cattle rejoices in cattle,<br>For attachments are a person's joy,<br>One without attachments cannot rejoice.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>He who has sons grieves over sons,<br>He who has cattle grieves over cattle,<br>For attachments are a person's sorrow,<br>One without attachments cannot grieve.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.2" },
{ text: `Laying aside the rod against all beings,<br>Not harming any of them,<br>One should not long for a son, let alone a friend.<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>From companionship intimacy arises,<br>From intimacy suffering arises.<br>Seeing the danger arising from intimacy,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Considering the welfare of friends and companions,<br>One who is attached neglects the goal.<br>Seeing this fear in friendship,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Like a spreading bamboo entangled,<br>One is bound by concern for children and spouse.<br>Like a bamboo shoot not clinging,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Like a deer in the forest, unfettered,<br>It goes wherever it wants to graze.<br>Seeing the freedom of the wise,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Among companions, when one is called upon,<br>At one's dwelling, while standing or walking,<br>Seeing the freedom that is not bound,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Like a peacock's tail, like a crested bird,<br>One who follows another's opinion<br>Will not attain the freedom that is still.<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>For friends and companions there is play and enjoyment,<br>For children there is great affection.<br>Being disgusted with attachment to the dear,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Without enmity toward all the four directions,<br>Content with this and that,<br>Enduring dangers without trembling,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Even some renunciants are hard to please,<br>And also householders living at home.<br>Being unconcerned with others' children,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having cast off the signs of a householder,<br>Like a koviḷāra tree that has shed its leaves,<br>Cutting all household ties, a hero,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>If one finds a prudent companion,<br>A wise fellow traveler leading a good life,<br>Overcoming all dangers, one should live with him,<br>Joyful and mindful.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `If one does not find a prudent companion,<br>A wise fellow traveler leading a good life,<br>Like a king who abandons a conquered realm,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Surely we praise the good friendship,<br>One should associate with those who are equal or better.<br>If they are not to be found, living faultlessly,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Seeing the danger in the strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Which are beautiful, sweet, and delightful,<br>Both in their form and in their formless aspect,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>These are a boil, a calamity,<br>A disease, a dart, and fear for me.<br>Seeing this danger in the strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Enduring cold and heat,<br>Hunger and thirst,<br>Wind and sun, flies and snakes,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Like a great elephant with massive shoulders,<br>Leaving the herd, living in the forest as it pleases,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `One who delights in company cannot attain<br>Even the temporary release of the mind.<br>Heeding the words of the Kinsman of the Sun,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Having transcended the maze of views,<br>Obtained the path, reached the fixed course,<br>Knowing 'My knowledge has arisen, not dependent on another,'<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Without greed, without deceit,<br>Without thirst, without malice,<br>With delusion and all stains removed,<br>Having no desire for the entire world,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Shun an evil friend who does not see the goal,<br>Who has abandoned the path, living crookedly.<br>One should not associate with a heedless, infatuated person.<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Associate with a learned friend who upholds the Dhamma,<br>A great-hearted, intelligent, and eloquent companion.<br>Knowing the meaning, dispelling doubts,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Not delighting in the pleasures of the world — song, dance, and sensual pleasures —<br>Wandering without adornment, without longing,<br>Uttering the truth, rejecting all ornament,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having given up children and spouse,<br>Father and mother, money and grain,<br>Relatives and the bonds of sensual desire,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Knowing that this is bondage, that the happiness is slight,<br>That the gratification is little, and the suffering far greater,<br>This is a hook; knowing this, the wise person,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having burst your bonds, cut them like a fish<br>Breaking a net in water, like a fire not returning to a burnt place,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>With eyes cast down, not footloose,<br>With guarded faculties, protected mind,<br>Not overflowing, not burning,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having cast off the signs of a householder,<br>Like a koviḷāra tree that has shed its leaves,<br>Wearing the yellow robe, going forth,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Not greedy for tastes, not attached, not feeding others,<br>Going from house to house for alms, mind not bound to families,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having abandoned the five hindrances, the defilements of the mind,<br>Having removed all stains, independent,<br>Cutting off attachment and hatred,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Having turned away from pleasure and pain,<br>And from joy and grief earlier felt,<br>Having attained equanimity, peace, and purity,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `With energy roused for the supreme attainment,<br>With mind not lazy, with effort firm,<br>With strength arisen, constant in exertion,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Not neglecting seclusion, loving meditation,<br>Constantly abiding in Dhamma, practicing in accordance with Dhamma,<br>Recognizing the danger in existences,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Intent on the destruction of craving, heedful,<br>Learned, mindful, not stupid,<br>Knowing the Dhamma, fixed in the Dhamma, striving rightly,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>Unstartled like a lion at sounds,<br>Unsnared like the wind in a net,<br>Unstained like a lotus by water,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Like a lion, strong-jawed, lord of beasts, living victorious,<br>Resort to remote and secluded lodgings,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>At the right time cultivate loving-kindness, equanimity, compassion, and release,<br>Approaching no one in the world with enmity or procrastination,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Having abandoned greed, hatred, and delusion,<br>Having broken the fetters, not trembling at the end of life,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.<br><br>They associate and live together for a motive,<br>Motiveless friends are rare nowadays.<br>The wise, knowing their own good, are unsullied,<br>Live alone like a rhinoceros.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3" },
{ text: `Bhāradvāja:<br>You call yourself a ploughman; I do not see your ploughing.<br>Being asked about ploughing, tell me of it,<br>So that we may know your ploughing.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Faith is the seed, austerity the rain,<br>Wisdom is my yoke and plough,<br>Moral shame is the pole, mind the yoke-tie,<br>Mindfulness my ploughshare and goad.<br><br>Body guarded, speech guarded,<br>Moderate in food, restrained in belly,<br>I make truth the weeding,<br>Meekness my release.<br><br>Energy is my beast of burden,<br>Yoking me to the security from bondage.<br>It goes onward without returning,<br>Where, having gone, one does not grieve.<br><br>In this way the ploughing is done,<br>Its yield is the Deathless.<br>Having done this ploughing,<br>One is released from all suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.4" },
{ text: `Cunda the smith:<br>I ask the Sage of great wisdom, the Buddha, the lord of the Dhamma,<br>The one free from craving, the best of bipeds, the foremost of charioteers:<br>How many ascetics are there in the world? Please tell me.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Four ascetics, no fifth; and if asked, Cunda, explain them:<br>The conqueror of the path, the teacher of the path,<br>One living on the path, and one who defiles the path.<br><br>Cunda:<br>What do the Buddhas call the conqueror of the path?<br>How is the teacher of the path unsurpassed?<br>Tell me about the one living on the path,<br>And then explain the one who defiles the path.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>One who has overcome doubt, freed from the dart,<br>Delighting in Nibbāna, without greed for anything,<br>Leader of the world with its devas and humans —<br>The Buddhas call such a one the conqueror of the path.<br><br>Knowing the supreme as supreme, the teacher here<br>Analyses and proclaims the Dhamma.<br>The seer without desire, who has cut off doubt —<br>That second ascetic is called the teacher of the path.<br><br>One who lives on the path of the Dhamma well proclaimed,<br>Self-controlled, mindful, treading the faultless path —<br>That third ascetic is called one living on the path.<br><br>One who, wearing the guise of a virtuous one, is boorish,<br>Intruding on families, insolent, deceitful,<br>Unrestrained, a gossip, dissembling —<br>He is the one who defiles the path.<br><br>A clansman who understands these, a learned person,<br>Having seen them, does not think: 'They are all the same.'<br>For when he sees that he has not attained the Deathless,<br>Why should he put trust in them?`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.5" },
{ text: `About the downfall of a person, I ask you, Gotama.<br>Having come to ask the Blessed One, tell me the cause of downfall.<br><br>It is easy to know a prosperous person, easy to know one who is down.<br>One who loves the Dhamma prospers; one who hates the Dhamma declines.<br><br>One who loves the bad and not the good,<br>Who approves of the bad — that is the cause of downfall.<br><br>One who is fond of sleep, fond of company, lazy, of little energy,<br>Given to anger — that is the cause of downfall.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.6" },
{ text: `Who, though well-to-do, does not support his aged mother or father —<br>That is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who deceives with a lie an ascetic or brahmin or any other mendicant —<br>That is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who has much wealth, gold and food, yet alone enjoys fine flavors —<br>That is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who prides himself on his birth, on wealth, on family,<br>And despises his own relatives — that is the cause of downfall.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.6" },
{ text: `Who is infatuated with women, with drink, with gambling,<br>And squanders all he has — that is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who is not content with his own wife, and is seen with prostitutes or others' wives —<br>That is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who, having passed youth, takes a young, still-breasted wife<br>And cannot sleep from jealousy — that is the cause of downfall.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.6" },
{ text: `Who places in authority a woman given to drink and extravagance,<br>Or a man of like behavior — that is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Who, born in a noble family, of high rank, with little wealth,<br>Yet longs for kingship — that is the cause of downfall.<br><br>Having understood these causes of downfall in the world,<br>The noble one, endowed with insight, goes to a happy realm.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.6" },
{ text: `May all beings be happy and secure;<br>May all beings be happy-minded.<br><br>Whatever living beings there are — frail or strong, without exception,<br>Long, large, medium, short, subtle or gross, seen or unseen,<br>Those living far or near, those already born or seeking birth —<br>May all beings be happy-minded.<br><br>Let no one deceive another nor despise anyone anywhere;<br>Through anger or hatred let no one wish suffering on another.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.8" },
{ text: `Just as a mother would protect her only child with her own life,<br>Even so, let one cultivate a boundless mind toward all beings.<br><br>Let one cultivate loving-kindness toward the entire world,<br>Above, below, and across, without obstruction, without enmity.<br><br>Whether standing, walking, sitting, or lying down, as long as one is awake,<br>One should establish this mindfulness — this is called the divine abiding here.<br><br>Not falling into wrong view, virtuous, endowed with right view,<br>Having overcome greed for sensual pleasures, one will never again come to a womb.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.8" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>Has that Blessed One, the Sage, indeed well resolved,<br>Doing what is good, of such a mind as this?<br>Has he well tamed his thoughts in all respects,<br>Both toward the agreeable and the disagreeable?<br><br>Sātāgira:<br>Indeed, Hemāvata, the Blessed One has well resolved,<br>Doing what is good, of such a mind as this.<br>He has well tamed his thoughts in all respects,<br>Both toward the agreeable and the disagreeable.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>Does he not take what is not given?<br>Is he well restrained toward beings?<br>Is he far from heedlessness?<br>Does he not neglect jhāna?<br><br>Sātāgira:<br>He does not take what is not given,<br>He is well restrained toward beings,<br>He is indeed far from heedlessness,<br>The Buddha does not neglect jhāna.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>Is he free from desire for sensual pleasures?<br>Is his mind not agitated?<br>Has he transcended delusion?<br>Does he have vision regarding all phenomena?<br><br>Sātāgira:<br>He is free from desire for sensual pleasures,<br>His mind is not agitated,<br>He has transcended all delusion,<br>The Buddha has vision regarding all phenomena.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>Is he endowed with clear knowledge?<br>Is his conduct pure?<br>Have his taints been destroyed?<br>Is there no renewed existence for him?<br><br>Sātāgira:<br>He is indeed endowed with clear knowledge,<br>His conduct is pure,<br>All his taints are destroyed,<br>There is indeed no renewed existence for him.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Sātāgira:<br>The sage's mind is fully accomplished,<br>His deeds are perfectly done.<br>Let us approach the Venerable Gotama,<br>Fully possessed of wisdom and good conduct.<br><br>Hemāvata:<br>His calves are like an antelope's, lean and steady,<br>With little food, not greedy, absorbed in jhāna.<br>Let us go and see the seer Gotama<br>Who practices jhāna in the remote forest.<br><br>Alone, like a lion, like an elephant, not grasping at pleasures,<br>Let us approach and ask him about release from the snare of death.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>By the arising of what does the world arise?<br>By the associating with what is the world established?<br>By clinging to what is the world troubled?<br>By the arising of what is the world tormented?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>By the arising of six the world arises,<br>By associating with six it is established,<br>By clinging to six the world is troubled,<br>By the arising of six the world is tormented.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>What is that clinging for which the world is troubled?<br>Being asked, tell us of the escape from suffering,<br>How suffering can be completely destroyed.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>The five strands of sensual pleasure with mind as the sixth;<br>Having removed desire for them, one is freed from suffering.<br><br>This, I say, is the escape from suffering.<br>Thus, I declare it to you: this is the way to release from suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>Who here crosses the flood?<br>Who crosses the ocean?<br>Without standing, without grasping,<br>Who does not sink into the deep?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>One always endowed with virtue, wise, well-concentrated,<br>Mindful, with mind turned inward — he crosses the flood so hard to cross.<br><br>One who has abandoned perception of sensual pleasures,<br>Who has overcome all fetters,<br>Who has destroyed delight in existence — he does not sink into the deep.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `Hemāvata:<br>One of deep wisdom, seeing the subtle goal,<br>Without possessions, not attached to the realm of desire,<br>Let us worship that All-Knowing One, the great sage<br>Walking on the noble path.<br><br>Today we have indeed seen a great auspicious sign,<br>The dawn's bright radiance,<br>For we have seen the Perfectly Enlightened One<br>Who has crossed the flood, without taints.<br><br>These thousand yakkhas here, possessed of psychic power and fame,<br>All of them go to your refuge.<br>You are our Teacher, unsurpassed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9" },
{ text: `What is the best of wealth for a person here?<br>What, when well practiced, brings happiness?<br>What is the sweetest of tastes?<br>Whose life is called the best?<br><br>Faith is the best of wealth for a person here.<br>The Dhamma, well practiced, brings happiness.<br>Truth is the sweetest of tastes.<br>One who lives by wisdom is said to live the best life.<br><br>How does one cross the flood?<br>How does one cross the ocean?<br>How does one overcome suffering?<br>How is one purified?<br><br>By faith one crosses the flood,<br>By heedfulness one crosses the ocean,<br>By energy one overcomes suffering,<br>By wisdom one is purified.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.10" },
{ text: `How does one obtain wisdom?<br>How does one obtain wealth?<br>How does one obtain fame?<br>How does one bind friends?<br>How, passing from this world to the next,<br>Does one not grieve?<br><br>Having faith in the Arahant's Dhamma for attaining Nibbāna,<br>One who is heedful, through learning, obtains wisdom.<br><br>One who does what is proper, who strives, obtains wealth.<br>By truth one obtains fame; by giving one binds friends.<br><br>The faithful householder who possesses these four things —<br>Truth, Dhamma, steadfastness, and giving —<br>Does not grieve when passing away.<br><br>Ask also other ascetics and brahmins,<br>Whether there is anything better than truth,<br>Self-control, giving, and patience.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.10" },
{ text: `A framework of sinews and bone, plastered with flesh and skin,<br>The body is covered by a skin — it is not seen as it really is.<br><br>Filled with a full belly: the liver, bladder, heart, lungs,<br>Kidneys and spleen, mucus, saliva, sweat, fat, blood, synovial fluid,<br>Bile, and serum.<br><br>From these nine streams, defilement constantly flows:<br>From the eyes, eye discharge; from the ears, ear discharge;<br>From the nose, nasal mucus; from the mouth, sometimes vomit,<br>Bile and phlegm; from the body, sweat and dirt.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.11" },
{ text: `The head is a hollow cavity filled with brain.<br>A fool led by ignorance thinks it beautiful.<br><br>When dead, lying down, swollen and discolored,<br>Discarded in a charnel ground, relatives no longer care.<br><br>Dogs, jackals, wolves, worms, crows, vultures,<br>And other creatures eat it.<br><br>Having heard the Buddha's words, a wise bhikkhu<br>Understands the body, seeing it as it really is.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.11" },
{ text: `Just as this is, so is that; just as that is, so is this.<br>Regarding the body both internally and externally,<br>One should abandon all desire for the body.<br><br>Having abandoned desire and greed, a wise bhikkhu<br>Attains the Deathless, peace, the Nibbāna element uncreated.<br><br>This two-footed body is impure, foul-smelling,<br>Filled with various carcasses, oozing here and there.<br><br>Who, with such a body, would think to exalt himself<br>Or despise another — save one who is blind.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.11" },
{ text: `From intimacy arises fear, from dwellings arise dust,<br>Without dwelling, without intimacy — such is the seer's vision.<br><br>One who has cut off existence, not producing further existence,<br>Destroyed birth, not desiring it again —<br>That one is called a sage, wandering solitary and silent.<br>The great seer has seen that peaceful state.<br><br>Having measured the earth, having known the seed,<br>Not longing for the perpetuation of craving,<br>That sage is truly a sage, seeing the end of birth,<br>Having transcended all reasoning, beyond classification.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Having known all abodes, not longing for any,<br>That sage is truly a sage, without greed, without clinging,<br>No longer striving, having reached the far shore.<br><br>All-conquering, all-knowing, of perfect wisdom,<br>Undefiled regarding all things, abandoning all,<br>With craving destroyed, liberated —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>Endowed with the power of wisdom, virtuous, observant,<br>Calm, delighting in jhāna, mindful,<br>Freed from all bonds, without taints —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Wandering alone, a sage, heedful,<br>Unmoved by praise or blame,<br>Like a lion unstartled by sounds,<br>Like the wind not caught in a net,<br>Like a lotus unstained by water —<br>A leader of others, not led by others —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>One who acts like a bath-pillar when others speak extremely,<br>Without craving, with well-controlled faculties —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>One who stands firm like a shuttle straight,<br>Disgusted with evil deeds, examining right and wrong —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `One who controls himself, doing no evil,<br>Youthful and middle-aged, a self-controlled sage,<br>One who cannot be angered and angers none —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>Receiving alms from the top, the middle, or the leftover,<br>Without praising or belittling —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>One who has abandoned sexual intercourse,<br>Living celibate, not bound even in youth,<br>Who has abandoned conceit and heedlessness, fully liberated —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>Knowing the world, seeing the supreme goal,<br>Crossing the ocean, having crossed it thus,<br>One who has cut the bonds, without dependencies, without taints —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Two different abodes: the householder with wife and children,<br>Not self-restrained, harming other beings,<br>And the sage always protecting beings.<br><br>As a crested peacock never matches the swiftness of a swan,<br>So a householder never matches a bhikkhu,<br>A sage meditating in the forest, secluded.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Killing and harming, striking, binding, stealing, lying, cheating, deceit,<br>Pretending to be learned, committing adultery — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.<br><br>Those who, unrestrained in sensual pleasures, greedy for tastes,<br>Mixed with impurity, holding nihilistic views, crooked, hard to guide — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `The rough, the cruel, the backbiter, the traitor, merciless, overbearing, ungiving — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.<br><br>Anger, conceit, stubbornness, opposition, deceit, envy, boastfulness, arrogance, and intimacy with the evil — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `Not by fish or flesh, not by fasting, nakedness, shaven head, matted hair, ashes, rough deerskin,<br>Not by tending the sacrificial fire, nor by many worldly austerities,<br>Nor by incantations, nor by seasonal sacrifices, does one become pure, if doubt is not overcome.<br><br>But by living with sense faculties guarded, restrained, established in Dhamma,<br>Loving uprightness and gentleness, beyond attachment, abandoning all suffering,<br>The wise one is not stained by things seen or heard.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `One who claims 'I am your friend' but does not do what can be done,<br>Knowing him as such, he is not my friend.<br><br>One who, for the sake of a friend, does what should be done with gentle speech,<br>But only in words — the wise know him as one who speaks but does not act.<br><br>One who is always looking for faults, suspecting deficiencies,<br>That one is not a friend. He in whom one can trust as a child on the breast,<br>That one is a friend whom no one can separate.<br><br>One who, desiring the fruit of benefit, cultivates conditions that bring joy,<br>That person bears the responsibility of a human being.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.3" },
{ text: `Not associating with fools, associating with the wise,<br>Honoring those worthy of honor — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Dwelling in a suitable place, having made merit in the past,<br>Directing oneself rightly — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Having much learning, skilled in craft, well-trained in discipline,<br>Speaking well-spoken words — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Supporting one's mother and father, cherishing one's wife and children,<br>Having an unconfused livelihood — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `Giving, living righteously, supporting one's relatives,<br>Doing blameless deeds — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Ceasing and abstaining from evil, abstaining from intoxicants,<br>Being heedful in the Dhamma — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Respectful and humble, content and grateful,<br>Hearing the Dhamma at the proper time — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Patient and of gentle speech, visiting ascetics,<br>Discussing the Dhamma at the proper time — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `Austerity and the holy life, seeing the noble truths,<br>The realization of Nibbāna — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>When touched by worldly things, one's mind does not tremble,<br>Sorrowless, stainless, secure — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Having performed these things, they are everywhere undefeated,<br>Everywhere they go in safety — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>From these causes, desire and ill-will arise;<br>From them arise liking and disliking, and fear.<br>From them arise the thoughts of the mind.<br>Like children releasing a crow, they go.<br><br>The identification with a self arises from affection,<br>Like a banyan tree from its trunk.<br>The manifold bonds of sensual pleasures are spread,<br>Like a maluva creeper in the forest.<br><br>Those who know whence it arises<br>Remove its root. They cross this flood,<br>So hard to cross, not crossed before,<br>And do not come to renewed existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.5" },
{ text: `Dhamma-conduct and the holy life are called the best conduct.<br>If one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>Yet if he is harsh of speech, fond of harming like a beast,<br>His life is evil, he increases the dust of defilements.<br><br>A bhikkhu who loves disputes, covered by ignorance,<br>Does not understand the Dhamma and Discipline taught by the Buddha.<br><br>Led by ignorance, he harms those trained in self-development,<br>Not knowing the defiled path that leads to hell.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.6" },
{ text: `Such a bhikkhu, fallen into a bad destination,<br>From this birth to that, from darkness to darkness,<br>After death comes to suffering.<br><br>Like a cesspit filled after many years,<br>So a defiled person is hard to cleanse.<br><br>Knowing such a one, O bhikkhus, attached to families,<br>With evil desires, evil thoughts, evil deportment, evil conduct and resort,<br>All of you, being of one mind, shun him.<br><br>Blow him away like dust, discard him like rubbish.<br>Drive out the chatterer, the fake ascetic.<br>Having expelled evil desires, evil deportment, evil conduct and resort,<br><br>Live pure, with the pure, mindful, mindful of the goal.<br>Then united and wise, make an end of suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.6" },
{ text: `The seers of old were self-controlled and austere,<br>Abandoning the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>They practiced for their own welfare.<br><br>Brahmin sages had no cattle, no gold, no grain.<br>Learning was their wealth; they guarded that treasure.<br><br>Whatever was prepared for them, they did not refuse.<br>They were protected by Dhamma, not defeated anywhere.<br><br>From youth to forty-eight years, those brahmins of old<br>Lived the holy life, seeking knowledge and good conduct.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.7" },
{ text: `They praised virtue, study, gentleness, austerity, and peace,<br>Non-harming, patience, and the holy life.<br>The best among them, the striving Brahmā, did not engage<br>In sexual intercourse even in a dream.<br><br>The wise in the world, practicing his conduct,<br>Praised virtue and patience, and the holy life.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.7" },
{ text: `From whom a person learns the Dhamma,<br>Let him pay homage to that person as the devas pay homage to Inda.<br>That one, being honored, with joyful mind,<br>Having learned much, proclaims the true Dhamma.<br><br>An attentive, wise person, reflecting, <br>Practicing Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma,<br>Becomes learned, intelligent, and careful.<br>By serving such a one, he becomes not heedless.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `Like one who, entering a flooded, turbulent river,<br>Is swept away by the current — how can he help others across?<br>So too, one who has not mastered the Dhamma,<br>Not understanding the meaning of the learned's words,<br>Himself not having overcome doubt — how can he help others meditate?`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `But one who has boarded a strong boat, well-fitted with oars and rudder,<br>Skilled and mindful, knowing the means, can ferry many across.<br>So too, one who is developed, learned, unshaken,<br>Can help others who are meditating, who are eager to hear the Dhamma.<br><br>Therefore, associate with a good person, a wise one, learned and intelligent.<br>Knowing the goal, practicing wisely, knowing the Dhamma, one attains happiness.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `What is virtue? What is good conduct? What should be developed?<br>What bodily, verbal, and mental deeds should be done<br>For one to rightly enter and attain the supreme goal?<br><br>Honoring elders, not envious, knowing the time for seeing the teacher,<br>Knowing the right moment for the Dhamma talk, carefully listening to the well-spoken words.<br><br>Going at the proper time to the teacher's presence, abandoning stubbornness, with humility,<br>Remembering and practicing the goal, the Dhamma, self-control, and the holy life.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.9" },
{ text: `Delighting in the Dhamma, joyful in the Dhamma,<br>Established in the Dhamma, knowing how to investigate the Dhamma,<br>Not engaging in talk that defiles the Dhamma,<br>Led by the well-spoken, truthful words of the teacher.<br><br>One who, delighting in the Dhamma taught by the noble ones,<br>Is unsurpassed in speech, mind, and action,<br>At peace, gentle, established in jhāna,<br>Attains the core of wisdom from the heard Dhamma.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.9" },
{ text: `Giving up laughter, chatter, lamentation, anger,<br>Deceit, fraud, greed, pride, aggression, harshness,<br>Adultery, arrogance, and intoxication,<br>One should live, having abandoned all, free from addiction, resolute.<br><br>Wisdom is the core of well-spoken words;<br>It is heard, and that core is concentration.<br>In a heedless, hurried person, wisdom does not grow.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.9" },
{ text: `Arise, sit up! What is the use of sleeping for one afflicted?<br>What sleep is there for one pierced by the dart of sorrow?<br><br>Arise, sit up! Train firmly for peace.<br>Do not let the King of Death, seeing you heedless,<br>Bewilder and conquer you.<br><br>Overcome this craving to which devas and humans cling,<br>Do not let the moment pass. Those who let the moment pass<br>Grieve when reborn in hell.<br><br>Heedlessness is dust; dust comes from heedlessness.<br>With clarity and heedfulness, draw out the dart.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.10" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>Abandoning the five strands of sensual desire, pleasant and agreeable,<br>With faith, go forth, make an end of suffering.<br><br>Associate with good friends, dwell in a remote lodging,<br>Secluded, quiet. Moderate in food,<br>Robes, almsfood, lodgings, and medicines —<br>Do not have craving for these things; do not return to the world.<br><br>Restrained in the Pātimokkha, guarded in the five senses,<br>Practice mindfulness of the body, live full of disenchantment.<br><br>Avoid the sign of the beautiful connected with passion;<br>Develop a mind unattached to the foul, concentrated, one-pointed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.11" },
{ text: `Develop the signless, discard the underlying tendency to conceit.<br>By breaking through conceit, you will live at peace.<br><br>Thus, having taught these conditions leading to the other shore,<br>You who have realized the Dhamma should live as one who has done what must be done.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.11" },
{ text: `From intimacy arises fear, from dwellings arise dust,<br>Without dwelling, without intimacy — such is the seer's vision.<br><br>One who has cut off existence, not producing further existence,<br>Destroyed birth, not desiring it again —<br>That one is called a sage, wandering solitary and silent.<br>The great seer has seen that peaceful state.<br><br>Having measured the earth, having known the seed,<br>Not longing for the perpetuation of craving,<br>That sage is truly a sage, seeing the end of birth,<br>Having transcended all reasoning, beyond classification.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Having known all abodes, not longing for any,<br>That sage is truly a sage, without greed, without clinging,<br>No longer striving, having reached the far shore.<br><br>All-conquering, all-knowing, of perfect wisdom,<br>Undefiled regarding all things, abandoning all,<br>With craving destroyed, liberated —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>Endowed with the power of wisdom, virtuous, observant,<br>Calm, delighting in jhāna, mindful,<br>Freed from all bonds, without taints —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Wandering alone, a sage, heedful,<br>Unmoved by praise or blame,<br>Like a lion unstartled by sounds,<br>Like the wind not caught in a net,<br>Like a lotus unstained by water —<br>A leader of others, not led by others —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>One who acts like a bath-pillar when others speak extremely,<br>Without craving, with well-controlled faculties —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },

{ text: `One who stands firm like a shuttle straight,<br>Disgusted with evil deeds, discerning right and wrong —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `One who controls himself, doing no evil,<br>Youthful and middle-aged, a self-controlled sage,<br>One who cannot be angered and angers none —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `One who lives on alms, receiving food,<br>From the top, the middle, or the leftover,<br>Without praising or belittling —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `One who has abandoned sexual intercourse,<br>Living celibate, not bound even in youth,<br>Who has abandoned conceit and heedlessness, fully liberated —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.<br><br>Knowing the world, seeing the supreme goal,<br>Crossing the ocean, having crossed it thus,<br>One who has cut the bonds, without dependencies, without taints —<br>The wise know that one as a sage.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Two different abodes: the householder with wife and children,<br>Not self-restrained, harming other beings,<br>And the sage always protecting beings.<br><br>As a crested peacock never matches the swiftness of a swan,<br>So a householder never matches a bhikkhu,<br>A sage meditating in the forest, secluded.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.12" },
{ text: `Killing and harming, striking, binding, stealing, lying, cheating, deceit,<br>Pretending to be learned, committing adultery — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.<br><br>Those who, unrestrained in sensual pleasures, greedy for tastes,<br>Mixed with impurity, holding nihilistic views, crooked, hard to guide — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `The rough, the cruel, the backbiter, the traitor, merciless, overbearing, ungiving — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.<br><br>Anger, conceit, stubbornness, opposition, deceit, envy, boastfulness, arrogance, and intimacy with the evil — this is rottenness, not mere meat-eating.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `Not by fish or flesh, not by fasting, nakedness, shaven head, matted hair, ashes, rough deerskin,<br>Not by tending the sacrificial fire, nor by many worldly austerities,<br>Nor by incantations, nor by seasonal sacrifices, does one become pure, if doubt is not overcome.<br><br>But by living with sense faculties guarded, restrained, established in Dhamma,<br>Loving uprightness and gentleness, beyond attachment, abandoning all suffering,<br>The wise one is not stained by things seen or heard.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.2" },
{ text: `One who claims 'I am your friend' but does not do what can be done,<br>Knowing him as such, he is not my friend.<br><br>One who, for the sake of a friend, does what should be done with gentle speech,<br>But only in words — the wise know him as one who speaks but does not act.<br><br>One who is always looking for faults, suspecting deficiencies,<br>That one is not a friend. He in whom one can trust as a child on the breast,<br>That one is a friend whom no one can separate.<br><br>One who, desiring the fruit of benefit, cultivates conditions that bring joy,<br>That person bears the responsibility of a human being.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.3" },
{ text: `Not associating with fools, associating with the wise,<br>Honoring those worthy of honor — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Dwelling in a suitable place, having made merit in the past,<br>Directing oneself rightly — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Having much learning, skilled in craft, well-trained in discipline,<br>Speaking well-spoken words — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Supporting one's mother and father, cherishing one's wife and children,<br>Having an unconfused livelihood — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `Giving, living righteously, supporting one's relatives,<br>Doing blameless deeds — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Ceasing and abstaining from evil, abstaining from intoxicants,<br>Being heedful in the Dhamma — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Respectful and humble, content and grateful,<br>Hearing the Dhamma at the proper time — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Patient and of gentle speech, visiting ascetics,<br>Discussing the Dhamma at the proper time — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `Austerity and the holy life, seeing the noble truths,<br>The realization of Nibbāna — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>When touched by worldly things, one's mind does not tremble,<br>Sorrowless, stainless, secure — this is the supreme blessing.<br><br>Having performed these things, they are everywhere undefeated,<br>Everywhere they go in safety — this is the supreme blessing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>From these causes, desire and ill-will arise;<br>From them arise liking and disliking, and fear.<br>From them arise the thoughts of the mind.<br>Like children releasing a crow, they go.<br><br>The identification with a self arises from affection,<br>Like a banyan tree from its trunk.<br>The manifold bonds of sensual pleasures are spread,<br>Like a maluva creeper in the forest.<br><br>Those who know whence it arises<br>Remove its root. They cross this flood,<br>So hard to cross, not crossed before,<br>And do not come to renewed existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.5" },
{ text: `Dhamma-conduct and the holy life are called the best conduct.<br>If one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>Yet if he is harsh of speech, fond of harming like a beast,<br>His life is evil, he increases the dust of defilements.<br><br>A bhikkhu who loves disputes, covered by ignorance,<br>Does not understand the Dhamma and Discipline taught by the Buddha.<br><br>Led by ignorance, he harms those trained in self-development,<br>Not knowing the defiled path that leads to hell.<br><br>Such a bhikkhu, fallen into a bad destination,<br>From this birth to that, from darkness to darkness,<br>After death comes to suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.6" },
{ text: `Like a cesspit filled after many years,<br>So a defiled person is hard to cleanse.<br><br>Knowing such a one, O bhikkhus, attached to families,<br>With evil desires, evil thoughts, evil deportment, evil conduct and resort,<br>All of you, being of one mind, shun him.<br><br>Blow him away like dust, discard him like rubbish.<br>Drive out the chatterer, the fake ascetic.<br>Having expelled evil desires, evil deportment, evil conduct and resort,<br><br>Live pure, with the pure, mindful, mindful of the goal.<br>Then united and wise, make an end of suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.6" },
{ text: `The seers of old were self-controlled and austere,<br>Abandoning the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>They practiced for their own welfare.<br><br>Brahmin sages had no cattle, no gold, no grain.<br>Learning was their wealth; they guarded that treasure.<br><br>Whatever was prepared for them, they did not refuse.<br>They were protected by Dhamma, not defeated anywhere.<br><br>From youth to forty-eight years, those brahmins of old<br>Lived the holy life, seeking knowledge and good conduct.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.7" },
{ text: `They praised virtue, study, gentleness, austerity, and peace,<br>Non-harming, patience, and the holy life.<br>The best among them, the striving Brahmā, did not engage<br>In sexual intercourse even in a dream.<br><br>The wise in the world, practicing his conduct,<br>Praised virtue and patience, and the holy life.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.7" },
{ text: `From whom a person learns the Dhamma,<br>Let him pay homage to that person as the devas pay homage to Inda.<br>That one, being honored, with joyful mind,<br>Having learned much, proclaims the true Dhamma.<br><br>An attentive, wise person, reflecting,<br>Practicing Dhamma in accordance with Dhamma,<br>Becomes learned, intelligent, and careful.<br>By serving such a one, he becomes not heedless.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `Like one who, entering a flooded, turbulent river,<br>Is swept away by the current — how can he help others across?<br>So too, one who has not mastered the Dhamma,<br>Not understanding the meaning of the learned's words,<br>Himself not having overcome doubt — how can he help others meditate?`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `But one who has boarded a strong boat, well-fitted with oars and rudder,<br>Skilled and mindful, knowing the means, can ferry many across.<br>So too, one who is developed, learned, unshaken,<br>Can help others who are meditating, who are eager to hear the Dhamma.<br><br>Therefore, associate with a good person, a wise one, learned and intelligent.<br>Knowing the goal, practicing wisely, knowing the Dhamma, one attains happiness.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.8" },
{ text: `I ask the sage of great wisdom, who has gone beyond, at peace, self-established.<br>How should a bhikkhu, leaving home and abandoning sensual pleasures,<br>Properly wander in the world?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>A bhikkhu who subdues greed for pleasures,<br>In the divine and human realms, beyond existence, knowing the Dhamma —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>A bhikkhu who has abandoned divisive speech, anger, and stinginess,<br>With all opposition completely destroyed —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.13" },
{ text: `Having abandoned both the dear and the not-dear,<br>Clinging to nothing, dependent nowhere,<br>Fully freed from the fetters —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>One who finds no core in any attachments,<br>Who has subdued greed for what is grasped,<br>Not dependent, not led by others —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>In speech, in mind, and in deed,<br>Not opposing anyone, rightly knowing the Dhamma,<br>Always striving toward the peaceful Nibbāna path —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.13" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu not conceited when honored,<br>Not angered when reviled,<br>Not greedy for food received from others —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>A bhikkhu who has abandoned greed and existence,<br>Not harming, not binding anyone,<br>Gone beyond doubt, with dart drawn out —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>A bhikkhu knowing what is proper for himself,<br>Not harming anyone in the world,<br>Knowing the Dhamma as it really is —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.13" },
{ text: `One in whom there are no underlying tendencies,<br>And whose unwholesome roots are uprooted,<br>Without desire, without longing —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>One who has destroyed the taints, destroyed conceit,<br>Who has subdued the entire path of passion,<br>Subdued, at peace, self-established —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>Faithful, learned, seeing the fixed course,<br>A noble one without factions among the many factions,<br>Able to subdue greed, hatred, and ill-will —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.13" },
{ text: `Pure and victorious, having drawn aside the veil,<br>Self-controlled in all things, gone to the far shore, unshaken,<br>With all activities ceased, skilled in final knowledge —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>In past times and in future times,<br>Transcending all doctrines, with wisdom truly pure,<br>In every direction, completely freed —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.<br><br>Knowing the Dhamma phrase, realizing the true Dhamma,<br>Seeing the expansion, with taints destroyed,<br>All attachments fully eliminated —<br>That bhikkhu properly wanders in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.13" },
{ text: `A bhikkhu should not go out at the wrong time;<br>At the right time he should enter the village for alms.<br>The Buddhas do not go at the wrong time,<br>For those who go at the wrong time are caught in snares.<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, scents, and touches —<br>These very things bewilder beings.<br>Subdue desire for these things,<br>And enter at the right time for the morning meal.<br><br>A bhikkhu who obtains almsfood at the right time,<br>Let him return alone and sit in a quiet place,<br>Reflecting inwardly, mind not running outside,<br>Making himself free from all grasping.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `Speak to him of the excellent Dhamma,<br>Not speaking divisively, not disparaging anyone.<br><br>But there are those who engage in verbal battles,<br>Little-minded people — we do not praise them.<br>Fetters bind them here and there;<br>They lead the mind too far.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `Almsfood, lodging, a place to sit, water for washing,<br>And the outer robe — after hearing the Dhamma taught by the Well-Gone One,<br>A wise disciple, having reflected, should use them.<br><br>Therefore, almsfood, lodging, water for washing, and the outer robe —<br>Do not become attached to these things.<br>A bhikkhu, like a water drop on a lotus leaf, should not cling.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `Do not kill living beings, nor cause them to be killed,<br>Nor approve of others killing.<br>Abandon all punishment toward all beings,<br>Both toward the strong and toward the timid.<br><br>Then, give up taking what is not given,<br>A wise disciple, understanding well,<br>Should not cause others to take nor approve of theft.<br>Abandon and end all taking of what is not given.<br><br>Abandon the non-celibate life, avoid it,<br>As a wise person avoids a burning pit of coals.<br>If you are unable to live the celibate life,<br>Do not transgress another's wife.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `When going to an assembly or a gathering,<br>Or when alone with a single person,<br>Do not speak falsehood, nor cause others to speak it,<br>Nor approve of false speech. Abandon all that is untrue.<br><br>Do not live a life of drinking intoxicants.<br>A lay follower who has accepted this Dhamma<br>Should not cause others to drink nor approve of drinking.<br>Knowing that drinking leads to madness.<br><br>Only fools, when drunk, do evil deeds<br>And cause other heedless people to live heedlessly.<br>Avoid this ground of non-merit,<br>Which deludes and delights the fool.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `Do not kill living beings, do not take what is not given,<br>Do not speak falsehood, do not drink intoxicants,<br>Abandon non-celibacy, abstain from sexual intercourse,<br>Do not eat at night, do not eat at the wrong time.<br><br>Do not wear garlands, do not use perfumes,<br>Lie down on the ground, on a spread mat.<br>This is called the eight-factored uposatha observance,<br>Taught by the Buddha for the end of suffering.<br><br>From now on, on the uposatha day,<br>Dividing the half-month into two parts,<br>On the fourteenth, the fifteenth, or the eighth of each month,<br>With joyful mind, practice the spiritual power<br>Complete with eight factors, well fulfilled.<br><br>Therefore, in the morning, observing the uposatha,<br>A wise person, with faithful mind,<br>With joyful mind, offering to the Saṅgha of bhikkhus<br>Food and drink according to one's ability.<br><br>Support mother and father righteously,<br>And engage in lawful trade.<br>A householder thus, not heedless in conduct,<br>Is reborn as a deva named 'Self-luminous'.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.14" },
{ text: `Ānanda:<br>Going forth, I praise it as the Dhamma-eye.<br>After examining, the Lord approved the going forth.<br><br>Bondage is the household life, gathering dust;<br>Freedom is the homeless life; seeing this, he went forth.<br><br>After going forth, he avoided evil bodily deeds,<br>Abandoned evil speech, and purified his livelihood.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.1" },
{ text: `The Buddha went to Rājagaha, to the mountain-surrounded city of Magadha,<br>Living the life of a wandering ascetic, bearing the radiant marks.<br><br>Beautiful, great, pure, accomplished in virtue,<br>Looking only a plough's length ahead, with eyes downcast, mindful,<br><br>Going from house to house for alms, with senses restrained,<br>His bowl quickly filled, mindful and clearly comprehending.<br>After gathering alms, the seer left the city.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.1" },
{ text: `On the slopes of the Snowy Mountain lives a tribe of upright people,<br>With abundant wealth and energy, in the Kosala land.<br><br>Born in the solar clan, the Sakya family,<br>Leaving that family, I went forth, O king.<br>I have no longing for sensual pleasures.<br><br>Seeing the danger in sensual pleasures, abandoning them is security.<br>I will go, striving; my mind is joyful.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.1" },
{ text: `By the Nerañjarā river, I strived with energy,<br>Making effort, meditating for security from bondage.<br><br>Even if my blood dried up, my bile and phlegm dried up,<br>Even if my flesh wasted away, my mind became more serene.<br>Mindfulness, wisdom, and concentration were further established.<br><br>Living thus, I attained the supreme feeling;<br>My mind did not seek sensual pleasures;<br>I saw beings as pure.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.2" },
{ text: `Sensual desire, your first army;<br>The second is called discontent;<br>The third is hunger and thirst;<br>The fourth is called craving.<br><br>Fifth is dullness and drowsiness;<br>The sixth is called fear;<br>The seventh is doubt;<br>The eighth is defamation and stubbornness.<br><br>Gain, fame, and honor wrongly obtained,<br>And whoever exalts himself and disparages others.<br><br>This is your army, Namuci,<br>The dark one's battle force.<br>A coward cannot conquer it;<br>Who conquers it gains bliss.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.2" },
{ text: `Having subdued the mind, well established in mindfulness,<br>I will wander from country to country,<br>Training many disciples.<br><br>Heedful, diligent, they will practice my teaching.<br>Though you may not wish it, they will go where they go,<br>And there they will not grieve.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.2" },
{ text: `Speak only such speech that does not harm oneself,<br>And does not hurt others.<br>That speech is truly well spoken.<br><br>Speak only kindly speech, speech that gladdens.<br>Speak no evil speech that others might dislike.<br><br>Truth is the deathless word; this is the ancient Dhamma.<br>The good, established in truth, goal, and Dhamma, speak thus.<br><br>The word the Buddha speaks for peace, for Nibbāna,<br>For the end of suffering — that is the supreme word.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.3" },
{ text: `I am not a brahmin, not a prince, not a merchant, not anything at all.<br>Knowing the classes of ordinary people,<br>I, a wise one, wander in the world, owning nothing.<br><br>Wearing the outer robe, I live homeless,<br>With shaven head, self-calmed,<br>Unstained in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Do not ask about birth, ask about conduct.<br>Indeed, from any wood a fire is born.<br>From a lowly family, a sage of wisdom,<br>Well-trained, restrained by moral shame,<br><br>Trained in truth, subdued and controlled,<br>One who has attained knowledge, fulfilled the holy life —<br>At the proper time offer him offerings.<br>Therefore, any brahmin seeking merit<br>Should perform the sacrifice with such offerings.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Those who have abandoned sensual pleasures, wandering homeless,<br>Well-controlled, like a shuttle straight —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those free from greed, with well-tranquil faculties,<br>Like the moon freed from Rāhu's jaws —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Not attached to anything, they wander in the world,<br>Always mindful, abandoning the view of 'mine' —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>One who has abandoned sensual pleasures, self-controlled, wandering,<br>Who knows the end of birth and death,<br>Peaceful, cooled like a lake —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>Equal to the equal, avoiding the unequal,<br>The Tathāgata has attained limitless wisdom,<br>Unstained, undefiled, in this world or the next —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `In whom there is no deceit, no conceit,<br>Who is without greed, without 'mine', without longing,<br>Hatred destroyed, self truly calmed,<br>That brahmin, freed from defilement and sorrow —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>One who has completely destroyed all mental abodes,<br>No longer grasping anything in the world,<br>Without clinging to this world or the next —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `One whose mind is truly concentrated, having crossed the flood,<br>Knowing the Dhamma with supreme vision,<br>Taints destroyed, bearing the final body —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>One in whom the taints and harsh speech are completely destroyed,<br>No longer existing, having attained knowledge,<br>Liberated in every way —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Among the attached, he is unattached;<br>Among the conceited, he is not conceited;<br>He has understood suffering, both field and ground —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>Not dependent on longings, he sees seclusion,<br>Beyond the knowledge and views of others,<br>Having no object of reliance —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>He has realized the Dhamma, far and near,<br>Completely destroyed, no longer existing,<br>Peaceful, without clinging, fully liberated —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Seeing the destruction of fetters in birth and death,<br>The path of passion is removed, leaving no trace,<br>Pure, faultless, stainless, undefiled —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>One who does not see a self as his own self,<br>With mind concentrated, upright, unwavering,<br>Without desire, without stubbornness, without doubt —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.<br><br>One in whom the cause of delusion no longer exists,<br>Knowing and seeing all phenomena,<br>Bearing this final body,<br>Attained to perfect enlightenment, the unsurpassed secure state —<br>Thus, the Tathāgata is worthy of the sacrificial offering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>One without intrusiveness, without agitation,<br>Free from sensual desires, who has abandoned dullness,<br><br>Leader of the border, skilled in birth and death,<br>A seer endowed with wisdom, has come to the sacrifice.<br><br>Having subdued arrogance, with folded hands pay homage,<br>Offer food and drink — such offering increases.<br><br>Brahmin:<br>You are the Enlightened One, worthy of offerings,<br>You are the unsurpassed field of merit,<br>The world's recipient of offerings.<br>Giving to the Venerable One yields great fruit.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4" },
{ text: `Young Maṇḍa said:<br>Venerable Gotama, I ask the peaceful one,<br>Wearing the robe, homeless.<br><br>A donor, a householder seeking merit,<br>Wishing to gain merit, gives food and drink to others.<br>Where should he give so that the offering is pure?<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Maṇḍa, a donor, a householder seeking merit,<br>Wishing to gain merit, gives food and drink to others,<br>He should give to those worthy of offerings.<br><br>Those who in this world are truly unattached,<br>Completely without possessions, self-controlled —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who have cut off all fetters,<br>Subdued, liberated, unshaken, without longing —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those who have destroyed greed, hatred, and delusion,<br>With taints destroyed, the holy life fulfilled —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who live without deceit, without conceit,<br>With taints destroyed, the holy life fulfilled —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those without greed, without 'mine', without longing,<br>With taints destroyed, the holy life fulfilled —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who are not entangled with anyone,<br>Crossed the flood, wandering without ownership —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those with no craving for anything in this world,<br>No longing for existence or non-existence, in this world or the next —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who have abandoned sensual pleasures, living homeless,<br>Skillfully controlled, like a shuttle straight —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those free from craving, with well-tranquil faculties,<br>Like the moon freed from Rāhu's jaws —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who are peaceful, free from greed, free from anger,<br>Having abandoned this world, with no further becoming —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Death and birth ended, leaving no remainder,<br>All doubt and uncertainty subdued —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Those who in this world make themselves an island,<br>Without possessions, completely freed —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>Those who in this very life truly know:<br>'This is my last birth, there is no further existence' —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.<br><br>One who has attained supreme wisdom,<br>Delighting in jhāna, mindful,<br>Attained enlightenment, the refuge of many —<br>At the proper time offer them the sacrifice.<br>The brahmin seeking merit, give thus.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Then young Maṇḍa further said:<br>A donor, a householder seeking merit,<br>Wishing to gain merit, gives food and drink to others.<br>Please tell me, O Blessed One, the complete Dhamma of sacrifice.<br><br>The Blessed One said to Maṇḍa:<br>Perform the sacrifice, sacrifice properly,<br>Making the mind completely pure in every way.<br>To the giver of the sacrifice, the recipients, and the gifts —<br>Establish yourself there, abandoning anger.<br><br>He, having abandoned greed, subdued anger,<br>Develops a mind of loving-kindness, immeasurable toward all,<br>By heedfulness, training day and night,<br>In all directions, pervading with boundless mind.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.5" },
{ text: `Sabhiya asked:<br>Venerable Gotama, by attaining what is one called a bhikkhu?<br>By what is one called gentle? By what is one called tamed?<br>How is one called awakened? Being asked this, please answer.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Sabhiya, one who, by the path he has made for himself,<br>Has gone to peace, crossed beyond doubt,<br>Abandoned both existence and non-existence,<br>Lived the holy life, ended renewed birth —<br>That one is rightly called a bhikkhu.<br><br>One who, wherever he dwells, equanimous and mindful,<br>Harming no one in the whole world,<br>Crossed the flood, with pure mind, unshaken,<br>One without impulse — that one is called gentle.<br><br>One whose faculties, both internally and externally,<br>Are trained and developed in the whole world,<br>Who has fully understood this world and the next,<br>Timely, trained — that one is called tamed.<br><br>One who analyzes all aeons completely,<br>The turning of both death and birth,<br>All dust removed, stainless, pure,<br>Attained the end of birth — that one is called a Buddha.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.6" },
{ text: `Sabhiya asked:<br>Venerable Gotama, by attaining what is one called a brahmin?<br>By what is one called an ascetic? By what is one bathed?<br>How is one called a great elephant? Being asked this, please answer.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Sabhiya, one who has expelled all evil states,<br>Without defilement, well-concentrated, steadfast, firm,<br>Who has crossed beyond the round of existence in every way,<br>Without dependencies — that one is called a brahmin.<br><br>Peaceful, calmed, abandoning both good and evil,<br>Without defilement, knowing this world and the next,<br>Subduing and controlling birth and death —<br>Such a virtuous one is called an ascetic.<br><br>One who has washed away all evil states,<br>Both internally and externally, in the whole world,<br>Among devas and humans subject to time,<br>Not falling into time — that one is called bathed.<br><br>One who does no evil deed in the world,<br>All fetters not clinging, not binding,<br>Throughout the whole world, not clinging, not bound —<br>Such a virtuous one is called a great elephant.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.6" },
{ text: `Sabhiya asked:<br>Venerable Gotama, how do the Buddhas call one who has conquered the field?<br>By what is one called skilled? By what is one called wise?<br>How is one called a seer? Being asked this, please answer.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Sabhiya, one who, having examined and subdued<br>All the field of devas and humans, the Brahma-field,<br>Freed from bonds, the root of all fields —<br>Such a virtuous one is called a conqueror of the field.<br><br>One who, having examined and subdued<br>All the treasure of devas and humans, the Brahma-treasure,<br>Freed from bonds, the root of all treasures —<br>Such a virtuous one is called skilled.<br><br>One who, having examined and subdued<br>Both mind and consciousness, internally and externally,<br>With wisdom pure, subduing dark and bright states —<br>Such a virtuous one is called wise.<br><br>One who, having known unwholesome and wholesome states,<br>Both internally and externally, in the whole world,<br>Is honored by devas and humans, beyond the net —<br>That one is called a seer.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.6" },
{ text: `Sabhiya asked:<br>Venerable Gotama, by attaining what is one called a wise one?<br>By what is one called a knower? What is called energetic?<br>How is one called mature? Being asked this, please answer.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Sabhiya, one who, having examined and fully understood<br>All proliferations, name-and-form, internally and externally,<br>The root of disease, freed from bonds, the root of all diseases —<br>Such a virtuous one is called a wise knower.<br><br>One who, having abandoned all evil states in the world,<br>With energy, crosses over all suffering in hell,<br>Energetic, ardent, diligent —<br>Such a virtuous one is called energetic.<br><br>One whose bonds are burst and destroyed,<br>The root of craving, freed from all roots of craving —<br>Such a virtuous one is called mature.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.6" },
{ text: `Sabhiya asked:<br>Venerable Gotama, by attaining what is one called learned?<br>By what is one called noble? How is one called of good conduct?<br>How is one called a wanderer? Being asked this, please answer.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Sabhiya, one who, having learned, has fully understood all states,<br>Faulty and faultless, all states in the world,<br>Conquered, doubt-free, liberated, completely unshaken —<br>That one is called learned.<br><br>One who, having cut off all attachments and taints,<br>Knowing, does not go to a womb,<br>Having abandoned the three defilements of perception,<br>Not entering time — that one is called noble.<br><br>One who here is accomplished in virtue,<br>Skilled in every sphere, knowing the Dhamma,<br>Throughout, unattached, liberated, without enmity toward anyone —<br>That one is called of good conduct.<br><br>One who does no deeds leading to suffering,<br>Above, below, across, or in between,<br>Living with full understanding, abandoning, not accepting<br>Deceit, conceit, greed, hatred, and anger,<br>Bringing name and form to an end —<br>That one is called a wanderer.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.6" },
{ text: `The life of humans in this world is not known,<br>Without sign, full of trouble, brief, bound to suffering.<br><br>There is no effort by which one can escape death.<br>After old age comes death — such is the nature of beings.<br><br>As ripe fruits are always in danger of falling,<br>So mortals, once born, are always in danger of death.<br><br>As a potter's clay vessels, large and small,<br>At last all break — so is the life of mortals.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.8" },
{ text: `Both young and old, both foolish and wise,<br>All are subject to death; all end in death.<br><br>Those overcome by death, passing to the next world,<br>A father cannot save his son, nor relatives a relative.<br><br>Behold, relatives stand by, weeping and looking on,<br>Each one is led to death like an ox to slaughter.<br><br>So the world is afflicted by death and old age.<br>Therefore, the wise, knowing the world, do not grieve.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.8" },
{ text: `One who does not know the path of coming and going,<br>Not seeing both ends, grieving is useless.<br><br>If grieving could bring any benefit,<br>Then the wise would do it. But the fool only harms himself.<br><br>Lamentation and sorrow do not bring peace of mind;<br>They only increase suffering and harm the body.<br><br>Pale and thin, harming oneself,<br>The dead are not protected; grieving is in vain.<br><br>Without abandoning grief, one suffers even more.<br>Lamenting over the dead, one falls under the power of grief.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.8" },
{ text: `Look at other people going according to their deeds,<br>Falling into death's power, beings full of fear.<br><br>People hope for this or that,<br>But what happens is quite different.<br>Such is the nature of non-permanence;<br>See the nature of the world.<br><br>If a person lives for a hundred years or more,<br>They still leave their relatives behind, abandoning life.<br><br>Therefore, hearing the Arahant's teaching,<br>One should stop lamentation when seeing a dead person,<br>Thinking: 'I no longer have that person.'`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.8" },
{ text: `As a burning house is extinguished by water,<br>So the wise one, skilled and wise,<br>Quickly dispels grief like the wind blows away cotton.<br><br>One who seeks happiness should draw out the dart —<br>The lamentation, longing, and sorrow within oneself.<br><br>Having drawn out the dart, independent, peaceful,<br>Having attained peace of mind, sorrowless, calmed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.8" },
{ text: `And I do not call one a brahmin merely because of birth,<br>Even if he is of high birth and wealthy,<br>But still attached to worldly gain.<br>One who is not greedy for gain, who has no attachments —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has cut off all fetters, fearless,<br>Gone beyond all clinging, freed from bonds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `Having cut the strap, the thong, the rope, and the bridle,<br>Thrown away the crossbar —<br>That awakened one, enlightened, I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who, without anger, endures abuse, beating, and binding,<br>With patience as his strength —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Without anger, dutiful, virtuous, without conceit,<br>Tamed, bearing his final body —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Like water on a lotus leaf, a mustard seed on a needle's point,<br>One not attached to sensual pleasures —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `One who in this very life knows the end of suffering,<br>Who has laid down the burden, freed from bonds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Of deep wisdom, intelligent, skilled in the path and non-path,<br>Attained the supreme goal —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Not associated with householders or renunciants,<br>Wandering with few wants, homeless —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `Who has laid down the rod against all beings,<br>Both the timid and the strong,<br>Who neither kills nor causes to be killed —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Friendly among the hostile, peaceful among the violent,<br>Not grasping among those who grasp —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One whose greed, hatred, pride, and hypocrisy have fallen away<br>Like a mustard seed from a needle's point —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `One who speaks gentle, beneficial, and truthful words,<br>Who does not offend anyone —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who in this world takes nothing not given,<br>Whether long or short, small or large, beautiful or ugly —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has no longings for this world or the next,<br>Without longings, freed from bonds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has no craving, wise, without doubt,<br>Who has reached the Deathless —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `One who here has transcended both good and evil,<br>Sorrowless, stainless, pure —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Pure as the moon, unstained, clear, tranquil,<br>Who has destroyed delight in existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Who has crossed this dangerous path, overcome delusion and saṃsāra,<br>Reached the far shore, meditative, unshaken,<br>Without doubt, without clinging, at peace —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who here has abandoned sensual desires,<br>Who has gone forth from home to homelessness,<br>Who has destroyed sensual existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },


{ text: `In this world, abandoning greed and evil,<br>Homeless, gone forth,<br>Having destroyed evil and existence —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has abandoned human bonds,<br>And crossed beyond divine bonds,<br>Free from all bonds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>Having abandoned pleasure and displeasure,<br>Cooled, without attachment,<br>A hero who has conquered all worlds —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who has no clinging to the past, future, or present,<br>Without clinging, without possessions —<br>Him I call a brahmin.<br><br>One who knows his former lives,<br>Sees heaven and hell,<br>Has reached the end of birth —<br>Him I call a brahmin.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `What the world calls 'name' and 'family' —<br>These are mere conventional designations,<br>Originating variously in common usage.<br><br>For a long time, ordinary people hold wrong views,<br>The ignorant declare: 'A brahmin is so by birth.'<br><br>Not by birth is one a brahmin,<br>Not by birth is one a non-brahmin.<br>By action one is a brahmin,<br>By action one is a non-brahmin.<br><br>By action one is a farmer,<br>By action one is a craftsman,<br>By action one is a merchant,<br>By action one is a servant.<br><br>By action one is a thief,<br>By action one is a soldier,<br>By action one is a priest,<br>By action one is a king.<br><br>The wise, seeing action as it really is,<br>Understand dependent origination,<br>And know the result of kamma.<br><br>By kamma the world revolves,<br>By kamma people wander.<br>Kamma binds beings<br>Like the wheel of a rolling chariot.<br><br>By austerity, by the holy life,<br>By restraint and self-control,<br>One becomes a brahmin.<br>Such a brahmin is supreme.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.9" },
{ text: `Whoever is born as a human being<br>Is born with an axe in his mouth.<br>The fool speaking evil cuts himself with that.<br><br>One who praises the blameworthy,<br>Or blames the praiseworthy,<br>Heaps up misfortune by his mouth.<br>Because of that misfortune, he does not find happiness.<br><br>The liar goes to hell,<br>One who says 'I did not do it' having done it.<br>Both after death are equal,<br>Lowly men of evil deeds.<br><br>One who bears ill will toward the innocent,<br>Toward a pure, faultless person,<br>That evil returns to that fool<br>Like fine dust thrown against the wind.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.10" },
{ text: `Homeless, I have come to ask the sage who lives on scraps,<br>Tell me, O seer, the supreme path,<br>The path of the sage.<br><br>The Blessed One replied:<br>Difficult to practice, hard to do — the path of the sage.<br>I will explain it to you; listen and pay attention.<br>I will speak to you; be firm in mind.<br>Follow the ascetic's life, not being shaken.<br>Amid praise and blame in the village, restrain anger;<br>Live peacefully, not arrogant.<br><br>High and low sounds arise like sparks from a fire.<br>Women may tempt — but do not let them tempt the sage.<br><br>Having abandoned sexual intercourse, abandon all higher and lower sensual desires.<br>Do not oppose or be attached to frail or strong beings.<br><br>As I am, so are they; as they are, so am I.<br>Comparing yourself to others, do not kill nor cause to be killed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11" },
{ text: `Abandon desire and greed, for this traps ordinary people.<br>One with vision, practicing the path, transcends hell and the human realm.<br><br>Eat in moderation when hungry, have few wants, not greedy.<br>One who has no desire, free from desire, is truly peaceful.<br><br>After gathering alms, the seer enters the deep forest,<br>Goes to the foot of a tree and prepares a seat for meditation.<br><br>The wise one, practicing jhāna, delights in the deep forest,<br>Meditating at the foot of a tree, content with one's own delight.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11" },
{ text: `When the night ends and morning comes, one should go to the village.<br>Do not delight in the almsfood brought from the village.<br><br>The seer should not go hurriedly to the village among families.<br>While seeking food, cut off talk; do not engage in trivial conversation.<br><br>'If I get something, that is good; if not, that is also good.'<br>Thinking thus on both counts, he returns to the tree.<br><br>Wandering with bowl in hand, not mute but appearing mute,<br>Do not despise a small gift, nor disparage the giver.<br><br>The ascetic teaches the high and low path,<br>But to reach the far shore, there is not only one way.<br>Yet do not think: 'This is only one path.'`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11" },
{ text: `For one without craving, a bhikkhu who has cut the stream,<br>Who has abandoned good and evil deeds, there is no sorrow.<br><br>The Blessed One further said:<br>I teach you the knowledge of the sage's practice.<br>Practice like a razor, pressing the tongue against the palate,<br>Restrain your belly.<br><br>Let your mind not be sluggish, but do not think too much.<br>Without defilement, independent, living the supreme holy life.<br><br>Train to sit alone, living the right ascetic life.<br>Living alone is called the sage's practice.<br>If you find comfort in solitude, that is good.<br><br>Having heard the voices of the wise, shine in the ten directions,<br>Practice jhāna, abandon sensual desires,<br>That my disciples may grow in mind and faith.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11" },
{ text: `Learn from the streams in mountain ravines.<br>Mountain streams flow noisily, but the great ocean moves in silence.<br><br>What is empty makes loud noise; what is full remains silent.<br>The fool is like a half-empty pot; the wise is like a full lake.<br><br>When an ascetic speaks much, speaking to the point,<br>Knowing the Dhamma, he should teach; knowing, he may speak much.<br><br>One who knows, knowing, restrains himself;<br>One who knows, not speaking much — that one is a sage,<br>Worthy of the sage's practice, having attained the sage's practice.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11" },
{ text: `One who does not fully understand suffering,<br>And the origin of suffering,<br>And where suffering is completely destroyed without remainder,<br>Who does not know the path leading to the calming of suffering,<br><br>Does not have liberation of mind or liberation by wisdom,<br>He cannot make an end of birth and old age.<br><br>Those who fully understand suffering,<br>And the origin of suffering,<br>And where suffering is completely destroyed without remainder,<br>And know the path leading to the calming of suffering,<br><br>Possess liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom,<br>They can make an end of birth and old age.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `From a basis, suffering arises.<br>All the various sufferings in the world arise from a basis.<br>The fool, because of ignorance, creates the basis,<br>Thus repeatedly encountering suffering.<br>Therefore, a wise person should not create a basis,<br>Contemplating the existence of birth and suffering.<br><br>Those who fall into the round of birth and death,<br>Going from this existence to that existence,<br>Their destination is due to ignorance.<br><br>This great ignorance leads to long wandering.<br>Beings who have attained true knowledge go no further.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whatever suffering exists,<br>All arises from volitional formations.<br>With the cessation of volitional formations,<br>There is no suffering.<br><br>Knowing this danger, that suffering arises from volitional formations,<br>Stilling all volitional formations, destroying perceptions,<br>Thus suffering ends. Knowing this as it really is,<br><br>The wise one, with right view, knowing with right knowledge,<br>Conquers Māra's fetter, and does not come to renewed existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whatever suffering exists,<br>All arises from consciousness.<br>With the cessation of consciousness,<br>There is no suffering.<br><br>Knowing this danger, that suffering arises from consciousness,<br>A bhikkhu who stills consciousness, without desire, is peaceful.<br><br>Those overpowered by contacts, running after existence,<br>Those following the wrong path are far from the destruction of fetters.<br><br>Those who understand contact, through wisdom delighting in peace,<br>Having directly known contact, without desire, are peaceful.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whether pleasant feeling, painful feeling,<br>Or neither-painful-nor-pleasant,<br>Internal feeling or external,<br>Whatever feeling there is,<br><br>Knowing this is suffering, deceptive, subject to destruction,<br>Seeing the end of contacts — thus, dispassionate,<br>A bhikkhu who has destroyed feelings, without desire, is peaceful.<br><br>One with craving as companion wanders for a long time,<br>Going from this existence to that existence, wandering without end.<br><br>Knowing this danger, that craving gives rise to suffering,<br>Free from craving, without clinging, mindful, the bhikkhu wanders.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whatever suffering exists,<br>All arises from nutriment.<br>With the cessation of nutriment,<br>There is no suffering.<br><br>Knowing this danger, that suffering arises from nutriment,<br>Fully understanding all nutriment, not depending on any nutriment,<br><br>With right knowledge, healthy, having destroyed the taints,<br>Using nutriment with reflection, abiding in the Dhamma,<br>That wise one does not fall into any category.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whatever suffering exists,<br>All arises from agitation.<br>With the cessation of agitation,<br>There is no suffering.<br><br>Knowing this danger, that suffering arises from agitation,<br>Therefore, abandoning agitation, stilling volitional formations,<br>Without hindrance, without clinging, mindful,<br>That bhikkhu wanders everywhere.<br><br>Without support, unshaken; with support, there is clinging.<br>Clinging to this or that existence, one cannot conquer the round.<br><br>Having known this danger, this great fear in supports,<br>One without support, without clinging, mindful,<br>That bhikkhu wanders everywhere.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Behold this world with its devas,<br>Delighting in what is not-self,<br>Established in name-and-form,<br>Thinking this is the truth.<br><br>Whatever they think, when name-and-form changes,<br>Name-and-form is illusory, deceptive, transient.<br><br>Nibbāna is not illusory — that the noble ones truly know.<br>Having directly known the truth, without craving, they are peaceful.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Forms, sounds, tastes, scents, touches —<br>All these things, desirable, pleasant, agreeable,<br>As long as they exist,<br><br>The world with its devas considers them pleasant.<br>But when they are destroyed, they see them as suffering.<br><br>The noble ones see as pleasant the destruction of the body.<br>This is completely opposite to what the whole world sees.<br><br>What others call pleasant, the noble ones call suffering;<br>What others call suffering, the noble ones know as pleasant.<br><br>The good are open, the seers have light.<br>Who outside the noble ones is worthy of enlightenment?<br>By that right knowledge, they attain taintless Nibbāna.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12" },
{ text: `Whoever longs for sensual pleasures, if they succeed,<br>They are surely joyful, having obtained what they desire.<br><br>But if those desires of the longing person fail,<br>They are struck by suffering like an arrow.<br><br>One who avoids sensual pleasures as one avoids a snake's head with one's foot,<br>Mindful, transcends this attachment in the world.<br><br>One who is greedy for sensual pleasures — land, gold, cattle, horses,<br>Servants, women, relatives —<br><br>Powerless, overcome by desires, calamities crush him,<br>Suffering follows him like water into a broken boat.<br><br>Therefore, always mindful, one should abandon sensual desires.<br>Having abandoned them, one crosses the flood,<br>Having bailed out the boat, one reaches the far shore.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.1" },
{ text: `Beings enter a cave,<br>Grasping, they are covered.<br>One who behaves thus<br>Sinks deep into delusion.<br>Seclusion is far from such a one,<br>For sensual pleasures in the world are not easily abandoned.<br><br>Driven by desire, bound to delight in existence,<br>They are very hard to free, and no one else can free them.<br>They look to the past, they long for the future,<br>They cling to present sensual pleasures and those of the past.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.2" },
{ text: `Those greedy for sensual pleasures, infatuated, bound,<br>Stingy, established in wrong,<br>When they fall into suffering, they lament:<br>'What will become of us after death?'<br><br>Therefore, a person should train here in this very life:<br>Whatever one knows as wrong in the world,<br>Let one not live wrongly because of it,<br>For the noble ones say: 'Life is short.'`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.2" },
{ text: `I see people in the world trembling,<br>Gone to craving for various kinds of existence.<br>Base people lament at the mouth of death,<br>Not free from craving for existence or non-existence.<br><br>See those people trembling in their own conceit,<br>Like fish in a drying river when water is low.<br>Seeing this, one should live without 'mine',<br>Not creating attachment to any existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.2" },
{ text: `Subdue desire for both extremes,<br>Fully understanding contacts, without greed,<br>Not doing what one would reproach oneself for,<br>The wise are not stained by what is seen or heard.<br><br>Having fully understood perceptions, one crosses the flood.<br>The sage is not stained by any clinging,<br>Having drawn out the dart, living heedfully,<br>Not longing for this world or the next.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.2" },
{ text: `Some speak with evil intent,<br>And some speak with truthful intent.<br>Whatever is said, the sage does not become involved.<br>Therefore, the sage has no barrenness anywhere.<br><br>One who, without being asked, speaks to others of his own virtues,<br>Knowing his own observances —<br>The skilled call that ignoble.<br>If one praises oneself, that is not the Dhamma.<br><br>A bhikkhu who is peaceful, fully calmed,<br>When praising his virtues, does not say 'I am thus.'<br>The skilled call that noble.<br>For that one, conceit does not arise anywhere in the world.<br><br>One who has washed away all views —<br>Prepared concerning existence or non-existence —<br>Having abandoned conceit and deceit, washed away,<br>With what can that one be grasped? He has no grasping.<br><br>One with grasping is criticized in the Dhamma.<br>One without grasping — what can be said of that one?<br>For that one, there is neither self nor non-self.<br>That one has washed away all views here.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.3" },
{ text: `Abandoning former views, relying on new ones,<br>Going to attachment, one does not cross beyond desire.<br>They grasp and reject, like a monkey releasing a branch<br>Only to grasp another.<br><br>Having adopted various observances themselves,<br>They go high and low, subject to perceptions.<br>But the wise one, with vast wisdom, having understood the Dhamma,<br>Does not go to high and low.<br><br>He is supreme among all states,<br>Whatever is seen, heard, felt, or cognized.<br>Thus living openly, not being measured,<br>No one in the world can classify him.<br><br>They do not construct, do not prefer,<br>Do not say: 'This is supreme purity.'<br>Unattached to the bonds of grasping,<br>They create no longing anywhere in the world.<br><br>For the brahmin who has crossed beyond,<br>Having known and seen, there is no grasping.<br>Not led by craving, not greedy or dispassionate,<br>That one here grasps nothing else.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.4" },
{ text: `One who dwells in a view, considering it supreme,<br>Placing it highest in the world,<br>Says all others are inferior,<br>Thus he does not transcend disputes.<br><br>When he sees a gain for himself in what is seen, heard,<br>Virtue, observance, or feeling,<br>There he grasps, he considers others as inferior.<br><br>The skilled say that is a bond — relying on which one regards others as inferior.<br>Therefore, a bhikkhu should not rely on what is seen, heard, felt, or observance.<br><br>Should not construct a view in the world by knowledge or by virtue,<br>Nor consider oneself equal or inferior;<br>Not thinking 'superior' or 'inferior'.<br><br>Having abandoned the self, not grasping anything,<br>Not depending on knowledge, not following factions,<br>Not holding to any view at all.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.5" },
{ text: `For one who has no extremes, no aspiration<br>For existence or non-existence, for this world or the next,<br>No fixed abode anywhere,<br>Having abandoned all doctrines.<br><br>For that one, regarding what is seen, heard, felt,<br>Not even a thought;<br>That brahmin, not grasping any view,<br>No one in the world can classify him.<br><br>They do not construct, do not prefer,<br>Do not take up any doctrine.<br>No brahmin is led by observance;<br>Gone to the far shore, that one does not return.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.5" },
{ text: `Brief is this life; within a hundred years, one dies.<br>Even if one lives longer, one still dies of old age.<br><br>People grieve for what they hold as 'mine';<br>All clinging is impermanent.<br>Seeing that this world is empty, one should live homeless.<br><br>People think: 'This is mine.'<br>But when they die, that is destroyed.<br>Knowing this, the wise person<br>Should not incline toward 'mine'.<br><br>Like a dream when one wakes up,<br>One sees nothing.<br>So too, what one holds dear and loved —<br>It dies, and one no longer sees it.<br><br>Thus, that person is seen and heard, called by this or that name.<br>But when one has died, only the name remains.<br><br>Greed for 'mine', they do not abandon.<br>Sorrow, lamentation, and stinginess.<br>Therefore, the seer, having abandoned grasping,<br>Lives a life of security.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.6" },
{ text: `For a bhikkhu living alone in seclusion,<br>Developing his mind, inclined to seclusion,<br>Such a life is said to be in harmony with him,<br>And he does not mention his own existence.<br><br>The sage, not dependent, not relying on anyone,<br>Does not create love nor create hate.<br>Lamentation and stinginess fall away from him<br>Like water from a leaf.<br><br>Like a water drop on a lotus leaf,<br>Not sticking, not wetting,<br>So the sage, regarding what is seen, heard, felt,<br>Is not attached.<br><br>Therefore, the one who has washed away does not think<br>About what is seen, heard, or felt.<br>He does not seek purity through another,<br>For he is neither attached nor dispassionate.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.6" },
{ text: `One who indulges in sexual intercourse<br>Forgets the teaching and follows a wrong path.<br>That is not the noble way.<br><br>One who formerly lived alone<br>And then indulges in sex —<br>Like a chariot that has swerved —<br>Is called a lowly worldling.<br><br>His former good reputation is lost.<br>Seeing this, one should train<br>To abandon sexual intercourse.<br><br>Overcome by thoughts, he broods like a pauper.<br>Hearing others' reproach, he is as if defeated.<br><br>Then he makes weapons of others' accusations,<br>Becomes greedy, clinging to false words.<br><br>Praised as wise, living alone,<br>If he falls into sex, he is tormented like a fool.<br><br>Seeing this danger, the sage<br>Remains steadfast alone, not practicing sex.<br><br>Train in seclusion — this is the noble supreme practice.<br>Do not think yourself best, even if you are near Nibbāna.<br><br>The sage's practice is empty, not desiring pleasure.<br>One who has crossed the flood is envied and coveted<br>By those bound by sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.7" },
{ text: `Those who enter a dispute, entering the assembly,<br>They blame each other, calling one another fools.<br>They go to others and start arguments,<br>Wanting praise, they call themselves skilled.<br><br>Delighting in disputes in the midst of assemblies,<br>Longing for praise, fearing defeat,<br>When defeated, they become dejected.<br>Angry when criticized, they seek others' faults.<br><br>Disputes arise among ascetics;<br>In these disputes, there is victory and defeat.<br>Seeing this, one should not delight in disputes,<br>For even praise is of no benefit.<br><br>One who is praised after speaking in the assembly,<br>Laughs and is puffed up with pride,<br>Having attained his mind's desire.<br><br>His conceit is also his downfall;<br>Yet he still speaks with conceit and pride.<br>Seeing this, one should not dispute,<br>For the skilled say purity is not thereby attained.<br><br>Like a king's soldier, a man of wisdom,<br>One should not dispute; there is no opponent here.<br>Go and reflect on views,<br>Be united with one who has been cleansed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.8" },
{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>Having seen craving, discontent, and greed,<br>There can be no desire for sexual intercourse.<br>Why would I desire this thing<br>Full of urine and excrement, which I would touch with my foot?`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.9" },
{ text: `Not by view, nor by tradition, nor by knowledge,<br>Nor by virtue and observance is purity attained.<br>Nor is it by lack of view, tradition, knowledge, virtue, or observance.<br>Abandoning these, not grasping anything,<br>One is not dependent, not longing for existence.<br><br>By thinking 'I am superior,' or 'I am inferior,' or 'I am equal,'<br>Disputes arise from such thoughts.<br>One who is not shaken by these three distinctions —<br>For that one, there is no superior or inferior.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.9" },
{ text: `Having abandoned all homes, living homeless,<br>The sage has no intimacy with anyone in the village.<br>Empty of sensual desires, not preferring anything,<br>He does not engage in disputes with anyone in the world.<br><br>Secluded from worldly things, a great elephant without grasping,<br>He does not speak of them.<br>Like a lotus born in water, with thorns,<br>Not stained by water or mud,<br>So the sage, speaking peace, without greed,<br>Is not stained by sensual pleasures or the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.9" },
{ text: `The wise one does not come to conceit through view or through feeling,<br>Nor through knowledge, nor through virtue and observance.<br>Not led by action, not led by tradition,<br>Not abiding in mental abodes.<br><br>One who is free from perceptions, without bonds,<br>Liberated by wisdom, not deluded —<br>Those who grasp at thoughts and views live in conflict with the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.9" },
{ text: `How does one live at peace? What view and virtue?<br>I ask Gotama, the supreme person.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Without anger, without fear, without boasting, without regret,<br>Speaking gently, not agitated — that sage is truly restrained in speech.<br><br>Not longing for the future, not grieving over the past,<br>Seeing seclusion among contacts, not led by views.<br><br>Living alone, without deceit, not greedy, not stingy,<br>Not intrusive, not weary, not going to divisive speech.<br><br>Not delighting in pleasant things, not over-conceited,<br>Gentle but responsive, not credulous, not greedy.<br><br>Not training for the sake of gain, not angry when not gaining,<br>Not disturbed by craving, not attached to tastes.<br><br>Equanimous, always mindful,<br>In the world, not thinking oneself<br>Equal, superior, or inferior — that one is not agitated.<br><br>Not dependent on anyone, knowing the Dhamma, not dependent,<br>That one has no craving for existence or non-existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.10" },
{ text: `I call one at peace who does not long for sensual pleasures.<br>He has no bonds, having transcended attachment.<br><br>He has no children, cattle, fields, or land.<br>Nothing is grasped as 'mine' or 'not mine'.<br><br>Whatever worldly people or ascetics and brahmins might reproach him with,<br>He is not concerned; his mind is not shaken.<br><br>Without greed, without stinginess, the sage does not speak of superiority,<br>Nor of equality, nor of inferiority. He does not fall into time,<br>For he has transcended time.<br><br>One who has nothing, not having, does not grieve.<br>Not going to (phenomena) — that one is called at peace.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.10" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>From what do disputes and quarrels arise,<br>Lamentation and sorrow, together with stinginess,<br>Conceit and arrogance, along with divisive speech?<br>From what do these many things arise? Please tell me.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>From what is dear arise disputes and quarrels,<br>Lamentation and sorrow, together with stinginess,<br>Conceit and arrogance, along with divisive speech.<br>Disputes and quarrels are connected with stinginess;<br>Divisive speech arises from disputes.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.11" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>From what cause do dear things arise in the world?<br>Or what craving circulates in the world?<br>From what cause do hopes and fulfillments arise for a person,<br>And future states of existence?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>From desire as a cause, dear things arise in the world.<br>It is desire that circulates in the world.<br>Hopes and fulfillments arise from desire,<br>And future states of existence arise from that.<br><br>Questioner:<br>From what cause does desire arise in the world?<br>From what cause do decisions arise?<br>Anger, false speech, and also doubt —<br>What are the things the ascetic speaks of?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>What is called pleasant and unpleasant in the world —<br>Dependent on these, desire arises.<br>Having seen in form both existence and non-existence,<br>A person makes decisions in the world.<br><br>Anger, false speech, and doubt —<br>These things exist when that pair exists.<br>Let the doubter train on the path of knowledge;<br>Having understood the Dhamma spoken by the ascetic.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.11" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>From what cause do pleasant and unpleasant arise?<br>When what is absent, do they not exist?<br>And regarding existence and non-existence —<br>Please tell me the cause of that.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>From contact as a cause, pleasant and unpleasant arise.<br>When contact is absent, they do not exist.<br>And regarding existence and non-existence,<br>I tell you, this is the cause of that.<br><br>Questioner:<br>From what cause does contact arise in the world?<br>And from what do clingings arise?<br>When what is absent, is there no 'mine'?<br>When what is absent, do contacts not exist?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Dependent on name-and-form, there is contact.<br>From desires, clingings arise.<br>When desire is absent, there is no 'mine'.<br>When form is absent, contacts do not exist.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.11" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>For one living in what way does form cease?<br>How do pleasure and pain cease?<br>Tell me this — I want to know —<br>How does that cessation come about?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Not having perceptions of perceptions,<br>Not having perceptions of non-perception,<br>Neither having non-perception nor having no perception —<br>For one living thus, form ceases,<br>For proliferations are born from perceptions.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.11" },
{ text: `Knowing these things as dependent,<br>The sage, seeing the support, with mind liberated,<br>Not entering disputes, not going to existence or non-existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.11" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>Each one says his own view is supreme,<br>And others are inferior; thus disputes arise.<br>The skilled say: 'Whoever knows this, knows the Dhamma.<br>Whoever criticizes this is not perfect.'<br><br>Thus they dispute, calling others fools,<br>Not skilled. Which of these statements is true?<br>Are all of them skilled speakers?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>If by not accepting another's Dhamma, one is called a fool of inferior wisdom,<br>Then all are fools of inferior wisdom,<br>For all hold to their own views.<br><br>But if they are purified by their own views,<br>With pure wisdom, skilled, wise,<br>Then they have no inferior wisdom;<br>Their views are perfected.<br><br>I do not say: 'This is the truth.'<br>Only fools say that to one another.<br>Each holds his view as true,<br>And thus considers others fools.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.12" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>Some say: 'This is the truth,'<br>And call others empty, false.<br>Thus they dispute. Why do ascetics not speak as one?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>There is only one truth, no second.<br>Knowing this, they do not dispute.<br>But they praise their own various truths,<br>Therefore ascetics do not speak as one.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.12" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>Why do they speak of different truths,<br>These skilled disputants?<br>Are there many and various truths,<br>Or do they follow their own reasoning?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Indeed, there are not many different truths<br>Eternal in the world, apart from perceptions.<br>Having formed a view about perceptions,<br>They speak of truth and falsehood.<br><br>Dependent on what is seen, heard, virtue, observance, felt,<br>They show contempt for others.<br>Having made decisions, they gloat, saying: 'The other is a fool.'<br><br>Because they call others fools, they call themselves skilled.<br>Calling themselves skilled, they despise others.<br><br>Intoxicated with his view, full of himself,<br>Considering himself perfect,<br>He has consecrated himself with his own mind.<br>Thus intoxicated with his view.<br><br>If another is called a fool by his own words,<br>He only increases disputes.<br>But one who abandons all such decisions<br>Has no opponent in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.12" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>I ask the great seer, the Kinsman of the Sun,<br>About seclusion and the peaceful state.<br>How, having seen, does a bhikkhu become cooled,<br>Without grasping anything in the world?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Let him cut off completely the root of proliferations<br>And the notion 'I am'.<br>Whatever craving there is internally,<br>Let him train always mindfully to subdue it.<br><br>Whatever he has known directly, whether internal or external,<br>Let him not be stubborn about anything.<br>That state is not called 'cooling' by the good.<br><br>Let him not think: 'That is better, this is inferior, or this is equal.'<br>Contacted by various differences, let him not dwell on conceit.<br><br>Let him gain peace within himself.<br>A bhikkhu should not seek peace from another.<br>For one at peace within, having no self,<br>Where would there be non-self?<br><br>Just as in the middle of the ocean no waves arise,<br>The ocean remains still.<br>So too, O bhikkhu, remain still, unshaken,<br>Do not be agitated by anything in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.14" },
{ text: `Questioner:<br>He with open eyes has clearly declared<br>The Dhamma that can be known, overcoming all dangers.<br>Please, O good one, explain the path,<br>Or about specific liberation, or about jhāna.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Do not be greedy for forms!<br>Block your ears to the noise of the village!<br>Do not be attached to tastes!<br>Let nothing in the world be considered 'mine'!<br><br>When contacted by contacts, let a bhikkhu not lament over anything.<br>Let him not long for any kind of existence,<br>And let him not tremble in the face of terrors.<br><br>Having obtained food and drink, solid food and clothing,<br>Let him not hoard them; if he does not obtain them, let him not be anxious.<br><br>Let him practice jhāna, not wandering about,<br>Not delighting in restlessness, not falling into heedlessness.<br>Let him dwell in silent lodgings, in seats and beds.<br><br>Let him sleep little, be wakeful, ardent,<br>Abandon laziness, deceit, laughter, play,<br>Sexual intercourse, and all adornments.<br><br>Let him not tremble when blamed,<br>Nor be elated when praised.<br>Let him abandon greed, stinginess, anger, and divisive speech.<br><br>Let him not engage in buying and selling,<br>Nor criticize anyone anywhere.<br>Let him not be angry in the village,<br>Nor, for the sake of gain, talk with people.<br><br>Let a bhikkhu not speak boastfully,<br>Nor speak with an ulterior motive.<br>Let him not train in insolence,<br>Nor utter provocative words.<br><br>Let him not be led into false speech,<br>Nor intentionally do deceitful things.<br>Let him not despise others for their life,<br>Their wisdom, or their virtue.<br><br>Having heard harsh words from ascetics or ordinary people,<br>Let him not respond with harsh words;<br>The peaceful, gentle one does not retaliate.<br><br>Knowing this Dhamma, a bhikkhu should train<br>Mindfully, always comprehending.<br>Knowing the state of peace, he is called 'calmed'.<br>Do not be heedless in Gotama's teaching.<br><br>He who is victorious is not defeated;<br>He sees the Dhamma for himself, not by hearsay.<br>Therefore, always train heedfully<br>With respect for the Blessed One's teaching.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.14" },
{ text: `The training has been taught here.<br>Do not become involved with worldly bonds.<br>Having completely pierced through sensual desire, train for Nibbāna.<br><br>Truthful, not intrusive, not deceitful, not divisive,<br>Without anger, the sage has gone beyond greed and stinginess.<br><br>One who thinks of Nibbāna abandons sleep, laziness, and drowsiness,<br>Does not live heedlessly, nor abide in conceit.<br><br>Do not fall into false speech, do not love forms.<br>Understand conceit fully; live by non-violence.<br><br>Do not delight in the old, do not cherish the new.<br>Do not grieve over loss, do not be attached to craving.<br><br>Craving I call a flood; longing is a whirlpool;<br>Sense objects are wide open; the mud of sensual desire is hard to cross.<br><br>The sage does not deviate from truth; the brahmin stands on dry ground.<br>Having abandoned all, he is truly called 'peaceful'.<br><br>Knowing thus, one is called a knower;<br>having known, he does not depend on any Dhamma.<br>Living rightly in the world, he does not crave anyone.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.15" },
{ text: `One who here has overcome sensual desires,<br>Craving so hard to cross in the world,<br>Without sorrow, without longing,<br>He has cut the stream and is free.<br><br>Dry up what is before you; have nothing after;<br>If you do not grasp in the middle, you will live peacefully.<br><br>For one who has no 'mine' at all regarding name-and-form,<br>And who does not grieve over what is not, he does not decay in the world.<br><br>Not thinking 'this is mine,' not thinking 'this is another's,'<br>Not finding a self, one does not grieve at 'I have not'.<br><br>Not harsh, not greedy, without desires, always the same,<br>Being asked, I speak of the benefit of the unshaken.<br><br>One without desire, knowing, has no deeds;<br>Released, there is no striving; seeing security everywhere.<br><br>The sage does not speak of himself as equal, inferior, or superior.<br>Peaceful, without stinginess, he neither takes nor rejects.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.15" },
{ text: `The Enlightened One, independent, truthful, without deceit,<br>Has come to the world as a leader of the host.<br>I have come with a question to the one freed from many bonds.<br><br>A bhikkhu who is disgusted, living in an empty, secluded place,<br>At the foot of a tree, in a charnel ground, in mountain caves —<br><br>In such low or high places, how many fears are there<br>That a bhikkhu should not tremble at, in his silent dwelling?<br><br>How many dangers in the world must a bhikkhu overcome,<br>On the path to the Deathless, in a remote dwelling?<br><br>What should be his speech and conduct?<br>What observances should he earnestly practice?<br><br>What training should a bhikkhu, unified,<br>Intelligent, mindful, take up<br>To cleanse his own defilements,<br>Like a smith purifying silver?`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16" },
{ text: `Sāriputta:<br>The Blessed One replied:<br>For one who is disgusted, what is comfortable?<br>Using seats and beds in quiet, empty places —<br>For one who wants to awaken, living in accordance with Dhamma,<br>I will explain his conduct, as I have known it.<br><br>A wise bhikkhu, mindful, living on the border,<br>Should not fear the five fearful things in the world:<br>Flies, mosquitoes, reptiles, human contact, and four-footed creatures.<br><br>He should not fear the views of others,<br>Even when he sees many frightening things.<br>The seeker of the good should conquer all other dangers.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16" },
{ text: `When afflicted by illness, when feeling hunger and thirst,<br>By cold and intense heat — he should endure them.<br>Contacted by many things, a homeless person<br>Should strive with diligence and firm energy.<br><br>He should not steal, not speak falsely.<br>He should feel loving-kindness toward the frail and the strong.<br>When he knows his mind is agitated,<br>He should remove the dark part.<br><br>He should not be overcome by anger or conceit;<br>He should uproot them and abide accordingly.<br>Toward the pleasant and toward the unpleasant,<br>He should completely conquer, not be overcome.<br><br>Preferring wisdom, delighting in the good,<br>He should block and remove those dangers.<br>He should conquer discontent in lonely lodgings<br>And conquer the four things that cause lamentation.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16" },
{ text: `'What will I eat? Where will I eat? I slept badly; where will I sleep tonight?'<br>With such thoughts, the learner, homeless, should remove them.<br><br>Having obtained food and clothing at the proper time,<br>He should know enough for contentment.<br>Guarding against them, restrained in mind,<br>Though angry, he should not speak harsh words.<br><br>With eyes cast down, not footloose,<br>Devoted to jhāna, very wakeful,<br>Practicing equanimity, with mind well composed,<br>He should cut off doubt and regret.<br><br>When reproached by words, mindful, he should rejoice,<br>Destroying stubbornness among fellow celibates.<br>He should speak good words at the proper time,<br>And not think about others' doctrines.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16" },
{ text: `Furthermore, the five kinds of dust in the world —<br>He should learn to overcome them, always mindful.<br>Regarding forms, sounds, tastes, scents, and touches —<br>He should subdue desire for these.<br><br>Regarding these things, a mindful bhikkhu,<br>With mind well liberated, should subdue desire.<br>Then, at the proper time, rightly reflecting on the Dhamma,<br>With one-pointed mind, he should destroy the darkness.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16" },
{ text: `Venerable Ajita:<br>By what is the world shrouded?<br>Because of what does it not shine?<br>Tell me what is called the defilement of the world.<br>What is its great fear?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Ajita:<br>The world is shrouded by ignorance.<br>Because of stinginess and heedlessness, it does not shine.<br>I say: longing is the defilement of the world.<br>Suffering is its great fear.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2" },
{ text: `Venerable Ajita:<br>Floods flow everywhere;<br>What is the barrier to the floods?<br>Tell me the restraint of the floods.<br>By what are the floods closed?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Mindfulness is the barrier to the floods in the world.<br>Mindfulness, I say, is the restraint of the floods.<br>And by wisdom they are closed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2" },

{ text: `Venerable Ajita:<br>Wisdom and mindfulness,<br>Together with name-and-form,<br>O Venerable sir, please answer my question:<br>From what are they destroyed?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Whatever you ask, Ajita,<br>I will answer you:<br>Where name-and-form is destroyed completely without remainder,<br>With the cessation of consciousness, name-and-form is destroyed.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2" },
{ text: `Venerable Ajita:<br>Those who know how to reflect on conditioned things,<br>Learners and ordinary people in the world,<br>Being asked, please tell me their way of living,<br>O careful, wise one, please speak!<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>Do not crave sensual pleasures, keep the mind peaceful,<br>Skilled in all phenomena, a bhikkhu mindful,<br>Living the homeless life.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2" },
{ text: `Venerable Tissametteyya:<br>Who is content in the world, who is unshaken,<br>Who has directly known the two extremes, not stuck in the middle,<br>Whom do you call a great person?<br>Who here has transcended the weaver of craving?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Tissametteyya:<br>Living the holy life among sensual pleasures, without craving, always mindful,<br>A bhikkhu quiet in reflection, peaceful, unshaken.<br><br>One who has directly known the two extremes, through reflection in the middle,<br>Not stuck, not stained — him I call a great person.<br>He here has transcended the weaver of craving and desire.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.3" },
{ text: `Venerable Mettagū:<br>I ask the Blessed One, may the Blessed One answer me,<br>The question I have asked — I think the Lord is wise,<br>Self-developed. From what in this world does this suffering arise,<br>With so many kinds?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Mettagū:<br>You ask me about the origin of suffering;<br>I will tell you as I have known:<br>From a basis, suffering arises, with many kinds,<br>Various in the world.<br><br>Those who, because of ignorance, create a basis,<br>That fool repeatedly encounters suffering.<br>Therefore, a wise person should not create a basis,<br>Seeing the origin of birth and suffering.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.5" },
{ text: `Venerable Mettagū:<br>What you have asked us, you have answered.<br>Now I ask another question; please explain it to me:<br>How do the wise cross the strong flood,<br>Cross birth and old age, lamentation and sorrow?<br>May the seer answer me well,<br>As you have known the Dhamma-nature.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>I will tell you the Dhamma directly seen,<br>Not handed down. Having known it,<br>Living mindfully, one overcomes attachment to the world.<br><br>Whatever you know above, below, across, and in between,<br>Abandon delight and dwelling,<br>Do not let consciousness settle on existence.<br><br>Living thus, mindful, a bhikkhu not heedless,<br>Having abandoned deeds leading to 'I' and 'mine',<br>Here, knowing birth and old age, lamentation and sorrow,<br>Abandon suffering.<br><br>That brahmin who has directly known and is wise,<br>Having nothing, not attached to existence,<br>Certainly crosses this flood,<br>Has gone to the far shore, without stiffness, without hesitation.<br><br>Having known and understood the sacred teaching,<br>Not caught in this attachment to existence or non-existence,<br>Free from craving, without distress, without longing —<br>Him I say has crossed birth and old age.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.5" },
{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Upasīva:<br>Mindful, not longing for anything,<br>You will cross the flood by relying on 'nothing'.<br>Abandoning sensual desires, free from doubt,<br>Seeing the destruction of craving day and night — that is Nibbāna.<br><br>One completely free from greed for all sensual pleasures,<br>Relying on nothing, abandoning everything else,<br>Fully liberated in supreme liberation,<br>There that one dwells, not moving on.<br><br>Just as a flame blown by a strong wind<br>Goes to an end and cannot be measured,<br>So the sage, freed from name and body,<br>Goes to an end and cannot be measured.<br><br>One who has reached the end cannot be measured —<br>With what could one speak of him?<br>When all phenomena are completely uprooted,<br>All pathways of speech are uprooted.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.7" },
{ text: `Venerable Nanda:<br>People say there is a sage in the world.<br>What do you think? Do they call one a sage<br>Because of having perfect knowledge, or because of having perfect livelihood?<br><br>Not by view, not by tradition, not by knowledge,<br>O Nanda, do the good call one a sage.<br>I call a sage one who has destroyed the army,<br>Without distress, without longing.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.8" },
{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Hemaka:<br>Regarding all things dear, seen, heard,<br>Sensed and cognized —<br>Removing desire and greed, that is the Deathless, Nibbāna.<br><br>Knowing this, mindful, cooled here and now,<br>That one is always peaceful, beyond attachment in the world.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.9" },
{ text: `Venerable Todeyya:<br>One in whom there is no sensual desire,<br>One in whom there is no craving,<br>One who has gone beyond doubt —<br>What is the liberation of that one?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Todeyya:<br>One in whom there is no sensual desire,<br>One in whom there is no craving,<br>One who has gone beyond doubt —<br>That one's liberation is not something else.<br><br>Venerable Todeyya:<br>One who lives without longing, or one who has longing,<br>Does that one have wisdom, or does one produce wisdom?<br>O All-Seeing One, please explain to me<br>So that I may know what a sage is, O Sakyan.<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>One who lives without longing, having no longing at all,<br>That one has wisdom; he does not produce wisdom.<br>Thus, Todeyya, know the sage:<br>He has nothing, is not attached to sensual existence.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.10" },
{ text: `Venerable Kappa:<br>Those standing in the water, in the strong current,<br>In great fear — please tell me, O Lord,<br>The island for those overcome by old age and death.<br>Tell me the island so that there is no further suffering like this.<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Kappa:<br>Those standing in the water, in the strong current,<br>In great fear — I tell you the island,<br>For those overcome by old age and death.<br><br>This island without possession, without clinging,<br>I call it Nibbāna — the destruction of old age and death.<br><br>Knowing this, mindful, cooled here and now,<br>One does not fall into Māra's power, is not Māra's follower.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.11" },
{ text: `Venerable Jatukaṇṇī:<br>Having heard of the hero not attached to sensual pleasures,<br>I have come here to ask the desireless one<br>Who has crossed the flood, born with the (wisdom-)eye.<br>Please tell the path of peace — let the Blessed One truly explain it to me.<br><br>Having conquered sensual desires, the Blessed One dwells in the world,<br>Like the sun illuminating the earth with radiance.<br>O one of vast wisdom, teach me the Dhamma,<br>So that I, of little wisdom, may know it<br>And here abandon birth and old age.<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Jatukaṇṇī:<br>Subdue greed for sensual pleasures;<br>See renunciation as security.<br>Do not grasp or abandon anything in the world.<br><br>Dry up what is before you; have nothing after.<br>If you do not grasp in the middle, you will live peacefully.<br><br>O brahmin, for one completely without greed for name-and-form,<br>Without taints — because of these taints one is overcome by death.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.12" },
{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Bhadrāvudha:<br>Subdue all grasping and craving<br>Above, below, across, and in between.<br>Whoever grasps anything in the world,<br>Because of that, Māra follows that person.<br><br>Therefore, a wise person, not grasping anything,<br>A bhikkhu mindful in the entire world,<br>Having no possessions, does not long.<br>Behold these people who grasp,<br>In Māra's domain, attached and clinging.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.13" },
{ text: `Venerable Udāya:<br>I have come with a question about all phenomena,<br>To ask the meditator, the dustless one seated in peace,<br>Duty done, without taints, gone to the far shore.<br>Speak of the knowledge of liberation for the destruction of ignorance.<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Udāya:<br>Abandon desire and sensual desire, and both kinds of grief,<br>Remove dullness, and ward off regret.<br><br>Knowledge of liberation for the destruction of ignorance —<br>Purity through equanimity and mindfulness, with reflection going before.<br><br>Venerable Udāya:<br>By what is the world bound? What is its movement?<br>By abandoning what is one called Nibbāna?<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>The world is bound by delight; thought is its movement.<br>By abandoning craving, one is called Nibbāna.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.14" },
{ text: `Venerable Posāla:<br>One who tells of the past, unshaken, doubt cut off,<br>Gone to the far shore — I have come with a question<br>About all phenomena.<br><br>For one in whom perception of form has ceased,<br>All body completely destroyed,<br>Seeing both internally and externally, truly nothing —<br>I ask the Sakyan: how is such a one led further?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Posāla:<br>The Tathāgata, having directly known all stations of consciousness,<br>Knows where one stands, liberated, reaching the ultimate.<br><br>Knowing the conditioned nature of nothingness,<br>Knowing that delight is a fetter,<br>Having directly known thus, seeing thus,<br>That is the true knowledge of the brahmin who has fulfilled the holy life.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.15" },
{ text: `Venerable Mogharāja:<br>The teacher of excellence, I have come with a question:<br>How should one see the world so that the King of Death does not see one?<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Mogharāja:<br>Look upon the world as empty, always mindful.<br>Removing the view of self, thus one crosses over death.<br>Looking upon the world in this way, the King of Death does not see you.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.16" },
{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Piṅgiya:<br>Seeing the harm in all forms, beings live heedless,<br>Afflicted by forms. Therefore, Piṅgiya,<br>Do not be heedless — abandon forms so as not to come to birth again.<br><br>Seeing beings, humans, fallen into craving,<br>Burned by old age, overcome by old age,<br>Therefore, Piṅgiya, do not be heedless —<br>Abandon craving so as not to be reborn again.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.17" },
         
               

{ text: `Elder Subhūti:<br><br>My hut is well thatched, peaceful, free from wind.<br>O deva of rain, rain if you wish!<br>My mind is well concentrated, liberated, dwelling ardently.<br>O deva of rain, rain if you wish!`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahākoṭṭhita:<br><br>Peaceful and stilled, reciting words of wisdom,<br>Mind not agitated, evil states discarded<br>Like leaves blown away by the wind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.2" },
{ text: `Elder Khaṅkhārevata:<br><br>See this wisdom of the Tathāgatas,<br>Like a fire burning at midnight,<br>Giving light, giving sight,<br>They subdue the doubts of those who come.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.3" },
{ text: `Elder Puṇṇa Mantānīputta:<br><br>Associate with the wise, who see the goal,<br>Great, deep, hard to see, subtle, fine,<br>Attained by the wise, not heedless, attentive.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.4" },
{ text: `Elder Dabba:<br><br>One who was hard to tame, now is tamed.<br>Dabba is content, doubt overcome,<br>Conquering, fearless, Dabba dwells at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.5" },
{ text: `Elder Sīlavānīya:<br><br>A bhikkhu going to the Sītavana forest,<br>Living alone, secluded, content, mind concentrated,<br>Conquering, not terrified, constantly guarding mindfulness of the body.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.6" },
{ text: `Elder Bhalliya:<br><br>Who drives away the King of Death with his army,<br>Like strong floods sweeping away a weak clump of reeds,<br>Conquering, fearless, subdued, he dwells at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.7" },
{ text: `Elder Vīra:<br><br>One who was hard to tame, now is tamed.<br>Vīra is content, doubt overcome,<br>Conquering, not terrified, Vīra dwells at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.8" },
{ text: `Elder Puṇṇamāsa:<br><br>I do not long for this world or the next.<br>Having attained wisdom, peaceful, self-controlled,<br>Not stained by any phenomena, knowing the arising and passing of the world.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.10" },
{ text: `Elder Cūḷagavaccha:<br><br>A bhikkhu of great joy in the Dhamma proclaimed by the Buddha,<br>Attains the peaceful state — the bliss of peace of all conditioned things.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.11" },
{ text: `Elder Mahāgavaccha:<br><br>Power of wisdom, virtue, concentration, jhāna happiness, mindfulness,<br>Eating only what brings good fruit,<br>Here, delighting in seclusion, awaiting the time of death.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.12" },
{ text: `Elder Vanavaccha:<br><br>Beautiful are the blue-green clouds, cool, clear-flowing water,<br>Covered by Indra's herdsmen, those rocky mountains delight my mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.13" },
{ text: `Novice Elder Sīvaka:<br><br>My teacher said to me: 'Go, Sīvaka!'<br>My body lives in the village, but my mind goes to the forest.<br>Even lying down, I go. One who knows is not bound.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.14" },
{ text: `Elder Belatthasīsa:<br><br>Like a good thoroughbred with horns pulling a plough,<br>Walking and standing without fatigue,<br>So I, day and night, walking and standing without fatigue,<br>Delight in non-material happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.16" },
{ text: `Elder Dasaka:<br><br>One who is drowsy, eats much, sleeps rolling about,<br>Like a great pig fed full — that fool comes to the womb again.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.17" },
{ text: `Elder Siṅgālapitar:<br><br>Look at the Bhesakaḷā forest, a bhikkhu living there,<br>Heir to the Buddha's teaching, contemplating the skeleton perception throughout this earth.<br>I think that bhikkhu will quickly abandon sensual desire.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.18" },
{ text: `Elder Kula:<br><br>Irrigators guide water, fletchers shape arrows,<br>Carpenters shape wood, the wise tame themselves.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.19" },
{ text: `Elder Ajita:<br><br>I have no fear of death, no desire for life.<br>I will lay down this body, mindful and clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.20" },
{ text: `Elder Nigrodha:<br><br>Fear does not frighten me who am fearless,<br>Understanding the Deathless path. Our Teacher does not find a foothold.<br>Where there is fear, a bhikkhu walking that path abides.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.21" },
{ text: `Elder Cittaka:<br><br>Peacocks, blue-green, with beautiful bright necks,<br>Calling each other in the Kāramviyā forest.<br>With cool breezes and clear sounds, they wake the sleeping meditator.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.22" },
{ text: `Elder Gosāla:<br><br>I fully accept the word of the worthy one.<br>Seeing the arising and passing of aggregates, I will go to the mountain<br>To develop the practice of seclusion.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.23" },
{ text: `Elder Abhaya:<br><br>Having heard the well-spoken words of the Kinsman of the Sun,<br>I pierced the subtle, like an arrow splitting a hair.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.26" },
{ text: `Elder Lomasakaṅgiya:<br><br>With my chest, I will push back the grass — dabba, kusa, munja, pabbaja.<br>From my chest, I will push them away, I will develop the practice of solitary seclusion.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.27" },
{ text: `Elder Son of Jambugāmika:<br><br>Are you satisfied with the robe you wear?<br>Are you delighted with adornments?<br>This fragrance emanates from your virtue,<br>Not from others producing such a scent!`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.28" },
{ text: `Elder Harīta:<br><br>Make yourself straight as a fletcher makes an arrow,<br>Harīta! Cut off ignorance.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.29" },
{ text: `Elder Uttiya:<br><br>While I was ill, mindfulness arose in me.<br>While I was ill, it is not the time for heedlessness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.30" },
{ text: `Elder Gahvaratīriya:<br><br>In the great forest, bitten by mosquitoes,<br>Like a battle elephant, there one lives mindfully.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.31" },
{ text: `Elder Suppiya:<br><br>Aged, may I become unaging; burning, may I become cooled.<br>May I attain supreme peace, unsurpassed security, free from bonds.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.32" },
{ text: `Elder Sopāka:<br><br>Just as a good mother loves her only child,<br>So toward all beings everywhere, have a good heart, loving and kind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.33" },
{ text: `Elder Posiya:<br><br>Not staying close is good — the wise always know this.<br>From the village to the forest, from the forest to the hut,<br>From there, rising, go forth without a backward glance, Posiya.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.34" },
{ text: `Elder Samaññakāni:<br><br>One seeking happiness obtains happiness if one acts rightly,<br>And moreover gains respect, fame increases.<br>One who practices the straight Noble Eightfold Path —<br>This is the way to the Deathless state.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.35" },
{ text: `Elder Son of Kuma:<br><br>Excellent is what is heard! Excellent is happy living!<br>Excellent is constant abiding in the homeless life!<br>Seeking the meaning of the true Dhamma, practicing with respect —<br>That is the ascetic practice of one who has nothing.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.36" },
{ text: `Elder Friend of Kuma's son:<br><br>Wandering many places with the practice of non-thinking,<br>Burning away jhāna — what is the use of wandering everywhere?<br>Therefore, stop agitation; without agitation, meditate.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.37" },
{ text: `Elder Tissa:<br><br>As if struck by a sword, as if one's head is on fire,<br>A bhikkhu who has gone forth should, mindful, abandon sensual desire.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.39" },
{ text: `Elder Sirivaḍḍha:<br><br>Between Vebhara and Paṇḍava, lightning strikes the cave entrance.<br>The son of the peerless one — thus he still sits in meditation.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.41" },
{ text: `Elder Sumaṅgala:<br><br>Well released! Well released indeed!<br>Truly I am well released from three crooked things:<br>From sickles, from ploughs, from hoes.<br>If there is this, there is this — enough disgust, enough disgust!<br>O Sumaṅgala! Meditate, O Sumaṅgala! O Sumaṅgala, live heedfully!`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.43" },
{ text: `Elder Ramaṇīyavihāri:<br><br>Like a good thoroughbred, well-trained, of good breed,<br>Having stumbled, stands up again, steady.<br>I possess right view, a disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.45" },
{ text: `Elder Samiddhi:<br><br>With faith, I went forth from home to homelessness.<br>My mindfulness and wisdom grow, my mind is concentrated.<br>Whatever form you produce, it does not frighten me.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.46" },
{ text: `Elder Ujjaya:<br><br>Homage to the Buddha, the hero, released everywhere.<br>In his conduct, including the scriptures,<br>I live without taints, no longer bound.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.47" },
{ text: `Elder Sañjaya:<br><br>From the time I went forth from home to homelessness,<br>I have not entertained worldly thoughts,<br>Unwholesome thoughts connected with anger.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.48" },
{ text: `Elder Rāmaṇeyyaka:<br><br>Though people shout, though birds make noise,<br>My mind is not agitated; I delight in solitude.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.49" },
{ text: `Elder Vimala:<br><br>Earth and rain water, wind blowing cool,<br>Lightning streaks across the sky — my thoughts are calmed, my mind is truly concentrated.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.50" },
{ text: `Elder Ghoḍika:<br><br>The rain sings as if to music. I am in my hut,<br>Sheltered from the wind, living happily,<br>My mind well concentrated. Rain if you wish.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.51" },
{ text: `Elder Kuṭivihāri:<br><br>Who is in the hut? A bhikkhu free from greed,<br>His mind well concentrated. Know him, O good sir,<br>The hut you built is not in vain.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.56" },
{ text: `Elder Kuṭivihāri (2):<br><br>This hut is old. You want a new hut.<br>Give up wanting a hut; a new hut brings new suffering.<br>Know this, O bhikkhu!`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.57" },
{ text: `Elder Rāmaṇīyakuṭika:<br><br>My hut is beautiful, donated by faithful donors,<br>With joyful mind, with faith they gave.<br>I have no need for young women — go, you women,<br>Go to those who need you.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.58" },
{ text: `Elder Kosalavihāri:<br><br>With faith, I went forth, living homeless.<br>In the forest, a hut was built for me.<br>I live heedfully, ardent, mindful, clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.59" },
{ text: `Elder Vappa:<br><br>One who sees, sees; the seer sees the non-seer.<br>One who does not see, does not see; the non-seer sees the seer.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.61" },
{ text: `Elder Vajjiputta:<br><br>We live alone in the wilderness,<br>Like a log discarded in the forest.<br>But many people love this life of mine,<br>Like those fallen into hell love the celestial realm.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.62" },
{ text: `Elder Pakkha:<br><br>They fall, they descend — what is falling down.<br>Driven by greed, they come again and again.<br>My duty is done, I rejoice,<br>With happiness, I welcome happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.63" },
{ text: `Elder Ukkhepakata Vaccha:<br><br>Wealth accumulated over many months and years —<br>The work of Vaccha, now Vaccha throws it away.<br>Thus he teaches the laypeople,<br>Sitting properly in an honored seat, with vast joyful mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.65" },
{ text: `Elder Meghiya:<br><br>The Great Hero teaches, having crossed all phenomena.<br>I heard his teaching, live joyfully beside him.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.66" },
{ text: `Elder Ekadhamma Sāvaṇīya:<br><br>Taints are burnt, all existences uprooted,<br>The cycle of birth is ended. Now there is no more becoming.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.67" },
{ text: `Elder Ekudāniya:<br><br>A seer with higher mind, heedless, developing,<br>On the path of right knowledge, that one does not grieve,<br>Always peaceful, ever mindful.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.68" },
{ text: `Elder Channa:<br><br>Having heard the Dhamma, the great sweetness, the great Dhamma,<br>Taught by the All-Conquering One, I set foot on the path to the Deathless.<br>He is truly skilled in the path of destroying suffering.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.69" },
{ text: `Elder Puṇṇa:<br><br>Here virtue alone is the supreme Dhamma.<br>But one with wisdom is supreme.<br>One with virtue and wisdom conquers gods and humans.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.70" },
{ text: `Elder Vacchapāla:<br><br>If one sees the truth, wonderful, subtle,<br>With wisdom skillfully, with humble mind,<br>Living according to the virtue prescribed by the Buddha,<br>Nibbāna is not hard to attain for that one.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.71" },
{ text: `Elder Māṇava:<br><br>I saw an old person, a suffering sick person,<br>I saw a dead person, life exhausted.<br>Therefore I left, went forth,<br>Abandoning alluring, delightful sensual desires.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.73" },
{ text: `Elder Suyamāna:<br><br>With sensual desire, ill-will, dullness and drowsiness,<br>Restlessness and remorse, doubt — a bhikkhu completely without these five hindrances,<br>He has abandoned the five hindrances.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.74" },
{ text: `Elder Susārada:<br><br>Excellent is the vision of the trained one.<br>Doubt is cut off, wisdom increases.<br>Even a fool becomes wise — therefore it is good to associate with good people.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.75" },
{ text: `Elder Piyajañha:<br><br>When people are proud, lower yourself.<br>When people are low, lift up your mind.<br>Live where people do not want to live;<br>don't delight in delightful seats.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.76" },
{ text: `Elder Hatthārohaputta:<br><br>Formerly this mind wandered, went where it liked,<br>Where it delighted, where it was happy.<br>Now I restrain it with wise reflection,<br>As a hook restrains a wild elephant.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.77" },
{ text: `Elder Rakkhita:<br><br>All greed is abandoned, all hatred uprooted,<br>All delusion abandoned — I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.79" },
{ text: `Elder Ugga:<br><br>All kamma I have done, whether little or much,<br>All is destroyed. Now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.80" },
{ text: `Elder Samitigutta:<br><br>The evil I did in previous lives<br>Is experienced here — I feel its result.<br>The root of other kamma truly no longer exists.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.81" },
{ text: `Elder Sīha:<br><br>O Sīha, live not heedlessly,<br>Day and night not lazy, persevere in training.<br>Practice wholesome states, quickly abandon the accumulated body.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.83" },
{ text: `Elder Nīta:<br><br>All night you sleep, during the day you delight in company.<br>Can a fool living thus ever end suffering?`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.84", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.84" },
{ text: `Elder Sunāga:<br><br>Skilled in the mind's sign, knowing the taste of seclusion,<br>Meditating, mindful, careful, he attains non-worldly happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.85" },
{ text: `Elder Nāgita:<br><br>Outside here, wanderers teach other paths<br>Not like this path leading to Nibbāna.<br>The Blessed One teaches the Saṅgha,<br>The Teacher shows Nibbāna as in the palm of the hand.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.86", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.86" },
{ text: `Elder Pavittha:<br><br>Seeing the aggregates as they really are,<br>All existence is destroyed.<br>The cycle of birth and death is ended; now there is no more becoming.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.87" },
{ text: `Elder Ajjuna:<br><br>I can draw water from the dry land,<br>Like a great flood sweeping away, I enter the truth.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.88" },
{ text: `Elder Devasabha:<br><br>Having crossed the mud, returned from the abyss,<br>Freed from the flood, all conceit destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.89" },
{ text: `Elder Samiddatta:<br><br>The five aggregates are fully known,<br>Standing with roots cut off.<br>The end of suffering is attained; I have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.90" },
{ text: `Elder Paripuṇṇaka:<br><br>Though one may enjoy food with a hundred flavors like nectar,<br>It cannot compare with the meal I have today.<br>This is the wonderful Dhamma taught to me<br>By Gotama Buddha, the one of limitless vision.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.91", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.91" },
{ text: `Elder Vijaya:<br><br>For one whose taints are destroyed, not dependent on food,<br>His range is the Void, the Signless, liberation as well —<br>Like a bird in the sky, his footprint is hard to trace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.92", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.92" },
{ text: `Elder Eraka:<br><br>O Eraka, suffering indeed are sensual desires!<br>O Eraka, not blissful are sensual desires!<br>Whoever delights in sensual desires delights in suffering.<br>Whoever does not delight in sensual desires does not delight in suffering.<br>O Eraka, know thus!`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.93" },
{ text: `Elder Cakkhupāla:<br><br>Though I am blind, though my eyes are ruined,<br>Though the path I walk is rough with thorns,<br>I will walk that path myself, alone.<br>But I will not walk with such an evil-doer.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.95" },
{ text: `Elder Khandasumana:<br><br>Having given up one flower, I enjoyed eighty thousand years in heaven,<br>And the remaining five years I have lived at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.96", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.96" },
{ text: `Elder Tissa:<br><br>Abandoning a hundred bowls of gold and precious metal,<br>I take an ordinary clay bowl.<br>This is the second time I have been consecrated.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.97" },
{ text: `Elder Abhaya (2):<br><br>Seeing a form, one loses mindfulness;<br>Attending to a pleasing sign, the mind is affected,<br>It persists with delight, grows attached.<br>The taints increase, leading to the root of existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.98" },
{ text: `Elder Uttiya:<br><br>Hearing a sound, one loses mindfulness;<br>Attending to a pleasing sign, the mind is affected,<br>It persists with delight, grows attached.<br>The taints increase, leading to defiled wandering.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.99" },
{ text: `Elder Devasabha (II):<br><br>Accomplished in right striving, practicing on the foundations of mindfulness,<br>Filled with the flower of liberation, he will attain cessation, taintless.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.100" },
{ text: `Elder Belatthakāni:<br><br>Leaving the household life, duty not yet done,<br>Using the mouth as a plough, belly full, lazy,<br>Like a great pig, food abundant —<br>The lazy one repeatedly goes to the womb.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.101" },
{ text: `Elder Setuccha:<br><br>Deceived by conceit, mind defiled in action,<br>Agitated by gain and loss — they do not attain jhāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.102" },
{ text: `Elder Bandhura:<br><br>I have no need for this or that.<br>I live happily, enjoying the taste of the Dhamma.<br>Having drunk the supreme, first sweetness,<br>I will not associate with poison.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.103", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.103" },
{ text: `Elder Khitaka:<br><br>My body is light, touched by great joy and bliss.<br>Like cotton blown by the wind, my body floats.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.104" },
{ text: `Elder Māḷitavambha:<br><br>I do not want to dwell when I am displeased.<br>Where there is pleasure, I leave immediately.<br>Where the goal is — not unrelated — there one with vision can dwell.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.105" },
{ text: `Elder Suhemanta:<br><br>Where a hundred characters and signs are contained,<br>The fool sees one part, the wise sees a hundred parts.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.106" },
{ text: `Elder Dhammasava:<br><br>Having reflected, I went forth homeless.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.107" },
{ text: `Elder Saṅgharakkhita:<br><br>Though one lives alone, with loving-kindness and compassion<br>Of one who has considered the supreme happiness,<br>He still does not think of the Teacher's instruction.<br>Thus he lives with raw faculties, like a young doe in the forest.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.109" },
{ text: `Elder Usabha:<br><br>Trees grow tall when irrigated by high rain clouds,<br>With new rain they become green and strong.<br>For Usabha, delighting in seclusion, aware of the forest,<br>That one produces many good things.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.110", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.110" },
{ text: `Elder Jenta:<br><br>Hard is the homeless life, hard is the household life.<br>Profound is the Dhamma, hard to find is wealth.<br>Choosing this life over that is difficult,<br>When the mind constantly contemplates impermanence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.111", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.111" },
{ text: `Elder Vacchagotta:<br><br>I have attained the three knowledges, attained great concentration,<br>Skilled in mind-stilling, I have reached the goal.<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.112", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.112" },
{ text: `Elder Vanavaccha:<br><br>Under the rocky cliff, cold water flows,<br>Monkeys and deer live nearby.<br>Covered with plants and trees — these mountains please me.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.113", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.113" },
{ text: `Elder Adhimutta:<br><br>In the conduct of mind directed toward abandoning,<br>With this coarse, heavy body,<br>If one desires to enjoy the pleasures of the body,<br>How can one fulfill the ascetic's practice?`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.114" },
{ text: `Elder Mahānāma:<br><br>Look, how the world ends right here,<br>With this many-peaked mountain, this forest?<br>The Nesaādaka mountain, a mountain of renown,<br>Covered with grass and trees, all hidden.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.115", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.115" },
{ text: `Elder Parāpariya:<br><br>Abandoning the six sense spheres, well-restrained at the sense doors,<br>The root of evil uprooted — I have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.116", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.116" },
{ text: `Elder Vajjiputta:<br><br>Go to the forest dense with roots,<br>Let Nibbāna sink deep into your mind.<br>O Gotama! Practice jhāna —<br>What is this bustling activity to you?`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.119", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.119" },
{ text: `Elder Isidatta:<br><br>The five aggregates are fully known, standing with roots cut off.<br>The end of suffering is attained — I have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.120" },
{ text: `Elder Uttara:<br><br>Nothing that exists remains forever;<br>No conditioned thing persists eternally.<br>Aggregates arise and cease in another existence.<br><br>Knowing this danger, I do not long for existence.<br>Abandoning all sensual desires, I attain the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.1" },
{ text: `Elder Piṇḍola Bhāradvāja:<br><br>Living this life is not without its rules,<br>But food does not come close to the heart.<br>Because there is food, the body survives.<br>Seeing this, I wander seeking food.<br><br>The wise have experienced that it is truly a mire.<br>Homage and offerings come from families.<br>Like a subtle arrow, hard to draw out,<br>So for a fool, honor is hard to abandon.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.2" },
{ text: `Elder Valliya:<br><br>In the small hut with five doors, a monkey enters,<br>Wandering around door by door, striking each moment!<br><br>Stop, monkey! Do not run like that.<br>You are no longer as before.<br>Wisdom holds you; you cannot go far as before.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.3" },
{ text: `Elder Gaṅgātīriya:<br><br>On the bank of the Ganges, using three palm leaves,<br>I built a little hut for myself.<br>My bowl is a pot used for offering milk to the dead,<br>My robe is sewn from dust-heap rags.<br><br>Living thus for two years, I spoke only one word.<br>In the third year, the mass of delusion was shattered.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.4" },
{ text: `Elder Ajina:<br><br>If one has attained the three knowledges, ended death, without taints,<br>Even so, one may not be known to people,<br>And fools, not knowing, might despise him.<br><br>When that person receives offerings of food and drink,<br>Even if of evil nature, they still respect him.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.5" },
{ text: `Elder Meḷajina:<br><br>When I heard the Dhamma taught by the Teacher,<br>I directly knew doubt — the All-Knowing, All-Conquering.<br><br>For the leader of the caravan, the great hero,<br>The supreme, unsurpassed among charioteers,<br>For the path, the way, I have no doubt.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.6" },
{ text: `Elder Rādha:<br><br>As rain penetrates a poorly thatched house,<br>So lust penetrates an undeveloped mind.<br><br>As rain does not penetrate a well-thatched house,<br>So lust does not penetrate a well-developed mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.7" },
{ text: `Elder Surādha:<br><br>My birth is ended, the teaching's victory is done,<br>The net of fame is destroyed, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>The goal of the homeless life, leaving home for homelessness,<br>That goal is attained, all fetters destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.8" },
{ text: `Elder Gotama:<br><br>Sages lie down, living happily and at ease.<br>They are not bound and dominated by women.<br>Women are always to be guarded and restrained.<br>The truth about women is hard to accept.<br><br>O sensual desires, I have killed you.<br>Now we have no debt to you.<br>We go now to the state called Nibbāna,<br>Going to that place without sorrow.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.9" },
{ text: `Elder Vasabha:<br><br>A brahmin is not by external beauty,<br>An orthodox brahmin must have inner beauty.<br>Whoever does evil deeds — he is the dark one, Sujā's husband.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.10" },
{ text: `Elder Mahācunda:<br><br>Good listening increases learning; learning increases wisdom.<br>By wisdom one knows the meaning; knowing the meaning brings happiness.<br><br>Dwell in remote places; live free from fetters.<br>If joy is not attained there, live among the Saṅgha,<br>Self-controlled, established in mindfulness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.11" },
{ text: `Elder Jotidāsa:<br><br>Those who use ropes, who rob in various ways,<br>Those cruel people who harm others —<br>Thus they cause harm, because kamma does not vanish.<br><br>Whatever kamma one does, good or evil,<br>One is the heir of that kamma, of the kamma one is doing.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.12" },
{ text: `Elder Heraññakāni:<br><br>Day and night pass, life diminishes,<br>Human life-span decays like water in a small stream.<br><br>The fool doing evil deeds does not understand his own action.<br>Afterwards he suffers when the evil ripens.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.13" },
{ text: `Elder Somamitta:<br><br>Like climbing a small plank on the ocean, one sinks;<br>So too, one of good conduct sinks when associating with others.<br>Therefore avoid the lazy, the indolent.<br><br>Live near the noble ones, the secluded, the energetic,<br>Meditative, always striving, the wise and clear-sighted.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.14" },
{ text: `Elder Mahākāla:<br><br>One who does not know thus, who creates a basis,<br>That fool goes on, experiencing suffering repeatedly.<br>Therefore one who knows should not create a basis.<br>I will not lie down with my head broken.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.16" },
{ text: `Elder Tissa:<br><br>Shaven-headed, wearing the robe, many enemies are there.<br>Receiving food, drink, clothing, and lodging.<br><br>Knowing this danger, knowing the great fear in honor and offerings,<br>A bhikkhu who has gone forth, receiving little, not greedy, always mindful.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.17" },
{ text: `Elder Kimbila:<br><br>In the Eastern Bamboo Grove, the Sakyan friends,<br>Having abandoned no small amount of wealth,<br>They delight in what they receive from their bowls.<br><br>Ardent, diligent, constantly energetic,<br>Delighting in the taste of the Dhamma, abandoning worldly pleasures.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.18" },
{ text: `Elder Nanda:<br><br>Through unwise attention, I adorned myself externally,<br>I was coarse, restless, infatuated with sensual desires.<br><br>With skillful means, the Kinsman of the Sun,<br>I was directed to the true purpose, which made me free from existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.19" },


{ text: `Elder Sirima:<br><br>Others praise that one,<br>The self not yet composed.<br>Others praise wrongly,<br>The self not yet composed.<br><br>Others criticize that one,<br>The self already composed.<br>Others criticize wrongly,<br>The self well composed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.20" },
{ text: `Elder Uttara:<br><br>I have fully understood the aggregates,<br>I have well uprooted craving,<br>I have developed the factors of enlightenment,<br>I have attained the destruction of taints.<br><br>Through fully understanding the aggregates,<br>I have escaped the one who sets the snare.<br>Having developed the factors of enlightenment,<br>I will attain Nibbāna,<br>The taints are destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.21" },
{ text: `Elder Sobhita:<br><br>A bhikkhu mindful, with wisdom and energy,<br>In one night I recalled five hundred aeons.<br><br>I developed the four establishments of mindfulness,<br>The seven factors of enlightenment, the noble eightfold path,<br>In one night I recalled five hundred aeons.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.23" },
{ text: `Elder Valliya:<br><br>The duties to be done with energy and diligence,<br>The duties to be done for one who wishes to awaken —<br>I will do them all, I will not backslide.<br>See my diligence, my effort!<br><br>Please tell me the path entering the Deathless.<br>With silent meditation I have attained noble silence,<br>Like the Ganges River entering the great ocean.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.24" },
{ text: `Elder Vitasoka:<br><br>Shave my head — the barber has come.<br>Taking a mirror, I observe my body.<br><br>The body is seen as empty, sunk in the darkness of night.<br>All bonds are cut; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.25" },
{ text: `Elder Puṇṇamāsa:<br><br>Abandoning the five hindrances, attaining security from bondage,<br>Holding the mirror of the true Dhamma, knowing and seeing oneself.<br><br>I contemplate this body, from within and without,<br>The body is seen as empty, inside and outside the body.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.26" },
{ text: `Elder Nandaka:<br><br>Like a good thoroughbred, of good breed, well trained,<br>Having fallen down, it struggles up again,<br>Gains more strength, does not abandon the load.<br><br>So, receive me, a disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One.<br>I possess right view, well trained, mature.<br>I am truly a legitimate son of the Perfectly Enlightened Buddha.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.27" },
{ text: `Elder Bharata:<br><br>Come, Nandaka, let us go together,<br>Let us go to the Teacher,<br>Let us roar the lion's roar before the supreme Buddha.<br><br>The seer, compassionate toward us, encouraged us to go forth.<br>We have attained the goal, all fetters are destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.28" },
{ text: `Elder Bhāradvāja:<br><br>Like lions in a mountain cave roaring the lion's roar,<br>So with wisdom, the hero, victorious over Māra and his army.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, honor the Dhamma and the Saṅgha,<br>I rejoice happily seeing the taintless one.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.29" },
{ text: `Elder Kaṇhadinna:<br><br>Serving the good person, always hearing the true Dhamma,<br>Having heard, I will step on the path to the Deathless.<br><br>In me, craving for existence is destroyed, craving for existence is no more.<br>Past and future are not in me,<br>The present also does not exist in me.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.30" },
{ text: `Elder Mīgasira:<br><br>From the time I went forth in the Dhamma of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Liberated, I advanced, I crossed the sensual realm.<br><br>Through the brahmin's contemplation, my mind was liberated.<br>I am liberated, unshaken, all fetters destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.31" },
{ text: `Elder Sīvaka:<br><br>Impermanent are the houses, built here and there.<br>Seeking the house-builder — birth is suffering.<br><br>O house-builder, you have been seen!<br>From now on you cannot build a house again.<br>All walls are broken, the roof is shattered.<br>The mind is driven from the stream, here it is blown away.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.32" },
{ text: `Elder Isidinnā:<br><br>I see laypeople holding the Dhamma in word only.<br>Sensual pleasures are impermanent, yet they love them,<br>Jewels and rings, they wait for wives and children.<br><br>Truly they do not know what the Dhamma is.<br>Even though they declare: 'Sensual pleasures are impermanent!'<br>They have no strength to cut off craving.<br>Therefore they long for wives, children, and wealth.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.34" },
{ text: `Elder Sambulakaccāna:<br><br>The rain pours down, the rain roars.<br>I live alone in a terrifying cave.<br>Though I live alone in a terrifying cave,<br>I am not frightened, not terrified,<br>No hair stands on end.<br><br>My Dhamma-nature is thus,<br>Therefore though I live alone in a terrifying cave,<br>I am not frightened, not terrified,<br>No hair stands on end.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.35" },
{ text: `Elder Nītaka:<br><br>The mind of craving, like a rock, stands firm, unshaken.<br>Toward delightful things, the mind has no craving.<br>Toward things that cause agitation, the mind is not agitated.<br>One whose mind is thus developed — from where can suffering come?<br><br>My mind, like a rock, stands firm, unshaken.<br>Toward delightful things, my mind has no craving.<br>Toward things that cause agitation, my mind is not agitated.<br>My mind is thus developed — from where can suffering come to me?`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.36" },
{ text: `Elder Soṇapoṭiriyaputta:<br><br>Teacher, do not sleep anymore,<br>With the night, the garland of stars.<br>This night, the wise one wakes up, does not sleep.<br><br>When the elephant attacks, falling from the elephant's back,<br>To die on the battlefield is better than living defeated.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.37", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.37" },
{ text: `Elder Nisabha:<br><br>Having abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Those truly delightful things that please the mind,<br>With faith, I went forth to make an end of suffering.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, mindful and clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.38" },
{ text: `Elder Kappatakura:<br><br>This is the rag robe of Kappatakura,<br>The robe covering him is truly too heavy.<br>In the Deathless bowl, filled with the true Dhamma,<br>Yet he does not practice the path of meditation.<br><br>O Kappata, do not wobble back and forth,<br>Do not make me strike sounds into your ears.<br>O Kappata, do not be a fool,<br>Sitting, wobbling back and forth in the assembled Saṅgha.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.40" },
{ text: `Elder Kumāra Kassapa:<br><br>O Buddha! O Dhamma! O accomplished Teacher!<br>Here, the disciple attains this true Dhamma.<br><br>Through countless aeons, I have produced this body.<br>This is the last body, this body's training is done.<br>On the path of life and death, now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.41" },
{ text: `Elder Dhammapāla:<br><br>A young bhikkhu who follows the Buddha's teaching,<br>Wakeful among those who sleep — his life is not in vain.<br><br>Therefore, the wise person, remembering the Buddha's words,<br>Develops faith and virtue, rejoicing in seeing the true Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.42", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.42" },
{ text: `Elder Brahmāli:<br><br>Those whose faculties have come to calm,<br>Well tamed by a charioteer,<br>Conceit destroyed, without taints —<br>Devas love those of such conduct.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.43" },
{ text: `Elder Mogharāja:<br><br>O Mogharāja, living in a hut of rough leaves,<br>With a good heart, always meditating in cold winter nights,<br>You are a bhikkhu. How then do you live? What will you do?<br><br>I have heard that in Magadha, a prosperous country,<br>All people live in plenty. Huts thatched with straw<br>Are far better than the comfortable life of other people.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.44", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.44" },
{ text: `Elder Visākha, son of Pañcāli:<br><br>Do not be conceited, do not despise others,<br>Not despising, not harming, one has gone to the far shore.<br>And do not praise yourself before the assemblies,<br>Unshaken, humble, speaking well, well-controlled.<br><br>One who sees the meaning, subtle and hidden,<br>Skilled in wisdom, well guarding one's conduct,<br>Living the Buddhas' virtue — for that one,<br>Nibbāna is not hard to attain.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.45" },
{ text: `Elder Cūḷaka:<br><br>Peacocks call, beautiful-crested, with lovely tail feathers,<br>Their necks bright blue, beaks beautiful, voices melodious.<br>This land is well covered with grass, well moistened with water,<br>Well covered by the sky, well covered by rain clouds.<br><br>The human body is well healthy, the mind good, practicing jhāna.<br>Excellent is the well-arisen mind in the Buddha's well-spoken teaching.<br>Experience the path leading to the Deathless,<br>That path is unsurpassed, the pure, healthy,<br>Subtle, fine path, well seen.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.46", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.46" },
{ text: `Elder Anupama:<br><br>The mind goes to delight and conceit, as if pierced by a sharp stake.<br>If one lives with such a mind, it is like living with a stake and rod.<br><br>O mind, I call you the breaker of happiness!<br>O mind, I call you the destroyer of my life!<br>Your Teacher, so hard to find, is now found.<br>Do not lead me to what is harmful to me!`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.47", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.47" },
{ text: `Elder Vajjita:<br><br>For a long time in saṃsāra, I have wandered in many realms.<br>I did not see the noble truths; I was a blind ordinary person.<br><br>With heedful conduct, I have broken through saṃsāra.<br>All realms of birth are cut off; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.48", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.48" },
{ text: `Elder Sandhita:<br><br>Under the Bodhi tree, with the light of green leaves,<br>As the tree was growing, in its strong vitality,<br>One perception of the Buddha's conduct — mindful, I attained it.<br><br>Thirty-one aeons have passed; I did not attain that perception before.<br>Now precisely through that perception, I have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.49" },
{ text: `Elder Aṅgaṇika Bhāradvāja:<br><br>In the forest I tended the sacred fire, following an incorrect tradition.<br>Not knowing the path of purity, following the austere practice of the Deathless.<br><br>With happiness, I attained happiness. See the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Formerly a brahmin's relative, now I am truly a brahmin.<br>I am consecrated with the three knowledges; I have attained security.<br>I rightly understand the true Dhamma; I have mastered the Buddha's word.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.1" },
{ text: `Elder Paccaya:<br><br>On the fifth day after my going forth, a learner, mind not yet attained,<br>I dwelt in seclusion, resolving thus:<br><br>'I will not eat or drink, I will not go outside the monastery,<br>I will not lie down, I will not lie on my side,<br>Until the dart of craving is drawn out.<br><br>'See my diligence — I lived thus.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.'`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.2" },
{ text: `Elder Bakula:<br><br>One who first intends to do something later —<br>That person destroys his own basis of happiness,<br>Later he experiences suffering in burning regret.<br><br>Speak only of what you do, not of what you don't.<br>The wise know the one who only speaks but does not act.<br><br>Nibbāna is wonderfully blissful, taught by the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Without sorrow, without greed, truly secure.<br>There, suffering is completely destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.3" },
{ text: `Elder Dhaniya:<br><br>If you desire happiness in the ascetic life,<br>Do not despise the Saṅgha's robe, do not despise the Saṅgha's food.<br><br>If you desire happiness in the ascetic life,<br>Use the dwelling like a snake or a rat.<br><br>If you desire happiness in the ascetic life,<br>Know contentment with anything,<br>And resolutely practice the one practice.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.4" },
{ text: `Elder Mātaṅgaputta:<br><br>'Oh, so cold! Oh, so hot! Oh, it's too late!'<br>With such lamentations, one abandons work,<br>And the precious moment passes by in silence.<br><br>One who thinks about cold and heat is no better than grass.<br>Doing human duties, one does not harm happiness.<br><br>With my chest I push back the dabba grass, the kusa grass,<br>The thorny grasses. I live developing seclusion.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.5" },
{ text: `Elder Khujja Sobhita:<br><br>Among the ascetics living in Pāṭaliputta —<br>Those skilled in debate, those of much learning —<br>There is an elder standing at the entrance,<br>Named Sobhita, deformed, hunchbacked.<br><br>Among the ascetics living in Pāṭaliputta —<br>Those skilled in debate, those of much learning —<br>There is an elder standing at the entrance.<br>He has come here, carried by the wind.<br><br>He fights well, he sacrifices well,<br>On the battlefield he has conquered.<br>With accumulated holy life, he has attained happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.6" },
{ text: `Elder Vāraṇa:<br><br>Whoever among people harms other beings,<br>That person harms himself in this life and the next.<br><br>But one with a compassionate heart, pitying all beings,<br>A person acting thus reaps abundant merit.<br><br>Learn to speak well, serve the ascetics,<br>Live alone secluded, with a peaceful mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.7" },
{ text: `Elder Vassika:<br><br>Though I alone have faith and wisdom among my relatives<br>Who have no faith, understanding the true Dhamma, endowed with virtue,<br>For the benefit and happiness of my relatives,<br><br>My relatives, out of love, I reproached.<br>Because they loved me, they did good to the bhikkhu.<br><br>When they passed away, they attained heavenly bliss.<br>My brothers and my mother rejoiced in what they desired.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.8" },
{ text: `Elder Yasoja:<br><br>Dark, lean, weak, full of veins,<br>Moderate in food, mind without distress.<br><br>In the great forest, bitten by flies and mosquitoes,<br>Like a battle elephant, I endure mindfully.<br><br>Living alone is like Brahmā, living with two is like devas,<br>Living with three is like a village, more is like a market.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.9" },
{ text: `Elder Sātimattiya:<br><br>The faith you once had is no longer in you.<br>What is yours remains yours; I have no evil conduct.<br><br>Impermanent and unsteady is your faith.<br>This is the seeing, this is my seeing.<br>Sometimes you love, then you dislike.<br>Why does the sage wither away here?<br><br>Food cooked for the sage, little by little from each family,<br>I will go for alms; my legs are still strong.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.10" },
{ text: `Elder Upāli:<br><br>Gone forth out of faith, a newly ordained novice,<br>Live with good friends, with pure life, not lazy.<br><br>Gone forth out of faith, a newly ordained novice,<br>A bhikkhu dwelling in the midst, wise, learn the Vinaya.<br><br>Gone forth out of faith, a newly ordained novice,<br>Knowing what should be done and what should not be done,<br>Let him live, not seeking honor.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.11" },
{ text: `Elder Uttarapāla:<br><br>I am truly good, reflecting on the wholesome goal,<br>Abandoning the five strands of sensual pleasure that delude the world.<br><br>Born in Māra's domain, struck by a strong arrow,<br>Yet I have escaped Māra's trap.<br><br>All sensual desires are destroyed, all existence is destroyed.<br>The path of birth and death is ended; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.12" },
{ text: `Elder Abhibhūta:<br><br>Hear, all relatives who have come here,<br>I teach the Dhamma to you: birth is suffering.<br><br>Strive, go forth, attend to the Buddha's word.<br>Defeat Māra's army like an elephant defeats a reed hut.<br><br>Whoever in this Dhamma and Discipline lives heedfully,<br>Abandoning the stream of rebirth, will end suffering.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.13" },
{ text: `Elder Gotama:<br><br>I was reborn in hell, then repeatedly in the ghost realm,<br>I lived many days in the suffering of the animal realm.<br><br>And I lived happily as a human, occasionally in heaven,<br>Dwelling in the form realm, formless realm,<br>Neither-perception-nor-non-perception.<br><br>I have well known existence — coreless, conditionally arisen,<br>Agitated, always changing, creating the self.<br>I have attained peaceful stillness, mindfully established.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.14" },
{ text: `Elder Harīta:<br><br>One who first intends to do something later —<br>That person destroys his own basis of happiness,<br>Later he experiences suffering in burning regret.<br><br>Speak only of what you do, not of what you don't.<br>The wise know the one who only speaks but does not act.<br><br>Nibbāna is truly blissful, taught by the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Without sorrow, without greed, truly secure.<br>There, suffering is completely destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.15" },
{ text: `Elder Vimala:<br><br>Avoid evil friends, associate with the noble ones.<br>Follow their advice, incline toward unshakable happiness.<br><br>Like climbing a small plank on the ocean, one sinks;<br>So too, one of good conduct sinks when associating with others.<br>Therefore avoid the lazy, the indolent.<br><br>Live near the noble ones, the secluded, the energetic,<br>Meditative, always striving, the wise and clear-sighted.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.16" },
{ text: `Elder Nāgasamāla:<br><br>Adorned, wearing fine clothes, wearing garlands, fragrant,<br>With sandalwood scent, in the crowd, on the main road,<br>A dancer was dancing, moving to the music.<br><br>I entered the city for alms, passing by, I saw her —<br>Adorned, wearing fine clothes, setting the snare of death.<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.1" },
{ text: `Elder Bhagu:<br><br>Overcome by drowsiness, I left the monastery,<br>Then walked back and forth on the walking path; there I fell to the ground.<br><br>Rubbing my hands and feet, I walked back and forth again.<br>Walking back and forth on the walking path, my mind became concentrated.<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sabhiya:<br><br>Others do not know that we are here for a time.<br>Here, the wise, knowing thus, live calm.<br><br>When they do not know, they act as if deathless.<br>When they know the Dhamma, among the sick, they are not sick.<br><br>One whose conduct is loose, whose precepts are defiled,<br>Whose holy life is dubious — such a one attains great fruit?<br><br>Living among fellow celibates, not respected, not honored,<br>That one is far from the true Dhamma, like the sky from the earth.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nandaka:<br><br>Disgusting, foul-smelling thing! Full of odor, stench!<br>Māra's possession, oozing with many streams,<br>This body has nine streams constantly flowing.<br><br>Do not despise the ancients! Do not offend the Tathāgata!<br>They do not long for the heavenly realm, let alone the human realm.<br><br>A fool, without wisdom, with evil intent, covered by delusion,<br>That one, full of greed, is thrown and bound by Māra.<br><br>Those who have escaped greed, hatred, and ignorance —<br>They are not greedy; the rope is cut, they are not bound.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.4" },
{ text: `Elder Jambuka:<br><br>For fifty-five years, my body covered with dust,<br>Eating once a month, plucking out my hair and beard.<br><br>I stood on one foot, I did not use a bed.<br>I ate dried excrement, I did not accept invitations.<br><br>My conduct was such that it led me to a bad destination.<br>I was swept away by the great flood until I went to the Buddha.<br><br>See the Buddha to whom I went for refuge!<br>See the Dhamma, the Dhamma-nature!<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.5" },
{ text: `Elder Senaka:<br><br>It was truly good for me when, in Gaya city,<br>In the spring festival month called Phagguna,<br>I saw the Perfectly Enlightened One teaching the supreme Dhamma.<br><br>The one of great radiance, the Teacher of the assembly,<br>Attained to the supreme state, the leader of the host,<br>Victorious over the deva and human realms,<br>The seer, hard to fathom.<br><br>The great elephant, the great hero,<br>The great light, taintless, all taints destroyed,<br>The Teacher, fearless.<br><br>For a long time I was defiled, bound by wrong view.<br>Now that Blessed One has liberated Senaka<br>From all bonds; he is autonomous, liberated.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.6" },
{ text: `Elder Sambhūta:<br><br>One who, when he should go slowly, goes quickly,<br>One who, when he should go quickly, goes slowly —<br>That fool, lacking right method, goes to suffering.<br><br>His benefit diminishes like the moon in the dark fortnight.<br>He meets disgrace and opposes his friends.<br><br>One who, when he should go slowly, goes slowly,<br>One who, when he should go quickly, goes quickly —<br>That wise one, with right method, goes to happiness.<br><br>His benefit is fulfilled like the moon in the bright fortnight.<br>He gains fame and honor, not opposing his friends.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.7" },
{ text: `Elder Rāhula:<br><br>My taints are destroyed, there is no more renewed existence.<br>I am an Arahant, worthy of offerings.<br>I have attained the three knowledges, seen the Deathless state.<br><br>Blinded by sensual desires, covered by the net of wrong views,<br>Craving acts as a veil, covering and hiding.<br>Bound by heedlessness, like a fish caught in a net.<br><br>I have crossed over those desires, cut Māra's bonds,<br>Uprooted the root of craving, I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.8" },
{ text: `Elder Candana:<br><br>Covered with gold, surrounded by maidservants,<br>Carrying her young child, my wife came to me.<br><br>Seeing the mother of my child coming from afar,<br>Well adorned and beautiful, like Māra setting a snare.<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.9" },
{ text: `Elder Dhammika:<br><br>Dhamma protects and guards one who practices the true Dhamma.<br>Dhamma brings happiness to one who well practices the Dhamma.<br>These are the benefits when the Dhamma is well practiced.<br>One who practices the true Dhamma does not go to a bad destination.<br><br>Dhamma and non-Dhamma do not have the same result.<br>Non-Dhamma leads to hell; Dhamma leads to a good destination.<br><br>Therefore, arouse desire for the true Dhamma, practice it,<br>With joyful mind, well come thus.<br>Established in the true Dhamma, a disciple of the Well-Gone One,<br>Wise, advancing, goes to the supreme refuge.<br><br>Breaking the root of the boil, uprooting the net of craving,<br>The round of rebirth is ended, there is no more basis.<br>Like the moon on the full moon night, in the clear, bright night.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.10" },
{ text: `Elder Sabbaka:<br><br>When I saw the heron spreading its pure white wings,<br>Frightened by the dark cloud, seeking a hidden shelter —<br>Then the Ajakaraṇī river gave me joy.<br><br>When I saw the heron spreading its pure white wings,<br>Frightened by the dark cloud, seeking a cave for shelter,<br>But finding none — then the Ajakaraṇī river gave me joy.<br><br>Who would not delight, seeing here on both banks<br>Jambu trees lining the river, making the shore radiant,<br>Behind the great cave?<br><br>Listen to the frogs, well escaped from the snakes,<br>Calling out joyfully with gentle sounds:<br>'Now is not the time to indulge in forest streams.'<br>The Ajakaraṇī river is truly safe, comfortable, peaceful —<br>How delightful!`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.11" },
{ text: `Elder Mudita:<br><br>To save my life, I went forth in the ascetic life.<br>I received full ordination, thereby gaining faith.<br>I persisted with energy, I advanced ardently.<br><br>Though this body is destroyed, though piece by piece the flesh decays,<br>Though the joints of the knees and the shins make me fall,<br><br>I will not eat or drink, I will not go outside the monastery,<br>I will not lie down, I will not lie on my side,<br>Until the dart of craving is drawn out.<br><br>See my diligence — I lived thus.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.12" },
{ text: `Elder Rājadatta:<br><br>A bhikkhu went to a charnel ground,<br>He saw a woman's body thrown there,<br>Discarded in the cemetery, a feast for worms.<br><br>Some, disgusted, seeing the miserable dead body,<br>In me, sensual desire arose; blind, I was bound.<br><br>Faster than boiling rice overflows, from there I departed.<br>Mindful, clearly comprehending, I came and sat to one side.<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.1" },
{ text: `Elder Subhūta:<br><br>Placing oneself in a place not considered suitable,<br>A person who wants to do a task but does not succeed —<br>That task is considered a failure.<br><br>If one abandons the winning stake, the root of suffering is drawn out.<br>It is like a gambler who, with bad luck, throws away the die.<br>If he throws away everything, he is no different from a blind man,<br>Not seeing the path, level or uneven.<br><br>Speak only of what you do, not of what you don't.<br>The wise know the one who only speaks but does not act.<br><br>Like a beautiful flower, colorful but without fragrance,<br>So well-spoken words are fruitful when acted upon.<br><br>Like a beautiful flower, colorful but also fragrant,<br>So well-spoken words are fruitless if not acted upon.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.2" },
{ text: `Elder Girimānanda:<br><br>The rain sings like a well-sung song with melody.<br>I sit in my hut, happy, sheltered.<br>There I dwell, comfortable and at peace.<br>O deva of rain, if you wish, rain, rain!<br><br>The rain sings like a well-sung song with melody.<br>I sit in my hut, happy, sheltered.<br>There I dwell, my mind truly calmed.<br>O deva of rain, if you wish, rain, rain!<br><br>The rain sings like a well-sung song with melody.<br>I sit in my hut, happy, sheltered.<br>There I dwell, my mind free from greed.<br>O deva of rain, if you wish, rain, rain!<br><br>The rain sings like a well-sung song with melody.<br>I sit in my hut, happy, sheltered.<br>There I dwell, my mind free from hatred.<br>O deva of rain, if you wish, rain, rain!<br><br>The rain sings like a well-sung song with melody.<br>I sit in my hut, happy, sheltered.<br>There I dwell, my mind free from delusion.<br>O deva of rain, if you wish, rain, rain!`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.3" },
{ text: `Elder Sumana:<br><br>What the Teacher wished, I understood in the true Dhamma.<br>For me, aspiring to the Deathless, what had to be done is done.<br><br>I have attained the Dhamma, realized it myself, not just by hearsay.<br>My knowledge is purified, there is no more doubt.<br>May I stand near you and speak of my direct knowledge.<br><br>I know my former lives, my divine eye is purified.<br>I have attained the goal; done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Training, not heedless, well hearing your instruction,<br>I have destroyed all taints; now there is no more renewed existence.<br><br>You taught me noble virtue; compassionately you protected me.<br>Your teaching was not in vain; I am your disciple, learning from you.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.4" },
{ text: `Elder Vaḍḍha:<br><br>Excellent was my mother who urged and encouraged me.<br>Hearing her advice, taught by my mother,<br>I became diligent, energetic, attaining supreme enlightenment.<br><br>I am worthy of offerings, with three knowledges, seeing the Deathless.<br>I have attained the state of an Arahant, worthy of offerings,<br>I have attained the three knowledges, seen the Deathless state,<br>I have conquered Māra's army; I live without taints.<br><br>All taints, internal and external, that were previously in me —<br>All are uprooted, they will not arise again.<br><br>Suffering is ended, this is the last body,<br>The path of birth and death is cut off; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nādīkassapa:<br><br>Truly it was beneficial for me that the Buddha came here,<br>To the river called Nerañjarā.<br>I heard his teaching, and my wrong views were destroyed.<br><br>I performed sacrifices, recited sacrificial chants,<br>I kindled the sacred fire, poured offerings into the fire,<br>Thinking I was purified — truly I was a blind worldling.<br><br>Wandering in the forest of wrong views, blinded by rites and rituals,<br>Not pure, thinking I was pure — blind, I did not see.<br><br>I have destroyed wrong views, broken all existence,<br>I kindle the fire, worthy of offerings,<br>I bow down in homage to the Tathāgata, the Tamer.<br><br>All delusion is destroyed, craving for existence is shattered,<br>The path of birth and death is cut off; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.6" },
{ text: `Elder Gayākassapa:<br><br>Morning, noon, evening — three times a day<br>I descended into the Gayā river, the Gayā Phaggū.<br><br>Whatever evil I did in previous lives,<br>Here I wash away — such was my former belief.<br><br>Hearing the well-spoken words, the path full of Dhamma and meaning,<br>With true meaning, I reflected wisely.<br><br>I have washed away all evil; I am unstained, pure.<br>I am pure, completely pure, heir of the pure one.<br>I am indeed the son, the legitimate son of the Buddha.<br><br>Plunging into the eightfold stream, I have washed away all evil.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.7" },
{ text: `Elder Vakkali:<br><br>Afflicted by a wind disease, you live in the deep forest,<br>With limited alms-gathering, lean and weak.<br>What will a bhikkhu do with such a body?<br><br>My body is flooded with spreading joy and bliss.<br>Even though lean, I will live in the forest.<br><br>Developing the four establishments of mindfulness,<br>The five faculties and the five powers,<br>Developing the factors of enlightenment, I will live in the forest.<br><br>Seeing fellow practitioners living harmoniously, strong,<br>Constantly persevering with energy, I will live in the forest.<br><br>Recollecting the Buddha, the supreme Tamer, in meditation,<br>Day and night not lazy, I will live in the forest.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.8" },
{ text: `Elder Vijitasena:<br><br>I will restrain you like a door restrains an elephant.<br>I will not urge you, O mind, toward evil.<br>You are the net of sensual desire, you are born from the body.<br><br>Restraining you, not going, like an elephant without an open door,<br>O mind, you sorcerer, though you try again and again,<br>You will no longer wander, delighting in doing evil.<br><br>Like one holding a hook, constantly restraining an untrained elephant,<br>Like one using force to reform the unwilling —<br>So toward you, I will reform you.<br><br>Like a perfect wheel, like a well-trained horse,<br>So I will tame you, relying on the five powers.<br><br>I will tie you tightly with firm mindfulness.<br>Having tamed myself, I will tame you.<br>Through the weight of energy, I will pressure you.<br>Therefore, O mind, you will not stray from me.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.9" },
{ text: `Elder Yasodatta:<br><br>With a mind inclined to criticism, a fool hearing the teaching<br>Of the conqueror — that person with such an attitude<br>Is far from the true Dhamma, as the earth from the sky.<br><br>With a mind inclined to criticism, a fool hearing the teaching<br>Of the conqueror — that person with such an attitude<br>Declines, far from the true Dhamma, like the moon in the dark fortnight.<br><br>With a mind inclined to criticism, a fool hearing the teaching<br>Of the conqueror — that person with such an attitude<br>Dries up in the true Dhamma, like a fish in shallow water.<br><br>With a mind inclined to criticism, a fool hearing the teaching<br>Of the conqueror — that person with such an attitude<br>Does not grow in the true Dhamma, like rotten seed in a field.<br><br>One whose mind is satisfied, hearing the noble one's teaching,<br>Abandons all taints, attains the unshaken,<br>Reaches supreme peace, attains taintless Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.10" },
{ text: `Elder Soṇakuṭikaṇṇa:<br><br>I received full ordination, I am liberated, without taints.<br>I saw the Blessed One, I lived in the monastery.<br><br>The Blessed One, for many days, lived out in the open.<br>The Teacher, well established, then entered the monastery.<br><br>Gotama laid down, spreading his outer robe,<br>Like a lion in a rocky cave, all fear destroyed.<br><br>Well selecting good words, a disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Before the excellent Buddha, Soṇa taught the sublime Dhamma.<br><br>Fully understanding the five aggregates subject to clinging,<br>Developing the noble path, attaining supreme peace,<br>Attaining taintless Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.11" },
{ text: `Elder Kosiya:<br><br>One who understands the words of the Teachers,<br>The wise person, dwelling, arouses loving remembrance.<br>The wise person, having faith, knows the supreme in the Dhamma.<br><br>When a great calamity arises, reflecting, not paralyzed,<br>The wise person, with persistence, knows the supreme in the Dhamma.<br><br>One who stands firm like the ocean, without desire, with deep wisdom,<br>Sees the true meaning, subtle and wonderful —<br>The wise person, unshaken, knows the supreme in the Dhamma.<br><br>One of much learning, bearing the Dhamma, practicing Dhamma and in accordance with Dhamma,<br>The wise call him 'such', knowing the supreme in the Dhamma.<br><br>One who understands the meaning of the words, knowing the meaning, practices accordingly,<br>The wise call him 'one of inner meaning', knowing the supreme in the Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.12" },
{ text: `Elder Uruvelakassapa:<br><br>Seeing the psychic powers of Gotama renowned,<br>I was not yet subdued, deceived by envy and conceit.<br><br>The Tamer of humans, knowing my thoughts,<br>Questioned me — I was startled, wonderfully hair-raising.<br><br>Formerly I was a matted-hair ascetic, with petty psychic powers.<br>Seeing them as useless, I went forth to the Buddha.<br><br>Formerly I was content with sacrifices, regarding the sensual realm as supreme.<br>Later I completely uprooted greed, hatred, and delusion.<br><br>I know my former lives, my divine eye is pure.<br>I have psychic knowledge of others' minds; I have attained the divine ear.<br><br>For the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>That goal I have attained — all fetters are destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.1" },
{ text: `Elder Tekicchakāri:<br><br>The rice is harvested, the grain is beaten and pounded,<br>But there is not even one morsel — what shall I do?<br><br>Recollect the immeasurable Buddha! The mind becomes joyful and at ease,<br>The body suffused with joyful feeling, always inspired.<br><br>Recollect the immeasurable Dhamma! The mind becomes joyful and at ease,<br>The body suffused with joyful feeling, always inspired.<br><br>Recollect the immeasurable Saṅgha! The mind becomes joyful and at ease,<br>The body suffused with joyful feeling, always inspired.<br><br>Living outside in the open — these nights are cold.<br>Do not let the cold harm you! Enter the monastery,<br>With the door closed and bolted.<br><br>I will experience the four immeasurable minds,<br>I will live happily with such thoughts.<br>The cold does not harm me; I live unshaken.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.2" },
{ text: `Elder Mahānāga:<br><br>Those who have no respect for fellow celibates —<br>They decline in the true Dhamma, like fish in shallow water.<br><br>Those who have no respect for fellow celibates —<br>They do not grow in the true Dhamma, like rotten seed in a field.<br><br>Those who have no respect for fellow celibates —<br>They are far from Nibbāna, in the teaching of the Dhamma King.<br><br>Those who have respect for fellow celibates —<br>They do not decline in the true Dhamma, like fish in abundant water.<br><br>Those who have respect for fellow celibates —<br>They grow in the true Dhamma, like good seed in a field.<br><br>Those who have respect for fellow celibates —<br>They are close to Nibbāna, in the teaching of the Dhamma King.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.3" },
{ text: `Elder Kulla:<br><br>Kulla went to the charnel ground, saw a woman discarded there,<br>Thrown in the cemetery, a feast for worms.<br><br>Kulla, look at the body, diseased, foul, stinking,<br>Oozing, dripping — delighted in by fools.<br><br>Taking the mirror of the Dhamma, attaining right view,<br>I contemplate this body — empty within and without.<br><br>As this is, so is that; as that is, so is this.<br>As below, so above; as above, so below.<br><br>As by day, so by night; as by night, so by day.<br>As before, so after; as after, so before.<br><br>Such a person does not delight even in the five kinds of musical instruments,<br>When one-pointed, rightly meditating on the Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.4" },
{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta:<br><br>Some live heedlessly, craving like a creeper grows.<br>They wander floating, from this life to the next,<br>Like a monkey in the forest, lusting after fruits.<br><br>This wretched craving poisons the whole world.<br>When it conquers anyone, it makes sorrow grow,<br>No different from wild grass spreading and thriving.<br><br>Whoever subdues this wretched, hard-to-conquer craving,<br>Sorrow falls away from that one, like a water drop on a lotus.<br><br>Now that you have come here, I teach you this good thing:<br>Dig up the root of craving, like seeking a sweet root of usīra grass.<br>Do not let Māra, like a stream, destroy you, a reed.<br>Thus continuously, forever.<br><br>Act on the Buddha's teaching; do not let the moment pass.<br>If the moment passes, you will grieve, suffering the result in hell.<br><br>Heedlessness is dust; dust comes from heedlessness.<br>With heedfulness and clear knowledge, draw out the dart from me.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.5" },
{ text: `Eler Sappadāsa:<br>Twenty-five years have passed since my going forth,<br>Yet in the snap of a finger, I did not attain peace of mind.<br><br>Not attaining one-pointedness, overwhelmed by sensual desire,<br>Wringing my hands, I lamented and left the monastery.<br><br>I will bring a knife — what is the meaning of my life?<br>My training has been abandoned; better for me to die.<br><br>Then I took the knife, I went to my sleeping place.<br>The knife was drawn out, to cut my own throat.<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.6" },
{ text: `Elder Kātiyāna:<br><br>O Kātiyāna, wake up, sit up!<br>Do not sleep too much; awaken yourself!<br>O heedless relatives, the passive, the lazy —<br>Do not let Death deceive and conquer you.<br><br>Like waves covering the great ocean,<br>So birth and old age cover and bury you.<br>Make yourself a safe island,<br>For no one else can serve and help you as a refuge.<br><br>The Teacher has laid down the path crossing beyond bonds,<br>Crossing beyond the fear of birth and old age.<br>In the evening and in the morning, live heedfully,<br>Attentive, persisting, in devoted effort.<br><br>Abandoning former bonds, wearing the outer robe,<br>Head shaven smooth, eating almsfood,<br>Do not delight in playing, do not indulge in sleeping.<br>Strive in meditation, O Kātiyāna!<br><br>Meditate, be victorious, O Kātiyāna!<br>Be skilled in the path, secure from bonds.<br>Attain supreme purity, you will attain Nibbāna,<br>Like water extinguishing fire.<br><br>Light is produced, the radiance is still weak,<br>Like a reed bent down by the wind.<br>O relative of Suda, do not grasp thus!<br>Expel Māra, dispassionate toward all feelings,<br>Wait for your time! Here you will be cooled.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.7" },
{ text: `Elder Migajāla:<br><br>Well spoken by the one with eyes, the radiance still weak,<br>All fetters are crossed, all wandering is destroyed.<br><br>The Dhamma leads onward, dries up the root of evil,<br>Cuts off the root of poison, destroys evil, attains peace.<br><br>Breaking the root of ignorance, ending the kamma of existence,<br>The diamond of knowledge shatters all clinging of consciousness.<br><br>Feelings are exposed, grasping is liberated,<br>Existence is like a pit of glowing coals, seen by wisdom.<br><br>The great one, well profound, stops old age and death,<br>The Noble Eightfold Path, the cessation of suffering, good fortune.<br><br>Knowing kamma as kamma, knowing the result of kamma as the result,<br>Thus seeing, contemplating phenomena arisen from conditions,<br>Leads to great security, peace, ultimate good.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.8" },
{ text: `Elder Jenta Purohitaputta:<br><br>I was intoxicated with pride in birth, wealth,<br>Even in power, position, and beauty.<br>I lived thus with conceit, with attachment and infatuation.<br><br>I was exceedingly proud, thinking no one equal to me,<br>Deluded, overly conceited, arrogant and haughty.<br><br>To mother, father, and others who were honored and respected,<br>I paid homage to no one, proud, without deference.<br><br>Seeing the foremost leader, the supreme Tamer,<br>Radiant like the sun, leading the assembly of bhikkhus,<br><br>Casting off conceit and pride, with truly peaceful mind,<br>With my head I bow to the supreme among beings.<br><br>Over-conceit, inferior conceit — abandoning, uprooting,<br>Conceit is cut off, all kinds of conceit destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.9" },


{ text: `Elder Sumana:<br><br>From the great lake named Anotatta,<br>I brought water back for my teacher.<br>Seeing this, the Teacher said of me:<br><br>'O Sāriputta, look at this young boy coming,<br>Carrying a pot of water, his mind well concentrated.<br>With a lovely task, his conduct truly pure.<br><br>'The novice disciple of Anuruddha<br>Has psychic power and might, mature and skilled.<br><br>'Tamed by the great tamer, well-behaved by the well-behaved,<br>Trained by Anuruddha, he has done what had to be done.<br><br>'Attaining supreme purity, attaining the unshaken,<br>The novice Sumana wishes: "Let no one know me."'`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.10" },
{ text: `Elder Nhātakamuni:<br><br>Afflicted by a wind disease, you live in the deep forest,<br>With limited alms-gathering, lean and weak.<br>What will a bhikkhu do with such a body?<br><br>My body is flooded with spreading joy and bliss.<br>Even though lean, I will live in the forest.<br><br>Developing the seven factors of enlightenment,<br>The five faculties and the five powers,<br>Possessing subtle jhāna, I live without taints.<br><br>Freed from the fetters, mind pure, unstained,<br>Always, well contemplating, I live without taints.<br><br>All taints, internal and external, that were previously in me —<br>All are cut off, they will not arise again.<br><br>The five aggregates are fully understood,<br>They stand with roots cut off.<br>The end of suffering is attained; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.11" },
{ text: `Elder Brahmadatta:<br><br>From where does anger arise toward one who is not angry,<br>Toward one who is tamed, living a balanced life?<br>Toward one who is liberated, one should be thus peaceful.<br><br>Whoever, when abused, abuses in return,<br>That person is worse than the one who abused first.<br>Whoever, when abused, does not abuse in return,<br>That person has won a victory on both fronts.<br><br>That person's conduct benefits both oneself and others.<br>Knowing another's anger, mindful, one calms down.<br><br>He is the doctor for both himself and the other.<br>People think him a fool, not understanding the true Dhamma.<br><br>If anger arises, think of the saw simile.<br>If greed arises, think of the son's flesh simile.<br><br>If your mind runs after sensual desires and existence,<br>Quickly seize it with mindfulness, like seizing a wild beast<br>That has entered the rice field.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.12" },
{ text: `Elder Sirimanda:<br><br>Rain is heavy on a covered fault.<br>Rain is not heavy on an exposed fault.<br>Where there is no exposure of fault, thus the rain is not heavy.<br><br>The world is oppressed by death, surrounded, encircled,<br>Pierced by the dart of craving, constantly infatuated by desires.<br><br>The world is oppressed by death and surrounded by old age,<br>Constantly harmed, never at peace, like bandits with sticks and swords.<br><br>They come like a mass of fire — death, disease, and old age.<br>No force can resist them, no speed can escape.<br><br>Do not let the day be empty; do a little or much.<br>The night is also wasted, life is shortened.<br><br>Therefore, whether walking, standing, sitting, or lying down,<br>The final night is drawing near — you have no time for heedlessness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.13" },
{ text: `Elder Sabbhakāma:<br><br>This two-footed creature is impure and foul-smelling,<br>Filled with various corpses, from which water oozes.<br><br>Deer are caught with traps, fish with hooks,<br>Monkeys with pits — ordinary people are caught like that.<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, scents, touches,<br>Desirable and pleasing — these five strands of sensual pleasure<br>Are known in the form of women.<br><br>Ordinary people, infatuated in mind, chase after women's forms,<br>Increasing the fearsome cemetery, accumulating renewed existence.<br><br>One who avoids women's forms as one avoids a snake's head with one's foot,<br>Mindful, crosses over the world's poisoner.<br><br>Seeing the danger in sensual pleasures, security in renunciation,<br>Escaping all sensual pleasures, I have attained the destruction of taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.14" },
{ text: `Elder Sundara-Samudda:<br><br>Adorned, wearing fine clothes, wearing garlands, decorated,<br>Her feet painted red, a courtesan wearing sandals,<br><br>Pulling off her sandals, folding her hands before her,<br>With a gentle voice, she began to speak to me:<br><br>'Young man who has gone forth, stop, take my domain.<br>Enjoy the five sensual pleasures, I will give you means.<br>I promise you truth, I bring you an oath of fire.<br><br>'When you and I are old, both leaning on sticks,<br>Both going forth, we will share good fortune.'<br><br>Seeing that courtesan, with folded hands pleading,<br>Adorned, wearing fine clothes, like Death setting a snare,<br><br>Then I reflected wisely, arousing right thought.<br>The danger appeared; disgusted, I became established.<br><br>And my mind was liberated — such is the Dhamma-nature.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 7.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag7.1" },
{ text: `Elder Lakuṇṭaka Bhaddiya:<br><br>Going out to the Ambātaka grove,<br>In the forest with clusters of trees,<br>Abandoning craving, the root of craving,<br>Bhaddiya sits in meditation — fortunate and happy.<br><br>Some delight in drums, flutes, and small cymbals,<br>But I, at the foot of a tree, delight in the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>If the Buddha grants a boon, I receive that boon.<br>I maintain mindfulness of the body constantly in all realms.<br><br>They laugh at me because of my body, they follow me because of my voice.<br>They do not know me, overcome by sensual desire.<br><br>Not knowing the inside, not seeing the outside,<br>The fool, blocked on four sides, is carried away by speech.<br><br>Not knowing the inside, seeing only the outside,<br>Seeing only the external fruit, also carried away by speech.<br><br>Knowing the inside, seeing the outside,<br>Seeing without obstruction, not carried away by speech.`, ref: "Theragāthā 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag7.2" },
{ text: `Elder Bhadda:<br><br>I was an only child, loved by father and mother.<br>Through many rites and observances, I was obtained with entreaties.<br><br>Out of compassion for me, wishing for my happiness,<br>Both my father and mother led me to the Buddha.<br><br>'This son of ours, obtained with great difficulty,<br>Raised with delicacy, nurtured and cared for,<br>We respectfully offer him to you, O savior,<br>To serve as your attendant, to serve the conqueror.'<br><br>The Teacher accepted me, saying to Ānanda:<br>'Let him go forth; he will become virtuous.'<br><br>After the Teacher had me go forth,<br>The conqueror then entered the monastery.<br>Before the sun rose, my mind was liberated.<br><br>Then my Teacher, to complete the task,<br>From silent meditation, stood up and called me:<br>'Come, Bhadda.' Thus I received full ordination.<br><br>From birth, at seven years, I received full ordination.<br>I have attained the three knowledges — O Dhamma, good Dhamma-nature!`, ref: "Theragāthā 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag7.3" },
{ text: `Elder Sārabhaṅga:<br><br>Breaking reeds with my hands, I made my own hut.<br>Therefore, my common name was 'Reed-breaker'.<br><br>Now it is no longer suitable to break reeds with my own hands,<br>Following the teaching of the one named Gotama.<br><br>Previously, Sārabhaṅga had never seen the entire disease completely and fully.<br>Now that disease is seen through the word of the supreme one.<br><br>Without craving, without clinging, the seven Buddhas attained Nibbāna.<br>This Dhamma is taught by those who have realized the Dhamma.<br><br>Out of compassion for beings, the four truths are taught:<br>Suffering, the origin of suffering, the path,<br>Cessation, the end of suffering.<br><br>In continuous existence, suffering rolls on without end.<br>When this body is destroyed, when life ends,<br>There is no other rebirth. I am truly well liberated,<br>Liberated from all bases.`, ref: "Theragāthā 7.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag7.5" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kaccāyana:<br><br>Do not do too many things, avoid competing with the crowd.<br>The diligent one attached to tastes abandons the goal that brings happiness.<br><br>I have experienced that the respect of families is a 'heap of mud',<br>A subtle arrow, very hard to draw out.<br>Respect is hard to abandon for the unworthy.<br><br>Human action is not in itself evil,<br>But depending on others — what others say or do,<br>One should not act for the sake of others, for relatives, for kamma.<br><br>Not because another says so does a person become a thief.<br>Not because another says so does a person become a noble one.<br>As one knows oneself, so the devas know one.<br><br>Others do not know that we are here for a time.<br>Those who know thus, the wise, live calmed.<br><br>Only the wise live strongly, even if their wealth is exhausted.<br>Without wisdom, having money is like not living.<br><br>With ears hearing all, with eyes seeing all,<br>The wise person abandons all, as if not seeing, not hearing.<br><br>Having eyes, like a blind person; having ears, like a deaf person;<br>Having wisdom, like a fool; having strength, like a weak person.<br>Let good deeds arise; lie down like a corpse.`, ref: "Theragāthā 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag8.1" },
{ text: `Elder Sirimitta:<br><br>Without anger, without hatred,<br>Without deceit, without divisive speech,<br>Such a bhikkhu, in the hereafter, does not grieve.<br><br>Without anger, without hatred,<br>Without deceit, without divisive speech,<br>A bhikkhu always guarding his senses,<br>In the hereafter, does not grieve.<br><br>Without anger, without hatred,<br>Without deceit, without divisive speech,<br>A bhikkhu maintaining good virtue,<br>In the hereafter, does not grieve.<br><br>Without anger, without hatred,<br>Without deceit, without divisive speech,<br>A bhikkhu with good friends,<br>In the hereafter, does not grieve.<br><br>Without anger, without hatred,<br>Without deceit, without divisive speech,<br>A bhikkhu with good wisdom,<br>In the hereafter, does not grieve.<br><br>One who has faith in the Tathāgata,<br>Unshakable, well established,<br>One whose virtuous conduct is praised by good people,<br>Approved by the noble ones.<br><br>One who has serene confidence in the Saṅgha,<br>With right view — they say of that person:<br>'That one is not poor, his life is not in vain.'<br><br>Therefore, O wise one, focus on faith, virtue,<br>Serene confidence, seeing the true Dhamma,<br>Enter the core of the Buddha's word.`, ref: "Theragāthā 8.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag8.2" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Panthaka:<br><br>When I first saw the fearless Teacher,<br>A strong emotion arose in me, seeing the supreme person.<br><br>Whoever, with hands and feet (clasped), prays to a lucky star,<br>With such an act hoping to please the Teacher,<br>That one cannot attain their wish.<br><br>But I, having abandoned wife, children, money, grain,<br>Having shaved off my hair and beard, went forth from home to homelessness.<br><br>Having learned, living fully, well restraining my faculties,<br>Honoring the Perfectly Enlightened One, I dwell, not conquered.<br><br>Then I aroused a resolution, my mind earnestly established:<br>I decided not to sit down even for a moment<br>Until the dart of evil craving was drawn out.<br><br>I dwelt thus — see my effort!<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>I know my former lives, my divine eye is purified.<br>I am worthy of offerings, liberated from all attachments.<br><br>Like night becoming day when the sun rises,<br>All craving dried up, I sat down cross-legged.`, ref: "Theragāthā 8.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag8.3" },
{ text: `Elder Bhūta:<br><br>When the wise person sees that old age and death are suffering,<br>The ordinary person, not seeing, grasps suffering.<br>Having fully understood suffering, mindful, practicing jhāna,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When craving is destroyed — craving that brings suffering and poison,<br>Creates proliferation and bondage, pushes toward suffering —<br>Having destroyed craving, mindful, practicing jhāna,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When with wisdom one sees the supreme good path,<br>Consisting of eight parts in two groups, purifying all defilements,<br>Having seen with wisdom, mindful, practicing jhāna,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When one develops the path — sorrowless, stainless,<br>Unconditioned, peaceful path, purifying all defilements,<br>Cutting the bonds of fetters, mindful, practicing jhāna,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When thundercloud drums roar in the sky,<br>Along the bird's path, a dense rain pours down,<br>A bhikkhu going to a cave, developing, sits in meditation,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When on the riverbanks, the forest garlands bloom and shine<br>With many colors and hues,<br>With a relaxed mind, sitting in meditation on the riverbank,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When in the dead of night, the forest silent,<br>A torrential rain pours down,<br>Tusked beasts are roaring as they live,<br>A bhikkhu going to a mountainside sits silently in meditation,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When applied and sustained thought are subdued,<br>In a mountain cave, sitting in meditation at ease,<br>Without fear, without obstruction,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.<br><br>When sitting with joy and bliss, without defilement, without sorrow,<br>Unconfined, free from craving, not struck by the dart,<br>All taints ended, that one sits in meditation,<br>He finds no happiness superior to this happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag9.1" },
{ text: `Elder Kāḷudāyī:<br><br>Blessed One, now is the time — the trees are blooming red,<br>Having shed their old leaves, they seek the time of fruit.<br>They are like blazing fires, shining and radiant.<br>O great hero, now is the time to enjoy the taste.<br><br>The trees are blooming beautifully, spreading fragrance everywhere.<br>Having shed their leaves, longing for fruit, now is the time to depart,<br>To leave this place, O hero.<br><br>Neither too cold nor too hot — the weather is good, Blessed One.<br>Let the Sakyans and Koliyans see you,<br>Facing west, crossing the Rohiṇī river.<br><br>In hope, fields are plowed; in hope, seeds are sown.<br>In hope, merchants cross the sea to bring back wealth.<br>The hope that sustains me — may that hope succeed.<br><br>People continue to sow seeds, the sky continues to rain,<br>Farmers continue to plow, grain continues to come,<br>Coming abundantly to the country.<br><br>Beggars continue to beg, donors continue to give.<br>Donors who continue to give continue to go to heaven.<br><br>A hero continues — for up to seven generations<br>That family produces a person of vast wisdom.<br>I think you could be the lord of devas.<br>In you, a true seer has been born.<br><br>Your father, the great seer, is named King Suddhodana.<br>The mother of the Perfectly Enlightened One is named Māyā.<br>She, having conceived the Bodhisatta, passed away and attained heaven.<br><br>Gotamī, after death, from there, after passing away,<br>Enjoying fully the sensual pleasures of heaven,<br>She delights in the five strands of sense pleasure, surrounded by celestial nymphs.<br><br>I am the son of the Buddha who conquers the unconquered,<br>The Aṅgīrasa, the incomparable one.<br>The Sakyan king, my father's father,<br>The Gotama king is my grandfather — in truth it is so.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.1" },
{ text: `Elder Ekavihāriya:<br><br>When there is no one in front or behind,<br>That is great happiness for one living alone in the forest.<br><br>I will go alone to the forest praised by the Buddha.<br>A bhikkhu enjoys the happiness attained through diligent living, alone.<br><br>I will quickly enter the forest, alone, living the ideal.<br>The forest where wild elephants live freely,<br>A dwelling that brings joy to a meditating seer.<br><br>In the Sītā forest, with rocky caves and cool water,<br>After washing my hands and feet, I walk back and forth alone.<br><br>Living alone, not with two, in the beautiful great forest,<br>I will live there, duty done, without taints.<br><br>Thus, I want to do it; may my aspiration succeed.<br>I will have faith — no one can do anything to me.<br><br>Tying on my armor, I will enter the deep forest.<br>I will not leave the forest until I attain the end of taints.<br><br>While a gentle breeze blows, cool and fragrant,<br>I sit on a mountain peak, I will shatter ignorance.<br><br>On a cave mat spread with forest flowers,<br>I enjoy the happiness of liberation in the mountain ring.<br><br>My resolve is fulfilled, like the full moon.<br>All taints are destroyed; now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.2" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kappina:<br><br>One who sees a matter early, before it arrives,<br>And knows both benefit and harm —<br>No enemy or friend can find a flaw in that person,<br>Even searching carefully.<br><br>One who well develops mindfulness of breathing,<br>Continually practicing to perfection as the Buddha taught,<br>Shines in this world like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>My mind is truly pure white, immeasurable, well developed,<br>Penetrative, firmly subdued, shining in all directions.<br><br>The wise one lives on, even if wealth is exhausted.<br>Without wisdom, having money is like not living.<br><br>Wisdom judges what is heard; wisdom increases fame.<br>A person of wisdom in this world finds happiness even in suffering.<br><br>This Dhamma is present here and now, not wonderful or rare.<br>Where there is birth, there is death — nothing rare about that.<br><br>Birth is unbroken; life always ends in death.<br>Born and dying there — such is the nature of beings.<br><br>What benefits the living does not benefit the dead.<br>Lamenting for the dead brings no fame, no purity,<br>Nor is it praised by ascetics and brahmins.<br><br>Lamentation harms the body and eyes, beauty, strength, and wisdom.<br>If the mind is joyful, all directions are also joyful.<br>Though one seeks happiness, there is no happiness.<br><br>Therefore, householders who wish to receive in the family<br>Only the wise and the learned,<br>With the strength of wisdom, they fulfill their duty,<br>Like a boat crossing a full river.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.3" },
{ text: `Elder Cūḷa Panthaka:<br><br>I was slow, progressing slowly, formerly despised by others.<br>My brother expelled me, saying: 'Now, go back home.'<br><br>Expelled thus, at the main gate of the monastery,<br>Sorrowful, standing there, longing for the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Then the Blessed One came, touched my head,<br>And taking me by the arm, led me into the monastery.<br><br>The Teacher, out of compassion, gave me a cloth to wipe my feet:<br>'Establish your mind on this single, pure object.'<br>And sitting down to one side, my mind was well established.<br><br>I heard his teaching, living joyful in the true Dhamma.<br>I practiced meditation to attain the supreme goal.<br><br>I know my former lives, my divine eye is purified.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Panthaka, transformed into a thousand forms,<br>Sat in the beautiful mango grove, awaiting the time of manifestation.<br><br>Then the Teacher, having kept me, sent a messenger to announce the time.<br>When the time was announced, I went through the sky.<br><br>Bowing at the Teacher's feet, I sat down to one side.<br>Knowing that I had sat down, the Teacher accepted me.<br><br>The recipient of sacrificial offerings from the entire world,<br>The field of merit for humans — He accepted the offerings.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.4" },
{ text: `Elder Kappa:<br><br>Full of various impurities, a place without any pure part,<br>Like a long-stagnant puddle, a great festering wound.<br><br>Full of blood and pus, sinking in a cesspit,<br>The body oozes, constantly flowing with impure water.<br><br>Bound by sixty sinews, plastered with flesh as mortar,<br>Wearing a coat of skin, the body is foul and useless.<br><br>Formed as a chain of bones, tied together with sinews,<br>Through their combined effort, they create various postures.<br><br>Constantly approaching death, nearing the realm of death,<br>There, it is discarded — people follow sensual desires.<br><br>The body is covered by ignorance, bound by four bonds,<br>Sinks in the flood, caught in the net of underlying tendencies,<br><br>Fettered by the five hindrances, obsessed by thoughts,<br>Following the root of craving, covered by the veil of delusion.<br><br>Thus this body rolls on, led by the chariot of kamma,<br>Now successful, now failing, experiencing many births through craving.<br><br>Whoever thinks 'the body is mine' is a foolish ordinary person,<br>Increasing the fearful cemetery, clinging to renewed existence.<br><br>One who avoids this body as one avoids a snake smeared with excrement,<br>They abandon the root of existence and attain taintless Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.5" },
{ text: `Elder Upasena, son of Vaṅganta:<br><br>In a secluded, quiet place, where wild beasts often dwell,<br>A bhikkhu prepares his seat and trains in the pure life.<br><br>From scattered rubbish, from a part of the highway,<br>Making an outer robe, wearing an old, worn-out garment.<br><br>With humble mind, continuing to go from house to house,<br>A bhikkhu living on alms, well-restrained at the sense doors.<br><br>Content with coarse food, not seeking other tastes;<br>If attached to tastes, the mind does not delight in meditation.<br><br>Of few desires and content, a seer living in seclusion,<br>Not associating with either householders or renunciants.<br><br>Like a fool, like a mute, show yourself thus.<br>A wise person among the Saṅgha should not speak at length.<br><br>Do not criticize anyone, avoid harming anyone.<br>Be restrained in the Pātimokkha, moderate in eating.<br><br>Grasping the signs well, skilled in the mind's manifestations,<br>Focus on peace, practice insight meditation at the right time.<br><br>With enough energy and patience, always devoted to duty,<br>Not yet having attained the end of suffering, the wise one advances with faith.<br><br>A bhikkhu wishing for purity, living thus,<br>All taints are destroyed, he attains supreme peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.6" },
{ text: `Elder Gotama:<br><br>Know your own happiness, observe what you hear.<br>What is suitable for the ascetic practice you follow?<br><br>Good friends on the path, practicing the great Dhamma,<br>Well hearing the Teacher — this suits the ascetic practice.<br><br>With mind revering the Buddhas, respecting the true Dhamma,<br>And loving the Saṅgha — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>Maintaining deportment in walking and standing, livelihood pure, without criticism,<br>Thoughts well stabilized — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>In actions done or not done, deportment is loved,<br>Established in the higher mind — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>Lodgings in forests and mountains, remote, quiet,<br>Associating with seers — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>Virtue and learning, investigating the Dhamma as it is,<br>Contemplating the truths — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>Contemplating impermanence, perception of non-self, foulness,<br>Not delighting in worldly things — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>Developing the factors of enlightenment,<br>The bases of psychic power, faculties and powers,<br>Gathering the noble eightfold path — this suits the ascetic path.<br><br>The seer who abandons craving, shatters the root of taints,<br>Dwells liberated — this suits the ascetic path.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.7" },
{ text: `Elder Saṅkicca:<br><br>What is your benefit, O dear sir,<br>In the deep forest during the rainy season at Ujuhāna?<br>The windy cave is lovely for you, living alone, practicing jhāna.<br><br>Like the seasonal wind driving clouds in the rainy season,<br>My perception spreads everywhere, unifying in seclusion.<br><br>A black crow, born from an egg, makes the charnel ground its home,<br>Arousing in me the perception of seclusion regarding the body.<br><br>Others do not protect one; one does not protect others.<br>A bhikkhu lives happily, not expecting sensual pleasures.<br><br>The rock with clear water, the meeting place,<br>Where black-faced monkeys and timid deer gather,<br>Under a canopy of flowers, water flowing — that rock delights me.<br><br>I live in the forest, in a rocky cave,<br>In a remote dwelling where wild beasts pass by.<br><br>'Kill them, destroy them! Make beings suffer!' —<br>I do not know such thoughts, ignoble, connected with hatred.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>For the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>That goal I have attained — all fetters are destroyed.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, like a worker waiting for wages.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, mindful, clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Theragāthā 11.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag11.1" },
{ text: `Elder Sīlava:<br><br>Here, learn virtue, well train in the world.<br>Virtue, fully achieved, leads to all success.<br><br>The wise should guard virtue, hoping for three kinds of happiness:<br>Fame, wealth, and after death, heavenly bliss.<br><br>The virtuous, self-controlled person gains many good friends.<br>The immoral person, doing evil, loses friends.<br><br>The immoral person gains only a bad reputation, not wealth.<br>The virtuous person always gains praise and fame.<br><br>At the start, virtue is the foundation, virtue is the mother of wholesome states.<br>Virtue stands first among all things; therefore, be pure in virtue.<br><br>Virtue restrains and guards, it brightens the mind.<br>It is the landing stage for the Buddhas; therefore, be pure in virtue.<br><br>Virtue is unequalled power, virtue is the supreme weapon,<br>Virtue is the foremost ornament, virtue is a rare armor.<br><br>Virtue is a mighty bridge, virtue is the supreme fragrance,<br>Virtue is the foremost ointment — through virtue, it spreads in four directions.<br><br>Virtue is the highest provision, virtue is the supreme traveling gear,<br>Virtue is the foremost vehicle — through virtue, one goes in four directions.<br><br>Here, the evil are blamed; after death, they are reborn in a bad destination.<br>Fools without established virtue worry everywhere.<br><br>Here, the good are praised; after death, they are reborn in liberation.<br>The wise with well-established virtue rejoice everywhere.<br><br>Here, virtue is supreme, but wisdom is supreme.<br>Among humans and devas, the one with virtue and wisdom is victorious.`, ref: "Theragāthā 12.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag12.1" },
{ text: `Elder Sunīta:<br><br>I was born into a low family, poor, without enough food.<br>My work was very lowly — I was a flower-scavenger.<br><br>I was despised by people, looked down upon and humiliated.<br>Lowering myself very much, I paid homage to the crowd.<br><br>Then I saw the Buddha, the head of the Saṅgha of bhikkhus,<br>The Great Hero entering the supreme city of Magadha.<br><br>Throwing down my carrying pole, I approached to bow down.<br>Out of compassion for me, the Supreme Person stood still.<br><br>After bowing at the Teacher's feet, I stood to one side.<br>I asked for the going forth from the supreme among all beings.<br><br>The compassionate Teacher, who cares for the whole world,<br>Said: 'Come, bhikkhu.' Thus I received full ordination.<br><br>Then I lived alone in the forest, not lazy,<br>Following the Teacher's instruction, as the conqueror taught.<br><br>In the first watch of the night, I recalled my former lives.<br>In the middle watch, my divine eye was purified.<br>In the last watch, I shattered the mass of delusion.<br><br>When the night opened, at dawn, as the sky grew light,<br>Sakka and Brahmā came, bowed to me with folded hands:<br><br>'Homage to you, O thoroughbred! Homage to you, O supreme man!<br>Your taints are destroyed; you are worthy of offerings.'<br><br>The Teacher, seeing me at the head of the deva host,<br>Smiled and spoke this meaning to me:<br><br>'Through austerity, through the holy life, through self-control and taming,<br>One becomes a brahmin. That is the supreme brahmin.'`, ref: "Theragāthā 12.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag12.2" },
{ text: `Elder Soṇa Koḷivisa:<br><br>Formerly, high in the state, serving the king of Aṅga,<br>Now high in the Dhamma, Soṇa has overcome suffering.<br><br>Five are cut, five abandoned, five higher qualities are developed.<br>A bhikkhu who has crossed five strands is called one who has crossed the flood.<br><br>A bhikkhu of arrogant nature, heedless, delighting in external tastes,<br>Does not perfect virtue, concentration, and wisdom.<br><br>What should be done is abandoned; what should not be done is done.<br>For the arrogant and heedless, the taints increase.<br><br>Those who are diligently, constantly developing mindfulness of the body,<br>Do not do what should not be done, persist in what should be done.<br>For the mindful and aware, the taints are destroyed.<br><br>The straight path is taught — walk on it, do not turn back.<br>Reproach yourself, bring Nibbāna near.<br><br>When I was striving with overstrained energy,<br>The Unsurpassed Teacher of the world,<br>Using the simile of the lute, the One with the Dhamma-eye, the Seer,<br>Taught me the Dhamma.<br><br>I heard his teaching and dwelled happily in that instruction.<br>Calm, I practiced to attain the supreme goal.<br>I have attained the three knowledges; done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>One who is intent on renunciation, mind inclined to seclusion,<br>One who is intent on non-hatred, destroying all grasping,<br><br>One who is intent on the destruction of craving, mind without delusion,<br>Seeing the arising of the base, the mind is well liberated.<br><br>A bhikkhu whose mind is pure, rightly liberated,<br>Has nothing stored up, nothing left to do.<br><br>Like a solid rock, not shaken by the wind,<br>So too, regarding all forms, tastes, sounds, scents, touches,<br><br>Pleasant and unpleasant phenomena — unshaken,<br>That one's mind is established, unattached,<br>Contemplating their destruction.`, ref: "Theragāthā 13.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag13.1" },
{ text: `Elder Khadiravaniya Revata:<br><br>From the time I went forth from home to homelessness,<br>I do not know any thought that is ignoble, connected with hatred.<br><br>Or harming, killing, or making beings suffer —<br>I do not know such thoughts for this long time.<br><br>I have developed loving-kindness, immeasurable, well cultivated,<br>Accumulated step by step as the Buddha taught.<br><br>I am a friend to all, compassionate toward all beings,<br>I cultivate a mind of loving-kindness, always joyful, without hatred.<br><br>I delight in the unshaken, unmoving mind.<br>I have developed the divine abode, practiced by the good.<br><br>I have attained the state of non-applied thought, a disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>And I have directly attained noble silence.<br><br>Like a stone mountain, unmoving, standing firm, well established,<br>So a bhikkhu who has destroyed delusion is like a mountain, unshaken by anything.<br><br>An unstained person always seeks purity.<br>A fault as small as a hair's tip is seen as heavy as a cloud of smoke.<br><br>Like a border fortress guarded within and without,<br>Guard yourself; do not let the moment pass.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, like a worker waiting for wages.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, mindful, clearly comprehending.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>For the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>That goal I have attained — all fetters are destroyed.<br><br>Strive, do not be heedless — this is my instruction.<br>I will attain Nibbāna, I am free from all attachments.`, ref: "Theragāthā 14.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag14.1" },
{ text: `Elder Godatta:<br><br>Like a good thoroughbred, well trained,<br>Yoked to a heavy load, pulls the load,<br>Pressed down heavily, does not tip over the load.<br><br>So too, a person of great wisdom, like water in the ocean,<br>Does not despise others — such is the noble Dhamma,<br>Toward all beings.<br><br>Living within time, conquered by time,<br>Ruled by existence and non-existence, humans suffer.<br>Their children and relatives grieve, right here in this life.<br><br>Rejoicing when gaining pleasure, weary when meeting pain,<br>Fools are afflicted, overwhelmed on both sides,<br>Not seeing things as they really are.<br><br>Those who, between pain and pleasure, are not woven by the weaver,<br>Stand firm like a doorpost, not elated or weary.<br><br>Regarding gain or loss, fame or disgrace,<br>Blame or praise, pain or happiness —<br><br>Where we are attached, like a water drop on a lotus,<br>The hero everywhere gains happiness, not defeated.<br><br>The righteous does not gain; the gainer is not righteous.<br>The righteous but not gaining is better than the gainer who is not righteous.<br><br>The famous but of little wisdom, the wise but not famous.<br>The not famous but wise is better than the little-wise but famous.<br><br>Praised by fools, criticized by the wise —<br>To be criticized by the wise is better than to be praised by fools.<br><br>Happiness from sensual pleasures, suffering from seclusion —<br>The suffering from seclusion is better than the happiness from sensual pleasures.<br><br>Living by unrighteousness, dying by righteousness —<br>Dying by righteousness is better than living by unrighteousness.<br><br>One who has abandoned desire and anger, with mind pure regarding existence and non-existence,<br>Living in the world without craving, without love or hate,<br><br>Having developed the factors of enlightenment, the faculties, and the powers,<br>Attains supreme peace, attains taintless Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 14.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag14.2" },
{ text: `Elder Aññā Koṇḍañña:<br><br>I rejoice exceedingly, having heard the great-tasting Dhamma,<br>The Dhamma taught of dispassion, completely without grasping.<br><br>On the round earth, with many colors and forms,<br>Enchanting the mind — I thought thus:<br>The sign of beauty is very alluring, connected with sensual desire.<br><br>Like dust blown by the wind, subdued by rain clouds,<br>The thoughts are calmed when seen with wisdom.<br><br>'All conditioned things are impermanent' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>'All conditioned things are suffering' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>'All phenomena are not-self' —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering;<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>The elder Koṇḍañña, awakened by awakening,<br>Has become sharp and detached, destroyed birth and death,<br>And the holy life is completely fulfilled.<br><br>Whether it is the flood, the snare, or the firm pillar,<br>A mountain hard to break — having cut them down,<br>Having cut the pillar and snare, the rock hard to break,<br>Meditating, he crosses to the far shore, freed from Māra's bonds.<br><br>A terrified bhikkhu, going to evil friends,<br>Sinks in the great flood, overwhelmed by great waves.<br><br>The wise one, not terrified, unshaken, careful,<br>With faculties well restrained, making good friends,<br>Such a wise person can end suffering.<br><br>A person dark, lean, weak, full of veins,<br>Moderate in food, mind without distress.<br><br>In the great forest, bitten by flies and mosquitoes,<br>Like a battle elephant, I endure mindfully.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, like a worker waiting for wages.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time, mindful, clearly comprehending.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>For the sake of which one goes forth from home to homelessness,<br>That goal I have attained — what need have I of the forest?`, ref: "Theragāthā 15.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag15.1" },
{ text: `Elder Udāyi:<br><br>The Buddha, born as a human, self-tamed, meditating,<br>With Brahmā-like conduct, joyful in pure mind.<br><br>People bow to him, the one who has reached the far shore,<br>Regarding all phenomena. Devas bow to him —<br>Thus I have heard, I am an Arahant.<br><br>Having crossed all fetters, from the forest to Nibbāna,<br>He delights in liberation from sensual desires, like gold freed from ore.<br><br>He is truly like an elephant, perfect, radiant,<br>Standing on a high peak of the Himālayan mountain range.<br>Among all Nāgas, he is the true unsurpassed Nāga.<br><br>Then I will praise this Nāga to the people.<br>A Nāga who does no evil is therefore called a Nāga.<br>Gentle, not harming — that is the two-footed Nāga.<br><br>Mindfulness and clear comprehension — these are other two-footed Nāgas.<br>The elephant Nāga is faith; the white tusk is equanimity.<br><br>Mindfulness is the neck, wisdom points to the head.<br>Applied and sustained thought, the trunk, indicates reflection on Dhamma.<br>Peaceful abiding is the belly of Dhamma, seclusion is like the tail of the elephant.<br><br>Meditating, breathing in happiness, mind well concentrated internally,<br>The Nāga walks concentrated, stands concentrated.<br><br>The Nāga lies down concentrated, sits concentrated.<br>In all situations, the Nāga lives restrained.<br>This is the Nāga's achievement.`, ref: "Theragāthā 15.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag15.2" },
{ text: `Elder Udāyi (continued):<br><br>Eating food without fault, not eating food with fault;<br>Receiving food and clothing, he abandons, does not store up.<br><br>Cutting all bonds, both subtle and coarse,<br>Wherever he goes, he walks without expectation.<br><br>Like a lotus born in water, grown and increased,<br>Not stained by water, fragrant and very delightful,<br><br>So the Perfectly Enlightened One, born and dwelling in the world,<br>Is not stained by the world, like a lotus not stained by water.<br><br>Like a blazing fire, without fuel, it dies down gradually,<br>Calmed in ashes, it is called 'extinguished'.<br><br>The wise teach this simile to explain the meaning.<br>The great Nāga will understand what concerns the Nāga,<br>As taught by that Nāga.<br><br>Without greed, without hatred, without delusion, without taints,<br>The Nāga, abandoning the body, will attain final Nibbāna,<br>No longer having taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 15.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag15.2" },
{ text: `Elder Pārāpariya:<br><br>When the bhikkhu named Pārāpariya<br>Sat alone in seclusion, meditating in solitude,<br>The following thoughts arose in him:<br><br>'What is step by step? What are rites and actions?<br>A person doing his duty, not harming anyone?<br><br>'The faculties of human beings bring benefit and harm.<br>If not guarded, they bring harm; if guarded, they bring benefit.<br><br>'One who restrains the faculties, one who guards the faculties,<br>One who does his duty, does not harm anyone.<br><br>'When the eye goes to forms, without restraining or checking,<br>Not seeing the dangers, that person does not escape suffering.<br><br>'When the ear goes to sounds, without restraining or checking,<br>Not seeing the danger, that person does not escape suffering.<br><br>'Not seeing the escape, enjoying fragrances,<br>That person does not escape suffering because of attachment to fragrances.<br><br>'Remembering the supreme sweet and sour, remembering the supreme bitter,<br>Enslaved by the taste of craving, the mind cannot awaken.<br><br>'Remembering pleasant, delightful physical contacts,<br>Infatuated, connected with craving, he encounters various kinds of suffering.<br><br>'For the mind regarding these five phenomena —<br>If unable to guard them, suffering follows that person.'`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.2" },
{ text: `Elder Pārāpariya (continued):<br><br>For the most part, the body is full of pus and blood,<br>Made by the excellent person into a beautiful painted box.<br><br>Bitter like a sweet taste, suffering is bound by the agreeable,<br>Like a sharp knife smeared with honey — the greedy person does not know.<br><br>Whoever is attached to women's forms, women's tastes, women's touches,<br>Whoever is infatuated with women's fragrances meets various kinds of suffering.<br><br>All streams from women, five kinds, flow to the five spheres.<br>A person with energetic strength can block them.<br><br>One with a goal, abiding in Dhamma, skilled and wise,<br>Delights in duty, connected with Dhamma and meaning.<br><br>Sunk in temporary gain, abandon what is not beneficial.<br>If he thinks that is not the thing to do,<br>He is not heedless, seeing clearly thus.<br><br>If it is a good action, rejoicing, acting righteously,<br>Seize that action immediately — that is truly the supreme happiness.<br><br>With high and low means, deceiving others,<br>Striking, killing, causing suffering, brutal, oppressing people.<br><br>Like a strong man carving wood, using a wedge to remove a wedge,<br>So the good person uses a faculty to remove a faculty.<br><br>Developing faith, energy, concentration,<br>Training mindfulness and wisdom, using five to defeat five,<br>He advances without stain.<br><br>He is a brahmin, one with a goal, abiding in Dhamma,<br>Following the Buddha's instruction, doing everything with full strength,<br>That person enjoys happiness.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.2" },
{ text: `Elder Telakāni:<br><br>For a long time, full of ardor, I reflected on the true Dhamma,<br>Asking ascetics and brahmins, but my mind was not at peace.<br><br>Who in this world has reached the far shore?<br>Who has attained and plunged into the Deathless?<br>Whose Dhamma should I accept, the Dhamma that penetrates the ultimate meaning?<br><br>The hook is inside, like a fish tasting bait,<br>I am caught, I am bound, no different from the asura Vepacitti<br>Bound by Indra's net.<br><br>I drag my chains, unable to escape sorrow and grief.<br>Who will untie me? Who will help me attain enlightenment?<br><br>Which ascetic or brahmin speaks of the destruction of these bonds?<br>Whose Dhamma should I accept, to abandon old age and death?<br><br>Bound by doubt, overpowered by intoxication,<br>Making the mind angry, making the mind hard,<br>Torn and cut by strong greed.<br><br>Pierced by the arrow of craving, bound by the thirty views,<br>Look at the strength of my chest — pressed down, it still holds.<br><br>The underlying views not cut off, thoughts are agitated.<br>Pierced by them, I tremble like a leaf blown by the wind.<br><br>Arising from within, burning quickly what is called 'mine',<br>The body with its six sense spheres — 'I am' arises from that.<br><br>I do not see a physician to draw out the dart from me,<br>Searching by other means, not using the scalpel.<br><br>Is there a physician who, without a scalpel, without a wound,<br>Without harming my hands and feet, draws out the dart for me,<br>The dart that has pierced my inner heart?<br><br>The supreme Lord of the Dhamma, dispelling the poison,<br>When I fell into the abyss, reached out his hand to help me<br>To safety on dry ground.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.3" },
{ text: `Elder Telakāni (continued):<br><br>I sank deep in a lake full of mud, unable to escape,<br>Full of deceit, envy, tension, and delusion.<br><br>Thunder of restlessness roared, clouds of fetters covered,<br>The waterfall of wrong thoughts connected with sensual desire<br>Swept me away into the ocean of wrong views.<br><br>Everywhere streams flow, creepers stand and sprout.<br>Who can stop those streams? Who can cut those creepers?<br><br>Make a dam, venerable sir, to block those streams,<br>Do not let the water born of mind sweep you away,<br>Like swiftly flowing water sweeping away a tree in its course.<br><br>So too, I am afraid of this shore, seeking the far shore.<br>Then the Teacher, with his noble assembly attending,<br>With the weapon of wisdom, waited to give support to people.<br><br>Lifting me, who was sinking, with a well-made staircase,<br>The pure Buddha, firm, made of the core of the Dhamma,<br>Then said to me: 'Do not be afraid.'<br><br>Climbing the tower of mindfulness, from there I see<br>People attached to the view of self — previously I was proud.<br><br>When I saw the path, the boat that must be boarded,<br>I did not abide in self, seeing the supreme destination.<br><br>The dart arises from self, born from the cause of existence.<br>He taught the supreme path, the cessation of those things.<br><br>The knot that had long lain hidden, abiding in the skin,<br>The Buddha untied and threw away, removing all poison.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.3" },
{ text: `Elder Raṭṭhapāla:<br><br>Look at the painted image, a heap of wounds, a composite body,<br>Diseased, full of many thoughts — nothing permanent or stable.<br><br>Look at the adorned form, with jewels and earrings,<br>A skeleton covered by skin, shining brightly by clothes.<br><br>Feet painted with lac and dye, face powdered with cosmetics,<br>It only deludes a fool, not one seeking enlightenment.<br><br>Hair arranged in eight coils, eyes smeared with collyrium,<br>It only deludes a fool, not one seeking enlightenment.<br><br>Like a newly painted ointment box, the foul body is adorned,<br>It only deludes a fool, not one seeking enlightenment.<br><br>The hunter set a trap; the wise deer does not touch the trap.<br>Having eaten the bait, I go — let the deer-catcher weep.<br><br>The hunter's snare is cut; the wise deer does not touch the trap.<br>Having eaten the bait, I go — let the deer-catcher grieve.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.4" },

{ text: `Elder Raṭṭhapāla:<br><br>I see wealthy people in the world,<br>Having gained wealth, they give not due to delusion.<br>Out of greed, they store away wealth,<br>Seeking ever more sensual pleasures.<br><br>A king, by force, conquers the earth,<br>Conquering to the sea's edge.<br>Unsatisfied with this near shore,<br>He longs for the far shore as well.<br><br>Kings and many others,<br>With craving not yet dead, have died.<br>Lacking, they are reborn,<br>They abandon this body,<br>But desire in the world<br>Is never satisfied.<br><br>Relatives lament for him,<br>With hair disheveled and tangled.<br>They say: 'Alas, we cannot attain the Deathless.'<br>Wrapped in cloth, they carry him,<br>They build a pyre and cremate him.<br><br>Pierced by stakes and prodded,<br>He is burned and consumed,<br>Wrapped in but a single cloth,<br>Abandoning all possessions.<br>The dead person has no refuge<br>In relatives or neighbors.<br><br>His heirs take away<br>His property and wealth.<br>But the person himself must go<br>According to the kamma he made.<br>Wealth does not follow<br>The one who has died.<br>No son, no wife,<br>No wealth, no kingdom [go with him].<br><br>Wealth cannot buy long life;<br>Riches cannot avoid decay.<br>The wise say:<br>This life is brief,<br>Truly impermanent,<br>Always subject to change.<br><br>The rich and the poor both experience [it],<br>The fool and the wise both feel [it].<br>The fool, struck by his own folly,<br>Falls down and lies prostrate.<br>But the wise one is not afraid<br>Of any feeling.<br><br>Therefore wisdom surpasses wealth;<br>Through wisdom perfection is attained.<br>Not having reached the final goal<br>Regarding existence and non-existence,<br>The fool does evil deeds,<br>Cruel and unwholesome.<br><br>Entering a womb, born into another life,<br>Wandering on, continuing to be born,<br>The unwise one, believing,<br>Enters a womb and is reborn.<br><br>Like a thief caught<br>In the act of stealing,<br>By his own kamma<br>He is harmed according to his evil offense.<br>So too, after death,<br>People in the hereafter,<br>By their own kamma,<br>Are harmed according to their evil offense.<br><br>Sensual pleasures are truly beautiful,<br>Sweet and agreeable,<br>They infatuate the mind<br>With form and formlessness.<br>Seeing the danger<br>In the qualities of sensual pleasure,<br>Therefore I went forth — so, O great king.<br><br>As fruits fall down,<br>So too youth,<br>Growing up and growing old,<br>Then the body breaks up and life ends.<br>Seeing this, I went forth — so, O great king.<br>The ascetic life is truly better, more excellent.<br><br>With faith I went forth<br>Into the community of the noble ones.<br>I went forth without offense,<br>Without debt, I receive alms.<br><br>Seeing sensual pleasures as a blazing fire,<br>Seeing gold as a knife,<br>Regarding entering a womb as suffering,<br>A great misfortune in hell.<br><br>Seeing this danger,<br>I felt terror.<br>When struck, when wounded,<br>I attained peace,<br>And I have destroyed<br>All three kinds of taints.<br><br>I serve the Teacher,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down,<br>The root of existence uprooted.<br><br>For the sake of which I went forth from home to homelessness,<br>That goal I have attained — all fetters are destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.4" },
{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta:<br><br>Seeing a form, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from form,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Hearing a sound, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from sound,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Smelling an odor, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from odor,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Tasting a flavor, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from flavor,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Experiencing a touch, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from touch,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Cognizing a phenomenon, mindfulness is infatuated;<br>If one attends to a pleasant sign,<br>The mind, greedily affected, feeling,<br>Enters and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Many kinds, born from mind,<br>Greed and harm grow strong,<br>They injure his mind.<br>Thus suffering accumulates,<br>Far, far from Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.5" },
{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta (continued):<br><br>Not infatuated with forms,<br>Seeing a form, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he sees form,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br><br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br>Not infatuated with sounds,<br>Hearing a sound, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he hears sound,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not infatuated with odors,<br>Smelling an odor, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he smells odor,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not infatuated with tastes,<br>Tasting a flavor, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he tastes flavor,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not infatuated with touches,<br>Experiencing a touch, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he experiences touch,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not infatuated with phenomena,<br>Cognizing a phenomenon, mindful,<br>The mind not greedily affected, feeling,<br>Does not enter and remain.<br><br>As he cognizes phenomenon,<br>So feeling occurs;<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, he practices thus.<br>Thus, not accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.5" },
{ text: `Elder Bhaddiya Kāḷigodhāyaputta:<br><br>When I sat on an elephant's neck,<br>Wearing fine garments,<br>Eating rice, truly fragrant,<br>With well-cooked meat dishes,<br><br>Now virtuous, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Wearing dust-heap robes, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Always going for alms, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Wearing three robes, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Going from house to house, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Eating one meal, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Eating from a bowl, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Not eating further, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Living in the forest, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Sitting at the foot of a tree, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Living in the open, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Dwelling in a charnel ground, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Living wherever assigned, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Living always seated, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.7" },
{ text: `Elder Bhaddiya Kāḷigodhāyaputta (continued):<br><br>Of few desires, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Content, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Practicing seclusion, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Not associating, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Dwelling energetically, persistent,<br>Delighting in food placed in a bowl,<br>Meditating, unattached,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Abandoning precious bowls of gold and fine resin,<br>I take a clay bowl —<br>This is my second consecration.<br><br>With high ramparts protecting,<br>With watchtowers and strong gates,<br>With soldiers holding swords,<br>I lived in fear.<br><br>Now virtuous, fearless,<br>Abandoning trembling and terror,<br>Meditating in the deep forest,<br>I am a son of Godha.<br><br>Established on the aggregate of virtue,<br>Mindful, developing insight wisdom,<br>Step by step I have attained<br>The destruction of all fetters.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.7" },
{ text: `Elder Aṅgulimāla:<br><br>O ascetic, you are walking, yet you say: 'I have stopped.'<br>While I am stopped, you say: 'Why have you not stopped?'<br>O ascetic, I ask you the meaning of this:<br>Why have you stopped while I am still walking?"<br><br>[Aṅgulimāla,]<br>I have always stopped,<br>With regard to all beings,<br>I have laid down the rod.<br>But you are unrestrained toward beings,<br>Therefore I have stopped while you have not stopped."<br><br>For a long time I have revered the great seer.<br>Now this ascetic has entered the great forest.<br>I will be ready to abandon a thousand evils,<br>Having heard your verse connected with the true Dhamma."<br><br>Having spoken, the bandit threw away his sword,<br>Threw away his weapons into a deep mountain gorge.<br>The bandit bowed down at the feet of the Well-Gone One,<br>And right there asked the Buddha for the going forth.<br><br>The Buddha, the great compassionate seer,<br>The Teacher of the world with its devas,<br>Said these words:<br>'Come, bhikkhu.' Thus for him<br>He became a bhikkhu.<br><br>One who was heedless before<br>And afterwards is not heedless,<br>Illumines this world<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>One who overcomes evil deeds<br>With wholesome deeds,<br>Illumines this world<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>A young bhikkhu who devotes himself<br>To the Buddha's teaching,<br>Illumines this world<br>Like the moon freed from clouds.<br><br>May my enemies hear the Dhamma.<br>May my enemies devote themselves to the Buddha's teaching.<br>May my enemies associate with those people<br>Who have attained peace and uphold the Dhamma.<br><br>May my enemies from time to time hear the Dhamma<br>Preached about patience, praising gentleness,<br>And may their conduct be in accordance with the Dhamma.<br><br>Such a person would not harm me,<br>Nor would they harm anyone else.<br>That one would attain the supreme peace,<br>And would protect and guard the strong and the weak.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.8" },
{ text: `Elder Aṅgulimāla (continued):<br><br>Irrigators guide water,<br>Fletchers shape arrows,<br>Carpenters shape wood,<br>The wise tame themselves.<br><br>Some are tamed by a stick, a hook, or a whip.<br>I was tamed by him without stick or sword.<br><br>My name was 'Harmless', yet formerly I was 'Harmful'.<br>Now I am truly 'Harmless', for I harm no one.<br><br>Formerly I was a bandit, renowned as 'Finger-garland'.<br>Swept away by the great flood, I went to the Buddha for refuge.<br><br>Formerly my hand was stained with blood, renowned as 'Finger-garland'.<br>See, I have gone for refuge, the root of renewed existence is uprooted.<br><br>Having done many deeds that lead to a bad destination,<br>Experiencing the result of kamma, free of debt, I receive alms.<br><br>Fools, lacking wisdom, delight in heedlessness.<br>The wise protect heedlessness as their greatest treasure.<br><br>Do not give way to heedlessness,<br>Do not be drawn into the enjoyment of sensual pleasures.<br>One who is heedful and meditative attains great happiness.<br><br>Good has come to me, not bad,<br>Advice to me, there is nothing not good.<br>Among the various doctrines in the world,<br>The supreme Dhamma, I chose and attained.<br><br>Good has come to me, not bad,<br>Advice to me, there is nothing not good.<br>I have attained the three knowledges;<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>In the forest, at the foot of a tree,<br>Or on a mountain in a cave,<br>Wherever I dwell, my mind is truly inspired.<br><br>I lie down happily, I rise up happily,<br>My mind is entirely happy.<br>This is my way of life, freed from Māra's trap —<br>O compassionate Teacher!<br><br>Formerly I was born a brahmin, of high lineage on both sides.<br>Now I am a son of the Well-Gone One, the Teacher, the Dhamma King.<br><br>Free from craving, without clinging,<br>With guarded senses, restrained,<br>Having abandoned the root of evil, I have attained the destruction of taints.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching,<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.8" },
{ text: `Elder Anuruddha:<br><br>Abandoning father and mother, relatives,<br>Abandoning brothers and sisters,<br>Abandoning the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Anuruddha meditates.<br><br>Living attached to dancing and singing,<br>Teaching with the sound of cymbals,<br>Living thus, one cannot attain the state of purity,<br>Because one delights in Māra's domain.<br><br>But I have overcome all,<br>Delighting in the Buddha's teaching,<br>Crossing all kinds of floods,<br>Anuruddha meditates.<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, scents, touches,<br>Alluring, very agreeable —<br>Overcoming them all,<br>Anuruddha meditates.<br><br>Returning from the alms round, alone,<br>That seer, seeking rags from the rubbish heap —<br>Anuruddha has attained<br>The state without taints.<br><br>He gathers rags from the rubbish heap,<br>Washes, dyes, and wears them.<br>Thus the wise Anuruddha<br>Is without taints.<br><br>Great desire, discontent,<br>Delighting in company, restless —<br>These things are evil, defiled.<br><br>Mindfulness and few desires,<br>Content, not troubled,<br>Delighting in seclusion, joyful,<br>Always energetic and diligent —<br><br>These things are the wholesome factors of enlightenment.<br>That one is without taints, so said the great seer.<br><br>Knowing my mind thus,<br>The unsurpassed Teacher of the world,<br>With a mind-made body,<br>Came to me with psychic power.<br><br>As I thought, he explained it all.<br>The Buddha, not delighting in proliferation,<br>Taught non-proliferation.<br><br>Having understood the Dhamma, I rejoiced,<br>Dwelling in his teaching.<br>I have attained the three knowledges;<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>I saw the Perfectly Enlightened One, the fearless Teacher.<br>Faith arose in him; I went forth from home to homelessness.<br><br>In jhāna with five factors, my mind peaceful and one-pointed,<br>My mind was tranquil, my divine eye purified.<br><br>I know birth and death, the coming and going of beings,<br>This life and the next. I abide in jhāna with five factors.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>In the village of Veḷuva, among the Vajji people,<br>I go to final cessation, ending the stream of birth and death.<br>Under the shade of a bamboo grove, I will attain Nibbāna,<br>No longer having taints.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.9" },
{ text: `Elder Pārāpariya:<br><br>These are the thoughts of an ascetic<br>In the grove called the Great Forest,<br>When the forest was in bloom,<br>He sat alone, in seclusion, mind concentrated.<br><br>Different were the deportments<br>Of the bhikkhus when the Supreme Person,<br>The Blessed One, was still alive.<br>Now what is seen is truly very different.<br><br>Robes to protect from cold wind,<br>To cover what is shameful —<br>They use them with moderation.<br>Contentment — from where does it come?<br><br>Whether delicious or plain, received little or much,<br>They use the food only to sustain life,<br>Without greed, without infatuation.<br><br>Necessities for living or various medicines —<br>They are not overly attached<br>To the destruction of taints.<br><br>At the foot of a tree in the forest,<br>Or in a cave or hollow,<br>They focus on seclusion,<br>Taking that as the final goal.<br><br>Living humbly, simply,<br>Gentle, patient in mind,<br>With refined deportment,<br>Not speaking crookedly,<br>Their minds directed to the welfare<br>Of themselves and others.<br><br>Therefore their conduct is truly lovely and good.<br>When they walk, when they eat,<br>When they use anything,<br>Their deportment is as smooth as flowing oil.<br><br>All taints destroyed, great jhāna, great benefit,<br>Those elders have completely attained Nibbāna.<br>Today there are few like them.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.10" },
{ text: `Elder Pārāpariya (continued):<br><br>Evil qualities, the age is defiled.<br>For those who abide in seclusion,<br>Hoping to realize the remaining sublime Dhamma,<br><br>Defilements increase, harming many.<br>They seem to play with fools,<br>Like demons playing with madmen.<br><br>Conquered by defilements, running after this and that,<br>Regarding defiled things, they shout loudly like people<br>Over what they have obtained.<br><br>Abandoning the true sublime Dhamma,<br>They quarrel with each other,<br>They run after wrong views,<br>Thinking: 'This is better.'<br><br>Turning their backs, abandoning<br>Wealth, children, and wives,<br>For the sake of a spoon of alms,<br>They do unworthy work.<br><br>They eat until their bellies are full,<br>They lie down and sleep.<br>After waking, they speak<br>What the Teacher would criticize.<br><br>All arts and crafts<br>They respect and learn,<br>Their minds not peaceful,<br>Neglecting the ascetic practice.<br><br>Earth, oil, various powders,<br>Water, seats, cooked rice —<br>They give to householders,<br>Hoping to get more.<br><br>Toothpicks, kaṭṭha fruits,<br>Leaves and flowers to chew,<br>Full almsfood,<br>Various mango fruits,<br>And amalaka fruits.<br><br>With various medicines,<br>They are like doctors.<br>They do work<br>No different from laypeople.<br>They adorn their robes<br>Like courtesans.<br>They show their authority<br>Like royalty.<br><br>Deceit and fraud,<br>False testimony and tricks,<br>With many schemes<br>To enjoy material goods.<br><br>Using deceptive means,<br>Following intrigues,<br>By such livelihood,<br>They bring in much wealth.<br><br>They gather assemblies<br>For profit, not for Dhamma.<br>They teach the Dhamma to people<br>For gain, not for the goal.<br><br>Those outside the Saṅgha<br>Quarrel and dispute<br>Over the Saṅgha's benefits,<br>Shameless and without moral dread,<br>They support themselves<br>With others' gains.<br><br>Some, lacking faith,<br>Though shaven-headed, wearing the robe,<br>Desire respect,<br>Crave power, gain, and fame.<br><br>Thus, as now, many things have declined.<br>It is no longer easy as in former times<br>Either to experience attainment<br>Of what has not been experienced,<br>Or to maintain and preserve<br>What has already been experienced.<br><br>Like a barefoot person walking on thorns,<br>Always mindful,<br>So too the seer,<br>When entering the village,<br>Should guard his mindfulness.<br><br>Remembering the practitioners of old,<br>Remembering their way of life,<br>Even now in later times,<br>One can still experience<br>The path to the Deathless.<br><br>Thus the ascetic in the sāla forest,<br>With faculties developed,<br>Spoke these words.<br>The brahmin has entered Nibbāna,<br>The seer has ended renewed existence.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.10" },
{ text: `Elder Phussa:<br><br>The seer Paṇḍara, seeing many faithful ones,<br>Self-developed, well-guarded and restrained,<br>Then asked the one named Phussa:<br><br>'In the future, what desires will there be?<br>What aspirations? What conduct?<br>Please answer our question.'<br><br>'Seer Paṇḍara, listen to my words,<br>Receive them carefully, I will speak of the future.<br><br>'Anger and resentment,<br>Concealment and stubbornness,<br>Much deceit and envy —<br>Thus it will be in the future.<br><br>'Considering themselves wise,<br>They have gone to the far shore of the profound Dhamma,<br>They despise the good Dhamma,<br>They do not respect one another.<br><br>'Many dangers in the world<br>Will occur in the future.<br>This well-taught Dhamma,<br>Fools will defile.<br><br>'In the Saṅgha, those of inferior virtue<br>Often proclaim themselves confident and fearless.<br>The unlearned, the talkative, will gain a strong position.<br><br>'In the Saṅgha, those of beautiful virtue,<br>When they proclaim what is true, are often weak,<br>Shy and lacking in ardor.<br><br>'Silver, gold, fields, land,<br>Goats and sheep,<br>Male and female servants —<br>Fools, lacking wisdom, will accept all these in the future.<br><br>'Fools are easily angered, not calm in virtue,<br>Arrogant, wandering here and there,<br>Like beasts fond of fighting.<br><br>'They become restless, always wearing blue robes,<br>Deceitful and stubborn, talkative, speaking falsely,<br>They imitate and pretend to be like the noble ones of old.<br><br>'With oil-slicked hair, restless, eyes painted blue,<br>Wearing ivory-white robes, they walk on the roads.<br><br>'The well-dyed yellow robe, the banner of the Arahants,<br>Worn by the liberated, is not despised by them.<br>But they despise the yellow robe, longing to wear white.<br><br>'They become greedy for gain, lazy, of little energy,<br>Hard to live with in the wilderness, delighting in village life.<br><br>'Those who fear gain, always fond of wrong livelihood,<br>They imitate such a one, associating, not restrained.<br><br>'Those who do not gain [honor], they do not respect or honor<br>Those worthy of respect, the wise; they do not associate.<br><br>'Despising their own banner, delighting in external colors,<br>Some wear white robes, the banner of outside sects.<br><br>'Not respecting the yellow robe, in that time they are thus.<br>They await the yellow robe, not of a bhikkhu.<br><br>'Overcome by suffering, pierced by the dart of pain,<br>They await great terror.<br>[But] this elephant does not think about that.<br><br>'When the six-tusked elephant saw the well-dyed Arahant banner,<br>He uttered verses connected with the goal.<br><br>'Whoever wears the robe<br>With mind not free from defilements,<br>Not self-controlled, not truthful,<br>Is not worthy of the robe.<br><br>'Whoever casts off defilements,<br>Well established in virtue,<br>Self-controlled, truthful,<br>Is indeed worthy of the robe.<br><br>'An immoral person of inferior wisdom,<br>Not self-controlled, greedy,<br>With distracted mind, uninspired,<br>Is not worthy of the robe.<br><br>'One complete in virtue,<br>Free from greed, concentrated,<br>With truly pure mind,<br>That one is worthy of the robe.<br><br>'Whoever is arrogant and heedless,<br>Foolish, without virtue,<br>Deserves to wear white —<br>What need has that one of a robe?<br><br>'Bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs with defiled minds, without faith,<br>Will in the future oppress those with compassionate minds.<br><br>'Fools wearing robes, though taught by elders,<br>Of weak wisdom, will not listen, not self-controlled, greedy.<br><br>'Though taught thus, fools will not respect one another,<br>Will not obey the words of the teacher,<br>Like a wild horse [fails to obey] the charioteer.<br><br>'Thus in the future, conduct will be like that.<br>Bhikkhus, bhikkhunīs, when the final time comes,<br>Be gentle and friendly, respect one another.<br><br>'Before this great calamity comes, before the great calamity arrives,<br>Be gentle and friendly, respect one another.<br><br>'Have a mind of loving-kindness and compassion,<br>Well restrained in virtue,<br>Devoted to energy and effort,<br>Always persistently inspired.<br><br>'Seeing the danger in heedlessness,<br>Security in non-heedlessness,<br>Develop the Noble Eightfold Path,<br>Realize the Deathless path.'`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.1" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta:<br><br>One who, according to one's ability,<br>Is virtuous, pure, mindful,<br>Practicing heedfully, with right thought,<br>Delighting inwardly, well concentrated,<br>Alone, knowing contentment —<br>Such a one is called a bhikkhu.<br><br>Whether eating wet or dry food,<br>One should not eat to satiety.<br>With an empty belly, eating moderately,<br>A bhikkhu dwells mindful.<br><br>Having eaten four or five morsels,<br>Then one should drink water.<br>That is sufficient for a diligent bhikkhu to dwell comfortably.<br><br>Receiving lawful [requisites], robes to meet needs,<br>That is sufficient for a diligent bhikkhu to dwell comfortably.<br><br>When sitting cross-legged, if the rain wets his knees,<br>That is sufficient for a diligent bhikkhu to dwell comfortably.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>One who sees pleasure as suffering,<br>Sees suffering as a dart,<br>Standing in the middle of both —<br>How can the world hold that one?<br><br>Not allowing evil desires,<br>Laziness, weak energy,<br>Little learning, no faith —<br>How can the world hold that one?<br><br>Much learning, wise,<br>Well concentrated in virtue,<br>Focused on mental stillness —<br>Stand up, be at the forefront.<br><br>One who devotes oneself to proliferation,<br>Like a beast delighting in proliferation,<br>Falls away, missing Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security from bondage.<br><br>One who abandons proliferation,<br>Delights in the non-proliferating path,<br>Reaches Nibbāna,<br>The unsurpassed security from bondage.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>In village or forest,<br>In valley or on hill,<br>Wherever an Arahant dwells,<br>That place is delightful.<br><br>Delightful are the forests,<br>Where people do not rejoice.<br>The passion-free rejoice there,<br>For they seek no sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>Just as a person points out a buried treasure,<br>So one who sees a fault and reproves,<br>Speaks what the wise would criticize —<br>Associate with such a wise person.<br>Associating with such a one, one becomes better, not worse.<br><br>One should advise, should teach,<br>Should restrain from the unwholesome.<br>Doing so, the good love him,<br>The bad do not like him.<br><br>The Blessed One, the One with Eyes, taught the Dhamma to others.<br>When the Dhamma was taught, I listened intently.<br>I heard without waste, I am liberated, without taints.<br><br>I have no need to know past lives,<br>No need for the divine eye.<br>I have no wish to attain knowledge of others' minds,<br>To know the passing away and rebirth of beings,<br>Or for the purified divine ear.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>Sitting at the foot of a tree, shaven-headed, wearing the great robe,<br>The elder of foremost wisdom, Upātissa, meditates.<br><br>Possessing jhāna without applied thought,<br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>At that very moment, he attained noble silence.<br><br>Like a stone mountain, unshaken, well established,<br>So a bhikkhu who has destroyed delusion,<br>That one, like a mountain, is not shaken.<br><br>An unstained person always seeks purity.<br>A fault as small as a hair's tip is seen as heavy as a cloud of smoke.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I will lay down this body, mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>I do not delight in death, I do not delight in life.<br>I will lay down this body, like a worker [leaving] his work.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>Both death and not-death — in future life or past life —<br>Advance, do not let it be in vain,<br>Not even a moment, an instant, let it not pass in vain.<br><br>Like a border fortress guarded within and without,<br>So guard yourself; do not waste the moment.<br>The moment passed brings sorrow, suffering in hell.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Sāriputta (continued):<br><br>Attaining peace, stillness,<br>Reciting, not conceited,<br>Sweeping away evil states like the wind sweeps leaves.<br><br>Attaining peace, stillness,<br>Reciting, not conceited,<br>Casting away evil states like the wind sweeps leaves.<br><br>Attaining peaceful silence,<br>Mind pure, unstained,<br>One of perfect virtue can end suffering.<br><br>There are those in whom no one has faith,<br>Whether householder or renunciant.<br>Some who were good later become bad,<br>Or who were bad later become good.<br><br>A bhikkhu who is greedy,<br>Lives with dullness and drowsiness,<br>Restlessness and doubt,<br>Has a mind full of the five defilements.<br><br>One who, regarding both [praise and blame],<br>Whether honored or not,<br>Is unshaken in jhāna,<br>Dwells heedfully, not heedless.<br><br>Meditating constantly with persistence,<br>With insight, seeing the subtle,<br>Delighting in the destruction of grasping,<br>That one is called a genuine person.<br><br>The great ocean, the great earth,<br>Mountains, and the directions of the sky —<br>They cannot compare with the Buddha's supreme liberation.<br><br>The elder who set in motion the Dhamma wheel,<br>Of great wisdom, meditative,<br>Like earth, water, and fire,<br>Without greed, without hatred.<br><br>Attaining supreme wisdom,<br>Greatly awakened, the great sage,<br>Neither slow nor sluggish,<br>Always living truly cooled.<br><br>I serve the Teacher, done is the Buddha's teaching.<br>The burden is laid down, the root of existence uprooted.<br><br>Strive, do not be heedless — this is my instruction.<br>I will attain Nibbāna, I am free from all attachments.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.2" },
{ text: `Elder Ānanda:<br><br>Divisive speech and anger,<br>Stinginess and delight in causing harm —<br>The wise do not associate with evil people, bad friends.<br><br>With the faithful, the amiable,<br>With the wise, the learned,<br>The wise associate, the good, with genuine persons.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.3" },
{ text: `Elder Ānanda (continued):<br><br>Respect the learned, do not harm learning,<br>That is the root of the holy life; therefore, bear the Dhamma.<br><br>Knowing the sequence of earlier and later, knowing the meaning, skilled in words and phrases,<br>Grasping what is well grasped, searching for the meaning.<br><br>Through the virtue of patience, one's aspiration is accomplished.<br>Having been diligent, one then reflects,<br>At the right time, makes effort, with mind well concentrated.<br><br>A learned one who bears the Dhamma, with wisdom, a disciple of the Buddha,<br>Knowing the Dhamma, waiting for the time — one should associate with that person.<br><br>The learned, bearing the Dhamma, guarding the treasure of the great seer,<br>The eye of the whole world — honor the learned.<br><br>Delighting in Dhamma, joyful in Dhamma,<br>Always reflecting on the true Dhamma,<br>A bhikkhu mindful of the Dhamma<br>Does not fall away from the sublime Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.3" },
{ text: `Elder Ānanda (continued):<br><br>Is the body heavy with selfishness, not fond of activity?<br>Time wears away — cannot you rise up?<br>Attached to bodily pleasures, from where will ascetic happiness come?<br><br>All directions are unclear; the Dhamma has not arisen in me.<br>My good friend has gone; darkness spreads everywhere.<br><br>The friend has passed away, the Teacher has passed away.<br>There is no such friend as mindfulness of the body.<br><br>The old ones have passed away; the new ones do not suit me.<br>Now I meditate alone, like a bird when the rain comes.`, ref: "Theragāthā 17.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag17.3" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kassapa:<br><br>Do not go at the head, honored by the crowd,<br>For the mind becomes disturbed; it is hard to attain jhāna.<br>Crowds are suffering; seeing this, avoid the crowd.<br><br>The seer does not go to families.<br>For the mind becomes disturbed; it is hard to attain jhāna.<br>One who is infatuated with tastes abandons the goal that brings happiness.<br><br>Honor and offerings arising from families —<br>Know them as truly a heap of mud.<br>Like a subtle arrow, very hard to remove,<br>It is hard for a bad person to abandon respect.`, ref: "Theragāthā 18.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag18.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kassapa (continued):<br><br>Returning from alms round, Kassapa climbs the rock,<br>Sits in meditation, without clinging, free from fear and terror.<br><br>Returning from alms round, Kassapa climbs the rock,<br>Sits in meditation, without clinging, burned, cooled.<br><br>Returning from alms round, Kassapa climbs the rock,<br>Sits in meditation, without clinging, duty done, without taints.<br><br>Enough for me, mindful, ardent, desiring to meditate.<br>Enough for me, a bhikkhu, ardent, desiring benefit.<br><br>Enough for me, a bhikkhu, ardent, desiring happiness.<br>Enough for me, a bhikkhu, ardent, practicing yoga.`, ref: "Theragāthā 18.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag18.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kassapa (continued):<br><br>The land is truly lovely, with garlands of kareṇī flowers,<br>Spread everywhere, with pleasing elephant calls — that mountain delights me.<br><br>Lakes with clear, cool water, beautiful, cloud-colored,<br>Covered by 'Indra's herders' — those rocky mountains delight my mind.<br><br>Cloud-blue hills, like beautiful towers,<br>With pleasing monkey calls — that mountain delights me.<br><br>The plain is truly lovely, moistened by rain,<br>The mountain is made a dwelling by seers.<br>Resounding with peacock calls — that mountain delights me.<br><br>Filled with flowering thorn trees, like a sky covered with clouds,<br>Full of all kinds of birds — that mountain delights me.<br><br>Not crowded with householders, a dwelling for herds of deer,<br>Full of all kinds of birds — that mountain delights me.<br><br>Under the rocky cliff, cold water flows,<br>Monkeys and deer live nearby.<br>Covered with plants and trees — those mountains delight me.<br><br>Such a person does not delight even in the five kinds of musical instruments,<br>When one-pointed, rightly meditating on the Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 18.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag18.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Kassapa (continued):<br><br>Do not do too many things, avoid competing with the crowd.<br>The diligent one attached to tastes abandons the goal that brings happiness.<br><br>Do not do many tasks, avoid this unbeneficial thing.<br>The body becomes exhausted, tired; the suffering one does not find peace.<br><br>Only stuttering with the lips, not seeing oneself,<br>One's neck stiffens; that one thinks: 'I am better.'<br><br>Not better, thinking better,<br>The fool thinks of himself.<br>The wise do not praise<br>One who is stiff with conceit.<br><br>I am better, or<br>I am not better,<br>Or I am worse —<br>I am the same as that.<br>One who is not shaken<br>By these kinds of conceit,<br><br>Having wisdom, speaking truthfully,<br>Well concentrated in virtue,<br>Attained to mental peace —<br>That one the wise praise.<br><br>One who among fellow celibates<br>Is not respected<br>Is far from the sublime Dhamma,<br>Like the earth from the sky.<br><br>Those with moral shame and moral dread,<br>Always rightly established,<br>Grow in the holy life;<br>They have destroyed renewed existence.<br><br>A conceited, restless bhikkhu,<br>Though wearing a dust-heap robe,<br>Like a monkey dressed in a lion's skin,<br>Cannot shine because of that robe.<br><br>Not conceited, not restless,<br>Careful, with faculties restrained,<br>He shines with the robe gathered from the rubbish heap,<br>Like a lion in a mountain cave.<br><br>Not stained by robes,<br>By lodgings or by food,<br>Immeasurable is the son of Gotama!<br>Like a pure lotus, not stained by water,<br>His mind inclined to renunciation,<br>Transcending the three realms.<br><br>The great seer, with neck raised on the foundation of mindfulness,<br>With hands leaning on faith,<br>With the head of wisdom —<br>The great wise one always practices truly cooled.`, ref: "Theragāthā 18.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag18.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa:<br><br>When will I go alone, without a second,<br>Into the caves of the mountains,<br>Contemplating all existence as impermanent?<br>Thus I am now; when will it be so?<br><br>When will I become a seer wearing patched robes,<br>Wearing a yellow cloth, without 'mine', without craving,<br>Destroyed, with greed for mind abandoned,<br>And also hatred and delusion abandoned?<br>I will go to the forest and dwell in happiness.<br><br>When will I see this body as impermanent,<br>Oppressed by death and old age,<br>A slaughterhouse, a disease?<br>I will dwell in the forest alone, contemplating fearlessness.<br>When will it be so?<br><br>When will I take the sharp sword of wisdom,<br>Cut the creeper of craving with its many entangled branches,<br>Which gives rise to fear, bringing suffering?<br>When will it be so?<br><br>When will I be strong, drawing the sword<br>Made of wisdom, a seer's blazing fire;<br>With that strength, crushing Māra and his army<br>On the lion's seat — when will it be so?<br><br>When will I gather with the good,<br>Be seen among them, take up heavy responsibilities,<br>Diligent with them, seeing things as they are,<br>Conquering the faculties — when will it be so?`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>When will laziness, hunger, thirst,<br>Wind, heat, reptiles and insects<br>Not afflict me, at Giribbaja,<br>Concerned for myself — when will it be so?<br><br>When can I, mindful, concentrated,<br>Understand with wisdom the four truths well taught by the great seer —<br>When will it be so?<br><br>When will I focus my mind on peace,<br>Seeing with wisdom forms, sounds, tastes, scents, touches,<br>These impermanent phenomena as a blazing fire —<br>When will I be so?<br><br>When, spoken to with harsh words,<br>Will my mind not be disappointed because of that?<br>And when praised, will my mind not be elated because of that?<br>When will I be so?<br><br>When, regarding wood, grass, creepers, trunks,<br>I will consider equally all these countless things,<br>Internal and external phenomena — when will I be so?`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>When will the cloud bring rain with its fresh water in the forest,<br>Wetting my robe as I walk on the wet path,<br>The seer's path — when will it be so?<br><br>When will I hear in the forest the call of birds,<br>Peacocks with crested heads,<br>In a mountain cave, I dwell reflecting,<br>To attain the Deathless state — when will I be so?<br><br>When will I, with psychic power, cross without sinking, without fear,<br>The Ganges, the Yamunā,<br>The Sarasvatī, with its terrifying river mouth,<br>With roaring, deep waters — when will it be so?<br><br>When, like an elephant attacking on the battlefield,<br>I will shatter to pieces the desire for sensory objects,<br>Focused on meditation, abandoning all signs of beauty —<br>When will it be so?<br><br>When, like a poor man in debt, unable to repay,<br>Pressed by the rich, finds buried treasure,<br>I will be relieved, having heard the teaching<br>Of the great seer — when will it be so?`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>For many years you have been asking me to do thus:<br>'That is enough; you live the household life.'<br>Now I have gone forth. Therefore, O mind,<br>For what reason are you not focused?<br><br>O mind, is it not that you ask me thus:<br>'At Giribbaja, the bright-feathered birds greet with their calls,<br>The thunder of great Indra. Make that one happy, meditating in the forest.'<br><br>In the family, friends, lovers, and relatives,<br>All the pleasures of the world, all objects of sensual desire —<br>All have been abandoned; I accept this.<br>O mind, are you not content with me?<br><br>This matter concerns only me, not another.<br>When the time for battle comes, why lament?<br>This whole world is agitated — that is to be expected.<br>Therefore I have set out to seek the Deathless path.<br><br>The one who speaks what is hard to speak, the supreme among two-footed beings,<br>The great King of Physicians, the charioteer taming humans,<br>With mind free from sensual desire, he has well tamed<br>The hard-to-tame, tamed the minds of people,<br>Agitated like a monkey.<br><br>In the forest resounds the call of peacocks and herons,<br>The preferred dwelling of leopards and tigers.<br>You dwell there, do not wait for the body,<br>Do not be overly infatuated.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Sensual pleasures have many forms, sweet, very agreeable.<br>Here, ordinary people, lacking wisdom, are bound.<br>Wishing to suffer, they seek renewed existence,<br>Led by their minds, they die in hell.`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>Develop jhāna, faculties, powers,<br>Develop concentration, factors of enlightenment,<br>Realize the three knowledges in the Buddha's teaching.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Develop the path to attain the Deathless,<br>The path leading to the penetration<br>Where all suffering is destroyed.<br>The eightfold path washing away all defilements —<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Contemplate the aggregates as suffering,<br>Abandon from you the causes of suffering.<br>In this very life, make an end of suffering.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Contemplate with wisdom: impermanent, suffering,<br>Empty, not-self, evil, murderous,<br>Restrain your mind, do not let it run.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Shaven-headed and ugly, going about reviled,<br>When begging alms from families, holding a skull-shaped bowl —<br>Now are you focused on the Teacher's instruction,<br>The word of the great seer? O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Walk on the path with self well tamed,<br>Among houses, with mind not attached to sensual desires,<br>Like the full moon without a cloud.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.<br><br>Live in the forest, eat almsfood,<br>Dwell in a charnel ground, wear dust-heap robes,<br>Always sitting, never lying down,<br>Delight in the ascetic practices.<br>O mind, encourage me, advise me as before.`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>Like one who plants a tree and immediately seeks fruit,<br>Now you desire fruit — why would you cut the root?<br>O mind, you have truly done like this simile,<br>When you encourage me in the impermanent, the agitated.<br><br>You, formless, solitary, a traveler from afar,<br>Now I will not act according to your words.<br>Sensual pleasures are suffering, bitter, a great fear.<br>My mind inclines to Nibbāna; I will step forward.<br><br>I went forth not because of misfortune,<br>Not as a game, not shamelessly,<br>Not on a whim, not because of exile,<br>Not for the sake of livelihood.<br>Since I have agreed with you, O mind,<br><br>Few desires are praised by genuine persons,<br>Even the abandonment of deceit and the calming of suffering.<br>Thus, O mind, when you encourage me,<br>Now you are going against what you used to do.<br><br>Craving and ignorance, pitiable and hateful,<br>Beautiful forms and pleasant feelings,<br>Alluring strands of sensual pleasure —<br>All are abandoned; I will not strive again<br>To go to things already abandoned.`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa (continued):<br><br>O mind, everywhere I have followed your command,<br>Through many lives, you have not been angry with me.<br>This body arisen internally is your gratitude!<br>On the long path of saṃsāra, suffering is caused by you.<br><br>O mind, you yourself have made this person,<br>You yourself have made me become a brahmin,<br>A royal warrior, a member of royalty,<br>One day a merchant, another day a servant,<br>Or even a deva —<br>All this is done by you, made by you.<br><br>Because of you, we became asuras.<br>By your doing, I fell to the bottom of hell.<br>One time an animal, one time a hungry ghost —<br>All this is done by you, made by you.<br><br>You will not deceive me again, many times, many occasions,<br>Like magicians performing tricks.<br>You play with me as with a madman.<br>O mind, tell me where I have erred.<br><br>Formerly this mind wandered,<br>Went where it liked, where it delighted, where it was happy.<br>Now I restrain it with wise reflection,<br>As a hook restrains a wild elephant.<br><br>For me, the Teacher declared the world as impermanent,<br>The world is not lasting, the world has no core.<br>O mind, push me into the Buddha's teaching,<br>Make me cross the flood so hard to cross.<br><br>Now I have gone forth in the Dhamma of the great seer.<br>Those like me do not accept loss.<br><br>Forests, oceans, rivers, dry land, the four directions, above and below —<br>All is impermanent, the three realms are a calamity.<br>O mind, where will you go to enjoy happiness?`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },


{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa:<br><br>Look, look, O mind,<br>My goal is truly firm.<br>What can you do to make me turn back?<br>O mind, I am no longer under your power.<br>No one touches a thing with two openings,<br>Disgusting thing, full of nine flowing streams.<br><br>O, you will like to live<br>On a mountain peak,<br>Where herds of deer live,<br>Or in beautiful nature,<br>Or in the deep forest,<br>Cool with fresh rain water.<br>There you will delight; you will take a cave as your home.<br><br>Birds with beautiful neck feathers,<br>With beautiful crests, beautiful wings,<br>With feathers of many colors,<br>Greeting the resounding thunder,<br>With sweet calls,<br>They will delight you,<br>You, practicing jhāna meditation,<br>In the deep forest.<br><br>When rain pours down<br>On the fertilized grass<br>And in the flowering forest,<br>With cloud-like flower heads,<br>In the forest I will lie down,<br>Like a piece of wood,<br>To me, very soft,<br>Just like a cotton bed.<br><br>Thus I will do,<br>Like a householder,<br>Whatever I receive,<br>I consider sufficient,<br>Like a leather worker, not lazy,<br>Skillfully making supple,<br>A bag of cat skin.<br><br>Thus I will do,<br>Like a householder,<br>Whatever I receive,<br>I consider sufficient.<br>With energy I will lead you,<br>Falling under my power,<br>Like a rutting elephant<br>Well tamed by a goad.<br><br>You, well subdued,<br>Well established firmly,<br>Like a horse trainer<br>With a well-trained horse,<br>I can step forward<br>On the peaceful path,<br>The path used by those<br>Who guard their minds.<br><br>I will tie you tightly<br>To the necessary object,<br>Like an elephant bound<br>To a post by a rope.<br>I will guard you well,<br>Well train you with mindfulness.<br>Thus, you will become<br>Not dependent on any existence.<br><br>With wisdom, cut off the wrong path,<br>With power, block and direct to the right.<br>Seeing origination and cessation,<br>You will become the heir<br>Of the supreme speaker.<br><br>O mind, you lead me<br>To a coarse village,<br>Establishing me under the power<br>Of the four perversions.<br>Come, follow that one<br>Who has cut off the fetters,<br>Who has a mind of great compassion,<br>The great seer.<br><br>Like a wild animal<br>In a beautiful forest,<br>You enter a beautiful mountain<br>With clouds as garlands.<br>There, without people,<br>In the forest you will delight.<br>Now, mind, surely thus<br>You will reach the far shore.<br><br>Those who still fall<br>Under the power of your desire,<br>Men and women,<br>Enjoying the happiness you give,<br>Lacking wisdom, fall<br>Under Māra's power.<br>Whoever delights in existence<br>Will be your servant,<br>O my mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Moggallāna:<br><br>We are forest dwellers,<br>Living on almsfood,<br>Content with the food<br>Discarded in the bowl.<br>We crush Māra and his army,<br>If the mind is well concentrated.<br><br>We are forest dwellers,<br>Living on almsfood,<br>Content with the food<br>Discarded in the bowl.<br>We drive away Māra and his army,<br>Like an elephant [crushes] a hut of reeds.<br><br>We dwell at the foot of a tree,<br>Patient, with persistent mind,<br>Content with the food<br>Discarded in the bowl.<br>We crush Māra and his army,<br>If the mind is well concentrated.<br><br>We dwell at the foot of a tree,<br>Patient, with persistent mind,<br>Content with the food<br>Discarded in the bowl.<br>We drive away Māra and his army,<br>Like an elephant [crushes] a hut of reeds.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Moggallāna (continued):<br><br>With a hut whose sides are made of bones,<br>Sewn together with sinews and flesh,<br>Disgusting, full of foul smell!<br>Carrying another's limbs<br>As one's own body!<br><br>A bag filled with excrement,<br>Covered by skin,<br>O that female demon!<br>With breasts like boils,<br>Your body, nine streams<br>Constantly flowing.<br><br>Your body, nine streams,<br>Foul-smelling, creating bondage,<br>A bhikkhu avoids that body,<br>Like a clean person avoids excrement.<br><br>If others knew you<br>As I know you,<br>They would avoid you,<br>As one avoids excrement when it rains.<br><br>Truly so, O great hero,<br>Like an ascetic, you say:<br>Here, some are stuck,<br>Like an old cow in mud.<br><br>Whoever thinks they can dye<br>The sky with turmeric,<br>Or with another color —<br>That one only fails.<br><br>My mind is like that sky,<br>Well concentrated internally.<br>Do not bring an evil mind<br>Like a bird falling into a fire.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Moggallāna (continued):<br><br>All conditioned things are impermanent,<br>Whatever arises must cease.<br>Having arisen, they cease;<br>Their calming is bliss.<br><br>Those who see the five aggregates<br>As other, not self,<br>Penetrate the subtle<br>Like an arrow splitting a hair.<br><br>Those who see conditioned things<br>As other, not self,<br>They penetrate the subtle<br>Like an arrow splitting a hair.<br><br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if one's head is on fire,<br>A bhikkhu who has gone forth,<br>Mindful, abandons sensual desire.<br><br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if one's head is on fire,<br>A bhikkhu who has gone forth,<br>Mindful, abandons craving for existence.<br><br>Not with this weakness,<br>Not with this little strength,<br>Can one attain Nibbāna,<br>Liberated from all bonds.<br><br>This young bhikkhu,<br>This supreme person,<br>Has conquered Māra and his army,<br>Bearing this final body.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1" },
{ text: `Elder Mahā Moggallāna (continued):<br><br>Between Vebhāra mountain,<br>Between Paṇḍava mountain,<br>Lightning strikes the cave.<br>The son of the peerless one,<br>Has entered the mountain cave,<br>Sitting, absorbed in jhāna.<br><br>Peaceful and comfortable,<br>The seer dwells in a remote place,<br>Heir of the supreme Buddha,<br>Praised by Brahmā.<br><br>O brahmin, pay homage to Kassapa,<br>He is the heir,<br>Of the supreme Enlightened One,<br>The seer dwelling in a remote place,<br>Peaceful and comfortable.<br><br>He, before his meal,<br>Sees the eight liberations,<br>In forward and reverse order,<br>Then goes for alms.<br><br>Such a bhikkhu, O brahmin,<br>Arouse faith in him,<br>In such an Arahant.<br>Quickly bow with folded hands,<br>Do not let your head be broken.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1" },
{ text: `Elder Vaṅgīsa:<br><br>For me who has gone forth,<br>Leaving home for homelessness,<br>These thoughts run wild,<br>Arising from darkness.<br><br>Skilled archers, well-trained in archery,<br>A thousand people shooting in all directions,<br>Would not be shaken at all.<br><br>If women come,<br>Even more, even a crowd,<br>They will not shake me,<br>For I abide in the true Dhamma.<br><br>I have heard from the Buddha,<br>The Kinsman of the Sun,<br>Teaching the path to Nibbāna.<br>Here my mind delights.<br><br>Thus I abide.<br>If you come, O evil one,<br>I will act thus —<br>You will not see my path.<br><br>I have abandoned pleasure and displeasure,<br>All household thoughts,<br>Creating no basis anywhere,<br>No foundation for sensual desire.<br>One who has escaped the forest, free from greed,<br>Is rightly called a bhikkhu.<br><br>Whatever earth, without basis,<br>Whatever form realm in the world,<br>All is subject to change, impermanent.<br>Understanding this, one lives with full knowledge.<br><br>Beings cling<br>To various attachments,<br>To what they see, hear,<br>Touch, and think.<br>Here, one who abandons desire,<br>With mind unstained,<br>Not sticking to anything,<br>Is called a sage.<br><br>Regarding the sixty-eight views<br>Of ordinary people, based on non-Dhamma,<br>Not learning from wrong factions,<br>That one is a true bhikkhu.<br><br>Perfect, with mind constantly concentrated,<br>Not deceitful, careful,<br>Free from craving, a sage,<br>Attains the peaceful path.<br>He waits for his time,<br>Entering Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag21.1" },
{ text: `Elder Vaṅgīsa (continued):<br><br>Disciples of Gotama,<br>Abandon conceit.<br>On the path of conceit,<br>Avoid it completely.<br>One infatuated with the path of conceit<br>Will regret for a long time.<br><br>Deceived by deceit,<br>Harmed by conceit,<br>People fall into hell.<br>They grieve for a long time,<br>Harmed by conceit,<br>They are reborn in hell.<br><br>Never does a bhikkhu who has conquered the path,<br>Who rightly steps forward,<br>Grieve.<br>He enjoys fame and happiness,<br>Truly called<br>One who has seen the Dhamma.<br><br>Therefore, in this world,<br>Not harsh, not conceited,<br>Having abandoned hindrances, pure,<br>Having abandoned conceit without remainder,<br>With clear knowledge, mind peaceful,<br>One has ended suffering.`, ref: "Theragāthā 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag21.1" },
{ text: `Elder Vaṅgīsa (continued):<br><br>Sensual desire burns me!<br>My mind is on fire.<br>Good, Gotama,<br>Out of compassion, speak<br>The Dhamma that extinguishes the blazing fire.<br><br>Because of perverted perception,<br>Your mind is burning.<br>Abandon the sign of beauty<br>Connected with sensual desire.<br><br>See conditioned things as impermanent,<br>Suffering, not-self.<br>Extinguish great sensual desire,<br>Do not be burned again and again.<br>Develop the mind on foulness,<br>One-pointed, well concentrated.<br>Practice mindfulness of the body,<br>Live with much disenchantment.<br><br>Practice the signless,<br>Abandon the underlying tendency to conceit.<br>By breaking through conceit,<br>Your practice will be peaceful.`, ref: "Theragāthā 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag21.1" },
{ text: `Elder Vaṅgīsa (continued):<br><br>Whoever speaks whatever speech<br>That does not torment oneself,<br>That does not harm others —<br>That speech is truly well spoken.<br><br>Whoever speaks affectionate speech,<br>Speech that gladdens,<br>Speech that is not evil —<br>That speech is affectionate.<br><br>Truth is the deathless word;<br>This is the ancient Dhamma.<br>The good, established in truth,<br>In the goal and in the Dhamma, speak thus.<br><br>The word spoken by the Buddha<br>Attains security, Nibbāna,<br>Ends all suffering —<br>That is truly the supreme word.`, ref: "Theragāthā 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag21.1" },


            
                
          { text: `Elder Nun Muttā:<br><br>O Muttā, liberated,<br>Be freed from the bonds,<br>Like the moon freed<br>From Rāhu's mouth.<br>With mind liberated,<br>Free from the bondage of debt,<br>Enjoy the food<br>Brought by alms round.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.2" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Puṇṇā:<br><br>O Puṇṇā, fill yourself<br>With the true Dhamma,<br>Like the full moon<br>On the full moon day.<br>Fill yourself with wisdom,<br>Shatter the mass of delusion.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Tissā:<br><br>Tissā, train<br>In the training rules.<br>Do not let the bonds<br>Overcome you.<br>Live unattached,<br>Not bound by any bond.<br>Living in this world,<br>Be without taints.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.4" },
{ text: `Another Elder Nun Tissā:<br><br>Tissā, fix your mind<br>Focused on the Dhamma.<br>Do not let any moment<br>Pass you by in vain!<br>Those whose moments have passed<br>Grieve in suffering<br>When they fall into<br>The realm of hell.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Dhīrā:<br><br>Dhīrā, experience<br>The experiences of cessation,<br>The calming of thoughts,<br>True happiness.<br>Incline toward Nibbāna,<br>The security from bondage, the unconditioned.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.6" },
{ text: `Another Elder Nun Dhīrā:<br><br>Dhīrā, be persistent,<br>Grasping wholesome states.<br>O bhikkhunī,<br>With faculties developed,<br>Carry this body,<br>The final body,<br>Having conquered<br>Māra and his army.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.7" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mittā:<br><br>O friend Mittā,<br>Gone forth with faith,<br>Train yourself,<br>Rejoicing in good friends.<br>Train yourself<br>In wholesome states,<br>Strive to attain<br>Security from bondage.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.8" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Bhadrā:<br><br>O good Bhadrā,<br>Gone forth with faith,<br>Live joyfully<br>In wholesome states.<br>Train yourself<br>In the highest wholesome states,<br>Strive to attain<br>Security from bondage.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.9" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Upasanā:<br><br>O Upasanā,<br>Cross the strong flood,<br>The flood so hard to cross,<br>Ruled by the King of Death.<br>Carry this body,<br>The final body,<br>Having conquered<br>Māra and his army.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.10" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Muttā:<br><br>Good is liberation, Muttā!<br>I am truly well liberated,<br>Liberated from<br>Three crooked, bent things:<br>From the mortar, from the pestle,<br>From my hump-backed husband.<br>O liberated Muttā!<br>I am liberated from life and death.<br>What leads to renewed existence<br>Is uprooted.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.11" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Dhammadinnā:<br><br>In one in whom the desire<br>To attain the unborn state<br>Has arisen and spread,<br>Filling the mind,<br>The mind not bound<br>By ruling sensual desires,<br>That one is called<br>A stream-enterer.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.12" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Visākhā:<br><br>Do, practice<br>According to the Buddha's teaching.<br>And after doing it,<br>Have no regret.<br>Quickly wash your feet,<br>And sit down to one side.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.13" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumānā:<br><br>Having seen the realms<br>With a suffering perception,<br>Do not return again<br>To the path of renewed existence.<br>Abandon, let go of<br>Desire for existence,<br>Live the holy life.<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.14" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Uttarā:<br><br>I have subdued<br>Body, speech, and mind.<br>I have conquered craving<br>Down to its very root.<br>I am cooled,<br>In peace, calm.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.15" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumānā:<br><br>O that elder nun,<br>Lie down happily,<br>Covered in your robe,<br>Made by yourself.<br>Your greed is calmed,<br>You are cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.16" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Dhammā:<br><br>Having gone for alms,<br>Weak, leaning on a stick,<br>With trembling hands and feet,<br>I fell on the ground.<br>Seeing the danger of the body,<br>My mind was liberated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.17" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sañjā:<br><br>Leaving home, going forth,<br>I abandoned my children,<br>Abandoned precious livestock,<br>Abandoned greed and hatred,<br>And regarding ignorance,<br>I live in seclusion.<br>Having conquered<br>The root of craving itself,<br>I live cooled,<br>Peaceful and calm.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.18" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Abhirūpa Nandā:<br><br>O Nandā, look at this body,<br>Gathered here, diseased, impure,<br>Full of stench and decay.<br>Develop your mind on foulness,<br>Concentrated, one-pointed.<br><br>Develop the signless,<br>Abandon the underlying tendency to conceit.<br>By breaking through conceit,<br>You will live at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Jentī:<br><br>These seven factors of enlightenment<br>Are the path to Nibbāna.<br>I have developed them all,<br>As the Buddha taught.<br><br>I have seen the Blessed One,<br>This is the last body.<br>The round of birth and death is ended,<br>Now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.2" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mother of Sumaṅgala:<br><br>O well-liberated nun,<br>Good is well liberation!<br>I am well liberated<br>From the rice-pounding pestle.<br>I am no longer ashamed<br>Of my umbrella-maker husband,<br>Of my cooking pots,<br>Of miserable poverty.<br><br>Greed and hatred are cut off,<br>I live without greed and hatred.<br>I go to the foot of a tree —<br>O, the bliss of my meditation!`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Addhakāsī:<br><br>My earnings were not inferior<br>To the Kāsi tax.<br>After comparing the price,<br>The village head set the price.<br><br>Now I am disgusted<br>With my own beauty.<br>I am weary of that form,<br>I no longer long for it.<br>Let me not continuously<br>Run after the round of rebirth.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Accomplished in the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.4" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Cittā:<br><br>Though I am tired,<br>Sick and very weak,<br>Leaning on a stick, I walk.<br>I climb the mountain.<br><br>With the great robe slung across,<br>With the bowl turned upside down,<br>I lean against a rock,<br>I shatter the mass of delusion.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mettikā:<br><br>Though I am in pain,<br>Weak, my youth has passed,<br>Leaning on a stick, I walk,<br>I climb the mountain.<br><br>With the great robe slung across,<br>With the bowl turned upside down,<br>I sit on a rock,<br>My mind is liberated.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Accomplished in the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.6" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mittā:<br><br>On the fourteenth, the fifteenth,<br>On the eighth of each half-month,<br>On the special fast-day of the lunar fortnight,<br>I observed the eight precepts.<br><br>I kept the uposatha observance,<br>Making the devas rejoice.<br>Eating one meal a day,<br>Shaven-headed, wearing the great robe,<br>I do not long for the heavenly realm,<br>I subdue the suffering of the mind.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.7" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mother of Abhayā:<br><br>From the soles of the feet up,<br>From the top of the head down,<br>Contemplate this body,<br>This body is truly impure,<br>Truly foul and stinking.<br><br>I abide thus.<br>All sensual desire is uprooted,<br>Fever is dispelled,<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.8" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Abhayā:<br><br>O fearless nun,<br>This body is truly frail.<br>Ordinary people here<br>Delight in it, often cling to it.<br>I will lay down this body,<br>Mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>Focusing, not heedless,<br>I strive to escape the Dhamma of suffering.<br>I have attained the destruction of craving,<br>Accomplished in the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.9" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sāmā:<br><br>Four times and five times,<br>I left the monastery,<br>But my mind was not at peace,<br>I could not subdue my mind.<br>But on the eighth night,<br>Craving was uprooted.<br><br>Focusing, not heedless,<br>I strive to escape the Dhamma of suffering.<br>I have attained the destruction of craving,<br>Accomplished in the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.10" },
{ text: `Another Elder Nun Sāmā:<br><br>Twenty-five years have passed<br>Since I went forth.<br>I did not directly know the mind,<br>Did not attain mental balance.<br><br>The mind was not peaceful,<br>I could not subdue my mind.<br>Therefore I was agitated,<br>Remembering the Buddha's words.<br><br>Focusing, not heedless,<br>I strive to escape the Dhamma of suffering.<br>I have attained the destruction of craving,<br>Accomplished in the Buddha's teaching.<br>Tonight, on the seventh night,<br>Craving has dried up.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Uttamā:<br><br>Four times and five times,<br>I left the monastery,<br>But my mind was not at peace,<br>I could not subdue my mind.<br><br>I went to a bhikkhunī,<br>A faithful woman like me.<br>She taught me the Dhamma,<br>About aggregates, sense spheres, and elements.<br><br>Having heard the Dhamma she taught,<br>As she instructed me,<br>For seven days sitting cross-legged,<br>I enjoyed joy and bliss.<br>On the eighth, I stretched my legs,<br>I shattered the mass of delusion.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.2" },
{ text: `Another Elder Nun Uttarā:<br><br>The seven factors of enlightenment,<br>The path to Nibbāna,<br>I have developed them all,<br>As the Buddha taught.<br><br>By contemplating the Void and the Signless,<br>I attained the desired fruit.<br>I am a daughter of the Buddha,<br>Born from his mouth.<br>I always rejoice<br>In the bliss of Nibbāna.<br><br>All sensual desires are destroyed,<br>Heavenly desires and human desires.<br>The round of existence is ended,<br>Now there is no more renewed existence.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Daṇḍikā:<br><br>Leaving the monastery,<br>For the day's rest,<br>On Vulture's Peak mountain,<br>I saw an elephant<br>Emerging from the water<br>Onto the river bank.<br><br>A man holding a hook<br>Asked for its leg.<br>The elephant stretched out its leg,<br>And the man climbed onto the elephant.<br><br>Seeing the unsubdued<br>Being subdued,<br>I saw it obeying<br>The man's power.<br>Thus I composed my mind<br>And entered that forest.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.4" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Ubbirī:<br><br>O Ubbirī,<br>You cry in the deep forest,<br>Lamenting 'O Jīvā, my daughter'.<br>Come to your senses,<br>O Ubbirī!<br>On this funeral pyre, all these eighty-four thousand<br>Persons named Jīvā —<br>For which Jīvā do you cry?<br><br>The dart, hard to see,<br>Implanted in my heart,<br>Surely has been drawn out by you,<br>Drawn out from my heart.<br>Sorrow for my daughter,<br>Which overwhelmed me, is completely ended.<br><br>Now the dart is drawn out,<br>All longing is calmed.<br>I go for refuge to the seer,<br>The sage, to the Buddha,<br>The Dhamma, and the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Bhaddā:<br><br>I am the heir of the Buddha,<br>Kassapa, well-concentrated.<br>I know my past lives,<br>See heavenly and hellish realms.<br><br>The seer who has destroyed birth,<br>Perfect in direct knowledge,<br>Along with these three knowledges,<br>Is a brahmin with three knowledges.<br><br>So too, you, Bhaddā Kapilānī,<br>You are one with three knowledges,<br>You have destroyed death,<br>Bearing your final body,<br>Having conquered Māra's army.<br><br>Seeing the danger in the world,<br>We both went forth.<br>We are tamed, our taints destroyed,<br>We are cooled, at peace, liberated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig4.1" },
{ text: `Unnamed Elder Nun:<br><br>Twenty-five years have passed<br>Since I went forth,<br>Yet in the snap of a finger,<br>My mind was not calm.<br><br>My mind was not at peace,<br>Full of sensual desire.<br>Wringing my hands, I cried,<br>I entered the monastery.<br><br>I went to that nun,<br>A faithful woman like me.<br>She taught me the Dhamma,<br>About aggregates, sense spheres, and elements.<br><br>Having heard the Dhamma she taught,<br>I sat down to one side.<br>I remembered my past lives,<br>My divine eye was purified.<br><br>With knowledge of others' minds,<br>My ear was purified.<br>I attained psychic power,<br>I attained the destruction of taints.<br>I attained the six direct knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Vimalā, formerly a courtesan:<br><br>Infatuated with my caste,<br>With my beauty and youth,<br>With fame and renown,<br>I relied on my youth,<br>Despising others,<br>Looking down on them.<br><br>I adorned this body,<br>I seduced fools,<br>I stood at the door,<br>At the shop of beauty,<br>Like a cruel hunter<br>Setting his trap.<br><br>I boasted of my adornments,<br>Revealed many hidden parts,<br>To mock many men,<br>I performed many tricks.<br><br>Today, going for alms,<br>Shaven-headed, wearing the great robe,<br>I sit at the foot of a tree,<br>I attain thought-free concentration.<br><br>All bonds are destroyed,<br>Both divine and human bonds.<br>Having abandoned all taints,<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.2" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sīhā:<br><br>Through unwise attention,<br>Obsessed by sensual desire,<br>I was previously agitated,<br>Unable to subdue my mind.<br><br>Overcome by defilements,<br>The perception of pleasure ruled me.<br>My mind was not balanced,<br>Overcome by a greedy mind.<br><br>For seven years I lived sickly,<br>Jaundiced, with bad complexion.<br>Day and night without happiness,<br>I lived in suffering.<br><br>Therefore I took a rope,<br>I went into the forest.<br>Better for me to hang myself<br>Than to live a low life.<br><br>Making the noose firm,<br>I tied it to a branch.<br>I put the noose around my neck —<br>Then my mind was liberated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sundarī Nandā:<br><br>Nandā, look at this body,<br>Diseased, impure, foul-smelling.<br>Develop your mind on foulness,<br>One-pointed, well concentrated.<br><br>As this body is, so is that;<br>As that body is, so is this.<br>Foul and rotting,<br>Only fools delight in it.<br><br>Thus contemplate this body,<br>Day and night without fatigue.<br>With your own wisdom,<br>Therefore abandon [desire];<br>With your own wisdom,<br>Escape from pride in beauty,<br>And see the fool<br>With a seeing that is real.<br><br>This city is built of bones,<br>Plastered with flesh and blood.<br>Here dwell old age and death,<br>Conceit and deceit are stored.<br><br>With mind not heedless,<br>Wisely contemplate that body,<br>The true nature of this body,<br>Seen within and without.<br>I am disgusted with the body,<br>My mind is dispassionate within.<br>Not heedless, detached,<br>I am at peace, calm.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.4" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Maṇḍuttarā:<br><br>Formerly I worshiped fire,<br>The moon, the sun, and devas.<br>I went to riverbanks,<br>I went down into the water, I bathed.<br><br>Accepting many observances,<br>I shaved only half my head.<br>I slept on the ground,<br>I did not eat at night.<br><br>Delighting in adornments and ornaments,<br>Loving to bathe and anoint,<br>I served this body,<br>Satisfying sensual desires.<br><br>Since I gained faith,<br>Homeless, I went forth.<br>I see the body as the Buddha [taught],<br>Thanks to the cleansing of sensual desires.<br><br>All existence is cut off,<br>All longing and aspiration.<br>All bonds are loosened,<br>I have attained peace of mind.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mittakāḷī:<br><br>With faith, I went forth,<br>Leaving home for homelessness.<br>My mind was strongly inclined<br>Toward gain and honor.<br><br>Abandoning the supreme goal,<br>I served a lowly goal.<br>Ruled by defilements,<br>I abandoned the goal of asceticism.<br><br>Sitting in my monastery room,<br>I felt agitated.<br>I entered the wrong path,<br>Craving ruled me.<br><br>My life is brief,<br>Old age and disease are pressing.<br>Before this body is destroyed,<br>There is no more time for heedlessness.<br><br>Contemplating as it really is<br>The arising and passing of the aggregates,<br>With mind liberated, I attained<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.6" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sakulā:<br><br>When living at home,<br>I heard a bhikkhu teach the Dhamma.<br>I saw the stainless Dhamma,<br>The path to the Deathless, Nibbāna.<br><br>Abandoning son and daughter,<br>All wealth and grain,<br>Shaving my hair, I went forth<br>To the homeless life.<br><br>While a novice, I trained,<br>Developing the right path.<br>I abandoned greed and hatred,<br>And the taints one by one.<br><br>Having received the bhikkhunī ordination,<br>I remembered my past lives.<br>My divine eye was purified,<br>Stainless, well developed.<br><br>Seeing the various external [worlds],<br>Due to conditions, subject to change,<br>I destroyed all taints,<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.7" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Soṇā:<br><br>I gave birth to ten children<br>From this accumulative body.<br>Therefore I was weak and aged.<br>I went to a bhikkhunī.<br><br>She taught me the Dhamma,<br>About aggregates, sense spheres, and elements.<br>Hearing the Dhamma she taught,<br>I shaved my hair and went forth.<br><br>I followed her instruction.<br>My divine eye was purified,<br>I know my past lives,<br>Where I lived before.<br><br>I developed the signless Dhamma,<br>One-pointed, well concentrated.<br>Instantly I was liberated,<br>Without clinging, at peace.<br><br>The five aggregates are fully understood,<br>They stand with roots cut off.<br>I have no sensual desire,<br>No firm foundation.<br>From now on, there is no<br>Issue of renewed existence.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.8" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Paṭācārā:<br><br>With a plough, plowing the field,<br>Sowing seeds in the ground,<br>People gain wealth,<br>Supporting their wives and children.<br><br>Why, when I am virtuous,<br>Following the Teacher's instruction,<br>Do I not attain Nibbāna?<br>Not lazy, not agitated.<br><br>When I was washing my feet,<br>Watching the water flow,<br>I saw the foot-water<br>Flowing from high to low.<br><br>Thus my mind became concentrated,<br>Like a fine, well-trained horse.<br>Then I took a lamp,<br>Entered the monastery.<br>Lying on a small bed,<br>I contemplated the lamp.<br><br>Then taking a small needle,<br>I lowered the wick.<br>Seeing the lamp's Nibbāna,<br>My mind was liberated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.10" },
{ text: `Thirty Elder Nuns:<br><br>People in their youth,<br>Holding pestles, pounding rice,<br>People gain wealth,<br>Supporting their wives and children.<br><br>Follow the Buddha's teaching.<br>Do nothing that causes distress.<br>Wash your feet quickly,<br>Sit down to one side,<br>Focus on mental stillness,<br>Do as the Buddha taught.<br><br>Having heard the teaching,<br>The words of Paṭācārā,<br>After washing their feet,<br>They entered and sat down to one side,<br>Focusing on mental stillness,<br>Doing as the Buddha taught.<br><br>In the first watch of the night,<br>They remembered their past lives.<br>In the middle watch,<br>Their divine eye was purified.<br>In the last watch,<br>They shattered the mass of delusion.<br><br>Rising, they bowed at the feet<br>Of their instructress.<br>Like the Thirty-three devas<br>Honoring Sakka,<br>The undefeated one remaining<br>On the battlefield,<br>They placed Paṭācārā<br>In the position of a leader.<br>We will live<br>With three knowledges, without taints.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.11" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Caṇḍā:<br><br>Formerly I was unfortunate,<br>Without husband and without children,<br>Without friends, without relatives,<br>Without food, without clothing.<br><br>Taking a stick and a bowl,<br>I went begging from house to house,<br>Tormented by cold and heat,<br>For seven years I lived thus.<br><br>Then I saw a bhikkhunī<br>Receiving food and drink.<br>Going to her, I asked<br>For the going forth into homelessness.<br><br>Paṭācārā, compassionate,<br>Let me go forth,<br>Then instructed me,<br>Guiding me to the ultimate goal.<br><br>Having heard her words,<br>I followed her instruction.<br>The word of that noble nun<br>Was not in vain.<br>I attained the three knowledges,<br>I am without taints.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.12" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Paṭācārā:<br><br>You do not know the path,<br>Its coming or its going.<br>From where the son came,<br>You cry: 'My son!'.<br><br>You do not know the path,<br>Its coming or its going.<br>Why do you lament over it?<br>Such is the nature of beings.<br><br>Without being asked, from there he came,<br>Without permission, from here he goes.<br>From somewhere he came here,<br>He lived for a few days.<br><br>Passing away, that human form<br>Will wander on in saṃsāra.<br>Coming thus, going thus,<br>What lamentation is there here?<br><br>The dart, hard to see,<br>From my heart, drawn out:<br>She has removed the sorrow for my son,<br>The sorrow that obsessed me.<br><br>Now the dart is drawn out,<br>Without desire, at peace,<br>I go for refuge to the seer,<br>The Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Saṅgha.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Vāseṭṭhī:<br><br>I grieved for my son,<br>Suffering, with mind confused and mad.<br>Naked, with disheveled hair,<br>Thus I lived.<br><br>Wandering on roads, on rubbish heaps,<br>In charnel grounds, on cart tracks,<br>For three years I lived,<br>Enduring hardship, hunger, and thirst.<br><br>Then I saw the Well-Gone One,<br>Coming to Mithilā city,<br>The tamer of the untamed,<br>The Awakened One, fearless.<br><br>Having regained my composure,<br>I bowed down and approached.<br>Out of compassion, Gotama<br>Taught me the Dhamma.<br><br>Having heard his teaching,<br>I went forth into homelessness.<br>Following the Teacher's instruction,<br>I attained the secure path.<br><br>All sorrow is cut off,<br>Ended, destroyed.<br>I have understood the basis<br>From which sorrow arises.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.2" },
{ text: `Māra:<br>You are young and beautiful,<br>I am young and youthful.<br>With a five-piece orchestra,<br>Enjoy yourself, Khemā."<br><br>Elder Nun Khemā:<br><br>With this foul body,<br>Diseased and frail,<br>I am disgusted and reject it.<br>Sensual desire is uprooted.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>The aggregates are like a chopping block.<br>What you call sensual pleasure<br>I have now abandoned.<br><br>Everywhere, joy is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are defeated, O Death.<br><br>You worship the morning star!<br>You worship fire in the deep forest!<br>Not knowing the truth,<br>Fools think it pure.<br><br>But I bow down<br>To the Awakened One, the Supreme Person.<br>Freed from all suffering,<br>I follow the Teacher's instruction.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sujātā:<br><br>Adorned, wearing fine clothes,<br>Wearing garlands, anointed with sandalwood,<br>Wearing all kinds of ornaments,<br>Leading a troop of maidservants,<br><br>Carrying food and drink,<br>Many kinds of solid and soft foods,<br>Leaving home, I went out<br>To enjoy the park.<br><br>There I enjoyed myself,<br>Then I went back home.<br>I saw the monastery<br>When I entered the grove<br>Called Añjanā,<br>In the Sāketa region.<br><br>Seeing the light of the world,<br>I bowed and approached.<br>Out of compassion, the One with the Dhamma-eye<br>Taught me the Dhamma.<br><br>Having heard the great seer,<br>I penetrated the truth.<br>There I realized the Dhamma,<br>The dustless, the Deathless.<br><br>Through understanding the sublime Dhamma,<br>I went forth into homelessness.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>The Buddha's word is not in vain.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.4" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Anopamā:<br><br>Born in a high family,<br>With many jewels and riches,<br>Complete with beautiful complexion,<br>Majjha's beloved daughter.<br><br>Courted by a king's son,<br>Asked in marriage by a rich man's son,<br>Messengers came to my father:<br>'Give me Anopamā.'<br><br>The princess, your daughter,<br>Weigh her — how much is she worth?<br>I will give eight times<br>That amount in pure gold and jewels.<br><br>I saw the Awakened One,<br>The Blessed One, unsurpassed,<br>I bowed at his feet,<br>Approached and sat to one side.<br><br>Out of compassion, Gotama<br>Taught me the Dhamma.<br>Right there on that seat,<br>I attained the third fruit.<br><br>Then I shaved my hair,<br>Went forth into homelessness.<br>Today, on the seventh night,<br>Craving has been washed away.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mahāpajāpatī Gotamī:<br><br>Awakened One, hero!<br>I bow down to you,<br>You are the Supreme One<br>Among all beings.<br>You free me from suffering,<br>And many others as well.<br><br>Having fully understood all suffering,<br>Having cleansed the root of craving,<br>The Noble Eightfold Path,<br>I have realized cessation.<br><br>Formerly I was a mother,<br>A son, a father, a brother,<br>A grandfather, a grandmother —<br>Such were previous lives.<br>Not knowing the truth,<br>Wandering in saṃsāra, I found nothing.<br><br>Now I have seen the Blessed One,<br>This is my final body.<br>The round of birth and death is ended,<br>Now there is no more renewed existence.<br><br>Diligent, energetic, striving,<br>Always persistent, ardent,<br>Conquer the Buddha's disciples,<br>United, pay homage to him.<br><br>For the happiness of many,<br>Māyā gave birth to Gotama,<br>Dispelling the mass of suffering<br>For those afflicted by disease and death.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.6" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Guttā:<br><br>For the supreme goal,<br>Guttā, you went forth,<br>Abandoning even your children,<br>Down to your own self.<br>Practice ardently,<br>Do not let the mind control you.<br><br>The mind deceives beings,<br>Loving Māra's domain.<br>Through many lives,<br>They wander, deluded.<br><br>Sensual desire and ill-will,<br>Together with personality view,<br>Plus clinging to rites and rituals,<br>And doubt as the fifth.<br><br>O bhikkhunī,<br>Abandon these fetters,<br>These lower fetters,<br>You will not return to this life.<br><br>Avoid greed and conceit,<br>Ignorance and restlessness.<br>Having cut off the fetter of views,<br>You will end suffering.<br><br>Having abandoned the round of birth,<br>Having fully understood renewed existence,<br>Not longing for the present,<br>You will live at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.7" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Vijayā:<br><br>Four times and five times,<br>I left the monastery,<br>My mind was not at peace,<br>I could not subdue my mind.<br><br>I went to a bhikkhunī,<br>I asked, I discussed the Dhamma.<br>She taught me the Dhamma,<br>About the aggregates and sense spheres.<br><br>The Four Noble Truths,<br>About the faculties, the powers,<br>The factors of enlightenment, the eightfold path,<br>Attaining the supreme goal.<br><br>Having heard her instruction,<br>I followed her teaching.<br>In the first watch of the night,<br>I remembered my past lives.<br><br>In the middle watch,<br>My divine eye was purified.<br>In the last watch,<br>I shattered the mass of delusion.<br><br>From then on I lived,<br>Pervading my body with joy and bliss.<br>On the seventh night, I stretched my legs,<br>The mass of delusion was shattered.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.8" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Uttarā:<br><br>People in their youth,<br>Holding pestles, pounding rice,<br>Youths gain wealth,<br>Supporting their wives and children.<br><br>Follow the Buddha's teaching,<br>Do nothing that causes distress.<br>Wash your feet quickly,<br>Sit down to one side.<br><br>Having established the mind,<br>One-pointed, well concentrated,<br>Contemplate conditioned things,<br>External, not belonging to self.<br><br>I heard the instruction,<br>The words of Paṭācārā.<br>After washing my feet,<br>I entered and sat down to one side.<br><br>In the first watch of the night,<br>I remembered my past lives.<br>In the middle watch,<br>My divine eye was purified.<br><br>In the last watch,<br>I shattered the mass of delusion.<br>From the three knowledges, rising,<br>The instruction is done.<br><br>Like the lord Sakka<br>In the Thirty-three heaven,<br>Never defeated<br>On any battlefield,<br>I live, honoring you<br>As the teacher and leader.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>I am without taints.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 7.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig7.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Calā:<br><br>Having established mindfulness,<br>A bhikkhunī training the faculties,<br>Penetrates the peaceful path,<br>The peaceful bliss of conditioned things.<br><br>For whom are you shaven-headed,<br>Showing the sign of an ascetic nun?<br>Not following any sect,<br>Why do you live deluded?<br><br>The outside sects<br>Rely on wrong views.<br>They do not understand the true Dhamma,<br>They are not mature in the Dhamma.<br><br>Born in the Sakya clan,<br>The Buddha, the peerless one,<br>Taught me the Dhamma,<br>To overcome all wrong views.<br><br>He taught the Noble Eightfold Path,<br>About suffering, the origin of suffering,<br>About overcoming suffering,<br>And the path to the end of suffering.<br><br>Having heard the Buddha's words,<br>I live delighting in the teaching.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Everywhere, joy is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered!<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are defeated, O Death.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig7.2" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Upacālā:<br><br>Mindful, with the Dhamma-eye,<br>A bhikkhunī training the faculties,<br>Penetrates the peaceful path,<br>Practiced by the supreme person.<br><br>Why do you not like birth?<br>One born enjoys sensual pleasures.<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures,<br>Do not regret it later.<br><br>One who is born is subject to death,<br>Hands and feet are cut off,<br>Killed, bound, afflicted.<br>Afterwards, suffering comes.<br><br>Born in the Sakya clan,<br>The Buddha, the undefeated one,<br>Taught me the Dhamma,<br>To overcome birth.<br><br>He taught the Noble Eightfold Path,<br>About suffering, the origin of suffering,<br>About overcoming suffering,<br>And the path to the end of suffering.<br><br>Having heard his words,<br>I live delighting in the teaching.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Everywhere, joy is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are defeated, O Death.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig7.3" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sīsupacālā:<br><br>A bhikkhunī guarding virtue,<br>Well guarding the faculties,<br>Attains the peaceful path,<br>The pure nectar.<br><br>Time after time, existence after existence,<br>They are led and ruled by personality view.<br>They do not overcome personality view,<br>They wander in the round of birth and death.<br><br>The whole world is burning,<br>The whole world is blazing,<br>The whole world is in flames,<br>The whole world is shaking.<br><br>The Buddha taught me the Dhamma,<br>The unshaken, peerless Dhamma,<br>Served and practiced by the non-ordinary.<br>There my mind delights and rejoices.<br><br>Having heard his words,<br>I live delighting in the teaching.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Everywhere, joy is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are defeated, O Death.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 8.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig8.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Mother of Vaḍḍha:<br><br>Vaḍḍha, never fall<br>Into the realm of sensual desire,<br>My son, do not share<br>In continuous suffering.<br><br>Happiness is for the seer,<br>Without greed, doubt cut off,<br>Living cooled, subdued,<br>Without any taints.<br><br>That seer practices<br>The path to right view,<br>Ending suffering.<br>Vaḍḍha! Practice.<br><br>With confidence, the mother spoke<br>This goal for you.<br>Dear mother! I think that you<br>No longer have sensual desire.<br><br>Vaḍḍha! Whatever conduct — low, high, or middle —<br>Not even a little sensual desire is in me.<br><br>I have destroyed all taints,<br>Not heedless, meditating.<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>Done is the teaching.<br><br>Wonderful is my mother,<br>Encouraging, urging me,<br>With verses of truth,<br>Out of compassion.<br><br>I heard the mother's instruction,<br>The advice of my dear mother.<br>Moved, I practiced the Dhamma,<br>Attaining security from bondage.<br><br>I am energetic, diligent,<br>Day and night not lazy.<br>Well urged by my mother,<br>I attained supreme purity.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig9.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Kisā Gotamī:<br><br>Good friendship with a seer<br>Is praised throughout the world.<br>Associating with good friends,<br>A fool becomes wise.<br><br>Associate with genuine persons.<br>Associating thus, wisdom grows.<br>Associating with genuine persons,<br>All suffering is escaped.<br><br>Know the Four Noble Truths:<br>Suffering and the origin of suffering,<br>Know the cessation of suffering,<br>And the Noble Eightfold Path.<br><br>Woe to women's fate,<br>The Tamer of those to be tamed has said.<br>Woe to having a common husband,<br>Many [wives] born at once.<br><br>In painful throat-cutting,<br>A weak mother drinks poison.<br>When encountering childbirth,<br>She dies in labor.<br>Both mother and child<br>Meet with disaster.<br><br>While pregnant, going back and forth,<br>I saw my husband dead on the road.<br>And when I gave birth,<br>I could not return home.<br><br>Both children died,<br>The husband of that miserable woman<br>Also died on the road.<br>Mother, father, and brother<br>All were burned together<br>On a single funeral pyre.<br><br>O miserable woman,<br>Born into a pitiful family,<br>You have suffered<br>Immeasurable, endless pain.<br>The tears you have shed<br>Over many thousands of births.<br><br>I saw in the charnel ground<br>My child's flesh being eaten,<br>The family destroyed,<br>Despised by everyone,<br>Yet the one whose husband died<br>Attained the Deathless.<br><br>I developed the Noble Path,<br>The eightfold path, the Deathless.<br>I attained Nibbāna,<br>Saw the mirror of the Dhamma.<br><br>The dart implanted in me<br>Has been drawn out.<br>The burden is laid down,<br>What should be done is done.<br>I am the elder nun<br>Kisā Gotamī,<br>With mind well liberated —<br>I speak this in this life.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 10.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig10.1" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Sukkā:<br><br>O people of Rājagaha,<br>What have you done?<br>Like a person lying in a stupor,<br>Intoxicated by drinking honey!<br>You do not serve<br>Sukkā who speaks the Buddha's words.<br><br>We think the wise have drunk<br>The nectar water,<br>The truly pure stream,<br>Unobstructed by anything,<br>Like a traveler<br>Receiving rainwater from the sky.<br><br>O Sukkā! Child of light!<br>Free from greed, concentrated,<br>By the light of the true Dhamma,<br>Carry your final body,<br>Having seen the army of Death.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.6" },
{ text: `Māra:<br>You will not escape,<br>Not escape from this life.<br>What use is this seclusion practice to you?<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures,<br>Do not regret it later."<br><br>Elder Nun Selā:<br><br>Sensual pleasures are like swords and spears,<br>They cut my aggregates.<br>What you call the happiness of life,<br>Those sensual pleasures —<br><br>Today, those sensual pleasures<br>Are not attractive to me.<br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are Death, you are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.7" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Somā:<br><br>That state hard to attain,<br>Only sages attain it.<br>With two-finger wisdom, a woman —<br>How could she hope to attain it?<br><br>What does womanhood matter<br>When the mind is well concentrated,<br>When wisdom unfolds,<br>Rightly seeing the sublime Dhamma?<br><br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are Death, you are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.8" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Uppalavaṇṇā:<br><br>Two, mother and daughter,<br>We lived with one husband.<br>What you said stirred me deeply,<br>A truly rare situation, making hair stand on end.<br><br>Disgusting are sensual pleasures,<br>Impure, foul, full of thorns.<br>Here, mother and daughter,<br>We took one husband.<br><br>Seeing the danger in sensual pleasures,<br>Seeing seclusion as secure,<br>I went forth from Rājagaha,<br>Left home for homelessness.<br><br>I know my past lives,<br>My divine eye is purified,<br>I have knowledge of others' minds,<br>The divine ear is purified.<br><br>I have attained psychic power,<br>I have attained the destruction of taints,<br>I have attained the six direct knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>With mind well subdued,<br>Psychic power well developed,<br>I have attained the six direct knowledges,<br>Done is the Buddha's teaching.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>They cut my aggregates.<br>What you call the happiness of life,<br>Those sensual pleasures —<br><br>Today, those sensual pleasures<br>Are not attractive to me.<br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know thus, Evil One!<br>You are Death, you are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 11.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig11.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Puṇṇā:<br><br>In winter I carry water,<br>Always going down into the water.<br>I fear the punishments,<br>The reproaches of the ladies.<br><br>O brahmin, whom do you fear,<br>Always going down into the water,<br>With trembling hands and feet,<br>You must be suffering from extreme cold like that?<br><br>Do you know, O Puṇṇikā?<br>Why do you ask one who does good deeds,<br>One who has stopped<br>Evil, unwholesome deeds?<br><br>Whether young or old,<br>Whoever does cruel deeds,<br>That person, by sprinkling water,<br>Is freed from evil deeds.<br><br>Who told you this,<br>Fool to fool,<br>That by sprinkling water one is freed from evil deeds?<br><br>Then all frogs and turtles<br>Would go to heaven,<br>Also snakes and crocodiles,<br>And other water creatures.<br><br>Cattle butchers, pig butchers,<br>Fishermen, hunters,<br>Thieves, murderers,<br>And other evil-doers,<br>By sprinkling water,<br>Could escape their evil deeds.<br><br>If these rivers could wash away<br>The evil deeds you did before,<br>They would also wash away<br>The good deeds you did,<br>Leaving you empty.<br><br>Brahmin, for what reason do you fear<br>to go down into the water?<br>Do not do that thing,<br>Do not let the cold harm your skin.<br><br>I was following the wrong path,<br>You have directed me to the noble path.<br>O lady, I give you this water-soaked cloth.<br><br>Keep the cloth for yourself,<br>I do not want the cloth!<br>If you fear suffering,<br>If you do not like suffering,<br><br>Do not do evil deeds,<br>Openly or in secret.<br>If you do or will do<br>Evil deeds,<br><br>You will not escape suffering,<br>Even if you see it and run.<br>If you fear suffering,<br>If you do not like suffering,<br><br>Go for refuge to the Buddha,<br>Go for refuge to the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>Undertake the precepts,<br>You will receive benefit.<br><br>I go for refuge to the Buddha,<br>I go for refuge to the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>I undertake the precepts,<br>I will receive benefit.<br><br>Formerly I was a relative<br>Of the Brahmā clan,<br>Now I am truly a brahmin.<br>I have realized the three knowledges,<br>Fully possessed of Vedic knowledge,<br>Security has come to me,<br>My mind is cleansed.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 12.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig12.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Rohinī:<br><br>You showed me that this is an ascetic,<br>You woke me up that this is an ascetic.<br>You praised the ascetic,<br>Wishing to become a female ascetic.<br><br>You seek for the ascetic<br>Much food and drink.<br>O Rohinī, why do you cherish the ascetic?<br><br>They are lazy, dislike work,<br>Live on what others give,<br>They desire gain, love sweet things,<br>Why do you cherish the ascetic?<br><br>(Rohinī): "Dear father, for a long time now,<br>You have asked about the ascetic.<br>I will praise them —<br>Wise, virtuous, diligent.<br><br>They love work, not lazy,<br>They do the supreme work,<br>They abandon greed and hatred,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>The three roots of evil,<br>They sweep away, purify,<br>All evil deeds destroyed,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Their bodily conduct is pure,<br>Their verbal conduct is likewise,<br>Their mental conduct is pure,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Without defilement, liberated,<br>Like a clean conch shell,<br>Pure within, pure without,<br>Their virtue is spotless white,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Learned, bearing the Dhamma,<br>Living righteously,<br>They teach meaning and Dhamma,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Learned, bearing the Dhamma,<br>Living righteously,<br>One-pointed, mindful,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Walking far, mindful,<br>With wise, humble words,<br>They end suffering,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Leaving the village,<br>Not looking at anything,<br>They walk without expectation,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>Not seeking a treasury,<br>No storing, no hoarding,<br>They seek the final goal,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>They do not grasp money,<br>Do not grasp gold or silver,<br>They live in the present,<br>Therefore I cherish them.<br><br>From families, from countries,<br>They have gone forth from different places,<br>Yet they love and respect one another,<br>Therefore I cherish them."<br><br>O Rohinī, you are born in this family,<br>You bring happiness to our family,<br>You have faith in the Buddha, Dhamma, Saṅgha,<br>Your faith is keen.<br><br>You know this well,<br>It is the unsurpassed field of merit.<br>We also will have faith<br>In these ascetics,<br><br>This sacrifice established here<br>Is very great for us."<br>(Rohinī): "If you fear suffering,<br>If you do not like suffering,<br><br>Go for refuge to the Buddha,<br>Go for refuge to the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>Undertake the precepts,<br>You will gain happiness."<br><br>(Rohinī's father): "I go for refuge to the Buddha,<br>I go for refuge to the Dhamma and Saṅgha,<br>I undertake the precepts,<br>I will gain happiness.<br><br>Formerly I was only a relative of Brahmā,<br>Now I am truly a brahmin,<br>I have attained the three knowledges,<br>I am safe and secure,<br>I have realized the three Vedas,<br>I have bathed completely clean.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 13.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig13.2" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Subhā:<br><br>Formerly wearing a white robe,<br>I heard the true Dhamma taught.<br>Through not being heedless,<br>I directly knew the truth.<br><br>Therefore, regarding all sensual desires,<br>I have no great longing.<br>Seeing the fear in personality view,<br>I longed for seclusion.<br><br>Abandoning, I went forth —<br>My household wealth was not small.<br>Because the sublime Dhamma was well taught,<br>I left with faith.<br><br>I cannot long for<br>Anything connected with household wealth.<br>I have abandoned gold and silver —<br>Why would I go back to them?<br><br>Gold and silver do not awaken,<br>Do not make one peaceful,<br>Are not suitable for the ascetic's practice,<br>Are not a noble treasure.<br><br>This gold and silver itself<br>Causes greed and infatuation,<br>Makes people foolish,<br>Increases the dust of defilements,<br>Brings many dangers and distresses —<br>It is not lasting.<br><br>Here, people attached,<br>Heedless, with defiled minds,<br>Oppose each other as enemies,<br>Widely quarrel and fight.<br><br>Killing, binding, torturing,<br>Loss of wealth, sorrow, anxiety —<br>Those who sink in sensual desires<br>Meet many misfortunes.<br><br>Why do my relatives,<br>Like enemies to me,<br>Bind me in the circle of sensual desires?<br>Know that I went forth<br>Because I saw the danger in sensual desires.<br><br>Silver and gold cannot<br>Destroy the taints.<br>Sensual desires are enemies,<br>Murderers, specialists in killing,<br>They are foes, arrows, bonds.<br><br>Why do my relatives,<br>Like enemies to me,<br>Bind me in the circle of sensual desires?<br>Know that I went forth,<br>Shaved my head, put on the great robe.<br><br>Living on food accumulated from alms round,<br>Robes made from rags gathered —<br>Living thus is suitable for me,<br>The basis of homelessness.<br><br>Great seers abandon sensual desires,<br>Desires of devas and humans,<br>They abide secure, liberated,<br>Unshaken, blissful.<br><br>Do not let me go to sensual desires,<br>In sensual desires there is no safety.<br>Sensual desires are enemies, murderers,<br>They give suffering, like a blazing fire.<br><br>The path is perilous, full of fear,<br>Full of suffering, thorns,<br>The path of craving is rough,<br>Vast, leading to delusion.<br><br>Disaster, full of terror,<br>Sensual desires are like a snake's head.<br>Fools delight in sensual desires,<br>Blind ordinary people.<br><br>Beings sink in muddy water,<br>Those who do not see the world,<br>They do not know<br>The end of birth and death.<br><br>Because of sensual desires, people<br>Go to evil destinations.<br>Most go that way,<br>Making themselves diseased.<br><br>Thus sensual desires produce enmity,<br>They burn, defile,<br>They are material things,<br>They bind people to death.<br><br>Sensual desires make one mad,<br>Cause confused speech and wandering mind,<br>Defile beings,<br>About to fall into Māra's trap.<br><br>Sensual desires are endlessly dangerous,<br>Full of suffering, great poison,<br>Little sweetness, they create conflict,<br>They wither the bright day.<br><br>Thus I have decided —<br>I will not turn back for sensual desires,<br>Which cause misfortune,<br>Always delighting in Nibbāna.<br><br>I will fight against sensual desires,<br>Waiting, cooled, calm,<br>I will live heedfully,<br>Destroying the fetter of sensual desire.<br><br>I follow that path<br>By which the great seers have gone,<br>Sorrowless, stainless,<br>Secure, straight, the eightfold path.<br><br>See this Subhā,<br>Established in the true Dhamma,<br>The daughter of a goldsmith,<br>Attaining non-attachment to sensual desires,<br>Sitting practicing jhāna<br>At the foot of a tree.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 13.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig13.5" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā:<br><br>The daughter of King Koñca,<br>With the chief queen,<br>In Mātavatī,<br>Sumedhā was born.<br>Joyfully striving to practice<br>The Teacher's instruction.<br><br>Skilled in virtue, well taught,<br>Learned, well trained,<br>Following the Buddha's teaching,<br>She went to her parents and said:<br>'Please, mother and father,<br>Both of you, listen to me!<br><br>'I rejoice in Nibbāna,<br>Even the existence of devas<br>Is impermanent.<br>What value are sensual pleasures?<br>Empty, with little sweetness,<br>Their harm is great.<br><br>'Sensual pleasures are truly bitter,<br>Like the venom of a poisonous snake.<br>Only fools are infatuated<br>With such sensual pleasures.<br>Those who enjoy sensual pleasures<br>For a long time<br>Suffer the torments of hell,<br>Afflicted and harmed.<br><br>'Those who do evil deeds,<br>Those with evil minds,<br>Experience painful suffering<br>In the realm of misery.<br>Fools do not restrain<br>Body, speech, and mind.<br><br>'Fools of weak wisdom,<br>Do not think, do not decide,<br>Do not stop the origin of suffering<br>When the time for teaching comes,<br>Do not care to learn,<br>Do not realize the noble truths.<br><br>'These truths, dear mother,<br>The supreme Buddha taught.<br>Most beings<br>Do not understand those truths.<br>They delight in renewed existence,<br>Long to be born in heaven.<br><br>'Birth in heaven is not lasting,<br>Existence is impermanent.<br>Fools are not afraid,<br>They are always reborn.<br><br>'Falling into the four lower realms,<br>Being born in heaven or human realm —<br>Hard it is to be born there.<br>Those who fall into the lower realms,<br>Into the realm of hell,<br>Have no chance to go forth.<br><br>'Please, both mother and father,<br>Let me go forth<br>In the teaching proclaimed<br>By the One with Ten Powers,<br>Living at ease,<br>Striving to end birth and death.<br><br>'Why should I delight in renewed existence<br>With this sinful body,<br>Empty, without core?<br>For the purpose of destroying<br>The craving for renewed existence,<br>Please let me go forth.<br><br>'Now a Buddha has arisen,<br>The wrong time is abandoned.<br>The time has now come.<br>Throughout my life,<br>I will not injure the precepts and the holy life.'`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā (continued):<br><br>What is this foul body,<br>Stinking, causing fear,<br>A bag of dead flesh,<br>Oozing impure fluids?<br><br>What is this body I know,<br>Disgusting, covered with blood and flesh,<br>A dwelling for worms,<br>Food for birds?<br>This body is thus —<br>To whom would I give it now?<br><br>The body, left in a charnel ground,<br>Before long, without consciousness,<br>Like a discarded log,<br>Despised even by relatives.<br><br>That body, thrown in a charnel ground,<br>Becomes food for others.<br>Formerly they washed it clean,<br>Now they are disgusted by it.<br>Even parents are thus —<br>What to say of the crowd?<br><br>They are infatuated with a body without core,<br>Bound by sinews and bones,<br>Full of saliva, full of tears,<br>Full of foul excrement and urine.<br><br>If the body were cut open,<br>Turning the inside out,<br>Even the mother would be disgusted,<br>Unable to bear the stench.<br><br>It is through aggregates, sense spheres, and elements<br>That these bodies are formed,<br>The root of renewed existence, of suffering.<br>They rightly say<br>They have no delight at all.<br>Therefore, whom would I want to marry?<br><br>Every day, a hundred spears<br>Always stabbing the body anew,<br>Even if harmed for a hundred years —<br>That would still be better,<br>For that suffering would finally end.<br><br>The wise person would consent<br>To such killing as described above.<br>The Teacher taught that<br>They wander for a long time,<br>With a mind that kills,<br>Continuously, one after another.<br><br>In the realms of devas and humans,<br>Animals, asuras,<br>Ghosts, and hells,<br>They suffer countless killings.<br><br>In hell, many<br>With defiled minds, fallen,<br>Find no refuge in heaven,<br>No bliss of Nibbāna.<br><br>Those who attain Nibbāna<br>Are intimately connected<br>With the teachings<br>Of the One with Ten Powers,<br>Living at ease, not restless,<br>Striving to end birth and death.<br><br>Dear father, today<br>I am determined to leave.<br>Those empty possessions<br>Have no value at all.<br>I am disgusted with sensual desires,<br>I am weary of sensual desires.<br>They have been cut apart<br>Like a tāla palm trunk.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā (continued):<br><br>Even if the seventeen treasures<br>Filled all ten directions,<br>No sensual desire would be satisfied,<br>One dies unsatisfied.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>Sensual desires are like a snake's head,<br>Like a blazing torch,<br>Like a greasy bone.<br><br>Sensual desires are not lasting,<br>They are not permanent,<br>Much suffering, great poison,<br>Like a red-hot iron ball,<br>The source of misfortune,<br>Their result is suffering.<br><br>Sensual desires are like the fruit of a tree,<br>Like a piece of meat, they cause affliction,<br>Like a dream, like an illusion,<br>Sensual desires are like a loan.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords, like stakes,<br>Disease and boil,<br>Misfortune and agitation,<br>Like a pit of glowing coals,<br>The source of misfortune,<br>Fear and slaughter.<br><br>For a long time, fools<br>Have cried over the continuous round of birth,<br>From beginningless time,<br>Weeping over death,<br>Weeping over slain brothers,<br>Weeping over being slain themselves.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time,<br>Tears, milk, and blood<br>Flowing in saṃsāra,<br>Never ceasing.<br>Remember the beings<br>Wandering, heaping up bones.<br><br>Remember the four oceans<br>Filled with tears, milk, and blood.<br>Remember the bones of one aeon<br>Heaped as high as Vepulla.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time,<br>There would not be enough<br>In all the land of Jambudīpa<br>To make date-stone sized mounds<br>For the mothers and fathers of saṃsāra.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time,<br>The grasses, trees, branches, and leaves<br>Would not suffice to hold<br>The four-finger-sized pots<br>Containing the fathers of saṃsāra.<br><br>Remember the image<br>Of the blind turtle in the eastern sea,<br>Putting its head through<br>The hole in a floating yoke —<br>This simile illustrates<br>How hard it is to be born human.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1" },
{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā (continued):<br><br>Remember the human body<br>Is compared to a water bubble,<br>Full of all kinds of misfortunes,<br>Empty, without core.<br>See the aggregates as impermanent!<br>Remember the many dangers of hell.<br><br>Remember the great charnel ground<br>Due to continued renewed existence,<br>Remember the fear of crocodiles,<br>Remember the Four Noble Truths.<br><br>The water of the Deathless is here —<br>Why drink a hundred bitter things?<br>All sensual pleasures<br>Are truly a thousand times bitter.<br><br>The water of the Deathless is here —<br>Why delight in the fever of sensual desires?<br>All sensual pleasures burn,<br>They bubble and seethe.<br><br>Here there is no enemy!<br>Why delight in enemy-like sensual desires?<br>The fire of kings, thieves, water, and hatred —<br>Common enemies are many.<br><br>Here there is liberation!<br>Why let sensual desires kill and bind you?<br>In sensual desires there is killing and binding!<br>Infatuated with sensual desires, much suffering.<br><br>A grass torch is blazing.<br>If you hold it and do not let go, you are burned.<br>Sensual desires are like a torch,<br>They burn whoever does not escape.<br><br>Do not accept small pleasures,<br>Abandoning great, widespread pleasures.<br>Do not be like a fish swallowing a hook,<br>Only to suffer misfortune later.<br><br>Subdue the desire within desire,<br>Like a dog tied with a rope.<br>Do not let desire eat you,<br>Like hungry people eat a dog.<br><br>Suffering is truly immeasurable,<br>It makes the mind very anxious.<br>You are attached to sensual desires —<br>Abandon impermanent sensual desires.<br><br>Here there is no aging!<br>Why follow sensual desires that age?<br>Everywhere, all beings<br>Are ruled by disease and death.<br><br>Here there is no aging, no death.<br>This is the path without aging,<br>Without death, without sorrow,<br>Without enmity, without bonds,<br>Without stumbling, without fear,<br>Without burning, without banishment.<br><br>This goal many have attained,<br>This goal is the Deathless.<br>Now it must be realized.<br>Whoever attends wisely —<br>Without effort,<br>One cannot attain it.<br><br>This is the cause, the source,<br>This is the very root:<br>Enduring the Teacher's instruction!<br>This is the first step.<br>That is Nibbāna,<br>If we love the Dhamma.<br><br>Thus with faith,<br>They spoke these words,<br>Words full of wisdom,<br>Supreme and excellent.<br>They are disgusted with renewed existence,<br>Through disgust, craving is destroyed.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1" },
            

         
        ];

       module.exports = { SuttaQuotesData };